<HEAD>LEGENDS OF SAINTS IN MS. LAUD 108.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="10" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>10 Sancta crux<NOTE PLACE="foot">This legend, which is counted as 10th in the MS. 1s preceded by (1) a poem on the Life and Passion of Christ (wanting the beginning and end), ed. by me under the title of 'Leben Iesu, ein Fragment,' M&uuml;nster, Regensberg, 1873, and (2) by a poem on the Infancy of Christ, ed. in 'Altengl. Legenden,' Paderborn, 1875, pp. 1-61. Eight pieces, therefore, are lost before the legend of the Holy Rood.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E holie rode i-founde was : ase ich eov nou&thorn;e may telle.<MILESTONE N="23" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Costantyn &thorn;e Aumperour : muche he&thorn;ene folk gan a-quelle,</L>
<L>For huy ore louerd iesu crist : to strongue de&thorn;e brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e he&thorn;ene men &thorn;at nei&yogh; him were : sone he dude to nou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Eleyne, &thorn;at was is moder : to Ierusalem he sende</L>
<L>to sechen after &thorn;e holie rode : and heo gladliche forth i-wende.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo cam &thorn;udere, heo liet crie : ase heo hire red hadde i-nome,</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;at alle &thorn;e giwes of &thorn;e cite : bifore hire scholden come.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e giwes i-somoned were : huy hadden grete fere;</L>
<L>gret conseil huy nomen &thorn;are-of : &yogh;wat &thorn;e enchesoun were.</L>
<L>&THORN;o seide on, &thorn;at hiet Iudas : "Ich wene &thorn;at ich wot</L>
<L N="12">&YOGH;wat &thorn;is somunce a-mounti schal : &yogh;if &thorn;at ich ou telle mot.</L>
<L>Ich wene &thorn;at &thorn;e quene enqueri wole : ase heo hadde i-&thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;e rode &thorn;at Iesu crist : to de&thorn;e was on i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;at non of eov ne beo so wod : &thorn;at &thorn;are-of a-knowe beo!</L>
<L N="16">In conseil ich eov telle wole : &thorn;at mi fader tolde me.</L>
<L>&THORN;o mi fade<SUP>r</SUP> symeon : in is de&thorn;e vuele lay,</L>
<L>In conseile he was to me a-knowe : &thorn;o he &thorn;ene dez on him i-sai&yogh;:</L>
<L>" 'Iudas,' he seide, 'leoue sone : &yogh;if hit bi-tidez so</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at men enquerieth aftur &thorn;e rode : &thorn;at Iesus was on ido,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at &thorn;ov beo a-knowe &thorn;are-of : are men &thorn;e aquelle!</L>
<L>&THORN;at Zachee, mi fader, tolde : in conseile ich &thorn;e telle;</L>
<L>A luyte bifore is de&thorn;e he seide me : &thorn;at he was at&thorn;e dede</L>
<L>to burie &thorn;e rode op-on Caluarie hulle : ase huy nomen heom to rede.
<PB REF="00000050.tif" N="2"></L>
<L>Leoue fader, ich seide &thorn;o : &yogh;wat eilede eov, alas,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wy wolde &yogh;e him to de&thorn;e do : &yogh;wane he so guod was?</L>
<L>he seide &thorn;at &thorn;oru&yogh; him it nas nou&yogh;t : ake for &thorn;at he with-sede</L>
<L N="28">Mine felawes of heore lawe : huy duden him to de&thorn;e,</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e in sepulchre leiden him : and he a-ros to liue</L>
<L>Fram de&thorn;e &thorn;ene &thorn;ridde day : Mid is woundene fiue,</L>
<L>&THORN;ene fourteo&thorn;e dai &thorn;are-Afterward : to heouene he wende an hei&yogh;</L>
<L N="32">In &thorn;e londe of Galilee : &thorn;at muche folk it i-sei&yogh;;</L>
<L>Twelf Mon&thorn;e it was &thorn;are-afterward : and half &yogh;er and more</L>
<L N="34">&THORN;at Steuene, &thorn;at [was] mi bro&thorn;ur : prechede of is lore,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Giwes him ladden with-oute &thorn;e toun : and &thorn;reowen him with stones</L>
<L>And &thorn;are-with brou&yogh;ten him to de&thorn;e : and debruysden alle is bones;</L>
<L>&THORN;ene Morewe aftur Midewinter day : to de&thorn;e huy him brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And nou&thorn;e he is in &thorn;e blisse of heuene : and &thorn;at he wel deore a|bou&yogh;te.' "</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o Iudas hadde &thorn;is tale i-told : &thorn;e giwes seiden, ase huy stode:</L>
<L N="40">"Neuer er ne heorde we telle : &thorn;us muche of &thorn;e rode."</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e tyme icome was, : bi-fore &thorn;e quyene huy come.</L>
<L>"Cheoseth," seide &thorn;e Quiene a-non : "on of &thorn;is tweie domes;</L>
<L>Lijf and deth eov is bi-fore : cheosez &yogh;we&thorn;ur &yogh;e wolle:</L>
<L N="44">bote &yogh;e me bringue &thorn;e holie rode : echone brenne &yogh;e schulle."</L>
<L>gret fuyr heo liet makie : ri&yogh;t bi-fore hore ei&yogh;en.<MILESTONE N="23b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e giwes bi-gonne to crien loude : &thorn;o huy &thorn;at fuyr i-sei&yogh;en,</L>
<L>And seiden : "&yogh;if any man &thorn;are-of wot : &thorn;anne wot Iudas,</L>
<L N="48">For Zachee, is fader fader : of swy&thorn;e gret power was</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke tyme &thorn;at Iesus : was op-on &thorn;e rode i-do."</L>
<L>&THORN;o liet &thorn;e Quiene nime Iudas : and alle &thorn;e o&thorn;ere he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">= heo</NOTE> liet go,</L>
<L N="51">And bad him beo a-knowe a-non. : he nolde for no &thorn;retningue.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Quiene him liet wel faste binde : and in strongue prisone bringue.</L>
<L>With-oute mete and drinke : &thorn;are seue dawes he lay;</L>
<L>For strong hounguer he criede loude : &thorn;ene seuen&thorn;e day</L>
<L>And seide : "bringueth me out of &thorn;is wo : and ich eov [wole]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> lede</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;are ich wene &thorn;at &thorn;e rode beo : ase mi fader me seide."</L>
<L>&THORN;o he out of prisone cam : with muche folk he wende</L>
<L>to &thorn;e place &thorn;are &thorn;e rode was : ase is fader him kende.
<PB REF="00000051.tif" N="3"></L>
<L>&THORN;o he to &thorn;e place cam : a-doun he sat a-kneo:</L>
<L N="60">"Louerd," he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. heo</NOTE> seide, "&yogh;if it is soth : &thorn;at &thorn;ou man and god beo</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ou of Marie were i-bore : siend us &thorn;ine grace,</L>
<L>Som tokningue, &thorn;at we finde mowe &middot; &thorn;e rode in &thorn;is place."</L>
<L>A-non so Iudas &thorn;is bone hadde : to ore louerd i-bede,</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;e hul bi-gan to quakien : and out of one stude</L>
<L>A smoke &thorn;are cam and wende an hei&yogh; : and muche place fulde&mdash;</L>
<L>Swottore &thorn;ing nas neuere non : &thorn;ane &thorn;at smoke<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. smake</NOTE> smulde.</L>
<L>&thorn;o Iudas &thorn;is i-sei&yogh; : loude he gan to crie :</L>
<L N="68">"Iesus is on Almi&yogh;ti god : i-bore he was of &thorn;e maydene Marie!</L>
<L>he is wod &thorn;at ani o&thorn;ur bi-leuez : ase ich habbe mani a day.</L>
<L>Taken ichulle cristin-dom : ich for-sake here &thorn;e giwene lay."</L>
<L>he liet him cristni hasteliche : and &thorn;o he icristned was,</L>
<L N="72">He liet him nenne Quiriac : &thorn;at erore hiet Iudas.</L>
<L>&THORN;o nomen huy spade and schouele : and ner &thorn;e place wende</L>
<L>And bi-gonne forto deluen deope : &thorn;are ase &thorn;e smoke out kende.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at huy founden roden &thorn;reo : &thorn;o huy hadden i-dolue longue:</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;e rode &thorn;at god was on ido : and &thorn;at &thorn;e tweie &thorn;eoues weren on an|honge</L>
<L>bi-side ore louerd, him for-to schiende. : &thorn;o nusten huy of &thorn;e &thorn;reo</L>
<L>&THORN;o holie croyz &thorn;at huy sou&yogh;ten : &yogh;wich it mi&yogh;te beo.</L>
<L>Na&thorn;eles huy nomen alle &thorn;reo : and toward toune heom bere</L>
<L N="80">To Dame Heleyne, &thorn;e guode Quene : with wel glade chere.</L>
<L>bi &thorn;e weye ase huy comen : men gonne a-&yogh;ein heom bringue</L>
<L N="82">A ded &yogh;ong man ope one bere : toward bure&yogh;ingue.</L>
<L>Quiriac nam &thorn;at o rode : and efft-sone &thorn;at o&thorn;ur,</L>
<L>And leide op-on &thorn;at dede man : ake he ne a-ros for no&thorn;ur.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde huy leide op-on him : and he a-ros wel bliue</L>
<L>And &thorn;onkede &yogh;eorne godes sone : &thorn;at fram de&thorn;e him brou&yogh;te to liue.</L>
<L>&THORN;o cam &thorn;e deouel &yogh;eollinde forth : loude he gan to grede:</L>
<L N="88">"Alas, nou&thorn;e [is] mi power idon : eueref[t] more," he sede;</L>
<L>"Iesus, Iesus, &yogh;wat, &thorn;enxt &thorn;ou : al folk to &thorn;e lede?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hauest here men to warde i-&yogh;iue : &thorn;ing &thorn;at ich mest drede,<MILESTONE N="24" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; &yogh;wan ich was furst ouer-come : ake nou&thorn;e ich am al at grounde.</L>
<L N="92">Alas &thorn;ulke soruwe : &thorn;at heo euere was i-founde!</L>
<L>For i-ne habbe power non so gret : on eor&thorn;e a-mong manne,
<PB REF="00000052.tif" N="4"></L>
<L>&YOGH;if man fourmeth enes &thorn;e croyz : a-non &thorn;at i-ne mot &thorn;anne.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore ich wot &thorn;at euerech man : wole nou &thorn;e so&thorn;e i-se</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;at &thorn;e croiz me hauez ouer-come : and al bi-leue me.</L>
<L>Allas, alas &thorn;e time, i sei&yogh;e : al ich wor&thorn;e nou&thorn;e for-sake!</L>
<L>Iudas, Iudas, &yogh;wat was &thorn;e : hou hauest &thorn;ou on i-take?</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; A Iudas, &thorn;at was &yogh;wilene : Iesus to de&thorn;e ich brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="100">And nov &thorn;oru&yogh; Iudas ouer-come ich am : and i-brou&yogh;t to nou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Strenc&thorn;e ne worth me neuereft non : bote ani man wolle with wille</L>
<L>Serui me to paye is flesch : is soule for-to spille;</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;e mi strenc&thorn;e is me bi-nome : fondi ich mot with ginne</L>
<L N="104">And with traisun, &yogh;if ich mai : ani man to me i-winne.</L>
<L>I-ne may here no leng bi-leue : for &thorn;is me &thorn;inchez longue;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e creoiz &thorn;at me is so nei&yogh; : in pine ich am ful strongue."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IVdas seide: "go heonne anon : and ne cum<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. ne cum he cum</NOTE> here non-more!</L>
<L N="108">I-founde is, &thorn;ei it late beo : &thorn;at schal ouer-come al &thorn;i lore.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at haueth here &thorn;is dede man : fram de&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t to liue,</L>
<L>Pulte &thorn;e and &thorn;i pouwer al : into helle grounde bliue."</L>
<L>Muche was &thorn;e Ioye of &thorn;e croyz : &thorn;at men maden &thorn;o &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>With gret song and with processioun : to &thorn;e Quiene huy hire bere.</L>
<L>&THORN;o nam Iudas cristindom : and &thorn;o he ibaptized was,</L>
<L N="114">he liet him cleopien Quiriac : &thorn;at erore hiet Iudas.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Quiene of seluer and of gold : one riche schrine heo wrou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And deorewurthe &yogh;imstones : and &thorn;e Rode &thorn;are-inne<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. innne</NOTE> heo brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Op-on &thorn;e hulle of caluarie : &thorn;are huy &thorn;e rode founde,</L>
<L N="118">A noble churche heo dude a-rere : I-hered beo &thorn;ulke stounde!</L>
<L>&THORN;o wilnede &thorn;e Quene muche : After &thorn;e nayles &thorn;reo</L>
<L N="120">&YOGH;ware-with ore louerd was : inailed to &thorn;e treo.</L>
<L>Quiriac, &thorn;at hiet er Iudas : wende to &thorn;e place</L>
<L>&THORN;are ase &thorn;e croiz i-founde was : and bad ore louerdes grace,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he, &yogh;if is wille were : &thorn;e &thorn;re Nailes him sende.</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;e Nailes with li&yogh;tingue gret : op of &thorn;e eor&thorn;e wenden.</L>
<L>Quiriac &thorn;onkede Ihesu crist : and with gret Ioye heom nam,</L>
<L>And bi-tok heom heleyne, &thorn;e guode Quene : &thorn;o he to hire cam.</L>
<L>&THORN;us was &thorn;e holie Rode i-founde : &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day of May,</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;at we holdez in holi churche : &thorn;e holie rode-day.
<PB REF="00000053.tif" N="5"></L>
<L>Quiriac, &thorn;at &thorn;e rode fond : seth&thorn;e bischop was&mdash;</L>
<L>he is nou&thorn;e in heouene seint Quiriac : &thorn;at erore hiet Iudas.</L>
<L>bi-seche we &thorn;e holie croiz : &thorn;at brou&yogh;te &thorn;ane Deuel to grounde,</L>
<L>And seint Quiriac and seinte heleyne : &thorn;oru&yogh; &yogh;wam heo was i-founde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy bi-sechen him for us : &thorn;at on &thorn;e Rode schedde is blod,</L>
<L N="134">&THORN;at we moten to &thorn;e Ioye come : of heuene &thorn;at is so guod.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Orou&yogh; a treo we weren fur-lore : and furst i-brou&yogh;t to grounde,<MILESTONE N="24b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;oru&yogh; a treo to liue i-brou&yogh;t : i-hered beo &thorn;ulke stounde!</L>
<L>Al it<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. A lit</NOTE> cam of one more : &thorn;at us to de&thorn;e brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at us brou&yogh;te to liue a-&yogh;en : &thorn;oru Iesus &thorn;at us bou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Appel-treo &thorn;at ore furste fader : &thorn;ane Appel of nam,</L>
<L N="140">In &thorn;e manere &thorn;at ich ov telle wole : &thorn;e swete rode cam.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Adam, ore furste fader : &thorn;e sunne hadde i-do,</L>
<L>I-driue he was out of parays : and eue, is wijf, also.</L>
<L>Aftur milce &yogh;eorne he cride : &thorn;ei it to late were.</L>
<L N="144">For one bi-heste &thorn;at he of ore louerd hadde : &thorn;o &thorn;e Aungel him drof out &thorn;ere:</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &yogh;wane &thorn;e time were fol-fuld : ore louerd him wolde bi-&thorn;enche</L>
<L>And with Oyle of milce smeorien him : and is sunnes a-quenche;</L>
<L>gret hope hadde Adam to his bi-heste : &thorn;ere-after euere-mo,</L>
<L N="148">Ase he in &thorn;e ualeye of Ebron : leouede with teone and wo.</L>
<L>Twei sones he hadde : &thorn;at hei&yogh;ten Caym and Abel;</L>
<L>For onde &thorn;e on a-slou&yogh; &thorn;at o&thorn;ur : ase &yogh;e i-wuten it wel.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Caym hadde is bro&thorn;er a-slawe : i-flemd he was &thorn;are-fore.</L>
<L N="152">And &thorn;o Adam i-sai&yogh; &thorn;at he hadde : beie is sones for-lore,</L>
<L>he weop and made deol i-nou&yogh; : "louerd," he seide, "&thorn;in ore!</L>
<L>Nei&yogh; womman ich habbe to muche i-beo : i-nelle nei&yogh; hire come non|more.</L>
<L>&THORN;reo harmes ich habbe for hire <SUP>i</SUP>-haued : mi-sulf furst for-lore,</L>
<L>And nou&thorn;e mine sones, a weilawei! : and of alle womman<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. wommen</NOTE> is more."</L>
<L>&THORN;o nolde Adam come nei&yogh; is wijf : to hundrede &yogh;er and more,</L>
<L N="158">For wo &thorn;at he hadde for hire i-haued : euere he liuede in sore.</L>
<L>Of ore louerd he hadde tockningue seth&thorn;e : &thorn;at he scholde to is wiue wiende;</L>
<L>&THORN;o ne dorste he nou&yogh;t &thorn;are-a&yogh;ein beo. : a child he hadde at&thorn;enende,</L>
<L>Seth: he liet it cleopie : and seth&thorn;e he hadde mo.
<PB REF="00000054.tif" N="6"></L>
<L N="162">Al is lijf &thorn;e selie man : leouede in teone and wo.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he was of Nin houndret &yogh;er : and to and &thorn;ritti old,</L>
<L N="164">&THORN;e strenc&thorn;e him failede in is limes : is bodi bi-cam al cold;</L>
<L>he ne mi&yogh;te nou&yogh;t a-boute &thorn;e eor&thorn;e swinke : ne &thorn;e weodes up drawe;</L>
<L>Of is lijf he was a-nuyd : and wolde beo ded wel fawe.</L>
<L>he sat and carede of is lijf : he cleopede is sone Seth:</L>
<L N="168">"leoue sone," he seide, "ich am weri of leoued : and wilni muche mi dez.</L>
<L>&THORN;o ich was out of parays idriue : ore louerd bi-hiet me &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>With eoyle of milce to smeorie me : &yogh;wane it time were.</L>
<L>So longue ich habbe &thorn;are abede : &thorn;at i-ne may libbe more;</L>
<L N="172">to parays &thorn;ov most &thorn;are-aftur go : and bidde him milce and ore.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Aungel &thorn;ov schalt &thorn;are finde : &thorn;at drof me fram &thorn;e &yogh;ate;</L>
<L>Seie, ich abide &thorn;ulke bi-heste : and me &thorn;inchez it comez to late,</L>
<L>And seie, elde me hath ouer-come : &thorn;at I-ne may libbe longue,</L>
<L N="176">bide him &thorn;at ich dei&yogh;e mote : and &thorn;e eoyle of milce a-fongue."</L>
<L>"I-ne can nanne wei," quath is sone : "&thorn;uder-ward, ase ich wene."</L>
<L>"Leoue sone," Adam seide : "&thorn;e wei is wel i-sene.</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane &thorn;ou comest to &thorn;e heued of &thorn;is valeie : a grene wei &thorn;ov schalt wiende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at gez euene ri&yogh;t puyr est : and to parays gez &thorn;at on ende;<MILESTONE N="25" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;are-forth comen &thorn;i moder an ich : &thorn;o ich parays for-liet:</L>
<L N="182">Euerech stape &thorn;at we stepen : for-barnde onder ore fet;</L>
<L>Ne mi&yogh;te &thorn;are neuere-eft gras on growe : and al &thorn;e wei elles is grene;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e foule sunnes &thorn;at we duden : ore stapen beoth euere i-sene.</L>
<L>&THORN;are &thorn;ov mi&yogh;t with-oute faille : to parays euene gon."</L>
<L N="186">Seth nam is fader blessingue : and wende him forth a-non.</L>
<L>&THORN;e stapen he fond for-welewede : ase is fader him sede.</L>
<L N="188">&THORN;o he to &thorn;e &yogh;ate cam, : he ne dorste gon in for drede.</L>
<L>An Aungel cam sone to<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. te?</NOTE> [&thorn;e] &yogh;ate : and axede &yogh;wat he sou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>he seide &thorn;at one ti&thorn;ingue to him : fram is fader he brou&yogh;te:</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wes old and weri of leoued : and &thorn;at he was of-longued sore</L>
<L>After &thorn;e bi-heste &thorn;at him was bi-hote : for he ne mi&yogh;te libbe non-more.</L>
<L>&para; "&YOGH;e," seide &thorn;e Aungel, "is he so? : he ne schal &thorn;arof nou&yogh;t doute.</L>
<L N="194">pult in &thorn;in heued here at&thorn;e &yogh;ate : and stond &thorn;i-sulf with-oute!"</L>
<L>So gret deli&yogh;t he hadde and Ioye : of &thorn;e foulene murie song;
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="7"></L>
<L>A grene he i-sai&yogh; of grete swotnesse : and faire flovres &thorn;are among,</L>
<L>Ech manere fruyt &thorn;are he i-sai&yogh; : &thorn;at smulde al-so wel swote:</L>
<L N="198">him &thorn;ou&yogh;te of eche manere vuel : Aman mi&yogh;te habbe is bote;</L>
<L>him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, &yogh;if he moste &thorn;ere : bi-holden In anie stounde,</L>
<L N="200">he mi&yogh;te euere in Ioye libbe : and is limes beon hole and sounde.</L>
<L>A-midde &thorn;e place, &thorn;at was so fair : he sai&yogh; a swi&thorn;e fair welle,</L>
<L>Fram &yogh;wam alle &thorn;e wateres on eor&thorn;e comiez : ase &thorn;e boc us dez telle.</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;e welle &thorn;are stod a treo : with bowes brode and lere,</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;are nas opon no&thorn;ur lief ne rinde : bote ase it for-oldet were;</L>
<L>An Addre it hadde bi-clupt a-boute : al naked with-oute skinne&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;at treo and &thorn;e Naddre : &thorn;at made Adam don furst<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. &thorn;e</NOTE> sunne.</L>
<L>he bi-heold In &thorn;are-ate eft-sone : &thorn;at treo him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he sei&yogh;</L>
<L N="208">Faire i-leued and i-woxe : op to &thorn;e heouene an hei&yogh;,</L>
<L>On ouewarde he i-sai&yogh; a luyte &yogh;ong child : in smale clo&thorn;es i-wounde,</L>
<L N="210">&THORN;e More of &thorn;e treo, ase him &thorn;ou&yogh;te : tilde into helle grounde;</L>
<L>Abeles soule is bro&thorn;er al-so : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he [&thorn;er] i-sei&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;o drof &thorn;e Aungel him fram &thorn;e &yogh;ate : &thorn;at he ne moste mor come so nei&yogh;.</L>
<L>"&THORN;at child," quath &thorn;e Aungel, "&thorn;at &thorn;ou i-sei&yogh;e : an hei&yogh; opon &thorn;e treo,</L>
<L>Godes sone<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. sone sone</NOTE> it was, &thorn;at on eor&thorn;e : for &thorn;ine fader sunnes wole beo</L>
<L>And bringue with him &thorn;e eoyle of milce : &yogh;wane &thorn;e tyme ifuld is,</L>
<L N="216">to smeorie &thorn;are-with and bringe of pine : &thorn;ine fader and alle his."</L>
<L>&THORN;o wende &thorn;e Aungel to &thorn;ulke treo : Ane Appel &thorn;are-of he nam</L>
<L>And bi-tok Seth &thorn;reo curneles &thorn;ar-of : &thorn;o he to him cam,</L>
<L>And bad him legge &thorn;ulke kurneles : onder is fader toungue</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane he were ded, and burien him : and lokie &yogh;wat &thorn;arof sprongue.</L>
<L>&para; Seth wende hamward ase he cam : &thorn;e wei was wel i-sene,</L>
<L N="222">For he isei&yogh; &thorn;e stapen &thorn;at weren i-brende : and &thorn;at o&thorn;ur wei was al grene.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he was i-comen hom a&yogh;en : his fader he fond ded.</L>
<L>he dude &thorn;e curneles onder is toungue : ase &thorn;e Aungel him hadde i-sed,</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e he burede him in &thorn;e valeie of Ebron : ase it was ri&yogh;t to don,<MILESTONE N="25b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And of-swonk is owene mete : &thorn;o he nuste non o&thorn;ur won.</L>
<L>In A fewe &yogh;er &thorn;are-Aftur-ward : &thorn;e curneles bi-gunne springe,</L>
<L N="228">&THORN;reo smale &yogh;erdene &thorn;are woxen of : faire &thorn;oru&yogh; alle &thorn;ingue.</L>
<L>&THORN;o huy weren i-woxe in leng&thorn;e : of one Elne, ich wene,
<PB REF="00000056.tif" N="8"></L>
<L>In &thorn;ulke stat huy stoden longue &thorn;are : and euere-more grene,</L>
<L>A-non for-to Moyses &thorn;e profete : &yogh;eode &thorn;are in londe,</L>
<L N="232">to lede &thorn;at folk of Israel. : and &thorn;o he fond &thorn;e &yogh;erdene stonde,</L>
<L>"lo here," he seide, "gret bi-tokningue : of &thorn;e holie trinite,</L>
<L>Of fader and sone and holie gost : bi &thorn;eose &yogh;eorde &thorn;reo."</L>
<L>he tok hem op with gret honour : and in faire clo&thorn;e heom wond&mdash;</L>
<L N="236">A suote smul &thorn;are cam of heom : &thorn;at smelde in-to Al &thorn;at lond.</L>
<L>to confermi &thorn;e bet is lawe : he bar heom forth on is hond;</L>
<L>Ech sick man &thorn;at heom A-nourede : is hele a-non he fond.</L>
<L>to techen is folk &thorn;e ri&yogh;te lawe : &thorn;e &yogh;eordene with him he ber,</L>
<L N="240">And for-to hele sike men : to and fourti &yogh;er.</L>
<L>Seth&thorn;e &thorn;o he dei&yogh;e scholde : &thorn;e &yogh;eordene he sette er</L>
<L>Onder &thorn;e hulle of Tabor : and deide him-suluen &thorn;er.</L>
<L>&THORN;are stoden &thorn;is &yogh;eordene grene : more &thorn;ane a &thorn;ousend &yogh;er,</L>
<L N="244">Forto seint Daui &thorn;e kyng cam : &thorn;at was of so gret power.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he was &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e holie gost : i-hote forto hi&yogh;e</L>
<L>To &thorn;e hulle of Tabor : in &thorn;e londe of Arabie,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he &thorn;ulke &yogh;eordene &thorn;reo : fette and with him nome.</L>
<L N="248">Nie dawes he was &thorn;uder-ward : are he &thorn;udere come.</L>
<L>With gret honur he nam heom op : &thorn;o he &thorn;e &yogh;eordene<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &yogh;eordere</NOTE> fond&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e swotnesse &thorn;at &thorn;arof cam : fulde al &thorn;at lond.</L>
<L>With grete melodie of is harpe : seint Daui &thorn;e &yogh;eordene nam</L>
<L N="252">And ladde heom to Ierusalem : &thorn;ene Nyn&thorn;e day hom he cam.</L>
<L>In a priue stude he heom sette : ase it was in &thorn;e eueningue,</L>
<L>For-to a-morewe, &thorn;at he i-sei&yogh;e : &yogh;wodere he mi&yogh;te heom bet bringue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A-Morewe, &thorn;o he cam &thorn;er-to : to one huy weren alle i-come,</L>
<L N="256">and weren i-morede suy&thorn;e faste : &thorn;at huy ne mi&yogh;ten beo op i-nome.</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy weren so alle to one i-woxe : &yogh;wat bi-toknede &thorn;is</L>
<L>bote &thorn;e fader and sone and &thorn;e holie gost : &thorn;at al o god it is?</L>
<L>Seint Daui a-boute &thorn;is holie &yogh;eorde : a strong wal he liet a-rere,</L>
<L N="260">And nam guode &yogh;eme hov longue it woxe : fram &yogh;ere to &yogh;ere:</L>
<L>With a bei&yogh; of seoluer he bond : eche &yogh;eres schute &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he mi&yogh;te at&thorn;e laste i-wite : hou old &thorn;at treo were.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at with-Inne &thorn;ritti &yogh;er : &thorn;is treo wax wel on hei&yogh;;</L>
<L N="264">hit ne wax &thorn;o none more : and<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. ase</NOTE> he wust wel bi &thorn;e seluerne bei&yogh;;
<PB REF="00000057.tif" N="9"></L>
<L>Ake euere-more<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. mon</NOTE> &thorn;are-Aftur-ward : fair and grene it stod.</L>
<L>Seint Daui it honourede muche : for he wuste &thorn;at it was guod.</L>
<L>&THORN;o<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;at</NOTE> seint Daui hadde i-wrou&yogh;t : &thorn;e sunne of lecherie</L>
<L N="268">And man-slau&yogh;t, &thorn;o for is owene wijf : he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;at</NOTE> het slen vrie,</L>
<L>And ore louerd nam &thorn;ar-of wreche : swi&thorn;e sori he bi-cam,</L>
<L N="270">Onder &thorn;at treo is penaunce he dude : &thorn;at he &thorn;are-fore nam.<MILESTONE N="26" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;o makede he &thorn;ere &thorn;ene sauter : is sunnes for-to bete;</L>
<L>&THORN;e sonere is sunnes him weren for-&yogh;iue : for &thorn;e holie treo so swete.</L>
<L>&THORN;o bi-gan he al-so for is sunnes : &thorn;e holie temple a-rere</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e noble in Ierusalem : ake he deide in &thorn;e fourteo&thorn;e &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>Salomon, his sone : &thorn;at after him was king &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="276">Aftur him bulde &thorn;e temple forth : al-&thorn;at heo &yogh;are were.</L>
<L>to and &thorn;ritti &yogh;er he was &thorn;are-a-boute : and is fader fourtene al-so;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at it was sixe and fourti &yogh;er : are &thorn;at weor[c] was al i-do.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;at weork was almest &yogh;are : heom failede a long treo.</L>
<L N="280">&thorn;at holie treo was fairest &thorn;o : &thorn;at huy mi&yogh;ten ou&yogh;were i-seo:</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e kyng Salomon it liet felle and hewe : ase quoynte-liche ase men mi&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And liet it meten and makien more : bi a fote &thorn;ane &thorn;e ri&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&THORN;o it was i-brou&yogh;t to &thorn;e ri&yogh;te stude : and scholde beon ilaced &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="284">&THORN;o was it bi a fote to schort : ase euene ase huy it meten er.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Carpenters it lieten a-don : in strongue wrath&thorn;e and grete;</L>
<L>to no &thorn;ing &thorn;at huy mi&yogh;ten it don : it nolde beon i-mete.</L>
<L>Ane brugge ouer ane olde diche : huy maden &thorn;arof ate laste,</L>
<L N="288">For wrath&thorn;e &thorn;at huy ne mi&yogh;ten in &thorn;e temple : to none o&thorn;ure weorke it caste.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-ouer eode mani man : &thorn;e &yogh;wile it &thorn;are lay&mdash;</L>
<L N="290">Nusten nou&yogh;t alle hov holi it was : &thorn;at defouleden it al dai.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Quiene of Saba cam &thorn;are forth : and a-non so &thorn;at heo it sei&yogh;,</L>
<L>A-kneo heo sat and honourede<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. honoureden</NOTE> it : and nolde nou&yogh;t come &thorn;are-nei&yogh;.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. nou&yogh;t</NOTE></L>
<L>bi ano&thorn;er wei heo wende forth. : to Saloman heo cam,</L>
<L>For heo him hadde wel wide i-sou&yogh;t : to leorni of him wisdom.</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; grace &thorn;at ore louerd hire &yogh;af : to Salomon he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">= heo</NOTE> seide:</L>
<L N="296">&THORN;at treo ne scholde nou&yogh;t ligge &thorn;ere : and he dude bi hire rede.</L>
<L>&yogh;eot heo seide, &thorn;are schal<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. scholde</NOTE> a man : deie on &thorn;ulke treo</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; &yogh;wam al &thorn;e lawe of giwes : destruyd scholde beo.
<PB REF="00000058.tif" N="10"></L>
<L>Salomon it liet nimen sone : and onder eor&thorn;e it caste</L>
<L N="300">Swi&thorn;e feor fram alle men : and burede hit wel faste.</L>
<L>So longue so it &thorn;are-aftur were : a faire welle &thorn;are sprong</L>
<L>And a fair &yogh;water with grete fischsches : bo&thorn;e deope and long.</L>
<L>Manie sike men &thorn;at &thorn;are come : and wuschschen heore fiet &thorn;aron</L>
<L N="304">O&thorn;ur heore hondene o&thorn;ur ba&thorn;eden Al : hel&thorn;e huy hadden a-non.</L>
<L>&THORN;at watur huy loueden swi&thorn;e muche : and wolden &thorn;are-inne wade;</L>
<L>Ake huy nusten nou&yogh;t of &thorn;at treo : &thorn;at al &thorn;e vertue made.</L>
<L>Seth&thorn;e &thorn;are-after longue it was : &thorn;at ore louerd on eor&thorn;e cam.</L>
<L N="308">Anon so &thorn;at folk bi-spac is deth : and heore red &thorn;are-of nam,</L>
<L>&THORN;at treo bi-gan to fleote : ase ore louerdes wille it was.</L>
<L>&THORN;e giwes comen and founden &thorn;at treo : fleotinde &thorn;are bi cas :</L>
<L>huy nomen it op, for it &thorn;ou&yogh;te fil and foul : and &thorn;are hadde i-lei&yogh;e longue,</L>
<L N="312">And maden &thorn;arof &thorn;e holie rode : ore louerd &thorn;aron to hongue,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at treo for-olded was : and huy heolden ore louerd lu&thorn;ur al-so&mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;eot heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at treo to fair : &thorn;at he were &thorn;are-on i-do.</L>
<L>&THORN;e croiz aftur ore louerdes deth : deope under eor&thorn;e huy caste,<MILESTONE N="26b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="316">&THORN;are ase huy him to de&thorn;e duden : and bureden it wel faste,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e tweie croiz al-so &thorn;are-bi : &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;eoues on i-hanguede were.</L>
<L>&THORN;are huy lei&yogh;en faste i-hudde : more &thorn;ane to hondret &yogh;eres.</L>
<L>For &thorn;o titus and vaspasian : Ierusalem nome<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. hadde i-nome</NOTE></L>
<L>And hadden alle &thorn;e giwes destruyd : &thorn;at neuere-eft huy &thorn;are ne come,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at lond was i-brou&yogh;t : in &thorn;e Aumperoures hond of Rome</L>
<L N="322">And with is men i-fuld and al i-set : to nimen &thorn;er-to gome,</L>
<L>Seth&thorn;e &thorn;are cam An Aumperour : &thorn;at hiet Adrian,</L>
<L N="324">he&thorn;ene he was and swi&thorn;e lu&thorn;ur : and werrede ech cristine man;</L>
<L>For he wuste &yogh;ware &thorn;e rode lai : &thorn;at god was on i-do,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at cristine men &thorn;e stude honoureden : &yogh;wane huy mi&yogh;ten come &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>he liet ane temple of Maumates : in &thorn;ulke stude a-rere,</L>
<L N="328">&THORN;at men ne mi&yogh;ten nou&yogh;t i-finde to louten heom to : bote maumates alle it were.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei cristine men &thorn;udere &yogh;eoden : huy ne dorsten o&thorn;ur for doute;</L>
<L N="330">And muche a&yogh;ein heore heorte it was : to ani maumete a-loute:</L>
<L>So &thorn;at huy lieten al &thorn;ulke stude : and wenden a-wei for fere,
<PB REF="00000059.tif" N="11"></L>
<L>&THORN;at with-inne ane fewe &yogh;eres &thorn;ere-aftur : no cristine man ne cam &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;ulke stude was al for-lete : and &thorn;are-after wel mani a dai,</L>
<L>&THORN;at cristine man ne paynim : nusten &yogh;ware &thorn;e rode lai,</L>
<L>Seth&thorn;e &thorn;are cam an<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. am</NOTE> Aumperour : &thorn;at hiet costantin;</L>
<L N="336">In weorre and bataylle he was so muche : &thorn;at &thorn;are-of nas no fin.</L>
<L>&THORN;o come is fon and wonne : muche del of is londe.</L>
<L>he &yogh;arkede al day al is Ost : a-&yogh;ein heom for-to stonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ASe he toward &thorn;e bataille wende : he bi-heold op and<NOTE PLACE="marg1">= an</NOTE> hei&yogh;:</L>
<L N="340">Him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at a fair Croiz : op in heouene he sei&yogh;;</L>
<L>Lettres he i-sei&yogh; &thorn;are-on i-write : he bi-gan heom to rede :</L>
<L>"With &thorn;is signe &thorn;ou schalt maister beo" : &thorn;ulke lettres seden.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Aumperour &thorn;is Onder-stod : &thorn;ei he he&thorn;ene were.</L>
<L N="344">Ane croiz he liet makien sone : &thorn;at is men bi-fore him bere</L>
<L>In stude of his baner : in-to &thorn;e bataylle a-non:</L>
<L>And &thorn;oru&yogh; vertue of &thorn;e holie croiz : he ouer-cam alle is fon,</L>
<L>he i-wan &thorn;e maistrie and al is lond : in a luyte stounde &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>[Muche he thouthe &thorn;er-afterward wat &thorn;ilke signe were.]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">This verse is added by a later hand on the margin.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e wiseste men of al is lond : he liet bi-fore him bringue</L>
<L N="350">And Axede heom of &thorn;e croyz : &yogh;wat were &thorn;e tokningue.</L>
<L>huy seiden him &thorn;at at Ierusalem : god was i-don on rode</L>
<L N="352">And &thorn;e giwes hudden &thorn;e croiz &thorn;ere : ase huy onder-stode.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;wane ich habbe &thorn;are-&thorn;oru&yogh;," quath &thorn;e Aumperour : "mine fon i-brou&yogh;t to grounde,</L>
<L>Of heorte ne wor&thorn;e ich neuere bli&thorn;e : are &thorn;e holie croyz beo i-founde."</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e Aumperour &thorn;e holie rode : and &thorn;e faire miracles i-sei&yogh;,</L>
<L N="356">he liet him baptizen of &thorn;e pope : seint Siluestre, &thorn;at was &thorn;o him ful nei&yogh;.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Quiriac, &thorn;at Bischop was : prechede godes lawe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lu&thorn;ere Aumperour Iulian : brou&yogh;te him of dawe,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e holie rode &thorn;at he fond : and for he men &thorn;ere-to drou&yogh;</L>
<L N="360">to bi-lieuen on Iesu crist&mdash; : for he heold it al wou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e Aumperour hadde seint Quiriac : bi-foren him i-brou&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="27" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he bad him bi-lieue on heore Maumates : and &thorn;o he nolde nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>his ri&yogh;t hond he liet of-smite : And seide, "ich do &thorn;e &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="364">For &thorn;ou hast &thorn;are-with i-write : a-&yogh;ein ore lawe, i-wis."</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou lu&thorn;ere hound," &thorn;is o&thorn;ur seide : "wel hast &thorn;ou i-don bi me,
<PB REF="00000060.tif" N="12"></L>
<L>Of mine guode &thorn;ou were wel onder-stonde : ich au&yogh;te wel blesci &thorn;e:</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou me hast<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. me hast me</NOTE> &thorn;at lime bi-nome : &thorn;at me hath ofte to sunne idrawe,</L>
<L N="368">And ofte ich habbe &thorn;are-with i-writen : a-&yogh;ein Iesu cristes lawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;wyle ich was a lu&thorn;er giv&yogh; : and on god ne bi-liefde nou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is Aumperour &thorn;at i-sai&yogh; : &thorn;at he nolde tuyrne is &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>he made him drinke lead i-weld : and in is mouth helde it &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="372">Euere sat &thorn;is guode man : ri&yogh;t ase him no-&thorn;ing nere.</L>
<L>Op one gredire he leide him seth&thorn;e : ouer a gret fuyr and strong,</L>
<L>To rosti ase men doth fersch flesch : &thorn;at were grece a-mong.</L>
<L>&THORN;at fuyr was i-maud of col and grece : and salt was eke &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L N="376">And is<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> of is</NOTE> flesch &thorn;at was for-brend : &thorn;e woundene huy selten al-so.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he ne mi&yogh;te &thorn;are-with tuyrne is &thorn;ou&yogh;t : and to de&thorn;e [him] bringue,</L>
<L>he &thorn;ou&yogh;te &yogh;if he mi&yogh;te him tuyrne : with anie o&thorn;ur &thorn;ingue.</L>
<L>"Quiriac," he seide, "&thorn;ench on &thorn;i-sulf : and do aftur mi lore:</L>
<L N="380">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou nelt ore godes honouri : bote &thorn;ou wolle more,</L>
<L>Sei&yogh;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne art cristine nou&yogh;t : and ichulle debonere beo;</L>
<L N="382">&THORN;at murie lijf &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;ar-after lede : sone &thorn;ou schalt i-seo."</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e guode man nolde aftur him do : a Caudron he liet fulle</L>
<L>With eoyle, he liet it seo&thorn;e faste : and &thorn;ane guode man &thorn;are-inne pulle,</L>
<L>And seth &thorn;are-inne &thorn;ane guode man : forto &thorn;at he weri was.</L>
<L>&THORN;e guode man herede ore louerd euere : and neuere &thorn;e worse him nas.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e Aumperour &thorn;at isai&yogh; : &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;te him so ouer-come,</L>
<L N="388">With a swerd he smot him &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e heorte : &thorn;o he was of ba&thorn;e i|nome.</L>
<L>his soule wende to &thorn;e Ioye of heouene : After is tormentingue.</L>
<L>Nou crist for &thorn;e loue of seint Quiriac : to &thorn;ulke Ioye us bringue AmeN.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E holie Rode was i-founde : ase &yogh;e wutez, in May:</L>
<L>He was an-hauset in septembre<NOTE PLACE="marg1">[ 14 Sept.]</NOTE> seth&thorn;e : on &thorn;e holie rode-dai&yogh;.</L>
<L>Aftur heruest he comez i-lome : and o&thorn;ur-&yogh;wyle &thorn;are-Inne.</L>
<L>god us graunti for his moder loue : &thorn;e Ioye of heouene i-wynne.</L>
<L>Mani a &yogh;er &thorn;are was bi-tweone. : ri&yogh;t is &thorn;at we telle</L>
<L N="396">Of ey&thorn;ur feste aftur o&thorn;ur : no&thorn;ur ouer-huppe i-nelle.</L>
<L>A kyng &thorn;are was in .perce. &thorn;o : Cosdroe was is name;</L>
<L>Cristine men &thorn;at he mi&yogh;te i-finde : Alle he brou&yogh;te to schame.
<PB REF="00000061.tif" N="13"></L>
<L>With his lu&thorn;ere power he i-wan al-so: &thorn;e londes al a-boute.</L>
<L N="400">And &thorn;o he cam to Ierusalem : of &thorn;e sepulchre he hadde doute</L>
<L>&THORN;at ore louerd was on i-leid : and a-non &thorn;at he &thorn;e sepulchre i-sei&yogh;,</L>
<L>Of al is power, &thorn;at was so lu&thorn;er : &yogh;eot ne dorste he come &thorn;are-nei&yogh;.</L>
<L>Ake ane partie of &thorn;e swete croiz : &thorn;at seinte [Helene]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">supplied on the margin.</NOTE> &thorn;udere brou&yogh;te</L>
<L N="404">he tok with him and wende him hom : and &thorn;udere non-more ne &thorn;ou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at treo he was wel prout : &thorn;ei he him-sulf luy&thorn;ur were.</L>
<L>A suy&thorn;e hei&yogh; tour of gold and seluer : he liet him sone a-rere;<MILESTONE N="27b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of &yogh;ymmes and of deorewur&thorn;e stones : &thorn;are-a-boue he liet do</L>
<L N="408">Foourme of sonne and of mone : and of steorrene al-so,</L>
<L>Schininde ase &thorn;ei it heom-seolue weren : and tuyrne a-boute faste;</L>
<L>Ase a &thorn;ondringue he made swy&thorn;e ofte : &thorn;at muche folk ofte a-gaste;</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; smale holes bi quoyntyse : &thorn;at watur al-so &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="412">Ofte he made to grounde falle : ri&yogh;t ase it rein were.</L>
<L>Ase feor forth ase ani man cou&thorn;e : he<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> made<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> makie</NOTE> with quoyntise,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fourme ase &thorn;ei it an heouene were : he made on alle wise.</L>
<L>On-ouewarde &thorn;e tour a-midde al &thorn;is : ane sege he liet a-rere,</L>
<L>to sitten him-seolf &thorn;ar-inne ase a god : in heouene ase &thorn;ei it were</L>
<L>In his ri&yogh;t half one sege he made : his o sone he sette &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="418">In stude ase &thorn;ei it were godes sone : &thorn;at non defaute it nere,</L>
<L>In his leoft half he made an o&thorn;ur : and a fair koc he liet fette</L>
<L N="420">And in stude of &thorn;e holie gost : on his leoft half bi him sette,</L>
<L>And he him-seolf sat<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;at</NOTE> &thorn;are-a-midde : &thorn;e fader ase &thorn;ei it were,</L>
<L N="422">Sone and holi gost on ei&thorn;ur side&mdash;: welle, gret pruyte was &thorn;ere!</L>
<L>Eraclius &thorn;e Aumperour : &thorn;at cristine man was, at rome,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Added on the margin.</NOTE> misfarinde pruyde : he heorde telle i-lome:</L>
<L>With his host he wende in-to is lond : and weorrede on him wel faste.</L>
<L>In his heouene ase a god he sat : ase &thorn;ei him no-&thorn;ing ne a-gaste;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at his eldeste sone : he hiet wienden at&thorn;e laste</L>
<L>Wit his Ost a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e Aumperour : and out of his lond him caste&mdash;</L>
<L>For he ne deignede nou&yogh;t him-seolf for him : of his heouene ene a|li&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="430">Non more &thorn;ane hit were a god : with eor&thorn;eliche manne to fi&yogh;te.</L>
<L>his sone a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e Aumperour : with is ost he wende.</L>
<L N="432">And &thorn;o huy toward &thorn;e bataille comen : ei&thorn;ur to o&thorn;ur sende
<PB REF="00000062.tif" N="14"></L>
<L>&THORN;at huy bi-twene heom-seoluen tweine : &thorn;e bataille scholden do</L>
<L>And al heore Ost stonden and bi-holde : and non ne come hem to;</L>
<L>&YOGH;we&thorn;ur of heom a-boue were : habbe scholde &thorn;e mi&yogh;te</L>
<L N="436">Of &thorn;e o&thorn;eres men and al is lond : aftur is wille it di&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is foreward was i-mad : to-gadere huy smiten to grounde</L>
<L>And fou&yogh;ten ase hit heore ri&yogh;te was : and maden heom wel bitere woundes.</L>
<L>At&thorn;e laste &thorn;e Aumperour : &thorn;ane o&thorn;erne ouer-cam,</L>
<L N="440">And al his folk, ase foreward was : into his power<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> baundoun</NOTE> heom nam.</L>
<L>he liet heom cristni euer-ech-one : and siwi him to is wille.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lu&thorn;ere king sat euere at hom : in his heouene wel stille</L>
<L>Ase a god, and nuste nou&yogh;t : &thorn;at he was bi-ne&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>So vuele he was of his men bi-loued : &thorn;at huy nolden him telle nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Aumperour wende him forth : in-to his heouene an hei&yogh;</L>
<L N="446">And fond him sitten &thorn;are ase a god : his sone him sat ful nei&yogh;.</L>
<L>"Ille hail beo &thorn;ou, false god : in &thorn;ine false heouene i-founde,</L>
<L N="448">With &thorn;i sone and &thorn;i holie gost! : &yogh;e beoth nei&yogh; a-swounde.</L>
<L>bi him &thorn;at &thorn;ou countrefetest : &thorn;at for us &thorn;olede wounde,</L>
<L>bote &thorn;ou wolle on him bi-lieue : &thorn;ou schalt here in a stounde</L>
<L>Of mine hondene &thorn;olie deth : and &thorn;i pruyte i-brou&yogh;t to grounde,<MILESTONE N="28" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="452">For al &thorn;ine heouene i-nelle bi-leue : for marke ne for pounde."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Nay certes," &thorn;is o&thorn;ur seide : "&thorn;ou ne schalt me so nou&yogh;t lere</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich to anie manne a-bouwie schulle : bote he herre &thorn;ane ich were."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Aumperour drou&yogh; out is swerd : and smot of is heued ri&yogh;t &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="456">his &yogh;ongue sone &thorn;at sat bi him : &thorn;at was in his teo&thorn;e &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>he liet cristny and maken him king : of al is fader lond.</L>
<L>his men he &yogh;af<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &yogh;at</NOTE> al &thorn;at seoluer : &thorn;at he &thorn;ere fond.</L>
<L>Mid &thorn;at gold and &thorn;e riche &thorn;ingues : &thorn;at he fond al-so &thorn;ere</L>
<L>&THORN;e churchene &thorn;at &thorn;e schrewes destruyden er : &thorn;are-with he liet a-rere,</L>
<L>And made &thorn;are a lond wel bi-lieued : and guod in godes lawe;</L>
<L N="462">Alle &thorn;at nolden tuyrne to god : he brou&yogh;te sone of dawe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e holie croiz &thorn;at he fond &thorn;ere : &thorn;at ore louerd was on i-do,</L>
<L N="464">A-doun he as nam with gret honour : and with him as ladde also</L>
<L>To &thorn;e boru&yogh; of Ierusalem. : and &thorn;o he cam &thorn;are-bi-side,</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e hulle of Oliuete : one stounde he gan a-bide.
<PB REF="00000063.tif" N="15"></L>
<L>Swy&thorn;e muche folk him cam a-boute : with gret honur with-alle</L>
<L N="468">And &thorn;onkeden god of &thorn;is cas : &thorn;at heom was &thorn;are bi-falle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e swete holie croiz : to heom a-&yogh;ein moste come</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e luy&thorn;ere kyng Cosdroe : heom hadde &thorn;are bi-nome.</L>
<L>A-doun of &thorn;e hulle wende &thorn;e Aumperour : with fair processioun</L>
<L N="472">Ri&yogh;t &thorn;ane wei &thorn;at ore louerd &yogh;eode : toward is passioun.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he cam ri&yogh;t to &thorn;e boru&yogh; : and wolde In at&thorn;e &yogh;ate,</L>
<L>A fair miracle ore louerd sende : &thorn;at huy ne mi&yogh;ten In &thorn;ar ate;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e stones &thorn;at &thorn;are weren a-boue : a-doun a-non huy a-li&yogh;ten</L>
<L>And stoden empne forth ri&yogh;t bi &thorn;e o&thorn;er walle : &thorn;at no man In ne mi&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Sori was &thorn;o &thorn;e Aumperour : and al is folk al-so,</L>
<L>And a-dradden &thorn;at he nou&yogh;t wuyr&thorn;e nere : swuch a dede for-to do.</L>
<L>On god huy criden and wepen sore : &thorn;at he scholde heom grace siende,</L>
<L N="480">&YOGH;if &thorn;at it is wille were : into &thorn;e boru&yogh; for-to wiende.</L>
<L>&thorn;o stod &thorn;are An Aungel ouer &thorn;e &yogh;ete : A croiz he heold on honde:</L>
<L>"Sire Aumperour," he seide, "&thorn;ulke time : &thorn;at ore louerd was here a-lonnde,</L>
<L>&THORN;o he com in at&thorn;usse &yogh;ate : to beo to de&thorn;e ido,</L>
<L N="484">Opon a seli Asse he rod : in feble clo&thorn;es al-so;</L>
<L>he ne cam with none nobleye : so as &thorn;ou dest nov,</L>
<L>With riche clo&thorn;es and o&thorn;ur pruyde : &thorn;ei he were as hei&yogh; as &thorn;ov."</L>
<L>Mid &thorn;is word he wende a-&yogh;en. : &thorn;is Aumperour a-non</L>
<L N="488">A-li&yogh;te a-doun and his clo&thorn;es : he caste of euer-ech-on</L>
<L>A-non to is schurte and to is briech : sore weopinde with-alle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e stones arisen op a-&yogh;en : &thorn;at weren er a-doun i-falle,</L>
<L>And ech lai in his ri&yogh;te stude : ase heo hadden er ido:</L>
<L N="492">&thorn;at &yogh;at was opene ase hit was er : &thorn;e wei was clene al-so.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Aumperour nam &thorn;e swete rode : and al a-fote in bar;</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk him siwede with gret pres : muche Ioye and blisse was &thorn;ar.</L>
<L>&THORN;are cam a-non so swote smul : ase hit fram heouene were;</L>
<L>Muche was &thorn;e suotnesse and &thorn;e Ioye : &thorn;at in &thorn;e contreie was &thorn;ere.<MILESTONE N="28b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Aumperour bar &thorn;e swete croiz : in-to &thorn;e temple an hei&yogh;,</L>
<L>He bi-gan to singue &thorn;at newe song : bi-fore alle &thorn;at &thorn;are were nei&yogh;:</L>
<L>"&THORN;is<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. &thorn;u</NOTE> croiz is<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. is</NOTE> bri&yogh;tore to &thorn;is world : &thorn;ane alle &thorn;e steorrene beo.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art for-to honori of alle men : and &thorn;ou art a suy&thorn;e louelich treo,</L>
<L>holiore &thorn;ou art &thorn;ane al &thorn;at is : for &thorn;ou one wuyr&thorn;e were
<PB REF="00000064.tif" N="16"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou &thorn;at tresor of al &thorn;e world : al one opon &thorn;e &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. &thorn;ou</NOTE> bere.</L>
<L>&THORN;ov swete treo &thorn;at bere on &thorn;e : &thorn;e swete nayles al-so</L>
<L N="504">And &thorn;e swete bur&thorn;ene of godes sone : &thorn;at on &thorn;e was i-do,</L>
<L>Saue nou&thorn;e al &thorn;is compaygnie : &thorn;at hidere i-gadered is</L>
<L>And here to-day to-gadere i-brou&yogh;t : in &thorn;ine here&yogh;yngue i-wis!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e Aumperour song &thorn;o &thorn;is song : &thorn;at wel is &yogh;vyt vnder-stonde&mdash;</L>
<L N="508">For &yogh;uyt men it singueth in holie churche : &yogh;wane huy berez &thorn;e croiz on honde.</L>
<L>Al folk onourede al-so &thorn;e croiz : so feor forth so huy mi&yogh;ten it do,</L>
<L>With offringues and with song : and with o&thorn;ur melodies al-so.</L>
<L>&THORN;oru vertue of &thorn;e swete rode : a-non-ri&yogh;t in &thorn;e place</L>
<L N="512">Mani miracle &thorn;are feol a-day : &thorn;oru ore louerdes grace.</L>
<L>A ded man a-ros fram deth to liue : and ten men &thorn;at meseles were,</L>
<L>And four men of strongue palasie : heore hele huy hadden ri&yogh;t &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And fiftene men &thorn;at blinde weren : and manie o&thorn;ere al-so</L>
<L N="516">I-held weren &thorn;oru&yogh; is swete grace : &thorn;at on &thorn;e rode was i-do.</L>
<L>&THORN;is was &thorn;e holie rode-day : &thorn;at in Septembre is:</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore men honouriez in holi churche : &thorn;ulke dai, i-wis.</L>
<L>Mani miracle of &thorn;e swete rode : &thorn;e man &thorn;at heom telle cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;are hath seth&thorn;e i-beo and al-so bi-fore : some we wollez telle nou&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN &thorn;e lond of costantyne &thorn;e noble : A gyw some-time &thorn;are was</L>
<L>In one churche him-seolf al one : ase it feol bi cas;</L>
<L>he stod and bi-heol[d] &thorn;e rode : ore louerd forto schiende,</L>
<L N="524">And<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. a = he?</NOTE> &thorn;ou&yogh;te to don &thorn;e rode schame : are eni man come &thorn;are-hende.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e &thorn;rote with a swerd : he smot &thorn;e suete rode;</L>
<L>&THORN;at blod sprong on him anon-ri&yogh;t al a-brod : &thorn;at he was al a-blode.</L>
<L>&THORN;o was &thorn;e schrewe a-ferd of cristine men : &thorn;at ani come at&thorn;e laste:</L>
<L N="528">&THORN;e rode he bar a-non-ri&yogh;t a-wei : and in a deop put hire caste,</L>
<L>And at-orn him-seolf for drede. : a cristine man sone he mette,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bi-heold him hou he was bi-bled : and on him faste he sette.</L>
<L>"Schrewe," he seide, "&yogh;ware hauest &thorn;ou ibeo? : &yogh;wam hast &thorn;ou i|brou&yogh;t of dawe?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt a-bide here with me : and beo an-hongue o&thorn;ur to-drawe."</L>
<L>"Certes," seide &thorn;es o&thorn;ur, "i-ne habbe i-do : no man bote guod."</L>
<L N="534">"&THORN;ou lixt," seide &thorn;e cristine man : "and &thorn;at man mai i-seo bi &thorn;is blod."
<PB REF="00000065.tif" N="17"></L>
<L>"Louerd, merci," seide &thorn;e giv&yogh; : "to so&thorn;e nou&thorn;e ich i-seo</L>
<L>&THORN;at cristinemannes god is muche and guod : betere<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> herre</NOTE> ne may non beo.</L>
<L>doth mid me &yogh;wat &yogh;e wollez : of-serued ich habbe i-wis:</L>
<L>For a rode ich smot a swi&thorn;e deop wounde : and heo bledde on me &thorn;is.</L>
<L>And ich eov bidde cristine-dom : are ich beo to de&thorn;e i-do."</L>
<L N="540">Cristine men &thorn;at &thorn;is i-heorden : ful sone huy &yogh;eoden him to,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at &thorn;e giv heom tolde : huy maden heom ful bold:<MILESTONE N="29" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>huy wenden forth and founden &thorn;e Rode : ase [he] heom hadde i-told.</L>
<L>huy wuschen hire clene and setten hire up : ase heo was er bi-fore ido.</L>
<L N="544">&YOGH;uyt is &thorn;e wounde in &thorn;e &thorn;rote i-sene : and euere heo wole so.</L>
<L>&THORN;e giv &thorn;at hire hadde so i-smite : i-cristned he was sone,</L>
<L>And guod lijf ladde, as it bi-feol : cristine man to done.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A Cristine man &thorn;are was &yogh;wile : in &thorn;e londe of Sicie,</L>
<L N="548">A rode he hadde in is hous : &thorn;er-on ofte to crie.</L>
<L>hit bifeol at is terme-day : &thorn;at he wende to an o&thorn;ur inne.</L>
<L>A giv cam seth&thorn;e and wonede &thorn;er : and nust nou&yogh;t &thorn;e rode &thorn;are-inne.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e rode was &thorn;are i-founde : alle &thorn;e giwes as nome</L>
<L N="552">And ladden as forth to heore Synagogue : ase huy ladden ore louerd to dome;</L>
<L>And also ase huy ore louerd beoten : &thorn;e rode huy beoten faste,</L>
<L>And spatten on hure and boffatteden al-so : and ofte a-doun hire casten;</L>
<L>At &thorn;e ri&yogh;t side huy smiten a spere : ful deope in at&thorn;e laste:</L>
<L N="556">&THORN;at blod sprong out with gret strem. : &thorn;o weren &thorn;e schrewes a-gaste.</L>
<L>For huy nolden bi-blede heore synagogue : a gret fat and a muche huy fette,</L>
<L>to hente &thorn;ane strem of blode : vnder &thorn;e rode huy it sette;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo bledde &thorn;at fat bretful : of blod, are hit stunte.</L>
<L N="560">&thorn;o ne dorsten huy more schame do : &thorn;e rode ase huy munte.</L>
<L>Ake huy &thorn;ou&yogh;ten to proui with &thorn;at blod : &yogh;we&thorn;er ore louerd were soth and guod<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. soth god</NOTE>:</L>
<L>Euerech sik giv &thorn;at huy kneowen : huy smeoreden with &thorn;at blod:</L>
<L>And heore hele huy hadden a-non. : &thorn;e schrewene onder-stode</L>
<L N="564">&thorn;at heore lawe nas ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t : &thorn;at ne bi-liefden nou&yogh;t on &thorn;e rode:</L>
<L>to &thorn;e bischop huy wenden a-non : and lieten heom cristni alle,</L>
<L>And tolden al heore luy&thorn;ere dede : ant hou it &thorn;are-of was bi-falle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischop wuste &thorn;is holie blod : ase relikes riche and guode.
<PB REF="00000066.tif" N="18"></L>
<L N="568">gret miracle &thorn;are cam alday : of &thorn;ulke swete blode;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at it was in-to manie studes : I-fet, wide and side,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it is nou&thorn;e for relikes i-holde : in mani a lond wel wide.</L>
<L>In mani stude men seggez it is : of ore louerdes owene blode;</L>
<L N="572">Ake in eche stude it may wel beo : among o&thorn;ere relikes guode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A Giv &thorn;are cam to Rome &yogh;wilene : &thorn;at ne mi&yogh;te herebeorewe non i-winne:</L>
<L>In an old hous<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. hous hous</NOTE> he lay him a-doun : feor fram euerech Inne.</L>
<L>For he was in so wilde stude : of &thorn;e deuel he dradde him sore.</L>
<L N="576">he &thorn;ou&yogh;te hou cristine men heom wusten : fram &thorn;e deoueles lore:</L>
<L>With &thorn;e croiz he blessede him al-a-boute : an-auntre &yogh;wat him bi-tidde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei he &thorn;are-on ne bi-liefde nou&yogh;t : and lay doun him-seolf a-midde.</L>
<L>A gret deouel &thorn;ere cam In at mid-ni&yogh;t : ase &thorn;ei it a maister were,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ur deuelene with him i-nowe : ane chaiere with him huy bere,</L>
<L>&THORN;are-oppon huy setten &thorn;is grete maister : and he heom eschte a-non</L>
<L>Ech after o&thorn;ur of heore dedes : and &yogh;ware-a-boute huy hadden i-gon.</L>
<L>&THORN;o euerech hadde i-&yogh;olde a-countes : of schreu-hede huy hadden ido,</L>
<L N="584">&THORN;e maister lokede him bi-side : &thorn;ane giv he i-sai&yogh; al-so.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;wat is," he seide, "&thorn;ilke maister : &thorn;at ich in &thorn;ulke huyrne iseo?</L>
<L>ho made him so hardi and so wod : at oure a-counte to beo?<MILESTONE N="29b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>goth forth a-non and fetteth him hider! : we schullen maken him with us telle."</L>
<L N="588">So sore werth &thorn;e giv a-drad : &thorn;at he werth nei&yogh; out of is felle.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e deuelene comen toward him : huy ne mi&yogh;ten come him nei&yogh;,</L>
<L>Ake ech of heom a-drad was sore : &thorn;o he &thorn;at creoiz i-sei&yogh;.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;wat nou?" quath &thorn;is bolde maister : "&yogh;wy ne habbe &yogh;e him i|brou&yogh;t?"</L>
<L>"Sire, merci," &thorn;is o&thorn;ere seiden : "we ne mowen come nei&yogh; him nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>he is in a veteles &thorn;at ampti is : ake with-oute i-armed faste."</L>
<L>&THORN;o flouwen &thorn;e deuelene for &thorn;e croiz : &thorn;at sore huy weren a-gaste.</L>
<L>&THORN;e giv bi-liefde in godes sone : &thorn;at on &thorn;e rode was i-do,</L>
<L N="596">And liet him cristni al-so sone : so he mi&yogh;te come &thorn;er-to.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A Nonne &thorn;are was of on Abbeie : &thorn;at in a day hire &yogh;eode plei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>A fair herbe, &thorn;at men cleopez letuse : heo i-sai&yogh; stonde bi &thorn;e wei&yogh;e:</L>
<L>In hire mouth heo pulte &thorn;arof a lef : and ne blessede it nou&yogh;t er:
<PB REF="00000067.tif" N="19"></L>
<L N="600">heo iwerth a-non out of hire witte : and feol a-doun ri&yogh;t &thorn;er.</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk made gret deol for hire : and ech man &thorn;at hire i-sai&yogh;.</L>
<L>An holi man &thorn;at &thorn;arof heorde : &thorn;uder-ward wende adai.</L>
<L>A-non so he cam toward hire : &thorn;e deuel gradde for fere</L>
<L N="604">And seide, "a weilawei! &yogh;wat dude ich here : bote op one herbe sat &thorn;ere</L>
<L>And heo me nam and swaluz<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. swal&yogh;</NOTE> me in : and bot me al-so wel sore?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mi&yogh;t &yogh;wite me &yogh;wat &thorn;ou wolt : ake i-ne habbe gult non more."</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou schalt," quath &thorn;is holi man : "an o&thorn;er.In. habbe to-&yogh;ere.</L>
<L N="608">For heo for-&yogh;at to blessi hure : ful redi &thorn;ou were &thorn;ere."</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; signe of &thorn;e holie croiz : &thorn;ene deuel he drof out &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>&YOGH;eollinde and fol sori he wende a-wei : with ful grislich bere.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore ich rede ech man beo i-war : &thorn;at wilnez wel to do,</L>
<L N="612">blessi is mete are he it ete : &thorn;at he ne beo i-serued so.</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;e, god, for &thorn;e rode loue : &thorn;at &thorn;ou were on ido,</L>
<L>bringue us to &thorn;e hei&yogh;e Ioye : &thorn;at &thorn;ou us bou&yogh;test to. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="11" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>11. S. Dunstan.<NOTE PLACE="foot">This legend, and S. Cristofer, I have edited before in 'Lemcke, Jahrbuch f&uuml;r rom, und engl. phil., 1875.'</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Dunston was of enguelonde : i-come of guode more.</L>
<L>Miracle ore louerd dude for him : &thorn;e &yogh;uyt he was un-bore.</L>
<L>For &thorn;o he was in his moder wombe : In a candel-masse day,</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;at folk was muche at churche : ase hit to &thorn;e tyme lay:</L>
<L>As huy stoden alle with heore li&yogh;t : ri&yogh;t also men stondeth &yogh;uyt nou,</L>
<L>heore li&yogh;t queincte ouer-al : &thorn;at no mon nuste hou;</L>
<L>here &thorn;at li&yogh;t barnde swi&thorn;e wel : and here it was al oute.</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;at folk stod al in gret wonder : and weren in grete doute,</L>
<L>And bispeken ech to o&thorn;ur : in &yogh;wuche manere it were</L>
<L>&THORN;at it queinte so sodeinliche : al &thorn;at li&yogh;t &thorn;at huy bere.</L>
<L>Also huy stoden and &thorn;arof speken : in gret wonder ech-on,</L>
<L N="12">Seint Dunstones moder taper : a-fuyre werth a-non</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo huld in hire hond&mdash; : heo nuste &yogh;wannes it cam.</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk stod and &thorn;at bihuld : and gret wonder &thorn;ar-of it nam;</L>
<L>No man nuste fro whannes it cam : bote &thorn;oru ore louerdes grace.</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;arof huy tenden alle heore li&yogh;t : &thorn;at weren in &thorn;e place.
<PB REF="00000068.tif" N="20"></L>
<L>&YOGH;wat was &thorn;at, &thorn;at ore louerd crist : fram heouene &thorn;at li&yogh;t sende<MILESTONE N="30" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;at folk &thorn;at &thorn;are stode aboute : heore taperes &thorn;arof tende,</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;at of &thorn;ulke holi child : &thorn;at was in hire wombe &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="20">Al enguelond scholde beo ili&yogh;t : bet &thorn;ane hit euer er were?&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is child was i-bore : his freond nomen &thorn;er-to hede,</L>
<L>huy leten hit do to Glastingburi : to norischci and to fede,</L>
<L>And to techen him his bileue al-so : his pater noster and crede.</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;at child wax and wel i-&thorn;ev&yogh; : ase it moste nede.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e world he nam luyte &yogh;eme : for to alle godnesse he drou&yogh;;</L>
<L>Ech man &thorn;at heorde of him speke : hadde of him ioye i-nov&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he cou&thorn;e mannes wit : to his vncle he gan go,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;e Erchebischop of caunterburi : Aldelm &thorn;at was &thorn;o.</L>
<L>With him he maude ioye i-nov&yogh; : and euere &thorn;e leng &thorn;e more,</L>
<L>&THORN;o he i-sei of his guodnesse : and of his wise lore.</L>
<L>For gret deinte &thorn;at he hadde of him : he dude him sone bringue</L>
<L N="32">To &thorn;e prince of Engelond : A&thorn;elston &thorn;e kyngue.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king him maude ioye i-nou&yogh; : and grauntede al his bone,</L>
<L>Of &yogh;wat &thorn;ing &thorn;at he wolde him bidde : &yogh;if it were to done.</L>
<L>Seint Dunston him bad ane place : &thorn;are he was forth i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="36">In &thorn;e toun of Glastingburi : &thorn;at he ne wernde him nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king grauntede him is bone a-non : and after him al-so</L>
<L>Edmund, is bro&thorn;er, &thorn;o he was king : and in his power ido.</L>
<L>To Glastingburi he wende sone : &thorn;e guode man seint Dunston,</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;o bo&thorn;e &thorn;e kingues &yogh;eue him leue : Eadmund and Athelston.</L>
<L>&para; A fair Abbeye he let &thorn;are a-rere : ase men i-seoth &thorn;are &yogh;uyt stonde,</L>
<L>Of blake Monekes, &thorn;at was a-rerd : &thorn;e furste of Enguelonde&mdash;</L>
<L>For ech Abbeie of Enguelonde : &thorn;at of blake Monekes is</L>
<L N="44">Of &thorn;e hous of Gastingburi : furst sprong and cam, iwis.</L>
<L>Him-sulf he nam &thorn;e Abite &thorn;ere : and Monek formest bi-cam;</L>
<L>Sone he was Abbot of &thorn;e hous : and gret couent to him nam.</L>
<L>he makede &thorn;are godes seruise : studefast and stable i-nov&yogh;;</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;at couent &thorn;at &thorn;are-inne was : to alle guodnesse drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;is holi Abbod seint Dunston : hadde gret power</L>
<L>With &thorn;e king Eadmund, &thorn;o he was king : he was is conseiller.</L>
<L>After &thorn;e king Eadmundes de&thorn;e : a guode &yogh;wyle it was a-gon
<PB REF="00000069.tif" N="21"></L>
<L N="52">&THORN;at Edwyne, is sone, was king i-maud : ake nou&yogh;t ri&yogh;t sone after a-non.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is Edwyne hadde ful vuel red : and &thorn;are-aftur he drov&yogh;.</L>
<L>With seint Dunston he was wroth : and with wel gret wov&yogh;</L>
<L>Of his Abbeye he drof him out : and dude him schame i-nov&yogh;;</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;e more schame &thorn;at he him dude : &thorn;e more &thorn;e guode man lov&yogh;.</L>
<L>he let driue him out of Enguelonde : and let crien him fleme.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode man wende out wel glad : ne tok he none &yogh;eme.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Abbeie of seint Amaunt : bi-&yogh;eonde se he drou&yogh;,</L>
<L N="60">And soriornede &thorn;are longue : and ladde guod lijf inov&yogh;.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;o &thorn;e king Edwyne was ded : Edgar, &thorn;at was is bro&thorn;er.</L>
<L>After him was king I-maud : for he was ner &thorn;ane ani o&thorn;ur.</L>
<L>Swy&thorn;e guod man he bi-cam : and louede wel holi churche,</L>
<L N="64">And ech man &thorn;at him to guode radde : aftur him he gan wurche.</L>
<L>&para; Men tolden him of seint Dunston : &thorn;at is bro&thorn;er drof out of londe</L>
<L>With vnri&yogh;tht for is guodnesse : and he bi-gan him vnderstonde:</L>
<L>After him he sende a-non : &thorn;at he come a-&yogh;en sone</L>
<L N="68">And with him bi-leue is conseiler : of &thorn;at he hadde to done.</L>
<L>Seint Dunston cam hom a-&yogh;en : and faire was vnder-fongue,</L>
<L>And hadde his Abbeye al in pays : fram &yogh;wuche he hadde i-beo longue.</L>
<L>Swy&thorn;e wel he was with &thorn;e king : and al his conseiller;</L>
<L N="72">Men speken muche of his guodnesse : wel wide feor and ner.</L>
<L>&para; Hit bi-fel &thorn;at &thorn;e Bischop : of wyrecestre was ded:</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng and &thorn;e Erchebischop Eode : &thorn;ar-of nomen heore red</L>
<L>And &thorn;ene holie Abbod seint Dunston : Bischop huy maden &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>For he scholde beo herre in godes lawe : &thorn;ei it a-&yogh;ein is wille were.</L>
<L>Some men axeden at &thorn;e Erchebischope : of Caunterburi sire Ode</L>
<L>&YOGH;ware-fore &thorn;at he him Bischop maude : and &yogh;wy his graces weren so guode.</L>
<L>"For he schal," seide &thorn;is guode Man : "aftur me here bee</L>
<L N="80">Erchebischop of Caunterburi : and &thorn;at Men schullen i-see."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;wat wost&thorn;ou?" &thorn;is o&thorn;ere seiden : "&thorn;ou spext folliche, i-wis,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou nost non more &thorn;ane &thorn;i fot : op-on god al it is."</L>
<L>"Mine leue frend," seide &thorn;is holie Man : "&yogh;e ne dorre me blamie nou&yogh;t,
<PB REF="00000070.tif" N="22"></L>
<L>For ich wot wel &yogh;wat ore louerd crist : in mi Mouth hath i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And ho-so with-seith ou&yogh;t of &thorn;ulke &thorn;inge : &thorn;at ich eov habbe i-sed,</L>
<L N="86">&THORN;e so&thorn;e he mai seo, &yogh;if he liueth : after &thorn;at ich am ded."</L>
<L>&para; Bischop he was of londone : seint Dunston, seth&thorn;e al-so,</L>
<L N="88">Of londone and of wyrecestre : and heold bo&thorn;e to.</L>
<L>hit bi-fel &thorn;at &thorn;e Erchebischop : of Caunterburi was ded:</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope and &thorn;e king Edgar : &thorn;ar-of nomen heore red</L>
<L>And mauden &thorn;ane guode man seint Dunstan : Erchebischop &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="92">Guode men &thorn;at him i-knewen : wel glade &thorn;ar-of were.</L>
<L>&THORN;e cristindom of Enguelonde : to guod stat he drov&yogh;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e ri&yogh;tes of holi churche : he heold up faste i-nov&yogh;.</L>
<L>he fourmede &thorn;oru&yogh; al enguelond : &thorn;at ech person scholde cheose</L>
<L N="96">To witien him chaste fram lecherie : o&thorn;ur his churche leose.</L>
<L>Seint Athelwold was &thorn;ulke tyme : Bischop of winchestre,</L>
<L>And Oswold, &thorn;e guode man : Bischop of wurecestre:</L>
<L>&THORN;eos twei Bischopes with seint Dunston : weren al at one rede,</L>
<L N="100">And Edgar &thorn;e guode king : to done &thorn;at guode dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;eos &thorn;reo Bischopes wenden a-boute : &thorn;oru&yogh; al Enguelonde</L>
<L>And euerech lu&thorn;er person casten out : heom ne mi&yogh;hte non atstonde;</L>
<L>heore churchene and heore o&thorn;er guod : clanliche heom bi-nome</L>
<L N="104">And bi-setten as on guode men : &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e popes graunt of rome.</L>
<L>Ey&yogh;hte an fourti Abbeies : of Monekes and of nonnes</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at tresur huy a-rerden in Enguelonde : &thorn;at of persones was so i-wonne.<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Here a leaf is torn out in the MS., with the rest of this and the beginning of the following legend; only the first words of vv. 131-151 are preserved on a fragment of the leaf. MS. Vernon, which has the same text, continues:]</NOTE></L>
<L>[ffor so hit was bet biset : &thorn;en hit were<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> was</NOTE> er on schrewe&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor whonne gode Maystres beo&thorn; : sum goodnesse heo wolle&thorn; schewe.</L>
<L>Gode weoren &thorn;e &thorn;reo Bisschopes : &thorn;at &thorn;ulke tyme weren &thorn;o&mdash;</L>
<L N="110">&THORN;e betere hit is in Engelonde : for hem euere-mo.</L>
<L>&para; Vr lord &yogh;af seint Dunston : on eor&thorn;e so feir grace</L>
<L N="112">&THORN;at on a tyme, as he was : in a priue place,</L>
<L>his ffader and his Modur ek : in &thorn;e Ioye of heuene an-heih,</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;at heo weoren dede : wel aperteliche he hem seih.</L>
<L>Gret loue vr lord him kudde : whon he him schewede &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="116">So muche of his priuyte : &thorn;e while he alyue were!
<PB REF="00000071.tif" N="23"></L>
<L>&para; As he lay a no&thorn;ur time : in his reste a niht,</L>
<L>he sayh &thorn;e Ioye of heuene : and &thorn;e place &thorn;er-inne wel briht;</L>
<L>Aungels he herde syngen also : a Murie song &thorn;er-Inne,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;at me synge&thorn; in holy Chirche : whon me &thorn;e Masse bi-ginne:</L>
<L>Kyrie leyson xpe leyson : was &thorn;at Murie song&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e holi Mon &thorn;at &thorn;is i-herde : hit ne &thorn;houhte him no-&thorn;ing long.</L>
<L>Wel ouhte he to heuene come : at his ende-day</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;at, while he was alyue : so muche of heuene he say!</L>
<L>&para; harpe he louede swi&thorn;e wel : for of harpe he cou&thorn;e i-nouh.</L>
<L>A day he sat in his solas : and a lay &thorn;er-on he drouh.</L>
<L>&THORN;e harpe he heng vp bi &thorn;e wouh : &thorn;o hit was tyme to ete;</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;o hit was redi &thorn;er-to ibrouht : he sat doun to his mete.</L>
<L>Of heuene he gon &thorn;enche sone : of ioye &thorn;at was &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Ioyful blisse &thorn;at &thorn;er was : among halewen &thorn;at &thorn;er were.]</L>
<L>he<NOTE PLACE="foot">These beginnings of the next verses are extant in L. on a fragment of the fol.</NOTE> sat [as &thorn;ei&yogh; he weore i-nome : so muche &thorn;er-on he &thorn;ouhte.]</L>
<L N="132">his h[arpe, &thorn;at heng so bi &thorn;e wouh : of whom he luyte Rouhte,]</L>
<L>heo gan [to kui&thorn;e his holy &thorn;ouht : ded treo &thorn;ei&yogh; hit were,]</L>
<L>Also it o[vr lordus wille was&mdash; : hire herden alle &thorn;at weoren &thorn;ere.]</L>
<L>Al bi hire-[self heo gon harpen : a Murie Antempne iwis]</L>
<L N="136">&THORN;at men s[inge&thorn; &yogh;ut in holy churche : &thorn;at on Englisch is &thorn;is]:</L>
<L>"halewene s[oulen glade beo&thorn; : &thorn;at in heuene beo&thorn; i-do,]</L>
<L>&THORN;at siweden [vr lordes wey : and for him schedden also]</L>
<L>heore blod for [his swete loue. : &thorn;erfore heo schulen wone]</L>
<L>And kyngues<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Vern. knyhtes</NOTE> be [wi&thorn;-outen ende : wi&thorn; crist Godus sone."]</L>
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;is</NOTE> Antenene &thorn;a[t murie is : as &thorn;is folk iherden alle,]</L>
<L>&THORN;e harpe song a[l bi hire-self : as heo heng bi &thorn;e walle.]</L>
<L>Faire grace ore l[ord him schewede &thorn;er : whon &thorn;at dede treo]</L>
<L N="144">Scholde so singue [of &thorn;ulke Ioye : &thorn;at he scholde Inne beo!]</L>
<L>Louerd, i-hered beo [&thorn;i grace : &amp; &thorn;i mi&yogh;te also]</L>
<L>&THORN;at woldest her<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. for</NOTE> [alyue for him : such miracle do.]<NOTE PLACE="foot">Vv. 143-4, om. in Vern., are added from MS. Harl.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &thorn;o &thorn;is holie man [hedde i-lyued : on eor&thorn;e mony a day]</L>
<L N="148">And his ende-dai [was neih i-come : as he him-self say&yogh;,]</L>
<L>An holi &thorn;oresdai [he wex sek : as hit fel in &thorn;e &yogh;ere.]</L>
<L>he liet him clep[e of his frendes : &thorn;at specials to hym were,]</L>
<L>his men &thorn;at h[im serueden ek : he lette hem clepe also,]</L>
<L N="152">[And for-&yogh;af hem heore trespas : &thorn;at heo him hedden misdo,</L>
<L>And a-soylede hem of heore sunnes : as he in Godus bendes lay.</L>
<L>And so he lay in &thorn;ulke tyme : and eke &thorn;ene ffriday.
<PB REF="00000072.tif" N="24"></L>
<L>he lette clepe &thorn;e saturday : &thorn;e ffreres bi-foren him alle</L>
<L>And bad hem alle haue god day : and seide what him<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. hem</NOTE> scholde bi-falle;</L>
<L>he let him don al his Rihtes : and vr lordus flesch he nom,</L>
<L>And wende out of &thorn;is world : and to heuene wel sone com.</L>
<L>Now, swete lord seint Dunston : &thorn;at vre Erchebisschop were,</L>
<L N="160">Bring vs to &thorn;e Ioye of heuene : as Angles &thorn;i soule bere. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="12" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>12 Austyn.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Augustin, &thorn;at cristendom : brouhte in-to Engelonde,</L>
<L>Riht is among o&thorn;ere i-wis : &thorn;at we him vndurstonde.</L>
<L>Seint Gregori &thorn;e holy Mon : pope was of Rome,</L>
<L N="4">Engelond he louede muche : &thorn;eih he &thorn;er neuer ne come.</L>
<L>Me tolde &thorn;at &thorn;e lond was good : and &thorn;at hit he&thorn;ene was.</L>
<L>Wel sori was seint Gregori : &thorn;at hit cristene nas.</L>
<L>him-self he wolde habben i-went : in-to Engelonde,</L>
<L N="8">Ac he ne moste for &thorn;e Cardinals. : ac he sende his sonde:</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ffourti goode men : seint Austyn he nom</L>
<L>And sende hym in-to Engelonde : to preche cristendom,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vchone Monkes weore : seint Austin and eke &thorn;e o&thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="12">ffor&thorn; heo wenden euerichone : &thorn;at were alle as bre&thorn;ere&mdash;</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;at God was i-boren : ffyue hundred &yogh;er hit was</L>
<L>&THORN;at seint Austin wende in-to Engelonde : to do &thorn;is goode cas.</L>
<L>he dredde him sore for he ne cou&thorn;e : &thorn;e speche of Engelonde:</L>
<L N="16">he nom men wi&thorn; him &thorn;at cou&thorn;en : &thorn;e speche vndurstonde.</L>
<L>&para; heo duden hem for&thorn; in &thorn;e s&eacute;&eacute;. : &thorn;o heo &thorn;ider comen,</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e he&thorn;ene of Engelonde : &thorn;e rihte wey heo nomen.</L>
<L>In an Ile bi &thorn;e Est : Riht atte on ende</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;is Goode Men gonnen aryue : as God wol[d]e hem grace sende.</L>
<L>&THORN;er heo nomen furst heore In : and nomen hem sone to Rede</L>
<L>hou heo mihten best on taken : to don &thorn;is holy dede.</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;e kyng A&thorn;elbert, &thorn;at was &thorn;o : kyng of Engelonde,</L>
<L N="24">Bi a qweynte Messager : feire heo senden heore sonde:</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo weoren Messagers : and from an hei&yogh; mon heo come</L>
<L>To don to him a Message : from &thorn;e Court of Rome,</L>
<L>&THORN;at scholde to him world wi&thorn;outen ende : and to alle in his londe</L>
<L>To gret prou ben and to gret Richesse : &yogh;if he hit wolde vndurstonde.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e kyng &thorn;is word herde : he stod a while in &thorn;ouht.</L>
<L>"Goode ti&thorn;inges," he seide, "mot hit beo : &thorn;at heo me habbe&thorn; i-brouht.</L>
<L>vndurfonge&thorn; hem feire inouh : and honoure&thorn; hem also,</L>
<L N="32">And fynde&thorn; hem plente inouh : of &thorn;at heo habbe&thorn; nede to,
<PB REF="00000073.tif" N="25"></L>
<L>fforte ich habbe wi&thorn; hem i-speke : and heore Message seo;</L>
<L>God leue, as heo me bi-hote&thorn; : &thorn;at hit mote to my prou beo."</L>
<L>his heste was ful wel i-holde : and me vndurfeng hem feire i-nouh.</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;e kyng toward &thorn;ulke Ile : sone &thorn;eraftur he him drouh.]<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Here L. continues, <MILESTONE N="31" UNIT="folio">]</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;o he to &thorn;e .yle. cam : to seint Austyn he sende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he to him with his felawes : to don is erende, i-wende.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Austyn him grei&thorn;ede wel : and his felawes echon,</L>
<L N="40">For-to fi&yogh;hte a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e Deuel : and to batayle gon:</L>
<L>huy mauden &thorn;e signe of &thorn;e croiz&mdash; : o&thorn;ure Armes ne hadden huy non</L>
<L>For-to done &thorn;is bataille : and to ouer-come heore fon.</L>
<L>Ane Croyz of seluer with &thorn;e fourme : of god huy leten a-rere</L>
<L N="44">And in stude of Banere : bi-fore heom huy bere,</L>
<L>And &yogh;eoden forth wel baldeliche : ase hardie kny&yogh;tes and guode,</L>
<L>huy siweden alle heore swete Baner : &thorn;e fourme of &thorn;e rode;</L>
<L>&THORN;e letanie huy gonne singue : for prov of &thorn;e londe,</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;at ore swete louerd heom sende grace : heore prechingue to vnder|stonde.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;ane kyng huy gretten swy&thorn;e faire : &thorn;o huy to him come,</L>
<L>And seiden him &thorn;e erende : &thorn;at huy brou&yogh;ten fram &thorn;e court of Rome,</L>
<L>And precheden him of cristindom : and of ore louerdes lawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. to</NOTE> goddere hele him and alle his : &yogh;if huy wolden &thorn;are-to drawe;</L>
<L>huy bi-heten him &thorn;e Ioye of heouene : &thorn;at so riche was and is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he scholde after &thorn;is lijf : tuyrne into &thorn;ulke blis</L>
<L>And be &thorn;ere with-outen ende : with god &thorn;at us bou&yogh;te.</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;e king stod, &thorn;o he heorde &thorn;is : ase &thorn;ei he were in &thorn;ou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&para; "Swy&thorn;e fair &thorn;ing," he seide, "it is : &thorn;at &thorn;ov bi-hotest me;</L>
<L>Mi&yogh;hte ich beo siker &thorn;at hit soth&thorn; were : ich wolde don after &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Ake ich ne concenti nou&yogh;t &thorn;er-to&mdash; : for it is &yogh;eot so neowe,</L>
<L N="60">Are ich habbe more vnder&yogh;ite : &yogh;we&thorn;ur &thorn;is Message beo trewe.</L>
<L>Ake for &yogh;e &thorn;us i-trauailede beoth : fram so ferre londe,</L>
<L>And for ore guode, ase &yogh;e seggeth : and &yogh;e doth&thorn; me onderstonde,</L>
<L>Ich eov nelle greui nou&yogh;t : ake wel faire bi eov do</L>
<L N="64">And onder-fonguen eov and finden also : &thorn;at &yogh;e habbez neode to;</L>
<L>And ich graunti also &thorn;at alle &thorn;ulke : &thorn;at wollez to eov torne,</L>
<L>Guode leue ich [&yogh;iue ech]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> man : for i-nelle no man weorne."
<PB REF="00000074.tif" N="26"></L>
<L>&para; Seint Austin and alle his : A swy&thorn;e fair woniingue</L>
<L>In &thorn;e toun of Douere he heom &yogh;af : to makie inne heore prechingue.</L>
<L>Seint Austin and is felawes also : bi-gonne to prechie faste,</L>
<L N="70">So &thorn;at some &thorn;at guode weren : to heom heore heorte caste</L>
<L>And turnden heom to cristindom : and euere &thorn;e leng &thorn;e mo;</L>
<L N="72">So &thorn;at &thorn;ut folk a-boute heom cam : ase &thorn;icke ase huy mi&yogh;ten go.</L>
<L>heore dede sprong so wide sone : &thorn;at to &thorn;e king it cam</L>
<L>&THORN;e faire miracles &thorn;at huy duden : as huy precheden cristindom.</L>
<L>&para; He wende and heorde eft heore prechingue : and sei&yogh; &thorn;at hit was guod;</L>
<L N="76">"To longue," he seide, "ich habbe a-bide : ar ich &thorn;is vnder-stod."</L>
<L>he turnde him to cristindom : and liet him baptisen anon</L>
<L>And biliefde on ihesu crist : and is Men ech-on.</L>
<L>Erchebischop of Caunterburi : &thorn;e furste &thorn;at euere cam,</L>
<L N="80">Seint Austin huy maden &thorn;o : to holde up cristindom.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Austin brou&yogh;te cristindom : &thorn;us into Enguelonde&mdash;</L>
<L>Wel au&yogh;te we his [dai] Anouri : &yogh;if we weren wel vnderstonde.<MILESTONE N="31b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; His day is toward &thorn;e ende of May : for in &thorn;at day he wende</L>
<L N="84">Out of &thorn;is lijf to ihesu crist : &thorn;at after him &thorn;o sende.</L>
<L>Bidde we &yogh;eorne seint Austin : &thorn;at cristindom so brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we moten to &thorn;ulke Ioye come : to &yogh;wan ore louerd us bou&yogh;te.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="13" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>13 Barnabe</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Barnabe &thorn;e Apostle : &thorn;at guod was and hiende,</L>
<L>I-Martred he was for godes loue : in strongue de&thorn;e at&thorn;enende.</L>
<L>After &thorn;at ore swete louerd : to heouene gan i-wende,</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;e Apostles precheden cristindom : ase he heom gan wit siende:</L>
<L>&para; Seint Barnabe i-sai&yogh; &thorn;o : &thorn;at his bi-leue nas nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>he turnde sone to &thorn;e Apostles : and to ore louerd al is &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Of lond he hadde ane grete feld : and he it solde wel faste,</L>
<L N="8">to &thorn;e Apostles he wende anon : and to heore fet &thorn;e panes caste</L>
<L>And for-sok al &thorn;is world<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. worldes</NOTE> guod : and heore felawe bi-cam,</L>
<L>And I-martred he was with heom : for loue of cristindam.</L>
<L>Seth&thorn;e &thorn;o seint powel : to &thorn;e Apostles wende,</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;e Apostles ne lefden it nou&yogh;t : &thorn;at ore louerd him to heom sende,</L>
<L>Ake wenden &thorn;at he a gylur were : so &thorn;at hit was longue&mdash;
<PB REF="00000075.tif" N="27"></L>
<L>For he hadde so lu&thorn;ur man i-be&mdash; : are huy dorsten him vnder|fongue.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Barnabe i-knev him ferst : so &thorn;at he formest brou&yogh;te</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;e apostles in cuthrade with him : and in ri&yogh;te &thorn;ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And tolde heom hov ore swete louerd : bi weye to him cam</L>
<L>And smot him and bi-nam him is si&yogh;t : and brou&yogh;te him to cristindom.</L>
<L>&para; Seth&thorn;e &thorn;o fram Ierusalem : &thorn;e Apostles gonne wende,</L>
<L N="20">For-to prechi godes lawe : &thorn;at so guod is and hende,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e londe of Cypre : seint Barnabe huy gonne &thorn;o sende:<NOTE PLACE="marg1">This v. om. in other MSS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ase he wende forth in is wei : in one stude he fond</L>
<L>A felau&yogh;schipe of quoynte Men : &thorn;e wiseste of al &thorn;e lond.</L>
<L N="24">he spac with heom so quoynteliche : ase he bi heom cam,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ar nas non of heom alle : &thorn;at ne wondrede of his wisdam.</L>
<L>"Sire sire," seide on of heom : &thorn;at was of grete fame,</L>
<L>"Tel us of &yogh;wannes &thorn;ou art : and &yogh;wat is &thorn;i name,</L>
<L N="28">And fram &yogh;wannes &thorn;ou art hidere i-come : and for &yogh;wuche &thorn;ingue;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou comest here into ore lond : ich wot for sume ti&thorn;ingue."</L>
<L>&para; Seint Barnabe &thorn;is holie Man : fondede in eche pointe</L>
<L>to answerien heom wel quoynteliche : for huy weren heom-self so quoynte.</L>
<L N="32">"Sire," he seide, "&thorn;ov axest wel : and ich ou wulle telle:</L>
<L>Barnabe ich am i-cleoped : &thorn;e deueles fo of helle,</L>
<L>Iesu cristes man ich am : &thorn;at me gan hidere siende,</L>
<L>Fram Ierusalem ich am i-come : and &thorn;us a-boute wiende</L>
<L N="36">For-to prechi is holie name : &thorn;at brou&yogh;te us out of biende.</L>
<L>Bi-leueth on him and &yogh;e wor&thorn;eth in Ioye : euere with-oute ende."</L>
<L>he prechede so &thorn;is grete men : &thorn;at huy turnden heore &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And weren &thorn;are to cristindom : &thorn;oru&yogh; seint Barnabe i-brou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="40">And bi-liefden on Iesu crist : and heore heorte ope him caste,</L>
<L>And prechede also of ihesu crist : and turnde &thorn;ut folk wel faste.<MILESTONE N="32" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Seint Barnabe wende him forth : and to &thorn;e londe of cipre he com,</L>
<L>to tuyrne men to ihesu crist : and to prechi cristindom.</L>
<L N="44">He cam and fond a foul dede : &thorn;at schendful was to do:</L>
<L>Men vrne nakede al a-boute : and wummen al-so.</L>
<L>Seint Barnabe was &thorn;ar-of a-schamed : for it was a schenful dede</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e schrewene neren a-schamede nou&yogh;t : to schewi heore wrechhede.
<PB REF="00000076.tif" N="28"></L>
<L N="48">To &thorn;e temple he wende a-non : ope &yogh;wan huy a-vouweden heore schame,</L>
<L>And a-mansede &thorn;at sori temple : in ore louerdes name.</L>
<L>A-non with &thorn;is mansingue : al &thorn;at on half dachste a-do<SUP>v</SUP>nn</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; grete wreche of &thorn;is temple : with gret noyse and soun.</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;o &thorn;e schrewes i-sei&yogh;en &thorn;e wreche : &thorn;at so schamelese were,</L>
<L>huy bi-lefden &thorn;ulke schendfole dede : huy ne dorsten non-o&thorn;ur for fere.</L>
<L>&thorn;is holie man wende him forth : ferrore in &thorn;e lond :<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. londe</NOTE></L>
<L>Tymon, &thorn;at was an holi man : in a stude he fond,</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;at in a strong acces was of a feuere : and al at&thorn;e de&thorn;e nei&yogh;.</L>
<L>Seint Barnabe of-&thorn;ou&yogh;te it sore : &thorn;o he him i-sei&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;e godspelles of seint Mathev : with him euere he ber</L>
<L>In a bok; ase god it wolde : with him he hadde as &thorn;er :</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;is bok he leide ope &thorn;is man : ase he so sijk &thorn;er lay :</L>
<L>he bi-cam anon hol and sound : ase al &thorn;at folk i-say,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. i isay</NOTE></L>
<L>And wende forth with him a-boute : hol and glad i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L>And prechede &yogh;eorne of ihesu crist : and folk fram sunne drov&yogh;.</L>
<L N="64">Of ore swete louerd of heouene : seint Barnabe hadde swich grace</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &yogh;if he founde ani sijk man : ase he wende in ani place,</L>
<L>And he leide ope him &thorn;is bok : &thorn;at so holi and guod was</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e godspelles of seint Mathev : so strong siknesse non nas</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;at he &thorn;oru&yogh; ore louerdes grace : ne helde &thorn;ar-of a-non;</L>
<L>&THORN;are-&thorn;oru&yogh; he maude mani men : to Iesu criste gon.</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; vertue of &thorn;is holie Man : and of &thorn;is holie bok al-so</L>
<L>Muche fair mi&yogh;thte ore louerd hath : in his seriaunz ido.</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;is holie man seint Barnabe : &yogh;et for&thorn;ere he wende</L>
<L>And prechede &thorn;e giwes faste : hore lijf for-to amende.</L>
<L>Manie he tornede to cristindom : and &thorn;ene holi gost on heom tende,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; miracles &thorn;at he dude : and &thorn;oru&yogh; grace &thorn;at god him sende.</L>
<L N="76">&para; Bareu was a lu&thorn;ur giv : &thorn;at euere weorrede faste</L>
<L>Seint powel and seint Barnabe : and cudde it at &thorn;e laste :</L>
<L>For &thorn;o he fond seint Barnabe : &thorn;at folk to ore louerd so w<SUP>i</SUP>ende,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere Iustise of &thorn;e lond : &thorn;e ti&thorn;ingue he gan siende.</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;is holi man was sone i-nome : and to dome i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>huy tormenteden him harde and stronge : forto torni is &thorn;ou&yogh;t
<PB REF="00000077.tif" N="29"></L>
<L>Alle manere turmenz huy him duden : &thorn;at huy mi&yogh;thten on bi-&thorn;enche :</L>
<L>huy ne mi&yogh;thten him nou&yogh;t &yogh;eot enes make : fram god is &thorn;ou&yogh;t blenche.</L>
<L>&para; Ase huy weren with al heore mi&yogh;te : a-boute him<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> faste and longue</L>
<L>For-to defouli &thorn;is holie man : with tormenz harde and strongue,</L>
<L N="86">&para; &THORN;e Aumperores o cosin : &thorn;at of gret power was,<MILESTONE N="32b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In-to toune cam &thorn;ulke time : ase it feol bi cas.</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;e giwes weren so sore a-drad : laste he hem bi-nome</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; strenc&thorn;e seint Barnabe : and ladde him to rome :</L>
<L>A-ni&yogh;ht huy nomen &thorn;is holie man : ase he was to-raunsed so,</L>
<L>And teiden ane rop a-boute is necke : and knutten him faste &thorn;erto</L>
<L N="92">And drowen him out of heore synagoge : with seoruwe and pine i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e al-so bi &thorn;e sweore : out at&thorn;e &yogh;ate men him drov&yogh;</L>
<L>And mauden a-boute him swi&thorn;e gret fuyr : and barnden him al-to nou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>his soule wende to &thorn;e Ioye of heouene : &thorn;at he wel deore a-bou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o nomen &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere men heore red : &yogh;wanne huy mi&yogh;ten at&thorn;e laste,</L>
<L>his bones &thorn;at weren bi-left vn-barnd : a-midde &thorn;e .se. to caste.</L>
<L>Ake cristine Men &thorn;at weren bi-side : stelen to bi ni&yogh;te</L>
<L>And bureden as wel stilleliche : with ase gret honour ase huy mi&yogh;te.</L>
<L N="100">Nov bidde we &yogh;eorne ihesu crist : king of alle kinge,</L>
<L>For loue of seint Barnabe : &thorn;at he us to heouene bringue.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="14" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>14 Ioh[an] Baptist</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Iohan was &thorn;e beste bern : &thorn;e holie baptist,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euere of womman was i-bore : with-oute ihesu crist.</L>
<L>Ake of al &thorn;at he on vr&thorn;e was : we ne findez nou&yogh;t i-write</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;at he ani Miracle dude : &thorn;at man mi&yogh;hte vnder-&yogh;ite.</L>
<L>Mani men &thorn;inchez &thorn;erof wonder : so guod man ase he was;</L>
<L>For manie miracles sum o&thorn;ur dude : &thorn;at fulliche so holi man nas.</L>
<L>Ake al it was for &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere giwes : &thorn;oru&yogh; ore louerdes wille so :</L>
<L N="8">For &yogh;if he hadde here on eor&thorn;e : ani miracle i-do,</L>
<L>&THORN;o giwes wolden habbe i-went : &thorn;at he ore louerd were,</L>
<L>For he bi-gan ferst cristindom : and &thorn;at folk &thorn;er-to lere.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore ore louerd dude miracles : and ne liet him do non,</L>
<L N="12">For &thorn;e giwes scholden i-wite : &yogh;wuch he were ech-on.
<PB REF="00000078.tif" N="30"></L>
<L>&para; Seint Iohan for ore louerdes loue : was seth&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t of dawe,</L>
<L>For-to holden up cristindom : and &thorn;e ri&yogh;hte lawe.</L>
<L>Heroudes, &thorn;at was &thorn;o king : in a time to rome</L>
<L N="16">Wende to &thorn;e Aumperour : ase is wone was for-to done.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at bi &thorn;e weie he wende : bi sire phelipe, his bro&thorn;ur;</L>
<L>And maude gret feste, ase ri&yogh;t was : heore ei&thorn;ur with o&thorn;ur.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heroudes spac : mid is bro&thorn;er wiue :</L>
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. &thorn;at</NOTE> he hire wolde to wiue habbe : &thorn;e &yogh;wuyle he were a-liue,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he wolde framward rome : &thorn;are-forth a-&yogh;ein wende</L>
<L N="22">And nimen hire and leden hire forth with him : and holde hire is liues ende.</L>
<L>At on a-cord huy weren sone : to don &thorn;is sorie dede&mdash;</L>
<L N="24">Ase twei schrewene a-cordiet sone : to ane lu&thorn;ere rede.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is kyng heroudes wende forth : in is wei toward rome</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh;te to take is bro&thorn;er wijf : &yogh;wane he a-&yogh;einward come.</L>
<L>His owene wijf it vnder-&yogh;at : ase sum freond hire word sende :</L>
<L N="28">to hire fader, &thorn;at [was] king : of Damasche, sone heo i-wende,</L>
<L>to beon &thorn;are forto heo wuste : hou &thorn;is dede wolde an-ende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king heroudes bi is bro&thorn;er : A-&yogh;einward gan eft i-wende :<MILESTONE N="33" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And, also it was er bi-speke : &thorn;is wijf with him he nam</L>
<L N="32">And heold hire with strenc&thorn;e ase is owene : in spous-bruche and horedam,</L>
<L>And tiemde bi hire deolfolliche : in sunne and with gret wou&yogh;.</L>
<L>his bro&thorn;er and is wiues fader : weren with him wro&thorn;e i-nou&yogh;</L>
<L>And duden him harm bi al heore mi&yogh;hte : and bo&thorn;e weren is fon;</L>
<L N="36">Ake he heold him faste in his folie : and bi-lefde euere in on.</L>
<L>&para; So &thorn;at seint Iohan &thorn;e Baptist : to him a day com</L>
<L>And calangede him of is sunne<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. sunnne</NOTE> : to ligge so in horedom,</L>
<L>And seide, it was a-&yogh;ein heore lawe : and a-&yogh;ein cristindom.</L>
<L N="40">Heroudes &thorn;are-fore in wrath&thorn;e : seint Iohan wel faste nam</L>
<L>And, for-to paye &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere hore : in strong prisun him caste&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;are-inne he lay al a &yogh;er : i-warded strangue and faste;</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e he liet smite of is heued : as &yogh;e i-hereth ofte telle,</L>
<L>Also man redez in is daye in heruest : bi-foren eov in &thorn;e godspelle.</L>
<L>&para; In &thorn;e Castel of Arabie : is heued was of i-smite;</L>
<L N="46">&THORN;e lu&thorn;ere quene it bi-nam hire dou&yogh;ter : and liet it faste wite.
<PB REF="00000079.tif" N="31"></L>
<L>his desciples wenden stilleliche : &thorn;oru&yogh; ore louerdes grace</L>
<L N="48">And bureden &thorn;is holie bodi : in a wel fair place:</L>
<L>Bi-twe[ne] Abel and Elysee : &thorn;at prophetes &yogh;wilene were,</L>
<L>Stille was is holie bodi : wel longue i-bured &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is false quene &thorn;at heued wuste : &thorn;at men ne founden it nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="52">laste it were in ani time : to &thorn;is bodie i-brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And a rise fram de&thorn;e to liue : and bi-come at &thorn;e laste</L>
<L>A prophete ase he was er&mdash; : &thorn;ere-fore heo wuste it faste.</L>
<L>A day ase heo bi-heold &thorn;at heued : inwardliche in &thorn;e face,</L>
<L N="56">heo feol a-doun ded a-non : as it was ore louerdes grace.</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke wreche to hire cam : &thorn;at deth hire a-doun caste&mdash;</L>
<L>Me &thorn;inchez heo ne ou&yogh;te nou&yogh;t bi-li&yogh;he : hire schreuhede at&thorn;e laste;</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;at lu&thorn;ere best, hire dou&yogh;ter, no&thorn;er. : for ase heo &yogh;eode a dai</L>
<L>And pleide upon .yse. in hire game : ase mani a man it<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. i-</NOTE> sai,</L>
<L>&THORN;at .ys. to-brak vnder hire : and heo a-dronk a-non</L>
<L N="62">And in &thorn;e deueles name (!) : bo&thorn;e flechs and bon.</L>
<L>&THORN;is hadde moder and eke Dou&yogh;ter : to heore Mede at&thorn;en ende,</L>
<L N="64">And also schal ech lu&thorn;ur man : &yogh;wanne vre louerd it wole him siende.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at heued was seth&thorn;e wel priueliche : to Ierusalem i-brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And i-bured stilleliche : &thorn;at Men ne founden it nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is holi bodi, &thorn;are it lay : manie Miracles come,</L>
<L N="68">Grete and faire, ny&yogh;ht and day : ase &thorn;at folk i-sai&yogh; i-lome.</L>
<L>A lu&thorn;er Aumperour &thorn;ere was &thorn;o : &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere Iulian,</L>
<L>&THORN;a[t] reneyede ore louerdes lawe : and was swy&thorn;e vuel Man.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Men tolden him of &thorn;is Miracles : In grete wrath&thorn;e and onde</L>
<L N="72">he liet nimen &thorn;is holie bones : and to-sprede into al &thorn;e londe</L>
<L>And casten heom a-boute ech fram o&thorn;ur : &thorn;at no man &thorn;are-nei&yogh; ne come</L>
<L>Ne ne founden<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. founde</NOTE> heom to fette is bote : ase men duden er i-lome.</L>
<L>Ake &yogh;ut for al is felonie : ne bi-lefde ore louerd nou&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="33b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="76">&THORN;at manie sike men &thorn;at comen &thorn;are-nei&yogh; : to hele weren i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o was &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere Iulian : wro&thorn;ere &thorn;ane he was er.</L>
<L>Ase is bones weren er to-[s]prad : his men he sende &thorn;er</L>
<L>And liet heom fette a&yogh;ein wel clene : and with-oute &thorn;e toun a-non</L>
<L N="80">he liet heom sette on strongue fuyre : and fur-berne echon,
<PB REF="00000080.tif" N="32"></L>
<L>And &thorn;ut doust &thorn;ar-of wel wide : he liet blowe mid &thorn;e winde,</L>
<L>For men ne scholden of him on vr&thorn;e : neuereft more i-finde.</L>
<L>&para; Ake his o finguer with &yogh;wan he tei&yogh;hte : &thorn;o he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. orig. ore louerd &thorn;o he him (so the other MSS.)</NOTE> ore louerd i|sai&yogh;</L>
<L N="84">Cominde toward baptisingue&mdash; : ase attwelfte day&mdash;</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e watere of Iordan : and loude gradde and cride and sede</L>
<L>"lo here godes lomb, &thorn;at bi-nimeth : &thorn;e worldes mis-dede:"</L>
<L>For-so&thorn;e no fuyr ne mi&yogh;te come : on &thorn;at fingur one;</L>
<L N="88">Ake elles was al to douste i-barnd : bodi and bones ech-one.</L>
<L>No fuyr ne mi&yogh;hte &thorn;at finguer brenne : for none cunnes &thorn;ingue,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e holie dede &thorn;at he &thorn;are-with : tei&yogh;hte to &thorn;e hei&yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. holie, on the margin hei&yogh;e</NOTE> kingue,</L>
<L>Ake he bi-lefde hol, and &yogh;uyt is : and &thorn;ere nis non more bi-leued</L>
<L N="92">On vr&thorn;e of him bote &thorn;ilke fingur : and his holie heued;</L>
<L>For al is bodi was for-barnd : bote vnne&thorn;e &thorn;ulke two.</L>
<L>his day, ase falleth in heruest : &thorn;is dede was i-do</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at is bodi was &thorn;us i-barnd. : and also &thorn;ulke day</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;er-aftur longue men founden is heued : vnder vr&thorn;e ase it lay.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ulke two &thorn;ingues men holdeth is feste : &thorn;anne, &thorn;at &yogh;e it wite;</L>
<L>For men ne mowen nou&yogh;t on ore leuedi day : &thorn;o is heued was of i-smite.</L>
<L>A manere martyrdom it was : is bones so to-drawe:</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;are-fore men mouwe &thorn;anne holde : is feste bi ri&yogh;te lawe.</L>
<L>&para; His holie heued, &thorn;at &thorn;us was : at Ierusalem i-hud,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; fair miracle of seint Iohan : formest was i-kud.</L>
<L>For to tweie Monekus at Ierusalem : him-sulf he cam bi ni&yogh;hte</L>
<L N="104">And schewede heom &yogh;ware is heued lay : ase it were in a si&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>huy wenden forth and sou&yogh;ten it<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. is</NOTE> sone : and in &thorn;ulke here i-wounde</L>
<L>&THORN;at he werede in wildernesse : at&thorn;e laste huy it founden;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ane fyngur huy founden al-so : &thorn;at was of him bi-leued.</L>
<L N="108">With gret honour huy beren forth : &thorn;at fingur and &thorn;is h[e]ued.</L>
<L>&para; For fair relike huy weren i-wust. : and &yogh;ut at&thorn;e laste</L>
<L>Eft-sone huy weren &yogh;uyt i-hud : and in a put i-caste:</L>
<L>And leyen &thorn;are longue i-hudde : ase fewe &thorn;ar-of &thorn;ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="112">Ake weren on vr&thorn;e al for-&yogh;ite : ase no-man of heom ne rou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Bote seint Iohan it nolde nou&yogh;t : &thorn;at huy lei&yogh;en to longue &thorn;ere:</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Abbod Marcel<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. Maroel</NOTE> he cam a ny&yogh;ht : in metyngue ase it were,
<PB REF="00000081.tif" N="33"></L>
<L>And bad him nime is heued up : and seide &yogh;ware it lay.</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;is guode man a-ros up sone : and ne a-bod nou&yogh;t forto day,</L>
<L>Ake he openede is celle dore : and bi-heold a-boute.</L>
<L>Ane steorre he fond bi-fore &thorn;e dore : houinde &thorn;are-with-oute,</L>
<L>&THORN;e clereste steorre &thorn;at mi&yogh;hte beo&mdash; : him wondrede &thorn;ar-of i-nov&yogh;.</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="34" UNIT="folio">he &thorn;onkede god with guode wille : and toward &thorn;e steorre he drov&yogh;,</L>
<L>And putte forth is hond and wolde hire take. : ake he ne mi&yogh;hte hire nou&yogh;t a-reche,</L>
<L N="122">Ake &thorn;e steorre gan softe to glide forth : also it were &thorn;ene wey to teche.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;is Abbod hire siwede euere forth : and &thorn;e steorre bi-fore wel softe&mdash;</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;e Abbot Anourede his ledare : fale si&thorn;es and ofte.</L>
<L>Forth wende &thorn;e steorre, forto huy comen : ouer &thorn;at ilke place</L>
<L>&THORN;are his holie heue[d] lay : &thorn;oru&yogh; ore louerdes grace;</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo cam ouer &thorn;ulke place : heo houede &thorn;are ane stounde,</L>
<L N="128">For-to Marcel &thorn;is holie Monek : hadde &thorn;is heued i-founde.</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;e guode bischop Iulian : Marcel tolde &thorn;is cas.</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; heom bo&thorn;e &thorn;at holie heued : I-nomen up of &thorn;e vr&thorn;e was.</L>
<L>his heued &yogh;ut, and is finguer al-so : bo&thorn;e huy beoth hole and sounde.</L>
<L N="132">A-seint Iohanes day in heruest<NOTE PLACE="marg1">29 Aug.</NOTE> : &thorn;us huy weren i-founde.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore &yogh;uit &thorn;oru&yogh; heste of Rome : so wijd so is cristindom</L>
<L>Men holdez &thorn;ane dai in ho[nu]raunce<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. hor|aunce</NOTE> : of is holi martyrdom.</L>
<L>&para; For in ore leuedie daye in leynte : as he was to de&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="136">For &thorn;e o&thorn;ur festene &thorn;at &thorn;are beoth : of him men ne redez nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;e seint Iohan &thorn;at in &thorn;e flym Iordan : baptisede godes sone,</L>
<L>Lieue us &thorn;oru&yogh; ore cristindom : to &thorn;e Ioye of heouene come.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="15" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>15 Iames.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Iemes &thorn;e holi Apostle : guod is to habbe in mone,</L>
<L>Seint Iohanes bro&thorn;ur &thorn;e Ewangelist : and ore louerdes aunte sone;</L>
<L>his Moder was ore leuedi soster : Marie cleophe&mdash;</L>
<L N="4">Of guode kunne he was i-come : non betere ne mi&yogh;hte be;</L>
<L>he au&yogh;hte wel him-self beo guod : ase &yogh;e mowe alle i-se.
<PB REF="00000082.tif" N="34"></L>
<L>In &thorn;e londe of Samarie he prechede : and al-so in Ivde;</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; is prechingue mani on : he turnde to cristindom.</L>
<L N="8">To hermogenes &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere prince : &thorn;e ti&thorn;ingue sone com.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;ilke prince was wichche strong : and enchauntour also,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; &thorn;e deuel he wolde al day : gret Miracle do.</L>
<L>Ane desciple he hadde of is Art : philet was is name:</L>
<L N="12">him he sende to seint Ieme : to fondi to don him schame,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at he mi&yogh;hte with is Art : seint Ieme ouer-come.</L>
<L>To-gadere huy comen forto playdi : ase &thorn;e day was i-nome.</L>
<L>Godes desciple and &thorn;e feondes : bi-gonne to playdi faste;</L>
<L N="16">Ac seint Ieme, &thorn;at was godes desciple : a-boue was at&thorn;e laste:</L>
<L>Blinde men he &yogh;af heore sij&yogh;ht : and maude hole in &thorn;e place</L>
<L>Meseles and &thorn;e crokede al-so : al &thorn;oru&yogh; ore louerdes grace.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o philet i-sai&yogh; him &thorn;us ouer-come : to is maister he wende sone,</L>
<L N="20">Hermogenes, and tolde him fore : ase is ri&yogh;hte was to done:</L>
<L>"Sire," he seide, "ne hope &thorn;ov nou&yogh;t : to come seint Ieme with|Inne;</L>
<L>For nau&yogh;t it is, for &thorn;ov ne schalt nou&yogh;t : ouer-come him with al &thorn;i ginne.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore do ase ichulle &thorn;e rede : and go we to him, we twei&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="24">And crie him merci and bicome we : his desciples beye.</L>
<L>For siker &thorn;ou beo, ichulle it do : &thorn;ei &thorn;ou nelle nou&yogh;t also."</L>
<L>So wroth was &thorn;e prince &thorn;at he nuste : &yogh;wat for wrath&thorn;e do;</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; strenc&thorn;e of &thorn;e deueles Art : he made philet a-non<MILESTONE N="34b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="28">&THORN;at he ne mi&yogh;hte non more &thorn;ane a stok : a fot of &thorn;at stude gon.</L>
<L>&para; "Nov," he seide, "we schullen i-seo : &yogh;wat Iemes &thorn;e mai don here,</L>
<L>&YOGH;we&thorn;er he &thorn;e mai a-&yogh;ein me vndo : and a-&yogh;ein mine godes pouwere."</L>
<L>he liet him ligge &thorn;are ase astok : and forth a-wei fram him wende.</L>
<L N="32">Philet nam ane man a-non : and seint Ieme word sende</L>
<L>hou faste &thorn;oru &thorn;e deueles mi&yogh;hte : he lai &thorn;er i-bounde,</L>
<L>And bad him helpe his desciple : and bringue &thorn;ene deuel to grounde.</L>
<L N="35">&para; Seint Ieme him sende a luyte cloth : &thorn;at he with him ber,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he touchede him &thorn;are-with : and seide &thorn;eos two vers of &thorn;e sauter:</L>
<L>"Ore louerd vn-bind &thorn;at beoth i-bounde : and &yogh;if &thorn;e blinde is si&yogh;hte,</L>
<L>Ore louerd ri&yogh;tht heom &thorn;at buth vn-ri&yogh;ht : for &thorn;ou louest<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> oure louerd loue&thorn;</NOTE> alle ri&yogh;hte."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o philet hadde &thorn;is i-do : ase seint Ieme word him sende,
<PB REF="00000083.tif" N="35"></L>
<L N="40">On-bounde he was of &thorn;e deueles bendes : and &yogh;wodere he wolde he wende.</L>
<L>he &thorn;rettnede faste hermogenes. : to seint Ieme sone he cam</L>
<L>And godes desciple was and is : and aveng cristindom.</L>
<L>&THORN;o hermogenes i-herde &thorn;is : &thorn;at he was so vn-bounde</L>
<L N="44">And &thorn;at seint Ieme hadde i-brou&yogh;t : al is dede to grounde,</L>
<L>&para; Manie deuelene he conIurede : &thorn;at huy to him wende.</L>
<L>"Wel &yogh;e wutez," he seide, "&yogh;wi it is : &thorn;at ich after eov sende:</L>
<L>Ore alre fo, Iemes, hath : mine desciple me bi-nome.</L>
<L N="48">Bote &yogh;e beon strengore &thorn;ane ich am : i-wis we beoth ouer-come.</L>
<L>Ich hote eov &thorn;at &yogh;e wenden a-non : and doth a god prei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Nimeth and bringuet heom to me : faste i-bounde bei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Certes, bote &yogh;e it mouwen do : ase &yogh;e wel i-seoth,</L>
<L N="52">Ouwer power nis nou&yogh;t wurth an hawe : for ouer-come we beoth."</L>
<L>&para; "We schulle sone," &thorn;e deuelene seiden : "with heom on vr&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Vern. a no&thorn;ur</NOTE> plei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Faste i-bounde al to &thorn;ine wille : we schulle heom bringue bey&yogh;e.</L>
<L>huy comen fleo oppe in &thorn;e loft : ouer &thorn;e apostle seint Ieme.</L>
<L N="56">And a-non so huy weren ouer him i-come : huy guonne to grenne and reme,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> feme</NOTE></L>
<L>Belewi and wel foule crie : "Iemes, Iemes, &thorn;in ore!</L>
<L>We brennez here are it ore tyme be : and beth i-tormented ful sore."</L>
<L>"Ho tormentede<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> tormente&thorn;</NOTE> eov," quath seint Ieme : "and &yogh;wat wolde &yogh;e nou&thorn;e here?"</L>
<L>"Bote we buth i-come," &thorn;e feondes seiden : "to nime &thorn;e and &thorn;i fere;</L>
<L>Hermogenes us made hidere wiende : &thorn;oru&yogh; is conIuringue,</L>
<L N="62">&THORN;at we eov scholden faste i-bounde : bei&yogh;e to him bringue.</L>
<L>Bote a-non so we comen here ouer &thorn;e : Aungles to us come</L>
<L N="64">With brenninde raketei&yogh;ene : and faste vs bounde and nome;</L>
<L>here huy us beteth and tormentieth : with brenninde fuyre.</L>
<L>A wey, wei, Iemes, &yogh;wat schulle we do? : we ne mowen nou&yogh;t &thorn;is duyre.</L>
<L>A, Iemes, Iemes, leoue louerd : of us wrechches haue reu&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="68">And neuereft we nelleth nei&yogh; &thorn;e come : pli&yogh;hte we wolleth ore treou&thorn;e."
<PB REF="00000084.tif" N="36"></L>
<L>&para; "&YOGH;e wrechche foles," quath seint Ieme : "I not &yogh;wat &yogh;e wolden here.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at &yogh;e &thorn;ou&yogh;ten me a-nuye : drawe &yogh;e schullen a-rere.</L>
<L>Al on-bounde ich &yogh;yue eov leue : a-&yogh;ein forto fleo,</L>
<L N="72"><MILESTONE N="35" UNIT="folio">And bringuth him &thorn;at hidere eov sende : faste i-bounde to me&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e ne don him non o&thorn;ur harm!&mdash; : for icholde with him speke."</L>
<L>"Wel is us nou&thorn;e," &thorn;e schrewen seide : "we wor&thorn;et wel a-wreke."</L>
<L>&para; To hermogenes huy comen sone : and to grounde him caste,</L>
<L>huy drowen him and is hondene bounden : bi-hinden him wel faste.</L>
<L>&THORN;us<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;ef</NOTE> huy seiden, "&thorn;ou sendest us : &thorn;are we gret wo i-fielde,</L>
<L N="78">In gret torment and brenningue : and nou&thorn;e we wollez &thorn;e &yogh;elde."</L>
<L>huy harleden forth &thorn;usne wrechche : and to seint Ieme heo him brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="80">And seiden, "lo sire, &yogh;ware he is her : &thorn;at to swuche torment us wrou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if us ferst leue &thorn;at we moten : ore tormens a-wreke</L>
<L>And &thorn;e muchele vnri&yogh;ht &thorn;at he us hath ido : are &thorn;ou with him speke!"</L>
<L>&para; "Nay, certes," quath &thorn;is holie man : "&yogh;e ne schullen nou&yogh;t so,</L>
<L N="84">For ore louerd us hiet &thorn;at we scholden : guod for vuele do.</L>
<L>&YOGH;wy ne come [&yogh;e] nou&yogh;t nei&yogh; philet : &thorn;at stant here bi me?"</L>
<L>"Wel &thorn;ou wost," &thorn;is o&thorn;ure seiden : "&thorn;at we ne moten for &thorn;e."</L>
<L>"No. goth &thorn;anne," quath seint Ieme : "to eower kuynde stude,</L>
<L N="88">And ne cometh neuer-eft nei&yogh; no guod man : &thorn;ei a fol eov habbe i|bede."</L>
<L>&para; Euere stod hermogenes : and criede milce and ore,</L>
<L>he quakede for drede and for pine : And wep swi&thorn;e sore.</L>
<L>&para; "Philete, philete," quath seint Ieme : "&thorn;es hath &thorn;e schame ido,</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;ov schalt don him guod a-&yogh;ein vuel : for mi louerd het me so.</L>
<L>he bond &thorn;e &thorn;o &thorn;ov were vn-bounde : and a&yogh;ein &thorn;ulke lu&thorn;ere dede<NOTE PLACE="marg1">The last half-lines are transposed in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ov schalt vn-binde him &thorn;at is bounde : for so mi louerd sede."<NOTE PLACE="marg1">The last half-lines are transposed in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>Philet vn-bond &thorn;ane wrechche : and dude him vuel for guod.</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;e wrechche ne dorste nou&yogh;woder gon for fere : ake quakyinde &thorn;are he stod.</L>
<L>"Go &yogh;ware &thorn;ov wolt," quath seint Ieme : "for mi louerd nele it nou&yogh;t
<PB REF="00000085.tif" N="37"></L>
<L>&THORN;at euere ani man a-&yogh;ein is wille : to him beo i-brou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>&para; "A, merci," quath hermogenes : "&thorn;is deuelen me beteh<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. beten</NOTE> so sore</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;at I-ne dar anne fot fram &thorn;e go : laste huy me nimen more;</L>
<L>huy me wullez a-sle, &yogh;if huy me a-fongueth eft : and &thorn;are-fore ich bidde &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ov me take sum &thorn;ing &thorn;at ich mouwe : for heom bere with me."</L>
<L>Seint Ieme him tok is staf on honde : "go nov forth," he seide,</L>
<L N="104">"&THORN;ere nis no deuel &thorn;at dorre nou&thorn;e : nei&yogh; &thorn;e come, for drede."</L>
<L>Hermogenes wende him forth. : his bokes alle he nam</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hadde of his enchauntemenz : to &thorn;e Apostle a-&yogh;ein he cam</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;at he as for-brenne scholde. : &thorn;e Apostle sone heom nam</L>
<L N="108">And caste heom in &thorn;e deope .se : faste i-bounde echon.</L>
<L>&para; Hermogenes criede him merci : and wilnede cristindom;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he i-cristned was : and swi&thorn;e holi man bi-cam.&mdash;</L>
<L>Abiatar, &thorn;at &thorn;o was : Iustise, lu&thorn;ur i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L N="112">For &thorn;is dede he was wroth : toward seint Ieme, with gret wou&yogh;.</L>
<L>he nam him faste and swor is oth&thorn; : &thorn;at he it scholde a-bugge deore;</L>
<L>to &thorn;e kyingue heroudes he liet him lede : a rop a-boute is swere.</L>
<L>Heroudes &yogh;af his dom a-non : his &thorn;rote to smite a-two,</L>
<L N="116">And Iosie &thorn;e quellare he was bi-take : &thorn;ulke dede for-to do.</L>
<L>Ane Rop he dude a-boute is necke : and ladde him toward is dome.<MILESTONE N="35b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ane Man he helde of &thorn;e palasie : are heo &thorn;udere come.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Iosie &thorn;is isai&yogh; : merci anon he criede;</L>
<L N="120">Seint Ieme &thorn;e holie Apostle : he bad wel sone a-bide</L>
<L>And cristni him in &thorn;e place : a-non-ri&yogh;tes &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>A-seinte marie day in leinte : bi-haueded bo&thorn;e heo were.</L>
<L>Ake holie curche halt of ore leuedi : feste &thorn;at ilke day;</L>
<L N="124">Bi-fore lamasse seueni&yogh;ht : we holdeth is day &thorn;er-fore,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. bi-fore</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;ulke daye is bodi was : in-to schrine i-bore.</L>
<L N="126">&para; A-non so seint Ieme &thorn;e holie man : bi-haueded was &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>his desciples him wolden lede a-wei : ac huy ne dorsten for fere.</L>
<L>heore tyme huy a-wayteden wel : &yogh;wanne none Men &thorn;are nei&yogh; nere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at bodi wel stilleliche : out of &thorn;e countreye bere.</L>
<L>In a schip huy leiden it in &thorn;e se : and forth &thorn;are-with&thorn; huy wende,</L>
<L>And none &yogh;eme ne nomen &yogh;woderward fare : bote ase god he[m] kende.</L>
<L N="132">&THORN;at schip wende forth bi him-seolf : and hit cam on a day
<PB REF="00000086.tif" N="38"></L>
<L>Into &thorn;e lond of Galeis : &thorn;are ase &thorn;e quene lay,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lu&thorn;ur [was] and schrewe inov&yogh;. : seint Iemes Men a-non</L>
<L>Op of &thorn;e schipe nomen &thorn;at holie bodi : and leiden it opon a ston.</L>
<L N="136">&THORN;e ston bi-gan to wexe a-brod : and holu&yogh; bi-cam a-midde,</L>
<L>Ase euene i-maud to &thorn;e holie bodi : as ani man wolde bidde&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; Ne scholde no man so euene a &thorn;rov&yogh; : in leng&thorn;e and i[n] brede</L>
<L>To<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> make to</NOTE> him ase &thorn;at ston bi-cam : ase ech man &thorn;at it i-sai&yogh; seide.</L>
<L N="140">his desciples, ase it was ri&yogh;ht : to &thorn;e Quene erest wende :</L>
<L>"Dame," huy seiden, "we habbeth i-brou&yogh;t : &thorn;at ore louerd &thorn;e hider sende,</L>
<L>Seint Iemes bodi his Apostle : of &yogh;wam &thorn;ov nome ofte &thorn;i red</L>
<L>To laten him nime &thorn;e &yogh;wyle he was quik : ase mani men it habbeth i-seid.</L>
<L>Ore louerd him hath hidere i-sent : ase he him-seolf bed.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. bad</NOTE></L>
<L N="145">Loke &yogh;ware &thorn;ov him legge wolt : for i-come he is to &thorn;e ded."</L>
<L>&para; "Ey, traytours," quath &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere Quen : "&yogh;we&thorn;er &yogh;e beon of his?</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane i-ne mi&yogh;hte of him beo a-wreke : of eov ichulle, i-wis."</L>
<L N="148">&THORN;is guode Men he nam ech-one : and to &thorn;e king of spaygne heom sende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he heom brou&yogh;te to strong deth&thorn;e : o&thorn;ur don heom heore lawe wende.</L>
<L>Echone &thorn;e king nam a-non : and in strongue prisone heom brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Ac ore louerd ne for-&yogh;at heom nou&yogh;t : ake wel sone on heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te :</L>
<L N="152">For an Aungel fram heouene cam : and &thorn;at prisoun brak wel sone.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e kyng was &thorn;ar-of i-war : he nuste &yogh;wat was to done.</L>
<L N="154">&para; Kny&yogh;htes he liet siende i-nowe : aftur heom wel wide;</L>
<L>&THORN;at febleliche a-gonne in heore neodes : for schame heom gan bi-tide.</L>
<L>For ase huy wolden ouer ane hei&yogh;e brugge : after &thorn;is guode men gon,</L>
<L>Vnder heom &thorn;e brugge brak : and huy a-drounken ech-on.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e ty&thorn;ingue to &thorn;e kingue cam : sori he was i-nov&yogh;;</L>
<L>Of is lu&thorn;ere [&thorn;ou&yogh;t]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> &thorn;at he &thorn;ou&yogh;te : for drede he him with-drov&yogh;.</L>
<L N="160">Mildeliche he to heom he sende : &thorn;at huy a-&yogh;ein comen him to,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he heom wolde a-mendi faire : of al &thorn;at he hadde heom mis-do.</L>
<L>A&yogh;ein huy wenden to &thorn;e kyng : and he faire a-&yogh;ein heom cam,<MILESTONE N="36" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;ware-&thorn;oru&yogh; he and al is Men : a-fenguen cristinedom.
<PB REF="00000087.tif" N="39"></L>
<L N="164">&para; &THORN;e king sende &thorn;e Quene word : &thorn;at heo scholde heore wille al do.</L>
<L>Ful sori was &thorn;e Quene &thorn;o : and sore a-nuyd al-so;</L>
<L>Ake heo ne dorste nou&yogh;t beo a&yogh;ein is heste : nere hire no so [wo].</L>
<L>Wilde bollokes heo wuste fale : ope ane hei&yogh;e hulle go :</L>
<L N="168">"Goth&thorn;," heo seide, "ope &thorn;ulke hulle : finde &yogh;e mowen &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Oxene and Bolen strongue inov&yogh; : forte leden with ouwer bere;</L>
<L>Tei&yogh;eth heom to &thorn;ulke wayne : and &thorn;at bodi leggez &thorn;ar-inne,</L>
<L>And ledeth it &yogh;ware eouwere wille beo&mdash; : godes leue &yogh;e habbe and minne."</L>
<L N="172">&para; For &thorn;e Bollokes wilde were : &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere Quene so seide,</L>
<L>For huy ne scholden heom temie nou&yogh;t : eni-&thorn;ing for-to lede.</L>
<L>his desciples wenden forth : to &thorn;ulke hulle hei&yogh;e :</L>
<L>A fuyr Drake &thorn;ar-opon : a-&yogh;ein heom cominde huy sei&yogh;e.</L>
<L N="176">Swi&thorn;e ferliche he blaste fuyr : and a-sayllede heom faste&mdash;</L>
<L>Mani a man he hadde a-slawe : and al &thorn;e contreie of him a-gaste.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is desciples mauden &thorn;e signe sone : of &thorn;e Creoyz heom bi-fore :</L>
<L>Anon hadde &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere worm : is pouwer al ilore,</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;at hit ne mi&yogh;hte ane fot for&thorn;ere passe. : &thorn;is desciples forth wende</L>
<L>And to-pouneden it al to de&thorn;e : and ech lime fram o&thorn;ur rende.</L>
<L N="182">&THORN;e Bollokes and &thorn;e &yogh;oungue steores : &thorn;at weren er so wilde,</L>
<L>Anon so huy touward heom<NOTE PLACE="marg1">superscribed.</NOTE> come : huy woxen tame and milde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e beste huy chosen &thorn;at huy wolden : and to &thorn;e wayne heom ladde;</L>
<L>And huy drowen &thorn;at bodi so mildeliche : &thorn;at ech man &thorn;arof wonder hadde.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is desciples nomen seint Iemes bodi : and opon &thorn;e wayne it leide,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bestes it drowen forth wel mildeliche : with-oute eche fole breide.</L>
<L N="188">huy comen and driue &thorn;ane wayn : &thorn;are as &thorn;e Quene was.</L>
<L>hire wondrede muche and dradde sore : &thorn;o heo isei&yogh; &thorn;at cas.</L>
<L>&para; Heo for-sok hire false bi-leue : and tok hire to cristindom,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e wonder &thorn;at heo isei&yogh; : and guod womman bicom.</L>
<L N="192">Al hure paleys &thorn;at heo was inne : and al heore o&thorn;ure bone,</L>
<L>For-to honouri &thorn;at holie bodi : heo grauntede heom wel sone.</L>
<L>A-midde &thorn;e paleys &thorn;is holi bodi : huy bureden with grete pruyte&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;are he hath euereft to &thorn;is dai i-beo : and so he is &yogh;uyte.</L>
<L N="196">&para; Heo liet arere ane noble churche : and gret tresor he &yogh;af &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L>And gret lond, &thorn;at &yogh;uyt &thorn;are-to lijth : and grete rentes al-so :
<PB REF="00000088.tif" N="40"></L>
<L>&YOGH;ware-&thorn;oru&yogh; of religioun : a gret hous nou&thorn;e &thorn;are is</L>
<L>Of Chanones, &thorn;at Men &yogh;eot i-seoth and secheth&thorn; : at seint Iemes of Galys.</L>
<L N="200">A gret pilegrimage it is i-holde : ouer-al, ase &yogh;e i-seoth&thorn;,</L>
<L>To sechen &thorn;at ilke holie stude : &thorn;are seint Iemes bones beoth&thorn;.</L>
<L>Mani miracle is pilegrimes seggeth : &thorn;at &thorn;are hath ofte i-come.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei we ne mouwen nou&yogh;t alle telle : &thorn;enche we moten on some.&mdash;</L>
<L N="204">&para; &THORN;ritti Men at one tyme : pilegrimes bi-come,</L>
<L>To seint Iemes &thorn;e holie stude : alle &thorn;ene wei huy nome.</L>
<L>Ase huy wenden bi &thorn;e wei&yogh;e : so gret loue huy hadden and trewe,</L>
<L>And so guod heorte ech to o&thorn;ur hadde : &thorn;at a foreward huy mauden newe<MILESTONE N="36b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="208">&THORN;at non ne scholde failli o&thorn;ur : in perile ne in neode,</L>
<L>Ake wed-bre&thorn;erne huy bi-comen echon : ase huy &thorn;at wei eode.</L>
<L>heore treu&thorn;es huy pli&yogh;hten alle bote on : ake he nolde his nou&yogh;t pli&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;at foreward he bi-het to holde : treuweliche ope al is mi&yogh;hte.</L>
<L N="212">&para; So &thorn;at it bi-feol bi &thorn;e weie : &thorn;at on i-vuelede a day</L>
<L>And vnder &thorn;e hulle of seint Mi&yogh;hel : longue sijk he lay.</L>
<L N="214">his felawes &thorn;at hadde him treou&thorn;e i-pli&yogh;ht : fiftene dawes &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Abiden him; so &thorn;at heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te longue : for sore a-nuyde huy were,</L>
<L>And seiden, "we ne mouwen no leng a-bide : late we him ligge<NOTE PLACE="marg1">ligge on the margin.</NOTE> stille;</L>
<L>Do we moten ore pilegrimage : god do bi him is wille."</L>
<L>huy nomen heore leue and lieten him ligge : and wenden forth ech-on,</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;ilke &thorn;at nolde is treu&thorn;e pli&yogh;hte&mdash; : he nolde nou&yogh;t fram him gon.</L>
<L>&para; "Certes," he seide, "god do is wille : and lieue eov wel to wende,</L>
<L>I nelle anne fot fram him gon : are ich wute of him sum ende."</L>
<L>Mid him he bi-lefde al one : for-to &thorn;at he ded were.</L>
<L>Betere is trewe dede &thorn;ane fals word : as it was isene &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="224">&THORN;is trewe Man &thorn;at was with &thorn;e bodi : ful sore a-drad he was,</L>
<L>For he was so feor fram toune : and no man nei&yogh;h him nas;</L>
<L>For he was with &thorn;e dede al one : and it was nei&yogh;h ni&yogh;hte,</L>
<L>he nuste &yogh;wat with &thorn;at bodi to do : bote seint Ieme him helpe mi&yogh;hte:</L>
<L N="228">his help he bad with guode heorte. : and in &thorn;e eueningue ri&yogh;ht</L>
<L>Seint Ieme cam to him ride : in wel fair a-tyr of kni&yogh;ht.
<PB REF="00000089.tif" N="41"></L>
<L>&para; "Cum here," he seide, "forth with me : ne haue &thorn;ou of no-&thorn;ing drede,</L>
<L>Bi-fore me cast &thorn;at bodi her : and ich it wolle hennes lede,</L>
<L N="232">And lupe &thorn;ou up bi-hynde me." : and &thorn;o &thorn;is was al ido,</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie Man ladde &thorn;ene dede forth : and &thorn;ene quike al-so,</L>
<L>Fyftene Iorneies grete are day&mdash; : in &thorn;ulke luytele &yogh;wile,&mdash;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e mount of Ioie : &thorn;at is bi-sides seint Iemes a mile.</L>
<L N="236">&THORN;o huy comen to &thorn;ulke Mount : seint Ieme gan a-bide,</L>
<L>"Go," he seide to &thorn;e quike manne : "to mine churche here-bi-side</L>
<L>And sei&yogh;e mine Canones &thorn;at &thorn;arinne beoth : &thorn;at ich heom word bi &thorn;e sende,</L>
<L>Mine pilegrim &thorn;at me was leof : &thorn;at in treowenesse mine wei wende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy him burien a-mong heom &thorn;ere : with fair seruise and li&yogh;hte&mdash;</L>
<L>For ded he schal &thorn;udere come : &yogh;wane he a-liue ne mi&yogh;hte.</L>
<L N="242">And seie heom &thorn;at &thorn;ine felawes were : &thorn;at heore wei is al i-lore,</L>
<L>For heore treou&thorn;e &thorn;at huy breke : heore felawe, &thorn;at is nov bi-fore.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ine &yogh;wyle ichulle &thorn;e &yogh;elde : &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast &thorn;us treowe i-beo."</L>
<L>Mid &thorn;usse worde he wende forth : &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;hte him none-more i-se.</L>
<L>&para; A-boute &thorn;at bodi for &thorn;is Miracle : folk cam &thorn;icke reke.</L>
<L>Here man mai sum-del i-seo : &yogh;wuch [it is] treou&thorn;e to breke,</L>
<L N="248">And &yogh;wuch it is &thorn;ane holie wey : to seint Iemes forto go.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Miracle is so Murie : ich mot &yogh;eot telle of mo.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; Hit was a guod man and is sone : &thorn;at toward seint Iemes wende;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e cite of Tolouse : a-&yogh;ein eue huy hem kende.</L>
<L N="252">Al ni&yogh;ht huy bi-lefden &thorn;ere : at ane lu&thorn;ere mannes Inne.<MILESTONE N="37" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he &thorn;ou&yogh;te with &yogh;wuche tricherie : he mi&yogh;hte panewes winne.</L>
<L>&para; Nou was &thorn;e lawe in &thorn;ulke stude : as &thorn;e schrewe wel onder-stod:</L>
<L>&THORN;at ho-so an-hengue anine<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. anne</NOTE> man : he scholde habbe al is guod.</L>
<L>&THORN;e schrewe heom made fair semblaunt : ase is manere was to done,</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy were for-dronke beie : and a-slepe lei&yogh;en sone.</L>
<L N="258">A coppe of seluer stilleliche : &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere Man gan bringue</L>
<L>And dude in heore schrippe softeliche : a-mong heore o&thorn;ur &thorn;ingue.</L>
<L N="260">&para; &THORN;is guode Man a-wok and is sone : so sone so it dai was,</L>
<L>And nomen heore leue and wenden forth : and nusten nou&yogh;t of &thorn;at cas.</L>
<L>&THORN;o huy come with-oute toune a luyte : &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere man aftur cam,
<PB REF="00000090.tif" N="42"></L>
<L>hotinde out, with grete siwte : and &thorn;is trewe men beie he nam</L>
<L>And seide huy hadden is coppe i-stole : and in heore scrippe i-bounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk &thorn;is i-liefde a-non : &thorn;o huy &thorn;e coppe founde.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is pilegrimes, &thorn;ei huy treowe weren : to dome weren i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Eche manere &thorn;eof&thorn;e huy fur-soken : ake &thorn;at folk ne liefde heom nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="268">For huy weren i-nome hond habbinde : &thorn;e court lokede a-non</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy heore dom with heom beren : and hanguy scholde &thorn;at on.</L>
<L>&para; "Alas, alas," &thorn;e fader seide : "&yogh;we&thorn;ur i schulle nov&thorn;e hongue</L>
<L>And are ich habbe seint Ieme i-sou&yogh;t : &thorn;is file deth&thorn; a-fongue?"</L>
<L N="272">"Nai certes," quath is sone : "&thorn;at nolde ich graunti &thorn;e,</L>
<L>For to beo louerd of al &thorn;e world : &thorn;at &thorn;ov deidest bi-fore me.</L>
<L>hanguy ichulle for us bo&thorn;e : &thorn;ene deth i-nelle nou&yogh;t for-sake,</L>
<L>And al-so wis ase we gultlese beoth : mine soule ich god bi-take."</L>
<L N="276">"A, mi leoue sone," quath &thorn;e fader : "so ne schal it nou&yogh;t beo;</L>
<L>Scholdest &thorn;ou dei&yogh;e and ich libbe : i-nelle neuere &thorn;ane day i-seo.</L>
<L>Swuch a child touward as &thorn;ou art : i-loked it were wro&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ov scholdest hanguy and ich libbe! : ichulle hangy for us bo&thorn;e."</L>
<L N="280">"A, fader, fader," quath &thorn;e sone : "be stille, ich bidde &thorn;e,</L>
<L>For I nelle neuere &thorn;ane day a-bide : &thorn;at &thorn;ou schulle hongue bi-fore me;</L>
<L>&para; Ake go &thorn;ane wey for us bo&thorn;e : and ichulle hangy for us beye,</L>
<L>And bide seint Ieme &thorn;at he me graunti : sum part of &thorn;ine weye."</L>
<L N="284">Bi-twene &thorn;e fader and &thorn;e sone : &thorn;e striuingue laste longue&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at ech man hadde deol &thorn;erof&mdash; : &yogh;we&thorn;ur scholde &thorn;ene deth&thorn; a-fongue.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at it ful at&thorn;enende : &thorn;ei it were with wrongue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e sone for heom bei&yogh;e : gulteles was an-hongue.</L>
<L N="288">&para; Alas, alas, &thorn;e deolfole cas : to heore so muche falshede!</L>
<L>Wel &yogh;eorne bo&thorn;e fader and sone : seint Ieme help huy bede.</L>
<L>Welle louerd, &thorn;e deol of &thorn;e fader&mdash; : grettore neuere non nas,</L>
<L>&THORN;o he isai&yogh; is sone an-hongue : and for he gulteles was!</L>
<L N="292">he bi-tey&yogh;te is soule Iesu crist : &thorn;o &thorn;are nas non o&thorn;ur won,</L>
<L>And is wei with sorewe i-nov : to seint Iemes he gan gon.</L>
<L>Also wel for is sone ase for him : seint Ieme he bad faste;</L>
<L>And wende, &thorn;o he hadde al ido : hamward at &thorn;e laste.</L>
<L N="296">Are he come &thorn;are is sone was : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te swy&thorn;e longue,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he mi&yogh;hte finde o&thorn;ur i-seo : ani lime of him hongue&mdash;<MILESTONE N="37b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For &thorn;e lawe was &thorn;ere &thorn;at euerech man : &thorn;at an-hangued were
<PB REF="00000091.tif" N="43"></L>
<L>hanguy scholde &thorn;e &yogh;wyle i-laste<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> he laste</NOTE> : and for-to ech lime fram o&thorn;ur to-tere.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is &yogh;oungue Man sixe and &thorn;ritti dawes : heng up-on &thorn;e galu-treo</L>
<L>Are is fader a-&yogh;ein to him come : &thorn;at i-roted he au&yogh;te to beo.</L>
<L N="302">he cam and fond him &yogh;uyt : and ner him he gan teo,</L>
<L>he weop and criede and wrong is hondene : &thorn;at deol it was to seo.</L>
<L N="304">&para; "Leoue fader," &thorn;e sone seide : "ne weop &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t to bliue,</L>
<L>For ich nam to bi-weope nou&yogh;t : &yogh;eot ich am a-liue.</L>
<L>Me nas neuere on eor&thorn;e so wel : ase me hath seth&thorn;e i-beo;</L>
<L>Ich am ase &thorn;ei ich were in heouene : &thorn;ei ich hanguy here on &thorn;is treo.</L>
<L N="308">For seint Ieme me halt up : and Ioye i-nov&yogh; me dieth make.</L>
<L>Me of-&thorn;uncheth &thorn;at &thorn;ou so sone come : laste &thorn;ov me a-doun take."</L>
<L>Louerd, &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;at &thorn;e fader : hadde &thorn;ulke stounde,</L>
<L>&THORN;o he aftur al is sor : his sone a-liue founde!</L>
<L>&para; To toune he orn with Ioye i-nou&yogh; : and cleopede folk wel faste.</L>
<L>Muche folk him siwede and al &thorn;e so&thorn;e : i-sei&yogh;en at&thorn;e laste.</L>
<L N="314">With&thorn; gret Ioye huy nomen him a-doun : and to &thorn;e toune him brou&yogh;ten.</L>
<L>&THORN;ene traitur &thorn;at him maude an-hongue : wel sone out huy sou&yogh;ten</L>
<L N="316">And an-henguen him wel hei&yogh;e a-non : and nou&yogh;t bote he wuyr&thorn;e were.</L>
<L>&THORN;us seint Ieme &thorn;e holie man : is pilegrim halp &thorn;ere.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; In &thorn;e Cite of leouns : a &yogh;oung man &thorn;are was al-so</L>
<L>&THORN;at ofte wende to seint Iemes : and gret loue hadde &thorn;ar-to.</L>
<L N="320">At one tyme ase he &thorn;udere wolde : he dude er ane folie</L>
<L>&THORN;at manie Men to helle bringueth : &thorn;e sunne of lecherie;</L>
<L>Toward seint Iemes he wende forth&thorn; : are he i-schriue were.</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel was wel &yogh;eorne a-boute : &yogh;if he mi&yogh;hte him mis-lere.</L>
<L N="324">&para; A-&yogh;ein him he cam in &thorn;e wei : swi&thorn;e milde and softe,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;ht ase it seint Ieme were : ase &thorn;e schrewe gyleth men wel ofte.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;wost &thorn;ou euere," he seide, "ho ich am?" : &thorn;e &yogh;oungue man seide nay.</L>
<L>"Icham &thorn;ilke," he seide, "&thorn;at &thorn;ov hast : I-serued wel mani a day,</L>
<L N="328">Seint Ieme to-ward &yogh;wam &thorn;ou art. : I ne may make no mone</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ov wel ne dest : of eche &thorn;ingue bote of one :</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou dust<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. de&dotb;<SUP>u</SUP>st; dust=dudest</NOTE> lecherie : are &thorn;ou wendest to me;</L>
<L>Among alle men, &yogh;if &thorn;at nere : mest ich preisie &thorn;e."</L>
<L>&para; "Seint Ieme, merci," quath &thorn;is man : "ich crie &thorn;e milce and ore,
<PB REF="00000092.tif" N="44"></L>
<L>For&yogh;if me &thorn;ulke lu&thorn;ere sunne : i-nelle don as neuereft more."</L>
<L N="334">"Ov, beau frere," quath &thorn;e schrewe : "strong is &thorn;e mis-dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;ov ne mi&yogh;ht me neuere paye wel : bote &thorn;ov do ase ich rede :</L>
<L>&THORN;e menbre &thorn;ov most keruen of : &yogh;ware-with&thorn; &thorn;ou i-sunegut hast;</L>
<L>&THORN;e sunne ichulle for-&yogh;iue &thorn;e &thorn;anne : &yogh;wanne he is fram &thorn;e i-cast;</L>
<L>Ak next me &thorn;ou scholdest in Ioye beo : in &thorn;e blisse of heouene a-boue,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou woldest beon a martyr : and &thorn;i-seolf martri for mi loue."</L>
<L>&para; "A, louerd seint Ieme," quath &thorn;is man : "&thorn;ov haue merci of me,</L>
<L>Ichulle, mine sunnes to bete, mi-sulf martri : and forto pay&yogh;e &thorn;e."</L>
<L>&THORN;is wrechche Man carf of is membres : and a-wei fram him caste.<MILESTONE N="38" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e false &thorn;eues rede : him-self he a-slov&yogh; at&thorn;e laste.</L>
<L N="344">Ful redi was &thorn;e schrewe &thorn;er : &thorn;e soule he nam a-non</L>
<L>And wel glad &thorn;are-with in his manere : to-ward helle he gan gon.</L>
<L N="346">Ne fur-&yogh;at nou&yogh;t seint Ieme is pilegrim : for &thorn;at cas &thorn;at him gan bi|tide :</L>
<L>A-&yogh;ein &thorn;e deuel he cam a-doun : and bad &thorn;ane schrewe a-bide,</L>
<L>And seide, "&thorn;ou berst more &thorn;ane &thorn;in owe. : &thorn;at i schal kuy&thorn;e &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&YOGH;wi hast &thorn;ou mine pilegrim bi-traid? : gret schame &thorn;ou dest me."</L>
<L N="350">"&YOGH;e, al for nau&yogh;t," quath &thorn;e schrewe : "&thorn;ou art hidere i-come :</L>
<L>In his sunne him-sulf he a-slou&yogh; : and &thorn;are-with ich him habbe i|nome.</L>
<L N="352">Ne may no man in dedlich sunne : in-to heuene wende.</L>
<L>Ase wel &thorn;ou mi&yogh;ht gon hom a-&yogh;ein : he is min with-outen enden."</L>
<L N="354">&para; "Bel amy," quath seint Ieme : "&thorn;ou bi-traidest him with fals|hede</L>
<L>And with tricherie &thorn;ou to him come. : lat him gon, ich rede!"</L>
<L>"Ich habbe leue," quath &thorn;e schrewe : "to bi-gyli and bi-traye al-so</L>
<L>Mid eche quointise &thorn;at ich mai. : &yogh;wi wolde he aftur me do?"</L>
<L>&THORN;is strif i-laste bi-twene hem longue. : ake &thorn;o seint Ieme ne mi&yogh;hte</L>
<L>habbe &thorn;e soule ne with-inne him come : with no resun ne ri&yogh;hte,</L>
<L N="360">"&THORN;ou schalt," he seide, "come with me : to an herre Iustise,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e schal cuy&thorn;e &thorn;i tricherie : of &yogh;wam &thorn;e schal a-grise."</L>
<L>Bi-fore ore leuedi swete and milde : &thorn;ane schrewe he gan lede;</L>
<L>he &yogh;al and quakede deolfulliche : &thorn;o he i-sei&yogh; hire, for drede.</L>
<L N="364">&para; "&THORN;ov lu&thorn;ere &thorn;ing," ore leuedi seide : "&yogh;wi fondeste in alle wise</L>
<L>To bi-nime us and bi-trai&yogh;e men : &thorn;at beth in ovre seruise?
<PB REF="00000093.tif" N="45"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou ne schalt neuere &thorn;e soule brouke : for &thorn;ine tricherie."</L>
<L>"leoue leuedi," quath &thorn;e schrewe : "merci ich &thorn;e crie.</L>
<L N="368">Vnder-stond &thorn;at ich habbe leue : to bi-gylie men inou&yogh;,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ich fond him in dedlich sunne : and &thorn;are-inne him-sulf he slov;</L>
<L>And no man neuere in swuch cas : to heuene come ne mi&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>Ase he is min mid alle lawe : hold me, ich bidde, to ri&yogh;hte!"</L>
<L>&para; "&THORN;ov lu&thorn;ere best," ore leuedi seide : "to muche ower pouwer is.</L>
<L>Alas &thorn;at men nellez beon i-war : are huy don a-mis!</L>
<L N="374">Ase &thorn;ou mid &thorn;ine tricherie : his lijf him bi-nome,</L>
<L>Al-so ichulle him &yogh;iuen a-&yogh;ein : is lijf with ri&yogh;hte dome.</L>
<L N="376">So &thorn;at &thorn;e ne tit of him no part : for guod man he wo[l] &yogh;eot be."</L>
<L>Ore leuedi made &thorn;e soule a-non : to &thorn;e bodi a&yogh;en fleo;</L>
<L>Fram de&thorn;e to liue he a-ros : &thorn;oru&yogh; ore leuedi ore,</L>
<L>And guod lijf ladde euere aftur-ward : and &thorn;e deuel doutede &thorn;e more.</L>
<L N="380">&para; His menbres, &thorn;at he carf of : euer-eft he dude misse,</L>
<L>Bote a luytel wise &yogh;ware-&thorn;oru&yogh; he mi&yogh;hte : &yogh;wane he wolde, pisse.</L>
<L>Manie Men for &thorn;ulke miracle : seint Ieme louieth &thorn;e more.</L>
<L>Nou bidde we &yogh;eorne euerech-one : seint Ieme milse and ore,</L>
<L N="384">&THORN;at he for &thorn;at holie stude : &thorn;at he hath in galiz,</L>
<L>helpe us and alle is pilegrimes : and bringue us to heouene blis.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="16" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>16 Oswold.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Oswold &thorn;e holie king : of &thorn;e on ende of enguelonde<MILESTONE N="38b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>King was, ase &thorn;ulke tyme bi-feol : in north&thorn;-homber-londe.</L>
<L>Cristine man he was guod i-nov&yogh; : and with al is pouwer</L>
<L N="4">he heold up &thorn;e lawe of cristindom : and tei&yogh;te as feor and ner&mdash;</L>
<L>For he was king are cristindom : puyrliche stable were.</L>
<L>Al is men &thorn;ar-to he brou&yogh;te : so wijsliche he gan heom lere.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e princes he sende of scoth-lond : and bad &thorn;at huy him sende</L>
<L N="8">Ane wise clerk, is men to wissi : heore lijf forto amende.</L>
<L>huy senden him ane holie man : &thorn;at icleoped was aydan,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wende and prechede al is lond : and tornede mani a man</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;oru&yogh; is prechingue and seint Oswold : &thorn;at to alle guodnesse hem drov&yogh;,</L>
<L N="12">Cristindom into al &thorn;at lond : stable was i-nou&yogh;.
<PB REF="00000094.tif" N="46"></L>
<L>Seint Oswold maude &thorn;esne holie man : Bischop in is londe,</L>
<L>And made him al is conseiler : and herede godes sonde;</L>
<L>he ne dude no&thorn;ing with-outen him : ake with him he heold him faste,</L>
<L N="16">And to-gadere al heore lijf huy weren : and in heouene at&thorn;e laste.</L>
<L>&para; A day ase he sat and eat is mete : seint oswold &thorn;e holie man,</L>
<L>And &thorn;is holie man bi him : &thorn;e Bischop guode aydan,</L>
<L>&THORN;at o seriaunt<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. seriannt</NOTE> seide &thorn;at &thorn;are withoute : manie pouere men were</L>
<L N="20">And beden sum guod for godes loue : and guod was &thorn;at men him<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. hem</NOTE> bere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king nam inov&yogh; of is mete : &thorn;at bi-fore him stod,</L>
<L>And sende &thorn;ar-of wel largeliche : heom &thorn;at beden him guod.</L>
<L>Ane Dischs of seluer he nam also : &thorn;at bi-fore him was i-do,</L>
<L N="24">And to-brak it al to smale peces : and sende heom al-so.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Bischop sat and bi-heold : ase &thorn;ei he were in &thorn;ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e hond &thorn;e king he nam : and a swete word out brou&yogh;te:</L>
<L>"Ne for-rotie neuere &thorn;is hond : ake i-blessed be heo," he sede,</L>
<L N="28">"And euere hol and sound bi-leue : &thorn;at dude so guod a dede!"</L>
<L>&para; His bone was fole wel i-heord. : for it bi-feol at&thorn;e laste</L>
<L>&THORN;at he&thorn;ene men come in-to is lond : and weorreden on him wel faste.</L>
<L>he stod a-&yogh;ein with al is mi&yogh;hte. : so bi-feol &thorn;at huy come</L>
<L N="32">And i-metten heom with heore host : and &thorn;e batayle nome.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e tounne of Maserfeld : huy smiten to-gadere faste,</L>
<L>And seint Oswold &thorn;e holie Man : a-slawe was at&thorn;e laste</L>
<L>&para; And I-martred of &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere men : for ore louerdes loue.</L>
<L N="36">Al huy to-heowen is bodi : &thorn;o huy weren a-boue;</L>
<L>Ake huy ne mi&yogh;hten for no &thorn;ing : makie none wonde</L>
<L>In no&thorn;er of is holie hond : ake smiten as of hole and sounde.</L>
<L>And so huy beoth &yogh;eot, of ase fair heu&yogh; : ase huy euerer were,</L>
<L N="40">And i-holde for fair relike : ase men mowe i-seo &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&para; He was of ei&yogh;te and &thorn;ritti &yogh;er : &thorn;o he i-martred was,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">[a. 642]</NOTE></L>
<L>And Nye &yogh;er he hadde king ibeo&mdash; : bote luytel &yogh;wile it nas.</L>
<L>Nov seint Oswold &thorn;e swete Martyr : ore erinde to gode beode,</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at he us for-&yogh;iue ore sunnes : and us helpe at alle ore neode</L>
<L>And ore soule for is swete loue : in-to blisse lede.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="17" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000095.tif" N="47">
<HEAD>17 Edward.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Edward &thorn;e &yogh;ungue : was kyng of Enguelonde.<MILESTONE N="39" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wel &yogh;oung he i-martred was : &thorn;oru&yogh; tricherie and onde.</L>
<L>&THORN;o is Moder &thorn;e guode Quene : ase god wolde, was ded,</L>
<L N="4">his fader nam an o&thorn;ur wijf : &thorn;at lu&thorn;ur was and qued;</L>
<L>&THORN;at sent Edward louede luyte : and euere radde lu&thorn;ur red.</L>
<L>Bi hure he hadde ane o&thorn;ur sone : &thorn;at i-hote was Atheldred.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Quene louede hire owene [sone]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> : ase ech man deth is blod;</L>
<L>Ake seint Edward heo louede luyte&mdash; : for stepmoder is selde guod.</L>
<L>heo wilnede more &thorn;ane ani-&thorn;ing : &thorn;at seint Edward ded were,</L>
<L N="10">&THORN;at hire owene sone aftur &thorn;e king : &thorn;e heritage bere.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e king wende out of &thorn;is world : seint Edward, and<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. as?</NOTE> is sone,</L>
<L N="12">Aftur him was king j-mad : ase lawe was and wone.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e guodnesse of &thorn;is &yogh;oungue king : ne may no man telle.</L>
<L>he was meoke and milde inou&yogh; : and fair of flechs and felle,</L>
<L>De-bonere for-to speke with : ant with pouere men mest,</L>
<L N="16">Chaste, and wis of conseil : and pruyte he louede lest;</L>
<L>Wylde Men ne louede he nou&yogh;t : &thorn;at rechelese weren of &thorn;ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And wise Men to him he drou&yogh; : and aftur heom he wrou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;e Erchebischope of Caunterburij : seint Dunston &thorn;at was &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="20">Ech dede &thorn;at he wolde do : &thorn;e meste del scholde go.</L>
<L>Glad was &thorn;e holie man of him : and al &thorn;at lond also,</L>
<L>Of swuch a king &thorn;at heore louerd was : &thorn;at alle &thorn;ing wolde wel do.</L>
<L>Guod pais &thorn;are was in Enguelonde : and loue and muru&thorn;e i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L N="24">Richesse and al o&thorn;ur guod : elles it were &yogh;wov&yogh;&mdash;</L>
<L>For &yogh;wanne &thorn;at heued hath&thorn; godes grace : and loueth alle guode,</L>
<L>Wonder it were bote alle his : &thorn;e betere heom onder-stode.</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;e guodnesse of &thorn;is holie Man : &thorn;e deuel hadde envie,</L>
<L N="28">And is stepmoder &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere Quene : &thorn;at ful was of tricherie;</L>
<L>For heo &thorn;ou&yogh;te Ni&yogh;ht and day : &yogh;if heo mi&yogh;hte in ani manere</L>
<L>&THORN;at seint Edward were a-slawe : and hire sone kyng were&mdash;</L>
<L>For he was eldest aftur him : and &thorn;e kingues sone al-so.</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;is lu&thorn;ere wumman narewe hire bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te : hou &thorn;is mi&yogh;hte beo do.</L>
<L>To some &thorn;at weren hire conseilers : hire lu&thorn;ere &thorn;ou&yogh;t he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">= heo</NOTE> seide,</L>
<L>&thorn;at huy holpen with some Gyle : to don &thorn;at lu&thorn;ere dede;</L>
<L>&THORN;is lu&thorn;ere<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;u&thorn;ere</NOTE> Men also forth&thorn; with hire : weren in grete &thorn;ou&yogh;te
<PB REF="00000096.tif" N="48"></L>
<L N="36">With &yogh;wuche gyle huy mi&yogh;hten do : &thorn;at huy to ende [it] brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&para; So &thorn;at heo hadde to hire conseil : I-nowe at&thorn;enende.</L>
<L>For fellere &thorn;ing nis non ase wumman : &yogh;ware heo wole to vuele wende.</L>
<L>Nadde &thorn;is &yogh;ungue king i-beo : in is kynedom vnne&thorn;e</L>
<L N="40">Bote &thorn;reo &yogh;er and Ey&yogh;hte dawes : &thorn;at he nas i-brou&yogh;t to de&thorn;e.</L>
<L>For a day he wente on honteth&thorn; : with is kni&yogh;htes bi cas</L>
<L>In a fayr wode in deorsete : &thorn;at bi-side waraygne was.</L>
<L>Fair wode &thorn;are was &thorn;ulke tyme : ake nou&thorn;e heo is al a-doune,</L>
<L N="44">Bote &thorn;ornes and &thorn;unne boskes : &thorn;at stondeth bi-sides &thorn;e toune.</L>
<L>&para; Ase &thorn;is &yogh;oungue king wende on honteth&thorn; : a gret wille him cam to</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="39b" UNIT="folio">For-te seo is &yogh;oungue<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &yogh;onngue</NOTE> bro&thorn;ur : and in eche manere he wolde it do.</L>
<L>For he was &thorn;ere a luyte bi-side : ase is stepmoder was</L>
<L>In a toun &thorn;at men clepeden Corf : &thorn;at bote &thorn;reo Mile &thorn;anne it nas.</L>
<L>A strong castel &thorn;are is nou&thorn;e : ake &thorn;e &yogh;uyt nas non &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="50">&THORN;is holie man &thorn;ou&yogh;te longue : are he at is bro&thorn;ur were;</L>
<L>Ane fewe men with him he nam : and &thorn;uderward he gan ride.</L>
<L N="52">his Men pleiden and Arnden bi &thorn;e weie : and spradden a-boute ful wide,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at with heom<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. him</NOTE> ne bi-lefde non : al one he was sone;</L>
<L>Ake na&thorn;eles forth he wende is wei : ase he &thorn;ou&yogh;te to done.</L>
<L>&THORN;e court he bi-heold a-fer : &thorn;are ase is bro&thorn;er was:</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;udere he wende wel mildeliche : ake no man with him nas&mdash;</L>
<L>he ne &thorn;ou&yogh;te to no man bote guod : ne no man he nadde mis-do.</L>
<L>To-war[d] is de&thorn;e forth&thorn; he wende : and mildeliche al-so.</L>
<L>&THORN;o is stepmoder &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere Quiene : al one i-sei&yogh; him come,</L>
<L>heo &thorn;ou&yogh;te to don hire wille of him : ase heo hadde hire red i-nome.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lu&thorn;ere Men heo cleopede sone : &thorn;at weren at hire rede,</L>
<L N="62">And bi-speken bi &yogh;wuche feolonie : to don &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere dede.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;o &thorn;is holie Man was nei&yogh; i-come : &thorn;e Quiene a-&yogh;ein him eode</L>
<L>With fair Meyne and gret honour : and gret loue gan him beode&mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;e feste &thorn;at heo with him made : no tongue telle ne may&mdash;</L>
<L N="66">And swor &thorn;at he scholde a-li&yogh;te : and with hire bi-leue alday.</L>
<L>"Nai certes, dame," seide &thorn;is king : "so ne may it nou&yogh;t beo.</L>
<L>Ake lat me speke with mi bro&thorn;ur : for me longueth him to seo.</L>
<L>For er &thorn;ane ich him habbe i-sei&yogh;e : Ine wor&thorn;e nou&yogh;t bli&thorn;e, i-wis,</L>
<L N="70">Min heorte is so muche opon him : and no wonder it nis."
<PB REF="00000097.tif" N="49"></L>
<L>&para; "A, sire," quath &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere Quiene : "&yogh;wane it ne mot o&thorn;ur beo,</L>
<L N="72">Furst ichulle to &thorn;e drinke : and &thorn;u schalt him seth&thorn;e i-seo."</L>
<L>I-redi was &thorn;e Botiler : and brou&yogh;te him drinke a-non.</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e o&thorn;ere &thorn;at &thorn;are weren : o schrewe &thorn;are cam gon</L>
<L>And wel-comede him with fair semblaunt : and made him Ioye i-nov&yogh;</L>
<L N="76">And custe him Iudases cos : and sone him &thorn;ere a-slov&yogh; :</L>
<L>For ase he stoupede and custe him : redi he was i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; is wombe he smot a knijf : and is gottes al-to-drov&yogh;</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie Man sat upri&yogh;ht : and bi-heold is de&thorn;es wounde.</L>
<L N="80">he ne rod bote wel luyte wei : are he feol to grounde</L>
<L>And liet &thorn;ere is swete lijf&mdash; : is soule to heouene wende.</L>
<L>Alas, luytel vuel &thorn;ou&yogh;te he : &thorn;o &thorn;e schrewe is wombe rende!</L>
<L>Ake he was lu&thorn;ur ase Iudas : &thorn;at so feolliche him custe</L>
<L N="84">And with tricherie is wombe rende : are he it euere wuste!</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is holie Man i-martred was : huy &thorn;at him brou&yogh;ten &thorn;er-to</L>
<L>Bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;ten hou huy mi&yogh;hten best : with &thorn;is holie bodie do :</L>
<L>In-to a dierne stude huy wenden : and &thorn;ar-inne is bodi huy caste</L>
<L N="88">Wel filliche and stilleliche : and bureden it &thorn;are wel faste.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;o &thorn;is holie Man i-martred was : &thorn;e Quiene hadde hire wille;</L>
<L>For li&yogh;htliche Men holdeth euere with &thorn;e quike : and &thorn;e dede is sone stille.</L>
<L>Men nomen &thorn;o &thorn;at child A&thorn;eldred : &thorn;at was &thorn;e Quiene sone,<MILESTONE N="40" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="92">And aftur is bro&thorn;ur mauden him king : as ri&yogh;ht was and wone.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e hei&yogh;e men alle of &thorn;e lond : with him heolden echon</L>
<L>Ase with heore prince and heore louerd : and &thorn;ene dede for-&yogh;ete a-non.</L>
<L>Ake among lowe Men and simple : deol &thorn;ere was i-nou&yogh;,</L>
<L N="96">huy corseden alle with-oute god : &thorn;at heore louerd a-slou&yogh;.</L>
<L>"Alas," huy seiden, "&yogh;wat schulle we nou&thorn;e? : ho schal for us beo?</L>
<L>ho schal us nou&thorn;e fram weorre wite<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. us wite</NOTE>? : &yogh;wodere schulle we nou&thorn;e fleo?</L>
<L>ho schal nou pais in londe holde? : ore ioye is al i-do!</L>
<L N="100">Of weorre and wo we mouwen beo sikere : al wrechhede cometh&thorn; us to."</L>
<L>&para; Grete wille hadden &thorn;e guode Men : of &thorn;e contreie bi-side</L>
<L>In sum fair place &thorn;at bodi legge : and sou&yogh;ten it wel wide;</L>
<L>huy ortreuweden wel &thorn;at it were : in sum foul stude i-do,
<PB REF="00000098.tif" N="50"></L>
<L>huy sou&yogh;ten it ofte wide a-boute : and ne cou&thorn;en nou&yogh;t come &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L>On a time ase &thorn;is guode men : of wareygne &thorn;are bi-side</L>
<L N="106">In &thorn;e contreye wenden and sou&yogh;ten : &thorn;is holie bodi ful wide,</L>
<L>huy stoden and bi-heolden<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. bi-heoldem</NOTE> heom bi-side : &thorn;o isei&yogh;en huy gret li&yogh;ht</L>
<L>And cler with-alle a-boute one place : ase apiler stonde upri&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>&para; Huy &thorn;ou&yogh;ten &thorn;at &thorn;ere was godes grace. : &thorn;udere huy wenden and sou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="110">And founden &thorn;ere &thorn;is holie bodi : and up of &thorn;e eor&thorn;e it brou&yogh;ten.</L>
<L>&THORN;are was wop and sor i-nov : &thorn;o huy sei&yogh;en is grisli wounde!</L>
<L>Ake &yogh;eot was heore heorte glad : and Ioyful, &thorn;o huy him founde.</L>
<L>With wel fair procession : &thorn;is bodi forth huy bere</L>
<L N="114">In-to &thorn;e toun of warayne : and faire it bureden &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>In a churche-&yogh;erd of ore leuedi : bi este &thorn;e churche a luyte,</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;are huy bureden &thorn;at swete bodi : with gret honur and pruyte.</L>
<L>A chapele &thorn;are is arerd : ase &thorn;at holie bodi lai</L>
<L>In &thorn;e toun of warygne : &thorn;at stant &yogh;eot to &thorn;is dai.</L>
<L>&THORN;e put &thorn;are he was feorst i-founde : a welle &thorn;are gan springue,</L>
<L N="120">Fair and cler, &thorn;at &yogh;eot i-last : and is ofte gret botningue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Men cleopieth &yogh;eot to &thorn;is day : "seint Edwardes welle;"</L>
<L>&thorn;are Mani Miracle hath i-beo : ase &thorn;e contreie deth&thorn; telle.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at holie bodi lay guode &yogh;wyle : &thorn;are it was i-do,</L>
<L N="124">In &thorn;e toune of waraygne : and Mani man cam &thorn;ar-to.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ti&thorn;ingue hov he i-martred was : sone sprong wel wide,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Miracles &thorn;at for him comen : a-boute in eche side.</L>
<L>An hei&yogh; Eorl &thorn;are was a-londe &thorn;o : &thorn;at i-hoten was Alfez,</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;at seint Edward louede muche : &thorn;e &yogh;wyle he liuede her :</L>
<L>&THORN;o he heorde of &thorn;e Miracles telle : &thorn;at ore louerd for him wrou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Glad and bli&thorn;e he was i-nou&yogh; : ase ech Man wel ou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>him &thorn;ou&yogh;te it was wel vuele i-do : &thorn;at he lai so lowe &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="132">&THORN;at he nere i-bured in herre stude : ase he wel wuyr&thorn;e were;</L>
<L>Gret deol he hadde in is herte : &thorn;at he was a-mor&thorn;red so,</L>
<L>And swuch a creature ase he was : in so lowe stude i-do.</L>
<L>In deorsete he wende wide a-boute : to &thorn;e hei&yogh;e men alle &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="136">To Bischopes and to Abbodes al-so : &thorn;at in Enguelonde were,<MILESTONE N="40b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And bad heom of &thorn;ulke holie bodi : &thorn;at huy it &thorn;annes bere
<PB REF="00000099.tif" N="51"></L>
<L>To herre stude ase it was wuyr&thorn;e : and &thorn;at huy &thorn;are-a-&yogh;ein nere.</L>
<L>his Messagers he sende a-boute : for &thorn;is &thorn;ing wel wide,</L>
<L N="140">And to &thorn;e Abbesse of wiltone : &thorn;at i-hote was wilfride,</L>
<L>And to Eadith&thorn;e &thorn;e holie wumman : &thorn;at Nonne al-so was &thorn;ar,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. &thorn;er</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at was seint Edwardes suster : and &thorn;e kingus dou&yogh;ter Edgar.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at Bischopus and Abbodes : and hei&yogh;e Men mani on</L>
<L N="144">To-gadere comen in a time : ase huy bi-speken echon.</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;is holi bodi huy wenden. : and &thorn;o huy &thorn;er-to come,</L>
<L>hol and sound huy founden it ligge : &thorn;o huy &thorn;at bodi up nome,</L>
<L>Al-so hol it was with-oute weomme : ase it euer er a-liue was&mdash;</L>
<L N="148">&THORN;are nas nou&yogh;t on &thorn;at it i-sei&yogh; : &thorn;at glad and Ioyful &thorn;ere-fore nas.</L>
<L>Ake Eadith&thorn;e, is holie suster : to &thorn;at bodi orn a-non</L>
<L>And bi-clupte &thorn;at bodi and custe it faste : bi-fore heom euerechon;</L>
<L>For gladnesse heo lov&yogh; and weop : teres wel mani on,</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo sai&yogh; hire bro&thorn;ur so a-slawe : and so sovnd of flechs and bon&mdash;</L>
<L>ho-so nadde neuere deol i-sei&yogh;e : of hire he mi&yogh;hte &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="154">&THORN;is hei&yogh;e men with gret honur : &thorn;at holie bodi forth bere,</L>
<L>With gret song and procession. : muche folk &thorn;uder-ward drov&yogh;.</L>
<L N="156">Ore louerd dude &thorn;are for is loue : fair Miracle i-nov&yogh;.</L>
<L>&para; For tweie crupeles &thorn;at in heore limes : al fur-crokede were,</L>
<L>Mid gret hope leien in &thorn;e wey : and a-biden &thorn;e bere :</L>
<L>hore limes bi-gunne to rechchen a-ri&yogh;ht : and hole bi-comen a-non;</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;are was Ioye and blisse i-nou&yogh; : a-mong &thorn;is men ech-on.</L>
<L>&para; His stepmoder, &thorn;at him &thorn;are-to brou&yogh;te : herof herde telle :</L>
<L>hire of-&thorn;ou&yogh;te, &thorn;o he swuch man was : &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">= heo</NOTE> him let so quelle.</L>
<L>Ope hire palefrey heo werth a day : aftur &thorn;at bodi to wiende,</L>
<L>To bidde for-&yogh;iuenesse of hire misdede : &yogh;if god hire wolde siende.</L>
<L>&para; Ase heo wolde &thorn;uder-ward wiende : and with hire mani on,</L>
<L N="166">huy ne mi&yogh;hten make hire palefrey : &thorn;at it ane fote wolde gon;</L>
<L>huy schouen it faste forth&thorn;e-ward and drowen : and neuere &thorn;e betere it nas.</L>
<L N="168">&THORN;e Quiene &thorn;ou&yogh;te on hire misdede : &thorn;at al &thorn;are-fore it was :</L>
<L>heo a-li&yogh;hte of hire palefrey : and wolde a-fote gon</L>
<L>To-ward &thorn;at holie cors. : ake heo nadde power non;</L>
<L>A-&yogh;ein-ward heo mi&yogh;hte wel gon : ake forth&thorn;e-ward for no-&thorn;ing.</L>
<L N="172">Heo bi-lefte, &thorn;o it was non o&thorn;ur : in gret deol and mournyng.
<PB REF="00000100.tif" N="52"></L>
<L>Of hire misdedes heo repentede hire sore : ase manie Men habbeth i-sed,</L>
<L>And cam to guod mendement : are &thorn;at heo were ded.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is Men ladden &thorn;is holie bodi : with gret honur and pruyte</L>
<L N="176">To &thorn;e Abbeye of Schaftesburi : &thorn;are ase he lijth &yogh;uyte</L>
<L>A-mong blake Nonnene &thorn;at &thorn;are beoth : and al-so &thorn;are weren &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fram &thorn;e toun of waraygne : is twenti Mile and mo;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e northha[l]f of &thorn;e hei&yogh;e Autere : in &thorn;e walle bi-side</L>
<L N="180">huy leiden &thorn;is holie bodi : &thorn;at manie men sechez wide.</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;ulke Abbeie of Schafteburij : seint Edward huy ladde,<MILESTONE N="41" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For &thorn;e kyng Alfred, is graunt-sire : &thorn;at hous a-rerd hadde</L>
<L>And made &thorn;ar-inne is dou&yogh;ter Nonne : &thorn;at was i-hote al&yogh;yue&mdash;</L>
<L N="184">For hire loue he hadde &thorn;at hous arerd : and muche guod &thorn;udere in i-&yogh;iue :</L>
<L>An hondret hidenene<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. hidene</NOTE> of guod lond : with hire he &yogh;af &thorn;er</L>
<L>&THORN;at hous, al-so freo in eche point : ase he him-sulf it heold er.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is Abbeie seint edward : lai on and twenti &yogh;er,</L>
<L N="188">So &thorn;at huy i-seien tokningue ofte : &thorn;at he nolde nonmore beo &thorn;er.</L>
<L>For &yogh;wane men comen ofte to is toumbe : ase li&yogh;thliche up huy as bere</L>
<L>And heuen as up and doun ase huy wolden : ase &thorn;ei it li&yogh;ht treov were.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Edward cam al-so ani&yogh;ht : ase in a visioun</L>
<L N="192">To an holi man &thorn;at &thorn;ere was nei&yogh; : in an o&thorn;ur religion;</L>
<L>"Go," he seide, "to Schafteburi : to &thorn;e Abbesse of &thorn;e house,</L>
<L>Dame Aldred &thorn;at clene Maide : &thorn;at is godes spouse,</L>
<L>And seie hire &thorn;at i-nelle nonmore : ligge &thorn;are ich nou do;</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich beo i-brou&yogh;t in an o&thorn;ur stude : and &thorn;at heo segge mi bro&thorn;er so."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is guode Man a-morewe a-ros : and ne fur-&yogh;at nou&yogh;t &thorn;is cas :</L>
<L N="198">To &thorn;e Abbesse he wende of Schafteburi : and tolde al hou it was.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode womman was glad i-nou&yogh;! : to &thorn;e kyngue heo wende sone</L>
<L N="200">And of is bro&thorn;ur tolde him al : and &yogh;wat &thorn;er-of were to done.</L>
<L>Welle, &thorn;e kyng was one glad : &thorn;o he i-heorde telle</L>
<L>So swete ti&thorn;ingue of is bro&thorn;ur : &thorn;ei is moder him liete a-quelle!</L>
<L>&para; He wolde habbe i-went to schafteburi : In shrine him to bringue,</L>
<L N="204">Ac he was so bi-set mid weorre : &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;hte for no &thorn;ingue :</L>
<L>For is fon ornen so faste him up-on : &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;hte &thorn;annes wiende.
<PB REF="00000101.tif" N="53"></L>
<L>To heie Men a-boute in &thorn;e londe : wel sone he gan siende,</L>
<L>And to wilfin &thorn;e guode bischop : &thorn;at was bischop &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="208">&THORN;at huy scholden with gret honour : to schafteburie go</L>
<L>And his bro&thorn;ur in schrine bringue : ase ri&yogh;th was forto done.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Bischop with &thorn;is o&thorn;ur Men : to schafteburi comen sone.</L>
<L>With swi&thorn;e fair procession : to is toumbe huy wende.</L>
<L>A swi&thorn;e fair Miracle a-mong heom alle : ore louerd for him &thorn;ere sende :</L>
<L>For a-non so huy openeden &thorn;at lid : of is swete toumbe &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="214">&THORN;are cam a-doun &thorn;oru&yogh; al &thorn;e churche : ase &thorn;ei it a mist were,</L>
<L>A-mong al &thorn;e prece &thorn;at &thorn;ere was : &thorn;at huy i-seien alle with ei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Fleu&yogh;<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> flen</NOTE> a-mon[g] heom al-so a myst&mdash; : so swote &thorn;ing neuere huy er ne sei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&para; So swote was &thorn;e smul and guod : &thorn;at alle &thorn;at &thorn;ere were</L>
<L N="218">For muru&thorn;e &thorn;ou&yogh;ten &thorn;at huy stoden : in parays and nou&yogh;t &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;is holi bodi up huy nomen : with gret honour and pruyte,</L>
<L N="220">And leiden it in a wel fair schrine : &thorn;are ase it lijth &yogh;uyte.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is manere he was i-schrined : in &thorn;e on an twenti&thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e hei&yogh;e men him brou&yogh;ten fro waram : and bureden him furst &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousend &yogh;er it was and on : after &thorn;ulke stounde</L>
<L>&THORN;at ore louerd was on eor&thorn;e i-bore : and a-li&yogh;hte for us to grounde.</L>
<L>&para; His bro&thorn;ur, &thorn;e king A&thorn;eldred : guod man was i-nou&yogh;;</L>
<L N="226">Edward was is sone i-hote : &thorn;at to alle guodnesse drou&yogh;,<MILESTONE N="41b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at king was seth&thorn;e aftur him : and hei&yogh; halewe in heouene is,</L>
<L>I-cleoped seint Edward aftur is vncle : at West-Munstre he lijth, i-wis.</L>
<L>&para; Op-on Mi&yogh;hel-masse fourtene-ny&yogh;ht : his day fallez in &thorn;e &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>And a-midde &thorn;e Mon&thorn;e of luyde<NOTE PLACE="marg1">18 March</NOTE> : seint Edwardes dai &thorn;ere.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">= &thorn;e ere</NOTE></L>
<L>Nov god for &thorn;e loue of heom bo&thorn;e : &thorn;et swete kingues were,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Ioye of heouene &thorn;at huy beoth inne : with heom us bringue &thorn;ere.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="18" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>18 Franceys.<NOTE PLACE="foot">This life is based on the Vita s. Fr. by S. Bonaventura, in Act. SS. Boll. Oct. 4, p. 742 ff.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Fraunceys, &thorn;e frere Menour : &thorn;at guod man was i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L>Marchaunt he was in his &yogh;onghede : and to eche treuwenesse drov&yogh;.</L>
<L>his Marchaundise he maude a<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> al</NOTE> day : in &thorn;e cite of Asise;
<PB REF="00000102.tif" N="54"></L>
<L N="4">And in almesdede he spendede an<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. an</NOTE> on pouere Men : muchedel is Marchaundise;</L>
<L>For no loue of catel : he it nolde bi-leue,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane ani pouere man him bede : bote he him som-&yogh;wat &yogh;eue.</L>
<L>&para; Ase he cam a day bi &thorn;e wei : he gan mieten bi cas</L>
<L N="8">Ane kni&yogh;t &thorn;at hadde Riche i-beo : and<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. and and</NOTE> swi&thorn;e a-pouered was;</L>
<L>vuele he was i-clo&thorn;ed al-so : and bad him sum guod.</L>
<L>Seint Fraunceys hadde reu&thorn;e of him : and one &yogh;wyle he with-stod,</L>
<L>&para; he strepte of is clo&thorn;es of is rug : and &yogh;af &thorn;is pouere kny&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="12">And &thorn;er-aftur ase he lay a-slepe : in is bedde a-ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>A swi&thorn;e noble paleys : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at he i-sei&yogh;;</L>
<L>he Axede was &thorn;at paleys were : &thorn;at so riche was and hei&yogh;;</L>
<L>Men seiden him &thorn;at it was his : and is kni&yogh;tes al-so.</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;o &thorn;is holie Man a-wok : sum-&yogh;wat he &thorn;ou&yogh;te do.</L>
<L>In &thorn;at paleys him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he sai&yogh; al-so : kny&yogh;htes Armes &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And with afair creoiz &thorn;oru&yogh;-out : I-markede alle huy were.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou&yogh;te he, "ore louerd it wole : &thorn;at ich mi-seolf kny&yogh;t beo,</L>
<L N="20">And swy&thorn;e feble ich am &thorn;are-to : bote ich me bet bi-seo."</L>
<L>An Eorl &thorn;are was in poile<NOTE PLACE="marg1">= Apoile</NOTE> : &thorn;at was corteys and hende :</L>
<L>he &thorn;ou&yogh;te kny&yogh;t beo i-maud of him : &thorn;uder-ward he gan wende.</L>
<L>Ase he wende towar[d] &thorn;is Eorl : for-to beo i-maud kni&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="24">Ore swete louerd in Auision : to him cam a ni&yogh;th;</L>
<L>"Sei&yogh;e me," he seide, "of &thorn;e louerd : and of &thorn;e hyne al-so,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e riche man and of &thorn;e pouere : &yogh;wuch may &thorn;e mest guod do?"</L>
<L>"Bote &thorn;e louerd," quath &thorn;is o&thorn;ur : "and he &thorn;at is riche."</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou haddest almest i-chose," ore louerd seide : "&thorn;at ful oni-liche :</L>
<L>For truste of &thorn;e hyne : &thorn;ene louerd &thorn;ou for-soke;</L>
<L N="30">&THORN;ov nome vuele &thorn;in Avision : &thorn;ou most &thorn;e bet bi-loke.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Armure and &thorn;e paleis : &thorn;at &thorn;ou so noble i-sei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Elles-&yogh;ware &thorn;ov schalt finde : Ake &thorn;ou ne comest nou&yogh;t &yogh;uit so hei&yogh;e;</L>
<L>Kny&yogh;tes &thorn;ov schalt habbe onder &thorn;e : &thorn;ulke Armes for-to lede.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore wend &thorn;e hom a-&yogh;ein : and bi-&thorn;ench bet &thorn;i dede!"</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is holi man, &thorn;o he a-wok : a-&yogh;ein wende to Asise,</L>
<L N="36">And &thorn;ou&yogh;te al on Ihesu crist : and bi-lefde is Marchaundise,</L>
<L>And bad ore louerd ny&yogh;ht and dai : &thorn;at he scholde him rede</L>
<L>And some tokningue senden him : hov he scholde is lijf lede.
<PB REF="00000103.tif" N="55"></L>
<L>&para; A day, ase &thorn;is holie man : with-oute Asise him drou&yogh;,<MILESTONE N="42" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="40">he mette a lodlich Mesel : &thorn;at revlich was i-nou&yogh;</L>
<L>And bad him sum guod for godes loue. : seint Fraunceys a-li&yogh;hte</L>
<L>And bi-clupte and custe &thorn;ane sike man : ase faire ase he mi&yogh;hte,</L>
<L>And of is seluer him tok : and bad him habbe guod day.</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;o nuste he &yogh;ware he was bi-come : ne in none stude him ne say.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;ou&yogh;te wel ho it was : and aftur &thorn;ulke dede</L>
<L>he wep and cride on ihesu crist : &thorn;at he scholde him sum-&yogh;wat rede;</L>
<L>And ofte he wolde bi costome : to Meseles fare</L>
<L N="48">And sechen heom at heore owene hous : bote he founde hem elles|&yogh;ware,</L>
<L>And cusse heore hondene and heore fet : and heore Mouth al-s[o]</L>
<L>And &yogh;yue heom guod wel largeliche&mdash; : bi costome he wolde it do.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">a later hand adds als</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Bi a churche of seint Damian : a day he cam gon,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;at ope &thorn;e poynte was to falle a-doun. : In he wende a-non</L>
<L>And kneolede a-doun bi-fore &thorn;e croiz : ase he dude wel ofte.</L>
<L>&THORN;o spac a voiz &thorn;are-inne : wel Mildeliche and softe</L>
<L>And seide, "Fraunceys, go &thorn;e forth : and a-rer up min hous an hei&yogh;,</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;at, &thorn;ou sixt, fallez to grounde : and al destruyd is nei&yogh;."</L>
<L>&para; Seint Fraunceys, for &thorn;e churche was : a-done-ward al i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Wende &thorn;at ore louer[d] &thorn;are-bi seide&mdash; : ake &thorn;ar-of nas it nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>he wende and solde is clo&thorn;es a-non : and muche of is o&thorn;ur &thorn;ingue,</L>
<L N="60">And &thorn;e panes &thorn;at he nam &thorn;are-with : to &thorn;is church gan bringue.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pr[e]ost of &thorn;e churche he fond &thorn;ere : &thorn;e panes he wolde him take,</L>
<L>To arere up &thorn;e pouere churche. : and he heom gan for-sake;</L>
<L>he ne dorste nou&yogh;t for is fader : ne for is o&thorn;ur freond, he seide,</L>
<L N="64">So muche tresor nime of him : bote it were bi heore rede.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Fraunceys nam &thorn;at tresor : &thorn;o &thorn;e o&thorn;ur it for-sok,</L>
<L>And in a fenestre leide it &thorn;ere : and in ore louerdes warde it tok.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e ty&thorn;ingue cam to is fader : &thorn;at he hadde i-sold is guod,</L>
<L N="68">Toward him he wende anon : and for wrath was nei&yogh; wod.</L>
<L>Seint Frau[n]ceys was i-war of him : and ne bi-lefte nou&yogh;t bi-hinde,</L>
<L>he wende and hudde him in a Dich : &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;hte him nou&yogh;t finde.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is Diche wel longue he lay : in hunguer and wrech-hede,</L>
<L N="72">And euere cride on Ihesu crist : &thorn;at he scholde him betere rede.
<PB REF="00000104.tif" N="56"></L>
<L>&para; So longue he was &thorn;are in meseise : &thorn;at he for-ferde nei&yogh;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vnne&thorn;e him cou&thorn;e i-knowe : ani man &thorn;at him sei&yogh;.</L>
<L>At&thorn;e laste in meseise i-nov&yogh; : he wende to Asise.</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;at folk, &thorn;o huy seien him com[e] : heom gan ful sore a-grise</L>
<L>And seiden "here cometh a wod Man" : huy harleden him wel faste</L>
<L>And smiten and pulten here and &thorn;ere : and dunge on him caste.</L>
<L>Seint Fraunceis wende euere forth : ase &thorn;ei him no-&thorn;ing nere.</L>
<L N="80">&para; his fader cam al-so bi cas : and i-mette him &thorn;ere:</L>
<L>he ladde him hom to is hous : and beot him sore i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L>And bad him bringue hom &thorn;at catel : &thorn;at he er a-wei drov&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he ne mi&yogh;hte habbe non o&thorn;ur word : he bond him swi&thorn;e strongue;</L>
<L N="84">So &thorn;at &thorn;is guode man : in prisone lay ful longue.</L>
<L>At&thorn;e laste, &thorn;e &yogh;wyle is fader : out of toune gan i-wende,<MILESTONE N="42b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>his Moder hadde reov&thorn;e of him : and brou&yogh;te him out of bende.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he was out of bendes i-brou&yogh;t : he ne bi-lefte no leng &thorn;er,</L>
<L N="88">he wende to &thorn;e Dich a&yogh;ein : fro &yogh;wannes he cam er.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;is housebonde cam hom : and ne founde him nou&yogh;t &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e sore he beot is wijf : and axede &yogh;ware he were.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e churche of seint Damian : &thorn;e housebonde wende &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="92">And fond &thorn;at tresor al-hol &thorn;ere : ase he it hadde i-do.</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e he wende to &thorn;e Dich : and founde is sone &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>he axede at him for &yogh;wat &thorn;ingue : &thorn;at tresor a-wei he bere;</L>
<L>And &thorn;o he i-sei&yogh; al &thorn;en ende : &thorn;at he luyte &thorn;ar-of rou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="96">he ladde Fraunceys forth with him : ant bi-fore &thorn;e Bischop him brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And bad, &yogh;if he alles wolde : &thorn;e worldes guod bi-leue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he bi-fore &thorn;e Bischope &thorn;er : &thorn;at tresor up &yogh;eue.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Fraunceis with &thorn;ulke worde : glad and Ioyful stod:</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;are and bi-fore god he &yogh;af up : al his eor&thorn;elich guod,</L>
<L>And streopte of is clo&thorn;es : a-non to is bare liche</L>
<L>And bi-fore &thorn;e Bischope tok is fader : and bad him beo guod and riche;</L>
<L>he seide, "ich &thorn;e habbe fader i-cleoped : euere to &thorn;is day,</L>
<L N="104">And nou&thorn;e it is so feor i-come : &thorn;at non more i-ne may;</L>
<L>Segge ich mot mi .pater-noster : heonne-forth&thorn;e-ward i-wis</L>
<L>And to mi fader holde me : &thorn;at in heuene is."
<PB REF="00000105.tif" N="57"></L>
<L>Nakede he wende fram is fader : bi-fore heom &thorn;are echon;</L>
<L N="108">Worldes guod aftur &thorn;ulke tyme : ne bod he neuereft non.</L>
<L>&para; A seli vplondischse Man : &thorn;at nakede sai&yogh; him go,</L>
<L>Gret deol in is heorte hadde : for is chele and for is wo:</L>
<L>he &yogh;af him ane olde Mantel : his bones &thorn;are-with to hele;</L>
<L N="112">Seint Fraunceis it vnder-feng : to witien him fram chele,</L>
<L>his licame he heolede &thorn;are-with : and in myseise i-nov&yogh;</L>
<L>A-&yogh;en &thorn;are he was i-bore : to Asise he him drov&yogh;.</L>
<L>&para; Ase he hadde er i-beo so riche : and so wel was i-knowe,</L>
<L N="116">A beggare he cam a[n]d bad is mete : &thorn;ere-aftur in a &thorn;rowe,</L>
<L>Fram dore to dore he bad is mete : and wonede him &thorn;ar-to;</L>
<L>Some weren wro&thorn;e for is dedes : and no guod nolden him do.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e ordre of frere Menours : he ne made no-&thorn;ing &yogh;uyte;</L>
<L N="120">he bi-gan in pouerte i-nov&yogh; : and with luyte pruyte.</L>
<L>&para; Men of &thorn;e contreie weren : a-boute for-to a-mende</L>
<L>Seint Damianes churche : &thorn;at al a-done-ward wende,</L>
<L>&THORN;are ase seint Fraunceys hadde i-beo : and tresor bi-left &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;o he ne mi&yogh;hte non o&thorn;ur do : &thorn;e churche for-to a-rere,</L>
<L>he wende &thorn;udere and sore swonk : and bar morter &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e he eode and bad is mete : &yogh;wane he hadde al i-do.</L>
<L>&para; Ane churche seth&thorn;e of seint peter : men arerden elles-&yogh;[w]are:</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;is holie man in is miseise : wel sone he was &thorn;are</L>
<L>And Morter and ston drou&yogh; &thorn;er-to : and sore swonk al-so,</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e eode and bad is mete : &thorn;o he hadde al i-do.<MILESTONE N="43" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;wane he heorde of ani churche : &thorn;at ou&yogh;wer was for-ta-rere,</L>
<L N="132">he wende &thorn;udere, and longue him &thorn;ou&yogh;te : are he were &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&para; To seinte Marie in desert : ate laste he wende wel stille</L>
<L>And criede on ore louerd ni&yogh;ht and day : &thorn;at he dude bi him is wille</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he &yogh;eue him is grace &thorn;ere : in &yogh;wat manere he best mi&yogh;hte</L>
<L N="136">his churche &thorn;at a-doneward was : best a-rere up and di&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at god him &yogh;af &thorn;e grace : &thorn;at he &thorn;are bi-gan</L>
<L>&THORN;e ordre of frere Menours : to saui mani a man.</L>
<L>&para; In &thorn;e bi-guynningue of &thorn;is ordre : ase ore louerd &yogh;ef &thorn;at cas,</L>
<L N="140">Ane masse he i-heorde a day : &thorn;at of &thorn;e Apostles was;</L>
<L>As man rat &yogh;uyt a-mong us : in &thorn;e godspelle it seide &thorn;o</L>
<L>&THORN;at ore louerd hiet is desciples : &thorn;o huy scholden a-boute go,
<PB REF="00000106.tif" N="58"></L>
<L>&THORN;at huy ne beren with heom gol[d] ne seluer : &yogh;wane huy wenden ouer lond,</L>
<L>Ne baggue, ne tweie curtles no&thorn;ur : ne schon, goinde with ouer lond<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Ashm. ne staf in hor hond</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; In &thorn;is manere ore louerd hiet : his Apostles gon.</L>
<L N="146">&THORN;o seint Fraunceis i-heorde &thorn;is : he dude of is schon,</L>
<L>And poruei&yogh;ede &thorn;at frere Menours : barefot scholden gon,</L>
<L N="148">With-oute bagge, with-oute staf : with-oute ani &thorn;ing to spene&mdash;</L>
<L>Bote ech frere Menour do al-so : he ne halt nou&yogh;t is ordre, ich wene.</L>
<L>In stude of is gurdel al-so : with rope he him bond&mdash;</L>
<L>In &thorn;is manere frere Menours : scholden go ouer lond.</L>
<L N="152">&para; Seint Fraunceis bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;us : to don &thorn;is holie dede</L>
<L>And made &thorn;e ordre of frere Menours : al ase &thorn;e godspel sede.</L>
<L>&para; Bernard, &thorn;at was a guod scholer : formest to him cam</L>
<L>And &thorn;e ordre of frere menours : of him formest he nam.</L>
<L>he axede at him hov he scholde best : &thorn;e world clanliche for-sake.</L>
<L>To seint Nicholas churche huy wenden : ane masse-bok huy gonne take.</L>
<L N="158">&THORN;e bok was i-closed faste to : seint Fraunceis hine gan vndo,</L>
<L>Al on-mundliche he on-dude &thorn;e bok : and &thorn;e furste &thorn;at he cam to</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;at was a godspel &thorn;at seith : "&yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt parfijt beo,</L>
<L>Sul al &thorn;i guod and &yogh;if pouere men : and seth&thorn;e siwe me!"</L>
<L>&para; Al vn-Mundlingue he cam eft-sone : to a godspel &thorn;at seide :</L>
<L>&THORN;at man ne scholde seluer ne gold : bi &thorn;e weie lede.</L>
<L N="164">&THORN;e &thorn;ridde tyme al on-Mundlingue : &thorn;e masse-bok he wende :</L>
<L>&THORN;o cam he opon &thorn;is godspel : ase ore louerd him grace sende :</L>
<L>"ho-so wole come after me : him-sulf he schal for-sake</L>
<L>And is owene rode bere : and &thorn;ene wei after me so take."</L>
<L N="168">&para; "&THORN;ov i-fuxt here," quath seint Fraunceis : "hou ore louerd in a stounde</L>
<L>Sent us grace ope &yogh;wuche &thorn;ingue : we schullen &thorn;is ordre founde :</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;eos &thorn;reo god-spelles, &thorn;ov fuxt : &thorn;at we habbeth furst i-founde</L>
<L>We schullen foundi al ore ordre : and opon &thorn;is strongue grounde."</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;is &thorn;is</NOTE> &thorn;reo godspelles he maude<NOTE PLACE="marg1">maudre</NOTE> is ordre : and is riule<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Ryvle on the margin.</NOTE> for|soth&thorn;&mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e frere Menor brekez is ordre : &thorn;at &thorn;are-a&yogh;ein ou&yogh;t doth&thorn;.</L>
<L>&para; Fre Gyles was &thorn;o &thorn;e ferste&mdash; : &thorn;at guod scoler hadde i-beo,
<PB REF="00000107.tif" N="59"></L>
<L>&THORN;at aftur frere Bernard &thorn;e ordre nam : and seth&thorn;e o&thorn;ur &thorn;reo.<MILESTONE N="43b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="176">So &thorn;at vnder heom alle sixe freres : to-gadere weren i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei &thorn;is ordre were i-maud : i-confermed nas heo nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Fraunceys &thorn;e holie Man : &thorn;o god &thorn;e tyme sende,</L>
<L>To confermi is ordre a-ri&yogh;ht : toward Rome he wende.</L>
<L N="180">Ake swi&thorn;e sore he was of-drad : laste &thorn;e pope were</L>
<L>Contrarious a-&yogh;ein is Ordre : &thorn;at heo i-confermed nere.</L>
<L>Ake forth he wende to fondi : he nolde nou&yogh;t beo bi-hynde;</L>
<L>And euere he bad Ihesu crist : &thorn;at he moste som grace finde.</L>
<L N="184">&para; &THORN;o &thorn;ou&yogh;te him in a wision : &thorn;at [he] i-sai&yogh; a gret treo,</L>
<L>So hei&yogh; &thorn;at he was a-drad : toward &thorn;e coppe i-seo;</L>
<L>And netheles on aunture he him dude : and nam &thorn;ar-of a bov&yogh;</L>
<L>Aboue in &thorn;e hexte stude : and toward him it drov&yogh; :</L>
<L N="188">hit bei&yogh; al a-doun to him : aftur is wille i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L>For al &thorn;at him dradde furst : &thorn;at it was hei&yogh; and tov&yogh;.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;is holie man a-wok : on &thorn;is sweuene he &thorn;ou&yogh;te longue</L>
<L>And &thorn;are-&thorn;oru&yogh; he hopede of &thorn;e pope : sum grace for-to afongue;</L>
<L N="192">For &thorn;e treo &thorn;at was so hei&yogh; : lij&yogh;thtliche to grounde drov&yogh;,</L>
<L>Also he hopede &thorn;ene hei&yogh;e pope : to is wille bringue i-nov&yogh;.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e pope Innocent : &thorn;o he to Rome cam,</L>
<L>he bad graunti is Religion : to amendi cristindam,</L>
<L N="196">A[n]t &thorn;at he scholde is ordre preouen : and is Revle al-so</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; &thorn;e godspel of godes word : and &thorn;er-aftur do.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e pope is Revle isei&yogh; : &thorn;at heo was clene and guod,</L>
<L>And ope &thorn;e godspelle i-founded al : ase he wel onder-stod,</L>
<L N="200">In is herte he grauntede it : ake nou&yogh;t with is Mouth a-non,</L>
<L>For he moste is cardinales : conseili &thorn;are-uppe ech-on.</L>
<L>&para; So &thorn;at a-Mong &thorn;is Cardinales : counseil &thorn;ere was i-nome.</L>
<L>Some heolden &thorn;are-a&yogh;ein : and also &thorn;are-with some.</L>
<L N="204">&THORN;o was &thorn;er a Cardinal : &thorn;at Bischop was al-so,</L>
<L>Maister Iohan of seint poul : &thorn;at faste heold &thorn;er-to</L>
<L>And seide, "&yogh;if we destourbieth him : a&yogh;ein &thorn;e godspelle we beoth&thorn;,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane he spechut al vpe godes word : ase we wel i-seoth&thorn;."</L>
<L N="208">&para; In Avisioun to &thorn;e pope : a-ni&yogh;ht also it cam</L>
<L>&THORN;at he grauntede him is Reule : to saui cristindom.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e pope grauntede him : al is Reule to do,
<PB REF="00000108.tif" N="60"></L>
<L>And confermede &thorn;oru&yogh; al &thorn;e court : and bi-hiet him more &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L N="212">&THORN;o wende forth&thorn; &thorn;is holie Man : and is freres with&thorn; him nam</L>
<L>And prechede a-boute &thorn;e godspelles : to amendi cristindom.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e contrei&yogh;e i-sei&yogh; heom ferst : gret speche was &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Some seiden &thorn;at Aunte-crist : o&thorn;ur is desciples it were;</L>
<L N="216">So &thorn;at in wel manie studes : luyte guod men heom sende</L>
<L>And huy weren ofte ofhungrede sore : ase huy a-boute wende.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at huy comen into a stude : and ofhungrede weren sore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at some of &thorn;e freres hadden i-&thorn;ou&yogh;t : in &thorn;e ordre to beo non-more.</L>
<L>&THORN;o cam &thorn;ere a wel fair man : and brou&yogh;te heom mete i-nov&yogh;&mdash;<MILESTONE N="44" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sone huy nusten &yogh;ware he bi-cam : ne &yogh;woder-ward he drov&yogh;.</L>
<L N="222">&THORN;is freres i-sei&yogh;en fule &thorn;o : &thorn;at an Aungel it was :</L>
<L>&THORN;e studefastore in heore ordre : huy weren for &thorn;is cas</L>
<L N="224">And bi-hieten god &thorn;at huy nolden neuere : for miseise ne for wo</L>
<L>In &thorn;e ordre bi heore mi&yogh;hte : pouerte fur-go.</L>
<L>&para; Bi-side &thorn;e toun of Asise : feor fram eche strete</L>
<L>huy wenden alle to one stude : &thorn;at was al fur-lete.</L>
<L N="228">Miseyse huy hadden &thorn;are i-nov&yogh; : and ofte wepen sore,</L>
<L>For defaute of heore sustinaunce : and for defaute of bokes more.</L>
<L>For huy ne hadde bokes none : &yogh;ware-on huy mi&yogh;hten loke,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e croiz huy bi-heolden al day : in-stude of heore boke,</L>
<L N="232">And beden god<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. guod</NOTE>, &yogh;if it were is wille : &thorn;at he scholde heom sum guod teche,</L>
<L>For huy nadden non o&thorn;ur bok : ne nusten &yogh;ware-with any a-reche.</L>
<L>&para; To seinte Marie in desert : &thorn;annes huy gunne i-wiende,</L>
<L>Ase huy bi-gunnen furst &thorn;e ordre : to bringue as &thorn;are to ende.</L>
<L N="236">Seint Fraunceis wende bi &thorn;e londe : and prechede a-boute &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Men wenden, &thorn;o huy sei&yogh;en him furst : &thorn;at of an o&thorn;ur worlde he were;</L>
<L>For he capede euere upward : toward heouene an hei&yogh;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men wondreden and speken &thorn;ar-of : euer-ech &thorn;at him i-sei&yogh;.</L>
<L N="240">Manie heolden him a truant : of &thorn;e deueles lore</L>
<L>And harleden him here and &thorn;er : and ofte beten him sore.</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie man ne tok none &yogh;eme : ake criede ore louerdes ore,</L>
<L>And &yogh;ware men duden him mest schame : &thorn;udere he drov&yogh; &thorn;e more.</L>
<L N="244">&para; Idel ne kepte he neuere beo : he ne louede no &thorn;in[g] so luyte</L>
<L>Ne hatede so muche ase he dude Aise : and idelnesse and pruyte.
<PB REF="00000109.tif" N="61"></L>
<L>"Frere Asse" he cleopede is owene flesch&mdash; : for &yogh;e wuten wel &thorn;at an Asse,</L>
<L>Nabbe heo neuere so luyte mete : is trauail nis no &thorn;e lasse,</L>
<L N="248">For heo is i-harled here and &thorn;ere : and to file weorke i-do,</L>
<L>I-priked and i-scourget eke : and sackes heo berez al-so;</L>
<L>Of &yogh;eomere &thorn;ingue heo is i-fed : &yogh;wane heo alles comez &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L>And selde heo is i-coureyd wel : with-ovte nail an scho.</L>
<L N="252">&para; He seruede so is owene flesch : and cleopede it "frere Asse":</L>
<L>Mete he &yogh;af him luyte i-nov : and to clo&thorn;ingue wel lasse;</L>
<L>he prikede also and scourgede ek : and &thorn;oru&yogh;-out &thorn;e contrei&yogh;e</L>
<L>harlede it and deope wod : bare-fot in deope weye.</L>
<L N="256">&YOGH;wane he i-sai&yogh; ani idel Man : &thorn;at louede glotonie</L>
<L>And ne trauailede nou&yogh;t for is mete : he cleopede him "frere flie":</L>
<L>For &thorn;e flie ne doth non o&thorn;ur guod : bote fleoth feor and neor</L>
<L>And a-waytez &yogh;wane men goth to mete : o&thorn;ur to heore soper;</L>
<L>A-non so &thorn;e Disch is i-set a-doun : heo wole beo ope &thorn;e brerde&mdash;</L>
<L>Of trauail ne wo ne kep[t]h&thorn; heo nou&yogh;t : bote &thorn;at heo wel ferde;</L>
<L N="262">&para; &YOGH;wane a Man hath al dai i-swounke : &thorn;ei he it hadde i-swore,</L>
<L>he ne schal to is Disch come so sone : &thorn;at &thorn;e flie nele beo bi-fore.</L>
<L N="264">&para; Also farez manie idele Men : &thorn;at non o&thorn;er guod nelleth do,</L>
<L>Bote &yogh;wanne o&thorn;ur Men beth to-ward &thorn;e mete : &yogh;are huy beth &thorn;ar-to;<MILESTONE N="44b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>At&thorn;e Dische huy wollez al-so sone beo : ase huy &thorn;at habbez i-swounke,</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne is al heore weork i-do : habben huy i-&yogh;ete and i-dronke;</L>
<L>&THORN;anne goth&thorn; huy ligge slepe : o&thorn;ur goth&thorn; to some folie.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore seint Fraunceys cleopede : swuche men "frere flie".</L>
<L N="270">&para; Of no&thorn;ing nas &thorn;is holie man : so glad ase of edwij&yogh;t:</L>
<L>For &yogh;wane ani Man opbraid is pouerte : he was in gret deli&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane Men cleopeden him hoxtare : o&thorn;ur cheorl o&thorn;ur cheorles sone&mdash;</L>
<L>For port-Men beoth ofte boistouse : and hoxtares bi wone&mdash;</L>
<L N="274">"leue bro&thorn;er," he seide : "certes, &thorn;ov seist soth&thorn;,</L>
<L>I-blessed beo &thorn;ou for &thorn;at word : and alle &thorn;at so doth&thorn;!</L>
<L>Preses<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. Perses (Ash. Peres)</NOTE> sone Bernard : it bi-cometh&thorn; bi ri&yogh;the lawe</L>
<L>To heore telle of is ri&yogh;hte : ich auch&yogh;te beo glad and fawe."</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane men preiseden ou&yogh;t of is cuynde : he nadde &thorn;are-of no deli&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore ho-so wolde him paye : segge him sum edwi&yogh;t;
<PB REF="00000110.tif" N="62"></L>
<L N="280">And bi-fore al folk a-brod : in is prechingue he seide</L>
<L>his Miseise and is defaute : ofte and is wrechhede.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; In poyle seint Fraunceis &yogh;eode : some time ouer lond,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at a porsful of panes : bi &thorn;e weie he fond;</L>
<L N="284">he ne tok non more &yogh;eme &thorn;are-to : &thorn;ane to so muche fen.</L>
<L>his felawe bad him nimen heom up : and dele pouere men.</L>
<L>"I nelle nou&yogh;t," seide seint Fraunceis : "of o&thorn;ur mannes dele."</L>
<L>"Me &thorn;unchez," seide is felawe &thorn;o : "&thorn;at &thorn;ov nart nou&yogh;t fele,</L>
<L N="288">&THORN;at &thorn;ou ne louest nou&yogh;t pouere men : &yogh;wane &thorn;ou nelt heom don no guod."</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie man i-heorde &thorn;is : and one &yogh;wile in &thorn;ou&yogh;te stod;</L>
<L>&para; "&THORN;ou schalt," he seide, "sone i-seo : &yogh;[w]at &thorn;is panes beoth ech-on."</L>
<L>he wende and nam up &thorn;at pors : and openede him a-non:</L>
<L N="292">&THORN;o crep &thorn;are out a naddre : &thorn;e fouleste &thorn;at mi&yogh;hte gon,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e pors al amti was : and peni bi-lefte non;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at was &thorn;e Deuel of helle : &thorn;at in &thorn;e fourme of panes lay,</L>
<L>For-to bi-traye &thorn;is holie man : &yogh;wane he &thorn;e panes i-sai&yogh;.</L>
<L N="296">&para; &THORN;is holie Man seint Fraunceis : among ech manere best</L>
<L>Muche he louede &yogh;oungue lambre : and a-nourede heom euere mest,</L>
<L N="298">For ore louerd euenede him-sulf to a lomb : &thorn;oru&yogh; seint Iohan &thorn;e Baptist,</L>
<L>And for it is with-oute felonie : and milde ase ihesu crist;</L>
<L>And ofte &yogh;wane men wolden heom quelle : fram de&thorn;e he heom brou&yogh;te</L>
<L>With biddingue and with is faire word : and fale si&thorn;es heom bou&yogh;te.</L>
<L N="302">&para; In &thorn;e Abbeye of seint verecunde : a &yogh;oung lomb he founde,</L>
<L>A souwe a-strangli it a-non : and fret it in a stounde.</L>
<L>Seint Fraunceis stod and bi-heold : "A-mong alle bestes," he seide,</L>
<L>"A-corsed &thorn;ou beo, lu&thorn;ere souwe : &thorn;at dudest &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere dede;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;i lijf beo schort and strong : and &thorn;i deth&thorn; beo strong al-so,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at no &thorn;ing ne ete of &thorn;i flesch : &yogh;wane &thorn;ou ert of liue i-do!"</L>
<L N="308">&THORN;o bi-gan &thorn;e souwe a-non : ase he &thorn;is word seide,</L>
<L>To beo ful of schabbe and of buyles : and of o&thorn;ur wrechhede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo orn out al of quiture : and ase &thorn;at folk i-sai&yogh;,<MILESTONE N="45" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In wrechhede and in sorewe inov : heo deide &thorn;ane &thorn;ridde day,</L>
<L N="312">And fur-rotede and stonk foule i-nov&yogh;. : no best &thorn;at it i-sei&yogh;,</L>
<L>Rauon ne pie no o&thorn;ur foul : nolde enes come &thorn;are-nei&yogh;.
<PB REF="00000111.tif" N="63"></L>
<L>&para; For seint Fraunceis louede lambre<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. lombre</NOTE> : ase al &thorn;at folk i-sai&yogh;,</L>
<L>On of is freond for godes loue : a lomb him &yogh;ef a day&yogh;.</L>
<L N="316">&THORN;is lomb wolde old and &yogh;oung : al dai nei&yogh; him beo</L>
<L>And maken with him Ioye i-nou&yogh; : &yogh;wanne it him mi&yogh;hte i-seo.</L>
<L>Seint Fraunceis hiet &thorn;is schep a day : &yogh;wanne it heorde freres singue,</L>
<L>To churche gon at eche tide : and ne lete for none &thorn;ingue.</L>
<L N="320">&THORN;at schep aftur &thorn;ulke time : selde wolde a-bide,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane hit i-heorde freres in &thorn;e queor : &thorn;at hit nas at eche tide;</L>
<L>Blete it wolde a-&yogh;enes heom : for it ne cou&thorn;e nou&yogh;t elles do;</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane it sai&yogh; &thorn;e freres sitten a-kneo : kneuli it wolde al-so,</L>
<L N="324">And &yogh;wane ani preost sacrede : kneoli it wolde &thorn;ar-to</L>
<L>And wel inwardliche bi-holde &thorn;udere : ase it sai&yogh; o&thorn;ur freres do.</L>
<L>Wel au&yogh;te we onouri &thorn;e sacringue : &yogh;wane a swuch best wolde!</L>
<L>A wonder bede-man it was : to come to godes<NOTE PLACE="marg1">A later hand adds: seruice so</NOTE> bolde!</L>
<L N="328">&para; Ase seint Fraunceis &thorn;is holie man : ouer lond ofte him drou&yogh;,</L>
<L>Wilde foules, smale and grete : honoureden him i-nov&yogh;.</L>
<L>For ase he wende in atyme : to prechie ouer lond,</L>
<L>An hep of foules grete i-nov&yogh; : In a stude he fond;</L>
<L N="332">huy songuen and maden noyse i-nov : euerech in is wise;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;uyt &thorn;e holie man a-mong heom cam : huy nolden nou&yogh;t enes arise.</L>
<L>&para; "Beu frere," quath &thorn;is holie Man : "ore sustren &thorn;at beoth here</L>
<L>honourieth god &thorn;at heom made : ech in his manere;</L>
<L N="336">Ri&yogh;ht is &thorn;at we don also : are we fram heom gon."</L>
<L>huy gonne to segge heore tidene : among &thorn;is foules ech-on.</L>
<L>&THORN;o maden &thorn;is foules so gret noise : &thorn;at huy ne mi&yogh;hten no&thorn;ing i-here.</L>
<L>"Sostrene," quath &thorn;is holie Man : "chaungiez eouwer manere,</L>
<L>Beoth&thorn; nou&thorn;e stille and lateh&thorn; me segge : mine tidene with mi frere,</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e &yogh;e mouwen aftur us : euer-ech with is fere."</L>
<L N="342">&para; &THORN;is foules a-non-ri&yogh;ht to is heste : stille weren al-so</L>
<L>And seten and heorden heore tidene : for-to huy hadden al ido.</L>
<L>"Nou sustren," quath &thorn;is holie man : "we habbuth&thorn; i-seid ore tide,</L>
<L>Bi-guynnez ouwer &yogh;wane &yogh;e wollez : &yogh;e ne &thorn;oruen no leng abide."</L>
<L N="346">&THORN;is foules bi-gonne singue anon : &thorn;e leste and eke &thorn;e meste&mdash;</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e gret pouwer he hadde of god : &thorn;at foules weren at is heste!</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is holie man wende him forth : to prechi ouer lond:</L>
<L>A gret hep eft-sone of foules : in on o&thorn;ur stude he fond.
<PB REF="00000112.tif" N="64"></L>
<L N="350">he wende forth&thorn; a-mong heom. : &thorn;is foules bi-gonne echon</L>
<L>Louten to him wel mildeliche : and honouri him a-non.</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie Man at-stod ane &yogh;wile : and &thorn;ou&yogh;te heom sum guod teche,</L>
<L>And ri&yogh;ht ase it weren men of witte : &thorn;is foules he gan to preche:</L>
<L>&para; "Leoue sostrene," he seide, "for godes loue : honourieth&thorn; ore creatur,</L>
<L>For a-mong alle liues : &yogh;e au&yogh;ten him don honour:</L>
<L N="356">For he &yogh;ifht eov nobleie i-nou&yogh; : wynguene for-to fleo,<MILESTONE N="45b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And fe&thorn;erene to beren eov up-on hei&yogh; : wide for-to seo,</L>
<L>And mete &yogh;ware &yogh;e wollez a-li&yogh;hte : with-oute eche-manere suynche,</L>
<L>he &yogh;ifth eov also muche pruyte and ayse : ase &yogh;e mouwen onne &thorn;enche;</L>
<L N="360">Delue ne diki ne &thorn;orue &yogh;e na&thorn;ur : ase manie Men moten do,</L>
<L>And &yogh;eot &yogh;e mouwen habbe mete i-nov&yogh; : &yogh;wane o&thorn;ere nabbeth nou&yogh;t so."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is foules heorkeneden him wel stille : &thorn;e &yogh;wile is prechingue i-laste,</L>
<L>And fram wodes and fram o&thorn;ur studes : &thorn;uder-word drowen faste.</L>
<L N="364">&THORN;o &thorn;is holie man hadde i-do : he wende forth a-non</L>
<L>And bi-tei&yogh;te heom ihesu crist : and blessede heom ech-on;</L>
<L>he pleide with heom murie i-nou&yogh; : ase he among heom gan gon,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">These vv. are out of order.</NOTE></L>
<L>And strokede heom with is longue fleue. : &thorn;ere nolde a-rise nou&yogh;t on,</L>
<L>Are he wolde bidden heom wende forth : &yogh;ware huy hadden to done.</L>
<L>&THORN;is foules, &thorn;o huy heorden &thorn;is : huy flouwen forth wel sone.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Fraunceis a-mong al o&thorn;ur &thorn;ingue : ri&yogh;ht at is heorte grounde</L>
<L>Ofte he &thorn;ou&yogh;te deope i-nov&yogh; : of ore louerdes wounden;</L>
<L N="372">So studefast-liche in is &thorn;ou&yogh;t : non o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing he ne nam.</L>
<L>hit bi-feol at &thorn;e holie rode-tid : &thorn;at a-&yogh;ein Mi&yogh;hel-Masse cam,</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e hul of Auuerne : ase it was ore louerdes wille,</L>
<L>Al one in is oresones : &thorn;ere he lai wel stille,</L>
<L>he &thorn;ou&yogh;te on ore louerdes woundene : so deope &thorn;at it nas non ende:</L>
<L>An Aungel he i-sai&yogh; an hei&yogh; : ri&yogh;ht fram heouene wiende,</L>
<L>&para; Six wingene him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he hadde : &thorn;at schinden bri&yogh;hte and wide,</L>
<L>&THORN;e tweie stoden up a-bouen is heued : and &thorn;e tweien bi is side,</L>
<L N="380">And &thorn;oru&yogh;-out ouer is wombe a-creoyz : tweien &thorn;ere weren al-so,</L>
<L>Ase men seoth&thorn; ofte in churche depeint : ho-so loketh&thorn; &thorn;are-to;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Armes weren a-long i-sprad : ase huy weren on &thorn;e rode,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e fet i-streitht a-long : al vrninde a-blode,</L>
<L N="384">&THORN;oru&yogh; &thorn;e ri&yogh;ht side he was i-smite : and &thorn;oru&yogh; fet and honde:
<PB REF="00000113.tif" N="65"></L>
<L>hit was in fourme of an Aungel : ore louerd, ich onder-stonde.</L>
<L>&para; So gret Ioye hadde &thorn;is holie Man : of &thorn;is noble si&yogh;hte</L>
<L>&THORN;at him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he was in an o&thorn;ur world : and &thorn;onkede godes mi&yogh;hte;</L>
<L N="388">he nuste &yogh;wat for Ioye do : &thorn;e &yogh;wyle he &thorn;is fourme i-sei&yogh;h.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e laste he fleu&yogh; a-&yogh;ein : in-to heouene an hei&yogh;h.</L>
<L>Seint Fraunceis was in Ioye i-nou&yogh; : for he hadde &thorn;at noble si&yogh;th,</L>
<L>And nameliche of ore louerdes wounden : &thorn;at he wilnede dai&yogh; and ny&yogh;ht.</L>
<L N="392">&THORN;o bi-heold he is owene hondene : and is fiet al-so:</L>
<L>&THORN;o weren huy &thorn;oru&yogh;-out i-smite : and &thorn;e nailes &thorn;ar-on i-do,</L>
<L>And is ri&yogh;ht side i-wounded al-so&mdash; : ake wel sore neren huy nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he hadde &thorn;e woundene him-sulf : &thorn;at so muche weren in is &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="396">&para; &THORN;e nailes weren blake i-nou&yogh; : &thorn;e hauedene rounde and grete,</L>
<L>&THORN;e poyntes weren euelongue : ase huy weren a-&yogh;ei[n]ward-i-bete;</L>
<L>Aboute &thorn;e nailes &thorn;at flesch stod up : ase it were al-to-swolle</L>
<L>And ase it al a-boute were : for Anguyse to-bolle.</L>
<L N="400">In &thorn;is manere we mouwen beo sikere : &thorn;at ore louerdes woundene were&mdash;</L>
<L>For bote ase a schewingue and Ansaumple : in seint Fraunceyse huy nere.<MILESTONE N="46" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;is holie man hadde : ore louerdes woundene fiue;</L>
<L>And bi-lefden on him aftur-ward : &thorn;e &yogh;wile he was a-liue.</L>
<L N="404">At &thorn;e holie rode-tid in Septembre : he gan furst &thorn;is &thorn;ing i-seo;</L>
<L>Ac ope &thorn;e hulle he hadde er : nei&yogh; a mon&thorn;e i-beo,</L>
<L>And fourtene ni&yogh;t &thorn;are-aftur-ward : he bi-lefte &yogh;uyt &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at euene vnder al : fourti dawes &thorn;ere were.</L>
<L N="408">&para; Ase Moyses opon synay : was bi olde dawe</L>
<L>Fourti dai&yogh;es in priuete : to seon &thorn;e olde lawe,</L>
<L>Also was &thorn;is holie Man : fourti dawes ri&yogh;ht</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e hulle of Auuerne : to seo &thorn;at holie si&yogh;ht.</L>
<L N="412">So &thorn;at Aboute Mi&yogh;helmasse : furst he wende to grounde;</L>
<L>Ac he hudde is fet and hondene faste : &thorn;at Men ne i-sei&yogh;en &thorn;e wounde.</L>
<L>With &thorn;e woundene he liuede two &yogh;er : and prechede a-boute wide,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e woundene ornen ofte a-blode : and nameliche of is side,</L>
<L N="416">And bi-bledde is cuyrtel ofte : and is briech al-so;</L>
<L>he carede muche hou he mi&yogh;hte : stilleliche it a-wei do.&mdash;
<PB REF="00000114.tif" N="66"></L>
<L>&para; Seth&thorn;e &thorn;are cam in &thorn;e londe : a swy&thorn;e strong qualm of orue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at schep and reo&thorn;eren and o&thorn;ur bestes : aldai lei&yogh;en a-storue.</L>
<L N="420">A guod Man &thorn;at hadde muchel orf : bad ore louerd wel faste</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne bi-nome him nou&yogh;t al is guod : ake &thorn;at som him moste i-laste.</L>
<L>Slepinde in ametingue : to him seide &thorn;oru&yogh;<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. &thorn;oru&yogh;?</NOTE> godes sonde</L>
<L>&THORN;at he scholde nime of &thorn;at watur : &thorn;at seint Fraunceis wusch inne is honde</L>
<L N="424">O&thorn;ur is fet and &thorn;ere-with : a-mong &thorn;e bestes sprenge,</L>
<L>And, &yogh;if him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;are were to luyte : with o&thorn;ur watur it Mienge.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is guode Man &thorn;are-afturward : a-waitede is point ofte</L>
<L>And stal of &thorn;is watur stilleliche : in huydeles wel softe,</L>
<L N="428">And spreinde a-mong is owene orf : and a-mong o&thorn;ure mani on:</L>
<L>And oueral &thorn;are it was i-spreind : huy weren hole ech-on.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; Seint Fraunceis was frere Menour : in &thorn;e ordre twenti &yogh;er,</L>
<L>And two &yogh;er and al-mest &thorn;reo wyke : ore louerdes woundene he ber,</L>
<L N="432">So &thorn;at he drou&yogh; to-ward &thorn;e de&thorn;e : and feblischede ful swi&thorn;e faste.</L>
<L>On him nas nou&yogh;t bote fel and bon : bi-leued at&thorn;e laste.</L>
<L>In torment he was strong i-nov&yogh; : and &yogh;wane he was in worst stounde,</L>
<L>his lene bones he wolde drawe : a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e harde grounde,</L>
<L N="436">For-to make &thorn;e more is pine : and &thorn;e eor&thorn;e he custe al-so</L>
<L>And &thorn;onkede god of alle guode : &thorn;at he him hadde i-do.</L>
<L>he lay sijk and deide sone : seint Fraunceis &thorn;e holie man</L>
<L>In ore leuedi churche : &thorn;are he furst &thorn;e ordre bi-gan.</L>
<L N="440">&para; &THORN;o he was &thorn;e de&thorn;e nei&yogh; : naked he liet him do,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e harde vr&thorn;e al bar : al nakede he lay so,</L>
<L>And het heom &thorn;at a-boute him were : &thorn;at aftur &thorn;ulke stounde</L>
<L>huy leten him ligge longue also : nakede on &thorn;e grounde,</L>
<L N="444">&THORN;at eor&thorn;e mi&yogh;hte on eor&thorn;e dei&yogh;e : for &thorn;at were is ri&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>he bi-gan to prechi is bre&thorn;ren : ope is feble mi&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>&para; At&thorn;e laste, &thorn;o he &thorn;ene deth&thorn; i-sai&yogh; : and i-felde hine ful strongue,<MILESTONE N="46b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"Voce mea" he bi-gan : one saume of euesongue,</L>
<L N="448">And seide forth&thorn; &thorn;e saume al out : and heold up is hondene hei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>And with &thorn;e laste word of &thorn;e saume : he bi-gan to dei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>he deide tweolf hundred &yogh;er : and sixe and twenti ri&yogh;ht</L>
<L>Aftur ore louerdes burtime : on a satur-day at ni&yogh;ht.</L>
<L N="452">&THORN;e sonendai he was i-bured&mdash; : he ne ferde nou&yogh;t ase &thorn;is riche
<PB REF="00000115.tif" N="67"></L>
<L>&THORN;at for bobaunt of &thorn;e world : liggeth&thorn; longue a-liche.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;is holie man was ded&mdash; : &thorn;ei it were bi ni&yogh;hte,</L>
<L>A gret hep of lauerkene : opon &thorn;e churche a-li&yogh;hte</L>
<L N="456">And murie sounguen al &thorn;e longue ni&yogh;ht : a-boute &thorn;e bodie &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e soule to heouene wende : a&yogh;ein kuynde &thorn;ei it were&mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e lauerke is a foul : &thorn;at muche louez li&yogh;ht</L>
<L>And hereth&thorn; &thorn;ane dai with hire song : and restez hire a-ni&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>A&yogh;ein kuynde huy sounguen &thorn;ere : ase &thorn;ei huy hadden in muynde</L>
<L>hou muche he was anoured er : of foules a-&yogh;ein hore kuynde.</L>
<L>&para; Frere Austyn, &thorn;at was ministre : under him i-do,</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is holie man was ded : at&thorn;e de&thorn;e he lai al-so</L>
<L N="464">In &thorn;e londe of labour<NOTE PLACE="marg1">[Terra di Lavoro]</NOTE> : &thorn;at feor was &thorn;are-bi-side.</L>
<L>Wel longue he lai speche-les : &thorn;ene deth&thorn; forto a-bide,</L>
<L>And ri&yogh;ht ase seint Fraunceis deide : feor in an o&thorn;ur londe,</L>
<L>&THORN;is frere Austin spac wel mildeliche : and heold up is two honden :</L>
<L N="468">"Abijd, bro&thorn;ur," he seide, "ane &yogh;wyle : ich come with &thorn;e a-non."</L>
<L>his freres axeden him &yogh;wat it were&mdash; : for heom wondrede ech-on.</L>
<L>&para; "Bote frere Fraunceis," he seide, "ore fader : i-brou&yogh;t hath is lif to ende</L>
<L>And is nou&thorn;e toward heouene : and with him i-chulle wende."</L>
<L N="472">With &thorn;is word he gan dei&yogh;e : and is soule al in pes</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Ioye of heouene wende : with is maister seint Fraunceis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are huy [beoth] bo&thorn;e : in Ioye with-outen ende.</L>
<L>Nou god for &thorn;e loue of seint Fraunceis : late us alle &thorn;udere wende. AmeN.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="19" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD><NOTE PLACE="marg2">&para; Vita sancti Albani.</NOTE>19 Albon.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Albon &thorn;e holie Man : was here of Enguelonde,</L>
<L>I-martred he was for godes loue : &thorn;oru&yogh; Iesu cristes sonde.</L>
<L>Formest he was he&thorn;ene man : and of he&thorn;ene men he cam,</L>
<L N="4">And seth&thorn;e, ase ore louerd it wolde : he tornede to cristindom.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e lu&thorn;ere prince &thorn;at was &thorn;o : dioclician,</L>
<L>And an o&thorn;ur &thorn;at was al so : &thorn;at hei&yogh;te Maximian,</L>
<L>Cristine men &thorn;at huy mi&yogh;hten i-wite : huy brou&yogh;ten alle to grounde;</L>
<L N="8">In eche londe huy lieten heom seche : &yogh;ware huy mi&yogh;hten beon i|founde,
<PB REF="00000116.tif" N="68"></L>
<L>And to strongue de&thorn;e heom duden : swi&thorn;e manie and fale;</L>
<L>huy ne spareden none &thorn;at huy mi&yogh;hten finde : no&thorn;ur grete ne smale.</L>
<L>&para; A lu&thorn;ur Iustise &thorn;at with heom was : to enguelonde he cam,</L>
<L N="12">To Martri alle cristine men : and destruyen cristindom.</L>
<L>A clerk, a guod cristine man &thorn;at was : heorde it telle wide</L>
<L>Of tormens &thorn;at huy duden o&thorn;ur men : he ne dorste no long a-bide,</L>
<L>Ake he fleu&yogh; elles-&yogh;wodere : &thorn;at he i-Martred nere;</L>
<L>To seint Albones house he cam : and bad is In &thorn;ere.<MILESTONE N="47" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; Seint Albon, &thorn;e &yogh;wile he with him was : a-waitede and i-sai&yogh;</L>
<L>hov he was in is oresones : bo&thorn;e ni&yogh;ht and dai&yogh;:</L>
<L>he &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at he was a fol : &thorn;at he was he&thorn;ene so longue,</L>
<L N="20">he gan to leue on Ihesu crist : and cristinedom ta-fongue.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Iustise &thorn;ane clerk liet seche : so &thorn;at it was i-kud</L>
<L>hou at seint Albones house : with him he was i-hud.</L>
<L>Kni&yogh;htes he sende to fechchen him : &yogh;if he i-founde were.</L>
<L>To seint Albon huy comen : and echsten after him &thorn;ere.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">[This v. is written on the margin; v. 25-6 are spurious.]</NOTE></L>
<L>huy comen and founden seint Albon : and axeden him a-non</L>
<L N="26">&YOGH;we&thorn;ur ani swuch &thorn;ere were. : "for gode," quath &thorn;is holie man,</L>
<L>"For gode," seide &thorn;is guode Man : "I nelle it nou&yogh;t for-sake,</L>
<L N="28">A swuch Man ich am mi-seolf : I nelle eou non o&thorn;ur take."</L>
<L>&para; "A, &thorn;eof," seiden &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere men : "art&thorn;ou i-come &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane &thorn;ou wolt for &thorn;at strongue &thorn;ef : to de&thorn;e beo i-do?"</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie man huy bounden faste : and to &thorn;e Iustise him brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="32">And tolden him &thorn;at he pulte him forth : for &thorn;at o&thorn;ur &thorn;ef &thorn;at huy sou&yogh;ten.</L>
<L>&para; "Bel ami," quath &thorn;e Iustise : "seie &yogh;wat is &thorn;i name</L>
<L>And of &yogh;wat kunne &thorn;ou art i-come : &thorn;at ore godes dost schuch<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. swuch</NOTE> schame."</L>
<L>"To &thorn;is Axingue," quath seint Albon : "ichulle answerie sone.</L>
<L N="36">Of &yogh;wat kunne ich am i-come : luyte &thorn;ou hast to-done;</L>
<L>Alban is mi name, i-wis : and ich honori al-so</L>
<L>God &thorn;at schop alle &thorn;ing : and euere-more wolle do."</L>
<L>&para; "A, traitur," quath &thorn;e Iustise : "art&thorn;ou i-come &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L N="40">I schal don tormenti &thorn;i bodi : fram heued to &thorn;in ho.</L>
<L>hast&thorn;ou i-hud &thorn;ane &thorn;ef at-hom : &thorn;at doth us so muche schame,</L>
<L>And pulst forth&thorn; &thorn;i-self, &thorn;o<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. &thorn;ou</NOTE> cheitif : to de&thorn;e in his name:
<PB REF="00000117.tif" N="69"></L>
<L>Anoure ore godes, ich rede, a-non : and heom sacrefise,</L>
<L N="44">O&thorn;ur ichulle &thorn;e tormenti so : &thorn;at men schullen of &thorn;e agrise."</L>
<L>"For nou&yogh;t &thorn;ou spext," quath Albon : "&thorn;ar-aboute &thorn;ou spillest &thorn;i breth&thorn;,</L>
<L>I-nelle neuere &thorn;ene deuel honoure : for drede of &thorn;e deth&thorn;."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o was &thorn;e Iustise swy&thorn;e wroth : &thorn;ane holie man he nam,</L>
<L N="48">Nakede, and<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> he</NOTE> liet him faste binde : and &yogh;af him sone is dom:</L>
<L>With schourges he made is tormentours : leggen on him i-nowe.</L>
<L>On him huy leiden &thorn;at huy werie weren : and al is bodi to-drowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e harde scourgene in is tendre flechs : deope gonne wade;</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;e more &thorn;at huy tormenteden him : &thorn;e gladdore he him made;</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">[53-4 added in L.]</NOTE>he &thorn;onkede god &thorn;at he moste : &thorn;are for is loue</L>
<L>To &thorn;e stat of cristindom : &thorn;oru&yogh; is torment come.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;o &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere Iustise i-sai&yogh; : &thorn;at it was al for nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;at he ne mi&yogh;hte fram Iesu crist : for no-&thorn;ing torne is &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>he hiet him lede with-oute toun : and is heued smite of sone.</L>
<L>I-redie weren &thorn;e tormentours : for-to do is bone,</L>
<L>huy harleden him wel filliche : &thorn;at schame it was to se,</L>
<L N="60">For-to huy comen to &thorn;ulke stude : &thorn;are he scholde i-martred be.</L>
<L>huy comen to an vrninde brok : &thorn;ere huy mosten ouer wade:</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">[63-4 added in L.]</NOTE>&THORN;e tormentores woden ouer al a-brod : and no strenc&thorn;e &thorn;ar-of ne maden.</L>
<L>&para; Ake ore louerd for seint Albones loue : dude miracle &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="64">A-non so &thorn;e schrewe tormentores : ouer i-wade were:</L>
<L>For &thorn;o &thorn;is holie Man to watere cam : &thorn;at watur him with-drou&yogh;</L>
<L>And ouer &thorn;e broke made ane wei : druy&yogh;e and clene i-nou&yogh;,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wende ouer al-so druy&yogh;e : ase it a-londe were;</L>
<L N="68">And euere &thorn;at watur bi-hinden him : smot to-gadere &thorn;ere</L>
<L>And cam al a-&yogh;ein ase it was er : &thorn;o he cam to londe.</L>
<L>Louerd, muche is &thorn;i mi&yogh;hte : ho-so him wole onder-stonde!</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e maister of &thorn;e tormentores : to &yogh;wam he was bi-take,</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;o he i-sai&yogh; &thorn;e faire miracle : &thorn;ene deuel he gan fur-sake,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">[73-4 spurious.]</NOTE>And seide he wolde to Ihesu crist : al is heorte wende,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e Miracle &thorn;at he &thorn;are i-sai&yogh; : &thorn;at so fair was and hende;</L>
<L>his sweord &thorn;at he on honde bar : wel feor fram him he caste</L>
<L>And to seint Albones fet he feol a-doun : and criede him merci faste,
<PB REF="00000118.tif" N="70"></L>
<L>&THORN;at he moste for him dei&yogh;e : o&thorn;ur, bote it o&thorn;ur were,</L>
<L N="78">&THORN;at he moste in &thorn;e place : &thorn;ene deth&thorn; a-fongue &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&para; Opon an hul huy wenden an hei&yogh; : ase huy weren a-signet to</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;is holie Man seint Albon : to &thorn;e de&thorn;e do.</L>
<L>Seint Albon wilnede aftur watur : &thorn;are ope &thorn;e hulle on hei&yogh;;</L>
<L>he bi-heold &thorn;at &thorn;are ne mi&yogh;hte : no watur come &thorn;are nei&yogh;:</L>
<L>Ore louerd he bad with guode heorte : &thorn;at he sende is grace</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;at som water moste to him come : in &thorn;at ilke place.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">[85-6 added in L.]</NOTE>Ore louerd heorde is bone : &thorn;are anon-ri&yogh;hte</L>
<L>bi-fore alle &thorn;e tormentores : in heore alre si&yogh;hte:</L>
<L>&para; For &thorn;o he hadde i-seid is oresun : and ore louerd i-bede,</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;are sprong out of &thorn;at hei&yogh;e [hul] : a fair welle in &thorn;ulke stude,</L>
<L>Of al-so guod water ase ani mi&yogh;hte beo&mdash; : &thorn;at &yogh;uyt lasteth&thorn;, ich wene.</L>
<L>Euere was &thorn;o and al-so nou&thorn;e : ore louerdes mi&yogh;hte i-sene.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode kni&yogh;ht &thorn;at bi-liefde on god : for &thorn;at he sei&yogh; er,</L>
<L N="92">Wel more he criede &thorn;o on him : for &thorn;ulke miracle &thorn;er,</L>
<L>And wilnede &yogh;eorne &thorn;at he moste : for him dei&yogh;e &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at in ore louerdes name : Imartrede bo&thorn;e huy were.</L>
<L>&para; Ake &thorn;e tormentour &thorn;at smot of : seint Albones heued,</L>
<L N="96">Luyte he &thorn;orte &thorn;ar-of &yogh;elpe : him were betere habbe bi-leued:</L>
<L>For &thorn;o he smot of is heued : ri&yogh;ht in &thorn;ulke stounde</L>
<L>his owene ey&yogh;ene out of is heued : &thorn;are ri&yogh;ht fullen to grounde.</L>
<L>Louerd, muche is &thorn;i mi&yogh;hte : ho-so him wole onder-stonde,</L>
<L>Ase men mouwe bi is wi&thorn;er-wine : godes mi&yogh;hte fonde.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">g. m. f. on the mar|gin; puyrliche onder-stonde ex|punged.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seint Albon i-martred was : here in Enguelonde</L>
<L>Bi-side ane toune &thorn;at widincestre : men cleopeden, ich onder-stonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;are is nou&thorn;e a churche a-rerd : and a gret Abbeye al-so,</L>
<L N="104">&THORN;at men cleopieth seint Albones : ase he was to de&thorn;e i-do.</L>
<L>Bidde we &yogh;eorne Ihesu crist : and seint Albon wel faste</L>
<L>&THORN;at we moten to &thorn;e Ioye come : &thorn;at euere schal i-laste.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="20" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>20 Wolston</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Wolston, bischop of wyrecestre : was here of engelonde,<MILESTONE N="48" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e holi man he was al is lif : ase ich me vnder-stonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;wile he was a &yogh;ong child : clene lif he ladde i-nov&yogh;;</L>
<L N="4">&YOGH;wane o&thorn;ur children ornen to plei&yogh;e : toward churche he drou&yogh;.
<PB REF="00000119.tif" N="71"></L>
<L>Seint Edward was kyng &thorn;o : &thorn;at nou&thorn;e in heouene is;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e bischop of wyricestre : bri&yogh;ttey hei&yogh;te, i-wis.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is bischop Bri&yogh;tei : seint wolston is ordre nam,</L>
<L N="8">Ech aftur o&thorn;ur, ase it fel : so &thorn;at he preost bi-cam.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischop vnder-feng him seth&thorn;e : and Monek him makede i-wis</L>
<L>In &thorn;e priorie of wiricestre : &thorn;at noble hous and gret is.</L>
<L>Swy&thorn;e wel is ordre he heold : in &thorn;at priorie</L>
<L N="12">And al is wille was for-to pay&yogh;e : god and seinte Marie.</L>
<L>In none bedde he nolde come : ake, &yogh;wane o&thorn;ere &yogh;eoden &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L>bi-fore on auter he wolde go : his oresones for-to do;</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane &thorn;e dede slep him ouer-eode : &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;te no leng gon,</L>
<L N="16">his heued he wolde legge a-doun : opon &thorn;e harde ston,</L>
<L>Ope one grece bifore &thorn;e Auter : o&thorn;ur is bok &thorn;are-vnder do,</L>
<L>And liggen ane stounde in dweole Miengyngue&mdash; : al is slep scholde beon so.</L>
<L>he nolde &thorn;reo dawes in &thorn;e wyke : no-&thorn;ing eten with-alle,</L>
<L N="20">Ne no word speken bote his beden : for nou&yogh;t &thorn;at mi&yogh;te bi-falle;</L>
<L>&thorn;e o&thorn;ur dawes wel luytel he spak : and wel luytel he eat al-so,</L>
<L>bote it were a luyte potage&mdash; : holde he wolde him &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L>So longue he leouede at wirecestre : in &thorn;at holie lijf wel stille,</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;at he was imaked prior of &thorn;at hous : muche a-&yogh;ein is wille.</L>
<L>his Couent he wuste swy&thorn;e wel : and to alle guodnesse hem drou&yogh;;</L>
<L>Of god and alle guode men : loue he hadde i-nou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prior[ie]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. prior</NOTE> of wyricestre : seint oswold bi-gan er,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;at was bi-fore seint Wolston : nei&yogh; ane hondred &yogh;er;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he hadde er bi-gonne : &thorn;e o&thorn;ur fulfulde, i-wis,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;oru&yogh; heore beire dede : strong weork and hei&yogh; &thorn;are is.</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;is holie Man seint wolston : in a tyme liet a-rere</L>
<L N="32">A bel-hous of swi&thorn;e strong weork : bellen to hanguy &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And Machouns a-boue and bi-nethe : &thorn;are a-boute were,</L>
<L>Bi laddren cloumben up and doun : and &thorn;at weork bi-twene al bere,</L>
<L>A man &thorn;are clemb up bi one laddre : an &thorn;o he was up on hei&yogh;</L>
<L N="36">Fram eor&thorn;e mo &thorn;ane fourti fet : ase al &thorn;at folk i-sei&yogh;,</L>
<L>Dounward he ful, ase he mis-stap&mdash; : Men weren sore a-gaste.</L>
<L>Seint wolston stod and bi-heold : hou he was a-dounward faste:</L>
<L>he made &thorn;e signe of &thorn;e croyz : ase he feol to-ward &thorn;e grounde:
<PB REF="00000120.tif" N="72"></L>
<L N="40">harmles he feol and hol man i-nov&yogh; : his limes weren hole and sounde,</L>
<L>And a-ros up and dude is weork : ase him no-&thorn;ing nere.</L>
<L>Louerd, muche is &thorn;i mi&yogh;te : and &thorn;at &thorn;ou cuddest wel &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at [he] so harde fram so hei&yogh;e feol : and of eche harme was sker;</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;ou art a louerd &thorn;at wonderes dest : ase seith &thorn;e sauter.</L>
<L>&para; Hit bi-feol so &thorn;at bri&yogh;tey : &thorn;e Bischop of wyricestre, was ded:</L>
<L>A clerk was bischop after him : &thorn;at Men cleopeden aldred,<MILESTONE N="48b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at seint wolston louede wel : and he louede him al-so&mdash;</L>
<L N="48">For ech guod man wole louien o&thorn;ur : it were elles vuele i-do.</L>
<L>Seth&thorn;e it bi-fel &thorn;at &thorn;e Erchebischop : of Euerwicke was ded:</L>
<L>Erchebischop huy maden &thorn;ar : &thorn;ene bischop aldred,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e bischopriche of wiricestre : vacaunt was and lere :</L>
<L N="52">Seint wolston was sone i-chose : and bischop i-maked &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Bischop him made &thorn;e holie man : seint Edward &thorn;e king,</L>
<L>And a-feng him in his dignete : and tok him is staf and ring.</L>
<L>his bischopriche he wuste wel : and also is priorie,</L>
<L N="56">And a-forcede him to serui wel : god and seint Marie.</L>
<L>Four &yogh;er he hadde bischop i-beo : and nou&yogh;t fulliche fiue</L>
<L>&thorn;o seint Edward &thorn;e holie kyng : wende out of &thorn;is liue.</L>
<L>Gret reu&thorn;e it was to al engelond : so weilawei &thorn;e stounde!</L>
<L N="60">For straunge men &thorn;ere comen seth&thorn;e : and brou&yogh;ten enguelond to grounde.</L>
<L>&para; Harold was &thorn;o ri&yogh;htest eyr : for non o&thorn;ur &thorn;ere nas;</L>
<L>&THORN;e croune he bar of Enguelonde : &yogh;wuche &yogh;wile so it was.</L>
<L>For willame Bastard, &thorn;at was &thorn;o : Eorl in Noremaundie,</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;ou&yogh;te to winne Enguelond : &thorn;oru&yogh; strenc&thorn;e and tricherie:</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">om.</NOTE>he let him grei&thorn;i folk i-nou&yogh; : and gret poer with [him]<SUP>1</SUP> nam</L>
<L>And with gret strenc&thorn;e in-to &thorn;e se he him dude : and to Enguelonde he cam.</L>
<L>he liet ordeinie is fierd wel : and is banere up arer[d]e,</L>
<L N="68">And destruyde and nam al &thorn;at he fond : and &thorn;at folk sore a-ferde.</L>
<L>&para; Harold heorde herof telle : &thorn;e king of Enguelonde:</L>
<L>he liet grei&thorn;ie faste is ost : a-&yogh;ein him for-to stonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e baronie of Enguelonde : redi was wel sone</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;e king to helpe and heom-sulue : ase ri&yogh;ht was for-to done.
<PB REF="00000121.tif" N="73"></L>
<L>&THORN;e weorre was &thorn;o in Enguelonde : deolful and strong i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L>And ey&thorn;ur of o&thorn;eres Men : al-to grounde a-slou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&para; No strenc&thorn;e ne hadden &thorn;is straunge men : &thorn;at were i-come so newe,</L>
<L N="76">A&yogh;einest heom of enguelonde : &thorn;e &yogh;wyle huy wolden beo trewe.</L>
<L>Ake alas &thorn;e muchele tricherie : &thorn;at &thorn;o was, and &yogh;eot is,</L>
<L>&thorn;at brou&yogh;te &thorn;o Enguelond : al-to grounde i-wis!</L>
<L>For &thorn;e englische barones bi-comen some : on-treowe and false also</L>
<L N="80">To bi-trai&yogh;e heom-seolf and heore kyng : &thorn;at so muche heom truste to.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is Noremauns and &thorn;is Englische men : ane dai of bataile huy nome,</L>
<L>&THORN;are ase &thorn;e Abbeie of &thorn;e bataille is : ate daye to-gadere huy come,</L>
<L>To grounde huy smiten and slowen al-so. : ake alas &thorn;ulke stounde,</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;at Enguelond was &thorn;oru&yogh; tresoun : &thorn;are i-brou&yogh;t to grounde!</L>
<L>For &thorn;ulke &thorn;at &thorn;e king truste to : failleden him wel faste;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he was bi-neo&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t : and ouer-come at&thorn;e laste</L>
<L>And to grounde i-brou&yogh;t, and alle his : and al Enguelond also,</L>
<L N="88">In-to vnecou&thorn;e mannes honde : &thorn;at no ri&yogh;ht ne hadden &thorn;ar-to;</L>
<L>And neuer-eft [it] ne cam a-&yogh;ein : to ri&yogh;hte Eyres none&mdash;</L>
<L>Vnkuynde Eyres &yogh;eot huy beoth&thorn; : ore kingues echone,</L>
<L>And nei&yogh;h-&yogh;wat alle &thorn;is hei&yogh;e Men : and of &thorn;e lo&yogh;we al-so.<MILESTONE N="49" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="92">For willam liet [him] crouni king : &thorn;o &thorn;e bataile was al i-do,</L>
<L>And bi-sette al enguelond : with men of o&thorn;ere londe&mdash;</L>
<L>Neuereft to is cuynde heritage : ne cam it, ich onder-stonde.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is willam bastard, &thorn;at was king : seth&thorn;e him onder-stod</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;at he mid vnri&yogh;hte hadde i-sched : mani ane mannes blod:</L>
<L>And &thorn;are as &thorn;e bataille was : ane Abbei&yogh;e he liet a-rere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at "&thorn;e Abbeie of &thorn;e bataille" is i-cleoped : &thorn;at wel noble stand &yogh;eot &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>for heore soulene he as liet a-rere : &thorn;at he with vnri&yogh;hte &thorn;are a-slou&yogh;;</L>
<L N="100">Ake euere he heold forth &thorn;e kynedom : of enguelonde with wou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&para; Ake sone so he was king i-mad : and al enguelond bi-sette,</L>
<L>Ase he wolde, with straunge men : and no man ne mi&yogh;hte him lette,</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie Bischop seint wolston : wel ofte him withseide</L>
<L N="104">&THORN;at he with on-ri&yogh;hte hadde i-do : a swuch lu&thorn;er dede,</L>
<L>And spac a-&yogh;ein him baldeliche : and ne sparede for no drede&mdash;
<PB REF="00000122.tif" N="74"></L>
<L>For he was &thorn;o &thorn;e cuyndeste englische man : &thorn;at was of enie manhede,</L>
<L>And for alle o&thorn;ure weren deseritede nei&yogh;h. : &thorn;e king was with heom<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. him</NOTE> wroth&thorn;</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;at he was so luyte a-drad of him : and swor a-non is oth&thorn;</L>
<L>To pulte him out of is bischopriche. : he liet [him] somoune al-so</L>
<L>To westmunstre, to answerien him : of &thorn;at he him hadde mis-do.</L>
<L>&para; Nou nas nou&yogh;t seint wulston : wel gret clerk in lore&mdash;</L>
<L N="112">For &thorn;o he scholde to scole gon : to churche he &yogh;eode wel more.</L>
<L>To westmunstre he cam to is day : ase he was i-somoned er.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king was in grete wrath&thorn;e : wel prest to kepe him &thorn;er,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e bischop of Caunterburi : lanfranc was is name,</L>
<L N="116">And &thorn;e bischop gondolf of Roucestre : alle to don him schame.</L>
<L>Seint wolston bi-fore heom cam : &thorn;at a-&yogh;ein him weren so strongue</L>
<L>Ase a &thorn;eof bi-fore Iustise : his dom to vnder-fongue.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e king and &thorn;e Erchebischop al-so : speken to him wordes grete,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;at he scholde, ase he wuyr&thorn;e was : is bischop-riche lete;</L>
<L>For-to holden swuch dignete : to luyte he cou&thorn;e of lore,</L>
<L>And huy him hadden to longue i-&thorn;oled : And &thorn;o nolden huy nonmore,</L>
<L>And grete foles huy weren &thorn;at swuch a fol : formest brou&yogh;te in swch mi&yogh;hte,</L>
<L N="124">And &yogh;if he was folliche onder-fongue : huy wolden don him out with ri&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>&para; Seint wolston stod wel mildeliche : and herknede al &thorn;at huy sede&mdash;</L>
<L>Nadde he noman bote god : to his answere him rede.</L>
<L>"Sires," he seide, "ri&yogh;ht it is : &thorn;at ich eoure heste do,</L>
<L N="128">For, sire king, &thorn;ou art mi souerein : and &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. &thorn;u</NOTE> erchebischop al-so.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Croce ich habbe &yogh;are i-bore : &thorn;at &yogh;e i-seoth&thorn; here, lo,</L>
<L>A-knowe ich am and wel ich wot : &thorn;at i-nam nou&yogh;t wuyr&thorn;e &thorn;er-to;</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane &yogh;e wollez &thorn;at ich as bi-leue : ase man &thorn;at vnwur&thorn;e is,</L>
<L N="132">Wel fain i-chulle eouwer heste do : ase mine souereines, i-wis.</L>
<L>Vn-bou&yogh;hsome to holie churche : i-wis i-nelle be nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>To &yogh;elden hire up ase &yogh;e me hotez : ich habbe as here i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; Ake, for &yogh;e ne token as me nou&yogh;t : I nelle eou take non,</L>
<L N="136">Ake him &thorn;at as me bi-tok : bi-fore eov euerech-on:</L>
<L>&THORN;e guode Man &thorn;at as me bi-tok : &yogh;eonde he lijth&thorn; wel stille,</L>
<L>Ich as wulle him taken up : and &thorn;anne ich do eoure wille."
<PB REF="00000123.tif" N="75"></L>
<L>&para; To seint Edwardes toumbe he wende : &thorn;at was of Marbre-ston,</L>
<L>A<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. and?</NOTE> nam up is croiz wel mildeliche : and smot &thorn;e point &thorn;ar-on.</L>
<L>&THORN;e staf wende into &thorn;e marbreston : ase it were in nesche sonde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;o heo was inne deope i-nou&yogh; : &thorn;e guode Man hine liet stonde.</L>
<L>"Nou," he seide, "ich him habbe bi-take : him &thorn;at as tok me</L>
<L N="144">And bi-fore eov here : i-&yogh;ollden op &thorn;e dignete.</L>
<L>Takez as nou&thorn;e &yogh;wam &yogh;e wollez : som &thorn;at bet beo in lore,</L>
<L>And habbez guod dai nou&thorn;e euerech-one&mdash;; &yogh;e ne mouwen esche me non-more."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is holie Man wende forth : a-mon[g] heom alle wel softe.</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk stod ase it were i-nome : and bi-heolden &thorn;e croce wel ofte,</L>
<L>hou heo stod in &thorn;e Marbre-ston : so deope and so faste;</L>
<L N="150">Of &thorn;e Miracle heom wondrede alle : and some weren sore a-gaste,</L>
<L>Some wenden &thorn;ar-to sone : &thorn;e croce up for-to drawe:</L>
<L N="152">&THORN;are nas non so strong of heom : &thorn;at mi&yogh;hte hire enes wawe.</L>
<L>huy porueiden er sire Gondolf : bischop of roucestre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he scholde aftur seint wolston : beon Bischop of wirecestre:</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Erchebischop aros him up : to saisi &thorn;e croiz a-non,</L>
<L N="156">&THORN;e Bischop of Roucestre wel baldeliche : &thorn;udere-ward gan gon,</L>
<L>&THORN;e croiz he nam and faste he drou&yogh; : in &thorn;e Marbre-ston:</L>
<L>he ne mi&yogh;hte hire nou&yogh;t enes wawien. : &thorn;at folk wondrede ech-on,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are-a-boute wel &thorn;icke ornen : &thorn;at wonder for-to seo.</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;o &thorn;e king and &thorn;e Erchebischop i-sei&yogh;en : &thorn;at non o&thorn;ur it ne mi&yogh;hte beo,</L>
<L>heom of-&thorn;ou&yogh;te heore dede : and after seint wolstan sende,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at huy wolden in faire manere : heore trespas a-mende.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Messagers i-redie weren : and aftur him sone wenden.</L>
<L N="164">&YOGH;eot &thorn;is holie Man for al &thorn;e gult : is heorte to heom bende,</L>
<L>And seide, "ich mot nede do : mine souereines wille;"</L>
<L>To court he wende a-&yogh;ein to heom : wel mildeliche and stille.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he was to court i-come : huy a-risen a-&yogh;ein him &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="168">&THORN;e king and &thorn;e Erchebischop al-so : and o&thorn;ere &thorn;at &thorn;are were;</L>
<L>With gret honur huy cleopeden him forth&thorn; : and for-&yogh;iuenesse him bede,</L>
<L>And boden a-mendi a-&yogh;ein him : al heore grete misdede,</L>
<L>And beden him nime a-&yogh;ein is croce : and don bi heore rede,
<PB REF="00000124.tif" N="76"></L>
<L N="172">For he was bet wuyr&thorn;e &thorn;are-to : &thorn;ane ani o&thorn;ur, huy seide.</L>
<L>&para; "Nai certes, sires," quath seint wolston : "&thorn;at nere me nou&yogh;t to do:</L>
<L>Ich wot wel &thorn;at &yogh;e seiden soth : &thorn;at i-nam nou&yogh;t wuyr&thorn;e &thorn;are-to;</L>
<L>Ake nimeth &yogh;wam eower wille be : an o&thorn;ur &thorn;at conne more."</L>
<L N="176">&THORN;e kyng and &thorn;e Erchebischop also : beden him milce and ore</L>
<L>And seiden &thorn;at &thorn;ere nas non o&thorn;ur : &thorn;at so wuyr&thorn;e were &thorn;are-to.</L>
<L>Longue it was are &thorn;is holie man : wolde heore wille do<NOTE PLACE="marg1">do added later.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>Ake, for-to obeien is souereins : he wende forth at&thorn;e laste</L>
<L>And nam &thorn;e croce wel mildeliche : &thorn;are he stikede hire er so faste.</L>
<L>&para; Also li&yogh;htliche ase ani-&thorn;ing : &thorn;e croce he gan up drawe<MILESTONE N="50" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="182">&THORN;at so mani men fondeden er : and ne mi&yogh;hten hire enes wawe.</L>
<L>&THORN;icke orn &thorn;at folk a-bouten him : and no wonder it nas!</L>
<L N="184">&THORN;e miracle was sone wide i-kud : &thorn;at so apert was.</L>
<L>Men anoureden &thorn;is holie Man : al-so muche ase huy mi&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>his power &thorn;at him was er bi-nome : he tok a&yogh;ein with ri&yogh;hte;</L>
<L>A-&yogh;ein to is bischopriche : with gret honour he him drou&yogh;;</L>
<L N="188">his Couent vnder-feng him faire : with grete noblei&yogh;e i-nou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is holie Man ladde al is lif : swy&thorn;e faire and clene.</L>
<L>Sijknesses &thorn;are weren wel fewe : &thorn;at man wolde him offe mene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne brou&yogh;te to hele a-non : &thorn;oru&yogh; ore louerdes grace;</L>
<L N="192">Sike men wel &thorn;icke comen : to him in eche place,</L>
<L>Deue and doumbe and blinde al-so : he helde &thorn;oru&yogh; godes grace</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane huy comen to him : ou&yogh;were in ani place.</L>
<L>So longue he leouede on eor&thorn;e here : &thorn;at he was of grete elde.</L>
<L N="196">His bodi bi-gan to heuegy swi&thorn;e : grete feblesse he fielde.</L>
<L>&para; A slou&yogh; feuere him cam on : &thorn;at ne nam him nou&yogh;t ful strongue,</L>
<L>Ac heo made is bodi to melte a-wei&mdash; : &thorn;at laste swi&thorn;e longue.</L>
<L>Seue ni&yogh;ht bi-fore &thorn;at he deide : his bre&thorn;ren he liet fette alle</L>
<L>And liet him alle is ri&yogh;htes do : and seide &yogh;wat heom scholde bi-falle.</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is world to heouene he wende : &thorn;are he schal ay bi-leue,</L>
<L N="202">In &thorn;e Mon&thorn;e of Ieneuer<NOTE PLACE="marg1">[19 Jan.]</NOTE> : a-seint Fabianes eue,</L>
<L>&para; A &thorn;ousend &yogh;er and nie hundret : and foure &thorn;are-bi-fore</L>
<L N="204">It was &thorn;at ore swete louerd : on vr&thorn;e was i-bore,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e teo&thorn;e &yogh;ere also : of &thorn;e kinedom</L>
<L>Of willam &thorn;e rede king : &thorn;at aftur willam bastard cam<NOTE PLACE="marg1">These two v. are written in one line.</NOTE></L>
<L>he hadde, are he heonne i-wende : foure and &thorn;ritti &yogh;er
<PB REF="00000125.tif" N="77"></L>
<L>And four Mon&thorn;es and four dawes : i-beo in worlde<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. wolde? the other MSS. bishop</NOTE></L>
<L>Four-score &yogh;er he was old : and seuene al-so nei&yogh;h</L>
<L>Are he wende out of &thorn;is lijf : to &thorn;e Ioye of heuene an hei&yogh;.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;is holie man was ded : &thorn;e Monekes comen sone</L>
<L N="212">In &thorn;e priorie of wirecestre : and duden &thorn;at was to done:</L>
<L>Wuschen &thorn;at bodi, ase it was ri&yogh;ht : and to churche it bere;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Monekes alle with gret honour : &thorn;at is bre&thorn;erne were,</L>
<L>&THORN;e seruise a-bouten him huy duden : ase it was wel ri&yogh;ht,</L>
<L N="216">And to seggen heore sauteres al-so : &thorn;are-bi huy woken a-ni&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o it was wel with-inne ni&yogh;ht : ase huy seiden in heore boke,</L>
<L>heom luste slepe swi&thorn;e wel : &thorn;at vnne&thorn;es huy mi&yogh;hten loke,</L>
<L>And some ne mi&yogh;hten nou&yogh;t fur-bere : ake lei&yogh;en and slepen faste,</L>
<L>Some ase it were in dweolkningue : heore ei&yogh;ene to-gadere huy caste.</L>
<L>&THORN;at holie bodi, &thorn;at lai &thorn;are ded : a-mong heom in &thorn;e bere,</L>
<L N="222">A-ros up wel mildeliche : ase &thorn;ei it a-liue were,</L>
<L>And a-wei&yogh;hte heom euer-ech-on : and bi-gan at&thorn;on ende</L>
<L N="224">And al along &thorn;e rewe : &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e queor he gan i-wiende;</L>
<L>And euere ase he a-wei&yogh;hte heom : sumdel he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">superscr.</NOTE> gan heom chide</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy nolden with heore slep : heore ri&yogh;hte tyme a-bide.</L>
<L>&para; So muche [was] is holi heorte : &thorn;e ordre for-to wite<MILESTONE N="50b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="228">&THORN;at he nolde, &thorn;ei he were ded : his bre&thorn;erne fur-&yogh;ite!</L>
<L>&THORN;is Miracle was sone i-kud : ase ri&yogh;ht was &thorn;at it were.</L>
<L>At wirecestre he was i-bured : and &yogh;uyt he liht &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;are Man may for is holie bodi : mani fair Miracle i-seo.</L>
<L>Nou god graunti &thorn;at we mote with him : in &thorn;e Ioye of heouene beo.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="21" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>21 Matheu.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Matheu &thorn;e Ewangelist : apostel he was and is,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> i-wis</NOTE></L>
<L>Ewangelist and eke a-postle : for-so&thorn;e he was and is:</L>
<L>Ewangelist, for he godspelles made : &thorn;at men doth ofte rede,</L>
<L>Apostel, for ore louerd here on vr&thorn;e : seint Matheu with him gan lede.</L>
<L>For ase ore louerd eode ouer lond : seint Matheu he sai&yogh; bi cas</L>
<L>his mester don of walkingue : for a follare<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> tollare</NOTE> he was,</L>
<L>Fals and trichor of is werk : and liuede bi falshede.</L>
<L N="8">Ore louerd him hiet bi-leue is weork : "cum siwe me," he seide.</L>
<L>And he bi-lefde &thorn;o is weork : and wiz ore louerd eode,
<PB REF="00000126.tif" N="78"></L>
<L>And is false mester liet : for he nadde &thorn;er-to non neode.</L>
<L>&para; Fair forebisne ore louerd &yogh;af : alle sunfole men &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="12">&YOGH;wane he ane so sunfole Man : het with him go!</L>
<L>Seint Matheu is sunnes bette : and tok to cristindom,</L>
<L>And siwede ore louerd swi&thorn;e faste : and is Apostel bi-com.&mdash;</L>
<L>Seth&thorn;e &thorn;o ore louerd was into : heouene i-wend,</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;e Apostles weren &thorn;o wel wide in londe : for-to prechie, i-send.</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e londe of Ethiope : seint Matheu sone &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>to prechie men to cristinedom : ase it was wel gret neode.</L>
<L>&para; He founde tweie lu&thorn;ere men : and strongue wichchene &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="20">Zaroen and Arphaxat : &thorn;at &thorn;e deueles limes were,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, ase huy wolden, in grete siknesse : manie men hadden i-do</L>
<L>And manie men &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e feonde : i-helde huy hadden al-so.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere men : in siknesse brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="24">Seint Matheu heom helde a-non : and wel clene heom out sou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Sorie weren &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere Men : huy nusten &yogh;wat was to done:</L>
<L>Tweie dragones, &thorn;at feondes weren : to heom huy cleopeden sone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at casten brumston and fuyr : and [slowe]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> &yogh;end al &thorn;e londe</L>
<L N="28">Mannes<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. men and</NOTE> bestes &thorn;ere-with wel &thorn;icke&mdash; : heom ne mi&yogh;hte no &thorn;ing at|stonde.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is lu&thorn;ere men nomen &thorn;e dragones to heom : for huy scholden to|drawe</L>
<L>&THORN;ane Apostel seint Matheu : and bringue him of lijf-dawe.</L>
<L>&THORN;o seint Matheu &thorn;is i-heorde : baldeliche he gan gon,</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;e signe he made of &thorn;e croiz : and to heom wende a-non.</L>
<L>A-non so &thorn;e dragones him i-sei&yogh;en : to is fet huy fullen a-doun,</L>
<L>huy ne mi&yogh;hten heom wawien hider ne &thorn;uder : ane fot for al &thorn;e toun.</L>
<L>"lo, &yogh;e wrechches," quath &thorn;e apostle : to &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere men tweie,</L>
<L N="36">"&YOGH;ware is nou&thorn;e al eouwere mi&yogh;hte? : ouer-come &yogh;e beoth&thorn; beine.</L>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if i-nadde nou&thorn;e mine louerdes grace : for eou &yogh;eorne bi-sou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>On eov-sulf it scholde nou&thorn;e bi-falle : ase &yogh;e hadden bi me i-&thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;is twei lu&thorn;ere dragones : &thorn;at &yogh;e habbuth hidere i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="40">A-rereth heom &yogh;if &yogh;e mowen : o&thorn;ur eower art nis nou&yogh;t."<MILESTONE N="51" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; Euere stoden &thorn;is wrechche men : ri&yogh;ht ase huy weren i-nome,</L>
<L>huy weren of seint Matheu a-ferde sore : and heolden heom ouer-come.</L>
<L>Seint Matheu &thorn;is tweie dragones : &thorn;oru&yogh; Iesu cristes lore
<PB REF="00000127.tif" N="79"></L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e londe heom drof a-non : &thorn;at huy ne comen &thorn;ere non-more.</L>
<L>he wende a-boute and prechede : and &thorn;e tweie schrewene liet go&mdash;</L>
<L N="46">Ouer-comene wrechches ase hui weren : nas heom neuer er so wo.</L>
<L>&para; Hit bi-feol &thorn;at &thorn;e kingues sone : of &thorn;e londe was ded.</L>
<L N="48">Sone &thorn;is twei&yogh;e deoueles limes : to-gadere nomen hore red</L>
<L>And wenden &thorn;udere, &yogh;if huy mi&yogh;hten : &thorn;oru&yogh; heore art him<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. heom</NOTE> a-rere;</L>
<L>And huy maden heore enchauntement : ase &thorn;e deuel heom gan lere.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;at child lai euere ded&mdash; : for heore mi&yogh;hte nas ri&yogh;th nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; &thorn;e kingue huy weren i-nome : and in strongue prisone i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e king sende aftur seint Matheu : ase men of him tolde,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he mi&yogh;hte is sone arere&mdash; : for he was so wis i-holde.</L>
<L>&THORN;o seint Matheu &thorn;udere cam : to ore louerd he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. heo</NOTE> dude is bone</L>
<L N="56">And a-rerde &thorn;at child : fram de&thorn;e to liue wel sone;</L>
<L>&THORN;at child a-ros and herede god : i-bore of mayde marie.</L>
<L>A-non so &thorn;e king &thorn;is i-sei&yogh; : wel loude he gan to crie :</L>
<L>"For-so&thorn;e," he seide, "ich i-seo : &thorn;at Matheu a god is;</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;ei he beo here in mannes fourme : he is a god, i-wis!</L>
<L>&para; Anoure we him ase it is ri&yogh;ht : with seluer and with golde."</L>
<L>huy offreden to him tresor i-nou&yogh; : more &thorn;ane he a-fongue wolde.</L>
<L>"Nai certes," quath &thorn;is holie man : "god nam ich nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="64">Ake godes seriaunt &thorn;at here on eor&thorn;e : to de&thorn;e was i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>ho-so wole on him bi-lieue : to heouene he schal i-wiende,</L>
<L>And ho-so nele nou&yogh;t, he worth i-wis : in pine with&thorn;-outen ende."</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e king and alle his : i-cristnede of him were.</L>
<L N="68">With &thorn;e tresor &thorn;at men him brou&yogh;te : a fair churche he liet a-rere.</L>
<L>&para; In &thorn;ritti dawes heo was arerd&mdash; : so gret hel[p] &thorn;are was to;</L>
<L>&THORN;are &thorn;e king and is heore beden bede : and al&thorn;e contrei&yogh;e al-so.</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;e tuei&yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. trei&yogh;e</NOTE> enchauntours : seint Matheu liet sende,</L>
<L N="72">Zaroes and Arphaxat : and made heom &thorn;annes wiende.</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e londe of perce : huy wenden with schame i-nov;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere &thorn;at folk mis-bi-leued : wel &thorn;icke a-boute heom drov.</L>
<L>&para; Seth&thorn;e seint symon and seint Iude : to perce &thorn;ene wei nome</L>
<L N="76">And &thorn;ulke two enchauntours : to grounde huy ouer-come,</L>
<L>&THORN;are huy neuereft cristine Men : non a-nuy ne wrou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Ase Man mai in heore liue i-seo : ho-so &thorn;are-after sou&yogh;te.&mdash;</L>
<L>Seint Matheu in Ethiope : &thorn;e kingues dou&yogh;ter nam,
<PB REF="00000128.tif" N="80"></L>
<L N="80">&THORN;at of hire-seolf was a clene &thorn;ing : and &yogh;af hire cristinedom,</L>
<L>A<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. and?</NOTE> made hire a-uouwe chastete : and clene lif to lede.</L>
<L>&thorn;at maide was wel a-paid euere-aftur-ward : of &thorn;at ilke dede.</L>
<L>&para; A king of an o&thorn;ur londe : is loue on hire he caste</L>
<L N="84">And wolde ire habbe to his spouse : and wowede hire wel faste.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is maide nolde is wille do : to seint Matheu he &yogh;eode<MILESTONE N="51b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at he scholde in his half beo : and bed him grete mede.</L>
<L>&para; "Cum," quath seint Matheu, "&thorn;ilke dai : and ich hire wolle rede</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;at heo heolde hire spoushod : and &thorn;are-inne hire lijf lede."</L>
<L>&THORN;e king was glad and wende wel : &THORN;at he bi him it seide,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wolde hire to him rede&mdash; : ake he nolde nou&yogh;t don so to quede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king cam aday, and muche folk : with him he gan bringue,</L>
<L N="92">And &thorn;is maide cam al-so : to hure seint Matheus prechingue.</L>
<L>Seint Matheu stod and prechede : &thorn;at folk al a-brod :</L>
<L>Mest he preisede of alle &thorn;ingue : in is sarmun spoushod,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ere nas no lijf so guod : &thorn;are it was trewe and clene.</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;e kyng was glad and hopede wel : &thorn;at he it dude bi him mene,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at Maide scholde : to him i-wedded beo;</L>
<L>Seint Matheu he louede muche : and hopede is wille i-seo.</L>
<L>&para; So &thorn;at seth&thorn;e seint Matheu : is prechingue for&thorn;ere drou&yogh;</L>
<L N="100">And seide, "&yogh;if &thorn;e king hadde a wif : &thorn;at he louede i-nou&yogh;,</L>
<L>And a fol come in spousbruche : and lei&yogh;e bi is wiue,</L>
<L>&THORN;e king wolde beo wroth i-nou&yogh; : and bringue him of liue,</L>
<L>For he him hadde is wijf bi-nome : and imad hire don amis.</L>
<L N="104">Of &thorn;e hei&yogh;e king of heouene : also it fareth, i-wis :</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he hath&thorn; a guod spouse : &thorn;at ledeth clene lijf,</L>
<L>A<SUP>nd</SUP> &thorn;are come forth&thorn; a fol : and bi-nime him is wijf,</L>
<L>To strongue de&thorn;e he wolde him bringue : and to &thorn;e pine of helle al-so.</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;are-fore ech man beo i-war : &thorn;at he swuch &thorn;ing ne do."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e kin[g] i-heorde &thorn;is : sone he onder-stod</L>
<L>&THORN;at it was ri&yogh;ht bi him i-seid. : for wrath&thorn;e he was nei&yogh;h wod,</L>
<L>And swor &thorn;at he nolde bli&thorn;e beo : are he were<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. he were a were</NOTE> awreke.</L>
<L>For[th]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. for</NOTE> he wende and bi-gan a-non : seint Matheus deth&thorn; bi-speke.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode man nas no-&thorn;ing aferd : he prechede euere faste</L>
<L>And confortede &thorn;at clene maide : &thorn;at ire heorte opon him al caste.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is Maide feol doun to is fet : and on him &yogh;eorne gradde;
<PB REF="00000129.tif" N="81"></L>
<L N="116">Euere &thorn;is guode man hire bi-sou&yogh;te : &thorn;at heo clene lijf ladde.</L>
<L>Seth&thorn;e he wende and grei&thorn;ede him : is masse forto singue.</L>
<L>lu&thorn;ere Men i-redie weren : i-sende &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e kingue.</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;ht ase he stod at is Masse : on of heom forth&thorn; wende</L>
<L>And smot him &thorn;oru-out with a swerd : and alle his gottes to-rende :</L>
<L>For he smot him In at&thorn;e Rugge : and at&thorn;e wombe out.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e guode Man a-slawe was : &thorn;e schrewe was wel prout.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at folk &thorn;at cristine was : wel &thorn;icke it cam a-non</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;e kingues paleis for-to brenne : and to a-quelle is men ech-on.</L>
<L>Ake seint Matheus desciples : for-boden heom ech-one</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy ne duden no such &thorn;ing : ake lieten god wur&thorn;e al-one.</L>
<L>huy wenden and nomen &thorn;is holie bodi : and swi&thorn;e faire on eor&thorn;e it brou&yogh;te.&mdash;</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;e king &yogh;uyt bi al is mi&yogh;te : after &thorn;at maide &yogh;eorne sou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;o he ne mi&yogh;hte in none manere : to is wille hire i-winne,</L>
<L>he wende forth and sette a-fuyre : &thorn;at hous &thorn;at heo was inne.<MILESTONE N="52" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ake seint Matheu ne for-&yogh;at nou&yogh;t &thorn;at Maide : &thorn;ei he ded were :<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. were ded</NOTE></L>
<L>Fram heouene he a-li&yogh;hte a-doun to hire : and is help ire cudde &thorn;ere<NOTE PLACE="marg1">added</NOTE> :</L>
<L>For &thorn;at fuyr he drof a-&yogh;ein : to &thorn;e kingues paleis a-non</L>
<L>And fur-brende it al-to nou&yogh;t : and is Men echon;</L>
<L>&para; Vnne&thorn;e he him-sulf and is sone : a-scapeden with heore liue.</L>
<L N="136">he mi&yogh;hte segge, to wro&thorn;erhele : he wilne[de] aftur wiue.</L>
<L>For suy&thorn;e sone &thorn;are-aftur-ward : Musel he bi-cam;</L>
<L>And &thorn;o he ne mi&yogh;hte nou&yogh;t beo hol : gret deol to him hee nam,</L>
<L>With is swerd him-sulf he a-slou&yogh; : and is bodi al-to-rende&mdash;</L>
<L N="140">Nou god it wot and seint Matheu : &yogh;wodere is soule wende.</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk wende forth a-non : and made ane newe king wel bliue,</L>
<L>&THORN;e clene maidenes bro&thorn;ur i-wis : &thorn;at he wilnede so muche to wiue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at seint Matheu &thorn;e apostel hadde : i-cristned with is honde;</L>
<L N="144">&YOGH;ware-&thorn;oru cristinedom : cam seth&thorn;e into al &thorn;e londe.</L>
<L>Nou Iesu crist us &yogh;iue is grace : &thorn;ulke Ioy&yogh;e i-winne</L>
<L>For &thorn;e loue of seint Matheu : &thorn;at he woneth inne.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="22" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>22 Liger.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">[2 Octob.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint leger a bischop was : and holi man i-nou&yogh;;</L>
<L>Mani a man &thorn;oru&yogh; is prechingue : to godes lawe he drou&yogh;.
<PB REF="00000130.tif" N="82"></L>
<L>A lu&thorn;ur Iustise &thorn;are was nei&yogh;h : Ebrom<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. Ebroin</NOTE> was is name :</L>
<L N="4">Men tolden him, ase he wende a-boute : of seint legeres fame.</L>
<L>he liet him wel sone nime : and bi-fore him bringue,</L>
<L>And fondede for-to tuyrne is &thorn;ou&yogh;t : fram &thorn;e heuene kingue.</L>
<L>&thorn;o he ne mi&yogh;hte &thorn;at don nou&yogh;t : he was wroth inou&yogh;;</L>
<L N="8">Ane lu&thorn;ere man he cleopede sone : &thorn;at bo&thorn;e is ei&yogh;ene ou&yogh;t drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o is ei&yogh;ene in grete pine : weren i-holede out bo&thorn;e,</L>
<L>he gan &thorn;e more prechi of god. : &thorn;are-fore huy weren wro&thorn;e.</L>
<L>A wei &thorn;er was of scharpe stones : and opward stoden echon :</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;are-oppe &thorn;is holie man : barefot huy maden gon,</L>
<L>huy driuen him barefot and a-blend : ope &thorn;is scharpe stones &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode man eode wel baldeliche : ase &thorn;ei him no-&thorn;ing nere,</L>
<L>And euere he prechede on Iesu crist&mdash; : he ne bi-lefte for no fere.</L>
<L>&para; For is longue prechingue &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere men : wro&thorn;est with him were :</L>
<L>huy coruen of is tongue a-non : ri&yogh;ht bi is &thorn;rote a-boue.</L>
<L>&THORN;are schewede ore swete louerd : fair Miracle for is loue :</L>
<L>For &thorn;o is tongue was of i-corue : &yogh;eot he prechede faste</L>
<L N="20">And al-so wel as he dude er. : &thorn;o weren &thorn;e schrewes a-gaste.</L>
<L>huy bi-speken to don him more schame : ake huy weren sumdel in doute.</L>
<L>huy [sto]den<NOTE PLACE="marg1">unreadable.</NOTE> and bi-heolden is heued : and &thorn;o<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;e?</NOTE> i-sei&yogh;en huy &thorn;are|a-boute</L>
<L>A ro[un]d croune and swi&thorn;e cler&mdash; : bri&yogh;htore ne mi&yogh;hte non beo,</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;at vnne&thorn;e huy mi&yogh;hten is holie heued : for &thorn;e leome i-seo.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is lu&thorn;ere Iustise het a-non : &thorn;at men smiten of is heued,</L>
<L>Four tormentores he was bi-take : &thorn;at it nere nou&yogh;t bi-leued.</L>
<L>huy ladden him with-oute toun : for-[to] don &thorn;at dede.</L>
<L N="28">Ase huy comen a-midde &thorn;e wei : &thorn;is holie man to heom seide :</L>
<L>"&YOGH;wat neode is it for-to trauailli : ferrore me to lede?<MILESTONE N="52b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Doth&thorn; anon &thorn;at &yogh;e scholden do : here ri&yogh;ht, ich eou rede."</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;reo quellares of &thorn;is word : anon weren in grete drede :</L>
<L N="32">To is fet huy feollen a-kneo : and for-&yogh;iuenesse him bede.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore was &thorn;e feor&thorn;e wroth : forth he hupte sone</L>
<L>And smot of &thorn;e guode mannes heued : ase he hadde heste to done.</L>
<L>&para; Sone &thorn;are-aftur cam a fuir : ase it of helle were,</L>
<L N="36">And al quik fur-barnde him : and &thorn;e deuelene a-wei him bere.
<PB REF="00000131.tif" N="83"></L>
<L>Seint leger was wel faire i-bured. : is soule to heouene wende,</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at bodi, ase it on eor&thorn;e lai : fair miracle ore louerd sende.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e lu&thorn;ere Iustise &thorn;at him liet a-quelle : &thorn;ere-of heorde telle,</L>
<L N="40">two &yogh;er aftur &thorn;ulke tyme : &thorn;at he him liet a-quelle :</L>
<L>To is toumbe ane kni&yogh;ht he sende : &thorn;e so&thorn;e for-to fonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e kni&yogh;ht to &thorn;e toumbe cam : &thorn;are-bi he gan stonde,</L>
<L>"In schendnesse," he seide, "mote he dei&yogh;e : and in strongue de&thorn;e al-so</L>
<L N="44">ho-so bi-lieueth&thorn; &thorn;at dede men : ani miracle mouwen do!"</L>
<L>Wel filliche also &thorn;e toumbe he smot. : and a-non-ri&yogh;ht with &thorn;e dede</L>
<L>Oppon him feol is owene bone : ase he bad and seide :</L>
<L>For deuelene a-strangleden him a-non&mdash; : for al redie &thorn;are huy were,</L>
<L N="48">And is soule, ase it was ri&yogh;ht : a-deuele wei huy bere.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Iustise sone &thorn;are-aftur-ward : to de&thorn;e was i-do</L>
<L>And a-slawe in grete schendnesse : and a-deuele wei wende also.</L>
<L>&THORN;us was &thorn;e bischop seint leger : a-wreke of is fon,</L>
<L N="52">And he him-sulf to &thorn;e Ioie of heouene : after is de&thorn;e gan gon.</L>
<L>Nou god for &thorn;e loue of seint leger : is swete grace us siende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we aftur &thorn;usse liue : moten to &thorn;e Ioye of heouene wiende.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="23" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>23 Seint fid[es]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">[6 Octob.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEinte Fey, &thorn;at holie Maide : of swi&thorn;e hei&yogh;e men heo com.</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e &yogh;ong in hire childhod : heo turnede to cristindom,</L>
<L>And holi lijf i-nou heo ladde&mdash; : &thorn;at word sprong wel wide</L>
<L N="4">Of hire guodnesse and of hire holi lijf : a-boute in eche side.</L>
<L>&para; A lu&thorn;er Aumperour &thorn;are was &thorn;o : &thorn;at hiet Dioclician,</L>
<L>And is felawe &thorn;at was al-so : &thorn;e schrewe Maximian;</L>
<L>A lu&thorn;ur Iustise huy hadden with heom : is name was dacian :</L>
<L N="8">To de&thorn;e huy brou&yogh;ten &yogh;ware huy founden : ani cristine Man.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Iustise Dacian : wende in-tal<NOTE PLACE="marg1">= in-to al</NOTE> &thorn;e lond</L>
<L>And a-slou&yogh; alle &thorn;e cristine men : &thorn;at he ou&yogh;were fond.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he heorde telle : ase he wende bi &thorn;e wey,</L>
<L N="12">Of &thorn;is holie maide and clene : and i-cristned, seinte Fey.</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;e toune &thorn;are heo was inne : ase a wod man he wende,</L>
<L>And burstinde in grete wrath&thorn;e : is bedeles a-boute he sende,</L>
<L>To crie a-boute in eche strete : &yogh;if men mi&yogh;hte ani finde</L>
<L N="16">Cristine man o&thorn;ur womman : &thorn;at huy heom scholden faste binde
<PB REF="00000132.tif" N="84"></L>
<L>And bi-fore him bringue haste-liche&mdash; : &thorn;at huy ne sparede non!&mdash;</L>
<L>And bote huy wolden heore [&thorn;ou&yogh;t] tuyrne : ano&thorn;ur it scholde gon.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e banne was &thorn;us i-cried : &thorn;are was Ioye I-nou&yogh;</L>
<L N="20">Among &thorn;e paeyns euerechone : &thorn;at Man cristine men so a-slou&yogh;;<MILESTONE N="53" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ake seoruwe and sor and deol i-nou&yogh; : among cristine men &thorn;are was,</L>
<L>&THORN;o huy sei&yogh;en heore deth i-come : and non o&thorn;ur bote &thorn;are nas.</L>
<L>&para; Seinte Fey was furst i-sou&yogh;t : for men wusten of hire wel wide.</L>
<L N="24">Ioyful heo was and glad i-nou&yogh; : &thorn;o men &thorn;e banne criede;</L>
<L>Ake forth heo wende wel baldeliche : nolde heo nou&yogh;t longue a-bide,</L>
<L>Ake profrede hire to &thorn;e tormentores : ase men sou&yogh;ten hire wide.</L>
<L>With hardie heorte heo wende forth. : &thorn;e tormentores hire nome</L>
<L N="28">And harleden hire wel filliche : forth toward hire dome.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Iustise for wrath&thorn;e wende<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. vemde</NOTE> &thorn;o : heo bi-fore him come.</L>
<L>heo made &thorn;e signe of &thorn;e croiz : and blessede hire i-lome;</L>
<L>heo bad ore louerd wel mildeliche : &thorn;at he ire &yogh;eue &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="32">Studefaste bi-leue and strenc&thorn;e of heorte : &thorn;at heo ouer-come nere,</L>
<L>And in hire tormenz treowe heorte : and &thorn;at he ire &yogh;eue is grace</L>
<L>To his onour answerie wel : &thorn;e Iustise in &thorn;at place.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Iustise bi-heold &thorn;at Maide : with ful sori chere,</L>
<L N="36">he grennede and femde touward hire : ri&yogh;ht ase he wod were :</L>
<L>"Dameisele," he seide, "&yogh;wat art &thorn;ou? : &yogh;wat &thorn;encst&thorn;ou for-to do?</L>
<L>Tel me on &yogh;wam &thorn;ou bi-lieuest : and &yogh;wat is &thorn;i name, al-so."</L>
<L>"Sire," seide &thorn;is holie Maide : "Fey ich hote nou&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="40">And cristine womman ich habbe i-beo : seth&thorn;e ich ani guod cou&thorn;e.</L>
<L>Mi name nelle ich nou&yogh;t for-sake : no mi cristindom no&thorn;ur;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mi&yogh;ht &thorn;retne al &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolt : of me ne worth &thorn;e non o&thorn;ur."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o bi-gan &thorn;is Dacian : fair semblaunt to make,</L>
<L N="44">"Maide," he seide, "ich rede &thorn;e : &thorn;at &thorn;ou an o&thorn;ur red take.</L>
<L>&THORN;ench &thorn;at &thorn;ou art fair and noble : and &thorn;at &thorn;e bet bi-come</L>
<L>A noble lauedi to beon and hei&yogh;h : &thorn;ane beo i-brou&yogh;t here to dome.</L>
<L>For &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt don aftur me : in grete Ioie &thorn;ou worst i-brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And in grete nobleie, ase &thorn;e bi-cometh&mdash; : &thorn;are-fore torne &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t."</L>
<L N="49">&para; "Certes, sire," &thorn;is maide seide : "&thorn;ou spext embe nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For i-nelle neuere him for-sake : &thorn;at so deore me hath&thorn; a-bou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>For ich habbe to him mi vou i-maked : &thorn;at i-nelle neuere breke.</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;are<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. &thorn;are-fore</NOTE> do elles &yogh;wat &thorn;ou wolt : bote &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;arof ne speke;
<PB REF="00000133.tif" N="85"></L>
<L>For I-nelle nou&yogh;t honouri &thorn;ine false godes. : for in &thorn;e sautere it is i-write</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle swuche Deouele beoth : and &thorn;at may ech Man i-wite."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o fierde &thorn;e Iustise ase he were wod : and made wel sori bere,</L>
<L>And was neih&yogh; wod for &thorn;is Maide seide : &thorn;at is godes deuelene were.</L>
<L>he liet fette a bed of bras : brod and hei&yogh;h also,</L>
<L N="58">And dude strepe &thorn;is Maide naked : and in &thorn;is harde bedde ire do.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is Maide, &thorn;o heo naked was : with glad semblaunt in wende;</L>
<L>huy strei&yogh;hten hire a-long and a-croiz : and gret fuyr &thorn;are-onder tende,</L>
<L>And casten on grece riue i-nou&yogh; : &thorn;at drof up so gret lei&yogh;e</L>
<L N="62">&THORN;at &thorn;is maide &thorn;ou&yogh;te al a-fuyre : ase huy &thorn;at stoden &thorn;are i-sei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;e tormentores stoden &thorn;are-bi-side : with kene oules and strongue</L>
<L N="64">And tur[n]den &thorn;at Maide side and o&thorn;ur : ouer &thorn;e fuyre wel longue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo &thorn;oru&yogh; strenc&thorn;e of &thorn;e grece : ofte al a-fuyre stod.<MILESTONE N="53b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Euere lai &thorn;at holie Maide : ase hire nere nou&yogh;t bote guod,</L>
<L>hire heu heo nolde chaungi enes : ne tuyrne hire &thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="68">Alle men &thorn;at &thorn;e wonder i-seien : &thorn;e enchesun nusten nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; Cristine men manie : &thorn;o huy herden telle</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e Iustise was &thorn;udere i-come : with tormenz heom to quelle,</L>
<L>huy ornen out of toune hem for-to huyde : ech in is side, for doute,</L>
<L N="72">And lei&yogh;en in puttes and in olde diches : &yogh;eon<SUP>t</SUP> al &thorn;e contreie a|boute.</L>
<L>An holi man &thorn;are hudde him so : &thorn;at men cleopeden capras,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;e north-side of &thorn;e toun : in one olde roche he was.</L>
<L>&para; He lai and darede out of is hole : ase he dorste for doute,</L>
<L N="76">And i-sai&yogh; al &thorn;e torment of seinte Fey : ase he [biheold aboute,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. (so Ash.)</NOTE>]</L>
<L>hou men rosteden hire with fuyr and grece : and to-drowen hire al-so&mdash;</L>
<L>For it was a luyte &thorn;are-bi-side : &thorn;at &thorn;is dede was i-do.</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;is fuyr bi-gan to brenne : &thorn;is holie man i-sei&yogh;,</L>
<L N="80">A coluere &thorn;are cam, so &yogh;wijt so milk : fram heouene fleo on hei&yogh;,</L>
<L>&para; A croune of guold heo bar a-doun : &thorn;at schinde swi&thorn;e bri&yogh;hte,</L>
<L>Bri&yogh;htore &thorn;ane &thorn;e sonne leom. : oppe &thorn;e maidenes heued<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Ash. maide heo</NOTE> ali&yogh;hte</L>
<L>And sette &thorn;e croune on hire heued : with &thorn;e winguen heo bleu faste</L>
<L N="84">A&yogh;ein &thorn;at fuyr, ase him &thorn;ou&yogh;te : &thorn;at it ne mi&yogh;hte nou&yogh;t i-laste&mdash;</L>
<L>Fram-ward &thorn;at Maide heo bleu it euere : &thorn;at it ne cam hire no-&thorn;ing nei&yogh;h,
<PB REF="00000134.tif" N="86"></L>
<L>And heo lai &thorn;are in alle Ioye : ase &thorn;is holie man i-sei&yogh;h.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore o&thorn;ure &thorn;at weren hire nei&yogh;h : nusten nou&yogh;t hou it was,</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;at &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at heo was al a-fuyre : and neuere &thorn;e worse hire nas.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is holie man seint capras : &thorn;at i-sei&yogh;h al &thorn;is,</L>
<L>to him-seolf he seide, "ich a-bide : nou sone to longue, i-wis;"</L>
<L>he sturte out of &thorn;is deope Roche : and &thorn;udere or[n] wel faste;</L>
<L N="92">to &thorn;is tormentingue sone he cam : no-&thorn;ing him ne agaste.</L>
<L>Loude he gradde with folle Mouth : "Ich am cristine Man,</L>
<L>I-nelle for-sake Ihesu crist : for drede of Dacian.</L>
<L>To longue ich habbe heonne i-beo&mdash; : &thorn;at me for-&thorn;uncheth sore.</L>
<L N="96">here is Ioye and blisse i-nou&yogh;h : &thorn;at schal bringue us to more."</L>
<L>&para; Tweie bre&thorn;ren &thorn;are comen &thorn;o al-so : seint Felician</L>
<L>And seint prime : &thorn;at seide also to &thorn;is Dacian.</L>
<L>Wod-wroth&thorn; was Dacian &thorn;o : he dude heom nime ech-on,</L>
<L N="100">Seinte Fey and alle &thorn;e o&thorn;ere : and smiten of heore heuedes a-non.</L>
<L>&THORN;e tormentores i-redie weren : and gonne &thorn;at maide take</L>
<L>And hire felawes forth with hire : &thorn;at nolden ore louerd for-sake,</L>
<L>And ladden heom forth to heore ende-day : and heore heuedes smiten of sone</L>
<L N="104">In gret wrath&thorn;e ech aftur o&thorn;ur : and duden heore maistres bone.</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;e Ioye of heouene a-non huy wenden : and &thorn;are bi-leue with|outen ende;</L>
<L>Aungles &thorn;are weren to bere heom forth&thorn; : &thorn;at ore louerd &thorn;udere gan siende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lu&thorn;ere men leten &thorn;e bodies ligge : &thorn;o huy weren i-brou&yogh;t of dawe,</L>
<L N="108">In a foul stude al on-bured : &thorn;are bestes heom scholden to-drawe.</L>
<L>Ake cristine men &thorn;at &thorn;are weren nei&yogh;h : &thorn;erto stelen bi ni&yogh;hte</L>
<L>And bureden heom in a derne stude : ase nobleliche ase huy mi&yogh;hten.<MILESTONE N="54" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Nou seinte Fey and hire felawes : ore erinde beode so,</L>
<L N="112">&THORN;at we moten to &thorn;e Ioye come : &thorn;are huy beoth inne i-do.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="24" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>24 XI Millia Virg.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ondleuene &thorn;ousend of virgines : for ore louerd i-martrede were;</L>
<L>Telle i-chulle of heore martyrdom : and ho heom &thorn;ar-to gan lere.</L>
<L>A kyng &thorn;are was in Brutayne : sire Maur was is name;</L>
<L N="4">Ane dou&yogh;ter he hadde &thorn;at hiet Ourse : &thorn;at was of noble fame;
<PB REF="00000135.tif" N="87"></L>
<L>Cristine heo was and al hire kun : swi&thorn;e hende and quoynte,</L>
<L>So fair womman Men nusten non : no so guod in euerech pointe.</L>
<L>&para; Of hire fair-hede and of hire guodnesse : men tolden in eche side,</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;at &thorn;e word cam into Enguelond : and elles-&yogh;woder wel wide.</L>
<L>A kyng &thorn;are was &thorn;o in Enguelonde : and Man of gret poer;</L>
<L>Gret nobleie he heorde telle : of &thorn;is maide feor and ner:</L>
<L>his wille was gret &thorn;at is sone : &thorn;is Maide in spoushod hadde.</L>
<L N="12">Ake Men &thorn;e &yogh;uyt in Enguelond : cristinedom non nadden.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e king of enguelond, &thorn;at was &thorn;o : to &thorn;e kyng of Brutayne gan siende</L>
<L>For is dou&yogh;ter to is sone : &thorn;at was is heyr so hende;</L>
<L>And seide, &yogh;if &thorn;at he &thorn;are-a&yogh;en were : &thorn;at &thorn;e dede nere i-do,</L>
<L N="16">him and alle his he wolde destruy&yogh;e : and al his lond al-so.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is Messagers comen to &thorn;is kyng : and heore erinde hadden i-seid,</L>
<L>Sori and dreori was &thorn;is king : he ne cou&thorn;e &thorn;are-of no red:</L>
<L>For &thorn;e king of Enguelond : was he&thorn;ene, and alle his,</L>
<L N="20">And for he wuste wel &thorn;at is dou&yogh;hter nolde : i-wedded beo, i-wis,</L>
<L>And also, for &thorn;e kyng of Enguelond : was of so gret mi&yogh;hte</L>
<L>&THORN;at he no strenc&thorn;e ne mi&yogh;hte habbe : a&yogh;ein him for-to fi&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>And na&thorn;eles Triwes of is answere : a&yogh;ein &thorn;e messagers he nam.</L>
<L N="24">Deol and sor and luyte gladnesse : in is heorte &thorn;are cam!</L>
<L>&para; He ne tolde no-&thorn;ing is dou&yogh;ter fore : of &thorn;is reuful cas;</L>
<L>&YOGH;eorne he bad god ni&yogh;ht and day : for he redles was,</L>
<L>And criede on him swi&thorn;e reufulliche : &thorn;at he him scholde rede.</L>
<L>A ni&yogh;ht an Aungel to is dou&yogh;ter cam : and &thorn;eos wordes to hire sede:</L>
<L>"Ne beo &thorn;ou nou&yogh;ht a-&yogh;ein &thorn;is sonde : Ake, &thorn;ine fader forto paye,</L>
<L N="30">Graunte i-wedded for-to beo : and bide &thorn;at he it delai&yogh;e</L>
<L>Ane &thorn;reo &yogh;er, &thorn;at &thorn;ou mouwe &thorn;e &yogh;wile : &thorn;i Maiden-hod anoure;</L>
<L N="32">And &thorn;at huy &thorn;e purchace clene maidenes : with &thorn;e to habbe in &thorn;i boure:</L>
<L>&para; And &thorn;at &thorn;e king of Enguelonde and is sone : and &thorn;i fader beon alle at one rede</L>
<L>&THORN;e for-to cheose ten clene Maidenes : with-oute eche wicke dede;</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane &yogh;e Endleue to-gadere beoth&thorn; : &thorn;at huy eou finden &yogh;eot &thorn;er-to</L>
<L N="36">Euer-ech of eov a &thorn;ousend maidenes : to serui eou al-so,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;wane &yogh;e alle to-gadere beoth : &thorn;at ech mouwe in is side
<PB REF="00000136.tif" N="88"></L>
<L>honouri hire Maiden-hod and &thorn;in : &thorn;at it beo couth wel wide,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at Men ne mouwen Maide non : alosed finde<NOTE PLACE="marg1">finde overlined</NOTE> a&yogh;ein &thorn;e;</L>
<L N="40">And &thorn;at he wolle cristine bi-come : &thorn;i louerd &thorn;at schal beo.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is foreward graunte him : aftur &thorn;e &thorn;ridde &yogh;ere</L>
<L>I-spoused to beon in godes lawe&mdash; : And ne haue &thorn;erof no fere!"</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at maide i-heorde &thorn;is : glad heo was of is lore,<MILESTONE N="54b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at heo wuste &yogh;ware-with heo mi&yogh;hte : bringue hire fader of is sore.</L>
<L>&para; Sone heo wende to hire fader : and bad &thorn;at he ire telle scholde</L>
<L N="46">&YOGH;wy &thorn;at he so mourninde &yogh;eode. : he seide &thorn;at he nolde.</L>
<L>"Ich wot wel &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t," &thorn;at maide seide : "&thorn;ei &thorn;ou it holde stille.</L>
<L N="48">Of &thorn;i sonde ne haue no doute : ichulle don al &thorn;i wille."</L>
<L>&THORN;o bi-gan heo tellen him in &yogh;wuche manere&mdash; : ase &thorn;e Aungel hire hadde i-seid&mdash;</L>
<L>heo wolde habbe &thorn;ene hei&yogh;e Man : &yogh;if &thorn;at it were is red.</L>
<L>&para; Welle, glad was &thorn;e kyng : &thorn;o &thorn;at he iheorde &thorn;is!</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;e Messagers he &yogh;af Answere : sone with gret blis.</L>
<L>&THORN;o huy [it] brou&yogh;ten &thorn;e kingues sone : &thorn;e ti&thorn;ingue wel him payde.</L>
<L>Sone he liet Baptizen him : for loue of &thorn;at Maide;</L>
<L>And &thorn;oru&yogh; is fader and &thorn;oru&yogh; him : and &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e o&thorn;ur kingue</L>
<L>Endleue &thorn;ousend of clene maidenes : to &thorn;is maide huy guonne bringue.</L>
<L>heo was glad of &thorn;e compaygnie : &thorn;at so fair to hire cam!</L>
<L N="58">Sone heo bigan in priueite : telle heom of cristinedom;</L>
<L>&THORN;at for hire loue and for hire prechingue : alle cristine huy were.</L>
<L N="60">Louerd, &yogh;wuch a compaygnie : of clene maidenes was &thorn;ere!</L>
<L>&para; So gret Ioye &thorn;e king of is dou&yogh;ter hadde : and of ire faire ferrade,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he liet heom makien a quoynte schip : of<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> of gret</NOTE> leng&thorn;e and of brede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy scholden in &thorn;e se : plei&yogh;e, &yogh;wane huy wolde,</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;at ech man a-londe and in watere : heore mayden-hod pre[i]sie scholde.</L>
<L>huy sounguen ofte a-watere and eke a-lond : and treches huy gonne lede</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ur-manere faire pleies : and al was of clene dedes.</L>
<L>Mete and drinke stilleliche : to &thorn;e schip huy lieten bringue</L>
<L N="68">To &thorn;reo &yogh;eres sustinaunce : with-oute leue of &thorn;e kingue.</L>
<L>&para; A dai huy wenten into &thorn;e se : and pleiden heom up and doun&mdash;</L>
<L>For Ioye &thorn;ere stoden, to bi-holden heom : Men of mani a toun.
<PB REF="00000137.tif" N="89"></L>
<L>Ase huy weren in mest Ioye of plei : ore louerd ane wynd sende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at drof heom feor into &thorn;e se : &thorn;at men nusten &yogh;wodere huy wende.</L>
<L>Welle, glade were &thorn;is maydenes &thorn;o! : &thorn;e wind heom drof wel bliue,</L>
<L N="74">To<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> ate</NOTE> &thorn;e cite of coloyne : formest huy gonne ariue.</L>
<L>&para; To Damoysele ourse, &thorn;e kyngues dou&yogh;hter : an Aungel cam &thorn;ere</L>
<L>And bad hire lede wel hire compaygnye : for-to huy i-martrede were;</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;at huy scholden for&thorn;ere fare : and alle a-&yogh;ein wende,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;ulke toune for ore louerdes loue : imartrede beon at&thorn;enende.</L>
<L>Glad was &thorn;at Mayde for &thorn;is word! : forth&thorn; huy wenden a-non.</L>
<L N="80">At&thorn;e cite of Basilie : huy a-riueden ech-on.</L>
<L>&para; Fram &thorn;ulke Cite euerechone : a-fote huy wenden to Rome.</L>
<L>Gret Ioye made &thorn;e pope with heom : &thorn;o huy &thorn;udere come&mdash;</L>
<L>For manie of heom weren nei&yogh;h him sibbe : and for he was of bru|tayne;</L>
<L N="84">Cyriac is name was. : huy weren of him wel fayne.</L>
<L>An Aungel cam to &thorn;e pope a ni&yogh;ht : and seide &thorn;at he scholde</L>
<L>With &thorn;is Maydenes i-martred beo : for ore louerd it so wolde.</L>
<L>After &thorn;at tyme &thorn;is holie man : honourede heom &thorn;e more,</L>
<L>And prechede heom ofte of clannesse : and of ore louerdes lore.<MILESTONE N="55" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Tweolf mon&thorn;e and endleue wokes : alle &thorn;is Maydenes were</L>
<L N="90">At Rome with &thorn;is holie pope : &thorn;at heom dude wel lere.</L>
<L>&para; Ake &thorn;e pope seint Ciriac : is conseil cleopie gan,</L>
<L N="92">His clerkes and is Cardinales : and Mani on o&thorn;er Man:</L>
<L>Bi-fore heom al is dignete : he tok up at&thorn;en ende,</L>
<L>And seide he wolde in-to an o&thorn;ur lond : with &thorn;is maydenes wende.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is Cardinales weren &thorn;are-a-&yogh;ein : and seiden &thorn;at he gan reue</L>
<L N="96">With fole wummen for-to go : and is dignete bi-leue.</L>
<L>Na&thorn;eles he wende forth with heom : al a-&yogh;ein heore rede;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Cardinales and is clerkes : gret schame &thorn;are-fore him seide.</L>
<L>Tweie lu&thorn;ere princes &thorn;are weren : Maximin and Affrican,</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;ou&yogh;ten &thorn;at &thorn;is Maydenes wolden : tuyrne mani a man:</L>
<L>To heore Mey, &thorn;e prince of Coloyne : huy senden for-&thorn;en-one</L>
<L>&THORN;at he, &yogh;wane huy &thorn;udere comen : A-slowe heom euerech-one.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at child &thorn;at scholde &thorn;is Mayde wedde : ase heo hadde i-seid,</L>
<L N="104">Kyng was i-maud of Enguelonde : &thorn;o is fader was ded;</L>
<L>&THORN;at ladde swi&thorn;e chaste lijf : and longuede swi&thorn;e sore
<PB REF="00000138.tif" N="90"></L>
<L>With &thorn;at clene Maide to speke and beo : &thorn;oru&yogh; strenc&thorn;e of godes lore.</L>
<L>An Aungel cam to him and bad : &thorn;at he on alle wise</L>
<L N="108">his Moder and is &yogh;ungueste soster : anon-ri&yogh;ht liete Baptize</L>
<L>And he with heom to Coloygne : wiende with al his mayne</L>
<L>A-&yogh;ein is trewe spouse, &thorn;at was : Mayde Ourse of brutayne;</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. he</NOTE> him to hire leide faste : in wille and eke in dede,</L>
<L>And endede heore lijf in godes seruise : ase heo heom wolde rede.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;is &yogh;ongue with gret ioye dude : &thorn;at &thorn;e Aungel him gan lere:</L>
<L N="114">his moder and is soster he nam : &thorn;o huy i-baptizede were,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Bischop Clement al-so : &thorn;at i-baptized heom hadde,</L>
<L N="116">Toward coloyne forth with him : a-&yogh;en &thorn;is Maydenes he ladde.</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e glad was &thorn;is &yogh;ongue king : &thorn;o he to is lefMan cam!</L>
<L>And also glad was &thorn;at Maide : &thorn;o heo sai&yogh;h him in cristinedom!</L>
<L>Mest Ioye heo made with is &yogh;ongue soster : &thorn;at hiet Florentyne,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;at heo, clene Mayde, scholde : soffrie de&thorn;es pine.</L>
<L>&para; Ourse of Brutayne &thorn;ene &yogh;oungue king : in grete Ioye of loue gan lere</L>
<L N="122">&THORN;at he him heolde faste to hire : and ne bi-lefde for no fere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy mi&yogh;hten in trewe loue : to-gadere i-martred beo</L>
<L>And wonye in heuene with Ihesu crist : &thorn;at bou&yogh;te heom on &thorn;e treo.</L>
<L>Al&thorn;is grauntede &thorn;is &yogh;oungue king : and is lefmane nou&yogh;t ne wernde;</L>
<L>his furste &thorn;ou&yogh;t into treowe loue : and into clannesse he turnde.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e he&thorn;ene prince i-redi was : &thorn;o huy to Coloyne come</L>
<L>With manie lu&thorn;ere he&thorn;ene Men : and al &thorn;is compaygnie huy nome,</L>
<L>And huweden and crieden on heom a-schame : and to grounde heom a-slowe,</L>
<L>And ase so fale wolues a-mong lambren : heore flechs huy to-drowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;o huy comen to &thorn;is clene &thorn;ing : Maide Ourse of Brutayne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy founden so fair a creature : of hire huy weren wel fayne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince hire nam and hire bi-hiet : to laten hire gon a-liue<MILESTONE N="55b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="134">And, for heo was so fair and noble : habbe hire to wiue.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is Maide seide &thorn;at heo nolde to hire spouse : him ne non o&thorn;ur take.</L>
<L N="136">&THORN;e prince nei&yogh;h for wrath&thorn;e wod : &thorn;o he was so fur-sake,</L>
<L>he liet hire to de&thorn;e scheote : with Aruwene at&thorn;enende
<PB REF="00000139.tif" N="91"></L>
<L>And &thorn;us heo and al hire compaygnie : to &thorn;e Ioye of heuene gan wiende;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e &yogh;ongue king of Enguelonde : and is Moder also,</L>
<L N="140">And is &yogh;ongue soster Florentine : to de&thorn;e weren i-do,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e pope Ciriac : and Bischopes mani on</L>
<L>&THORN;at for trewe hope of Martyrdom : with heom weren i-gon.</L>
<L>Ore louerd hadde swi&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Ou louerd &thorn;e</NOTE> gret Ioye : of &thorn;at swete ferrede,</L>
<L>&thorn;at swuch martyrdom for is<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;i</NOTE> loue : a-fenguen with-oute drede.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e to hondrede &yogh;ere<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> : and ei&yogh;te and &thorn;ritti&thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L>After ore louerdes buyrtyme : &thorn;is maidenes i-martrede were.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is endleue &thorn;ousend of clene maydenes : and al &thorn;is compaygnie</L>
<L N="148">I-burede weren in Coloyne : in one Nonnerie.&mdash;</L>
<L>An Abbot &thorn;ere was bi-side : &thorn;at heorde of &thorn;is cas,</L>
<L>And ofte of &thorn;is clene Maydenes : &thorn;at gret Miracle &thorn;ere was:</L>
<L>he bad &thorn;e Abbesse of Coloyne : &thorn;at heo him graunti scholde</L>
<L N="152">A bodi of &thorn;is clene Maydenes : and he wolde it don in golde.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is bodi was him i-take : twelf Mon&thorn;e he liet it beo</L>
<L>With-oute seluer o&thorn;ur gold : in one cheste of treo.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e twelf mon&thorn;es weren a-go : ase &thorn;e Monekes weren ech-one</L>
<L N="156">A ny&yogh;t at Matines, &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;is &thorn;is</NOTE> holie bodi : a-ros hire up allone,</L>
<L>heo beu&yogh; hire to &thorn;e hei&yogh;e weued : and wende mildeliche</L>
<L>A-mong al &thorn;e Couent forth&thorn; : and out wel stilledliche.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. stilleliche</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e Monekus, &thorn;o huy &thorn;is i-sei&yogh;en : of-dradde and sorien<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. sorie</NOTE> were:</L>
<L N="160">huy eoden to &thorn;e cheste &thorn;are heo [was] inne i-leid : and ne founden ire nou&yogh;t &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&para; "&THORN;is," quath &thorn;e Abbod, "is ore wreche : for we hire i-do nadde</L>
<L>In a schrine of gold, ase we bi-heten : &thorn;o we ire hidere ladden."</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Abbesse of Coloyne : &thorn;e Abbod wende a-non</L>
<L N="164">And tolde &thorn;is cas al-hou it was : of &thorn;at Maide i-gon.</L>
<L>huy wenden forth&thorn; to &thorn;ulke stude : &thorn;are heo was i-leid inne er,</L>
<L>And heuen up &thorn;e &thorn;rouwes lid : and founden hire ligge &thorn;er</L>
<L>Faire and euene ase heo dude er&mdash; : so luyte lime &thorn;ere nas</L>
<L N="168">&THORN;at ne lai ase heo was furst i-leid. : a fair Miracle &thorn;ere was!</L>
<L>&THORN;e Abbesse was &thorn;o swy&thorn;e glad : and &thorn;e Nonnes euerechon,</L>
<L>And &thorn;onkede god of &thorn;at faire Miracle : and hei&yogh;e sounguen a-non.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Abbot bad &thorn;at he moste habbe : &thorn;is holie bodi eft-sone,
<PB REF="00000140.tif" N="92"></L>
<L N="172">And seide he wolde honouri it faire : ase he au&yogh;te for-to done.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;e Abbesse nolde graunti it nou&yogh;t : ne &thorn;at couent no&thorn;ur</L>
<L>&THORN;at eft it scholde habbe a-wei : &thorn;ei he hadde i-beo heore bro&thorn;ur;</L>
<L>For buy i-sei&yogh;en &thorn;at it was godes wille : &thorn;at it bi-lefde &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="176">&THORN;is Abbod wende him hom a-&yogh;ein : with wel dreorie chere.</L>
<L>Nou God us graunti, &yogh;if is wille is : &thorn;at we moten i-winne</L>
<L>&THORN;e hei&yogh;e Ioye of heouene : &thorn;are alle &thorn;is Maydenes beoth inne,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;at we neuere &thorn;arof ne missen : for none<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. nome</NOTE> sorie sunne.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="25" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>25 Katerine.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEinte Katerine of noble kunne: cam, bi olde dawe;<MILESTONE N="56" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Hire fader was king, hire Moder Quyene : bo&thorn;e of &thorn;e olde lawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e king . Coste. hire fader het. : gret clerk &thorn;is Mayde was;</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;are nas non of &thorn;e seue .Ars : &thorn;at heo maister of nas.</L>
<L>Maxentius het &thorn;e Aumperour : In eche londe he let crie</L>
<L>&THORN;at ech kynerich under him : come to Alisaundrie,</L>
<L>Euerech Man for is stat : to don to heore godes sacrefise;</L>
<L N="8">ho-so i<SUP>t</SUP> lete, men scholde of him don : swy&thorn;e stronge Iustise.</L>
<L>&THORN;o ech lond was &thorn;udere i-come : to don heore lawe,</L>
<L>Seinte katerine wel harde-liche : to-ward heom gan drawe;</L>
<L>bi-halues heo stod and bi-heold : heore wrechche gydi-hede,</L>
<L N="12">heo sai&yogh; Anouri &thorn;e Maumates : and manie cristine Men for drede.</L>
<L>&THORN;o hadde heo gret deol in hire heorte : and blesse[de] hire a-non</L>
<L>And forth anon to &thorn;e Aumperour : baldeliche heo gan gon.</L>
<L>"Sire," heo seide, "riche Aumperour &thorn;ou art : swi&thorn;e noble and hende,</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;ov scholdest &thorn;i wisdom and &thorn;i wit : to some guode wende.</L>
<L>&THORN;at i segge for &thorn;e folie : &thorn;at ich i-seo eov do&mdash;</L>
<L>So muche feorrene folk : &thorn;ov hast i-cleopet &thorn;ar-to.</L>
<L>Grete Ioie in ouwer heorte : &thorn;is temple &yogh;e makiez i-fo</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at is ymaud of lym and ston : and of ouwer Maumates also;</L>
<L>&YOGH;wy ne bi-holde &yogh;e &thorn;e hei&yogh;e temple&mdash; : for &thorn;er-of wondri ov mai&mdash;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e heie heuene &thorn;at geth a-boute : a-bouen eov ni&yogh;t and dai,</L>
<L>Of sonne and Mone and steorrene al-so : fram &thorn;e este to &thorn;e weste</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;at trauaillieth and neuere werie ne beoth : ne neuere ne habbeth reste?
<PB REF="00000141.tif" N="93"></L>
<L>bi-&thorn;ench &thorn;e wel and turne &thorn;i wit : to some wisdome, ich rede,</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane &thorn;in owene In-wit it seith : &thorn;at nou&yogh;were nis swuch dede,</L>
<L>Al-mi&yogh;ti god &thorn;ou him hold : &thorn;at swuch wonder can make;</L>
<L N="28">bi-fore alle o&thorn;ere Anoure him : and &thorn;ine Maumates for-sake."</L>
<L>With o&thorn;ere resones of clergie : &thorn;at mayde proffrede also</L>
<L>&THORN;at heore godes nau&yogh;tes ne were : &thorn;at heo Anoureden heom to.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Aumperour stod and ne cou&thorn;e &thorn;ar-to : Answerie In none wise;</L>
<L N="32">Gret wonder him &thorn;ou&yogh;te of hire fair-hede : and of hire Quoyntise;</L>
<L>"Mayde," he seide, "a-bijd here-with : for-to aftur ore sacrefise</L>
<L>And we schullen more with &thorn;e speke : ich o&thorn;ur mi Iustise."</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e sacrefise was i-don : &thorn;e Aumperour sat In is trone,</L>
<L N="36">And al is folk a-bouten him. : men brouten &thorn;at Maide sone.</L>
<L>"Maide," seide &thorn;e Aumperur : "&thorn;ou &thorn;inchest gent and freo;</L>
<L>Of &yogh;wat kunrade art &thorn;ou i-come? : gret wonder us &thorn;inchez of &thorn;e."</L>
<L>&para; "Sire Aumperur," &thorn;is Maide seide : "I-ne wilni bote luyte</L>
<L N="40">to tellen &thorn;e of mine kunne : for it were signe of pruyte;</L>
<L>For In is boke &thorn;e wise Man : Catun seith al-so:</L>
<L>&THORN;at Man ne schal him-sulue preisi : ne blamie no-&thorn;e-mo,</L>
<L>For so doth foles &thorn;at wilniez muche : of &yogh;elpingue and of sunne.</L>
<L N="44">Na&thorn;eles ichulle, ake for no pruyte : tellen eov of mine kunne:</L>
<L>Ich am &thorn;e kingus dou&yogh;ter coste : &thorn;at &thorn;ou wost &yogh;wuch is.</L>
<L>hidere ich cam to speke mid eov : of &thorn;at &yogh;e bi-leuez a-mis;</L>
<L>Mid vn-ri&yogh;te heo beoz&thorn; i-cleped godes : &thorn;at o fot ne mouwen go<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. gon</NOTE><MILESTONE N="56b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ne no man helpe in none neode : ne heom-sulue no-&thorn;e-mo."</L>
<L>&para; "Maide," seide<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. seide seide</NOTE> &thorn;is Amperur : "&yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;is soth&thorn; were,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;is world were fals and guydi : &yogh;if &thorn;ou one heom<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. heom heom</NOTE> scholdest [lere];</L>
<L>And we schulle betere i-leue alle men : and more it wole beo note,</L>
<L>&THORN;ane ani fol womman ase &thorn;ou art&mdash; : for ouwer bolt is sone i-schote."</L>
<L>"Sire," seide &thorn;is Maide &thorn;o : "&thorn;ei &thorn;ou luyte telle of me,</L>
<L N="54">Also guod mai beo mi reson : ase &thorn;at comez of &thorn;e.</L>
<L>For, sire Aumperur, &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. ich &thorn;ou</NOTE> art : ase ech man is al-so</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;at hote mai and hys men moten : nede hys hestes do,</L>
<L>Of bodi and of soule &thorn;ou art y-maud : ase &thorn;i-sulf mi&yogh;t i-seo;</L>
<L>Mid ri&yogh;te &thorn;i soule Maister is : and &thorn;i bodi is hyne schal beo.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;i bodi maister is : and &thorn;i soule<NOTE PLACE="marg1">superscribed later.</NOTE> is hyne,</L>
<L N="60">A&yogh;en kuynde it is : and &thorn;ou worst sikur : &thorn;are-fore of helle pine."
<PB REF="00000142.tif" N="94"></L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; hire clergie &thorn;at holi Maide : resones made so quoynte</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e Aumperour ne non of his : ne cou&thorn;e hire ansuerie in none pointe.</L>
<L>"Maide," he seide, "&thorn;ou schalt a-bide : In warde here mid me</L>
<L N="64">And o&thorn;ere ichulle bi tyme finde : &thorn;at schullen Answerie &thorn;e."</L>
<L>&THORN;is Aumperour sende anon : wide a-boute is sonde</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e gretteste maistres of clergie : to him comen In eche londe,</L>
<L>grete Mede of him to habbe : to don a luytel Maystrie,</L>
<L N="68">And for-to susteinen op heore lawe : &thorn;oru strenc&thorn;e of clergie.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;are comen fifti Maistres : &thorn;e gretteste &thorn;at man fond</L>
<L>Also wide ase men mi&yogh;ten seche : ou&yogh;were In ani lond.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Aumperour heom seide a-non : &yogh;ware-fore he after heom sende:</L>
<L N="72">For-to desputi a-&yogh;ein a &yogh;ong womman : &thorn;at al heore lawe schende.</L>
<L>"Nou is &thorn;is," &thorn;at .o. Maister seide : "gret schame, ich onder-stonde,</L>
<L>An Aumperur to sende a-boute : so wide in eche londe</L>
<L>After &thorn;e gretteste Maistres, for-to despuyti : a-&yogh;en a fol wenche,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane on of heore knaue mi&yogh;ten sone : hire resones alle a-quenche!"</L>
<L>"Nai," seide &thorn;is Aumperour : "heo is wisore &thorn;ane &yogh;e wene;</L>
<L N="78">&YOGH;if &yogh;e mouwen ou&yogh;t a&yogh;en hire don : sone it worth i-sene.</L>
<L>For ich habbe leouere &thorn;at &yogh;e hire ouer-come : with resones In some wise,</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;ane we with strenc&thorn;e hire maden : to don &thorn;e sacrefise."</L>
<L>"Lat bringue hire<NOTE PLACE="marg1">superscribed.</NOTE> forth," seide &thorn;at on : "and heo schal segge a-non</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo ne spac neuere wit wisore men : are heo fram us gon."</L>
<L>&para; An Aungel to &thorn;is maide cam : and bad hire of no-&thorn;ing drede,</L>
<L>And seide heo scholde heom alle &thorn;oru hire reson : to cristinedom lede,</L>
<L>And heo alle scholden &thorn;oru hire reson : a-fonge martyrdam.</L>
<L N="86">&THORN;o &thorn;at Maide i-herde &thorn;is : gret Ioie to hire heo nam,</L>
<L>baldeliche heo eode forth : &thorn;o men aftur hire come.</L>
<L>"Sire," he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">= heo</NOTE> seide to &thorn;e Aumperur : "&yogh;ifst &thorn;ou a wis dom</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;us fale maistres of clergie : bringest and sest a-benche,</L>
<L>And me-self to desputy a-&yogh;eines heom : &thorn;at nam bote a fol wenche?</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;at heo me ouer-comez : &thorn;ou bi-hast heom gret mede,</L>
<L N="92">And makest me mid strenc&thorn;e with heom speke : and ne bi-hast me bote luyte!<MILESTONE N="57" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000143.tif" N="95"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;inchez me with on-ri&yogh;te it is : &yogh;wane ich am one a-&yogh;ein heom alle.</L>
<L>&para; Nov ichulle, for god is min help : a-fonge &thorn;at me wole falle."</L>
<L>"Seie, dame conIoun, &yogh;wat art&thorn;ou?" : &thorn;is o legistre seide,</L>
<L N="96">"&THORN;enchest&thorn;ou speke a-&yogh;ein ore clergie? : turne &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t, ich rede!</L>
<L>&THORN;ov seist &thorn;at god al-mi&yogh;ti : dethz on eor&thorn;e &thorn;olede here:</L>
<L>I-chulle proui &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;te a-liue beo : nou&thorn;e In none manere.</L>
<L>For, ho-so deiez, he ne may : neuerefft to liue come,</L>
<L N="100">&YOGH;wane &thorn;e vertue of al is bodi : &thorn;oru de&thorn;e him is bi-nome;</L>
<L>And &thorn;i god al-mi&yogh;ti is ded : &thorn;ou ne mi&yogh;t libbe nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he &thorn;at scholde &yogh;iue &thorn;e lijf : is to de&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>&para; "Nai," seide &thorn;is holi mayde : "&thorn;ou faillest of &thorn;in art,</L>
<L>An-o&thorn;ur &thorn;ou most segge, &yogh;if &thorn;ou &thorn;encst : of &thorn;ine maistrie to habbe part.</L>
<L>God hadde euere and euere he schal : mid him is god-hede,</L>
<L N="106">And for loue of us In ore flesche : he nam him man-hede:</L>
<L>Of twei &thorn;ingus he was &thorn;o imaked : ei&thorn;ur moste &thorn;o is kuynde a-fonge.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e kunde of man-hede us to bugge : he &thorn;olede deth wel stronge;</L>
<L>Ake for-to bi-leue ded, a-&yogh;en kuynde it was : ase of is god-hede,</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore he aros fram de&thorn;e to liue : &thorn;o he hadde i-don al is dede.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e stronge de&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;oru&yogh; Adam : we weren to i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; is godhede, i-meynd In ore kuynde : nede moste beon i-bou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou with-seist &thorn;is reson : an o&thorn;ur i-chulle &thorn;e make</L>
<L N="114">&THORN;at grete clerkes seiden In heore lawe : &thorn;at man ne may nou&yogh;t for-sake.</L>
<L>&para; Platon, &thorn;e grete philosophe : &thorn;at was he&thorn;ene of ouwer lawe,</L>
<L N="116">he seide &thorn;at god wolde deie : and him-selue to liue a&yogh;en drawe.</L>
<L>Lokiez In is boke,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">omit in is boke</NOTE> hov it mi&yogh;te beo soth : nou&thorn;e In ouwere<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. o&thorn;er</NOTE> manere,</L>
<L>bote &thorn;e muchele god of heuene : bi-come a luyte Man here.</L>
<L>Also Balaam, ouwer prophete : &thorn;at he&thorn;ene was al-so,</L>
<L>In is bok he seide&mdash;&yogh;e wuten wel &yogh;ware : &yogh;if &yogh;e wollez loki &thorn;er-to&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;are scholde of Iacobes kuynde : a steorre a-rise wel bri&yogh;t</L>
<L N="122">&THORN;at scholde kinges and princes : al bi-nimen heom heore mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;at ore louerd wolde : of Iacobes kuynde beon i-bore</L>
<L N="124">&amp;<NOTE PLACE="marg1">added.</NOTE> ouer-comen alle &thorn;at euere weren : seth&thorn;e o&thorn;er bi-fore.</L>
<L>And &yogh;uyt &thorn;re kinges of ouwer lawe : on &thorn;ulke steorre &thorn;ou&yogh;ten,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e steorre &thorn;o god was i-bore : and &thorn;are-fore lok him brou&yogh;ten."</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;eos Maistres heorden &thorn;is mayde speke : of so grete clergie,
<PB REF="00000144.tif" N="96"></L>
<L N="128">heo ne cou&thorn;en answerie hire of neuere a word : and &yogh;euen hire &thorn;e maistrie.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o seide &thorn;e Aumperur In grete wrath&thorn;e : "nis non of eov &thorn;at can&mdash;</L>
<L>A-mong so manie grete Maistres&mdash; : answerie a fol womman?"</L>
<L>"Certes, sire," &thorn;is Maistres seiden : "so gret clerk nov nis</L>
<L N="132">&THORN;at scholde to hire reson &yogh;iue answere : for heo seith so<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> so&thorn;</NOTE> i-wis,</L>
<L>We seggeth, &thorn;e holie gost is with hire : and In hire mou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we ne conne hire answerie nou&yogh;t : ne we ne dorren &thorn;ei we cou&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore, bote we betere of oure lawe : &thorn;ane we &yogh;eot i-seon,</L>
<L N="136">Alle we seggez with one mou&thorn;e : cristine we wollez beon."</L>
<L>"Ey, trichours," seide &thorn;e Aumperur : "is it icome &thorn;er-to?<MILESTONE N="57b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Certes, &yogh;e schullen euerech-one : beo to stronge de&thorn;e i-do."</L>
<L>he het &thorn;at Men scholden a-midde toun : fur-berne heom echone.</L>
<L N="140">And huy afenge &thorn;e deth for godes loue : with-oute anie mone,</L>
<L>And muche reu&thorn;e heo maden to katerine : I-baptizede &thorn;at heo nere.</L>
<L>&THORN;at Maide heom confortede wel : and cristine lawes gan heom lere,</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;at heore stronge martyrdom : &thorn;at heo &thorn;oleden &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="144">In stude of cristine-dom scholde beon : &yogh;if heo stude-faste were.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is Maistres weren wel glade &thorn;o : gladliche forth heo eode</L>
<L>And nomen &thorn;ane deth for godes loue : &thorn;at men heom wolde beode;</L>
<L>Heo maden &thorn;e signe of &thorn;e croiz : &thorn;o men in &thorn;at fuyre hem caste.</L>
<L N="148">And &thorn;o heo hadden longe i-barnd : and dede weren at&thorn;e laste</L>
<L>And &thorn;at fuyr was al a-queynt : al-hole heo leien &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wittore and wel fairore [of]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> heu&yogh; : &thorn;ane heo euere er were;</L>
<L>&THORN;are nas so luyte wem on heom : &thorn;at &thorn;e leste of heore here</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur of heore clo&thorn;us a-peirede weren&mdash; : heo leien with faire chere.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Aumperur let fette a-non : &thorn;at Maide katerine:</L>
<L N="154">"haue reu&thorn;e of &thorn;i-sulf," he seide : "and schild &thorn;e fram pine!</L>
<L>haue reu&thorn;e of &thorn;i noble bodi : &thorn;at is so fair and hende!</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou schalt beon in grete nobleye : &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t wende:</L>
<L>In mi paleis ich schal &thorn;e make : hext after &thorn;e quene;</L>
<L>After &thorn;i fourme ichulle &thorn;e make : An ymage, bri&yogh;t and schene,</L>
<L>Ouer-guld and quoynte i-nov : and sette as a-midde &thorn;e cite,</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;at ech man hire honouri schal : for honour of &thorn;e</L>
<L>Ase men schullen to one god do. : &thorn;ou ne schalt mid al &thorn;i lore</L>
<L>So muche nobleie bi-&thorn;enche &thorn;e : &thorn;at I nelle don &thorn;e more."
<PB REF="00000145.tif" N="97"></L>
<L>&para; "Sire Aumperur," &thorn;is Maide seide : "let &thorn;i fole &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="164">For &thorn;ov nast non more &yogh;wile to spille : &thorn;ane speken embe nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>god almi&yogh;ties spouse ich am : and al &thorn;i blaundisinge</L>
<L>Ne alle &thorn;ine tormenz ne schullen min heorte : enes fram him bringe."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Aumperur hire let strep[e] naked : and to a piler faste hire bounden,</L>
<L N="168">With stronge schourges men beoten hire sore : and maden hire harde wounden.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo ne mi&yogh;ten &thorn;are-with-al : turnen hire &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In depe prisone and swi&thorn;e deorke : sone heo was i-brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;at no man hire mete ne &yogh;af ne drunch : &thorn;ei heo scholde for hungur deie,</L>
<L N="172">For heo scholde to heore lawe hire &thorn;ou&yogh;[t] tuyrne : and beon i-brou&yogh;t out of teie.</L>
<L>In &thorn;at prison &thorn;at Maide lai : twelf dawes and twelf ni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo no&thorn;er .et. ne dronk : ne i-sai&yogh; non eor&thorn;elich li&yogh;t;</L>
<L>A &yogh;wit coluere &thorn;are cam fram heuene : to hire euer-ech dai</L>
<L N="176">And brou&yogh;te hire fram heuene mete : In-to prisone ase heo lai.</L>
<L>A day ase &thorn;e Aumperur was : out of &thorn;e toune i-fare,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Aumperesse &thorn;ou&yogh;te on katerine : and hadde of hire gret care:</L>
<L>Of hire bede wel priueliche : heo a-ros at mid-Ni&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="180">And nam with hire sire porfirie : &thorn;at was hire priue kny&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo to &thorn;e prisone come : heo i-sei&yogh;en &thorn;are gret li&yogh;t;</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="58" UNIT="folio">gret wounder heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te &yogh;war-of were : &thorn;e deorke stude so bri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo i-sei&yogh;en<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> sei&yogh;en heo</NOTE> seinte katerine : was In &thorn;e prisone grounde</L>
<L>And an Aungel of heuene with hire stonde : and smerede hire wounde:</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Aumperesse cride a-non : "Katerine," heo seide, "&thorn;in ore!</L>
<L>Mine ri&yogh;te bi-leue &thorn;ov tech me : I nelle beo fol non more."</L>
<L>&THORN;e kni&yogh;t al-so, sire porfirie : loude cride al-so,</L>
<L N="188">&THORN;at muche folk &thorn;at &thorn;are-a-boute was : sone cam &thorn;er-to;</L>
<L>Sire porfirie ful a-doun to hire fet : and merci he gan crie.</L>
<L>With grete Ioye &thorn;is Maide prechede heom : of god and seinte marie;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at Aumperesse and porfirie : &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;is Maide &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="192">And twei hondred of o&thorn;ur folk : I-baptizede weren.</L>
<L>&para; Ore louerd him-sulf cam seth&thorn;e a-doun : to seinte katerine :</L>
<L>"Lo," he seide, "here ich am : for &yogh;wam &thorn;ou hast &thorn;is pine.</L>
<L>In &thorn;ine tormenz beo studefast : Ichulle beo mid &thorn;e;
<PB REF="00000146.tif" N="98"></L>
<L N="196">&THORN;i sege is in heue[ne] i-maud : &thorn;are &thorn;ov schalt wonien mid me."</L>
<L>An o&thorn;ur dai &thorn;e Aumperour : after &thorn;is Maide sende;</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo were ded, o&thorn;ur al fur-fare : swi&thorn;e wel he wende.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Maide was bi-fore him y-brou&yogh;t : swi&thorn;e fat and round.</L>
<L N="200">"&YOGH;wat," he seide, "hou geth &thorn;is? : heo is hol and sound?</L>
<L>&YOGH;ware beoth &thorn;is traitores," he seide : "&thorn;at hire In prisone wuste?</L>
<L>Stilleliche heo hire habbeth i-fed : &thorn;at no man it nuste.</L>
<L>bi &thorn;e treu&thorn;e &thorn;at i schal to Mahon : heo ne schullen so non-more!"</L>
<L N="204">he let nime alle &thorn;e gayholers : and tormenti heom ful sore.</L>
<L>&para; "Sire Aumperur," &thorn;is Maide seide : "is &thorn;is a guod Ivggement,</L>
<L>gulte-lese Men for mine gulte : to bringe in swuche torment?</L>
<L>he &thorn;at hath me i-fed : him ne drat of &thorn;e ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="208">For an Aungel it was of heuene : &thorn;at mete me hath i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Do me &yogh;wat torment &thorn;at &thorn;ov wolt : and lat heom quite gon:</L>
<L>For-so&thorn;e, &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> of &thorn;at</NOTE> &thorn;ou on heom seist : gult heo ne habbez non."</L>
<L>"Ey., hendie Maide Katerine" : seide &thorn;is Aumperour,</L>
<L N="212">"&THORN;ench op-on &thorn;i noble stat : of alle Maidenes &thorn;ov art flour;</L>
<L>Torne &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t and &thorn;ou schalt beon : &thorn;e Aumperesse per;</L>
<L>heo ne schal no-&thorn;ing bi-fore &thorn;e habbe : bote &thorn;at heo me mot beo ner."</L>
<L>"guode man," seide &thorn;is holie mayde : "&thorn;ov spext embe nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="216">For al &thorn;i pouwer &thorn;ou ne schalt : fram ihesu crist wende mi &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at torment &thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t &thorn;enche : And of alle [day longe,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">d. l. wr. by a later hand on an erasure.</NOTE>]</L>
<L>&THORN;ov mi&yogh;t don me &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt : redi ich am to fonge;</L>
<L>For ich ne wilni no-&thorn;ing so muche : ase mi flechs and mi blod, i-wis,</L>
<L N="220">to &yogh;iue for mi louerdes loue : &thorn;at for me he &yogh;af his."</L>
<L>&THORN;o was &thorn;e Aumperur so wroth : &thorn;at he was nei&yogh; i-swowe.</L>
<L>Four &yogh;weles of Iren he let fullen : with rasores, kene I-nowe,</L>
<L>And with ginne heom makede tuyrne a-boute : &thorn;e tweien on &thorn;at on half opward,</L>
<L N="224">&THORN;e o&thorn;ur tweine euene heom a-&yogh;ein : In &thorn;at o&thorn;ur half a-done-ward,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, ho-so bi-twene were : In none half ne mi&yogh;te him wende</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e rasores nolden al is flechs : to-drawen and to-rende.</L>
<L>Sone so &thorn;is Maide was i-don &thorn;ar-on : hire bodi for-to schende,<MILESTONE N="58b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="228">Ore swete louerd fram heuene : an Aungel to hire gan sende:</L>
<L>&THORN;is Aungel with a drawe swerd : &thorn;e &yogh;weoles al-to-hev,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e peces a-boute flowen : ase corn &yogh;wane man it sev,
<PB REF="00000147.tif" N="99"></L>
<L>And smot<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> smite</NOTE> of &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere men : wel harde to &thorn;e grounde;</L>
<L N="232">Four &thorn;ousend &thorn;[er]e weren a-slawe : In a lutel stounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;o nuste &thorn;e Aumperur &yogh;wat he mi&yogh;te don : for deol ne for sore.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Aumperesse nolde hele hire stat : lengore &thorn;o nam-more:</L>
<L>&para; "Sire," heo seide, "hou gez &thorn;is? : for godes loue, &thorn;in ore!</L>
<L N="236">Ich i-seo &thorn;at &thorn;is mayde is guod : and of holi lore,</L>
<L>Ower Maumates ichulle for-sake : Inelle on hem bi-leue more."</L>
<L>&THORN;o gan &thorn;e Aumperur for wrath&thorn;e : loude &yogh;eolle and rore.</L>
<L>he ne mi&yogh;te fram Ihesu crist : hire &thorn;ou&yogh;t no-&thorn;ing wende:</L>
<L N="240">he het men &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. &thorn;at men</NOTE> scholden hire lede : to &thorn;e tounes ende</L>
<L>And hire bresten fram hire bodi : with Irene crokes rende</L>
<L>And &thorn;are-after smiten of hire heued : &thorn;e more forto<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. hire to</NOTE> schende.</L>
<L>Wit guode heorte &thorn;e Aumperesse : &thorn;ane deth gan a-fonge;</L>
<L N="244">&THORN;e quellares heo bad hi&yogh;en faste : and ne a-biden nou&yogh;t to longe.</L>
<L>Heo nomen &thorn;e kene crokes of Ire : &thorn;at hire flechs depe gnowe,</L>
<L>And, also man draweth with combes wolle : hire tetes heo to-drowe</L>
<L>Fram hire bodi mossel mele : and seth&thorn;e smiten of hire heued.</L>
<L N="248">&THORN;at bodi, for houndes it scholden ete : vn-bured it was bi-leued.</L>
<L>Ake porfirie it burede a-ni&yogh;t : &thorn;at holi bodi and guod.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e Aumperur &thorn;at bodi miste : he was wroth and wod;</L>
<L>he tormentede &thorn;are-fore manie Men : &thorn;at ne mi&yogh;ten heom nou&yogh;t skere.</L>
<L N="252">&THORN;o eode porfirie forth : and seide, "sire, lo me here,</L>
<L>Ich burede &thorn;at holie bodi : &thorn;at was cristus make;</L>
<L>And to Ihesu crist ich habbe al-so : al min heorte i-take;</L>
<L>For no pouwer &thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t don : I-nelle him for-sake."</L>
<L N="256">&THORN;o gan &thorn;e Aumperur for deol and sor : alle is lymes to schake.</L>
<L>&para; "Mahun," he seide, "hou schal &thorn;is beo? : &yogh;wat schal ich nou do,</L>
<L>Nov Ich habbe mi wif for-lore : and mi kni&yogh;t porfirie al-so?</L>
<L>And porfirie al min heorte was! : &yogh;wy nelt&thorn;ou me rede?"</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;o wenden &thorn;is o&thorn;ure kny&yogh;tes forth : and loude heo gonne grede,</L>
<L>"We nellez &thorn;ane deth for godes loue : no leng bi-leue for drede."</L>
<L>&THORN;o gan &thorn;e Aumperur to-drawe is her : and sore siche and grone,</L>
<L>"Mahun," he seide, "&yogh;wat schal ich do? : hov schal ich bi-leue allone?</L>
<L N="264">&YOGH;wi nelt&thorn;ou ra&thorn;er fette me : and bringe me of &thorn;usse liue,</L>
<L>&THORN;ane soffri alle mine men to leose : after mine leoue wiue?</L>
<L>&THORN;ei &thorn;ou nelle, mahun, helpe me : I-ne for-sake &thorn;e nou&yogh;t,
<PB REF="00000148.tif" N="100"></L>
<L>&THORN;is foles &thorn;at habbez &thorn;e for-sake : to de&thorn;e heo schulle beo brou&yogh;t."</L>
<L N="268">He let nime porfire &thorn;ene guode kny&yogh;t : and is felawes echone</L>
<L>And smiten of heore heuedes with-oute toun : ase Mahones fon.</L>
<L>&THORN;o let he fette katerine : "Dameysele," he seide,</L>
<L N="271">&THORN;ei &thorn;ov me bi-nome mi wijf : mid &thorn;ine fole rede,</L>
<L>I-chulle, &yogh;if &thorn;ou wul torni &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t : fur-&yogh;iue &thorn;ine misdede<MILESTONE N="59" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And with gret nobleie ase min Aumperesse : ouer-al with me &thorn;e lede."</L>
<L>&para; "Certes, sire," &thorn;is Maide seide : "&thorn;is wordes beoth alle for nau&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;ov ne schalt me neuere bringue fram him : &thorn;at hath min heorte i-cau&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="276">Do &thorn;at &thorn;ov wolt, and haue i-don : and bring &thorn;i wille to ende,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou ne schalt neuere for no-&thorn;ing : min herte fram Ihesu wende."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;ware beo &yogh;e, mine quellares?" : &thorn;e Aumperur &thorn;o seide,</L>
<L>"Faste &yogh;e schulle &thorn;e wychche binde : and with-oute toune lede,</L>
<L N="280">And smitez<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. smite</NOTE> of hire heued a-non : an don &thorn;e guode dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo ne bringe us neuereft : In soruwe ne In drede."</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is Maide was i-brou&yogh;t : to slene with-oute &thorn;e toun,</L>
<L>hire preiere heo maude to god : a-knes heo sat a-doun:</L>
<L>"Louerd," heo seide, "graunte &thorn;ou me : &thorn;at ech man &thorn;at hath in<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. in</NOTE> mone</L>
<L>In ani neode o&thorn;ur in ani anuy : of mine passione,</L>
<L N="286">graunte &thorn;at he mote to is wille : help a-fonge sone."</L>
<L>&THORN;o cam ore louerd him-self to hire : and grauntede hire bone.</L>
<L>&para; "Cum forth," he seide, "mi suete leman : mi leue spouse al-so:</L>
<L>heuene-&yogh;at a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e I-opened is : &thorn;are &thorn;ou schalt comen to."</L>
<L>A quellare hire heued of smot. : &thorn;at folk &thorn;at a-boute heom stode,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wijt Milk heo i-sei&yogh;en eorne out of &thorn;e wounde : and nou&yogh;t o drope of blode.</L>
<L N="292">Aungles comen and nomen &thorn;at bodi : a-mong alle &thorn;e manne</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e hul of synay it beren : tuenti Iorneies &thorn;anne,</L>
<L>And bureden it &thorn;are In one faire place : wit grete nobleye and riche;</L>
<L>&THORN;are &thorn;oru&yogh; Ihesu cristes grace : hire bones restez &yogh;uyte.</L>
<L N="296">&THORN;are-of &yogh;eot to &thorn;is day : &thorn;are eornez eoille wel riue,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ware-with manie sike Men : beoz to hele i-brou&yogh;t and to liue;</L>
<L>Wide In londe it is i-lad : &thorn;at ho-so it habbe mote,</L>
<L>Noble relike it is al-so : sike Men to don bote.</L>
<L N="300">&THORN;re hundred &yogh;er and twenti : after &thorn;at god was i-bore,</L>
<L>I-Martred was &thorn;is holie Maide : of &yogh;wam we tolden bi-fore.
<PB REF="00000149.tif" N="101"></L>
<L>Ihesu crist, for &thorn;e suete loue : of seinte Katerine</L>
<L>graunti us &thorn;e Ioye of heuene : and schilde us fram helle pine.</L>
<L N="304">Amen amen, segge we alle : for is holie tyme.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="26" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>26 Vita sancte Lucie uirginis.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEinte lucie, &thorn;at holie Mayde : In Cezile was i-bore;</L>
<L>&YOGH;ong heo bi-gan to serui god : and bi-lefde sunne and hore;</L>
<L>Dame Evtice hire Moder het : &thorn;at hire to wommane brou&yogh;te&mdash;</L>
<L N="4">Of hire childe wel glad heo was : ase heo suy&thorn;e wel ou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>So bi-feol &thorn;at on Dame Eutice cam a siknesse : swi&thorn;e greuous and long&mdash;</L>
<L>Four &yogh;er he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">= heo</NOTE> hadde gret pine&mdash; : &thorn;e menison of blode wel strong.</L>
<L>On leches heo hadde i-spendet<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. i spendedet</NOTE> : Muche del of hire guod,</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;are nas non &thorn;at hire hele mi&yogh;te : &thorn;at heo ne bledde euere blod.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at wide In &thorn;e londe Men tolden : of seinte Agace,</L>
<L N="10">Of Miracles &thorn;at comen at hire schrine : &thorn;oru ore louerdes grace</L>
<L>In &thorn;e cite of Cathenes : &thorn;ere &thorn;is holi womman lay;</L>
<L N="12">Folk wende &thorn;udere wel wide : bo&thorn;e Ni&yogh;t and day</L>
<L>bi manie scor to-gadere : of eche londe a-boute.<MILESTONE N="59b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;o seinte lucie &thorn;is i-sai&yogh; : al dai so gret route,</L>
<L>"Moder," heo seide, "&thorn;ou hauest an vuel : ful greuous with-alle</L>
<L N="16">And we hereth of miracles al day : &thorn;at of seinte Agace doth falle:</L>
<L>go we &thorn;udere forth mid o&thorn;ure : to &thorn;e holie seint Agace,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are &thorn;ou schalt to hele come : &thorn;oru&yogh; ore louerdes grace."</L>
<L>&para; Nov was lucie stilleliche : I-torned to cristine-dom,</L>
<L N="20">Ake hire Moder he&thorn;ene was : and al &thorn;at heo of com;</L>
<L>Lucie to ane he&thorn;ene manne : was i-weddet In hire &yogh;ong-hede,</L>
<L>Ake Na&thorn;eles clene Mayde heo was : with-oute eche fol dede.</L>
<L>Hire Moder heo nam stilleliche : and with o&thorn;ere Men heo wende</L>
<L N="24">To seinte Agace Toumbe : hire Moder for-to amende.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">vv. 25-6 are tr. in the other MS.</NOTE>And i-heorde &thorn;e Masse a dai : mid o&thorn;ure &thorn;at &thorn;ere were,</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo weren &thorn;udere i-come&mdash; : so longue<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> a stounde</NOTE> heo lefden &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e godspel was &thorn;at day : ase lucie onder-stod,</L>
<L N="28">Of a womman &thorn;at &yogh;wylene hadde : &thorn;e menison of blod</L>
<L>And cam ant touchede &thorn;e lappe : of ore louerdes clo&thorn;es ene</L>
<L>Ase he eode In grete prece : and was hol a-non and clene.
<PB REF="00000150.tif" N="102"></L>
<L>"Leoue Moder," seide lucie : "&yogh;if &thorn;ov bi-leuest on holi churche</L>
<L N="32">And &thorn;e wordes of &thorn;is godspel : and &thorn;er-after wolt wurche,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; touchingue of seinte Agace toumbe : &thorn;ou&yogh; schalt beo hol a-non,</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;eo womman &yogh;wylene was : &thorn;at aftur ore louerd gan gon."</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at folk was al i-went : seinte lucie cam</L>
<L N="36">To seinte Agace holie toumbe : and ire Moder with hire nam;</L>
<L>&THORN;are heo leien In heore beden : heo nolden &thorn;annes gon.</L>
<L>&para; So &thorn;at lucie, &thorn;at clene Maide : werth a-slepe a-non.</L>
<L N="39">Seinte Agace, &thorn;at holie Maide : to hire fram heuene a-li&yogh;te,</L>
<L>With gret felau&yogh;-schipe of Aungles&mdash; : hire croune schon wel bri&yogh;te;</L>
<L>"Lucie," heo seide, "leoue soster : &yogh;wy trauaillest&thorn;ou so</L>
<L>And &yogh;wy biddest&thorn;ou me so &yogh;eorne &thorn;at &thorn;ing : &thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t &thorn;i-self do</L>
<L>For &thorn;ine bi-leue, &thorn;at is so guod : helpez &thorn;i Moder, i-wis:</L>
<L N="44">And nov &thorn;oru &thorn;e and &thorn;ine guod-nesse : &thorn;i Moder i-held is.</L>
<L>And also ase &thorn;is cite is : i-wuyr&thorn;et muche &thorn;oru&yogh; me,</L>
<L>Also schal &thorn;i contreie : Anoured beon for &thorn;e;</L>
<L>For &thorn;i clene Maiden-hod : and for &thorn;i holie lif, i-wis,</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;i woneingue is wel &yogh;are i-maket : with us in heuene-blis."</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is holie Maide a-wok : heo bi-gan to quakien sore;</L>
<L>&para; "Moder," heo seide, "&thorn;ov art hol : ne &thorn;arf&thorn;e drede non-more.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e loue of &thorn;at holie Maide : &thorn;at &thorn;e hath to hele i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="52">Ne fonde &thorn;ov neuere to bringue me : of mi clene &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And ne soffre &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t mine spouse in folie : mi Maiden-hod a-spille,</L>
<L>Ne lat me nou&yogh;t leose &thorn;at longue lif : for a luytel fol wille!</L>
<L>Ake al &thorn;at &thorn;ou i-grauntet hast : for-to &yogh;iue him with me,</L>
<L N="56">Lat me it &yogh;iue &thorn;e pouere men : Moder, ich bidde &thorn;e."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Moder, &thorn;o heo hol was : guod womman bi-cam,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e dou&yogh;ter bi hire Moder wille : &thorn;at guod to hire heo nam;<MILESTONE N="60" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>heo hit delte a-mong pouere Men : &thorn;e &yogh;wyle &thorn;are i-laste ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="60">to him &thorn;at hire spouse was : &thorn;e teo&thorn;ingue was i-brou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>he wende to seinte lucies norice : and axede hire wel stille</L>
<L>&YOGH;wat lucie were on bi-come : heore guod for-to a-spille,</L>
<L>&para; And &yogh;wi heo dude it so a-wei : and &yogh;wodere heo dude it bere.</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;is norice wel quoyntelich : &yogh;af him a-non answere:</L>
<L>"heo hath ifounde forto sulle : swy&thorn;e derewur&thorn;e &thorn;ing, i-wis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is suych a &thorn;ousent more wurth : &thorn;anne al &thorn;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at is;
<PB REF="00000151.tif" N="103"></L>
<L>&THORN;e beste chaffare it is i-bou&yogh;t : &thorn;at euere Man to drou&yogh;;</L>
<L N="68">Woldest&thorn;ou gon &thorn;are-Inne In part : riche man &thorn;ou were i-nou&yogh;"&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at was &thorn;e chaffare &thorn;e blisse of heuene : &thorn;at heo hadde i-bou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>gret wonder he hadde of &thorn;ulke Answere : and stod in gret &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he onder-&yogh;at sone : &thorn;at heo cristine was.</L>
<L>In grete wrath&thorn;e he tolde fore : &thorn;e Iustice, &thorn;at het pakas.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;akas</NOTE></L>
<L N="73">Lucie was sone i-fet : and bi-fore &thorn;e Iustice i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>"Maide," seide &thorn;e Iustice : "&yogh;wat hast &thorn;ou i-&thorn;ou&yogh;t?</L>
<L>&para; Let &thorn;i folie," he seide : "Ich rede, on alle wiffe,</L>
<L N="76">And to ore godes, ase ri&yogh;t is : do &thorn;ine sacrefise!"</L>
<L>"Ich habbe," quat<SUP>h</SUP> &thorn;is holie Maide : "al &thorn;is &thorn;re &yogh;er i-do</L>
<L>Mine sacrefise to Iesu crist : and &yogh;uyt i-chulle al-so:</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at ich hadde ich habbe ispended : and bi-take In is lore;</L>
<L N="80">And &thorn;er-to ichulle mi bodi take : &yogh;wane me nis bi-leued nomore.</L>
<L>Spene<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>corr. to</I> spend <I>by a later hand.</I></NOTE> i-chulle nou al mi bodi : fram &thorn;e fot to &thorn;e heued</L>
<L>And euerech lime In is seruise : nov me nis more bi-leued;</L>
<L>Ich &yogh;elde him op al mi bodi : sire Iustise, here bi-fore &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="84">to spene<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>corr. to</I> spend <I>by a later hand.</I></NOTE> ech lime In is seruise&mdash; : do &yogh;wat &thorn;ou wolt bi me!"</L>
<L>&para; "Nov ich wot," quath &thorn;e Iustise : "&yogh;ware-to &thorn;ou tornest &thorn;i mod:</L>
<L>For In hore-dom and In lecherie : &thorn;ou hast i-spend al &thorn;i guod,</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-on &thorn;ou wolt &thorn;i bodi al spene<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>corr. to</I> spend <I>by a later hand.</I></NOTE> : and &thorn;ar-of &thorn;ou dest preche;</L>
<L N="88">&YOGH;wane &thorn;ov nast non more to spene<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>corr. to</I> spend <I>by a later hand.</I></NOTE> : for-so&thorn;e &thorn;ou worst a wrechche:</L>
<L>For &thorn;ov spext ase an hore strong : &yogh;wane &thorn;ou wolt for-sake</L>
<L>&THORN;i louerd &thorn;at &thorn;ou art to i-weddet<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>corr. to</I> i-wedded.</NOTE> : and to lechours &thorn;e take."</L>
<L>"I-wedded ich was to Ihesu crist" : &thorn;is holie maide him tolde</L>
<L N="92">"&THORN;o ich was i-baptized : and &thorn;ulke weddingue ichulle holde.</L>
<L>Ake to hore-dome &thorn;ov woldest me bringue : &yogh;wane &thorn;ov me woldest make</L>
<L>Mine spousede louerd Ihesu crist : for ani o&thorn;ur man for-sake."</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou schalt for-sake him," quath &thorn;e Iustise : "haddest&thorn;ou it i-swore:</L>
<L N="96">For to &thorn;e commune bordel &thorn;ov schalt beo : i-lad o&thorn;ur i-bore,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">The following part of this legend is written as prose, in two columns on each page on f. 60b.</NOTE>And &thorn;are schal mani a moder-child : go to &thorn;i foule licame</L>
<L>And ligge bi &thorn;e, alle &thorn;at wollez : in hore-dom and in schame."
<PB REF="00000152.tif" N="104"></L>
<L>&para; "Ne mai no wumman," quath &thorn;is maide : "of hire maiden-hod beo ido</L>
<L N="100">For no dede &thorn;at men deth &thorn;e bodie : bote ire herte beo<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>a later hand adds</I> consente.</NOTE> &thorn;erto.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e more &thorn;at mi bodi a-&yogh;ein mi wille : here defouled is,</L>
<L>&THORN;e clenore<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. clenore</NOTE> is mi mayden-hod : and &thorn;e more mi mede, i-wis."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Iustise let wide a-boute : into al &thorn;e contreie crie :</L>
<L N="104">&THORN;at alle &thorn;at wolden : bi a swuch fair wumman don anie folie,</L>
<L>Comen to hire, alle &thorn;at wolden : for alle heo scholde heom take,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>a later hand adds</I> consente.</NOTE></L>
<L>For in bordel heo scholde beo i-do : &thorn;are heo ne scholde non fur-sake.<MILESTONE N="60b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he hiet is men nimen hire faste : and to &thorn;e bordel hire lede anon</L>
<L N="108">Alle &thorn;at mi&yogh;hten nei&yogh;h hire come : faste huy hire drowen ech-on,</L>
<L>huy schoue and drowe al &thorn;at huy mi&yogh;hte : ake huy ne mi&yogh;hten hire anne fote i-winne</L>
<L>Ne o fote uchchen of &thorn;e stude : &thorn;are as heo stod inne.</L>
<L>&THORN;o nomen huy ropes strongue i-nou&yogh; : ant to fet and hondene teide,</L>
<L N="112">And alle &thorn;at mi&yogh;hten &thorn;ere nei&yogh;h come : faste huy drowen and breide;</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousend men with al heore main : on hire gonne drawe :</L>
<L>Ac euere heo lai stille a-&yogh;ein : huy ne mi&yogh;hten hire enes wawe.</L>
<L>&para; "&YOGH;wat, hou goth &thorn;is?" quath &thorn;e iustise : "&yogh;wat resun mai &thorn;is beo</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;at a &thorn;ousend ne mouwen nou&yogh;t &thorn;is womman : of &thorn;e stude enes teo?"</L>
<L>&para; "Sire iustise," &thorn;at Maide seide : "&thorn;ou hontest a-boute nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>For, &thorn;ei &thorn;ou haddest &yogh;eot to heom : ten &thorn;ousend mo i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&YOGH;uit it scholde bi-foren eov alle : bi folfuld bi me her</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;at holie vers &thorn;at seint Dauid : seith&thorn; in &thorn;e sauter:<NOTE PLACE="marg2">[Ps. 90]</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at a &thorn;ousend men scholden in mi side falle : and to grounde beon i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And ten &thorn;ousend in mi ri&yogh;ht side : and nei&yogh;h me ne comen nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore it is al for nou&yogh;t : &thorn;at &thorn;ou hontest here-a-boute;</L>
<L N="124">God is strengore &thorn;ane &thorn;ou be : and &thorn;are-fore i-nabbe no doute."</L>
<L>&para; "&THORN;ou art strong wichche," quath &thorn;e iustise : "and &thorn;ar-of Man schal &thorn;e bringue,</L>
<L>Mine clerkes and mine enchauntours : bi-nime schullen &thorn;i wich|chingue."
<PB REF="00000153.tif" N="105"></L>
<L>His clerkes he let bringue forth : and his enchauntours echone:</L>
<L N="128">And huy maden heore coniurisones : a-boute &thorn;is Maide alone.</L>
<L>And &thorn;o huy hadden al ido &thorn;at huy cou&thorn;en : &thorn;at folk gan eft-sones drawe:</L>
<L>Ake euere heo lai i-liche stille : huy ne mi&yogh;hten hire enes wawe.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Iustise, &thorn;o he &thorn;is i-sei&yogh; : for wrath&thorn;e he was nei&yogh;h wod.</L>
<L>"Certes," he seide, "hire wichchingue : ne schal do hire no guod."</L>
<L>Strongue temene he liet fette : of Oxene mani on</L>
<L N="134">And bringue &thorn;ere &thorn;is Maide was : and to hire tei&yogh;en ech-on;</L>
<L>He liet heom prikie and harli faste : and huy guonne drawe and pluchche:</L>
<L N="136">And euere lai &thorn;is Maide stille : huy ne mi&yogh;hten hire enes wawe.</L>
<L>&para; "Certes," he seide, "ore fare nis nou&yogh;t : o&thorn;ur-&yogh;wat we moten do,</L>
<L>With o&thorn;er &thorn;ing we schullen hire to nau&yogh;te bringue : &yogh;wane we ne mouwen so.</L>
<L>Makieth ope &thorn;e hore, &thorn;are heo lijth&thorn; : &yogh;wane we ne mouwen hire winne heonne,</L>
<L N="140">Also strong fuyr ase &yogh;e conne : &thorn;at heo al-to douste brenne!"</L>
<L>A strong fuir and gret i-nou&yogh; : &thorn;is tormentores wrou&yogh;te</L>
<L>Aboute &thorn;is holie clene maide : to brenne hire al-to nou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is fuyr was wel strongue i-maud : heo sat a-midde ful stille;</L>
<L N="144">&THORN;at fuyr ne mi&yogh;hte don hire non harm : &thorn;at were wurth a fille.</L>
<L>&THORN;o nomen huy pich and brumston : and welden it wel faste</L>
<L>And ope hire nakede tendre bodi : al-fuyri it casten.</L>
<L>&para; Euere sat &thorn;is Maide stille : it ne greuede hire no-&thorn;ing,</L>
<L N="148">Ake euere heo prechede with glade heorte : of Ihesu, heuene king.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o nuste &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere iustise : &yogh;wat he mi&yogh;hte don more.</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane he ne mi&yogh;hte &thorn;is clene &thorn;ing : ouer-come mid al is lore,</L>
<L>A scharp swerd and a kene : &thorn;oru&yogh; hire &thorn;rote he liet do,</L>
<L N="152">To bi-nimen hire speche : and hire lijf also.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo was &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e &thorn;rote i-smite : &thorn;e betere heo spac i-nou&yogh;,</L>
<L>And prechede euere of Ihesu crist : and wel smere lou&yogh;:</L>
<L>&para; "&YOGH;e &thorn;at beoth cristine : glade and bli&thorn;e &yogh;e beo,</L>
<L N="156">Of no-&thorn;ing ne habbe &yogh;e drede : for gret ioy ich i-seo!</L>
<L>Ane Ioyeful &thorn;y&thorn;ingue ich eou telle : &thorn;at soth&thorn; is and nou&yogh;t les:</L>
<L>&THORN;at ri&yogh;ht nou&thorn;e is holi churche : i-brou&yogh;t in guod pes:
<PB REF="00000154.tif" N="106"></L>
<L>For hire tweie wi&thorn;erwines : &thorn;at habbez i-beo so &yogh;are,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;ht nou&thorn;e beoth to nau&yogh;t i-brou&yogh;t : &yogh;e &thorn;orue habbe of heom no kare.</L>
<L N="161">For &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere dioclician : &thorn;at so muche harm hath i-do,</L>
<L>he is i-pult out of his kynedom : he ne cometh non-more &thorn;ar-to;</L>
<L>And also Maximian : &thorn;at so lu&thorn;ur hath i-beo,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;th nou&thorn;e he deide in lu&thorn;ur deth : &yogh;e schulle him non-more i-seo;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere wi&thorn;er-wines : &thorn;at a-&yogh;ein holie churche were,</L>
<L N="166">Out of heore mi&yogh;hte beoth i-brou&yogh;t : ne habbe &yogh;e none fere.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;us glade ty&thorn;ingue ich eov bringue : &thorn;ei huy feor heonne beo&mdash;</L>
<L N="168">I-hered beo god, &thorn;at ich moste : &thorn;is dai a-liue i-seo!</L>
<L>I-chulle bi-teche ou ihesu crist : for fram eov ich mot wende.</L>
<L>Bringuth me ore louerdes flechs and is blod : for &thorn;at schal beo mi<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>corr. to</I> my</NOTE> ende."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e preostes wenden forth anon : and folk &thorn;at &thorn;ere stod,</L>
<L N="172">And fetten to &thorn;is holie maide : godes fl[e]chs and is blod.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo it hadde under-fongue : and hire ri&yogh;htes al-so,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e oresones weren alle i-seid : &thorn;at bi-fullen &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>Mid &thorn;e laste [word]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> heo &yogh;af &thorn;ene gost : ase huy amen seide.</L>
<L N="176">Aungles &thorn;are weren redie I-nowe : hire soule to heuene lede.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere heo is with ihesu crist : in Ioye with-outen ende.</L>
<L>Nou god for seinte lucie loue : &thorn;udere us late i-wiende! Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="27" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>27 &para; Ici poez oyer coment seint Thomas de Kaunterbures nasqui. e de quev manere gent de pere e de Mere.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WOlle &yogh;e nou&thorn;e i-heore &thorn;is englische tale : &thorn;at is here i-write<MILESTONE N="61" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of seint Thomas of Caunterburi : al-hou he was bi-&yogh;ite?</L>
<L>Of londone is fader was : A bordeys<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. borgeys</NOTE> hende and fre,</L>
<L N="4">Gilbert Bekat was is name : &thorn;e bok tellez me.</L>
<L>Ake is Moder was of he&thorn;enesse. : nov sone &yogh;e mouwen i-heore</L>
<L>Al-hou heo cam into engelonde : are heo i-cristned were.</L>
<L>Gilebert him bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te : &thorn;e Croiz for-to fo</L>
<L N="8">In-to &thorn;e holie lond : his penaunce &thorn;e bet to do.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at, &thorn;o he &thorn;udere cam : he was sone i-nome,</L>
<L>Ase A sclaue forth i-lad : and i-don In prisone,</L>
<L>And faste was i-gwiued : he and manie mo,</L>
<L N="12">And i-wust wel sikerliche : &thorn;at he ne scholde a-wei go.
<PB REF="00000155.tif" N="107"></L>
<L>In &thorn;e Amirales prisone<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. prisones</NOTE> : heo hadden i-beo so longue,</L>
<L>To &yogh;eres and an half : In bendes swi&thorn;e strongue,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at god &yogh;af &thorn;e Amiral : bo&thorn;e heorte and wille</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;e more to louien Gilebert : for he was meoke and stille.</L>
<L>Eche daie &yogh;wane &thorn;e Amiral : to is mete wolde go,</L>
<L>he bad, Gilebert to is mete : scholde come also&mdash;</L>
<L>gret auantage, for-so&thorn;e, it was : &thorn;at he mi&yogh;te so gon;</L>
<L N="20">Ake euere he hadde ane peire feteres : faste him up-on.</L>
<L>And ofte-si&thorn;es &thorn;e Amiral : dude for Gilebardes loue</L>
<L>Auantage to is felawes : &thorn;at with him weren In prisone.</L>
<L>hit bi-feol &thorn;at Amiral : Ane faire dou&yogh;ter hadde&mdash;</L>
<L N="24">Childrene of is owene : none mo for-so&thorn;e he nadde.</L>
<L>priueliche heo dude for Gilebert : Auantages manie and fele.</L>
<L>And ofte-si&thorn;e heo wolde speke with him : &yogh;wane heo mi&yogh;te to bi|stele&mdash;</L>
<L>For heo ne dorste bi-fore hire fader : laste he it onder-&yogh;ete</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;at it were for gyle : &thorn;at heo with him speke.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eot it bi-feol In a dai : &thorn;at heo sai&yogh; &thorn;o heo mi&yogh;te:</L>
<L>to Gillebert heo eode priueliche : and echste him &yogh;wat he hi&yogh;te</L>
<L>And of &yogh;wat bi-leue he were : and of &yogh;wyche londe,</L>
<L N="32">And &yogh;if he wolde for is louerdes loue : &thorn;ene deth a-fonge.</L>
<L>Gilbert hire Ansuerede &thorn;o : In swi&thorn;e fair manere:</L>
<L>"Of engelonde ich am, and cristine Man : &thorn;ei ich beo nou&thorn;e here;</L>
<L>Mi name is Gilbert beket : of Londene &thorn;e cite;</L>
<L N="36">gladliche icholde &thorn;ane deth a-fongue : for is loue &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;ad.</NOTE> bou&yogh;te me,</L>
<L>And for-to saui mi cristine-dom : and mine trewe bi-leue al-so."</L>
<L>&THORN;is womman to Gilbert wel sone : &thorn;eos wordes heo seide to:</L>
<L>"Cristine-dom ichulle onder-fonge : for &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="40">And &thorn;ou a-non aftur-ward : treweliche weddi me."</L>
<L>Gilbert was ful sore a-drad : of &thorn;is wommane sawe,</L>
<L>Laste heo wolde bi-Meldi him : &yogh;ware-&thorn;oru&yogh; he were a-slawe.</L>
<L>To &yogh;eres and an half he was sclaue : and &thorn;at him &thorn;ou&yogh;te longe:</L>
<L N="44">So &thorn;at he and is felawes : gonne heom onder-stonde</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo wolden &thorn;et prison breke : and A-weiward gon;</L>
<L>Sore heo weren alle a-ferd : for traison of &thorn;at womman.<MILESTONE N="61b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at prison heo breken : ri&yogh;t &thorn;ulke daie at eue;
<PB REF="00000156.tif" N="108"></L>
<L N="48">Forth heo wenden alle a-wei : &thorn;are nolde non bi-leue.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e morewe-tide heo weren i-sou&yogh;t : bote &thorn;er nas non i-founde.</L>
<L>Ak &thorn;o bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at Maiden hire : In wel luyte stounde</L>
<L>hov heo mi&yogh;te best on take : and &yogh;wat heo mi&yogh;te do;</L>
<L N="52">So &thorn;at heo porueide hire : and fort a-wei gan go.</L>
<L>Al-bi ny&yogh;te heo wende a-wei : men nusten &yogh;ware heo bi-cam.</L>
<L>Ne heo ne cou&thorn;e nanne wei : bote god was hire lodes-man.</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; godes grace heo was i-lad : with men &thorn;at onder-stoden hire langage,</L>
<L N="56">So &thorn;at heo cam to &thorn;e se : and redi fond hire passage.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane wei heo Axede In hire langage : In-to engelonde;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo cam with pilegrimes : ase ich me onder-stonde,</L>
<L>Ouer &thorn;e se sauf and wel : &thorn;oru&yogh; grace &thorn;at heo hadde</L>
<L N="60">Of Iesu crist, and socur of men : &thorn;at hire ouer ladden.</L>
<L>heo ne cou&thorn;e no-&thorn;ing conteini hire : ne speken no-&thorn;e-mo;</L>
<L>Ake euere heo axede In hire langage : to londone for-to go.</L>
<L>Mid pilegrimes and &thorn;oru grace of god : to londone heo cam.</L>
<L N="64">And &thorn;o heo was &thorn;udere i-come : &thorn;are ne knev heo no man,</L>
<L>Ne heo ne cou&thorn;e speke ne hire bi-seo : bote ase a best &thorn;at a-strayed were.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore on hire gapede alday : swy&thorn;e muche fol[c] &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>bo&thorn;e Men and wommen : and children suy&thorn;e fale&mdash;</L>
<L N="68">for hire continaunce was wonderful : and hire speche no Man ne cou&thorn;e &thorn;are.</L>
<L>In Manie stretes heo hadde i-wandret&mdash; : &thorn;at Man may wel i-wite,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at bi-fore gilbertes house : &thorn;e Noyse was onder-&yogh;ite.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e knaue &thorn;at hadde with him : In he&thorn;enesse i-beo,</L>
<L N="72">to &thorn;e dore he orn swy&thorn;e : &thorn;e dune for-to i-seo.</L>
<L>he i-sai&yogh; &thorn;at it was &thorn;e Amirales dou&yogh;ter : &thorn;at al &thorn;e wondringue was on:</L>
<L>hasteliche he tornede In a-&yogh;en : to is louerd a-non,</L>
<L>And seide, &thorn;e Amirales dou&yogh;ter was : In &thorn;e strete &thorn;are-oute,</L>
<L N="76">And suy&thorn;e gret prece of gurles and Men : comen hire al-a-boute;</L>
<L>he seide, "al &thorn;e gredinge is for hire : &thorn;at &yogh;e doth nou&thorn;e i-heore."</L>
<L>"Louerd," seide gilbert, "&yogh;we&thorn;ur heo beo : al-one with-outen fere?"</L>
<L>he het is knaue loki soth&thorn;eliche : &yogh;if &thorn;at heo it were;
<PB REF="00000157.tif" N="109"></L>
<L N="80">And bad hire leden to ane guode wyues house : and a-stunte with hire &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at heo hire scholde finde i-nou&yogh; : of al &thorn;at heo hadde neode,</L>
<L>ri&yogh;t ase heo wolde is owene bodi : and he hire &thorn;ar-of bede.</L>
<L>Al-so tyme ase &thorn;is knaue : to &thorn;is Mayde cam,</L>
<L N="84">For Ioye heo ful a-doun i-swowe : opon &thorn;e harde ston.</L>
<L>&THORN;o hire stat was a-&yogh;ein i-come : &thorn;e knaue hire op nam,</L>
<L>And heo wel gladliche with him eode : to &thorn;ulke guode womman.</L>
<L>An<SUP>d</SUP> heo hire onder-feng swi&thorn;e faire : for gilberdes loue;</L>
<L N="88">heo makede hire wel an-Ayse : and was hire swy&thorn;e wel-come.</L>
<L>Gilbert him bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te : a-non so he hadde i-ete,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e bischop for-to gon : with him forto speke,</L>
<L>&THORN;are he was at seint poules : of him to habbe red a-non<MILESTONE N="62" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="92">Al-&yogh;wat him were of &thorn;at Maide : is beste forto don.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane bischop of londone : for-so&thorn;e he fond &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And fyue o&thorn;ur bischopes : with him &thorn;are were;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he fond &thorn;are six bischopes : &thorn;e beste of Engelonde.</L>
<L N="96">And &thorn;o Gilbert i-sai&yogh; heom alle : bi-fore heom he eode stonde;</L>
<L>he bi-gan to telle is tale : &thorn;oru&yogh; is owene Mouth,</L>
<L>And are he hadde al i-told : heo was swy&thorn;e selcouth.</L>
<L>he tolde hou he In &thorn;e Amirales prisone : in he&thorn;enesse hadde i-be</L>
<L>And hov &thorn;e Amirales dou&yogh;ter to him seide : &thorn;at was so fair and fre,</L>
<L>Al-hov &thorn;at heo wolde cristine bi-come : for enchaison of him</L>
<L N="102">&YOGH;if he wolde weddi hire : and for-saken al hire kun;</L>
<L>And hou he and is felawes : bi-twene hem alle bi-speke</L>
<L N="104">For drede of hire wordes : &thorn;at prison for-to breke,</L>
<L>&YOGH;If &thorn;at heo mi&yogh;ten grace habbe : a-wei for-to gon,</L>
<L>laste heo weren alle for hire : to stronge de&thorn;e i-don;</L>
<L>And al-hou heo was to londone i-come : and fram so fer i-gon,</L>
<L N="108">gret wonder &thorn;ar-of he hadde : for language ne cou&thorn;e heo non.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is bischopes hadden i-heord : &thorn;at gilbert heom hadde i-told,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischop of wynchestre it wel onder-stod : for he was wis and bold:</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit was al &thorn;oru&yogh; godes grace : &thorn;at heo was so fer i-come,</L>
<L N="112">Out of hire owene londe so fer : &thorn;at heo &thorn;oru miseise ne hadde i-be nome;<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. nonome.</NOTE></L>
<L>For heo ne cou&thorn;e language non : with men for-to speke,
<PB REF="00000158.tif" N="110"></L>
<L>With &yogh;wan heo mi&yogh;te i-winnen hire : herboruwe and drinke and mete.</L>
<L>he seide, "with-oute faille : &yogh;if god hath&thorn; i-porueid so</L>
<L N="116">&thorn;at heo for gilberdes loue : cristinedom wole onder-fo,</L>
<L>And gilberd hire wolde weddi : sum blede of hire schal come</L>
<L>&THORN;at schal holie churche holde to ri&yogh;te : and serui godes sone.</L>
<L>For we it mowen wel i-wite : and we wollen us onder-stonde:</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;at heo is in-to &thorn;is londe i-come : it is godes sonde.</L>
<L>for &thorn;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at god helpe wole : ne schal nou&yogh;t beo for-fare."</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;eos o&thorn;ure bischopes : a-cordeden to &thorn;is tale,</L>
<L>And seiden &thorn;at gilberd scholde weddi hire : and holden hire to wiue,</L>
<L N="124">&YOGH;if heo wolde i-cristned be : and tuyrne to clene liue.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at a-non-ri&yogh;t &thorn;ene moruwe : i-porueid it was al-&yogh;are</L>
<L>At seint poules churche, &thorn;at heo scholde : Icristned beo ri&yogh;t &thorn;are.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e baptisterie was al-redi : to hire baptizingue,</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;e bischopes beden &thorn;at Men scholden : &thorn;e womman bi-fore heom bringe.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo cam bi-fore &thorn;e bischopes : heo axeden hire wel sone</L>
<L>&YOGH;if heo wolde i-cristned beo : ase lawe was for-to done.</L>
<L>heo answerede In hire langage : wel sone heom a-&yogh;en:</L>
<L N="132">&YOGH;if gilbert wolde hire weddi : i-cristned heo wolde ben</L>
<L>And bote he hire weddi wolde : heo nolde cristinedom a-fongue,</L>
<L>heo seide heo wolde ra&thorn;er tuyrne a&yogh;en : In-to hire owene londe.</L>
<L>Gilberd cou&thorn;e hire language. : &thorn;are he stod wel stille:</L>
<L N="136">to &thorn;e bischopus he seide : he wolde don heore wille.<MILESTONE N="62b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo i-cristned was : ase god hire &yogh;af &thorn;e grace,</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e six bischopes : and i-spouse in &thorn;e place.</L>
<L>hire he&thorn;ene name ne j nou&yogh;t telle : for-so&thorn;e &yogh;wat heo hiet,</L>
<L N="140">&THORN;e name &thorn;at heo of cristindom hadde : i-wute &yogh;e schullen &yogh;et:</L>
<L>heo was i-nemd Alisaundre : as ich me onder-stonde;</L>
<L>Seint Thomas was on hire bi-&yogh;ite : pris-martyr of engelonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Gilbert<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. Gilberd</NOTE> hire hadde i-weddet : wel glad of him heo was.</L>
<L N="144">&THORN;e furste Nij&yogh;t &thorn;at he knovlei&yogh;te hire : he bi-&yogh;at seint thomas.</L>
<L>Fram &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at he was bi-&yogh;ite : for-to &thorn;at he was i-bore</L>
<L>he ne lai non more bi hire : &thorn;ane he dude bi-fore.</L>
<L>Anon-ri&yogh;tes a-morewe : so gret wille him nam</L>
<L N="148">to &thorn;e holi londe for-to gon : &thorn;at he cam erore fram,
<PB REF="00000159.tif" N="111"></L>
<L>&THORN;at him &thorn;oute dei&yogh;e he scholde : bote he wende a-&yogh;enward sone.</L>
<L>Ake he bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te him of is wiues stat : &yogh;wat were of hire to done,</L>
<L>laste heo wolde mourny swy&thorn;e : &yogh;wane he were a-gon,</L>
<L N="152">And gret deol to hire nime&mdash; : for langage ne cou&thorn;e heo non</L>
<L>&THORN;at ani Man cou&thorn;e onder-stonde : &thorn;at heo speke to,</L>
<L>bote gilbert o&thorn;ur [his] knaue. : &thorn;are-fore him [was] ful wo.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at gilbert was in grete &thorn;ou&yogh;te : and bi-gan to sike sore,</L>
<L N="156">laste is wif gret harm habbe scholde : &yogh;wane he i-wend weore.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore gilbert mournede muche : and si&yogh;te stille and softe,</L>
<L>laste is wif fur-fare scholde : he bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te him ofte.</L>
<L>for &thorn;e mourningue &thorn;at he makede : is wif it onder-stod,</L>
<L N="160">And for he si&yogh;te i-lomeliche : &thorn;at i-chaunged was is mod.</L>
<L>his wif him axede swi&thorn;e &yogh;eorne : and a-raysonede him wel tou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if him mis-likede ani-&thorn;ing : &thorn;at grefde him in &thorn;ou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>So streitliche heo fraynede him : &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;te no leng for-sake:</L>
<L N="164">he tolde hire hov gret wille he hadde : &thorn;ene wei a-&yogh;ein to take,</L>
<L>For-to trauaili is bodi more : ase euerech man wel ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Al for-to honouri Iesu crist : &thorn;at him so deore a-bou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo sai&yogh; gilbertus wille : &thorn;at it was so guod,</L>
<L N="168">heo nolde no-&thorn;ing a-&yogh;en him beo : for-to chaungi is mod,</L>
<L>Ake heo &yogh;af him conseil &thorn;ane wei to gon : &thorn;at he hadde In &thorn;ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And forto queme Iesu crist : &thorn;at him deore bou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&THORN;are was i-sene &thorn;at heo was treowe : and of studefast mod!</L>
<L N="172">heo nolde letten hire louerd nou&yogh;t to done : &thorn;at him &thorn;ou&yogh;te god,</L>
<L>Ake euere heo bad him &thorn;ane wei gon : &thorn;at he hadde In &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>For-to serui is creatour&mdash; : &thorn;are-a-&yogh;ein he<SUP>o</SUP> nolde beo nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &yogh;eorne he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">= heo</NOTE> bad for enchaison of hire : he ne scholde it nou&yogh;t bi-leue.</L>
<L N="176">Saue<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. sone</NOTE> heo bi-sou&yogh;te gilbert : &thorn;at he one bone hire &yogh;eue:</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo moste is knaue with hire habbe : &thorn;at hire langage cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>And for he scholde hire solas beo : and speke to hire with mou&thorn;e.</L>
<L>heo truste so muche to Iesu crist : &thorn;at to cristinedom ire hadde i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;at heo ne scholde nou&yogh;t fur-fare&mdash; : so treowe was hire &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Gilebard lefde is knaue wit hire : his name was Richard Mone.<MILESTONE N="63" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he grei&thorn;ede him wel haste-liche : and wende is wei wel sone.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e holie londe he wende : In penaunce ase he dude er,
<PB REF="00000160.tif" N="112"></L>
<L N="184">And &thorn;are he bi-lefde &thorn;o : fulle furth&thorn;e-half &yogh;er.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he hadde &thorn;re &yogh;er &thorn;are i-be : and an half &yogh;er more,</L>
<L>Into is owene londe : a-longued he was sore.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at he was &thorn;are ou&yogh;t i-knowe : I-ne can ou tellen non ende;</L>
<L N="188">bote, ase &thorn;e bok us tellez : hamward he gan &thorn;o wende.</L>
<L>And &thorn;o he to londene<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. londe<SUP>ne</SUP></NOTE> cam : Ichot wel, &thorn;are he founde</L>
<L>his wif and thomas, is &yogh;onge sone : bo&thorn;e hole and sounde.</L>
<L>Welle, muche was &thorn;e Ioie : &thorn;at he makede with is sone,</L>
<L N="192">And also he dude with is wif : &thorn;o he was hom I-come;</L>
<L>And is wif gret Ioie made : with hire housebonde,</L>
<L>For he was hire swi&thorn;e wel-come : In-to engelonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;at child heo setten to lore : are it were seue &yogh;er eld;</L>
<L N="196">Ich wot, it leornede swi&thorn;e wel : and wax swi&thorn;e quointe and beld.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at he was wel i-woxe : of bodi and of clergise,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e bischop of londone : wilnede is seruise,</L>
<L>he nolde serui &thorn;e bischope nout : ake he bi-lefde at-hom,</L>
<L N="200">And preide is fader wel &yogh;erne : &thorn;at he moste to schole gon.</L>
<L>Of is fader and of is moder : &yogh;e habbez i-heord telle,</L>
<L>Acke of seint thomas him-selue : &thorn;at beste cometh nou to spelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>&para; Hic Isci Comence la vie seint Thomas Erceeueske de Kaunterbury.</HEAD>
<L>ENgelond, wel glad &thorn;ov beo : for &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t wel e&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="204">And al-so holi churche : for one Mannes de&thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;e erchebischop seint Thomas : &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at ou</NOTE> wel deore bou&yogh;te</L>
<L>With is blod and with is brayn : &thorn;at &thorn;e scharpe swerd sou&yogh;te!</L>
<L>Seint Thomas, &thorn;is holi Man : to Alle guodnesse he drov&yogh;.</L>
<L N="208">At londone he was i-bore : of guode Men i-nou&yogh;,</L>
<L>For of londone is fader was : a wel guod emne Man.</L>
<L>&THORN;is child was &yogh;ong to schole i-set : And swi&thorn;e wel he bi-gan.</L>
<L>His Moder him wolde al day rede : and wel ofte on him crie</L>
<L N="212">Chaste lijf and clene for-to lede : and for-sake lecherie,</L>
<L>And louien bi-fore al o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing : god and seinte Marie,</L>
<L>And serui hem and holi churche : and bi-leuen alle folie.</L>
<L>&THORN;is child, &thorn;ei it were &yogh;ong : swi&thorn;e wel &thorn;is under-stod&mdash;</L>
<L N="216">For seli child is sone i-lered : &thorn;are he &thorn;enchez to beon guod.
<PB REF="00000161.tif" N="113"></L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is child was bet in elde : and of to and twenti &yogh;er,</L>
<L>his moder wende out of &thorn;is liue : &thorn;at so muchel him louede her.</L>
<L>&THORN;is child wolde lengore gon to scole : ake is fader him nolde finde&mdash;</L>
<L N="220">For &thorn;at child &thorn;at is modur for-leost : is help is muche bi-hinde.</L>
<L>&THORN;is child &thorn;oru&yogh; is fader heste : ase man &thorn;at o&thorn;ur red not,</L>
<L>Seruede A borgeys of &thorn;e toun : and his a-countes wrot.</L>
<L>So longe &thorn;at he cam to court : and was in guod offiz</L>
<L N="224">With &thorn;e erchebischop of Kaunterburi : sire tebaud, guod and wis.</L>
<L>He seruede him so hendeliche : &thorn;at In a luytel stounde</L>
<L>he makede him his conseiller : so studefast he him founde;</L>
<L>his ercedekne he makede him seth&thorn;e : and dude al bi is rede.</L>
<L N="228">Swy&thorn;e wel bi-gan &thorn;is Ercedekne : holi churche bi-lede,</L>
<L>And stifliche heold op hire ri&yogh;te&mdash; : &thorn;at alle Men i-seie,</L>
<L>An &thorn;ar-of nolde he &thorn;olien no wrong : &thorn;ei he scholde &thorn;are-fore deie.</L>
<L>Wel ofte he wende to rome : for holi churche al-so&mdash;</L>
<L N="232">Swuche prelatus al-to fewe : beoth nou&thorn;e In office i-do!</L>
<L>&para; So &thorn;at henri king of Engelonde : after sire steuene &thorn;e blays&mdash;</L>
<L>Duyk of Normandie&mdash; : y-maked was al In pays.</L>
<L>&THORN;is king henri &thorn;e &yogh;ongue : &thorn;o he to londe cam,</L>
<L N="236">louede muche wel to do : and guode Men to him nam,</L>
<L>And fondede to habben guod conseil : and wis bi al is mi&yogh;te,</L>
<L>For-to holden riche and pouere : euerech man to ri&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Ercedekne Thomas : Men tolden him sone i-nou&yogh;,</L>
<L N="240">hov he was stable Man and wis : and to alle guodnesse drou&yogh;:</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; &thorn;e Erchebischopes graunt : he makede him chaunceler&mdash;</L>
<L>For euere Man mot him a-bouwie : &thorn;at hauez mest pouwer.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is holi Man was i-torned : fram &thorn;e office of holi churche</L>
<L N="244">To a gret office of &thorn;e world : &thorn;are-after he moste wurche:</L>
<L>Al-to nobleie of &thorn;e worlde : his continaunce he brou&yogh;te&mdash;</L>
<L>Of swuche porture neuere Man i-holde nas&mdash; : &thorn;ei o&thorn;ur were is &thorn;ou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>With more nobleie he rod i-nou&yogh; : &thorn;ane he was i-wonet to do:</L>
<L N="248">his loreins weren al of seluer : stirapes and spores al-so;</L>
<L>pley he siwede of hauekus : and of houndes I-nou&yogh;;</L>
<L>And ase men &thorn;ou&yogh;ten, In euereche point : to alle pruyte he drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>bote In is heorte it was an-o&thorn;ur : hov-so he him bere;</L>
<L N="252">And euere he was chaste &thorn;oru&yogh; alle &thorn;ing : hov-so it euere were.
<PB REF="00000162.tif" N="114"></L>
<L>Ake euere he was for holi churche : and for pouere Men al-so,</L>
<L>A-&yogh;en &thorn;e proute courteoures : &thorn;at a-&yogh;en heom wolden ou&yogh;t do.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Both verses were orig. transposed in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; To holden op holi churche ri&yogh;te : so muche wo he gan drie</L>
<L N="256">A-&yogh;en &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere courteours : &thorn;at a-nuyden him of is liue,</L>
<L>Also he tolde &thorn;e Erchebischope : wepinde swi&thorn;e sore,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ere ofte In priueite : &thorn;at loueden him &thorn;e more:</L>
<L>he wilnede mest of alle &thorn;inge : and on ore louerd he gan crie,</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;at he moste with honour : bi-leue &thorn;ulke baillie</L>
<L>And ech o&thorn;ur seruise of court : with &thorn;e kingus gode wille,</L>
<L>For he ne mi&yogh;te nou&yogh;t is court paie : bote he wolde is soulle spille.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;e king him fond so stable : and so guod conseiller,</L>
<L N="264">&THORN;at he nolde make for no-&thorn;ing : non o&thorn;ur chaunceler;</L>
<L>he ne truste to no man so muche : ne &thorn;are nas non so hei&yogh;</L>
<L>&THORN;at he tolde is priueite so muche : ne &thorn;at him were so nei&yogh;.</L>
<L>So muche he caste is heorte on him : &thorn;at In his warde he let do</L>
<L N="268">his eldeste sone sire henri&mdash; : he was is .Eyr. al-so&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at he were is wardein : and al is ordeinour,</L>
<L>Aftur is wille to wissi him : to &thorn;e kingus honur.<MILESTONE N="64" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e king wende In-to Normandie : for-to soiorni &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="272">And lefde is sone with seint Thomas : &thorn;at he is wardein were.</L>
<L>&para; bo&thorn;e &thorn;e fader and &thorn;e sone : mest heore heorte heo caste</L>
<L>Ope seint thomas &thorn;e holi Man : &thorn;e &yogh;wile it wolde i-laste;</L>
<L>&THORN;are nas Man In engelond : &thorn;at hadde so gret power</L>
<L N="276">Of &thorn;e reaume ase seint thomas : bo&thorn;e fer and ner.</L>
<L>Hit bi-fel &thorn;at sire Tebaut : ase god &thorn;e grace sende,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Erchebischop of Kaunterburi : out of &thorn;is liue wende.</L>
<L>&THORN;at word was sone wide couth : a-mong &thorn;euwe and freo,</L>
<L N="280">&THORN;at seint Thomas after him : scholde Erchebischop beo.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king al-so In Noremandie : &thorn;o men tolden him &thorn;at cas,</L>
<L>A-non bar is heorte him mest : to don &thorn;are seint thomas;</L>
<L>&THORN;at couent of Caunterburi : desirede him also.</L>
<L N="284">So ase ech Man it wolde : i-brou&yogh;t he<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> it</NOTE> was &thorn;ar-to.</L>
<L>At West-munstre he was i-chose : to &thorn;at heie pouwer,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fifte &yogh;er &thorn;at he was i-mad : &thorn;e kingus Chaunceler;</L>
<L>he was of elde &thorn;ulke tyme : of foure and fourti &yogh;er&mdash;</L>
<L N="288">his owene deth he onder-feng : and is Martyr-dom &thorn;er.
<PB REF="00000163.tif" N="115"></L>
<L>For &thorn;e king was In Normandie : Ipresented he was</L>
<L>to henri, is sone, In Engelonde : &thorn;o non o&thorn;ur kyng &thorn;ere nas.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;ei it were a-&yogh;en is wille : he nolde it nou&yogh;t for-sake.</L>
<L N="292">&para; &THORN;o<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;o he Axede In &yogh;wuche Manere : &thorn;o Axede he in &yogh;wuche m.</NOTE> Axede he in &yogh;wuche manere : &thorn;e croiz he scholde take.</L>
<L>Men seiden him &thorn;at he scholde a-fongue : holi churche so freo</L>
<L>&THORN;at he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. heo</NOTE> ne scholde onder noman : bote onder &thorn;e pope beo,</L>
<L>Ne no-&thorn;ing &thorn;enche bote holden op wel : holi churche lawe.</L>
<L N="296">"In &thorn;is manere," quath seint thomas : "ich hire a-fongue fawe."</L>
<L>&THORN;is was ri&yogh;t at wit-sonentid : &thorn;at &thorn;is dede cam to ende.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode Man to Caunterburi : a-non bi-gan to wende.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e contreie, to don him honour : a-&yogh;en him cam and drov;</L>
<L N="300">&THORN;are was for him In Caunterburi : Ioie and blisse I-nov.</L>
<L>&THORN;at dai of &thorn;e Trinite : bischop i-sacret he was</L>
<L>And onder-feng &thorn;is dignete : &thorn;e guode Man seint thomas.</L>
<L>Sire henri, &thorn;e kingus sone : was at his sacringue,</L>
<L N="304">And sixtene bischopus al-so : &thorn;is dede to ende bringue.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is dede was i-don : heo gonne sende sone</L>
<L>Aftur is palliun to rome : ase ri&yogh;t was for-to done.</L>
<L>Alisaundre, &thorn;at was pope &thorn;o : he was at Mount-pellers:</L>
<L N="308">&THORN;udere wenden &thorn;is wise men : &thorn;at weren is Messagers.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Abbod Adam of Euesham : heore cheuenteyn huy nome,</L>
<L>to &thorn;e pope Alisaundre : to Mount-pellers heo come.</L>
<L>heore erinde heo hadden sone of him : for [he] hem no-&thorn;ing ne wernde,</L>
<L>And heo nomen heore leue of him : and hamward a-&yogh;ein heo turnden.</L>
<L>And &thorn;is pallion wel sone was : to seint thomas i-brou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;is holi Man it a-fonge : with wel milde &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o he was in is dignete : al clanliche i-do,<MILESTONE N="64b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="316">he chaungede euerech-del is lif : and is maneres al-so.</L>
<L>&THORN;e here he dude on next is liche : is flesches maister to beo,</L>
<L>Schuyrte and brech streit i-nov : a-non doun to is kneo&mdash;</L>
<L>For him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at he wel mi&yogh;te : of o&thorn;ure habbe &thorn;e maistrie,</L>
<L N="320">&YOGH;if he hadde of is owene flesche : al-ovt &thorn;e seignorie;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if is soule Maister were : and is flesch is hyne,</L>
<L>him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he mi&yogh;te is dignete : bringue to guode fine.</L>
<L>Seth&thorn;e on-ouewarde &thorn;e here : &thorn;e Abite of Monek he nam,
<PB REF="00000164.tif" N="116"></L>
<L N="324">And a-boue al &thorn;an clerkene Robe : ase to is stat bi-cam;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he was clerk with-oute : and with-Inne Monek al-so,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; &thorn;e Abite &thorn;at he hadde on him : priueliche i-do.</L>
<L>In penaunce and In fastingue : he was ni&yogh;t and dai,</L>
<L N="328">And In is oresones, bote som &yogh;wile : &thorn;at he slepe lai;</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane he scholde eten is mete : for &thorn;at he moste nede,</L>
<L>Euere he preide ore swete louerd : &thorn;at he moste wel spede;</L>
<L>And euere &yogh;wane he Masse song : he wep and si&yogh;te sore;</L>
<L N="332">he hastede euere &thorn;are-with faste : ne mi&yogh;te no man more.</L>
<L>&para; Swi&thorn;e faire he fedde him at is bord : with grete nobleie and pruyte</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e beste him-sulf he et : ake ofte bote luyte.</L>
<L>Of is ordres he was ful streit : and he was in grete fere</L>
<L N="336">For-to ordeinen ani Man : bote he &thorn;e betere were.</L>
<L>Idul nolde he neuere beo : ake euere doinde he was;</L>
<L>In eche manere of betere liue : neuere no bischop nas.</L>
<L>Sire henri, &thorn;e kingus sone : &thorn;at with him was er i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="340">bi-lefde euere In is warde : fram him nolde he nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e loue &thorn;at was hem bi-twene : nas neuere more i-seie,</L>
<L>Ne of no Man &thorn;is child nadde : neuere more loue ei&yogh;e.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> ne ei&yogh;e</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Reditus regis.</NOTE>HIt bi-fel &thorn;at &thorn;e king : ovt of Noremandie cam</L>
<L N="344">In-to Enguelonde, &thorn;e stat to loke : and al-so is kynedom.</L>
<L>Seint Thomas nam with him : sire hanri, is sone,</L>
<L>And wel faire with honour : wende to south-hamptone.</L>
<L>&THORN;are was Ioie and blisse i-nou&yogh; : &thorn;o heo to-gadere come;</L>
<L N="348">heo custen and heo clupten faste : and hereden god i-lome.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king bi-lefde In Engelonde : to wardi is kynedom.</L>
<L>Seint thomas to is priueitez : euere-more he nam</L>
<L>And heold him euere ase he dude er : is hexte conseiller;</L>
<L N="352">bi is wille he nolde habbe i-haued : non o&thorn;ur chaunceler.</L>
<L>Euere &yogh;wane he ani-&thorn;ing dude : &thorn;at were a-&yogh;en &thorn;e ri&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Seint thomas it with-seide : euere with al is mi&yogh;te.&mdash;</L>
<L>Hit bi-fel &thorn;at &thorn;e bischop of wirecestre : sone &thorn;ere-after ded was,</L>
<L N="356">And &thorn;e bischop of hereforde al-so : ase ore louerd &yogh;af &thorn;at cas.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischopriches fullen bo&thorn;e : In-to &thorn;e kingus hond,</L>
<L>For-to onder-fonge al &thorn;e prov &thorn;are-of : ase lawe was in &thorn;e lond.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e king heom nolde nou&yogh;t &yogh;iue sone : bote heold heom swi&thorn;e longe
<PB REF="00000165.tif" N="117"></L>
<L N="360">In his hond, &thorn;at he mi&yogh;te &thorn;ar-of : &thorn;e more prov a-fonge.<MILESTONE N="65" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Hit ne likede nou&yogh;t seint Thomas : &thorn;at holi churche so</L>
<L>Scholde for a luytel coueitise : In &thorn;e kingus warde beon i-do;</L>
<L>he &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at it was swi&thorn;e muche : a-&yogh;en ore louerdes wille,</L>
<L N="364">And &thorn;at &thorn;e king mi&yogh;te In swuche manere : holi churche a-spille.</L>
<L>he bad &thorn;e kinge In faire manere : &thorn;at he ne scholde it nou&yogh;t bi-leue</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ulke tweie bischoperiches : some guode Men he &yogh;eue.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king him grauntede mildeliche : and nas nou&yogh;t a-&yogh;en is bone,</L>
<L N="368">Ake &THORN;eos bischopriches bo&thorn;e he &yogh;af : twei guode Men wel sone.</L>
<L>&para; Seint thomas &thorn;ou&yogh;te wel : &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;te nou&yogh;t paie</L>
<L>&thorn;e kingue ne his conseil : bote he wolde holi churche bi-traie;</L>
<L>In gret care and in soruwe he was : hov he mi&yogh;te best do,</L>
<L N="372">For he ne mi&yogh;te nou&yogh;t paien Ihesu crist : and &thorn;ene kingue also.</L>
<L>Seint Thomas halewede &thorn;at ilke &yogh;er : &thorn;e churche of Redinge,</L>
<L>&THORN;at i-founded was and a-rerd : &thorn;oru&yogh; henri &thorn;e o&thorn;ur kingue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;eot lith &thorn;are wel faire i-bured&mdash; : willames sone bastard.</L>
<L N="376">In &thorn;ulke &yogh;ere seint thomas : schrinede seint edward</L>
<L>At westmunstre, &thorn;are he lijth : &thorn;at bi-fore king willame was;</L>
<L>bote king harald heom was bi-tueone : for-to is power no leng nas.</L>
<L>&THORN;e loue was euere gret i-nou&yogh; : bi-tweone seint thomas</L>
<L N="380">And &thorn;e kinge, for-to &thorn;e feond : destourbede hit, allas!</L>
<L>luyte an luyte &thorn;at contek sprong : for pouere Mannes ri&yogh;te:</L>
<L>paie ore louerd and &thorn;e kinge : &thorn;is holi man ne mi&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste tyme &thorn;at seint thomas : ovtliche him with-seide,</L>
<L N="384">hit was for &thorn;e king a-&yogh;en pouere Men : dude onri&yogh;tful dede.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e king nam fro &yogh;er to &yogh;ere : &thorn;oru&yogh; Engelond wel wide</L>
<L>After is wille ane summe of panes : i-deld bi-eche side,</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e &thorn;oru an-queste : he let &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e contreies an-quere</L>
<L N="388">hov muche ech Man scholde pai&yogh;e : and hov muche is ri&yogh;te were.</L>
<L>So longue he nam taillage : &thorn;at he axede at&thorn;e laste</L>
<L>Eche &yogh;ere ane certeyne rente : &thorn;oru&yogh; al engelond wel faste.</L>
<L>&YOGH;wat for ei&yogh;e, &yogh;wat for loue : no man him ne with-seide;</L>
<L N="392">bote euere &thorn;ou&yogh;te seint thomas : &thorn;at hit was an onri&yogh;tful dede.</L>
<L>he &thorn;ou&yogh;te al on god and on is soule : and bi-lefde al his manhede,</L>
<L>And wende forth wel baldeliche : to &thorn;e king with-outen drede:</L>
<L>"Sire," he seide, "&yogh;if it is &thorn;i wille : &thorn;ou art riche and hende,
<PB REF="00000166.tif" N="118"></L>
<L N="396">And king of gret pouwer i-nov&mdash; : ore louerd &thorn;e more sende.</L>
<L>A taillage &thorn;ov taxt fram &yogh;er to &yogh;er : &thorn;oru&yogh;-out al &thorn;i londe,</L>
<L>And axest it for a certeine rente : with onri&yogh;te, ich onder-stonde;</L>
<L>For ri&yogh;te rente &thorn;ov dest it take : at a certein daie in &thorn;e &yogh;ere,</L>
<L N="400">A certeyn summe a-signed : And so ne dude no king ere.</L>
<L>&YOGH;ware-&thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;at certein rente, me &thorn;inchez : &thorn;ov ne mi&yogh;t it nou&yogh;t make:</L>
<L>A taillage it is, and sumdel : with vnri&yogh;te i-take."</L>
<L>&para; "Thomas, thomas," quad &thorn;e king : "&thorn;ou art mi chaunceler,</L>
<L N="404">&THORN;ou au&yogh;test more to holden op : &thorn;ane to with-seggen mi power."</L>
<L>&para; "Sire," quath &thorn;is holi Man : "ich habbe i-beo with &thorn;e,<MILESTONE N="65b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;ou hast, ore louerd fur-&yogh;elde &thorn;e : gret guod i-don me:</L>
<L>An o&thorn;ur baillie ich habbe a-fongue : &thorn;ei it were a-&yogh;en mi wille,</L>
<L N="408">And I ne mai nou&yogh;t loki bo&thorn;e wel : bote ich scholde min owene a-spille;</L>
<L>For ich am to luyte wuyrth : &thorn;at on for-to loke:</L>
<L>&THORN;anne dude he gret folie : &thorn;at bo&thorn;e me bi-toke.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore ich &thorn;e &yogh;elde up here : al-out &thorn;e chauncelerie,</L>
<L N="412">And take me al to holi churche : to god and to seinte Marie."</L>
<L>&THORN;o was &thorn;e king wel of I-nou&yogh; : wro&thorn;ere &thorn;ane he was er;</L>
<L>Ake na&thorn;eles is heorte bar : euere to Thomas &thorn;er.</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ridde &thorn;ing &yogh;eot mest of alle : and sonest in wrath&thorn;e hem brou&yogh;te:</L>
<L N="416">A preost, &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;er</NOTE> was a lu&thorn;er Man : &thorn;at luyte of god rou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>&THORN;at of Manslau&yogh;t was bi-cleoped : and &thorn;are-fore i-nome also</L>
<L>And In &thorn;e bischopes prisone of Salesburi : &thorn;are-fore he was i-do.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Mannes frend &thorn;at was a-slawe : siweden ope him so faste,</L>
<L N="420">So &thorn;at &thorn;e preost to Iuggement : Ibrou&yogh;t was at&thorn;e laste.</L>
<L>Men acuseden him faste of &thorn;e dede. : he ne answerede nou&yogh;t &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>Acke heold him faste to holi churche : and ope none o&thorn;ere he nolde him do.</L>
<L>&para; I-loked him was to puyrgi him : &thorn;oru&yogh; clergie, &yogh;if he mi&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="424">And dai him was &thorn;ar-to i-set : &thorn;oru&yogh; holi churche ri&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e dai was i-come : he ne mi&yogh;te him puyrgi nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>he was sone i-lad a-&yogh;en : and into prisone i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;o was &thorn;e bischop in grete care : &yogh;wat &thorn;er-of were to done;</L>
<L N="428">For-to habbe &thorn;e wisore red : to seint thomas he sende sone.
<PB REF="00000167.tif" N="119"></L>
<L>And he him sente word a-&yogh;en : &thorn;at he scholde &thorn;ene preost take</L>
<L>And on-ordeini him of euerech ordre : and ase a lewede Man him make,</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e don him in strongue warde : &thorn;at he neuer-eft &thorn;ar-of ne wende,</L>
<L N="432">In penaunce and in pine i-nou&yogh; : his sunnes for-to a-mende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischop of Salesburi : dude seint thomas heste;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e preost was i-brou&yogh;t : In tormenz bi &thorn;e meste.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ti&thorn;inge her-of sone : to &thorn;e kinge cam,</L>
<L N="436">&THORN;at a lu&thorn;er &thorn;ef, a manquellare : hadde a so li&yogh;t dom.</L>
<L>him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at it nas nou&yogh;t ri&yogh;t : ne &thorn;at it ne mi&yogh;te nou&yogh;t beo so.</L>
<L>And phelipe de boys, a Chanoyne : him hadde al-so mis-do:</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore was ech o&thorn;ur clerk : &thorn;e more him a-&yogh;en wille;</L>
<L N="440">him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at swuch lawe scholde : &thorn;e pais of &thorn;e londe a-spille.</L>
<L>To westmunstre he let somony : alle &thorn;e bischopes of engelonde,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ure, &thorn;e gretteste clerkes al-so : and &thorn;e hexte, ich onder-stonde.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Ait Rex.</NOTE>&para; "Beav seignours," &thorn;e king seide : "I not &yogh;wat &yogh;e habbeth i-&thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="444">&YOGH;if &yogh;e goth forth with ower wille : ore pais ne worth ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if a clerk hath ane Man a-slawe : o&thorn;ur strong &thorn;eff&thorn;e i-do,</L>
<L>And he mouwe &thorn;anne desordeined beo : and to liue comen so,</L>
<L>heo wollez &thorn;anne mis-don al day : and beon &thorn;are-oppe wel bolde,</L>
<L N="448">And so schal &thorn;e pays of &thorn;e londe : wel vuele beon i-holde.</L>
<L>Luyte heom wolde rechche : to leosen heore ordre so,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane heo for heore ordre ne spariez nou&yogh;t : &thorn;ef&thorn;e for-to do!<MILESTONE N="66" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And euere &thorn;e herre heore ordre is : me &thorn;inchez bi puyr lawe,</L>
<L>&thorn;e strengore scholde heore dom beo : &yogh;wane heo wolden to &thorn;ef&thorn;e drawe."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Ait Thomas.</NOTE>&para; "Sire, sire," quad seint Thomas : "&yogh;if it is &thorn;i wille,</L>
<L N="454">Lothz vs were any-&thorn;ing to don : &thorn;i pays for-to a-spille.</L>
<L>&THORN;e clerkus &thorn;at beot<SUP>h</SUP> I-ordeynede : &thorn;ov wost wel heo berez a signe</L>
<L N="456">&THORN;at heo beoth lymes of holi churche : &thorn;at so noble is and digne;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if heo weren with &thorn;ulke signe : to vile de&thorn;e i-do,</L>
<L>A-viled were al-holi churche : and foule i-schend al-so.</L>
<L>And &yogh;if heo beoth formest onordeined : and for &thorn;ulke sulue dede</L>
<L N="460">Seth&thorn;e &thorn;oru&yogh; dom to de&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t : it nere nou&yogh;t wel to rede:</L>
<L>For it nas neuere lawe ne ri&yogh;t : double dom to take</L>
<L>For o trespas, ase &yogh;e wel wuteth : and sunne it were to make;
<PB REF="00000168.tif" N="120"></L>
<L>And vnwuyr&thorn;ere &thorn;ane a lewed Man : holi churche were so:</L>
<L N="464">A lewed Man for o trespas : bote o Iuggement nis i-do.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore &thorn;ine grace we biddeth &thorn;e : &yogh;if it is &thorn;i wille,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ov ne a-rere none newe lawe : holi churche to spille,</L>
<L>For we biddez ni&yogh;t ant day : ase ri&yogh;t is for-to do,</L>
<L N="468">&THORN;at god holde &thorn;e &thorn;ine ri&yogh;te : and &thorn;ine reavme al-so."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Rex.</NOTE>&para; "beav sire," quath &thorn;e king &thorn;o : "&thorn;ov seist wel i-nov&yogh;.</L>
<L>Ich hadde lothz bi mi concience : don holi churche wov&yogh;;</L>
<L>For lawes &thorn;ere beoth and costomes : &thorn;at habbethz euere beon i-holde</L>
<L N="472">Of bischopus &thorn;oru&yogh; al Engelond : ase ovre Aunceteres us tolde,</L>
<L>And bi &thorn;e kingus daye henries : &thorn;at ovre graunt-sire was</L>
<L>I-confermede weren and i-holde : And no man &thorn;are-a&yogh;en nas.</L>
<L>Wolt&thorn;u &thorn;ulke lawes holde? : do me to witene sone!"</L>
<L N="476">"We schullen do," seint Thomas seide : "al &thorn;at is to done&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="marg2">Thomas.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e lawes and &thorn;e costomes : we schullen holde bi ore mi&yogh;te</L>
<L>&THORN;at beothz to holde and habbeth i-beo : sire,&mdash;sauue oure ri&yogh;te."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Rex.</NOTE>"Sauue ouwer ri&yogh;te?" quath &thorn;e king : "bev sire, &yogh;wi seist&thorn;ou so?</L>
<L N="480">bi &thorn;ulke worde Ine scholde no-&thorn;ing : a&yogh;en &thorn;ine wille do</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ov noldest segge &thorn;at it were : a-&yogh;en holi churche ri&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And so &thorn;ou mi&yogh;test bringe al &thorn;at lond : In contek and In fi&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e moten holde &thorn;e lawes : for-so&thorn;e ich onder-stonde,</L>
<L N="484">&THORN;at word me &thorn;inchez venimous : to &thorn;e pays of &thorn;e londe."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Thomas.</NOTE>"Sire," quath &thorn;is holi man : "ne meue &yogh;e ov ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t!</L>
<L>Wel &thorn;ov wost &thorn;at ech of us : are we weren here-to i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Trewenesse we &thorn;e sworen ase ri&yogh;t was : and eor&thorn;elich honour al-so,</L>
<L N="488">Sauue ore ordre and ore ri&yogh;te&mdash; : bote &thorn;at was out i-do.</L>
<L>hou scholde we, sire, nou&thorn;e o&thorn;ur do? : &yogh;e ne Au&yogh;ten it us nou&yogh;t beode.</L>
<L>For godes loue hold us to ri&yogh;te : for nou&thorn;e we habbez neode."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Rex.</NOTE>&para; "Ich i-seo nou&thorn;e, thomas," quath &thorn;e king : "&yogh;ware-to &thorn;ou wult drawe;</L>
<L N="492">&THORN;ov art I-come to late : to bi-nimen us ovre lawe.</L>
<L>&THORN;ov woldest makien me more wrechche : &thorn;ane euere ani kyng was:</L>
<L>&THORN;are-to &thorn;ov art i-come to late : &thorn;ou cast aumbes as."</L>
<L>&thorn;e king [aros] in wrath&thorn;e a-non : and let heom sitte ech-one;<MILESTONE N="66b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="496">In-to is chaumbre he wende : and ne grette heom neuer one.</L>
<L>Fram londone he wende sone : In wrath&thorn;e ase &thorn;ei it were,
<PB REF="00000169.tif" N="121"></L>
<L>he ne seide no man of is &thorn;ou&yogh;t : ake bi-lefde heom alle &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischopus &thorn;ou&yogh;ten &thorn;o ech-one : &thorn;at he was wroth i-nou&yogh;,</L>
<L N="500">&THORN;are weren fewe bote seint thomas : &thorn;at toward him ne drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&para; On seint Thomas heo criden faste : is &thorn;ou&yogh;t forte wende,</L>
<L>O&thorn;uer he wolde al &thorn;at lond : for &thorn;ulke one worde schende.</L>
<L>kni&yogh;tes and o&thorn;ure ofte comen : &thorn;at with &thorn;e kinge were</L>
<L N="504">And beden seint Thomas ententifliche : &thorn;at he &thorn;at word for-bere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at it were him gret folie : &thorn;e kinge In wrath&thorn;e bringe,</L>
<L>And also destourbi al &thorn;at lond : for so luytel &thorn;ingue.</L>
<L>Seint thomas stod longe in &thorn;ou&yogh;te. : "leoue bre&thorn;ren," he seide,</L>
<L N="508">"A-&yogh;en &thorn;e kyngus honur I-ne schal : neuere don no dede,</L>
<L>Ake euerech word ichulle bi-leue : &thorn;at a-&yogh;en is honur is."</L>
<L>&THORN;o weren &thorn;is o&thorn;ure glade i-nou&yogh; : &thorn;o heo i-heorden &thorn;is,</L>
<L>And radden him wende to &thorn;e kinge : is wrath&thorn;e for-to stille.</L>
<L N="512">"Lef me were," quath seint Thomas : "with ri&yogh;te to don is wille."</L>
<L>He wende to &thorn;e kinge to Oxenford : and with him &thorn;are he fond</L>
<L>grete Eorles and barones also : &thorn;e hexte of al &thorn;e lond.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king welcomede seint Thomas : ake he ne made him nou&yogh;t fair chere;</L>
<L N="516">bischopes and Eorles he let cleopien : alle &thorn;at &thorn;ere were.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Rex.</NOTE>&para; "Bev sire," he seide, "ich am king : with ri&yogh;te of &thorn;is londe;</L>
<L>Customes here weren bi-fore : I-vsed, ich onder-stonde,</L>
<L>And so muche wrechche nam ich nou&yogh;t : &thorn;at ich nelle &thorn;e lawes holde</L>
<L N="520">&THORN;at ovre Auncestres heolden &yogh;wyle : ase ore conseil us tolde.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore ichulle &thorn;at &thorn;ulke lawes : i-confermede beoth ech-on</L>
<L>Of mine eorles and mine barones al-so : heo ne with-seggez non.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore ich hote ov euerechone : &thorn;at &yogh;e beon &thorn;at ilke dai</L>
<L N="524">At mi maner at Clarindone : with-outen ani de-lai,</L>
<L>For-to confermi &thorn;is lawes. : ope peyne &thorn;at i schal ou sette,</L>
<L>Ich hote &thorn;at &yogh;e beon &thorn;are ech-one&mdash; : &thorn;at non o&thorn;ur ne lette."</L>
<L>So departede &thorn;e court &thorn;o : and euerech to is In drou&yogh;;</L>
<L N="528">And euere was seint thomas : In care and soruwe i-nou&yogh;.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Clarendon.</NOTE>&para; &thorn;is bischopes and &thorn;e baronie : alle comen to &thorn;e dai&yogh;e</L>
<L>to clarindone In wilte-schire : &thorn;e kingue for-to paye.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo comen to &thorn;e parlement : &thorn;e king axede heom a-non</L>
<L N="532">&YOGH;we&thorn;ur heo wolden holde &thorn;e lawes : ase heore Auncestres heolden ech-on.
<PB REF="00000170.tif" N="122"></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Thomas.</NOTE>&para; "Sire, sire," quath seint thomas : "&yogh;if it &thorn;i wille is,</L>
<L>Ech man mot speke for him-selue : and ich for me, i-wis.</L>
<L>For mi stat and for holi churche : Ich answerie &thorn;ar-to</L>
<L N="536">&THORN;at alle &thorn;e olde guode lawes : And &thorn;at &yogh;eot beoth al-so</L>
<L>graunti ichulle for holi churche : for-to habben &thorn;in ore,</L>
<L>Sauue ore ri&yogh;tes and ore ordre. : &thorn;ou ne mi&yogh;t axi nonmore."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e king was wod-wroth for &thorn;at word : &thorn;at him gan &thorn;o mislike,</L>
<L N="540">Seint Thomas wep In is heorte : and sore bi-gan to sike.<MILESTONE N="67" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Al-to blodi was &thorn;at word i-seid : and deore it was a-bou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore was seint Thomas : to stronge de&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischop of Salesburi : and of Northwiche al-so</L>
<L N="544">Wepinde knevleden to seint thomas : &thorn;at he scholde ano&thorn;ur do</L>
<L>And habbe rev&thorn;e of al-holi churche : and of heom echone,</L>
<L>"&THORN;at we ne beon alle to grounde i-brou&yogh;t : for &thorn;ulke worde one."</L>
<L>hei&yogh;e Men &thorn;at with &thorn;e kingue weren : mani on al-s[o] wende</L>
<L N="548">And knevleden to seint Thomas : &thorn;at word for-to a-mende.</L>
<L>&para; "Louerdyngues," quath seint Thomas : "ich am &yogh;et a &yogh;ong man</L>
<L>And luyte &yogh;wule habbe bischop i-beo : and &thorn;ar-on luytel ich can:</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore of ower olde lawes : transcrit &yogh;e me take,</L>
<L N="552">And &thorn;are-oppe ichchulle conseillen me : &yogh;wuche beon to for-sake."</L>
<L>&thorn;e king him let a traunscrit take : of &thorn;is customes echon.</L>
<L>Seint Thomas grauntede some of heom : and with-seide mani on.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Prima lex.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;e lawes &thorn;at ichulle nou&thorn;e telle : he grauntede wel fawe:</L>
<L>'&YOGH;if a bonde-man hath ane sone : &thorn;at to clergie beo i-drawe,</L>
<L>He<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. Ne</NOTE> schal nou&yogh;t with-oute is louerdes leue : no&yogh;were i-crouned beo,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ev-Man ne mai nou&yogh;t beon i-maket : a-&yogh;en is louerdes wille freo.'</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Alia lex.</NOTE>&para; An o&thorn;ur lawe he grauntede al-so : &thorn;at &yogh;e mowen nou&thorn;e i-seo:</L>
<L N="560">'&YOGH;if ani man of holi churche : halt ani-&thorn;ing of lay-fe,</L>
<L>person, preost, o&thorn;ur &yogh;wat-so he beo : he schal don &thorn;ere-fore</L>
<L>&THORN;e seruise &thorn;at to &thorn;e kinge bi-fallez : &thorn;at is ri&yogh;te nere for-lore;</L>
<L>And In plaidingue stonde in eche place : and In iuggement al-so,</L>
<L N="564">bote &yogh;ware ani Man schal beon bi-leomed : o&thorn;ur to de&thorn;e i-do.'</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Tertia lex.</NOTE>&para; He grauntede also, '&yogh;if ani Man : &thorn;e kingues traytur were</L>
<L>And ani man is chateus : to holi churche bere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at holi churche ne scholde nou&yogh;t : &thorn;e chateus with strenc&thorn;e lette,</L>
<L N="568">Ake &thorn;e king hem scholde wel baldeliche : ase is howene fette.
<PB REF="00000171.tif" N="123"></L>
<L>For al &thorn;at &thorn;e kingus feloun hath : &thorn;e kingus catel it is,</L>
<L>And ech man in holi churche : is owene take i-wis.'</L>
<L>Seint Thomas grauntede blu&thorn;eliche : &thorn;eos and o&thorn;ure mo,</L>
<L N="572">Ake &thorn;eos o&thorn;ere he with-seide&mdash; : &thorn;at dude him muche wo:</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">I<SUP>a</SUP> contradicta.</NOTE>&para; '&YOGH;if bi-twene tweie lewede men : were ani striuingue,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur bi-tuene a lewed man and a clerk : for holi churche &thorn;ingue,</L>
<L>Ase for Avouweson of churche : &yogh;we&thorn;ur scholde &thorn;e churche &yogh;iue,</L>
<L N="576">&THORN;e king wolde &thorn;at In his court : &thorn;at plai scholde beon i-driue,</L>
<L>&para; for ase muche ase a lewed Man : &thorn;e o partye, was</L>
<L>clanliche onder &thorn;e kingue : and onder no bischop nas.'</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">ija.</NOTE>&para; An o&thorn;ur lawe was '&thorn;at no bischop : ne clerk no&thorn;e-mo</L>
<L N="580">Scholde out of engelonde : with-oute &thorn;e kingus leue go,</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne heo scholden swerien heore oth : opon &thorn;e boke, i-wis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo ne scholden purchaci non vuel : &thorn;e kingue ne none of his.'</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">iij<SUP>a</SUP>.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;e &thorn;ridde was, '&yogh;if ani man : In mansingue were i-brou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="584">And seth&thorn;e come to amendement : and a-&yogh;en ri&yogh;te nere nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne scholde nou&yogh;t swerie op-on &thorn;e boke : ake borewes finde he scholde<MILESTONE N="67b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>to stonde to al &thorn;at holi churche : with ri&yogh;te him lokie wolde.'</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">iiij<SUP>a</SUP>.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;e fer&thorn;e was '&thorn;at no man : &thorn;at of &thorn;e kinge heolde ou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="588">In chief o&thorn;ur In seruise : in mansingue nere i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>bote &thorn;e wardeins of holi churche : brou&yogh;te<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at br.</NOTE> him &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;e kyng s.</NOTE> seiden, o&thorn;ur is baillifs : &yogh;wat he hadde mis-do,</L>
<L>And lokede formest &yogh;we&thorn;er heo wolden : to amendement it bringe,</L>
<L N="592">And bote huy wolden, bi heore leue : &thorn;anne don &thorn;e mansingue.'</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">v<SUP>a</SUP>.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;e fifte was '&thorn;at no bischopriche : ne non Abbeie also,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at bischopriches: &amp; abbayes also</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at were voyde with-oute prelat : In &thorn;e kingus hond were I-do</L>
<L>And &thorn;e king scholde al &thorn;at lond : ase is owene take,</L>
<L N="596">For-to at&thorn;e laste &thorn;at him luste : ani prelat make;</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne scholde &thorn;ilke prelat : of is chapele i-chose beo,</L>
<L>Of is clerkus &yogh;wuch &thorn;at he wolde : &thorn;at benefiz to bi-seo;</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne &yogh;wane he were i-chose : In is chapele &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="600">homage he scholde don to him : are he j-confermed were.'</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">vj<SUP>a</SUP>.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;e sixte was, '&yogh;if ani plait : to chapitle were i-drawe</L>
<L>And ani man made ani apel : &yogh;if men duden him a-&yogh;en lawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e bischop fram &thorn;e Ercedekne : his apel [he]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> scholde make,
<PB REF="00000172.tif" N="124"></L>
<L>And fram &thorn;e bischop to &thorn;e Erchebischop : and seth&thorn;e non herre take;</L>
<L>bote &thorn;e Erchebischopes court : to ri&yogh;te him wolle<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. wolde</NOTE> bringe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he scholde fram &thorn;ulke court : bi-cleopien to &thorn;e kinge,</L>
<L>And fram &thorn;e kinge non herre'&mdash; : so &thorn;at at&thorn;enende</L>
<L N="608">&THORN;e playdingue fram holi churche : to &thorn;e kingue scholde i-wende,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e king a-mendi scholde : &thorn;e Erchebischopes dede</L>
<L>And beon chief of holi churche&mdash; : ake seint thomas it with-seide.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">vij<SUP>a</SUP>.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;e seue&thorn;e was '&thorn;at playdingue : &thorn;at of dette were,</L>
<L N="612">for-to &yogh;elde &thorn;oru&yogh; treu&thorn;e i-pli&yogh;t : and nou&yogh;t i-holde nere</L>
<L>Al-&thorn;ei it &thorn;oru&yogh; treu&thorn;e were : &thorn;e playdinge scholde beon i-brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>bi-fore &thorn;e kinge and is baillifs : and to holi churche nou&yogh;t.'</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">viij<SUP>a</SUP>.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;e ei&yogh;te&thorn;e was '&thorn;at In &thorn;e londe : citation non nere</L>
<L N="616">&THORN;oru&yogh; bulle of &thorn;e pope of rome : Ake clanliche bi-leued were.'</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">ix<SUP>a</SUP>.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;e Nin&thorn;e was '&thorn;at peteres panes : &thorn;at men gaderiez mani on,</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope nere nou&yogh;t on i-send : ake &thorn;e kingue euerech-on.'</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">x<SUP>a</SUP>.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;e teo&thorn;e was, '&yogh;if ani clerk : ase felun were i-take</L>
<L>And for kingus felon j-proued were : and he ne mi&yogh;te nou&yogh;t for-sake,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men scholden furst desordeini him : and seth&thorn;e &thorn;oru&yogh; ri&yogh;te lawe</L>
<L N="622">And &thorn;oru&yogh; ri&yogh;t Iuggement of &thorn;e londe : bringe him of lijf-dawe.'</L>
<L>&THORN;eos customes, and manie o&thorn;ere : &thorn;e king pulte forth a-non,</L>
<L N="624">And het &thorn;oru&yogh;-out al &thorn;is lond : &thorn;at Men heom heolden echon.</L>
<L>&THORN;ene feor&thorn;e dai bi-fore candelemasse : &thorn;o &thorn;is was ido,</L>
<L>&THORN;e king het seint thomas a-non : and &thorn;e o&thorn;ere bischopus al-so</L>
<L>On &thorn;is chartre heore seles sette : &thorn;at non aftur-tale nere,</L>
<L N="628">&THORN;at &thorn;ulke costomes weren i-holde : &thorn;oru&yogh; al &thorn;e londe &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>"Sire, sire," quath seint thomas : "for godes loue &thorn;in ore,</L>
<L>to conseili us betere &yogh;if us furst : are we speken her-of more!"<MILESTONE N="68" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So &thorn;at respit was &thorn;ar-of I-nome : and ech wende In his side.</L>
<L N="632">&para; Seint thomas nam &thorn;at transcrit : and nolde no lengore a-bide,</L>
<L>to winchestre he wende &thorn;anne : with soruwe and care i-nov&yogh;</L>
<L>hov he mi&yogh;te holi churche schilde : fram &thorn;is muchele wov&yogh;.</L>
<L>&yogh;wane o&thorn;ur Men weren faste a-slepe : he wep and si&yogh;te sore,</L>
<L N="636">"And Iesus<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &amp; bad god</NOTE> helpe holi churche" : and cride him milce and ore.</L>
<L>he i-sai &thorn;at &thorn;er nas bote o wei : o&thorn;ur he moste stif beo,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur holi churche was al bi-ne&thorn;e : &thorn;at with ri&yogh;te was so freo.</L>
<L>Sori and careful he was I-nov : &thorn;at he tok on so,
<PB REF="00000173.tif" N="125"></L>
<L N="640">For-to entri into Answere : &thorn;are he ne ou&yogh;te nou&yogh;t to do,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he a-feng &thorn;at transcrit : and respit hadde i-bede:</L>
<L>For him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at al-holi churche : In &thorn;at he misdude;</L>
<L>For holi churche ne scholde : In none stude stonde to dome</L>
<L N="644">Ne Ansuerie kinge ne prince no&thorn;ur : bote &thorn;e pope of rome.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e deol &thorn;at thomas makede : no tounge telle ne may.</L>
<L>"Louerd," he seide, "alas, alas : &thorn;at ich euere i-sai&yogh; &thorn;is day,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich &thorn;e warde of holi churche : so folliche scholde take,</L>
<L N="648">And so freo ase heo was er : &thorn;us &thorn;eu seth&thorn;e hire make!</L>
<L>heo &thorn;at was er so hei&yogh; and freo : bi mine Auncestres daye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich hire scholde bi-neo&thorn;e bringe : Allas! and so bi-traie,</L>
<L>for &thorn;is Martyrs &thorn;at &yogh;wylene weren : for hire to stronge de&thorn;e i-do,</L>
<L N="652">heo is nou&thorn;e &thorn;ev &thorn;oru&yogh; me i-maked! : Allas, &yogh;wi dude ich so?</L>
<L>luytel wuyrth ich am of holi churche : wardein for-to beo,</L>
<L>And al-so vnwurth&thorn;eliche &thorn;ar-to i-nome&mdash; : &thorn;at ech man may i-seo:</L>
<L>For ich nam nou&yogh;t, ase ri&yogh;t was : fram none ordre i-nome,</L>
<L N="656">Ake fram hei&yogh;e kingus court to holi churche : and &thorn;at wolde vuele bi-come.</L>
<L>Of houndes ich was wardeyn : and of hauekes with &thorn;e king,</L>
<L>And nov am wardein of soulene i-maked : and &thorn;at ne Ioyneth no-&thorn;ing;</L>
<L>Ich &thorn;at for-sok min owene : &thorn;e &yogh;wyle ich was chaunceler,</L>
<L N="660">So manie soulene habbe to loke : allas! &yogh;wat schal ich her?</L>
<L>Ich drede &thorn;at god habbe me fur-sake : hov tok ich on, alas!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e deol &thorn;at &thorn;is holi man makede : with-outen ende it was:</L>
<L>he wep and si&yogh;te ny&yogh;t and dai : and heold him al for-lore.</L>
<L N="664">&YOGH;if he mi&yogh;te a-soilled beo : to &thorn;e pope he wolde &thorn;er-fore,</L>
<L>And wende toward Caunterburi. : sone &thorn;e kinge men tolde</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e Erchebischop nolde nou&yogh;t : &thorn;e newe statuz holde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king het his baillifs sone : and sende a-boute is sonde,</L>
<L N="668">&THORN;at heo scholden greui seint thomas : ouer-al on is londes.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is baillifs weren preste i-nov&yogh; : and ope is maneres wel faste,</L>
<L>Nomen is bodene and greueden him&mdash; : heo wenden &thorn;are-with him a-gaste.</L>
<L>Seint thomas let heom al i-wor&thorn;e : and op-on ore louerd is heorte caste,
<PB REF="00000174.tif" N="126"></L>
<L N="672">And wende him wel priueliche : bi ny&yogh;te at&thorn;e laste</L>
<L>to &thorn;e se, toward rome : &thorn;at none of is men it nuste,</L>
<L>bote twey Men &thorn;at he tok with him : &thorn;at is priuete mest wusten.</L>
<L>Seth&thorn;e &thorn;o is men him misten : and nusten &yogh;ware he bi-cam,<MILESTONE N="68b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And seien &thorn;at heo with-oute louerd weren : euer-ech is red nam</L>
<L>for-to don euerech is beste : ech wende In is side,</L>
<L N="678">Ase men &thorn;at weren louerdlese&mdash; : heo nusten &yogh;wat a-bide.</L>
<L>&THORN;is holi Man wende him forth : and dude him In schipe sone,</L>
<L N="680">And wende for&thorn;eward in &thorn;e se : ase he &thorn;ou&yogh;te for-to done.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e wind cam ase ore louerd it wolde : and drof him a-&yogh;en to londe.</L>
<L>Seth&thorn;e he wende eft in-to &thorn;e se : &thorn;e passage for-to fonde:</L>
<L>&THORN;e wind cam and drof him a-&yogh;ein. : and ofte<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> eft</NOTE> In he wende,</L>
<L>And euere he was a-&yogh;en i-driue : ase ore louerd &thorn;e grace him sende.</L>
<L>&THORN;o i-sai&yogh; &thorn;is holi man wel : &thorn;at it nas nou&yogh;t godes wille</L>
<L N="686">&THORN;at he &thorn;e &yogh;eot of londe wende : he turnde a&yogh;en wel stille.</L>
<L>On of is seriaunz sat a ni&yogh;t : &thorn;e &yogh;wile &thorn;at men woke,</L>
<L>In his chaumbre at caunterburi<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. caum|terburl</NOTE> : &thorn;e chaumbre for-to loke;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e Eueninge he bad is knaue : to steken &thorn;e dore faste.</L>
<L>&THORN;is knaue eode toward &thorn;e dore : is ei&yogh;ene a-boute he caste:</L>
<L>&THORN;o i-sai&yogh; he &thorn;is holi man : In one huyrne stonde.</L>
<L N="692">he orn and tolde his maister fore : and &thorn;onkede godes sonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e seriaunt ne lefde &thorn;at nou&yogh;t : na&thorn;eles op he a-ros</L>
<L>And fond seint Thomas In &thorn;e huyrne : and sum-del him a-gros.</L>
<L>&THORN;are was sone Ioye i-nov&yogh;! : &thorn;at folk sone to him drov&yogh;</L>
<L N="696">And welcomeden him and maden him guod semblaunt : with Ioye and blisse i-nou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&para; Heo setten bord and spradden cloth : and bi-gonne to soupe faste.</L>
<L>Seint thomas tolde hem &thorn;o : wel Mildeliche at&thorn;e laste</L>
<L>&YOGH;wodere he &thorn;ou&yogh;te to habbe i-went : and &yogh;wuch cas god him sende,</L>
<L N="700">And hou it nas nou&yogh;t godes wille : &thorn;at he &thorn;e &yogh;wyt forth wende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ti&thorn;inge to &thorn;e kinge cam : &thorn;at &thorn;e guode Man sein thomas,</L>
<L>A&yogh;en &thorn;e status of clarindone : of londe i-went he was&mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at o statuit was &thorn;at no bischop : ne scholde bi none ende</L>
<L N="704">With-oute leue of &thorn;e kinge : oute of londe wende.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;e king sende is men sone : to saisi al is lond</L>
<L>And al-so al is bischopriche : ase is traitores, In-to is hond.
<PB REF="00000175.tif" N="127"></L>
<L>&THORN;is baillifs comen to caunterburi : ase heo i-hote were.</L>
<L N="708">&para; &THORN;o heo wenden to habben al heore wille : heo founden seint thomas &thorn;ere:</L>
<L>No-&thorn;ing ne mi&yogh;ten heo saisi &thorn;o : heore wei heo hadden for-lore;</L>
<L>Also huy comen heo wenden a-&yogh;en : and tolde &thorn;e kinge fore.&mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;uyt seint thomas him bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te : &thorn;at he wolde fondi more</L>
<L N="712">&YOGH;if he mi&yogh;te of &thorn;e kinge habbe : betere grace and ore:</L>
<L>he &yogh;arknede him wel mildeliche : and to him &thorn;ane wei he nam,</L>
<L>At is manere at wodestoke : to &thorn;e kinge he cam.</L>
<L>Ase is er&thorn;eliche louerd : he grette him, faire i-nov&yogh;.</L>
<L N="716">&THORN;e king bi-heold him ful hokerliche : and a-scorn som-del lou&yogh;.</L>
<L>"thomas," he seide, "hou is &thorn;is? : beo we so grete fon</L>
<L>&THORN;at we ne mowen in one londe wonie? : thomas, hov schal &thorn;is gon?"</L>
<L>"Sire, sire," quath seint thomas : "god ne late hit neuere so beo,</L>
<L N="720">Ake god us sende, and holi churche : betere grace to &thorn;e,<MILESTONE N="69" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And sende &thorn;e wille to louien hire bet : And Iesus for is mi&yogh;te</L>
<L>Ne late me neuere a-&yogh;ein &thorn;i wille : don &thorn;ing with on-ri&yogh;te."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Erchebischop of Euerwyke : fondede for-to bringe</L>
<L N="724">A-cord and loue bi is pouwer : bi-twene thomas and &thorn;e king.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king swor a-non is oth&thorn; : &thorn;at non o&thorn;ur a-cord he nolde</L>
<L>bote &thorn;at &thorn;e status of clarindone : ech bischop holde scholde;</L>
<L>And nameliche &thorn;eos bi-fore alle o&thorn;ure : '&yogh;if a clerk hath mis-do</L>
<L N="728">And he &thorn;e kingus felun i-preoued were : and for &thorn;eof&thorn;e also,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Men him<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. him him</NOTE> scholden desordeini : and seth&thorn;e a-non &thorn;oru&yogh; lawe</L>
<L>to &thorn;e kingus baillifs deliueri him : to an-hangi o&thorn;ur to-drawe.'</L>
<L>Seint thomas i-sai&yogh; wel &thorn;o : &thorn;at &thorn;are nas wei bote on:</L>
<L N="732">O&thorn;ur he moste stif with-stonde : o&thorn;ur is ri&yogh;tes for-gon.</L>
<L>&para; he &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at he nolde neuere : holi churche bi-traye,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;at heo ne scholde beo in suyche seruage : neuere bi is daye;</L>
<L>Ra&thorn;ur he wolde, ase o&thorn;ere weren : to Martyrdom beon i-do,</L>
<L N="736">&THORN;ane holi churche were so bi-neo&thorn;e&mdash; : I-redi he was &thorn;ar-to.</L>
<L>Neuere ne mi&yogh;ten &thorn;e king ne he : no-&thorn;ing a-cordi &thorn;er,</L>
<L>Ake departeden al with wrath&thorn;e : ase heo hadden i-don ofte er.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king makede him wroth i-nov&yogh; : &thorn;at so ofte in barate was</L>
<L N="740">For o man &thorn;at him with-seide : and non o&thorn;ur a-&yogh;ein him nas:</L>
<L>In grete wrath&thorn;e he swor is oth : &thorn;at he wolde of him beon a-wreke,
<PB REF="00000176.tif" N="128"></L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;e holi Man scholde : ano&thorn;ur with him speke.</L>
<L>he let somony seint thomas : &thorn;at &thorn;e nexte &thorn;oresdaie he were</L>
<L N="744">At Norehamptoune bi-fore seint lucus dai : to &yogh;iuen him Answere;</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e bischopus of &thorn;e lond : And &thorn;e baronie al-so,</L>
<L>he het beon &thorn;are at &thorn;ulke daie : is hestes for-to do.</L>
<L>Alle seint thomas londes : in-to is hond his men nome,</L>
<L N="748">Ase it were for-to destreynen<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. destruyen</NOTE> him : &thorn;at he to his court come.</L>
<L>&para; Ore louerd helpe nou&thorn;e seint thomas : for o&thorn;ur frend nath he non,</L>
<L>A-mong so manie tyraunz for-to come : &thorn;at weren alle is fon!</L>
<L>bodi and soule he bi-tok : Iesu, godus sone,</L>
<L N="752">And to is daie ase he Isomoned was : wende to Norehamptone.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e castel sat &thorn;e motinge : of &thorn;is tyraunz ech-on.</L>
<L>&THORN;is holi man a-godes name : a-mong<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. a mond</NOTE> heom wende a-non.</L>
<L>&para; "Sire king," he seide, "god &thorn;e loke : and saui &thorn;i dignite!</L>
<L N="756">Somounz ich hadde at &thorn;is daie : here to Ansuerien &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Ake non Erchebischop of caunturburi : nas neuere i-somoned so,</L>
<L>Ne so destreyned of no king. : I not &yogh;wat &thorn;ov me &thorn;encst to do,</L>
<L>I not &yogh;wat is &thorn;e newe statuit : &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;encst forth to drawe,</L>
<L N="760">bote hit beo on of clarindone : &thorn;at &thorn;ou woldest bringe to lawe.</L>
<L>On me nast&thorn;u power non : swych destresse for-to do:</L>
<L>Heued of holi churche ich am i-maked : &thorn;ei ich onwuyrth beo &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L>And also ich am &thorn;i gostlich fader : &thorn;ei<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;ei &thorn;ou</NOTE> of me luytel &thorn;ov lete:</L>
<L N="764">It nas neuere ri&yogh;t ordre &thorn;at &thorn;e sone : is fader scholde bete,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;at desciple beote is maister. : al &thorn;is were a-&yogh;en lawe.<MILESTONE N="69b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Al &thorn;is, ho-so ri&yogh;t bi-halt : &thorn;ov bi-ginnest forth to drawe.</L>
<L>And &thorn;is bischopes al-so guod : &thorn;at wardeins beoth mid me</L>
<L N="768">to holde op &thorn;e honur of holi churche : and &thorn;e &thorn;i dignite,</L>
<L>heo beoth nou&thorn;e a-boute hire forto schende : and bringe In-to vilte.</L>
<L>gret reu&thorn;e it is &thorn;at Man schal so : hire bringe bi-ne&thorn;e for me;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ov wolt ou&yogh;t to me : &thorn;ov wost wel i-ne may nou&yogh;t fi&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="772">Ich am &yogh;are deth for-to a-fonge : for holi churche ri&yogh;te."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Rex.</NOTE>&para; "I-nelle no man," quad &thorn;e king : "for holi churche quelle.</L>
<L>beau sire, &thorn;ov spext ase a fol : a-no&thorn;ur &thorn;ov schalt me telle.</L>
<L>Acke com to-morewe bi speche-tyme&mdash; : &thorn;at &thorn;ov &thorn;inne dai ne breke!&mdash;</L>
<L N="776">And Ansuere me of o&thorn;ur &thorn;inge : &thorn;at ichulle to &thorn;e speke."</L>
<L>&THORN;us departede &thorn;e court &thorn;o. : a-morewe, &thorn;ene friday,
<PB REF="00000177.tif" N="129"></L>
<L N="778">Seint thomas wende &thorn;udere a-&yogh;en : &thorn;o he &thorn;e time i-sai.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king [sat] an hei in is sce : and a-coupede him wel faste.</L>
<L>"&THORN;ov were," he seide, "mi chaunceler&mdash; : ake al-to longe it laste,</L>
<L>Ich &thorn;e lende &thorn;o fif hondred pound : and &thorn;ov ne &yogh;olde me nou&yogh;t on:</L>
<L>Sete me &thorn;ar-of ane schorte day : for &thorn;ov schalt heom &yogh;elde ech-on."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Thomas.</NOTE>&para; "Sire, sire," quath seint thomas : "god sende us bet &thorn;in ore!</L>
<L N="784">I-ne wende neuere of &thorn;ulke panes : i-heore a-countes more.</L>
<L>For ich hadde &thorn;ulke tyme : betere grace to ov&yogh;</L>
<L>&THORN;ane ich habbe nou&thorn;e : and &thorn;at me &thorn;ingchez wou&yogh;;</L>
<L>guode grace ich hadde to &thorn;e : &thorn;ou me louedest i-nou&yogh; &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="788">&THORN;ulke panes &thorn;o &thorn;ov me &yogh;eue : and woldest &yogh;et wel mo.</L>
<L>Sire, &thorn;ar-of ich am suy&thorn;e wel a-knowe : &thorn;at ich heom a-feng of &thorn;e:</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ine &yogh;ifte with guode heorte : for-so&thorn;e &thorn;ov &yogh;eue hem me,</L>
<L>And so hei&yogh; man ase &thorn;ov art : it mi&yogh;te wel beo stille</L>
<L N="792">to Axi &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ov &yogh;eue er : with &thorn;ine so guode wille."</L>
<L>&THORN;e king him axede &yogh;if ani man : &thorn;ulke &yogh;ifte i-sai&yogh;,</L>
<L>And &yogh;we&thorn;ur he mi&yogh;te prouen &thorn;e &yogh;ifte. : Seint thomas seide nay&yogh;.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Rex.</NOTE>&para; "Nov, louerdingus," quath &thorn;e king : "alle &yogh;e i-heorez &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="796">&THORN;at of &thorn;at tresor &thorn;at he is a-knowe : &thorn;at ich him tok i-wis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;ifte ne mai he proui nou&yogh;t : Ase alle &yogh;e mowen i-seo.</L>
<L>Iugement ich axi of &thorn;is court : hou it &thorn;are-of schal beo."</L>
<L>&THORN;e court him lokede : ase he was : a-knowe of &thorn;at &thorn;ing,</L>
<L N="800">And ne mi&yogh;te nou&yogh;t &thorn;e &yogh;ifte preoui : to &yogh;elden ech fer&thorn;ing.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king him het &thorn;e panewes &yogh;elde : o&thorn;ur sikernesse him make,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur is Marschales scholden swi&thorn;e anon : is bodi to prisone take.</L>
<L>&THORN;is holi man of is bischopriche : hadde wel luytel guod,</L>
<L N="804">Ake al helples a-mong is fon : with-oute conseille he stod.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Marchales i-redie weren : to prisone him lede a-non;</L>
<L>heo heten him don heom sikernesse : o&thorn;ur he scholde with hem gon.</L>
<L>&THORN;is holi man nuste non o&thorn;ur red : bote soffri al heore wou&yogh;.</L>
<L N="808">&para; Some guode men &thorn;at &thorn;are weren : hadden of him reu&thorn;e i-nou&yogh;:</L>
<L>Fif kni&yogh;tes nomen hem to rede : and wenden to &thorn;e kingue</L>
<L>And token an hond for seint thomas : of alle &thorn;ulke &thorn;inge,<MILESTONE N="70" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>euerech of an hondret pound : for &thorn;is seli man to paie.</L>
<L N="812">&THORN;o was &thorn;is guode Man quit I-nov : ase at &thorn;ulke daie.</L>
<L>&para; A-Moruwe, &thorn;ene saturdai : to court eft-sone he wende,
<PB REF="00000178.tif" N="130"></L>
<L>For-to heore &thorn;e kingus wille : &yogh;if is heorte wolde ou&yogh;t a-mende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng sat a-doun In is sce : thomas bi-fore him stod.</L>
<L N="816">"bel ami, &thorn;ou hast," quad &thorn;e king : "i-stole me muchel guod.</L>
<L>Mi chaunceler &thorn;ov were, al-to longe : and haddest In &thorn;in hond</L>
<L>Abbeies and bischopriches : and muche del of &thorn;at lond,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ov ne &yogh;olde me &thorn;ar-of none a-countes. : &thorn;at rewez me wel sore;</L>
<L N="820">&THORN;ar-of &thorn;ritti &thorn;ousent pound : &thorn;ov me schalt, and wel more.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore make &thorn;e &yogh;are i-nov : &thorn;ine a-countes to &yogh;elde,</L>
<L>Sikur &thorn;ov beo &thorn;ov schalt it do : &yogh;if ich &thorn;e may a-welde."</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at heorden &thorn;eos demaunde : In grete wonder stoden &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And to<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> ech to o.</NOTE> o&thorn;ur seide &thorn;o : &thorn;at heo ne heorden &thorn;er-of neuer er,</L>
<L N="825">And &thorn;at seint thomas was al bi-ne&thorn;e : and ope &thorn;e pointe he was</L>
<L>to beon i-cast In prisone : for non o&thorn;ur wei &thorn;are nas.</L>
<L>Seint thomas stod In &thorn;ou&yogh;te longue : and with ri&yogh;te &thorn;e kinge bed</L>
<L N="828">&THORN;at he moste is conseil nime : of &thorn;at he hadde to him i-seid.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischopes he nam to is conseil : &thorn;e king ne wernde him nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>In one Chaumbre, faste i-loke : alle heo weren i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne scholden a-scapien : are heo hore answere seide.</L>
<L>"Nov, louerdinges," quad &thorn;is guode man : "her-of &yogh;e moten me rede.</L>
<L>For, al-so god me bringe of care : Ine habbe &thorn;ar-of gult non,</L>
<L N="834">Ake me for-to schende he axeth &thorn;is : with on-ri&yogh;te ech-on.</L>
<L>For ich was with him er wel i-nov : and &thorn;at bringeth me nou&thorn;e in teone:</L>
<L N="836">&THORN;are ne tok ich no witnesse : of &thorn;at us was bi-tweone."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Consilium. episcopus Wincestrie.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;e bischop henri of winchestre : furst bi-gan him rede.</L>
<L>"S[i]re," he seide, "&thorn;us me &thorn;inchez : &thorn;ov mi&yogh;t don of &thorn;is dede.</L>
<L>For-so&thorn;e me &thorn;inchez with gret wrong : &thorn;e calangez &thorn;e king;</L>
<L N="840">&THORN;o &thorn;ov wendest of his seruise : he ne Axede &thorn;e no-&thorn;ing,</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;ov &thorn;e bischopriche a-fenge : so clene and so freo</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ov of none o&thorn;ur &thorn;inge : ne scholdest i-charget beo;</L>
<L>And he quath &thorn;e quit al clanliche : of ech o&thorn;ur wike &thorn;er,</L>
<L N="844">An ne axede &thorn;e no-&thorn;ing : of &thorn;at &thorn;ov haddest i-don er.</L>
<L>&YOGH;ware-&thorn;oru me &thorn;inchez of none &thorn;inge : &thorn;ou ne schal<SUP>t</SUP> ansuerien nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>bote to god and holi churche&mdash; : of alle o&thorn;ere &thorn;ov art i-brou&yogh;t."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">episcopus london'.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;e bischop gilbard of londone : seide &thorn;o his a-vis:</L>
<L N="848">"Sire," he seide, "&yogh;if &thorn;ov &thorn;e bi-&thorn;enchest : ase a guod Man schal and wis,
<PB REF="00000179.tif" N="131"></L>
<L>&YOGH;wat power &thorn;e king &thorn;e hath bi-take : and to &yogh;wuche guode i-br[o]u&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Al is wille &thorn;ov most soffri : and a-&yogh;en him ne beo &thorn;ov nou&yogh;t!</L>
<L>In muche wo &thorn;ov bringst us alle : and holi churche also,</L>
<L N="852">And &thorn;in owene bodi In perile : bote &thorn;ov is wille do.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ov &thorn;is wel onder-stode : me &thorn;inchez for-so&thorn;e, i-wis,</L>
<L>&THORN;ov woldest fondi him to paye : and elles &thorn;ov dudest a-mis."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">episcopus Wincestrie.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;o seide &thorn;e bischop of wynchestre : "sire gilbert, beo stille!<MILESTONE N="70b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="856">We sospendiez swuch conseil : for it nis nou&yogh;t wurth a fille.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;e Erchebischop scholde beo : al to &thorn;e kynges wille,</L>
<L>&THORN;e honour of holi churche he lore : and is soule he mi&yogh;te so spille."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">episcopus Cicestrie.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;e bischop hyllarie of Chichestre : bi-gan to speke &thorn;o:</L>
<L N="860">"Sire," he seide, "mi conseil is : hou-so it euere go,</L>
<L>Forto fondi In faire manere : to paie &thorn;e kingues wille</L>
<L>With faire bi-heste, for-to eft-sone : &thorn;at it were sumdel stille;</L>
<L N="863">&THORN;anne we mi&yogh;ten, &yogh;wane we weren : of &thorn;usse destresse i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;e betere a-cheui In ore conseille&mdash; : for nou&thorn;e ne do we ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">episcopus lincoln'.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;e bischop Robert of lincolne : radde wel &thorn;are-to.</L>
<L>"Sire Erchebischop," he seide : "for-so&thorn;e &thorn;ov most it do;</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur &thorn;ov schalt leose &thorn;ine bischopriche : and per-Auenture &thorn;i lif;</L>
<L N="868">&THORN;anne bi-&yogh;ete &thorn;ov wel luyte : me &thorn;inchez, of &thorn;is strif."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">episcopus Exon'.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;e bischop bartholmev of Eccetre : bi-gan to segge is &thorn;ou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>"In al &thorn;e soruwe of &thorn;e world : and care we beoth i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>betere it were &thorn;at on heued : In peril him brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="872">&THORN;ane al-holie churche were bi-ne&thorn;e : and i-do to nou&yogh;te."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">episcopus Wigorn'.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;e bischop Roger of wyrecestre : longe in &thorn;ou&yogh;te stod;</L>
<L>"I-nelle ov segge on ne o&thorn;ur : for i-not &yogh;wat is guod.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ich radde him for-ta-bouwien : al-to &thorn;e kingus wille,</L>
<L N="876">Min owene Mouth him-sulf demez : al-holi churche to spille;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if ich rede a&yogh;en him to beo : In &thorn;is place sum is</L>
<L>&THORN;at wolde telle &thorn;e kinge fore : and maken him mi fo, i-wis&mdash;"</L>
<L>bi &thorn;e bischope of londone : &thorn;at ilke word he sede;</L>
<L>for he was euere a-&yogh;ein seint thomas : with wordes and with dedes.</L>
<L>"&THORN;are-fore," he seide, "on ne o&thorn;ur : I-nelle segge i-wis.</L>
<L N="882">guod conseil god us &yogh;iue&mdash; : for muche neod it is."</L>
<L>&THORN;are nas non &thorn;at cou&thorn;e is conseil : with menske bringe to ende,</L>
<L N="884">Ne &thorn;at wuste hov heo mi&yogh;ten best : ovt of &thorn;e chaumbre wende.
<PB REF="00000180.tif" N="132"></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Thomas.</NOTE>&para; At&thorn;e laste ope seint thomas : &thorn;is conseil moste al gon.</L>
<L>Tweie eorles of &thorn;e kingus hous : he let cleopie a-non,</L>
<L>"Louerdingus," he seide, "we habbez i-speke : faste of &thorn;usse &thorn;inge,</L>
<L N="888">And al-so fer forth ase we mowen : we wollez paye &thorn;e kinge.</L>
<L>Ake for we nabbeth nou&yogh;t i-redi here : ore conseil al-clene,</L>
<L>For-to &thorn;e nexte daie we biddez furst : &thorn;at &yogh;e it graunti nou&thorn;e ene."</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heom was respit i-graunted : and ech wende in is wei&yogh;e.</L>
<L N="892">Manie of seint thomas men : bi-lefden him for ei&yogh;e;</L>
<L>And kni&yogh;tes &thorn;at with him weren : alle fram him heo drowe.</L>
<L>Seint thomas nam pouere men : bi &thorn;e weie i-nowe,</L>
<L>And ladde hem to is Inne : and to &thorn;e mete heom sette;</L>
<L N="896">he seruede heom is owene bodi : And i-nov&yogh; mete and drinke heom fette.</L>
<L>"&THORN;is beoth," he seide, "godes kni&yogh;tes : &thorn;is o&thorn;ur men me habbeth for|sake.</L>
<L>&THORN;eos kni&yogh;tes ich loue more : to heom ichulle me take."</L>
<L>&THORN;ene sonenday &thorn;are nas no court i-holde : for it was an hei&yogh;-day.</L>
<L N="900">And &thorn;e Monenday sore syk : &thorn;e bischop thomas lay,<MILESTONE N="71" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In &thorn;e syknesse of maldeflanke : &thorn;at to him ofte cam</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e care &thorn;at he was Inne : wel &thorn;e worse him nam.</L>
<L>Men seiden &thorn;at he makede him sik : for he ne dorste to court wende.</L>
<L N="904">&THORN;e king in grete wrath&thorn;e i-nov&yogh; : after him gan sende.</L>
<L>"Wel &yogh;e i-seoth," quath seint thomas : "&thorn;at I-ne may come nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For-so&thorn;e to-moruwe ichulle : hov-so ich beo &thorn;udere i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei ich schulle beo &thorn;udere i-bore : In baruwe o&thorn;ur In bere,</L>
<L N="908">&THORN;udere ichulle, &thorn;oru&yogh; godes grace&mdash; : crist me helpe &thorn;ere."</L>
<L>A-morewe, &thorn;ane tywesday : ore louerd him gan a-rere,</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste dai after seint lucus dai : ase it fallez In &thorn;e &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;at dai he au&yogh;te onder-stonde : and mani an o&thorn;ur al-so:</L>
<L N="912">For bi custome alle is grete a-nuy : bi twyesdai cam him to.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e bischopes &thorn;ane tywesday : erliche to him wende,</L>
<L>And seiden, "sire, &thorn;ov art in feble point&mdash; : god it &thorn;e a-mende.</L>
<L>We habbez ore red &thorn;arof i-nome : and mid one mou&thorn;e ech-on</L>
<L N="916">to queme &thorn;e kinge we redez &thorn;e : hov-so it euere gon;</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur he &thorn;e wole bere on hond : &thorn;at &thorn;ov art is traitur,</L>
<L>And fur-swore &yogh;wore<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &yogh;wane &thorn;u swore</NOTE> him to don : eor&thorn;elich honovr,
<PB REF="00000181.tif" N="133"></L>
<L>And ne dost him non ake tricherie&mdash; : he &thorn;e wole bere on honde,</L>
<L N="920">And bi-nime &thorn;e &thorn;i stat : and perantur bringue &thorn;e out of londe."</L>
<L>&para; "Mine leoue bre&thorn;ren," quad seint thomas : "&yogh;e i-seoz wel echon</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;e world grat on me one : and alle [beoz] mine fon;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at [is] &yogh;uyt mest reu&thorn;e of alle : &thorn;at &yogh;e &thorn;at mine bre&thorn;ren beoz,</L>
<L N="924">And me, &thorn;ei ich sunful beo : ouwer fader In torment i-seoz,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e beoz mine meste fon of alle : and also &yogh;e bez al-&yogh;are</L>
<L>In seculer court to demen me : and &thorn;at nolde nou&yogh;t wel fare.</L>
<L>For &yogh;e habbez &thorn;is a-mong ov to-day : bi-speke swy&thorn;e i-lome.</L>
<L N="928">Nov god helpe al-holi churche : and take &thorn;ar-to gome!</L>
<L>Ake In obedience ich ov hote : &thorn;at &yogh;e &thorn;are-nei&yogh; ne beon</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ich am i-brou&yogh;t to Iuggement : ake &thorn;at &yogh;e ra&thorn;ur fleon.</L>
<L>And &yogh;if ani man hond on ov<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> me</NOTE> set : ich ov hote al-so</L>
<L N="932">&THORN;at &yogh;e &thorn;e sentence of holi churche : for swuche violence &yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. &yogh;e</NOTE> do;</L>
<L>And holdez vp holi churche ri&yogh;te : &thorn;at ov is bi-take&mdash;</L>
<L>Man ne schal for none drede of de&thorn;e : hire ri&yogh;tes for-sake."</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischopes weren &thorn;o wro&thorn;e i-nou&yogh; : ant wenden to court ech-one.</L>
<L N="936">Nou god helpe &thorn;is holi man : for he was &thorn;are al one!</L>
<L>bote &thorn;e bischop of wynchestre : &thorn;ere ne lefde with him nou&yogh;t on,</L>
<L>And Iocelin, &thorn;e bischop of Salesburi : &thorn;at ne weren alle fram him i-gon.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is holi man truste muche to god : and grei&thorn;ed him a-non,</L>
<L N="940">And song ane Masse of seinte steuene : are he come a-mong is fon.</L>
<L>he song &thorn;ulke masse i-lome : for al-so heo bi-ginnez,</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste offiz is propre inov : to &thorn;e stat &thorn;at he was Inne&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e bi-ginninge of &thorn;ulke masse : In englischs so is &thorn;is:</L>
<L>"For &yogh;wane &thorn;e princes habbez i-sete : and a&yogh;en heom men spekez,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> a&yogh;en me speke</NOTE> i-wis,</L>
<L>And lu&thorn;ere men pursiweden me : louerd, min help &thorn;ov beo!"<MILESTONE N="71b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg1">Ps. 119.</NOTE></L>
<L N="946">Manie seiden &thorn;at &thorn;is i-heorden : "nov&thorn;e we mouwen wel i-seo</L>
<L>&THORN;at he singuth &thorn;is Masse for &thorn;en-ones : for &thorn;e kinge and for alle his,</L>
<L N="948">And &thorn;at he halt heom alle lu&thorn;ere : &thorn;at a&yogh;en him spekez, i-wis."</L>
<L>&THORN;is word cam to court wel sone&mdash; : &yogh;ware-&thorn;oru&yogh; heo weren ech-on</L>
<L>In &thorn;e more wrath&thorn;e a-&yogh;ein him : and wel &thorn;e more is fon.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o seint thomas hadde is masse i-songue : his chesible he gan of weue;</L>
<L N="952">Alle is o&thorn;ur uestimenz : on him he let bi-leue&mdash;</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur Armure nadde he non : for holi churche to fi&yogh;te;
<PB REF="00000182.tif" N="134"></L>
<L>A-boue he caste is cope : &thorn;at bi-feol to is ri&yogh;te.</L>
<L>he tok godes flechs and is blod : with him swi&thorn;e stilleliche,</L>
<L N="956">Ane Creoyz he nam in is hond : and wende forth baldeliche.</L>
<L>&THORN;e uestimenz was is Armure : ase bi-feol to swuche ane kni&yogh;te;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fourme of &thorn;e creoiz was is baner : for holi churche to fi&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Forth wende &thorn;is guode kni&yogh;t : a-mong alle is fon&mdash;</L>
<L N="960">Swete Iesus beo is help : o&thorn;ur frend nadde he non.</L>
<L>&THORN;e creoiz in is hond he bar forth : and a-rerde op is baner.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischop Robert of hereford : bi-gan to gon him ner,</L>
<L>"Sire," he seide, "ich crie &thorn;in ore : &thorn;i chapeleyn ich mote beo,</L>
<L N="964">bi-fore &thorn;e lat me bere &thorn;e croiz : for it ne fallez nou&yogh;t to &thorn;e."</L>
<L>"&THORN;e &yogh;wyle ich hire bere," quad seint thomas : "and &thorn;e fourme i-seo,</L>
<L>Ich ne drede me of no man : &thorn;e hardiore ich may beo."</L>
<L>&THORN;anne seide &thorn;e bischop of londone : &thorn;at euere was is fo:</L>
<L N="968">"I-ne rede nou&yogh;t &thorn;at &thorn;ou bi-fore &thorn;e kingue : In swyche manere go;</L>
<L>For wrathi he wole him a-non : and a-wreken him In &thorn;e place."</L>
<L>&para; "Ich bi-take me," quath seint thomas : "al to godus grace."</L>
<L>"&THORN;ov hast euere al &thorn;i lif," &thorn;is o&thorn;ur seide : "a muche fol i-beo,</L>
<L N="972">And &thorn;i folie nelt neuere bi-leue : ase men mai nou&thorn;e i-seo."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Curia.</NOTE>&THORN;is holi Man wiz is creoiz : In-to &thorn;is court gan gon.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Rex.</NOTE>And &thorn;o &thorn;e king i-sai&yogh; him so come : he wrath&thorn;ede him a-non.</L>
<L>&para; "Louerdinges," he seide, "here &yogh;e i-seoz : hov &thorn;is man me schent!</L>
<L N="976">In &yogh;wuche manere is he In-to &thorn;is court : among us hidere i-went!</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;ei we ne lefden nou&yogh;t on cristindom : ne In godes name.</L>
<L>Ne mot ich nedes awreke me? : ne doth he me gret schame?"</L>
<L>&THORN;o seide al &thorn;e court a-non : "sire, wel &yogh;e mouwen i-seo</L>
<L N="980">&THORN;at [he] is prou&yogh;t and conteckor : and euere hath i-beo;</L>
<L>In despijt of &thorn;e and alle &thorn;ine : &thorn;is dede he hath i-do.</L>
<L>For &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt, &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t beon i-war : eft-sone to take on so,</L>
<L>to bringe men In so gret povwer : swiche ase he is,</L>
<L N="984">to beon &thorn;e hexte of &thorn;ine londe : ase &thorn;ou madest him, i-wis.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore we ne bi-menez &thorn;e nou&yogh;t : &thorn;ou noldest beo i-war bi-fore.</L>
<L>We seggez bi him echone : &thorn;at he is puyrliche for-swore:</L>
<L>And ase bi a swuch Man &thorn;ou do bi him : and ase bi &thorn;ine fon!</L>
<L N="988">For he &thorn;e swor eorth&thorn;elich honur : and nele don &thorn;e non."</L>
<L>&THORN;e budeles and &thorn;e o&thorn;ur schrewes : grenneden on him faste,
<PB REF="00000183.tif" N="135"></L>
<L>And euere a-biden &thorn;e kinges heste : In prisone him to caste.<MILESTONE N="72" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e king let crie a-non a-boute : &yogh;if ani so wod were</L>
<L>&THORN;at stode In conseile wit seint thomas : o&thorn;ur felau&yogh;schipe him bere,</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;e kingus traitour : Men scholden him nime a-non,</L>
<L N="994">And laten him al one stonde : and fondi &yogh;wodere he wolde gon (!).</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischop of Eccestre to seint thomas : he feol a-doun a-kne,</L>
<L N="996">"For godes loue &thorn;in ore! : for soruwes &thorn;at &thorn;ov mi&yogh;t i-se,</L>
<L>haue reu&thorn;e of &thorn;e and of us : o&thorn;ur &thorn;ou wolt us alle schende;</L>
<L>Alle we wor&thorn;ez i-brou&yogh;t to nou&yogh;te : bote &thorn;ov &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t wende."</L>
<L>"Sire bischop," quad seint thomas : "ase wel &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t be stille.</L>
<L N="1000">go henne fram me &yogh;if &thorn;ov wolt : and lat ech man don is wille."</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischopes wenden to-gadere ech-one : and heore conseil nome.</L>
<L>And &thorn;o heo hadden heore fourme i-set : to &thorn;e kinge a-&yogh;en heo come.</L>
<L>&para; "Sire," heo seiden, "&yogh;e beoth a-nuyd : and &thorn;at us for-&thorn;inchez sore;</L>
<L N="1004">For-&yogh;if us &thorn;at &yogh;e on us berez : we nellez &thorn;e mis-don non-more.</L>
<L>Wel we wutez &thorn;at &thorn;is wrechche : &thorn;at scholde ore chief beo,</L>
<L>he is fals and for-sworen : and [&thorn;at]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> mai ech man wel i-seo:</L>
<L>For he suor to holde &thorn;e eor&thorn;elich honur : and hath i-broke is oth;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at man mai wel proui on him : &yogh;if &yogh;e nellez nou&yogh;t beo wroth.</L>
<L>Fur-&yogh;if us &thorn;ine wrath&thorn;e, we biddez &thorn;e : ant to rome we wollez wende</L>
<L N="1010">to bi-nimen him is Erchebischopriche : and ase a wrechche him schende:</L>
<L>Puyrliche for-suore we schullen him preoui : sire king, bi eovwer rede."</L>
<L N="1012">&THORN;e king bi-het heom gret honur : to don &thorn;at ilke dede.</L>
<L>to seint thomas, &thorn;are he was : heo wenden alle a-non.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischop hyllarie of Chichestre : tolde for heom ech-on.</L>
<L>"Sire," he seide, "ore gostliche fader : &thorn;ov were here-bi-fore,</L>
<L N="1016">For fader we fur-saketh [&thorn;e] : &thorn;ov art fals and for-swore.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou suore &thorn;e kynge eor&thorn;elich honour : and nelt don him non.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore to &thorn;e court of rome : we bi-cleopiez &thorn;e echon,</L>
<L>to ansuerien us bi-fore &thorn;e pope : of &thorn;at &thorn;ov hast ido a-mis."</L>
<L N="1020">"Louerdingus," quath &thorn;is holie man : "ich i-heore wel al &thorn;is."</L>
<L>&para; Nov suete Ihesu beo is freond : &yogh;wane alle o&thorn;ure were is fon!</L>
<L>&THORN;e king him let cleopien faste : &thorn;at he come forth a-non.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Eorl Robert of lecestre : and o&thorn;ur men mani on</L>
<L N="1024">Comen after him and heten him sone : bi-fore &thorn;e kingue gon.
<PB REF="00000184.tif" N="136"></L>
<L>"Louerdingues," quath seint thomas : "&yogh;e wuyten wel ech-on</L>
<L>hou wel ich was with &thorn;e king : &thorn;ei ich habbe nou&thorn;e manie fon:</L>
<L>Erchebischop he made me&mdash; : for-so&thorn;e a-&yogh;ein mi wille,</L>
<L N="1028">For euere ich dradde for oncunninge : mi soule forto spille.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o axede ich bifore al &thorn;at folk : In &yogh;wuche manere he me toke</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maistrie of holi churche : to wardi and to loke.</L>
<L>holi churche me was bi-take : In eche manere so freo,</L>
<L N="1032">&THORN;at ich were quit of alle o&thorn;ure courtes&mdash; : and &yogh;eot with ri&yogh;te it scholde so beo.</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane holi churche is so freo : I-nelle ansuerien &thorn;e kingue</L>
<L>Ne non o&thorn;ur in his court : of none eor&thorn;eliche &thorn;inge.</L>
<L>For gold ne passez nou&yogh;t so muche : In bounte led, i-wis,<MILESTONE N="72b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1036">Al-so dignete of &thorn;e preost : herre &thorn;ane &thorn;e kingus is.</L>
<L>And is gostliche fader ich am : &yogh;if he wolde nime &yogh;eme,</L>
<L>And it nere no lawe &thorn;at &thorn;e sone : &thorn;e fader scholde deme.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore i segge at o word : &thorn;at I-nelle me no-&thorn;ing take</L>
<L N="1040">to Iuggement of kingus court : ake clanliche it wolle for-sake,</L>
<L>And take me to holi churche : and to none er&thorn;eliche dome:</L>
<L>And Ich bi-cleopie ov here ech-one : to &thorn;e court of rome.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e stat of holi churche : and al mi dignite</L>
<L N="1044">&para; &THORN;oru&yogh; Ihesu crist it beo i-wardet : &yogh;wan it ne mai o&thorn;ur beo.</L>
<L>And ou bischopus ich bi-cleopie : to &thorn;e court of rome also,</L>
<L>for &yogh;e Anourieth more ane er&thorn;eliche king : &thorn;ane &yogh;e god al-mi&yogh;ti do.</L>
<L>And so &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e ri&yogh;te of holi churche : fram &thorn;is court ich wende,</L>
<L N="1048">to bringe &thorn;eos cause of holi churche : bi-fore &thorn;e pope to ende."</L>
<L>&THORN;is holi Man wel mildeliche : out of &thorn;is court gan gon.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king, and &thorn;at mid him was : wrath&thorn;eden heom a-non;</L>
<L>heo criden on &thorn;is holi man : and beleweden ech-on</L>
<L N="1052">Wit Also<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. A<SUP>h</SUP>so</NOTE> grete noyse : ase anie Men mi&yogh;ten don;</L>
<L>heo ne mi&yogh;ten makie non more cri : &thorn;ei al &thorn;e toun were a-fuyre,</L>
<L>Ase<NOTE PLACE="marg1">al. &thorn;ane</NOTE> heo duden opon &thorn;is holi man : &thorn;at wide men it mi&yogh;ten i-huyre.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode man eode softe forth : ase him no-&thorn;ing ne rou&yogh;te&mdash;</L>
<L>for &yogh;uyt more men schenden Ihesu crist : &thorn;o men him to de&thorn;e brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>he werth opon is palefrai : and to is Inne he wende also.</L>
<L N="1058">Vnne&thorn;e he mi&yogh;te with is hondene : &thorn;eos &thorn;re &thorn;ingus do:</L>
<L>blessi &thorn;at folk and bere &thorn;e croiz : and is bridel wisse.
<PB REF="00000185.tif" N="137"></L>
<L N="1060">&THORN;at simple folk orn a-bouten him : with Ioye i-nov&yogh; and blisse;</L>
<L>for heo wenden &thorn;at he hadde i-beo : at&thorn;e court faste i-nome,</L>
<L>heo &thorn;onkeden muche Ihesu crist : &thorn;at he moste a-mong heom come.</L>
<L>&para; to is In, at seint Andreues : heo siweden him faste i-nov&yogh;;</L>
<L>Seint thomas alle &thorn;e pouere men : with him to &thorn;e mete he drov&yogh;,</L>
<L>And seide, "comiez here forth with me : for mine freond &yogh;e beoth;</L>
<L N="1066">Ine habbe none freond bote eov : ase alle men nou&thorn;e i-seoth."</L>
<L>he let heom Alle fede wel : a gret hous-ful nei&yogh;;</L>
<L N="1068">&THORN;e guode man wel &thorn;e gladdore was : &thorn;at he heom alle i-sei&yogh;.</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;is holi man sat at is mete : &thorn;ei he grete wille &thorn;er-to nadde,</L>
<L>&THORN;is word &thorn;at ore louerd het : is redare bi-fore him radde:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;if Men ov pursiwiet In one toune : In-to ano&thorn;ur toun &yogh;e fleo."</L>
<L>&THORN;is holi man &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at bi him-self : &thorn;at word mi&yogh;te wel soth beo</L>
<L>And &thorn;at it godes wille was : In-to An o&thorn;ur londe gon,</L>
<L N="1074">As &thorn;e holi godspel seith : a man for-to fleo is fon.</L>
<L>&THORN;is holi man was &thorn;o wel &thorn;e hardiore : of londe for-to wende,</L>
<L N="1076">&YOGH;wane he mi&yogh;te a-schapie wel : and god wolde &thorn;e time sende.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o it was to-war[d] eue : twei seriaunz &thorn;are come,</L>
<L>Sore weopinde, and warneden him : &thorn;at he sum red him nome,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e kyngus Men hadden i-swore : &thorn;oru&yogh; heste of &thorn;e kinge,</L>
<L N="1080"><MILESTONE N="73" UNIT="folio">&YOGH;ware-so heo him mi&yogh;ten finde : to stronge de&thorn;e him bringe.</L>
<L>Seint thomas &thorn;ou&yogh;te an-o&thorn;ur. : he let maken is bed a&yogh;en ni&yogh;t</L>
<L>Op In&thorn;e heie churche : bi-twene twei weuedes ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;o alle o&thorn;ur men weren a-slepe : and no man nas him nei&yogh;,</L>
<L N="1084">he aros up and bi-heold : on &thorn;e ymage an hei&yogh;;</L>
<L>bi-fore &thorn;e auter he feol don a-kne : and on ore louerd bi-gan to crie,</L>
<L>And formest he seide &thorn;e seuen salmes : and seth&thorn;e &thorn;e letanie;</L>
<L>Al wepind ech haluwe he bad : is help for-to beo;</L>
<L N="1088">bi-fore ech ymage he op aros : and eft he sat a-doun a-kne.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he hadde iseid is beden : stilleliche he gan gon,</L>
<L>A luyte bi-fore &thorn;e cockes crowe : out of &thorn;e churche a-non,</L>
<L>And wende him out-ward of engelonde : &thorn;at no man with him nas</L>
<L N="1092">bote a frere of Semplingham : &thorn;at wel priue to him was.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode Man flev al Engelond : for holi churche ri&yogh;te;</L>
<L>Of al is wo ne &yogh;af he nou&yogh;t : &yogh;if he it a-mendi mi&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e ti&thorn;ingue cam of &thorn;is cas : to &thorn;e kingue ful sone.
<PB REF="00000186.tif" N="138"></L>
<L N="1096">&THORN;e hei&yogh;e men nomen heore red : &yogh;wat were &thorn;ar-of to done.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king and al is baronie : and &thorn;e bischopes echon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at au&yogh;ten with seint thomas habbe i-be : and weren mest is fon,</L>
<L>to &thorn;is conseil euer-ech-one : heo concenteden at &thorn;en ende:</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e king scholde of is hexte Men : to &thorn;e court of rome sende</L>
<L>A-&yogh;en him &yogh;wane [he] &thorn;udere come : and &thorn;e pope don onder-stonde</L>
<L N="1102">&THORN;at he was fals and for-swore : and destourbour of &thorn;e londe.</L>
<L>For-to don &thorn;is grete neode : &thorn;e wiseste Men heo nome,</L>
<L N="1104">And &thorn;at is &thorn;ing were al in pais : for-to heo a&yogh;en come.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Erchebischop of Euerwike : and &thorn;e bischop of Eccestre</L>
<L>to rome<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. rome rome</NOTE> heo wenden for &thorn;is neodes : and &thorn;e bischop of Cicestre</L>
<L>And &thorn;e bischop of londone : and of winchestre al-so,</L>
<L N="1108">And also eorles and barouns : and manie clerkes &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>to beren witnesse of &thorn;e fals-hede : &yogh;wane heo to court come.</L>
<L>Noble &yogh;iftes and o&thorn;ur Iueles : with hem al-so heo nome&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;are-with man mai ofte at court : &thorn;e ri&yogh;te bringe to wou&yogh;.</L>
<L N="1112">Nou&yogh; crist helpe &thorn;is holi man : for he is &yogh;uyt pouere i-nou&yogh;!</L>
<L>he nadde none &yogh;iftes forto &yogh;iue : to holden up is ri&yogh;te;</L>
<L>Fram Norehamptone bar he eode : for holi churche to fi&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&para; Fram seint Andreues &thorn;is holi man : of Norehamptone he wende</L>
<L N="1116">With a frere of Semplingham : are god &thorn;ane dai heom sende.</L>
<L>Fiue and twenti mile he wende : to &thorn;e toune of graham</L>
<L>Are he stunte in anie stude : with &thorn;e frere of Sempringham&mdash;</L>
<L>Al North-ward he drou&yogh; him furst : a-wei al fram &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e kinges Men ne scholden him finde : to nimen ne for-to sle.</L>
<L>Seth&thorn;e he wende fram graham : fiue and tuenti Mile al-so</L>
<L N="1122">to &thorn;e toun<NOTE PLACE="marg1">added later.</NOTE> of lincolne : are he wolde reste i-fo.</L>
<L>&THORN;ene moruwe ope seint lucus day&mdash; : tiwes-dai it was &thorn;o,</L>
<L>he departede fram &thorn;e kingus court : with much seoruwe and wo<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. we</NOTE>;</L>
<L>his wei &thorn;ane wodnes-ni&yogh;t : out of &thorn;e toune he nam;<MILESTONE N="73b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1126">Sone morewe &thorn;ene &thorn;ores-dai : to lincolne he cam:</L>
<L>At one follares house : his In he nam ri&yogh;t &thorn;are.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">&thorn;are <I>corr. to</I> &thorn;ere</NOTE></L>
<L N="1128">And bi ni&yogh;te euere he eode is wei : &thorn;at he a-waited ne ware.</L>
<L>At lincolne he dude him into watere : are god &thorn;ane dai sende,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ane fridai fourti mile : al bi watere he wende,</L>
<L>to &thorn;e Ermitage of Sempling-ham : &thorn;at a-midde &thorn;e watere is;
<PB REF="00000187.tif" N="139"></L>
<L N="1132">And &thorn;are he bi-lefde al hardiliche : &thorn;re dawes, i-wis.</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e he wende to seint botulf : &thorn;at was heonnes ouer ten mile:</L>
<L>&THORN;are he dude him eft In-to watere : and cam in a luytel &yogh;wile</L>
<L>to &thorn;e hous of hauer-holt : &thorn;at of Simpling-ham is&mdash;</L>
<L N="1136">&THORN;e frere him ladde bi &thorn;ulke house : &thorn;e sikerore to beon, i-wis.</L>
<L>Fram &thorn;annes he wende to eistre&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. estreye</NOTE> : his o maner with ri&yogh;te,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Erchebischopes of kaunterburi : &yogh;if he hadde ani mi&yogh;te;</L>
<L>&THORN;are he was nei&yogh; &thorn;e se i-nov&yogh; : he a-bod wel &thorn;ere</L>
<L>And a-waitede is point to passi ouer : &yogh;wane hit best tyme were.</L>
<L>&para; Seue-ni&yogh;t he bi-lefde &thorn;are : for-to alle soulene dai;</L>
<L N="1142">In A Chaumbre ri&yogh;t bi &thorn;e churche : dai&yogh; and ni&yogh;t he lai,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no man no scholde him onder-&yogh;ite : ne i-war of him beo;</L>
<L N="1144">&THORN;oru&yogh; &thorn;e churche he made an hol : &thorn;e sacringe for-to seo</L>
<L>And for-to heren &thorn;are is masse&mdash; : and Men &thorn;at to churche come</L>
<L>Nusten nou&yogh;t &thorn;at he was so nei&yogh; : ne &thorn;er-of heo ne token none gome.</L>
<L>An alle soulene dai, &thorn;ene tywesdai&yogh; : are god &thorn;ene dai sende,</L>
<L N="1148">he bi-tok god al holi churche : and In-to &thorn;e se he wende.</L>
<L>heo roweden forth al &thorn;ane dai : and a-&yogh;en &thorn;e eueninge</L>
<L>bi-sides ane hauene heo a-riueden : &thorn;at men cleopez graueninge,</L>
<L>In Flaundres, ase god it wolde. : bote hors ne hadde he non:</L>
<L N="1152">&THORN;is holi man al a-fote : forth is wei gan gon.</L>
<L>&THORN;at no man ne scholde him knowe : &thorn;e Abite of frere he nam</L>
<L>And al-so a frere forth he eode : &thorn;o he to Flaundres cam.</L>
<L>blac was is cope a-boue : is Cuyrtel &yogh;wijt blaunket;</L>
<L N="1156">Opon is rugge is cope he bar : &yogh;if he mi&yogh;te go &thorn;e bet.</L>
<L>&THORN;e reyn was gret and suy&thorn;e st[r]ong : and &thorn;e wei ful deop:</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e weri was &thorn;e holi man : onne&thorn;e he bar up is fet.</L>
<L>he was so trauailled In &thorn;e weie : and in &thorn;e se bi-fore,</L>
<L N="1160">&THORN;at he sat a-doun and ne mi&yogh;te no fer : bote he were i-bore.</L>
<L>&THORN;o wende forth a man, &thorn;at with him eode : and huyrde him a mere,</L>
<L>For an Englichs peni, with an haltre : &thorn;is holi man to bere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e holi Man is clo&thorn;es tok : and op-on &thorn;e Mere heom caste,</L>
<L>And werth op a-boue alle is clo&thorn;es : and rod him forth wel faste.</L>
<L>&para; Allas &thorn;at suych a noble man : vuele was it is ri&yogh;te</L>
<L N="1166">So febleliche ouer lond to wende&mdash; : wel muche is godes mi&yogh;te;</L>
<L>Vuele was it is ri&yogh;te to gon a-fote : o&thorn;ur ope swuch a best to ride&mdash;
<PB REF="00000188.tif" N="140"></L>
<L N="1168">holi churche he a-bou&yogh;te deore : &thorn;at men tellez of wel wide!</L>
<L>With one haltre ope &thorn;e mere : forth rod &thorn;is holi man</L>
<L>As &thorn;ei it were a frere, and let him cleopie : frere cristian;<MILESTONE N="74" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For he nolde nou&yogh;t lie : &thorn;at cristian he was,</L>
<L>And he was a-drad to beon i-knowe : &yogh;if man cleopede him thomas.</L>
<L>At one gode mannes house : his In a-ni&yogh;t he nam;</L>
<L N="1174">At &thorn;e bordes ende he sat : Ase vuele it him bi-cam,</L>
<L>And al with-Inne seten is men : as &thorn;ei he lowest were.</L>
<L N="1176">his oste nam wel gode &yogh;eme : hov heo heom alle bere.</L>
<L>he tok kepe of &thorn;e holi man : &thorn;at sat at&thorn;e bordes ende,</L>
<L>hou milde he was a-mong alle : and mest corteis and hende,</L>
<L>And hou hendeliche he delde is mete : heom &thorn;at bi-fore him stode,</L>
<L N="1180">And hov luytel he .et. him-selue : with wel simple mode;</L>
<L>his limes al-so he bi-heold : hou faire heo weren and freo,</L>
<L>&THORN;e hondene faire and longe fingres : fairore ne mi&yogh;ten none beo;</L>
<L>his face was brod and long al-so : his fore-heued large i-nov&yogh;:</L>
<L N="1184">And euere mest bi-fore alle o&thorn;ere : is heorte to him drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&para; Of &thorn;e Erchebischope of Caunterburi : he gan him vnderstonde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it was couth ouer-al aboute : &thorn;at he was i-wend out of londe:</L>
<L>his heorte him bar &thorn;at it was he. : In gret studie he was i-brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="1188">he rounede in is wiues ere : and tolde hire al is &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>his wijf after &thorn;ulke tyme : &thorn;at so&thorn;e al-so &thorn;ou&yogh;te:</L>
<L>heo bi-gan to serui &thorn;is holi man : and deinte&thorn;es to him brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Applene. &amp; peoren. and notes also : and fondede in alle manere</L>
<L N="1192">A-mong alle &thorn;is o&thorn;ur men : to gladien wel &thorn;ene frere;</L>
<L>heo bi-lefde to serui alle &thorn;e o&thorn;ere : and opon him was al hire &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Seint thomas it vnder-&yogh;at : and &thorn;are-with ne paide him nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he bi-heold a-boute : a-non after soper,</L>
<L N="1196">Wel mildeliche he bad is oste : for-to comen him ner</L>
<L>And to sitte bi him a-doun : for solaz, one stounde.</L>
<L>"A, sire, merci," quad &thorn;is oste : "Ichulle sitte on &thorn;e grounde,</L>
<L>And sat him a-doun at is fet. : seint thomas him bad arise.</L>
<L N="1200">"Certes, sire," quad &thorn;is oste : "I-nelle In none wise.</L>
<L>&para; Nolde god &thorn;at ich bi &thorn;e sete! : mi louerd, i-hered &thorn;ou beo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at In mine house &thorn;ov scholdest come : and &thorn;at ich &thorn;ane dai mi&yogh;te i-seo."
<PB REF="00000189.tif" N="141"></L>
<L>"Luyte deinte," quat seint thomas : "of a swuch pouere man,</L>
<L N="1204">Of swuch a frere ase ich am : i-cleoped frere cristian."</L>
<L>"Sire, &thorn;in ore," quat<SUP>h</SUP> &thorn;is oste : "wel ich onderstonde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ov art Erchebischop of Caunterburi : i-wend out of engelonde."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;wy seist&thorn;ov so?" quad seint thomas : "&thorn;ov hauest selde i-sei&yogh;e</L>
<L>&THORN;ene Erchebischop of caunterburi : wende in swuche manere bi weie!"</L>
<L>"Sire," quad &thorn;e oste, "&thorn;ov it art : al-so me seith mi &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And ich bidde &thorn;e for &thorn;e loue of god : ne with-sak it a-&yogh;ein me nou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>&THORN;is holi man him bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te : &thorn;at o&thorn;ur he moste lie</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur beo bi-knowe &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. heo</NOTE> it was : so heo gonnen on heom<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> so &thorn;e o&thorn;er gan on him</NOTE> crie.</L>
<L>Ate laste he was a-knowe : ake with him a-morewe he nam</L>
<L N="1214">his oste, &thorn;at he ne scholde him wrei&yogh;e : forto he aftur<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. a fer</NOTE> weie cam.</L>
<L>to [&thorn;e] Abbeie of seint Bertin : &thorn;is holi man i-wende,<MILESTONE N="74b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;are he bi-lefde : forto ore louerd o&thorn;ur grace him sende.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischopus of engelonde : and &thorn;e barones al-so,</L>
<L N="1218">toward &thorn;e court of rome he<SUP>o</SUP> wenden : heore erinde forto do.</L>
<L>to &thorn;e kinge of Fraunce heo comen : and lettres with heom bere</L>
<L N="1220">fram &thorn;e king of engelond : &thorn;at &thorn;us muche an Englisch were :</L>
<L>"to is louerd &thorn;oru&yogh; godes grace : sire lowis &thorn;e kinge,</L>
<L>henri king of engelonde : sende loue and gretinge.</L>
<L>&para; Thomas, &thorn;at Erchebischop was : of caunterburi bi-fore,</L>
<L N="1224">Out of mine londe he is i-wend : ase mi traitore and for-suore.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore ase min er&thorn;eliche louerd : ich bidde &thorn;e bi mine sonde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ov ne suffri nou&yogh;t &thorn;at he beo : Irecetted In &thorn;ine londe."</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is king &thorn;is bone i-heorde : ane &yogh;wile in &thorn;ou&yogh;te he stod.</L>
<L N="1228">"Certes," he seide, "ase me &thorn;inchez : &thorn;is bone nis no-&thorn;ing god.</L>
<L>So strong &thorn;eof nis non in engelonde : &yogh;if he in Fraunce come,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne mi&yogh;te In Fraunce duelle : ase heo doth i-lome;</L>
<L>And wel ra&thorn;ur scholde a suych hei&yogh; man : ne come he no so sone.</L>
<L N="1232">Ake no&thorn;ur ich ne &thorn;e king of engelonde : with ore bischopes nabbez to done;</L>
<L>For mine bischopes with holi churche : heore wille ich late heom do,</L>
<L>And fairore were &thorn;e kinge anouri him : and late him i-wor&thorn;e also."</L>
<L>&para; Ne mi&yogh;ten &thorn;is hei&yogh;e men of him : non o&thorn;ur word a fonge;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he<SUP>o</SUP> wenden forth heore wei : &thorn;o heo hadden a-bide longe.</L>
<L>Maister herebard of Boseham : and o&thorn;ure seth&thorn;e i-wende
<PB REF="00000190.tif" N="142"></L>
<L>to &thorn;e kinge lowis of Fraunce : ase seint thomas him sende,</L>
<L>And tolden &thorn;e kinge of al &thorn;e wo : &thorn;at seint thomas hadde with wou&yogh;.</L>
<L N="1240">&THORN;e king weop, &thorn;o he i-heorde &thorn;is : and made deol inou&yogh;,</L>
<L>And tolde heom hov &thorn;e kingus men : at him weren bi-fore,</L>
<L>And &yogh;wuch ansuere he heom &yogh;af : &thorn;at heore [wei]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> was for-lore.</L>
<L>&THORN;is gode men with ioie inov : heore leue of him heo nome,</L>
<L N="1244">And &thorn;annes heo wenden sone i-nou&yogh; : to &thorn;e court of rome.</L>
<L>&THORN;are neren heo nou&yogh;t faire onder-fonge : for &thorn;e bischopes comen bi-fore</L>
<L>And desclaundreden seint thomas : &thorn;at he was fals and for-suore.</L>
<L>Ake na&thorn;eles &thorn;e grace heo hadden : &thorn;at to &thorn;e pope heo mi&yogh;ten go.</L>
<L N="1248">him-sulue heo tolden in priuete : al seint thomases wo:</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e status of clarindone : hou heo furst forth come,</L>
<L>And hou he was i-brou&yogh;t at norehamptone : bi-fore &thorn;e kinge to dome,</L>
<L>And hov he wende out of engelonde : In muchele miseise and wo,</L>
<L N="1252">And al-hov he chaungede is name : &thorn;e sikerloker forto go.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">papa.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;e pope bi-gan to siche sore : and<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> with ful dreori &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;e teres fullen out of is ei&yogh;ene : he ne mi&yogh;te with-holden heom nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1255">he &thorn;onkede god &thorn;at swuch a prelat : under him moste beo,</L>
<L>So studefast to holi churche : and &thorn;at he mi&yogh;te &thorn;ane dai i-seo.&mdash;</L>
<L>A-morewe comen &thorn;is bischopes : and &thorn;e eorles also,</L>
<L>To procuri seint thomas al &thorn;at vuel : &thorn;at heo mi&yogh;ten do;</L>
<L>bi-fore &thorn;e pope, ase [he] sat : ful nobleliche heo come,</L>
<L N="1260">And bi-fore &thorn;e cardinales : and al &thorn;e court of rome.<MILESTONE N="75" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">episcopus london'.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;e bischop of londone : &thorn;at euere lu&thorn;ur was,</L>
<L>bi-gan formest to telle is tale : a-&yogh;ein seint thomas.</L>
<L>he stod up bi-fore al &thorn;e court : "beu pere," a-non he seide,</L>
<L>"To &thorn;e we comieth to make ore mone : of strong lif &thorn;at we ledez.</L>
<L>Ower ri&yogh;te it is up to holde : alle &thorn;at guode beoth,</L>
<L N="1266">And foles to bringuen of heore folie : &yogh;wane &yogh;e heom i-seoth.</L>
<L>A destaunce &thorn;are is i-sproungue : li&yogh;tliche in Engelonde,</L>
<L N="1268">&THORN;at destourbez al &thorn;at lond : with onri&yogh;te, ich onder-stonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Erchebischop of Caunterburi : is al a&yogh;ein ore wille,</L>
<L>Folliche he bi-gan In engelonde : holi churche for-to spille,</L>
<L N="1271">And to bi-nime &thorn;e kynge is fraunchise : and is ri&yogh;tes also.</L>
<L>Ake he ne mi&yogh;te us make for no-&thorn;ing : concenti &thorn;er-to.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">This verse on the margin.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000191.tif" N="143"></L>
<L>And for wrath&thorn;e &thorn;at we nolden : alle is wille do,</L>
<L>Op-on us he caste is owene gult : and opon &thorn;e kinge also.</L>
<L>And at&thorn;e laste, ase &thorn;ei it were : &thorn;ut lond forto blende,</L>
<L N="1276">&THORN;o noman ne dude him strenc&thorn;e : of londe he gan i-wende:</L>
<L>for men nusten nou&yogh;t &thorn;e so&thorn;e : &thorn;at heo scholden onder-stonde</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e king him dude onri&yogh;th : and driue him out of londe."</L>
<L>&THORN;o he hadde al is tale i-told : and i-maked is grete wise,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">episcopus Chichestrie.</NOTE>he sat a-doun; an &thorn;e bischop of chichestre : sone gan op a-rise.</L>
<L>&para; "bev pere," he seide to &thorn;e pope : "me &thorn;inchez it fallez to &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1282">To on-don ech &thorn;ing &thorn;at fallez to harme : In &thorn;e communaute,</L>
<L>&THORN;at o Man ne beo i-soffred : to gon forth mid is wille,</L>
<L N="1284">to bring al &thorn;at lond to schame : and holi churche to spille.</L>
<L>&THORN;at hath &thorn;e Erchebischop i-&thorn;ou&yogh;t : and &thorn;at is i-sene, i-wis,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane ech man of al &thorn;at lond : faste a-&yogh;ein him is."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Archiepiscopus Eboracensis.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;e Erchebischop of Euerwike : &thorn;o he is tyme i-sei&yogh;,</L>
<L N="1288">Aros op and bi-gan to telle : is tale al on hei&yogh;.</L>
<L>"Sire," he seide, "no man ne knoweth : so wel ase ich do</L>
<L>&THORN;ene Erchebischop of Caunterburi : ne &thorn;e bischopriche al-so.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Erchebischop is willesful : and &yogh;wane he is alles i-brou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1292">In ani wille &thorn;at is luytel wuyrth : he nele bi-leue it nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;at man ne may for no-&thorn;ing : bringe him of is &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>he is nou&thorn;e In swuyche folie&mdash; : &thorn;at we habbeth deore a-bou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>li&yogh;tliche he is &thorn;are-Inne i-come : ake he it nele lete neuere mo,</L>
<L N="1296">bot &yogh;e &thorn;oru&yogh; ower pouwer : bringe us out of wo."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">episcopus Exon'.</NOTE>&para; "Sire," quath &thorn;e bischop of eccetre : baldeliche he spac &thorn;o,</L>
<L>"&THORN;is cas &yogh;e moten a-mendi sone : hov-so it euere go.</L>
<L>And &yogh;e ne leuen nou&yogh;t &thorn;e so&thorn;e : &thorn;at men doth ov to onder-stonde,</L>
<L N="1300">Send with us fot with fot : ane legat in-to Engelonde,</L>
<L>And lat him of-gropi &thorn;e so&thorn;e &thorn;ere : and &thorn;are-after &thorn;u lat him wurche.</L>
<L>for-so&thorn;e, bote &yogh;e &thorn;aron<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> o&thorn;er</NOTE> &thorn;enche : &yogh;e schendez holi churche."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Comes Arondelie</NOTE>&para; &THORN;e Eorl of Arundel aros op &thorn;o : a man of gret dignete.</L>
<L N="1304">"Sires," he seide, "for godes<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. guodes</NOTE> loue : ane stounde herkneth me!</L>
<L>&THORN;e lewede Men &thorn;at here beoth : &thorn;at ne connen latin non,</L>
<L>We ne onder-stondez nou&yogh;t : of &thorn;at &yogh;e habbez i-told ech-on;<MILESTONE N="75b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ake In langage &thorn;at we conne : swuche men ase we beoth,</L>
<L N="1308">hei&yogh;e barouns and noble kni&yogh;tes : ase &yogh;e nou&thorn;e i-seoth,
<PB REF="00000192.tif" N="144"></L>
<L>&para; Tellen ichulle for us alle : &yogh;wy we beoth hidere i-wend.</L>
<L>For ore louerd &thorn;e king of Engelonde : &THORN;at hauez us hidere i-send</L>
<L>to schewi furst &thorn;e reuerence : and grete loue also</L>
<L N="1312">&THORN;at he hath to eov i-bore : and euere he &thorn;enchez to do;</L>
<L>And &thorn;are-of he sent &thorn;e word bi us : ase we bi-fore &thorn;e stondez,</L>
<L>Eorles, barones, and bischopes : &thorn;e hexte of &thorn;e londe&mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he hadde ani herre i-haued : hidere he hadden i-wend.</L>
<L N="1316">Ake to one so hei&yogh;e court ase &thorn;eos is : he hath us hidere i-sent,</L>
<L>to schewi eov furst in his name : &thorn;at, also wid ase &thorn;e world is,</L>
<L>So trewe prince nis onder god : ne &thorn;at so muche ov loueth, i-wis,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;at so muche Anoureth holi churche : and euere hath i-do.</L>
<L N="1320">&THORN;e Erchebischop of Caunterburi : is a noble man also,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &yogh;if omanere of him nere : ase ich me onder-stonde,</L>
<L>&THORN;are nere no lond In cristinedom : a-&yogh;einest engelonde,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. engelonge</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne holi churche so wel i-wust : and i-schild fram ech wou&yogh;,</L>
<L N="1324">Onder noble prince and prelat : bo&thorn;e guode men i-nou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;es thomas, &thorn;is guode Erchebischop : so hath a luyte wille,</L>
<L>&THORN;at muchel a-peirez his guodnesse : and bi-guynneth &thorn;at lond to spille.</L>
<L>his wille is suych &thorn;at, &yogh;wane he is : icomen in fole &thorn;ou&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">This verse on the margin.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1328">he nele &thorn;oru&yogh; conseil ne &thorn;oru&yogh; no rerd : &thorn;arof beo i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>In swuche folie he is nou&thorn;e i-come&mdash; : ore louerd is &thorn;ou&yogh;t wende!</L>
<L>bote men mouwen is &thorn;ou&yogh;t wenden : &thorn;at lond he wole al schende.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-for mi louerd &thorn;e king ov bit : &thorn;at &yogh;e with us sende</L>
<L N="1332">Ane legat into engelonde : to ofgropi al &thorn;en ende,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur certus he is ope &thorn;e poynte : al &thorn;at lond to spille;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &yogh;e him chasti &thorn;oru&yogh; ri&yogh;te lawe : &amp; bi-nime him is fole wille."</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e clerkes &thorn;at &thorn;are seten : non of heom &thorn;ar nas</L>
<L N="1336">&THORN;at ne preisede muche &thorn;is hei&yogh;e man : for he so renable was.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">papa.</NOTE>&para; "Louerdingues," quath &thorn;e pope : "wel we onder-stondez i-nou&yogh;</L>
<L>&THORN;at [&yogh;e] to-ward &thorn;e Erchebischop tellez : with ri&yogh;te o&thorn;ur with wou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Ake we ne mouwen &thorn;ar-of non dom &yogh;iue : bote him-sulue here were,</L>
<L N="1340">For we ne mowen bi-hinden him no Iuggement &yogh;yue : ne no ri&yogh;t i-wis it nere."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">comes.</NOTE>&para; "Sire," quath &thorn;e Eorl of Arundel : "&yogh;e moten bet onder-stonde.</L>
<L>A certein dai us is i-set : to come in-to engelonde,
<PB REF="00000193.tif" N="145"></L>
<L>And &thorn;ane dai ne dorre we nou&yogh;t breke : for ore louerd &thorn;e kingue.</L>
<L N="1344">&THORN;are-fore &yogh;e moten us grace don : sumdel of &thorn;is &thorn;inge:</L>
<L>&YOGH;e moten, &yogh;if it is ower wille : ane legat wis<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. wiz</NOTE> us sende,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ene Erchebischope hoten also : to Engelonde i-wende;</L>
<L>And ase &thorn;e legat &thorn;are enquereth : &thorn;ar-aftur he mai do."</L>
<L N="1348">&para; "Certes, beu frere," quat &thorn;e pope : "I-nelle nou&yogh;t take on so.</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane &thorn;e erchebischop hidere comez : I-not &yogh;wat he wole telle;</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore are ich i-heore him speke : no-&thorn;ing don &thorn;ar-of i-nelle."</L>
<L>"Certes, sire," seide &thorn;is o&thorn;ur : "we ne dorren a-bide nou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>"Nov de pardeus," quath &thorn;e pope : "doth ase &yogh;e habbeth i-&thorn;ou&yogh;t!"<MILESTONE N="76" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;is o&thorn;ure weren wro&thorn;e i-nou&yogh;. : wel faire heore leue heo nome</L>
<L N="1354">And wenden heom forth in grete wrath&thorn;e : And to londone heo come.&mdash;</L>
<L>Seint Thomas was &thorn;o In Flaundres : In huydinge ase &thorn;ei it were,</L>
<L N="1356">In &thorn;e Abbeie of seint Bertyn : and longe he hadde i-beo &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>At&thorn;e laste he aros bi ni&yogh;te : and out of Flaundres wende</L>
<L>Al priueliche In-to Fraunce : ase ore louerd him grace sende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king of Fraunce &thorn;at was &thorn;o : louwis guod and hende,</L>
<L N="1360">heorde telle of &thorn;is holi Man : he let sone after him sende.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is holi Man to him cam : gret Ioye he gan him make,</L>
<L>And het him in eche stude opon is lond : j-nov&yogh; of his take,</L>
<L>&para; to spene to him and alle his : &yogh;ware-so heo euere come.</L>
<L N="1364">Nolde seint thomas nou&yogh;t a-bide : are he come to rome.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king him fond spence i-nov&yogh; : to him and alle his,</L>
<L>And sende with him guod conduyt : to bringe him &thorn;are, i-wis.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;o seint thomas to Rome cam : faire he was onder-fonge;</L>
<L N="1368">And sumdel &thorn;e pope was anuyd : &thorn;at he hadde i-beo so longe.</L>
<L>Men a-coupeden him of &thorn;ulke trespas : &thorn;at &thorn;e bischopes tolden er,</L>
<L>And beden him ansuerie for is stat : and aleggi &thorn;are-fore &thorn;er.</L>
<L>Seint thomas wolde op arise : Men beden him sitte a-doun,</L>
<L N="1372">And he bigan a-godes name : and schewede &thorn;is reson.</L>
<L>"Sire," he seide, "ich am I-maked : &thorn;ei ich onwuyrth beo,</L>
<L>to wardi &thorn;e churche of Caunterburi : ase &yogh;e mowen iseo.</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke churche was i-woned to beo : Ase lauedi, and schynde wide</L>
<L N="1376">bri&yogh;te ase &thorn;e sonne a-mong alle o&thorn;ure : of al &thorn;e west-side.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sonne &thorn;at was erore so cler : deork heo is bi-come,
<PB REF="00000194.tif" N="146"></L>
<L>brode cloude and strongue i-nou&yogh;: &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. &thorn;at?</NOTE> hire li&yogh;t habbeth bi-nome;</L>
<L>Ouer-cast heo is with &thorn;is cloudene: &thorn;at heo ne &yogh;ifth lij&yogh;t non</L>
<L N="1380">And alle &thorn;e churchene of Engelonde: deorke beoth ech-on.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng, &thorn;at hire scholde up-holde: he bi-nimez al hire ri&yogh;te</L>
<L>And ase &thorn;e cloudene hire ouer-cast: &thorn;at heo ne mai no leng li&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Ich &thorn;at scholde hire wardein beo: &thorn;are-a&yogh;ein ich mot fi&yogh;te</L>
<L>And stonde a&yogh;en and with-segge: &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere costomes bi al mi mi&yogh;te.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ei ich hadde a &thorn;ovsend liues: ase ich nabbe bote on,</L>
<L N="1386">ra&thorn;ur &thorn;ane ich it &thorn;olie wolde: &yogh;yue ich wolde ech-on.</L>
<L>&THORN;e costomes a&yogh;en holi churche: &thorn;at &thorn;e king hath forth i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1388">here &yogh;e mouwen heom i-heore: &yogh;if heo buth to graunti ou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is holi man bi-gan to rede &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere lawene: ase he heom hadde i-write;</L>
<L>he wep &thorn;at &thorn;e teres ornen a-doun: &thorn;at deol it was to wite.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope and alle is cardinales: &thorn;at sei&yogh;en him wepe so sore</L>
<L N="1392">And heordene alle &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere lawene: heo ne mi&yogh;ten for-bere non|more,</L>
<L>Ake bi-gonnen to wepe faste ech-one: and hereden god al-so</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo mi&yogh;ten finde a swuch prelat: ouer holi churche i-do,</L>
<L>&THORN;at holi churche so heold to ri&yogh;te: and ne soffrede no wov&yogh;;</L>
<L N="1396">heo &thorn;onkeden god of swuch a Man: and honoureden him inov&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope het is clerkes alle: &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. &thorn;at?</NOTE> &thorn;oru&yogh; al cristindome<MILESTONE N="76b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at heo wit-seiden suyche lu&thorn;ere lawes: &yogh;ware-so huy euere come,</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. And</NOTE> &thorn;at heo neren i-soffrede nou&yogh;ware: hov-so heo comen to ende,</L>
<L N="1400">And &thorn;at heo &yogh;euen heore lijf &thorn;are-fore: ra&thorn;ur &thorn;ane holi churche schende.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Thomas</NOTE>&para; &THORN;o spac eftsone seint thomas: wepinde swy&thorn;e sore:</L>
<L>"I-nabbe nou&yogh;t," he seide, "so muche wo: &thorn;at i-nere wur&thorn;e wel more.</L>
<L>For &thorn;oru&yogh; strenc&thorn;e of eor&thorn;eliche manne: In &thorn;is pouwer ich am i-do,</L>
<L>Ake ich me drede a-&yogh;en godes wille it be: for onwuyrth ich am &thorn;ar-to;</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore ore louerd for ri&yogh;te wreche: vuel biginninge me deth sende,</L>
<L>And ich drede for mine wrechche gultes: &thorn;at worse worth &thorn;e ende.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore, &thorn;at holi churche: ne beo to grounde i-brou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1408">For mine sunnes and for mine onmi&yogh;te: &thorn;at I-ne may hire wardi nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ich &yogh;elde ov op here &thorn;e bischopriche&mdash;: an o&thorn;er &yogh;e moten &thorn;are do
<PB REF="00000195.tif" N="147"></L>
<L>&THORN;at mowe bet loki holi churche: for onwuyrth ich am &thorn;arto."</L>
<L>&para; his Ryng he nam and bi-tok &thorn;e pope: and op &yogh;eld &thorn;e bischopriche.</L>
<L N="1412">&THORN;e pope swi&thorn;e deolfulliche: and wel Inliche bigan to siche.</L>
<L>&THORN;erof conseillede al &thorn;e court: &yogh;wat &thorn;e beste red were:</L>
<L>to laten him witien holi churche: o&thorn;ur to don a-no&thorn;ur &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>"Me &thorn;inchez," quath a cardinal: "In swuch cas ase nou&thorn;e is,</L>
<L N="1416">best it were to don an o&thorn;ur: In his stude, i-wis,</L>
<L>Forto paien bet &thorn;e kinge: and swuc[h] cas mi&yogh;te bi-falle</L>
<L N="1418">&THORN;at &thorn;e kyng wolde a-swagi and bi-leue: is lu&thorn;ere lawene alle.</L>
<L>For betere it were In faire manere: ho-so it mi&yogh;te to ende bringue,</L>
<L>&THORN;ane contec arere In swuche londe: and nameliche a&yogh;en &thorn;e kingue.</L>
<L>And man mi&yogh;te purveien &thorn;is gode manne: an al-so guod ase &thorn;at is.</L>
<L>I-ne wot &yogh;wat conseil &yogh;e wollez rede: for i-chulle reden &thorn;is."</L>
<L>&THORN;o seide an o&thorn;ur cardinal: "Ine rede nou&yogh;t so, i-wis,</L>
<L N="1424">For &thorn;at wolde &yogh;iuen men an-saumple: al dai to don a-mis;</L>
<L>For &yogh;wane &thorn;e king were wroth with ani bischop: for anie cunnes &thorn;inge,</L>
<L>to don &thorn;ane bischop a-non a-doun: &thorn;e mo vuele lawene he wolde bringe,</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne were holi churche i-schend: &thorn;at lauedi scholde be.</L>
<L N="1428">For &thorn;is red me &thorn;inchez feble: a betere &yogh;e moten bi-seo."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">papa.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;e pope nam &thorn;o seint thomas: and tok him a-&yogh;ein is ring,</L>
<L>to bi-leue erchebischop forth: and stable &thorn;oru&yogh; alle &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>studefastliche to holden up: al-holi churche ri&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="1432">And he him wolde a&yogh;en ech man: helpen bi is mi&yogh;te;</L>
<L>Ake he ne scholde nou&yogh;t &thorn;e &yogh;eot: to engelonde wend[e],</L>
<L>Ake a-bide betere grace of &thorn;e king: &yogh;if god it wolde sende.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e grete Abbeie to pountenie: forto soriourni &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="1436">he sende &thorn;is holi Man: for-to it betere were.</L>
<L>With luytel folk and luytel aise: &thorn;are he dude bi-leue,</L>
<L>For he nadde him-sulf nou&yogh;t to spene: bote ase heo him &yogh;eue.</L>
<L>his men he bro&yogh;te In seruise: heore mete to wynne &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="1440">And him-sulf he was al one nei&yogh;: &thorn;ei he hei&yogh; Man were.</L>
<L>hard lijf he ladde i-nov&yogh;!: And he hadde of harde here</L>
<L>Schuyrte and brech streit i-nov&yogh;: hardore neuere nere;<MILESTONE N="77" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e strapeles weren swi&thorn;e streite: with mani a knotte al-so;</L>
<L N="1444">A-non to is &thorn;ies &thorn;e schuyrte tilde: &thorn;e brech ri&yogh;t to is to;
<PB REF="00000196.tif" N="148"></L>
<L>&THORN;e knottes gnowen al is flechs: a-boute bi eche side.</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e on-aisi was is brech: a-boute for-to ride;</L>
<L>harde mi&yogh;te he sitte a-doun: and harde ligge al-so.</L>
<L N="1448">Louerd, deore a-bou&yogh;te he heuene: wel au&yogh;te he come &thorn;er-to!&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e bischopes of Engelonde: &thorn;at a-&yogh;ein him weren at rome,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Eorles and &thorn;e o&thorn;ere hei&yogh;e Men: &thorn;o heo to Engelond come,</L>
<L>heo tolden &thorn;e kinge al heore cas: hov heo hadde i-sped.</L>
<L N="1452">&THORN;o was &thorn;e king bo&thorn;e sori and wroth: &thorn;at he was nei&yogh; a-wed.</L>
<L>&para; "A," he seide, "&thorn;ilke traitour: &thorn;at ich habbe forth i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he me schal swuch schame don nou&thorn;e!: Ine may it &thorn;olie nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And he fleu&yogh;th<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. fleu&yogh;ch?</NOTE> out of londe: &thorn;at Ine may to him come,</L>
<L N="1456">I-chulle me of is cunne a-wreke: heo schullen a-bugge some."</L>
<L>he let seche out clene al is kun: and is o&thorn;ur frend ech-on:</L>
<L>Ovt of Engelonde he let heom driue: &thorn;at &thorn;are ne moste leue non,</L>
<L>Sike ne feble, . &yogh;ung ne old: ne womman &thorn;at was with childe,</L>
<L N="1460">Ne &thorn;e children &thorn;at soukinde weren: &mdash;muche was he on-milde!</L>
<L>In hire Armes &thorn;e moder bar &thorn;at child: and In heore wombene some.</L>
<L>&THORN;are hadde &thorn;e king, ase me &thorn;inchez: a feble wreche i-nome!</L>
<L>I-harlede heo weren in grete Miseise: out of londe, alas!</L>
<L N="1464">Ech guod man hadde rev&thorn;e of heom: &thorn;at heorden of &thorn;at cas,</L>
<L>And seiden stilleliche bi-twene heom: &thorn;at he a lu&thorn;ur king was.</L>
<L>Mo lu&thorn;ere dedene &thorn;e king bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te: &yogh;eot ope seint thomas:</L>
<L>&THORN;eos Men &thorn;at he of londe drof: were heom lef o&thorn;ur loth,</L>
<L N="1468">Ech aftur o&thorn;ur he made heom swerie: opon a boke gret oth</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo ne scholden in none stude: bi-leue none stounde</L>
<L>Are heo to &thorn;e Erchebischope comen: &yogh;ware-so heo him founden,</L>
<L>And tellen him fore hov heo weren: out of londe i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1472">to bringue him jn &thorn;e more sor: &yogh;if heo mi&yogh;ten tuyrne is &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; &YOGH;eot &thorn;e king bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te a lu&thorn;er dede: more ope seint thomas:</L>
<L>he for-bed &thorn;oru&yogh; al Engelond: ase fer ase his pouwer was,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no man ne scholde for him bidde: In churche ne elles &yogh;ware,</L>
<L>Ase men doth nou&thorn;e for Erchebischopes: and habbez i-don wel &yogh;are.</L>
<L>Louerd, muche was &thorn;e schame &thorn;o: &thorn;at holi churche bi-tidde,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane heo ne moste a-mong o&thorn;ur men: for so holi a man bidde!&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk of seint thomas kunne: wel &thorn;icke a-bouten him drou&yogh;&mdash;</L>
<L>Aldai heo weren i-flemde for him&mdash;: In miseise and soruwe i-nou&yogh;;
<PB REF="00000197.tif" N="149"></L>
<L>Heo weopen and criden deolfulliche : and tolden him al heore cas,</L>
<L>hov heo weren for him defoulede : and &yogh;wuch hore soruwe was.</L>
<L>Seint thomas bi-heold heom deolfolliche : and bi-gan to siche sore;</L>
<L>And euere he maked<SUP>e</SUP> fair semblaunt : to conforti heom &thorn;e more,</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;is word to gladie hem : &thorn;at men onder-stoden wel longe:</L>
<L>"Ech lond," he seide, "is owene contreie : to &thorn;ulke &thorn;at beoth stronge"&mdash;</L>
<L>Ase Man &thorn;at seith, &thorn;ei &yogh;e beon here : In vnkou&thorn;e londe i-brou&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="77b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1488">&YOGH;if &yogh;e beoth stronge in godes lawe : it ne schal ov greui nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e hei&yogh;e men of &thorn;e londe : &thorn;at heorden of &thorn;at cas,</L>
<L>Corseden &thorn;e kinge, and seiden al-so : &thorn;at he a lu&thorn;ur man was.</L>
<L>&THORN;is selie men a-boute men nomen : for loue of seint thomas</L>
<L>And founden heom liflode i-nou&yogh; : &thorn;at in miseise neuer on nas.&mdash;</L>
<L N="1493">&THORN;o &thorn;eos ti&thorn;inges to &thorn;e kingue : of Engelonde cam</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;is folk was wel onder-fonge : gret deol to him he nam.</L>
<L>"Certes," he seide, "&yogh;wane I-ne may : in &thorn;is manere is heorte buye,</L>
<L>In more miseise ichulle him bringe : &thorn;at is lijf him schal a-nuye."</L>
<L N="1497">&para; Greye Monekes of Cistevs : fram &yogh;ere to &yogh;ere</L>
<L>A Chapitre makeden generale : of Abbodes &thorn;at &thorn;ere were;</L>
<L>For euerech Abbod of greie Monekes : to &thorn;ulke chapitle cam</L>
<L N="1500">With-Inne &thorn;re &yogh;er,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> a terme</NOTE> ase [huy] &yogh;uyt doth : &thorn;oru&yogh; al cristindom.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e chapitle plenere was : &thorn;udere &thorn;e king sende</L>
<L>to &thorn;e Abbotus alle plenereliche : &thorn;at to &thorn;ulke chapitle wende,</L>
<L>And sende heom word &thorn;at him &thorn;ou&yogh;te wunder : more &thorn;ane i-nou&yogh;</L>
<L N="1504">&THORN;at heo wolden him so muche do : on-kuynde dedes and wou&yogh;</L>
<L>for-to susteiny is wi&thorn;erwyne : a-mong heom and is fo</L>
<L>In &thorn;e house of pounteneye : &thorn;at brou&yogh;te him in swuch wo;</L>
<L>And bote heo wolden him bi-leue : and ne susteyni him non-more,</L>
<L N="1508">Alle &thorn;e greye Monekes of Engelonde : a-bugge it scholden sore;</L>
<L>For heo susteineden is fo : ne<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. no</NOTE> wonder he seide it nere</L>
<L>&THORN;ei he awreke him of &thorn;at hous : &thorn;at ine his londe were.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;eos lettres to Cisteus : a-mong &thorn;is Abbotes come,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e &thorn;retningue heo dradden heom sore : and conseil &thorn;arof heo nome.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo beden seint thomas : his heste forto do,</L>
<L N="1514">For heo ne dorsten nou&yogh;t a&yogh;en &thorn;e kingus wille : non-more holden him so.</L>
<L>&THORN;o seint thomas &thorn;is i-heorde : he gan forto siche sore,
<PB REF="00000198.tif" N="150"></L>
<L>And bad Ihesu crist him helpe &thorn;o : and cride him milce and ore.</L>
<L N="1517">&para; "Louerdingus, &yogh;e &thorn;at habbez me : I-susteyned mani a day<NOTE PLACE="marg2">Thomas.</NOTE></L>
<L>In mine grete neode, Ihesu crist it ov &yogh;elde : &thorn;are ich mi-sulf ne mai.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king &thorn;retnez ov so faste : &thorn;at &yogh;if<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. &yogh;if &thorn;at?</NOTE> &yogh;e holdez me here ou&yogh;t longe:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if crist wole, &yogh;e ne schullen neuere : for me harm a-fongue;</L>
<L N="1521">&YOGH;ware-so ich euere mai on eor&thorn;e beo : fram eov ichulle wende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e ne beon for me a-peirede&mdash; : ore louerd is grace me sende.</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e habbeth on me i-spend : after me cometh on</L>
<L>&THORN;at swy&thorn;e wel it wole<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. it wole it wole</NOTE> a-quiten : hou-so it euere gon.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">v. 1523-4 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1525">For ich mai &yogh;uyt mine mete bidde : I-nam nou&yogh;t to guod &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>Ore louerd &thorn;at fedeth &thorn;e wilde bestes and foules : he mai me fede al-so.</L>
<L>Ake hov-so it euere of me bi-come : god, &yogh;if it is his wille,</L>
<L N="1528">holde up &thorn;e ri&yogh;tes of holi churche : &thorn;at heo fulliche naspille."</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;is holi man in &thorn;ou&yogh;te stod : &yogh;wodere he mi&yogh;te wende,</L>
<L>&THORN;e king of Fraunce, &thorn;at was so guod : sone he gan him word sende</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wolde bi-leue op-on is londe&mdash; : &yogh;ware is heort best drou&yogh;</L>
<L>Cheose he him-sulf, and he wolde : finden him spense i-nou&yogh;.<MILESTONE N="78" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For it is soth i-seid, &yogh;wane a man is : In mest soruwe and teone,</L>
<L N="1534">&THORN;anne is ore louerdes grace next&mdash; : ase it was &thorn;are i-sene.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is holi man nam is leue &thorn;are : mildeliche and softe,</L>
<L N="1536">And sore wepinde he wende forth : he &yogh;oxede and si&yogh;te wel ofte.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Abbas ponten'.</NOTE>&THORN;e Abbot of pounteneye : sumdel forth-ward him brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And Axede him &yogh;wi he were : In so deolfule &thorn;ou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>"Ichulle &thorn;e telle," quath seint thomas : "&yogh;wi ich carie so&mdash;</L>
<L N="1540">bot &thorn;at &thorn;ov ne telle no man fore : are mine ende-day beo i-do!</L>
<L>Ich am siker &thorn;at i schal &yogh;eot : deie in Martyrdom.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Sompnium.</NOTE>For to-ni&yogh;t ase ich was a-slepe : a wonder<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &yogh;onder</NOTE> metinge me com.</L>
<L>&para; In &thorn;e churche of Caunterburi : me &thorn;ou&yogh;te i stod, i-wis,</L>
<L N="1544">And striuede for holi churche : a&yogh;en &thorn;e kinge and his :</L>
<L>&THORN;o comen &thorn;ere four kni&yogh;tes gon : and smiten me opon &thorn;e croune</L>
<L>Ech after o&thorn;ur, &thorn;at mi brayn : schedde al a-brod &thorn;are doune.</L>
<L>For [me] nou&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> me</NOTE> ich &thorn;onki Ihesu crist : &thorn;at i schal dei&yogh;en so,</L>
<L N="1548">Ake for mine Men i siche sore : I-not &yogh;wat heo schullen do."</L>
<L>&THORN;is holi man wende forth : In care and deol bi wei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Forto he cam to senouns : twelf mile fram pounteneie.
<PB REF="00000199.tif" N="151"></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">ad Senon'.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;are he bi-lefde In soiourninge : al&thorn;e &yogh;wile &thorn;at he wolde,</L>
<L N="1552">And &thorn;e king him fond to spene i-nov&yogh; : of seluer and of golde.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode Man bi-lefde &thorn;ere : In pais and reste i-nov&yogh;;</L>
<L>An euere he carede for holi churche : &thorn;at &thorn;e king dude hire wou&yogh;.</L>
<L>he sende to &thorn;e kinge of Engelonde : &thorn;at he scholde late beo stille</L>
<L N="1556">And ne weorri non more op-on holi churche : &yogh;if it were is wille.</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;as<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> se&thorn;&thorn;e</NOTE> &thorn;e king of Engelonde : ase is wille him nam,</L>
<L>Ouer se wende, ase god it wolde : and in-to Fraunce he cam.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e king of Fraunce was a-boute : &yogh;if god wolde him grace sende,</L>
<L N="1560">A-cordi him and seint thomas : &yogh;if he mi&yogh;te it bringe to ende.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo weren to-gadere i-brou&yogh;t : at one dai&yogh;e I-set.</L>
<L>Seint thomas cam bi-fore &thorn;e king : and ase is louerd him gret,</L>
<L>And to is fet fel a-kne : he wep and cride is ore,</L>
<L N="1564">"haue reu&thorn;e of holi churche : and ne weorre &thorn;ov hire non-more,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ine wille i-chulle do : ase ich seide er, bi mine mi&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Saue mine louerdes honur : and holi churche ri&yogh;te."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e king makede him wroth i-nov&yogh; for &thorn;at word : ase he hadde ofte i-beo.</L>
<L N="1568">"Nov&thorn;e &yogh;e movwen," he seide, "ech-one : his falshede i-seo,</L>
<L>For man<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> i-ne</NOTE> ne mi&yogh;te don ope is<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;is</NOTE> worde : no&thorn;ing a&yogh;en is wille</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne wolde segge &thorn;at icholde : al-holi churche spille</L>
<L>And &thorn;at it<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> ic</NOTE> were a&yogh;en godes lawe&mdash; : and In swyche manere he mi&yogh;te</L>
<L>&THORN;at lond destourbi and me bi-nime : mi fraunchise and mi ri&yogh;te.</L>
<L>And gode bischopes &thorn;are habbez i-beo : bi-fore him ase [&yogh;e] wyten, i-wis;</L>
<L>Ake, &thorn;at &yogh;e i-seon alle mine treowenesse : and &thorn;at al &thorn;e wronge is his :</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> as &thorn;e</NOTE> wiseste and &thorn;e beste bischopes : &thorn;at bi-fore him were,</L>
<L>A-&yogh;en &thorn;e meste fole kinge &thorn;at bi-fore me was : faire heo heom bere:</L>
<L>Do he al-so a&yogh;en me nou&thorn;e : and ich me pai&yogh;e wel i-nov&yogh;;<MILESTONE N="78b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1578">And &yogh;if he is a&yogh;en &thorn;is fourme : me &thorn;inchez he hauez wou&yogh;:</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur him &thorn;inchez &thorn;at neuere bischop : so wis ase he non nas,</L>
<L N="1580">O&thorn;ur he me halt &thorn;e meste wrechche king : &thorn;at euere i-bore was."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">rex francie.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;o seide &thorn;e king of Fraunce : and alle &thorn;at heorden &thorn;is:</L>
<L>"Certes, &thorn;ov bedest him loue i-nov&yogh; : al &thorn;at wrong is his."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">thomas.</NOTE>&para; Seint thomas stod and bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te him : and gan to siche sore,</L>
<L N="1584">"&THORN;ei ichabbe i-haued a-nuy : to come me is wel more.
<PB REF="00000200.tif" N="152"></L>
<L>"&YOGH;if &thorn;e bischopus," he seide, "bi-fore me : hadden i-do heore mi&yogh;te,</L>
<L>hit ne hadde i-beo non<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. nou?</NOTE> neod &thorn;are-fore : to contecki ne to fi&yogh;te,</L>
<L>For are &thorn;is it were stable i-nov&yogh; : &thorn;oru&yogh; gode mannes si&yogh;te.</L>
<L N="1588">Nou&thorn;e god for is grace : sende holi churche hire ri&yogh;te!</L>
<L>For &thorn;at &thorn;e bischopus bifore me weren to nesche : ase ich nou&thorn;e i-finde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e studefastore i mot beo : o&thorn;ur it worth al bi-hinde.</L>
<L>Ich wot wel &thorn;at heo habbeth here-bi-fore : &thorn;e customes in engelonde</L>
<L N="1592">.I.-vsed heom al-to muche : holi churche to schonde;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei heo habben i-beon suffred longe : and to custome i-drawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;are ne may no man for-so&thorn;e segge : &thorn;at heo beoth ri&yogh;t ne lawe.</L>
<L>For ore louerd louez ri&yogh;t and sothnesse : and none vuele costomes, i-wis,</L>
<L N="1596">And &thorn;at he schewez wel bi o word : &thorn;at In &thorn;e godspel is:</L>
<L>For ore louerd euenez him-self : to sothnesse &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Ake he ne eueneth him in none stude : to costome &thorn;at a&yogh;ein &thorn;e ri&yogh;te were.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-[fore] me &thorn;inchez ri&yogh;t it is : &thorn;at we to soth&thorn;nesse drawe,</L>
<L N="1600">And destourbi &thorn;e vuele costomes : &thorn;at beth a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e lawe;</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore i-nelle none costomes : soffri bi mine mi&yogh;te</L>
<L>&THORN;at a&yogh;ein sothnesse beoth : and a-&yogh;en holi churche ri&yogh;te."</L>
<L>here man mai i-se &thorn;at vuele lawes : no guod Man nele a-fonge,</L>
<L N="1604">Ake destourbi heom mid al is mi&yogh;te : &thorn;ei heo habben i-beo i-holde longe;</L>
<L>For he &thorn;at sosteinez vuele lawes : ase wel he haueth sunne,</L>
<L>bote he heom a-legge &yogh;if he may : ase he &thorn;at heom deth bi-gynne.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e king of Fraunce i-heorde : and o&thorn;ure &thorn;at &thorn;are were,</L>
<L>&THORN;at seint thomas ne dude &thorn;e kinges wille : no-&thorn;ing apayd heo nere.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">rex francie.</NOTE>&para; "Sire bischop," quath &thorn;e king of Fraunce : "Ich i-seo wel nov&thorn;e &thorn;i wrong:</L>
<L N="1610">&THORN;e king &thorn;e beot loue i-nov : &thorn;et strif is nov on &thorn;e i-long.</L>
<L>Wolt<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. wost</NOTE> &thorn;ov nou&thorn;e is lawes him bi-nime : &thorn;at neuere him nere bi-nome,</L>
<L>&THORN;e kingus heo[m] habbeth alle i-holde : &thorn;at bi-fore him habbeth i-come,</L>
<L>gret Maister &thorn;ov woldest a-londe beo : to muche were &thorn;i power.</L>
<L N="1614">to muche ich habbe honouret &thorn;e : In mine londe her;</L>
<L>bote &thorn;ov suffri him is ri&yogh;te lawes : Ichulle bi-come &thorn;i fo,</L>
<L N="1616">And &yogh;if we beoth &thorn;ine fon bo&thorn;e : I-not &yogh;wodere &thorn;ov mi&yogh;t go."
<PB REF="00000201.tif" N="153"></L>
<L>&para; Seint thomas heold him euere In on. : &thorn;e kingues heom makeden wro&thorn;e,</L>
<L>And departede fram him<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. heom</NOTE> so : In grete wrath&thorn;e bo&thorn;e;</L>
<L>huy &thorn;retneden and maden noyse i-nov : seint thomas heold him stille,</L>
<L N="1620">Ra&thorn;ur he wolde deth a-fonge : &thorn;ane &thorn;olie heore lu&thorn;ere wille.</L>
<L>Nov help crist seint thomas : for neode he hath &thorn;ere-to!</L>
<L>Nov bo&thorn;e &thorn;e kingus beoth is fon : &yogh;ware may he nov go?<MILESTONE N="79" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I-flemd he was out of Engelonde : and out of Fraunce also.</L>
<L N="1624">Alle is men maden deol i-nov : heo nusten &yogh;wat forto do,</L>
<L>And nameliche is cunnes-Men : &thorn;at for him i-flemd were.</L>
<L>"Louerd," heo seiden, "allas, allas : &thorn;at we lifles nere!</L>
<L>For i-driue we beoth out of Engelonde : and nei&yogh; of Fraunce al-so;</L>
<L N="1628">Louerd, &yogh;wat scholde more sorewe : &thorn;ane us is i-come nou&thorn;e to?"</L>
<L>&para; Seint thomas made him glad i-nov : and confortede is men a-non;</L>
<L>"beth stille," he seide, "&yogh;e makiez deol : neodeles nou&thorn;e ech-on;"</L>
<L>And seide "&yogh;e mouwen of-swinke ouwer mete : ase guode men doth mani on;</L>
<L N="1632">For beo &yogh;e fram me, huy wollez beo ouwer freond : &thorn;at nou&thorn;e beot ower fon.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e ne habbez hate of no man : bote for me, with wou&yogh;,</L>
<L>And beo &yogh;e fram me i-wend : men wollez louien ov i-nou&yogh;."</L>
<L>"A, sire, merci," &thorn;is o&thorn;ure seiden : "we wuten wel al &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="1636">For us-sulf nis us nou&yogh;t : bote for &thorn;e, i-wis;</L>
<L>We schullen wel nou&thorn;e ore mete i-winne : ake we nuten &yogh;wat &thorn;ov schalt do,</L>
<L>bote &thorn;ov schulle for honger dei&yogh;e. : louerd, &yogh;we&thorn;er &thorn;ov schulle so?"</L>
<L>"Ich mai bidde mine mete," quath seint thomas : "for i-nam nou&yogh;t to guod &thorn;er-to;</L>
<L N="1640">Ore louerd it &yogh;elde heom alle &thorn;at ani guod : for his loue me habbez<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. wollez</NOTE> i-do.</L>
<L>bi-twene borgoyne and prouence : ase men doth me onder-stonde,</L>
<L>gvode men beoth and al-mes-fole : &thorn;oru&yogh; kuynde of &thorn;e londe:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if I-ne mot In Fraunce beo : &thorn;udere ichulle i-wende</L>
<L N="1644">And bidde mine mete for godes loue : &yogh;if he me wole it sende.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eot sum<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. sun</NOTE> guod man me may i-seo : and it beo godes wille,
<PB REF="00000202.tif" N="154"></L>
<L>And habbe rev&thorn;e of me and beon min help : &thorn;at miseise me ne spille."</L>
<L>His men for him and for hem<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. him</NOTE> sulf : makeden deol i-nov&yogh;;</L>
<L N="1648">&THORN;e guode man among al is wo : confortede heom and lou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Allas &thorn;e deol &thorn;at &thorn;are was : &thorn;at swuch an hei&yogh; man bi-tidde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e Erchebischop of Caunterburi : is mete scholde bidde!</L>
<L>Deore a-bou&yogh;te he holi churche : and holi churche ri&yogh;te!</L>
<L N="1652">Wel au&yogh;te ech man here-after drede : a-&yogh;en holi churche to fi&yogh;te.&mdash;</L>
<L>Ase ech man at o&thorn;ur is leue nam : a-boute for-to wende,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e holi man In his side : &yogh;wodere god him wolde sende,</L>
<L>&THORN;are ase god wolde to bidde is mete : fort god him sende betere won,</L>
<L N="1656">god sende is grace a-mong heom alle : &thorn;at sorie weren ech-on.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e kingus Messager of Fraunce : to seint thomas cam gon,</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;at is louerd him bad : come to him a-non.</L>
<L>&para; Fort<SUP>h</SUP> wende &thorn;is holi man : ake he nuste for &yogh;wuche &thorn;inge;</L>
<L N="1660">he tok him al-to godes wille : and cam bi-fore &thorn;e kinge.</L>
<L>&para; A-non so &thorn;e king him sai&yogh; come : a-&yogh;en him he gan gon</L>
<L>And ful a-doun to is fote a-kne : and cride him merci a-non;</L>
<L>"blind," he seide, "ich habbe i-be : and &thorn;at nov&thorn;e ich onder-stonde.</L>
<L N="1664">Al mi lond to &thorn;ine wille : ich take &thorn;e an honde;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;wule ich am in Fraunce king : ichulle finde &thorn;e i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L>For ich onder-stonde &thorn;e so&thorn;e nou&thorn;e : &thorn;at &thorn;e king hath al &thorn;e wou&yogh;."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e king sende &thorn;is holi man a-&yogh;en : to Senouns, i-wis,<MILESTONE N="79b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1668">And fond him &thorn;ere spense i-nou&yogh; : him and alle his.</L>
<L>More he dude is mi&yogh;te &yogh;eot : and bi-tuene he sende is sonde</L>
<L>For-to bringue a-cord bi-twene him : and &thorn;e kinge of enguelonde.</L>
<L>At Momartre In Fraunce : &thorn;is dai was i-nome,</L>
<L N="1672">&THORN;udere weren &thorn;is kingues bo&thorn;e : and seint thomas i-come.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king of Fraunce dude is mi&yogh;te : &thorn;at heo weren to a-cord i-brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;o heo hadden to-gadere i-speke : al it was undo for nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>For &thorn;e king swor euere grete o&thorn;us : &thorn;at a-cord he nolde non</L>
<L N="1676">bote &thorn;e status of Clarindone : i-holde weren euerech-on;</L>
<L>And seint thomas swor &thorn;at bi is dai&yogh;e : he nolde &thorn;arof holde non,</L>
<L>Ra&thorn;ur he wolde deth a-fonge : bote &thorn;are were o&thorn;ur i-won.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo departeden with wrath&thorn;e : &thorn;o heo nolden non o&thorn;ur do.</L>
<L N="1680">Seint thomas bi-gan to siche sore : and Inliche wep al-so,</L>
<L>"Louerd," he seide, "help me nou&thorn;e : for &thorn;ine swete fif wounde,
<PB REF="00000203.tif" N="155"></L>
<L>O&thorn;ur holi churche is ope &thorn;e pointe : to beon i-brou&yogh;t to grounde."</L>
<L>Maister bernard of bosham : &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;af</NOTE> is .o. clerk was,</L>
<L N="1684">In priueite bi-twene heom to : seide to seint thomas:</L>
<L>"Sire," he seide, "&thorn;e mount-martre : &thorn;is hul i-cleoped is</L>
<L>&THORN;are ase &yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. ase &yogh;e ase &yogh;e</NOTE> habbez pais bi-speke : of holi churche i-wis:</L>
<L>And ase &thorn;e name seith of &thorn;is hulle : ase ich douti in mi &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; &thorn;i martyrdom holi churche : worth formest to pais i-brou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>&para; Sore sichinde seint thomas seide : "god wolde &thorn;at it were so</L>
<L N="1690">And &thorn;oru&yogh; mine de&thorn;e holi churche : Into ri&yogh;t pais were i-do,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ich hadde with mine blode : and with mine liue i-bou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1692">&THORN;at heo were in ri&yogh;te lawe : and Into guod pais i-brou&yogh;t!"&mdash;</L>
<L>A-&yogh;ein Midsomer it bi-ful : &thorn;at &thorn;e king him gan onderstonde</L>
<L>And In wrath&thorn;e of seint thomas : wende In-to engelonde,</L>
<L>For-to saisi sire henri is sone : mid al is kinedom</L>
<L N="1696">And for-to crouny him&mdash;longe him &thorn;ou&yogh;te : are he &thorn;are-to com.</L>
<L>And is conseil seide &thorn;at it was : mest of alle &thorn;inge</L>
<L>Holi churche and seint thomas : In vnri&yogh;te for-to bringe;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e Erchebischopes ri&yogh;te it were : &thorn;at of Caunterburie is</L>
<L>To crouny &thorn;ene kyng of Engelonde : and non o&thorn;ur bischop, i-wis.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king in preIudice of him : and to bi-nimen him is ri&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="1702">Let o&thorn;ur bischopes crouni is sone : and [cud]de a luyte mi&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&para; Four bischopus him crouneden : a-&yogh;en ri&yogh;te and a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e wone:</L>
<L N="1704">&THORN;e Erchebischop of Euerwyke : and &thorn;e bischop of londone</L>
<L>And &thorn;e bischop of salesburi : and of roucestre al-so;</L>
<L>In seint peteres churche at west-Munstre : &thorn;eos dede was ido.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fader seruede &thorn;e sone : at &thorn;e mete a-dai,</L>
<L N="1708">And with [&thorn;e] reaume saisede him : ase al &thorn;at folk i-sai.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ty&thorn;ingus of &thorn;usse &thorn;ingue : to seint thomas huy come:</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ulke on-ri&yogh;te he sende sone : to &thorn;e court of rome.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope him sende lettres a&yogh;en : and bulle &thorn;at he scholde</L>
<L>A-mansi &thorn;e king and is conseil : &yogh;wuch tyme &thorn;at he wolde,<MILESTONE N="80" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And suspendi &thorn;e bischopes : &thorn;at swuch on-ri&yogh;t duden &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And entre-diten al engelond : for-to it a-mendet were.</L>
<L>&para; Seint thomas heold &thorn;e lettres to him : for-to god him grace sende</L>
<L>&THORN;at he mi&yogh;te him-sulf &thorn;e neodes<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> dede</NOTE> do : &yogh;wane he to engelond wende.&mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;uyt cam king henri &thorn;e olde : eft-sone into Fraunce.
<PB REF="00000204.tif" N="156"></L>
<L N="1718">&THORN;e king of Fraunce was euere a-nuyd : of &thorn;ulke desturbaunce</L>
<L>And wende a-boute to makien a-cord : and bi-tweone he sende faste;</L>
<L N="1720">So &thorn;at heo weren, ase god it wolde : a-cordut at-&thorn;e laste.</L>
<L>A-seinte Marie dai Maudeleyne : Idon was &thorn;is dede,</L>
<L>In ane Mede &thorn;at men cleopiez &yogh;uyte : "&thorn;e traitores mede"&mdash;</L>
<L>Al-so ferde &thorn;ulke a-cord : ase &thorn;e Mede i-cleoped was,</L>
<L N="1724">For &thorn;er-aftur a luyte stounde : no-&thorn;ing i-sene it nas.</L>
<L>Muche heo speken In priueite : and in grete loue heo wenden a-two,</L>
<L>And seint thomas wende &thorn;at &thorn;e king : al is wille wolde do.</L>
<L>Maister herebard of boseham : to &thorn;e kinge he sone wende</L>
<L N="1728">For &thorn;e foreward &thorn;at heo hadde bi-speke : ase seint thomas him sende,</L>
<L>And bad him hote &yogh;elde a-&yogh;en : ase forth ase he mi&yogh;te</L>
<L>&THORN;at is baillifs in is bischopriche : nomen with onri&yogh;te.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e," quath &thorn;e king, "wolde he so? : &yogh;eot he schal a-bide,</L>
<L N="1732">Ichulle i-wite hov he wole him bere : formest In o&thorn;ur side;</L>
<L>par-auntur so faire he may : bere him a-&yogh;en me,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ichulle &yogh;elden him ech feor&thorn;ing. : &thorn;are-fore cheose he."</L>
<L>&para; Maister herebard wende a-&yogh;ein : ant tolde seint thomas fore.</L>
<L N="1736">"&YOGH;e," &thorn;ou&yogh;te seint thomas : "&thorn;is pais is al-for-lore."</L>
<L>Seth&thorn;e seint thomas him-sulue : to &thorn;e kinge he wende,</L>
<L>to speken more of &thorn;e a-cord : &yogh;if he it mi&yogh;te a-mende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king him welcomede al li&yogh;tliche : ase he ne heolde nou&yogh;t &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>And wende him forth to heren is masse : and seint thomas al-so.</L>
<L>he was i-woned to habbe is masse : ase it ful to &thorn;e dai&yogh;,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. dai&yogh;e</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;o he let singen him &thorn;e soule-masse : &thorn;at no-&thorn;ing &thorn;are-to ne lai&yogh;,</L>
<L>For he nolde nou&yogh;t at&thorn;e pe<SUP>i</SUP>s : cussen seint thomas.</L>
<L N="1744">&THORN;e holi Man &thorn;ou&yogh;te wel : &yogh;wat &thorn;e Anchaisoun was.</L>
<L>Wel narewe &thorn;e king him gan bi-&thorn;enche : to derne is lu&thorn;ere &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ake to him &thorn;at wot ech derne &thorn;ing : &thorn;ing<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. &thorn;ing</NOTE> it nas [to] hele nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e Masse was i-do : In conseil longue heo stode;</L>
<L N="1748">Wel ofte &thorn;e king him opbraid : &thorn;at he dude him er of guode,</L>
<L>And &yogh;wuch a lov&yogh; man he cam to him : and In &yogh;wuche pouwer he him brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he au&yogh;te vuele a-&yogh;ein him beo : &yogh;if he him wel bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo weren to-gadere longe : and &thorn;o heo hadden al i-do,
<PB REF="00000205.tif" N="157"></L>
<L N="1752">&THORN;ei it luytel &yogh;wile i-laste : with loue heo departeden ato.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; Seint thomas bi-gan to sike sore : &thorn;o he gan him onder-stonde</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">reprimacio thome.</NOTE>&THORN;at he hadde longe i-beo : oute of engelonde;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei it were a-&yogh;ein is wille : it &thorn;ou&yogh;te him lu&thorn;er dede</L>
<L N="1756">&THORN;at is bischopriche so longe was : with-oute conseille and rede:</L>
<L>to &thorn;e king of Fraunce he wende furst : and to o&thorn;ere guode and hende<MILESTONE N="80b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And faire he tok is leue at heom : to engelond for-to wende;</L>
<L>he &thorn;onkede heom of alle honur : &thorn;at heo him hadden i-do;</L>
<L N="1760">With fair conduyt and gret loue : fram heom he wende so.</L>
<L>Fram Fraunce he wende with gret honour : toward engelonde;</L>
<L>At one hauene he gan a-bide : &thorn;at Men cleopiez &yogh;wit-sonde.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">[near Calais]</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e lettres &thorn;at he hadde of rome : to Engelond he sende,</L>
<L N="1764">to don &thorn;e sentence al a-brod : bi-fore him ase he wende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Erchebischop of Euerwyke : In sentence he let do</L>
<L>And &thorn;ene bischop of salesburi : and of londone al-so;</L>
<L>for heo hadden i-crouned &thorn;ene &yogh;onge king : a-&yogh;en &thorn;e dignete</L>
<L N="1768">With onri&yogh;te In is bischopriche : he a-mansede hem alle &thorn;re.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e ti&thorn;inge to heom cam : heo maden heom wro&thorn;e i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L>And &thorn;retneden &thorn;is holi man : &thorn;ei it were with wou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Seint thomas eode toward &thorn;e schipe : In-to engelonde for-to wende:</L>
<L N="1772">A man &thorn;are cam fram engelonde : a&yogh;en heom,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. him</NOTE> guod and hende.</L>
<L>"A, sire," he seide, "for godesloue : ne passe nou&yogh;t &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>For &thorn;are beoth kni&yogh;tes in Engelonde : Iporueide &thorn;e for-to sle;</L>
<L>At eche hauene Men a-waytiez : to kepe &thorn;e, mani on;</L>
<L N="1776">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou comest a-mong heom ov&yogh;t : &thorn;ov worst a-slawe a-non."</L>
<L>"Certes," quath &thorn;is holi Man : "Inelle no leng a-bide,</L>
<L>to Engelonde Ichulle me drawe : tide &yogh;wat bi-tide;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei ich beo drawe lime mele : I-nelle bi-leue non-more,</L>
<L N="1780">to longe ich habbe &thorn;aunes i-beo : &thorn;at rewez me wel sore.</L>
<L>&THORN;e soulene &thorn;at ich habbe &thorn;are for-to loke : six &yogh;er and more, i-wis,</L>
<L>With-oute wardein habbez i-beo : allas! to longe it is.</L>
<L>A-slawe ich wor&thorn;e, wel ich wot : &thorn;are, are come ou&yogh;t longe,</L>
<L N="1784">Ichulle for holi churche ri&yogh;te : gladliche &thorn;ene deth a-fonge.</L>
<L>Ake biddez for me Ihesu crist : i bidde eov par charite!</L>
<L>bi-fore alle o&thorn;ere nameliche : o &thorn;ing biddeth for me:
<PB REF="00000206.tif" N="158"></L>
<L>&THORN;at god for is holi grace : to Caunterburi me sende,</L>
<L N="1788">&THORN;at ich mote a-liue o&thorn;ur ded : In-to mine owene churche [wende];</L>
<L>&YOGH;if i-ne mai &thorn;udere a-liue come : are ich i-martred beo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mi bodi mote &yogh;wan ich am ded&mdash; : god it graunti me."</L>
<L>his leue he nam wel deolfolliche : and to schipe he wende so;</L>
<L N="1792">he &thorn;onkede heom al honour : &thorn;at Men him hadden i-do,</L>
<L>And bi-tei&yogh;te al Fraunce Ihesu crist : and blessede it wel faste;</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk wep and makede sorewe gret : heore deol longe i-laste.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; At douere were kni&yogh;tes &yogh;are : &thorn;at heorden of him telle,</L>
<L N="1796">Sone ase he come op &thorn;ere : al aredi him to quelle:</L>
<L>Sire Reinaud of wareygne : and sire Randolf &thorn;e brok;</L>
<L>And also Gerueis &thorn;e schyrreue : gret folk with him tok,</L>
<L>to kepe &thorn;is holi Man at douere : ase he come op of &thorn;e se,</L>
<L N="1800">And bote he wolde heore wille do : al-&yogh;are him for-to sle.</L>
<L>to &thorn;e hauene of sandwiche : &thorn;at schip wel euene drou&yogh;&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e o&thorn;ere a-biden him alle at douere : with &thorn;retninge and bost i-nou&yogh;.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e schipes seile an hei&yogh; : &thorn;is holi man let do<MILESTONE N="81" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1804">Ane Croiz, &thorn;at Man fer isai&yogh; : Iseuwed faste &thorn;er-to:</L>
<L>&THORN;at was signe of is baner : o&thorn;ur ne kepte he non.</L>
<L>Men stoden at sandwich and bi-heolden : &thorn;e Croiz wel manion,</L>
<L>And seiden, "we i-seoth nou&thorn;e hider-ward come : oure bischop thomas;"</L>
<L N="1808">&THORN;e &yogh;uyt he was fer in &thorn;e se : heo wusten &yogh;wat he was.</L>
<L>&THORN;at cri was sone wide couth : &thorn;at folk orn faste i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L>And are he were to londe i-come : muche folk a-&yogh;ein him drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>heo criden and &thorn;onkeden Ihesu crist : &thorn;at heo mosten him a-liue i-seo,</L>
<L>And welcomeden him with Ioye i-nov&yogh; : non more ne mi&yogh;te beo.</L>
<L>&THORN;ene &thorn;ridde day of &thorn;e Aduent : bi-fore cristemasse it was</L>
<L N="1814">&THORN;at he to Engelonde cam : &thorn;e guode man seint thomas;</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuen&thorn;e &yogh;er &thorn;at he wende furst : out of engelonde&mdash;</L>
<L N="1816">Six &yogh;er and a Month&thorn;e he was fleme : ase ich me onder-stonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;is was endleue hondret &yogh;er : and sixti &yogh;er and tene</L>
<L>After &thorn;at ore swete louerd : In is moder a-li&yogh;te, ich wene.&mdash;</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Accusatio militum.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;at word to &thorn;e kni&yogh;tes cam : to douere of &thorn;is cas,</L>
<L N="1820">hov seint thomas &thorn;e holi man : at sandwych a-riued was:</L>
<L>to sandwich heo wenden faste. : seint thomas heo founden a-non;
<PB REF="00000207.tif" N="159"></L>
<L>With<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. withith</NOTE> lu&thorn;er semblaunt and fals heorte : heo welcomeden him ech-on,</L>
<L>And seiden, "hou hauest&thorn;ov &thorn;ene wei : to engelonde i-nome,</L>
<L N="1824">&THORN;at destourbest al &thorn;at lond : sone so &thorn;ov art i-come,</L>
<L>And al-so al-holi churche : ase we alle i-seoth,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ov a-mansest &thorn;us &thorn;eos bischopes : &thorn;at &thorn;ine felawes beoth!</L>
<L>&THORN;ov au&yogh;test mid alle lawe : loue and pais a-rere,</L>
<L N="1828">And &thorn;are nas neuere a-londe pais : seth&thorn;e &thorn;ov bischop were!</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ov wenest wel for-to do : with-drau&yogh; &thorn;ine dede sone;</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur Man schal bi &thorn;e do : ase with swuch a man is to done."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Responsio thome.</NOTE>&para; "Mine leue freond," quath seint thomas : "soth&thorn; it is i-nov&yogh;</L>
<L>&thorn;e mansinge &thorn;at ich let do : it was with ri&yogh;te and nou&yogh;t with wou&yogh;,</L>
<L>And bi mine louerdes leue &thorn;e king : &thorn;at ech man in ri&yogh;te were,</L>
<L N="1834">&THORN;at so gret trespas ne wende forth : &thorn;at it a-mendet nere,</L>
<L>And were eft-sone after-ward : with on-ri&yogh;te and a-&yogh;ein lawe</L>
<L N="1836">In desertison of mine churche : to costome i<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. it</NOTE>-drawe."</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e kni&yogh;tes heorden &thorn;at &thorn;e king : consentede &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>heo bi-leueden al heore grete mod : and heore &thorn;retningue al-so,</L>
<L>And in faire Manere beden him : ondon is Mansingue,</L>
<L N="1840">to norisi loue with is felawes : and bi-twene him and &thorn;e kinge.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at respit bi-tuene heom : of &thorn;is Ansuere heo nome,</L>
<L>For-to seint thomas a-moruwe : to Caunterburie come.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Aduentus Cantuar.</NOTE>&para; Seint thomas a-moruwe : to Caunterburi him drou&yogh;.</L>
<L N="1844">Al &thorn;e contreie a-&yogh;ein him cam : with Ioye and blisse i-nou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Ech preost somonede is paroche : clanliche in euerech ende</L>
<L>to beon alle &yogh;are a-&yogh;ein him : with procession for-to wende:</L>
<L>So &thorn;at with processiones : manie and faire i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L N="1848">With croyz and with taperes : &thorn;e contreie a-&yogh;ein him drou&yogh;.<MILESTONE N="81b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;are was Ioie and blisse i-nou&yogh; : more ne mi&yogh;te non beo;</L>
<L>heo &thorn;onkeden &yogh;eorne Ihesu crist : &thorn;at a-liue him mosten i-seo.</L>
<L>Of bellene and of tabours : so gret was &thorn;e soun,</L>
<L N="1852">Of eche manere gleo and of song : &thorn;o he cam into toun,</L>
<L>&THORN;at man ne mi&yogh;te i-heore non o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing : bote &thorn;e noise &thorn;at was so gret;</L>
<L>Non more ioie ne mi&yogh;te beo : &thorn;ane &thorn;are was In euereche stret.</L>
<L>&para; Ase ore louerd a-palme-sonenday : honovred was i-nov&yogh;</L>
<L N="1856">&THORN;o he rod into Ierusalem : and toward is de&thorn;e drov&yogh;,
<PB REF="00000208.tif" N="160"></L>
<L>Al-so was &thorn;is holi man : ase men mi&yogh;ten i-seo &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>For ore louerd wolde &thorn;at is deth : semblable to his were.</L>
<L>Are seint thomas &thorn;e holi man : to is churche come,</L>
<L N="1860">&THORN;e Monekus with procession : a-&yogh;ein him &thorn;ene wei heo nome.</L>
<L>Of is palefrai he li&yogh;te a-don : and custe &thorn;e Monekes ech-on;</L>
<L>to &thorn;e weuede wel mildeliche : heo ladden him a-non.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he hadde at churche i-do : al &thorn;at him was to done,</L>
<L N="1864">With is men wel mildeliche : to is In he wende sone.&mdash;</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Milites retro veniunt.</NOTE>&para; Seint thomas ne hadde i-beo : at is paleis nou&yogh;t longe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e kni&yogh;tes ne comen : heore answere forto afonge.</L>
<L>heo beden him ase heo beden er : on-don is mansinge</L>
<L>And a-soilli &thorn;e bischopes<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. bischepes</NOTE> : &thorn;at he let &thorn;are-Inne bringe.</L>
<L>"bev freres," quath seint thomas : "&thorn;at ne mai i do nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1870">For heo beoth In mansinge : &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e pope i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And .I.-ne mai nou&yogh;t on-do is dede : &yogh;e wuten wel, in none place.</L>
<L N="1872">Ake nou&yogh;t-for-&thorn;an ich truste wel : so muche In his grace,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ichulle a-soilli heom : In &thorn;usse fourme fawe:</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo don sikernesse for-to stonde : at holi churche lawe</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e lokinge of holi churche&mdash; : ake in o&thorn;ur fourme non."</L>
<L N="1876">&THORN;e kny&yogh;tes, &thorn;o heo herden &thorn;is : chidden faste ech-on,</L>
