<L>For &thorn;e ri&yogh;tes of holi churche : I-nelle nou&yogh;t det for-sake."<MILESTONE N="84" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;are wende forth on of heom : and is huyre of him drou&yogh;,</L>
<L N="2076">And is mantel a-non after-ward : with gret uilte i-nou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Sire Reynaud le fiz ours : pursiwede him anon.</L>
<L>&para; "Sire Reynaud," quat seint thomas &thorn;o : "hov schal &thorn;is nou&thorn;e gon?</L>
<L>Ofte ich habbe &thorn;e guod i-do : and manie o&thorn;ure mo."</L>
<L N="2080">"&THORN;ov schalt sone," quath &thorn;is o&thorn;ur : "i-wite hou it go.</L>
<L>Traitour, &thorn;ou art ded a-non : non o&thorn;ur nelle ich do."</L>
<L>"For-so&thorn;e," quath &thorn;is holi man : "wel prest ich am &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e ri&yogh;tes of holi churche : dei&yogh;e ichulle wel fawe,</L>
<L N="2084">&YOGH;if heo mi&yogh;te &thorn;ere-after-ward : in pais beo and in lawe.</L>
<L>Ak ich ov bidde &yogh;if &yogh;e sechez me : in ovre louerdes name,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e ne comen nei&yogh; non o&thorn;ur man : harm ne do ne schame;</L>
<L>For non o&thorn;ur gulti nis : of &thorn;at &yogh;e witez me,</L>
<L N="2088">heo buth alle gultlese bote ich one : &thorn;ar-of sikere &yogh;e beo;</L>
<L>And al-so ase heo gultlese beoth : harmles latez heom wende."</L>
<L>&THORN;e guode man sat a-doun a-kneo : &thorn;o he sai al &thorn;e ende;</L>
<L>Forto a-fonge &thorn;ene stronge deth : is heued he buyde a-doun,</L>
<L N="2092">And softe, ase some i-herden : he seide &thorn;is oresoun :</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Oratio thome.</NOTE>&para; "Ore louerd and seinte Marie : and seint Denis al-so</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e avouwes of &thorn;is churche : In &yogh;was ore ich am i-do,</L>
<L>Ich bi-take mine soule here : and holi churche ri&yogh;te."</L>
<L N="2096">&YOGH;eot he bad for holi churche : &thorn;o he nadde non o&thorn;ur mi&yogh;te!</L>
<L>Sire Reynaud le fiz ovrs : mest schrewe of ech-on,</L>
<L>For-to smite &thorn;is holi man : is swerd he drou&yogh; a-non.</L>
<L>&para; Ake Edward grim, &thorn;at was is clerk : in g[ra]unte-brugge i-bore,</L>
<L N="2100">his louerd to helpe &yogh;if he mi&yogh;te : his Arm he pulte bi-fore.</L>
<L>he woundede is Arm swy&thorn;e sore : &thorn;at blod orn faste a-doun.
<PB REF="00000215.tif" N="167"></L>
<L>W[i]th &thorn;ulke dunte he smot al-so : seint thomas ope &thorn;e croun,</L>
<L>&THORN;at blod orn bi<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. bi <I>corr. to</I> to</NOTE> is face a-doun : In is ri&yogh;t half of &thorn;e wounde.</L>
<L N="2104">Lovde gradde &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere kni&yogh;t : "smitez alle to grounde!"</L>
<L>Edward grim and<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. and and</NOTE> alle is men : &thorn;at &thorn;o a-boute him were,</L>
<L>At-ornen a-boute ech in is side : ope &thorn;e weuedes for fere.</L>
<L>Ase it bi ore louerd ferde : &thorn;o &thorn;e giwes him nome :</L>
<L N="2108">his desciples flovwen anon : men nusten &yogh;ware heo bi-come;</L>
<L>For in &thorn;e godspel it is i-writen : &thorn;at ore louerd him-self seide</L>
<L>"&YOGH;wane a man smit &thorn;ene schepherde : &thorn;e schep wollez to-sprede";</L>
<L>And ore louered bad for is desciples : &thorn;at men ne scholden hem<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. him</NOTE> non harm do.</L>
<L N="2112">&THORN;aron &thorn;ou&yogh;te seint thomas : he bad for is men al-so.</L>
<L>An o&thorn;ur kni&yogh;t smot seint thomas : in &thorn;ulke sulue wounde,</L>
<L>And made him bouwie is face a-doun : and loke toward &thorn;e grounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde in &thorn;ulke sulue stude : &thorn;are-after him smot a-non,</L>
<L N="2116">And makede him loute a-doun : is face to &thorn;e ston.</L>
<L>In &thorn;ulke stude &thorn;e feor&thorn;e smot : &thorn;are &thorn;e o&thorn;ere hadden er i-do,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e point of is swerd brak : In &thorn;e Marbre ato.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; &YOGH;eot &thorn;at ilke point at Caunterburi : &thorn;e Monekus doth wite,<MILESTONE N="84b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2120">For honour of &thorn;e holi man : &thorn;at &thorn;are-with was i-smite.&mdash;</L>
<L>With &thorn;ulke stroke he smot al of : &thorn;e scholle and &thorn;e croune,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ut brain ful on &thorn;e pauement : al a-brod &thorn;are doune.</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;wite brayn<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. braym</NOTE> was i-meind : with &thorn;e rede blod &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="2124">&THORN;at colur was wel fair to seo : &thorn;ei ich<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> hit</NOTE> reulich were.</L>
<L>Al round it orn a-boute is heued : ase it were a dyademe,</L>
<L>And al-round &thorn;are-a-bouten it lay : &yogh;ware-of men token grete &yogh;eme.</L>
<L>For &yogh;wane men peyntiez an Anletnesse<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> halewe</NOTE> : &yogh;e ne seoth it nou&yogh;t bi-leued</L>
<L N="2128">&THORN;at &thorn;ere nis depeint a Roundel : al-a-boute &thorn;e heued:</L>
<L>&THORN;at rondel men cleopiez &thorn;e diademe. : for manie i-seien &thorn;at cas,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> as me se&yogh; &thorn;er a fair cas</NOTE></L>
<L>bi &thorn;e diademe of is brayne : &thorn;at he holi was.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is holi man i-martret was : &thorn;is kni&yogh;tes graden ech-on,</L>
<L N="2132">"&THORN;is traitour is to de&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t : wende we henne a-non.</L>
<L>Siwieth us &yogh;e kingus men alle : and alle &thorn;at with him beoth!</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is traytur &yogh;e beoth a-wreke : ase &yogh;e nou&thorn;e i-seoth.</L>
<L>he &thorn;ou&yogh;te beo herre &thorn;ane &thorn;e king : and bi-nimen him is croune</L>
<L>And bringe to nou&yogh;t al engelond : ake nou&thorn;e he lijth &thorn;are doune."
<PB REF="00000216.tif" N="168"></L>
<L>Ase &thorn;e giwes bi ore louerd seiden : &thorn;o heo wolden him to de&thorn;e do,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he made him kin[g] and non nas : and godes sone al-so.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere kni&yogh;tes weren : fram &thorn;is holi man igon,</L>
<L N="2140">Robert de brok him bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te : and turnede him a-&yogh;en a-non</L>
<L>And &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e scolle smot is swerd : deope with-Inne is heued,</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e scolle al amti was : and no brayn Inne bi-leued.</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;e giwes leten smite ore louerd : to &thorn;e heorte grounde</L>
<L N="2144">After &thorn;e de&thorn;e with a spere : and maden &thorn;e fifte wounde.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is lu&thorn;ere men alle in one stude : smiten seint thomas,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e scolle ri&yogh;t euene a-brod : &thorn;are is croune was.</L>
<L>he nas nou&yogh;t &thorn;e man &thorn;at he wolde : is heued enes with-drawe</L>
<L N="2148">Ne fondi for-to fleo heore strokes : ne enes a-weiward wawe,</L>
<L>Ne nou&yogh;t enes groni ne makien cri : bote mildeliche and softe</L>
<L>Euere he heold is heued forth : al-&thorn;ei heo smiten him ofte.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is lu&thorn;ere kni&yogh;tes wenden a-non : to is tresorie,</L>
<L N="2152">breken is doren and is coffres : and duden gret robberie;</L>
<L>heo nomen is clo&thorn;es and is hors : and is tresor al-so.</L>
<L>Chartres and o&thorn;ur priue writes : &thorn;at in is coffres weren i-do,</L>
<L>heo it bi-token sire Randolf de brok : &thorn;at he &thorn;are-with wende</L>
<L N="2156">to &thorn;e kinge in-to Noremandie : and segge &thorn;at heo him sende</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he dude &thorn;are-with &yogh;wat he wolde : and &yogh;if &thorn;are ani were</L>
<L>A&yogh;en is wille o&thorn;ur is fraunchise : &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. heo</NOTE> sone to-tere.</L>
<L N="2159">A-mong is tresor heo founden al-so : tweie wel stronge heren :</L>
<L>Wel filliche heo casten heom a-wei : ase &thorn;ei heo nou&yogh;t wurth nere.</L>
<L>Ake na&thorn;eles heo bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;ten heom &thorn;o : and weren somdel in fere,</L>
<L>And seiden bi-twene heom stilleliche : "guod man we wenez he were."</L>
<L>Sire willam traci tolde seth&thorn;e : of &thorn;is guode man seint thomas</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischope of Eccetre in is schrifte : ase he of him i-schriue was:<MILESTONE N="85" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;o &thorn;e guode man was a-slawe : and heo ovtward were,</L>
<L N="2166">So sore heom a-gros &thorn;at heo weren : nei&yogh; witlese for fere;</L>
<L>For heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te euere ase heo eoden outward : ne wenden heo no so bliue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e eor&thorn;e openede onder heom : for-to swolewen hem a-liue.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;is guod man i-martred was : and &thorn;e kni&yogh;tes weren out i-gon,</L>
<L N="2170">In-to al &thorn;e toun of Caunterburi : couth it was anon.</L>
<L>&THORN;at folc cride deolfulliche : and to churche heo drowe
<PB REF="00000217.tif" N="169"></L>
<L N="2172">And onovreden &thorn;at holi bodi : and custen it ofte i-nowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Monekus comen sone &thorn;er-to : and &thorn;is holi bodi toke</L>
<L>And leiden faire In one bere : and bi-fore &thorn;e Autere it bi-woke.</L>
<L>&THORN;at face was &yogh;wy&yogh;t and cler i-nou&yogh; : and no blod nas &thorn;ar-inne,</L>
<L N="2176">bote fram &thorn;e ri&yogh;t half of is frount : toward &thorn;e left chinne</L>
<L>A smal rewe &thorn;ere was of blode : &thorn;at ouer is nose drou&yogh;;</L>
<L>More blod &thorn;ar nas in al is face : ase folk i-sai&yogh; i-nou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;e woundene bledden al &thorn;e ni&yogh;t : and men henten &thorn;are-of, i-wis&mdash;</L>
<L N="2180">And In &thorn;e churche of Caunterburi : of &thorn;ulke blode &yogh;eot is.</L>
<L>Ake he nas neuere of &thorn;e worse hewe : for al &thorn;at he bledde &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>bote in guode heowe and cler inov : ri&yogh;t ase he liues were,</L>
<L>And somdel ley&yogh;inde with &thorn;e mou&thorn;e&mdash; : he lai ase &thorn;ei he slepe.</L>
<L N="2184">Muche folk was a-boute him : &thorn;at blod for-to kepe,</L>
<L>And forto gaderi of &thorn;e blode : &thorn;at i-sched was on &thorn;e grounde,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;at eor&thorn;e &thorn;at was bi-bled : and glade weren &yogh;wan heo it founden&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; For &thorn;at nolde heom noman werne&mdash; : &thorn;icke a-wei men it drou&yogh;;</L>
<L N="2188">And ho-so mi&yogh;te enes &thorn;at bodi cusse : he was glad i-nou&yogh;.</L>
<L>A-morewe &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere kni&yogh;tes : Armeden heom eft-sone</L>
<L>And with-oute toun nome heore red : &yogh;wat heom was to done;</L>
<L>heo bi-radden for-to nime &thorn;at holi bodi : and with wilde hors to-drawe</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e hangen it on a waritreo&mdash; : heo seiden &thorn;at it was lawe,</L>
<L>For he nas nou&yogh;t wuyr&thorn;e to beon i-bured : In churche ne In churche|&yogh;erd.</L>
<L N="2194">&THORN;e Monekus &thorn;ou&yogh;ten &thorn;is swi&thorn;e wel : and weren ful sore a-ferd:</L>
<L>heo bureden &thorn;at holi bodi : hasteliche &thorn;ere-bi-side</L>
<L>With luyte solempnete i-nov&yogh; : for heo ne dorsten no leng a-bide:</L>
<L>&THORN;is holi bodi was i-bured : In &thorn;e munstre of ihesu crist,</L>
<L N="2198">bi-fore seint Austines weuede : and seint Iohanes &thorn;e baptist.</L>
<L>heo ne dorsten nou&yogh;t so longue : for-to &thorn;at bodi i-wasche were,</L>
<L N="2200">Al ongrei&thorn;et to leggen it In : [heo] hei&yogh;eden bliue for fere.</L>
<L>Ase heo strepten of is clo&thorn;es : al a-boue heo founde</L>
<L>Clerkene clo&thorn;es ase him to bi-feol : and o&thorn;ere bi &thorn;e grounde:</L>
<L>Monekene Abite with-Inne : ase heo founden &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="2204">bo&thorn;e Covele and stamin : he founden next is here.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he was Monek with-Inne : and seculer with-oute&mdash;
<PB REF="00000218.tif" N="170"></L>
<L>Nuste no man is priueite : of &thorn;a[t] him was a-boute.</L>
<L>And next is flesche &thorn;e here was : with knottes mani on,</L>
<L N="2208">&THORN;at deope in is flesche seten : some ri&yogh;t to &thorn;e bon;</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-of he hadde schurte and brech : luytel aise he mi&yogh;te i-fele,<MILESTONE N="85b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So &thorn;at he was &thorn;are-inne i-bounde : fram &thorn;e scholdre to &thorn;e hele;</L>
<L>With luytel aise he mi&yogh;te sitte : and ful on-aisi-liche ride,</L>
<L N="2212">And on-aisiliche ligge also : opon e&thorn;ur side.<NOTE PLACE="marg2">This v. on the margin.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ful of wormes was is flesch : to al o&thorn;ur wo,</L>
<L>In none creature, ich onderstonde : neuere ne weren i-seie mo;</L>
<L>For in euereche stude of is flesche : so &thorn;icke heo weren i-sete,</L>
<L N="2216">&THORN;at &thorn;e grete ne mi&yogh;ten for &thorn;e smale : comen to heore mete;</L>
<L>Faste heo schouen and cropen al-so : ase ametene<NOTE PLACE="marg1">formice <I>overwr</I>.</NOTE> al a-boute,</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;e smale cleoueden faste to : &thorn;e grete bi-lefden with-oute.</L>
<L>&para; he deide endleue houndret &yogh;er : and seuenti and on</L>
<L N="2220">After &thorn;at ore swete louerd : of is moder nam flesch and bon.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;reo and fifti &yogh;eres elde : him-sulf he was &thorn;o&mdash;</L>
<L>Mani a fair dai he hadde i-leoued : in care and in wo.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e king was in normandie : and her-of nuste nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>he made deol and sorewe i-nou&yogh; : &thorn;o &thorn;e ti&thorn;inge him was i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e Castel of Argenteyn : he soiornede &thorn;o;</L>
<L N="2226">With-oute &thorn;e &yogh;ates ne cam he nou&yogh;t : fourti dai&yogh;es ne mo,</L>
<L>Ake euere he heold him in priuete : In wepinge and o&thorn;ur wo;</L>
<L N="2228">For none neode &thorn;at Man mi&yogh;te habbe : with-oute he nolde go;</L>
<L>Ne rou&yogh;te he no-&thorn;ing of &thorn;e world : wel luyte he eat al-so;</L>
<L>&THORN;e sorewe and &thorn;e deol &thorn;at he made : ne mi&yogh;te neuere beo i-do.</L>
<L>he sende a-non to Caunterburi : for &thorn;is deolful dede</L>
<L N="2232">And bad &thorn;e Monekus pitousliche : &thorn;at heo for him bede;</L>
<L>And sende heom &thorn;at it nas : no-&thorn;ing bi is rede,</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;at &thorn;e kni&yogh;tes wenden forth : and no-&thorn;ing him fore ne seide,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he sende after heom : for-to comen a-&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&para; And are &thorn;e messeger were to heom i-come : huy weren fer in &thorn;e se.</L>
<L>to &thorn;e pope al-so god : &thorn;e king sende sone</L>
<L N="2238">And bad is conseil pitousliche : &yogh;wat him were to done,</L>
<L>he bad him for &thorn;e loue of god : In swyche anguise him rede,</L>
<L N="2240">&THORN;at he were i-schriue and a-soilled : of so lu&thorn;er a dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope hadde ful gret pite : &thorn;at he swuch word him sende,
<PB REF="00000219.tif" N="171"></L>
<L>&para; And gret Ioye for he hadde wille : is lif for-to amende.</L>
<L>twei cardinales he sende him : wise men bo&thorn;e to,</L>
<L N="2244">to schriuen him of &thorn;ulke sunne : and a-soilli him al-so,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e bischopus for-to a-soilli al-so : &thorn;at weren in mansinge.</L>
<L>Welle, &thorn;at &thorn;e Cardinales : welcome weren &thorn;e kinge!</L>
<L>&THORN;e king bad heom deolfulliche : to schriuen him of &thorn;e dede,</L>
<L N="2248">And bi-het heom studefastliche : to stonden al-to heore rede.</L>
<L>he swor on &thorn;e halidom : &thorn;at &thorn;oru&yogh; him nas it nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ne bi is wille, ne bi his heste : &thorn;at he was to de&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And &yogh;et he seide &thorn;at for is fader de&thorn;e : so sori man he nas,</L>
<L N="2252">Ne for is moderes no-&thorn;e-mo : Ase he for is de&thorn;e was;</L>
<L>And he seide he wolde with guode heorte : alle &thorn;e penaunces a-fonge</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo wolden on him legge : ne weren heo no so stronge:</L>
<L>For he was enchaison of is de&thorn;e : and of is anuy al-so:<MILESTONE N="86" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2256">&THORN;e kni&yogh;tes, for-to paien him : brou&yogh;ten him &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e Cardinales i-sei&yogh;en &thorn;is : &thorn;at he to repentaunce drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>heo a-soileden him and setten on him : stronge penaunce i-nou&yogh;,</L>
<L>In priuete ase ri&yogh;t was : &thorn;at no man &thorn;ar-of nuste,</L>
<L N="2260">And &thorn;is al-so &thorn;at ichulle nov&thorn;e telle : &thorn;at alle Men of wusten.</L>
<L>his priue penaunces some weren : fastinge for-to make,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">vv. 2261-2 om. in the other MSS.</NOTE>And In fale tymes linne cloth and schurte of selk : for is sunnes for-sake.</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e holie londe he scholde finde : to hundret kny&yogh;tes, to fi&yogh;te</L>
<L N="2264">Al ane &yogh;er with &thorn;e templers : for holi churche ri&yogh;te;</L>
<L>&para; And &thorn;at he scholde &thorn;e status of Clarindone : al clanliche with|drawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru &yogh;wuche statuz &thorn;is holi man : i-brou&yogh;t was of lijf-dawe;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he clanliche &yogh;olde a-&yogh;ein : al &thorn;at bi-nome was</L>
<L N="2268">&THORN;e bischopriche of Caunterburi : for wrathe of seint thomas;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he scholde is vuele wille : also clanliche for-&yogh;iue</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at he hadde out of londe : for wrathe of him i-driue.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king grauntede al heore wille : weopinde swi&thorn;e sore,</L>
<L N="2272">And seide &thorn;at it was to luyte : and bad on him legge more,</L>
<L>And &yogh;eot, "al to ouwer wille here : mi bodi ich bi-take,</L>
<L>&YOGH;iueth me penaunces i-nowe : I-nelle neuer on for-sake."</L>
<L>he wende out at&thorn;e Churche dore : a-soiled forto beo,
<PB REF="00000220.tif" N="172"></L>
<L N="2276">And seide &thorn;at he nas nou&yogh;t wurthe : &thorn;at men scholde him with-inne i-seo;</L>
<L>And with-oute churche pitousliche : he sat a-doun a-kne.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;e Cardinales nolden nou&yogh;t : is bodi al on-wreo,</L>
<L>And somdel a-boue is clo&thorn;es : heo a-soileden him ri&yogh;t &thorn;ere;</L>
<L N="2280">For deol heo weopen pitousliche : and manie &thorn;at &thorn;are were.</L>
<L>his sone al-so made one bi-heste : with wel dreorie chere:</L>
<L N="2282">&THORN;e faderes penaunce to folfulle : &yogh;if he of power nere</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur &yogh;if he felle in-to feble stat : &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;te it nou&yogh;t ful-ende,</L>
<L>Opon him-self &thorn;e charge he nam : and dude ase guod and hende.</L>
<L>&THORN;us was &thorn;e holi man : i-brou&yogh;t to martyrdom;</L>
<L>Mani was &thorn;e fair miracle : &thorn;at for him sone com.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Both verses are written in one line.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Jerusalem.</NOTE>&para; For In Ierusalemes londe men wusten : of is martyrdom</L>
<L N="2288">With-Inne &thorn;e furste fourtene-Ni&yogh;t : &thorn;at he &thorn;e det nam.</L>
<L>For a Monek in &thorn;ulke londe : In is de&thorn;e vuele lai,</L>
<L>And is Abbod cam to him : bi-fore is ende-dai<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Both verses are written in one line.</NOTE></L>
<L>And conIurede him<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. him &thorn;at him</NOTE> &thorn;at he scholde : after is de&thorn;e &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="2292">to him comen and tellen him fore : in &yogh;wuch stat he were.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;is Monek deide sone : ase ore louerd &yogh;af &thorn;at cas.</L>
<L>to is Abbod seth&thorn;e he cam : ase he I-conioured was,</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;at he i-saued was : In &thorn;e Ioie of heuene an hei&yogh;;</L>
<L N="2296">he tolde him muche of &thorn;e Ioye : &thorn;at he &thorn;are i-sei&yogh;.</L>
<L>he tolde him &thorn;at &thorn;ulke tyme : &thorn;at he to heuene cam</L>
<L>&THORN;e Erchebischop of Caunterburi : &thorn;olede martyrdom,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at is soule &thorn;ulke tyme : to heuene wende a-non;</L>
<L N="2300">"Fair was &thorn;at processioun : &thorn;at a-&yogh;en him cam gon</L>
<L>Of Aungles and of patriarks : and of apostles al-so,</L>
<L>Of Martirs and of confessours : and of virgines &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L>heo nome alle &thorn;eos holi soule : And bi-fore ore louerd sone<MILESTONE N="86b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2304">brou&yogh;ten hire with Ioye and blisse : ase he sat in is throne.</L>
<L>his croune was al of i-smite : and blodi was is heued,</L>
<L>And is brayn was al i-sched : &thorn;are nas nou&yogh;t bi-leued.</L>
<L>&para; 'Thomas, thomas,' quath ore louerd : '&thorn;us it fallez to &thorn;e</L>
<L N="2308">To &thorn;ine louerdus court to come : In swuche manere to me!</L>
<L>For &thorn;i seruise ich &thorn;e &yogh;yue : ase muchel Ioie and blis</L>
<L>Ase ich &yogh;af seint peter : &thorn;at min Apostel is.'
<PB REF="00000221.tif" N="173"></L>
<L>he sette ane Croune op-on is heued : of golde cler and guod,</L>
<L N="2312">Swy&thorn;e wel bi-cam &thorn;at bri&yogh;te gold : op-on &thorn;e rede blod.</L>
<L>More Ioie ne mi&yogh;te non beo : &thorn;ane In heuene for him was,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e Erchebischope of caunterburi : is name was seint thomas.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Tywesdai after Cristemasse : &thorn;e furste &thorn;at &thorn;ere cam,</L>
<L N="2316">&THORN;is holi man in Engelonde : &thorn;olede martyrdom;</L>
<L>And &yogh;wan &thorn;ov i-heorst of is de&thorn;e telle : of Men of Engelonde,</L>
<L>&THORN;ov i-leue me of &thorn;is tale : and &thorn;e so&thorn;e onder-stonde."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Abbod sone a-morewe : ne fur-&yogh;at nou&yogh;t seint thomas,</L>
<L N="2320">Ake &thorn;e patria[r]cke of Ierusalem : he tolde al hov it was.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at for&thorn;ere in &thorn;e &yogh;ere : it was wel onder-stonde,</L>
<L>&THORN;o pilegrimes &thorn;udere comen : out of Engelonde,</L>
<L>In &yogh;wat manere he was a-slawe : and &yogh;wuch tyme he was ded:</L>
<L N="2324">&THORN;e pilegrimes tolden al &thorn;e so&thorn;e : ase &thorn;e Monek hadde er i-seid.</L>
<L>&THORN;us was i-kud In Ierusalem : &thorn;e deth of seint thomas</L>
<L>With-Inne &thorn;e furste fourtene ny&yogh;t : &thorn;at he i-martred was.&mdash;</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Guerra regum.</NOTE>&para; &thorn;e fifte &yogh;er, ich onder-stonde : after is martyr-dom</L>
<L N="2328">bi-twene kyng henri and is sone : gret contek &thorn;are bi-com.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sone bi-cam prout a-non : for is kynedom,</L>
<L>And of is fader tolde luyte : and werre ope him nam.</L>
<L>&THORN;e meste del was with is sone : of al Engelonde,</L>
<L N="2332">And &thorn;e kyng of Fraunce al-so : and &thorn;e king of scotlonde.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;is seli oldeman : In sorewe was I-nov&yogh;.</L>
<L>Al he it wuste &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere dede : &thorn;at man seint thomas a-slou&yogh;.</L>
<L>he wende him out of Normundie : to-ward Engelonde,</L>
<L N="2336">Are he come to Caunterbiri : he nolde nou&yogh;were at-stonde;</L>
<L>And &thorn;o he cam fer w[i]th-oute &thorn;e toun : he gan to li&yogh;te a-doun,</L>
<L>Al a-fote and bare-fot : he wende into &thorn;e toun.</L>
<L>In is Curtel one and on-gurd : ase al &thorn;at folk i-sai&yogh;,</L>
<L N="2340">Ri&yogh;t so he wende to &thorn;e stude : &thorn;ere seint thomas lai.</L>
<L>At is toumbe he feol a-doun a-kneo : wepinde wel sore,</L>
<L>he heold op is hondene deolfolliche : and cride him milce and ore.</L>
<L>&para; Wepinde in is oresones : al fastinde he lai</L>
<L N="2344">At &thorn;is holi mannes toumbe : a ny&yogh;t and al a dai;</L>
<L>Of euerech Monek of &thorn;e hous : he tok is discipline</L>
<L>With a smart &yogh;eorde, and &yogh;eot him &thorn;ou&yogh;te : &thorn;ere was to luyte pine.
<PB REF="00000222.tif" N="174"></L>
<L>he bad heom alle deolfulliche : bidden for him one,</L>
<L>And swor he wolde legge a-doun : &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere lawene ech-one.<MILESTONE N="87" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; So &thorn;at he let singe ane masse : are he &thorn;annes wende,</L>
<L N="2350">In &thorn;e honour of seint thomas : &thorn;at he is grace him sende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;wyle men &thorn;e masse songe : ase ore louerd &yogh;af &thorn;at cas,</L>
<L N="2352">&THORN;e kyng of Scotlond was i-nome : &thorn;at mest is fo was;</L>
<L>And manie o&thorn;ere also with him : &thorn;at weren is stron[ge] fon;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo &thorn;at weren vn-nome : to him nadden power non.</L>
<L>his folk dude &thorn;e bataille : &thorn;e &yogh;wyle &thorn;e masse i-laste<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. staste</NOTE>;</L>
<L N="2356">&THORN;ar-to heo hadden luyte help : and weren wel sore agaste,</L>
<L>Ake ore louerd for seint thomas loue : his grace wel sone him caste,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heore fon weren some<NOTE PLACE="marg1">m MS. sone</NOTE> i-nome : and some flouwen wel faste.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;is seli olde king : &thorn;at al bi-ne&thorn;e er was,</L>
<L N="2360">Al a-boue was sone i-brou&yogh;t : &thorn;oru&yogh; bone of seint thomas;</L>
<L>And is sone was al bi-ne&thorn;e : and so he bi-&yogh;at wel luyte</L>
<L>For-to weorri a&yogh;ein is fader : for is sori pruyte.</L>
<L>bi him men mowen nime ensaumple : to beon to hastiue:</L>
<L N="2364">to &yogh;iuen heore sones op heore lond : &thorn;e &yogh;wyle heo hem-sulue beoth a-liue.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kingus sone &thorn;are-after-ward : prouede vuele i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L>And wel longe bi-fore &thorn;e fadere : toward &thorn;e de&thorn;e he drou&yogh;</L>
<L>And fur-pinede in &thorn;e menisone : &thorn;at is lif him &thorn;ou&yogh;te long;</L>
<L N="2368">he deide seth&thorn;e deol-folliche : in gret pine and strong.</L>
<L>his bro&thorn;er also, sire Geffrei : &thorn;at Erl of brutayne was,</L>
<L N="2370">Deide al-so in &thorn;e menison : In &thorn;ulke sulue cas.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at after is fader de&thorn;e : &thorn;are ne lefde eir non</L>
<L>bote heore &yogh;ongue bro&thorn;er king Richard : and seth&thorn;e &thorn;e king Iohan&mdash;</L>
<L>Ake sire Geffreies child : with ri&yogh;te lawe of londe</L>
<L>&THORN;e heritage scholde habbe i-bore : ase ich me onder-stonde.&mdash;</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Mors Militum.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;eos lu&thorn;ere kni&yogh;tes alle foure : &thorn;at slowen seint thomas</L>
<L N="2376">Deiden in stronge de&thorn;e i-nou&yogh; : ase wel ri&yogh;t it<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. it it</NOTE> was.</L>
<L>heo weren echone repentaunt : ne mi&yogh;ten none men more,</L>
<L>euere heo criden on seint thomas : to &yogh;iuen heom milce and ore.</L>
<L>Sone after-ward &thorn;at he was a-slawe : al heore guod huy lete</L>
<L N="2380">And wenden to &thorn;e holi lond : heore sunnes for-to bete.</L>
<L>Ake sire Willame traci ne wende nou&yogh;t : forth with &thorn;e o&thorn;ere &thorn;reo,
<PB REF="00000223.tif" N="175"></L>
<L>he hopede here In Engelonde : Inou&yogh; repentaunt to beo.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">These two verses are tr. in the MS.</NOTE>&THORN;are-after-ward he bi-cam : in grete meseise and strong:</L>
<L>his flesch bi-gan to breken out : and rotede an fovle stonk,</L>
<L>So longue &thorn;at he stonk so foule : &thorn;at deul it was to se,</L>
<L N="2386">&THORN;at onne&thorn;e ani man mi&yogh;te : for stunche nei&yogh; him beo.</L>
<L>his flesch rotede on him al-so : and al dai ful awei,</L>
<L N="2388">&THORN;at is bones weren al bare&mdash; : &thorn;o ne likede him no plei!</L>
<L>Wit is hondene he to-drou&yogh; al-so : his flesch at&thorn;e laste,</L>
<L>pece and o&thorn;ur al a-brod : a-wei fram him he caste;</L>
<L>hondene and Armes he to-drov&yogh; : mest of ech-on,</L>
<L N="2392">&THORN;at &thorn;ere nas no flesch bi-leued : bote senue and bare bon.</L>
<L>Manie men it &thorn;ou&yogh;ten wel : &thorn;at bi is wille it were,<MILESTONE N="87b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Al for-to biete<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. bi<SUP>e</SUP>te</NOTE> is sunnes here : &thorn;at is soule in helle nere.</L>
<L>Wrechchedore gost ne mi&yogh;te non beo : &thorn;ane &thorn;is prisun was;</L>
<L N="2396">And euere he cride deolfulliche : "merci, seint thomas."</L>
<L>At&thorn;e laste he let is lijf : In wel stronge pine,</L>
<L>And &yogh;if ore louerdes wille was : he cam to guode fine.</L>
<L>&THORN;is kni&yogh;tes aftur heore lu&thorn;ere dedene<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> dede</NOTE> : deiden sone ech-on,</L>
<L N="2400">So &thorn;at with-Inne &thorn;e &thorn;ridde &yogh;ere : a-liue ne lefde &thorn;er non.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e sauter seith &thorn;at swuche men : &thorn;at of tricherie beoth,</L>
<L>Ne schullen nou&yogh;t halue heore dawes libbe : ase &yogh;e alda[i] i-seoth;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei heo beon swy&thorn;e repentaunt : ase &thorn;is kni&yogh;tes weren, ich wene,</L>
<L>&YOGH;uyt ne libbeth heo nou&yogh;t half heore lif : ant &thorn;at was bi heom i-sene.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; Seint thomas &thorn;is holi man : onder eor&thorn;e he lay,</L>
<L N="2406">Are &thorn;at he I-schrined were : wel mani a long day;</L>
<L>he lai &thorn;ere nine<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> inne</NOTE> and fourti &yogh;er : and half a &yogh;er &thorn;er-to</L>
<L N="2408">And a-boute ane Ei&yogh;te dawes : are he were of eor&thorn;e i-do.</L>
<L>god wolde a-bide ane guode tyme : to don so noble &thorn;ing:</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;are weren bo&thorn;e guode : Erchebischop and king.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e king Iohan &thorn;at longue was : euere of lu&thorn;ere rede,</L>
<L N="2412">luyte &thorn;ou&yogh;te bi is daie : to don so guode dede.</L>
<L>&para; Ake &thorn;e king henri, is &yogh;onge sone : nolde nou&yogh;t longe a-fine,</L>
<L>After &thorn;at he was king i-mad : are seint thomas were in schrine.</L>
<L>he nas nou&yogh;t &thorn;rettene &yogh;eres old : &thorn;o he dude &thorn;is noble &thorn;ing,</L>
<L N="2416">And it was in &thorn;e feor&thorn;e &yogh;ere : &thorn;at he was i-mad &yogh;ong king.</L>
<L>&THORN;e guode Erchebischop steuene : radde faste &thorn;er-to:
<PB REF="00000224.tif" N="176"></L>
<L N="2418">So &thorn;at bi hore bo&thorn;e redes : &thorn;is dede was i-do.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope honorie, &thorn;at was &thorn;o : hidere he gan sende</L>
<L>Ane legat fram Rome, &thorn;at het pandulf : to bringe &thorn;is dede to ende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope &yogh;af alle pardon : &thorn;at &thorn;udere wolden gon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men nusten in Engelonde : suuych pardon non.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore, for-to honouri &thorn;is holi man : &thorn;ere cam folk i-nov&yogh;;</L>
<L N="2424">Of bischopes and of Abbodes : mani on &thorn;udere drou&yogh;,</L>
<L>Of priores and of persones : and manie o&thorn;ur clerkes al-so;</L>
<L>Of Eorles and of barones : and manie kni&yogh;tes heom to;</L>
<L>Of seriaunz and of squiers : and o&thorn;ere house-bondes i-nowe;</L>
<L N="2428">And &thorn;e simple men of &thorn;e londe : so &thorn;icke &thorn;udere drowe</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;e contreie &thorn;are-a-boute : &thorn;e tounes wide and longe<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. londe</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnne&thorn;e mi&yogh;ten al &thorn;at folk : &thorn;at &thorn;udere cam a-fonge.</L>
<L>&para; So &thorn;at &thorn;is hei&yogh;e men : &thorn;at scholden &thorn;is dede do</L>
<L N="2432">Weren in care hov heo mi&yogh;ten : for prece comen &thorn;er-to;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at Erchebischop steuene : of &yogh;wam ich er ov seide,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e bischop Richard of Salesburi : &thorn;ar-of heom nomen to rede,</L>
<L>And prior water of &thorn;e house : and &thorn;e couent al-so,</L>
<L N="2436">Wenden heom in priuete : &thorn;is dede for-to do.</L>
<L>bi ni&yogh;te, &thorn;o men weren a-slepe : and luyte &thorn;ar-on &thorn;ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>heo nomes<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. nomen</NOTE> op &thorn;e holi bones : and in one cheste brou&yogh;te,<MILESTONE N="88" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And setten heom in a priue stude : for-to &thorn;e time was i-come</L>
<L N="2440">&thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. hit</NOTE> was i-crid into al &thorn;at lond : &thorn;at heo scholden beo up i-nome.</L>
<L>It was in &thorn;e mon&thorn;e of Iulie : euene &thorn;ene seuenthe dai,</L>
<L>bi a tiwesdai it was &thorn;o : ase al &thorn;at folk i-sai&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e dai was i-come : to &thorn;e munstre heo wenden a-non,</L>
<L N="2444">Kyng henri &thorn;at &yogh;onge child : an &thorn;e hei&yogh;e men ech-on;</L>
<L>A-boute onderne of &thorn;e daie : to &thorn;is holi bones heo come.</L>
<L>PAndulf wende furst &thorn;er-to : &thorn;at legat was of rome,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Erchebischop of Caunterburi : and &thorn;e Erchebischop of reins al-so,</L>
<L N="2448">&THORN;at for &thorn;ulke &thorn;inge cam : fram bi-&yogh;eonde se &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>And sire hubert de boru&yogh; : &thorn;at &thorn;o was hei&yogh; Iustise.</L>
<L>&THORN;eos foure grete louerdes : &thorn;at noble men weren and wise,</L>
<L>On heore scholdres huy nomen up : &thorn;is holi bodi a-non;</L>
<L N="2452">&para; Bischopus and Abbodes al-so : it beren ful mani on.
<PB REF="00000225.tif" N="177"></L>
<L>to &thorn;e hei&yogh;e weuede of &thorn;e trinite : &thorn;e holie bones heo bere,</L>
<L>And leiden &thorn;e Cheste al &thorn;are-with : In a noble schrine &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;is king henri was so &yogh;ong : &thorn;at he ne dorste nou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="2456">With &thorn;e o&thorn;ere bere &thorn;at holi bodi : laste men him hurten ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>It was bi a tiwesdai : &thorn;at heo &thorn;e bones op nome;</L>
<L>Alle is chaunces &thorn;at he hadde : bi tiwesdawes him come.</L>
<L>In a tiwesdai he was i-bore : and of is moder wombe he cam;</L>
<L N="2460">And also ase men bringuth ane &thorn;eof : for-to a-fonge is dom,</L>
<L>bi-fore &thorn;e kynge at Norehaumptone : op-on a tiwes-dai&yogh;</L>
<L>Wit gret schame he was i-brou&yogh;t : ase al &thorn;at folk i-sai&yogh;&mdash;</L>
<L>Filloker &thorn;ane ani &thorn;ef : folk him &thorn;are schende;</L>
<L N="2464">bi tiwesday he was i-flemd al-so : and out of londe he wende;</L>
<L>And bi a tiwesdai&yogh; at pounteneie : ore louerd to him com</L>
<L>And seide to him &thorn;at swete word : of is martyrdom&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; "Thomas," seide ore swete louerd : "&yogh;eot schal of &thorn;ine blode</L>
<L N="2468">Al mi churche honoured beo&mdash;" : &thorn;is wordes weren wel guode;</L>
<L>bi a tiwesdai also gud : to engelonde he cam,</L>
<L>After &thorn;at he was i-flemd : to a-fonge is martirdom;</L>
<L>bi a tiwesdai at Caunterburi : to de&thorn;e he was i-do;</L>
<L N="2472">And seth&thorn;e bi a tiwes-dai : Ischrined he was al-so.</L>
<L>&THORN;eos seuen Auntres bi tiwesday : him comen at&thorn;e leste:</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore we i-seoth manie men : makien one bi-heste</L>
<L>to bi-leue flesch &thorn;ene tiwesdai : o&thorn;ur to o mel faste,</L>
<L>For-to heo comen to Caunterburi : o&thorn;ur &thorn;e &yogh;wyle heore lif i-lastez.</L>
<L>Nov Iesu crist for &thorn;ulke loue : &thorn;at seint thomas on &thorn;ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="2478">&YOGH;yue us part of &thorn;ulke Ioie : &thorn;at he so deore a-bou&yogh;te.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="28" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>28 [Prologue] Fabian Sebastian.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AL &thorn;is bok is i-maked of holi dawes : and of holie mannes liues</L>
<L>&THORN;at soffreden for ore louerdes loue : pinene manie and riue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ne spareden for none ei&yogh;e : godes weorkes to wurche;</L>
<L N="4">Of &yogh;was liues &yogh;wane heore feste fallez : men redez in holi churche.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei ich of alle ne mouwe nou&yogh;t telle : ichulle telle of some,<MILESTONE N="88b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ase euerech feste after o&thorn;ur : In &thorn;e &yogh;ere doth come.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste feste &thorn;at in &thorn;e &yogh;ere comez : we cleopiez &yogh;eres-dai,</L>
<L N="8">Ase ore louerd was circumciset : In &thorn;e giwene lay,
<PB REF="00000226.tif" N="178"></L>
<L>For to fulfullen heore lawe : and for cristinedom non nas</L>
<L>Are longe &thorn;are-afturward : &thorn;at he I-cristned was.</L>
<L>&para; He was Nyne and twenti &yogh;er : and &thorn;rettene dawes old</L>
<L N="12">Are he i-baptized were : ase &thorn;e bok us hath i-told:</L>
<L>Al-so it fel a twelfte-dai : seint Iohan &thorn;e baptist</L>
<L>Baptizede in &thorn;e flum Iordan : ore louerd Ihesu crist.</L>
<L>In &thorn;at dai a twelf-mon&thorn;e : ore louerd was at one feste,</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;are he turnde water to win : &thorn;oru&yogh; is moder heste.</L>
<L>We holdez al-so &thorn;at dai feste : of &thorn;e &thorn;ridde &thorn;inge:</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;e &thorn;re kingues to ore louerd : presaunt dude bringe;</L>
<L>to him heo comen ase is moder : a-child-bedde lay,</L>
<L N="20">After &thorn;at he i-bore was : &thorn;ane &thorn;rette&thorn;e day,</L>
<L>Ase it fallez a-twelfte-dai&mdash; : longe heo erore him sou&yogh;ten,</L>
<L>gold. and. mirre. and An-sens : In presaunt heo him brou&yogh;ten.&mdash;</L>
<L>Seint Fabian &thorn;rettene &yogh;er : pope was<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. was was</NOTE> In rome;</L>
<L N="24">he turnede mani men &thorn;at lu&thorn;ere weren : in-to cristine-dome.</L>
<L>Decius, &thorn;at prince was : of he&thorn;enesse &thorn;o,</L>
<L>he let him martri &thorn;ere-fore : and o&thorn;ere with him mo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Vita sancti Sebastiani.</HEAD>
<L>Telle ichulle of &thorn;e holi man : seint Sebastian.</L>
<L>he seruede ane he&thorn;e amperour : &thorn;at het dyoclician;</L>
<L>hext maister he was onder him : to don al is wille.</L>
<L N="4">Cristine Man he was bi-come : bote &thorn;ar-of he heold him stille,</L>
<L>for no doute of Martyrdom : ake for &thorn;at he wolde longe</L>
<L>Serui god almi&yogh;ti, are he wolde : deth onder-fonge.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e men &thorn;at cristine weren : &thorn;at &thorn;e Aumperor ou&yogh;wer founde</L>
<L N="8">Sone he let to de&thorn;e bringe : with fuyre o&thorn;ur mid wounde.</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane ani man for cristindom : to de&thorn;e scholde beon brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Seint Sebastian heom confortede : &thorn;at heo ne dradden heom nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Deth a-fonge for godes loues : Ake &thorn;at heo studefaste were;</L>
<L N="12">Mani he heold in &thorn;e ri&yogh;te bi-leue : &thorn;at flechchi wolden for fere.</L>
<L>&para; Marcus and Marcellian : bre&thorn;ren weren tweie,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Aumperour for cristinedom : I-nome hadde heom bei&yogh;e:</L>
<L>he let heom binde to-gadere faste : bo&thorn;e to o piler,</L>
<L N="16">And to &thorn;e Eor&thorn;e naylli heore fet : &thorn;at heo ne mi&yogh;ten fer ne ner.
<PB REF="00000227.tif" N="179"></L>
<L>So heo stoden al ane day and a ni&yogh;t : &thorn;at non ne mi&yogh;ten fram o&thorn;er;</L>
<L>Ei&thorn;ur of heom ofte to o&thorn;ere seide : "here is ioye, leue bro&thorn;er!"&mdash;</L>
<L>guod it is and murie : bre&thorn;ren to wonie i-fere!</L>
<L N="20">Euere heo precheden cristindom : mid wel glade chere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Aumperor let nimen ane spere : ase heo stoden to-gadere i-bounde,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; heore heortene he let heom smite : &thorn;at heo deiden in a luyte stounde.</L>
<L>Sebastian was &thorn;o i-wreid : &thorn;at he heom &yogh;af &thorn;ane red</L>
<L N="24">to holden op faste heore cristindom : &thorn;ei heo scholden beo ded.<MILESTONE N="89" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e Aumperor let him cleopie : "Sebastian," he sede,</L>
<L>"to &thorn;e al mi truste was : mi lond to wissi and rede,</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;ing &thorn;at min is : Ich &yogh;af &thorn;e mest power,</L>
<L N="28">to holden op min honour : and to saui it fer and ner:</L>
<L>Ich habbe to &thorn;e suspecion : Ake for-so&thorn;e i-ne segge it nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ov a-&yogh;en me and a-&yogh;en min honour : Itorned hast &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;[t]."</L>
<L>Sebastian seide, "sire Aumperour : A&yogh;en &thorn;e neuere I nas,</L>
<L N="32">Ake mid &thorn;e and al &thorn;ine &thorn;inge : to &thorn;in honour ich was,</L>
<L>And ofte ich habbe ni&yogh;t and dai&yogh; : godes sone bi-sou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Al-so wisliche ase he with is heorte blode : deore us hauez i-bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he &thorn;e &yogh;yue power gret : and wille and eke &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="36">to leten &thorn;ine false godes&mdash; : for heo ne helpeth &thorn;e nou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>&para; Wod-wroth was &thorn;is Aumperor. : "Sebastian," he seide,</L>
<L>"habbe ich &thorn;us i-holde &thorn;e? : turne &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t, ich rede!</L>
<L>bote &thorn;ov honouri ore godus : to swuche pine i schal &thorn;e take</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at, are &thorn;ov beo to de&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t : ech lime &thorn;e schal ake."</L>
<L>"Sire," seide Sebastian : "&thorn;ine &thorn;retningue ne drede i nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>More me greuez &thorn;at &thorn;ou nelt : habbe reu&thorn;e in &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And honouri him &thorn;at made &thorn;e man : ant &thorn;ine maumates bi-leue,</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at ne mouwe helpe nou&yogh;t : for heo beoth doumbe and deue."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Aumperour in grete wrath&thorn;e was : &thorn;esne holi man he let take,</L>
<L>And dude him leden into &thorn;e feld : and binde him to a stake,</L>
<L>he let archers to him scheote : ase it were to one marke;</L>
<L>With quareles and with Arewene : heo maden him woundes starke.</L>
<L>Mani on wende &thorn;oru&yogh;-out him : in a luytel &yogh;wyle</L>
<L N="50">heo stikeden al-so &thorn;icke on him : so yrichon deth of piles.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at he was ded : hom heo gonne i-wende;
<PB REF="00000228.tif" N="180"></L>
<L N="52">On-bured heo bi-lefden him &thorn;are : his bodi for-to schenden.</L>
<L>A cristine womman, &thorn;at hei&yogh;te Yreine : wende &thorn;udere bi ni&yogh;te</L>
<L>Forto burien &thorn;at holi bodi : &yogh;if heo it finde mi&yogh;te.</L>
<L>heo cam and fond him hol and sound : he nadde nou&yogh;t one wounde;</L>
<L N="56">With gret Ioye heo ladde him to hire hous : and glad was &thorn;at heo him founde.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;ene feor&thorn;e dai Sebastian : wende to &thorn;e Aumperour.</L>
<L>"Sire," he seide, "ichulle &thorn;e telle : &thorn;at fallez to &thorn;in honour:</L>
<L>&YOGH;e mis-bi-leuez, and men doth eov : a-mis to onderstonde</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;at cristine men scholden harm do : to &thorn;e and to al &thorn;ine londe.</L>
<L>For i-sosteyned and i-saued : it is &thorn;oru&yogh; heore bone</L>
<L>More &thorn;ane &thorn;oru&yogh; ouwer Maumates : &thorn;at ne beoth nou&yogh;t wurh&thorn; a spone.</L>
<L>For we biddez ny&yogh;t and day : god, &thorn;at me hidere sende,</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;at he eov &yogh;iue long lijf : &yogh;if &yogh;e eov wollez a-mende."</L>
<L>"hou is &thorn;is?" quath &thorn;e Aumperour : "&yogh;we&thorn;ur &thorn;ov a-liue beo?</L>
<L>Nart&thorn;ou nou&yogh;t Sebastian : &thorn;at ich a-felde let sle?"</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e," he seide, &thorn;is holi man : "a-liue ich am nou&thorn;e her,</L>
<L N="68">hol and sound, with-oute wounde : to schewen &thorn;e godus pouwer,</L>
<L>And to schewen &thorn;at &yogh;e onri&yogh;t doth : cristine Men to sle,<MILESTONE N="89b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For heore bi-leue is ri&yogh;tful and guod : and ouwere nis wuyrth a stre.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore on &thorn;ine soule &thorn;ench! : ne bi-lef &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t on a stone,</L>
<L N="72">Ake on him &thorn;at us deore a-bou&yogh;te : &thorn;at is godes sone al one."</L>
<L>&para; "Ov&yogh;," seide &thorn;e Aumperovr &thorn;o : "&yogh;ware is ovre mi&yogh;te?</L>
<L>Schal &thorn;is &thorn;eof &thorn;oru&yogh; is wichchinge : a-&yogh;en us with wordes fi&yogh;te?"</L>
<L>he let nimen sebastian : and hom to is paleis lede.</L>
<L N="76">For no miracle &thorn;at he dude : to wide scholde sprede,</L>
<L>Laste Men torneden to cristindom : In-to a priue stude he him ladde,</L>
<L>With staues he let him to de&thorn;e beten. : and &thorn;o heo a-slawe him hadde,</L>
<L>In one Chaumbre foreine : a-midde &thorn;e fuylth&thorn;-hede</L>
<L N="80">he let him honge with a rop&mdash; : and &thorn;at was a vil dede&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at bodi forto schende : for he hadde drede</L>
<L>&THORN;at cristine Men him wolden stele : and is bodi a-wei lede.</L>
<L>bi ni&yogh;te cam &thorn;is holi Man : to a womman, &thorn;at het lucine,</L>
<L N="84">And tolde hire hou he ymartred was : and in &yogh;wuche pine,</L>
<L>An hou filliche is bodi heng : and &thorn;at heo ase sone ase heo mi&yogh;te</L>
<L>his bodi fette, and burien it : a-mong cristine men bi ni&yogh;te.
<PB REF="00000229.tif" N="181"></L>
<L>&THORN;is guode womman at Midni&yogh;t : dude ase he hadde i-bede:</L>
<L N="88">Fette &thorn;at bodi and burede hit : In a wel fair stude.</L>
<L>&THORN;us seint sebastian &thorn;e holi man : is lif brou&yogh;te to ende,</L>
<L>And fram &thorn;e pine of is liue : to &thorn;e blisse of heuene he gan iwende.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="29" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>29 Vita sancte agnetis.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Anneis, &thorn;at holi Maide : wel &yogh;ong heo bi-gan</L>
<L>to serui god al-mi&yogh;ti : to beon cristine womman.</L>
<L>heo nas bote of &thorn;rettene &yogh;er : &thorn;o heo was to de&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="4">For &thorn;e loue of Ihesu crist : &thorn;at deore us hath i-bou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>In rome, &thorn;are he wonede : so fair creature nas non</L>
<L>Ase was &thorn;is maide forthward : of felle no&thorn;er of bon.</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;is Maide-child cam a dai : goinde fram schole,</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;e constables sone hire i-sai&yogh; : and heold hire for fole;</L>
<L>he gan to louien hire in folie : and for hire was in mourninge,</L>
<L>And carede hov he mi&yogh;te best : to ende his fole &thorn;ou&yogh;t bringe.</L>
<L>For stille mourninge &thorn;at he hadde : he i-werth swuy&thorn;e lene.</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;ar-of wondrede muche is frend : and &yogh;erne him duden bi-men[e].</L>
<L>heo axeden him a dai in priuete : hov he dude fare.</L>
<L>he gan to telle fram on to o&thorn;ur : &yogh;ware-of was is care,</L>
<L>And hou he wolde him-self a-sle : bote he &thorn;at maide hadde.</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;e consta[b]le non o&thorn;ur ne sai&yogh; : is sone forth he ladde;</L>
<L>heo comen to Anneyse, &thorn;at Maide hende : and nomen hire bi &thorn;e honde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fader seide : "lo here mi sone : &thorn;at wurth riche heyr of londe:</L>
<L>&para; A fair grace &thorn;e is i-come : he hath is heorte to &thorn;e i-take;</L>
<L N="20">Riche womman &thorn;ou worst i-nou&yogh; : he schal habbe &thorn;e to make;</L>
<L>hext &thorn;ov worst of al &thorn;i kun : of londe and o&thorn;ur &thorn;inges,</L>
<L>gold and seluer &thorn;e worth i-nou&yogh; : broches and eke ringus."</L>
<L>&THORN;at maide seide : "go fram me : &thorn;ov lu&thorn;e[r] de&thorn;es fode!</L>
<L N="24">Woldest&thorn;ov defouli mi bodi? : &thorn;ov ne bringest me neuere in &thorn;at mode.<MILESTONE N="90" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ich habbe me one spouse i-nome : &thorn;ou ne wost nou&yogh;wer swuch non,</L>
<L>bri&yogh;tore &thorn;ane &thorn;e sonne o&thorn;ur ani li&yogh;t : &thorn;at euere on eor&thorn;e schon.</L>
<L>Of &yogh;was kuynde wondri may ech &thorn;ing : for is moder is clene mayde,</L>
<L N="28">his fader of womman neuere ne wuste : so &thorn;e prophetus us saide;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;ene world he made of nou&yogh;t : and &yogh;af us ovre fode;
<PB REF="00000230.tif" N="182"></L>
<L>Wel deore with is swete blod : he bou&yogh;te us on &thorn;e rode.</L>
<L>Ane marke he hathz on me i-do : &thorn;at I-ne scholde non o&thorn;ur take,</L>
<L>Deorewur&thorn;e &thorn;ing he hath me bi-hote : I-nelle him neuere fur-sake."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Constable het Symproni. : "hov geth &thorn;is," he seide,</L>
<L N="34">"&YOGH;we&thorn;ur &thorn;ov bi-leue on &thorn;e false gode? : torne &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t, ich rede</L>
<L>And nim &thorn;is child to &thorn;i spouse : and &thorn;enk on &thorn;ine owene guod,</L>
<L N="36">O&thorn;ur ischal do &thorn;e so tormenti : &thorn;at &thorn;ov schalt nei&yogh; beo wod."</L>
<L>"beo stille," seide &thorn;is maide &thorn;o : "be stille, &thorn;ou deueles lime,</L>
<L>&THORN;ov ne schalt to-dai for no &thorn;retning : mi guode &thorn;ou&yogh;[t] me bi-nime.</L>
<L>Ich am redi for is loue : &thorn;at deore me hath i-bou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="40">tormenz a-fonge, and &thorn;e deth al-so : for Ine drede me ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>&thorn;e Constable let somony al &thorn;e cite : and brou&yogh;te &thorn;is mayde heom bi-fore;</L>
<L>hire for-to schiende, he dude hire strepe : so naked so he<SUP>o</SUP> was i-bore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ech man scholde i-seon hire derne limes : &thorn;e more hire to schende.</L>
<L N="44">"Onwreste man," &thorn;is mayde seide : "schame &thorn;e worth at&thorn;enende.</L>
<L>&para; Ne schameth &thorn;e no-&thorn;ing in &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t : bi womman &thorn;us to do,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wan &thorn;ou of womman art i-come : and ech man is al-so?"</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at maide</NOTE> was not<NOTE PLACE="marg1">ags. hnot</NOTE> for hire &yogh;ong-hede : are hire smok were of i-nome,</L>
<L>&THORN;are was<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. was was</NOTE> on hire swete heued : so muche fair her i-come,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hudde al hire swete bodi : &thorn;at it tilde bi-neothe hire kne<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. kneo</NOTE>;</L>
<L>&THORN;o ne mi&yogh;ten men for here : of hire bodi nou&yogh;t i-se.</L>
<L>An hous &thorn;at seruede of bordel : &thorn;are was bi-side:</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;are-Inne &thorn;e constable hire let do : and seth&thorn;e het crie wide</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;at wolden folie don : &thorn;udere scholden wende</L>
<L>And finde &thorn;are a fol womman : of bodie fair and hende.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at Maide was &thorn;are-Inne i-do. : so ful was &thorn;at hous of li&yogh;te</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;at no man for brij&yogh;t-hede : &thorn;at Mayde i-seo ne mi&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&THORN;at Maide sat a-doun a-kneo : and seide hire oresun &thorn;ere:</L>
<L>"Louerd," heo seide, "&yogh;ong ich am : a-mong mine fon i-brou&yogh;t here,</L>
<L>Euerech fondeth to don me schame : &thorn;at he[r]-a-boute wendez:</L>
<L>Louerd, ne &yogh;if neuere no lu&thorn;er man power : mi bodi for-to schende!"</L>
<L>&THORN;is Maide sat euere in hire beden : to ore louerd heo gan crie:</L>
<L N="62">hire ne mi&yogh;te no man for li&yogh;te i-seo : &thorn;at come &thorn;ere-In for folie,</L>
<L>Ake euere &yogh;wane heo comen In : to don heore fole &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>heo heorden hire crie on ore louerd so &yogh;erne : and hire ne sei&yogh;en nou&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Vv. 63, 64 are tr. in the MS.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000231.tif" N="183"></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o bi-gan ech after o&thorn;ur : ase euer-ech with-Inne cam,</L>
<L N="66">For Miracle &thorn;at heo sei&yogh;en &thorn;ere : tuyrne to cristindom,</L>
<L>And bi-gonne forth with hire : to ore louerd &yogh;eorne crie&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;o was &thorn;at an hous of beden : &thorn;at ra&thorn;er was of folie.</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;at maide sat and bad hire beden : an Aungel &thorn;are cam gon,<MILESTONE N="90b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A Roket he brou&yogh;te on is hond to hire : &yogh;wittore nas neuere non.</L>
<L>&THORN;at [maide]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> dude on &thorn;is Roket. : al naket heo was er,</L>
<L N="72">Na&thorn;eles heo ne mi&yogh;ten nou&yogh;t hire bodi seo : for li&yogh;te ne for her;</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo hadde ido &thorn;is Roket on : non-more i-hud heo nas;</L>
<L>Fairore lijf nas neuere i-seie : &thorn;ane &thorn;is &yogh;onge maide &thorn;o was.</L>
<L>&THORN;e constables sone cam for-to don with hire : ase he hadde er i-seid:</L>
<L N="76">And are he mi&yogh;te &thorn;at Maiden handli : he fel a-doun stan-ded.</L>
<L>his felawes &thorn;at with him comen : with-oute heo weren wel stille,</L>
<L>And hopeden, for he so longe was : &thorn;at he dude is wille.</L>
<L>&para; Na&thorn;eles, &thorn;o he to longe was : is o felawe gan in gon,</L>
<L N="80">And fond &thorn;at child ligge ded : so cold ase a ston.</L>
<L>he leop him out in-to &thorn;e strete : loude he gan to grede:</L>
<L>"Comiez hidere, men, and sleth &thorn;is wichche : for heo hath i-do a lu&thorn;er dede:</L>
<L>&THORN;e Constables sone heo hath a-slawe : here &yogh;e mouwen i-seo.</L>
<L N="84">Comiez nou&thorn;e bliue and nimeth hire : &thorn;at heo a-wei ne fleo!"</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk cam reke a-boute &thorn;is hous : and founden &thorn;at it was ded.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e baillifs &thorn;udere comen : to nimen &thorn;ar-of red.</L>
<L>Some seiden &thorn;at heo wichche was : some &thorn;at heo was guod,</L>
<L N="88">And alle for &thorn;e childes de&thorn;e : wro&thorn;e weren in heore mod;</L>
<L>heo stoden and Iuggeden hire a-mong heom alle : &thorn;at quelle heo wolden hire sone.</L>
<L>&THORN;at maide sat a-doun on hire knes : and made to god hire bone:</L>
<L>"louerd," he seide, "&yogh;if &thorn;i wille beo : &yogh;if me<NOTE PLACE="marg1">&yogh;if me <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> &thorn;ine mi&yogh;te and &thorn;ine grace:</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;ov kuyth&thorn; &thorn;ine mi&yogh;te<NOTE PLACE="marg1">&thorn;. m. <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> and send &thorn;is child : lijf here In &thorn;is place,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is folk &thorn;at here is luy&thorn;ur : &thorn;ine mi&yogh;te mouwen i-seo;</L>
<L>Ne lat none mo men deth a-fonge : for enchesun of me."</L>
<L>&para; A-doun &thorn;ar cam an Aungel : "mayde Anneis," he seide,</L>
<L N="96">"Ore louerd hath i-heord &thorn;ine bone : &thorn;at &thorn;ou to him bede."</L>
<L>heo blessede &thorn;at child, and hit aros : fram de&thorn;e to liue,</L>
<L>And &thorn;onkede god, and orn him out : at &thorn;e dore wel bliue;
<PB REF="00000232.tif" N="184"></L>
<L>he cam out a-mong al &thorn;at fo[l]k : loude he gan to crie:</L>
<L N="100">"On god &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. &thorn;at</NOTE> is In heuene : &thorn;at was i-bore of &thorn;e Maidene Marie,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is fader and sone and holi gost : louerd of alle &thorn;inge,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wille hadde &thorn;oru&yogh; is mi&yogh;te : fram de&thorn;e to-day me bringe.</L>
<L>Fur-sakez eovwer false godes : for heo nabbeth mi&yogh;te non</L>
<L N="104">Forto meoui heom enes of &thorn;e stude : non more &thorn;ene a ston."</L>
<L>&THORN;e childes fader and mani o&thorn;ure : swi&thorn;e glade bi-come,</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo i-sei&yogh;en &thorn;e Miracle : and cristindom hem nome.</L>
<L>Wod-wro&thorn;e weren &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere men : heo gonne bi-twene heom telle</L>
<L N="108">In &yogh;wuche martyrdome heo mi&yogh;ten : &thorn;is holi maide a-quelle.</L>
<L>heo leten makien a gret fuyr : &thorn;are a-midde &thorn;e place,</L>
<L>For-to brenne seint<SUP>e</SUP> Anneis. : and &thorn;ar<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;at</NOTE> ore louerd cudde is grace.</L>
<L>&para; For &thorn;o &thorn;at Mayde was &thorn;udere i-brou&yogh;t : In &thorn;e fuyr men hire &thorn;rev&yogh;:</L>
<L N="112">&THORN;at fuyr clef a-middes a-to : and &thorn;e luy&thorn;ere men it wel i-knev&yogh;,</L>
<L>For &thorn;o it smot in ei&thorn;ur side : and barnde heom al-clene.</L>
<L>&THORN;at Maide nas i-wemned nou&yogh;t : for it ne touchede hire nou&yogh;t ene;<MILESTONE N="91" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>bote heo sat hire a-doun a-kne : and in ei&thorn;ur half was &thorn;e lei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>"Louerd," he<SUP>o</SUP> seide, "&yogh;if &thorn;i wille it beo : &thorn;at ich here schulle dei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>I-redi ich am for-to a-fonge &thorn;at fuyr : &thorn;at is me In ey&thorn;ur side,</L>
<L N="118">&YOGH;if ich schal here I-martred beo : o&thorn;ur lengore a-bide."</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo hadde &thorn;is word i-seid : &thorn;at fuyr a-queinte a-non,</L>
<L>Non more hete nas in &thorn;e place : &thorn;ane in &thorn;e colde ston.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eot &thorn;ulke &thorn;at bi-lefden a-liue : on god &thorn;at ne<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. &thorn;at</NOTE> bi-lefden nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And Iuggeden hov heo mi&yogh;ten don : &thorn;at heo were to de&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;[t]:</L>
<L>heo leten nime a kene suerd : and &thorn;oru&yogh; hire &thorn;rote it smite;</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;at rede blod orn a-doun : on hire limes so &yogh;wite.</L>
<L>Fairore ne mi&yogh;te no-&thorn;ing [be] : &thorn;ane was &thorn;at ilke blod</L>
<L>On hire limes &thorn;at weren so &yogh;wite : &thorn;o hit &thorn;aron stod.</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;is Mayde seinte Annes : brou&yogh;te hire lijf to fine,</L>
<L N="128">And wende to &thorn;e Ioye of heuene : after hire muchele pine.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="30" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>30 Vita sancti vincentij Martyris.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Vincent In spayne : to a cristine bischop cam,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men cleopeden valentin : and cristindom of him nam.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> iustice</NOTE> of &thorn;e londe&mdash; : Dacian was is name&mdash;</L>
<L N="4">For &thorn;e bischop cristine was : he &thorn;ou&yogh;te to don him schame:
<PB REF="00000233.tif" N="185"></L>
<L>he let him nime and binde : and don him in grete pine.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischop cride &yogh;erne on god : he nolde o&thorn;ur fine.</L>
<L>With heom &thorn;at him tormenteden : he spac with milde speche.</L>
<L N="8">Seint Vincent was &thorn;are-fore wrath : and seide: "ich mot &thorn;e teche;</L>
<L>&YOGH;wy spext &thorn;ov so mildeliche : ase &thorn;ei &thorn;ov a-drad were?</L>
<L>Wenst&thorn;ou &thorn;at heo &thorn;ine Maistres beon? : &yogh;war-of hauest &thorn;ov fere?</L>
<L>Spec hardiliche, and conforte wel : o&thorn;ure &thorn;at cristine beoth,</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;at heo mowe to &thorn;e de&thorn;e hardie beon : ase heo &thorn;e i-seoth!"</L>
<L>"hov is &thorn;is?" seide &thorn;e king : "&yogh;we&thorn;ur &thorn;es &thorn;ef wene fi&yogh;te</L>
<L>And with-segge us al a-brod? : Ich him schal euene di&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Lateth &thorn;ene bischop a-wei gon : for is milde speche,</L>
<L N="16">Nimez vincent and bindez a-non : we schullen him o&thorn;ur tech[e].</L>
<L>With scourges and with staues : faste &yogh;e him bete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne mouw i-w<SUP>i</SUP>elde neuere a lime : are &thorn;at &yogh;e him lete!"</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e," seide vincent, "&thorn;ov pai&yogh;est me wel : &thorn;i word ne &thorn;inchez me nou&yogh;t ille,</L>
<L N="20">I-ne fond neuere Man &thorn;at so wel : a-cordede to mi wille:</L>
<L>&para; Nov ich hopie to habbe game : for erore me &thorn;ou&yogh;te longe;</L>
<L>hit schal me tuyrne to Ioye and gleo : and &thorn;e to<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. to &thorn;e</NOTE> pines stronge."</L>
<L>&THORN;e tormentores nomen &thorn;ane holie Man : and to a piler him bounde,</L>
<L N="24">With staues and scourges heo leiden on him<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> him on</NOTE> : and maden him mani a wounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo &yogh;euen him sorest duntes : lei&yogh;en he gan wel smere;</L>
<L>&THORN;e tormentores seten a-doun and cleopeden help : &thorn;o heo werie were,</L>
<L>And seiden : "we beoth nou&thorn;e ouer-come : ore Armes aketh sore;</L>
<L N="28">he[l]pez us and betez &thorn;esne<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;esne &thorn;esne</NOTE> &thorn;eof : for we ne mowen non<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. nou</NOTE> more."</L>
<L>&THORN;o was &thorn;e king wroth with heom : he let heom a-nou take,</L>
<L>Some he let tormenti sore : &thorn;at ech bon heom gan Ake,</L>
<L>And some he let to de&thorn;e bringue : and some in o&thorn;ur turment.<MILESTONE N="91b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="32">Euere he let ferschi and nevny<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. nevuy?</NOTE> : tormentores to seint Vincent.</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane heo weren werie of bete : &thorn;e holi man bi-gan to speke:</L>
<L>"Louerd, i-wuyr&thorn;ed beo &thorn;i name : nou&thorn;e ich am swi&thorn;e wel a-wreke:</L>
<L>&THORN;e more &thorn;at heo betez me : &thorn;e betere me is, i-wis;</L>
<L N="36">to heom i[t] torne&thorn; to pine and sor : and me to Ioie and blis."</L>
<L>&para; "Ne mowe we nov&yogh;t," seide &thorn;e king : "with no-&thorn;ing &thorn;ar-to it bringe
<PB REF="00000234.tif" N="186"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ov nelt nemme &thorn;ine false god : for no lu&thorn;ur betinge?"</L>
<L>"&THORN;ov lu&thorn;ere Man," seide Vincent : "&yogh;eot &thorn;ou most tormenti more,</L>
<L N="40">I-ne habbe nou&yogh;t &yogh;eot tormenz i-nouwe : &thorn;ar-after me longez sore."</L>
<L>&THORN;o he was i-scourget so : &thorn;at men mi&yogh;ten i-seo ech bon</L>
<L>And euerech Ioynt and senue : &thorn;e king gan ner him gon,</L>
<L>"Vincent," he seide, "haue of &thorn;i-self : rev&thorn;e and merci,</L>
<L N="44">Ne lat &thorn;ov non-more &thorn;i fa[i]re bodi : &thorn;us defouli!</L>
<L>bi-lief on ovre godes and torne anon : &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t and &thorn;i mod</L>
<L>And i-schal &thorn;e &yogh;iue ope al mi lond : pouwer gret and guod."</L>
<L>"beo stille," seide seint vincent : "al Atter is &thorn;i lore,</L>
<L N="48">beo stille a-non, &thorn;ou deueles tonge : &thorn;ou makest me drede sore:</L>
<L>hit me greueth &thorn;at &thorn;ov feinest &thorn;e : more &thorn;ane al &thorn;e pine</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e tormens &thorn;at &thorn;ov me dest : &thorn;ov and alle &thorn;ine;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ov bi-leuest &thorn;ine tormenz so sone : and art bi-neo&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="52">&YOGH;eot &thorn;ou most more Ioye : bringen in mi &thorn;ou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>"&THORN;ov schalt &yogh;eot," seide &thorn;e king : mo tormenz a-fonge."</L>
<L>he let him lede with-oute &thorn;e toun : and on a gibet him honge.</L>
<L>Vincent for Ioie bi-gan to eorne : &thorn;o he i-heorde &thorn;is dom,</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;are nas non &thorn;at him mi&yogh;te ouer-take : are he to &thorn;e gibat com.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at he an-hengut was : gret Ioye he made and blisse,</L>
<L>Euere he prechede ase he heng : godes wordes to wisse;</L>
<L>&THORN;e lengore &thorn;at he &thorn;are heng : &thorn;e more Ioie he made.</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;o gradden &thorn;e tormentores : "we ne schullen neuere ouer-come &thorn;is tade."</L>
<L>&para; At&thorn;e laste he nomen him a-doun : and ladden bi-fore &thorn;e kinge,</L>
<L>And seiden &thorn;at heo ne mi&yogh;ten him : for no&thorn;ing to de&thorn;e bringe.</L>
<L>"Alas," seide &thorn;e king &thorn;o : "is ore mi&yogh;te us bi-nome?</L>
<L N="64">&YOGH;ware-of seruieth ovre godes : &thorn;at &thorn;es &thorn;eof us schal ouer-come?</L>
<L>Ledez him with-oute &thorn;e toun : a gret fuyr &yogh;e &thorn;are make;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he beo a-midde i-brou&yogh;t : and i-bounde to one stake;</L>
<L>For-brenne he schal euerech lime : ne schal he &thorn;us him wer[e]:</L>
<L N="68">And &yogh;wane he is to douste I-barnd : we beoth i-brou&yogh;t of care."</L>
<L>&THORN;e tormentores nomen seint Vincent : and duden &thorn;e kingus heste.</L>
<L>&THORN;e holi man wende in-to &thorn;e fuyr : ase gladliche ase to one feste.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo wenden &thorn;at seint vincent : to douste i-brend were,</L>
<L>heo ornen hom and tolden &thorn;e kinge fore : gladdore neuere heo nere.
<PB REF="00000235.tif" N="187"></L>
<L>heo ne mi&yogh;ten so sone hom come : &thorn;at seint vincent nas er</L>
<L N="74">At home and stod bi-fore &thorn;e kinge&mdash; : mani sori man was &thorn;er!</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e tormentores tolden &thorn;e kingue : hov he i-barnd was.</L>
<L>"Alas! alas!" &thorn;e king seide : "neuerer i-schend i-nas!<MILESTONE N="92" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Schal &thorn;eos &thorn;ef us ouer-come? : Mahun, nou &thorn;in ore!</L>
<L>&THORN;ei he grete tormenz habbe i-haued : &yogh;eot ich can bi-&thorn;enche more."</L>
<L>he let nime platus of Ire : sum-del &thorn;unne and brode,</L>
<L N="80">And let heom legge amidde &thorn;e place : wel nei&yogh; ane cartes lode;</L>
<L>gret fuyr he let &thorn;ar-on make : and &thorn;o heo glowinde were,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wode-fuyr heo duden al a-wei : &thorn;ane guode man &thorn;udere heo bere</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e berninde plates him casten : and some &thorn;arof heo toke</L>
<L N="84">And leiden an-ouewarde is holi bodi : mid one Irene croke.</L>
<L>Al he was &thorn;ar-on ihud&mdash; : &thorn;e &yogh;ut nadde he none fere!</L>
<L>&THORN;at grece of him orn a-brod : ase &thorn;ei it frijnge were.</L>
<L>&THORN;e swy&thorn;ere &thorn;at he barnde : &thorn;e gladdore he him made;</L>
<L N="88">he lou&yogh; smere, &yogh;wane &thorn;e plates : In is flesch gonne wade;</L>
<L>At&thorn;e bi-ginningue he was glad : and gladdore at&thorn;enende.</L>
<L>"Alas! alas," &thorn;e king seide &thorn;o : "&thorn;es &thorn;ef us wole schende!</L>
<L>&THORN;is torment ne helpez us nou&yogh;t : an-o&thorn;ur we moten bi-&thorn;enche."</L>
<L N="92">he let maken a swy&thorn;e gret fuyr : &thorn;at no-&thorn;ing ne mi&yogh;te a-quenche:</L>
<L>&para; Seint Vincent huy lei[den] a-mide-warde : and seth&thorn;e salt heo nome</L>
<L>And Mid ladeles on is wondene it casten : in<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &amp; in</NOTE> &thorn;e fuyr i-lome,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e salt scholde is woundene frete : with &thorn;e brenninde fuyre;</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;e spranglinge of &thorn;e blode i-selt : wide men mi&yogh;ten i-huyre.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e," seide &thorn;is guode man : "&thorn;is is a swete feste!</L>
<L>Mani Ioye ichabbe i-haued : ake &thorn;is is on &thorn;e meste."</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane is blod spreinde In &thorn;e rof an hei&yogh; : he gan to lei&yogh;en smere.</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;anne was &thorn;e king and alle is men : In swy&thorn;e grete fere,</L>
<L>And seiden : "&thorn;es &thorn;ef us wole ouer-come. : Mahun, &yogh;ware is &thorn;i mi&yogh;te?</L>
<L>Schal &thorn;es &thorn;ef with is wichchinge : a&yogh;en &thorn;i power fi&yogh;te?"</L>
<L>"&YOGH;eot Ich &thorn;enche," seide &thorn;e king : "of one pine stronge;</L>
<L N="104">beo &thorn;es &thorn;ef &thorn;ar-on i-do : he ne schal nou&yogh;t libbe longe."</L>
<L>heo setten him in a swy&thorn;e deork put : &thorn;at in &thorn;e gayhole was,</L>
<L>So ful of sweordes pointes i-pi&yogh;te : ase Mede is ful of gras:</L>
<L>&THORN;are-oppe &thorn;anne holi man : heo casten, faste i-bounde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e pointes of &thorn;e swerdes scholden : &yogh;iuen him de&thorn;es woundes.
<PB REF="00000236.tif" N="188"></L>
<L>Faste heo loken alle &thorn;e dore : and leten him longe &thorn;ere beo</L>
<L N="110">Ope &thorn;e swerdes pointes in deorkhede : he ne mi&yogh;te no&thorn;ing i-seo.</L>
<L>&THORN;are cam an Aungel with a taper : brenninde in is hond,</L>
<L N="112">Of his pine he bar him op&mdash; : and &thorn;are was godes sonde!</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Aungel was &thorn;ar with him : ase longe ase he &thorn;are was,</L>
<L>Mid a brenninde taper, and Ioie gret : &thorn;at neuere more nas.</L>
<L>&THORN;o it was longe &thorn;are-afturward : &thorn;is men comen &thorn;erbi-side,</L>
<L N="116">And wende &thorn;at he were ded : ane stounde heo gonne a-bide:</L>
<L>&THORN;o i-heorden heo &thorn;is holi man : loude and murie singe</L>
<L>And herede god in heuene. : heo tolden &thorn;at &thorn;e kinge.</L>
<L>&THORN;o was &thorn;e &thorn;ing nei&yogh; i-swowe : and seide, sichinde wel sore:</L>
<L>"Alas, we beoth nou&thorn;e ouer-come : I-ne can<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. cam</NOTE> &thorn;enche non more;</L>
<L>Ovre godes ne helpez us nou&yogh;t : &thorn;at alle &thorn;ing habbeth to wolde.<MILESTONE N="92b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I-nelle neuere-eft a-&yogh;ein him fi&yogh;te : creaunt ichulle me holde.</L>
<L>&para; &YOGH;wane no pine ne mai him sle : o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing ichulle fonde:</L>
<L>"goth," he seide, "and maketh a bed : &thorn;at softeste in anie londe,</L>
<L>Of quoiltene and of materasz : of cheisel and of palle,</L>
<L N="126">And &thorn;anne leggez him &thorn;ar-on : swi&thorn;e softe with-alle."</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at bed was i-maket : to &thorn;e gayhole heo wende,</L>
<L N="128">And founden &thorn;are &thorn;at lij&yogh;t of heuene : &thorn;at ore louerd &thorn;udere sende.</L>
<L>Wel softe heo nomen &thorn;is holi man : and custen is sore wounden,</L>
<L>to Relikes heo gadereden stilleliche : &thorn;at heo of is blode founden;</L>
<L>heo leiden him in &thorn;at nesche bed. : and &thorn;o he was &thorn;aron,</L>
<L N="132">his preiere he dude to ore louerd crist : and deide &thorn;o a-non.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e king isai&yogh; &thorn;is &thorn;at he deide : so mildeliche in is bedde,</L>
<L>"tormenz," he seide, "we him habbeth i-do : vuele &thorn;arof us spedde:</L>
<L>Ded we wolleth him ouer-come : &yogh;wane we ne mi&yogh;ten a-liue.</L>
<L N="136">Into &thorn;e wilde felde : &thorn;at bodi &yogh;e beren wel bliue,</L>
<L>Wilde bestes and foules : to-drawe heo schullen it sone."</L>
<L>&THORN;is men brou&yogh;ten &thorn;at bodi &thorn;are : and duden &thorn;e kingus bone.</L>
<L>&THORN;are cam fleo a Rauon : and a-doun &thorn;are-bi he a-li&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="140">Kene and suy&thorn;e dredful : i-redi he was to fi&yogh;te;</L>
<L>&yogh;if &thorn;are come ani foul to : &thorn;at &thorn;is bodi i-sei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Rauon smot to grounde : ne mosten &thorn;are come non nei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&para; Ake Euere he drof heom a-wei : &thorn;udere &yogh;wane heo come;</L>
<L N="144">Ne mi&yogh;te &thorn;are come none so kene : &thorn;at o mossel &thorn;arof nome.
<PB REF="00000237.tif" N="189"></L>
<L>A wolf cam also &thorn;uder-ward : is mete for-to fette,</L>
<L>And wolde of &thorn;at bodi nime. : &thorn;e Rauon a-&yogh;ein him sette,</L>
<L>he flev and smot with bile and fot : &thorn;at &thorn;e wolf at&thorn;en ende</L>
<L N="148">blodi was and ouercome : a&yogh;en hamward he gan wende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Rauon wuste &thorn;is bodi longe : Iwemmed nou&yogh;t it nas.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e king it onder-&yogh;at : &thorn;at &thorn;e bodi i-hol was,</L>
<L>hom he let it fette a&yogh;en : and seide, "&yogh;wat may beo ovre red,</L>
<L N="152">&thorn;at we ne mouwen him ouer-come : no&thorn;er quik ne ded?</L>
<L>&YOGH;if we ne mouwen quik ne ded : ouer-come him a-londe</L>
<L>For no<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. ne</NOTE> quoyntise &thorn;at we mouwen do : a-watere we wollez fonde."</L>
<L>he let it lede fer into &thorn;e se : and bonde &thorn;arto mani a ston,</L>
<L N="156">And casten it out of a schip. : it bi-gan to sinke a-non.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;e Mariners i-seien &thorn;is : glade heo weren and bli&thorn;e;</L>
<L>For-to telle &thorn;e kinge fore : heo hi&yogh;eden hom wel bliue.</L>
<L>heo ne mi&yogh;ten so sone to londe come : &thorn;at heo ne founden a-londe</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;is holi Man wel faire ligge : a-bouen &thorn;e se-sonde.</L>
<L>Sore a-gremed and a-schamed : hom huy gonne wende;</L>
<L>&THORN;e kinge heo tolden al heore cas : fram &thorn;e furste to &thorn;e ende.</L>
<L>"Alas, alas," &thorn;e king seide : "&thorn;e schame and &thorn;e schonde!</L>
<L>We ne mowe him neuere ouer-come : quik ne ded, a-watere ne a-londe.</L>
<L>&para; Do we him out of ovre &thorn;ou&yogh;t : we ne mouwen us neuere a-wreke;</L>
<L>Ich drede &thorn;at he mi bane wor&thorn;e : I-here ich more of him speke."<MILESTONE N="93" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A-ni&yogh;t In slepe seint Vincent cam : to A womman &thorn;are-bi-side</L>
<L>And tolde hire &yogh;ware is bodi lai : and bad hire nou&yogh;t to longe a-bide</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;at heo it scholde burie sone : for him longuede after reste.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode womman it onderstod : &thorn;o heo a-wok, with &thorn;e beste:</L>
<L>heo wende and sou&yogh;te &thorn;is holi bodi : and fond it swi&thorn;e sone;</L>
<L N="172">heo dude it burie with gret honour : ase ri&yogh;t was for-to done.</L>
<L>&THORN;us seint vincent &thorn;e holie man : in Spayne endede is lif</L>
<L>And wende to &thorn;e blisse of heuene : after &thorn;is pines and strif.</L>
<L>Men nusten neuere martyr non : &thorn;at hadde more torment</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;at with som pine ouer-come nas : bote &thorn;e gode man seint vincent.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="31" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>31 Vita sancti Pauli.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint powel was a lu&thorn;er Man : are he i-couerted were.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e cristine Men of &thorn;e lond : hadden of him gret fere,
<PB REF="00000238.tif" N="190"></L>
<L>For he was muche and strong and feol. : &yogh;ware-so he eni founde,</L>
<L N="4">In chaumbre ne in bedde he ne sparede nou&yogh;t : &thorn;at he ne slov&yogh; heom alle to grounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he hadde a-boute Ierusalem : In eche stude i-sou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e cristine men &thorn;at he fond : to stronge de&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>he cam to &thorn;e souereyns of &thorn;e lawe : and seide, "ich habbe i-mad al clene</L>
<L N="8">Al &thorn;is lond of cristine Men : [&yogh;e]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> ne dorre of heom more mene:</L>
<L>Wende ichulle to Dam[a]sche : and clansi &thorn;at lond al-so;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at ich a-liue finde mai : to de&thorn;e ichulle heom do,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur ichulle heom faste binde : and hidere to eov sende;</L>
<L N="12">Alle &thorn;at ich a-liue finde may : ichulle a-sle o&thorn;ur schende."</L>
<L>&para; Saul was &thorn;o is ri&yogh;te name. : he gan forth i-wende,</L>
<L>I-Armed, and mani a man with him : to bringe is &thorn;ou&yogh;t to ende.</L>
<L>Ase he cam a-midri&yogh;t &thorn;e wei : a li&yogh;t him cam a-boute,</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;at he ne mi&yogh;te for li&yogh;te i-seon. : &thorn;o gan him sore a-doute;</L>
<L>he stod ase &thorn;ei he a-stoned were. : &thorn;o cam &thorn;are in a stounde</L>
<L>A drem ase &thorn;ei it a &thorn;ondre were. : &thorn;are-with he ful to grounde</L>
<L>And lai, &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;te him wawie nou&yogh;t. : &thorn;o herde he a uoiz telle :</L>
<L N="20">"Saul, &yogh;wi werrest&thorn;ov opon me : mine Men for-to quelle?"</L>
<L>"ho art &thorn;ov?" seide saul : "louerd, art&thorn;ov &thorn;are?"</L>
<L>A voiz seide, "&yogh;e, ich am &thorn;i god : &thorn;at &thorn;ov hast i-weorred so &yogh;are.</L>
<L>to wynci a&yogh;ein &thorn;e pricke : swi&thorn;e strong it is &thorn;e."</L>
<L N="24">"Louerd," seide Saul &thorn;o : "&yogh;wat wolt&thorn;ov do mid me?"</L>
<L>"&THORN;ov schalt," seide ore louerd &thorn;o : "In-to &thorn;e toune wende;</L>
<L>&THORN;ine ri&yogh;te bi-leue &thorn;e schal teche : a man, to &yogh;wam i-schal &thorn;e sende."&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is was &thorn;ene fourteo&thorn;e &yogh;er : aftur &thorn;ulke stounde</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;at Ihesu crist soffrede on &thorn;e rode : for us de&thorn;es wounde.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;o Saul hadde longe i-leie : wel softe he op a-ros</L>
<L>And stod op&mdash;he ne mi&yogh;te i-seo neuere a del : ful sore him a-gros.</L>
<L>he let him lede to &thorn;e toun. : it was &thorn;ane &thorn;ridde dai</L>
<L N="32">Are he .et. o&thorn;ur dronk : o&thorn;ur ani si&yogh;t i-sai&yogh;.</L>
<L>&para; Ore louerd cam to a guod preost : is name was ananye,</L>
<L>"go," he seide, "in-to &thorn;e toun : and to Iudases hous &thorn;ov hi&yogh;e:</L>
<L>Saul &thorn;ov schalt &thorn;are finde : &thorn;at i-weorred me hauez longue;<MILESTONE N="93b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="36">&YOGH;if him cristindom in mine name : and he it wole onder-fonge.
<PB REF="00000239.tif" N="191"></L>
<L>sei&yogh;e &thorn;at god &thorn;e &thorn;udere sende : &thorn;at In &thorn;e weie a-&yogh;ein him cam</L>
<L>&THORN;o he wolde a&yogh;ein him weorri : and is power him bi<NOTE PLACE="marg1">bi <I>overlined</I></NOTE>-nam."</L>
<L>'Louerd," seide Ananie : "ich habbe muche i-heord telle</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at Saul was a lu&thorn;er man : and cristine men dude quelle."</L>
<L>"Ne dred &thorn;e nou&yogh;t," ore louerd seide : "lomb he is bi-come,</L>
<L>him &thorn;inchez longe are he habbe : cristinedom i-nome.</L>
<L>to beo prechour of mi word : i-chose ich him habbe;</L>
<L N="44">he schal beo wis and studefast : nanne betere i-nabbe."</L>
<L>&THORN;o Ananie i-heorde &thorn;is : hardiliche forth he wende.</L>
<L>he cam to Saule and seide him so : &thorn;at ore louerd him &thorn;udere sende</L>
<L>&THORN;at he scholde cristine beo. : saul was &thorn;o wel bli&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="48">And er &thorn;ane he i-baptized was : ech &yogh;wyle him &thorn;ou&yogh;te fiue.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he i-baptized was : powel was is name.</L>
<L>Wel au&yogh;ten men herien &thorn;ane god : &thorn;at of &thorn;e wilde makez &thorn;e tame!</L>
<L>A-non so he I-baptized was : &thorn;are feol out of ei&thorn;er ei&yogh;e</L>
<L N="52">Fuyl&thorn;e ase &thorn;ei it were slym : &thorn;at alle &thorn;e men it sei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&thorn;o mi&yogh;te he swi&thorn;e wel i-seo. : he heold op is honde,</L>
<L>&para; A-knevwes he sat in his bedes : and &thorn;onkede godes sonde.</L>
<L>tendre metes men grei&thorn;ede him : and &yogh;af him &thorn;ar-of wel ofte,</L>
<L N="56">&YOGH;if he mi&yogh;te is strenc&thorn;e coueri : heo beddeden him wel softe.</L>
<L>&THORN;o seint powel i-couered was : and hadde strenc&thorn;e of Manne,</L>
<L>he purueide him of prechingue : and wende a-non ri&yogh;t &thorn;anne</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e giwene synagogue : and prechede cristindom.</L>
<L N="60">Ech man wondrede &thorn;at him i-sai&yogh; : &thorn;o he prechour bi-cam,</L>
<L>And seiden : "nis &thorn;is &thorn;ilke man : &thorn;at weorrede alle &thorn;eo</L>
<L>In &thorn;e londe of Ierusalem : &thorn;at he mi&yogh;te o&yogh;were cristine men I-seo?"</L>
<L>Manie Men he tornede to cristinedom : and manie him &thorn;ou&yogh;ten quelle</L>
<L>And bi-speken hov heo mi&yogh;ten do : for he bi-gan a-&yogh;ein heom telle.</L>
<L>he ne let for no drede : &thorn;at he ne prechede wel bliue.</L>
<L>For euere &thorn;oru ore louerdes grace : he ascapede with &thorn;e liue.</L>
<L>he sou&yogh;te &yogh;ware &thorn;e Apostles weren : to heom he cam wel sone,</L>
<L N="68">to prechi mid heom godes word : ase hore ri&yogh;te was to done.</L>
<L>&THORN;e apostles weren formest a-ferd of him : and leueden him wel vnne&thorn;e,</L>
<L>For he so muche cristine folk : hadde i-brou&yogh;t to de&thorn;e;</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;o heo wusten hou it was : to felawe [heo] him toke&mdash;</L>
<L N="72">For &thorn;are ne i-werth non so wis : holi churche to loke.
<PB REF="00000240.tif" N="192"></L>
<L>Seint powel to cristinedom : cam In &thorn;usse manere.</L>
<L>god us graunti for is loue : In heuene to ben is fere.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="32" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>32 Vita sancte Brigide virginis.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seinte Bride of hei&yogh;e men : In scotlond heo cam,</L>
<L>Of riche men and of gret power : In lawe of cristindom.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Maide bi-gan wel &yogh;ong : to beo of porture hende;</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;are ne scholde vil dede ne word : neuere fram hire wende.</L>
<L>heo bigan ore louerd crist to serui : in worde and in dede;</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane hire &yogh;ongue felawes weren at&thorn;e plei&yogh; : hire oresones heo seide.<MILESTONE N="94" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; hire moder louede hire swi&thorn;e wel : &thorn;at, &thorn;o heo was of elde,</L>
<L N="8">Al hire chese and al hire milk : heo bi-tok hire to welde,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;et &yogh;wijt &thorn;at In &thorn;e court was : heo scholde ope hire helde,</L>
<L>At a certeyn dai &thorn;arof : trewe a-countes &yogh;elde.</L>
<L>&THORN;at Maide let gaderi swi&thorn;e clene : &thorn;e Milk ant &thorn;e chese,</L>
<L N="12">botere and al &thorn;at &thorn;arof cam : nolde heo nowi&yogh;t leose :</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane heo sei&yogh;e anie pouere Men : heo delde it heom wel clene&mdash;</L>
<L>hire deierie was euere of chese and botere : bar and swi&thorn;e lene.</L>
<L>&YOGH;wan hire dai&yogh; was nei&yogh; i-come : a-countes forto &yogh;elde,</L>
<L N="16">Of hire moder heo was a-ferd : glad heo was ful selde.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eorne heo bad ore louerd crist : &thorn;at he scholde beo hire red,</L>
<L>he nadde &yogh;warof a-countes &yogh;elde : ase hire moder hadde i-seid.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e day was i-come : heo nuste &yogh;ware-with hire a-quite,</L>
<L N="20">For &thorn;are nas in &thorn;e deierie : nou&yogh;t adel of none &yogh;wite.</L>
<L>Na&thorn;eles &thorn;e moder eode &thorn;udere : to loke hou it ferde :</L>
<L>heo fond ech lome i-heped ful : al a-boue &thorn;e brerde,</L>
<L>Of chese and of botere : and of o&thorn;ur &yogh;wijte also.</L>
<L N="24">he ne may neuere is &yogh;wyle leose : &thorn;at for &thorn;e guode wole ou&yogh;t do.</L>
<L>hit bi-feol &thorn;at &thorn;is Maydenes frend : nomen heom to rede</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo i-weddet scholde beo. : and heo anon-ri&yogh;t heom with-seide.</L>
<L>to &thorn;e bischope heo wende a-non : and a-vouwede chastete,</L>
<L N="28">And seide heo nolde neuere man habbe : &thorn;e sikerore for-to beo.</L>
<L>For Ioye &thorn;at &thorn;e bischop hadde of hire : he seide &thorn;a[t] he wolde ete,</L>
<L>And alle is Men, a dai with hire : he bad hire maken heore mete.</L>
<L>&THORN;arof was &thorn;is Maide glad : and na&thorn;eles sore heo hire dradde,</L>
<L N="32">For bote bred and Ale and one kou : non more mete heo nadde.
<PB REF="00000241.tif" N="193"></L>
<L>heo bi-gan to milken &thorn;is cov : and muche milk of hire heo nam<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. mam</NOTE>;</L>
<L>&THORN;e lengore &thorn;at heo hire Milkede : &thorn;e more milk &thorn;are cam :</L>
<L>&THORN;is kov &yogh;af so muche Milk : &thorn;at &thorn;are-mide heo fedde</L>
<L>&THORN;ene bischop and alle is Men &thorn;at dai : and muche &thorn;onk &thorn;arof hadde.</L>
<L>&para; hit bi-feol &thorn;are-after-ward : &thorn;at Maide a-feld wende,</L>
<L>Forto loki to hire schep. : so gret rein ore louerd to eor&thorn;e sende</L>
<L>&THORN;at hire clo&thorn;es al wete weren. : and a-&yogh;en hom<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. heom</NOTE> heo gan gon.</L>
<L N="40">heo wolde hangi hire clo&thorn;us forto druye : and heo ne sai&yogh; nou&yogh;t &yogh;waron.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sonne schon In at one hole : and ope &thorn;e bem of &thorn;e sonne</L>
<L>hire wete clo&thorn;es heo heng forto druy&yogh;e : &thorn;at &thorn;e stremes a-doun ronne.</L>
<L>Museles comen to hire adai : of-hongrede and of-cale,</L>
<L N="44">heo beden hire mete and drinke for godes loue. : he nadde nou&yogh;t a spone-ful ale.</L>
<L>A fat &thorn;are stod fol of ba&thorn;e-water : heo &yogh;af it hire blessinge :</L>
<L>&THORN;e beste Ale a-liue it bi-cam : he &yogh;af it &thorn;e Museles drinke.</L>
<L>A womman cam and bad hire salt : and heo ne hadde non :</L>
<L N="48">With hire blessingue heo turnede to salte : ane wel grete ston.</L>
<L>&THORN;re sike men beden hire guod : ase heo to hire come.</L>
<L>A seluerne coppe heo [heom] &yogh;af : and gladliche heo hire nome;</L>
<L>And bi-gunne for-to striui : hov heo hire dele mi&yogh;te.<MILESTONE N="94b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="52">"Abidez," seide &thorn;is Maide : "and ichulle it euene di&yogh;te."</L>
<L>&THORN;is Coppe heo smot a&yogh;en a ston : &thorn;at heo to-brak a&thorn;re;</L>
<L>Euerech heo &yogh;af iliche muche : ase euene ase it mi&yogh;te beo.</L>
<L>&THORN;eos miracles, and manie o&thorn;ure : seinte Bride wrou&yogh;te;</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;e blinde and &thorn;e doumbe : to guode hele heom brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste dai of feuerer : hire lijf heo brou&yogh;te to ende.</L>
<L>god us graunti alle forth with hire : te<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. to &thorn;e</NOTE> blisse of heuene wende.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="33" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>33 Vita sancte Agathe.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEinte Agace, &thorn;at guode Maide : In cisile was i-bore;</L>
<L>Wel &yogh;ong heo bi-gan cristine to beon : &thorn;at hire soule nere fur|lore.</L>
<L>Of faire porture &thorn;is Mayde was : and stable in godes lore.</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;e Duyk of &thorn;e londe it onder-&yogh;at : it him of-&thorn;ou&yogh;te sore.</L>
<L>he ne mi&yogh;te for rev&thorn;e don hire in pine : Al for hire &yogh;onghede;
<PB REF="00000242.tif" N="194"></L>
<L>And for heo so fair was : he hopede hire out of &thorn;ulke bi-leue lede.</L>
<L>An old quene &thorn;are was bi-side : strong hore and baudestrote;</L>
<L N="8">heo hadde Ni&yogh;e dou&yogh;tren li&yogh;t wummen. : &thorn;e Duyk bi-gan hire gret mede bi-hote,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo scholde &thorn;at maide wite : and mis-techen hire and rede,</L>
<L>And fondi &yogh;if heo mi&yogh;te hire bringe : in fol &thorn;ou&yogh;t o&thorn;ur in fol dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;is clene &thorn;ing was to &thorn;is hore i-brou&yogh;t : &thorn;at hei&yogh;te Affrodose.</L>
<L N="12">heo, and hire dou&yogh;tren al-so : maden hire &thorn;e glose,</L>
<L>And bi-hete hire quoynte &thorn;ingus fale : of seluer and of golde,</L>
<L>Richesse and o&thorn;ur Ioye i-nou&yogh; : &thorn;at heo hire &thorn;ou&yogh;t chaungi scholde;</L>
<L>heo seiden : "hov mi&yogh;te a swuche creature : &thorn;us gent and &thorn;us freo,</L>
<L N="16">hende and milde and swete i-nov&yogh; : with-oute Iolifte [beo]?</L>
<L>&THORN;i &yogh;ongue blod nolde it &thorn;olie nou&yogh;t : scholde &thorn;i Ioie beon &thorn;e bi-nome;</L>
<L>In &thorn;is lond nis prince so hei&yogh; : &thorn;at &thorn;ov ne mi&yogh;test him wel bi-come."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is Maide, &thorn;ei heo were &yogh;ong : bi-gan to Answerie a-non,</L>
<L>And seide, "beo stille, &thorn;ou deueles bouk! : &thorn;e ne worth here non i-won.</L>
<L>&THORN;e hexte prince &thorn;at is ani : In loue ich habbe i-take,</L>
<L N="22">In mine &yogh;onghede and euere-more : to holde him for mi make.</L>
<L>Swete and hende and milde he is : on him is al mi &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ich am so faste to him i-bounde : &thorn;ar-of ne bringuest &thorn;ou me nou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>&THORN;is lu&thorn;ere wummen weren ech-one : studefastliche Ni&yogh;t and dai&yogh;</L>
<L N="26">A-boute to bringue lu&thorn;er &thorn;ou&yogh;t : In-to &thorn;is swete &yogh;ounge may&yogh;;</L>
<L>&THORN;ritti dawes heo was with heom : &thorn;at heo fondeden euere</L>
<L N="28">to bringue hire into &thorn;e deueles lore : Ake heo ne spedden neuere.</L>
<L>&THORN;is wychche wende to &thorn;e Duyk &thorn;o : &thorn;at het quincian,</L>
<L>And seide, "sire, i-ne mai chaungi nou&yogh;t : &thorn;e &thorn;ou&yogh;t of &thorn;is womman;</L>
<L>Li&yogh;tloker man may &thorn;ane hardeste ston : make nesche ase wolle</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;ane &thorn;at Maide &thorn;oru&yogh; any gin : of hire &thorn;ou&yogh;t bringe schulle."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Duyk let a-non &thorn;is mayde fette : and Axede &yogh;wat heo were.</L>
<L>"godes schulchone," heo seide, "ich am" : heo nadde none fere.</L>
<L>he Axede of &yogh;wat kunne heo were. : heo seide, "of gent and freo."</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;e Duyk seide, "hov mi&yogh;t &thorn;ov gentil womman : and eke a schulchone beo?"</L>
<L>"&YOGH;us," seide &thorn;at maide &thorn;o : "hit is more fraunchise</L>
<L>to beon gode[s]schulchene o&thorn;er is &thorn;ral : &thorn;ane king o&thorn;ur Iustise."<MILESTONE N="95" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"Anovre ovre godes!" seide &thorn;e Duyk : "ne spec of &thorn;i god non-more,
<PB REF="00000243.tif" N="195"></L>
<L N="40">O&thorn;ur ichulle &thorn;e swuch pine do : &thorn;at it schal &thorn;e rewe sore."</L>
<L>"I-ne schal so sone," &thorn;at maide seide : "In pine beo i-brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at it nele a-swagi &yogh;if ich habbe : on ihesu crist mi &thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou bringest me in ani fuyre : and ich me bi-&thorn;enche</L>
<L N="44">On &thorn;e pine &thorn;at he &thorn;olede for me : a-non it wole a-quenche."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Duyk let nime &thorn;at maide a-non : and In-to &thorn;e gayhole lede;</L>
<L>&THORN;at maide was &thorn;o also glad : ase &thorn;ei men hire to feste bede.</L>
<L>In stronge prisone heo was i-do : &thorn;ar-inne longe heo lay.</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;e Duyk let &thorn;are-after-warde : at-fore him &thorn;at mayde bringe a day.</L>
<L>&para; "Agace," he seide, "bi-&thorn;ench &thorn;e wel : bi-lef &thorn;i fole &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Anovre ore<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. ore ore</NOTE> godes &thorn;at mowen &thorn;e helpe : are &thorn;ou beo in pine i-brou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>&THORN;at maide seide, "&thorn;ou spillest &thorn;i breth : and &thorn;ou tellest embe nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="52">Ake ich rede &thorn;at &thorn;ou Anouri him : &thorn;at deore us hath i-bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And bi-lef &thorn;ine false godes : &thorn;at power nabbez non,</L>
<L>&THORN;at beoth i-mad of an old stoc : o&thorn;ur of &thorn;e harde ston."</L>
<L>"Nelt&thorn;ou [nou]&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. Nelt&thorn;ou&yogh;t</NOTE>," seide &thorn;e duyk : "&thorn;ine folie &yogh;uyt bi-leue,</L>
<L N="56">In stronge pine &thorn;ov schalt beo i-don : to-day are it beo eue."</L>
<L>hokes and witthene he let nime : and faste to hire breoste binde,</L>
<L>And let is tormentores with &thorn;e with&thorn;ene : hire breostene of wynde.</L>
<L>"&THORN;ov onwreste bouk," &thorn;is Maide seide : to &thorn;e duyk quincian,</L>
<L N="60">"Ne hast&thorn;ov no schame in &thorn;ine heorte : defouli &thorn;us ani man</L>
<L>&THORN;at lyme &thorn;at &thorn;ov &thorn;i moder of soke : and &thorn;e hath forth i-brou&yogh;t?</L>
<L>Do &thorn;ov &thorn;in owene confusion : and ne dred &thorn;e ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>&para; gret pine &thorn;olede &thorn;is clene [may] : are heo weren of i-drawe;</L>
<L N="64">So muche was hire &thorn;ou&yogh;t on gode : &thorn;at it ne greuede hire nou&yogh;t an hawe.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo weren of i-drawe : In-to prisone heo was eft i-do.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Duyk let witie &thorn;at prison faste : &thorn;at no man ne come hire to</L>
<L>hire woundene to hele with ani-&thorn;ing : o&thorn;ur hire pines forto lisse.</L>
<L N="68">Ake ore louerd ne for-&yogh;at nou&yogh;t hire : &thorn;o ne &thorn;orte he misse.</L>
<L>Ase heo in prisone al one was : an old man &thorn;are cam gon,</L>
<L>boxes fulle of Oygneme[n]z : he brou&yogh;te mani on</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;at he hire hele wolde. : "&thorn;ov ne schalt," heo seide;</L>
<L N="72">"I-ne kepe no man bote god : &thorn;at me hele and rede."</L>
<L>"Ich am," seide &thorn;e olde man : "In his name hidere i-wend,
<PB REF="00000244.tif" N="196"></L>
<L>For ich am his apostle&mdash; : to &thorn;e he me hath i-send</L>
<L>&THORN;ine woundene forto hele : &thorn;at &thorn;ov hast for him stronge.</L>
<L N="76">In &thorn;e Ioye of heuene : &thorn;ine mede &thorn;ou schalt afonge."</L>
<L>&THORN;e woundes he gan smeorie : heo weren hole in one stounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;at Maide nuste &yogh;ware he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. heo</NOTE> bi-cam : &thorn;o he hadde i-held hire wounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Duyk let &thorn;at maide bi-fore him bringe : &thorn;ene feor&thorn;e day,</L>
<L>he seide, "hast&thorn;ov &yogh;eot i-chaunget &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t?" : &thorn;at mayde seide "nay.</L>
<L>&THORN;i word," heo seide, "ne doth non o&thorn;ur : &yogh;wane &thorn;ov spext &thorn;us to me,</L>
<L N="82">bote fuylez swi&thorn;e foule &thorn;e eyr : &thorn;at it deth inne fleo.</L>
<L>he is wod &thorn;at stok o&thorn;ur ston : wole to helpe calle,<MILESTONE N="95b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="84">And nou&yogh;t to god of heuene : &thorn;at hath i-heled mine wounden alle."</L>
<L>"Darst&thorn;ou &yogh;eot," seide &thorn;e Duyk : "of &thorn;ine false gode more telle?</L>
<L>Beo &thorn;ov so wod to nemmen him more : in stronge de&thorn;e Man schal &thorn;e quelle."</L>
<L>"Onwreste bouk," &thorn;at Maide seide : "I-nelle it lete nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;e &yogh;wyle &thorn;at ich libbe may : to nemen him with worde o&thorn;ur with &thorn;ou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Duyk het men hire for-brenne : a gret fuyr he let make.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo [hire] wolden &thorn;ar-inne do : &thorn;e eor&thorn;e bi-gan to quake,</L>
<L>&para; Ase wide ase &thorn;e cite was : and felde a-doun &thorn;e dom-halle;</L>
<L>Twei men &thorn;at hire Iuggeden to de&thorn;e : a-slawe weren with &thorn;e walle.</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk of &thorn;e cite was a-drad. : to &thorn;e duyke heo seiden:</L>
<L N="94">"&THORN;is Mayde is guod, and we beth for hire : In grete perile and in drede.</L>
<L>gret pine &thorn;ov hast [hire] i-don : &thorn;ou ne schal so non-more."</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;o &thorn;e Duyk i-herde &thorn;is : a-drad he was wel sore;</L>
<L>&THORN;at Mayde he let to prisone lede : and he him-seolf a-scapede a-wey</L>
<L>bi one posterne stilleliche : &thorn;at no man him ne sey&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at mayde into prisone cam : a-doun heo sat a-kneo,</L>
<L N="100">"Louerd," he seide, "fram mani pine : &thorn;ou hast i-saued me,</L>
<L>fram fuyr and fram woundes stronge : &thorn;ou me hast i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And fram mi child-hod &thorn;ou me hast i-wust : &thorn;at ine mis-bi-lefde nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Lat me, louerd, to reste wende : for here me &thorn;inchez long,</L>
<L N="104">Tyme it is to endi mi lijf : mine soule &thorn;ov onder-fong."</L>
<L>Mid &thorn;usse worde bi-fore al &thorn;at folk : heo bi-gan to dei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;are was mani a sori man : and mani a wepinde ei&yogh;e.
<PB REF="00000245.tif" N="197"></L>
<L>&THORN;at folk &thorn;at hire louede : siwede hire wel faste,</L>
<L N="108">hire bodi heo nomen with gret honour : and bureden it at&thorn;e laste.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo bureden &thorn;at holi bodi : a felawe-schipe &thorn;are cam go</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e faireste children &thorn;at mi&yogh;ten beo : &thorn;re hondret and wel mo,</L>
<L>&YOGH;onge &thorn;ingus of on age : in &yogh;wite clo&thorn;us of palle;</L>
<L N="112">Ane table of Marbre In is hond : &thorn;e on bar at-fore heom alle:</L>
<L>&para; heo Ioyneden it to seinte Agace toumbe : &thorn;o heo comen &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>Wel sweteliche heo wenden a&yogh;en : &thorn;o heo hadden so i-do&mdash;</L>
<L>Angles it weren &thorn;at &thorn;are a-li&yogh;ten : for seinte Agace to grounde.</L>
<L N="116">Clerkes bi-heolden &thorn;e table &yogh;eorne : &thorn;are-Inne i-write huy founde:</L>
<L>"&THORN;is Maide hadde holi &thorn;ou&yogh;t : god heo dude honour,</L>
<L>A-serued heo hath to alle &thorn;e contreie : deliueraunce of langour."</L>
<L>For-so&thorn;e heo mi&yogh;ten &thorn;is laste word : &thorn;ar-after onder-stonde:</L>
<L N="120">&thorn;ulke time a twelf-Mon&thorn;e : of an hul in &thorn;e londe</L>
<L>Strong fuyr &thorn;are cam eornen out : ase water doth of welle,</L>
<L>And barnde al &thorn;at &thorn;are was a-boute : quic &thorn;ing it gan a-quelle;</L>
<L>hit spradde wide into al &thorn;at lond : &thorn;at folk hadde grete fere,</L>
<L N="124">And barnde &thorn;e hard roche of ston : ase &thorn;ei it Col were.</L>
<L>heo ne dorsten bi-leue at no toun : ake ornen ase men &thorn;at were wode:</L>
<L>At seinte Agace Toumbe : &thorn;are heo formest at-stode.</L>
<L>Al-so it bi-feol in hire daye : ase sone ase heo weren &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;at fuyr queinte a-non in-to al &thorn;at lond : ase &thorn;ei it neuere nere;<MILESTONE N="96" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And bi-fore it hadde six dawes i-last : and six Nij&yogh;t al-so,</L>
<L>And orn ase &thorn;ei it water were : for-barnde al &thorn;at him cam to.</L>
<L>&THORN;o schewede ore louerd &thorn;at it was soth : &thorn;at &thorn;e maide seinte Agas</L>
<L>A-seruede deliueraunce to al &thorn;e Contree&mdash; : &thorn;are wel i-sene it was.</L>
<L>Al-so w[i]sliche we schullen hire bidde : ase heo &thorn;e contreie &yogh;af bote,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we to &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;are heo is Inne : with hire come we mote.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="34" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>34 [Scholace]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEinte scholace, &thorn;at holie mayde : heo was of clene liue,</L>
<L>Leouere heo hadde to beon Nonne : &thorn;ane beon i-widdet to wiue.</L>
<L>Seint Beneit hire bro&thorn;er was : and &thorn;e Ordre furst bi-fond</L>
<L N="4">Of Nonnes and of blake Monekus : &thorn;at is &yogh;uyt into al &thorn;at lond;</L>
<L>Of blake Monekus at Duyn : An Abbeye he let a-rere,</L>
<L>him-sulf &thorn;e Abite furst he nam : &thorn;e &yogh;ongore for-to lere.
<PB REF="00000246.tif" N="198"></L>
<L>Seinte Scholace, his soster : blac Nonne he let hire make,</L>
<L N="8">And tei&yogh;te hire penaunce forto don : to faste and to wake.</L>
<L>&THORN;eos twei&yogh;e holie creatures : eche &yogh;ere hadden ane wone</L>
<L>to comen to-gadere some Tyme : and tellen of godes sone;</L>
<L>Ake heore no&thorn;er in o&thorn;eres Abbeye : bi-leue come ne mi&yogh;te</L>
<L N="12">Ne duelle for none &thorn;inge : oute of heore celle bi Ni&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;is guode holi mayde : i-brou&yogh;t was in grete Elde,</L>
<L>hire longuede with hire bro&thorn;er to speke : feble heo hire felde.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo hadde to him i-sent : and to-gadere heo weren i-come,</L>
<L N="16">Al dai heo tolden of godes priuetez : seinte Marie sone,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Ioye of heuene : hou holi men heore [lif] ladden;</L>
<L>&THORN;are-of al heore Ioye was : &thorn;at heo to-gadere hadden.</L>
<L>Sorie weren &thorn;is holie &thorn;ingus bo&thorn;e : for it was sumdel nei&yogh; Eue.</L>
<L N="20">Seint Beneit to is soster seide : &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;te no leng bi-leue.</L>
<L>Seinte scholace sori was. : "bro&thorn;ur," heo seide, "&thorn;in ore,</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie wordus so murie beoth : &yogh;eot we moten telle more;</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane we In godes seruise beoth : we ne doz nou&yogh;t ore ordre breke.</L>
<L N="24">Ich am so feble &thorn;at ich ne wene : neuer-eft more with &thorn;e speke;</L>
<L>bi-leue we &thorn;is one Ni&yogh;t to-gadere : for his loue &thorn;at deore us bou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Ich wot &thorn;at he it wole us for-&yogh;iue : &yogh;wane we it doth in guode &thorn;ou&yogh;te."</L>
<L>"beo stille," seide seint beneit : "loke &yogh;wat &thorn;ou dest telle,</L>
<L N="28">Wel &thorn;ov wost &thorn;at ine mai beo : bi ni&yogh;te fram mine celle."</L>
<L>&THORN;o scholace i-sai&yogh; &thorn;at it ne heold : to bidde hire bro&thorn;ur more,</L>
<L>hire heued he hangede a-doun : and bi-gan to wepe sore.</L>
<L>"Louerd," heo seide, "&thorn;at &thorn;ov art : ful of milce and ore,</L>
<L N="32">Lat me, louerd, &yogh;if &thorn;i wille it beo : i-heore more of &thorn;i lore;</L>
<L>&para; Ne lat nou&yogh;t mi bro&thorn;ur to-Ni&yogh;t : fram me, louerd, wende,</L>
<L>Ake soffre us with tales of &thorn;e : bringe &thorn;is ni&yogh;t to ende."</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;is Maide loke<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. lokede</NOTE> opward : &thorn;o heo hadde i-don hire bone,</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;at weder &thorn;at was so cler and fair : bi-gan to chaungie sone;</L>
<L>hit bi-gan to &thorn;ondri and hauli : lei&yogh;ten and eke rine,</L>
<L>&THORN;at feor with-Inne Ni&yogh;te it was : er &thorn;at weder wolde a-fine.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o ne mi&yogh;te seint beneit : for &thorn;e wedere &thorn;annes i-wende.<MILESTONE N="96b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"Soster," he seide, "&yogh;wat hast&thorn;ov i-don? : &thorn;ou fondest me to schende;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if it nere ore louerdes wille : wel ne dost &thorn;ov nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="42">&THORN;at i-schal mine ordre breke : so nadde ich neuere i-&thorn;ou&yogh;t."
<PB REF="00000247.tif" N="199"></L>
<L>"Leue bro&thorn;er," &thorn;at maide seide : "ich bad &thorn;e swi&thorn;e &yogh;erne</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at &thorn;ou &thorn;is ni&yogh;t bi-lefdest here : and euere &thorn;ov dudest me werne:</L>
<L>Ich bad mi louerd of heuene : and he me i-herde a-non.</L>
<L>Cheos nou&thorn;e &yogh;wa&thorn;er &thorn;ov bi-leue wolt : o&thorn;ur heonnes for-to gon,</L>
<L>bi-lef me alone &yogh;if &thorn;ov mi&yogh;t : for no &thorn;onk ne can ich &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="48">Ake ich &thorn;onki god of heuene : &thorn;at so sone i-heorde me."</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo ne mi&yogh;ten departi nou&yogh;t : to-gadere al ni&yogh;t heo woke,</L>
<L>And tolden of godes suettnesse : and of is mi&yogh;te : In tale and eke in boke.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Ni&yogh;t heom &thorn;ov[&yogh;te] suy&thorn;e schort : and sorie at &thorn;ene ende</L>
<L>heo weren &thorn;o heo &thorn;ane dai&yogh; i-sei&yogh;en : &yogh;wane heo scholden a-to i-wende.</L>
<L>heo ne dorsten no lengore to-gadere beo : ac wenden to heore celle,</L>
<L>heo weren bo&thorn;e swi&thorn;e sorie : &thorn;at heo ne mi&yogh;ten no leng to-gadere duelle.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at Maide was hom i-come : sore sik heo lay&yogh;,</L>
<L N="56">And ase it godes wille was : heo deide &thorn;ane &thorn;ridde dai&yogh;.</L>
<L>Seint Beneit in is celle eode : his soster soule he i-sei&yogh;</L>
<L>In fourme of a &yogh;wi&yogh;t Coluere : fleon op into heuene an hei&yogh;;</L>
<L>heouene openede a-&yogh;eines hire : &thorn;e Coluere gan in fleo.</L>
<L N="60">glad was &thorn;is holi man : &thorn;at he it mi&yogh;te i-seo!</L>
<L>A-moruwe he and is couent : &thorn;udere wenden sone</L>
<L>And bureden &thorn;at holi maide : ase it was ri&yogh;t to done.</L>
<L>bidde we suete Ihesu crist : &thorn;at is so fair and hende,</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;at we moten &thorn;udere comen : ase scholace dude i-wende.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="35" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>35 Purgatorium sancti Patrici abb[at]is.<NOTE PLACE="foot">I have published this legend before in <I>Altengl. Legenden</I>, Paderborn, 1875, p. 177 ff, together with two other versious.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint paterik &thorn;oru godes grace : makede ane put in Irlonde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at seint patrike purgatorie is icleoped : &yogh;eot, ase ich onderstonde.</L>
<L>Ore louerd him bi-tok ane staf : mid is owene honde,</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;at he fond &thorn;ulke purgatorie with : i-hered beo godes sonde!</L>
<L>In Irlonde is &yogh;eot &thorn;ilke staf i-wust : derewor&thorn;eliche i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L>For gret relike he is i-holde : and elles it were wou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Seint paterik in &thorn;ulke stude : &thorn;at his purgatorie is,</L>
<L N="8">Of religion bi-gan an hous : &thorn;at &yogh;eot stant, i-wis,</L>
<L>Ant Chanoynes &thorn;are-inne he makede : ase &yogh;eot &thorn;are beoth al-so.
<PB REF="00000248.tif" N="200"></L>
<L>&THORN;ane put he let faste closi a-boute : &thorn;at noman ne come &thorn;ar-to.</L>
<L>&para; In &thorn;e churche-&yogh;erd is &thorn;at ilke putt : ri&yogh;t toward &thorn;e Est-side,</L>
<L>ri&yogh;t est fram &thorn;e hei&yogh;e Au&yogh;ter : &thorn;at manie men &yogh;wylene sou&yogh;ten wide.</L>
<L>he is bi-walled faste a-boute<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. abooute</NOTE> : and faste i-loke &thorn;e &yogh;ate,</L>
<L N="14">And &thorn;e prior haueth &thorn;e kei&yogh;e in warde : &thorn;at no man ne mot In &thorn;ar-ate.</L>
<L>Al bi seint paterikes dai&yogh;e : men wenden &thorn;udere i-lome,</L>
<L N="16">And seth&thorn;e also mani on : and fewe a&yogh;en &thorn;are come;</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;ulke &thorn;at &thorn;are comen a&yogh;en : of &thorn;at heo i-sei&yogh;en, heo tolde,</L>
<L>Ase it is in &thorn;e house i-write : and in priue conseile i-holde.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e manere is of euerech man : &thorn;at for-so&thorn;e &thorn;udere i-went,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it beo to bete is sunnes : &yogh;if ore louerd him grace [sent].<MILESTONE N="97" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>to &thorn;e bischope of &thorn;e lond : furst he schal him schriue,</L>
<L N="22">And bidde him leue &thorn;ene wey to go : in amendement of is liue.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;e bischop schal rede heom<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. him</NOTE> &thorn;are-a-&yogh;ein : and manie resones schewe,</L>
<L>And segge &thorn;at manie &thorn;udere wendeth : and a&yogh;ein &thorn;are comieth fewe.</L>
<L>Ake &yogh;if he is stable in is &thorn;ou&yogh;t : for al &thorn;at men him habbez i-bede,</L>
<L N="26">&THORN;e bischop him wole is lettre make : to &thorn;e prior of &thorn;e stude.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e prior him wole al-so rede i-nov&yogh; : for-to chaungi is &thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="28">And, &yogh;wane he si&yogh;kz him studefast : &thorn;at he nele bi-leue it nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In-to churche he wole him lede : and sette him a-doun a-kne;</L>
<L>Fiftene dawes he schal &thorn;are : in is oresones beo.</L>
<L>And &yogh;if heo ne mouwen for no-&thorn;ing : maken chaungi is &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="32">With gret procession<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. precession</NOTE> of preostes : to &thorn;e putte he worth i-brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>With &thorn;e croiz and with &thorn;e haliwatur : heo schullen blessi him ech-on,</L>
<L>him-sulf he schal him blessi al-so : and &thorn;anne into &thorn;e putte gon;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at procession schal tuyrne a&yogh;en : ase ri&yogh;t is for-to done.</L>
<L N="36">A-moruwe In &thorn;ulke tyme : heo schullen come &thorn;udere eft-sone,</L>
<L>And, bote heo finden him &thorn;anne a&yogh;en i-come : with gret deol and sor</L>
<L>heo schullen tuyrne a-&yogh;ein, and sikere beoth : &thorn;at he ne comez a&yogh;en non-more.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; hit bi-fel bi &thorn;e kingus dai&yogh;e steuene : &thorn;at nov&thorn;e late was,</L>
<L N="40">Of a kni&yogh;t, &thorn;at hei&yogh;te sire Ovwayn : a swi&thorn;e wonder cas.</L>
<L>to &thorn;e bischop &thorn;is kni&yogh;t eode : and to schrifte to him he cam,</L>
<L>In grete repentaunce of is sunnes : deol and sorewe to him he nam.
<PB REF="00000249.tif" N="201"></L>
<L>&THORN;e bischop bi-gan to chide faste : for &thorn;at he hadde mis-do,</L>
<L N="44">And seide &thorn;at he was manne worst : for-to sunegun so,</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;te so muche schame a-fonge : &thorn;at he nere wuyr&thorn;e more.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kni&yogh;t sat with careful heorte : he si&yogh;te and weop ful sore.</L>
<L>&para; "Sire," seide &thorn;e kni&yogh;t, "&yogh;wan ich habbe : manne worst i-do,</L>
<L N="48">to &thorn;e sunne &thorn;at grettest is : mest penaunce mot &thorn;ar-to;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if ich a-mong alle men : mest sunful am, alas,</L>
<L>&THORN;e gretteste penaunce ichulle take : &thorn;at euere bi-founde was:</L>
<L>Ichulle me take to godes grace : and in is name i-wende</L>
<L N="52">Into seint paterikes purgatorie : and take &thorn;at god me wole sende."</L>
<L>"Ov, beu frere," quath &thorn;e bischop : "be stille, &yogh;wi seist&thorn;o<SUP>v</SUP> so?</L>
<L>Crist for-beode &thorn;at &thorn;ov euere : swuch folie do!</L>
<L>Onne&thorn;e comez &thorn;are ani a-&yogh;en : &thorn;at doth &thorn;are-In i-wende;</L>
<L N="56">Nolde god &thorn;at &thorn;ov &thorn;e dede dudest : bodi and soule to schende!</L>
<L>Ake wend into religion and bi-lef &thorn;are : to &thorn;ine liues ende:</L>
<L>&THORN;ine sunnes &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t bete wel : &yogh;if god &thorn;e wole grace sende."</L>
<L>"Certes, sire," quath &thorn;is kni&yogh;t : "ase wel &thorn;ov mi&yogh;t beo stille,</L>
<L N="60">For &thorn;ulke penaunce ichulle do : &yogh;if it is godes wille;</L>
<L>For ase muche ase ich habbe of-serued : Ine mai nou&yogh;t habe of wo.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere-fore sei&yogh;e &yogh;wat i schal : for &thorn;udere ichulle go."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e bischop prechede him faste i-nov&yogh; : for-to chaungi is &thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="64">Ake at&thorn;e laste, &thorn;o he isai&yogh; : &thorn;at it was al for nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e prior of &thorn;e stude : his lettres made sone,<MILESTONE N="97b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at he scholde bi him do : ase bi swuch a man was to done.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e prior prechede him faste i-nov&yogh; : and schewede him resones i-nowe,</L>
<L N="68">&YOGH;if he mi&yogh;te changi is &thorn;ou&yogh;t : &thorn;at he him with-drowe;</L>
<L>bote is prechinge was al for nou&yogh;t. : ase he sai&yogh; at&thorn;en ende</L>
<L>&THORN;at he nolde lete for no-&thorn;ing : &thorn;ene perilouse wei to wende,</L>
<L>&THORN;e prior nam him bi &thorn;e hond : and in-to churche him brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;are he ful akne adoun : and ore louerdes grace bi-sou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>In fastingues and in oresones : fourtene ni&yogh;t he lai,</L>
<L>Forte bidde ore louerdes grace. : and in &thorn;e fourte&thorn;e dai</L>
<L>&THORN;at Couent cam a-boute him : and o&thorn;ere preostes al-so</L>
<L N="76">And clerkes, with procession : &thorn;e seruise for him to do.
<PB REF="00000250.tif" N="202"></L>
<L>&para; For him heo songun &thorn;e hei&yogh;e-masse : and to ore louerd criden faste,</L>
<L>And ore louerdes flechs and is blod : heo &yogh;euen him at&thorn;e laste,</L>
<L>And spreinden him with holi watur : and heore oresones heo seide.</L>
<L N="80">With Croiz and with procession : to &thorn;e put heo gonne him lede,</L>
<L>And hei&yogh;liche songun &thorn;e letanie : and holi water with hem bere,</L>
<L>And alle louerdes halewe beden : &thorn;at heo heore<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. his</NOTE> help were.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prior on-lek &thorn;e puttes dore : bi-fore heom ech-on,</L>
<L>And seide : "beu frere, lo here &thorn;e wei : &thorn;at &thorn;ou wilnest for-to gon.</L>
<L>Ake &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt bi ore rede do : &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;ou schalt wende</L>
<L>And in o&thorn;ur manere &thorn;ine sunnes bete : ase god &thorn;e grace wole sende;</L>
<L>Fewe here comen euere a&yogh;en : &thorn;at wenden here-In bi-fore,</L>
<L>Ake heo beoth for tormentingue and for wo : lif and soule for-lore."</L>
<L>&para; "Certes, sire," quath &thorn;is kni&yogh;t : "rede &yogh;wat &thorn;ov me rede,</L>
<L N="90">In ore louerdes name &thorn;ane wei ich take : to bete mine misdede.</L>
<L>Ake for is loue &thorn;at us deore bou&yogh;te : biddez for me ech-on!</L>
<L N="92">Lif and soule god ich bi-take : and In his name ichulle In gon."</L>
<L>he blessede him, and wende forth In : and bi-tok god is flesch and is bon;</L>
<L>&THORN;e prior spreinde him with holi water : and lek &thorn;e dore a-non.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode kni&yogh;t wende him forth : wel baldeliche and faste,</L>
<L N="96">In one holewe weie onder eor&thorn;e : and to god is heorte caste;</L>
<L>Swy&thorn;e deork it was, &thorn;at he ne say ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t : ne no-&thorn;ing him ne a-gaste.</L>
<L>So longe &thorn;at him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he i-sai&yogh; : wel feor li&yogh;t at&thorn;e laste.</L>
<L>&THORN;uderward he wende baldeliche : so &thorn;at he cam &thorn;ere nei&yogh;:</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;e faireste feld &thorn;at mi&yogh;te beo : at&thorn;e wei&yogh;es ende he isei&yogh;.<NOTE PLACE="marg2">Pulchra via.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;are-Inne he wende murie i-nov&yogh; : and a-midde &thorn;e felde he fond</L>
<L>&THORN;e faireste halle and &thorn;e nobleste : &thorn;at mi&yogh;te beo in ani lond.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;et weder nas nou&yogh;t cler : bote ase it were nei&yogh; eue.</L>
<L N="104">Forto bi-holde &thorn;at noble weork : ane stounde he gan bi-leue.</L>
<L>&THORN;e walles neren nou&yogh;t i-hole : ake al a-boute i-wis</L>
<L>With pilers and with q<SUP>v</SUP>oynte Arches : ase &thorn;is Monekene cloistre is.</L>
<L>In he wende a godes name : and sette him al one an hei&yogh;;</L>
<L N="108">he bi-heold a-boute in-to eche huyrne : and &thorn;at quoy[n]te weork he sei&yogh;.
<PB REF="00000251.tif" N="203"></L>
<L>Ase he bi-heold al-so a-boute : &thorn;are come In at &thorn;e on ende</L>
<L>Twelf men in &yogh;wite clo&thorn;es : swi&thorn;e faire and hende;<MILESTONE N="98" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Alle heore crounes weren newe schaue&mdash; : and suy&thorn;e faire heo him gretten,</L>
<L>And alle heo seten faire a-doun : and &thorn;ane [kni&yogh;t] bi heom heo setten.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o seide on of heom, ase &thorn;ei it &thorn;e prior were : wel mildeliche and stille:</L>
<L>"bev frere, i-hered beo Ihesu crist : &thorn;at on &thorn;e brou&yogh;te swuche wille,</L>
<L>And late &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou&yogh; a-godes name hast bi-gonne : for is holi grace wel ende!</L>
<L N="116">leue bro&thorn;ur, &yogh;wane &thorn;ou woldest &thorn;is wei : for &thorn;ine sunnes wende,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur &thorn;ov most beon studefast and hardi : and in none manere tuyrne &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur &thorn;ov worst for-lore, lif and soule : and sone to &thorn;e deuel i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>For also-sone ase we beth heonne i-went : &thorn;e feondes lu&thorn;ere and wicke</L>
<L N="120">heo wollez come a-boute &thorn;e : In-to &thorn;is hous ful &thorn;icke,</L>
<L>And don &thorn;e tormens and wo i-nov&yogh; : and bi-hote &thorn;e wel more;</L>
<L>And heo wollez also bi-hote &thorn;e Ioye i-nov&yogh; : &yogh;if &thorn;ov wolt leue heore lore;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if heo mouwen &thorn;oru&yogh; ani bi-heste : o&thorn;ur enie gile, &thorn;e ouer-come,</L>
<L N="124">For-so&thorn;e &thorn;ov worst, lif and soule : a-deuele wei al clene i-nome.</L>
<L>Ake &yogh;if &thorn;ov art studefast of heorte : and on Ihesu crist wolt &thorn;enche,</L>
<L>Ne for bi-heste<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. heste heste</NOTE> ne for wo : fram him &thorn;ou nelle blenche,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou worst quit of alle &thorn;ine sunnes : &thorn;at &thorn;ov hast euere i-wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ov schalt i-seo alle &thorn;e Ioies : &thorn;at guode men beoth inne i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And al-so &thorn;e pine &thorn;at lu&thorn;ere men : habbez for heore mis-dede.</L>
<L>Ake in &yogh;wat wo &thorn;at &thorn;ov euere art : euere &thorn;ench on god, ich rede,</L>
<L>&para; And euere &yogh;wane heo tormentiez &thorn;e : cri Iesu milce and ore,</L>
<L N="132">And, &yogh;if &thorn;ou art studefast in gode bi-leue : heo ne schullen defouli &thorn;e non-more.</L>
<L>We bi-takez &thorn;e god of heuene : and ich rede &thorn;ov do bi ovre lore."</L>
<L>&THORN;o nuste &thorn;e kni&yogh;t &yogh;ware heo bi-comen. : he sat and si&yogh;te sore,</L>
<L>Elinge he bilefte alone : and cride on godes mi&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="136">And Armede him with holie beden : a&yogh;en &thorn;e deuelene to fi&yogh;te,</L>
<L>On &thorn;e holi gost he cride faste : &thorn;at he ne scholde him faile;
<PB REF="00000252.tif" N="204"></L>
<L>he lokede euere &yogh;wane heo comen : him for-to a-saille.</L>
<L>Ase he sat a-godes name : &thorn;e bataille for-to a-bide,</L>
<L N="140">&THORN;are cam a sori reuful cri : a-boute in eche side,</L>
<L>Ase al&thorn;e world to-borste and to-breke : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te it was al-so,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &thorn;ei alle &thorn;e bestes of &thorn;e worlde : to-gadere weren i-do,</L>
<L>Ase<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &amp; ase</NOTE> loude and ase grisliche ase heo mi&yogh;ten : &yogh;eollinde ech-one heo were.</L>
<L N="144">Ake<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> heo ne mi&yogh;ten a-mong heom alle : make so grisliche bere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at &yogh;if</NOTE> is hope and is heorte on ihesu crist : euere-more heo were,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. nere</NOTE></L>
<L>Elles he hadde wod bi-come : and i-lore is wit for fere.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o comen heo a-bouten him : &thorn;icke and grisliche &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="148">&YOGH;eonijnde and grenninde on him : with ful lodlich chere.</L>
<L>"bel ami," quath &thorn;e on of heom : "&thorn;ou hast a-ri&yogh;t i-do,</L>
<L>We owez wel alle a-nouri &thorn;e : for al to fewe doth so.</L>
<L>For alle o&thorn;ere men wollez a-bide : &thorn;at heore lif heom beo bi-nome,</L>
<L N="152">And &yogh;eot it is a&yogh;en heore wille : &thorn;at heo schullen hidere come:</L>
<L>And &thorn;ov art i-come al bi &thorn;ine liue : and bi &thorn;ine guode wille al-so;</L>
<L>Wel ou&yogh;te we &thorn;ine mede &yogh;elde : and gre[t] &thorn;onk also &thorn;e do.</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane &thorn;ov hast bo&thorn;e bodi and soule : i&yogh;yuen us bi &thorn;ine liue,<MILESTONE N="98b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="156">Saunt faille we ne beoth nou&yogh;t so onkuynde : &thorn;at we it nellez &yogh;elde &thorn;e bliue,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e kundenesse &thorn;at &thorn;ov to us come : al bi &thorn;ine owene lore.</L>
<L>Ake na&thorn;eles, &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt on eor&thorn;e : habbe Ioye more,</L>
<L>Sikere us an hond &thorn;at &thorn;ov wolt : In ore seruise bi-leue</L>
<L N="160">And we &thorn;e wollez a&yogh;en to eor&thorn;e bringe : al sauf, are hit beo eue,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ov schalt habbe &thorn;are Ioye i-nou&yogh; : in halle and eke in boure&mdash;</L>
<L>For none men ne fareth so murie &thorn;are : ase &thorn;ulke &thorn;at beoth ovre.</L>
<L>hei&yogh; man and noble &thorn;ov schalt beo : and alle men schullen honouri &thorn;e.</L>
<L N="164">&YOGH;wane &thorn;ov art ded ant comest to us : &thorn;ou schalt habbe ase guod ase we."</L>
<L>&THORN;is kni&yogh;t &thorn;ou&yogh;te euere on Iesu crist : and nolde chaungi is wille,</L>
<L>For &thorn;retninge ne for fair bi-heste : ake sat him euere stille.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he nolde graunti nou&yogh;t : to heom for-to wende,</L>
<L N="168">heo &yogh;ollen and grenneden on him foule : and strong fuyr bi-gonne for-to tiende;
<PB REF="00000253.tif" N="205"></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is kni&yogh;t heo bounden honden and fet : and a-midde &thorn;e fuyre him<NOTE PLACE="marg2">Prima pena.</NOTE> caste,</L>
<L>With Irene Ovles and pikes : heo to-drowen him wel faste.</L>
<L>&THORN;is kni&yogh;t hadde gret pine : wel loude he cride a-non:</L>
<L N="172">"Ihesus, Ihesus, help me nou&thorn;e : and do a-wei mine fon!"</L>
<L>A-non so [he] hadde &thorn;is word i-seid : &thorn;at fuyr a-queinte ech spronke,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e deuelene ne mi&yogh;ten him non more to-drawe. : ore louerd he gan &thorn;onke,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e hardiore he was i-nou&yogh; : &thorn;o he &thorn;is i-sei&yogh;,</L>
<L N="176">And &thorn;e lasse he was of heom a-drad : &thorn;at weren him so nei&yogh;.</L>
<L>Wel grisliche heo &yogh;ollen, &thorn;e schrewes : &thorn;o heom faillede heore mi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And flouwen echone out of &thorn;e halle : and drowen with heom &thorn;is kni&yogh;t.</L>
<L>A-&yogh;en &thorn;e grounde heo drowen him harde : bo&thorn;e bi fet and honde,</L>
<L N="180">longe, him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, and swi&thorn;e feor : al-a-boute in a waste londe.</L>
<L>So blac and deork was al &thorn;at lond : &thorn;at no-&thorn;ing he ne sei&yogh;</L>
<L>bote &thorn;e feondes &thorn;at him to-drowen : &thorn;at so &thorn;icke weren him nei&yogh;.</L>
<L>Ake swi&thorn;e softe wind &thorn;are was : &thorn;at he heorde onne&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Ake so scharpe he bleu&yogh; and colde : &thorn;at brou&yogh;te him nei&yogh; to de&thorn;e;</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t colde he wende &thorn;oru&yogh; is heorte : and &thorn;oru&yogh; al is bodi also,</L>
<L>&THORN;at him were leouere &thorn;ane al &thorn;e world : &thorn;at &thorn;e pine were ido.</L>
<L>&THORN;us colde heo drowen him, ase heom<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. him</NOTE> &thorn;ou&yogh;te : forth ri&yogh;t est, i-wis,</L>
<L N="188">Ase &thorn;e sonne a-rist in somer : &yogh;wane &thorn;e dai lengest is.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo comen, ase heom<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. prima Secunda<SUP>1</SUP> pena</NOTE> &thorn;ou&yogh;te : ri&yogh;t to &thorn;e worldes ende,</L>
<L>bi a brod valeie heo torneden heom : and southward gonne i-wende,</L>
<L>toward &thorn;e stude &thorn;at &thorn;e sonne : In winter doth a-rise.</L>
<L N="192">&THORN;is seli kni&yogh;t was i-drawe : and i-pined in fale wise.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;ou&yogh;te him &thorn;at he i-heorde feor : bi-fore him ase it were,</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e deolful cri and wop : and swy&thorn;e revful bere;</L>
<L>Euere &thorn;e neor &thorn;at heo comen : &thorn;e revlokur was &thorn;at cri.</L>
<L>So longe [heo] drowen him, &thorn;at him &thorn;ou&yogh;te : &thorn;at heo weren ri&yogh;t &thorn;er-bi.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o comen heo into a wid feld : non more ne mi&yogh;te beo,</L>
<L N="198">So long and brod in eche side : &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;te non ende i-seo.</L>
<L>Of men and of wummen &thorn;is feld was : ful in eche side,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wombene to-ward &thorn;e grounde : i-spradde a-brod ful wide,<MILESTONE N="99" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>hondene and fet al a-brod : to &thorn;e eor&thorn;e faste i-bounde
<PB REF="00000254.tif" N="206"></L>
<L>With Irene nailles al fuyrie : i-smite &thorn;oru&yogh; heom to grounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;is wrechche gostes weren<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> so i-pinede : with Irene and with fuyre.</L>
<L N="204">So deolful cri heo maden &thorn;are : &thorn;at gret deol it was to huyre;</L>
<L>heo criden merci deolfulliche : Ake no merci men nolde heom do;</L>
<L>For Anguische &thorn;e eor&thorn;e heo freten : and hore tongene gnowen al-so.</L>
<L>&THORN;e deoulene ornen opon hem : and treden heom to &thorn;e grounde,</L>
<L N="208">And with Ovles swi&thorn;e kene : maden heom mani a wounde.&mdash;</L>
<L>Allas, &yogh;wy nellez men beon i-war : and heore sunnes here bete,</L>
<L>Are heo comen to purgatorie : and with &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere gostes mete!</L>
<L>For ase wel beth &thorn;e schrewes in purgatorie : and ouer-al, ase in helle,</L>
<L>And schullen for-to &thorn;e dai&yogh;e of dome come : telle &yogh;wat men telle.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e feondes seiden, "ri&yogh;t ase [&thorn;is] men beoth i-pinede : &thorn;ov schalt beo also,</L>
<L>bote &thorn;ov wolle &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t wende : and after ovre rede do."</L>
<L>&para; And &thorn;o he nolde in none manere : to grounde harde heo him caste</L>
<L N="216">And tormenteden him ase &thorn;e o&thorn;ere weren : and to &thorn;e eor&thorn;e naileden him faste.</L>
<L>Ake he criede a-non to ihesu crist : &thorn;o him smert so sore:</L>
<L>&THORN;are nas non of &thorn;e schrewes &thorn;o : &thorn;at mi&yogh;ten serui him so more.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Tertia pena.</NOTE>&THORN;o &thorn;e schrewes i-sei&yogh;en &thorn;at heo ne mi&yogh;ten : heore wille habben &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="220">heo drowen him into an o&thorn;ur felde : wel ful of more wo.</L>
<L>Of Men and wummen it was ful : op-ri&yogh;t i-sprad to grounde,</L>
<L>Fet and hondene a-to i-drawe : and to &thorn;e eor&thorn;e faste i-bounde,</L>
<L>With glowinde biendes al of Ire : i-nailede heo weren &thorn;er-to;</L>
<L N="224">Al fuyrie naddrene ope heom seten : and foule crapoudes al-so.</L>
<L>Some of &thorn;e naddrene bi-clupten heom : so faste al a-boute</L>
<L>&THORN;at heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te heo scholden to-berste : so streite heo gurden heom with-oute;</L>
<L>Some seten ope heom : and heore flesch al-to-gnowe</L>
<L N="228">And with kene tieth al fuyrie : wombe and breoste to-drowe,</L>
<L>Some with hore scharpe tounges : &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e heorte sore heom smite;</L>
<L>Some heo gnowen, and some heo stounge : and some with scharpe tieth heom bite.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Crapoudes al-so, &thorn;at weren so foule : op-on heore breostene sete</L>
<L N="232">And stoungen heom &thorn;oru&yogh; heore heortene : with heore foule wrottes grete.
<PB REF="00000255.tif" N="207"></L>
<L>&THORN;e lu&thorn;ere gostes ornen al-so : a-boute heom i-nowe</L>
<L>With hokes and with ou&yogh;les : a[nd]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. a</NOTE> with gret eir heom to-drowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e wrechche gostes, so for-pinede : in swuch torment weren<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="236">heo criden alle deolfulliche : ake hit ne halp heom nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e feondes nomen &thorn;is seli kni&yogh;t : and wolden him pini al-so:</L>
<L>Ake anon so he cride on Ihesu crist : ne mi&yogh;ten heo bringe him &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eot &thorn;e feondes eft-sone him nomen : and to &thorn;e &thorn;ridde feld him<NOTE PLACE="marg2">Quarta pena.</NOTE> brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L N="240">In stronge pine he sai&yogh; &thorn;are wrechche gostes : &thorn;at of heom-self luyte rou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>&THORN;at weren i-spradde on &thorn;e eor&thorn;e abrod : and i-smiten &thorn;oru&yogh;-out ech-one</L>
<L>with nailes &thorn;icke al abrod : ase &thorn;are mi&yogh;ten stikie one,</L>
<L>&THORN;at man ne mi&yogh;te finde ane amtie place : on al heore bodie so luyte</L>
<L>&THORN;at man mi&yogh;te for &thorn;e &thorn;icke nailles : a fingres ende to heom puyte.</L>
<L>&para; A smart wind also to o&thorn;ur wo : on heom bleu&yogh; wel faste,<MILESTONE N="99b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te heo weren i-barnd : &thorn;oru&yogh;-out with eche blaste.</L>
<L>&THORN;e feondes ornen faste a-boute : fram ech to o&thorn;ur i-nowe</L>
<L>And heore wrechche flesch with o&thorn;ur wo : mid Ovles heom to-drowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;eos wrechche gostes, so fur-pinede : and in swuch torment i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Revliche heo criden ase heo mi&yogh;ten : ake it ne halp heom ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>For heo weren so clene ouer-come : &thorn;at heo ne mi&yogh;ten onne&thorn;e</L>
<L>Ani voiz out-bringe bote ase a man : &thorn;at were ope &thorn;e pointe of de&thorn;e:</L>
<L>In heore &thorn;rote heo criden dimmeliche : for heore strenc&thorn;e heom was bi-nome</L>
<L>With muche pine, and no wonder it nas : &thorn;ei heo weren ouer-come.</L>
<L>&THORN;e feondes nomen &thorn;is seli kni&yogh;t : and to grounde him caste,</L>
<L N="256">And seiden, bote he wolde turne is &thorn;ou&yogh;t : heo wolden naili him &thorn;are wel faste.</L>
<L>Ake he cride on Ihesu crist : and nemde is holi name:</L>
<L>&THORN;e schrewes ne hadden none mi&yogh;te &thorn;o : to don him more schame.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Quinta pena.</NOTE>&YOGH;eot heo nomen and drowen him : into &thorn;e feor&thorn;e felde,</L>
<L N="260">Ful of brumston al brenninde : with stronge lei&yogh;e and spelde.</L>
<L>&para; Ech manere pine &thorn;at mi&yogh;te beo : In &thorn;ulke felde he sei&yogh;:</L>
<L>Some with chaines of Ire : al fuyrie, hengen on hei&yogh;,</L>
<L>Some bi Armes, some bi fet : and bi &thorn;e necke mani on,
<PB REF="00000256.tif" N="208"></L>
<L>heo weren an-hangede in stronge fuyre : of pich and eke brumston;</L>
<L>Some hengen bi stronge crokus : I-pulte &thorn;oru&yogh; ei&thorn;ur Ey&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="266">&THORN;oru&yogh; &thorn;e &thorn;rote some also : and &thorn;oru&yogh; ei&thorn;ur ere wel hei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>And some &thorn;oru&yogh; heore derne limes : and some &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e tete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at leuere heom were &thorn;ane al &thorn;e world : heore lyf to habbe i-lete.</L>
<L>Some op-on grediles of Ire : i-rostede weren also,</L>
<L>Some ase gyes, &thorn;e spites of Ire : &thorn;oru&yogh;-out heom i-do;</L>
<L>Some leyen opri&yogh;t a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e grounde : &yogh;eonijnde wel faste,</L>
<L N="272">&THORN;e feondes welden led and bras : and in heore mou&thorn;es caste.</L>
<L>he ne mi&yogh;te bi-&thorn;enche no manere pine : &thorn;at he ne sai&yogh; mo &thorn;er.</L>
<L>him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he sai&yogh; &thorn;are mani on : &thorn;at he knev on eor&thorn;e her.</L>
<L>&THORN;e feondes him casten a-midde &thorn;is pine : a-mong &thorn;is o&thorn;ere ech-on:</L>
<L N="276">And he cride on Iesu crist : and was deliured a-non.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Sexta pena.</NOTE>&para; &YOGH;eot &thorn;is feondes &thorn;is selie kni&yogh;t : into an o&thorn;ur place huy drowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-Inne he i-sai&yogh; a grislich &yogh;weol : with spokene longe i-nowe;</L>
<L>&THORN;at on ende hangede toward &thorn;e grounde : &thorn;at o&thorn;ur op-on hei&yogh;,</L>
<L N="280">Ful it was of hokes and pikes : wel &thorn;icke, ase he i-sei&yogh;;</L>
<L>&THORN;is hokes and &thorn;is pikes weren : faste i-riuen al-so,</L>
<L>With wrechche gostes al-a-boute : &thorn;at &thorn;aron weren i-do.</L>
<L>Al brenninde was &thorn;is sorie &yogh;weol : and stinkinde of brumston;</L>
<L N="284">&THORN;e wrechche gostes &thorn;at &thorn;ar-on hengen : brenninde weren ech-on.</L>
<L>&THORN;is feondes wenden forth a-non : and heore hokes &thorn;aron caste</L>
<L>In ei&thorn;ur side, a[nd]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. a</NOTE> tur[n]den a-boute : &thorn;is sori &yogh;weol so faste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of &thorn;e gostus &thorn;at &thorn;aron hengen : no-&thorn;ing heo ne sei&yogh;e&mdash;</L>
<L>So faste heo torneden &thorn;at &yogh;weol a-boute&mdash; : bote &thorn;e brenninde lei&yogh;e;</L>
<L>Ake deolfulliche heo criden and &yogh;ollen : euer-ech in is ende.&mdash;</L>
<L>Alas, &yogh;wi nellez men beon i-war : are heo heonnes wende,<MILESTONE N="100" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;wane he mi&yogh;ten here with a luytel pine : bete heore mis-dede</L>
<L N="292">And &thorn;are heo schullen so bitere a-bugge : alas, &thorn;e wrechhede!&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is feondes nomen &thorn;is seli kni&yogh;t : and on &thorn;is &yogh;weol him caste</L>
<L>And with &thorn;is o&thorn;ere wrechche gostes : torneden him a-boute faste:</L>
<L>Sone he cride on Ihesu crist : deliuered he was a-non;</L>
<L N="296">&THORN;e feondes stoden and bi-heolden : with dreori mod ech-on.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Septima pena.</NOTE>&para; Eft heo nomen him bitterliche : and ferrore &yogh;uyt him ladde,</L>
<L>And harleden him forth wel revfulliche : and loude &yogh;ollen and gradde.</L>
<L>bi-fore him he sai&yogh; an hous stonde : long and brod i-nov&yogh;;
<PB REF="00000257.tif" N="209"></L>
<L N="300">stunch and hete &thorn;at &thorn;arof cam : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te al-mest [him] a-slou&yogh;.</L>
<L>he with-stod, and nolde, is &thorn;onkes : for stunche gon non ner;</L>
<L>"Ferrore &thorn;ov schalt," &thorn;e fendes seiden : "&thorn;ou ne schalt nou&yogh;t a-bide her;</L>
<L N="303">A bath it is &thorn;at &thorn;ov isijcst : and &thorn;ar-inne &thorn;ov schalt beo</L>
<L>And ba&thorn;i with o&thorn;ere &thorn;at &thorn;are beoth : ne schalt &thorn;ov nou&yogh;t so fleo."</L>
<L>&THORN;e gostes &thorn;at &thorn;are-inne weren : wel deolfulliche cride</L>
<L>And &yogh;ollen loude, ase he i-heorde : a-boute in eche side.</L>
<L>&THORN;is kni&yogh;t with &thorn;is foule wi&yogh;tes : Into &thorn;e grete house cam.</L>
<L N="308">Of tormens &thorn;at he &thorn;are isai&yogh; : gret gome with-alle he nam.</L>
<L>ful of puttes and of diches : &thorn;at hous with-inne it was;</L>
<L>More seoruwe ne more stunch : neuere i-sei&yogh;e nas:</L>
<L>heo weren folle of stronge tormens : boillinde euer-ech-on</L>
<L N="312">Of wallinde led, and i-fulde heo weren : of piche and brumston.</L>
<L>Wrechche gostus &thorn;are-inne seten : &thorn;e torment tilde wel hei&yogh;e:</L>
<L>Some a-boue &thorn;e heued : and some ri&yogh;t to &thorn;e Ey&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Some to &thorn;e nose, and some to &thorn;e mouth : and some op to &thorn;e swere</L>
<L>And some to heore breostene : and a-bou&yogh;ten heore sunnes ful deore,</L>
<L N="317">And some to heore nauele : and some ne&thorn;errore more,</L>
<L>And some stoden op to heore knen : and criden and weopen sore,</L>
<L>And some stoden In with bo&thorn;e fet : and some with &thorn;at on;</L>
<L N="320">Deolfolliche heo weopen and criden : and &yogh;ollen euerechon.</L>
<L>&para; "Nov &thorn;ov i-sixt," que&thorn;en &thorn;e feondes : "&yogh;woder-In &thorn;ov schalt gon,</L>
<L>bote &thorn;ov wolle an-o&thorn;ur speke : and to us tuyrne a-non."</L>
<L>heo nomen and casten him In a putte. : on Iesus a-non he cride:</L>
<L N="324">Op he cam a-non a-&yogh;en : and no lengore he ne moste &thorn;are a-bide.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">[Octaua pena.]</NOTE>heo nomen him in grete wrath&thorn;e : and harleden him ferrere more,</L>
<L>And brou&yogh;ten him opon a swy&thorn;e gret hul : ful of sorewe and sore.</L>
<L>he stod and bi-heold a-boute : &thorn;o he cam &thorn;are-op an hei&yogh;;</L>
<L N="328">him wondrede of &thorn;e manie gostes : &thorn;at he &thorn;are i-sei&yogh;.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e pinene<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at alle</NOTE> &thorn;at he hadde er i-sei&yogh;e : &thorn;are-a&yogh;en nou&yogh;t nere:</L>
<L>I-clui&yogh;te heo seten ope heore ton : and quakeden revliche for fere.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e south-half of &thorn;e hul : a deop water &thorn;are was and lou&yogh;,</L>
<L N="332">&THORN;at foule stonk, and caldore was : &thorn;ane ani ys o&thorn;ur snov&yogh;.</L>
<L>A nor&thorn;erne wind faste blev&yogh; : &thorn;at him &thorn;ou&yogh;te is flesch to-rende;</L>
<L>Euere &thorn;are seten gostes : and a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e winde heom wende,
<PB REF="00000258.tif" N="210"></L>
<L>heo quakeden and chyuereden faste : in grete pine and stronge,<MILESTONE N="100b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ase ho-so seith a-bidet &thorn;are heore time : heore deth for-to a-fonge.</L>
<L>"lo," seide on of &thorn;e feondes : "&thorn;ov nost nou&yogh;t &yogh;wat istis;</L>
<L>bote &thorn;ov torne &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t sone : &thorn;ou schalt i-wite, i-wis."</L>
<L>Ne hadde he bote &thorn;is word i-seid : &thorn;at &thorn;are ne cam a wind blowe</L>
<L N="340">And drof alle &thorn;is wrechche gostes : into &thorn;e deope watur ful lowe;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Nor&thorn;erne wynd drof heom a-doun : al mid one blaste,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e gostes, and &thorn;ene kni&yogh;t : a-midde &thorn;e watere hem caste.</L>
<L>More pine ne mi&yogh;te non beo : of stronge chele ne of stunche</L>
<L N="344">&THORN;ane &thorn;is gostes &thorn;arinne hadden : &thorn;are ne mi&yogh;te non at-blenche.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e kni&yogh;t &thorn;e stronge pine : of &thorn;is water i-felde,</L>
<L>he gan to crie on Ihesu crist : &thorn;at faillede him ful selde:</L>
<L>A-non-ri&yogh;t with-oute lette : op of &thorn;is watere man him<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> he (man om.)</NOTE> drov&yogh;.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;is wrechche gostes lefden &thorn;ere : with sorewe and wo i-nov&yogh;.</L>
<L N="349">For in &thorn;at water, &thorn;at was so cold : and so foule stonk also,</L>
<L>&THORN;is gostes swymden op and doun : in muche sorewe and wo;</L>
<L>&THORN;e feondes ornen opon &thorn;e watere : so men doth on &thorn;e londe,</L>
<L N="352">And &yogh;wane ani wolde coueri<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> cleueri</NOTE> op : with fote o&thorn;ur with honde,</L>
<L>heo pulten him a-doun a-&yogh;en : &thorn;at &thorn;are ne a-scapede non;</L>
<L>&THORN;are was wo and sorewe i-nou&yogh; : a-mong heom euerechon.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is feondes wenden forth a-non : and &thorn;e seli kni&yogh;t eft nome,</L>
<L N="356">And drowen him into a sori stude : &thorn;are neuer er heo ne come.</L>
<L>heo comen and stoden ouer a put : wyd it was and deop i-nov&yogh;;</L>
<L>A brenninde smoke, &thorn;at foule stonk : op of &thorn;e putte drov&yogh;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at onne&thorn;e &thorn;e kny&yogh;t mi&yogh;te stonde : for sori stunch &thorn;are-nei&yogh;.</L>
<L N="360">Wrechche gostes in &thorn;is put : in &thorn;at sori smoke he sei&yogh;</L>
<L>Fleo op and doun al brenninde : ase speldene doth of fuyre,</L>
<L>And in-to &thorn;e putte eft fullen a-doun : &thorn;o heo ne mi&yogh;ten no leng duyre.</L>
<L>him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he was al ouer-come : for &thorn;e stunche &thorn;at &thorn;ar-op of drov&yogh;;</L>
<L>&THORN;are-bi him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at in &thorn;e grounde : was soruwe and deol i-nov&yogh;.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;wy stanst &thorn;ov so?" &thorn;e fendes seiden : "&thorn;inch&thorn; &thorn;e &thorn;arof wonder,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is swete smoke &thorn;at here bloweth : and &yogh;wat put beo &thorn;are-onder?</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Puteum Inferni.</NOTE>&para; In &thorn;is put is ovre woneingue : for &thorn;e put of helle it is;</L>
<L N="368">And, for &thorn;ov us hast i-serued wel : here &thorn;ov schalt wonie, i-wis,</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;at us seruieth wel : hidere heo schullen wende;</L>
<L>And, &yogh;if &thorn;ov comest here-in with us : &thorn;ov worst here with-outen ende.
<PB REF="00000259.tif" N="211"></L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore i rede torne &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t : and do us here man-rede</L>
<L N="372">And we schullen &thorn;ene wei ase we come<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. conne</NOTE> : al sauf a-&yogh;en &thorn;e lede;</L>
<L>&THORN;ov schalt on eor&thorn;e al &thorn;i lijf habbe : richesse, and Ioye al-so,</L>
<L>For we schullen on eor&thorn;e &thorn;e finde i-nov&yogh; : ase ri&yogh;t is &thorn;at we do."</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e kni&yogh;t for-sok heore bi-heste : ase he hadde er i-lome,</L>
<L N="376">heo smiten heom a-doun into &thorn;e putte : and &thorn;ene kni&yogh;t with heom nome.</L>
<L>&THORN;e deoppore &thorn;at heo comen : &thorn;[e] braddere &thorn;e put was;</L>
<L>Ake<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at</NOTE> al &thorn;e wo &thorn;at he isai&yogh; er : a-&yogh;ein &thorn;at nou&yogh;t it nas.</L>
<L>Of stunch, of brenninge, and of o&thorn;ur wo : &thorn;e kni&yogh;t was so ouer-come</L>
<L N="380">&THORN;at is &thorn;ov&yogh;t toward Iesu crist : nei&yogh; him was bi-nome;<MILESTONE N="101" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So muche pine nas neuere i-sei&yogh;e&mdash; : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te ase &thorn;ei he felde</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was nei&yogh; ope &thorn;e pointe : &thorn;ene gost op to &yogh;elde.</L>
<L>Ake ore louerd a-mong al is wo : grace him &yogh;af at&thorn;e laste</L>
<L N="384">&THORN;at he &thorn;ou&yogh;te on Ihesu crist : and to him cride [faste].<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. at&thorn;e laste</NOTE></L>
<L>A smoke &thorn;are cam smite up a-non : mid one wel stronge blaste</L>
<L>&THORN;ene kni&yogh;t an hei&yogh; a-boue &thorn;e putte : and manie o&thorn;ere<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> gostes, caste.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kni&yogh;t &yogh;wirlede op in &thorn;is blast : ase speldene doth, wel wide,</L>
<L N="388">At&thorn;e laste he li&yogh;te a-doun : a-boue &thorn;e putte bi side.</L>
<L>&THORN;are he stod and bi-heold a-boute : ase man &thorn;at witles were,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for &thorn;e pine &thorn;at he hadde i-haued : he nuste hov he cam &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he hadde longe i-stonde al one : and bi-holde a-boute,</L>
<L N="392">&THORN;are comen blaste op of &thorn;e putte : deuelene a gret rou&yogh;te</L>
<L>And [stoden] bi him al a-boute : al newe as &thorn;ei heo were;</L>
<L>Ase him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, he ne sai&yogh; hem : neuer er bote &thorn;o &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>heo bi-heolden him wel grisliche : and grenneden on him al-a-boute,</L>
<L N="396">And seiden, "&yogh;wi stanst &thorn;ov here al one? : &thorn;ov most come into ovre rovte."</L>
<L>heo seiden, "tolden ore felawes &thorn;e : &thorn;at &thorn;is was &thorn;e put of helle?</L>
<L>hit nis nou&yogh;t so, ake we wollez sone : for ri&yogh;te so&thorn;e &thorn;e telle.</L>
<L>Nost&thorn;ov nou&yogh;t &thorn;at it is ore ri&yogh;te : to li&yogh;en euere-mo,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at we with lesingues bi-traieth men : bote it mowe o&thorn;ur go?</L>
<L N="401">And so ore felawes louwen &thorn;e : &thorn;at &thorn;is was &thorn;e put of helle;</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;ov schalt come &thorn;udere with us : and &thorn;e so&thorn;e we wollez &thorn;e telle."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is deouelene harleden &thorn;ane kni&yogh;t forth : &thorn;at wo was him to-drawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at him were leouere &thorn;ane ani-&thorn;ing : &thorn;at he hadde i-beo of lif-dawe.
<PB REF="00000260.tif" N="212"></L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo comen to a swy&thorn;e gret watur : deop and brod i-nov&yogh;;</L>
<L N="406">A strong mist, &thorn;at foule stonk : op of &thorn;is watere drov&yogh;</L>
<L>Of brumston and of o&thorn;ur wo&mdash; : so strong stunch neuere he ne sei&yogh;,</L>
<L N="408">&THORN;at mid al &thorn;e pine of &thorn;e world : onne&thorn;e he stod &thorn;ere-nei&yogh;.</L>
<L>A brugge &thorn;are was ouer &thorn;at watur : smallere ne mi&yogh;te non beo;</L>
<L>&THORN;e smoke was so &thorn;icke al-a-boute : &thorn;at onne&thorn;e he mi&yogh;te [it] i-seo.</L>
<L>&thorn;o seiden &thorn;e sorie fendes : "we seggez &thorn;e i-wis</L>
<L N="412">&THORN;at onder &thorn;is deope watere : &thorn;e put of helle so is.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ov schalt sone i-wite : for &thorn;ov schalt sone a-non</L>
<L>ouer &thorn;is watur, &thorn;at is so deop : opon &thorn;is brugge gon,</L>
<L>And we schullen &thorn;e sende swuch a wynd : &thorn;at schal &thorn;e amidde caste,</L>
<L>And ore felawes &thorn;at beoth bi-neothe : schullen &thorn;e nime wel faste</L>
<L>And drawe &thorn;e doun forth with hem : Into helle grounde a-non.</L>
<L N="418">Cum nov&thorn;e forth and &thorn;ou&yogh; schalt : op-on &thorn;is brugge gon."</L>
<L>heo nomen &thorn;is seli kni&yogh;t : and op-on &thorn;is brugge drowe,</L>
<L N="420">And maden him go &thorn;ere, is on-&thorn;onkes : with wrechhedes i-nowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;reo &thorn;ingus vuele i-nowe : on &thorn;is brugge were:</L>
<L>&THORN;at on was, for heo was so hei&yogh; : &thorn;at no gost ne<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> vnne&thorn;e me</NOTE> mi&yogh;te for fere</L>
<L>&THORN;are-oppe gon and so deope a-doun : habbe so grisliche si&yogh;te;</L>
<L N="424">&THORN;at o&thorn;ur was, for heo was so narov&yogh; : &thorn;at onne&thorn;e ani-&thorn;ing<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> me</NOTE> mi&yogh;te</L>
<L>&THORN;are-oppe sette ani fot : &thorn;at he ne fulle a-doun a-non;<MILESTONE N="101b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde, &thorn;at heo was so slider : &thorn;at man ne mi&yogh;te &thorn;are-oppe gon</L>
<L>bote he slide and felle a-doun : so slei&yogh; man neuere nere.</L>
<L N="428">&THORN;eos &thorn;reo &thorn;inges &thorn;esne selie kni&yogh;t : brou&yogh;ten in grete fere,</L>
<L>For heo was narov&yogh;, and slider, and hei&yogh; : &thorn;at he ne scholde him so bi-telle,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at he glufte<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> glide</NOTE> in ani half : &thorn;at he ne fulle in-to helle.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;are-oppe he was with strenc&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t : and &thorn;are-oppe i-maket to gon.</L>
<L N="432">So gret drede, ase him &thorn;ou&yogh;te : ne hadde he neuer er non.</L>
<L>Ake sone he &thorn;ou&yogh;te on ihesu crist : &thorn;at so ofte him sauede er,</L>
<L>And cride on is holie name : &thorn;at he were is helpe &thorn;er.</L>
<L>he eode forth we[l] baldeliche : and &thorn;e innore &thorn;at he cam</L>
<L>&THORN;e hardiore him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he was : and &thorn;e betere heorte to him he nam,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e braddore was is wei&mdash; : so longe forth he eode,</L>
<L N="438">&THORN;at it was so brod &thorn;at &thorn;ere mi&yogh;te : a carte gon for neode,
<PB REF="00000261.tif" N="213"></L>
<L>And so longe, &thorn;at tuei cartes mi&yogh;te : meten heom wel i-nov&yogh;.</L>
<L N="440">&THORN;e kni&yogh;t &thorn;o wel baldeliche : ase a maister forth him drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;e feondes stoden bi-ne&thorn;e &thorn;e brugge : and sei&yogh;en him so faste gon,</L>
<L>And for al &thorn;e wo &thorn;at heo him duden : ne ouer-cam him nou&yogh;t on;</L>
<L>heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te, it was al for nou&yogh;t : after him to honten more:</L>
<L>grisliche heo gonne forto &yogh;eolle : ant to crie and wepe suy&thorn;e sore,</L>
<L N="445">&THORN;at for &thorn;e &yogh;eollinge &thorn;at heo maden : he hadde wel more fere</L>
<L>&THORN;ane of al &thorn;e pine &thorn;at he hadde er : so lodlich was &thorn;e bere;</L>
<L>&para; heore Oules heo nomen and heore hokes : and toward him casten an hei&yogh;;</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;are nas non &thorn;at him touchi mi&yogh;te : ne no-&thorn;ing come him nei&yogh;.</L>
<L N="449">So &thorn;at al sauf with alle Ioye : ouer &thorn;is watere he him drov&yogh;,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e feondes lefden bi-hinde : with grete soruwe ant sor i-nou&yogh;&mdash;</L>
<L>In helle is heore kuynde heritage : and elles for-so&thorn;e it were wov&yogh;!</L>
<L>heo leten him go &yogh;wodere he wolde : and ne fondeden him non more,</L>
<L>And heolden heom cleneliche ouer-come : for al heore false lore.</L>
<L N="454">&THORN;is kni&yogh;t wende him forth, sauf i-nou&yogh;&mdash; : &thorn;at he hadde erore deore a|bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &thorn;onkede &yogh;eorne Ihesu crist : &thorn;at &thorn;e feondes ne siweden him nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;at watur he passede sauf inov&yogh; : and for&thorn;ere &thorn;ene wey he nam.</L>
<L>&THORN;e contrie him &thorn;ou&yogh;te murie i-nou&yogh; : &thorn;are-forth &thorn;at he cam;</L>
<L N="458">&THORN;e for&thorn;ere &thorn;at he wende : &thorn;e more murev&thorn;e he sei&yogh;.</L>
<L>So [longe] &thorn;at he i-sai&yogh; ane wal : swi&thorn;e noble and hei&yogh;&mdash;</L>
<L>So riche weork nas neuere i-sei&yogh;e : ase him [&thorn;ou&yogh;te] &thorn;at &thorn;ar-on was;</L>
<L>And swy&thorn;e fair &yogh;at &thorn;aron he sai&yogh; : &thorn;at neuere swuch i-sei&yogh;e nas;</L>
<L N="462">&THORN;at &yogh;at schon swy&thorn;e bri&yogh;te : ase &thorn;ei it al gold were,</L>
<L>Folle of derewur&thorn;e stones i-pi&yogh;te : none richere neuere nere.</L>
<L N="464">him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, are he &thorn;udere cam : is wei ful longe laste.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he cam for&thorn;ere a luytel wi&yogh;t : he stod and bi-heold it faste.</L>
<L>&THORN;at [&yogh;at]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> wende op a&yogh;en him : and a-non-ri&yogh;t with &thorn;e dede</L>
<L>&THORN;are cam smite out a swote smel : and wide a-boute gan sprede,</L>
<L N="468">&THORN;at him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, &thorn;ei al &thorn;e world : swote spices were,</L>
<L>So muche swotnesse ne mi&yogh;te &yogh;iuen : ase &thorn;at suote smul dude &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>In so gret Ioye him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he was : &thorn;at &thorn;ei he hadde beo i-brou&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="102" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In-to al &thorn;e soruwe &thorn;at he was er : it ne schulde him habbe i-greued nou&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000262.tif" N="214"></L>
<L N="472">he bi-heold in at &thorn;is &yogh;ate : &thorn;o he cam &thorn;er-nei&yogh;:</L>
<L>More clernesse nas neuere i-sei&yogh;e : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, &thorn;ane he &thorn;ere i-sei&yogh;.</L>
<L>Ase he wolde &thorn;are-In wende : a&yogh;ein him &thorn;are cam gon</L>
<L>A procession fair i-nov&yogh; : of noble men ech-on,</L>
<L N="476">with creoiz and with taperes : and with baneres clere;</L>
<L>I-reuested faire muche folk was : and ech hadde is fere,</L>
<L>Some were bischopus and Ercedeknes : and some Monekes and freres,</L>
<L>And euerech, him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, hadde &thorn;e Abite : &thorn;at heo wereden here.</L>
<L N="480">with &thorn;e meste Ioye &thorn;at mi&yogh;te beo : &thorn;is kni&yogh;t was onder-fonge,</L>
<L>And i-lad In with Ioye i-nov&yogh; : mid solas and murie songe.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is murie song was i-do : to him sone &thorn;are come</L>
<L>Tweien ase it maistres weren : and bi &thorn;e honde him nome,</L>
<L>And welcomeden him wel mildeliche : and &thorn;onkeden ore louerd faste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at him sende so guode bi-leue : so stableliche for-to laste.</L>
<L>heo ladden him a-boute and scheweden him : &thorn;at lond fer and ner:</L>
<L>So muche Ioie and clernesse : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he ne sai&yogh; neuer er.</L>
<L N="488">&para; Ase &thorn;e sonne bi-nimez &thorn;e li&yogh;t : of Candle a-boute Midday,</L>
<L>Also it bi-nam &thorn;e sonne hire leom : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, ase<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;e li&yogh;t &thorn;at</NOTE> he &thorn;are i-sai&yogh;.</L>
<L>So long and brod &thorn;e place was : &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;te non ende i-seo:</L>
<L>A fair Medwe he sai&yogh;<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Al murie med</NOTE> with swete floures : swottere ne mi&yogh;te non beo,</L>
<L>Treon al-so with noble fruyt : &thorn;at smulde swote Inov&yogh;;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> So gret</NOTE> swotnesse of euer-ech stude : al a-boute op drou&yogh;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;are with-oute mete and drunch : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, euere-mo</L>
<L>he mi&yogh;te libbe with alle Ioie : &yogh;if he moste &thorn;are-Inne go.</L>
<L N="496">It was &thorn;ere euere i-liche li&yogh;t : and euere it was dai.</L>
<L>So muche folk in none place, him &thorn;ou&yogh;te : neuer er he ne sai&yogh;.</L>
<L>Ech Compaygnie to o&thorn;ur drov&yogh; : and ech bi o&thorn;ur stod,</L>
<L>With murie song and Melodie : and gladnesse in heore mod,</L>
<L N="500">&THORN;at ech of o&thorn;ur &thorn;e more Ioye : to-gadere heo mi&yogh;ten a-fonge;</L>
<L>Al-mi&yogh;ti god, &thorn;at heom schop : heo hereden In heore songe.</L>
<L>And ase sum steorre &thorn;at &yogh;e i-seoth : bri&yogh;tore &thorn;ane o&thorn;ur is,</L>
<L>Also was bi heom, for some weren : clerore &thorn;ane some, i-wis;</L>
<L N="504">Ake &thorn;ulke &thorn;at mest dosk was : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, was more cler</L>
<L>And bri&yogh;tore schon, &thorn;ane ani gold : &thorn;at he i-sai&yogh; euer er.</L>
<L>&para; Ech werede clo&thorn;es of &thorn;e en-taile : &thorn;at heo wereden on eor&thorn;e here:</L>
<L>Monekes ase it to Monek bi-feol : and freres ase to frere;
<PB REF="00000263.tif" N="215"></L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo hadden heore ri&yogh;te fourme : ake wel bri&yogh;tore was hore hev,</L>
<L>Ant &yogh;wat men heo were on eor&thorn;e : bi heore clo&thorn;inge he knev.</L>
<L N="510">Some hadden &thorn;e croune of golde : an-ouewarde &thorn;e heued ido,</L>
<L>And some beren in heore hond : &yogh;eordene of golde al-so.</L>
<L>And alle heo &thorn;onkeden Ihesu crist : &thorn;at so studefast heorte him sende,</L>
<L>&THORN;e kni&yogh;t, for al &thorn;e pine &thorn;at he hadde : is heorte enes ne wende;</L>
<L N="514">Ech-one heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at for him : In &thorn;e more Ioye heo were.</L>
<L>he stod and bi-heold al &thorn;is Ioie : as &thorn;ei no wit on him nere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e on, ase it heore maister were : is Mouth ondude wel softe<MILESTONE N="102b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And welcomede him wel mildeliche : and &thorn;onkede ore louerd ofte,</L>
<L N="518">&THORN;at swuch porpos him hadde i-send : and studefast heorte al-so,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne chaungede nou&yogh;t is &thorn;ou&yogh;t : for al &thorn;at him was i-do.</L>
<L>"bev frere," he seide, "i-herd beo god : &thorn;at &thorn;e hauez hidere i-brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And a-mong alle &thorn;ine stronge fon : studefast i-wust &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t!</L>
<L N="522">Of &thorn;e pine of sunfule gostes : I-fondet &thorn;ov hauest i-nou&yogh;,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are-with &thorn;ine sunnes i-bet : and elles it were wou&yogh;.</L>
<L N="524">&para; &THORN;ov mi&yogh;t here sumdel i-seo : &thorn;at &thorn;ov wilnest more,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;at guode soulene habbez : &thorn;at comieth to milce and ore.</L>
<L>&THORN;is place &thorn;at we inne beoth : ich wene &thorn;ov ne knowest nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>It is eor&thorn;elich parays : &thorn;at Adam was Inne i-brou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="528">And &thorn;at he was Inne ymad : and seth&thorn;e for is mis-dede</L>
<L>he was i-cast out &thorn;ar-of, and we also : on eor&thorn;e into alle wrechchehede;</L>
<L>&para; Al &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;at &thorn;ov i-sixt her : he hadde to is wille,</L>
<L>Ake he ne mi&yogh;te, &thorn;o he was out i-cast : &thorn;ar-of i-seo wurth a fille.</L>
<L N="532">Of wrechhede we beoth i-kened : and of sunful blode i-come:</L>
<L>And &thorn;at us is &thorn;oru&yogh; godes grace : ant &thorn;oru&yogh; ore cristinedom bi-nome.</L>
<L>Ak &thorn;at we aftur ore cristindom : of sunne on eor&thorn;e wrou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>On eor&thorn;e o&thorn;ur in purgatorie : wel deore we it bou&yogh;te:</L>
<L N="536">For we alle &thorn;at &thorn;ou here i-sixt : &thorn;are-forth hidere come</L>
<L>And ore sunnes &thorn;are betten : and harde penaunce nome,</L>
<L>Ne mi&yogh;te we elles here come. : ase guod bi &thorn;e it is:</L>
<L>For &yogh;if &thorn;ine sunnes nere for-&yogh;iue : &thorn;ov ne come nou&yogh;t here, i-wis.</L>
<L N="540">And alle &thorn;at &thorn;ov &thorn;are i-sei&yogh;e : to us &thorn;udere heo schullen wende,</L>
<L>And al dai doth some, &yogh;wane heo habbez : heore penaunce i-brou&yogh;t to ende.</L>
<L>Neuer on not hov longe he schal : &thorn;are bi-leue, i-wis;
<PB REF="00000264.tif" N="216"></L>
<L>For ho-so ani freond on eor&thorn;e hath : mid him &thorn;e betere it is:</L>
<L N="544">&THORN;oru&yogh; massene and &thorn;oru&yogh; o&thorn;ur beden : and &thorn;oru&yogh; almes-dede</L>
<L>Man mai hore pine muche a-legge : and &thorn;e sonore ovt &thorn;ar-of heom lede.</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane ani of heom hidere comez : a&yogh;en him we wendez ech-on,</L>
<L>Ase we duden a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e, with Ioye : and ledez him In a-non.</L>
<L N="548">Ake non of us nis &yogh;uyt wuyrth&thorn;e : in-to heuene for-to wende,</L>
<L>Ne neuere on not &yogh;wane ovre louerd : after ani of us wole sende;</L>
<L>For ech man &thorn;at in-to heuene schal : &thorn;oru&yogh; purgatorie mot</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e into eor&thorn;eliche parays : ase we beoth nov&thorn;e, wel ich wot.</L>
<L N="552">For &thorn;is is ovre kuynde heritage : i-wrou&yogh;t we weren &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L>Al for-to ore furste fader it a-gulte : and for-to he hadde mis-do;</L>
<L>here we scholden alle habbe i-beon i-bore : and i-leoued ore lif al-so,</L>
<L>For ore louerd wold &thorn;at we weren : In &thorn;e more Ioye i-do.</L>
<L N="556">&THORN;ei men beon ovt heonnes i-cast : here-forth heo moten wende</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. and</NOTE> a&yogh;en, ar heo to heouene come : aftur heore liues ende.</L>
<L>Ake al &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;at is here : nis no-&thorn;ing, i-wis,</L>
<L>A-&yogh;ein &thorn;e leste Ioye of heouene : wel muche &thorn;e meste is.</L>
<L N="560">Sum-&thorn;ing &thorn;ov schalt of heuene i-seo : In a place here-nei&yogh;."</L>
<L>he ladde him op-on an hei&yogh; hul : and bad him bi-holde on hei&yogh;,<MILESTONE N="103" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And axede him of &yogh;wuch colur were : heuene op-ri&yogh;t &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>he seide, him &thorn;ou&yogh;te ri&yogh;t ase gold : &thorn;at puyr wallinde were.</L>
<L N="564">"&YOGH;e," seide &thorn;is o&thorn;ur, "&thorn;is is &thorn;e wei : &thorn;at geth ri&yogh;t to heuene blis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at is &thorn;e &yogh;at of parays : &thorn;at with-oute heuene &yogh;eond is.</L>
<L>&para; Ech day some of purgatorie : comez hidere us to,</L>
<L>And some of us to heuene wendez : euer-eche daye also;</L>
<L N="568">So &thorn;at [we] wexez eche daie : and waniez, &thorn;ov sixt lo;</L>
<L>We nutez &yogh;wuch of us it schal beo next : bote as god wole habbe i-do.</L>
<L>Ech dai &thorn;e &yogh;wuyle we here beoth : ore louerd us fedez ene</L>
<L>with riche metes of heuene : &thorn;at swete is and clene;</L>
<L N="572">&yogh;wuche &thorn;ulke metes beon : are &thorn;ov heonnes wende</L>
<L>with us &thorn;ov schalt sone i-wite : &yogh;wane god it wole us sende."</L>
<L>Ne hadde he bote o word i-seid : &thorn;at &thorn;are ne cam a-li&yogh;te</L>
<L>A manere brez fram heouene a-doun : &thorn;at schon wel clere and bri&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="576">&THORN;at ouer-spradde al &thorn;at lond : and a cler leome &thorn;are-with-oute,
<PB REF="00000265.tif" N="217"></L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> opon euereches heued a-li&yogh;te a-doun : wel faire, with-outen doute,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> clerore &thorn;ane aboute</NOTE></L>
<L>And op-on &thorn;is kni&yogh;tes heued al-so : an &thorn;oru&yogh; him smot a-non,</L>
<L>And &thorn;oru&yogh; euerech lime and lith of him : &thorn;at swete li&yogh;t gan gon;</L>
<L N="580">&THORN;a[t] so muche wille<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. winne?</NOTE> and Ioye : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, neuere he nadde.</L>
<L>he stod, ase &thorn;ei he were i-nomen : for Ioye &thorn;at he &thorn;o hadde,</L>
<L>&YOGH;we&thorn;ur he were quik o&thorn;ur ded : bote ase he in metingue were.</L>
<L>louerd, murie is &thorn;e Ioye of heuene : ase he i-felde wel &thorn;ere!</L>
<L N="584">Ake it ne laste heom bote luytele &yogh;wile : &thorn;at &thorn;e leome ne with|drov&yogh;;</L>
<L>And na&thorn;eles, &thorn;ei it luyte laste : &thorn;ar-of heo weren fulle i-nov&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kni&yogh;t stod and bi-heold a-boute : and is ri&yogh;te stat onder-stod.</L>
<L>So fol he was of &thorn;at holi leome : &thorn;at so swete was and guod:</L>
<L N="588">him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, &thorn;ei he leouede euere-more : and neuereft more ne ete,</L>
<L>Ne scholde him neuer-eft to mete luste : so guod was &thorn;e leome and swete.</L>
<L>"Lo," seide &thorn;is o&thorn;ur gost : &thorn;at schewede him al &thorn;is place,</L>
<L>"Sum-del &thorn;ov hast nou&thorn;e isei&yogh;e : of ore louerdes grace</L>
<L N="592">&para; Of &thorn;e pine &thorn;at &thorn;e wrechche gostes : habbeth for heore mis|dede,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;at guode gostes : in parays doth lede,</L>
<L>And sum-del of &thorn;e grete Ioie : &thorn;at in &thorn;e ri&yogh;te heuene is.</L>
<L>Eche dai&yogh;e we beoth i-fedde : ones with swuche Ioie and blis,</L>
<L N="596">And &thorn;anne beo we al dai fulle i-nov&yogh; : for-to ore louerd more us sende:</L>
<L>In swuche Ioie heo beoth &thorn;at beoth in heouene : and wor&thorn;ez with|oute ende,</L>
<L>And &yogh;uyt sum-del in more : it ne faillez heom neuere mo,</L>
<L>And we ne beoth a day bote enes : for-to we &thorn;udere go;</L>
<L N="600">And &yogh;wan &thorn;at we &thorn;udere comieth : we schulle with-outen ende,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou, &yogh;if &thorn;ov a-seruest heuene forth : &thorn;udere for-to wende.</L>
<L>&THORN;ov mi&yogh;t don ase &thorn;ov wolt : &yogh;wane &thorn;ov comest to eor&thorn;e, i-wis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;udere anon a-&yogh;en &thorn;ou most&mdash; : for-so&thorn;e, at &thorn;e time it is;</L>
<L N="604">And &yogh;if &thorn;ov wolt guod lif lede : &thorn;ine mede &thorn;ov mi&yogh;t i-seo;</L>
<L>And &yogh;wat pine heo habbez, &thorn;ov hast i-seie : &thorn;at lu&thorn;ere wollez beo.</L>
<L>A-&yogh;ein &thorn;ou most wende a-non : go forth a-godes name!<MILESTONE N="103b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000266.tif" N="218"></L>
<L>For sikerliche &thorn;ov mi&yogh;t gon : &thorn;e feondes ne mowen don &thorn;e no schame;</L>
<L N="608">heo beoth a-dradde wel sore of &thorn;e : and a-schamede in eche side.</L>
<L>A-godes name go forth &thorn;i wei : &thorn;ov ne mi&yogh;t no leng here a-bide!"</L>
<L>"A, sire, merci!" quath &thorn;is kni&yogh;t : "bi-tide &yogh;wat me bi-tide,</L>
<L>A fote i-nelle fram eov go : for wrechche-hede<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. hedede</NOTE> goth so wide.</L>
<L>&para; Ake soffriez me bi-leue here with ov! : for, &yogh;if ich fram eov wende,</L>
<L N="613">A-drad ich am of &thorn;e feondene mi&yogh;te : laste heo with sunne me schende."</L>
<L>"Do wei, beu frere," &thorn;is o&thorn;ur seide : "ase wel &thorn;ov mi&yogh;t beo stille,</L>
<L>A-&yogh;en &thorn;ov schalt to eor&thorn;e a-non : and<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> &thorn;ov mi&yogh;t don &thorn;are &thorn;ine wille;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ov seruest wel ore louerd &thorn;ere : siker &thorn;ov mi&yogh;t beo</L>
<L N="617">to comen a-&yogh;ein hidere to us : and seth&thorn;e to heuene fteo.</L>
<L>A-godes half wend a-&yogh;en a-non : for-so&thorn;e, &thorn;ov schalt so."</L>
<L>"Alas, alas!" quath &thorn;is kni&yogh;t : "&yogh;wat schal ich nou&thorn;e do?</L>
<L N="620">Al &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;at ich habbe nou&thorn;e isei&yogh;e : it worth me bi-nome,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e wrechhede of &thorn;e worlde : alas, schal ich nov&thorn;e come!"</L>
<L>Ovt ate &yogh;ate heo brou&yogh;ten him : wepinde, at &thorn;e laste,</L>
<L>And beden him gon wel hardiliche : and herien ore louerd wel faste;</L>
<L N="624">A-non so he was with-oute i-gon : &thorn;at &yogh;at heo maden wel bliue.</L>
<L>With dreori mod he wende a-&yogh;en : and was a-drad of is liue;</L>
<L>Ase he cam er, with careful mod : &thorn;ene wei a-&yogh;ein he nam.</L>
<L>And, &yogh;wane ani deuel &thorn;at him pinede er : ou&yogh;were a-&yogh;en him cam,</L>
<L N="628">Ase wode schrewene heo flouwen faste : and ne dorsten a-bide him nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>So at&thorn;e laste &thorn;is kni&yogh;t was : to &thorn;e halle a-&yogh;ein i-brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;are as &thorn;e holie compaygnie : &thorn;uder-ward to him wende;</L>
<L>And sat him a-doun wel softe &thorn;ere : for-to ore louerd him grace sende.</L>
<L N="632">Ase he sat and bi-heold a-boute : to him heo comen &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at faire compaygnie : &thorn;at a-&yogh;ein him cam er,</L>
<L>And honoureden him wel faire : and conforteden him wel faste,</L>
<L>And &thorn;onkeden Iesus, godes sone : &thorn;at his bi-leue so wel i-laste.</L>
<L N="636">&para; "bev frere," heo seiden, "&yogh;wane &thorn;ov hast : swuch penaunce i|driue,</L>
<L>Siker beo &thorn;ou &thorn;at &thorn;ine sunnes : al clene &thorn;e beoth for-&yogh;iue.</L>
<L>loke, &yogh;wane &thorn;ov comest to eor&thorn;e a-&yogh;en : &thorn;at &thorn;ov clene lif lede,
<PB REF="00000267.tif" N="219"></L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ov neuer-eft in pine ne come : for sunne ne for mis-dede!</L>
<L N="640">&THORN;ov most don &thorn;e heonnes a-non : for at hom in &thorn;ine londe</L>
<L>hit dawez clere and is nei&yogh; dai : ase ich me onder-stonde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e prior with procession : to &thorn;e &yogh;ate comez wel sone</L>
<L>to loki &yogh;we&thorn;ur &thorn;ov beo i-come : ase ri&yogh;t is forto done,</L>
<L N="644">And, bote he &thorn;e finde &thorn;ere : he wole maken &thorn;at &yogh;at a-non</L>
<L>And wole beo siker &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne comest non-more : and sori wole a-&yogh;en gon."<NOTE PLACE="marg1">This verse on the margin.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ene kni&yogh;t heo brou&yogh;ten out of &thorn;e halle : and blesseden him ech-on</L>
<L>And bi-tei&yogh;ten god bo&thorn;e lif and soule : fel and flesch and bon.</L>
<L N="648">Forth he wende wel dreoriliche : bote ase he nede moste it do.</L>
<L>And ri&yogh;t ase he cam to &thorn;e &yogh;ate : &thorn;e prior cam al-so</L>
<L>A-&yogh;ein him with procession : to loke hou it were.</L>
<L N="651">A-non so he hadde &thorn;e &yogh;ate on-loke : &thorn;ene kni&yogh;t heo founden &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;are was Ioye and blisse i-nov&yogh; : &thorn;o huy to-gadere come!<MILESTONE N="104" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>With song and o&thorn;ur melodie : &thorn;ane kny&yogh;t &thorn;are-out huy nome,</L>
<L>Ant ladden him forth to churche a-non : ant &thorn;onkeden god wel faste.</L>
<L>&THORN;is kni&yogh;t bi-fore &thorn;e hei&yogh;e auctere : a-knes wel sone him caste,</L>
<L N="656">Ant stableliche in his oresones : fiftene dawes he lay,</L>
<L>And &thorn;onkede ore louerd &amp; on him cride : bo&thorn;e ny&yogh;t and day.</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e on his bare flesch : &thorn;e holie croiz he nam</L>
<L>And wende to &thorn;e holie lond : ant suy&thorn;e holi man bi-cam.</L>
<L N="660">he ne tolde neuere-eft nou&yogh;t of &thorn;e world : bote ase he were euere in &thorn;ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Ake wende euere forth wel stilleliche<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> simpleliche</NOTE> : as he of no-&thorn;ing ne rou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Ofte he tolde of alle &thorn;e men : &thorn;at in parays were;</L>
<L>As him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, grei&yogh;e Monekes : mest Ioye hadden &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="664">None-manere men in so gret Ioye : ne in so grete honour he ne sei&yogh;&mdash;</L>
<L>hit nis no wonder sikerliche : for &thorn;e ordre is noble and hei&yogh;.&mdash;</L>
<L>Nov&thorn;e &yogh;e habbez alle i-heord : &thorn;oru&yogh; ore louerdes grace,</L>
<L>hou seint paterik &thorn;ulke purgatorie : founde in &thorn;at place,</L>
<L N="668">For-to warni men a-boute : heore sunnes here to bete.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e loue of Iesu crist : and of is moder swete</L>
<L>Alle ower sunnes betez here : as god ov wole grace sende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e mouwen with-oute pine : to parays hennes wende.
<PB REF="00000268.tif" N="220"></L>
<L N="672">god leue us ovre sunnes here so biete : for is holie wounde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we ne &thorn;oruen in purgatorie : bi-leue bote luyte stounde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="36" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>36 Vita sancti Brendani, Abbatis de Hybernia.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint brendan, &thorn;e holi man : was here of ovre londe.</L>
<L>Monek he was of harde liue : as ich me under-stonde,</L>
<L>Of fastingue and o&thorn;ur penaunce i-nov : and Abbot he was &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="4">Of a &thorn;ousend Monekes : &thorn;at alle under him were.</L>
<L>hit bi-feol in a day : as ore louerdes wille was,</L>
<L>&THORN;at beryn,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> barint</NOTE> an o&thorn;ur Abbot : to him cam bi cas.</L>
<L>Seint brendan him bi-sou&yogh;te anon : him don onder-stonde</L>
<L N="8">Ant tellen him &yogh;wat he hadde i-sei&yogh;e : a-boute in o&thorn;ur londe.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode man, &thorn;o he i-heorde &thorn;is : sichingues he made i-nowe</L>
<L>Ant in grete &thorn;ou&yogh;te bi-gan for-to weope : and fel a-doun i-suowe.</L>
<L>bi-twene his armes seint brendan : &thorn;is holie man op nam</L>
<L N="12">&amp; custe him faste, &amp; cride on him : al for-to is wit him cam;</L>
<L>"Fader," he seide, "par charite : o&thorn;ur red &thorn;ov most take;</L>
<L>hidere &thorn;ou come for ovre solas : and nou&yogh;t suych deol to make.</L>
<L>tel us &yogh;wat &thorn;ou hast i-sei&yogh;e : a-boute as &thorn;ou hast i-wend</L>
<L N="16">In &thorn;e .se. of Occean : as ore louerd &thorn;e hath i-send."</L>
<L>Nou is &thorn;e .se. [of] Occean : grettest and mest al-so:</L>
<L>heo goth a-boute al &thorn;e world : and alle o&thorn;ere cometh &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at berin, &thorn;is olde man : ri&yogh;t of is heorte grounde</L>
<L N="20">Al weopinde he hem tolde : &yogh;wat he hadde i-founde.</L>
<L>he seide, he<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> ic</NOTE> hadde a wel guod sone : and Mernok was is name,</L>
<L>"A Monek he was, as we beoth : and man of grete fame;</L>
<L>his heorte him &yogh;af for-to wende : in-to a priue stude and stille,<MILESTONE N="104b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="24">&THORN;are he mi&yogh;te beo al one : to a-serui godes wille.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at bi mine wille he wende : ase ich it telle ov,</L>
<L>to an yle fer in &thorn;e se : &thorn;at delitable was i-nov,</L>
<L>bi-side &thorn;e Montayne of stones : &thorn;at is couth wel wide.</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;e Monek likede &thorn;are wel : and longue gan &thorn;are a-bide,</L>
<L>And hadde &thorn;are under him : Monekes mani on.</L>
<L>&THORN;o ich heorde tellen &thorn;at : &thorn;uder-ward ich gan gon.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at in auision : ore suete louerd him sende,</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;at a-&yogh;en me, are ich to him come : &thorn;re Iorneies he wende.
<PB REF="00000269.tif" N="221"></L>
<L>And in a schip we duden us sone : and Astward euere kenden</L>
<L>In &thorn;e .se. of Occean : as ore louerd is grace us sende.</L>
<L>toward &thorn;e est so fer we wenden : &thorn;at we comen ate laste</L>
<L N="36">In suy&thorn;e &thorn;uyster stude : and clouden us ouer-caste;</L>
<L>Al ane tide of &thorn;e daye : we weren in deorkhede.</L>
<L>Ate laste ore suete louerd : for&thorn;ere us gan lede.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at we i-sei&yogh;en a newe lond : &thorn;uder-ward ore schip drov;</L>
<L N="40">bri&yogh;ttore it &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;ane &thorn;e sonne : Ioye &thorn;are was i-nov,</L>
<L>Of treon and herbes, &thorn;ikke j-nov&yogh; : bi-set in eche side,</L>
<L>And of suete preciouse stones : &thorn;at bri&yogh;tte schynen and wide;</L>
<L>Euerech herbe was ful of floures : and ech treo was ful of fruyt;</L>
<L N="44">bote it were in heuene : nas neuere more duyt.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-Inne with Ioye and blisse I-nov&yogh; : longue we duden i-wende;</L>
<L>&YOGH;eot us &thorn;ou&yogh;te luytel &yogh;wyle : ne mi&yogh;te we finde non ende</L>
<L>So &thorn;at we comen to a watur : cler and bri&yogh;t I-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L N="48">&thorn;at euere fram-ward &thorn;e est : toward &thorn;e west it drov&yogh;.</L>
<L>We stoden and bi-heolden a-boute : for we ne mi&yogh;ten ouer i-wende:</L>
<L>&THORN;are cam to us a &yogh;ong &yogh;omman : swi&thorn;e fair and hende,</L>
<L>And welcomede us euerech-one : wel mildeliche and swete;</L>
<L N="52">he nemnede euerech is ri&yogh;tte name : and faire gan us grete,</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;at we ou&yogh;ten<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &yogh;e a&yogh;te</NOTE> Ihesu crist : &thorn;onki suy&thorn;e wel with ri&yogh;te</L>
<L>'&THORN;at schewez eov is priuete : and al-so of is mi&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&THORN;is is &thorn;at lond &thorn;at he wole : &yogh;uyt are &thorn;e worldes ende</L>
<L>[his dernelinges an er&thorn;e &yogh;yue : &yogh; hyder he schal<NOTE PLACE="marg1">heo scholle, on the margin.</NOTE> wende.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">This verse added by a later hand in the text and on the mar|gin.</NOTE>]</L>
<L>&THORN;is lond is half in &thorn;usse half : ase &yogh;e i-seoz wel wide,</L>
<L>And bi-&yogh;eonde &thorn;e watere haluen-del : al bi &thorn;at o&thorn;ur side&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at watur ne mowe &yogh;e passi nou&yogh;t : &thorn;at o&thorn;ur del to seo.</L>
<L N="60">For<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> here &yogh;e habbez al a &yogh;er : meteles i-beo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e ne eten ne dronken : ne slepen nou&yogh;t with ey&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Ne chele ne hete ne greuede ev nou&yogh;t : no&thorn;ur lowe ne hei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;is<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> For &thorn;is</NOTE> is ore louerdes priue stude : and &thorn;oru&yogh; him it is &thorn;us li&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;are-fore it is [her] euere day : and neuere-more ni&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&yogh;if Adam a-&yogh;ein godes heste : ne hadde no-&thorn;ing mis-do,</L>
<L>here-Inne he hadde &yogh;uyt i-beo : and is of-sprung al-so.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e ne mowen no leng here bi-leue : a-&yogh;en &yogh;e moten fare;<NOTE PLACE="inter">[<I>Here</I> 2 <I>fol. are torn out in the MS. I supply the gap from MS. Harl.</I> 2277.]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000270.tif" N="222"></L>
<L>[&THORN;e&yogh; hit ne &thorn;enche &yogh;ou bote a while : &yogh;e habbe&thorn; ibeo her &yogh;are.'<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 2277 folio" N="42b"></L>
<L>&THORN;at so<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> So &thorn;at</NOTE> he brou&yogh;te ous in oure schip : &amp; faire his leue nom;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;o<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;e</NOTE> we were hamward in &thorn;e see : we nuste whar he bi-com&mdash;</L>
<L>A&yogh;e-ward he wende a&yogh;en oure wille : &thorn;at of-&thorn;o&yogh;te ous sore ynou&yogh;.</L>
<L N="72">A&yogh;en to &thorn;is o&thorn;er monekes : &thorn;is schip wel euene drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is monekes vrne a&yogh;en ous : &thorn;o hi ous mi&yogh;te iseo,</L>
<L>&amp; sori were &amp; wro&thorn;e ynou&yogh; : &thorn;at we hadde so longe ibeo.</L>
<L>we seide hem &thorn;at we hadde ibeo : in gret ioye &amp; feste,</L>
<L N="76">Bifore &thorn;e &yogh;ates of parays : in &thorn;e lond of biheste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at oure suete louerd ha&thorn; bihote : hem &thorn;at he loue&thorn; her,</L>
<L>&THORN;er is euere dai &amp; neuere ni&yogh;t : &amp; euere li&yogh;t suy&thorn;e cler.</L>
<L>&para; 'Certes,' qua&thorn; &thorn;is monekes : '&thorn;is we mowe iseo</L>
<L N="80">Bi &thorn;e suete smyl of &yogh;ou : &thorn;at &yogh;e habbe&thorn; &thorn;er ibeo.' "&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o seint Brendan ihurde &thorn;is : he &thorn;o&yogh;te &amp; stod stille;</L>
<L>[he &thorn;o&yogh;te fondi more her-of : &yogh;if it were godes wille.]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">This verse, om. in H., is taken from Ashm.</NOTE></L>
<L>he wende aboute his monekes : &amp; tuelue out he nom,</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;at he triste to mest of alle : whan eni neode him com.</L>
<L>&THORN;use he nom in consail : &amp; in priueite [hem] sede:</L>
<L>["I &thorn;enche do a priue &thorn;ing : &thorn;er-of &yogh;e mote me rede,</L>
<L>To seche &thorn;at lond of biheste : &yogh;if god wolde ous &thorn;uder lede.]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">These 2 v. om. in H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="88">Sigge&thorn; what &yogh;oure consail is : to do such a dede."</L>
<L>"Leoue fader," qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;ere : "oure wille we habbe&thorn; forsake,</L>
<L>&para; Oure freond &amp; al oure o&thorn;er god : &amp; clanliche to &thorn;e itake:</L>
<L>&amp; whan al oure dede is on &thorn;e : &amp; &thorn;u wolt &thorn;at hit beo,</L>
<L N="92">we schulle bli&thorn;eliche wi&thorn; &thorn;e wende : godes grace to seo."</L>
<L>So &thorn;at hi faste fourti dawes : &amp; gret penance dude also,</L>
<L>&amp; bede &yogh;urne oure louerdes grace : &thorn;ulke veyage to do.</L>
<L>hi leten hem di&yogh;te a gret schip : &amp; aboue hit albi<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. abbi</NOTE>-caste</L>
<L N="96">wi&thorn; bole-huden stronge ynou : ynailed &thorn;erto faste,</L>
<L>&amp; si&thorn;&thorn;e ipiched al abou[t]e : &thorn;at &thorn;e water [in] necome.<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 2277 folio" N="43"></L>
<L>hi wende to here bre&thorn;eren : &amp; wel faire here leue nome,</L>
<L>And si&thorn;&thorn;e in oure louerdes name : to schipe wende anon;</L>
<L N="100">here bre&thorn;eren &thorn;at bihynde were : sori were echon.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;o hi were in &thorn;e schip : after &thorn;er come go<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> tuo</L>
<L>&amp; bede faste &thorn;at hi moste : &thorn;ane wei mid hem go.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e mowe wel," qua&thorn; seint brendan : "ac &yogh;oure on schal atta[n] ende</L>
<L N="104">Repenti er he come a&yogh;e : &amp; al quic to helle wende."</L>
<L>&THORN;ider<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> vor&thorn; him</NOTE> wende &thorn;is holi man : whoder oure louerd hem sende;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;is tuei monekes &thorn;at come last : also wi&thorn; hem wende.</L>
<L>&para; In &thorn;e grete see of occian : for&thorn; hi rewe faste,</L>
<L N="108">&amp; triste alto oure louerdes grace : &amp; no&thorn;ing nere agaste.
<PB REF="00000271.tif" N="223"></L>
<L>&THORN;e see drof here schip after wil : &thorn;e wynd was gret ynou&yogh;;</L>
<L>As &thorn;e wynd hem drof est for&thorn; : wel euene &thorn;e schip him drou&yogh;,</L>
<L>Euene a&yogh;e &thorn;at &thorn;e sonne arise&thorn; : a-midsomeres day&mdash;</L>
<L N="112">Nou nuste non of hem whar he was : ne no lond he nesay.</L>
<L>Euene for&thorn;ri&yogh;t fourti dayes : &thorn;e wynd hem drof faste:</L>
<L>So &thorn;at hi se&yogh;e in &thorn;e nor&thorn;side : a gret ylle<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. yle</NOTE> atte laste,</L>
<L>Of harde roche &amp; gret ynou : in &thorn;e see wel he&yogh;e;</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;reo dayes hi wende &thorn;er-aboute : er hi mi&yogh;te come &thorn;er-ne&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&para; A lute hauene hi<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. he</NOTE> fonde &thorn;o : alond hi wende &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>hi wende alond as maskede<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> masid</NOTE> men : hi nuste whar hi were.</L>
<L>&THORN;er com go a wel fair hound : as hit were hem to here;</L>
<L N="120">At seint Brendanes fet he ful adoun : &amp; makede him faire chere.</L>
<L>&para; "Beau freres," qua&thorn; seint brendan : "&yogh;e ne&thorn;ore no&thorn;ing drede:</L>
<L>Ich wot &thorn;is is a messager : &thorn;e ri&yogh;te wei ous to lede."</L>
<L>&THORN;is hound ladde &thorn;is holi man : to an halle, fair ynou&yogh;,</L>
<L N="124">Gret &amp; starc &amp; suy&thorn;e noble : euene in he drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;is monekes fonde in &thorn;is halle : bord &amp; clo&thorn; isprad,</L>
<L>&amp; bred &amp; fisch &thorn;er-vppe ynou&yogh;&mdash; : &thorn;er nas non &thorn;at nas glad.</L>
<L>hi sete adoun &amp; ete faste&mdash; : for hem luste wel &thorn;erto.</L>
<L N="128">Beddes &thorn;er were, al &yogh;are ymaked : er here soper were ido:</L>
<L>After here soper to bedde hi wende : to resten hem, as &thorn;e wise.</L>
<L>&THORN;o hi hadde alle islepe ynou&yogh; : sone hi gonne arise,</L>
<L>&amp; wende to here schip : as hi hadde er ibeo.</L>
<L N="132">In &thorn;e see wel longe hi were : er hi mi&yogh;te lond iseo.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o hi se&yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. se&yogh;e hi</NOTE> as bi &thorn;o&thorn;er side : an ylle fair ynou&yogh;,</L>
<L>Grene &amp; [wi&thorn;] wel fair lese. : &thorn;iderward here schip drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;o hi come on &thorn;is faire lond : &amp; bihulde aboute wide,<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 2277 folio" N="43b"></L>
<L N="136">&THORN;e faireste scheep &thorn;at mi&yogh;te beo : hi se&yogh;e in eche side;</L>
<L>A scheep was grettere &thorn;an an oxe : whittere ne mi&yogh;te non beo.</L>
<L>Gret ioye hi hadde in here hurte : &thorn;at hi mi&yogh;te &thorn;is iseo.</L>
<L>&THORN;er com<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;o com &thorn;er</NOTE> go a wel fair man : &amp; grette hem wi&thorn; faire chere,</L>
<L N="140">&amp; seide, "&yogh;e beo&thorn; hider icome : &thorn;er &yogh;e neuere nere.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is is icliped &thorn;e lond of scheep : for scheep wel faire her beo&thorn;,</L>
<L>Mochele &amp; white &amp; grete ynou&yogh; : as &yogh;e aldai iseo&thorn;;</L>
<L>Fairere hi beo&thorn; &thorn;an &yogh;oure scheep : &amp; grettere vnyliche,</L>
<L N="144">For murie weder is her ynou&yogh; : &amp; lese suy&thorn;e riche.</L>
<L>her nis neuere wynter non : for her nis non<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> ne non hei</NOTE> ifounde,</L>
<L>Ac hi ete&thorn; &thorn;erbes nue : as hi springe&thorn; of &thorn;e g[ro]unde.</L>
<L>Ne me ne gadere&thorn; no&yogh;t of here mulc : &thorn;at hi scholde &thorn;e worse beo;</L>
<L N="148">&para; For &thorn;is &thorn;ing, &amp; meni o&thorn;er : &thorn;e bet hi mowe i&thorn;eo.</L>
<L>To a stede &yogh;e schulle hunne wende : &thorn;urf oure louerdes grace,
<PB REF="00000272.tif" N="224"></L>
<L>&THORN;at is foweles parays : a wel ioyful place :</L>
<L>&THORN;er &yogh;e schulle &thorn;is ester beo : &amp; &thorn;is wit-sonedai also.</L>
<L N="152">Wende&thorn; for&thorn; a-godes name : &thorn;at &thorn;is veyage were ido!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Brendan &amp; his bre&thorn;eren : to schipe wende anon,</L>
<L>&amp; rue for&thorn; faste in &thorn;e see : wi&thorn; tempest meni on.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at hi se&yogh;e in ano&thorn;er side : an ylle gret ynou&yogh;.</L>
<L N="156">here schip &thorn;urf godes grace : &thorn;iderwardes drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;o hit cam almest &thorn;erto : vpe &thorn;e roche hit gan ride,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hit ne mi&yogh;te no&yogh;t to &thorn;e yle come : ac bileuede biside.</L>
<L>&THORN;is monekes wende<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> wode</NOTE> vp to &thorn;is yle : ac seint brendan no&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;is monekes gonne makie here mete : of &thorn;at hi hadde ibro&yogh;t :</L>
<L>hi makede fur &amp; soden hem fisch : in a caudroun faste.</L>
<L>Er &thorn;is fisch were isode [I-nou&yogh;] : somdel hi were agaste :</L>
<L>For &thorn;o &thorn;is fur was &thorn;urf-hot : &thorn;e yle quakede anon</L>
<L N="164">&amp; wi&thorn; gret eir hupte al vp&mdash; : &thorn;is monekes dradde echon,</L>
<L>[&amp; &thorn;e wei toward hor schip : ech after o&thorn;er nom,</L>
<L>God leuest hem &thorn;o&yogh;te he was : &thorn;at sonest &thorn;uder com.]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. in H.</NOTE></L>
<L>hi bihulde hou &thorn;e yle : in &thorn;e see wende faste</L>
<L N="168">&amp; as a quic &thorn;ing hupte vp &amp; doun : &amp; &thorn;at fur fram him caste;</L>
<L>he suam more &thorn;an tuei myle : while &thorn;is fur ilaste.</L>
<L>&THORN;e monekes ise&yogh;e &thorn;e fur wel longe : &amp; were sore agaste :</L>
<L>hi cride &yogh;urne on seint brendan : what &thorn;e wonder were.</L>
<L>"Beo&thorn; stille," qua&thorn; &thorn;is gode man : "for no&yogh;t &yogh;e nabbe<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> habbe&thorn;</NOTE> fere.</L>
<L N="173">&YOGH;e wene&thorn; &thorn;at hit beo an yle : ac &yogh;e &thorn;enche&thorn; amis :</L>
<L>hit is a fisch of &thorn;is grete see : &thorn;e gretteste &thorn;at &thorn;er is.</L>
<L>Iastoni he is icleped : &amp; fonde&thorn; ni&yogh;t &amp; dai<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 2277 folio" N="44"></L>
<L N="176">To pulte his tail in his mou&thorn; : ac for gretnisse he nemai."&mdash;</L>
<L>For&thorn; hi rue in &thorn;e see : euene west wel faste,</L>
<L>&THORN;reo dayes, er hi se&yogh;e lond : hi were somdel a-gaste.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o se&yogh;en hi a wel fair lond : of floures &thorn;ikke ynou&yogh;&mdash;</L>
<L N="180">wel glade hi were &thorn;o hi se&yogh;e : &thorn;at here schip &thorn;ider drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is faire lond hi wende : lengere &thorn;an i<SUP>c</SUP> telle :</L>
<L>So &thorn;at hi fonde in a place : a suy&thorn;e noble welle.</L>
<L N="183">Bi &thorn;e welle stod a treo : brod &amp; round ynou&yogh;;</L>
<L>Foweles white &amp; faire ynou&yogh; : were in euerech<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> so &thorn;icke were in ech</NOTE> bou&yogh;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vne&thorn;e eni leef : hi mi&yogh;te &thorn;eron iseo&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;er was ioye &amp; blisse ynou&yogh; : to lokie on suche o treo.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Brendan for ioye wep : &amp; sat adoun akneo</L>
<L N="188">And bad oure louerd schowi him : what such a cas mi&yogh;te beo.</L>
<L>&THORN;o fle&yogh; &thorn;er vp alute fowel : &thorn;o he gan to fleo,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &amp; toward him gan te</NOTE></L>
<L>As a fi&thorn;ele his wynges furde : &thorn;o he to him-ward gan teo.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;o he gan to fleo</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000273.tif" N="225"></L>
<L>Murie[re] Instrument neuere nas : &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;at</NOTE> his wyngen were!</L>
<L N="192">he bihuld seint brendan : wi&thorn; wel faire chere.</L>
<L>"Ich hote [&thorn;e,]" seide seint brendan : "if &thorn;u ert messager,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;u sigge me what [&thorn;u] ert : &amp; what &yogh;e do&thorn; her."</L>
<L>&THORN;e&yogh; hit &thorn;o&yogh;te a&yogh;e cunde : &thorn;is fowel ansuerede anon :</L>
<L N="196">"We were," he seide "sum-tyme was : angles in heuene echon.</L>
<L>As<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. ac sone so</NOTE> sone as we were ymaked : oure maister was so prout,</L>
<L>Lucefer, for his fairhede : &thorn;at he ful sone out,</L>
<L>&amp; mid him also meni on : as here dede was;</L>
<L N="200">&para; &amp; we fulle also a-doun : ac for no synne hit nas,</L>
<L>for<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. Ac for</NOTE> no&thorn;ing &thorn;at we assentede : to his foule vnri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Bote soulement forto schewe : oure louerdes suete<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> suete louerdes</NOTE> mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Ne we ne beo&thorn; her in pyne non : ac in ioye ynou&yogh; we beo&thorn;,</L>
<L N="204">And somdel oure suete louerdes : mi&yogh;te we seo&thorn;.</L>
<L>&amp; bi &thorn;e vr&thorn;e we fleo&thorn; : &amp; bi &thorn;e lifte also,</L>
<L>As gode angles, &amp; li&thorn;ere ek : ri&yogh;t is for-to do,</L>
<L>&THORN;e gode [for]-to do men god : &thorn;e li&thorn;er li&thorn;ere makie&thorn;.</L>
<L N="208">&para; &amp; sonedai, &thorn;at is dai of rest : such forme we take&thorn; :<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. make&thorn;</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e forme of suche white foweles : as &thorn;u mi&yogh;t iseo,</L>
<L>[&amp;] honure&thorn; god &thorn;at ous makede : her on &thorn;is brode treo.</L>
<L>Tuelf-mon&thorn; hit [is] ipassed nou : &thorn;at &yogh;e gonne out wende,</L>
<L N="212">&amp; alle &thorn;is six &yogh;er &yogh;e schulle fare : er &yogh;e schulle<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> bringe &yogh;oure wille to ende;</L>
<L>For whan &yogh;e habbe&thorn; iwend soue &yogh;er : oure louerd wole &yogh;ou sende<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 2277 folio" N="44b"></L>
<L>A si&yogh;t &thorn;at &yogh;e habbe&thorn; longe iso&yogh;t : anon after &thorn;e soue &yogh;eres ende.</L>
<L>Eche &yogh;er &yogh;e schulle her mid ous : holde ester-feste,</L>
<L N="216">As &yogh;e nou do&thorn;, forte &yogh;e come : to &thorn;e lond of biheste"&mdash;</L>
<L>Nou was hit an ester-day : &thorn;at al &thorn;is was ido.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e fowel nom his leue of hem : &amp; to his felawes wende &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&THORN;e foweles, &thorn;o hit eue<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> time</NOTE> was : bigonne here euesong&mdash;</L>
<L N="220">Muriere song nemi&yogh;te beo : &thorn;e&yogh; god silf were among.</L>
<L>&THORN;e monekes wende to bedde &amp; slepe : &thorn;o soper was ido;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;o hit was tyme of matyns : hi arise &thorn;erto.</L>
<L N="223">&para; &THORN;e foweles sunge ek here matyns : wel ri&yogh;t, &thorn;o hit was tyme,</L>
<L>&amp; of &thorn;e sauter seide &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> uers : &amp; si&thorn;&thorn;e also<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. alto</NOTE> prime,</L>
<L>&amp; vnderne si&thorn;&thorn;e, &amp; middai : &amp; afterwardes non,</L>
<L>&amp; eche tyde songen of &thorn;e dai : as cristene men scholde don.</L>
<L>&THORN;is monekes were in &thorn;e lond : ei&yogh;te wyke also,</L>
<L N="228">Forto al&thorn;e feste of ester : &amp; of witsonedai were ido.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o com atte trinite : &thorn;is gode man to hem &thorn;er</L>
<L>&THORN;at spac wi&thorn; hem in &thorn;e lond of scheep : &amp; ladde aboute er :
<PB REF="00000274.tif" N="226"></L>
<L>he chargede here schip suy&thorn;e wel : mid mete &amp; drinke ynou&yogh;,</L>
<L N="232">&amp; nom his leue wel hendeliche : &amp; a&yogh;eward drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o seint brendan was in his schip : &amp; his bre&thorn;eren also,</L>
<L>&THORN;is fowel, &thorn;at spac wi&thorn; hem er : wel sone com hem to;</L>
<L>he seide, "&yogh;e habbe&thorn; her wi&thorn; ous : &thorn;is he&yogh;e feste ibeo;</L>
<L N="236">Gret trauayl &yogh;ou is to come : er &yogh;e eftsone lond iseo.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e schulle&thorn; after soue mon&thorn;es : iseo a wel fair yle.</L>
<L>&THORN;at abbey is icliped : &thorn;at is hunne meni a myle;</L>
<L>&YOGH;e schulle&thorn; beo mid holie men : &thorn;is myde-wynter &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="240">&YOGH;oure ester &yogh;e schulle holde &thorn;er : as &yogh;e dude to-&yogh;ere :</L>
<L>Vpe &thorn;e grete fisches rugge : &thorn;er &thorn;i monekes were in-fere,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;oure ester [be] mid ous : ri&yogh;t as &yogh;e nou were."</L>
<L>Seint brendan a-godes name : &amp; his bre&thorn;eren echon,</L>
<L N="244">In &thorn;e grete see of occian : for&thorn; wende anon.</L>
<L>&THORN;e wynd hem harlede vp &amp; doun : in peryls meni on.</L>
<L>So weri hi were of here lyue : &thorn;at hi nuste whoder gon.</L>
<L>Four mon&thorn;es hi were<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> wende</NOTE> in &thorn;e see : in &thorn;is grete turment,]<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Here L. goes on again.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="248">&THORN;at huy ne ysei&yogh;en no-&thorn;ing bote &thorn;e se : ant &thorn;e firmament.<MILESTONE N="105" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;o huy ysei&yogh;en<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> seie hi</NOTE> fer fram heom : ane yle ase &thorn;ei it were;</L>
<L>heo criden faste on Ihesu crist : &thorn;at huy mosten a-riuie &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eot after &thorn;at seint Brendan : &thorn;is yle furst y-sei&yogh;,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. sai&yogh;</NOTE></L>
<L N="252">Fourti dawes heo wenden in &thorn;e se : er huy comen &thorn;ere nei&yogh;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te heore lif was heom loz. : &thorn;e Monekes weren a-gaste,</L>
<L>heo criden &yogh;eorne on Ihesu crist : and is help heo beden faste.</L>
<L>A luytel hauene and swy&thorn;e streit : huy founden at&thorn;e laste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vnne&thorn;es heore schip mi&yogh;te &thorn;erinne come : Aunker<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. Annker</NOTE> for-to caste</L>
<L N="257">&THORN;is Monekes wenden a-lond &thorn;o : wel longue heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te er.</L>
<L>huy bi-heolden al-a-boute : murie heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;er.</L>
<L>&THORN;o ysei&yogh;en heo twey faire wellene : &thorn;at on was suy&thorn;e cler,</L>
<L>And sumdel wori and &thorn;icke &thorn;at o&thorn;er was. : &thorn;e Monekes &yogh;eoden ner,</L>
<L N="261">to drinken of &thorn;at faire welle. : seint Brendan it i-sei&yogh;,</L>
<L>And seide, "with-oute leue of o&thorn;ur men : ne come &yogh;e nou&yogh;t &thorn;ere nei&yogh;,</L>
<L>Of olde men &thorn;at here-inne beoz : al &thorn;oru&yogh; godes wille<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> for mid gode wille</NOTE>;</L>
<L>For<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> heo wollez party &thorn;ar-of mid us : and &thorn;are-fore beoz &yogh;eot stille."</L>
<L N="265">A fair old man and swi&thorn;e hor : a-&yogh;ein heom &thorn;ere cam gon;</L>
<L>he wel-comede heom faire i-nov&yogh; : and seint Brendan he custe a-non,</L>
<L>And ladde heom forth with him : bi a wel fair wei
<PB REF="00000275.tif" N="227"></L>
<L N="268">A-boute in many a murie stude : and seth&thorn;e in-to on Abbey.</L>
<L>Seint Brendan bi-heold a-boute : and axede &yogh;wat it were,</L>
<L>And &yogh;wat-manere men weren &thorn;are-inne : and ho &thorn;are<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> woneden &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Stille was &thorn;is olde man : and ne &yogh;af him none Answere.</L>
<L N="272">&THORN;o cam &thorn;ere gon a fair couent : and ane croyz bi-fore heom bere,</L>
<L>With taperes in ey&thorn;ur side&mdash; : Monekes it weren ech-on,</L>
<L>A<SUP>nd</SUP> yreuested faire and in queor-copes : a-&yogh;ein heom huy comen gon,</L>
<L>With procession faire i-nou&yogh;. : &thorn;e Abbod bi-hinde com,</L>
<L N="276">And wel faire custe seint Brendan : and bi &thorn;e hond him nom.</L>
<L>he ladde him and is monekus : in-to a noble halle,</L>
<L>And setten<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> sette</NOTE> heom a-doun alle on a rewe : and wuchs heore fet alle;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e worie welle heore fet he wuchs : &thorn;at huy er i-sei&yogh;e.</L>
<L N="280">In-to &thorn;e freytore he ladde heom &thorn;o : and sette heom wel hei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>I-medlede with heore<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> his</NOTE> owene couent. : and &thorn;o heo weren alle i-sete,</L>
<L>&THORN;are cam on and seruede : and brou&yogh;te heom alle mete :</L>
<L>And ane wel faire &yogh;wite lof : he sette bi-twene to &amp; to,</L>
<L N="284">&YOGH;wite moren, ase it of herbes were : bi-fore heom he sette al-so&mdash;</L>
<L>Swettore mete ne mi&yogh;te non beo : huy ne knewen it nou&yogh;t on;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e clere welle &thorn;at huy er i-sei&yogh;en : &thorn;e Monekes dronke ech-on.</L>
<L>"beoz nou&thorn;e glade," &thorn;e Abbot seide : "and drinkez nou&thorn;e i-nov&yogh;</L>
<L N="288">In charite of &thorn;ulke welle : &thorn;at &yogh;e wolden er with wou&yogh;&mdash;</L>
<L>Betere it is drinke in charite : &yogh;wan it is ov i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;ane &yogh;e it &thorn;eofliche nomen : ase &yogh;e hadden i-&thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;is bred &thorn;at we eteth of : we nuten of &yogh;wan it is :</L>
<L N="292">An straunge man eche daye it bringuth : In-to ovre celere, i-wis,</L>
<L>We nutez nou&yogh;t bote ope godes grace : wanne it is ibrou&yogh;t&mdash;</L>
<L>For ho-so trust to ihesu crist : him ne schal failly nou&yogh;t.<MILESTONE N="105b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>We beoz foure-ant-twenti freres : and &yogh;wane we beoz i-sete,</L>
<L N="296">twelf &yogh;wite Miches<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> suche loues</NOTE> men brynguth us : eche daye to ore mete;</L>
<L>Ate feste of eche hali-daye; and &yogh;wan it sonen-day is,</L>
<L>Foure-and-twenti loues us comieth : so &thorn;at euer<SUP>e</SUP>ch man hath his;</L>
<L>&THORN;at euerech frere of &thorn;at him leuez : witiez to is soper.</L>
<L N="300">I-doublet it worth nou&thorn;e for ov : ase &yogh;e i-seoth wel her :</L>
<L>Al<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> vor al</NOTE> ore couent nis nou&yogh;t here : ake muche<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> muchedel</NOTE> it hath vn-ete.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at ore louerd &thorn;oru&yogh; is grace : sent us alle mete.
<PB REF="00000276.tif" N="228"></L>
<L>Fram seint paterikes Abbeye<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> dai : &amp; seint ailbi also</NOTE> : &thorn;at in yrlonde is al-so,</L>
<L N="304">Four-score &yogh;er we habbez i-beon here : &thorn;at no man ne cam us to;</L>
<L>euere-eft ore louerd &thorn;oru&yogh; is grace : I-fed us hath ech-on.</L>
<L>And &thorn;is weder is euere murie i-nou&yogh; : syknesse here nis non.</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane we schullen ore seruise don : ore louerd sent us li&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="308">Ore taperes ne beoz no-&thorn;e lasse : &thorn;ei huy brenne day and ny&yogh;t."</L>
<L>heo a-risen op and wenden to churche : &thorn;o heo hadden y&yogh;ete :</L>
<L>And twelf o&thorn;ere freres heo i-metten : Inward to &thorn;e mete.</L>
<L>"hov is &thorn;is?" quath seint Brendan : "&yogh;wy neren &thorn;eose nou&yogh;t with us?"</L>
<L N="312">"Leoue fader," quath &thorn;e Abbot : "nede it mot beo &thorn;us;</L>
<L>&THORN;er ne mouwen bote foure-and-twenti Monekes : in ore freitore beon ido,</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane &yogh;e weren &thorn;are-inne with us : &thorn;eos ne mi&yogh;ten nou&yogh;t al-so.</L>
<L N="315">&THORN;e &yogh;wile we singuth euesong : heo schullen sitte and ete,</L>
<L>And heore euesong huy schullen syngue : &yogh;wane heo habbez i-&yogh;et[e]."</L>
<L>Seint brendan bi-heold &thorn;at weued : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at hit was al,</L>
<L>weued and chaliz and Cruettes : &thorn;oru&yogh;-out cler cristal.</L>
<L>Seue taperes weren in &thorn;e queor : for &thorn;are ne weren non mo,</L>
<L N="320">And foure-and-twenti segene : &thorn;at Monekes scholden to&mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;are weren foure-and-twenti Monekes : and euerech hadde his;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Abbodes sege was : a-midde &thorn;e queor, i-wis.</L>
<L>Seint Brendan axede &thorn;e Abbode : "do sei&yogh;e me, leue bro&thorn;ur,</L>
<L N="324">hov holde &yogh;e so silence : &thorn;at neuer on ne spekez with o&thorn;ur?"</L>
<L>"Ore louerd it wot," &thorn;e Abbot seide : "&thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> we habbez here i-beo</L>
<L>Four score &yogh;er in swuche lyue : ase &yogh;e mowen here i-seo,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are nas neuere a-mong us alle : yspeke in none wise</L>
<L N="328">Are &thorn;is tyme non o&thorn;ur word : bote ore louerdes seruise;</L>
<L>Ne we neren neuer-eft in feblesse : ne sike of us nou&yogh;t on."</L>
<L>Seint brendan, &thorn;o he i-heorde &thorn;is : for Ioy&yogh;e he weop a-non.</L>
<L N="331">"Leoue fader," he seide : "mote we bi-leue here?"</L>
<L>"&THORN;ov wost wel," &thorn;e Abbot seide : "&yogh;e ne mowen in none manere.</L>
<L>Ne haueth ore louerd i-schewed ov wel : &yogh;wat &yogh;e schullen do?</L>
<L>Come &thorn;ov schalt to yrlonde i-wis : and &thorn;ine twelf bre&thorn;ren al-so;</L>
<L>And fram &thorn;e to &thorn;e yle of Ankres : &thorn;e &thorn;reotteo&thorn;e schal i-wende,</L>
<L N="336">&THORN;e fourteo&thorn;e al quic to helle : and beon &thorn;are with-outen ende."
<PB REF="00000277.tif" N="229"></L>
<L>&THORN;o cam<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. com</NOTE> &thorn;are-In a fuyri Arewe : at a fenestre a-non,</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;ei heo fram heouene come : and &thorn;e taperes tende ech-on,<MILESTONE N="106" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And flev&yogh; out a-&yogh;ein ase heo cam In : bi &thorn;ulke fenestre &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="340">&THORN;e taperes barnden longue Inov : and no-&thorn;e lasse huy nere.</L>
<L>"Louerd crist," quath seint brendan : "Ich wondri In mi &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>hou&yogh; &thorn;is taperes bernez &thorn;us : and ne waniez nou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>"Ne hast&thorn;ou," quath &thorn;e Abbod : "In &thorn;e olde lawe i-founde</L>
<L N="344">hov Moyses say A &thorn;orn berne : fram &thorn;e toppe to &thorn;e grounde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e More &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;orn barnde : &thorn;e grenore &thorn;e leues were?</L>
<L>Ne wenest&thorn;ou nou&yogh;t &thorn;at ore louerd beo : ase mi&yogh;ti here as &thorn;ere?"&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;eos Monekes weren to-gadere : for-to Midewynter was al i-do,</L>
<L N="348">For-to after twelfte-day : are huy departeden a-to.</L>
<L>Anon to seint hyllaries day : seint Brendan forth i-wende</L>
<L>With is Monekus in &thorn;e se : &thorn;oru&yogh; grace &thorn;at god heom sende.</L>
<L>huy floten op and doun in soruwe I-nov&yogh; : &thorn;e se heom caste hei&yogh;e;</L>
<L N="352">Fram &thorn;ulke tyme forto in leinte : no lond huy ne i-sei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at a-boute palme-sonenday : heo bi-heolden a-boute faste :</L>
<L>heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te heo i-sei&yogh;en swi&thorn;e fer : ase a cloude ate laste.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Monekes hadden wonder &thorn;ar-of : &yogh;wat &thorn;e cloude were.</L>
<L N="356">"beoth stille," seide seint brendan : "&yogh;e habbez i-beon &thorn;ere :</L>
<L>&THORN;are is ore procuratour : &thorn;at muche guod us hath i-do</L>
<L>In [&thorn;e] foulene parays : and In &thorn;e lond of schep al-so."</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heore schip ate laste : to &thorn;at yle drou&yogh;&mdash;</L>
<L N="360">A-schere&thorn;ores-day huy comen &thorn;udere : in gret trauaile inou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;is procuratour heom cam a&yogh;ein : and welcomede heom a-non,</L>
<L>Ant custe seint brendanes fet : and &thorn;e Monekes echon;</L>
<L>And sette heom seth&thorn;e to &thorn;e soper : for &thorn;e day it wolde so,</L>
<L N="364">And seth&thorn;e he wuchs hore fet alle : &thorn;e maunde for-to do.</L>
<L>huy heolden &thorn;are heore maunde&mdash; : and &thorn;are heo gounnen bi-leue</L>
<L>A-gode friday al &thorn;e longue day : for-to an ester eue.</L>
<L>An ester eue heore procuratour : bad heom heore schip take</L>
<L N="368">And heore resurrection : opon &thorn;e fisches rugge make,</L>
<L>And aftur heore resurrection : he bad heom euene teo</L>
<L>to &thorn;e foulene parays : ase heo hadden er i-beo.</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie men wenden forth : and ore louerdes grace nome,</L>
<L N="372">&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> so &thorn;at</NOTE> to &thorn;is grete fischse : &thorn;ulke daye huy come,
<PB REF="00000278.tif" N="230"></L>
<L>&THORN;at houede ase it were a lond. : heore caudron heo founden &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Ase heo it bi-leften opon is rugge : in &thorn;at o&thorn;ere &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>Louerd crist, &thorn;at swch a best : scholde houi so stille</L>
<L N="376">And soffri men op-on him gon : and don al heore wille!</L>
<L>&THORN;is Monekes op-on &thorn;e fisches rugge : bi-leften al &thorn;e ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And songuen matynes and euesong : and seth&thorn;e, &thorn;o it was li&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Op-on is rugge huy sounguen : heore massene echon;<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. echone</NOTE></L>
<L>And euere<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. eueuere</NOTE> houede &thorn;is muche fichs : stille so eny ston.</L>
<L N="381">&THORN;o heore resurrection was : with gret honour i-do</L>
<L>And &thorn;is Monekus hadden i-songue : heore Massene al-so,</L>
<L>A-boute onderne of &thorn;e daye : to &thorn;e schipe huy heom nome,<MILESTONE N="106b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="384">And to &thorn;e foulene parays : &thorn;at ilke day huy come.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is foules i-sei&yogh;en heom come : huy gonne singue ech-one</L>
<L>A&yogh;enest heom with gret melodie : ase it were for &thorn;enone.</L>
<L>&THORN;e foul &thorn;at spac with [heom] er : a-&yogh;ein hem<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. him</NOTE> sone he drou&yogh;&mdash;</L>
<L N="388">&thorn;e drem of is winguene murie was&mdash; : he welcomede heom faire ynou&yogh;.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e Au&yogh;ten," he seide, "ore louerd crist : &thorn;onky mid &thorn;e beste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at porueiez ou &thorn;eos four studes : to habben on ouwer reste :</L>
<L>With ouwer guode procratour : ouwer maunde for-to do,</L>
<L N="392">And seth&thorn;e ouwer resurrection : ope &thorn;e fisches rugge al-so,</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e with us &thorn;is ei&yogh;te wokes : a-non to witsonen-day,</L>
<L>And fram Mide-winter to candele-masse : In &thorn;e yle of Abbey.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. Aylbey</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e se [of] Occean : in gret peril &yogh;e schullen i-wende</L>
<L N="396">In trauail al &thorn;at o&thorn;ur tyme : for-to &thorn;e seuen &yogh;eres ende :</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e &thorn;at lond of bi-heste : god wole &thorn;at &yogh;e i-seon,</L>
<L>And fourti [dawes] seth&thorn;e &thorn;ar-inne : In ioy&yogh;e &yogh;e schullen beon.</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e contreye &thorn;at &yogh;e beoz of : seth&thorn;e &yogh;e schullen i-wende</L>
<L N="400">With-oute trauail al aisieliche : and &thorn;are ower lif ende."</L>
<L>&THORN;is holi men bi-lefden &thorn;are : for-to &thorn;e trinite :</L>
<L>heore procratour to hem cam : and<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at</NOTE> was euere in plente,</L>
<L>he brou&yogh;te heom mete and drinke i-nou&yogh; : ase he hadde er i-do,</L>
<L N="404">And chargede heore schip &thorn;ere-with : and let heom wenden so.</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie men wenden forth : ase god heom wolde sende&mdash;</L>
<L>For godes grace was with heom : &thorn;e betere huy mi&yogh;ten wenden.&mdash;</L>
<L>Al-so huy wenden In a tyme : In strong tempeste j-nou&yogh;,<NOTE PLACE="marg2">Pissis mala.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000279.tif" N="231"></L>
<L N="408">A gret fisch huy sei&yogh;en and grislich : after &thorn;e schipe he drou&yogh;;</L>
<L>brenninde fom out of is mouth : after heom he caste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at water was herre &thorn;ane heore schip : bi-fore heom at eche blaste;</L>
<L N="411">he cam wolchi after ase an hous : a<SUP>n</SUP>d porsiwede heom so faste;</L>
<L>So<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> so faste</NOTE> he schef with is breostene : &thorn;e Monekes weren a-gaste,</L>
<L>And criden &yogh;eorne on seint brendan : and on ore louerd al-so.</L>
<L>After heore schip so swy&thorn;e he schef : &thorn;at he cam al-mest &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L>And &thorn;o he heom hadde al-mest ouer-take : [&amp;] huy ne tolden nou&yogh;t of hore liue,</L>
<L N="416">An o&thorn;ur fisch out of &thorn;e west : &thorn;are cam swymme bliue,</L>
<L>he gan i-mete &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere fisch : and smot to him faste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he for-clef is foule bouk : in &thorn;re partyes at&thorn;e laste;</L>
<L>&THORN;at ilke<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &amp; &thorn;ane</NOTE> wey &thorn;at he cam er : wel euene a-&yogh;ein he drou&yogh;.</L>
<L N="420">&THORN;is monekes &thorn;onkeden iesu crist : and weren [gladde]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">added later; <I>al.</I> ioyful</NOTE> ynou&yogh;.&mdash;</L>
<L>Longue<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> So longe</NOTE> wenden &thorn;is gode men : in &thorn;e se forth so,</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy weren of-hongred sore : and heore mete was al i-do.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Auis paradisi.</NOTE>&THORN;o cam &thorn;are fleo a luytel foul : and brou&yogh;te a gret bou&yogh;</L>
<L>Fol of grapus swy&thorn;e rede : and euene to heom he drou&yogh;.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">A v. om.: &thorn;is grapes he tok s. brendan : &thorn;is gode man som|del lou&yogh;.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;are-bi heo liueden fourtene ni&yogh;t : and hadden mete i-nou&yogh;.</L>
<L N="426">&THORN;o &thorn;is grapes weren i-don alle : of-hongrede huy weren sore :</L>
<L>bi &thorn;one side huy i-sei&yogh;en an yle : and mete &thorn;ar-inne more.</L>
<L>&THORN;e yle was ful of faire treon : and so ful was euerech bou&yogh;<MILESTONE N="107" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of swuche grapes ase huy hadden er : &thorn;at on &thorn;e grounde it drou&yogh;.</L>
<L N="430">Seint brendan wende op of &thorn;is schip : &thorn;e grapes he nam faste</L>
<L>And bar into &thorn;e schipe, to libbe &thorn;er-bi : &thorn;at fourti dawes it<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> i-laste</NOTE> laste.&mdash;</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;are cam a gryp fleoinde : after heom in &thorn;e se</L>
<L N="433">And a-saillede heom in heore schip : and fondede heom to sle.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Monekes criden deolfolliche : and tolden luyte of heore lyue.</L>
<L>&THORN;o isei&yogh;en huy come &thorn;at luytel foul : toward hem wel bliue</L>
<L>&THORN;at heom<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> in foulene parays : so ofte heom hadde irad.</L>
<L N="437">&THORN;o seint brendan i-sai&yogh; him<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. heom</NOTE> come : he nas nou&yogh;t a luytel glad.</L>
<L>&THORN;is luytel [foul]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">added later.</NOTE> smot to &thorn;is gryp : and nam is dunt so hei&yogh;e</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e furste dunte : he smot out ey&thorn;ur ey&yogh;en;</L>
<L N="440">Sone he a-slou&yogh; &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere best : &thorn;at he fel doun in-to &thorn;e se&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ing &thorn;at god wole habbe i-wust : ne schal it no wi&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. man, <I>al.</I> &thorn;ing</NOTE> sle.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie Men wenden in &thorn;e se : a-boute here and &thorn;ere :
<PB REF="00000280.tif" N="232"></L>
<L>In on of &thorn;e four studes : &thorn;e hey&yogh;e festes huy were.</L>
<L N="444">In a seint peteres day : gret feste huy maden with heore tounge</L>
<L>And swi&thorn;e murie of seint peter : In &thorn;e se huy sounge.</L>
<L>In a stude of &thorn;e se : so cler &thorn;e se huy founde,</L>
<L>A-boute heo i-sei&yogh;en in eche side : clerliche to &thorn;e grounde :</L>
<L>heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;e ground was on eche half<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> iheled was</NOTE> : with fisch al on hepe.</L>
<L N="449">&THORN;is Monekes beden seint brendan : &thorn;at he softe speke,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he ne a-wei&yogh;te nou&yogh;t &thorn;e fisches : laste huy heore schip breke.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e fisches lei&yogh;en stille : ase &thorn;ei heo weren a-slepe.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">This v. follows after 448 in the other MSS.</NOTE></L>
<L N="452">"beo &yogh;e a-ferde?" quath seint brendan : "&yogh;warof beo &yogh;e a-drad?</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e maisteres rugge of alle fisches : &yogh;e habbez i-beon wel glad</L>
<L>And fuyr i-maked op-on is rugge : and doth fram &yogh;ere to &yogh;ere!"</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie Man &thorn;e luddere song : for &thorn;es ones<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;en one</NOTE> ase &thorn;ei it were.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fisches sturten op with &thorn;is song : ase &thorn;ei huy a-woken a-slepe,</L>
<L N="457">And comen a-boute &thorn;is monekes : alle to one hepe;</L>
<L>So &thorn;icke huy floten bi eche side : no water man ne i-sei&yogh;,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. sa&dotb;<SUP>e</SUP>i&yogh;</NOTE></L>
<L>And bi-setten &thorn;at schip al-a-boute : Ake no water<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> ac hi</NOTE> ne cam &thorn;are nei&yogh;.</L>
<L N="460">So &thorn;icke huy weren a-boute &thorn;is schip : And euere syweden it so,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;wyle brendan is Masse song : for-to heo was al ido;</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;e Masse was al<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. all</NOTE> ido : ech fisch wende in is ende&mdash;</L>
<L>Muche &yogh;wounder man may i-seo : &thorn;at wide wole i-wende.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e wynd was bo&thorn;e strong and stif : and drof heore schip so faste;</L>
<L>Al-so feor ase heo mi&yogh;ten seue-ny&yogh;t wenden : &thorn;at clere water i-laste,</L>
<L N="466">&thorn;at heo isei&yogh;en in &thorn;e se : ase clerliche ase huy mi&yogh;ten a-londe&mdash;</L>
<L>gret wonder hadden &thorn;is gode Men : and &thorn;onkeden godes sonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;o cam sone a sou&thorn;erne wynd : and north&thorn;e-ward drof heom faste;</L>
<L N="469">Ri&yogh;t euene with heom he was : and ei&yogh;te dawes he laste.</L>
<L>&THORN;o i-sei&yogh;en huy feor in &thorn;e north : a lond deork i-nou&yogh;,</L>
<L>Smoke stynkinde foule<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> smokie as it smythes were</NOTE> : and &thorn;uder-ward heore schip drou&yogh;.</L>
<L N="472">&THORN;o i-heorden heo gret blowynge : of manie beolies &thorn;ere</L>
<L>And gret betynge and noyse i-nou&yogh; : &thorn;ondre ase &thorn;ei it were.<MILESTONE N="107b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;o was brendan sori j-nou&yogh; : and blessede him wel faste.</L>
<L>&THORN;o cam &thorn;are out a lu&thorn;er wy&yogh;t : ful Atelich ate laste,</L>
<L N="476">&THORN;oru-out swart and brenninde&mdash; : ope heom is ei&yogh;ene he caste</L>
<L>And tornede him anon a-&yogh;en&mdash; : &thorn;is Monekes weren a-gaste.
<PB REF="00000281.tif" N="233"></L>
<L>&THORN;at lu&thorn;ere wi&yogh;t &yogh;af a cri : &thorn;at Men mi&yogh;ten i-heore him wide.</L>
<L N="479">&THORN;o come &thorn;are out swuch<SUP>e</SUP> schrewes mo : &thorn;icke on eche side,</L>
<L>With tongen<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. tongene</NOTE> and with hameres : brenninde mani on;</L>
<L>Op-on &thorn;e watere heo ornen faste<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> To &thorn;e brimme h. o. of &thorn;e se</NOTE> : After &thorn;at schip ech-on.</L>
<L>&thorn;o huy ne mi&yogh;ten &thorn;are-nei&yogh; come : huy gounnen to &yogh;eolle faste,</L>
<L N="483">heore hameres al brenninde : after &thorn;is men huy casten,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men ne mi&yogh;ten no-&thorn;ing bote fuyr : no&thorn;er iseo ne huyre;<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. he&dotb;<SUP>u</SUP>o&dotb;<SUP>y</SUP>re</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e se was brenninde al-a-brod : ase &thorn;ei heo were a-fuyre.</L>
<L>euer-ech caste is owel op o&thorn;ur : and some huy &thorn;rewen an hei&yogh;,</L>
<L N="487">huy &thorn;rewen alle a-boute &thorn;at schip : ake non ne cam &thorn;are-nei&yogh;.</L>
<L>Ate laste heo torneden alle a&yogh;ein : &thorn;o huy ne spedden nou&yogh;t &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at lond &thorn;ou&yogh;te of heom : a-fuyre ase &thorn;ei it were,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e se &thorn;are a-boute : barnde and smokede faste&mdash;</L>
<L N="491">Strong was &thorn;e stunch and &thorn;e smoke : and longe, i-wis, it laste.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e smoke<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> monekes</NOTE> was sum-del feor : &thorn;at heo ne isei&yogh;en non more,</L>
<L>&YOGH;eot heo i-heorden heore &yogh;eollinge : &thorn;e &thorn;eoues weopen sore.</L>
<L N="494">"hou &thorn;inchez ou," quath brendan : "was &thorn;is a murie pas?</L>
<L>We nellez non-more come &thorn;are-nei&yogh;&mdash; : &thorn;at on ende of helle it was,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e feondes hopeden suy&thorn;e wel : habbe i-haued a wel god cas;</L>
<L N="497">Ake i-hered beo swete ihesu crist : huy casten Aumbes as!"&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e sou&thorn;erne wind laste &yogh;uyt : and &yogh;uyt drof heom forth.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at huy i-sei&yogh;en ane hul : wel feor in &thorn;e north,</L>
<L N="500">glowinde and brenninde smoke : gret stunch so was &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>&THORN;e lei&yogh;e stod op an hei&yogh; : ase &thorn;ei it a wal were;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;are was muche in &thorn;at o&thorn;ur stude : &thorn;are was &yogh;eot wel more.</L>
<L>On of &thorn;e monekes &thorn;o bi-gan : to weope and &yogh;eollen sore :</L>
<L N="504">For is tyme was &thorn;o i-come : he ne mi&yogh;te no leng bi-leue.</L>
<L>he hupte out of &thorn;at schip : and amidde &thorn;e se he gan weue</L>
<L>And orn faste op-on &thorn;e watere : to-ward &thorn;at ilke fuyre.</L>
<L>he cride &yogh;eorne and &yogh;al deolfulliche : &thorn;at gret deol it was to huyre;</L>
<L N="508">"Alas," he seide, "mi wrechche lijf! : for nou i seo min ende.</L>
<L>In ioye ich habbe with ou i-beo : ake i-ne may nou&yogh;t a&yogh;en wende.</L>
<L>A-corsed beo &thorn;at me bar : and &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at ich was i-bore,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e fader &thorn;at me bi-&yogh;at! : for ich am nou&thorn;e for-lore."</L>
<L N="512">&THORN;e feondes comen him a-&yogh;ein : and nomen &thorn;at wrechche faste</L>
<L>And defouleden him stronge Inou&yogh; : and a-midde &thorn;e fuyre him caste.
<PB REF="00000282.tif" N="234"></L>
<L>&THORN;o fond he soth &thorn;at seint brendan : seide, &thorn;o he out wende :</L>
<L>him failede grace, hou-so it was : his sunnes for-to a-mende.&mdash;</L>
<L N="516">So faste barnde &thorn;e Montayne : &thorn;at no-&thorn;ing huy ne i-sei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;uyt heo weren feor &thorn;are-fram : no-&thorn;ing bote ley&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;o tornede &thorn;e wynd in-to &thorn;e North : and drof heom south-ward faste,<MILESTONE N="108" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In &thorn;ulke side stronge Inou&yogh; : &thorn;at seuen-Ni&yogh;t fulle he laste.</L>
<L N="520">So longe huy wenden euene south : &thorn;at huy i-sei&yogh;en at &thorn;en ende<NOTE PLACE="marg2">Judas.</NOTE></L>
<L>One harde roche In &thorn;e se : and &thorn;e se &thorn;are-ouer wende;</L>
<L>&THORN;are-ouer &thorn;e se caste i-lome : and ofte he was bar.</L>
<L>Ant &thorn;o heo comen &thorn;e roche nei&yogh; : of a gost heo weren i-war :</L>
<L N="524">heo i-sei&yogh;e on-ouewarde &thorn;e roche sitte : &yogh;wane &thorn;e se with-drou&yogh;,</L>
<L>A wrechche gost, naked and bar : in stronge meseise j-nou&yogh;;</L>
<L>A-boue him was a cloth i-tild<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> teid</NOTE> : with tweie tonguene faste,</L>
<L>to is chin tilde &thorn;e neo&thorn;er ende&mdash; : &thorn;e wynd it wide caste,</L>
<L N="528">&THORN;at euere &yogh;wane &thorn;at water him with-drou&yogh; : &thorn;at cloth, &thorn;at heng hei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>beot him,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> ase &thorn;e wynd him blev&yogh; : &thorn;at wrechche gost<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> in &thorn;en ei&yogh;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;e wawes of &thorn;e se beoten also : bi-fore and bi-hynde&mdash;</L>
<L>A &yogh;eomerore gost &thorn;ane he was : ne mi&yogh;te no man finde.</L>
<L N="532">Seint Brendan him bad a-godes name : telle &yogh;wat he were</L>
<L>And &yogh;wat he hadde ore louerd mis-don : and &yogh;wi he sete &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>"Ich am," he seide, "a deolful gost : ich hote wrechche Iudas,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ore louerd for panewes solde : and on eor&thorn;e with him was.</L>
<L N="536">&THORN;is nis nou&yogh;t mi ri&yogh;te stude : ake ore louerd doth me grace</L>
<L>to habben mi parays : here in &thorn;is place,</L>
<L>For no guodnesse &thorn;at ich dude : bote ore louerdes ore.</L>
<L>I-ne habbe nou&yogh;t so muche pine : &thorn;at ich nere wur&thorn;e more.</L>
<L N="540">For in &thorn;e brennynde hulle : &thorn;at ech of eov i-sai&yogh;,</L>
<L>Mi ri&yogh;te is to brennen Inne : bo&thorn;e ny&yogh;t and day&yogh;;</L>
<L>&THORN;are ich was &thorn;is &yogh;eondere dai&yogh; : &thorn;o ower bro&thorn;er &thorn;udere cam</L>
<L>And was into pine i-lad : and &thorn;are hadde is dom.</L>
<L N="544">&THORN;are-fore helle was so glad<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. gled</NOTE> : and makede so grete lei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at he was &thorn;udere i-come : and so nei&yogh; him<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at &yogh;e so ver</NOTE> i-sei&yogh;e&mdash;</L>
<L>So huy doz &yogh;wane ani soule : is formest &thorn;udere i-come.</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; godes hei&yogh;e milce : &thorn;are-fram ich am i-nome :</L>
<L N="548">For here ich am euer-ech sonenday : and fram saterday&yogh;es eue
<PB REF="00000283.tif" N="235"></L>
<L>For-to euen-song tyme &thorn;ane sonenday : here i schal bi-leue;</L>
<L>Ant at Midewinter al-so : for-to twelfte-dai beo ido,</L>
<L>Ant fram &thorn;e bi-guynninge of estur : &thorn;at &yogh;wit-sonenday come, al-so,</L>
<L N="552">Ant al-so at ore lauedi festes&mdash; : so ful of milce heo is;</L>
<L>Ake alle o&thorn;ure tymene : In helle ich am, i-wis,</L>
<L>With pilatus. ant with heoroudus : and al-so with<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Anne and</NOTE> cayphas&mdash;</L>
<L>A-corsed beo &thorn;e tyme : &thorn;at ich i-boren was!</L>
<L N="556">Ich bidde &thorn;e for &thorn;e loue of god : fonde on alle wise</L>
<L>For-to bi-leuen<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at ich bileue</NOTE> here al &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> ni&yogh;t</NOTE> : &thorn;at &thorn;e sonne a-rise,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &yogh;e wyten me fram &thorn;e feondes : &thorn;at sone comieth aftur me."</L>
<L>Seint Brendan seide, "&thorn;oru&yogh; godes grace : we schullen schilde &thorn;e.</L>
<L>tel me nou&thorn;e &yogh;wat is &thorn;at cloth : &thorn;at so hei&yogh;e hanguth her<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. here</NOTE>."</L>
<L N="561">"&THORN;o ich was on eor&thorn;e : and godes panewes ber,</L>
<L>&THORN;is cloth ich &yogh;af a musel : and min owene it nas nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For it was with ore louerdes panes : ant mine felawes i-bou&yogh;t.<MILESTONE N="108b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="564">Ant for ich it &yogh;af for godes loue : nou&thorn;e it is me bi-fore&mdash;</L>
<L>So luyte ne schal man for him do : &thorn;at schulle beo i-lore.</L>
<L>For it was of o&thorn;ur mannes : ase ich me under-stod,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei it hangy bi-fore me : it doth me more harm &thorn;ane guod :</L>
<L N="568">In mine ei&yogh;ene it bat sore : ant doth hem harm i-nou&yogh;."&mdash;</L>
<L>Man mai i-seo &yogh;wuch it is : to &yogh;yuen o&thorn;ur mannes &thorn;ing with wou&yogh;;</L>
<L>As wollez manie of &thorn;is riche men : with onri&yogh;te al day take</L>
<L>Of pouere men here ant &thorn;er : and almesse &thorn;ar-of make.</L>
<L N="572">&THORN;at heo doth for godes loue : ne schal nou&yogh;t beo for-&yogh;ite,</L>
<L>Ake to pine it heom turne schal : ant &thorn;at huy schullen i-wite!&mdash;</L>
<L>"&THORN;e tonguene al-so," quath Iudas : "&thorn;at &yogh;e so hei&yogh;e i-seoth,</L>
<L>tweye preostes ich &yogh;af on eor&thorn;e : and &thorn;are-fore here heo beoth&mdash;</L>
<L N="576">For man schal clanliche ech &thorn;ing finde : &thorn;at he doth for is loue.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ston &thorn;at ich op-on sitte : and makez me sitte a-boue,</L>
<L>In one wei&yogh;e ich hyne fond : &thorn;are non neode nas no ston :</L>
<L>In a fenni dich ich it caste : &thorn;at men mi&yogh;ten &thorn;are-ouer gon.</L>
<L N="580">Fewe goddedes ich haue i-don : of &yogh;wan ich nou&thorn;e may telle;</L>
<L>Nis non so luyte &thorn;at man ne may fynde : in heuene o&thorn;ur in helle."</L>
<L>&THORN;o it was .eue. &thorn;e sonenday : &thorn;e feondes comen blaste,</L>
<L>For-to leden to helle &thorn;at sori gost&mdash; : huy weopen ant &yogh;ollen faste.
<PB REF="00000284.tif" N="236"></L>
<L N="584">"Wend heonne," heo seiden, "&thorn;ou gode<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> godes</NOTE> man : &thorn;ou nast nou&yogh;t here to done;</L>
<L>Lat us habbe ore felawe : ant to helle leden him sone :</L>
<L>For we ne dorren ore mayster i-seo : are we him<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. him him</NOTE> habben i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wend fram him, for it is tyme : and ne lete us nou&yogh;t!"</L>
<L N="588">"Ich ne lette ov nou&yogh;t," quath seint brendan : "to don ouwer mester,</L>
<L>Ake doth ore louerd iesu crist : &thorn;at is of more pouwer."</L>
<L>"hou darst &thorn;ou," &thorn;e feon[des] seide : "bi-fore him nemme is name?</L>
<L>Ne bi-trayde he him and solde him al-so : to de&thorn;e with grete schame?"</L>
<L N="592">Seint Brendan seide, "in his name : ich hote ov, ase ich may,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e ne derien him to-ny&yogh;t : are to-morewe &thorn;at hit beo day."</L>
<L>Reuliche &thorn;e feondes &yogh;ollen &thorn;o : ant hamward gonne fleo.</L>
<L>Iudas &thorn;onkede reufolliche : &thorn;at it was deol to seo.</L>
<L N="596">A-morewe, a-non so &thorn;at it was day : &thorn;e feondes comen blaste.</L>
<L>Grysliche heo &yogh;ollen ant weopen : ant gonnen to chide faste.</L>
<L>"A-wey," huy seiden, "gode man! : a-corsed beo &thorn;e stounde</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou come here us so nei&yogh; : and &thorn;at we &thorn;e here founde :</L>
<L N="600">Ore Maister us haueth i-pyned : bitterliche al &thorn;is ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>Ant swy&thorn;e strongue, for we ne brou&yogh;ten : with us &thorn;is sorie wi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Ake we wollez &thorn;eos six dawes : doubli al is wo</L>
<L N="603">And so we wollez a-wreken us : for on him-sulf it schal go!"</L>
<L>&THORN;at wrechche gost quakede &thorn;o : &thorn;at reu&thorn;e it was to seo o&thorn;ur telle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fendes nomen &thorn;o &thorn;is gost : ant ladden in-to helle;</L>
<L>Ant seint Brendan hem for-bed : In ore louerdes name</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo ne scholden for &thorn;at ny&yogh;t : don him &thorn;e more schame.&mdash;</L>
<L N="608">Seint Brendan and is Monekus : In &thorn;e se forth wende<MILESTONE N="109" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;re dawes euene south : ase ore louerd hem grace<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> sende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e feor&thorn;e dai heo i-sei&yogh;en ane yle : albi sou&thorn;e an hei&yogh;.</L>
<L>Seint Brendan si&yogh;te sore : &thorn;o he &thorn;at [yle] i-sei&yogh;.</L>
<L N="612">"Powel &thorn;e heremite : is in &thorn;e yle &thorn;at ich i-seo,</L>
<L>here he haueth with-oute mete : fourti &yogh;er i-beo."</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo comen to &thorn;is yle : heo wenden in ech-on.</L>
<L>&THORN;is heremite, &thorn;at was so old man : a-&yogh;ein hem cam a-non.</L>
<L N="616">his her tilde doun to is fet : of berde and of heued,</L>
<L>and helede is bodi al-a-boute&mdash; : ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t &thorn;are nas bar bi-leued;
<PB REF="00000285.tif" N="237"></L>
<L>None o&thorn;ur clo&thorn;es nadde he on : is limes weren al hore.</L>
<L>Brendan stod and bi-heold : and weop swi&thorn;e sore,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">A v. om.: Alas, he sede, ichabbe so &yogh;are: in stude of monek ibe,</NOTE></L>
<L>"And nou&thorn;e In liue of Aungele : ane man ich i-seo."</L>
<L N="621">"beo stille," quath &thorn;e hermite : "for god doth wel bi &thorn;e;</L>
<L>For he schewez &thorn;e more &thorn;ane ani o&thorn;ur : of is priuete.</L>
<L>For a Monek liuez muche : bi swunche of mannes<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> is owe</NOTE> honde,</L>
<L N="624">Ant &thorn;ou liuest bi godes grace : ant &thorn;oru&yogh; is owene sonde.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e Abbeye of seint paterich : Monek ich was, i-wis</L>
<L>And of is churche a wardein : &thorn;are is purgatorie is.</L>
<L>A day &thorn;are cam a man to me : ich eschte him &yogh;wat he were.</L>
<L N="628">he seide, 'ich am &thorn;in Abbot : ne haue of me no fere.'</L>
<L>'Non o&thorn;ur man &thorn;ane seint paterik : min Abbot nis,' ich sede.</L>
<L>'Ich it am,' quath he a-&yogh;ein : 'ne haue of me no drede.</L>
<L>to-morewe,' he seide, '&yogh;wane it is day : to &thorn;e se &thorn;ou most i-wende :</L>
<L N="632">Al-&yogh;are &thorn;ou schalt finde a schip : &thorn;at god &thorn;e wole sende;</L>
<L>Ant do &thorn;e forth in &thorn;e se : in &thorn;ine schipe wide :</L>
<L>hit wole &thorn;e lede to &thorn;e stude : &thorn;are &thorn;ou schalt a-bide.'</L>
<L>Sone morewe ich oup a-ros : to don is holie bone :</L>
<L N="636">And &thorn;o ich cam to &thorn;e se : &thorn;at schip ich fond wel sone.</L>
<L>Mid me ich bad<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. let</NOTE> &thorn;at schip i-wor&thorn;e : wel euene forth it wende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e seuen&thorn;e dai to &thorn;is yle : ore louerd me hydere sende.</L>
<L>&THORN;o ich was out of &thorn;at schip : &thorn;ane wei a-non ich<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> a&yogh;en it</NOTE> nam</L>
<L N="640">Ri&yogh;t euene &thorn;oru&yogh; godes grace : so &thorn;at ich<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> ri&yogh;t as it</NOTE> hidere cam.</L>
<L>Elinge ich &yogh;eode here al one : confort nad-ich non :</L>
<L>So &thorn;at on is hindore fet : An .Otur. &thorn;are cam gon,</L>
<L>Bi-twene is for&thorn;ere fet he brou&yogh;te : a fuyr-Ire ant a ston,</L>
<L N="644">&THORN;are-with to smite me fuyr : and fisch he brou&yogh;te seth&thorn;e guod won.</L>
<L>&THORN;is [otur] wende sone a-&yogh;ein. : ich makede me fuyr faste</L>
<L>Ant seth me fisch a-godes name&mdash; : &thorn;re dayes it i-laste.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at euere &thorn;ene &thorn;ridde day : &thorn;is .Otur. to me drou&yogh;</L>
<L N="648">And brou&yogh;te me mete, &thorn;at ich hadde : &thorn;re dawes &thorn;ar-on i-nou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Watur of &thorn;is harde stone : &thorn;oru&yogh; ore louerdes sonde</L>
<L>&THORN;are sprong out of eche daye<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> ech sonedai</NOTE> : to drinke and wasche min honde.</L>
<L>&THORN;is welle bi-gan furst hire to schewen : &thorn;at &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t i-seo,</L>
<L>here<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;o</NOTE> ich hadde<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. habbe</NOTE> &thorn;ritti winter : In swuche liue i-beo;<NOTE PLACE="marg1">both vv. are transp. in other MS.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000286.tif" N="238"></L>
<L>bi &thorn;is welle ich habbe I-leoued : fourti &yogh;er and on,</L>
<L>And fifti &yogh;er ich was old : are ich gan hidere gon;<MILESTONE N="109b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So &thorn;at of an hondred &yogh;er : and twenti &yogh;er &thorn;are-to</L>
<L N="656">Ich am nou&thorn;e bi &thorn;is time&mdash; : ore louerd is wille bi me do.</L>
<L>And mi deth ich a-bide here : &yogh;wane god it wole sende,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wanne mi louerd wole &thorn;at ich come to him : and of &thorn;is world i-wende.</L>
<L>Ake nim with &thorn;e of &thorn;is watur : &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast neode to,</L>
<L N="660">And wiend &thorn;e forth in &thorn;e se : for &thorn;i wei nis nou&yogh;t al i-do.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou schalt &yogh;eot in &thorn;e se : fourti dawes fare,</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;ine Ester holde : ase &thorn;ou hast i-don are,</L>
<L>And fram &thorn;anne &thorn;ou schalt wiende forth : to &thorn;e londe of bi-heste</L>
<L N="664">And &thorn;are &thorn;ou schalt fourti dawes : bi-leuen at&thorn;e leste,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;in owene londe a&yogh;ein : &thorn;ou schalt wiende so."</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode men with deol i-nou&yogh; : &thorn;us de-parteden a-two.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie men wenden hem forth : in tempeste<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> in &thorn;e se</NOTE> wel faste,</L>
<L N="668">Fourti dawes euene south : &thorn;e &yogh;wile &thorn;at leinte i-laste.</L>
<L>to heore guode procratour : an ester eue huy come.</L>
<L>With heom he made ioie i-nou&yogh; : ase he dude er i-lome.</L>
<L>he ladde heom to &thorn;is grete fisch. : &thorn;udere huy comen an eue;</L>
<L N="672">&THORN;e Ester ni&yogh;t for-to a-moruwe : &thorn;are huy gounne bi-leue;</L>
<L>&THORN;are huy songuen heore matynes : and heore masse al-so.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fisch bi-gan to meouen him : &thorn;o &thorn;e masse was al i-do,</L>
<L>And bar &thorn;is Monekes forth with him : And swam swi&thorn;e faste</L>
<L N="676">In &thorn;e se wel stuyrneliche&mdash; : &thorn;e monekes weren a-gaste.</L>
<L>A wonder &thorn;ing it was to seo : ho-so it hadde i-sei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>A so gret best a-boute wiende : ase it were a gret contreie!</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t to foulene parais : &thorn;is monekes he ladde ech-on,</L>
<L N="680">And sette heom up hole and sounde : and wende a-&yogh;ein a-non.</L>
<L>&THORN;is monekes, &thorn;o huy &thorn;udere comen : wel glade and bli&thorn;e huy were.</L>
<L>For-to aftur &thorn;e trinite : huy bi-lefden &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>For heore guode procuratour : &thorn;ulke tyme brou&yogh;te heom mete and drink i-nou&yogh;,</L>
<L N="684">Ase he hadde er ido&mdash; : into heore schip he it drou&yogh;,</L>
<L>And al-so he wende forth with heom : &yogh;wodere-so god heom sende.</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t euene towar<SUP>d</SUP> &thorn;e est : fourti dayes huy wende.
<PB REF="00000287.tif" N="239"></L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e fourti dai&yogh;es weren a-gon : hit gan to hauli faste;</L>
<L N="688">A wel deork mijst &thorn;are com al-so : &thorn;at swi&thorn;e longue i-laste.</L>
<L>"beoth glade," seide &thorn;is procuratour : "and makiez grete feste,</L>
<L>For ichot wel &thorn;at &yogh;e beoth : in<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> nei</NOTE> &thorn;e londe of bi-heste."</L>
<L>&THORN;o huy comen out of &thorn;is Mijst : and mi&yogh;ten a-boute i-seo,</L>
<L N="692">In<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> vnder</NOTE> &thorn;e faireste lond huy weren : &thorn;at euere mi&yogh;te beo.</L>
<L>So cler and so li&yogh;t it was : &thorn;at Ioye &thorn;are was I-nou&yogh;;</L>
<L>Treon &thorn;are weren fulle of fruyt : wel &thorn;icke euer-ech bou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;icke it was i-set wit<SUP>h</SUP> treon : &thorn;e treon wel faire were,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &amp; &thorn;e treon &thorn;icke bere</NOTE></L>
<L N="696">&THORN;e Applene weren ripe inou&yogh; : ri&yogh;t ase it heruest were.</L>
<L>Fourti dawes in &thorn;is londe : a-boute huy gounne i-wiende,</L>
<L>In none half huy ne mi&yogh;ten finde : of &thorn;is lond non ende.<MILESTONE N="110" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>hit was euere-more day : heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te, and neuere-more ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="700">huy ne founden in none stude : neuere so muche li&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;e eyr was euere in o stat : na&thorn;ur to hot ne to cold&mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;wat [ioie] huy &thorn;ere founden : ne may neuere beon i-told.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at huy comen to a fair watur. : huy nolden nou&yogh;t ouer i-wiende.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">A v. om.: Ac ouer hi mi&yogh;te &thorn;e lond ise : vair wi&thorn;-outen ende.</NOTE></L>
<L N="704">&THORN;o cam to heom a &yogh;onglich man : swi&thorn;e fair and hiende,</L>
<L>Fairore ne mi&yogh;te neuere non beo : ase god him gan &thorn;are<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;ure</NOTE> siende.</L>
<L>he wel-comede euerech bi is name : and custe heom ech-on,</L>
<L>Faire he honourede seint Brendan : and on is hond him nam a-non.</L>
<L N="708">"Lo," he seide, "here &thorn;e lond : &thorn;at &yogh;e habbez i-sou&yogh;t so wide.</L>
<L>For ore louerd nele nou&yogh;t : &thorn;at &yogh;e here-Inne longue &thorn;us a-bide,</L>
<L>Ake &yogh;e schullen in &thorn;e se : is priuetez i-seo,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">These vv. are corrupt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Chargiez ower schip with of &thorn;is fruyt : for &yogh;e ne mouwen no leng here beo."</L>
<L N="712">to seint Brendan he seide And spak : &thorn;is &yogh;ounge man fair and hende :<NOTE PLACE="marg1">This v. <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&THORN;ou most to &thorn;in owene lond : a-&yogh;einward a-non i-wiende :</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou schalt sone out of &thorn;is world : &thorn;i lijf is nei&yogh; at&thorn;ende.</L>
<L N="715">&THORN;is watur &thorn;at &yogh;e here i-seoth : delez &thorn;is world a-two;</L>
<L>&THORN;eos half ou &thorn;inchez fair i-nov&yogh; : and bi-&yogh;eonde half al-so.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e ne mouwen nou&yogh;t comen a-&yogh;end<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &yogh;ende</NOTE> half : for it<NOTE PLACE="marg1">is</NOTE> nis nou&yogh;t ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;is fruyt is euere i-liche ripe : and &thorn;is lond i-liche bri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane ore louerd eche-manere men : to him haueth i-drawe
<PB REF="00000288.tif" N="240"></L>
<L>And &yogh;wane alle-manere men knowez him : and vnder-stondez is lawe,</L>
<L N="721">&THORN;at lond he wole &thorn;anne schewe : toward &thorn;e worldes ende</L>
<L>heom &thorn;at beth to him i-core : are huy heonnes i-wiende."</L>
<L>Seint Brendan a[n]d is Monekes : of &thorn;is fruy<SUP>t</SUP> token faste,</L>
<L N="724">And of preciouse stones al-so : and into hore schipe it caste;</L>
<L>And faire and wel heore leue nomen : &thorn;o al &thorn;is was i-do,</L>
<L>And with wop and sor and deol i-nov : departeden a-two;</L>
<L>And wenden hamward in &thorn;e se : ase ore louerd heom sende.</L>
<L N="728">Wel sonere, ich wot, hom huy come : &thorn;ane huy outward wende.</L>
<L>heore bre&thorn;ren, &thorn;o huy comen hom : Ioyfule weren i-nou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Seint Brendan, &thorn;e holie man : sone to de&thorn;e drou&yogh;&mdash;</L>
<L>For neueref[t] aftur &thorn;ulke tyme : of &thorn;e world he ne rou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="732">Bote as a man of an o&thorn;ur worlde : and ase he were in &thorn;ou&yogh;te&mdash;</L>
<L>And deide sone in yrlaunde : aftur &thorn;ulke stounde.</L>
<L>Mani fair miracle men habbez seth&thorn;e : for him &thorn;are i-founde;</L>
<L>And a fair Abbeie &thorn;are is a-re[r]d : ase is bodi was i-do.</L>
<L N="736">God bringue us to &thorn;ulke Ioye : &thorn;at is soule wende to. AmeN.<NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>Fol</I>. 110 <I>b is left vacant</I>.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="37" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>37 [Vita sancti Nicholai]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEynt Nicholas &thorn;e holie Man : &thorn;at guod confessour was,<MILESTONE N="111" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of hei&yogh;e men he was i-come : In &thorn;e cite of patras :</L>
<L>For in patras he was i-bore&mdash; : nelle ich &thorn;ar-of nou&yogh;t lye;</L>
<L N="4">his moder name was Ione : his faderes epiphanie.</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste day &thorn;at he was i-bore : &thorn;at child, &thorn;at was so guod,</L>
<L>Ase it was in ane mele i-ba&thorn;ed : al one upri&yogh;t it stod.</L>
<L>Ano[n] so he was i-bore : he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. and</NOTE> gan to beo guod and clene;</L>
<L N="8">he nolde fridai ne wodnesday : souke nou&yogh;t bote ene.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he cou&thorn;e gon ant speke : he ne pleide neuere mo,</L>
<L>Ake &yogh;wane o&thorn;ur children rageden<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. raieden</NOTE> faste : to churche he wolde go;</L>
<L>he nolde speke non ydel word : ase swuche children doth;</L>
<L N="12">Lei&yogh;ingue and plei&yogh;es and ragingues : he bi-lefte al-so.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he was seth&thorn;e of grettore elde : to scole he was i-set;</L>
<L>So wel he leornede : &thorn;at man nuste, no child leorni bet.</L>
<L>Seth&thorn;e &thorn;o he more<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> m. wit</NOTE> cou&thorn;e : al his studie he tok</L>
<L N="16">to guodespelles ant to holi writes : and alle o&thorn;ere bokes for-sok.
<PB REF="00000289.tif" N="241"></L>
<L>So clene lijf he ladde &yogh;ong : &thorn;at deinte it was to wite;</L>
<L>More godnesse ne mi&yogh;te beo : &thorn;ane we findeth of him i-write.</L>
<L>&THORN;o is fader and is moder weren dede : &thorn;is holie child Nicholas</L>
<L N="20">luyte tolde of heore guode : &thorn;ei he heore eyr was :</L>
<L>to pouere Men he &yogh;af it clene : &yogh;ware he sai&yogh; neode;</L>
<L>And heo &thorn;at nolden bidde him non : stilleliche he gan hem beode.&mdash;</L>
<L>An hei&yogh; Man &thorn;are was bi-side : &thorn;at seth&thorn;e &thorn;oru&yogh; lu&thorn;er cas</L>
<L N="24">his guod was al-clene a-wei i-go : and al pouere bi-come he was.</L>
<L>he hadde &thorn;re dou&yogh;tren faire i-nou&yogh; : clene and guode al-so;</L>
<L>In so gret Meseise heo weren i-brou&yogh;t : &thorn;at heo nusten &yogh;wat to do.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo nusten &yogh;ware-bi libbe&mdash; : for heore guod heom was bi-nome&mdash;</L>
<L N="28">heore red huy nomen alle &thorn;reo : fole wommen to bi-come</L>
<L>And ra&thorn;er &thorn;anne heo in swuche houngur weren : to libbe bi hore|<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. heore</NOTE> dom.</L>
<L>&THORN;e olde man, heor alre fader : gret deol to him he nom.</L>
<L>gret pite hadde in is heorte : &thorn;e guode seint Nicholas,</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;o he i-heorde &thorn;e deolfole mone : &thorn;at a-mong heom alle was.</L>
<L>Of is fader guode a ny&yogh;t : ane bei&yogh;<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> weg</NOTE> of gold he nam,</L>
<L>I-wounde in one cloute : and stilleliche to heore house he cam,</L>
<L>to a derne wyndouwe softeliche : seint Nicholas gan gon</L>
<L N="36">And caste in &thorn;at gold priueliche : and wende a-&yogh;ein a-non.</L>
<L>&THORN;is housebonde a-ros a-Moruwe : ant &thorn;ar-of nuste nou&yogh;t :</L>
<L>he com and fond &thorn;ane bei&yogh; of gold : &thorn;at seint Nicholas hadde i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-of he was glad i-nou&yogh; : &thorn;ei he nuste ho it brou&yogh;te;</L>
<L N="40">he it nam and &thorn;onkede Iesu crist : &thorn;at on is meseise &thorn;ou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-with he conseilede swy&thorn;e wel : his eldeste dou&yogh;ter sone</L>
<L>With fair bruydale and gret honour : ase ri&yogh;t was for-to done.</L>
<L>Seint Nicholas i-sai&yogh; al &thorn;is : and na&thorn;eles &yogh;uyt he &thorn;ou&yogh;te</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at &thorn;is selie Man neode hadde : &thorn;at he more guod to him brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>A ni&yogh;t he a-waitede swy&thorn;e wel : ase ore louerd it wolde,</L>
<L>And at one fenestre caste In eft-sone : ane o&thorn;ur bei&yogh; of golde.<MILESTONE N="111b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;is housebonde a-morewe a-ros : &thorn;at gold he fond sone;</L>
<L N="48">he &thorn;onkede god with guode heorte : &thorn;at hadde i-heord is bone.</L>
<L>And natheles him wondrede muche : ho is freond so wel were,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at he a-waiti wolde : &yogh;if he more come &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>he conseilede is o&thorn;ur dou&yogh;ter : swi&thorn;e wel with &thorn;is golde,
<PB REF="00000290.tif" N="242"></L>
<L N="52">With gret nobleie and fayr bruydale : ase ore louerd it wolde.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eot &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;is guode Nicholas : &thorn;o &thorn;is was al i-do,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it were guod to conseili : &thorn;e &thorn;ridde dou&yogh;ter al-so :</L>
<L>A ni&yogh;t he wende wel stilledliche : to &thorn;at fenestre eft-sone</L>
<L N="56">And caste In ane bei&yogh; of gold : ase he was i-woned to done.</L>
<L>&THORN;is housebonde hadde i-waked longue : for-to wayti of &thorn;is cas :</L>
<L>So &thorn;at, &thorn;o seint Nicholas cam : wakiende he was.</L>
<L>Op he sturte and siwede him : and bi is clo&thorn;us heold him faste,</L>
<L N="60">he ne let nou&yogh;t go are &thorn;e guode man : i-kneu&yogh; him<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> was iknowe</NOTE> at &thorn;e laste.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eorne bad seint Nicholas : &thorn;at he to no man ne sede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;wyle &thorn;at he a-liue were : of &thorn;is priue dede.</L>
<L>With &thorn;is gold &thorn;e &thorn;ridde dou&yogh;ter : wel i-conseilled was;</L>
<L N="64">And alle &thorn;reo weren riche<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> gode</NOTE> wiues : &thorn;oru&yogh; seint Nicholas.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is manere seint Nicholas : ase ich nou&thorn;e habbe i-sed,</L>
<L>Delde al is heritage : &thorn;o is fader was ded.</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane o&thorn;ur Men eoden to habbe solas : he nadde &thorn;ar-to no<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. ne</NOTE> wille :</L>
<L>to churche he wolde and in one huyrne : is beden bidde wel stille.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; Hit bi-feol &thorn;at &thorn;e bischop : of Mirre was ded,</L>
<L>And folk cam to cheose ane o&thorn;ur : and &thorn;ar-of hy nomen heore red;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo weren in hore beden : ny&yogh;t and dai wel faste</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;at ore louerd heom sende ane guode man. : and he herde heom ate laste.</L>
<L>For a ny&yogh;t &thorn;are cam a voiz : ase it were in metingue,</L>
<L>to a bischop &thorn;at was maister &thorn;er : and tolde him &thorn;is ty&thorn;ingue<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> of &thorn;e cheosinge</NOTE></L>
<L>And seide, "goth to-morewe to churche<NOTE PLACE="marg1">to ch. on the margin.</NOTE> sone : ri&yogh;t are hit dai beo :</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste man &thorn;at &yogh;e &thorn;are mouwen : i-heore o&thorn;ur i-seo</L>
<L>And &thorn;at hote Nicholas : takez him wel sone</L>
<L N="78">And makez him bischop of Mirre! : god hath i-heord ower bone."</L>
<L>&thorn;e bischop and &thorn;at o&thorn;ur folk : a-risen are hit dai were,</L>
<L N="80">And comen to churche, and founden sone : Nicholas stonde &thorn;ere :</L>
<L>In one huyrne he stod ful stille. : heo axeden &yogh;wat he was</L>
<L>And &yogh;wat were is ri&yogh;te name. : he seide hem "Nicholas."</L>
<L>heo nomen and ladden him with gret honour : to &thorn;e churche of Mirree</L>
<L N="84">And sacreden him to bischop &thorn;ere : and setten him in is se.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he was hei&yogh; man i-maked : &thorn;is guode Nicholas,
<PB REF="00000291.tif" N="243"></L>
<L>More bou&yogh;sum and milde he bi-cam : &thorn;ane euer er [he] was;</L>
<L>luyte pruyte he hadde of is power : &yogh;wane men him wolden a-loute,</L>
<L N="88">And &yogh;if it nere for ei&yogh;e of god : leouere him were with-oute.</L>
<L>So prest he was to alle men : &thorn;at on him beden &amp; cride,</L>
<L>And so muche for heom he dude : &thorn;at men speken &thorn;ar-of wide.&mdash;</L>
<L>Muche folk In a time : In-to &thorn;e se i-wende<MILESTONE N="112" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In a schip, to don heore neode : &yogh;if ore louerd &thorn;e grace heom sende.</L>
<L N="93">So &thorn;at &thorn;ere cam a gret tempeste : &thorn;at heo wenden alle a-drenche.</L>
<L>Alle guodnesse heo bi-hei&yogh;ten god : &thorn;at heo mi&yogh;ten on bi-&thorn;enche.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo &thorn;ou&yogh;ten, ase heore schip : toward &thorn;e grounde was,</L>
<L N="96">On &thorn;e guodnesse &thorn;at men tolden : of &thorn;e bischop Nicholas :</L>
<L>"Leoue louerd Nicholas" : wel loude alle heo criden,</L>
<L>"&YOGH;if it is<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. it</NOTE> soth &thorn;at we habbez : i-heord tellen of &thorn;e wide,</L>
<L>In &thorn;is peril saue us nou&thorn;e : &thorn;at we ne beon a-dreint;</L>
<L N="100">Louerd Nicholas, help us nou&thorn;e : are ore schip beo a-seint!"</L>
<L>Ase heo gradden, &thorn;are cam on eorne : on-owarde &thorn;e watere bi-side</L>
<L>A bischop in abite swi&thorn;e fair. : wel loude on him huy cride.</L>
<L>"Lo me here," quath &thorn;is holie man : "&yogh;e cleopeden me wel faste.</L>
<L N="104">Seggez &yogh;wat ouwer wille beo : and &yogh;warof &yogh;e beon a-gaste!"</L>
<L>"Louerd," heo seiden, "Nicholas : &yogh;if it is &thorn;i wille,</L>
<L>Saue us nou&thorn;e of &thorn;is tempeste : &thorn;at we he[re]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. he</NOTE> ne a-spille"</L>
<L>"Ne habbe &yogh;e," quath &thorn;is holie man : "her-of none drede!"</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;at weder bi-cam &thorn;o stille inou&yogh; : &thorn;o he &thorn;eos wordes sede.</L>
<L>heo bi-heolden &thorn;o after him&mdash; : heo nusten &yogh;ware he was;</L>
<L>And &thorn;onkeden muche ore swete louerd : and &thorn;ene bischop Nicholas.</L>
<L>&THORN;ene wei stille and murie : toward &thorn;e londe huy nome;</L>
<L N="112">With-oute eche destourbingue : to londe wel glade heo come.</L>
<L>Alle heo duden heom fort a-non : to &thorn;e bischope Nicholas,</L>
<L>Ase to a man &thorn;at heo neuere ne sei&yogh;en : ne nusten &yogh;wuch he was.</L>
<L>Ech of heom bi-heolden him faste : &thorn;at to &thorn;is guode man com :</L>
<L N="116">Alle heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at it was he : &thorn;at &thorn;ene deth heom bi-nam.</L>
<L>"Louerd," heo seiden, "i-hered &thorn;ou beo! : to &thorn;e we gradden bliue;</L>
<L>On-ouewarde &thorn;e se &thorn;o &thorn;ou come : and brou&yogh;test us to liue.</L>
<L>I-hered beo &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ou most : a-mong men on eor&thorn;e beo!</L>
<L N="120">For swuche grace ne hadde neuere eor&thorn;elich Man : ase man may on &thorn;e i-se."
<PB REF="00000292.tif" N="244"></L>
<L>&THORN;is guode Man, &thorn;o he i-heorde &thorn;is : &thorn;onkede and herede al-so</L>
<L>Ore louerd, &thorn;at wolde for is loue : suych miracle do.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; hit bi-feol In ane o&thorn;ur tyme : of &thorn;e bischop Nicholas,</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;at gret hongur al-a-boute : In is bischopriche was;</L>
<L>So lu&thorn;ere fullen &thorn;e &yogh;eres alle : &thorn;at no corn nou&yogh;were nas.</L>
<L>gret deol hadde &thorn;is guode bischop : of &thorn;at lu&thorn;ere cas.</L>
<L>Fram feorrene contreies<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> &thorn;are comen schipes : with muche corn &thorn;are|bi-side :</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;is bischop wende a-&yogh;ein heom sone : and bad heom one stounde a|bide,</L>
<L>"For &thorn;e loue of Iesu crist : leneth me," he sede,</L>
<L>"Ane hondret quarters of &thorn;at corn : &thorn;at &yogh;e &thorn;are doth lede,</L>
<L>to &thorn;is selie men &thorn;at beoth here : nei&yogh; for houngur dede;</L>
<L N="132">heo ne habbeth no corn to libbe bi : to sede ne to brede."</L>
<L>"Certes, sire," &thorn;is schipmen seiden : "&thorn;at ne dorre we nou&yogh;t :</L>
<L>For al &thorn;is corn &thorn;at &thorn;ou i-sixt : &thorn;at we habbez here i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>With swy&thorn;e schars met with-alle : bitau&yogh;t it is us echone</L>
<L>&THORN;at we it leden &thorn;e Aumperour&mdash; : ne dorre we make no lone."<MILESTONE N="112b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"With-oute faille," quath &thorn;is gode man : "ne dredez ou ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="138">&YOGH;if &yogh;e me wollez &thorn;ar-of lene : &thorn;at eov schulle faili ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;e folle &yogh;e schulle &yogh;elden &thorn;e Aumperoure : ase men token ou for-to lede,</L>
<L N="140">No-&thorn;ing ne schal ou failli : ne &thorn;arf ov no-&thorn;ing drede."</L>
<L>&THORN;e schipmen ope truste of is word : wel largeliche him mete</L>
<L>And token &thorn;e bischope wel i-metene : Ane houndred quarteres &yogh;wete;</L>
<L>And wenden forth to &thorn;e Aumperour : and is corn him ladde;</L>
<L N="144">And beden is stiwardes meten wel : &yogh;if heo &thorn;e folle hadden.</L>
<L>huy meten, and founden al &thorn;e fulle : and wel more &thorn;are-to.</L>
<L>For wonder heo axeden &thorn;e schipmen : &yogh;wi it woxe so.</L>
<L>heo &thorn;onkeden a-non &thorn;ane gode bischop : &thorn;at is neode to heom mende,</L>
<L>And tolden fore &thorn;e Aumperoure : hou muche corn heo him lende,</L>
<L>And hou he bi-het heom &thorn;at it ne scholde : &thorn;are-fore ne wanie nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And hou heo hadden bi large met : wel more corn i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode bischope heo hereden swi&thorn;e : and &thorn;onkeden muche also,</L>
<L N="152">&THORN;at hadde &thorn;oru ore louerdes grace : swche miracle i-do.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e contreie hadde i-nou&yogh; : to mete and to sede,
<PB REF="00000293.tif" N="245"></L>
<L>To &yogh;er and more, of &thorn;at corn : &thorn;at heo gonne &thorn;are lede.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; In an o&thorn;ur tyme &thorn;is guode bischop : bi a fair treo com :</L>
<L N="156">he fond &thorn;are men &thorn;at duden &thorn;ing : a-&yogh;ein heore cristine-dom :</L>
<L>heo stoden &thorn;are, ase heo ofte duden : and maden heore sacrefise</L>
<L>to &thorn;e deuel onder &thorn;is treo : &thorn;at men<NOTE PLACE="marg1">superscribed.</NOTE> mi&yogh;ten &thorn;ar-of a-grise.</L>
<L>Seint Nicholas heom tornede echone : gode men for-to be,</L>
<L>And dude heom for-sake &thorn;e feondes lore : and hewe a-doun &thorn;at treo.</L>
<L N="161">&THORN;e deuel after &thorn;ulke tyme : to him hadde gret onde :</L>
<L>For-to a-batien is pouwer : in alle manere he gan fonde.&mdash;</L>
<L>pilegrimes weren in &thorn;e se : to seint Nicholas for-to wende,</L>
<L N="164">For &thorn;e guodnesse &thorn;at huy of him herden : &yogh;if god heom wolde &thorn;e grace sende.</L>
<L>In fourme of a fair womman : &thorn;e deuel cam heom to</L>
<L>And seide, "louerdingues, wel is eou : &thorn;at &yogh;e mouwen ouwer wille do</L>
<L>For-to seche &thorn;is holie man : &thorn;at so milsful is and hende!</L>
<L N="168">Leouere ich hadde &thorn;ane ani-&thorn;ing : mi&yogh;te ich with ou wende :</L>
<L>For ich ne wilni no-&thorn;ing so muche : ase &thorn;ane holie man to seo.</L>
<L>A luyte &thorn;ing &yogh;e moten for me don : &yogh;wane it ne may o&thorn;ur beo :</L>
<L>Nimeth here &thorn;is guode oygnement : &thorn;at deorewur&thorn;e is with-alle,</L>
<L N="172">And &yogh;wane &yogh;e into is churche comiet : smeorieth in eche walle,</L>
<L>For-to wurthschipien &thorn;ane guode man : &thorn;at is of so gret pouste;</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane ich ne mai to him come : doth &thorn;at In &thorn;e muynde of me!"</L>
<L>&THORN;is pilegrimes with glade heorte : &thorn;is oynement to heom nome,</L>
<L N="176">to smerien with &thorn;is holie churche : &yogh;wane heo &thorn;udere come.</L>
<L>Ase he wenden forth in &thorn;e se : sone it dude bi-falle</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;are cam to heom a schip : with faire men with-alle;</L>
<L>A bischop &thorn;are was a-mong heom : swi&thorn;e fair man and hende.</L>
<L>he grette heom faire and axede a-non : &yogh;wodere heo &thorn;ou&yogh;ten wende.</L>
<L>heo seiden &thorn;at heo wolden : &yogh;if it godes wille were,<MILESTONE N="113" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="182">to &thorn;e churche of Mirree : for-to Anouri seint Nicholas &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;wat was &thorn;e womman," &thorn;e bischop seide : "&thorn;at &yogh;wile er eou cam to,</L>
<L N="184">And &yogh;wat was it &thorn;at heo eou bi-tei&yogh;te? : &yogh;wat schulle &yogh;e &thorn;are-with do?"</L>
<L>"Sire, it is an oynement" : &thorn;eos pilegrimes seden,</L>
<L>"&THORN;e guode womman &yogh;eorne us bad : to &thorn;e holie churche it lede</L>
<L>And &thorn;are-with in muynde of hire : &yogh;wane it were &thorn;udere i-brou&yogh;t,
<PB REF="00000294.tif" N="246"></L>
<L N="188">Smeorie &thorn;e holie churche wowes&mdash; : &thorn;at we ne leten it nou&yogh;t!"</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e, &yogh;e," quath &thorn;is holie man : "&yogh;e nuten nou&yogh;t &yogh;wat heo is.</L>
<L>takez me &thorn;at oynement : and &yogh;e schullen i-seo, i-wis."</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode man nam &thorn;at oynement : and a-midde &thorn;e se it caste.</L>
<L N="192">&THORN;at watur bi-gan to berne a-non : a-&yogh;ein is kuynde, wel faste;</L>
<L>Fram stude to stude &thorn;at fuyr orn : and barnde &thorn;e se, i-wis.</L>
<L>&THORN;o seide &thorn;e guode man, "here &yogh;e iseoth : &yogh;wat ouwer oynement is.</L>
<L>hadde &yogh;e ani-&thorn;ing &thorn;arof : on &thorn;e churche-walles i-do,</L>
<L N="196">Al &thorn;e churche hadde for-barnd : and al &thorn;e toun al-so.</L>
<L>hit was &thorn;e foule feond of helle : &thorn;at it ou tok with honde</L>
<L>For-to brenne &thorn;ulke churche : for he haueth &thorn;ar-to onde."</L>
<L>Forth wende &thorn;is bischop and alle his : anon-ri&yogh;t &thorn;oru&yogh; godes sonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pilegrimes roweden<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. rewe</NOTE> &thorn;ene nexte wey : so &thorn;at huy comen to londe.</L>
<L>to seint Nicholas heo wenden &thorn;o : &thorn;at heo so wide sou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>A-non so heo i-sei&yogh;en &thorn;is guode man : heo stoden in grete &thorn;ou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at it &thorn;e bischop was : &thorn;at in &thorn;e se to heom cam,</L>
<L N="204">&THORN;at sche<SUP>w</SUP>ude hem &thorn;at oynement : and &thorn;e feondes swykedam.</L>
<L>"Louerd," heo seiden, "nov &thorn;in ore! : muche is &thorn;i pouwer :</L>
<L>&THORN;at we i-sei&yogh;en in &thorn;e se : are we comen her."</L>
<L N="207">heo hereden muche &thorn;ene holie man : as it wel ri&yogh;t was.</L>
<L>&THORN;e guode man faste heom for-bed : &thorn;at heo ne tolden nou&yogh;t &thorn;is cas.</L>
<L>Fairore Miracle on eor&thorn;e : ne mi&yogh;te we neuere i-wite</L>
<L>&THORN;ane we of seint Nicholas : findeth ofte i-write!&mdash;</L>
<L>In a tyme lu&thorn;ere men weorreden : &thorn;ene Aumperour of rome</L>
<L N="212">And destruyden is londes faste : and bataille a-&yogh;ein him nome.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Aumperour nam &thorn;re grete louerdingues : and o&thorn;ere wel mani on,</L>
<L>For-to wenden, I-armede swy&thorn;e wel : to fi&yogh;ten a-&yogh;ein is fon.</L>
<L>&THORN;is &thorn;reo princes with heore men : in &thorn;e se forth i-wenden,</L>
<L N="216">to fi&yogh;ten a-&yogh;ein is wy&thorn;erwynes : ase &thorn;e Aumperour heom sende.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e wynd heom drof : ase it were bi cas,</L>
<L>to &thorn;e contreie of Mirree : &thorn;are &thorn;is bischop was.</L>
<L N="219">&THORN;e bischop heorde of hem telle. : a&yogh;en heom he wende sone,</L>
<L>And bad heom come and ete with him : and huy graunteden is bone.</L>
<L>&THORN;is [&thorn;e]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> guode man dude for heo ne scholden : none robberie do.</L>
<L>he made hem suy&thorn;e wel an ayse : and fair semblaunt al-so;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;is holie bischop : heo and heore fon
<PB REF="00000295.tif" N="247"></L>
<L>With-oute dunt o&thorn;ur blod i-sched : a-corded<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. acordet</NOTE> weren a-non,</L>
<L>Al-to &thorn;e Aumperores guode : ant to his honour al-so.</L>
<L>&THORN;eos &thorn;re maistres wenden hamward : &thorn;o &thorn;is dede was i-do.<MILESTONE N="113b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>heo comen and tolden &thorn;e Aumperour : hov heo hadden on i-take.</L>
<L N="228">&THORN;e Aumperour was wel a-payd : and gret feste gan heom make.</L>
<L>heore lu&thorn;ere felawes comen sone : and &thorn;are-to hadden envie,</L>
<L>And seiden heo hadden &thorn;e Aumperoure : i-don gret tricherie</L>
<L>And with is fon imaked a fol pays : and with grete feolonie,</L>
<L N="232">to &thorn;e deseritisun of &thorn;e Aumperour : ope heom heo gunne lye.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Aumperour in grete wrath&thorn;e : let heom nime faste</L>
<L>And binden &thorn;eos &thorn;re princes : and in strongue prisone caste.</L>
<L>So faste weren &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere men : ope &thorn;is princes &thorn;reo</L>
<L N="236">&THORN;at &thorn;e Aumperour swor is oth : A-slawe heo scholden beo.</L>
<L>he let somony is kny&yogh;tes alle : &thorn;at heo a-morewe come</L>
<L>For-to bringuen &thorn;eos &thorn;reo princes : to de&thorn;e &thorn;oru&yogh; heore<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> his</NOTE> dome.</L>
<L>A-non so &thorn;e ti&thorn;ingue was i-brou&yogh;t : to &thorn;is princes<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> prisons</NOTE> &thorn;reo,</L>
<L N="240">heo weopen and criden deolfulliche : &thorn;at reu&thorn;e it was to se,</L>
<L>heo weopen and heore clo&thorn;es teren : and heore her al-so;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh;ten on &thorn;e grete godnesse : &thorn;at seint Nicholas hadde i-do.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 241-2 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Louerd," heo seiden, "Nicholas : fro &yogh;wam wel glade we eode,</L>
<L N="244">And also wis ase we gultelese beoth : help us in ore neode,</L>
<L>Ne lat us neuere &thorn;us gulte-lese : to de&thorn;e beon i-brou&yogh;t!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e holie bischop Nicholas : ne fur-&yogh;at heom nou&yogh;t :<NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 245-6 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L>For a ny&yogh;t, ase &thorn;e Aumperour : ase a louerd lay and ase a sire,</L>
<L N="248">In-to is paleis, &thorn;at was so strong : and i-barred al with ire,</L>
<L>to him ri&yogh;t bi-fore his bed : &thorn;is holi bischop com,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. ca<SUP>o</SUP>m</NOTE></L>
<L>And seide, "sire Aumperour, &yogh;wat &thorn;encst &thorn;ou : with &thorn;i false dom?</L>
<L>&YOGH;wi hast &thorn;ou &thorn;is gultelese men : In &thorn;i prisone i-brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And gulteles &thorn;enchest heom a-quelle? : ich rede, with-drau&yogh; &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t!</L>
<L N="253">A-ris op sone, ich rede &thorn;e : and lat heom of prisone wende,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur ichulle mine louerd bidde : &thorn;at he &thorn;e weorre sende,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> schal &thorn;e schende</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;are-inne &thorn;ou worst al-to-boned : and i-brou&yogh;t of lijf-dawe,</L>
<L N="256">&THORN;at foules schullen and wilde bestes : &thorn;i caroyne al-to-drawe."<NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 255-6 <I>al.</I> om</NOTE></L>
<L>"&YOGH;wat artov," quath &thorn;e Aumperour : "o&thorn;ur of &yogh;wat pouste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;is tyme art i-come : in-to mi paleys to me</L>
<L>And swuche bolde wordes spext? : wonder me &thorn;inchez of &thorn;e!"
<PB REF="00000296.tif" N="248"></L>
<L N="260">"Ich am," quath &thorn;is Nicholas : "bischop of mirree."</L>
<L>&para; Seint Nicholas wende al-so : to &thorn;e Aumperoures hei&yogh;e Iustise,</L>
<L>&THORN;are he lai bi-side in &thorn;e paleys : and made him sum-del a-grise :</L>
<L>"&THORN;ov witlese wrechche," he seide : "&yogh;wat hauestou i-&thorn;ou&yogh;t?</L>
<L N="264">Rastov &thorn;at &thorn;is gultelese men : to de&thorn;e beon i-brou&yogh;t?</L>
<L>With-drau&yogh; &thorn;i red, ich &thorn;e rede, sone : o&thorn;ur &thorn;ou schalt al for-dwyne</L>
<L>And for-leose al &thorn;i guod : and dey&yogh;e in strongue pine."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;wat artou," &thorn;is o&thorn;ur seide : "&thorn;at spext wordes &thorn;us grete</L>
<L N="268">And &thorn;e Aumperores hei&yogh;e Iustise : &thorn;us baldeliche darst &thorn;rete?"</L>
<L>"Ich am," he seide, "Nicholas : bischop of Mirree.</L>
<L>bote &thorn;ou with-drawe &thorn;i red sone : &thorn;ou schalt i-leue me."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Aumperour lai and quakede sore : and sende after is Iustise,<MILESTONE N="114" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="272">&THORN;at was al-so sore a-drad : and soruful in eche wise.</L>
<L>Ey&thorn;ur tolde o&thorn;ur fore : hou he to heom seide</L>
<L>And wel baldeliche &thorn;retnede heom. : &yogh;ware-fore heo weren in drede.</L>
<L>For-to schilden heom fram is wrath&thorn;e : an-o&thorn;ur heo mosten rede :</L>
<L N="276">&THORN;is &thorn;re prisones heo leten up nime : and sone bi-fore heom lede.</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e sore heo weren a-dradde : for heo wenden a-non beo dede;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e bischop Nicholas : reuliche heo gonne grede.</L>
<L>"beaus amis," quath &thorn;e Aumperour : "&yogh;wat-manere men beo &yogh;e,</L>
<L N="280">&THORN;at &thorn;us &thorn;oru&yogh; ouwer enchauntement : a-ni&yogh;t drechcheth<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> derie&thorn;</NOTE> me?"</L>
<L>"A, sire, merci," &thorn;is o&thorn;ure seide : "&yogh;wi wolle &yogh;e seggen so?</L>
<L>Of anchauntement ne cou&thorn;e we neuere : ope god we wollez us do.</L>
<L N="283">Ake gultelese men we buth : with onri&yogh;te hidere i-brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Al-so wis god schilde us fram &thorn;e deth : ase we ne beth gultie nou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>"I-knowe &yogh;e ani Man," quath &thorn;e Aumperour : "&thorn;at hote Nicholas?"</L>
<L>&THORN;are nas neuere on, for &thorn;is word : &thorn;at in gre[t] hope ne was!</L>
<L N="287">heore hondene heo heolden op on hei&yogh; : and wel loude gradden</L>
<L>to &thorn;e bischope<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. bi bischope</NOTE> Nicholas : &thorn;at he reu&thorn;e of heom hadde.</L>
<L>"&THORN;oru&yogh; him," quath &thorn;e Aumperour : "&yogh;e beth to liue i-do,</L>
<L>Ich ou &yogh;iue lijf and lime : and ouwer chateles al-so.</L>
<L>goth nou&thorn;e hasteliche to him : and tellez him wel bliue</L>
<L N="292">hou &thorn;at for &thorn;e loue of him : ich let ov gon a-liue;</L>
<L>biddeth &thorn;at he for-&yogh;iue me is wrath&thorn;e : and non harm for eu me do,</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;at he bidde god for me : and for mi kynedom al-so."<NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 293-4 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is prisones wenden with glade heorte : to &thorn;e bischope Nicholas,
<PB REF="00000297.tif" N="249"></L>
<L N="296">And &thorn;onkeden him, ase heo au&yogh;ten wel : of &thorn;is Ioyfule cas.</L>
<L>Ich wene, &thorn;ere nas neuere haluwe : seint Nicholases i-per,</L>
<L>&THORN;at so manie faire Miracles : bi is liue dude her;</L>
<L>For to come into so strong paleis : and gon op-on &thorn;e se al-so,</L>
<L N="300">gret wonder was &thorn;at ani-bodi : swuch miracle mi&yogh;te do!</L>
<L>Muche of &thorn;e kuynde of heuene : ore louerd here him sende,</L>
<L>Aungles dede a-liue to do : are he hennes i-wende.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 297-302 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;o ore louerdes wille was : &thorn;at he scholde hennes w<SUP>i</SUP>ende,</L>
<L N="304">he bad ore louerd &thorn;at he scholde : aungles to him sende.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he i-say &thorn;e Aungles to him come : he &thorn;onkede ore louerd faste.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ritti&thorn;e saume of &thorn;e sauter : he bi-gan &thorn;us ate laste</L>
<L>"In &thorn;e, louerd, ich habbe i-hoped : &thorn;at ich i-confundet ne beo,</L>
<L N="308">&THORN;ine holie ere bei&yogh; a-doun to me : hei&yogh;e and deliuere me."</L>
<L>he deide ate sixte vers : &thorn;at on e[n]glichs to seggen is</L>
<L>"Mine soule, louerd, ich bi-take &thorn;e : &thorn;ou bou&yogh;test hire, i-wis."</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule out wende with &thorn;ulke worde : and &thorn;e Aungeles forth hire bere;</L>
<L N="312">Alle &thorn;e felaweschipes of heuene : wel glade &thorn;ere-with were.</L>
<L>he deide &thorn;re houndret &yogh;er : and in &thorn;e &thorn;reo and fourty&thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L>After &thorn;at god was i-bore : as &thorn;e bok us deth lere.</L>
<L>In one toumbe of Marbre he was i-leid : swy&thorn;e faire with-alle.</L>
<L N="316">Out of &thorn;e harde Marbre-ston : &thorn;e oyle gan out walle;<MILESTONE N="114b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A welle of eoyle &thorn;are sprong out : ri&yogh;t at is heued a-non,</L>
<L>And at is fet a welle of water : of &thorn;e harde Marbre-ston.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 317-8 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sike men &thorn;are gonnen sone : wel &thorn;icke &thorn;udere gon.</L>
<L N="320">&THORN;ar-of men beren wide a-boute : and &yogh;eot men doth al-so;</L>
<L>gret botningue &thorn;ar is &yogh;uyt : of men &thorn;at comieth &thorn;are-to&mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e welle of eoyle and of watur : ase manie men i-seoth,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e harde ston lastez &yogh;eot : &thorn;are is holie bones beoth.&mdash;</L>
<L N="324">Many fair Miracle &thorn;are<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. &thorn;are</NOTE> hath of him : seth&thorn;e he deide, i-come.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei we ne mouwen nou&yogh;t tellen alle : we moten tellen of some.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 320-5 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; To a gyv at one tyme : a cristine man &yogh;eode</L>
<L>For-to borewi gold of him : to is muchele neode.</L>
<L N="328">he ne mi&yogh;te finden him nanne boru&yogh; : ne wed nadde he non :</L>
<L>&THORN;ane gyv to seint Nicholas churche : he bad with him gon;</L>
<L>Op-on seint Nicholases auter he swor : at one certeyne daye,
<PB REF="00000298.tif" N="250"></L>
<L>So god him helpe and seint Nicholas : his gold him for-to paye.</L>
<L N="332">&THORN;is giv for seint Nicholas loue : his oth nou&yogh;t ne for-sok,</L>
<L>Ake seint Nicholas to borewe he nam : and &thorn;at gold him bi-tok.</L>
<L>&THORN;is lu&thorn;ere cristine man : &thorn;o it cam to is daye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at gold nolde he &yogh;elde nou&yogh;t : ake &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;ane giv bi-traye.</L>
<L N="336">&THORN;e giv cam and axede him : &yogh;wanne he it &yogh;elde wolde.</L>
<L>"&THORN;ov false schrewe," &thorn;e o&thorn;ur seide : "ich it &thorn;e habbe i-&yogh;olde."</L>
<L>&THORN;e giv seide nay, and he &yogh;us : bote al ne heold it nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e giv let him somoni : &thorn;at he was to court i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="340">Ake &thorn;is false cristine man : &thorn;ou&yogh;te op one feolle gynne :</L>
<L>Ane staf he nam op-on is hond : &mdash;holu&yogh; he was with-inne&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;are-inne he dutte al &thorn;at gold : &thorn;at he scholde &thorn;e giwe &yogh;elde,</L>
<L>And feolliche dutte hine and faste : &thorn;at men ne scholden him bi|melde.</L>
<L N="344">bi-fore &thorn;e bayllifs huy comen : &thorn;e giv and he bo&thorn;e.</L>
<L>he with-sok &thorn;e giwes dette : and was i-don to ane o&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he scholde is oth do : is false staf he bi-tok</L>
<L>&THORN;e giwe, and bad him &yogh;witie &thorn;e &yogh;wile : he leide is hond on &thorn;e bok;</L>
<L N="348">And seide, "al-so muche gold al-so ich borewede : of &thorn;e giv &thorn;at here is,</L>
<L>So helpe me crist and seint Nicholas : ich tok him a-&yogh;ein, i-wis."</L>
<L>&THORN;is lu&thorn;ere man with is fals oth : swi&thorn;e wel i-leued was,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e o&thorn;ur, for he was a giv : no-&thorn;ing i-leued he nas.</L>
<L N="352">"&YOGH;wane &thorn;ou me hast bi-giled : with &thorn;i false cas,</L>
<L>Ich bidde &thorn;ine borou&yogh; &thorn;at he it me &yogh;elde : &thorn;e guode seint Nicholas."</L>
<L>&THORN;e giv with wel sorie chere : wende him forth a-non,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e false man nam is staf : and hamward bi-gan to gon.</L>
<L>Al-so he wende bi &thorn;e weie hamward : to slepe he hadde grete wille :</L>
<L N="357">&THORN;are twei wei&yogh;es to-gadere comen : a-doun he lai wel stille.</L>
<L>As &thorn;is false man lay and slep : a cart &thorn;are cam gon,</L>
<L>And al-to-bruysde is false bones : &thorn;at he deide a-non.</L>
<L N="360">&THORN;at o &yogh;weol to-brak &thorn;ane false staf : ase mani a man i-sai&yogh; :<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Here a fol. is wanting; MS. Harl continues :]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>[&THORN;at gold schadde out al-abrod : &amp; amidde &thorn;e weye lay.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e gyw, &thorn;o he &thorn;is ise&yogh; : loude he gan to crie
<PB REF="00000299.tif" N="251"></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;onkede seint Nicholas : &thorn;at schewede his tricherie.</L>
<L N="364">For &thorn;e miracle men him radde : cristene forto beo.</L>
<L>"Certes, ynelle," qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er : "er i<SUP>c</SUP> more iseo;</L>
<L>Ac if god &amp; seint Nicholas : wolde &thorn;is li&thorn;er manes<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> man is</NOTE> lyf sende,</L>
<L>Cristene i<SUP>c</SUP> wolde &thorn;anne beo : &amp; serui hem to mi lyues ende."</L>
<L N="368">&para; Fram de&thorn;e to lyue &thorn;is false man : &thorn;urf seint Nicholas com.</L>
<L>Anon so &thorn;e gyw &thorn;is ise&yogh; : he wilnede cristendom,</L>
<L>&amp; bileouede on ihesu crist : &amp; god man euereft was.</L>
<L>&THORN;is me &thorn;in&yogh;&thorn; a fair miracle : of seint Nicholas!</L>
<L N="372">her &yogh;e seo&thorn; hou hit go&thorn; bi men : &thorn;at wi&thorn; gyle swerie&thorn;, iwis;</L>
<L>&THORN;e&yogh; he &thorn;urf gyle swerie so&thorn; : iwis forswore he is.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; A god man &thorn;er was in a tyme : &thorn;at longe was mid his wyue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no childe nemi&yogh;te habbe : &thorn;at euere cam to lyue.</L>
<L N="376">To seint Nicholas ofte hi bede : achild hem to sende,</L>
<L>&amp; bihete him, if hit so were : to him forto wende.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Nicholas ihurde here bone : &mdash;for god he is &amp; mylde :</L>
<L>hit biful &thorn;er-after sone : &thorn;at his wyf was mid chylde,</L>
<L N="380">&amp; brou&yogh;te for&thorn; afair sone. : glad &thorn;is gode man was!</L>
<L>he let &yogh;arki a fair coupe : to seint Nicholas.</L>
<L>So faire was &thorn;e coupe of golde : &thorn;o heo was &yogh;aru iwrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;is hosebonde heo was so leof : &thorn;at he nolde leue hire no&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="384">Ac athuld hire in his owe hous : him-silue &thorn;er-of to drinke;</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er to seint Nicholas : &thorn;e goldsmyth he let biswinke.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e coupe was ymaked : to &thorn;e louerd seint Nicholas,</L>
<L>he wiste hire wi&thorn; gret drueri : ac &thorn;o&thorn;er fairere was.</L>
<L N="388">&para; &THORN;o his sone was wel i-woxe : &amp; hadde stren&yogh;&thorn;e &amp; mi&yogh;te,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e pelgrimage of seint Nicholas : &thorn;is gode man him di&yogh;te,</L>
<L>&amp; nom wi&thorn; him his leoue sone : &amp; &thorn;e coupen beye,</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste, &thorn;at him was so leof : to serui him bi &thorn;e weye,</L>
<L N="392">&THORN;o&thorn;er, to ofri seint Nicholas : whan hi &thorn;ider come.</L>
<L>hi grei&thorn;ede hem a-godes name : &amp; &thorn;e holi wei hi nome.</L>
<L>&para; So &thorn;at hi come in &thorn;e see : as hi &thorn;ane wei wende.</L>
<L>After water of &thorn;e see : &thorn;is gode man his sone sende :</L>
<L N="396">"Fech me," he seide, "of &thorn;e water : in myn owene coupe!"</L>
<L>&THORN;at child dude his fader heste : &amp; to &thorn;e water gan stoupe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e coupe ful out of his hond : &amp; anon to grounde sonk;</L>
<L>&THORN;e child ful in afterward : &amp; in &thorn;e water adronk.</L>
<L N="400">Gret deol makede &thorn;is gode man : &thorn;o he se&yogh; &thorn;is cas,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he nadde bote &thorn;at o child : &amp; he adronke was.</L>
<L>"Awei," he seide,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at i<SUP>c</SUP> schal</NOTE> "&thorn;is dai abide! : leoue louerd, allas!
<PB REF="00000300.tif" N="252"></L>
<L>wel i<SUP>c</SUP> wot, i<SUP>c</SUP> haue agult : &thorn;e louerd seint Nicholas,</L>
<L N="404">&THORN;at i<SUP>c</SUP> bynom him &thorn;e furste coupe. : louerd, what schal i<SUP>c</SUP> do?</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore i<SUP>c</SUP> habbe ilore nou mi child : &amp; &thorn;e coupe also.</L>
<L>Seint Nicholas, for&yogh;if hit me : &amp; ynelle no&yogh;t bileue, iwis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ynelle siche &thorn;e : &thorn;e&yogh; me beo bifalle &thorn;is!"</L>
<L N="408">&para; &THORN;is gode man [him] wende for&thorn; : in deol &amp; sori &thorn;o&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Er he to seint Nicholas com : he neturnde a&yogh;e no&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he to &thorn;e weued com : &thorn;at he hadde wide iso&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;e coupe he offrede &thorn;erto : &thorn;at he hadde &thorn;ider ibro&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="412">&thorn;e coupe hipte anon a&yogh;e : he nolde astinte &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Ac hipte into &thorn;e flor : wreche as &thorn;e&yogh; hit were.</L>
<L>&THORN;is gode man hire nom vp : &amp; offrede hire eft &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Eftsone heo hipte fram &thorn;e weued : for&thorn;ere &thorn;an heo dude ere.</L>
<L N="416">&para; &THORN;o was &thorn;is gode man agrise : &amp; &thorn;o&thorn;ere aboute also.</L>
<L>"Louerd," he seide, "seint Nicholas : i<SUP>c</SUP> haue &thorn;e moche misdo.</L>
<L>Ich wolde offri &thorn;o&thorn;er coupe : ac ynemai &thorn;erto come :</L>
<L>vnderfong &thorn;us, if hit beo &thorn;i wille : for &thorn;o&thorn;er me is bynome.</L>
<L N="420">vnderfong &thorn;o&thorn;er of mi sone : for &thorn;u wost wher he is;</L>
<L>Let mi sone to &thorn;e offri &thorn;ulke : &amp; let me offri &thorn;is."&mdash;</L>
<L>For no hope of his sones lyf : &thorn;e gode man &thorn;is nesede,</L>
<L>Ac for he scholde his soule helpe : &amp; &thorn;e whatlokere do what he bede.&mdash;</L>
<L N="424">&para; Mid &thorn;is word &thorn;er com in : his sone, &thorn;at was adronke,</L>
<L>&amp; bar &thorn;e coupe on his hond : &thorn;at was mid him asonke;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e weued he &yogh;eode &amp; offrede : to seint Nicholas.</L>
<L>wele, louerd, &thorn;e grete ioye : &thorn;at of &thorn;e miracle was!</L>
<L N="428">Gladliche &thorn;e fader &amp; &thorn;e sone : here offring vp bere;<MILESTONE N="182" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; wende hom wi&thorn; gret ioye : &amp; leuede &thorn;e coupen &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&amp; herede moche seint Nicholas : as hi wel au&yogh;te, iwis.&mdash;</L>
<L>Meni is &thorn;e faire miracle : &thorn;at of seint Nicholas is!&mdash;</L>
<L N="432">&para; A gyw was while in a tyme : &thorn;at i-hurde meni o tale</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e miracles of seint Nicholas : &thorn;at he dude so fale.</L>
<L>So [&thorn;at], &thorn;e&yogh; he were a gyw : vpe him his hurte he caste,</L>
<L>&amp; honurede him ynou&yogh; : &amp; bi&thorn;o&yogh;te him atte laste :</L>
<L N="436">An ymage priueiliche he makede : of seint Nicholas</L>
<L>&amp; honurede hit in his hous : &thorn;o hit &yogh;are was.</L>
<L>&para; In a tyme hit biful : &thorn;at he hadde to done</L>
<L>In &thorn;e contrai &thorn;er-aboute : to come a&yogh;e wel sone.</L>
<L N="440">he nuste wham his god bitake : forte he a&yogh;e come :</L>
<L>Seint Nicholas ymage he bad : nyme &thorn;er-to gode gome.</L>
<L>"Ich &thorn;e habbe," he seide, "iloued ynou&yogh; : do me som god &thorn;erfore :
<PB REF="00000301.tif" N="253"></L>
<L>wite mi god forte i<SUP>c</SUP> come : &thorn;at hit ne beo forlore!</L>
<L N="444">For, bi seint Nicholas &thorn;at i<SUP>c</SUP> louie : if hit beo awei ibore</L>
<L>whan i<SUP>c</SUP> come a&yogh;e, &thorn;u schalt : sore abigge &thorn;erfore."</L>
<L>&THORN;e gyw wende for&thorn; his wei : &amp; tok al his god to wite</L>
<L>&THORN;e ymage, forte he come a&yogh;e : as hit is iwrite.</L>
<L N="448">Si&thorn;&thorn;e hit biful &thorn;at li&thorn;ere men : &amp; &thorn;eoues &thorn;er come<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Here L. goes on again.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And to<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE>-breken &thorn;e giwes hous : and is guod a-wei nome.<MILESTONE N="115" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e giv cam hom a-&yogh;ein : and miste al is gvod,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. good</NOTE></L>
<L>gret deol he made and seoruwe i-nov&yogh; : and ferde ase he were wod.</L>
<L N="452">to &thorn;ane ymage he wende a-non : ase he bi &thorn;e walle stod :</L>
<L>"Seie," he seide, "&yogh;wat hauest &thorn;ou i-do? : &thorn;ou hauest i-set harm a-brod.</L>
<L>Ich bi-tok &thorn;e to witene al mi guod : &thorn;at god lente me :</L>
<L>hit is nou&thorn;e al i-bore a-wei : and &thorn;at ich wite &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="456">&YOGH;wan ich it bi-tok &thorn;e in warde : and &thorn;ou were of pouste</L>
<L>to witen it wel, &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;ou woldest. : &thorn;are-fore &thorn;ou haue maugre.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 456-7 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &yogh;wane ich truste so muche to &thorn;e : and &thorn;ou noldest do mi bone,</L>
<L>bi ri&yogh;te lawe, ase ich &thorn;e bi-het : &thorn;ov schalt a-bugge sone,</L>
<L N="460">&YOGH;wane &thorn;ou &yogh;olde mine godhede : so vuele at&thorn;e laste."</L>
<L>harde scourgene he nam and stronge : and beot &thorn;is ymage wel faste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at grete peces borsten a-wei&mdash; : he ferde ase he were wod,</L>
<L>And euere he bad &thorn;at seli treo : bringue a&yogh;en is guod.</L>
<L N="464">Seint Nicholas &thorn;are-afterward sone : to &thorn;e &thorn;eoues wende,</L>
<L>Al for-woundet and to-drawe : ase &thorn;e giv him to-rende;</L>
<L>"Lo," he seide, "hov ich am for ov : I-woundet and for-gnawe,</L>
<L>blok and blodi, ase &yogh;e i-seoth : and al mi bodi to-drawe.</L>
<L>bringez a-&yogh;en, ich red ov, sone : &thorn;at &yogh;e habbez a-wei<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. a-&yogh;en</NOTE> i-bore</L>
<L>And istole of &thorn;e giwes guode : o&thorn;ur &yogh;e schulle hangi &thorn;are-fore.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 466-9 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L N="470">For-so&thorn;e i segge, &yogh;e schullen hangen : bote &yogh;e it hom anon lede,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e schullen some a-bugge with me : ouwer foule mis-dede."</L>
<L N="472">&THORN;eos &thorn;eoues weren sore of-dradde : heo nomen heom to rede</L>
<L>And ladden hom a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e giwes guod&mdash; : huy ne dorsten o&thorn;ur for drede,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. fere</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000302.tif" N="254"></L>
<L>And weren a-knowe of al hore gult : and &thorn;e Miracle him sede</L>
<L>hov seint Nicholas to heom cam : with is sidene blod-rede.</L>
<L N="476">&THORN;e giv, and &thorn;e &thorn;eues al-so : to seint Nicholas bede</L>
<L>&THORN;at he for-&yogh;eue heom heore gult : and nolden more don to quede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;eues bi-comen trewe men : and ne stelen neuereft more,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e giv him let cristny sone : and tok him al-to godes lore,</L>
<L N="480">And euereft more euerechone : loueden seint Nicholas.</L>
<L>Me &thorn;incheth, a-mong alle o&thorn;ere : a fair Miracle &thorn;at was!<NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 480-1 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; In ano&thorn;ur time a guod man was : &thorn;at hadde a clerk to sone;</L>
<L>Eche &yogh;ere he wolde for is loue : a-seint Nicholas dai bi wone</L>
<L N="484">Of manie clerkus gret feste holden : and wurthschipien<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> seint Nicholas al-so,</L>
<L>with offringue and seruise at churche : gret honur him do.</L>
<L>&THORN;e feond hadde &thorn;ar-to onde. : a dai he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. ase he</NOTE> cam &thorn;ere</L>
<L>A-seint Nicholas day to &thorn;e &yogh;ate : ase &thorn;ei it a beggare were,</L>
<L N="488">And bad, for seint Nicholas loue : &thorn;at man sum guod him<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. heom</NOTE> &yogh;eoue.</L>
<L>Anon so &thorn;at child wuste him &thorn;ere : he nolde no leng bi-leue</L>
<L>Ake bred he nam in is hond : &thorn;ane schrewe forto beode.</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;at child cam toward &thorn;e &yogh;ate : &thorn;e schrewe aweiward &yogh;eode;</L>
<L N="492">&THORN;at child eode euere after-ward : to &yogh;iuen him of &thorn;e brede,</L>
<L>Ake he &yogh;eode euere forth, ase it were : a-weiward &thorn;at child to lede :</L>
<L>And &thorn;o he cam in-to a derne stude : he bi-turnde him ate laste,<MILESTONE N="115b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ase it were to nime &thorn;at bred : and anon he nam wel faste</L>
<L>&THORN;at child bi is seli &thorn;rote<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;<SUP>r</SUP> ote</NOTE> : and a-stranglede him a-non;</L>
<L>&THORN;at child lai &thorn;are and deide sone : and &thorn;e schrewe a-wei gan gon.</L>
<L N="498">&THORN;e guode man, &thorn;o he miste is child : he sou&yogh;te it wel wide;</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;o he fond it ligge a-slawe : wel deolfulliche he cride.</L>
<L>"Louerd," he seide, "seint Nicholas : ich bidde &thorn;e milce and ore!</L>
<L>honoured ich &thorn;e habbe mani a dai : ant &yogh;eot ich hopie more,</L>
<L>And for anchaisun of mi sone : &thorn;e more, and for is lore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou me sendest Ioie of him : and schildest me fram sore :</L>
<L N="504">&YOGH;wi &yogh;elstov mine &yogh;wyle &thorn;us? : louerd, &yogh;wi dest &thorn;ou so?</L>
<L>hov mi&yogh;t&thorn;ou &thorn;us, seint Nicholas : for reu&thorn;e bi me do?</L>
<L>&YOGH;if me gladnesse of mi child : &thorn;at ich mote him a-liue i-seo,
<PB REF="00000303.tif" N="255"></L>
<L>And ich him bi-hote to &thorn;ine seruise : and &thorn;at he schal guod man beo."</L>
<L N="508">Ase he was &thorn;us in is beden : &thorn;at child a-ros op allone,</L>
<L>And herede god and seint Nicholas : a-mong heom euerechone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at him hadde lijf i-sent : for is fader bone &thorn;er;</L>
<L>And he tolde al-hou &thorn;e deuel hadde : him a-strangled er,</L>
<L>For al-so muche ase he honourede so : &thorn;ane guode seint Nicholas.</L>
<L N="513">&THORN;is, me &thorn;inchez, a-mong alle o&thorn;ere : a fair Miracle it was!</L>
<L>Louerd, [&thorn;at] for &thorn;e loue of seint Nicholas : mani Miracle hast i-do,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schild us fram &thorn;e pine of helle : and fram dedliche sunne also.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="38" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>38 Vita sancti Iuliani confessoris.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Iulian &thorn;e confessour : was i-bore at rome;</L>
<L>Muche folk &thorn;oru&yogh; is prechingue : cristine heo bi-come.</L>
<L>Of noble kunne he was i-come : and renable he was i-nou&yogh;;</L>
<L N="4">After &thorn;e Apostles he cam sone : and muche folk to guode dro&yogh;.</L>
<L>In-to a cite he was i-sent : &thorn;e prechour guod and trewe,</L>
<L>Ase a-postel for-to prechi : &thorn;e &yogh;wile cristinedom was newe.</L>
<L>Cristinedom was &thorn;o vnwur&thorn;e : in &thorn;ulke cite &thorn;ere :</L>
<L N="8">gret scorn heo hadden of alle &thorn;ulke : &thorn;at icristnede were,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at speken of cristinedom : heo defouleden heom i-nou&yogh;.</L>
<L>In Aunter him dude &thorn;is holie man : and &thorn;uder-ward &yogh;uyt him drou&yogh;,</L>
<L>And a-mong heom he cam wel mildeliche : and prechede faste a-non.</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;at folk drof to busemare : &thorn;e meste del ech-on;</L>
<L>Ake ore louerd sende him grace : and fair miracle for him wrou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at folk &thorn;oru&yogh; is prechingue : to cristinedom he brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Ore louerd him &yogh;af so fair grace : &thorn;at with one worde he mi&yogh;te</L>
<L N="16">helen Meoseles and guidie Men : and &thorn;e blinde &yogh;iuen heore si&yogh;te;</L>
<L>&THORN;are nas no-manere vuel : nou&yogh;wer &thorn;are he cam gon,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; &thorn;e vertue of &thorn;e croiz : &thorn;at he ne helde heom<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> a-non.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he tornede to cristine-dom : al &thorn;at folk &thorn;are-a-boute;</L>
<L N="20">And siweden him al-so in-to al &thorn;at lond : of heom wel grete route.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo comen in one stude : a-&thorn;urst heo weren wel sore;</L>
<L>heo nusten &yogh;ware to drinke come : it greuede heom ful sore :<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;e more</NOTE></L>
<L>heo criden alle on seint Iulian : &thorn;at he sum drinke heom founde.
<PB REF="00000304.tif" N="256"></L>
<L N="24">&THORN;is holie man nam op is staf : smot doun in-to &thorn;e grounde<MILESTONE N="116" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And pi&yogh;te &thorn;ane poynt a luyte in &thorn;e eor&thorn;e. : &thorn;are cam walle out a-non</L>
<L>&THORN;et beste water &thorn;at mi&yogh;te beo : a-mong heom euerech-on,</L>
<L>And fond heom alle drinke i-nou&yogh; : &thorn;are neuer er welle nas,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;oru&yogh; vertue of &thorn;is holie man&mdash; : fair miracle &thorn;are was!</L>
<L>So mani fair Miracle ore louerd dude : for loue of seint Iulian,</L>
<L>&THORN;at muche del of &thorn;at folk : heolden him a god a[nd] no man.</L>
<L>In godes seruise ate laste : his lijf he brou&yogh;te to ende</L>
<L N="32">And a luyte bi-fore candel-masse : to heouene he gan i-wende,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e latere ende of Ieneuer : &thorn;is confessour so hende.</L>
<L>Nou god for is swete loue : us &thorn;udere alle sende.&mdash;</L>
<L>An o&thorn;ur seint Iulian &thorn;are is : &thorn;at men biddeth wel faste</L>
<L N="36">After guod .In. in onecouth stude : &yogh;wane heo beoth sore a-gaste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>Vita sancti Iuliani boni hospitis.</HEAD>
<L>SEint Iulian &thorn;e guode herebeger : of noble kuynde com;</L>
<L>stalewarde and strong man he was : and louede wel cristin|dom;</L>
<L>he louede al-so game i-nou&yogh; : of hauekes and of houndes&mdash;</L>
<L N="4">A noblere bodi &thorn;ane he was : nou&yogh;were nas non i-founde.</L>
<L>Ase he hountede In a dai : In Iolifte j-nou&yogh;,</L>
<L>A swy&thorn;e fair heort he i-sai&yogh; : and &thorn;are-after faste he drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>he strenc&thorn;ede him to nime &thorn;at best : and siwede after faste.</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;o &thorn;is heort hadde longe I-orne : he bi-turnde him ate laste,</L>
<L>And spak with him, ase god it wolde : "Iulian, Iulian," he sede,</L>
<L>"&YOGH;wi siweste me so faste?" he seide : "&thorn;ou schalt don ano&thorn;ur dede :</L>
<L>bo&thorn;e &thorn;i fader and &thorn;i moder : &thorn;ou schalt &yogh;eot a-quelle.</L>
<L N="12">Ake ne beo &thorn;ou no-&thorn;e wro&thorn;ure with me : &thorn;ei ich it &thorn;e telle."</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is guode man &thorn;is i-heorde : him bi-gan wondri, and drede,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at wilde best so spack : and for wordes &thorn;at he sede;</L>
<L>him wondrede, ase him mi&yogh;te wel : for it spak a-&yogh;ein kuynde,</L>
<L>he was a-ferd for &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1">superscribed.</NOTE> he him bi-het : and ofte it hadde in muynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he scholde fader and moder sle. : And to fleo &thorn;at dede,</L>
<L N="18">he wende out of contreie stilledliche : ase god him wolde lede.</L>
<L>Into feorrene contreie he wende. : so &thorn;at he cam bi cas
<PB REF="00000305.tif" N="257"></L>
<L N="20">to a gret prince of a lond : and in seruice wiz him was.</L>
<L>So wel he paide is louerd in Armes : and in alle o&thorn;ur dedes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he made him maister of is ferd : al for-to gwie and lede;</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e he made him we<SUP>d</SUP>di wijf : riche and noble al-so,</L>
<L>A lauedi of a gret contreie<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> castel gret</NOTE> : and of grete moru&yogh;iue al-so.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &THORN;erto</NOTE></L>
<L>bi-twene him and is guode lauedie : loue &thorn;are was i-nov&yogh;;</L>
<L N="26">For to alle guodness bi heore mi&yogh;te : ey&thorn;ur to o&thorn;ur drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Ake is guode fader and is Moder : &thorn;at he bi-lefte him atom bi-hinde,</L>
<L N="28">Swy&thorn;e sorie weren for heore sone : &thorn;at heo ne mi&yogh;ten him nou&yogh;wer finde.</L>
<L>heo wenden forth in atyme bo&thorn;e : and sou&yogh;ten him wel wide,</L>
<L>Fram o contreie to o&thorn;ur faste : a-boute in eche side.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo i-heorden of him tellen : &thorn;ei it were longue.</L>
<L>to is castel huy drowen heom a-non : and faire weren onder-fongue :</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="116b" UNIT="folio">heo ne founden nou&yogh;t him-seo[l]f athom : ake is wijf, heo was &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="34">Fair semblaunt heo made heom : &thorn;o heo wuste &yogh;wat heo were!</L>
<L>heo honourede heom &thorn;e more : for hire louerd ne was nou&yogh;t &thorn;are,</L>
<L>And leide heom in heore owene bed : and hire-seolf lay elles-&yogh;ware.</L>
<L>A-morewe, are hit were dai : heo a-ros op wel softe</L>
<L N="38">And to churche &yogh;eode wel stilleliche : ase heo was i-woned ofte.</L>
<L>&THORN;o cam hire louerd hom : In &thorn;e moreweningue sone,</L>
<L N="40">And drou&yogh; him to chaumbre toward is bed : ase he was i-woned to done.</L>
<L>&THORN;o i-heorde he wel softe slepe : and swei&yogh;en &thorn;ar-inne tweie,</L>
<L>Ase Men and wommen nede moten : &thorn;at beoth werie of weie.</L>
<L>he &yogh;eode ner and i-sai&yogh; &thorn;are ligge : Man and womman al-so.</L>
<L N="44">"&YOGH;e," &thorn;ou&yogh;te he, "&thorn;is is mi wijf : and sum gering is i-comen hire to;</L>
<L>I seo wel nou&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;e hore : is i-wonet here-to.</L>
<L>huy ne schullen neuereft ete mete : ne more schame me do."</L>
<L>he slou&yogh; is fader and is moder : mid is swerde &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="48">And wende bi heom &thorn;at is wijf : and hire horeling it were.</L>
<L>Wel softe he &yogh;eode out a&yogh;ein : &thorn;o &thorn;is dede was i-do,</L>
<L>And &yogh;eode him toward churche : And tuynde &thorn;e dore to.</L>
<L>Ase he toward churche was : his wijf hamward he mette.
<PB REF="00000306.tif" N="258"></L>
<L>"Louerd, merci," he &thorn;ou&yogh;te, "hou is &thorn;is?" : with gret wonder he ire grette;</L>
<L>"Dame," he seide, "hou goth &thorn;is? : &yogh;wat dost &thorn;ou nou&thorn;e here?</L>
<L>ho liggez in ore bedde athom : Man and womman i-fere?"</L>
<L>"A, sire," quath &thorn;is guode leuedi : "wel glad mi&yogh;t &thorn;ou beo,</L>
<L N="56">I-hered beo ore louerdes grace : &thorn;at &thorn;ov most &thorn;is day i-seo :</L>
<L>&THORN;i fader and &thorn;i moder it is : &thorn;at wide &thorn;e habbez i-sou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>I-hered beo ore louerdes sonde : &thorn;at hidere heom hath i-brou&yogh;t!</L>
<L>Leoue sire, hi&yogh;e &thorn;e hom : &thorn;ou schal<SUP>t</SUP> heom faire a-fonge</L>
<L N="60">And make with heom Ioie i-nou&yogh; : me &thorn;inchez er wel longe."</L>
<L>"Nai, certes," quath &thorn;is Iulian &thorn;o : "&yogh;if &thorn;at it is so,</L>
<L>Al mi blisse of &thorn;usse liue : and mi Ioye is al i-do.</L>
<L>Alas &thorn;at ich habbe &thorn;us longe i-leoued : &thorn;at i-ne hadde er i-beo ded!</L>
<L N="64">habbe ich a-slawe fader an Moder! : louerd, &yogh;wat mai beo mi-red?</L>
<L>Al-to soth me seide &thorn;at wilde best : alas &thorn;ulke stounde;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei ich habbe i-folewed<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> i-flowe</NOTE> his bi-heste : &thorn;e so&thorn;e ich habbe i-founde.</L>
<L>haue nou&thorn;e, dame, wel guod day : for i-nelle habbe no reste</L>
<L N="68">Er ich habbe mine penaunce ido&mdash; : god leue me don mi beste."</L>
<L>"A, sire, merci," seide is wijf : "&yogh;ware-fore seist&thorn;ou so!</L>
<L>Sikerliche &thorn;ou schalt athom bi-leue : and &thorn;ine penaunce do."</L>
<L>"beo stille, dame," Iulian seide : "&thorn;ou spext al embe nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="72">certes, I-nelle neuere a-stunte : are ich me habbe of londe i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Ake haue guod dai, mi treowe spouse : and god &thorn;e leue wel do;</L>
<L>led clene lijf; and bide for me : for I-ne wene neuere come &thorn;e to."</L>
<L>"Alas," seide &thorn;is guode wijf : "sire, &yogh;wi seist&thorn;ou so!</L>
<L>&YOGH;if god wole, &thorn;e &yogh;wyle we a-liue beoth : ne schulle we departi atwo;</L>
<L N="77">bote &thorn;ou wolle bi-&thorn;enche &thorn;e bet : And at hom bi-leue here,</L>
<L>Certes, &yogh;wodere &thorn;ou euere i-wenst : i-chulle beo &thorn;i fere<MILESTONE N="117" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And parti with &thorn;e of &thorn;i wo : ase ich dude er of &thorn;i blis&mdash;</L>
<L>For ho-so deth &thorn;at on, he schal &thorn;at o&thorn;ur : &thorn;ou wost wel &thorn;at ri&yogh;t it is."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Is guode Man and is trewe wijf : wel stille forth heo i-wende</L>
<L>And leten lond and leode : and al &thorn;at god heom sende.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo wenden feor and longue : &thorn;at at&thorn;e laste heo come</L>
<L N="84">to a deop watur and perilous : &thorn;are Men a-dreinten i-lome.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode Men [a-stynte<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. adreinten <I>expunged</I>, a stynte <I>by a later hand</I>.</NOTE>] &thorn;er : and leten heom sone a-rere</L>
<L>A luytel hous&mdash;bote hit was guod i-nou&yogh;&mdash; : bi-side &thorn;e watere &thorn;ere.
<PB REF="00000307.tif" N="259"></L>
<L>Alle Men &thorn;at &thorn;are-forth comen : And with-oute he[r]borewe were,</L>
<L N="88">he fond heom hereborewe, guod i-nou&yogh; : &thorn;at with-oute none nere,</L>
<L>bed and clo&thorn;es guode i-nowe : and wel aysiliche heom di&yogh;te;</L>
<L>heore fet he wuchs and ba&thorn;ede heom : and duden<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> dude</NOTE> al &thorn;at heo mi&yogh;te&mdash;</L>
<L>For is fader soule and for is moder : he dude al &thorn;is dede;</L>
<L N="92">he bad alle &thorn;at to him come : &thorn;at for heore soulene huy bede.</L>
<L>he porueide him of a schip : and ouer &thorn;e watere ladde</L>
<L>euer[e]ch tyme, dai&yogh; and ny&yogh;t : alle &thorn;at to him gradde&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;are-with he swonk sore i-nou&yogh; : of noman ne tok he nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="96">&YOGH;wane he hadde ani miseise man : ouer &thorn;e watere i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>he ne let him nou&yogh;t fram him gon : are huy<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. he</NOTE> a-mendede were :</L>
<L>he ladde heom in-to is house a-non : and aisede heom swi&thorn;e wel &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Al heo duden<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. he dude</NOTE> for-to bete &thorn;e sunne : of &thorn;at cas &thorn;at him bi-tidde,</L>
<L>For is fader soule and is Moder : and bad Men for heom bidde.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore Men &yogh;eot to &thorn;is day : &thorn;at ouer lond doth i-wende,</L>
<L>heo biddeth to seint Iulian faste : &thorn;at he guod .In. heom sende;</L>
<L>And seint Iulianes pater-noster : ofte heo seggez al-so</L>
<L N="104">For is fader soule and is Moder : &thorn;at he bringue heom &thorn;ar-to.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is holie Man seint Iulian : In &thorn;is trauail hadde<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. hadden</NOTE> i-beo longe</L>
<L>And mani Miseise Man in is hous : wel loueliche vnder fonge,</L>
<L>A day, ase he hadde i-beo : in trauaile strong i-nou&yogh;,</L>
<L N="108">Ase ladde &thorn;is men ouer : and into is Inne heom drou&yogh;,</L>
<L>And a-&yogh;ein middel ny&yogh;t to is bed : &yogh;eode at&thorn;en ende,</L>
<L>For-to habbe sum reste &thorn;ere : &yogh;if ore louerd it wolde him sende :</L>
<L N="111">At&thorn;e mid-ny&yogh;t, ase he bi-gan : sum-del reste a-fongue,</L>
<L>A &yogh;eond half &thorn;e watere &thorn;are cam on : in grete forste and strongue :</L>
<L>"A-ris, Iulian, a-non," he gradde : "hider-ward &thorn;ou most go</L>
<L>And bringue me ouer &thorn;is watere sone : o&thorn;ur ich dei&yogh;e for wo."</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode man heorde sone &thorn;is : and &thorn;ei he weri were,</L>
<L N="116">he wende to &thorn;is seli man : and ladde him ouer &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at he was onne&thorn;e a-liue : for he was al ouer-come,</L>
<L>Mid chele and mid o&thorn;ur wo : is limes him weren bi-nome;</L>
<L>A lodlich musel he &thorn;ou&yogh;te al-so : and &thorn;e fouleste &thorn;at mi&yogh;te beo&mdash;</L>
<L N="120">A Miseisiore man &thorn;ane he &thorn;ou&yogh;te : no man ne mi&yogh;te iseo.</L>
<L>Seint Iuliane ladde &thorn;is seli man : In-to is house bi ni&yogh;te</L>
<L>And fondede to maken him an-Ayse : bi al is trewe mi&yogh;te :
<PB REF="00000308.tif" N="260"></L>
<L><MILESTONE N="117b" UNIT="folio">gret fuyr he dude him makien and guod : &thorn;at he were of chele i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And leide [him] &thorn;are-bi wel softe&mdash; : ake al it was for nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;o he ne mi&yogh;te with fuyre him hete : ne with none o&thorn;ur ginne,</L>
<L>his owene bed he let faire spreden : and brou&yogh;te him &thorn;are-Inne;</L>
<L>clo&thorn;es i-nowe opon him he spradde : and helede<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. holede (corr.?)</NOTE> him wel faste.</L>
<L N="128">&YOGH;eot he &thorn;ou&yogh;te ful sore of cale : for al &thorn;at he on him caste.</L>
<L>Swy&thorn;e sori was &thorn;is guode man : and sore him a-gaste,</L>
<L>&THORN;o he him dude al &thorn;at he mi&yogh;te : and &thorn;e chele so longe i-laste.</L>
<L>he stod and bi-heold &thorn;is selie man : a Musel ase he wende :</L>
<L N="132">Sone so ore louerd it wolde : is hev&yogh; bi-gan a-mende,</L>
<L>At&thorn;e laste he werth so fair a man : ase euere any mi&yogh;te beo,</L>
<L>And so cler he bi-cam sone : &thorn;at vnne&thorn;es men mi&yogh;ten him seo.</L>
<L>"Iulian," he seide, "god it &thorn;e &yogh;elde : &thorn;at &thorn;ou me hast i-do!</L>
<L N="136">In ore louerdes erinde of heuene : i-come ich am &thorn;e to :</L>
<L>Ore louerd &thorn;e sente word bi me : &thorn;at &thorn;ou art clanliche i-schriue</L>
<L>And &thorn;ine penaunce hast wel i-do : and &thorn;ine sunnes beoth for-&yogh;iue;</L>
<L>Swy&thorn;e wel &thorn;ou him hast i-paid : &thorn;ou and &thorn;i wijf al-so,</L>
<L N="140">And bo&thorn;e &yogh;e schullen with alle Ioye : newene come him to."</L>
<L>&THORN;o he hadde &thorn;is word i-seid : he nuste &yogh;ware he bi-cam.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode man seint Iulian : to godes seruise him nam</L>
<L>And to his bi-hof&thorn;e him makede al-&yogh;are : he and is wijf al-so.</L>
<L N="144">Sone after-ward in his seruise : heo deiden bo&thorn;e-to</L>
<L>And wenden to &thorn;e blisse of heuene : &thorn;are heo schullen euere beo.</L>
<L>guod it is to hereborewi Miseise men : bi heom &thorn;at men mowen i-seo,</L>
<L>For &thorn;are-with &thorn;is holie man : his sunnes bette inou&yogh;,</L>
<L>And a gret haluwe in heouene he is : &thorn;ei he fader and moder a-slou&yogh;.</L>
<L N="149">bidde we &yogh;eorne sein Iulian : &thorn;at he ore erinde beode</L>
<L>&THORN;at ore louerd us &yogh;iue milce and ore : and alle &thorn;at habbez neode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;wanne we o&thorn;ur any cristine man : ouer lond schullen wende,</L>
<L>For is fader soule and is moder : &thorn;at he guod hereborewe us sende,</L>
<L>And at&thorn;e laste &thorn;oru&yogh; godes wille : &thorn;at we moten teo</L>
<L N="154">Into &thorn;e blisse of heuene : and &thorn;are with-outen ende beo.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="39" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>39 Vita sancte Marie Egiptiace.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEinte Marie egyptiane : In egypte was i-bore;</L>
<L>Al hire &yogh;ounge lijf heo liuede : in sunne and in hore.
<PB REF="00000309.tif" N="261"></L>
<L>Vnne&thorn;e heo was tweolf &yogh;er old : are heo dude folie :</L>
<L N="4">hire bodi and al hire wille heo dude : to sunne of lecherie.</L>
<L>&THORN;aron heo hadde so gret delijt : &thorn;at in hire owene londe</L>
<L>heo ne mi&yogh;te fulfulle hire owene wille<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> al hire</NOTE> : &thorn;o bi-gan heo hire vnder|stonde,</L>
<L>heo wende into Alisaundrie : and &thorn;are heo wonede longue.</L>
<L N="8">Alle &thorn;at bi hire ligge wolden : gladliche he dude a-fongue;</L>
<L>heo ne sparede leinte ne o&thorn;ur tyme : preost ne o&thorn;ur non,</L>
<L>riche ne pouere, ne o&thorn;ur<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> weddede men : &thorn;at heo ne let to hire gon.</L>
<L>Men &thorn;at ne hadden none wille : swuch sunne forto do,</L>
<L>with faire wordes and fol semblaunt : heo brou&yogh;te heom ofte<MILESTONE N="118" UNIT="folio"> &thorn;er-to;</L>
<L>&THORN;are nas man in no mester : so gleu ne so quoynte</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE>&THORN;at heo nas to bringue men to sunne : wel prestore in eche poynte.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ulke dede heo ne tok : of no man mede ne wunne&mdash;</L>
<L N="16">for non ne scholde for defaute : bi-leue &thorn;e foule sunne;</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur any<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> mede bote hire foule wille : heo kepte of no man;</L>
<L>with spinningue and with seuwingue : hire liflode heo wan.</L>
<L>hit is sun<SUP>n</SUP>e and schame to ani man : to &thorn;enche o&thorn;ur to wite</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;e fuyl&thorn;e of &thorn;e wrechche sunnes : &thorn;at we findeth of hire i-write.</L>
<L>For to hire-sulue one heo seide : &thorn;at schame it was to huyre,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wa&thorn;ur ani womman euere on eor&thorn;e were : so sunful a creature;</L>
<L>hit was wonder &thorn;at &thorn;e eor&thorn;e i-opened nadde : ase heo hire-sulf gan telle,</L>
<L>And i-swoluwe hire ase heo &thorn;ar-on &yogh;eode : into &thorn;e putte of helle.&mdash;</L>
<L N="25">In Alisaundrie heo liuede &thorn;is foule lijf : &yogh;eres seuentene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at so muche vildede of womman : nas neuere i-sei&yogh;e, ich wene.</L>
<L>On a day in heruest : as &thorn;is womman bi-heold a-boute,</L>
<L N="28">bi &thorn;e wei&yogh;e heo sai&yogh; muche folk : and manie grete route.</L>
<L>heo &thorn;ou&yogh;te, for heo was so i-knowe : in Alisaundrie in euer-eche ende,</L>
<L>&THORN;e lasse sockne heo hadde of hire folie : &thorn;annes heo wolde i-wende;</L>
<L N="31">heo &thorn;ou&yogh;te, "a-mong &thorn;is straunge men : so fale ase ich i-seo,</L>
<L>Mi wille ich mi&yogh;te muche of heom habbe : with heom i-chulle beo."</L>
<L>A-mong heom heo cam and axede heom : &yogh;wodere huy alle &thorn;ou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>heo seiden, heo wolden to Ierusalem : for &thorn;e swete rode heo sou&yogh;ten</L>
<L>&THORN;at scholde op-on &thorn;e holie rode-day : eche manne i-schewed beo,
<PB REF="00000310.tif" N="262"></L>
<L N="36">And &thorn;at euer-ech guod man &thorn;udere wolde : for-to honouri &thorn;at swete treo.</L>
<L>"Mot ich," seide &thorn;is womman : "with eov &thorn;udere wende?</L>
<L>And of &thorn;at craft &thorn;at ich i-leorned habbe : to eov ichulle beon prest and hende."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e," seide on of heom, "hast&thorn;ou &yogh;warof : to a-quiti &thorn;i schip-huyre,</L>
<L N="40">A-mendet worth muche ore compaygnie : for swuch a creature."</L>
<L>"Non o&thorn;ur Moneye," heo seide, "ich ne habbe : bote mi-self her :</L>
<L>Ichulle beo corteis of &thorn;at ich habbe : a&yogh;ein &thorn;e mariner;</L>
<L>to him, and to eov al-so : so prest i-chulle beon and hende,</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at hit ne schal for-&thorn;unche ov nou&yogh;t : &thorn;ei ich with eov wende."</L>
<L>&THORN;is womman wende forth with &thorn;is men : In muche sunne, alas!</L>
<L>to alle &thorn;at with hire sunegy wolde : euere redi heo was.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo cam to &thorn;e se : at&thorn;e furste &thorn;ingue</L>
<L N="48">heo &yogh;af &thorn;e Marinere hire bodi : ouer &thorn;e se forto bringue;</L>
<L>to &thorn;e Mariner, and to alle his : &thorn;at in &thorn;e schipe were,</L>
<L>I-redi heo was forto sunegun with : alas, heo nadde none fere.</L>
<L>Iesu, muche is &thorn;i merci : and muche &thorn;ou &thorn;oledest &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;at water o&thorn;ur schip wolde heom bere : &thorn;at heo a-dreinte nere!&mdash;</L>
<L>bi-fore &thorn;e holie rode-day : to Ierusalem heo cam.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at folie wolden do : gladliche to hure heo nam.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e holie rode-day was i-come : &thorn;at men scheoweden &thorn;at swete treo,</L>
<L N="56">Mani on to &thorn;e temple eoden : &thorn;e rode forto seo.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Marie was with &thorn;e o&thorn;ere : to &thorn;e temple-dore i-come,<MILESTONE N="118b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Anne fot heo ne mi&yogh;te &thorn;are-Inne go : hire mi&yogh;te was hire al bi-nome;</L>
<L>hire &thorn;ou&yogh;te, &yogh;wane heo wolde In go : &thorn;at sum man hire a-&yogh;en-drou&yogh;.<SUP>1</SUP></L>
<L>For heo fram alle o&thorn;ere stod with-oute : of-schamed heo was j-nou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eot heo wolde in-ward go : and hire &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at men a-&yogh;en hire pulte.</L>
<L>heo weop for scame, and hire bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te : &thorn;at it was for grete gulte.</L>
<L>In-to one huyrne heo wende al one : fram hire ferene alle.</L>
<L N="64">heo i-sai&yogh; &thorn;e fourme of ore leuedi : depeint &thorn;are on &thorn;e walle :</L>
<L>heo weop and ful a-doun a-kneo : and seide : "leuedi, &thorn;in ore!</L>
<L>Sunful womman ich habbe i-beo : so nelle ich neuere-eft more;</L>
<L>&THORN;e sunnes &thorn;at ich habbe i-do : heo me reweth sore :</L>
<L N="68">&YOGH;if me grace heom for-to bete : &thorn;oru&yogh; holie churche lore,</L>
<L>And &yogh;if me grace in to go : &thorn;e swete rode forto seo :
<PB REF="00000311.tif" N="263"></L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; grace of hire and of &thorn;e : &thorn;e betere womman i schal beo.</L>
<L N="71">here ich for-sake mi sunful lijf : and alle mine lu&thorn;ere dede,</L>
<L>In clenesse<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. clanesse</NOTE> and in penaunce i-chulle : mi lijf here-afturward lede."</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo hadde to &thorn;ulke ymage : longue i-crid and i-bede,</L>
<L>Mildeliche, with careful heorte : heo eode fram &thorn;ulke stude</L>
<L>And eode hire to &thorn;e temple dore : ac &yogh;uyt heo was sore of-drad.</L>
<L N="76">With-oute lettingue In heo &yogh;eode&mdash; : welle, &thorn;at heo was &thorn;o bli&thorn;e and glad!</L>
<L>heo &yogh;eode In bi-fore &thorn;e rode : and &thorn;o heo hire mi&yogh;te i-seo,</L>
<L>Sore wepinde heo cride on hire : and feol a-doun a-kneo,</L>
<L>And bad for-&yogh;yuenesse of hire sunnes : &thorn;e rode, &thorn;at was so swete;</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;e worldes blisse &thorn;are heo for-sok : hire sunnes for-to bete;</L>
<L>Ofte heo custe &thorn;e pauement : &thorn;are &thorn;e rode hadde on i-stonde.</L>
<L>to ore lauedie ymage heo wende a&yogh;en : weopinde and wrong hire honde.</L>
<L>&THORN;are mi&yogh;te ech man deol i-seo : ho-so of pite cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="84">Of deol and soruwe &thorn;at heo made : with heorte and with mou&thorn;e.</L>
<L>heo bad ore leuedi &thorn;at heo hire tei&yogh;te : &yogh;if it were hire wille,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ware heo mi&yogh;te hire sunnes bete : priueliche and stille.</L>
<L>heo ne sai&yogh; no man, ake a uoiz heo heorde : &thorn;at &thorn;is word to hire sede :</L>
<L N="88">"&THORN;e flum Iordan &thorn;ou schalt passi : and in pays &thorn;i lijf lede."</L>
<L>heo &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;e wordes weren to hire iseid : al for hire guode;</L>
<L>heo a-ros and &thorn;onkede ore leuedi &yogh;eorne : and &thorn;e swete holie rode.</L>
<L>bi-for &thorn;e none heo wende : toward &thorn;e flum Iordan,</L>
<L N="92">biddinde hire beden. &thorn;o gan heo i-mete : In &thorn;e wey a man,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;af hire &thorn;reo rounde panes : and heo nuste &yogh;ware he bi-cam.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-with heo bou&yogh;te hire &thorn;reo loues : and forth with hire heom nam.</L>
<L>&para; Heo cam to &thorn;e watere : a luytel are hit were eue.</L>
<L N="96">In seint Iohanes chapele &thorn;e baptist : al &thorn;e ni&yogh;t heo gan bi-leue.</L>
<L>heo let hire schriue and hoseli also : swy&thorn;e wel &thorn;oru godes grace,</L>
<L>And with &thorn;e watur of &thorn;e flum Iordan : heo wusch hire in &thorn;at place.</L>
<L>A-morewe heo carf ane lof atwo : and et &thorn;at haluen-del,</L>
<L N="100">Of &thorn;e flum heo dronk &thorn;er-to : and made hire a murie mel.</L>
<L>Heo wende into wildernesse : ouer &thorn;e flum Iordan :</L>
<L>&THORN;are heo liuede mani a &yogh;er : &thorn;at heo ne sai&yogh; best ne man.</L>
<L>&THORN;e tweie loues and &thorn;e halue lof : &thorn;at heo with hire nam,
<PB REF="00000312.tif" N="264"></L>
<L N="104">bi-come so harde so ani ston : &thorn;o heo ouer &thorn;e watere cam :<MILESTONE N="119" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;are-bi he liuede in wildernesse : &yogh;eres seuentene.</L>
<L>hire clo&thorn;es roteden and feollen hire fram : clout mele in &thorn;e grene.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eot heo leouede twenti &yogh;er : after &thorn;e seuentene bi-fore</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;at heo ne et no mannische mete : bote weodes and wilde more.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;wyle hire loues i-lasten : heo was ofte and sore</L>
<L>I-fondet of hire hote flesch : &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e feondes lore :</L>
<L>hire longede after mete and drinke : and aftur o&thorn;ur wede,</L>
<L N="112">And on lecherie heo &thorn;ou&yogh;te muche : ase heo hire-sulf sede;</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;o heo ne et nou&yogh;t bote weodes and mores : of alle &thorn;e twenti &yogh;er,</L>
<L>Enes heo nas of hire flesch : i-fondet ase heo was er,</L>
<L>Of mete ne of drinke ne of folie : of hete ne of colde;</L>
<L N="116">heo ne &thorn;ou&yogh;te on no-&thorn;ing bote on god : ase hire-sulfue tolde.</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e seuene-and-&thorn;ritti &yogh;er : &thorn;at heo leouede &thorn;ere</L>
<L>heo ne sai&yogh; no&thorn;ur best ne man. : bote in &thorn;e sixe-and-&thorn;ritti&thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L>A Monuk cam to hire, are heo deide : as &thorn;e bok us doth lere&mdash;</L>
<L>For ore louerd wolde &thorn;at hire lijf : a-mong Men i-kud were.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AN<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. SN</NOTE> Abbeye &thorn;are was in paleis<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. palestine?</NOTE> : of ordre swi&thorn;e strongue;</L>
<L N="122">heore &yogh;at was swi&thorn;e faste i-mad : &thorn;oru&yogh; al &thorn;e &yogh;ere longue,</L>
<L>For no Monuk ne scholde gon out &thorn;ar-of : &thorn;e worldes weole to seo :</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;ene furste sonenday of leinte : &thorn;at &yogh;at scholde i-opened beo,</L>
<L>For ech Monek scholde &thorn;at ilke day : beon i-hoseled and i-schriue,</L>
<L>ech Monek scholde o&thorn;eres blessingue afongue : and euerech to o&thorn;ur it &yogh;iue,</L>
<L>And wenden al one in-to wi[l]dernesse : and<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> euer-ech in is ende,</L>
<L>to bieten heore sunnes; ake huy scholden : alle at ester hom wende.</L>
<L>On holi man was &thorn;are-inne : is name was frere Zosime,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wel and treoweliche is ordre heold : ase bi-feol to euerech time.</L>
<L>Sone so &thorn;at &yogh;at was vndo : and &thorn;at &thorn;e leinte com,</L>
<L N="132">he wente forth &thorn;ene wei : toward &thorn;e flum Iordan.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he &thorn;at watur i-passed hadde : feor he wende and longue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne sai&yogh; no&thorn;er best ne man : confort of to fongue;</L>
<L>Twenti dai&yogh;es &thorn;ar-inne he &yogh;eode : ake euere hope he hadde</L>
<L N="136">&THORN;at ore louerd wolde him some Miracle schewen : and no drede he nadde.</L>
<L>&THORN;ene twenti&thorn;e dai a-boute noon : a-kneo he sat a-doun,
<PB REF="00000313.tif" N="265"></L>
<L>he tornede him estward ase he was i-woned : and seide is oresoun :</L>
<L>On is ri&yogh;t side him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he sai&yogh; : in a wonder<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> wilde</NOTE> stude and derne</L>
<L N="140">Ase &thorn;ei it a mannes schadewe were : ligge al plat in one huyrne.</L>
<L>he wende it were sum foul wi&yogh;t : and blessede him a-non.</L>
<L>&THORN;o bi-cam he hardiore in godes name : and &thorn;are-ner he gan gon.</L>
<L>him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at hit a womman was : naked, and swi&thorn;e broun,</L>
<L N="144">Ase heo was with &thorn;e sonne i-brent : al plat heo lai a-doun;</L>
<L>hire her was hor and swi&thorn;e &yogh;wij&yogh;t : as &thorn;ei it were wolle,</L>
<L>&THORN;unne and schort, &thorn;at it mi&yogh;te : onne&thorn;e helie hire scholle.</L>
<L>&THORN;o was &thorn;is Monek swi&thorn;e glad&mdash; : for he nadde nanne Man</L>
<L N="148">I-sei&yogh;en, seth&thorn;e he i-passed hadde : &thorn;at watur of flum Iordan.</L>
<L>toward &thorn;is womman he &yogh;eode : and &thorn;is womman up a-ros,<MILESTONE N="119b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>estward heo gan eorne bliue&mdash; : &thorn;e Monek ful sore a-gros.</L>
<L>Na&thorn;eles he orn euere aftur hire : ake &thorn;is womman was euere bi-fore;</L>
<L N="152">&THORN;e Monek so weri nas of orne : neuere seth&thorn;e he was i-bore.</L>
<L>"Abijd," he seide, "&yogh;wi fleu&yogh;st&thorn;ou me : &thorn;at am with-oute mi&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Old and feble? ne dred &thorn;e nou&yogh;t : &thorn;at ich with &thorn;e wulle fi&yogh;te!"</L>
<L>&YOGH;eot nolde &thorn;is womman with him speke : Ake gan<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;o gan he</NOTE> to weope sore.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">2 vv. om. here</NOTE></L>
<L N="156">"haue reu&thorn;e of me and spek sum-&yogh;wat : with me of godes lore,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou art a-godes half : womman of flesch and felle;</L>
<L>Ich coiuri &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ov a-bide : and of &thorn;i stat me telle."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is womman bi-gan &thorn;o for-to speke : "Frere Zosime, &thorn;in ore," he sede,</L>
<L>"Ne wilne &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t &thorn;at ich &thorn;e a-bide : for ich am with-oute wede;</L>
<L>Ne wilne &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t &thorn;at ich schewie &thorn;e : o&thorn;ur wummen forto schende,</L>
<L>Mi licame, for ich naked am : ake lat me a-wei fram &thorn;e wende."</L>
<L>&THORN;is Monek weop and cride &yogh;eorne : nolde he stunte nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="164">For heo is name nemde so : he was a-ferd in is &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;is womman seide, "&yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt : i-wite &yogh;wat ich beo,</L>
<L>Cast me sum &thorn;ing to helie<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. holie; r. heolie?</NOTE> me with : and on oresun bide for me!"</L>
<L>With guode heorte &thorn;is Monuk hire caste : A luytel wede &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="168">&YOGH;ware-with to helie hire derne limes. : and to him heo gan go,</L>
<L>And seide, "Frere Zosime, &yogh;wi wilnest&thorn;ou : a sunfol wrechche to seo?</L>
<L>graunte me &thorn;at ich mote : in &thorn;ine beden beo."</L>
<L>&THORN;is Monek ful a-doun a-kne : and heo a-&yogh;ein him al-so,
<PB REF="00000314.tif" N="266"></L>
<L N="172">And ey&thorn;er bad o&thorn;ures blessingue : and no&thorn;ur nolde it do.</L>
<L>Ase heo leien longue to-gadere : bi-twene heom o&thorn;ur word huy ne sede</L>
<L>bote "blesse &thorn;u me," "ake blesse &thorn;ou me"&mdash; : &thorn;e Monek swatte for drede.</L>
<L N="175">&THORN;o seide &thorn;is womman, "i-blessed be god : &thorn;at bringueth &thorn;e soule bote."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e," seide &thorn;e Monek, "god us graunti : &thorn;at we &thorn;arof parti mote."</L>
<L>&THORN;is womman, &thorn;o heo weren a-rise : to &thorn;e Moneke sone heo sede :</L>
<L>"Frere Zosyme, ho gan &thorn;e hidere : to a swuch wrechche lede?</L>
<L N="179">hou is &thorn;e stat of holi churche : i-loked, and cristine-dom,</L>
<L>And hou is it of &thorn;e he&thorn;ene prince : &thorn;at heore ri&yogh;tes heom bi-nam?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"LEoue Moder," &thorn;is Monek sede : "&thorn;e betere is in eche stude</L>
<L>holi churche and cristine-dom : i-loked for &thorn;ine bede.</L>
<L N="183">bide for me for godes loue : nou&thorn;e ich bi-seche &thorn;e!"</L>
<L>&THORN;is womman seide, "for &thorn;ou art preost : &thorn;ou schalt bidde for me.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;at ich onbou&yogh;sum ne beo i-seie : &thorn;ei ich sunful beo,</L>
<L>I-chulle bidde for &thorn;e, mi leoue fader : &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt i-seo."</L>
<L>&THORN;is womman tornede hire estward : and a-knes heo sat a-doun,</L>
<L N="188">hire ei&yogh;ene and hire hondene opward heo heold : and seide hire oresoun.</L>
<L>A-non so heo bi-gan hire oresun : wonder men mi&yogh;ten i-seo :</L>
<L>Fram &thorn;e eor&thorn;e heo was op i-houe : &thorn;e hei&yogh;&thorn;e of fet &thorn;reo;</L>
<L>&THORN;are heo houede stilleliche : as &thorn;ei heo were with-oute bre&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="192">heo ne wawede leome non : bote hire lippene vnne&thorn;e</L>
<L>&YOGH;ware-with heo seide hire oresun&mdash; : and no-&thorn;ing hire op ne bar</L>
<L>bote ore swete louerdes grace&mdash; : fair Miracle was &thorn;ar!<MILESTONE N="120" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;is Monek stod and bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te him : gret wonder he hadde and fere :</L>
<L>he ne heold hire no womman : ake treouwede &thorn;at hit sum gost were,</L>
<L N="197">For heo houede so a-boue. : ake after hire oresun</L>
<L>&THORN;is holi &thorn;ing wel stilleliche : to &thorn;e eor&thorn;e ali&yogh;te a-doun;</L>
<L>"Leoue fader," heo seide, "&yogh;wat is &thorn;e? : &yogh;wy chaungest &thorn;ou &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t?</L>
<L N="200">Ich am a womman of sunful flesch : a gost nam ich nou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>"Moder, &thorn;in ore!" &thorn;e Monek seide : and feol a-doun a-kne,</L>
<L>"to schewi ore swete louerdes mi&yogh;te : &thorn;i lijf tel &thorn;ou me!"</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode womman nam him up : "leoue fader," heo sede,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. seide</NOTE></L>
<L N="204">"Schame it is to heore telle : of mine sunful dede.
<PB REF="00000315.tif" N="267"></L>
<L>Ake for &thorn;ou me i-sei&yogh;e naked er : and &thorn;at mi bodi was al bar,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was for schendnesse of mine foule dedes : of sunne beo euere i-war.</L>
<L>So foule beth mine sunfole dedes : &thorn;at, bote god &thorn;e &yogh;iue is grace,</L>
<L N="208">&YOGH;wane &thorn;ou i-heorst me hem telle : fleo &thorn;ou wolt out of &thorn;is place.</L>
<L>Na&thorn;eles, leoue fader, bide for me : &thorn;at god heom me for-&yogh;iue;</L>
<L>Ich hopie, it is godes wille : &thorn;at ich beo of &thorn;e i-schriue."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heo bi-gan &thorn;o telle alle hire dedes : to &thorn;e Monek Zosime,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo dude seth&thorn;e heo was i-bore : forto &thorn;at ilke tim[e].</L>
<L>"Leoue fader," he seide, "for godes loue : ich bi-seche &thorn;e</L>
<L N="214">&THORN;at &thorn;ou here-of ne schewe noman : are &thorn;at ich ded beo.</L>
<L>go nou&thorn;e hom, and led clene lijf : as &thorn;ou hast er ido :</L>
<L N="216">And eft in &thorn;is tyme a twelf-mon&thorn;e : hidere cum to me.</L>
<L>For &thorn;at ower ordre is swuch : &thorn;at ech Monek schal oute be</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste sonendai of leinte : ake &thorn;ou ne schalt nou&yogh;t so :</L>
<L>&THORN;ei &thorn;ou habbe wille out forto go : &yogh;wile ne tit &thorn;e non :</L>
<L N="220">Ake a-schere[&thorn;ore]s<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. scheres</NOTE>-day at eue : hidere &thorn;ou schalt gon;</L>
<L>Ore louerdes flesch and is blod : hidere bring with &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich enes, are ich dei&yogh;e : mouwe i-hoseled beo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at time &thorn;at ore swete louerd : a-schere-&thorn;ores-day at eue</L>
<L N="224">A-mong his desciples made is cene&mdash; : &thorn;at &thorn;ou it nou&yogh;t bi-leue!</L>
<L>For i nas neuereft I-hoseled : seth&thorn;e ich passede &thorn;e flum Iordan,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is nou&thorn;e seuene-and-&thorn;ritti &yogh;er : &thorn;at I-ne say&yogh; neuereft man.</L>
<L>do &thorn;at ich &thorn;e habbe i-bede : mi leoue fader Zosime,</L>
<L>And blesse me, for ich mot heonne wende : for it is nou&thorn;e al time."</L>
<L N="229">&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e Monek hire i-blesset hadde : Astward heo gan gon.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Monek custe &thorn;e wey &thorn;are heo eode : &thorn;o he nuste non o&thorn;ur won;</L>
<L>&YOGH;eorne he bi-heold after-ward : &thorn;e &yogh;wile he ire mi&yogh;te i-seo,</L>
<L N="232">And &thorn;o he ne sai&yogh; hire nonmore : weopinde he gan hom teo;</L>
<L>&THORN;o he cam hom, in penaunce : clene lijf he gan lede;</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;at he hadde<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. hath</NOTE> oute i-founde : no-&thorn;ing he ne sede.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;e &yogh;er, are he were ido : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te swi&thorn;e longue,</L>
<L N="236">&THORN;at he mi&yogh;te of &thorn;at holi womman : sum confort eft afongue.</L>
<L>&THORN;o leinte cam, and euerech Monek : wende out in is side,</L>
<L>A strong feuere nam frere Zosime : &thorn;at he moste athom a-bide.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;ou&yogh;te he on &thorn;at word : &thorn;at Marie to him seide er :<MILESTONE N="120b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000316.tif" N="268"></L>
<L N="240">&THORN;at, &thorn;ei he wolde out i-wende : he scholde habbe no power.</L>
<L>&THORN;e feuere him heold, ase heo seide : a-non to &thorn;e schere&thorn;ores-dai at eue.</L>
<L>A-non so he was hol, he wende forth : no lengore he nolde bi-leue;</L>
<L>he nam godes flesch and is blod : and to &thorn;e flum is wei he nam.</L>
<L N="244">&THORN;at schere&thorn;ores-dai a&yogh;en<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. at</NOTE> eue : to &thorn;e watere he cam.</L>
<L>Ake he ne mi&yogh;te finde no schip : him ouer for-to lede.</L>
<L>he sat and weop and bi-heold ouer-ward : and bad ore louerd him rede.</L>
<L>"Alas," he seide, "&thorn;e defaute of schip! : hou schulle we to-gadere wende?"</L>
<L N="248">Euere he waytede, &yogh;if ore louerd : ani grace him wolde sende.</L>
<L>&THORN;o sai&yogh; he Marie : bi-&yogh;eonde &thorn;e watere stonde.</L>
<L>he heold op is hondene and sat on is knes : and &thorn;onkede godes sonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Marie hadde i-blessed : &thorn;at watur with hire honde,</L>
<L N="252">With-oute wetingue &thorn;are-ouer he<SUP>o</SUP> &yogh;eode : ase it were on druy&yogh;e londe;</L>
<L>heo orn and ne watte neuere a to. : wel bri&yogh;te &thorn;e Mone schon.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Monek wolde kneuli a-&yogh;einest hire : &thorn;o heo toward him cam gon.</L>
<L>"Stond op," heo seide, "&thorn;ou art a preost : kneuli ne schalt &thorn;ou&yogh; nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="256">for reuerence of &thorn;at holi &thorn;ing : &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast with &thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Ake, leoue fader, blesse &thorn;ou me : for i-ne may a-bide nou&yogh;t longue;</L>
<L>bide for me &thorn;at ich beo wuyr&thorn;e : &thorn;at holi &thorn;in[g] a-fongue!"</L>
<L N="259">&THORN;is womman sat a-doun a-kne : to ore louerd heo gan crie,</L>
<L>heo seide hire crede and hire pater-noster : and<NOTE PLACE="marg1">overlined.</NOTE> &thorn;e holie aue Marie,</L>
<L>heo custe &thorn;e Monekes hond in-stude of pays : and seide hire oresun,</L>
<L>And nam godes flesch and is blod : with gret deuociun.</L>
<L>"louerd," heo seide &thorn;o heo hadde i-do : "&yogh;if it is &thorn;i wille,</L>
<L N="264">&THORN;at &thorn;ou bi-leue &thorn;ine schulchene : in pays swy&thorn;e stille,</L>
<L>for mine ey&yogh;ene habbeth nou&thorn;e i-sei&yogh;e : &thorn;ine swete mi&yogh;te</L>
<L>And ore hele &thorn;at &thorn;ou i-&yogh;arket hast : al mankun for-to li&yogh;te.</L>
<L>"fader Zosime, god it &thorn;e &yogh;elde : &thorn;at &thorn;ou hidere woldest gon!</L>
<L N="268">bide for me and for mine foule sunnes : and go &thorn;ou hom a-non.</L>
<L>An-o&thorn;er &yogh;er in &thorn;is time : loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou hidere to me wende,</L>
<L>And ore louerd &thorn;e wole bi &thorn;ulke tyme : of me o&thorn;ur ty&thorn;ingues sende.
<PB REF="00000317.tif" N="269"></L>
<L>haue nou&thorn;e guod day, mi leoue fader : a&yogh;en ich mot a-non."</L>
<L>"Ore louerd it wolde," &thorn;is monek seide : "&thorn;at ich mi&yogh;te with &thorn;e gon!</L>
<L>bide for me, &yogh;if it is &thorn;i wille : and al-so for holi churche,</L>
<L>And for alle cristine men : &thorn;at heo moten cristes wille wurche."</L>
<L>Marie blessede eft &thorn;at watur : al druye heo wende a-boue&mdash;</L>
<L N="276">Mani fair Miracle ore louerd schewez : for cristine mannes loue!</L>
<L>&THORN;ane nyn&thorn;e day of Aueril : &thorn;is Miracle was i-do,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Marie and frere Zosime : with wop departeden a-to.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Monek bi-heold after hire : and &thorn;o he ne sai&yogh; hire nonmore,</L>
<L N="280">A-&yogh;ein he wente to is Abbeie : wepinde swi&thorn;e sore.</L>
<L>Sorest him rev &thorn;at he nuste : &yogh;wat hire name was,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he nadde i-axed hire&mdash; : ofte he seide alas.</L>
<L>&para; Longue him &thorn;ou&yogh;te are &thorn;ulke &yogh;er : were icome to ende.</L>
<L N="284">Anon so leinte was icome : a-&yogh;ein he gan i-wende.<MILESTONE N="121" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at watur he passede of flum Iordan : into wildernesse wel wide</L>
<L>he &yogh;eode, &thorn;at he ful weri was : for he nadde &yogh;waron to ride.</L>
<L>Ne mi&yogh;te he nou&yogh;were &thorn;is womman i-seo : a-watere ne a-londe;</L>
<L N="288">he nolde stunte are &thorn;at he cam : &thorn;are ase he furst hire founde.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;o &thorn;at he ne fond hire nou&yogh;t &thorn;are : he gan to weopen sore,</L>
<L>For he nuste &yogh;woderward gon : hire for-to sechen more.</L>
<L N="291">Ase he lokede est-ward : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at he i-sei&yogh;</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;ei it a bri&yogh;t sonne were<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. it were</NOTE> : In &thorn;e heir houi an hei&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;uder-ward he &yogh;eode in grete Ioye : for him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;ar-of wonder.</L>
<L>&THORN;o fond he &thorn;is womman ligge ded : In one diche &thorn;are-onder,</L>
<L>hire heued i-torned estward. : &thorn;e Monek bi-gan to weope sore,</L>
<L N="296">At hire fet he feol a-doun : for he ne mi&yogh;te stonde more.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SO sore he weop &thorn;at he wusch hire fet : with teres of is eie.</L>
<L>And euere houede &thorn;is clere lij&yogh;t : ouer hire faire and hei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Monek nuste &yogh;wat he mi&yogh;te do : with &thorn;at holi bodi &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="300">And mest him for-&thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at he nuste : &yogh;wat hire name were.</L>
<L>bi-side hire he sai&yogh; ligge a writ : and he it nam up on is hond.</L>
<L>&THORN;eos wordes, &thorn;at ich ou wolle nou&thorn;e telle : &thorn;aron i-write he fond :</L>
<L>"Frere Zosime, bure &thorn;at bodi : of &thorn;is wrechche wommane Marie,</L>
<L N="304">And prey to god &thorn;at he hire for-&yogh;iue : hire sunnes and hire folie,</L>
<L>&THORN;at deide anon-ri&yogh;t after hire hosel : &thorn;e nyn&thorn;e dai after Aueril;</L>
<L>And &yogh;eld to eor&thorn;e &thorn;at to hire bi-falle : and &thorn;anne heo hath hire wil."
<PB REF="00000318.tif" N="270"></L>
<L>glad was &thorn;e Monek, &thorn;at he wuste : &yogh;wat he scholde do</L>
<L N="308">with &thorn;at bodi &thorn;at &thorn;are lay : and &yogh;wat heo het, al-so;</L>
<L>Ant gret Ioie he hadde of &thorn;e faire Miracle : &thorn;o he &thorn;at writ dude rede,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e womman &thorn;at twelf Mon&thorn;e hadde i-leie : ded, ase it sede,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at heo, a-non so heo i-hoseled was : bi-&yogh;eonde &thorn;e flum Iordan,</L>
<L N="312">Deide &thorn;are in wildernesse : &thorn;at so feor was &thorn;are-fram,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at heo eode bi-fore hire de&thorn;e : In a stounde of &thorn;e day<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. daye</NOTE></L>
<L>Twenti dawene Iorneies : &thorn;are ase heo ded<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. det</NOTE> lay.</L>
<L>Ake hou hire put mi&yogh;te beon i-maket : gret care &thorn;ar-of he hadde :</L>
<L>for &thorn;e eor&thorn;e was hard, and he was old : and none spade he nadde.</L>
<L N="317">Ake na&thorn;eles he fond ane staf : &thorn;at was scharp at&thorn;e ende :</L>
<L>&THORN;are-with he dalf. ake luyte he mi&yogh;te : &thorn;are-with &thorn;e eor&thorn;e wende,</L>
<L>for he was feble for fastingue : and for gret trauail al-so.</L>
<L N="320">&THORN;o he i-sai&yogh; ane leon licke &thorn;at bodi : and &thorn;are-a-boute go.</L>
<L>Sore was &thorn;e Monek a-drad : &thorn;o he sai&yogh; &thorn;at best so gon,</L>
<L>And for Marie him hadde bi-fore i-seid : &thorn;at heo neuere ne i-sai&yogh; &thorn;are non,</L>
<L>And for it was a stuyrne best&mdash; : he hadde &thorn;ar-of gret<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. gred</NOTE> doute.</L>
<L N="324">&THORN;is leon bo&thorn;e with heued and bodi : to him he gan a-loute.</L>
<L>&THORN;o was &thorn;is Monek hardi a-non : and to &thorn;e leon he sede :</L>
<L>"For &thorn;ou art &thorn;oru&yogh; god hidere i-sent : cum help me to &thorn;is dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is put were wel i-maket!" : and &thorn;o &thorn;e leon i-heorde &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="328">Mildeliche &thorn;ane put he schrapede : wel euene and nou&yogh;t a-mis&mdash;</L>
<L>for it was a-cordinde to &thorn;e bodi : in leng&thorn;e and in brede;<MILESTONE N="121b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he fourmede euene &thorn;ane put : with-oute ani mis-dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e put was imaket : &thorn;is Monek and &thorn;e leon</L>
<L N="332">Mildeliche nomen &thorn;is holi bodi : and leiden it &thorn;are-inne a-doun.</L>
<L>huy nadden nou&yogh;t &yogh;[w]are-inne hire winde&mdash; : bote a pece &thorn;are was i-leued</L>
<L>of &thorn;ulke wede &yogh;ware-with heo hadde : hire derne limes bi-weued :</L>
<L>&THORN;are-with huy heoleden &thorn;at huy mi&yogh;ten : and casten eor&thorn;e hire a-boue,</L>
<L N="336">&THORN;is holie man and &thorn;at best : and bureden hire with grete loue.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is bodi was i-bured : &thorn;e leon &yogh;eode is wei,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Monek wel mildeliche in penaunce : a&yogh;en to his Abbei.</L>
<L>Al clanliche he tolde is bre&thorn;ren fore : al &thorn;at he fond oute,</L>
<L>And liet write &thorn;is holie wommanes lif : and despeopli hit al-a-boute.
<PB REF="00000319.tif" N="271"></L>
<L>&THORN;us seinte Marie egyptiane : out of hire fole dede</L>
<L N="342">Wende to heouene blisse : &thorn;oru&yogh; penaunce &thorn;at heo gan lede.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="40" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>40 Vita sancti Cristofori.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Cristofre was a saracen : in &thorn;e londe of canaan.</L>
<L>In none stude bi is daie : nas so gret a man :</L>
<L>Foure-and-twenti fet he was long : and &thorn;icke and brod i-nou&yogh; :</L>
<L N="4">A scwuch bote he were strong : me &thorn;inchez it were wou&yogh;!</L>
<L>Al a contreie &thorn;are he were : for him wolde fleo.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at noman : a&yogh;en him scholde beo :</L>
<L>He seide, he nolde with no man bi-leue : bote with on &thorn;at were</L>
<L N="8">hext louerd ouer alle men : and onder non o&thorn;ur nere.</L>
<L>Swuch a Man he wente to seche. : and so &thorn;at men him tolde</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e hexte manne &thorn;at on eor&thorn;e was : and of mest power i-holde.</L>
<L>Seint Cristofre sou&yogh;te feor : and at&thorn;e laste he cam him to.</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;e king axede him a-non &yogh;wat he were : and &yogh;wat he sou&yogh;te also.</L>
<L>Cristofre him seide &yogh;wat he was : and &thorn;at he serui wolde</L>
<L>&THORN;ene hexte Man &thorn;at ou&yogh;were were : and &thorn;at non o&thorn;ur abouwie ne scholde,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he mi&yogh;te ani scwych<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. scwuch</NOTE> finde. : &thorn;is king to him sede</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;at he ne heold of no man : ne a-bouwie he nolde ne drede.</L>
<L>Ei&thorn;ur was of o&thorn;ur glad. : Cristofre him seruede longue.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng louede muche Melodie : of fie&thorn;le<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. fi&thorn;ele</NOTE> and of songue :</L>
<L>So &thorn;at is Iugelour a day : bi-fore him pleide faste,</L>
<L N="20">And nemde in is ryme and in is song : &thorn;ene deuel at&thorn;e laste.</L>
<L>Anon so &thorn;e kyng &thorn;at i-heorde : he blessede him a-non.</L>
<L>Seint Cristofre nam wel guode &yogh;eme : and nolde ane fot feor gon</L>
<L>Are he wuste &yogh;wi it were. : &thorn;e king was ful loth to telle.</L>
<L N="24">Cristofre seide, "bote &thorn;ou me segge : no leng serui &thorn;e I-nelle."</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e kyng ne i-sai&yogh; non o&thorn;ur : "leoue Cristofre," he sede,</L>
<L>"Ich blessede me &thorn;o ich heorde him nemme : for ich habbe of him gret drede."</L>
<L>"&THORN;anne he is," quath Cristofre : "herre Maister &thorn;ane &thorn;ou?"</L>
<L N="28">"&THORN;at ne may ich," quath &thorn;e kyng : "for-so&thorn;e for-sake nov."</L>
<L>"Haue guod day," quat Cristofre &thorn;o : "Inelle neuereft with &thorn;e beo.</L>
<L>Ichulle seche &thorn;ane deuel<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. feond; deuel on the margin.</NOTE> and serui him : &yogh;if ich him owere iseo."
<PB REF="00000320.tif" N="272"></L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng was sori, and alle his : &thorn;at huy ne mi&yogh;ten him make a-bide.</L>
<L>Forth he wende &thorn;ene deuel to seche : ake natheles nou&yogh;t wel wide&mdash;<MILESTONE N="122" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For &thorn;e schrewe wole euere a-redi beo : to heom &thorn;at beoth to him i-nome.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Cristofre cam with-oute toun : gret folk he sai&yogh; come</L>
<L>wel on horse, with grete nobleye : swy&thorn;e fierce and proute.</L>
<L N="36">Cristofre heom mette we[l] baldeliche&mdash; : he nadde of heom no doute.</L>
<L>&THORN;e maister, fiers with-alle : cam and mette with him a-non,</L>
<L>"Beu sire," he seide, "&yogh;wat art &thorn;ou? : and &yogh;wodere &thorn;enxt &thorn;ou gon?"</L>
<L>"Ich am a ma[n] opon mi seruiz : and noman serui i-nelle</L>
<L N="40">Bote mi louerd &thorn;at ich seche : &thorn;e hei&yogh;e deuel of helle."</L>
<L>"Beu frere," quath &thorn;e o&thorn;ur, "ich it am : wel-come ar &thorn;ov to me!</L>
<L>&THORN;e beste seruiz &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolt cheose : man schal deliueri &thorn;e."</L>
<L>Cristofre sai&yogh; is grete folk : and &thorn;at he was of gret pouwer :</L>
<L N="44">Of swuch a louerd he was wel glad : and al-so of &thorn;at grete mester.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maister hei&yogh;te al is folk a-wei : bote heom-seoluen tweie,</L>
<L>To teche him is mester priueliche : ase huy wenden bi &thorn;e weie.</L>
<L>Ase huy wenden tale&yogh;inde forth : of &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere seruise,</L>
<L N="48">In &thorn;e wei heo iseien one croiz stonde. : &thorn;e deuel gan &thorn;arof a-grise :</L>
<L>his wei in breres and in &thorn;ornes : wel feor bi-side he nam;</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo &thorn;e croiz i-passede hadden : a-&yogh;ein to &thorn;e weie he cam.</L>
<L>Cristofre him Axede &yogh;wi it were. : and him was loth to telle.</L>
<L N="52">"Certes," he seide, "bote &thorn;ou me segge : no leng serui &thorn;e i-nelle."</L>
<L>"Cristofre, mi leoue freont," quath &thorn;e deuel : "ichulle &thorn;e telle fayn,</L>
<L>with &thorn;at &thorn;ou serui me after-ward : &thorn;e betere with al mi mayn :</L>
<L>with a swuch croiz ase we &thorn;are i-seien : &thorn;e heie god &thorn;at was here</L>
<L N="56">Ouer- cam and in soruwe brou&yogh;te : me and alle mine fere."</L>
<L>"&THORN;anne is he herre," quath Cristofre : "and hath power more?"</L>
<L>"&THORN;at ne may ich nou&yogh;t for-sake," &thorn;e feond seide : "and &thorn;at me for|&thorn;inchez sore."</L>
<L>"Da&thorn;eit &thorn;anne," Cristofre seide : "&thorn;at leng beo in &thorn;ine seruise,</L>
<L N="60">&YOGH;if ich of &thorn;ane heie manne may o&yogh;t i-wite : in anie kunnes wise!"</L>
<L>Forth he wende and sou&yogh;te ore louerd. : wel wide he gan gon.</L>
<L>At&thorn;e laste he fond ane hermite : to him he wende a-non,</L>
<L>he tolde him clanliche al-hou it was : and hou he a swych man sou&yogh;te.
<PB REF="00000321.tif" N="273"></L>
<L N="64">"&YOGH;e," seide &thorn;e heremite, "ihered he beo : &thorn;at &thorn;e in swyche wille brou&yogh;te!</L>
<L>Leue bro&thorn;er," seide &thorn;e heremite, "he is &thorn;i louerd : for to manne he &thorn;e wrou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And with is owene flechs and is blod : wel deore he &thorn;e a-bou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou most sum-&yogh;wat soffri for him : and festen eche friday."</L>
<L N="68">"Ine faste neuere," seide Cristofre : "ne, certes, &yogh;eot Ine may."</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou most," seide &thorn;e heremite, "to churche gon : and &thorn;ine beden bidde also."</L>
<L>"I-not," seide Cristofre, "&yogh;wat it is : ne i-ne can hit nou&yogh;t do."</L>
<L>&para; "No," seide &thorn;e heremite, "&thorn;ou art strong : and here is a water bi|side</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;at no man may &thorn;are-ouer come : bote he &thorn;e herre ride:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou most in lesnesse of &thorn;ine sunnes : habbe &thorn;ine wone&yogh;ingue &thorn;ere</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane ani man to &thorn;e neode hath : &thorn;are-ouer &thorn;ou most him bere,</L>
<L>In fur&yogh;iuenesse of &thorn;ine misdedes." : he grauntede &thorn;at a-non.</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;e heremite &yogh;af him cristine-dom : and het him &thorn;udere gon.</L>
<L>&para; CRistofre bi-side &thorn;ulke watere : one hole he made him &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>In his hond a long perche he bar : is staf as &thorn;ei it were;<MILESTONE N="122b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;wane any man wolde ouer &thorn;at watur : opon is rug he him caste</L>
<L>And tok is perche and bar him ouer : he stap hardeliche and faste,</L>
<L>For he was bo&thorn;e strong and long&mdash; : &thorn;are ne cam so heui non</L>
<L>&THORN;at Cristofre ouer &thorn;e deope watere : ne bar heom ouer ech-on.</L>
<L>A ni&yogh;t in &thorn;e o&thorn;ur half of &thorn;e watur : a uoiz &thorn;are cam and gradde</L>
<L N="84">"Hale, hale," to seint Cristofre : &thorn;at he him &thorn;are-ouer ladde.</L>
<L>Cristofre a-ros him op a-non : is perche on honde he nam</L>
<L>And wod ouer &thorn;e watur&mdash;and ne fond no man : &thorn;o he to londe cam.</L>
<L>he nas bote i-come hom a-&yogh;en : &thorn;at on ne gradde eft-sone &thorn;er.</L>
<L N="88">Cristofre wod ouer, and ne mi&yogh;te finde : non more &thorn;ane he dude er.</L>
<L>&YOGH;uyt it gradde &thorn;e &thorn;ridde tyme : &thorn;o he cam hom to londe.</L>
<L>And with is rodde wod a-&yogh;en. : a luyte child he fond &thorn;are stonde;</L>
<L>&THORN;at child bad him par charite : ouer &thorn;e watere him lede.</L>
<L N="92">"Cum forth, &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt here ouer" : cristofre to him sede;</L>
<L>Swy&thorn;e li&yogh;tliche &thorn;at child he nam : and in is Armes it caste.</L>
<L>Euere ase he was ouer-ward : it gan to heuegy faste;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at watur wax al-so : &thorn;at Cristofre sore agaste
<PB REF="00000322.tif" N="274"></L>
<L>To a-drenche &thorn;at child &thorn;at was so heui&mdash; : vnne&thorn;e he stod at&thorn;e laste.</L>
<L>Neuere so clene he nas ouer-come : at eche stape he grunte and blaste;</L>
<L N="98">And laste &thorn;at child hadde a-dreint : he ne dorste it a-doun caste.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he was to londe i-come : ase him &thorn;ou&yogh;te ful longue er,</L>
<L>&THORN;at child he sette a-doun to grounde : and stod op, to reste him &thorn;er.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;wat art &thorn;ou, &thorn;at art so luyte : and so heui bi-come,</L>
<L>So heui &thorn;at ich was ope &thorn;e poyinte : to habbe a-dreint i-lome?</L>
<L>&THORN;ei al &thorn;e world hadde ope me i-leie : me &thorn;inchez so heui it nere."</L>
<L N="104">"No wonder, cristofre," seide &thorn;at child : "&thorn;ei ic<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. it</NOTE> heuiore were</L>
<L>&THORN;ane al &thorn;e world, for ich [am] more&mdash; : and no wonder it nis<NOTE PLACE="marg1">and&mdash;nis on an erasure.</NOTE>:</L>
<L>For ich made al &thorn;e world of nou&yogh;t : and al o&thorn;ur &thorn;in[g] &thorn;at is.</L>
<L>And for &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;e so&thorn;e i-seo : &thorn;ine staf piche in &thorn;e grounde:</L>
<L>And he schal bere lef and blowe : and fruyt bere in luyte stounde."</L>
<L>With &thorn;is word &thorn;at child wende forth. : Cristofre is staf nam</L>
<L>And pi&yogh;te hit in &thorn;e grounde a-morewe : and ri&yogh;t soth it &thorn;are bi-cam.</L>
<L>&THORN;o was he sikerore &thorn;ane he was er : and ore louerd he louede more.</L>
<L N="112">Forth he wend[e], to siwi him : and forto prechi is lore.</L>
<L>he heorde telle &yogh;ware Cristine men : In torment weren ibrou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>To conforti heom he wende &thorn;udere : &thorn;at heo ne scholden flechchie nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>"Beoth hardie," he seide, "and studefaste : and doth as ich ou lere!"</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;e Iustise sturte forth a-non : and smot him vnder &thorn;e Ere;</L>
<L>"Art&thorn;ou," he seide, "on of &thorn;ulke : &thorn;ou it schalt a-corie sore."</L>
<L>"Site &thorn;ou wel stille," Cristofre seide : "and ne smijt &thorn;ou me non|more!</L>
<L>For &yogh;if ich a cristine man nere : Ich me wolde a-wreke a-non.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e bi-leuez on ouwer Maumates," he seide : "I-maket of treo and ston,</L>
<L>&THORN;at none Miracles ne mouwen do : non more &thorn;ane a treo.</L>
<L>Sum of &thorn;e power &thorn;at mi louerd hath : bi mi staf &thorn;ou schalt i-seo:"<MILESTONE N="123" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>his rodde he pi&yogh;te in &thorn;e grounde : and heo bi-gan a-non</L>
<L N="124">To leui and blowe and bere fruyt : bi-fore heom euerech-on.</L>
<L>"On swuch a god &yogh;e schullen bi-leue : &thorn;at swuch Miracle mai do."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iustise ne dorste, for he was muche : a bold word segge him to.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e faire Miracle of is staf : and for is prechingue al-so,
<PB REF="00000323.tif" N="275"></L>
<L>To god heo[m]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. heo</NOTE> torneden in &thorn;e place : seuen &thorn;ousende and mo.</L>
<L>Toward a-maner wildernesse : seint Cristofre wende,</L>
<L>In godes seruise to lede is lijf : ase ore louerd him grace sende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iustise tolde &thorn;e kyngue fore : of swych a man &thorn;at he i-sei&yogh;</L>
<L N="132">Turne &thorn;at folk and he ne dorste : for strenc&thorn;e come him nei&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king het sone to hundret kni&yogh;tes : seche forto heo him founde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at huy scholden him nimen and leden : bi-fore him, faste i-bounde.</L>
<L>Forth wenden &thorn;is kny&yogh;tes : wel I-armede, a-non.</L>
<L N="136">Toward Cristofre huy comen a luyte : and bi-heolden him echon:</L>
<L>huy alle ne dorsten come him nei&yogh; : ake hamward huy gonne fleo,</L>
<L>And tolden, &thorn;o huy comen hom : &thorn;at huy ne mi&yogh;ten him no&yogh;were i-seo.</L>
<L>"Ou&yogh;, &yogh;e cowardes," quath &thorn;e king : "nabbe &yogh;e him nou&yogh;t i-founde?</L>
<L N="140">Ichulle, &yogh;if he a-liue is : habbe him, faste i-bounde."</L>
<L>he sende to hundret o&thorn;ur kny&yogh;tes : &thorn;at hy him wide sou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at huy ne comen neuere a-&yogh;en : are huy him with heom brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Wel I-armede heo wenden forth. : and a-non so huy Cristofre i-seie,</L>
<L N="144">huy stoden and ne dorsten gon him ner : o&thorn;ur vnne&thorn;e bi-holden him with ei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&para; Cristofre stod and him<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. hem</NOTE> bi-heold : and axede hem &yogh;wat huy wolden.</L>
<L>"For no-&thorn;ing ne dorre we," &thorn;e kny&yogh;tes seiden : "bi &thorn;e don &thorn;at we scholden:</L>
<L>&THORN;e king us het bringue &thorn;e to him : and &thorn;ine hondene faste binde.</L>
<L N="148">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt, we wollez him segge : &thorn;at we ne mouwen &thorn;e finde."</L>
<L>"Nay, certes," seide Cristofre &thorn;o : "&yogh;e scholden beo i-blamede so;</L>
<L>Ake with ou ichulle<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. ichulle ichulle</NOTE> gon : and loki &yogh;wat he wulle habbe i-do."</L>
<L>he made heom al a-&yogh;ein heore wille : ase a &thorn;ef, faste him binde,</L>
<L N="152">&thorn;at heo neren i-blamede, and leden him forth : his hondene him bi-hinde.</L>
<L>Of godes lawe bi &thorn;e weie : Cristofre heom gan so lere,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. lerere</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at echone, are huy comen hom : faire i-cristnede were.</L>
<L>Natheles huy ladden him forth : bi-fore &thorn;e kyngue, faste i-bounde,</L>
<L>And seiden, "here is godes kny&yogh;t : nou&thorn;e we him habbeth i-founde."</L>
<L>&thorn;e king sat an hei&yogh; op-on is sege. : and a-non so he Cristofre i-sei&yogh;,</L>
<L N="158">For drede he feol doun to grounde : &thorn;at is necke to-barst nei&yogh;.
<PB REF="00000324.tif" N="276"></L>
<L>his kny&yogh;tes nomen him up a-non. : and ase tyme ase is wit him cam,</L>
<L N="160">he bad Cristofre to him take : and leten beo is cristindam.</L>
<L>"&thorn;ou mi&yogh;t, guode man," seide cristofre : "al-so wel beo stille.</L>
<L>Mi bodi &thorn;ou hast here faste i-bounde : &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t don al &thorn;i wille."</L>
<L>&para; "Certes, sire," &thorn;is kni&yogh;tes seiden : &thorn;at hadden him &thorn;udere i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="164">"Cristindom we habbez itake : and we nelleth it bi-leue nou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>&thorn;e king let &thorn;o in grete wrath&thorn;e : Cristofre in prisone do,</L>
<L>And binden alle &thorn;e kny&yogh;tes faste : and heore heuedes smiten of al-so.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;eos kny&yogh;tes bi-hauedede weren : &thorn;e king sone bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te<MILESTONE N="123b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="168">And tweyen faire wommen with-alle : to cristofre he brou&yogh;te&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at on het Nice, &thorn;at o&thorn;ur Aquiline&mdash; : for-to tornen is mod.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is wommen iseien Cristofre : ase he in prisone stod,</L>
<L>heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te is face wel bri&yogh;tore schine : &thorn;ane &thorn;e sonne o&thorn;ur &thorn;e Mone.</L>
<L>"Cr[i]stofre, merci," loude heo gradden : "make us cristine sone!"</L>
<L>Cristofre heom tei&yogh;te &thorn;e ri&yogh;te bi-leue : and cristnede heom a-non &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="174">A-morewe &thorn;e kying let heom fette : to lokie hou it were;</L>
<L>he hopede heo hadden &thorn;ane guode man : in lecherie i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="176">&thorn;e wommen Answereden to his Axingue : as huy ne tolden of him no&yogh;t.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;wat, hou goth &thorn;is," quat &thorn;e kyng : "habbe &yogh;e i-turnd ower &thorn;ou&yogh;t?</L>
<L>honourieth mine godes, ich rede : &thorn;e &yogh;wyle ou is wel i-&thorn;ou&yogh;t."<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> ido&yogh;t</NOTE></L>
<L>"Ouwer godes beoth wur&thorn;e," &thorn;is Maydenes seiden : "in fa[i]r stude honoured to beo:</L>
<L N="180">&thorn;are-fore lat swope &thorn;e stretes faire : &thorn;at al folk mouwe i-seo,</L>
<L>And we heom wollez honouri, i-wis : ase ri&yogh;t is and lawe."</L>
<L>&thorn;e king let don ase heo seiden : swi&thorn;e sone and fawe.</L>
<L N="183">&thorn;o &thorn;is Maumates weren i-brou&yogh;t : in &thorn;e strete at &thorn;e laste,</L>
<L>&thorn;is maydenes nomen heore gurdles bo&thorn;e : ant to heom teiden faste</L>
<L>And to-drowen heom in-to al &thorn;e strete : and heowen heom to peces &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>"Goth," heo seiden, "ant fechchiez heom leches : &thorn;at heo i-helede were!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e kying was nei&yogh; for wrath&thorn;e wod : &thorn;at o maide he let hongue</L>
<L N="188">And to hire fet bynden heuie stones : &thorn;at hire de&thorn;es &thorn;rowes weren strongue.</L>
<L>A-non so &thorn;is mayde was up i-drawe : hire leomes borsten with-inne,
<PB REF="00000325.tif" N="277"></L>
<L>Necke and senewes and o&thorn;ur limes&mdash; : wel au&yogh;te heo heuene i-winne.</L>
<L>he let don &thorn;at o&thorn;ur in strong fuyr&mdash; : ake &thorn;are ne mi&yogh;te non come hire nei&yogh;:</L>
<L N="192">Ake seth&thorn;e he let hire heued of smite : &thorn;o he &thorn;at o&thorn;er cas i-sei&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;is twei holie maydenes : to &thorn;e blisse of heuene i-wende,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru &thorn;e grace &thorn;at ore swete louerd : for seint Cristofre heom sende.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e king let &thorn;o cristofre fecche : and axede him a-non</L>
<L N="196">&YOGH;we&thorn;ur he wolde his Maumates serui : o&thorn;ur to &thorn;e de&thorn;e gon.</L>
<L>Cristofre for-sok heore Maumates : and heore seruiz also.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king het a-non &thorn;at Men him scholden : op-on a strong gredile do</L>
<L>And with strong fuyr and pich rosti him. : and &thorn;o he was i-leid &thorn;ar-on,</L>
<L N="200">As wex &thorn;at gredile malt a-wei : and &thorn;at fuyr a-queynte a-non,</L>
<L>And he a-ros up with-oute harme. : wroth was &thorn;e kyng &thorn;o.</L>
<L>To a piler he let him binde faste : and kny&yogh;tes a-boute him go,</L>
<L>For-[to] scheoten him to de&thorn;e : with Mani a kene flo.</L>
<L N="204">With bouwe and Areblast &thorn;are schoten to him : four hondret kny&yogh;tes and mo:</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;are nas non Arewe &thorn;at nei&yogh; him cam : ake alle heo gliden bi-side</L>
<L>And heo[n]gun<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. heogun</NOTE> in &thorn;e Eyr a-boute him : and &thorn;are huy gunne a-bide.</L>
<L>A-non so &thorn;e king &thorn;is i-sai&yogh; : for wrat&thorn;e &thorn;udere he wende.</L>
<L N="208">An Arewe &thorn;at ouer &thorn;is guode man heng : a-&yogh;ein him sone kende,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e is e&yogh;ene heo smot out : and deope into &thorn;e heued.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king stod for Anguysche and for drede : ase is wit him were bi-reued.</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou onselie wrechche," seide cristofre : "&yogh;wat is nou&thorn;e wurth &thorn;i mi&yogh;te?</L>
<L N="212">A-&yogh;ein him &thorn;at &thorn;ov hauest bi-gonne : feble &thorn;ou art to fi&yogh;te!<MILESTONE N="124" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;i wrechhede ich habbe reu&thorn;e : And &thorn;at i schal cuy&thorn;e &thorn;e:</L>
<L>For to-Moruwe mi louerd soffri wole : &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt laten a-quelle me,</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne smeore &thorn;ine ei&yogh;ene with mi blod : and fonde mi louerdes mi&yogh;te:</L>
<L N="216">And &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt a-ri&yogh;t bi-leue : &thorn;ou schalt habbe &thorn;i si&yogh;te."</L>
<L>&THORN;e blinde kyng &thorn;ar-to hopede : and swi&thorn;e wel it onder-stod:</L>
<L>A-morewe he let is heued of-smyte : and smeorie him with is blod:</L>
<L>he hadde is si&yogh;t guod and cler : &thorn;oru&yogh; godes grace wel sone.</L>
<L N="220">&thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e bone of seint cristofre : he tournede to cristine-dome.
<PB REF="00000326.tif" N="278"></L>
<L>he let burien faire seint Cristofre : and bi-liefde on god a-non</L>
<L>and let him cristni in godes lawe : and is men ech-on.</L>
<L>&THORN;us seint Cristofre &thorn;ene hexte louerd : at &thorn;e laste of-sou&yogh;te.</L>
<L N="224">God us bringue to &thorn;ulke Ioye : &thorn;at he is soule brou&yogh;te.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="41" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>41 &para; Vita sancti Dominici confessoris.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Domenic, &thorn;e holie frere : in spayne was i-bore,<MILESTONE N="124" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In &thorn;e toune of Caylre&mdash; : wel guod was &thorn;e more:</L>
<L>Sire felice is fader het : is moder dame Ione.</L>
<L N="4">glad was &thorn;e Moder of &thorn;e sone : &thorn;at for him gan ofte grone.</L>
<L>&THORN;eo &yogh;wile &thorn;at &thorn;is holie child : in is Moder wombe was,</L>
<L>hire &thorn;ou&yogh;te, ase heo lay a-slepe : ase ore louerd &yogh;af &thorn;at cas,</L>
<L>&thorn;at heo bar in hire wombe a best : &thorn;at faireste in any lond,</L>
<L N="8">And &thorn;at best bar ri&yogh;t in is Mouth : ane berninde brond;</L>
<L>&thorn;e brond in &thorn;usse bestes mouth : &thorn;o it was of hire i-bore,</L>
<L>Schon so &thorn;at al cristine-dom : &thorn;e bri&yogh;tore was &thorn;are-fore,</L>
<L>And so wide so was cristinedom : And &thorn;are was so deork so ny&yogh;t</L>
<L N="12">&thorn;e brond in &thorn;e bestes Mou&thorn;e : hire &thorn;ou&yogh;te &yogh;af gret li&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;at child was i-bore : and i-brou&yogh;t to cristin-dom,</L>
<L>Al-so bi-feol &thorn;at a guod lauedi : &thorn;at him of watere nam,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at &thorn;are was a steorre : In his fore-heued so bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="16">&thorn;at &thorn;oru-out al cristine-dom : schon and &yogh;af gret lij&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&YOGH;wat was &thorn;is schiningue of &thorn;is child : bote &thorn;at he scholde bringue</L>
<L>to godes lawe Mani a man : &thorn;oru&yogh; is guode prechingue,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he scholde an ordre make : of frere prechours, &thorn;at &yogh;et is;</L>
<L N="20">&thorn;at &thorn;are-&thorn;oru&yogh; al cristine-dom : a-mendi scholde, i-wis?</L>
<L>&thorn;is child, &thorn;eo &yogh;wyle it was &yogh;ong : to guode drou&yogh; a-non,</L>
<L>to fastingue and to almes-dede : and wolle werie<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Vern. wolleward</NOTE> to gon;</L>
<L>In is bedde he nolde beo : bote wel luyte stounde,</L>
<L N="24">Ake ligge in is oresones : op-on &thorn;e harde grounde.</L>
<L>&thorn;o he was seth&thorn;e to scole i-set : a deore &yogh;er &thorn;are cam:</L>
<L>his bokes he solde and al is guod : and alle &thorn;e panes he nam</L>
<L>And delde heom alle to pouere men : ant ne lefde him-sulf ri&yogh;t no&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="28">&thorn;e ty&thorn;ingue of is godhede : was sone wide i-brou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e bischop of &thorn;e lond : louede him wel i-nou&yogh;</L>
<L>And enqueorede of is dedes : &thorn;at to alle guode he drou&yogh;:
<PB REF="00000327.tif" N="279"></L>
<L>hei&yogh; man he made him sone : and chanun seculer&mdash;</L>
<L N="32">Wel luyte tolde &thorn;e holie Man : of is grete power.</L>
<L>&THORN;are weren false cristine Men : a-boute in &thorn;e londe,<MILESTONE N="124b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at nolden nou&yogh;t clanliche : &thorn;e ri&yogh;te bi-leue onder-stonde,</L>
<L>Ne huy ne bi-lefden nou&yogh;t &thorn;at ore louerd were i-bore : of &thorn;e maide Marie&mdash;</L>
<L N="36">Swuch manere fals bi-leue : Men cleopeden heresie.</L>
<L>A-&yogh;ein heom &thorn;is holie man : despuytede alday faste,</L>
<L>And manie of heom &thorn;oru&yogh; godes grace : into ri&yogh;te bi-leue heom caste.</L>
<L>An Eorl &thorn;are was in &thorn;e londe &thorn;o : &thorn;at guod Man was i-nou&yogh;:</L>
<L N="40">Sire Symon de Mountfort : &thorn;at to alle guodnesse drou&yogh;,</L>
<L>his fader &thorn;at was here a-slawe : a-mong us in Engelonde</L>
<L>At&thorn;e batayle of Euesham : &thorn;at longue worth onder-stonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode kny&yogh;t sire Symon : strong kny&yogh;t was i-nou&yogh;</L>
<L N="44">And a-&yogh;ein &thorn;is vuele cristine Men : to batayle al day he drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Seint Domenic al-so a-boute &yogh;eode : and prechede a&yogh;ein heom wel faste:</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;is tweye guode Men : to-gadere heore heorte caste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy weren bo&thorn;e at one rede : &thorn;e on with his prechingue,</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;e o&thorn;ur with strenc&thorn;e of bataille : &thorn;at folk to guode bringue.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e guode Erol<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. Eorl</NOTE> syre symon : &thorn;e &yogh;wile is lijf i-laste,</L>
<L>Euere heold op with his power : seint Dompnic wel faste;</L>
<L>And &thorn;oru&yogh; is pouer muche-del : &thorn;e ordre he bi-gan</L>
<L N="52">Of frere prechours, &thorn;at &yogh;eot is : for-to saui mani a man.&mdash;</L>
<L>bi-twene &thorn;is men for heore heresie : &thorn;e striuingue ofte was</L>
<L>And &thorn;e holie Manne seint Domenic. : ase ore louerd &yogh;af &thorn;at cas,</L>
<L>Op-on &thorn;e hul of vittorie : A day &thorn;are was i-nome</L>
<L N="56">Of desputisun bi-tweone heom : and &thorn;o &thorn;e day was i-come,</L>
<L>Seint Domenic cam forth &thorn;o : and In a writ he brou&yogh;te</L>
<L>his resones for cristin-dom : and &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere Men it bi-tau&yogh;te,</L>
<L>to counseilie heom &thorn;are-upon bet : and Answerien &thorn;are-to</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur beon studefastore in heore bi-leue : bote huy heom cou&thorn;en ondo.</L>
<L>&thorn;is Men of heore heresie : lou&yogh;wen &thorn;o wel smere;<NOTE PLACE="marg1">A v. om.</NOTE></L>
<L N="62">A gret fuyr huy maden a-non : and &thorn;at writ heo casten In &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And seiden, &yogh;if it barnde &thorn;o : of none vertue it nere.</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;at writ lay longue in &thorn;at fuyr : and neuere &thorn;e weorse it nas,</L>
<L>Ne nou&yogh;t i-wemned of one lette[r] : and &thorn;at was a fair cas!
<PB REF="00000328.tif" N="280"></L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere Men i-seien &thorn;is : a-nuyde huy weren sore;</L>
<L>huy nomen &thorn;at bok and seiden a-non : &thorn;at huy wolden &yogh;eot fondi more:</L>
<L N="68">huy casten eft-sone in-to &thorn;e fuyr : and &thorn;e &thorn;ridde tyme al-so:</L>
<L>And euere &thorn;at writ was al-so sound : as it was &thorn;are-inne i-do.</L>
<L>&thorn;is Men of heore heresie : i-schende heom heolden &thorn;o&mdash;</L>
<L>And nolden nou&yogh;t &yogh;eot al clanliche : out of heore folie go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="72">Seint domenic &thorn;is holie Man : ase ore louerd &yogh;af &thorn;at cas,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e Cite of tolouse : ten &yogh;er to-gadere he was.</L>
<L>he &thorn;ou&yogh;te bi-guynne a-godes name : &yogh;if he mi&yogh;te it bringue to ende,</L>
<L>An ordre of Men to prechi faste : and a-boute &thorn;e world to wende,</L>
<L N="76">&thorn;at mi&yogh;ten &thorn;oru&yogh;-out cristindom : Men wissi and rede;</L>
<L>&YOGH;eorne he bad to Iesu crist : helpe him to &thorn;is dede.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e pope Innocent : a gret counseil I-nou&yogh;<MILESTONE N="125" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Makede at rome &thorn;ulke tyme : and muche folk &thorn;udere drou&yogh;.</L>
<L N="80">Seint Domenic wel mildeliche : &thorn;udere gan to wende,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he mi&yogh;te anie grace habbe : to bringue is ordre to ende.</L>
<L>he cam and bad &thorn;e pope leue : swuch &thorn;ing for-to do.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pope makede him dauncherous : and nolde ensenti &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L N="84">&para; A ni&yogh;t, as &thorn;e pope lai a-slepe : ase ore louerd &yogh;af &thorn;at cas,</L>
<L>him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at &thorn;e churche of rome : al a-doneward was</L>
<L>Of "seint Iohanes de lateran" : and as he lai &thorn;ere</L>
<L>he lokede euere and al &thorn;at folk : &yogh;wane huy ouer-falle were;</L>
<L N="88">And seint Domenic heold up a-&yogh;en : and faste schef with-oute,</L>
<L>Wal ant tymber he pulte a-&yogh;ein : and faste orn a-boute.</L>
<L>&thorn;e pope, &thorn;o he a-wok : In grete &thorn;ou&yogh;te lay</L>
<L>&YOGH;wat &thorn;is bi-tocningue mi&yogh;te beo : &thorn;at he slepinde i-sai&yogh;.</L>
<L N="92">he &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at &thorn;e stat of holi churche : swuy&thorn;e i-febled were</L>
<L>And &thorn;at cristine-dom in Manie studes : in ri&yogh;t guod stat it nere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at seint Domenic &thorn;oru&yogh; is ordre : hire scholde helpe a-rere</L>
<L>&thorn;oru&yogh; his prechingue wide in londe : cristine men to lere.</L>
<L N="96">&thorn;e pope a-morewe sente aftur him : and grauntede him wel fawe</L>
<L>to maken is ordre a-godes name : and folk to guode drawe;</L>
<L>bote &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">he on the margin.</NOTE> heom scheowede is ruyle : to alle is cardinales &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at huy weren i-prouede guode : are huy i-confermede were.</L>
<L N="100">So &thorn;at &thorn;e ordre of frere prechours : seint Domenic bi-gan &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&thorn;at hath i-saued wel mani a man : and &yogh;eot it schal wel mo.
<PB REF="00000329.tif" N="281"></L>
<L>clerkes huy onder-fenguen sone : &thorn;at &thorn;e Abite nome;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at euere mo and mo : freres &thorn;ere bi-come.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="104">SEint Domenic matte &thorn;o In a ni&yogh;t : &thorn;at seint petur him bi-tok</L>
<L>Ane staf, ase he cam to him : and seint powel ane bok.</L>
<L>&THORN;o porueide he in is ordre : &yogh;wane freres wenden ouer lond,</L>
<L>to bere ane bok at heore rugges : and ane staf in heore hond.</L>
<L N="108">Seth&thorn;e him &thorn;ou&yogh;te a-slepe al-so : &thorn;at he sai&yogh; &thorn;e freres go</L>
<L>&thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e londe, two and two : and to-gadere non mo.</L>
<L>In-to Tolouse he wende &thorn;o : and bi-lefte him-sulf &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And sone<NOTE PLACE="marg1">V. summe</NOTE> he sente is freres a-boute : &thorn;at huy de-partet were;</L>
<L>In-to spaynne he sente some : and to paris al-so,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ridde Couent to boloygne : heore ordre forth to do;</L>
<L>he het heom wende to and two : and prechi in &thorn;at lond,</L>
<L>At heore rugge bere ane bok : and ane staf in hore hond.</L>
<L N="116">&para; A wonder sweuene seint Domenic : In his slep i-sei&yogh;:</L>
<L>Ore louerd him wrath&thorn;ede swi&thorn;e : op in &thorn;e eyr an hei&yogh;,</L>
<L>&thorn;reo launcene he heold in is hond : &thorn;e poynt toward &thorn;e grounde,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t ase he wolde al &thorn;ene world : &thorn;oru&yogh; smyte In one stounde;</L>
<L N="120">So ferelich he was to bi-holde : &thorn;at it nas non ende.</L>
<L>&thorn;o cam ore leuedi li&yogh;te a-doun : &thorn;at is so milde and hende;</L>
<L>"A, mi sone," heo seide, "&yogh;wat &thorn;enest &thorn;ou? : mcrci and &thorn;in ore!"</L>
<L>"I-nelle," seide ore louerd : "&thorn;is sunne : &thorn;olie more."<MILESTONE N="125b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="124">he seide, "al &thorn;is world is ful of sunne : and ful &yogh;are hath i-beo,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are-fore i-chulle al &thorn;ene world a-sle : with &thorn;eose launces &thorn;reo."</L>
<L>Ore leuedi heold up hire hondene : and sat a-doun a-kneo,</L>
<L>And seide, "leoue sone, nou&thorn;e &thorn;in ore! : &thorn;ov most &thorn;e bet bi-seo,</L>
<L N="128">&thorn;ou most &thorn;ine wrat&thorn;e mienge : with milce and with ore,</L>
<L>And &thorn;enche &thorn;at &thorn;ou most milsful beo : And &thorn;at &thorn;ou bou&yogh;test man ful sore."</L>
<L>"Moder," seide ore louerd &thorn;o : "hov mi&yogh;te ich don &thorn;i lore?</L>
<L>Ne sixt&thorn;ou hou men me mis-doth : &thorn;at I-ne mai hit &thorn;olie more?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="132">"Leoue sone," ore lauedi seide : "a-bijd &yogh;eot one stounde:</L>
<L>Ich habbe ane guode Caumpiun : to &thorn;ine bi-hof&thorn;e i-founde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at schal muche del of &thorn;at folk : onder &thorn;ine wille do;</L>
<L>And anne felawe i-chulle him bi-take : &thorn;at schal helpe him &thorn;er-to."
<PB REF="00000330.tif" N="282"></L>
<L N="136">"Lat me iseo," ore louerd seide : "i-chulle loki &yogh;we&thorn;er huy beon ou&yogh;tes."</L>
<L>Ore leuedi nam &thorn;o seint domenic : and bi-fore [ore] louerd him brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And seint Fraunceis al-so guod : "mi sone," heo seide, "lo</L>
<L>Mi chaumpiun and his felawe : &thorn;at schullen &thorn;is dede do."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e," seide ore louerd, "&thorn;eos beoth bo&thorn;e : strongue and guode &thorn;er-to :</L>
<L>I-chulle heom helpe in heore dedes : and &yogh;iue heom grace al-so."</L>
<L N="142">&para; Seint Domenic a-morewe a-ros : ant to churche wende sone,</L>
<L>And on is sweuene &thorn;ou&yogh;te muche : &yogh;wat him was to done.</L>
<L N="144">he stod and bi-heold a-boute : his felawe he gan to<NOTE PLACE="marg1">V. of</NOTE> seo</L>
<L>&thorn;at ore lauedi him brou&yogh;te a-ni&yogh;t : is felawe for-to beo.</L>
<L>he ne hadde neuer er him i-sei&yogh;e : he descreuede him faste a-non,</L>
<L>his face and is bodi al-so : and<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. in V.</NOTE> him &thorn;ou&yogh;te it was swych on.</L>
<L N="148">he tok and custe him a-non : ase it was wel ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And tolde him al<NOTE PLACE="marg1">V. of al</NOTE> &thorn;at cas : hov him matte a-ni&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And Ey&thorn;er bi-gan to schewi o&thorn;ur : heore wille and heore &thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at huy weren, ase god wolde : in o consent i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="152">And ei&thorn;ur dude bi o&thorn;eres rede : and &thorn;eos tweie ordres wrou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Of frere prechours and of frere Menores : ase ore leuedi heom on brou&yogh;te :</L>
<L>&para; Seint Domenic &thorn;e ordre of frere prechours : ase ich habbe i-seid,</L>
<L>And seint Fraunceis of frere Menores : ei&thorn;er bi o&thorn;eres red.</L>
<L N="156">And sire Symon de Mount-fort : &thorn;at guod kni&yogh;t was and hende,</L>
<L>Sosteinede &thorn;is holie Men : to bringue &thorn;is dede to ende.&mdash;</L>
<L>Ich wene, ich may for so&thorn;e it segge : &yogh;if huy nadden i-beo bi-founde,</L>
<L>&thorn;e world hadde for grete sune i-beo : are &thorn;is i-brou&yogh;t to grounde!</L>
<L N="160">&YOGH;eot, for al &thorn;at heo mouwen a-boute go : to prechi and to schriue,</L>
<L>Sunne is &yogh;eot into al &thorn;is lond : and wrechhede, al-to riue!</L>
<L>here mouwen &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere men i-seo : &thorn;at euere spekez to quede,</L>
<L>In &yogh;wuche manere &thorn;is guode men : bi-gunne furst &thorn;is dede.</L>
<L N="164">Manie of &thorn;is deoueles limes : bi-twene heom seggez al day&yogh; :</L>
<L>"Wel murie was &thorn;e world and guod : are man ani frere i-say&yogh;."</L>
<L>Al-so huy spekez, heom bi-fallez : for ore louerd seide, i-wis :</L>
<L>"bi &thorn;e fruyt man may i-seo : &yogh;wat-manere treo it is :</L>
<L N="168">For &thorn;are ne may of no luy&thorn;ur treo : no guod fruyt springue;"<MILESTONE N="126" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>vnne&thorn;e may a luy&thorn;ur man ani guod word : out of him-sulue bringue.
<PB REF="00000331.tif" N="283"></L>
<L>huy mouwen loki &yogh;wanne ore louerd : heom smyt, harde i-nou&yogh;,</L>
<L>with one of his launces &thorn;reo : &thorn;at he to heom drou&yogh;,</L>
<L N="172">&thorn;at was for &thorn;is tweie holie men : &thorn;ulke tyme on-do;</L>
<L>Fondi heo mouwen heore wy&thorn;er-wine [&yogh;wan]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> huy comiez &thorn;ar-to.</L>
<L>Ake hit ne worth neuere fals : &thorn;at ore louerd him-self sede :</L>
<L>&thorn;at his desciples scholden i-blessede beo : &yogh;wanne men hem spekez to quede</L>
<L N="176">And seggez heom scorn and bysemare : for ore louerdes name.</L>
<L>bi &thorn;e freres &thorn;us it is : of Men &thorn;at seggez heom schame;</L>
<L>Ake ore louerd him-sulf wole wreche nime : &thorn;ei it were &thorn;o with-drawe</L>
<L>For seint Domenic &thorn;e holie Man : and seint Fraunceis, is felawe.&mdash;</L>
<L N="180">&thorn;is holie Man seint dominic : In-to his ordre he nam</L>
<L>Ane &yogh;oungue clerk at one tyme : &thorn;at frere prechour bi-cam</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e feondes lore : with-drou&yogh; him at&thorn;en-ende</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;at he wolde a-&yogh;ein : to &thorn;e worlde wende;</L>
<L N="184">he dude of is Abite : and is schurte on him caste.</L>
<L>Seint Dominic sat a-doun a-kneo : and for him bad wel faste.</L>
<L>Ase he seide is oresones : &thorn;e clerk bi-gan to weopen sore</L>
<L>And pitou[s]liche bi-gan to crie : "a! nou&thorn;e merci, louerd, &thorn;in ore!</L>
<L>&thorn;is schurte<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. schrurte</NOTE> &thorn;at is a-boute me : for-brennez me to grounde;</L>
<L>Drawez hire of for godes loue : o&thorn;ur ich deie in luyte stounde."</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;oru&yogh; ore louerdes grace : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he was for-brent,</L>
<L>Are he nome a-&yogh;ein is Abite : and hadde is heorte i-wend.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="192">BI a frere al-so at boloyne : bi-feol swych a cas</L>
<L>&thorn;at of &thorn;e feond i-fondet was : and with-inne him al-so he was.</L>
<L>Seint Domenic it of-&thorn;ou&yogh;te sore : and het a-godes name</L>
<L>&thorn;ene feond to helle wende a-non : and seide, "&yogh;wi dost&thorn;ou me schuch schame?"</L>
<L N="196">"&thorn;ov ne &thorn;art me blamie nou&yogh;t : for with ri&yogh;te ich am here,"<NOTE PLACE="marg2">Diaboius.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e feond Answerede seint Domenic : ase he was in &thorn;e frere,</L>
<L>"For &thorn;es frere cam &yogh;ursterday to toune : and dronk with-oute leue.</L>
<L>Ase a luyte mot &thorn;are-Inne ich lay : and bi-gan with-inne him weue;</L>
<L N="200">For he ne blessede nou&yogh;t is drinke : and with-oute leue it nam,</L>
<L>Wit lawe ich mai in him beo : and with lawe in him ich am."</L>
<L>"Certes," seide &thorn;is frere, "he seith soth : and ri&yogh;t so it is.</L>
<L N="203">Ichot, i dronk &yogh;urstai in toune : with-oute leue, i-wis,
<PB REF="00000332.tif" N="284"></L>
<L>And Ine blessede nou&yogh;t mi drinke : and a swuch mot &thorn;are was Inne,</L>
<L>And with &thorn;at drinke &thorn;at ich dronk : it schet me sone with-Inne.</L>
<L>Euer-eft he hath I-greued me. : ore louerd fram me him bringue!"</L>
<L>Ase huy tolden here-a-boute : to Matynes huy gonne ringue.</L>
<L N="208">&para; "Out, out," quath &thorn;e deuel &thorn;o : "a-wei ich mot gon :</L>
<L>&thorn;is &thorn;eues with &thorn;is wide hodes : a-rise wollez a-non,</L>
<L>And I-ne dar nou&yogh;t a-bide heore song : adrad ich am wel sore."</L>
<L>he fleu out of &thorn;is selie man : and ne cam nei&yogh; him non-more.&mdash;</L>
<L N="212">As &thorn;e holie man seint Domenic : and his felawes come</L>
<L>with-oute Tolouse bi a watur : ase huy hadden er i-lome,<MILESTONE N="126b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>heore bokes fullen into &thorn;e watur : and sonken a-non to grounde.</L>
<L>huy wenden forth in heore wei : &thorn;o huy ne mi&yogh;ten beon i-founde.</L>
<L N="216">&thorn;are cam &thorn;ane &thorn;ridde day : a fischare with is ginne</L>
<L>And caste is nettes in &thorn;at watur. : &thorn;o felde he heui with-Inne.</L>
<L>&thorn;ou&yogh;te he, "here is fisch i-nou&yogh;" : and bi-gan to drawe faste :</L>
<L>&thorn;e holie manness bokes it weren. : &thorn;o huy comen forth at&thorn;e laste,</L>
<L N="220">Also sounde huy weren and druye : ase huy euerer were;</L>
<L>For al &thorn;at huy leien in &thorn;at watur : no-&thorn;ing &thorn;e worse huy nere.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; At one tyme seint Domenic : at rome was i-sete,</L>
<L>And fourti of is freres al-so : with him to &thorn;e mete.</L>
<L N="224">huy nadden bote a luyte bred&mdash; : wel luyte was &thorn;e lestes,</L>
<L>And alle huy maden heom also Ioifole : ase huy weren at one feste.</L>
<L>Ake natheles huy weren of-hungrede sore : &thorn;ei huy so glade were.</L>
<L>&thorn;o comen &thorn;are tweie children In : with wel milde chere;</L>
<L N="228">Abite of freres huy hadden up-on : fairore neuere nere :</L>
<L>In heore lappene huy brou&yogh;ten mete : ant to seint Domenic hit bere.</L>
<L>&thorn;o huy hadden him &thorn;is mete i-take : huy nusten &yogh;ware huy bi-come.</L>
<L>&thorn;is freres maden heom glade I-nou&yogh; : and wordeliche forth it nome.&mdash;</L>
<L N="232">&para; A dai, as &thorn;is holie Man : in &thorn;e Contreie we[n]de,</L>
<L>&thorn;at lodlokeste weder &thorn;at mi&yogh;te beo : ore louerd ouer him sende.</L>
<L>he bi-gan to maken is oresun : his felawe was in doute.</L>
<L>&thorn;at weder bi-gan to reinie faste : in eche side a-boute;</L>
<L N="236">Ake sone it &yogh;af him roume<NOTE PLACE="marg1">V. Ac hit bigon to &yogh;iue him</NOTE> wei : and al-a-boute with-drawe,</L>
<L>&thorn;at bi fif fet it ne cam nou&yogh;t him nei&yogh; : ne al-so nei&yogh; his felawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>BI-side &thorn;e Cite of Toluse bi a watur huy come.</L>
<L>A man ladde heom ouer In a schip : ase he dude o&thorn;ere i-lome.
<PB REF="00000333.tif" N="285"></L>
<L N="240">Seint Domenic wolde wende is wei : &thorn;o he to londe cam.</L>
<L>&thorn;e passour him het a-bide : and bi &thorn;e cope him nam,</L>
<L>And seide, he scholde him paye is huyre : were him leof &thorn;e loth,</L>
<L>he nolde him serui so for nou&yogh;t : and &thorn;arto he swor is oth.</L>
<L N="244">"Lat me," seide &thorn;is holie Man : "par charite forth quijt gon,</L>
<L>And god wole &yogh;elden &thorn;i trauail : for i-ne habbe seoluer non."</L>
<L>"Al for nou&yogh;t," seide &thorn;es o&thorn;ur : "bi &thorn;e fei &thorn;at i schal to &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Mi trauail &thorn;ou schalt me paie : o&thorn;ur &thorn;i cope bi-leue with me."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;wane &thorn;ou nelt," quath &thorn;e holie man : "for godes loue nou&yogh;t do,</L>
<L>Ich bidde god, &yogh;if is wille beo : &thorn;at he helpe me &thorn;er-to."</L>
<L N="250">&thorn;o lay bi-side &thorn;e schipe &thorn;ere : a peni, fair I-nov&yogh;.</L>
<L>&thorn;e passour beu&yogh; a-doun a-non : and &thorn;ane peni to him drou&yogh;.</L>
<L N="252">"NIm &thorn;are," seide &thorn;is holie man : "ase ore louerd sende &thorn;e.</L>
<L>For i-nabbe mi-sulf nou&yogh;t : ore louerd a-quitez me."</L>
<L>Ore suete louerd nolde nou&yogh;t : &thorn;at &thorn;e freres i-lette were;</L>
<L>him-sulf he sende heom heore schip-huyre. : fair miracle was &thorn;ere!&mdash;</L>
<L N="256">&para; Al-so &thorn;is holie man a ni&yogh;t : In his oresones lay</L>
<L>bi him-sulf in priueite : ase he dude ni&yogh;t and day,</L>
<L>&thorn;e deuel cam and stod bi him : In Abite of frere.<MILESTONE N="127" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"Womme," seide &thorn;e holie man : "&yogh;wat dost &thorn;ov nou&thorn;e here?</L>
<L N="260">&YOGH;wy nart&thorn;ov In &thorn;ine bedde a-slepe : In &thorn;e dortour with &thorn;ine fere?</L>
<L>&thorn;ov wost wel it nis nou&yogh;t ordre : ne non ri&yogh;t guod manere."</L>
<L>&thorn;e Deuel stod and made him signe : ase ho-so seith "i-nelle nou&yogh;t speke</L>
<L>Ne so muche mis-don a-&yogh;eines god : is ordre for-to breke."<NOTE PLACE="marg1">V. has 2 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
<L N="264">&para; Seint Domenic hadde wonder &thorn;ar-of : &yogh;wat frere it mi&yogh;te beo</L>
<L>&thorn;at so wel is ordre heold. : he &thorn;ou&yogh;te he wolde i-seo :</L>
<L>he wende and li&yogh;te ane candle : and bi-heold &thorn;is frere.</L>
<L>&thorn;o he wuste &yogh;wat he was : he &thorn;ou&yogh;te &yogh;wat dost &thorn;ou here;</L>
<L N="268">he blamede him<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. he&dotb;<SUP>i</SUP>o&dotb;m</NOTE> suy&thorn;e muche : &yogh;wat he dude &thorn;o &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>For it were betere is ri&yogh;te : &thorn;at he in helle were.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">diabolus.</NOTE>&para; "&thorn;ou mis-dest more," &thorn;e deuel seide : "&thorn;in ordre for-to breke :</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou wost wel &thorn;is tyme : it ne fallez &thorn;e nou&yogh;t to speke."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Dominicus.</NOTE>&para; "&thorn;ou ne seist nou&yogh;t ri&yogh;t," quath seint Domenic : "for &thorn;e prior may,</L>
<L>For-to wissi is &yogh;oungue freres : speken ni&yogh;t and day.</L>
<L N="274">Ich hote &thorn;at &thorn;ou me telle : nou&thorn;e &thorn;ou art allingues here,
<PB REF="00000334.tif" N="286"></L>
<L>&YOGH;ware-with &thorn;ou fondest mest : In churche ani frere."</L>
<L N="276">&para; "bote ich makie," seide &thorn;e deuel &thorn;o : "late to churche gon,<NOTE PLACE="marg2">diabolus.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;wane he alles &thorn;are-inne is : out &thorn;annes to wiende a-non."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Dominicus.</NOTE>Of &thorn;e dortore he axede him : &yogh;wat were &thorn;are is dede.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">diabolus.</NOTE>&para; "bote ich makie freres to ligge longue : in heore bedde," he sede,</L>
<L N="280">"And &thorn;e [&yogh;wile]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> huy &thorn;arinne beoth : huy &thorn;enchez<NOTE PLACE="marg2">V. &thorn;enken on</NOTE> vuel &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>hit is on of Mine beste hous : Inelle bi-leue it nou&yogh;t."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Dominicus.</NOTE>&para; Seint Domenic axede of &thorn;e freitore : "&yogh;wat is &thorn;i dede &thorn;ere?"</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">diabolus.</NOTE>"bote ich fondi &thorn;e dedes &thorn;ere : of glotonie for-to a-rere;</L>
<L N="284">Ich makie freres to muchel ete : and to drinke al-so,</L>
<L>For-to maken heom feble : godes seruise to do."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Dominicus.</NOTE>&para; "&YOGH;wat In &thorn;e parlore?" seint Domenic seide : "beo nou&thorn;e soth a-knouwe!"</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">diabolus.</NOTE>"A, beo stille," seide &thorn;e schrewe &thorn;o : "&thorn;at hous is al min owe :</L>
<L N="288">For ich heom makie telle &thorn;ere : euerech o&thorn;ur ty&thorn;ingue,</L>
<L>And make heom &thorn;enche and speke al-so : of folies and lesinge."</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Dominicus.</NOTE>&para; "And &yogh;wat &thorn;e chapitle?" seint Domenic seide : "mi&yogh;t &thorn;ou &thorn;are ou&yogh;t winne?"</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">diabolus.</NOTE>"A, beo stille," &thorn;e schrewe seide : "neuere Ine cam &thorn;are-Inne.</L>
<L N="292">Longue, for &thorn;ou it hast i-nemd : &thorn;e worse me schal beo.</L>
<L>God ne suffri me neuere &thorn;are-inne come : ne enes it i-seo!</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at ich habbe i-wonne a-day : and &thorn;e ni&yogh;t bi-fore,</L>
<L>Sone so &thorn;ine freres &thorn;udere comieth : al ich habbe i-lore;</L>
<L N="296">I-wyped it is al<NOTE PLACE="marg1">V. as</NOTE> clene a-wey : ase it neuere nere.</L>
<L>A-corsed is al &thorn;ulke stude : ne come ich neuere &thorn;ere."</L>
<L>&thorn;o wende &thorn;e schrewe is wei : and luyte hadde i-wonne,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e holie man is beden seide : ase he hadde bi-gonne.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="300">LOngue leouede &thorn;is holie man : in guode liue i-nou&yogh;,</L>
<L>And is ordre in guod poynt brou&yogh;te : are he to de&thorn;e drou&yogh;;</L>
<L>At &thorn;e laste, ase god it wolde : &thorn;at he scholde heonnes wende,</L>
<L>A<NOTE PLACE="marg1">V. Atte</NOTE> frere prechur[s] of boloygne : [he] drov toward is ende.<MILESTONE N="127b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he hadde a couent of [twelue] freres : &thorn;o he drou toward &thorn;e de&thorn;e.</L>
<L>his<NOTE PLACE="marg1">V. &thorn;is</NOTE> twelf freres bi-fore him comen : him-seolf was &thorn;e &thorn;rette&thorn;e :<NOTE PLACE="marg1">The half-lines transp. in V.</NOTE></L>
<L>he prechede heom faire i-nou&yogh; : to siwi godes lore,</L>
<L N="307">For-to holden &thorn;e ordre wel : and to echen as more and more.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;reo &thorn;ing he made is testament<NOTE PLACE="marg1">V. quide</NOTE> : ri&yogh;t bi-fore his de&thorn;e :
<PB REF="00000335.tif" N="287"></L>
<L>pouerte,. and loue,. and Meoknesse : his bre&thorn;ren he dude<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. in V.</NOTE> bi-que&thorn;e;</L>
<L>&thorn;at huy weren euere in guode loue : and in Meoknesse al-so,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at huy ladden heore lijf in pouerte : and euere heolden &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L N="312">For he foundede hore ordre furst : ope &thorn;eos &thorn;ingues &thorn;reo</L>
<L>And bi-quath seth&thorn;en alle &thorn;o : &thorn;at wolden is bre&thorn;ren beo.</L>
<L>he &yogh;af alle godes curs and his : &thorn;at his ordre fuylden ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>with grete richesse and worldes feo : for &thorn;e ordre it nolde nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="316">&thorn;o he hadde imaked is testament : he deide ri&yogh;t in &thorn;e place</L>
<L>And bi-tei&yogh;te &thorn;e ordre and is soule : al In ore louerdes grace.</L>
<L>he deide twelf hundred &yogh;er : and four-score<NOTE PLACE="marg1">V. twenti</NOTE> &yogh;er and on<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. two</NOTE></L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;at ore louerd nam : of is moder flechs and bon.</L>
<L N="320">And endleue houndret &yogh;er : and four-score &yogh;er and tene</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;at ore louerd on eor&thorn;e cam : he bi-gan &thorn;e ordre, ich wene.</L>
<L>Wel au&yogh;te we blessi &thorn;e tyme : &thorn;at euere he was bi-gunne :</L>
<L>For mani a soule, ichot, he hath : to godes bi-hof&thorn;e i-wonne.&mdash;</L>
<L N="324">&para; &thorn;o &thorn;is holie Man seint Dominic : bi-gan of &thorn;is liue gon,</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e Ioye of heuene : his soule wende a-non.</L>
<L>For ase &thorn;e prior of bixe<NOTE PLACE="marg1">V. Bride</NOTE> : &thorn;o in is bedde a-slepe lay,</L>
<L>hym &thorn;ou&yogh;te ri&yogh;t &thorn;ulke tyme : &thorn;at he a gret laddre i-say,</L>
<L N="328">&thorn;e laddre schon swy&thorn;e bri&yogh;te : into heuene an hei&yogh;;</L>
<L>Ore louerd on-ouewarde : and ore leuedi he i-sei&yogh;,</L>
<L>Al bi-neo&thorn;e sat a frere : in is scapelori &yogh;wijt,</L>
<L>his hod i-drawe ouer is ei&yogh;en : ri&yogh;t in his Abijt;</L>
<L N="332">Ase he sat on &thorn;is laddre lowe : on &thorn;e ne&thorn;emeste roungue,</L>
<L>Aungles &thorn;are eoden up and doun : And swi&thorn;e murie huy songue.</L>
<L>Ore louerd heold &thorn;is laddre an hei&yogh; : and ore leuedi also,</L>
<L>And drowen &thorn;ane frere up &thorn;are-bi : &thorn;at &thorn;ar-on was i-do,</L>
<L N="336">In his Abijte huy drowen him up : in-to heouene an hei&yogh;;</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at clere lij&yogh;t of heouene : him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at he i-sei&yogh;,</L>
<L>And heouene smot to-gadere a-non : &thorn;o he was with-Inne i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is prior a-wok : he lay in grete &thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="340">his bre&thorn;ren he let cleopie a-non : and seide, "ichot, i-wis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is holie man seint Domenic : out of &thorn;is liue he is;</L>
<L>For i sai&yogh; him ri&yogh;t nou&thorn;e," he seide : "to &thorn;e Ioye of heuene go."</L>
<L>&THORN;e so&thorn;e huy of-Axeden seth&thorn;e : &thorn;at he deide ri&yogh;t &thorn;o.&mdash;</L>
<L N="344">bidde we &yogh;eorne seint Dominic : &thorn;at &thorn;e ordre hath i-wrou&yogh;t,
<PB REF="00000336.tif" N="288"></L>
<L>&THORN;at we beon forth with him : to &thorn;e Ioye of heuene i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>bidde we ore louerd and ore lauedi : for seint Dominikes loue</L>
<L>&THORN;at we moten aftur ore ende-day : to &thorn;e blisse of heuene come.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="42" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>42 [Teofle.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TEofle was a swy&thorn;e gret man : And guod clerk he was al-so,</L>
<L>hext Maister bi-fore alle o&thorn;ere : under &thorn;e bischope i-do.<MILESTONE N="128" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e bischop was ded : Teofle was forth ibrou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="4">to beon bischop aftur him. : ake natheles he nolde [nout],<NOTE PLACE="marg1">nout added later.</NOTE></L>
<L>And seide &thorn;at he nas nou&yogh;t wuyr&thorn;e &thorn;are-to : and guod he cou&thorn;e to luyte.</L>
<L>&THORN;at folke made ane o&thorn;e<SUP>r</SUP>ne sone : with grete nobleye and with pruyte.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e bischop in<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. is</NOTE> his power was : to teofle wrath&thorn;e he caste,</L>
<L N="8">For he was ra&thorn;ur to bischope i-chose : and with &thorn;e o&thorn;ur bischope heold faste :</L>
<L>he dude him out of his mester : and is guod him bi-nam.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at Teofle &thorn;are-aftur-ward : in-to grete pouerte bi-cam;</L>
<L>Al-so riche man ase he was er : ase pouere he was &thorn;o;</L>
<L N="12">So &thorn;at he nuste &yogh;ware-bi libbe. : welle, &thorn;at him was wo!</L>
<L>&THORN;o he was in Miseise i-brou&yogh;t : him schamede swi&thorn;e sore :</L>
<L>Men &thorn;at him honoured er : &thorn;o nolden huy non-more;</L>
<L>Ech man tolde luyte of him&mdash; : for of &thorn;e pouere Men wollez so.</L>
<L>he ne mi&yogh;te for schame a-mong men come : he nuste &yogh;wat for-to do,</L>
<L>&THORN;ene deth he wilnede &thorn;ingue mest. : so &thorn;at he him bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te</L>
<L>&THORN;at, ho-so &thorn;ene feond serui wolde : in grete richesse he him brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>to a giv he wende a ny&yogh;t : &thorn;at wonede &thorn;are-bi-side;</L>
<L N="20">he bad him helpe of &thorn;at cas : &thorn;at gan him &thorn;are bi-tide,</L>
<L>And him to serui for richesse : &thorn;ene deuel a-boute wel wide.</L>
<L>"Wel, it schal beo," &thorn;e giv seide : "ake &yogh;eot &thorn;ou most a-bide;</L>
<L>Cum o&thorn;ur ny&yogh;t &thorn;is tyme : In &thorn;is stude here to me</L>
<L N="24">And i-chulle &thorn;e swuch red do : &thorn;at wel schal liki &thorn;e."</L>
<L>&para; Teofle ne fur-&yogh;at nou&yogh;t &thorn;is. : to &thorn;e giv he eode</L>
<L>In &thorn;at ilke stude &thorn;at o&thorn;ur ni&yogh;t : to beten is grete neode.</L>
<L>"Cum forth with me," quath &thorn;e giv : "ase ich &thorn;e wolle lede.</L>
<L N="28">Ake of &yogh;wat &thorn;u iseo o&thorn;ur heore : ne haue &thorn;ou none drede,</L>
<L>Ne make no signe of &thorn;e creoyz : ne &thorn;eron ne &thorn;ench ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t,
<PB REF="00000337.tif" N="289"></L>
<L>And in swuche richesse nere &thorn;ou neuere : ase &thorn;ov worst sone i-brou&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TEofle wende forth with him : and dude ase he him sede.</L>
<L N="32">Into a priue stude he cam sone : ase &thorn;e giv gan him lede :</L>
<L>&THORN;ene heie feond he fond &thorn;ere : Maister of alle quede,</L>
<L>And al his maynie a-boute him : for-to a-counti heore mis-dede.</L>
<L N="35">"&YOGH;wat is he &thorn;at ilke," quath &thorn;e schrewe : "&thorn;at &thorn;ov bringuest with &thorn;e?"</L>
<L>"he schal beon of &thorn;ine," quath &thorn;e giv : "and for neode he cam to &thorn;e.</L>
<L>A man he was of gret pouwer : &thorn;at is nou&thorn;e him bi-nome,</L>
<L>And for-to bringue him into richesse<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> him in</NOTE> a-&yogh;ein : &thorn;i Man he schal bi|come."</L>
<L>"Wel-come, beu frere," &thorn;e feond seide : "nou&thorn;e &thorn;ou dost wel, i-wis!</L>
<L N="40">haddest &thorn;ov i-don &thorn;us mani day : riche &thorn;ou were are &thorn;is.</L>
<L>bi-com mi Man, and do me homage : and &thorn;ov schalt beo riche i-nov&yogh;;</L>
<L>For I-nelle no man helpe bote mine owene : and elles I dude wov&yogh;."</L>
<L>&para; "Ich bi-come &thorn;i man," quath Teofle : "and clanliche to &thorn;e take."<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 4 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
<L N="44">"Certes, beau frere," quath &thorn;e Deuel : "wel muche &thorn;ov most for|sake :</L>
<L>&THORN;ov most fur-sake god &thorn;at &thorn;e schop : and alle halewene also."</L>
<L>"And ich heom for-sake," Teofle seide : "for &thorn;ine wille ichulle do."<MILESTONE N="128b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"Saunz faille, beu frere," &thorn;e Deuel seide : "&thorn;ou ne mi&yogh;test speke no bet.</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;ou art nou&thorn;e sone riche man I-nov&yogh;. : ake o&thorn;ing &yogh;eot &thorn;e let;</L>
<L>bote &thorn;ou it do, it is for nou&yogh;t : al &thorn;at we habbez i-do :</L>
<L>&THORN;ou most for-sake for-with<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> for&thorn; mid</NOTE> god : Marie, is moder, al-so;</L>
<L>For bote &thorn;ou it wolle do : i-nam siker of &thorn;e nou&yogh;t&mdash;</L>
<L>For manie &thorn;at weren in Mine se[r]uise : heo hath fram me ibrou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>"And ich fur-sake," Teofle seide : "hire sone, and hire al-so,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e ich bi-take lijf and soule : al &thorn;ine wille to do."</L>
<L>"Ov, beu frere," &thorn;e deuel seide : "&yogh;eot ich am a-drad :</L>
<L N="56">For Marie so ofte hath : mine Men fram me i-lad;</L>
<L>Word nis a-&yogh;ein hire bote wind : for &thorn;ei a man hire for-sake,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he wole a-&yogh;ein to hire i-wende : gladliche heo wole him take.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore ichulle beon siker of &thorn;e : er ich mongy with &thorn;e :</L>
<L N="60">guode chartres of &thorn;is foreward : &thorn;ou schalt makie me,</L>
<L>And writen hire with &thorn;ine owene honde : and a-selen hire al-so.
<PB REF="00000338.tif" N="290"></L>
<L>&YOGH;wan &thorn;ou hast i-don al &thorn;is : &thorn;ine wille ichulle do."</L>
<L>Teofle grauntede &thorn;is a-non : &thorn;e chartre he wrou&yogh;te sone</L>
<L N="64">And a-selede hire with is ryng : ase foreward was to done;</L>
<L>he sat on kneo and tok is maister : and custe is fet al-so.</L>
<L>"Nou&thorn;e, teofle," &thorn;e schrewe seide : "&thorn;ov hast al wel i-dc.</L>
<L>&THORN;is chartre ichulle so faste bi<NOTE PLACE="marg1">bi superscrbd.</NOTE>-louke : In helle, &yogh;wanne ich hom come,</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;at I ne drede me nou&yogh;t &thorn;at heo wor&thorn;e : &thorn;oru&yogh; Marie me bi-nome.</L>
<L>And wiend &thorn;ou hom, and beo studefast : ase ichulle a&yogh;ein &thorn;e :</L>
<L>So riche man nere &thorn;ou neuere : ase &thorn;ou worst sone &thorn;oru me."</L>
<L>&THORN;e feond wende hom to helle : and teofle hom al-so,</L>
<L N="72">And &thorn;onkede &thorn;e gywe alle guode : &thorn;at he him hadde ido.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A-Morewe, so sone ase hit was day : &thorn;e bischop after teofle sende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he to him wel hasteliche : with-oute ani defaute wende.</L>
<L>Merci he criede wel deolfulliche : &thorn;o he to him cam,</L>
<L N="76">And bi-tok him a&yogh;ein is power : &thorn;at he er him bi-nam.</L>
<L>Teofle bi-cam a-non so riche : &thorn;at so riche man non nas;</L>
<L>Ase louerd and sire ech man him heold : wel muche is power was;</L>
<L>Eche man was glad to queme him. : Men wondreden of &thorn;at cas,</L>
<L N="80">And seiden, "it nis in &thorn;is world : bote si haut e si bas."</L>
<L>Worldes richesse he hadde i-nou&yogh; : and worldes blisse al-so.</L>
<L>Alas, &thorn;at ani cristine Man scholde : in &thorn;at manere come &thorn;are-to!</L>
<L>&para; Hit bi-feol &thorn;are-after-ward : In wel luyte stounde</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;at &thorn;e giv &thorn;at him &thorn;ere-to brou&yogh;te : with tricherie was i-founde;</L>
<L>I-nome he was and to dome i-brou&yogh;t : and to strongue de&thorn;e i-do :</L>
<L>Fur-barnd he was &thorn;oru Iuggement : and to late he was so!</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o teofle him onder-stod&mdash;: In is heorte he &thorn;ou&yogh;te</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;at &thorn;e Deuel, with &yogh;wam &thorn;e giv was : to &thorn;ulke de&thorn;e him brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh;te he, "nam ich al-so with him? : and &thorn;ei ich beo riche ane stounde,</L>
<L>Ne schal ich neuere i-wite &thorn;e tyme : are he me bringue to grounde :</L>
<L>&THORN;anne were ich fur-lore lijf and soule! : and ich am to him i-bounde<MILESTONE N="129" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So faste, &thorn;at Ine may me with-drawe. : alas &thorn;at ilke stounde!</L>
<L>Alas, &yogh;wy ne hadde ich i-beo ra&thorn;ur ded : &thorn;ane<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;anne</NOTE> i-don &thorn;ulke dede!</L>
<L>Nabbe ich fur-sake heom echone : &thorn;at me scholden helpe and rede?</L>
<L N="95">hou mi&yogh;te ich hopie of grace : &yogh;wane ich heom habbe fur-sake?</L>
<L>A sunful wreche ich am, alas : nas neuere i-seie mi make!
<PB REF="00000339.tif" N="291"></L>
<L>god is so ri&yogh;tful &thorn;at to him : ne hopie ich nou&yogh;t &thorn;ere-fore.</L>
<L>bote ich habbe ore leuedie grace : certus, ich am fur-lore.</L>
<L>For heo was euere ful of milce : and &thorn;ei ich hire habbe for-sake,</L>
<L N="100">hou ich euere &thorn;are-of spede : to hire grace ichulle me take."</L>
<L>To churche he wende to ore leuedi auter : and cride hire milce and ore,</L>
<L>his kneon he beot a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e eor&thorn;e : weopinde swy&thorn;e sore</L>
<L>On hire he cride and weop ful sore : bo&thorn;e ny&yogh;t and day,</L>
<L N="104">Out of &thorn;e chapele nolde he nou&yogh;t : ake euere &thorn;are-inne he lay.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>FOurty dayes and fourty ny&yogh;t : on hire he criede faste.</L>
<L>hire milce, &thorn;at euere was so guod : heo scheowede him at &thorn;e laste :</L>
<L N="107">For ase he criede on hire so &yogh;eorne : &thorn;at swete mayde so hende</L>
<L>cudde hire milde-hede, and fram heouene : to him a-doun gan wende.</L>
<L>"hov mi&yogh;te ich," heo seide, "&thorn;ou wrechche Man : eny grace &thorn;e take,</L>
<L>And hou mi&yogh;te ich to mi sone for &thorn;e bidde : &yogh;wane &thorn;ou hast him for-sake?"</L>
<L>"A, leuedi, leuedi," teofle seide : "nou&thorn;e, leuedi, &thorn;in ore!</L>
<L N="112">Ich habbe i-sunegut manne mest : &thorn;at rewez me wel sore.</L>
<L>haue merci of &thorn;is sunfule wrechche! : I-nelle do sunne non-more,</L>
<L>Ake, &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt me &thorn;ine grace &yogh;iue : Ichulle don al &thorn;i lore."</L>
<L>"&THORN;ov sunfule man," ore leuedi seide : "ase muche ase on me is,</L>
<L N="116">to &thorn;e ichulle beo milde I-nov&yogh; : and to alle cristine men, i-wis :</L>
<L>For ich louie muche cristine Men : And norichi heom al-so,</L>
<L>and euere am redi to heom a-li&yogh;te : heore bone forto do;</L>
<L>And swi&thorn;e muche ich &thorn;olie ofte : mine sone to maken li&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;at he ne nimez of heom grete wreche : ase he wolde ofte-si&thorn;e.</L>
<L>Ake sch[r]yf &thorn;e to him of &thorn;ine sunnes : &thorn;at was i-bore of me</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;olede deth for sunfule men : and ichulle bidde for &thorn;e."</L>
<L>"Leuedi, merci," Teofle seide : "vnwuyr&thorn;e ich am &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L N="124">with &thorn;at Mouth &thorn;at ich him for-sok : swuch schrift to him do."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;us, hardiliche," ore leuedi seide : "for he is milde and softe;</L>
<L>Wel &thorn;ou wost &thorn;at sunfule men : gret loue he cuth wel ofte.</L>
<L>For he was for sunfule Men i-bore : and to de&thorn;e for heom i-do,</L>
<L N="128">he mot nede to heom beo milde : for ri&yogh;t kuynde it wole so."
<PB REF="00000340.tif" N="292"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Teofle bi-gan &thorn;o weope and crie : "louerd, merci," he sede,</L>
<L>"to &thorn;e ich me schriue with deolful heorte : for mi lu&thorn;er mis|dede.</L>
<L>haue merci of me, al-so wisliche : ase &thorn;ou were for me i-bore</L>
<L N="132">And for us &thorn;oledest deth : &thorn;at we ne scholden beo fur-lore!</L>
<L>&THORN;ench nou&thorn;e, louerd, on mine wrechhede! : swete Ihesu, &thorn;in ore!</L>
<L>Do me &thorn;ine milce, ich bidde &thorn;e, louerd : i-nelle do sunne neuere-eft more."</L>
<L>&para; "Teofle, teofle," ore leuedi seide : "for &thorn;i cristine-dom,</L>
<L N="136">An for pite &thorn;at ich habbe of cristine men : seth&thorn;e mi sone mi flesch nom,</L>
<L>I-chulle bidde on mine bare kneon : mi sone for &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. me</NOTE> wel sone.</L>
<L>beo studefast, ase &thorn;ou hast bi-gonne<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. bi-goume</NOTE> : and he wole i-heore &thorn;i bone."</L>
<L>with &thorn;is word Teofle nuste : &yogh;ware ore leuedi bi-com.</L>
<L N="140">he weop and cride euere &yogh;eorne : and al to hire grace him nom.</L>
<L>&THORN;reo dawes with-oute mete and drinke : &thorn;are he gan a-bide</L>
<L>In wop and sor and deol j-nou&yogh; : on ore leuedi euere he criede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ore lauedi cam &thorn;o al li&yogh;inde : and with glade semblaunt also,</L>
<L N="144">"Teofle," heo seide, "&thorn;ou hast nou&thorn;e sone : penaunce i-nou&yogh; i-do;</L>
<L>beo glad and bli&thorn;e, for ich habbe i-bede : mine sone milce and ore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hath &thorn;ine sunnes &thorn;e fur-&yogh;yue. : ne sunegue &thorn;ov nonmore!"</L>
<L>"I-hered beo &thorn;ov," teofle seide : "and &thorn;i holie grace,</L>
<L N="148">And i-blessed beo &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at ich to &thorn;e : criede in &thorn;usse place!</L>
<L>Leuedi, euere ich am a-drad : and siker nam ich nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Are &thorn;e chartre &thorn;at ich him<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. him</NOTE> made : leuedi, to me beo i-brou&yogh;t :</L>
<L>Leuedi, &thorn;ou art ful of milce : &thorn;at &thorn;ou me schewest in &thorn;is place :</L>
<L N="152">&YOGH;wane &thorn;i milce, leuedi, is so muche : do me &thorn;erof &thorn;ine grace!"</L>
<L>"Nov sone, theofle," ore leuedi seide : "&yogh;eot ichulle &thorn;e milde beo,"</L>
<L>with &thorn;is word heo wende forth : &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;te hire more i-seo.</L>
<L>hire milce heo scheowede, for heo cam : to him &thorn;ene &thorn;ridde day</L>
<L N="156">And brou&yogh;te &thorn;e chartre and bi-tei&yogh;te as him : ase he a-slepe lay,</L>
<L>And wende a-&yogh;ein wel stilleliche&mdash; : and &thorn;o Theofle a-wok,</L>
<L>&THORN;e chartre he heold in is hond : &thorn;at ore leuedi him bi-tok.</L>
<L>glad and bli&thorn;e he was i-nou&yogh; : and me &thorn;unchez &thorn;at he wel ou&yogh;te!
<PB REF="00000341.tif" N="293"></L>
<L N="160">Ore lauedie he &thorn;onkede and hire grace : &thorn;at to swuche guodnesse him brou&yogh;te.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 2 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is cas bi-feol in leinte : on a satures-day at ni&yogh;t.</L>
<L>A-morewe, &thorn;ene sonenday : &thorn;e day was cler and bri&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> as &thorn;e day was li&yogh;t</NOTE>,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischop and is clerkes : and muche folk al-so</L>
<L N="164">to churche comen, ase ri&yogh;t was : godes seruise to do.</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t &thorn;o godspel was i-rad : Theofle forth him wende,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e bischopes fet he feol a-doun : and &thorn;ene Deuel more he schende :</L>
<L>he tolde &thorn;e bischope euerech del : and al &thorn;e folke al-so,</L>
<L N="168">&THORN;at foreward<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. fereward</NOTE> and &thorn;e sikernesse : &thorn;at he hadde &thorn;e Deuele i-do,</L>
<L>And hov of &thorn;e Deueles mi&yogh;te : ore swete leuedi him caste</L>
<L>And brou&yogh;te him &thorn;e chartres &thorn;at he made : &thorn;at bi-loke was in helle faste.</L>
<L>&THORN;e chartre bi-fore al &thorn;at folk : he let &thorn;e bischope rede,</L>
<L N="172">&THORN;at ech man i-sei&yogh;e is lu&thorn;ere sunne : and ore leuedie mildhede.</L>
<L>&THORN;a[t] folk wolde &thorn;e chartre witen : for miracle, &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> as</NOTE> huy bede.</L>
<L>"A, Merci, merci, for godes loue" : Theofle ofte seide,</L>
<L>"For &thorn;e &yogh;wyle &thorn;e chartre is i-hol : &yogh;eot euere-more me dredeth;</L>
<L N="176">Are heo beo to douste i-brent : siker lijf ne mai ich lede."</L>
<L>&THORN;e chartre huy barnden bi-fore heom alle : &thorn;at ech man mi&yogh;te i-seo.</L>
<L>"Certes, nou&thorn;e ich hopie," theofle seide : "&thorn;at siker ich mouwe beo."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e bischop hadde is masse i-do : &thorn;at folk cam mani-folde</L>
<L N="180">A-boute Theofle in eche side : &thorn;at wonder to bi-holde.</L>
<L>bri&yogh;tore &thorn;ane &thorn;e sonne, heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te : he schon in-to al is face,</L>
<L>&THORN;at non ne mi&yogh;te for bri&yogh;thede : bi-holde him in &thorn;at place.<MILESTONE N="130" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he liet dele and &yogh;iue pouere men : &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> his</NOTE> guod wel clene &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="184">And seide &thorn;at he out of churche nolde : &thorn;e &yogh;wile he a-liue were.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e stude he wende a-non : &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;er</NOTE> ore leuedi to him a-li&yogh;te</L>
<L>And brou&yogh;te him &thorn;e chartres of is sunnes : &thorn;oru&yogh; hire swete mi&yogh;te.</L>
<L>A-non-ri&yogh;t he bi-gan to sikni : and &thorn;are ri&yogh;t a-doun lay;</L>
<L N="188">his bre&thorn;ren he custe echone : and deide &thorn;ene &thorn;ridde day.</L>
<L>&thorn;at folk dude bi him &thorn;at was to done : and bureden him ri&yogh;t &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>his soule wende to heuene<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. henene</NOTE> anon : &thorn;are I-cholde we alle were.</L>
<L>For he is a seint in heuene an hei&yogh; : and his day fallez in &thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L N="192">A luyte bi-fore Aueryl : ase &thorn;e bok us doth lere.</L>
<L>Wel fair Miracle ore leuedi dude : &thorn;at brou&yogh;te him of &thorn;ulke wo,</L>
<L>Ase heo hath manye o&thorn;ere i-don : and &yogh;eot heo wole wel mo.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="43" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000342.tif" N="294">
<HEAD>43 [George]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint George &thorn;e holie man : ase we findez i-write,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e londe of Cappadoce : he was i-bore and bi-&yogh;ite.</L>
<L>&thorn;e false godes he for-sok : and tornede to cristine-dom,</L>
<L N="4">And louede Iesu crist swi&thorn;e wel : and holi man bi-com.</L>
<L>Dacian, &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere prince : &thorn;at was in &thorn;ulke stounde,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e cristine men &thorn;at he fond : he let bringue to grounde.</L>
<L>A day, ase he honourede is false godes : and o&thorn;ere manie on,</L>
<L N="8">Seint George I-sai&yogh; al &thorn;is : ase he cam &thorn;are-forth gon.</L>
<L>&thorn;e signe he made of &thorn;e croiz : and blessede him al-a-boute</L>
<L>And Armede him &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e holie gost : with-Inne and with-oute,</L>
<L>he wende him forth wel baldeliche : and wel loude bi-gan to grede</L>
<L N="12">To Dacian and to Alle his : and &thorn;eose wordes sede :</L>
<L>"Alle false godes so beoth : deuelschine, i-wis;</L>
<L>For ore louerd made heuene : ase in &thorn;e sautere i-writen it is."</L>
<L>&thorn;o Dacian i-heorde &thorn;is : he grennede and femde faste,</L>
<L N="16">And lourede with sori semblaunt : and &thorn;eos wordes out he caste :</L>
<L>"Belamy, &yogh;wat art &thorn;ou : &thorn;at so gret fol art and so bold,</L>
<L>&thorn;at in ovre power and bi ovre godes : swuche wordes hast i-told?</L>
<L>&thorn;ov ne dost us nou&yogh;t one schame : ase we alle I-seoth,</L>
<L N="20">Ake ore godes and us, &yogh;wane &thorn;ou seist : &thorn;at huy deuelene beoth.</L>
<L>Tel me sone of &yogh;wannes &thorn;ou art : and &yogh;wat is &thorn;i ri&yogh;te name,</L>
<L>&thorn;at darst us segge and ore godes : &thorn;us baldeliche swch<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. schwch</NOTE> schame."</L>
<L>"George, ich hote," &thorn;is o&thorn;ur seide : "and cristine man ich am,</L>
<L N="24">And out of &thorn;e lond of cappadoce : hidere to eov ich cam."</L>
<L>"bel amy," seide Dacian : "torne &thorn;i word a-non</L>
<L>And honoure here ovre godes : o&thorn;ur it schal an-o&thorn;ur gon."</L>
<L>"Beo stille, &thorn;ov fol," seint George seide : "&thorn;ou spext embe nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="28">For ich habbe on Iesu crist : I-fastned al mi &thorn;ou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>"A, traytour," seide Dacian : "wolt &thorn;ov take on so?</L>
<L>&thorn;ov schalt in o&thorn;ere ribaudies : sone dai&yogh;es beo i-do."</L>
<L>he liet him hangi up an hei&yogh; : In one-manere rode</L>
<L>And &thorn;are-to him binde faste al naked : with ropes strongue and guode.</L>
<L>with kene Owles &thorn;er-under : &thorn;e tormentores stode<MILESTONE N="130b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="34">And to-drowen is holie lymes : &thorn;at faste huy ronne on blode;</L>
<L>Al huy to-teren is te[n]dre flesch : &thorn;e peces fullen to grounde;
<PB REF="00000343.tif" N="295"></L>
<L N="36">Brenninde eoyle huy nomen seth&thorn;e : and casten In &thorn;e wounde.</L>
<L>&thorn;o huy hadden him so longue to-drawe : &thorn;at reou&thorn;e it was to seo,</L>
<L>huy bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;ten heom of more wo : and nomen him a-doun of &thorn;e treo :</L>
<L>with smarte scourges huy leiden on him : and wounde op-on o&thorn;ur made&mdash;</L>
<L N="40">to &thorn;e bare bon &thorn;e scourgene comen : ase &thorn;e Owles hadden i-wade;</L>
<L>&thorn;e woundene huy selten seth&thorn;e : and salt ful &thorn;icke caste,</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e with a clout of here : roddeden &thorn;e woundes faste.</L>
<L>louerd, muche was &thorn;e pine &thorn;at he hadde : ech ope o&thorn;ur &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="44">&thorn;o men selten so is quike flesch : and roddeden so with here!</L>
<L>Reu&thorn;e it was swuch pine to se : ho-so ou&yogh;t of reu&thorn;e were;</L>
<L>And euere lay &thorn;e guode Man : ase &thorn;ei him no&thorn;ing nere.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;o Dacian i-sai&yogh; &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;te : ouer-comen him so,</L>
<L N="48">he let binde &thorn;ene holie man : and in strongue prisone do.</L>
<L>&thorn;are he lai al &thorn;e longue ni&yogh;t : to o&thorn;ur wo &thorn;at he hadde.</L>
<L>A-morewe &thorn;e tormentores eft-sone : bi-fore Daciane him ladden.</L>
<L>In eche manere huy fondeden &thorn;o : &yogh;if huy mi&yogh;ten tuyrne is &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="52">Ake &thorn;o huy i-sei&yogh;en euerech-one : &thorn;at it was al for nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Dacian let makie a weol of bras : so strong ase he mi&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And scharpe sweordes wel &thorn;icke a-boute : &thorn;are-on faste he pi&yogh;te :</L>
<L>he let nime &thorn;is holie man : and &thorn;are-aboue him do,</L>
<L N="56">&thorn;at &thorn;e swerdes scholden is bodi to-rende : and to-drawe al-so.</L>
<L>So sone ase huy &thorn;is guode man : a-boue &thorn;usse &yogh;weole brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;weol to-brac, ase god it wolde : and to-bruysde al-to nou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;is holie man : harmles &thorn;arof he was.</L>
<L N="60">Dacian was swi&thorn;e wroth : &thorn;o he i-sai&yogh; &thorn;at cas.</L>
<L>&para; A forneis he let maken<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> nyme</NOTE> of bras : and fullen it ful of led;</L>
<L>he let maken a strong fuyr i-nov&yogh; : ase he nam sone is red.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at led was al i-molte : and boylede swi&thorn;e faste,</L>
<L N="64">he let nimen &thorn;is holie man : and ri&yogh;t a-middes caste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint George nam up is hond : and &thorn;e croiz bi-fore him made,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e wallinde led : baldeliche he gan wade.</L>
<L>&thorn;are-Inne he sat wel softe a-doun : ase &thorn;ei him no&thorn;ing nere,</L>
<L N="68">And leonede to &thorn;e brerde stille : ase &thorn;ei he a-slepe were;</L>
<L>he lai ase &thorn;ei he in reste were : for-to &thorn;at led at&thorn;e laste</L>
<L>was al in-to &thorn;e colde i-turnd : &thorn;at boylede er so faste.
<PB REF="00000344.tif" N="296"></L>
<L>Louerd, muche is &thorn;i mi&yogh;te : ase men mi&yogh;ten &thorn;are i-seo,</L>
<L N="72">&thorn;at ani man mi&yogh;te in &thorn;e wallinde led : so longue harmles beo!</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;o Dacian &thorn;is i-sei&yogh; : his wit him was nei&yogh; bi-nome;</L>
<L>"Mahun," he seide, "hov geth &thorn;is? : &yogh;ware is nov&thorn;e &thorn;i mi&yogh;te bi-come?</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane I-ne may &thorn;is foule &thorn;eof : ouer-come in &thorn;usse wise,</L>
<L N="76">I schal bi-nime him sone is lijf : &thorn;are he ne schal neuere a-rise."</L>
<L>his dom he gan to &yogh;iue a-non : &thorn;at huy seint George nome</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="131" UNIT="folio">And drowen him &thorn;oru&yogh;-ovt<NOTE PLACE="marg1">out superscribed.</NOTE> al &thorn;e toun : for-to-huy with-oute come,</L>
<L>[&amp; &thorn;at]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. in the MS.</NOTE> huy smiten of his heued : with-oute &thorn;e toun at&thorn;e laste,</L>
<L N="80">And is bodi &thorn;are in sum foul place : to wilde bestes it caste.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is dom was &thorn;us I&yogh;yue : hit nas nou&yogh;t i-lete :</L>
<L>huy nomen and drowen &thorn;is holie man : villiche &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e strete,</L>
<L>Forto huy comen with-oute toun : &thorn;are huy wolden is heued of smite.</L>
<L N="84">heore wepne huy drowen forth and &yogh;wetten hem : kene forto bite.</L>
<L>"Leoue bre&thorn;ren," seint George seide : "one stounde a-bidez &yogh;uyte,</L>
<L>For-to ich habbe to Iesu crist : mine bone i-bede a luyte."</L>
<L>&para; his hondene he heold up on hei&yogh; : a-doun he sat on kneo,</L>
<L N="88">And seide, "swete louerd Iesu crist : &thorn;at alle &thorn;ing mi&yogh;t i-seo,</L>
<L>graunte me, &yogh;if &thorn;i wille is : &thorn;at, ho-so in guode manere</L>
<L>halewez mine day in Aueril : for mi loue on eor&thorn;e here,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;are ne falle in &thorn;at hous : no qualm in al &thorn;e &yogh;ere,</L>
<L N="92">Ne gret sijknesse ne hongur strong : &thorn;at &thorn;arof beo no fere;</L>
<L>And ho-so in perile of &thorn;e se : to me bit is bone,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur in any o&thorn;ur stude perilous : louerd, &thorn;ov helpe heom sone!"</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;o i-heorden huy a voiz in heuene : &thorn;at to him seide, i-wis :</L>
<L N="96">"Mi blessede child, cum here forth to me : &thorn;i bone i-heord is."</L>
<L>&thorn;o is heued was of i-smite : ase al &thorn;at folk i-sei&yogh;,</L>
<L>Aungles nomen is swete soule : and to heuene beren on hei&yogh;.</L>
<L>&thorn;are he is in grete Ioye : &thorn;at last with-outen ende.</L>
<L N="100">Nov god for seint Georges loue : late ore soule &thorn;udere wende.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="44" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>44 Vita sancti Eadmundi regis.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Eadmund &thorn;e holie kyng : i-bore was here bi este<NOTE PLACE="marg1">The half-lines <I>al.</I> transposed.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e on ende of Engelonde : of &yogh;wam Men makiez feste;</L>
<L>For of southfolke he was kyng : and of &thorn;e contreie wel wide.</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;are weren in Enguelonde &thorn;o : kyngus in fale side.
<PB REF="00000345.tif" N="297"></L>
<L>Swy&thorn;e fair kny&yogh;t and strong he was : and hardi and quoynte,</L>
<L>Meoke and milde and ful of milce : and large in eche poynte.</L>
<L>Twey princes of an o&thorn;ur lond : &thorn;at weren in lu&thorn;ere &thorn;ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="8">Nomen heore red to-gadere faste : to bringue enguelond to nou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>hubba was &thorn;at on i-hote : and &thorn;at o&thorn;ur hei&yogh;te hynguar.</L>
<L>Into enguelond huy comen with gret fierd : are ani man were i-war :</L>
<L>In North-humberlond huy bi-gunne : and &thorn;are huy slowen to grounde</L>
<L N="12">And robbeden and barnden al to nou&yogh;t : and destruyden al &thorn;at huy founde.</L>
<L>&thorn;o huy hadden north-humberlond : clanliche a-doun i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Al-so huy wolden al enguelond : and &thorn;ou&yogh;ten huy nolden blinne nou&yogh;t :</L>
<L>hynguar, &thorn;at &thorn;e o. maister was : his felawe he bi-lefde &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="16">hubba, [&amp;] wende here bi este : to quelle &thorn;at &thorn;are were.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e guodnesse of seint Eadmund : he heorde muche telle :</L>
<L>Into is lond he wende a-non : to fondi him to quelle.</L>
<L>Into is hexte toune he cam : er any man were i-war,</L>
<L N="20">And robbede furst al &thorn;at he fond : and made &thorn;ane toun wel bar;</L>
<L>And al-so he slov &thorn;at folk to grounde : al &thorn;at he mi&yogh;te of-gon,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ong and old, wyf and Mayde : he ne sparede neuere on.</L>
<L>children fram heore moder breste : he drov and let heom quelle<MILESTONE N="131b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="24">And al-to-hewe bi-fore &thorn;e moderes : &thorn;at reu&thorn;e it was to telle;</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;are-After he let &thorn;e Moderes a-sle : sorewe &thorn;are was I-nov&yogh;!</L>
<L>&thorn;ane toun he barnde al to douste : and al &thorn;at folk a-slov&yogh;.</L>
<L>he axede at some of &thorn;e men : &yogh;ware heore kyng were;</L>
<L>And huy tei&yogh;ten him &yogh;ware he was : huy ne dorsten non-o&thorn;ur for fere :</L>
<L N="29">In &thorn;e toune of Eglesdone : a guod wei &thorn;annes, he was.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere prince heorde &thorn;at : he ne made no softe pas,</L>
<L>Ake wende him &thorn;udere ful hastifliche : with is lu&thorn;ere men ech-one.</L>
<L N="32">huy comen and metten &thorn;ane holie kyng : with-oute &thorn;e &yogh;ate al one.</L>
<L>A-non so hynguar wuste &thorn;at it was he : he let him nime &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And bi-segi is Men alle : &thorn;at with-Inne were.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;is holie kyn[g] was faste Inome. : and In a luyte stounde</L>
<L>Bi-fore &thorn;e prince he was i-lad : naked and faste i-bounde,</L>
<L N="37"><NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 37-8 are to be transposed.</NOTE>For-to a-fongue &thorn;are is dom : and non so men him nome (!),<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.:</I> &thorn;o his dom was i&yogh;yue, faste me him nom</NOTE></L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t as men ladden ore louerd bi-fore pilatus : for-to a-fongue is dome.</L>
<L>In a wode as he was i-lad : to a treo huy him bounde
<PB REF="00000346.tif" N="298"></L>
<L N="40">And with smarte scourges beoten him sore : and maden him many a wounde.</L>
<L>&thorn;is holie man stod euere stille : he ne grochchede nou&yogh;t ene,</L>
<L>Ake euere he cride "god, &thorn;in ore!" : and non o&thorn;ur he nolde him mene.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere tormentores : &thorn;at beoten him so sore,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou&yogh;ten &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;ei</NOTE> huy him schame duden : and<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> hov huy mi&yogh;ten don him more.</L>
<L>huy benden heore bouwene and stoden a-feor : and heore Arewene ri&yogh;ten :</L>
<L>Ase to ane marke huy schoten to him : ase euene ase huy mi&yogh;ten.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Arewene stikeden on him ful &thorn;icke : and al is bodi to-drowe;</L>
<L N="48">And euere stod &thorn;is holie man : ri&yogh;t stille, ase &thorn;ei he lowe.</L>
<L>Ase ful ase is an Irchepil : of piles al-a-boute,</L>
<L>So ful he stikede of Arewene : with-Inne and with-oute,</L>
<L>So ful, &thorn;at in none stude : on Arewe ne mi&yogh;te In wende</L>
<L N="52">bote he for-korue some o&thorn;ure : more is bodi to rende.</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;e holie man i-Martred was : seint sebastian,</L>
<L>Also huy serueden is holie bodi : and schoten &thorn;ane holie man,</L>
<L>&thorn;at euerech pece fram o&thorn;ur fleu : &thorn;at wonder was of is liue.</L>
<L N="56">And euere he stod ase him no rou&yogh;te : and cride on god wel bliue.</L>
<L>&thorn;o hynguar i-sai&yogh; &thorn;at huy ne mi&yogh;ten : &thorn;are-with ouer-come him nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>A-non he let is heued of smyte : &thorn;at he were of liue i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ase &thorn;is holie man is beden bad : a man smot of is heued;</L>
<L N="60">And<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> ac</NOTE> is bodi was<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> was er</NOTE> al-to-rend : and nou&yogh;t i-hol bi-leued.</L>
<L>And for it was so al-to-drawe : huy leten it ligge &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Ake, for men ne scholden nou&yogh;t finde is heued : forth with heom huy it bere</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e wode of Eglesdone : ane<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. ane ane</NOTE> derne stude huy founde :</L>
<L N="64">A-mong &thorn;icke &thorn;ornes huy it casten : and hudden it in &thorn;e grounde.</L>
<L>&thorn;o heo hadden of &thorn;is holie kyng : al heore wille &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>glade and bli&thorn;e huy wenden forth : lu&thorn;ere Men ase it were.</L>
<L>&thorn;at heued huy hudden derneliche : &thorn;at no cristine man ne come,</L>
<L N="68">&YOGH;if &thorn;at &thorn;are ani bi-lefte a-lyue : and with him &thorn;annes it nome.<MILESTONE N="132" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A wilde wolf &thorn;are cam sone : and to &thorn;e heuede he drov&yogh;,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are oppe he lai and wuste it faste : a-&yogh;ein is kuynde i-nouv&yogh;&mdash;</L>
<L>For is kuynde were more to for-swolewen it&mdash; : and lickede<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. lickeden</NOTE> it ofte and custe,
<PB REF="00000347.tif" N="299"></L>
<L N="72">And ri&yogh;t ase he wolde is owene &yogh;welp : with wilde bestes it wuste.</L>
<L>&para; Seth&thorn;e &thorn;are comen cristine Men : and in sum power weren i-brou&yogh;t :</L>
<L>&thorn;at holie bodi huy founden sone : for it nas i-hud ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Ake for huy ne founden nou&yogh;t &thorn;at heued : a-boute huy wenden wide</L>
<L N="76">And sou&yogh;tten it longue, In manie studes : euerech in his side.</L>
<L>huy ne mi&yogh;ten it finde for no &thorn;yng. : so &thorn;at huy comen ane day</L>
<L>bi-sides &thorn;ulke &thorn;icke &thorn;ornes : &thorn;are ase &thorn;at heued lai.</L>
<L>huy nusten nou&yogh;t &thorn;at it was &thorn;ere. : &thorn;o bi-gan &thorn;at heued to grede,</L>
<L N="80">Ase it a-mong &thorn;e &thorn;ornes lay : and ri&yogh;t &thorn;eose wordes sede :</L>
<L>&para; "Here, here, here," with swete voyz : ase &thorn;ei he were a-liue.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;at folk i-heorde &thorn;at : &thorn;uder-ward huy wenden bliue :</L>
<L>&thorn;at heued huy founden in &thorn;ulke stude : ase hit him-sulf sede.</L>
<L N="84">Louerd, i-hered beo &thorn;i mi&yogh;te : &thorn;at &thorn;are was a fair dede!</L>
<L>&thorn;at heued huy beren to &thorn;e bodi : and setten it euene &thorn;are-to,</L>
<L>And beren it forth with gret honovr : ase ri&yogh;t was forto do.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 4 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TO seint Eadmundesburie huy ladden him : ase men cleopiez nou&thorn;e &thorn;ene toun&mdash;</L>
<L N="88">&thorn;are is on Abbeie of blake Monkes : ase huy setten him a-doun.</L>
<L>In swy&thorn;e noble schrine huy brou&yogh;ten him : ase ri&yogh;t was for-to do.</L>
<L>&thorn;are he lijth &yogh;eot hol and sound : ase heo i-seoth &thorn;at comieth him to :</L>
<L>For is bodi &thorn;at was so to-drawe : hol bi-cam a-non</L>
<L N="92">And sound, as &thorn;e &yogh;wyle he a-liue was : bo&thorn;e of flesch and bon;</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;at heued al-so faste to &thorn;e bodi : ase it was euerer.</L>
<L>In al is bodi nas o weom : &thorn;at man mi&yogh;te i-seo &thorn;er,</L>
<L>bote ase is heued was of I-smyte : ase ore louerd it wolde,</L>
<L N="96">A smal red line is al-a-boute : schininde ase of golde.</L>
<L>A swy&thorn;e fair pilegrimage it is : &thorn;udere forto fare,</L>
<L>For-to honouri &thorn;at holie bodi : &thorn;at &thorn;are hath i-leie so &yogh;are.</L>
<L>Nov&thorn;e god for &thorn;e loue of seint Eadmund : &thorn;at was so noble king,</L>
<L N="100">graunte us &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;at he is Inne : aftur ovre ending. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="45" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>45 [Mi&yogh;hel].<NOTE PLACE="foot">This legend I have published before in 'Lemcke, Jahrbuch f&uuml;r rom. und engl. phil., 1874.'</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEynt MI&yogh;hel &thorn;e Archaungel : and is felawes also,</L>
<L>huy beoth bi-tweone ore louerd and us : to schewi &yogh;wat we schulle do.
<PB REF="00000348.tif" N="300"></L>
<L>Ane day huy habbez in &thorn;e &yogh;ere : &thorn;oru&yogh; al cristinedom.</L>
<L N="4">&thorn;oru&yogh; fair miracle of seint Mi&yogh;hel : &thorn;e day a man<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> me</NOTE> furst nom.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e one ende of Apuyle : a gret hul &thorn;are was and hei&yogh;</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e hul gargan is i-cleoped : for a man &thorn;at &thorn;are was nei&yogh;,</L>
<L>&thorn;at gargan i-cleoped was&mdash; : &thorn;e hul &thorn;are-fore hatte so.</L>
<L N="8">&thorn;is gargan was wel riche man : and in gret power i-do.</L>
<L>hit bi-feol &thorn;reo hundret &yogh;er : and euene twenti ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;at ore louerd for us : In is Moder was a-lij&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at garganes reo&thorn;eren : and o&thorn;ure bestes I-nowe</L>
<L N="12">A Morewenes op-on &thorn;e hei&yogh;e hulle : to heore lesewe heom drowe.</L>
<L>An eue &thorn;is ru&thorn;erene wenden hom : as heore wone was, ech-one.</L>
<L>Bote o bole, &thorn;at he louede muche : was bi-hynden al one :</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e hexte toret of &thorn;e hul : &thorn;e bole wel euene drov&yogh;.</L>
<L N="16">And &thorn;o &thorn;e louerd hine miste an euen : a-nuyd he was i-nov&yogh;;</L>
<L>With him he nam men i-nowe : and sou&yogh;te into al &thorn;at lond :</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e hexte hurste of al &thorn;e hulle : at&thorn;e laste he him fond.</L>
<L>he nam one aruwe envenimed : in grete wrathe I-nov&yogh;</L>
<L N="20">And schet to &thorn;is selie bole : and with grete strenc&thorn;e i-nov&yogh;.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> drou&yogh;</NOTE></L>
<L>Ake &thorn;is Arewe tornede euene a-&yogh;ein : to him &thorn;at hire schet,</L>
<L>And smot him, ase it in wreche were : deope wounde and gret.</L>
<L>Nov was &thorn;at a wonder Arewe : and wonder wei heo sou&yogh;te!</L>
<L N="24">I-ne kepte nou&yogh;t leorni so forto scheote : ne swuch arewe &thorn;at man me brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>A wonder schere-wynd heo was on : womme &yogh;wat heo &thorn;ou&yogh;te!</L>
<L>Ake euere me &thorn;inchez he &thorn;at hire schet : &thorn;e game sore a-bou&yogh;te.&mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;at folk &thorn;at &thorn;are-a-boute stod : in grete wonder was;</L>
<L N="28">to &thorn;e bischope huy wenden anon : and tolden him al &thorn;at cas.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bischop was in grete fere : and in grete &thorn;ou&yogh;te stod;</L>
<L>A tokningue it was, he wuste wel : of vuele o&thorn;ur of guod :</L>
<L>he hiet al &thorn;e contreye a-boute : In oresones anon-ri&yogh;t to beo</L>
<L N="32">And &thorn;re dawes in fastingue al-so : &thorn;is tokningue forto seo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seint MI&yogh;hel after &thorn;ene &thorn;ridde day : to &thorn;e bischope he com,</L>
<L>And seide, "hou &thorn;inchez &thorn;e of &thorn;is dede? : was it a wonder dom?</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;inche ov no wonder &thorn;ar-of : for mi wille it was, i-wis :</L>
<L N="36">For Ichulle witie wel &thorn;ulke stude : &thorn;at in mine warde is;</L>
<L>And In &thorn;usse manere ich it schewi eov : &thorn;at &yogh;e &thorn;e so&thorn;e i-seo,
<PB REF="00000349.tif" N="301"></L>
<L>And &thorn;at &yogh;e honouri &thorn;ulke stude : for is wardein ichulle beo."</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e bischop with procession : swy&thorn;e fair and hende,</L>
<L N="40">For-to honouri &thorn;ulke holie stude : mildeliche he gan i-wende.</L>
<L>A noble churche huy founden &thorn;are : with walles faire and proute;</L>
<L>huy ne dorsten nou&yogh;t &thorn;are-nei&yogh; come : heore preiere huy duden with-oute.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">v. 41-2 spurious?</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;are-aftur-ward al &thorn;at folk of &thorn;e lond : &thorn;at I-cristned were</L>
<L N="44">Aldai comen to &thorn;ulke hulle : heore beden to bidde &thorn;ere.&mdash;</L>
<L>Seth&thorn;e [it ful]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> &thorn;are-after-ward : &thorn;at Saracines &thorn;are come</L>
<L>And weorreden &thorn;e cristine men : and bataylle a-&yogh;ein heom nome :</L>
<L>&thorn;o het &thorn;e bischop of<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> al</NOTE> &thorn;at folk : &thorn;ulke dayes &thorn;reo</L>
<L N="48">to seint MI&yogh;hel bidden faste : and in fastingue al-so beo.</L>
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;ridde ny&yogh;t seint Mi&yogh;hel : to &thorn;e bischope cam eft-sone,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. eft ftsone</NOTE></L>
<L>And seide, "lat &yogh;arki al &thorn;i folk : &thorn;e bataille for-to done.</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e to-day &thorn;are-Inne beon : ri&yogh;t at&thorn;e feor&thorn;e tyde,</L>
<L N="52">And with eov Ichulle &thorn;are beo : sum-&yogh;ware &thorn;are-bi-side."</L>
<L>&thorn;e bischop was &thorn;o glad i-nou&yogh;. : &thorn;at folk was sone &yogh;are,</L>
<L>&thorn;e tyme &thorn;at he hadde i-set : to &thorn;e batayle forto fare.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>TO-gadere huy smiten opon &thorn;e hulle : ake it was ido a-non :</L>
<L>for &thorn;are cam a gret deork cloude : and ouer-caste heom ech-on,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e leitingue smot &thorn;ere and &thorn;ere : &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere men to grounde;</L>
<L N="58">Six hundret it a-slov of heom : in wel luytel stounde.<MILESTONE N="133" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>heore felawes flowen faste a-non : and ascapeden onne&thorn;e;</L>
<L N="60">&thorn;are nas non &thorn;at ne was longue sijk : o&thorn;ur deide in strongue de&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&thorn;us seint Mi&yogh;hel sturede him &thorn;o : a-mong heom feor and ner.</L>
<L>&thorn;o was it soth &thorn;at seint Dauid : seide in &thorn;e sauter :</L>
<L>"&thorn;at ore [louerd] makez is Aungles : ase gostes fleojnde,</L>
<L N="64">And heom &thorn;at beoth is ministres : ase fuyr berninde."</L>
<L>Godes ministres aungles beoth : seint Mi&yogh;hel and o&thorn;ere mo;</L>
<L>&thorn;at ase gostes flowen &thorn;o vn-seie : in fourme of fuyre &thorn;o.</L>
<L>A wonder game huy pleiden &thorn;ere&mdash; : &thorn;at mi&yogh;te segge heore fon;</L>
<L N="68">Betere heom hadde at hom i-beo : and i-piked heore ton!</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;is cristine Men a-morewe : &yogh;arkeden heom fule wel</L>
<L>And wenden to &thorn;is holie hul : to &thorn;onki seint Mi&yogh;hel.</L>
<L>&thorn;o founden huy ane churche &thorn;ere : swy&thorn;e quoynte a rerd.</L>
<L N="72">&thorn;e bischop was &thorn;o glad I-nov&yogh; : and sumdel he was a-ferd :
<PB REF="00000350.tif" N="302"></L>
<L>he nuste hou &thorn;e churche cam : ne ho hire hadde a-rerd &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Ne &yogh;we&thorn;er seint Mi&yogh;hel wolde : &thorn;at heo i-halewed were&mdash;</L>
<L>For him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at hit was ri&yogh;t : to halewi churchene newe.</L>
<L N="76">Seint Mi&yogh;hel wel &yogh;eorne he bad : &thorn;at was is freond wel trewe,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he heom sende sum tokningue : &yogh;wat he scholde &thorn;arof do;</L>
<L>&thorn;reo dawes he let &thorn;at folk fasten : and heore beden bide al-so.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eot cam seint Mi&yogh;hel eft-sone : to &thorn;e bischope &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And seide, "ne &thorn;ench nou&yogh;t on mine churche : &thorn;at ich let mi-seolf a-rere!</L>
<L N="81">For ich habbe &thorn;e churche a-rerd : and I-halewed al-so.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar-of &thorn;ov schalt signe i-finde : &yogh;wane &thorn;ov comest &thorn;ere-to:</L>
<L>For wiend In at&thorn;e est-porche : and ase ich habbe i-gon</L>
<L N="84">Mine fet &thorn;ov schalt finde I-sene : ri&yogh;t in &thorn;e Marbre-ston.</L>
<L>Sing &thorn;are &thorn;ine hei&yogh;e-masse : and &yogh;if &thorn;at folk also</L>
<L>Ore louerdes flesch and is blod : &yogh;wane &thorn;e masse is ido!"</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e bischop wel sone a-Morewe : to &thorn;e churche him drov&yogh;,</L>
<L N="88">And &thorn;is folk al-so with him : with offringue fair I-nov&yogh;.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e est-porche huy wenden In : and in &thorn;e Marbre-ston</L>
<L>&thorn;e stapes huy founden I-sene : ase seint Mi&yogh;hel hadde igon.</L>
<L>Innore-more huy wenden &yogh;uyt : weouedes huy founden &thorn;reo,</L>
<L N="92">With rede palles huy weren i-heoled : &thorn;e faireste &thorn;at mi&yogh;ten beo:</L>
<L>Ore swete lauedies was &thorn;at on : &thorn;at men scholden to bidde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at o&thorn;ur seint Iohanes &thorn;e baptist<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. bastist</NOTE> : And seint peteres &thorn;at &thorn;ridde.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e bischop song is masse &thorn;ere : and seth&thorn;e at&thorn;en ende</L>
<L N="96">&thorn;at folk he dude hoseli al : are he wolde &thorn;anne wende.</L>
<L>&thorn;at folk to &thorn;ulke holie stude : aldai faste drou&yogh;;</L>
<L>And ore louerd dude &thorn;are ofte a-day : fair Miracle I-nov&yogh;.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e pope, &thorn;at was &thorn;o : &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e Cardinales rede</L>
<L N="100">For honour of &thorn;ulke stude : and seint Mi&yogh;heles holie dede,</L>
<L>And also for &thorn;e Miracle : [&thorn;at] &thorn;oru&yogh; seint Mi&yogh;hel com,</L>
<L>Mi&yogh;heles-masse-day he hiet halewi : &thorn;oru&yogh; al cristin-dom.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seint MI&yogh;hel In nouembre : hath &yogh;eot an-o&thorn;ur dai,<MILESTONE N="133b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="104">bi-fore &thorn;e feste of seint Luc : as ich ou telle mai.</L>
<L>&thorn;oru&yogh; seint Mi&yogh;heles wille : ri&yogh;t ase &thorn;e o&thorn;ur was,</L>
<L>And &thorn;oru&yogh; is heste he was bi-founde : i-hereth &thorn;oru&yogh; &yogh;wat cas.</L>
<L>Hit bi-feol seue hundred &yogh;er : and in &thorn;e teo&thorn;e &yogh;ere ri&yogh;t</L>
<L N="108">After &thorn;at ore swete louerd : in is Moder was a-lij&yogh;t,
<PB REF="00000351.tif" N="303"></L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e bischope Albert : seint Mi&yogh;hel cam a-ni&yogh;t</L>
<L>Bi-side &thorn;e Montaygne of Toumbe : ase it were in a sij&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e hulle of Toumbe : ane churche he him liete<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. het</NOTE> a-rere,</L>
<L N="112">Ri&yogh;t swuch one ase ope &thorn;ulke of gargan : and &thorn;at it bi-tyme were.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bischop axede in &yogh;wuche stude : he scholde &thorn;e churche make.</L>
<L>"I-chulle &thorn;e," quath seint Mi&yogh;hel : "guode tokne &thorn;arof take:</L>
<L>Ane bole &thorn;ov schalt &thorn;are finde : &thorn;at &thorn;eoues habbet &thorn;are i-hud,</L>
<L N="116">Opon &thorn;e hei&yogh;e hulle of toumbe : &thorn;at nis nou&yogh;t &yogh;eot i-kud.</L>
<L>&thorn;are ase &thorn;ou finst &thorn;e bole I-hud : &thorn;ov schalt mine churche a-rere."</L>
<L>&thorn;e bischop &thorn;at wel onder-stod : and bi-gan is churche &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are a-rerde hire faire I-nov : to &thorn;e helpe of mani a man,</L>
<L N="120">In &thorn;e honour of seint Mi&yogh;hel : ase hul<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. &thorn;ulke</NOTE> of gargan.</L>
<L>Opon hei&yogh;e hulles &thorn;is churchene weren : bo&thorn;e of seint Mi&yogh;hel&mdash;</L>
<L>hei&yogh; man me &thorn;inchez he wolde beo : for he louede hulles wel.</L>
<L>he dude wel, for he mi&yogh;te beo : at hom opon is owe</L>
<L N="124">And sittinde a-boute him wide i-seo : and &thorn;e contreie bet i-knowe,</L>
<L>And hom a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e sonere fleo : &yogh;wane &thorn;at he li&yogh;te lowe;</L>
<L>he ne &thorn;urte carie of non o&thorn;ur weork : no&thorn;ur to ripe ne mowe.</L>
<L>For he let opon ei&thorn;er hulle : areren a chapel,</L>
<L N="128">Muche folk &thorn;at &yogh;eot on eor&thorn;e is : onder-stant &thorn;at wel,</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane huy a-rereth anie churche : to massi Inne o&thorn;ur rede godspel,</L>
<L>Opon an hul bi custome : huy makiez of seint Mi&yogh;hel,</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;e Mount of seint Mi&yogh;hel : and &thorn;e Mount a-gv al-so,</L>
<L N="132">And also o&thorn;ere in fale studes : ho-so nimez &yogh;eme &thorn;ar-to.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN &thorn;e grete se of Occean : &thorn;e hul of Toumbe is,</L>
<L>&thorn;at geth a-bouten al &thorn;e world : In &thorn;at on ende, i-wis.</L>
<L>Al-a-boute &thorn;e hulle geth &thorn;e se. : and In &thorn;e feste-daie euere-mo</L>
<L>&thorn;e se. with-drauth<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. hire w. hire</NOTE> hire twies aday : &thorn;at ech man may druy&yogh;e gon</L>
<L N="137">Forto honouri &thorn;ulke holie stude&mdash; : and in non o&thorn;ur tyme it nis</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e .se. ne geth al-a-boute : bote on &thorn;e feste-daie, i-wis.</L>
<L>&para; So bi-feol In one time : &thorn;at &thorn;e se hire with-drou&yogh;</L>
<L N="140">In &thorn;e feste-dai&yogh;e of &thorn;ulke stude : and folk &thorn;are wende In I-nov&yogh;:</L>
<L>So &thorn;at a womman grete with childe : cam In at&thorn;en ende,</L>
<L>And nas nou&yogh;t so swift ase o&thorn;ere weren : a-&yogh;einward forto wende:</L>
<L>&thorn;e .se. for-closede hire sone : and heo bi-lefte with-Inne;</L>
<L N="144">heo floterede &thorn;are in luyte reste : and in wel feble wunne.
<PB REF="00000352.tif" N="304"></L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo bi-lefte &thorn;are : In wonder cas I-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L>For-to it was on o&thorn;ur &yogh;er : &thorn;at &thorn;e .se. hire with-drou&yogh;;</L>
<L>And hadde child &thorn;are In &thorn;e .se. : and at &thorn;e &yogh;eres ende</L>
<L N="148">hol and sound with hire childe : &thorn;udere heo gan i-wiende&mdash;<MILESTONE N="134" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I-saued heo was in &thorn;e deope .se. : &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e grace of seint Mi&yogh;hel.</L>
<L>For-so&thorn;e, nis nou&thorn;e no man aliue : &thorn;at hire cou&thorn;e habbe i-wust so wel,</L>
<L>Ne so hire i-fed and hire child : &thorn;at ne costnede nou&yogh;t a strav&yogh;:</L>
<L N="152">For &thorn;ei heo hadde fisch and drinke : &yogh;e wuten wel it was rav&yogh;.</L>
<L>And so to floteri in &thorn;e grete .se! : wounder, &thorn;at heo nadde i-beo ded.</L>
<L>Seint Mi&yogh;hel was a guod wardein : &yogh;wane we habbeth al i-sed;</L>
<L>Icholde ech man me hadde ane peny i-&yogh;yue : &thorn;at no cou&thorn;e nou&yogh;t witen hire so!</L>
<L N="156">At&thorn;e feste-day at &thorn;e hul of Toumbe : &thorn;is dede was i-do.&mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;e hul of Toumbe he is i-cleoped : for he is sumdel<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. sundel</NOTE> nare</L>
<L>And long, ase Man may i-seo : ane Mannes burieles fare</L>
<L>&thorn;at mannes bodi is Inne I-leid : &yogh;wane huy beoth here dede;</L>
<L N="160">Also &thorn;ilke hul is long : and nou&yogh;t wel large In brede.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at is, ase &thorn;e .se. hath i-bete : faste on ei&thorn;ur side</L>
<L>And hath &thorn;at sond a-rerd up on hei&yogh; : &thorn;at men mouwen i-seo wel wide,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar-of Imaket ane hul : narv and long i-wis;</L>
<L N="164">More &thorn;ane four hondret fet : &thorn;e hul so hei&yogh; is.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>MEn synguez a-Mi&yogh;heles-masse-day : In holie churche also</L>
<L>Of one bataile &thorn;at seint Mi&yogh;hel : with a dragun scholde do:</L>
<L>&thorn;at was &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere lucifer : &thorn;o he was<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at was</NOTE> is felawe</L>
<L N="168">And sumdel is souerein : for-to he gan mis-drawe,</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;o he &thorn;at Aungel was : &thorn;oru&yogh; is wicke pruyte</L>
<L>Bi-cam to a lu&thorn;er feond&mdash; : he bi-&yogh;at &thorn;are-with luyte!</L>
<L>he feol out of is hei&yogh;e sege : &thorn;at he ches a-mis,</L>
<L N="172">To &thorn;e deope putte of helle : &thorn;are is wonijngue is.</L>
<L>fram &thorn;e hexte stude &thorn;at is : with one swenge he cam</L>
<L>To &thorn;e loweste stude, i-wis&mdash; : ane wonder wei he nam!</L>
<L>Nov sori beo he! &yogh;wat was him? : &yogh;wi ferde &thorn;e schrewe so?</L>
<L N="176">he pleyde with &thorn;e fallingue tourn : so wel he cou&thorn;e hine do,</L>
<L>Iaumbe leue he cam swenge : Into helle grounde.</L>
<L>A muregore In he hadde bi-fore : &thorn;at worse &thorn;are he founde!</L>
<L>A wonder sweng, me &thorn;inchez, he made! : his bi-&yogh;ete was ful luyte;
<PB REF="00000353.tif" N="305"></L>
<L N="180">he may corsi euere-more : his mis-farinde pruyte.</L>
<L>for al-so sone as ore louerd I-maud : heouene and eor&thorn;e and helle,</L>
<L>he makede him furst and is felawes : ase ich ov mai here telle.</L>
<L>And he ase-sone ase he was imaud : he bi-gan to smite in pruyte:</L>
<L>Al-so hei&yogh; ase ore louerd he wolde beo : he bi-&yogh;at &thorn;are-with wel luyte.</L>
<L N="185">Manie heolden faste with him : and nou&yogh;t alle of one lore:</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> manie likeden wel is dedene : some lasse and some more,</L>
<L N="187">Some ferden ase huy ne rou&yogh;ten : no&thorn;er of on .ne of o&thorn;ur.</L>
<L>&thorn;are ne bi-lefte in heouene non of heom : ne heore maister no&thorn;er.</L>
<L>Seint Mi&yogh;hel was maister to driuen heom : out of heuene a-doun:</L>
<L>&thorn;at was &thorn;e batayle &thorn;at he made : with &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere dragoun.</L>
<L>&thorn;e maister-dragoun lucifer : and is ri&yogh;te felawes ech-on</L>
<L N="192">&thorn;at faste heolden with is pruyte : he drof heom to helle anon.</L>
<L>Ake huy &thorn;at heolden sumdel with him : and nou&yogh;t fulliche so faste,<MILESTONE N="134b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Out of heouene he drof heom : and In-to &thorn;e lofte heom caste,</L>
<L>Al here bi-ne&thorn;e toward &thorn;e eor&thorn;e : &thorn;are mest tempeste is:</L>
<L N="196">And &thorn;are heo schullen in tempest and<NOTE PLACE="marg1">in t. and <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> in pine beo : to &thorn;e daye of dome, i-wis;</L>
<L>And ase hore gult &thorn;e more was : heore pine was<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> is</NOTE> al-so,</L>
<L>&thorn;e worse stude heom [was] i-take : heore penaunce for-to do.</L>
<L>Ake to helle huy ne schullen nou&yogh;t : are domes-day i-wende;</L>
<L N="200">Ak &thorn;are huy schullen after-ward : bi-leue with-outen ende.</L>
<L>O&thorn;ure &thorn;are weren &thorn;at for heom<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. him</NOTE> : sumdel in mis-&thorn;ou&yogh;te weren,</L>
<L>Ake natheles huy heolden betere with god : and<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> ac</NOTE> vnne&thorn;e fur-bere:</L>
<L>&thorn;ulke wenden out of heouene al-so : and a-boue &thorn;e o&thorn;ure beoth,</L>
<L N="204">An hei&yogh; onder &thorn;e firmament : and godes wille i-seoth,</L>
<L>And so schullen sumdel in pine beo : a-non to &thorn;e worldes ende,</L>
<L>Ake huy schullen at domes-day : a-&yogh;ein to heouene wende.</L>
<L>In eorth&thorn;eliche parays : some beoth &yogh;eot al-so,</L>
<L N="208">And in o&thorn;ur studes on eor&thorn;e : heore penaunce for-to do.&mdash;</L>
<L>For heore defaute in heouene : &thorn;oru&yogh; ore louerdes grace</L>
<L>Man was formest on eor&thorn;e i-wrou&yogh;t : to fulfulle &thorn;ulke place.</L>
<L>&para; For ten ordres of Aungles : &thorn;are weren i-makede &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="212">And &thorn;e teo&thorn;e ordre ful a-doun : In-to pine and wo:</L>
<L>And &yogh;eot &thorn;are beot ordres Nyne : and &thorn;are-fore man is i-wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To fulfulle &thorn;e teo&thorn;e ordre : &thorn;at was out of heouene i-brou&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000354.tif" N="306"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SOne so man was i-wrou&yogh;t : sunne he bi-gan to do</L>
<L N="216">And fur-gulte &thorn;e murie Ioie : &thorn;at he was i-maket to:</L>
<L>In helle he was with lucifer : and with o&thorn;ure lu&thorn;ere fode,</L>
<L>For-to ore louerd it bou&yogh;te : In flesch and in blode.</L>
<L>&thorn;e lu&thorn;ere gostes beoth a-boute : with heore lu&thorn;ere pouwer</L>
<L N="220">To bi-traye wrechche men : and bringue into heore paunter;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e guode beoth al-so a-boute : with power &thorn;at heore is</L>
<L>For-to witien men fram sunne : &thorn;at huy ne wurchen a-mis.</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere and &thorn;e guode : a-li&yogh;teth ofte a-doun</L>
<L N="224">And to men in hore slepe comieth : ase In a visioun,</L>
<L>And scheowieth in metingue : mani a wounder dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e guode of guode &thorn;ingues : and &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere euere of quede,</L>
<L>And deriez men in heore slep : and bodieth seoruwe and care,</L>
<L N="228">And ofte huy ouer-liggez [men] : and<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at</NOTE> men cleopiet &thorn;e ni&yogh;t-mare&mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at is al heore delii&yogh;t : &yogh;wane huy mowen don men wo.</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;eoues huy cheoseth &thorn;e ni&yogh;t : a-boute to fleo and go.</L>
<L>Mest huy greuieth selie men : &yogh;wane huy liggez upri&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="232">heuie huy liggez on heom i-nov : nere heom erore so lij&yogh;t:</L>
<L>huy liggez ase an heui stok : &thorn;at wolde ane Man a-stoffe,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he ne may him wawie fot ne hond : ne vnne&thorn;es ani-&thorn;ing poffe.</L>
<L>&para; Da&thorn;eheit a swuch lu&thorn;er Caumberleyn : &thorn;at a-wakez men so sore,</L>
<L N="236">And god him &yogh;iue sorewe I-nou&yogh; : and euere so leng &thorn;e more,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at louiez is compaygnie! : for he nas neuere hende.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ani man him louez wel : ore louerd hyne him sende.&mdash;<MILESTONE N="135" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;e schrewene wollez also ofte : mankun to bi-trai&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="240">A-li&yogh;te a-doun in mannes forme : bi ni&yogh;te and bi daye,</L>
<L>And liggez ofte bi wommen : ase huy weren of flesch and of blode&mdash;</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;ulke bi-&yogh;ete &thorn;at huy bi-&yogh;itez : neuere ne cometh to guode.</L>
<L>And ofte in fourme of womman : a-day and eke a-ny&yogh;t</L>
<L N="244">huy latez men ligge heom bi : and bi-trayez heom ou&yogh;t-ri&yogh;t&mdash;</L>
<L>for huy wutez wel &yogh;wuche beoz &thorn;e men : &thorn;at to folie habbeth wille:</L>
<L>Al-one in some deerne stude : huy stondez &thorn;anne wel stille,</L>
<L>And Mani fol heom lijth so bi : In wodes and in mede.</L>
<L N="248">Ake &thorn;are nis non &thorn;at deth so : &thorn;at huy ne acoriez &thorn;e dede:</L>
<L>heore membres to-swellez sone : and some a-scapieth onne&thorn;e,</L>
<L>And some for-dwynez al awei : for-to huy beon i-brou&yogh;t to de&thorn;e;
<PB REF="00000355.tif" N="307"></L>
<L>More wonder it is, for-so&thorn;e : hov ani a-scapiez a-liue&mdash;</L>
<L N="252">for a swi&thorn;e attri &thorn;ing it is : to lefman o&thorn;ur to wyue.</L>
<L>And ofte in fourme of wommane : In many derne weye</L>
<L>grete compaygnie men i-seoth of heom : bo&thorn;e hoppie and plei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&thorn;at Eluene beoth i-cleopede : and ofte heo comiez to toune,</L>
<L>And bi daye muche in wodes heo beoth : and bi ni&yogh;te ope hei&yogh;e dounes.</L>
<L N="257">&thorn;at beoth &thorn;e wrechche gostes : &thorn;at out of heuene weren i-nome,</L>
<L>And manie of heom a-domesday : &yogh;eot schullen to reste come.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;eo schrewene &thorn;at beoth in toune<NOTE PLACE="marg1">in t. <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> : bi ni&yogh;te and bi day&yogh;e</L>
<L N="260">fondieth with &yogh;wuche feolonie : huy mouwen mest men bi-traie.&mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ulke tyme &thorn;at &thorn;e feond : ore furste fader i-wan</L>
<L>&thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;at appel &thorn;at he him &yogh;af : mayster he was of man;</L>
<L>he hadde faste al to him men i-bounde : for-to ore louerd us bou&yogh;te:</L>
<L N="264">And for men weren so alle his : &thorn;e lasse of heom he rou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Ne no&thorn;ing he nas ginful : ase &thorn;e schrewene nou&thorn;e beoth&mdash;</L>
<L>for plente nis no deinte : ase we al day i-seot.</L>
<L>he fierde ase doth a port-doggue : I-norischet in port-toun:</L>
<L N="268">for he geth ofte in prece of Men : a-mong heom op and doun,</L>
<L>Ne &yogh;eme ne nimeth he to men : to beorken on heom nou&yogh;t ene,</L>
<L>Ake a-mong men he goth stille I-nov&yogh; : bote ani man him hene:</L>
<L>Al-so fierde &thorn;e deuel &thorn;o : for mankun was al his,</L>
<L N="272">And hadde of him<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> hem</NOTE> so gret plente : he ne tolde nou&yogh;t &thorn;ar-of, iwis.</L>
<L>he nas no-&thorn;ing clib to heom : for-to a-sailli heom with wou&yogh;,</L>
<L>Non more &thorn;ane &thorn;e port-hound : &thorn;at nei&yogh; men geth I-nou&yogh;;</L>
<L>Ne he nis<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> nas</NOTE> no&thorn;ing grim to bi-gyli men : ase he was bi-fore,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> nou&thorn;e is</NOTE></L>
<L N="276">Er &thorn;ane<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Si&thorn;&thorn;e</NOTE> ore swete louerd : of Marie was i-bore.</L>
<L>Hadde he i-beo swuch bi-fore : ase he was er<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> ha&thorn; si&thorn;&thorn;e</NOTE> i-wis,</L>
<L>Onne&thorn;e was &thorn;are ani Man : &thorn;at ne hadde i-beon al his.</L>
<L>Ake ore louerd after is de&thorn;e : In harde logge him brou&yogh;te</L>
<L>And teide &thorn;ane schrewe faste Inov&yogh; : and da&thorn;eheit &thorn;at hit of-&thorn;ou&yogh;te!</L>
<L N="281">A teie doggue is clib I-nov : &yogh;wane man comez In is si&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And grennez and beorkez faste I-nov : and drau&yogh;th with al is mi&yogh;te;</L>
<L>Ake &yogh;if ani man cometh so nei&yogh; : &thorn;at he sette on him is toth,<MILESTONE N="135b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="284">for-so&thorn;e he bitez sore I-nov&yogh; : ase all[e] swuche doth;</L>
<L>he is clibbest op-on heom : &thorn;at arriet him with ston:</L>
<L>Ake nei&yogh; no man ne may he come : bote &thorn;at to nei&yogh; him wollez gon.
<PB REF="00000356.tif" N="308"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou&thorn;e late, seth&thorn;e he was iteid : &thorn;e deuel farez al-so:</L>
<L N="288">he beorkez and grennez toward Men : ake he ne may heom nou&yogh;t do;</L>
<L>In is owene wrath&thorn;e he brennez : him-sulf he doth mest wo,</L>
<L>Ake he ne mai no man a-reche : bote ho-so wole allingues to him go.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 289-290 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;wane ani Man cometh him so nei&yogh; : &thorn;at he mouwe him a-reche,</L>
<L N="292">Bite he wole harde I-nov&yogh; : and is lessun him teche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, bote he tuyrne to amendement : and take to godes leche</L>
<L>And of preoste beo wel i-schriue : him worth i-don gret wreche.</L>
<L>&para; Hardest &thorn;e deuel bitez &thorn;e men : &yogh;wane ani comez him to</L>
<L N="296">Of heom &thorn;at arreden him er : and guodnesse habbez i-do&mdash;</L>
<L>for &thorn;are-with Men him arrieth mest&mdash; : and &yogh;wuch so him wole with|drawe</L>
<L>And comez so nei&yogh; &thorn;at he him mouwe a-reche : he cachchez him wel fawe</L>
<L>And opon is pouwer harde bit&mdash; : his bitingues beoth wel ille.</L>
<L N="300">he ne may no man, ase &yogh;e i-seoth : taken a-&yogh;ein is wille,</L>
<L>Nonmore &thorn;ane a tei&yogh; doggue : &thorn;at is in strongue tei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane he ne may a-reche Men : ful wide he cast is ei&yogh;e</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he may ani man i-seo : &thorn;at toward him wole drawe;</L>
<L N="304">he bi-guynnez a-non for-to tolli him : ase man doth his felawe&mdash;</L>
<L>for &yogh;wane a man ne mai : his felawe bringue him nere,</L>
<L>with is hond he tollez him : ase man &thorn;at seith "Ich am here."</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e Deuel tollez with is hond : ase wel as doth a man,</L>
<L N="308">And fif fingres &thorn;are-on he hath : &thorn;at he wel bi-sette can.</L>
<L>Ech of is fingres hath is name : ase we cleopiez ovre al-so.</L>
<L>&thorn;e leste hatte "luttle man" : for he is lest &thorn;ere-to.</L>
<L>&thorn;e nexte finguer hatte "leche" : for &yogh;wane &thorn;e leche makez ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="312">with &thorn;at finguer he wole hit tasti : &yogh;if it is a-ri&yogh;t i-wrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; "Longueman" hatte &thorn;e midleste : for he lenguest is.</L>
<L>&thorn;e feor&thorn;e finguer hatte "techere" : for &thorn;ere-with men techez i-wis,</L>
<L>Ase a man &thorn;at seith "lo he &thorn;ere : of &yogh;wam we speken er longue."</L>
<L>for mannes &thorn;oumbe strenguest is : &thorn;are-fore he hatte "&thorn;e strongue."</L>
<L N="317">&thorn;anne hatte &thorn;e leste luttle man : and &thorn;e nexte hatte leche,</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e &thorn;at o&thorn;ur longueman : &thorn;e techare for he doth [teche],</L>
<L>Strongue is &thorn;e &thorn;oumbe I-cleoped : &thorn;ou wost wel &yogh;wy it is:
<PB REF="00000357.tif" N="309"></L>
<L N="320">&thorn;eos fif fingres &thorn;e deuel hath : and heore names, i-wis.</L>
<L>&thorn;are-with he tollez men to him : &yogh;wanne men stondez feor a-to</L>
<L>And with fol &thorn;ou&yogh;t toward him lokiez : and nutez &yogh;wat he wollez do,</L>
<L>And heore Inwit heom seith : &thorn;at swy&thorn;e gret sunne it were,</L>
<L N="324">And grete wille huy habbez &thorn;er-to : &yogh;if huy dorsten for fere.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e deuel stant and wolde fain : henten heom bi &thorn;e polle:</L>
<L>with "luttle man," is leste finguer : he bi-guynneth heom furst to tolle</L>
<L>And seith, "&yogh;ware-of art &thorn;ou of-drad? : a luyte sunne it is"&mdash;</L>
<L N="328">he makez &thorn;e sunne luyte Inov&yogh; : for &thorn;e finguer is luyte, i-wis.<MILESTONE N="136" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;if he ne may with is luytel finguer : ane man to sunne teche,</L>
<L>with is felawe he tolleth next : &thorn;at men cleopieth "leche,"</L>
<L>And seit, "&yogh;e, god is leche guod : and ful of milce and ore,</L>
<L N="332">he wole wel hele and fur-&yogh;iue : &thorn;ei &thorn;e sunne were wel more;</L>
<L>he nis nou&yogh;t so wrechful ase men weneth : he hath &thorn;e deore a-bou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>wel more sunne he wole fur-&yogh;yuen : &thorn;are-fore ne dred &thorn;e nou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>And bote he mouwe &thorn;are-with i-winne : he pult forth is felawe,</L>
<L N="336">&thorn;e "longue finguer," &thorn;at sit him next&mdash; : &thorn;at alle weren huy to|drawe!&mdash;</L>
<L>And seith, "man, &thorn;ov art &yogh;ung I-nov : &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t libben &yogh;eot wel longue</L>
<L>And &thorn;ine sunnes bieten wel : &thorn;ei huy weren ten so strongue.</L>
<L>Scholdestov nou&thorn;e &thorn;ine wille lete : &yogh;wat scholde &thorn;i &yogh;ungue blod?</L>
<L N="340">&thorn;ou mi&yogh;t libbe longue I-nov&yogh; : and a-mendi al &thorn;i mod."</L>
<L>Bote he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &yogh;e</NOTE> mouwe &yogh;eot makie man : &thorn;are-with don a-mis,</L>
<L>he tollez him with &thorn;e "techare" : &thorn;at is nexte felawe is.</L>
<L>And seith, "lo &thorn;ere &thorn;ilke preost : and &thorn;ilke kny&yogh;t al-so</L>
<L N="344">And &thorn;ilke person, and manie o&thorn;ure : &thorn;at more sunne habbez i-do,</L>
<L>And natheles huy beoth guode men : and guod lijf ledez i-nou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&thorn;ilke man nas neuere I-bore : &thorn;at o&thorn;ur-&yogh;wile ne dude sum wou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Seint powel with is owene hond : Manie men he slov&yogh;,</L>
<L N="348">And &thorn;e Marie Maudeleine : &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> to lecherie drov&yogh;,</L>
<L>Seint peter &thorn;ries in one nij&yogh;t : for-sok ore louerd al-so;</L>
<L>And al-so loke &thorn;is o&thorn;ur helewe : &yogh;wat sunne huy habbez i-do:</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;ei huy beoth In heouene nou&thorn;e : ne worst &thorn;ou neuere so hei&yogh;e.</L>
<L N="352">More sunne &thorn;ane &thorn;ou wolt do : &thorn;ov mi&yogh;t biete, are &thorn;ou dei&yogh;e:</L>
<L>&thorn;ou woldest beo holiore &thorn;ane ani man. : bi-holt &thorn;e al-a-boute:</L>
<L>A misdede wole beo sone ibet. : &yogh;ware-of hast &thorn;ou doute?"
<PB REF="00000358.tif" N="310"></L>
<L>&YOGH;if he ne may with is techare : maken is wei roume,</L>
<L N="356">with is "strongue" he tollez &thorn;anne : with is schrewe &thorn;oume,</L>
<L>And seith, "&thorn;ov art strong i-nov : more sunne to biete;</L>
<L>woldest &thorn;ou bi-leue so murie &thorn;ing? : &thorn;ench &thorn;at it is swete,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 2 vv more.</NOTE></L>
<L>And biet &thorn;ine sunnes aftur-ward : for &thorn;e ne faillez stren&thorn;e non;</L>
<L N="360">And wel fieblore &thorn;ane &thorn;ou art : ofte wolleth mis-don</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e doth heore penaunce : ake natheles nou&yogh;t wel strongue,</L>
<L>For ore louerd is euere &yogh;are : sunful Man to fongue."</L>
<L>In &thorn;is manere &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere schrewe : &yogh;wane he vnder-&yogh;it ou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="364">&thorn;at men lokiez touward him : and sumdel chaungiez heore &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>he tollez heom euere ner and ner : with is fingres a-rewe.</L>
<L N="366">Nou&thorn;e lu&thorn;er &thorn;rift on al is hond : for euere he was a schrewe!</L>
<L>Da&thorn;eit &thorn;at sori wolde beo : &thorn;ei he were al-to-hewe!</L>
<L>For he bringuez to sunne mani on : and to amendement wel fewe.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore &thorn;enchez, &yogh;wane he wole : eou to sunne puyte</L>
<L N="370">And with is fingres tollez eov : and seiz &thorn;e sunne is luyte</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ore louerd is guod leche and milsful : and &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt libbe longue</L>
<L N="372">And &thorn;at o&thorn;ure sunegiez more : &thorn;at ne beoth nou&yogh;t so strongue:</L>
<L>A-non so &yogh;e &thorn;enchez swuch a &thorn;ou&yogh;t : bi-&thorn;enchez ov &thorn;er-to<MILESTONE N="136b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>hou &thorn;e schrewe tollez eov : and with wuch finguer al-so:</L>
<L>Seggez him &thorn;at he ly&yogh;th loude : ho-so it dorste him telle,</L>
<L N="376">Saue &thorn;at he is maister : in &thorn;e deope putte of helle;</L>
<L>&THORN;at god holde him is dignete : and is grete maistrie</L>
<L>For-to sum riche man &yogh;iue al is guod : to bi-nimen him is baylie.</L>
<L N="379">For-so&thorn;e, he deoth vuele I-nouv&yogh; : &thorn;at comez in his tollingue:</L>
<L>He wole him bringue euere ner ant ner : In deoppore suneguyngue,</L>
<L>Atenende In-to &thorn;e putte of helle : &thorn;are euere he worth fur-lore,</L>
<L>&thorn;at onne&thorn;e him worth &thorn;e grace : to with-drawen him bi-fore.&mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;ei we ne mouwen nou&yogh;t &thorn;e feondes i-seo : a-mong us huy beoth wel &thorn;icke;</L>
<L N="384">And &thorn;ei huy ovte of helle beon : heore pinene beoth strongue and wicke.</L>
<L>For huy farez ase doth &thorn;e man : &thorn;at in ane hache<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> acces</NOTE> of &thorn;e feueres is:</L>
<L>Beo he in house o&thorn;ur in fielde : is brenningue i-last, i-wis;</L>
<L>Feor and neor he may go : ake euere i-last is pine.
<PB REF="00000359.tif" N="311"></L>
<L N="388">Hit is bi &thorn;e Deouele here : al-so and bi is hyne:</L>
<L>For &thorn;ei huy ovte of helle beon : huy ne schullen nou&yogh;t so at-route</L>
<L>&thorn;at huy &thorn;e brenningue of helle : with heom ne bereth a-boute.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="46" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>46</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;E ri&yogh;te put of helle is : a-midde &thorn;e eor&thorn;e with-Inne,</L>
<L N="392">&thorn;at ore louerd it made i-wis : &thorn;at quoynte was of ginne.</L>
<L>heouene and eor&thorn;e he made furst : and seothe alle &thorn;ing &thorn;at is.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Eor&thorn;e nis bote a luytel hurst : a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e ri&yogh;te heouene, i-wis.</L>
<L>Heouene geth al-a-boute &thorn;e eor&thorn;e : euene it mot wey&yogh;e;</L>
<L N="396">A-midde ri&yogh;t heouene &thorn;e eor&thorn;e is : ase &thorn;e streon a-midde &thorn;e Ey&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Muche is &thorn;at on &thorn;anne more &thorn;ane &thorn;at o&thorn;ur : for &thorn;e leste steorre is</L>
<L>In heouene, ase &thorn;e bok us tellez : [more] &thorn;ane al &thorn;e eor&thorn;e, i-wis.</L>
<L>For ho-so were an hei&yogh; bi ane steorre : &yogh;if it so mi&yogh;te beo,</L>
<L>So luyte wolde &thorn;e eor&thorn;e &thorn;inche : &thorn;at vnne&thorn;e he scholde it ou&yogh;t i-seo.</L>
<L N="401">&thorn;e heouene geth ene a-boute : &thorn;oru&yogh; dai&yogh;e and &thorn;oru&yogh; ny&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&thorn;e Mone and &thorn;e steorrene with him heo berth : and &thorn;e sonne &thorn;at is so bri&yogh;t:</L>
<L>For &thorn;at is euene a-boue &thorn;in heued : ri&yogh;t at&thorn;e nones stounde,</L>
<L N="404">Ounder &thorn;ine fet euene it is : at midni&yogh;t onder &thorn;e grounde,</L>
<L>And cometh up &yogh;wane &thorn;e sonne a-rist : and [o]uer &thorn;e is at none;</L>
<L>heo makez euene &thorn;us hire cours : and comez a-boute wel sone.</L>
<L>Ase an Appel &thorn;e eor&thorn;e is round : so &thorn;at euere-mo</L>
<L N="408">half &thorn;e eor&thorn;e &thorn;e sonne bi-schineth : hov-so it euere go,</L>
<L>And Noon it is bi-nethen us : &yogh;wane it is here mid-ni&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Ase man may &thorn;e so&thorn;e i-seo : ho-so hauez guod In-si&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Ase &yogh;if &thorn;ov heolde ane clere candele : bi-side an Appel ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="412">Euene half &thorn;e Appel : heo wolde &yogh;iuen hire lij&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">firmamenta.</NOTE>EI&yogh;te firmamenz &thorn;are beoth : swuche ase we i-seoth.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Ouemeste is &thorn;e ri&yogh;tte heouene : in &yogh;wan &thorn;e steorrene beoth&mdash;</L>
<L>for godes riche is &thorn;are a-boue : &thorn;at last with-outen ende;</L>
<L N="416">&thorn;arto we beoth i-maked&mdash; : god leue us &thorn;udere i-wende.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;are-bi-neo&thorn;e beoth seoue firmamenz : &thorn;at euerech of heom, i-wis,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">planete.</NOTE>One steorre hath with-oute mo : &thorn;at planete i-cleoped is.<MILESTONE N="137" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ichulle nemmen heore seoue names : and formest bi-guynne hext:</L>
<L N="420">Saturnus is al a-boue : and Iupiter seth&thorn;e next,</L>
<L>&thorn;anne Mars bi-neo&thorn;en him : and seth&thorn;e &thorn;e sonne is,</L>
<L>Venus seth&thorn;e, &thorn;e clere steorre : Mercurius &thorn;anne, i-wis,
<PB REF="00000360.tif" N="312"></L>
<L>&thorn;at wel selden is of us i-sei&yogh;e : &thorn;e Mone is next &thorn;e grounde.</L>
<L N="424">&thorn;oru&yogh; gret wit of clergie : heore names weren furst bi-founde:</L>
<L>for euerech of &thorn;eos seouene mouwen : gret wonder on eor&thorn;e do,</L>
<L>bo&thorn;e of wederes and of fruyt : ase heore power &yogh;if &thorn;are-to.</L>
<L>And al-so man,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. men &thorn;at beoth</NOTE> &yogh;wane he is i-bore : onder heore power, i-wis,</L>
<L N="428">Schullen habbe diuers lijf : euere ase heore vertue is :</L>
<L>Some lechours, some glotones : and some of o&thorn;ur manere.</L>
<L>And natheles a man of guod Inwit : of alle he may him skere :</L>
<L>for &thorn;e planetes ne doth non o&thorn;ur : bote &yogh;iuez in mannes wille,</L>
<L N="432">To beon lu&thorn;ur o&thorn;ur guod : ase heore uertue wole to tille,</L>
<L>And &yogh;iuen<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. &yogh;iuez</NOTE> him al-so qualite : to don so and so;</L>
<L>Ake nou&yogh;t-for-&thorn;an after is inwit : ech wys man may do :</L>
<L>for swuch qualite no man ne hath : to beon lechor o&thorn;ur schrewe,</L>
<L N="436">&thorn;at he &thorn;are-with ne may him wite&mdash; : ake natheles so doth fewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;e seoue planetes al-so guod : heore power &yogh;e i-seoth,</L>
<L>for &thorn;e seoue Dawes in &thorn;e wyke : &thorn;are-aftur I-nemde beoth :</L>
<L>Of Saturnus so is satur-day : and sonen-day of &thorn;e sonne,</L>
<L N="440">And of &thorn;e Mone Monen-day : &yogh;if &yogh;e wel rikeni konne;</L>
<L>Of one planete euerech day : In &thorn;e wike i-cleoped is,</L>
<L>On englisch o&thorn;ur latyn : bote &yogh;e telle a-mis.</L>
<L>And for mars and saturnus : In heore power lu&thorn;ere beoth</L>
<L N="444">And luyte guod on eor&thorn;e doth : ase &thorn;is clerkes i-seoth,</L>
<L>&thorn;are-fore Men schoniez muche : &thorn;ene satur-day bi-guynne,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ene tywesday, euerech [werc]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> : to guode ende it forto wynne.</L>
<L>Among alle &thorn;e planetes : &thorn;e sonne a-midde heom is</L>
<L N="448">Ase is &thorn;e kyng a-Midde is men : to conseili heom i-wis :</L>
<L>Al-so &thorn;e sonne, &thorn;at heo mouwe : schyne a-boute eche-on :</L>
<L>for alle habbez lij&yogh;t of hire : and with-oute hire nou&yogh;t on.</L>
<L>Ase man may bi &thorn;e Mone i-seo : &thorn;e &yogh;wyle heo is neowe ri&yogh;t :</L>
<L N="452">A luyte rondel ase a sikel : Men seoth &thorn;ar-on li&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;at o&thorn;ur del with-Inne : swi&thorn;e blak as a rauon<NOTE PLACE="marg1">as a r. on the margin.</NOTE> it is.</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t so blac is al &thorn;e mone : of hire-sulf, i-wis,</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;are ase &thorn;e sonne schynez : &thorn;at hire li&yogh;t &yogh;if hire al</L>
<L N="456">And Makez hire schyne a-boute : bri&yogh;tore &thorn;ane ani cristal.</L>
<L>for &yogh;wanne &thorn;e sonne schynez on cristal : o&thorn;ur in watere cler,</L>
<L>A gret leome it &yogh;if out a-&yogh;ein : and schynez feor and ner :
<PB REF="00000361.tif" N="313"></L>
<L>Al-so fareth &thorn;e Mone, i-wis : &thorn;e sonne schynez doun ri&yogh;t</L>
<L N="460">Euene on hire and heo a&yogh;ein : and a-mong us sent hire li&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e sonne is feor a-boue : ri&yogh;t at-fore &thorn;e prime,</L>
<L>bi-neo&thorn;en hire &thorn;e Mone is euene : and &thorn;e sonne schyne[z] bi-tyme</L>
<L>Al In &thorn;e ouere side of &thorn;e Mone : and hider-ward nowi&yogh;t :<MILESTONE N="137b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="464">&thorn;anne ne seo we nou&yogh;t of hire : ne heo ne &yogh;ifth no li&yogh;t.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e sonne bi-fore geth : luyte and luyte, i-wis,</L>
<L>And schyneth on &thorn;e hiderore half : on &thorn;ulke &thorn;at ner him is:</L>
<L>Heo makez &thorn;e Mone wexe so : luyte and luyte bi stounde,</L>
<L N="468">So &thorn;at &thorn;e Mone is hei&yogh;ful : &yogh;wane &thorn;e sonne geth to grounde.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Mone bi-gynnez bi este a-rise : euene a-&yogh;en hire ri&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="marg1">ri&yogh;t on the margin.</NOTE>,</L>
<L>&thorn;at in &thorn;ulke half to-ward us : &thorn;e sonne sent hire lij&yogh;t :</L>
<L>&thorn;anne is &thorn;e ouere half deork : and &thorn;e hiderore half al bri&yogh;t</L>
<L N="472">And sent hire leome hidere to us : and schinez al &thorn;e ni&yogh;t.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo drauth hire<NOTE PLACE="marg1">on the margin.</NOTE> feor &thorn;e sonne : and luyte and luyte is blak,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> a-bac</NOTE></L>
<L>And euere is cler toward &thorn;e sonne : and &thorn;at o&thorn;ur del is blak;</L>
<L>And ate laste toward us is al blac : at&thorn;e mon&thorn;es ende</L>
<L N="476">And cler a-boue ase is &thorn;e sonne : &thorn;at to hire li&yogh;t deth sende.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e sonne in &thorn;e haluendele : schinez euere-mo,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wat a-boue and &yogh;wat bi-neo&thorn;e : hov-so hit euere go&mdash;</L>
<L>Ase man may i-seo bi ane candele : &thorn;at is bi-side ane balle,</L>
<L N="480">&thorn;at &yogh;ifth li&yogh;t on &thorn;at haluendel : hov-so it euere falle.</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane &thorn;e sonne is onder &thorn;e eor&thorn;e : and &thorn;e Mone a-boue a-ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>bi-side &thorn;e eor&thorn;e in &thorn;at on half : &yogh;eot &thorn;e sonne sent hire li&yogh;t.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; An hundret si&thorn;e and fiue and sixti : ase it is i-write,</L>
<L N="484">&thorn;e sonne is more &thorn;ane &thorn;e eor&thorn;e : ho-so it wole i-wite;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e eor&thorn;e is more &thorn;ane &thorn;e Mone : nye si&thorn;e, i-wis.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Mone &thorn;inchez wel &thorn;e more : for heo so nei&yogh; us is.</L>
<L>&thorn;e sonne is herre &thorn;ane &thorn;e Mone : More &thorn;ane schwche &thorn;reo</L>
<L N="488">&thorn;ane it beo heonnes to &thorn;e Mone&mdash; : &thorn;e lasse heo is to seo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Muche is bi-twene heouene and eor&thorn;e : for &thorn;e man &thorn;at mi&yogh;te go</L>
<L>euereche daye fourty mile : and &yogh;eot sumdel mo,</L>
<L>He ne scholde nou&yogh;t to &thorn;e hexte heouene : &thorn;at &yogh;e alday i-seoth,</L>
<L N="492">comen in ei&yogh;te &thorn;ousende &yogh;er : &thorn;ere ase &thorn;e steorrene beoth;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei adam, ore furste fader : hadde bi-gonne a-non</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;at he was furst i-mad : and toward &thorn;e heouene i-gon
<PB REF="00000362.tif" N="314"></L>
<L N="495">And hadde eche daie fourti mile : euene opri&yogh;t i-go,</L>
<L>he ne hadde nou&yogh;t &yogh;eot to heuene i-come : bi a &thorn;ousende mile and mo.</L>
<L>Sikere &yogh;e beon isegge &yogh;eov soth : I-leue ho-so i-leue&mdash;</L>
<L>hov schulle we &thorn;at comiez so late : after Adam and eue?</L>
<L>Ake &yogh;wane a man is on eor&thorn;e ded : and is soule beo guod,</L>
<L N="500">heo nath with hire non heuinesse : of flesche<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. of flechs of flesche</NOTE> ne of blod :</L>
<L>&YOGH;if heo is &thorn;anne with-oute sunne : heo hath Aungles cuynde</L>
<L>And mai beo nou&thorn;e here and &thorn;er : ase quik ase mannes muynde.</L>
<L N="503">for ase &yogh;e I-seoth &thorn;e li&yogh;tingue : out of &thorn;e cloudene i-wende</L>
<L>&thorn;at comieth of &thorn;at on half of &thorn;e world : and al-so sone in &thorn;e o&thorn;ur ende,</L>
<L>wel smart-loker scheot ane mannes soule : &yogh;e more &thorn;ane swuche seuene,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if heo is oute of sunne : &thorn;ene ri&yogh;te wei into heouene.</L>
<L>Ake wel sonere he may to helle come&mdash; : &thorn;are-fore it is i-sene</L>
<L N="508">&thorn;at wel mo to helle wendez : &yogh;e ich drede swuche tene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Elementa.</NOTE>BI-neo&thorn;e &thorn;e loweste heuene : &thorn;at &thorn;e mone is on i-brou&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="138" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>so beoth &thorn;e foure Elemenz : of &yogh;wan we beoth i-wrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Next &thorn;e Mone &thorn;at fuyr is hext&mdash; : ech-one huy beoth rounde&mdash;</L>
<L N="512">&thorn;e eir is &thorn;anne next bi-neothe : and tillez ri&yogh;t to &thorn;e grounde,</L>
<L>Seth&thorn;e is watur, and seth&thorn;e &thorn;e eor&thorn;e&mdash; : &thorn;eos beoth foure, i-wis;</L>
<L>of &yogh;wan man and eche quic &thorn;ing : for-so&thorn;e I-maked is.</L>
<L>Ore louerd in ech-on of &thorn;is foure : al dai scheweth is mi&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="516">Ase &yogh;e mowe in &thorn;e stude of fuyre : I-seo a wonder si&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Scheote as &thorn;ei it a steorre were : bi &thorn;e lofte an hei&yogh;,</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;e steorrene beoth feorre a-boue : for &thorn;at is sumdel nei&yogh;.</L>
<L>&thorn;e sonne may here a-mong us : gret strenc&thorn;e and mi&yogh;te do :</L>
<L N="520">heo drauth up &thorn;e kuynde of &thorn;e watere : and of &thorn;e eor&thorn;e al-so,</L>
<L>he drau&yogh;th up of<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. op</NOTE> &thorn;e eor&thorn;e in druye wedere : ase it were a druye breth,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;oru&yogh; hete of &thorn;e sonne : a-boue<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. aboute</NOTE> &thorn;e eir it geth,</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane it comez a-mong &thorn;e fuyre : sone it bi-gynnez forto tiende</L>
<L N="524">And al berninde it scheot forth : &thorn;at hit beo i-bar[n]d to ende.</L>
<L>&thorn;are-fore men ne i-seoth no swuch &thorn;ing : bote it beo in hete.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Fuigur.</NOTE>&para; Li&yogh;tingue comez al-so &thorn;are-of : &yogh;wane it comez to wete :</L>
<L>for al &thorn;at ilke druye breth : &thorn;at is so i-drawe an hei&yogh;</L>
<L N="528">&thorn;oru&yogh; hete &thorn;at was bi-fore : and a cloude &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> &thorn;are was<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> is</NOTE> nei&yogh;,</L>
<L>A-non so it is a-fuyre : it scheot &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e cloude,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e &yogh;wile it is in &thorn;e watere : it go&thorn;eleth swy&thorn;e loude.
<PB REF="00000363.tif" N="315"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ase &yogh;if a man nome ane sclabbe of Ire : &thorn;at glowynde were a-fuyre</L>
<L N="532">And pulte in watere, it wolde go&thorn;eli loude : &thorn;at men mi&yogh;ten it feor i-huyre.<NOTE PLACE="marg2">Tonitruum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al-so &thorn;at fuyr up an hei&yogh; : &thorn;at bi &thorn;e cloude is i-tend;</L>
<L>hit go&thorn;elez in &thorn;e watere loude : as it &thorn;oru&yogh;-out I-went&mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at is &thorn;e &thorn;ondre, i-wis : and siker non o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing;</L>
<L N="536">And &yogh;wane &thorn;at fuyr scheot &thorn;oru&yogh;-out : &thorn;at is &thorn;e li&yogh;ting,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at scheot a-brod &thorn;oru al &thorn;e world&mdash; : &thorn;at comez aftur &thorn;e dunte;</L>
<L>And natheles it &thorn;inchez bi-fore : for it ne may nou&yogh;were at-stunte.</L>
<L N="539">&YOGH;if here were an hei&yogh; stepel : and a man a-boue sete</L>
<L>And men i-sei&yogh;en him smiten al an hei&yogh; : guode duntes and grete,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou mi&yogh;test him seo wel longue smite : &thorn;e duntes with &thorn;ine ei&yogh;e</L>
<L>Are &thorn;ov scholdest &thorn;ene dunt i-heore : &yogh;if he were ou&yogh;t hei&yogh;e&mdash;</L>
<L N="543">for man mai i-seo wel feor a &thorn;ing : a-non so it is ido,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;are nis no-&thorn;ing bi-tweone : ake man ne may nou&yogh;t i-heore so.</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane &thorn;at fuyr comez into &thorn;e &yogh;water : gret noyse a-non &thorn;are is,</L>
<L N="546">Ake men ne heorez it nou&yogh;t a-non : for it is so feor, i-wis;</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e li&yogh;tingue we i-seoth a-non : &yogh;wane it is &thorn;oru&yogh; i-brou&yogh;t&mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;are-fore men &thorn;inchez it comez bi-fore : bote natheles it ne doth nou&yogh;t :</L>
<L>for &yogh;wane &thorn;e li&yogh;tingue is i-come : A-non we habbez &thorn;e si&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;et sovn ne may nou&yogh;t : so sone a-doun to us a-li&yogh;te.&mdash;</L>
<L>Nov&thorn;e nis &thorn;e druy&yogh;e breth of eor&thorn;e : neuere with-oute hete</L>
<L N="552">Idrawe up, &thorn;at comez bi-fore : ne a-queint with-oute wete :</L>
<L>&thorn;are-fore bote after hete : man ne schal no &thorn;ondre i-seo,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;e weder smite in wete : for non-o&thorn;ur ne mai it beo.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at man schal in puyr somer : selde &thorn;ondre i-huyre :<MILESTONE N="138b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="556">For &thorn;er is &thorn;anne selde wete : to maken quenchingue of fuyre;</L>
<L>Ne in puyr winter no-&thorn;e-mo : for &thorn;anne nis non hete</L>
<L>To drawe up &thorn;e drou&yogh;&thorn;e of &thorn;e eor&thorn;e : for &thorn;e muchele wete.</L>
<L>&thorn;are-fore Men seggez &thorn;at wynter-&thorn;ondre : selde man schal guod i-seo,</L>
<L N="560">For he ne may neuere come : bote &thorn;at weder onkuynde beo.</L>
<L>Ake bi-tweone somer and wynter : ase in Aueril and may,</L>
<L>And eft-sone fram heruest : forto seint Clementes day,</L>
<L>&thorn;anne is &thorn;e &thorn;ondre kuynde Inov : and li&yogh;tingue al-so :</L>
<L N="564">For &thorn;anne is &thorn;at weder wet : and ofte hot &thorn;ar-to.&mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;e mouwen axi, &yogh;wane it<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> &thorn;undre is : I-meingt of fuyr in wete,
<PB REF="00000364.tif" N="316"></L>
<L>hov is &thorn;at hit a-quellez men : ofte bi weye and strete,</L>
<L>And smit a-doun wel grete treon : and deth wel mani a wonder?</L>
<L N="568">&thorn;are-fore ich mot eov more telle : of kuynde of &thorn;e &thorn;onder.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;O ore louerd &thorn;olede on eor&thorn;e deth : and bond &thorn;ene deuel for man</L>
<L>A[n]d debruysde helle-&yogh;ates : with &thorn;ondre &thorn;udere he cam.</L>
<L N="571">&thorn;are-fore euereft Aftur-ward : &yogh;ware-so &thorn;e deouelene beo,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ondre huy beoth so sore a-ferd : &thorn;at huy nutez &yogh;wodere to fleo;</L>
<L>And huy &thorn;at woniez in &thorn;e lufte : and o&thorn;ure ase wel so heo,</L>
<L>In strongue fere comieth a-doun : and nutez &yogh;wodere teo,</L>
<L>And huy slez men bi &thorn;e weie : ase man may ofte I-seo&mdash;</L>
<L N="576">&thorn;at muche fere god heom &yogh;yue : and no-&thorn;e worse us ne beo!</L>
<L>In o&thorn;ur manere &thorn;are comez &yogh;eot harm : of &thorn;e &thorn;ondre a-mong :</L>
<L>For &thorn;are ase &thorn;at weder is : &thorn;e tempeste is ful strong,</L>
<L>Of wynd, . of watur,. and of fuyr : &thorn;at &thorn;ei &thorn;are were<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. weren</NOTE> &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="580">A Mulleston, he scholde al-to-driue : &thorn;ei he of molten bras were.</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane &thorn;e tempeste is &thorn;are so strong : me &thorn;inchez, it nis no wonder</L>
<L>&thorn;ei &thorn;are come leome ofte a-doun : with &thorn;e dunte of &thorn;e &thorn;onder;</L>
<L N="583">&YOGH;wane &thorn;e wynd and &thorn;at fuyr smiteth : &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e watur-cloude,</L>
<L>with swy&thorn;e grete strenc&thorn;e it li&yogh;t a-doun : ase man mai i-huyre loude,</L>
<L>And smit ase it were a dunt : o&thorn;ur blast of grete mi&yogh;te&mdash;</L>
<L>No wonder &thorn;ei it smite harde : &yogh;wane it so deth a-li&yogh;te&mdash;</L>
<L>And brekez treon and quellez men : and deth gret o&thorn;ur wonder.</L>
<L N="588">In &thorn;is manere comez &thorn;e harm : &thorn;at men i-seoth of &thorn;e &thorn;onder.</L>
<L>Men I-seoth ofte li&yogh;tingue : brenne hous and schrenche,</L>
<L>&thorn;at vnne&thorn;e mai ani watur : &thorn;at fuyr &thorn;arof a-queenche;&mdash;</L>
<L N="591">For of &thorn;e watur-cloude a-boue : &thorn;at fuyr is out i-brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And for it out of &thorn;e watere comez : &thorn;at fuyr nele quenche nou&yogh;t.&mdash;</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;e mouwe &yogh;e Axi in &yogh;wuche manere : &yogh;water comez so hei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>And &yogh;warof comez rein and snov&yogh; : &thorn;at &yogh;e i-seoth with ei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e sonne, &thorn;at is al maister here : sent a-doun hire hete</L>
<L N="596">And makez &thorn;e wateres bre&thorn;i up-ri&yogh;t : as &thorn;ei huy scholden swete,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e &thorn;e .sees. an ferchse wateres : and drau&yogh;th op so &thorn;ane breth,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at a-boue in &thorn;e lufte : &thorn;ilke mist euene geth.</L>
<L>Nov&thorn;e is &thorn;are uppe in &thorn;e lufte : a swy&thorn;e cold stude, i-wis,</L>
<L N="600">For bi-tweone heoue and eor&thorn;e : so cold non &thorn;are nis,<MILESTONE N="139" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;are ase &thorn;e blake cloudene beoth : and o&thorn;ur wederes al-so&mdash;
<PB REF="00000365.tif" N="317"></L>
<L>hit nis up-ri&yogh;t fram &thorn;e eor&thorn;e : bote Ane mile o&thorn;ur two.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Plunia.</NOTE>&YOGH;wane &thorn;e sonne hath &thorn;udere i-drawe : &thorn;ene mist for hete,</L>
<L N="604">It ne may no feor for &thorn;e colde : ake bi-cometh al to wete,</L>
<L>And gaderez &thorn;are to one watur-cloude : and houeth &thorn;are ane stounde,</L>
<L>For-to &thorn;e tyme come &thorn;at it Ryne : and droppinde falle to grounde.</L>
<L N="607">&YOGH;if it is cold up an hei&yogh; : &thorn;e dropen bi-cometh to snowe,<NOTE PLACE="marg2">Nix.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;anne<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> As Grando.</NOTE> huy freosez adoneward : are huy comen here ou&yogh;t lowe;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if it is &thorn;oru&yogh;-out cold : &thorn;at huy alle<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> al</NOTE> i-frozen beo,</L>
<L>&THORN;anne it is haul puyr : ase &yogh;e mouwen al day i-seo.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e breth of &thorn;e watere &thorn;at &thorn;e sonne : drau&yogh;th op a-&yogh;ein eue,</L>
<L N="612">&yogh;wane &thorn;e sonne is to grounde i-go : it ne may nou&yogh;t bi-leue,</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane no-&thorn;ing ne halt it up : and &thorn;e hete is al i-do,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Ros.</NOTE>&thorn;anne it fallez softe adoun : and to dewe bi-comez ri&yogh;t so,</L>
<L>And hangueth on leues and on gras : for-to &thorn;e hete a-morewe come</L>
<L N="616">And &thorn;e sonne luyte and luyte : it habbe eft-sone up i-nome.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e hore-forst cometh &yogh;wane it is so cold : &thorn;at it freoseth a-ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Dev freose a-doneward : &yogh;wane he is a-doun a-li&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;e Dev&yogh; is al-so up i-drawe : and a-doneward i-falle al-so</L>
<L N="620">And &thorn;are come a &thorn;icke myst : and a cold forst &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>&thorn;anne freost &thorn;e &thorn;icke Myst : and cleouez an hei&yogh; on &thorn;e treo:</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">pruyna.</NOTE>And &thorn;arof comez &thorn;e Rym-forst : ase &thorn;ilke Mist deth fleo;</L>
<L>he cleouez on hegges al a-bovte : and In &thorn;e wodes al-so,</L>
<L N="624">On treo, on stones, on bestes al-so : &thorn;are it may cleouien to&mdash;</L>
<L>I-chot wel, on mi fore-top : it hauez wel ofte i-do&mdash;.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is manere<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. manere manere</NOTE> &yogh;e mowen i-seo : &thorn;e kuynde of reyne and snowe,</L>
<L>Of hawel., of snov&yogh;<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. dev</NOTE>., of Rym-forst : of hore-forst &thorn;at freost lowe,</L>
<L N="628">Of cloudene and of Mist al-so&mdash; : for al o &thorn;ing it is:</L>
<L>For alle huy comiez of water-breth : &thorn;at &thorn;e sonne drau&yogh;th up, i-wis.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOv&thorn;e is watur here on eor&thorn;e : wel more &thorn;ane &thorn;e londe:</L>
<L>For sum o see, with-oute mo : is more, ich onder-stonde.</L>
<L N="632">For &thorn;e gret . se . of occean : In &thorn;e on ende, i-wis,</L>
<L>Is more &thorn;ane al &thorn;e eor&thorn;e beo : and gret wonder it is.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. nis</NOTE></L>
<L>For a-boute al &thorn;e eor&thorn;e heo geth : and brod heo is &thorn;are-to,</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;e &yogh;wyte of &thorn;e Eye goth a-boute &thorn;e &yogh;eolke : and more is al-so.</L>
<L N="636">Ech o&thorn;ur . se . a-mong us here : ne beo heo so gret non,</L>
<L>Nis bote a lime of &thorn;ulke se : and &thorn;udere In huy goth ech-on.
<PB REF="00000366.tif" N="318"></L>
<L>&para; Wellene comiez of grete wateres : and muche del of &thorn;e se</L>
<L>&thorn;oru&yogh; veynes al vnder eor&thorn;e : and to &thorn;e se wendez a&yogh;e.</L>
<L N="640">For &thorn;are beoz ase it veynene weren : onder eor&thorn;e mani on,</L>
<L>&thorn;at sikeniez out of &thorn;e se : and &thorn;arof springueth &thorn;is wellene ech-on;</L>
<L>And &thorn;are-&thorn;oru&yogh; eornth &thorn;at watur faste : a-boute fram &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are-ate wellen springuth out : and eft eorneth In a&yogh;e.</L>
<L N="644">So &thorn;at for alle &thorn;e grete wateres : &thorn;at to &thorn;e se goth echon</L>
<L>Vnne[&thorn;e] is &thorn;e se eni-&thorn;ing &thorn;e more : ake euere heo is bi on.</L>
<L>For ase swi&thorn;e it geth under eor&thorn;e : ase it comez in-to &thorn;e se,<MILESTONE N="139b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And euere to wellene it geth a-brod : and eft-sone ernth in a&yogh;e;</L>
<L N="648">And al-so sone ase ech watur comez : to &thorn;e se in is ende,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e grete se of occean : ase swi&thorn;e it deth i-wende.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore [for] alle &thorn;e wateres : &thorn;at to &thorn;e se doth gon,</L>
<L>&thorn;e se mot nedlingus beo : euere-more bi on.</L>
<L N="652">&thorn;at heo flowez and ebbez : and wexet In a &thorn;rowe,</L>
<L>&thorn;at is &thorn;oru&yogh; kuynde of &thorn;e mone : and ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t &thorn;oru&yogh; hire owe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Terra.</NOTE>&THORN;E eor&thorn;e a-midde &thorn;e grete se : ase a luy[te] bal is round,</L>
<L>And puyr helle a-midde &thorn;e eor&thorn;e : ho-so sou&yogh;te &thorn;ene ground.</L>
<L N="656">And &yogh;eot ase gret ase &thorn;e eor&thorn;e &thorn;inchez : and ase luyte ase heo is,</L>
<L>&thorn;are nis bote &thorn;at seouen&thorn;e del : &thorn;at Men woniez on, i-wis.</L>
<L>For In &thorn;e north side here : ho-so lie nele,</L>
<L>For it is feor fram &thorn;e sonne : no Man ne wonez for chele,</L>
<L N="660">Ne In &thorn;e south half no&thorn;e-mo : for &thorn;e grete hete</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e sonne &thorn;at is a-boue&mdash; : &thorn;e leomene beoth so grete<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> kete</NOTE>;</L>
<L>And manie o&thorn;ur studes al-so : &thorn;ei men mi&yogh;ten wonien &thorn;are-Inne,</L>
<L>huy ne berez no&thorn;ur corn ne fruyt : Manne is mete to wynne.</L>
<L N="664">And &thorn;ei &thorn;e eor&thorn;e were al to-delt : ho-so mi&yogh;te bi Art,</L>
<L>&YOGH;eot nis &thorn;are, to wonien Inne : onne&thorn;e &thorn;e seuen&thorn;e part.&mdash;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is foure elemenz : ech quic &thorn;ing I-make is:</L>
<L>Of eor&thorn;e., of watur., and of &thorn;e eyr : and of fuyre, i-wis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="668">MAn hath of eor&thorn;e al is bodi : and of watere he hauez wete,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e Eyr he hath breth and wind : of fuyr he hath hete.</L>
<L>Ech quic &thorn;ing [hath] of alle &thorn;eos foure : of some more and lasse.</L>
<L>Ho-so hath of &thorn;e eor&thorn;e mest : he is slou&yogh; ase &thorn;e Asse,</L>
<L N="672">Of fade colur, of hard huyde : boistous fourme and ded strong,</L>
<L>Of muche &thorn;ou&yogh;t, of luyte speche : stille groyninde and wrath long,
<PB REF="00000367.tif" N="319"></L>
<L>Of slou&yogh; wreche and Aru&yogh; mouth<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> fereblet</NOTE> : fast. and loth to gyue guod,</L>
<L>Sone old and nou&yogh;t willesfol : stable and studefast of mod.</L>
<L N="676">Ho-so hath of &thorn;e watere mest : he schal beo &yogh;wit and fat al-so,</L>
<L>Of nesche her and no-&thorn;ing crips : gret slepare and slov&yogh; &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L>Snvuelinde nose and wet mouth : of fewe wordes : and luyte drinke,</L>
<L>Of schorte wrath&thorn;e and de-bonere : Arv&yogh;. <NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> fereblet</NOTE>and luyte luste swinke.</L>
<L N="680">&para; ho-so haueth of &thorn;e eir mest : he is of guod colour,</L>
<L>Fat and of nesche her : wel large and gret lechour,</L>
<L>Li&yogh;Inde and of glad semblaunt : and somdel of pruyte;</L>
<L>Habbe he mete and drinke I-nov&yogh; : he carez elles luyte;</L>
<L N="684">Wrath&thorn;e he berth luytel &yogh;wyle : he wole beo ballede sone;</L>
<L>glad and bli&thorn;e, and onstable : of &thorn;at he hath to done.</L>
<L>&para; ho-so hath of fuyre mest : he is smal and red,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur he is blac with cripse here : lene and sumdel qued,</L>
<L N="688">Hinderful<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> hinder</NOTE> and of bost I-nov&yogh; : hardi and ofte lie,</L>
<L>Sweriare and of manie word : and fol of lecherie,</L>
<L>Proud and wemod, and drinkare : and in wrath&thorn;e al-mest wod,</L>
<L>Hardi and li&yogh;t and stalewarde : and wakiare wel guod.<MILESTONE N="140" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="692">Ake euerech of &thorn;eos foure elemenz : en-tempriez o&thorn;ur, i-wis,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at vnne&thorn;e In ani Man : any ri&yogh;[t] puyr maister is.</L>
<L>Ake<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> ase</NOTE> &yogh;if &thorn;ov nimst ri&yogh;t puyr hot watur : and dost cold &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L>&thorn;ov mi&yogh;t it makien euene wlach : and entempri it so.&mdash;</L>
<L N="696">&para; &thorn;o ore louerd formest made man : he made him, i-wis,</L>
<L>Of alle foure Elemens : ase man &yogh;eot i-mad is.</L>
<L>&thorn;o made he &thorn;e kuynde in eche manne : ase &yogh;e mouwe i-wite,</L>
<L>bi-twene Man and womman : of &yogh;wan we beoth bi-&yogh;ite.</L>
<L N="700">A swy&thorn;e foul &thorn;ing is &thorn;at sed : of &yogh;wan Man is i-spreind;</L>
<L>bo&thorn;e Man and womman : to-gadere huy beoth i-meind.</L>
<L>Of &yogh;wij&yogh;t colour it bi-leuez : ase it is i-write,</L>
<L>for-to a-boute &thorn;e twelfte day : &thorn;at it was bi-&yogh;ite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="704">FOrmest &thorn;are keniez &thorn;ar-of : smale bollene &thorn;reo,</L>
<L>Ake euerech hangez faste on o&thorn;ur : ho-so it mi&yogh;te i-seo.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e hexte bolle comez &thorn;at brayn : &thorn;e heorte of &thorn;ane a-midde,</L>
<L>&thorn;e liuere, &thorn;at is ne&thorn;emest : heo comez of &thorn;e &thorn;ridde.</L>
<L N="708">&thorn;is beoth &thorn;e &thorn;reo hexte limes<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. limest</NOTE> : &thorn;at formest i-kenede beoz,</L>
<L>And In heom is al ane Mannes lijf : ase [&yogh;e] nou&thorn;e i-seoth;
<PB REF="00000368.tif" N="320"></L>
<L>&thorn;are nis non of &thorn;ulke &thorn;reo : &thorn;at hadde any wounde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at euereft mi&yogh;te I-held beo : to libbe anie stounde.</L>
<L N="712">Aftur &thorn;e twelf formeste dawes : &thorn;at &thorn;et sed hath &yogh;wij&yogh;t i-beo,</L>
<L>hit bi-comez to a &thorn;icke blod : and chaungez al is bleo.</L>
<L>Hit &thorn;ickez to<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> so</NOTE> Nye dawes : for-to &thorn;e on and twenty&thorn;e day :</L>
<L>&thorn;anne it tornez formest to flesch : ase &thorn;e kuynde may.</L>
<L N="716">Aftur ei&yogh;te and twenti dawes : fourme it bi-gynnez to nyme,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at In-with fourti dawes : it haueth euerech lime,</L>
<L>And in lasse &yogh;if it is a knaue : for he is of more hete.</L>
<L N="719">&YOGH;wane &thorn;e limes beoth formest i-mad : huy ne beoz nou&yogh;t ful grete.</L>
<L>A smal weob it bi-cluppez al-a-boute : to holden it to-gadere faste,</L>
<L>Fram &thorn;at hit is formest i-kened : forto hit beo i-bore at&thorn;e laste.</L>
<L>&para; Al round it lith in &thorn;e wombe : and i-bouwed ase an hare</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane &thorn;at heo in fourme lith : for is .In. is sumdel nare.</L>
<L N="724">Al I-buyd &thorn;e leggues beoz : it nolde nou&yogh;t elles fei&yogh;e,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> veie</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e helene to &thorn;e bottokes : &thorn;e kneuwene in ei&thorn;ur ei&yogh;e;</L>
<L>&thorn;at heued is i-buid a-doneward : &thorn;e Armes al with-Inne,</L>
<L>&thorn;e elbouwes ri&yogh;t in &thorn;e schere : &thorn;e fustus to &thorn;e chinne;</L>
<L N="728">Al i-buyd is &thorn;e rug : so &thorn;at nei&yogh; round it is.</L>
<L>Man, &yogh;war-of cometh &thorn;i pruyte? : for &thorn;are nis non, i-wis!</L>
<L>So hei&yogh; &thorn;ov makest &thorn;e here : and to no man &thorn;ou nelt a-buye :</L>
<L N="731">Loke hov crekede<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. croked</NOTE> &thorn;ov were &thorn;are : and nou&thorn;e to no man &thorn;ov nelt a-buye (!).</L>
<L>&thorn;ou ne mi&yogh;test nou&yogh;t &thorn;o holde up &thorn;in heued : ne enes on-do &thorn;in ei&yogh;e;</L>
<L>Fra<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. fram</NOTE> &yogh;wam cam it seth&thorn;e &thorn;e : to beren &thorn;in heued so hei&yogh;e?</L>
<L>&YOGH;if man him wolde bi-&thorn;enche : and ri&yogh;t him onder-stonde,</L>
<L N="735">he scholde beo meoke, and milde of heorte : and to no man habben onde.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 734-5 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN eche manne &thorn;reo soulene beoth : ake nou&yogh;t alle I-liche guode,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Anime.</NOTE>Ase ich seide eov er of &thorn;reo bollene : &yogh;if &yogh;e it onder-stode.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e Ne&thorn;emeste bolle : &thorn;at &thorn;e liuere deoth of springue,</L>
<L>&thorn;are comez o-manere soule : at &thorn;e bi-guynningue</L>
<L N="740">Ase it were a-manere lijf : &thorn;at sent norischingue</L>
<L>To &thorn;e limes al-a-boute : and bi-ginnez<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> bringeth</NOTE> in is wexingue;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at ane mannes norischingue : and is wexingue al-so</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ulke furste soule comez : and of &thorn;e liuere &thorn;er-to.
<PB REF="00000369.tif" N="321"></L>
<L N="744">&thorn;ulke manere soule is : in ech wexinde &thorn;ingue,</L>
<L>In treon and in gras al-so : huy ne mi&yogh;ten nou&yogh;t elles springue.</L>
<L>&thorn;oru&yogh; vertue of &thorn;ulke soule : &yogh;wane it is &thorn;er-to i-brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;at mannes lymes i-fourmede beoth : &thorn;at &thorn;are ne faillez nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="748">&thorn;anne comez &thorn;are In &thorn;e heorte : &thorn;at &thorn;e o&thorn;ur bolle was,</L>
<L>A soule &thorn;at bringuz &thorn;at lijf : &thorn;are it neuer er nas.</L>
<L>&thorn;at child is &thorn;anne quick a-non : ake strenc&thorn;e nath it nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Enes for-to wawie him : are hit beo feorrore i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="752">Of &thorn;ulke soule hath ech man : &thorn;at he mai wawi an gon</L>
<L>In is bi-guynningue,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Is velynge</NOTE> and al is lijf : and is fif wittes ech-on.</L>
<L>&thorn;ulke soule hath ech &thorn;ing : &thorn;at vuel<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> vele</NOTE> may ouer<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> o&thorn;er</NOTE> -go,</L>
<L>Best, . and foul, and fisch al-so : worm and o&thorn;ure mo.</L>
<L N="756">&thorn;eos soule &thorn;at bringuez &thorn;at lijf : is ate heorte grounde :</L>
<L>&thorn;are-fore ho-so is &thorn;are i-smyte : he dei&yogh;ez in luyte stounde.</L>
<L>&thorn;eos soule comez of mannes cuynde : and &thorn;e o&thorn;ere bi-fore al-so :</L>
<L>&thorn;are-fore, &yogh;wane a man dei&yogh;ez : huy dei&yogh;ez bo&thorn;e-to.</L>
<L N="760">&YOGH;eot &thorn;are is &thorn;e &thorn;ridde soule : &thorn;at al heore maister is :</L>
<L>For &yogh;wane a child hath alle is limes : [&amp;]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> quike huy beoth, i-wis,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e ende of &thorn;e feor&thorn;e mon&thorn;e : &thorn;at it was bi-&yogh;ite,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur sone &thorn;ar-aftur-ward : ase we findez i-write :</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="764">&THORN;E cuynde &thorn;at ore louerd made : and porueide al-so</L>
<L>&thorn;o he hadde Man formest I-mad : and in parays i-do,</L>
<L>To myenge &thorn;e kuynde of heuene : to mannes kuynde her,</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Ane</NOTE> soule of witte and of liue : &thorn;at is Aungelene i-pier,</L>
<L N="768">heo comez fram &thorn;e kuynde of Aungles : and in &thorn;is fourme a-li&yogh;t</L>
<L>And miengez with &thorn;is wrechche flesch : ase ore louerd it hath i-di&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And makez &thorn;e kuynde &thorn;at nas er : bote ase a best onne&thorn;e</L>
<L>&thorn;e kuynde of aungles with him bere : for-to he come to de&thorn;e.</L>
<L N="772">&thorn;ulke soule nimth hire In : and bi-leuez, i-wis,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e childes brayn an hei&yogh; : &thorn;at is hexte lime is.</L>
<L>&thorn;ulke soule i-last euere : and ne dei&yogh;e[z] neuere mo,</L>
<L>And went, &yogh;wane a man schal dei&yogh;e : to weole o&thorn;ur to wo.</L>
<L N="776">Al &thorn;at man hath bi-fore a best : o&thorn;ur more resun can,</L>
<L>Al he it hath of &thorn;ulke soule : &yogh;ware-&thorn;oru&yogh; he is man.</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane man went out of &thorn;is liue : &thorn;ulke soule, i-wis,</L>
<L>Bi-guynnez departi fram &thorn;e bodie<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. soule</NOTE> : &thorn;e &yogh;wile he a-liue is,
<PB REF="00000370.tif" N="322"></L>
<L N="780">And wend, ase heo hauez of-serued : to Ioye o&thorn;ur to pine;</L>
<L>&thorn;e soulene &thorn;at hire ferene weren : beoth sone i-brou&yogh;t to fyne.</L>
<L>&thorn;ulke &thorn;at halt ane Mannes lijf : and stikez in &thorn;e heorte,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane heo schal with &thorn;e bodie [dei&yogh;e] : &thorn;at in strong Anguysche deth smeorte,</L>
<L N="784">&YOGH;if he onder-&yogh;it his felawe : to Ioye fram him i-wende,</L>
<L>&thorn;are-fore heo maketh signe of Ioye : and deth as &thorn;e hiende;</L>
<L>And [&yogh;wan] heo deiez with &thorn;e bodie : fair chere heo makez and softe,</L>
<L>And bi-lef &thorn;at bodi in swych point : ase man may i-seon wel ofte :</L>
<L N="788">&thorn;e ei&yogh;ene I-closede faire i-nov&yogh; : &thorn;e mouth of faire chere,</L>
<L>Ech lyme al-so faire i-strei&yogh;t : In guod poynt ase he were.</L>
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;ridde soule al-so &yogh;eot : &thorn;at deiez at&thorn;en ende,</L>
<L>&thorn;at norischingue to al &thorn;at bodi : ant to &thorn;e limes deth sende,</L>
<L N="792">he deth ane<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> ek</NOTE> signe in &thorn;e bodie : &yogh;if is felawe geth to guode,</L>
<L>And bi-lefth &thorn;at bodi in fair hev : &yogh;wij&yogh;t o&thorn;ur red of blode.</L>
<L>&thorn;eos soulene<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> soule</NOTE> dei&yogh;ez in a man : &yogh;wane &thorn;e hete is al i-do,</L>
<L>&thorn;e ra&thorn;ur &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;e erore whan</NOTE> he leost is breth : and wawe&yogh;Ingue al-so.</L>
<L N="796">&YOGH;wane huy i-seoz heore felawe : to torment i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Lu&thorn;ur semblaunt huy makiez bo&thorn;e : as it ne likede heom nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And bi-leueth &thorn;at bodi in foule heowe : &thorn;e ei&yogh;ene stareInde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e mouth of foul semblaunt : and ofte is<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> grenninde.</L>
<L N="800">Swuche signes &thorn;at fereliche beoth : &thorn;at man may ofte i-seo,</L>
<L>Beoth signes &thorn;at &thorn;e wrechche soule : in lu&thorn;ere weie beo.</L>
<L>Nov Iesu crist, &thorn;at us soule &yogh;af : graunte us &thorn;at we hire moten so here rede</L>
<L>&thorn;at seint Mi&yogh;hel hire mote a-fongue : and bi-fore to Ioye lede. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="47" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>47 [Clement.]<MILESTONE N="141" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Clement was I-bore at Rome : I-furn bi olde dawe.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e hexte men he was i-come : &thorn;a[t] weren in &thorn;ulke lawe.</L>
<L>his Moder hiet Macidiane : his fader Faustinian.</L>
<L>Twei bre&thorn;ren he hadde, eldore &thorn;ane he : heore namen ich telle kan :</L>
<L N="5">&THORN;at on hiet Faust, &thorn;at o&thorn;ur Faustyn : twynnes bo&thorn;e huy were;</L>
<L>Fader and moder weren glade of heom : &thorn;at heom bi-&yogh;ete and bere.</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e fair womman heore Moder<NOTE PLACE="marg1">added later.</NOTE> was : &thorn;e faireste &thorn;at Men wuste;</L>
<L N="8">hire louerd heo louede treweliche&mdash; : non-o&thorn;ur of heom men nuste.
<PB REF="00000371.tif" N="323"></L>
<L>For hire fair-hede hire louerdes bro&thorn;er : fondede with al<NOTE PLACE="marg1">overlined.</NOTE> is mi&yogh;te</L>
<L>To bringue hire in fole loue : bi dai&yogh;e and eke bi ny&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode womman was<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. wast</NOTE> studefast : he nolde nou&yogh;t don is wille;</L>
<L N="12">Ake euere Ansuerede him fayre i-nov : and bar hire faire and stille.</L>
<L>he of-sou&yogh;te hire so swi&thorn;e : &thorn;at no pais heo nadde.</L>
<L>heo nust[e] &yogh;wat was hire beste red : ake sore of him heo dradde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh;te &yogh;if heo tolde hire louerd fore : &thorn;at he wolde beo wroth</L>
<L N="16">And &thorn;e more hatie is bro&thorn;er&mdash; : &thorn;at were hire swi&thorn;e loth.</L>
<L>heo &thorn;ou&yogh;te hou heo mi&yogh;te on take : &thorn;at heo ane &yogh;wyle nere</L>
<L>Ovt of is si&yogh;te in o&thorn;ur stude : &thorn;at heo fur-&yogh;ite were.</L>
<L>heo hire bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te of one quoyntise : &thorn;at to hire louerd heo seide.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. leide?</NOTE></L>
<L>A ni&yogh;t In hire bed heo bi-gan to sike : ase &thorn;ei heo of slepe a-breyde :</L>
<L N="21">"A, sire," heo seide, "merci, &thorn;in ore! : ich am in grete drede :</L>
<L>An hard metingue me hath i-mat : I-not &yogh;wat me is to rede :</L>
<L>Me &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at on of ovre godes : cam here bi-fore &thorn;e</L>
<L N="24">And hiet me grei&thorn;i hastifueliche : mine twei sones and me</L>
<L>And wiende with hem and wonie : feor In an o&thorn;ur londe,</L>
<L>For-to ich o&thorn;ur<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. o&thorn;ur o&thorn;ur</NOTE> heste hadde : of him o&thorn;ur is sonde;</L>
<L>And bote &yogh;if ich sone dude so : he swor with grete o&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="28">To lu&thorn;ere de&thorn;e he wolde do : us and ore children bo&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore, sire, bi-&thorn;ench &thorn;e wel : &yogh;wat &thorn;ar-of &thorn;ov wolt rede :</L>
<L>For bote it beo sone ido : for-so&thorn;e we beoth dede."</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode Man<NOTE PLACE="marg1">overlined.</NOTE> lai in grete care : And &thorn;ene deth sore he dradde,</L>
<L N="32">bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te him strete In swuche neode : &thorn;ene beste red he radde :</L>
<L>"Dame," he seide, "&yogh;wane it is so : to schilden us fram care</L>
<L>&THORN;ov schalt nime &thorn;ine twei sones : a[n] to<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. ato</NOTE> Atenes fare.</L>
<L>&THORN;ov schalt habbe with &thorn;e men I-nowe : And tresor al-so.</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;ov schalt, &yogh;wane &thorn;ou &thorn;udere comest : &thorn;ine sones to lore do,</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy leornien of clergie. : and &yogh;wan ore god &thorn;e sent tokningue</L>
<L>For-to comen hom a-&yogh;ein : &thorn;ov schalt heom with &thorn;e bringue."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Glad was &thorn;o &thorn;is guode wijf : of &thorn;at leoue rede.</L>
<L N="40">heo grei&thorn;ede hire and wende forth : ase hire louerd sede :</L>
<L>heo gan hire twei sones : toward atenes lede.</L>
<L>Ake seint clement athom with is fader : bi-lefde, for &yogh;ong-hede,</L>
<L>For he was onne&thorn;es fif &yogh;er old : and for &thorn;at he scholde beo</L>
<L N="44">his fader solas, and<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> for he nadde : bote childrene &thorn;reo.&mdash;
<PB REF="00000372.tif" N="324"></L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is guode wijf was forth i-went : and hire louerdes bro&thorn;er it wuste</L>
<L>&THORN;at hire louede in fole loue : no red &thorn;ar-of he nuste;</L>
<L>&para; For wrath&thorn;e to is bro&thorn;ur he seide : "sire, hov geth &thorn;is?</L>
<L N="48">Is &thorn;i wijf fram &thorn;e I-went? : heo is strong hore, i-wis.</L>
<L>heo haueth me wel longue i-loued : ne<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. no</NOTE> leng hele ich ne may,</L>
<L>And to bringue me in fole dede : heo fonde[de]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. fonde</NOTE> ni&yogh;t and day;</L>
<L>Onne&thorn;e ich me mi&yogh;te with hire wite : for, siker, i-nolde it do,</L>
<L N="52">For sunne, ne for &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e : ne for mi treovnesse al-so.</L>
<L>Anon so heo it onder-&yogh;at : &thorn;at i-nolde don hire wille,</L>
<L>On of &thorn;ine hynene heo louede : In folie wel stille,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hath bi hire wel ofte i-leie. : ake, &thorn;at &thorn;ov it ne onder-&yogh;ete,</L>
<L N="56">heo &thorn;ou&yogh;te hov heo mi&yogh;te with him beo&mdash; : for heo nolde him nou&yogh;t lete :</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore heo &thorn;ou&yogh;te ane feolle wrench : of wommanes kuynde lore,</L>
<L>And is i-go with hire copiner : &thorn;ov ne sixt hire nonmore.</L>
<L>For ofte men seggez, and soth it is : &thorn;at &thorn;is wommen beoth</L>
<L N="60">Feolle and false, and &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> me for-&thorn;inchez : &thorn;at we &thorn;e so&thorn;e i-seoth."</L>
<L>Sori was &thorn;is guode Man : &thorn;o he heorde &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his wijf, &thorn;at he louede muche : scholde so don a-mis,</L>
<L>Ant &thorn;at heo was so fram him i-went : and &thorn;at heo ne bi-lefde bi-hinde</L>
<L>his sones, &thorn;at him so leoue weren : ne he nuste &yogh;ware heom finde.</L>
<L>After he wolde habbe i-went : ake he ne dorste for care</L>
<L>Of cleme[n]te, is &yogh;ongue sone : laste he scholde for-fare.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 2 vv. more.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>Forth wende &thorn;is wijf with hire sones : ase god hire wolde sende.</L>
<L N="68">In scipe heo dude hire in &thorn;e se : in-to an o&thorn;ur londe to wende.<MILESTONE N="142" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A-midde &thorn;e se a-&yogh;ein ane roche : &thorn;at schip bi-gan to glide,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it alto-drof, and huy fullen out : euer-ech in is side.</L>
<L>A wawe &thorn;are cam of &thorn;e se : &thorn;oru ore louerdes sonde,</L>
<L N="72">And caste &thorn;is guode wijf al quik : a-non-ri&yogh;t to &thorn;e londe.</L>
<L>A-non so heo was up i-cast : and to hire ri&yogh;te witte cam,</L>
<L>And miste hire twei leoue sones : gret deol to hire heo nam;</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e se heo wolde habbe i-lope : hire-seolf for-to a-drenche,</L>
<L N="76">&YOGH;if it nadde i-beo for grete hope : of &thorn;ing &thorn;at heo gan &thorn;enche :</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e se wolde some tyme : hire sones to londe caste&mdash;</L>
<L>For men seggez heo wole ech ded &thorn;ing : weorpen up at&thorn;e laste;</L>
<L>hadde heo enes heore bodies i-sei&yogh;e : hire &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at heo ne rou&yogh;te.
<PB REF="00000373.tif" N="325"></L>
<L N="80">Wide and longue heo &yogh;eode a-boute : and heore bodies sou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo ne mi&yogh;te heom finde : heo &yogh;al and weop ful sore,</L>
<L>heo drov&yogh; of hire tressene and caste a-wei : for heo ne hopede to heom nonmore,</L>
<L>hire hondene heo wrong and to-gnov&yogh; : &thorn;at flesch, ri&yogh;t to &thorn;e bone,</L>
<L N="84">And al-to-gnov&yogh; &thorn;e senewes : and made ful sori mone.</L>
<L>heo orn ase heo witles were : a-boute in-to al &thorn;e londe.</L>
<L>Wimmen<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. wumnen</NOTE> hadden of hire gret rev&thorn;e : &thorn;at heo to<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE>-gnov so hire honde,</L>
<L>And fondeden &yogh;eorne to conforti hire : ake huy alle ne mi&yogh;ten make</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;at heo wolde into hire heorte : ani gladnesse take.</L>
<L>Into a wommanes hous heo cam : &thorn;at longue was bedrede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at gret rev&thorn;e hadde &thorn;o heo i-heorde : hire so weope and grede :</L>
<L N="91">heo confortede hire, &yogh;wat so heo mi&yogh;te : and made hire bi-leue</L>
<L>with hire aldai, with glad semblaunt : for-to it was nei&yogh; eue.</L>
<L>So heo confortede &thorn;is guode wijf : &thorn;at heo bi-lefte &thorn;are at<NOTE PLACE="marg1">at superscr.</NOTE> Inne,</L>
<L>Mid<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. And, <I>al.</I> And mid</NOTE> weorke of hire hondene : hire liflode for<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> gan</NOTE>-to winne,</L>
<L>With spinningue and with sevwyngue : &thorn;at heo wel cou&thorn;e do;</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;are-with heo fedde hire swi&thorn;e wel : and hire ostesse al-so.</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;are-after &thorn;e senewes : of hire hondene bi-gonne to schrinke,</L>
<L>For heo heom hadde er so for-gnawe&mdash; : &thorn;at heo ne mi&yogh;te non-more swinke;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo ne mi&yogh;te i-welde : no&thorn;ur Arm ne honde</L>
<L N="100">to pulte enes mete to hire mouth : ase hit was godes sonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;at deol &thorn;at heo made [&thorn;o] : no tongue it telle may.</L>
<L>"Alas," heo seide, "&thorn;us longue i-leoued : and &thorn;at ich euere a-bod &thorn;is day!</L>
<L>For more sorewe &thorn;ane me is on : neuere womman ne hadde.</L>
<L N="104">&THORN;e Ioye of mi louerd furst i for-les : for sunne &thorn;at ich dradde,</L>
<L>And bi-lefde clement mi &yogh;ongue : &thorn;at me was so leof, i-wis;</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e les mine tweie sones in &thorn;e se : &thorn;at weren al mi blis;</L>
<L>And al one fram mine freond : &thorn;us feor in one-cou&thorn;e londe</L>
<L N="108">Mit deol and soruwe ich habbe i-leoued : &thorn;oru&yogh; swunch of mine honde :</L>
<L>Nov&thorn;e mine hondene me beoth bi-nome : &thorn;at I-ne may heom enes wawe.</L>
<L>Alas, &thorn;us longue in care i-leoued : &thorn;at i-nere i-brou&yogh;t of lijf-dawe!"
<PB REF="00000374.tif" N="326"></L>
<L>&THORN;at deol &thorn;at heo made : rev&thorn;e it was to telle;</L>
<L N="112">Ofte heo was ope &thorn;e pointe : hire-sulf for-to a-quelle.</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="142b" UNIT="folio">Fram dore to dore hire mete heo bad : and with &thorn;at he mi&yogh;te I-winne,</L>
<L>heo fedde hire-sulf and hire hostesse : &yogh;wane heo cam to hire Inne.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HIre louerd athom aftur hire : of-longet was wel sore,</L>
<L N="116">And sente men to sechen hire : ake huy ne comen a-&yogh;ein nonmore.</L>
<L>O&thorn;ere he sente into al &thorn;at lond : and &thorn;o huy hadden longue i-sou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>huy comen a-&yogh;ein and tolden him : &thorn;at huy ne mi&yogh;ten hire finde nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;o gan he Clement, is &yogh;ongue sone : In-to guode warde take,</L>
<L N="120">And wend him-sulf into al &thorn;at lond : forto sechen is make.</L>
<L>he ne cam neuer-eft hom a-&yogh;ein&mdash; : wel wide he hire sou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And &yogh;eode a-boute and bad is mete : &thorn;at of is lijf he ne rou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&para; Twenti &yogh;er he bad is mete : and is wijf &yogh;eot wel mo.</L>
<L>he ful into feblesse of elde : &thorn;at vnne&thorn;e he mi&yogh;te go.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 2 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
<L N="125">Seint clement, &thorn;is &yogh;ongue child : to clergie was i-do;</L>
<L>he i-werth sone a gret clerk : quoynte and guod al-so.</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; his clergie him &thorn;ou&yogh;te : &thorn;at heore lawe nas nau&yogh;t:</L>
<L>he wilnede muche to wyten of god : &yogh;if ani man him hadde i-tau&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="129">HIt bi-feol &thorn;at seint Barnabe : Into Rome cam,</L>
<L>And clement hyne heorde a day : prechi of cristinedom:</L>
<L>So &thorn;at of &thorn;is holie Apostle : he lette him cristni a-non,</L>
<L N="132">And bi-cam &thorn;e beste prechur : &thorn;at mi&yogh;te on eor&thorn;e gon.</L>
<L>he heorde telle of seint peter : &thorn;at In &thorn;e londe of Iudee was:</L>
<L>Are he to him were I-come : glad ne bli&thorn;e he nas:</L>
<L>he bi-cam is o desciple : and a-boute with him wende</L>
<L N="136">For-to prechie cristine-dom : &thorn;oru&yogh; wit &thorn;at god him sende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Symon Magus, &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere Man : &yogh;eode in Ane o&thorn;ur londe,</L>
<L>To prechi a&yogh;ein Cristinedom : &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e deoueles sonde.</L>
<L>Tweie desciples he hadde with him : &thorn;at, &thorn;o huy onder-&yogh;ete</L>
<L N="140">&THORN;e falshede &thorn;at with him was : huy gonne him sone for-lete;</L>
<L>To seint peter huy wenden a-non : and his desciples bi-come.</L>
<L>glad was seint peter of heom : and &thorn;onkede god i-lome.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Clement tolde a day : to seint peter wel stille</L>
<L N="144">hov hit of is freond bi-feol : as it was godes wille,</L>
<L>And al-hov is Moder &yogh;eode a-wei : with is bre&thorn;ren tweie,
<PB REF="00000375.tif" N="327"></L>
<L>&THORN;at he wende &thorn;at huy a-dronke weren : o&thorn;ur i-storue bi &thorn;e weie,</L>
<L>And hov is fader wende to sechen heom : &thorn;o he ne sai&yogh; o&thorn;ur red;</L>
<L N="148">And [he]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> wende &thorn;at he were a-dreint : o&thorn;ur for deole ded;</L>
<L>And hov frendles he was op i-brou&yogh;t : Into<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &amp; to</NOTE> swyche lore.</L>
<L>&THORN;o seint peter i-heorde &thorn;is : he gan to weope sore.&mdash;</L>
<L>Ase seint petur &yogh;eode a dai : prechinde ouer lond,</L>
<L N="152">Ane womman, &thorn;at him &thorn;ou&yogh;te gent and freo : In grete miseise he fond,</L>
<L>&YOGH;ware heo &yogh;eode and bad hire mete. : he Axede hire a-non</L>
<L>&YOGH;wy heo ne mi&yogh;te hire mete I-winne : and &yogh;wy heo wolde so gon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Is womman seide, "swuch day was : Ich cou&thorn;e minne mete I|winne,</L>
<L N="156">Ake nou&thorn;e mine hondene me beoth bi-nome : &thorn;at Ine may sevwy ne spinne.</L>
<L>More sor<SUP>e</SUP>we &thorn;ane me is on : neuere nas i-founde;</L>
<L>Alas &thorn;at ich nadde me a-dreint : a-wei, &thorn;at ilke stounde!"<MILESTONE N="143" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; "Womman," seide seint peter &thorn;o : "folliche &thorn;ov dest telle:</L>
<L>For &thorn;e Man &thorn;at him-seolfue a-slowe : his soule scholde into helle."</L>
<L>"Sire," heo seide, "wuste ich &thorn;e so&thorn;e : &thorn;at soulene libbe scholde</L>
<L>After &thorn;usse liue, I-nolde bi-leue : &thorn;at me-seolf a-quelle i-nolde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Ich mi&yogh;te one stounde : mine sones i-seo;</L>
<L N="164">I-ne rou&yogh;te seth&thorn;e, &thorn;ei ich scholde : euer-eft in helle beo.</L>
<L>For mi louerd and mi<NOTE PLACE="marg1">overlined.</NOTE> &yogh;ongore sone : ich<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;at ich</NOTE> bi-lefte at rome</L>
<L>And wende forth with mine tweie sones : ake &thorn;o we in &thorn;e se come,</L>
<L>&THORN;at schip brak, and mine leoue sones : ne mi&yogh;ten neuereft beo i|founde;</L>
<L N="168">Ake me heo caste to londe al quik : allas &thorn;ulke stounde!</L>
<L>Ine mai for feblesse wende a-&yogh;ein : ne Ine habbe no man &thorn;at me lede,</L>
<L>And not &yogh;we&thorn;er mi louerd and mi &yogh;ongue sone : beon quike o&thorn;ur dede."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Clement," seide seint peter : "&thorn;at min o desciple nou&thorn;e is,</L>
<L>Seith &thorn;at is fader and is moder : &thorn;is cas bi-feollen,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> bifel</NOTE> i-wis."</L>
<L>&THORN;is womman feol a-don i-swowe : &thorn;o heo i-heorde &thorn;is.</L>
<L N="174">&THORN;o heo a-ros, heo cride &yogh;eorne : and weop for Ioie and blis,</L>
<L>And seide, "sire, &thorn;at is mi sone. : tech me &yogh;ware he beo!</L>
<L>Ine wilne mi lijf no leng to habbe : bote &thorn;at ich him enes i-seo."
<PB REF="00000376.tif" N="328"></L>
<L>Seint peter seide, "cum forth with me : to him ichulle &thorn;e lede.</L>
<L N="178">Ake ne beo &thorn;ov nou&yogh;t a-knowe to him : erore &thorn;ane ich &thorn;e rede."</L>
<L>he nam &thorn;is wommane bi &thorn;e hond : and to hire sone hire brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&THORN;o seint Clement i-sai&yogh; him lede ane womman : vuel bi him he &thorn;ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And seide, "nou&thorn;e In &thorn;ine olde liue : wolt&thorn;ou with wommane beo?"</L>
<L N="182">So wroth he was &thorn;at vnne&thorn;e he wolde : toward him bi-seo.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is guode wijf stod bi hire sone : heo ne mi&yogh;te for-bere non-more,</L>
<L>heo bi-cluppte him faste and custe a-non : for Ioye heo weop ful sore.</L>
<L>hire hondene &thorn;at hire weren bi-nome : anon-ri&yogh;t hole huy were,</L>
<L N="186">For Ioye, and for grete vertue : of &thorn;e holie men &thorn;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Clement was wroth with hire : for heo bi-clupte him and custe,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. clupte</NOTE></L>
<L>And in grete wrath&thorn;e hire pulte a-wei : and to &thorn;e grounde upri&yogh;t &thorn;ruste.</L>
<L>"Clement," seide seint peter &thorn;o : "darst&thorn;ov &thorn;ine moder pulte?</L>
<L N="190">&THORN;ov cri hire Merci and lat &thorn;e schriue : for &thorn;ine foule gulte!"</L>
<L>"Louerd," seide seint cleme[n]t [&thorn;o] : "&yogh;we&thorn;ur &thorn;is mi moder beo?</L>
<L>Louerd, i-hered beo &thorn;i mi&yogh;te : &thorn;at ich moste &thorn;is day i-seo!"</L>
<L>To is moder he ful a-doun : and bi-clupte hire and custe.</L>
<L N="194">Welle, &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;at &thorn;are was : &thorn;o ei&thorn;ur of o&thorn;ur wuste!</L>
<L>&THORN;is wyf seide, "leoue sone, &thorn;in ore : &yogh;we&thorn;ur &thorn;i fader a-liue beo?"</L>
<L>"Certes, moder," he seide, "i-not : Ine wene neuer-eft him i-seo.</L>
<L N="197">Twenti &yogh;er it is ago : &thorn;at he After &thorn;e i-wende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuer-eft Ine heorde word of him : ne he ne cam ne sende."</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode wyf bi-gan to weope sore : ake natheles for blisse</L>
<L>Of hire sone &thorn;at heo hadde I-founde : hire seoruwe heo gan to lisse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="201">Euere stoden bi seint peter : his o&thorn;ere desciples tweie</L>
<L>&THORN;at fram symon Magus weren i-come to him : and &yogh;eorne bi|heolden beie;</L>
<L>huy i-heorden hou &thorn;is guode wyf tolde : to clemente, hire sone, &thorn;ere,<MILESTONE N="143b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="204">hov hire tweie leoue sones : in &thorn;e se a-dreinte were.</L>
<L>&THORN;o huy hadden &thorn;is tale i-heord : huy weren swi&thorn;e glad,</L>
<L>For Ioye huy stoden ase &thorn;ei huy weren : witlese o&thorn;ur<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig.and</NOTE> a-mad.
<PB REF="00000377.tif" N="329"></L>
<L>"louerd," huy seiden, "&yogh;we&thorn;er &thorn;is beo soth : &thorn;at we i-heorez nou&thorn;e telle,</L>
<L N="208">o&thorn;ur us &thorn;inchez ase in metingue : o&thorn;ur in manere of spelle?"</L>
<L>"hit is soth," seint peter seide : "o&thorn;ur me &thorn;inchez &yogh;e beoth wode."</L>
<L>huy nusten &yogh;we&thorn;ur to beon stille o&thorn;ur speke : bote ase gydie men huy stode.</L>
<L>&para; "Louerd," huy seiden, "here is ore Moder : &thorn;at a-dreint was ase we wende,</L>
<L N="212">I-hered he beo &thorn;at hire hath to liue i-brou&yogh;t : And &thorn;at hire to us sende!</L>
<L>And &thorn;is is Clement, ore &yogh;ongue bro&thorn;ur : &thorn;at longue hath i-beo ore fere;</L>
<L>Nuste we neuere er &yogh;wat he was : are &thorn;oru&yogh; godes grace nou&thorn;e here."</L>
<L>Louerd, &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;at &thorn;e[re] was : And &thorn;at manie Mi&yogh;ten i-seo,</L>
<L N="216">bi-twene &thorn;e guode wyf and hire sones : &thorn;e swete bre&thorn;ren &thorn;reo!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Is guode wyf axede hire tweye sones : hov huy to liue come.</L>
<L>"Dame," huy seiden, "ase god it wolde : a bord of &thorn;e schype we nome</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar-on we hienguen, and hit bar us forth : into &thorn;e se wel wide.</L>
<L>Marineres us token into heore schipe : ase we floten heom bi-side.</L>
<L N="221">Are huy us hadden to londe i-brou&yogh;t : huy nolden neuere a-fine.</L>
<L>To Ane holie wydewe huy solden us : &thorn;at hiet dame Iustine;</L>
<L>&THORN;at us lokede nesche I-nov&yogh; : as &thorn;ei we hire sones were,</L>
<L N="224">And, god &yogh;ielde it hire! of clergie : heo liet us sone lere.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at we beoth nou&thorn;e godes desciples : and with his Apostle here.</L>
<L>Ore bro&thorn;ur clement we knoweth nou&thorn;e furst : &thorn;at &yogh;are hath i-beon ore fere.</L>
<L>And nou&thorn;e we beoth here to-gadere come : we mowen i-seo godes mi&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="228">&THORN;at euere wole mannes &yogh;wyle &yogh;elde : &thorn;at seruez him with ri&yogh;te."</L>
<L>Ech man wot wel &thorn;at &thorn;is I-heorth : &thorn;ey we ne seggen it i-lome,</L>
<L>gret Ioye bi-twene heom alle was : &thorn;o huy to-gadere come.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;is guode wyf heom tolde of hire hostesse : &thorn;at Innede hire bi ny&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="232">&THORN;at heo was a guod womman and was bedrade : &yogh;if huy hire hele mi&yogh;ten.
<PB REF="00000378.tif" N="330"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint petre hire let fette : and &thorn;oru&yogh; ore louerdes grace</L>
<L>Made hire hol, bi-fore al &thorn;at folk : anon in &thorn;ulke place.&mdash;</L>
<L N="235">Ase seint petre prechede a day : he seide in his prechingue</L>
<L>&THORN;at, ho-so seruede ore louerd wel : scholde habbe guod endingue.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o stod &thorn;are op a swi&thorn;e old man : his lockes weren ful hore;</L>
<L>pouere and stoupinde and miseise. : he bi-gan to siken sore.</L>
<L>"gret rev&thorn;e," he seide, "ich habbe of eov : &thorn;at &yogh;e bi-trayez men so;</L>
<L N="240">Ech man bi-fallez ase his &yogh;wate is : &yogh;wat-so he euere do.</L>
<L>&para; For &thorn;ei a man swyncke and crie on god : and bidde &yogh;eorne is bede,</L>
<L>him schal bi-falle, guod o&thorn;ur vuel : ase it is him i-que&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei mani man beo wis and euere swynke : he ne may neuere bate;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei manie don vuele and euere folie : &yogh;eot he hath guod &yogh;wate."</L>
<L N="245">&para; Seint petre hiet &thorn;e &thorn;reo bre&thorn;ren : &thorn;at is desciples were,</L>
<L>Despuyti a&yogh;ein &thorn;is olde man : of &thorn;at he tolde &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>huy stoden and heore [r]esones<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. oresones</NOTE> seiden : &thorn;at ech man scholde a-fongue</L>
<L N="248">After &thorn;at he wurche wolde : And elles it were with wrongue;<MILESTONE N="144" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"For, ho-so nath no guod, ne swinke nele : ne of porueance beo,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wat-so-euere man beo Ique&thorn;e : he ne may it neuere fleo;<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. i-&thorn;eo</NOTE></L>
<L>And [ho]-so is wys to winne guod : and wel it witie can,</L>
<L N="252">&YOGH;wat-so-euere is &yogh;wate beo : he worth riche man.</L>
<L>For ore louerd wole here and elles-&yogh;ware : &yogh;elden ane mannes seruise</L>
<L>After &thorn;at he him-seolf wurche wole : ake aftur &yogh;wate in none wise."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>GRet clerk was &thorn;is olde Man : he desputede wel faste</L>
<L N="256">A-&yogh;ein &thorn;e &thorn;reo bre&thorn;ren with gret reson. : &thorn;at playt wel longue laste.</L>
<L>Seint Clement was grettest clerk : &thorn;are-fore at&thorn;enende</L>
<L>Maister he was, &thorn;oru&yogh; grace : &thorn;at ore louerd him wolde sende.</L>
<L>At&thorn;e laste &thorn;is olde Man : bi-gan to sike and grone,</L>
<L N="260">And seid[e], "wel, icholde i-leue : ower resones ech-one,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if I-ne hadde to muche i-fondet : of &thorn;inge &thorn;at geth bi &yogh;wate.</L>
<L N="262">Alas &thorn;ulke soruful tyme : for mi confort cometh to late!</L>
<L>Riche man ich was elles-&yogh;ware : &thorn;ei ich beo nou&thorn;e a wrechche here;</L>
<L>Ich hadde &thorn;reo &yogh;oungue children : and a guod wif &thorn;at was mi fere.</L>
<L>Mine tweie sones heo ladde awei : &thorn;o we heom hadden al bi-swonke :</L>
<L>Ine heorde neuereft word of heom : Ich wot huy beoth a-dronke.</L>
<L>Alle myne freond and al mi guod : Ich bi-lefte me bi-hynde
<PB REF="00000379.tif" N="331"></L>
<L N="268">And habbe here i-walke in onkov&thorn;e londe : &yogh;if ich heom mi&yogh;te i-fynde.</L>
<L>Mi &yogh;ongeste child ich bi-lefte athom : Ich wene &thorn;at he beo ded.</L>
<L>Worse &yogh;wate nadde neuere man : Inot &yogh;wat is mi red.</L>
<L>And ich am,<NOTE PLACE="marg">overlined.</NOTE>&thorn;are no man me ne knoweth : mid miseise ouer-come;</L>
<L N="272">honguer and chele hath myne leomes : and elde, me bi-nome.</L>
<L>Seggez ov-sulf &yogh;if &yogh;e euere I-heorden : Ani so deolful cas!</L>
<L>ho is &thorn;at ne may i-leue : &thorn;at lu&thorn;ur &yogh;wate it nas?"</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;is &thorn;reo bre&thorn;ren hore fader i-knewen : &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;at he hadde i-sed,</L>
<L>Sturten huy wolden and cussen him. : ake seint petre heom for-bed,</L>
<L N="277">And seide, "&yogh;if ich bringue bi-fore &thorn;e i-hole : &thorn;ine children and &thorn;i wijf,</L>
<L>Wolt&thorn;ov for-hote &thorn;ine mis-bi-leue : and a-mendi &thorn;i lijf</L>
<L>And i-leue &thorn;at &thorn;ing<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &thorn;ing &thorn;at</NOTE>comez ase god wole : and no-&thorn;ing after &yogh;wate?"</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e, sire," seide &thorn;is olde man : "Ake &thorn;at worth so wel late.</L>
<L>Also ase it neuere ne worth : &thorn;at ich i-seo heom alle,</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE>so ne worth hit neuere &thorn;at muche &thorn;ing : nele bi &yogh;wate falle."</L>
<L>&para; "Lo," seide seint petre &thorn;o : "&thorn;is beoth &thorn;ine sones &thorn;reo,</L>
<L N="284">&THORN;at, for-to bringue &thorn;e in godes lawe : plaidiez a&yogh;ein &thorn;e."</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is olde Man i-heorde &thorn;is : his limes him bere nolde,</L>
<L>huy nescheden ase doth wex a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e fuyre : And ful a-don on &thorn;e molde;</L>
<L>he lai al cold with-oute bre&thorn;e : ase &thorn;ei he no lyf nadde.</L>
<L N="288">his [sones] him clupten a[n]d custen him : sore huy weopen and gradde;</L>
<L>huy beren him a-boute and bleowen on him : &yogh;if huy him mi&yogh;ten in stat bringue.</L>
<L>Longue it was are heo mi&yogh;ten : i-seo of liue : Ani ri&yogh;t tokningue.</L>
<L>&THORN;o is stat him was i-come : he axede a-non-ri&yogh;t &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="292">hov huy weren a-liue forth i-brou&yogh;t : so freondlese ase huy were.</L>
<L>Euerech tolde in his wise : ore swete louerdes mi&yogh;te,<MILESTONE N="144b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at he on heom i-schewed hadde : ho-so onder-stode &thorn;e ri&yogh;te.</L>
<L N="295">Ase huy tolden of heore lijf : euerech in his side,</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode wif orn ase heo were wilde : and swi&thorn;e loude heo cride:</L>
<L>"&YOGH;ware is mi louerd? &yogh;ware is mi spouse? : schewez him me a-non!"</L>
<L>huy bi-clupten heom and fullen a-doun : a fote ne mi&yogh;ten huy gon.
<PB REF="00000380.tif" N="332"></L>
<L>More Ioye ne mi&yogh;te beo i-sei&yogh;e : bi none mannes liue,</L>
<L N="300">&THORN;ane was, &thorn;o huy to-gadere comen : a-mong heom alle fiue.</L>
<L>here we mouwen alle i-seo : ore swete louerdes mi&yogh;te,</L>
<L>&THORN;at euere at&thorn;enende he wole &yogh;elde : &thorn;e manne &thorn;at him seruez with ri&yogh;te.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="303">HIt bi-ful &thorn;at &thorn;e Aumperour : ouer-al sende is sonde,</L>
<L>Symon Magus, &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere man : to sechen him into al &thorn;e londe,</L>
<L>For-to sleen him, ho-so him mi&yogh;te I-finde : al for his lu&thorn;er-hede.</L>
<L>And &thorn;o symon Magus i-heorde &thorn;ar-of : he was in grete drede.</L>
<L>On feolonie he &thorn;ou&yogh;te for wrath&thorn;e : of &thorn;e bre&thorn;ren tweie,</L>
<L N="308">Faust and Faustin, &thorn;at weren with him : and departed fram him bei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>bi hore fader he cam a day : ase &thorn;e deuel him gan lere,</L>
<L>And caste on him is owene fourme : ase &thorn;ei it him-sulf were,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; is foul enchauntement&mdash; : ho-so &thorn;e<SUP>ne</SUP> olde manne i-sei&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="312">wenden &thorn;at symon magus it were. : &thorn;are was &thorn;e deuel to slei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e Ioye &thorn;at his sones hadden : of him &thorn;are in one stounde;</L>
<L>And for he schold<SUP>e</SUP> beon for him a-slawe : &yogh;if he mi&yogh;te beon i-founde.</L>
<L>For euere &thorn;e deuel, and alle his : of feolonie doth &thorn;enche;</L>
<L N="316">Ake at&thorn;e laste huy wor&thorn;eth bi-traid : with heore feolle wrenche.</L>
<L>&para; Symon Magus wende a-wei<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. a&yogh;en</NOTE> : &thorn;o al &thorn;is i-don was.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode [man] &yogh;eode forth to is children : he nuste nou&yogh;t of &thorn;at cas :</L>
<L>he cam and wolde gret Ioye make : with heom and with is wiue.</L>
<L>huy spatten on him, euerechone : and heten him a-wei wel bliue,</L>
<L N="321">For he was &thorn;e deueles lyme : huy nolden nou&yogh;t with him dele,</L>
<L>Ake bote he &thorn;e sonere fram heom &yogh;eode : him to wro&thorn;er hele.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>" Alas," seide &thorn;is olde Man : "Mine leoue<NOTE PLACE="marg1">overlined.</NOTE> children &thorn;reo,</L>
<L N="324">&YOGH;wi wolle &yogh;e ouwer fader &thorn;us pulte and bete? : nelle &yogh;e me nonmore i-seo?"</L>
<L>"Nay," seiden &thorn;is bre&thorn;ren &thorn;reo : "&thorn;ov nart ore fader nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;ov art symon Magus, godes trichor. : to de&thorn;e &thorn;ov worst i-brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;e Aumperores [men] &thorn;e mouwen finde : &thorn;at wide &thorn;e habbez i-sou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="328">&THORN;ov worst to-drawe ase &thorn;e deueles lime : for falshede &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast i|wrou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>&para; "Louerd, merci," seide &thorn;is olde man : "&yogh;wodere may ich nou&thorn;e iwende,
<PB REF="00000381.tif" N="333"></L>
<L>Nou&thorn;e mi wijf ne mine sones me nellez i-knowe : o dai to &thorn;enende?</L>
<L>Mest wrechche ich am of alle men : nou&thorn;e Ine habbe freond non</L>
<L>bote heom, and huy me wollez a-sle. : &yogh;wodere may ich nou&thorn;e gon?"</L>
<L>&para; Symon Magus &thorn;are-at-fore : in Auntioche ase<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> he wende,</L>
<L>And seint petre bi-fore al &thorn;at folk : with lesingues foule he schende;</L>
<L>he seide &thorn;at he man-quellare was : and wichche, and eke for-swore :</L>
<L N="336">&THORN;at folk a-waytede him for-to sle : In Auntyoche &thorn;are-fore.</L>
<L>&para; Seint petre &thorn;is onder-&yogh;at : he wolde beon a-wreke, he &thorn;ou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>he cam to &thorn;is seli oldeman : &thorn;at him wel longue sou&yogh;te;<MILESTONE N="145" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"beo stille," he seide, "and do Aftur me : and soffre a luytel &thorn;rowe,</L>
<L N="340">And Ichulle makien &thorn;at &thorn;i wijf : and &thorn;ine sones : &thorn;e schullen sone i-knowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;ov schalt gon In-to Auntioche : &thorn;are symon Magus was,</L>
<L>Ase he me desclaundret hath : and segge of &thorn;is ilke cas</L>
<L>In his name, ase ech man weneth : &thorn;at &thorn;ov he him-sulue beo,</L>
<L N="344">And segge &thorn;at hit lesingue is : &thorn;at &thorn;ov seidest op-on me,</L>
<L>And line al-so &thorn;ine owene Mouth : as &thorn;ei it beo in his name,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at hit was al les &thorn;at &thorn;ov seidest : to bringue me in lu&thorn;er fame,</L>
<L N="347">And &thorn;at &thorn;ov art &thorn;arof repentaunt : sori, and swi&thorn;e wel I-schriue,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e lesingue &thorn;at &thorn;ov bi me seidest : and bide heom it &thorn;e for-&yogh;yue."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;Is olde Man &yogh;eode him forth : In-to Auntioche a-non,</L>
<L>And &yogh;ede a-boute to Mani a stude : &thorn;are symon hadde I-gon;</L>
<L>"Guode Men," he seide, "&yogh;if ich habbe i-told : bi seint petre eni|&thorn;ing</L>
<L N="352">bote guod and gret trewenesse : for-so&thorn;e, it is lesing;</L>
<L>here bi-foren eov euerech-one : ich lixni minne owene Mouth.</L>
<L>For he is treowe and studefast : and is guodnesse is wide couth.</L>
<L>For-to saui al &thorn;at lond : ore louerd him hath i-sent :</L>
<L N="356">bi-lieueth and wurcheth aftur him : o&thorn;ur &yogh;e beoth alle I-schent!</L>
<L>For &yogh;e eov-seolf and Al eower guod : &thorn;oru&yogh; ore louerdes wreche</L>
<L>hit schal for-fare, bote &yogh;e don : ase he eov wole lere ant teche.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ich euere-eft more am so : in &thorn;e deoueles weorke I-brou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="360">&THORN;at Ich ani-&thorn;ing o&thorn;ur bi him segge : ne leuez me &thorn;ar-of nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ake doth me<NOTE PLACE="marg1">overlined.</NOTE> schame and betez me : ant bringuez me of dawe,</L>
<L>Ase men schullen a strong liare : and man of false lawe."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;are-Aftur-ward he cam to seint petre : and he is leomen ri&yogh;te
<PB REF="00000382.tif" N="334"></L>
<L>And brou&yogh;te him a-&yogh;ein to is owene fourme : al &thorn;oru&yogh; godes mi&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&THORN;o was &thorn;ere gret Ioye bi-tweone [is sones]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> : and him and eke is wiue,</L>
<L>&thorn;o huy weren in ri&yogh;te fourme : to-gadere alle fiue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="367">Euere is strengore ore swete louerd : &thorn;ane &thorn;e deuel at&thorn;ende!</L>
<L>And symon Magus-is tricherie : op-on him-sulf it gan i-wiende.</L>
<L>Al<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> for</NOTE> Auntioche wel gret loue : opon seint petre caste,</L>
<L>And sore heom longuede after him : and leten him seche faste.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Petre cam to Auntioche : ase he hadde er I-lome :</L>
<L N="372">Men and wommen of &thorn;e lond : wel glade a-boute him come,</L>
<L>And Anoureden him suy&thorn;e muche : ase ane prince of godes lawe</L>
<L>And Ase heore maister and heore louerd&mdash; : huy weren of him wel fawe;</L>
<L>In riche chayre huy setten him : and knevlede him bi-fore,</L>
<L N="376">And beden wel &yogh;eorne him wardi heom : and techen, &thorn;at heore soulene neren for-lore.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is was a-seint petres day : &thorn;at comez in feuerer,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for &thorn;e honour of &thorn;ulke dede : men helewiez feor and ner.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is dede was al I-don : and seint petre &thorn;annes i-wend,</L>
<L N="380">Symon Magus hyede &thorn;udere : and heold him foule I-schend.</L>
<L>bi-fore al &thorn;is folk he cam : "Muche wonder me &thorn;inchez," he sede,</L>
<L>"&THORN;at ich ouwer soule-bote here-bi-fore : and to eouwer guod gan eov rede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e ne flouwen petre, &thorn;ane trichour : &thorn;at he a-mong eov ne come;<MILESTONE N="145b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And nou&yogh;t one ne<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &yogh;e</NOTE> Anoreden him : ake wit grete nobleie him nome</L>
<L>And an hei&yogh; in chaire<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. in chaire In chaire</NOTE> setten him : ase he eouwer crist were.</L>
<L>Fleoth fram him, &yogh;if &yogh;e wollez i-sauede beon : and doth ase ich eov lere!"</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o al &thorn;at folk i-heorde &thorn;is : for wrath&thorn;e heo weren nei&yogh; wode;</L>
<L N="388">"False trichour," huy seiden, "&thorn;is o&thorn;ur day : bi-fore us here &thorn;ov stode</L>
<L>And seidest &thorn;at he was treowe and guod : and &thorn;at we after him do scholde,</L>
<L>And seist nou&thorn;e &thorn;at he is lu&thorn;er and fals! : &thorn;i &yogh;wile worth sone i-&yogh;olde,"</L>
<L>huy sturten forth and beoten &thorn;is foule &thorn;eof : &thorn;at he was nei&yogh; a-slawe;
<PB REF="00000383.tif" N="335"></L>
<L N="392">Nadde he &thorn;e revlocur i-cried on heom : hey<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. huy</NOTE> wolden him habbe to-drawe.</L>
<L>Ase he mi&yogh;te, he crep a-wei : with many a lu&thorn;ur strok.</L>
<L>&THORN;are he him-seolf, ase euerech swyke doth : him-seolf he bi-swok!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seint petre &yogh;eode to rome : with his desciple &thorn;reo.</L>
<L N="396">he wuste &thorn;at is tyme was nei&yogh; : &thorn;at he Imartred scholde beo :</L>
<L>Seint Clement al bi is daye : he made him pope at rome,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he guode &yogh;eme after him : to holie churche nome.</L>
<L N="399">&para; &THORN;o seint petre I-martred was : seint clement him bi-sou&yogh;te :<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> bi&thorn;ou&yogh;te vv. 401-4 are corrupted.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;if he bi-lefte pope forth : ase &thorn;at folk him bi-sou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> pope ne<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> mi&yogh;te aftur him : Ane o&thorn;urne pope make,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wam so huy wolden, &thorn;oru&yogh; heore wille : o&thorn;ur for<NOTE PLACE="marg1">on the margin.</NOTE> eni mede take;</L>
<L>&THORN;at he him bad for godes loue : &thorn;at no pope bi is daye</L>
<L N="404">Non o&thorn;ur pope ne scholde maken so : holie churche to bi-traye;<NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 403-4 added.</NOTE></L>
<L>For a wardein of holie churche : &thorn;oru&yogh; is godnesse man schal take,</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.; r. and?</NOTE> nou&yogh;t, ase it were bi heritage : &thorn;at o freond &thorn;at o&thorn;ur make.</L>
<L>he tok up is dignete : for al &thorn;at man him bad,</L>
<L>And seint lyn, &thorn;at was a guod man : was pope in his stude Imad.</L>
<L N="409">After seint lynes daye : alle &thorn;e men wolde</L>
<L>Seint clemente habbe pope Imad : ake for no-&thorn;ing &yogh;eot he nolde;</L>
<L>Se[int]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. Se</NOTE> Clete huy maden pope &thorn;o. : ake after is dai&yogh;e a-non</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk heold seint clement faste : huy nolden him nou&yogh;t for-gon;</L>
<L><SUP>h</SUP>Alflingue with strenc&thorn;e huy maden him pope. : and &thorn;o hit cam &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L N="414">he fondede to paye euer-ech Man : riche and pouere al-so.</L>
<L>he honourede more &thorn;e pouere Men : &thorn;ane he dude &thorn;e riche,</L>
<L>to helpe more is<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;e</NOTE> soule &thorn;ane is<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;e</NOTE> bodi&mdash; : for huy ne beot nou&yogh;t Iliche.</L>
<L>Sisyme, &thorn;e Iustise of &thorn;e lond : hadde a swi&thorn;e guod wijf,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;oru&yogh; se[int] cleme[n]t I-cristned was : for-to amendi hire lijf.</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane heo mi&yogh;te, fram hire louerd [heo stole] : al with-oute fiere.</L>
<L N="420">A day, ase<NOTE PLACE="marg1">on the margin.</NOTE> heo wolde to churche gon : he siwede hire wel swi&thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">2 vv. om.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sone so heo to churche cam : and hire hovse-bonde onder-&yogh;at,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. it onder-&yogh;at</NOTE></L>
<L>A-drad heo was, and hudde hire : in one [derne] stude heo sat.</L>
<L N="423">&THORN;o seint clement seide is oresun : and is clerkes amen seide,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iustise i-werth bo&thorn;e def and blind. : wel loude he gan to grede :</L>
<L>"&YOGH;ware beo &yogh;e nou&thorn;e, mine men? : ovt &yogh;e moten me lede,</L>
<L>For Ine mai mi-seolf I-seo ne heore. : &yogh;wat mai ich to-rede?
<PB REF="00000384.tif" N="336"></L>
<L>cometh forth to me euerechone : and out heonnes &yogh;e me leden!"<NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 426-7 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L N="428">his Men sturten forth And nomen him op : huy swatten alle for drede.<MILESTONE N="146" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>huy beren him al-a-boute &thorn;e churche : huy ne mi&yogh;ten &thorn;e dore finde :</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane huy wenden at&thorn;e dore to beo : &thorn;anne weren huy feor bi-hinde.</L>
<L N="431">Sore was &thorn;is guode wijf a-drad : &thorn;o heo i-sai&yogh; heom so fare :</L>
<L>heo Axede &yogh;wat hire louerd were&mdash; : for no leng ne mi&yogh;te heo spare.</L>
<L>huy seiden, "for he wolde<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. huy wolden</NOTE> I-seon and I-heore : o&thorn;ur &thorn;ane to him bi-come,</L>
<L>bi-come he is blijnd and def : here in &thorn;e churche of Rome."</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode wijf bad ore louerd &yogh;eorne : &thorn;at huy mosten &thorn;annes ovt wende :</L>
<L N="436">&THORN;o founden &thorn;is men &thorn;e dore a-non : and wenden out at&thorn;enende.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode wijf bad Clement &yogh;eorne : to hire louerd come</L>
<L>And amendi him &thorn;oru&yogh; godes grace : of is limes, &thorn;at him weren bi-nome.</L>
<L>&para; Seint clement and &thorn;is guode wijf to &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere man gonne teo :</L>
<L N="440">huy founden him loki swi&thorn;e brode : and no-&thorn;ing ne mi&yogh;te i-seo.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 439-40 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seint clement bad ore louerd for him : and &thorn;o he i-don hadde,</L>
<L>his heoringue and is si&yogh;t him cam a-&yogh;ein. : ake neuere &thorn;onk he ne hadde.</L>
<L>For a-non so he i-sai&yogh; seint clement stonde : bi is wiue, he wende</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;at he hadde bi hire i-leie : and &thorn;are-fore he him a-blende.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode wijf &yogh;eode into hire preuetez : and Iesu crist [bad] wel faste</L>
<L N="446">&THORN;at hire louerd &thorn;oru&yogh; is grace : in-to betere bi-leue him caste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint petre fram heouene : to hire a-li&yogh;te a-doun</L>
<L>And s[e]ide, hire louerd scholde i-saued beo : &thorn;oru&yogh; hire oresun;</L>
<L N="449">"For seint powel seide <NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. seide seide; <I>al.</I> For me sai&thorn;</NOTE> &thorn;at a lu&thorn;er man : scholde i-saued beo</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; guodnesse of a godwomman : And so it worth bi him and &thorn;e."</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode wyf eode to hire louerd : and prechede him of cristine-dom :</L>
<L N="452">So &thorn;at he &thorn;oru&yogh; godes grace : in-to guode bi-leue he com.</L>
<L>he liet him cristni sone a-non : and al is may[n]e &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&THORN;re hondret men and tweolue : with him i-cristnede were.</L>
<L>&para; TraIan, &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere Amperour : herof he heorde speke :</L>
<L N="456">he swor he wolde for his Iustise : of seint clement beo a-wreke.
<PB REF="00000385.tif" N="337"></L>
<L>he comaundede Mamertyn : &thorn;at was an o&thorn;ur Iustise,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he scholde maken clement &thorn;e pope : to don heom<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> sacrefise</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur maken him out of londe fleme&mdash; : &thorn;at he ne lete it nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="460">Laste heore lawe and heore godes weren : &thorn;oru&yogh; him to grounde i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is Iustise wende &thorn;o wi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;ou&yogh;</NOTE> gret power : And seint clement he nom;<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. nam</NOTE></L>
<L>And for he nolde don heore godes<NOTE PLACE="marg1">h. g. <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> sacrefise : he &yogh;af him an o&thorn;ur dom :</L>
<L>&THORN;at he scholde beon out of londe i-driue : into wildernesse.</L>
<L N="464">Ase a &thorn;eof he was i-harlet forth : in wel fyl destresse.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he into wildernesse cam : to &thorn;ousende he fond &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Of cristine Men, &thorn;at hadden &thorn;er : longue i-woned for fere,</L>
<L>Laste &thorn;e Aumperoures men : In torment heom hadden i-brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="468">And huy for drede of strongue de&thorn;e : weren in feble &thorn;ou&yogh;t.&mdash;</L>
<L>For manie men bi &thorn;ulke daie : for drede of &thorn;ulke &thorn;ingue</L>
<L N="470">Ase bestes huy leoueden in wildernesse : &thorn;o cristinedom bi-gan furst springue.&mdash;</L>
<L>Wel glade weren &thorn;is guode men : &thorn;o huy seint clement i-sei&yogh;e :</L>
<L>heo &yogh;eoden a-&yogh;ein him and &thorn;onkeden god : weopinde with heore eie.</L>
<L>huy maden seint clement heore Maister &thorn;ere : pope ase he was.<MILESTONE N="146b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;are nas non &thorn;at in studefast lijf : for him a-mendet ne was.</L>
<L>Water huy nadden nei&yogh; heom non : bi six Mile wei wel longue,</L>
<L N="476">Al heore drinke huy fetten &thorn;are : in wei&yogh;e swi&thorn;e stronge.</L>
<L>Seint clement [bad] ore louerd crist : &yogh;if hit is wille were,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he holpe is trewe couent : and sende heom watur &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>he i-sai&yogh; a lomb stonde and marki : with is ri&yogh;t fot ane stude :</L>
<L N="480">he i-sai&yogh; &thorn;at hit ore louerd was : to don &thorn;at he hadde i-bede.</L>
<L>&para; Seint clement &yogh;eode and smot in &thorn;ulke stude : as &thorn;at lomb markede er :</L>
<L>&THORN;are sprong a welle fair and guod&mdash; : wel gret Ioye was &thorn;er.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Miracle was widen i-cud : fif hondret men &thorn;are-fore</L>
<L N="484">bi-comen cristine and blesseden &thorn;e time : &thorn;at seint clement was i-bore.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &yogh;ede he for&thorn;ere a-mong &thorn;e men : and so fair Miracle wrou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e muche folk to guode bi-leue : and to Iesu crist he brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Fyf hondred of Maumates : to grounde he brou&yogh;te &thorn;ere;</L>
<L N="488">And sixti churche and fiftene : in heore studes he liet a-rere.
<PB REF="00000386.tif" N="338"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So &thorn;at traIan &thorn;e Aumperour : her-of heorde telle :</L>
<L N="490">Ane duyk of gret power he sende &thorn;udere : &thorn;ane guode man for|to quelle.</L>
<L>&THORN;is duyk him nam and liet to<NOTE PLACE="marg1">overlined.</NOTE> him binde : grete<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. and gr.</NOTE> stones wel faste,</L>
<L>And ladden him feor in-to &thorn;e deope se : and ri&yogh;t a-midde him caste.</L>
<L>Welle, muche was &thorn;e deol : &thorn;at is desciples for him made!</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e se huy ornen to sechen him : ase feor ase huy dorsten wade.</L>
<L>&THORN;o huy ne mi&yogh;ten nei&yogh; him come : ore louerd wel &yogh;eorne huy beade<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. bade</NOTE></L>
<L N="496">to &yogh;iuen heom a si&yogh;t of seint clement : &thorn;e more to beon glade.</L>
<L>Ase huy seten opon &thorn;e .se : and crieden on him wel faste and &yogh;eorne,</L>
<L>&THORN;e .se. wel swiftliche hire with-drav&yogh;<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> wi&thorn;drou&yogh;</NOTE> : and with gret eyr In gan eorne :</L>
<L>So &thorn;at with-inne &thorn;e deope .se : &thorn;reo grete Milene and more</L>
<L N="500">A swi&thorn;e fair wei and druye &thorn;are was : i-here[d] beo godes ore!</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode men bi &thorn;is faire wei : In-to &thorn;e .se. gonne to wende :</L>
<L>Ane churche hui founden, of Marbre i-maud : ri&yogh;t at&thorn;e weies ende.</L>
<L>With-Inne &thorn;e churche huy founden ane cofre : of seluer and of golde</L>
<L N="504">And &thorn;arinne seint clementes bodi : ase ore louer[d] it wolde.</L>
<L>Welle, louerd, muche was &thorn;e Ioye : &thorn;at &thorn;is guode Men inne were,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e faire Miracle of seint clement : &thorn;at huy founden &thorn;ere!</L>
<L>huy beden heore beden &yogh;wat-so huy wolden : and wenden a&yogh;en at|&thorn;enende :</L>
<L N="508">euere orn &thorn;e se after heom wel faste : at heore helene bi-hinde,</L>
<L>For-to heo cam to hire ri&yogh;te stude : and &thorn;are heo gan atstonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode men serueden god &thorn;e bet : and &thorn;onke[den] &yogh;eorne is sonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Longue &thorn;er-aftur it bi-feol : &thorn;oru&yogh; ore louerdes heste,</L>
<L N="512">fram &yogh;er to &yogh;ere seue dawes : at seint clementes festes</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e se ire wolde so with-drawe : and makie ane wei wel druye</L>
<L>To &thorn;e holie chapele of seint clement : &thorn;at no watur ne scholde man a-nuye;</L>
<L>&THORN;at ech Man alle &thorn;e seuen dawes : al druye wende and clene,</L>
<L N="516">For-to honouri &thorn;at holie bodi : ase it bi-feol eche &yogh;ere ene;</L>
<L>And Anon-ri&yogh;t &thorn;e se wende a-&yogh;ein : with watur and with slyme</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="147" UNIT="folio">After &thorn;e ei&yogh;te dawes, and heold him so : for-to an o&thorn;ur &yogh;er &thorn;at tyme.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Awommon cam<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. cam cam</NOTE> &thorn;udere at one tyme : and a child &thorn;at was hire sone,
<PB REF="00000387.tif" N="339"></L>
<L N="520">For-to A-novri &thorn;at swete bodi : as it was mannes wone.</L>
<L>hit feol at<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;at</NOTE> &thorn;e endingue : of &thorn;e seue&thorn;e dai&yogh;e</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e se cam eorne &amp; rotte &yogh;eorne : ase &thorn;at child a-slepe laye.</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk, &thorn;at &thorn;are was bi-leued : bi-gonne ateorne faste;</L>
<L N="524">&THORN;is womman louede hire lyf al-so : &thorn;at heo nas nou&yogh;t &thorn;e laste.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo was to londe i-come : and hire sone<NOTE PLACE="marg1">overlined.</NOTE> mid hire nadde,</L>
<L>Muche was &thorn;e deol &thorn;at heo made : loude heo weop and gradde.</L>
<L>gredinde heo orn and longue sou&yogh;te : a-boute bi &thorn;e se-side,</L>
<L N="528">&YOGH;if &thorn;e .se. him hadde up i-cast&mdash; : heo sou&yogh;te a-boute wel wide.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo ne mi&yogh;te him nou&yogh;were i-finde : weopinde hom heo wende,</L>
<L>And bad seint clement, of hire childe : &thorn;at he sum gladnesse hire sende.</L>
<L>heo bi-lefte al &thorn;e &yogh;er : in gret sor and in care.</L>
<L N="532">Ano&thorn;ur &yogh;er at seint clementes tid : &thorn;uder-ward heo wolde fare.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> was &yogh;are</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e chapele &yogh;eorne heo orn : &thorn;o &thorn;e se was In i-weved :<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. i-wend</NOTE></L>
<L><SUP>h</SUP>Ire<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. Ire; h added.</NOTE> sone heo fond in &thorn;ulke stude : &thorn;are heo hine hadde bi-leued.</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;is womman nam him up : and wende &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. heo</NOTE> ded were.</L>
<L N="536">&THORN;at child, ase &thorn;ei it woke of slepe : Axede &yogh;wat heo wolde &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;is womman for Ioie gradde loude : &thorn;at folk a-boute hire wende,</L>
<L>And &thorn;onkeden god with grete Ioye : &thorn;at swuche miracle him sende.</L>
<L>huy axeden hov he hadde so longue i-leued : And &yogh;if he were ou&yogh;t i-drei&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="540">"hit nis nov&yogh;t longue," &thorn;at child seide : "ake to sone &yogh;e me<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. me me</NOTE> habbez a-wei&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Softe and swote i habbe<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &yogh;e habbez</NOTE> i-slepe : onne&thorn;e me &thorn;inchez o ny&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Moste ich lengore habbe i-lei&yogh;e : me hadde i-beo wel i-di&yogh;t."</L>
<L>With gret Ioye huy ladden &thorn;is child hom. : &thorn;is miracle was couth wel wide.</L>
<L N="544">Mani fair Miracle sein<SUP>t</SUP> clement dude : bi &thorn;e sees sides.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e se with-drov&yogh; hire wel mani a &yogh;er : to maken men druye i-wende;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ulke miracle for mannes [sunne] : bi-lefde seth&thorn;e at&thorn;en ende.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Men founden &thorn;is holie &yogh;wuchche : In a fair place stonde</L>
<L N="548">with &thorn;is holie bodi a-boue &thorn;e se : al on druye londe;</L>
<L>Muche folk with fair procession : &thorn;is holie bodi nome</L>
<L>And ladden it forth with gret honour : to &thorn;e churche of rome.</L>
<L>&THORN;are is nou&thorn;e seint clementes churche : I-mad with quoynte gynne.
<PB REF="00000388.tif" N="340"></L>
<L N="552">god &yogh;iue us part of &thorn;ulke Ioy&yogh;e : &thorn;at seint clement is inne.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="48" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>48 [Laurence.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEynt laurence guod man was : and in strong Marty<SUP>r</SUP>dom</L>
<L>he endede here on eor&thorn;e is lijf : and to &thorn;e Ioye of heuene he com.</L>
<L>Decius &thorn;e Aumperour : &thorn;at lu&thorn;ur was i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L N="4">And is Iustise Valerian : &thorn;at to alle schrewe-hede drov&yogh;,</L>
<L>huy wenden and sou&yogh;ten cristine Men : and &yogh;wane huy enie founde,</L>
<L>huy pineden heom with gret torment : and brou&yogh;ten heom sone to grounde.</L>
<L>huy comen<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. comenen</NOTE> and founden &thorn;ene bischop sixte : and a-slowen him with gret wou&yogh;.</L>
<L N="8">Seint laurence was is Ercedeckne : &thorn;at guod man was i-nov&yogh;.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;o &thorn;e bischop scholde beon i-nome : and he &thorn;at cas i-sei&yogh;,</L>
<L>Seint laurence, is Ercedekne : he cleopede, &thorn;at was him nei&yogh; :</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at tresor of holie churche : &thorn;at he to-gadere drov&yogh;<MILESTONE N="147b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="12">Seint laurence he it bi-tok : to witien it wel i-nov&yogh;.</L>
<L>&thorn;e tormentores, &thorn;at &thorn;is i-sei&yogh;en : heom bo&thorn;e huy nome faste,</L>
<L>Seint sixte and seint laurence : and strongue biendes on heom caste.</L>
<L>huy ladden seint sixte to heore false godes : and is tweie felawes al-so,</L>
<L N="16">And scheweden heom heore false hymages : and beden heom a-loute &thorn;ar-to;</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is guode men nolden don so : ake on ore louerd huy crieden faste,</L>
<L>huy smiten of heore heuedes sone : and heore bodies &thorn;are caste.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Aumperoure huy senden word : al &yogh;wat huy hadden i-do,</L>
<L N="20">And hov seint laurence in prisone was : in strongue bendes, al-so,</L>
<L>And hou he al &thorn;at tresor hadde : of churchene to him i-drawe.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">A v. om.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e Aumperov[r] i-heorde &thorn;is : he was glad &thorn;arof and fawe :</L>
<L>For he &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at tresor al habbe : &thorn;ei it were a-&yogh;en lawe.</L>
<L N="24">&para; &THORN;ane holie Man he liet fette : and bi-fore him lede,</L>
<L>And bi-heold him wel stuyrneliche : and wrot&thorn;eliche<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. wort&thorn;eliche</NOTE> to him sede :</L>
<L>"&YOGH;ware is &thorn;at tresor of &thorn;e churchene : &thorn;at &thorn;e was i-brou&yogh;t?"</L>
<L>Seint laurence stod wel stille : and ne ansuerede<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. ansueredede</NOTE> him ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;e Aumperour was swi&thorn;e wroth : &thorn;o he ne &yogh;af him non Answere;</L>
<L>A-non he wolde habbe defouled him : vnne&thorn;e he it<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> ni&yogh;te for-bere.</L>
<L>he liet cleopie valerian : &thorn;at was is hei&yogh;e Iustise,
<PB REF="00000389.tif" N="341"></L>
<L>"Nim," he seide, "&thorn;eosne Man : wel faste in alle wise</L>
<L N="32">And win of him &thorn;at tresor : and make him don sacrefise,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur bring him in swuch torment : &thorn;at o&thorn;ure of him a-grise."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iustise nam &thorn;ene holie Man : and liet him binde faste,</L>
<L>And bi-tok him Ypolite, &thorn;e kny&yogh;t : In strong prisone to caste.</L>
<L N="36">he brou&yogh;te [him] in strong prisoun : and bi-lek him faste al-so,</L>
<L>with &thorn;eoues and with lu&thorn;ere Men : &thorn;at hadden &thorn;e Aumperoure mis-do.&mdash;</L>
<L>On he&thorn;ene man &thorn;are was Inne : lucille was is name,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hadde &thorn;are-inne so muche i-wope : for seoruwe and for schame,</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at he weop out bo&thorn;e is ei&yogh;ene : and al blynd was bi-come.</L>
<L>Seint laurence hadde reu&thorn;e : &thorn;at is si&yogh;t him was bi-nome :</L>
<L>"bi-lief," he seide, "on Iesu crist : &thorn;at for us schedde is blod,</L>
<L>And afong cristinedom : ant &thorn;ov schalt habbe &thorn;i si&yogh;t wel guod."</L>
<L N="44">"Ich bi-lieue," &thorn;is o&thorn;ur seide : "on him with al mi &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And for-sake alle &thorn;eos false godes : &thorn;at ne mowen me helpe nou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>&para; Seint laurence baptizede him : and a-non-ri&yogh;t with &thorn;e dede</L>
<L>his si&yogh;t him cam wel cler and guod. : &thorn;o bi-gan he a-non to grede :</L>
<L N="48">"I-hered beo swete Iesu crist : &thorn;at here hath i&middot;cud is mi&yogh;te</L>
<L>And &thorn;oru&yogh; is seriaunt, seint laurence : me hath i-sent mi si&yogh;te!</L>
<L>For ase &yogh;e wuten euerechone : mi si&yogh;t me was bi-nome,</L>
<L>And &thorn;oru&yogh; Iesu crist and seint laurence : it is me a&yogh;ein i-come."</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;is ty&thorn;ingue sprong sone wide : so &thorn;at o&thorn;ore i-nowe</L>
<L>&THORN;at wide a-boute blinde weren : &thorn;uder-ward faste huy drowe.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o Ypolite &thorn;is i-sai&yogh; : &thorn;at ore louerd hadde swuch mi&yogh;te</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;e blinde &thorn;at &thorn;udere comen : anon hadden heore si&yogh;te,</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="148" UNIT="folio">"Merci!" he criede, "seint laurence" : and to Iesu<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. Iusu.</NOTE> crist him nam,</L>
<L>And he, and al is maynie : nomen cristine-dom.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="58">Valerian &thorn;are-after-ward sone : ase it cam in is &thorn;ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Sende to ypolite &thorn;e kny&yogh;t : &thorn;at he seint laurence him brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L N="60">"Nov, laurence," quath ypolite : "forth ich mot &thorn;e lede."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e, go we forth," seide laurence : "ne schal us no-&thorn;ing drede :</L>
<L>&THORN;e Ioye of heouene is al-&yogh;are : to us bo&thorn;e in alle wise."</L>
<L>&THORN;o ladde ypolit laurence forth : bi-fore &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere Iustise.</L>
<L N="64">Valerian &thorn;e Iustise : bi-heold laurence faste,
<PB REF="00000390.tif" N="342"></L>
<L>And seide, "bel ami, hov longue : schal ower folie i-laste?</L>
<L>Tuyrn &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t, ich rede, sone : and schewe us &thorn;at tresour</L>
<L>Of churchene &thorn;at &thorn;e was bi-take : and de-liuere it &thorn;e Aumperour!"</L>
<L>&para; "Sire Iustise," seint laurence seide : "&yogh;if &thorn;ov onder-stanst resoun,</L>
<L>&THORN;ov wost wel &thorn;at ich habbe i-leye : longue in &thorn;at prisoun,</L>
<L N="70">So &thorn;at i-ne habbe nou&yogh;t &thorn;at tresor : of churche here nov &yogh;are;</L>
<L>Ake &yogh;if me &thorn;reo dawes furst : &thorn;at ich mouwe a-boute fare,</L>
<L N="72">And ich it wolle to-gadere bringue : and here bi-fore &thorn;e lede."</L>
<L>&THORN;o was &thorn;e Iustise swy&thorn;e glad : of wordes &thorn;at he sede;</L>
<L>For hope of<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. op</NOTE> &thorn;at grete tresor : and for none o&thorn;ur<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. o&thorn;ur &thorn;ur</NOTE> &thorn;ingue,</L>
<L>he &yogh;af him respit of &thorn;reo dawes : &thorn;at tresor forth to bringue,</L>
<L N="76">And bi-tok him ypolite in warde : &thorn;at he him a&yogh;ein brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Forth huy wenden wide a-boute : and guod tresor huy sou&yogh;te :</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e men &thorn;at huy mi&yogh;ten finde : &thorn;at pouere and feble were,</L>
<L N="79">In sicnesse o&thorn;ur in miseise : to-gadere huy brou&yogh;ten &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And in ypolitus house hudden heom : And wenden to &thorn;e Aumperour.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Aumperour heom Axede sone : &yogh;ware were &thorn;at tresour.</L>
<L>&para; "Sire," seide seint laurence : "redi it is a-non."</L>
<L>he wende out after &thorn;e selie Men : and bad heom with him gon.</L>
<L N="84">In-to &thorn;e paleis<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. palais</NOTE> he ladde heom forth : bi-fore &thorn;e Aumperour,</L>
<L>"Lo, sire," he seide, "ich habbe i-brou&yogh;t : holi churche tresour.</L>
<L>&THORN;is tresour is swi&thorn;e holi and guod : and euere it wole i-laste,</L>
<L>hit ne schal neuere wanie : ake euere wexe faste;</L>
<L N="88">In eche londe it is redi : &yogh;wodere-so ani man wiende;</L>
<L>&THORN;are-with Man may &thorn;e blisse of heouene : bugge with-outen ende."<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 2 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Ei, traitre," seide &thorn;e Aumperour : "is it i-come here-to?</L>
<L>hast&thorn;ov us &thorn;us to scorn i-driue? : &thorn;ov ne schalt non-more so."</L>
<L N="92">he liet him streope nakede a-non : and with smarte scourgene him bete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at blod orn bi is limes a-doun : bo&thorn;e in leng&thorn;e and in grete (!).</L>
<L>&THORN;o seide &thorn;is holie man : "louerd, ich &thorn;onkie &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at a-mong &thorn;ine holie compaynie : &thorn;i wille is to bringue me.</L>
<L N="96">And &thorn;ov, wrechche lu&thorn;ere &thorn;ing : &thorn;ov art in gret torment i-wis,</L>
<L>In wrath&thorn;e and soruwe of heorte : and neuere &thorn;e worse me nis."</L>
<L>"A, traytour," seide &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere Man : "nelt&thorn;ov non-o&thorn;ur singue?"</L>
<L>Alle manere of tormenz : bi-fore him he liet bringue,
<PB REF="00000391.tif" N="343"></L>
<L N="100">Hokes of .Ire., and &yogh;weoles also : with rasores al-a-boute,</L>
<L>And a bed of Ire with kene pikes : al brenninde with-oute,<MILESTONE N="148b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Scourgene of led and raketei&yogh;es : and o&thorn;ere wel mani on,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we ne conne nou&yogh;t alle tellen : on eor&thorn;e nou&thorn;e nis swuch non.</L>
<L N="104">"Lo," seide &thorn;e Aumperour : "bi-hold nou&thorn;e al-a-boute,</L>
<L>And honovre ore godes, ich rede, a-non : o&thorn;ur herto &thorn;ov schalt loute;<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> route</NOTE></L>
<L>For alle &thorn;e tormenz &thorn;at &thorn;ov i-sixt : and &yogh;eot wel mo &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>bote &thorn;ov tuyrne &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t a-non : on &thorn;i bodi schullen beo i-do."</L>
<L>&para; "&THORN;ov wrechche," seide &thorn;is holie man : "mi wille hath euere i-beo</L>
<L>For-to come to &thorn;is murie solas : &thorn;at ich here nou&thorn;e i-seo.</L>
<L N="110">Wel mo tormenz &thorn;ane here beoth : to &thorn;e beoth i-mad al-&yogh;are</L>
<L>In &thorn;e pine of helle : &yogh;wane ich schal to &thorn;e Ioye of heuene fare."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="112">Decius &thorn;e Aumperour &thorn;o : fierde ase he were wod.</L>
<L>&THORN;e compaynie of tormentores : wel prest bi-fore him stod :</L>
<L>he het heom with grete staues : leggen on him to grounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e tormentores leiden on him : and maden him mani a wounde.</L>
<L N="116">Ase huy beoten &thorn;is holie bodi : seint laurence him sede :</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou wrechche, nou&thorn;e &thorn;ov mi&yogh;t i-seo : &thorn;at I-nabbe of &thorn;e no drede."</L>
<L>"Nimez a-non," quath &thorn;e Aumperour : "and makiez is torment more!"</L>
<L>Wel redie weren &thorn;e schrewes alle : to don aftur is lore :</L>
<L N="120">Irene plates al brenninde : In is woundes huy duden so sore.</L>
<L>"Swete louerd," &thorn;is holi man seide : "ich bidde &thorn;e milce and ore :</L>
<L>For &thorn;o ich was harde a-coupet : I-ne for-sok &thorn;e nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;o me Axeden me, ich was a-knowe of &thorn;e : with worde and with &thorn;ou&yogh;t."</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;o decius i-heorde &thorn;is : for wrath&thorn;e he gan grede,</L>
<L>And liet nime scourgene : with grete bottene<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> battes</NOTE> of lede</L>
<L>And liet beten &thorn;is holi man : &thorn;at is bones breken some;</L>
<L>&THORN;at he was op-on &thorn;e pointe of deth : and is strenc&thorn;e nei&yogh; bi-nome.</L>
<L N="128">&para; "Louerd," he seide, "Iesu crist : &thorn;at &thorn;oledest deth [for<NOTE PLACE="marg1">added later</NOTE>] me,</L>
<L>Onder-fong, &yogh;wane ich heonnes wiende : mine soule, ich bidde &thorn;e!"</L>
<L>&THORN;o cam &thorn;are a swete voiz : a-doun fram heuene anon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;eos wordes to him seide : &thorn;at huy heorden ech-on :</L>
<L N="132">"&YOGH;eot &thorn;e beoth for godes loue : tormentes<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. tormentores</NOTE> to come wel mo."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o Decius i-heorde &thorn;is : for wrath&thorn;e he gradde and wo :
<PB REF="00000392.tif" N="344"></L>
<L>"Lo," he seide, "mine barones : &thorn;at mi conseileres &yogh;e beoth,</L>
<L>Conseil nimez here-of<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> To con|seile me</NOTE> in mine court : of &thorn;ingue &thorn;at &yogh;e i-seoth :</L>
<L N="136">&YOGH;e i-heorez wel hov &thorn;e deuele[n] : with him spekez nov here&mdash;</L>
<L>For of &thorn;ing &thorn;at &yogh;e i-heorez alle : he ne may him nou&yogh;t skere.</L>
<L>huy comieth here and confortiez him : ase &yogh;e i-heorez ech-on.</L>
<L>Strong wichche [he] is, &thorn;at ne doutez : of ore godes ech-on;</L>
<L N="140">Wel hardi he is, for he ne tellez : of alle ore tormenz non.</L>
<L>bi &thorn;e fei &thorn;at ich owe to mahun : an-o&thorn;ur it schal gon!"</L>
<L>Scourgene he liet nime of Ire : &thorn;at harde weren i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L>And is flesch, &thorn;at was er bi-leued : &thorn;are-with he<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> me</NOTE> to-gnov&yogh;.</L>
<L N="144">&THORN;o is flesch &thorn;us defouled was : &thorn;at reov&thorn;e it was to seo,</L>
<L>"&THORN;eof," he seide, "&yogh;eot &thorn;ov schalt : In wel more torment beo."</L>
<L>his chekene and is mouth a-boute : he liet<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. liete</NOTE> bete with stones,<MILESTONE N="149" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And daschte &thorn;e tiez out of is heued : and to-breken is bones.</L>
<L N="148">"&THORN;ov wrechche," he seide, "bi-&thorn;iench &thorn;i-seolf : and torne sone &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t!"</L>
<L>&para; "Sire Aumperour," laurence seide : "&thorn;ov spext al embe nou&yogh;t :</L>
<L>I-nelle honovri none o&thorn;ur godes : &thorn;ane Iesus, in none wise;</L>
<L>For him ich louie, and euere wolle : don him sacrefise."</L>
<L N="152">&THORN;o Decius him hadde i-do : al &thorn;at he cou&thorn;e bi-&thorn;enche,</L>
<L>"Certes," he seide, "&thorn;ov schalt beo ded : ne schalt&thorn;ov nou&yogh;t so at|blenche."</L>
<L>Strong fuyr he lieth maken and gret : and a gredire &thorn;ar-on sette,</L>
<L>&THORN;ene holie Man, seint laurence : &thorn;ar-to he liet fette</L>
<L N="156">And al-a-long opon &thorn;e gredire : ouer &thorn;e fure him caste.</L>
<L>&THORN;e tormentores stoden al-a-boute : and bleowen &thorn;at fuyr wel faste;</L>
<L>with Irene pikes huy pulten him : and schouen In<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> him</NOTE> faste a-boue.</L>
<L>Louerd, muche was &thorn;e pyne : &thorn;at he soffrede for &thorn;i loue!</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;at fuyr bi-neo&thorn;e rostede him : al quic mid flesch and blode,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Irene pikes in is flesch : ful bitterliche huy wode.</L>
<L>Seint laurence bi-gan to speke [&thorn;o] : and to &thorn;e Aumperore he sede :</L>
<L>"&THORN;ov lu&thorn;ere wrechche, it ne deriez me nou&yogh;t : al &thorn;ine lu&thorn;ere dede.</L>
<L N="164">Nim &yogh;eme &thorn;at &thorn;ine fuyrie coles : wel muche a-kelez me,</L>
<L>And into &thorn;e strongue fuyre of helle : huy schullen bringue &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"LOuerd Iesu crist, &thorn;ov it wost : I-ne habbe &thorn;e nou&yogh;t for-sake,</L>
<L>Ake clanliche mi bodi and al mi &thorn;ou&yogh;t : &thorn;e ich habbe bi-take."
<PB REF="00000393.tif" N="345"></L>
<L N="168">&THORN;o bi-heold he &thorn;ene Aumperour : with fair semblaunt and louv&yogh; :</L>
<L>"&THORN;ov wrechche," he seide, "&thorn;ou hast i-rosted : &thorn;ulke one side i-nou&yogh; :</L>
<L>Torne hire opward and .et. hire nou&thorn;e : for &yogh;are heo is &thorn;are-to;</L>
<L>And wiend and roste &thorn;at o&thorn;ur side : &thorn;at heo beo i-nov&yogh; al-so."<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 2 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o bi-heold he up on hei&yogh; : and toward heouene is Eyene caste,</L>
<L>And seide : "swete Iesu crist : Ich &thorn;onki &thorn;e wel faste</L>
<L N="174">&THORN;at ich it habbe of-serued : at &thorn;ine &yogh;ates In to wiende."</L>
<L>With &thorn;ulke worde he deide &thorn;o : and broute is lijf to ende.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 2 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
<L N="176">Ypolit, &thorn;e guode kny&yogh;t : &thorn;at he brou&yogh;te to cristine-dom,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at him wuste in prisone .er : swy&thorn;e sori bi-com :</L>
<L>bi ni&yogh;te he wende stillede-liche : and &thorn;is holie bodi he nom</L>
<L>And burede hit wel stillede-liche : after is harde dom.</L>
<L N="180">Louerd, muche was &thorn;e pine : &thorn;at he &thorn;olede here :</L>
<L>hit<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. his</NOTE> is wel ri&yogh;t &thorn;at he beo : Apostles i-fere.</L>
<L>Nov&thorn;e, Iesu, for &thorn;e grete pine : &thorn;at seint laurence here hadde,</L>
<L>Vs bringue to &thorn;ulke Ioye : &thorn;at &thorn;ine Aungels his soule ladde. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="49" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>49 Vita sancti Kenelmi. Regis.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Kenelm, &thorn;e &yogh;ongue kyng : &thorn;at holi martyr is,</L>
<L>he was kyng in Engelonde : of &thorn;e Marche of Walis.</L>
<L>Kyng kenulf his fader hiet : he was kyng &thorn;are also;</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;e Abbeie of wynchecoumbe he liet arere : And &thorn;are-inne monekes do;</L>
<L>And Aftur is de&thorn;e he was &thorn;are i-bured : and &yogh;eot he lijth &thorn;ere</L>
<L>In &thorn;e Abbei&yogh;e, &thorn;at &yogh;eot stant : &thorn;at he him-seolf liet a-rere.</L>
<L>&THORN;o was wynchecombe gret cite : and mest of i-nov&yogh;</L>
<L N="8">Of al &thorn;ulke half of Engelonde : so feor so his lond drou&yogh;.<MILESTONE N="149b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Fyf kingues &thorn;are weren &thorn;ulke tyme : In engelonde i-do,</L>
<L>For Enguelond was guod and long : and sum-del brod al-so.</L>
<L>A-bouten ei&yogh;te hondret mile : Engelond long is</L>
<L>Fram<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. fran</NOTE> &thorn;e South into &thorn;e North : and to houndret brod i-wis</L>
<L>Fram &thorn;e Est into &thorn;e West. : al-so &thorn;are-inne beoth</L>
<L N="14">Manie wateres guode i-nowe : &thorn;at men al dai i-seoth.</L>
<L>bote &thorn;reo wateres principales : of alle ne beoth, i-wis :</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;at .on. is homber, &thorn;at o&thorn;ur seuerne : and temes &thorn;e &thorn;ridde is.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e North-se hombur geth : &thorn;at is on of &thorn;e beste,
<PB REF="00000394.tif" N="346"></L>
<L>And Temese into &thorn;e est-se : and seuerne into &thorn;e weste.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;eos fijf kyngus of Engelonde : &thorn;at weren bi olde dawe,</L>
<L>hadden heore part ech bi him-seolf i-deld : ase it was ri&yogh;t and lawe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng &thorn;at was of &thorn;e March : he hadde al &thorn;at beste :</L>
<L N="22">Muche del he hadde of Engelond : &thorn;at on half al-bi weste,</L>
<L>Wyrecestre-schire, and ware-wike-schire : and &thorn;e schire of gloucestre&mdash;</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;at is nei&yogh;wat al o bischopriche : &thorn;e bischopes of wyrecestre.</L>
<L>he hadde &thorn;ar-to chastre-schire : and derbi-schire al-so,</L>
<L>And stafford-schire&mdash;&thorn;at beoth alle : to<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> in</NOTE> one bischope-riche i-do,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e bischop-riche of Chastre : and &yogh;eot heo beoth &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L N="28">Schrobbe-schire sum : and warewyke-schire haluen-del al-so.</L>
<L>&THORN;is king hadde al-so hereforde-schire : &thorn;at o bischopriche is,</L>
<L>Ake Schrob-schire fallez haluendel : to &thorn;ulke schire,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> bischopriche</NOTE> i-wis,</L>
<L>And sum of warewike-schire : and of gloucestre-schire al-so.</L>
<L N="32">Seth&thorn;e hadde &thorn;e king of &thorn;e March : wel more lond &thorn;er-to :</L>
<L>Nore-hampte-sc<SUP>h</SUP>ire, and boking-ham-schire : and &thorn;e schire of Oxen|ford,</L>
<L>Leycestre-schire, . lincolne-schire : and &thorn;e schire of hert-ford&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is al o bischopriche : &thorn;at of lincolne nou&thorn;e is,</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;at &yogh;wuylene was of deorkcestre : bi-side Oxenforde, i-wis.</L>
<L>Seth&thorn;e hadde &thorn;e king of &thorn;e March : Notingham-schire &thorn;er-to&mdash;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e bischopriche of Euerwike : bote &thorn;o nas it nou&yogh;t so.</L>
<L>&THORN;o was al &thorn;is lond i-cleoped : &thorn;e Marche of Walis :</L>
<L N="40">Of al &thorn;is seint kenelmes fader : he was king, i-wis.</L>
<L>Non of alle &thorn;e o&thorn;ere kyne-riches : a-&yogh;ein &thorn;is kinedom nas;</L>
<L>And wynche-coumbe of al &thorn;is lond : chef Cite &thorn;o was.</L>
<L>&THORN;is fijf kyngues &thorn;at weren &thorn;o : &thorn;at on was of kent, i-wis,</L>
<L N="44">And &thorn;e o&thorn;er, ase ich ou seide er : of &thorn;e Marche of walis,</L>
<L>Of Esex,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. Westsex</NOTE> and of North-homberlond : and of est-lond al-so&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is fijf kynedomes in engelond : in &thorn;at time weren i-do.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king of west-sex hadde &thorn;o : al wilte-schire, i-wis,</L>
<L N="48">And Deorkecestre,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Dorsete</NOTE> and barroke-schire : &thorn;at al o bischopriche is,</L>
<L>To<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> &thorn;e bischopriche of salesburi&mdash; : ake &thorn;o nas it so nou&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. nou&yogh;t so</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;e chief stude of &thorn;e bischopriche : at schirbourne was i-wrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Seth&thorn;e hadde &thorn;e kyng of west-sex : south-sex al-so,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;e welde and al &thorn;e bischopriche : of Cicestre &thorn;er-to;
<PB REF="00000395.tif" N="347"></L>
<L>And southampte-schire and so&thorn;ereye : &thorn;at of &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. o</NOTE> bischopriche is,<MILESTONE N="150" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e bischopriche of wynchestre : &thorn;at &yogh;uyt is &thorn;ere, i-wis;</L>
<L>And somer-sete [&thorn;at] to welles : &thorn;ulke tyme drou&yogh;&mdash;</L>
<L N="56">Nov it is &thorn;e bischopriche of ba&thorn;e : &yogh;e schullen i-wyten.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &yogh;e wite&thorn; wel inou&yogh;</NOTE> <NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 63-4 are transp. in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e kyng of west-sex hadde seth&thorn;e : al deuene-schire, i-wis,</L>
<L>And Cornwaile, &thorn;at in &thorn;e bischopriche : of Eccestre nou&thorn;e is.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e king of kent was &thorn;o kyng : of al &thorn;e londe of kent,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;at weren inne tweie bischopriches : and &yogh;eot nis it nou&yogh;t i-went :</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischopriche of Caunterburi : &thorn;at in Engelonde &yogh;eot is hext,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e bischopriche of Roucestre : &thorn;at in&thorn;e west-side is next.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e king &thorn;at was of ast-londe : king was of North-folk,</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;e bischopriche of Northwich : and al-so of south-folk</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e bischopriche of hely : &thorn;at &thorn;e Yle of hely &yogh;eot is,</L>
<L>And grauntebrugge-schire : &thorn;are-to fallez, i-wis;</L>
<L>Seint Eadmund was of &thorn;at lond : kyng bi olde dawe&mdash;</L>
<L N="68">For he was in is owene lond : for is guodnesse a-slawe.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng of North-humber-lond : was kyng, ich onder-stonde,</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;e londe bi-&yogh;eonde houmber : A-non into scotlonde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischopriche of Eouerwik : and of Duyrham, i-wis;</L>
<L N="72">Seint Oswold bi olde dawe : was kyng of al &thorn;is.</L>
<L>&THORN;us manie kyngues weren : &yogh;wylene in Engelonde,</L>
<L>And heore londes de-partede weren : &thorn;us, ich under-stonde.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng &thorn;at was of &thorn;e march : ase ich telle bi-gan,</L>
<L N="76">Kenulf kyng he was i-cleoped : swi&thorn;e holi and guod man :</L>
<L>Seint kenelm was is sone : and is eir al-so;</L>
<L>Borewenild and quendrith : weren is dou&yogh;trene two.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e foure-and-twenti&thorn;e &yogh;ere : of is kynedom</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;e kyng<NOTE PLACE="marg1">on the margin.</NOTE> kenulf deide : and to &thorn;e IoIe of heuene he com&mdash;</L>
<L>hit was afftur &thorn;at ore louerd : in his moder a-li&yogh;te</L>
<L>Ei&yogh;te hundret &yogh;er and Nyntene : bi a-countes ri&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&para; Seint kenelm, is &yogh;onge sone : In is seuen&thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L N="84">kyng was I-mad aftur him : al-&thorn;ei he &yogh;ong child were.</L>
<L>his [o] soster Borewenild : louede him i-nou&yogh;</L>
<L>And in eche manere : to alle guod-nesse heo drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Quendrith, &thorn;e o&thorn;ur soster : of hire maneres nas nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="88">For heo tornede to feolonie : and<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. ant</NOTE> to quede hire &thorn;ou&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000396.tif" N="348"></L>
<L>&para; heo i-sai&yogh; &thorn;at hire &yogh;ungue bro&thorn;er : &thorn;at nas nou&yogh;t of seue &yogh;er,</L>
<L>kyng was i-mad of al &thorn;at lond : &thorn;at heore fader hadde er :</L>
<L>to him heo hadde gret onde : &thorn;at he scholde so riche beo</L>
<L N="92">And eir of hire fader lond : and of more power &thorn;ane heo;</L>
<L>heo &thorn;ou&yogh;te, &yogh;if heo mi&yogh;te bringue : &thorn;is child of lijf-dawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo wolde of is heritage : beo quene with lawe.</L>
<L>Al hire &thorn;ou&yogh;t was ni&yogh;t and day : to bi-&thorn;enche sum outrage,</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;at &thorn;is child were i-brou&yogh;t of dawe : for-to habbe is heritage.</L>
<L>heo porueide hire ri&yogh;t feolonliche : A poysun, strong i-nou&yogh;,</L>
<L>For-to &yogh;iue &thorn;is &yogh;ongue child : to slen him with wou&yogh;.<MILESTONE N="150b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at poysun him was i-&yogh;iue : &thorn;at so strong and lu&thorn;er was,</L>
<L N="100">Ore louerdes mi&yogh;te was so muche : &thorn;at no-&thorn;e worse him nas.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere quene &thorn;at i-sai : &thorn;at hit was al for nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no poysun ne mi&yogh;te him sle : heo &thorn;ou&yogh;te an o&thorn;ur &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;is &yogh;ongue child ane maister hadde : &thorn;at his wardein was&mdash;</L>
<L N="104">Askebert he was i-cleoped : a strong trichour, alas!</L>
<L>For noman ne may to o&thorn;ur : sonere tricherie do</L>
<L>&THORN;ane &thorn;ilke &thorn;at is him euere nei&yogh; : and &thorn;at he trist mest to.</L>
<L N="107">&para; &THORN;is lu&thorn;ere quene bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;te hire : of one false wrenche&mdash;</L>
<L>Men seith &thorn;at feolonie nas neuere non : &thorn;at womman ne can bi-&thorn;enche.</L>
<L>with &thorn;is Askebert heo spac : &thorn;is child to slen and spille;</L>
<L>heo bi-het him mede and guod i-nov&yogh; : and of eche &thorn;ing don is wille.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;is to lu&thorn;ere &thorn;ingues : weren at one rede,</L>
<L N="112">And bi-speken hou huy mi&yogh;ten best : don &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;wyle huy bi-speken bo&thorn;e : &thorn;is &yogh;ongue child to quelle,</L>
<L>&THORN;is swete sweuene &thorn;is child matte : &thorn;at ich ov wolle nou&thorn;e telle :</L>
<L>him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at &thorn;are stod a treo : ri&yogh;t bi-fore is bedde,</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;at a-non to &thorn;e steorrene it tilde : and swy&thorn;e wide it spradde;</L>
<L>&THORN;is treo was fair and noble i-nov&yogh; : And schon wel bri&yogh;te and wide,</L>
<L>Ful of blostmene and of fruyt : and mani a riche bou&yogh; bi-side,</L>
<L>berninde wex and laumpes al-so : &thorn;icke brenninde and li&yogh;te&mdash;</L>
<L N="120">So noble treo nas neuere i-sei&yogh;e : ne non &thorn;at schon so bri&yogh;te.</L>
<L>him &thorn;ou&yogh;te he c[l]am<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. cam</NOTE> op-on &thorn;at treo : to &thorn;exte bowe an hei&yogh;</L>
<L>And bi-heold a-boute in-to al &thorn;e world : and a-perteliche<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> prute inou&yogh;</NOTE> i-sei&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;wyle he stod opon &thorn;is treo : and bi-heold a-boute so,</L>
<L N="124">him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at on of is nexte frend : and &thorn;at he truste mest to,
<PB REF="00000397.tif" N="349"></L>
<L>On &thorn;e grounde stod bi-ne&thorn;e : and smot a-to &thorn;is treo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it feol a-doun to grounde : &thorn;at deol it was to seo.</L>
<L>to aluyte foul he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. ich</NOTE> bi-cam : non fairore ne mi&yogh;te non<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. non</NOTE> beo,</L>
<L N="128">And bi-gan with Ioye i-nov&yogh; : ri&yogh;t into heouene fleo.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is child &thorn;ou&yogh;te so : at wynchecombe he lay :</L>
<L>he a-wok and [in] grete &thorn;ou&yogh;te was : bo&thorn;e ni&yogh;t and day.</L>
<L>he nuste &yogh;wat tockninge it was : wel &thorn;e more was his<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. hire</NOTE> &thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="132">Are he &thorn;arof sum-&thorn;ing wuste : bli&thorn;e nas he nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>his norice, &thorn;at him hadde i-fed : and with hire milk forth i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at child heo louede euere muche : with dedes and with &thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>To hire &thorn;at child triste mest : &mdash;woluene hire name was :</L>
<L N="136">&THORN;is child tolde hire priueliche : of is metingue al is cas.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is Norice hadde i-heord : &thorn;e sweuene, &thorn;at was so guod,</L>
<L>heo bi-gan to siche sore : and in grete &thorn;ou&yogh;te stod;</L>
<L>"Alas," heo seide, "&thorn;at ich scholde : euere &thorn;is day a-bide,</L>
<L N="140">&THORN;at mi child, mi swete heorte : swych cas schal bi-tide!</L>
<L>Alas, mi child, mi swete fode : &thorn;at ich habbe forth i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;i soster, &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> bi-spekez &thorn;i deth : to quelle &thorn;e heo hath i-&thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;e foul, &thorn;at &thorn;ou bi-come to : and to heuene gan i-wende,<MILESTONE N="151" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="144">&THORN;at was &thorn;i soule, &thorn;at &thorn;udere schal : aftur &thorn;i liues ende."&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is metyngue bi-cam soth i-nou&yogh; : &thorn;at he fond at&thorn;e laste.</L>
<L>For is soster and Askebert : bi-speken is deth wel faste.</L>
<L>Askebert seide a day : &thorn;at &thorn;is child scholde wende</L>
<L N="148">An hontingue, to plei&yogh;en him : bi &thorn;e wodes ende,</L>
<L>And he with him, ase hit was ri&yogh;t : to witien him bi &thorn;e wei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">= heo, huy</NOTE> wende to &thorn;e wode of clent : ase it were heom for-to pleie.</L>
<L>Ase huy wenden a-boute &thorn;e wode : ase ore louerd &yogh;af &thorn;e grace,</L>
<L N="152">grete wille &thorn;at child hadde : &thorn;are to slepen in one place;</L>
<L>A-doun he lai wel soffteliche : and gan to slepe a-non.</L>
<L>Askebert ne &thorn;ou&yogh;te nou&yogh;t : &thorn;at he scholde &thorn;annes gon.</L>
<L>bi-side in one derne stude : he gan to deluen faste</L>
<L N="156">Ane put, &yogh;wane &thorn;at child were ded : &thorn;are-inne him to caste.</L>
<L>&THORN;at child bi-gan a-wakien sone : ase &thorn;ei it were bi cas,</L>
<L>After is maister he bi-heold : and ne sai&yogh; nou&yogh;t &yogh;ware he was.</L>
<L>Ake ore louerd him &yogh;af &thorn;e grace : &thorn;ei he nuste nou&yogh;t of is dede,</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;at he spac to his maister : and &thorn;eos wordes sede :
<PB REF="00000398.tif" N="350"></L>
<L>"&THORN;ou trauailest," he seide, "a-boute nou&yogh;t : and &thorn;ine &yogh;wyle &thorn;ou dost spille,</L>
<L>For in ane o&thorn;ure stude i schal deie : &yogh;ware hit is godes wille;</L>
<L>And &thorn;oru&yogh; tokningue of &thorn;is &yogh;eorde : &thorn;ou schal wel i-seo</L>
<L N="164">&THORN;are<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> whane</NOTE> al &thorn;i wille &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t do : &thorn;at ich i-martred beo."</L>
<L>Forth wende &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere man : and &thorn;is child also.</L>
<L>huy comen to on o&thorn;ur stude : &thorn;are &thorn;e dede was i-do.</L>
<L>&THORN;is maister nam &thorn;e &yogh;eorde : and sette hire on &thorn;e grounde :</L>
<L N="168">And heo bi-gan to leui &thorn;are : in wel luyte stounde,</L>
<L>And a swy&thorn;e gret Asch bi-cam seth&thorn;e : and &yogh;eot stant in &thorn;ulke place,</L>
<L>to schewi &thorn;e mi&yogh;te of seint kenelm : and ore louerdes grace.</L>
<L>&THORN;es lu&thorn;ere man nam &thorn;is child : in &thorn;e wode of klent</L>
<L N="172">And ladde him, ase men doth a &thorn;eof : to a-fongue is Iuggement,</L>
<L>he ladde him into a priue stude : al out of &thorn;e wei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>bi-twene [twei]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> hulles hei&yogh;e : into a deop ualeie.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is child &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e holi gost : &thorn;ei &thorn;e o&thorn;ur it nolde him telle,</L>
<L N="176">Wuste wel is lu&thorn;ere &thorn;ou&yogh;t : &thorn;at he him wolde a-quelle;</L>
<L>And &thorn;o he targede a luyte : &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere dede to done,</L>
<L>&THORN;at child seide wel mildeliche : "&yogh;wy ne dost &thorn;ou sone?"</L>
<L>he bi-gan Ane saume &thorn;at men singuth : in holie churche a-day,</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;at was "te deum laudamus" : are &thorn;at he a-doun lay.</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t ase he scide an holi vers : &thorn;at &thorn;are-inne was and is,</L>
<L>A-latyn i-write, as alle &thorn;e o&thorn;ure : and &thorn;e englisch so is &thorn;is</L>
<L>"&THORN;e faire compaygnie of Martyrs : louerd, herieth &thorn;e :"</L>
<L N="184">Ri&yogh;t ase he hadde &thorn;at fers i-seid : as &thorn;e boc tellez me,</L>
<L>&THORN;e lu&thorn;ere man smot of is heued : onder an haw&yogh;&thorn;orn-treo,</L>
<L>&THORN;are ase godes wille was : &thorn;at he i-martred scholde beo.</L>
<L>A coluere, &yogh;wi&yogh;t so eni milk : out of him gan teo</L>
<L N="188">And ri&yogh;t euene heo was i-sei&yogh;e : into heouene fleo.<MILESTONE N="151b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Onne&thorn;e he was seue &yogh;er old : are he i-martred were&mdash;</L>
<L>Alto soth is sweuene was : ase [men] mi&yogh;ten i-seo &thorn;ere!</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is lu&thorn;ere man &thorn;at him a-slov&yogh; : bi-gan to delue faste</L>
<L N="192">And made ane put, deop i-nou&yogh; : and &thorn;are-inne &thorn;is child caste;</L>
<L>he burede hit &thorn;are faste i-nou : &thorn;at he i-founde nere,</L>
<L>And wende hom a-&yogh;ein in is wei : and liet him ligge &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>To Quendrith, his lu&thorn;ere soster : a-non-ri&yogh;t he gan i-wende
<PB REF="00000399.tif" N="351"></L>
<L N="196">And tolde al &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere dede : hou he was i-brou&yogh;t to ende.</L>
<L>&THORN;eos womman was &thorn;o glad i-nou&yogh;! : A-boute heo sende a-non</L>
<L>For-to saisi alle his londes to hire : and &thorn;e maneres euerech-on,</L>
<L>And liet hire makien quiene of &thorn;e Marche : ase hire bro&thorn;ur was king.</L>
<L N="200">A schrewe lauedi heo was i-nov&yogh; : and wicke &thorn;oru&yogh; alle &thorn;ing!</L>
<L>heo wende a-boute ope al hire lond : and nam hire manrede,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. manrade</NOTE></L>
<L>And bi-cam stuyrne and bi-ladde hire men : harde with muche wrech-hede.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 2 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
<L>heo liet hote into al &thorn;at lond : &thorn;at no man so wod nere</L>
<L N="204">to nemmen hire bro&thorn;er name : for loue ne for fere;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if man mi&yogh;te ani i-wite : &thorn;at nadde it nou&yogh;t bi-leued,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he were sone i-nome : and i-smiten of is heued.</L>
<L N="207">&THORN;us fierde &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere womman : and sturede hire wel faste;</L>
<L>&THORN;at no man ne dorste hire bro&thorn;ur bi-mene : huy weren so sore a-gaste.</L>
<L>And euere lai &thorn;is holie bodi : i-bured swi&thorn;e stille,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no man ne dorste of him speke : a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e quiene wille.</L>
<L>So longue, &thorn;at he was al for-&yogh;ite : &thorn;o men ne moste of him speke.</L>
<L N="212">Ake hit nas nou&yogh;t &thorn;at at&thorn;e laste : ore louerd him nolde a-wreke.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane no man nolde, &thorn;at witti was : of him &thorn;enchen ene,</L>
<L>Ore louerd nolde nou&yogh;t &thorn;at he were : allingues for-&yogh;ite so clene;</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane no man, &thorn;at witti was : of him ne hadde muynde,</L>
<L N="216">A doumb best, &thorn;at is with-oute witte : hadde, a-&yogh;ein kuynde.</L>
<L>For a wydewe hadde ane &yogh;wite kov : &thorn;at wonede &thorn;are-bi-side,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;eode a-dai to fetten hire mete : in &thorn;e wode wel wide</L>
<L>&THORN;o seint kenelm was i-bured : in &thorn;e valeie &thorn;are doune.</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;is kou wolde eche daye : &yogh;wane heo come fram toune</L>
<L>to gaderi hire mete, with o&thorn;ure kuyn : heo wolde gon al one</L>
<L>Fer a-doun into &thorn;is valeie : and hire felawes bi-leue ech-one,</L>
<L>And sitte bi &thorn;is holie bodi : al &thorn;e longue dai,</L>
<L N="224">Ase it were for-to honouri him : for hit so one lay;</L>
<L>And so heo sat with-oute mete : al &thorn;e day to &thorn;en ende,</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane hit at&thorn;e eue was : hamward heo wolde wende.</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane heo cam hom at eue : fair and round heo was,</L>
<L N="228">And swy&thorn;e Mielch al-so : &mdash;&thorn;at was a wonder cas!</L>
<L>For &thorn;are ne was no o&thorn;ur kov : &thorn;at half so muche milk &yogh;eoue;</L>
<L>heo ne &yogh;af a-morewe no&thorn;e lasse : &thorn;ei heo were i-milked an eue.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 2 vv. more.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000400.tif" N="352"></L>
<L>Folk &thorn;at &thorn;is wonder i-sai&yogh; : guode &yogh;eme alle huy nome</L>
<L N="232">And a-waiteden wel a dai : &yogh;ware &thorn;e kou bi-come.<MILESTONE N="152" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Heo seien hire sitte al &thorn;e day : in &thorn;e valeie &thorn;are doune,</L>
<L>Stille in one stude, meteles : for-to heo eode an eue to toune.</L>
<L>Ake &yogh;wi heo sete &thorn;are so : heo ne mi&yogh;ten i-wite no&thorn;ing;</L>
<L N="236">bote in heore heorte huy onder-stoden : &thorn;at it was sum tokning.</L>
<L>For &thorn;is kov wonede so &thorn;ere : and adai drou&yogh; hire &thorn;are-to,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ualeye men cleopeden "koubache" : and &yogh;eot men doth al-so.&mdash;</L>
<L>In kovbache &thorn;at holie bodi : lai wel mani a &yogh;er,</L>
<L N="240">&THORN;at men nusten of him no-&thorn;ing : ase ich ov seide er :</L>
<L>For is soster, &thorn;at was so forth<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> fers : and</NOTE> : in grete pruyte i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>So gret &thorn;retningue for him heo made : &thorn;at men ne dorsten him nemme nou&yogh;t.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is bodi ne moste beo : i-founde in Engelonde,</L>
<L N="244">Ore louerd, &thorn;at wot alle &thorn;ing : to him he sende is sonde.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;erto sette is honde</NOTE></L>
<L>Ase &thorn;e pope stod at rome : in his masse a day</L>
<L>At seint peteres weouede : ase muche folk &thorn;at i-sai,</L>
<L>A coluere, &yogh;wi&yogh;t so ani snov : cam fram heouene fleo</L>
<L N="248">And leide on &thorn;e weuede a luyte writ : and seth&thorn;e a&yogh;en gan steo,</L>
<L>he flev&yogh; op into heouene an hei&yogh; : ase ore louerd it wolde.</L>
<L>&THORN;at writ was &yogh;wijt and schon wel bri&yogh;te : &thorn;e lettres weren of golde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope &thorn;onkede ihesu crist : and &thorn;at folk dude al-so.</L>
<L N="252">he nam &thorn;e lettre on his hond : and &thorn;o heo was ondo,</L>
<L>he nuste &yogh;wat it was to segge : ne non in-si&yogh;t he ne cou&thorn;e i-wite&mdash;</L>
<L>For he ne cou&thorn;e englisch non : and on englis it was i-write.</L>
<L>he liet cleopie eche-manere men : of eche diuerse londe,</L>
<L N="256">&yogh;if any cov&thorn;e of &thorn;is holie writ : Ani-&thorn;ing onder-stonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;o weren &thorn;are men of Engelonde : &thorn;at wusten &yogh;wat it sede,</L>
<L>And onder-stoden wel &thorn;at writ : &thorn;o heo i-heorden it rede.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at writ was puyr on Englisch i-write : ase men it radden &thorn;ere;</L>
<L N="260">And for-to tellen with-oute ryme : &thorn;eos wordes it were :</L>
<L>"In klent covbache kenelm, kyngues sone,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> bern</NOTE> lijth onder ane &thorn;orne, is<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> heued him<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> bi-reued."</L>
<L>&THORN;is writ was wel nobleliche : i-wust and up i-do,</L>
<L>And i-holde for gret relike : and &yogh;eot it is al-so;</L>
<L N="264">&THORN;e nobleste relike it is on &thorn;ar-of : &thorn;at is in &thorn;e churche of rome&mdash;
<PB REF="00000401.tif" N="353"></L>
<L>So it ou&yogh;te wel ho-so it under-stode : fram &yogh;wanne &thorn;at it come:</L>
<L>For &yogh;wane it out of heouene cam : fram ore louerdes honde,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wat noblere relike mi&yogh;te beo? : I-ne can non onder-stonde.</L>
<L N="268">&THORN;are-fore seint kenelmes day : ase &thorn;e pope makede is heste,</L>
<L>At rome huy holdez hei&yogh;liche : and makiez wel hei&yogh; feste.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e pope, &thorn;o he &thorn;e so&thorn;e wuste : &thorn;at it was swuch tockningue,</L>
<L>his messagers in-to Engelonde : he sende wit &thorn;is ti&thorn;ingue;</L>
<L N="272">To &thorn;e Erchebischope of kaunterburi : wolfred &thorn;at was &thorn;o,</L>
<L>his lettre he sende, &thorn;at he scholde : of swuche &thorn;ingue onder-go</L>
<L>And seche after &thorn;e wode of klent : &yogh;if ani man mi&yogh;te i-wite,</L>
<L>And seche ane &thorn;orn in kovbache : ase it was in &thorn;e write,</L>
<L N="276">And for-to seche &thorn;at holie bodi : &thorn;at derneliche lay &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And nimen it up with gret honour : &thorn;at hit i-schrined were.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e lettre fram &thorn;e pope : to &thorn;e Erchebischope cam,<MILESTONE N="152b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of bischopes and of clerkus : conseil &thorn;ar-of he nam:</L>
<L N="280">So &thorn;at in &thorn;e wode of klent : &thorn;at in wyricestre-schire is,</L>
<L>he liet seche &thorn;at holie bodi : and fond it out, i-wis,</L>
<L>Onder &thorn;e &thorn;orne at covbache : ase &thorn;at writ seide of rome.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e contreie-men bi-side : manie &thorn;udere huy come,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &amp; for &thorn;e miracle of &thorn;e cou : &thorn;e what|loker &thorn;erto hi come.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;o<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> For</NOTE> men of &thorn;are-bi-side : onder-&yogh;eten<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at o.</NOTE> &thorn;at cas,</L>
<L>Ortreweden wel &yogh;ware it lay : for &thorn;e miracle so fair was.</L>
<L>A-non so &thorn;at bodi was op i-nome : &thorn;e &yogh;wile &thorn;at folk &thorn;are stod,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere sprong a welle, &thorn;are he lay : &thorn;at &yogh;eot is fair and guod.</L>
<L N="288">A welle &thorn;are is cler i-nou&yogh; : and eucreft hath i-beo,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e stude &thorn;are he lai on : ase man mai &thorn;are i-seo,</L>
<L>Men<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at me</NOTE> cleopieth "seint kenelmes welle"&mdash; : &thorn;at mani man hath i-sou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And manie &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e watere : of grete Anguisse beoth i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="292">Of &thorn;e cite of wynchecumbe : and of &thorn;e contreie &thorn;are-bi-side</L>
<L>&THORN;e men weren &thorn;at sou&yogh;ten so : &thorn;at holie bodi so wide:</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> for</NOTE> &thorn;e bischopes hadden er i-loked : &thorn;at it scholde to winchecumbe beo i-bore</L>
<L>And i-schrined, &thorn;are is fader lai : &thorn;at a-rerde &thorn;at hous bi-fore.</L>
<L N="296">&THORN;is men nomen up &thorn;at holie bodi : &thorn;at of gloucestre-schire were,</L>
<L>And nobleliche toward wynchecumbe : with procession it bere.</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk of wyricestre-schire : &thorn;at woneden &thorn;are-bi-side,
<PB REF="00000402.tif" N="354"></L>
<L>Nomen heom to rede manie : to maken &thorn;at bodi a-bide,</L>
<L N="300">And sworen &thorn;at huy it wolden habbe : and noman ne scholde it heom bi-reue,</L>
<L>For in &thorn;e schire &thorn;are it i-founde was : huy seiden, it scholde bi-leue.</L>
<L>bi &thorn;e watere of pireford : &thorn;is two schirene hem mette,</L>
<L>And conteckeden for &thorn;is holie bodi : and faste to-gadere sette.</L>
<L N="304">So &thorn;at huy nomen ane fourme of pays : to don bi<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> vp</NOTE> godes grace,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if god heom wolde is wille sch[e]wen : are huy wenden fram &thorn;at place.</L>
<L>Feor huy weren i-trauailed and sore : so &thorn;at heom luste slepe ech-on:</L>
<L>huy maden ane fourme &thorn;at huy scholden alle : ligge slepe a-non,</L>
<L N="308">And &yogh;we&thorn;ur of &thorn;is twei schires : mi&yogh;ten sonore a-wake</L>
<L>huy scholden sauf i-nov&yogh; wenden forth : and &thorn;at bodi with hem<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. him</NOTE> take.</L>
<L>&para; Stille huy lei&yogh;en slepe faste : &thorn;is schirene bo&thorn;e-to,</L>
<L>And resten heom of hore werienesse&mdash; : for ore louerd it wolde so.</L>
<L N="312">[So] &thorn;at huy of gloucestre-schire : a-woken sone ech-on</L>
<L>At one tyme alle, ase god it wolde : and of wyricestre-schire nou&yogh;t on.</L>
<L>In pais huy wenden forth heore wey : and &thorn;is bodi with heom toke.</L>
<L N="315">Wel fif mile wei huy weren i-wende : are &thorn;e o&thorn;ere a-woke.</L>
<L>&THORN;is o&thorn;ere i-sei&yogh;en heom bi-gylede : anon so huy bi-gounne a-wake:</L>
<L>And siweden &thorn;is o&thorn;ere swi&thorn;e faste : ake huy ne mi&yogh;ten heom nou&yogh;t of-take.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is men toward wy[n]checombe : &thorn;at holie bodi huy bere.</L>
<L>Are heo mi&yogh;ten it &thorn;udere bringue : swy&thorn;e werie huy were.</L>
<L N="320">So &thorn;at huy comen into one wode : a luyte bi este &thorn;e toune,</L>
<L>And resten heom, &thorn;o huy weren so nei&yogh; : op-on ane hei&yogh;e doune.</L>
<L>A-&thorn;urst huy weren for werienesse : so &thorn;at it nas non ende.</L>
<L>huy beden ore louerd for seint kenelmes loue : &thorn;at he scholde heom drinke sende.<MILESTONE N="153" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="324">A fair welle &thorn;are sprong op : an hei&yogh; op-on &thorn;e doune&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;uyt is &thorn;are, cler and cold : half a mile fram toune;</L>
<L>heo is nou&thorn;e wel faire i-heoled : with freo ston, ase ri&yogh;t is,</L>
<L>I-redi ech man to drinken of : &thorn;at cometh &thorn;are-forth, i-wis.</L>
<L N="328">&para; &THORN;e Monekes of Wynchecombe : arerd habbez &thorn;are-bi-side</L>
<L>A fair chapele of seint kenelm : &thorn;at men sechez ful wide.&mdash;</L>
<L>Quendrith, &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere womman : at wynchecumbe &thorn;o was;
<PB REF="00000403.tif" N="355"></L>
<L>bote heo nuste nou&yogh;t hire bro&thorn;er so nei&yogh; : ne no-wi&yogh;t of &thorn;at cas.</L>
<L N="332">In seint peteres churche heo sat : bi-side &thorn;e Abbeie-&yogh;ate,</L>
<L>In a soler in&thorn;e est-side : and lokede out &thorn;are-ate.</L>
<L>heo i-sai&yogh; al &thorn;is grete folk come : a-doneward of &thorn;e doune hei&yogh;e</L>
<L>Toward wynchecumbe : a-luyte fram suyd-lei&yogh;e.</L>
<L N="336">heo Axede &yogh;wat men it weren : and &yogh;wat huy &thorn;ou&yogh;ten &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Men seiden &thorn;at huy to churche wolden : and &thorn;at huy hire bro&thorn;er bere.</L>
<L>&THORN;o was &thorn;is Quiene sori i-nov&yogh;! : in grete deole and fere</L>
<L>hire sauter heo nam on honde : ase &thorn;ei heo witles were.</L>
<L N="340">Of &thorn;e sauter &thorn;e laste saume : bi-fore &thorn;e Euesongus, i-wis,</L>
<L>of corsingue and<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> of lu&thorn;ere men : and of mansingue i-maked heo is:</L>
<L>"Deus laudem" [heo] is i-cleoped. : &thorn;is saume &thorn;e Quiene radde,</L>
<L>For-to a-corsi hire bro&thorn;ur bodi : and alle &thorn;at him &thorn;udere ladde.</L>
<L N="344">&THORN;o heo cam to &thorn;e Ninteo&thorn;e vers : ase &thorn;e mansingue endez, i-wis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at "hoc opus eorum" : a-latin i-cleoped it is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at seit &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> what</NOTE> men it beo scholden : &thorn;at duden<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> afonge&thorn;</NOTE> &thorn;at ilke dede:</L>
<L>Opon hire owene heued it cam : ase heo &thorn;at vers gan rede:</L>
<L N="348">For ri&yogh;t ase heo &thorn;at vers radde : out-borsten bo&thorn;e hire ei&yogh;e</L>
<L>And fullen a-doun op-on hire sauter : ase manie men i-sei&yogh;e.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 2 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e sauter is &yogh;uyt at wynchecombe : and ho-so come wole &thorn;are-to,</L>
<L>Aperteliche man may &thorn;are i-se : &yogh;ware &thorn;e dede was i-do.&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 2 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
<L N="352">&THORN;is holie bodi was forth i-bore : with gret honour ate fine,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e Abbeie, &thorn;are he lijth &yogh;uyt : i-don in wel noble schrine.</L>
<L N="354">&THORN;is lu&thorn;ere Quiene deide seth&thorn;e : in schrewedenesse i-nou&yogh;;</L>
<L>&THORN;at bodi, ase a corsede wrechche : into ane diche man it drov&yogh;,</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e fouleste &thorn;at was &thorn;are a-boute : and &thorn;are-inne man it slong&mdash;</L>
<L N="357">bote hire endingue sunful<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> scenfol</NOTE> were : me &thorn;inchez elles it hadde i-beo wrong!</L>
<L>Nov god for &thorn;e loue of seint kenelm : is swete grace vs<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. it</NOTE> sende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we moten to &thorn;ulke Ioie : &thorn;are he is inne,i-wiende. AmeN.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="50" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>50 Vita sancti Gregorij.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Gregori &thorn;e confessour : in Ciscile was i-bore.</L>
<L>In holienesse he ladde is lijf : &thorn;at is soule nere for-lore.</L>
<L>gret clerk he was and guod prechour. : in Cycile he liet a-rere
<PB REF="00000404.tif" N="356"></L>
<L N="4">Sixe Abbeies of Monekes : with-inne a fewe &yogh;eres,</L>
<L>Se seouen&thorn;e he dude a-rere : in &thorn;e Cite of rome;</L>
<L>&THORN;are he and manie o&thorn;ur with him : &thorn;e Abite of monekes nome.</L>
<L>In so gret fastingue he was : and so luyte he wolde ete,</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;at al is wille he for-les : of drinke and of mete;</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="153b" UNIT="folio">For defaute he scholde ra&thorn;ur deie : &thorn;ane beo of-houngred ene&mdash;</L>
<L>So he was to fastingue i-woned : his lijf he ladde so clene.</L>
<L>Wel sielden for al is feblesse : Idel he beo scholde,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. wolde.</NOTE></L>
<L N="12">&THORN;at of ore louerdes seruise : rede o&thorn;ur singue he [no]lde<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. wlde, w over an erasure.</NOTE></L>
<L>O&thorn;ur writen o&thorn;ur telle : o&thorn;ur rimes &thorn;ar-of make,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur he wolde bidde is beden : &thorn;e &yogh;wyle he mi&yogh;te wake.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope is guodnesse under-&yogh;at : &thorn;ei he &thorn;are-of were stille :</L>
<L N="16">At rome he made him cardinal : al a-&yogh;ein is wille.</L>
<L>So wijs and holi he was in &thorn;ou&yogh;te : and so ri&yogh;tful of is dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e conseil of holie churche : muche was bi is rede.&mdash;</L>
<L>Out of is paleys in a day : &thorn;is holie man gan i-wiende :</L>
<L N="20">he founde Marchauns at rome : with Mercerie wel hiende.</L>
<L>to sullen huy ladden on heore hond : swete children &thorn;reo,</L>
<L>Fairore &thorn;ingus &thorn;ane huy weren : ne mi&yogh;te no man i-seo.</L>
<L>Seint Gregori &yogh;eorne heom bi-heold : a stounde he gan at-stonde,</L>
<L N="24">And axede &yogh;wat &thorn;e childre weren : and of &yogh;wuche londe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Marchaunz seiden, "Englische huy beoth : of Engelonde i-nome,</L>
<L>And swuch is &thorn;e kuynde of alle &thorn;e men : &thorn;at of &thorn;at lond doz come."</L>
<L>"Wel au&yogh;te," seide &thorn;is holie man : "&thorn;at lond beo guod and riche,</L>
<L N="28">For<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> huy beoth Englische swy&thorn;e wel i-cleoped : engles huy buth i-liche.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at [lond]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> is swuch ase [&thorn;e]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> men beoth : name it hauez with ri&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Englene lond it au&yogh;te wel beo : and engles &thorn;are-inne a-li&yogh;te;</L>
<L>And swuch folk au&yogh;te in heouene : beon englene i-fere."</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;o Axede he &yogh;wat bi-leue : in engelonde were.</L>
<L>&THORN;e marchaunz seiden, "al engelond : is puyr he&thorn;enesse."</L>
<L>"Alas," seide seint Gregori : "a-las, &thorn;e sorienesse</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e prince of &thorn;e deorke helle : schal habbe in powere</L>
<L N="36">A lond fol of so fair folk : &thorn;at au&yogh;ten beo Engles i-fere!"</L>
<L>he wende a-&yogh;ein in-to is paleis : with wel dreorie chere,</L>
<L>And carede muche &thorn;at in Engelond : cristinedom i-brou&yogh;t nere.
<PB REF="00000405.tif" N="357"></L>
<L>At &thorn;e commuyn conseil a day : seint Gregori a-ros sone,</L>
<L N="40">And bad &thorn;e pope and is cardinales : graunti him ane bone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy him senden in-to engelond : to prechie cristinedom.</L>
<L>&THORN;o<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> &thorn;e pope mid is cardinales : gret conseil &thorn;ar-of nam;</L>
<L>Nolden huy him graunti nou&yogh;t. : ake euere he bad so faste,</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at huy dorsten werne none lengore : and graunteden at&thorn;e laste.</L>
<L>Seint Gregori was &thorn;o glad i-nou&yogh;! : he nolde a-bide non lengore more,</L>
<L>&THORN;o wende he toward engelonde : to prechie godes lore.</L>
<L>A-non so he was fram rome i-wend : defaute of him men hadde;</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;at folk cam to &thorn;e pope al day<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. al day</NOTE> : and echone on him huy gradde,</L>
<L>Ase he to seint peteres munstre i-wende : &thorn;o in ane dai&yogh;e,</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou &thorn;encst," huy seiden, "with &thorn;i conseil : al rome to bi-trai&yogh;e;</L>
<L>he &thorn;at halt op &thorn;e conseile of Rome : heonnes &thorn;ou hast i-send;</L>
<L N="52">bote &thorn;ou him of-sende sone : al rome worth i-schend."</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope hadde gret loue ei&yogh;e : of &thorn;at &thorn;e folk him seide.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">A v. om.</NOTE></L>
<L>he nas nou&yogh;wer nei&yogh; at&thorn;e se : are he him of-sende.<MILESTONE N="154" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>With wel dreorie chere &thorn;o : &thorn;is holie man a&yogh;en wende.&mdash;</L>
<L N="56">Ase god it wolde, &thorn;are-aftur-ward : sone it dude bi-falle</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e pope wende out of &thorn;e world : so we schullen alle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e cardinales and &thorn;e bischopes : and al &thorn;at conseil of rome,</L>
<L>Ane pope to cheose afturward : alle to-gadere huy come.</L>
<L N="60">huy hieten &thorn;at ech man &thorn;at of &thorn;e conseile was : eche dai&yogh;e faste scholde</L>
<L>And in heore bedes beon ni&yogh;t and day : &yogh;if ore louerd heom sende wolde</L>
<L>Ani tokningue a-mong heom : &yogh;if ani of heom wuyr&thorn;e were</L>
<L>In rome pope for-to beo : cristine men wel to lere.</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;o huy hadden in heore oresones i-beon : &thorn;reo daies and &thorn;reo ni&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e huyrne of one chapele : huy sei&yogh;en swy&thorn;e gret li&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at stod ase &thorn;ei hit a piler were : into heouene up-ri&yogh;t&mdash;</L>
<L>huy ne i-sei&yogh;en neuer er no &thorn;ing : so cler ne so bri&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;o huy comen to &thorn;e place : onder &thorn;e li&yogh;te huy founde</L>
<L>&THORN;ane holie man, seint Gregori : plat i-falle to grounde;</L>
<L>For werinesse of is oresones : he lai al<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> as</NOTE> in suoddringue.</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk bi-gan to herien god : and loude huy guonne si[n]gue;</L>
<L N="72">huy nomen &thorn;esne holie man : and maden him pope a-non.
<PB REF="00000406.tif" N="358"></L>
<L>Fair and swete was &thorn;at li&yogh;t : &thorn;at op-on him schon!&mdash;</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e wel he wuste cristine-dom : and holie lijf he ladde.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e mis-bi-leue of Engelonde : gret deol and care he hadde.</L>
<L N="76">Seint Austin was a Monek &thorn;o : him and o&thorn;ere he nam</L>
<L>And sende heom in-to engelonde : to prechi cristindom.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Austin and is Monekus : &thorn;o huy weren in Engelonde,</L>
<L>wide huy precheden cristindom&mdash; : i-hered beo godes sonde.</L>
<L N="80">Seint Austin wende to &thorn;e kingues court : and so he prechede &thorn;ere,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">v. 80-3 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e king and alle is men : sone i-baptizede were.</L>
<L>&THORN;o huy hadde i-brou&yogh;t in-to godes lawe : &thorn;ene kyng and is pouwer,</L>
<L>&THORN; t folk tornede &thorn;oru&yogh; godes grace : to him feor and ner.</L>
<L N="84">So longue &thorn;at &thorn;is holie men : heore wille hadden at &thorn;en ende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al folk of eche toune : to cristindom gan i-wende.</L>
<L>&THORN;o wende seint Austin a-&yogh;en. : &thorn;e pope he tolde at rome<NOTE PLACE="marg1">v. 86-95 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L>hou alle &thorn;e men of engelonde : cristin-dom nome.</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;o was &thorn;e pope seint Gregori : i-brou&yogh;t in grete blisse,</L>
<L>And liet seint Austyn wende a-&yogh;en : &thorn;at lond more to wisse</L>
<L>And make Bischopes and Ercedeknes : and o&thorn;ure prelatus al-so,</L>
<L>Cristin-dom to witie in engelonde : &thorn;at men ne scholde neuere ondo.</L>
<L N="92">Seint Austin wende a-non a-&yogh;en : and &thorn;o he to engelonde cam,</L>
<L>Twelf bischopes &thorn;are-inne he made : to witien cristin-dom,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ere prelates of holi churche : &thorn;at we a-mong us i-seoth.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is manere to cristindom : alle i-brou&yogh;t we beoth</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;oru&yogh; &thorn;e bone of seint gregori : &thorn;at hidere sende is sonde;</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore we cleopiez him in holie bok : Apostul of Engelonde,</L>
<L>For he us sende ore ri&yogh;te bi-leue : &thorn;at we<NOTE PLACE="marg1">overlined.</NOTE> holdez &yogh;uyte,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">The text is corrupted here.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="154b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And in his dai&yogh;e sette children to lore : &thorn;e &yogh;wyle huy beoth luyte&mdash;</L>
<L>God for &thorn;e loue of seint gregori : &thorn;ulke lore us leue so wite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he us sende bi seint Austin : and neuereft hire for-&yogh;ite.</L>
<L N="102">Wel au&yogh;ten cristine men to louien him : &thorn;at in ri&yogh;te bi-leue heom brou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>For he was &thorn;e furste man : &thorn;at cristin-dom to hem bi-sou&yogh;te.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">This v. is corrupted.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>Muche folk &thorn;are was in Rome : &thorn;at in guode bi-leue nere</L>
<L>Ne bi-lieueden nou&yogh;t &thorn;at &thorn;e sacringe : ore louerdes licame were.</L>
<L N="106">&THORN;are-fore &thorn;e pope seint Gregori : prechede heom a day,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are-of schewede heom fair miracle : &thorn;at ech of heom it sai&yogh; :
<PB REF="00000407.tif" N="359"></L>
<L>Of ore louerdes licame a luyte he brac : bi-fore heom ase huy stode:</L>
<L>Sone it bi-cam to a luyte childes fingur : al wringuynde<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> vrninge</NOTE> a-blode.</L>
<L>huy bi-liefden wel &thorn;o aftur-ward : on ihesu crist ech-on,</L>
<L>And onder-stoden &thorn;et sacrement : &thorn;oru&yogh; lore of &thorn;at holie mon.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">110-1 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L N="112">&THORN;us &thorn;e holie man seint Gregori : pope was in rome,</L>
<L>And sende us in-to engelonde : &thorn;e lawes of cristindome.</L>
<L>holi churche and cristindom : &thorn;oru&yogh; him was so i-loked here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he is nou&thorn;e in heouene : with Aungles i-fere.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">v. 114-5 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L N="116">Bidde we &thorn;anne &thorn;ene holie man : apostle of Engelonde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he bi-fore ihesu crist : ore neode ounder-stonde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="51" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>51 Vita sancti Cuthberti.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Cudbert was i-bore : here in Engelonde.</L>
<L>god dude for him gret miracle : ase &yogh;e schulle under-stonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;wyle &thorn;at he was a &yogh;ong child : and in is ei&yogh;teteo&thorn;e &yogh;ere,</L>
<L N="4">With &yogh;ounge children he pleide at&thorn;e bal : &thorn;at is felawes were.</L>
<L>&THORN;are cam gon a luyte child : hit ne &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;reo &yogh;er old,</L>
<L>A swete creature and fair : milde it was and bold;</L>
<L>to &thorn;e &yogh;onge Cudbert he &yogh;eode : "leue bro&thorn;er," he sede,</L>
<L N="8">"Ne &thorn;ench nou&yogh;t on swuche idele games : &thorn;anne dost &thorn;ou a guod dede."</L>
<L>Seint Cudbert ne tok none &yogh;eme : to &thorn;e childes rede,</L>
<L>And pleide forth with his felawes : ase huy alle him bede.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is &yogh;ongue child i-sai&yogh; : &thorn;at he is red for-sok,</L>
<L N="12">A-doun he feol to grounde : and gret deol to him tok,</L>
<L>And bi-gan to weopen sore : and his hondene forto wringue.</L>
<L>&THORN;e children hadden alle deol of him : and bi-lefden heore pleiingue,</L>
<L>huy gladeden him ase huy cou&thorn;en : sore huy gonne to siche;</L>
<L N="16">And euere made &thorn;is &yogh;oungue child : reulich deol i-liche.</L>
<L>"A weilawei," &thorn;is Cudbert seide : "&yogh;wi weopest &thorn;ou so sore?</L>
<L>&YOGH;if we &thorn;e habbez ou&yogh;t mis-don : we ne schullen none more."</L>
<L>&THORN;anne spac &thorn;is &yogh;ounge child&mdash; : for sore huy weopen bei&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="20">"Cuthbert," he seide, "it ne falleth &thorn;e nou&yogh;t : with &yogh;ongue children to plei&yogh;e;</L>
<L>None swuche idele games : ne bi-cometh &thorn;e for-to wurche,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane god hath i-porueid &thorn;e : on heued of holie churche."
<PB REF="00000408.tif" N="360"></L>
<L>With &thorn;usse worde men nusten : &yogh;wodere &thorn;at &yogh;ongue child i-wende&mdash;</L>
<L N="24">An Aungel of heouene it was : &thorn;at ore louerd &thorn;udere sende.</L>
<L>&THORN;o bi-gan<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. bigan gan</NOTE> seint Cudbert : to weope and siche sore,</L>
<L>And lette a-wei is idele games : &thorn;o nolde he plei&yogh;e more:</L>
<L>he made his fader and is freond : setten him to lore,<MILESTONE N="155" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="28">And in his &yogh;onghede ny&yogh;t and day : of-seruede cristes ore.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he in grettore eolde was : ase &thorn;e bok us hauez i-seid,</L>
<L>hit bi-feol &thorn;at &thorn;e bischop seint Aydan : sone &thorn;are-Aftur was ded.</L>
<L>Cudbert a-felde was with schep : Aungles of heouene he i-sei&yogh;</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;e bischopes soule seint Aydan : to heouene bere an hei&yogh;.</L>
<L>"I-nelle schep wite," seint Cudbert seide : "fol ich am to longue,</L>
<L>Schep i-nelle wite none lengore nou&thorn;e&mdash; : a-fongue ho-so heom<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> a|fongue."</L>
<L>he wende to &thorn;e Abbeye of Gireuaus : grei&yogh; monek he bi-cam&mdash;</L>
<L N="36">gret Ioye mauden &thorn;e Monekes alle : &thorn;o he &thorn;e Abite nam.</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e wel he is ordre heold : he was of grete penaunce,</L>
<L>&THORN;e holieste monek he was i-holde : in engelonde o&thorn;ur in Fraunce.&mdash;</L>
<L>hit bi-feol &thorn;are-aftur-ward : &thorn;at &thorn;are cam a goute</L>
<L N="40">In is kneo, of Anguische gret : &yogh;ware-of he hadde doute;</L>
<L>So longue, &thorn;at is kneo to-swal : gret Anguysche he i-fielde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e senewes in is hamme schronken : he ne mi&yogh;te &thorn;anne leg i-wielde,</L>
<L>Ne strechche forth is leg bi-neo&thorn;e : &thorn;at Ioynede to is &thorn;i&yogh;;</L>
<L N="44">Ase a crupel lame he was&mdash;: he i-werth swi&thorn;e sori.</L>
<L>No man ne cou&thorn;e him &thorn;are-of rede : &thorn;at is leg i-sei&yogh;;</L>
<L>Ake nath&thorn;eles euere was is hope : to iesu crist a-hei&yogh;.</L>
<L>In A day, solas for-to habbe : he liet him bere a-boute,</L>
<L N="48">And in &thorn;e fielde he i-mette a wel fair kny&yogh;t : with loreins swi&thorn;e proute.</L>
<L>&THORN;e knyt bad heom one stounde a-bide : &thorn;at seint Cudbert bere;</L>
<L>he bi-heold and handlede &thorn;ane sore leg : ase &thorn;ei he leche were.</L>
<L>"Nim," he seide, "&thorn;e milk of one kov : &thorn;at is of o colour,</L>
<L N="52">Iuys of smal-Ache do &thorn;ar-to : and clene &yogh;wetene flour;</L>
<L>Seoth it to-gadere swi&thorn;e wel : and leie it al hot &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L>A-brod ase &thorn;ei hit a plastre were : and guod it schal &thorn;e do."</L>
<L>&THORN;o he hadde &thorn;is i-seid : &thorn;e kny&yogh;t is wei forth wende&mdash;</L>
<L N="56">An Aungel of heouene it was : &thorn;at ore louerd &thorn;udere sende.
<PB REF="00000409.tif" N="361"></L>
<L>Are seint Cudbert &thorn;e plastre hadde : longue, him &thorn;ou&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. him &thorn;ou&yogh;te</NOTE> to is legge i-bounde,</L>
<L>his leg and is senewes : bi-comen hole and sounde.&mdash;</L>
<L>hit nas nou&yogh;t longue &thorn;are-aftur-ward : ase &thorn;e bok us doth telle,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;at &thorn;e Abbot sende him out : to one of heore celles;</L>
<L>hostiler he was &thorn;are i-mad : gistes to onder-fongue.</L>
<L>god dude fair miracle for him : are he hadde i-beo &thorn;are ou&yogh;t longue.</L>
<L>Aungles &thorn;are comen to him ofte : and with him huy ete</L>
<L N="64">Ase &thorn;ei it o&thorn;ure gistes weren&mdash; : &thorn;e gistningue was ful swete!</L>
<L>gistes wel gladliche &thorn;ene mete he &yogh;af : he nolde no man werne,</L>
<L>heom &thorn;at beden par charite : for he nas no&thorn;ing stuyrne.</L>
<L>him-seolf he wolde &yogh;iue heom watur : to waschen with hire<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. here</NOTE> hond,</L>
<L N="68">And serui heom of alle &thorn;e mes : and bi-fore heom stonde.&mdash;</L>
<L>hit bi-feol &thorn;at an hiendi gist : and a wel fair &thorn;are cam</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;e mete par charite : and Cudbert In him nam;</L>
<L>watur to is hondene he him &yogh;af<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> largeliche</NOTE> : and<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> on &thorn;e hei&yogh;e deis him sette,</L>
<L N="72">Mete and drinke he him &yogh;af : and with guod heorte it fette,<MILESTONE N="155b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>to &thorn;e bachouse he &yogh;eode him-seolf : ase &thorn;e bakares hadden i-bake,</L>
<L>hi[s] giste to fetten bred al hot : &thorn;e gladdore him for-to make.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he cam a-&yogh;ein with &thorn;e hote bred : his gist ne fond he nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;are-of hadde &thorn;is holie man : gret wonder in is &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;icke snov&yogh; was &thorn;are-oute : he ne mi&yogh;te nou&yogh;t finde is fore,</L>
<L>&yogh;ware-forth he wende a-wei : in snowe ne in &thorn;e flore.</L>
<L>Ase he sou&yogh;te &thorn;eosne holie man : a[n] wende a-boute wel wide,</L>
<L N="80">he smulde a suy&thorn;e swote smul : in a chaumbre &thorn;are-bi-side.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he into &thorn;e caumbre cam : he fond a bord i-sprad,</L>
<L>And &thorn;reo loues &thorn;are-op-on al hote. : &thorn;o was he wel glad,</L>
<L>An<SUP>d</SUP> seide, "&thorn;is was godes Aungel : &thorn;at hath &thorn;is hidere i-brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="84">he cam hidere us for-to fede : and him-seolf ne beo i-fed nou&yogh;t."&mdash;</L>
<L>eche ni&yogh;te &yogh;wane &thorn;eos monekes : to bedde weren i-gone,</L>
<L>Cudbert wel stilleliche : wende him forth al one,</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e colde se he &yogh;eode : a-non op to &thorn;e chinne;</L>
<L N="88">For-to hit was midni&yogh;t nei&yogh; : so he stod &thorn;are-inne.</L>
<L>&THORN;anne he wende up &thorn;are-of : and &thorn;o<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> whan</NOTE> he cam to londe,</L>
<L>For feblesse he lai a-doun : he ne mi&yogh;te nou&yogh;t wel stonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;anne comen &thorn;are op of &thorn;e se : tweie oteres wel grete;
<PB REF="00000410.tif" N="362"></L>
<L N="92">Ouer-al huy lickeden &thorn;is holie man : are huy him wolden lete.</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane huy him hadden i-lickede so : huy wenden in-to &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>And seint Cudbert hol and sound : in-to is celle a-&yogh;e;</L>
<L>with o&thorn;ure he &yogh;eode to matynes : &yogh;eorne he song and radde,</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;e Monekes wenden euer-echone : &thorn;at he come fram is bedde.</L>
<L>A monek &thorn;at &thorn;are-inne was : onder-&yogh;at it ech del,</L>
<L>Ake ase seint Cudbert him bad : he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;at he</NOTE> it for-hele[de]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. for hele</NOTE> swi&thorn;e wel.&mdash;</L>
<L>Ase ore louerdes wille was : &thorn;are-aftur it dude bi-falle</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;at &thorn;e bischop of Duyrham deide : al-so we schullen alle:</L>
<L>Men nomen &thorn;o seint Cudbert : and maden him bischop &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Swy&thorn;e wel he wuste is bischopriche : &thorn;at folk he dude wel lere.</L>
<L>&thorn;o was &thorn;at so&thorn;e to ende i-brou&yogh;t : &thorn;at &thorn;e Aungel him seide,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he scholde an heued of holi churche beo : &thorn;o he at&thorn;e bal pleide.</L>
<L N="105">&thorn;o he hadde god i-serued longue : aftur him he sende:</L>
<L>In &thorn;e Mon&thorn;e of luyde : of &thorn;is worlde he wende</L>
<L>to &thorn;e Ioye of heouene. : and god us graunti al-so,</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;oru&yogh; &thorn;e bone of seint cudbert : &thorn;at we moten comen &thorn;ar-to.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="52" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>52 Vita sancti Marci ewangeliste.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Marc, &thorn;e holie godspellare : wide wende in londe</L>
<L>For-to prechi cristine-dom : &thorn;oru&yogh; ore louerdes sonde.</L>
<L>In egypte he prechede longue : and seth&thorn;e at &thorn;en ende</L>
<L N="4">Into &thorn;e lond of Alisaundre : &thorn;annes he gan i-wiende.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he into Alisaundre cam : his on newe scho</L>
<L>with-oute hurtingue of ani-&thorn;ing : gan to berste a-two.</L>
<L>&THORN;o was &thorn;is guode man of-drad : longue he stod in &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="8">And seide, "mi porpos and mi wei : is nou&thorn;e to ende i-brou&yogh;t!</L>
<L>&YOGH;if it mi louerdes wille were : &thorn;at he me wolde &thorn;ane deth sende,<MILESTONE N="156" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ich am redi his wille a-fongue : &yogh;wodere<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &amp; wh.</NOTE> he wole &thorn;at ich<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> to</NOTE> wiende."</L>
<L>he wende forth to a soutere : &yogh;if he is scho makie mi&yogh;te.</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;e soutare at&thorn;e furste stiche : ful vuele is hond he p[r]i&yogh;te.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. pi&yogh;te</NOTE></L>
<L>Sori and wroth &thorn;is soutare was : for him smert so sore.</L>
<L>Seint Marc bi-gan to prechi &thorn;o : and tolde him of godes lore,</L>
<L>And bad him bi-lieue on Iesu crist : and cristine-dom vnder-fongue,</L>
<L N="16">And he is hond hele wolde : &thorn;at i-hurt was so strongue.</L>
<L>Seint Marc with is spottle : watte a luyte vr&thorn;e on &thorn;e grounde
<PB REF="00000411.tif" N="363"></L>
<L>And &thorn;are-with he smeorede his sore hond : and heo werth hol in a stounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e soutere, and alle his, bi-gonne &thorn;o : and euerech &thorn;at in &thorn;e strete cam,</L>
<L N="20">to bi-lieue on crist, godes sone : and a-fenguen cristine-dam.&mdash;</L>
<L>Seint Marc &yogh;eode wide in londe : to prechi godes lawe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince of &thorn;e londe it onder-&yogh;at : and &thorn;ou&yogh;te to don him of dawe.</L>
<L>he liet him seche into al &thorn;at lond : and &thorn;o he him hadde i-founde,</L>
<L N="24">"Ich hote eov," he seide to is men : "&thorn;at he beo faste i-bounde<NOTE PLACE="marg1">v. 24 corrupted.</NOTE></L>
<L>For-to he to &thorn;e prisone come : and &thorn;are-inne &yogh;e him caste a-non."</L>
<L>Ouer-al is flechs was to-drawe : ri&yogh;t to &thorn;e bare bon,</L>
<L>with Irene crokes,as men him drowe : &thorn;e mosseles lei&yogh;en wel grete;</L>
<L N="28">And al blodie weren of is blod : &thorn;e stones in &thorn;e strete.</L>
<L>A-ni&yogh;t, ase he in prisone lai : ore louerd to him cam,</L>
<L>In fourme &thorn;at he on eor&thorn;e was : &thorn;o he manhede nam;</L>
<L>"Marc," he seide, "beo wel glad : and &yogh;arkne &thorn;e wel bliue,</L>
<L N="32">For &thorn;i name is i-write : in eche boke of liue :<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> in &thorn;e b. of eche l.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ov schalt to-morewe for mi loue : soffri deth wel stronge<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. stronde</NOTE></L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e mine blisse of heouene : with-outen ende a-fongue."</L>
<L>Seint Marc &thorn;onkede ore louerd ful &yogh;eorne : ase he<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> and</NOTE> in his bedes lay.</L>
<L N="36">A-morewe &thorn;e prince him liet up fette : sone so it was dai.</L>
<L>A strong rop he liet nime : and a-boute is swere binde,</L>
<L>And teiden<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. teien</NOTE> him seth&thorn;e to a wilde hors : at &thorn;e taile bi-hinde;</L>
<L>he liet him drawe &thorn;oru&yogh; al &thorn;e toun : &thorn;at ech lime fram o&thorn;er wende.</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;us seint Marc &thorn;e holie man : his soule to ore louerd sende.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e Mon&thorn;e of Aueril &thorn;is was. : men scholden faste is eue;</L>
<L>Ake for &thorn;e hei&yogh;e feste of eastur-dai : men it doth bi-leue.</L>
<L>his dai men fastez &thorn;oru&yogh; al &thorn;at lond : for him-seolf nis it nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ake for reuerence of &thorn;e baneres : [&thorn;at] in &thorn;at dai beoth fort i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>For men berez heom eche &yogh;ere a-boute : ase red is &thorn;are-of i-nome,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 45-50 om. in most MSS. (except MS. Vernon).</NOTE></L>
<L N="46">to bidden for &thorn;e eor&thorn;e blede : &thorn;at it mote wel forth come.</L>
<L>Men fastez, &yogh;wane huy formest berez heom out : a-seint Marcus dai &thorn;are-fore,</L>
<L>And &thorn;reo dawes a-&yogh;ein halewe-&thorn;oresday : &yogh;wane huy bez for&thorn;er i-bore.</L>
<L>bidde we nou&thorn;e seint Marc : &yogh;was lijf we habbez i-heord to &thorn;e ende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ore soule mote &thorn;oru&yogh; his Arndingue : into heouene i-wiende.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="53" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000412.tif" N="364">
<HEAD>53 Apostolorum Philippi et Iacobi.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint phelipe and seint Iacob : Apostles weren twei&yogh;e:</L>
<L>&THORN;e formeste dai &thorn;at comez in may : deth huy &thorn;oleden bei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Aftur ore louerdes passione : in &thorn;e twenti&thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Seint phelipe prechede in Sythie : to men &thorn;at lu&thorn;ere weren.<MILESTONE N="156b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;is men nomen seint phelipe : and to heore Maumates<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> maumet</NOTE> him ladde.</L>
<L N="6">And sone so he bi-foren hem cam : &thorn;is maumates loude gradde;</L>
<L>Fuyr huy bleuwen out of heore Mou&thorn;es : &thorn;at &thorn;are-with huy brou&yogh;ten of dawe</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;e princes sone of &thorn;e lond : and tweie constables of &thorn;e lawe;</L>
<L>And manie men &thorn;at &thorn;are-nei&yogh; weren : wel grete siknesse to heom nome,</L>
<L>Some fullen in-to &thorn;e dropesie : and some meoseles bi-come.</L>
<L>Muche reu&thorn;e was into al &thorn;at lond : of &thorn;is misauenture.</L>
<L N="12">"Wulle &yogh;e," seide seint phelip &thorn;o : "mi conseil alle i-huyre,</L>
<L>And ichulle &thorn;oru&yogh; godes grace : helen eov euer[e]ch-on."</L>
<L>Glad was &thorn;is folk of &thorn;at word : and graunteden him a-non.</L>
<L>"berez awei," he seide, "&thorn;is foule wi&yogh;t : &thorn;at &yogh;e habbez to i-bede,</L>
<L N="16">And nimez &thorn;e fourme of &thorn;e holie croiz : and settez in his stude!"</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk was fayn of his bi-heste : i-redie &thorn;are weren i-nowe,</L>
<L>Ane rode huy setten up on hei&yogh; : &thorn;e maumates huy al-to-drowe.</L>
<L>Seint pheolip &thorn;oru&yogh; godes grace : drof out bi-fore heore ei&yogh;e</L>
<L N="20">A foul deouel of &thorn;at on : &thorn;at huy alle i-sei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is rode was up i-set : and &thorn;e Maumet i-brou&yogh;t to grounde,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e sike men &thorn;at &thorn;are-nei&yogh; weren : bi-comen hole and sounde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e &thorn;reo men &thorn;at weren a-slawe : a-&yogh;ein to liue come&mdash;</L>
<L N="24">Muche was &thorn;e Ioye into al &thorn;at lond : &thorn;at men &thorn;are-of nome.</L>
<L>Cristinedom huy guonne a-fongue : and Anouri &thorn;e swete rode,</L>
<L>And bi-lieueden on him &thorn;at bou&yogh;te us alle : &thorn;are-on with is blode.</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; &thorn;e vertuwe of &thorn;is faire miracle : muche folk of &thorn;e londe</L>
<L N="28">bi-gan cristine for-to beo : and &thorn;e ri&yogh;te bi-leue onder-stonde;</L>
<L>After &thorn;e wissingue of seint phelip : alle heore lijf huy guonne lede&mdash;</L>
<L>For prophesie and ri&yogh;t-w[i]snesse : huy heolden al &thorn;at he seide.</L>
<L>&THORN;o phelipe was sixti &yogh;er : and seouene and twenti old,</L>
<L N="32">In pays he deide in his bed : ase &thorn;e bok us hath i-told.
<PB REF="00000413.tif" N="365"></L>
<L>Gret deol &thorn;at folk made &thorn;o : and wel faire huy him nome</L>
<L>And bureden him with gret honour : ase a swuch man to bi-come.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="54" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>54 Vita sancti Iacobi.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Iacob was ore louerdes kun : and ore lauedie soster sone.</L>
<L>telle i-chulle sum-&yogh;wat of ore louerdes kunne : nou&thorn;e it is mi &thorn;ou&yogh;t i-come.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> nou it me come&thorn; in mone</NOTE></L>
<L>Seinte Anne, ore leuedie Moder, : housebondes hadde &thorn;reo:</L>
<L N="4">Ioachim, and cleophas : and &thorn;e &thorn;ridde hiet salomee;</L>
<L>heo hadde euer-ech aftur o&thorn;ur : for heo was i-wedded &thorn;rie;</L>
<L>bi euerech of heom ane dou&yogh;ter heo hadde : and euerech hie&yogh;te marie.</L>
<L>Ioachimes dou&yogh;ter : was eldest of &thorn;e &thorn;reo,</L>
<L N="8">And Iosep hadde i-wedded. : &thorn;e Marie cleophe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was cleophases dou&yogh;ter : and &thorn;e Midleste i-bore,</L>
<L>I-wedded heo was to Zebede : &thorn;at was hire louerd i-core.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;e &yogh;ongeste of alle &thorn;reo : &thorn;e Marie salomee,</L>
<L N="12">to a guod man i-wedded heo was : his name was Alfe.</L>
<L>bi him heo hadde seint Iacob : and al-so tweie o&thorn;ure:</L>
<L>Seint symon and seint Iude : &thorn;at alle &thorn;reo weren i-bro&thorn;re.</L>
<L>&THORN;e midleste soster : &thorn;e Marie cleofe,<MILESTONE N="157" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="16">hadde tweie holie sones : bi hire louerd Zebede:</L>
<L>Seint Ieame &thorn;e holie man : and seint Iohan &thorn;e ewangelist,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was, ich wene, berne best : with ore louerd crist.</L>
<L>&THORN;e eldeste soster of alle &thorn;reo : ore lauedi swete and milde.</L>
<L N="20">heo bar ore louerd Iesu crist : best of alle childe.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heo &thorn;at eldest was : ne hadde child bote on,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e midleste hadde tweie sones : seint Ieame and seint Iohan,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e &yogh;oungueste of &thorn;e &thorn;reo : sones hadde &thorn;reo&mdash;</L>
<L N="24">huy weren ore louerdes cosines : ase &yogh;e mouwen i-seo.</L>
<L>Ech of heom fiue Apostle was : and swi&thorn;e holi man.</L>
<L>telle ichulle of seint Iacob : of &yogh;wam ich formest bi-gan.&mdash;</L>
<L>A-mong men of pharise : &thorn;at lu&thorn;ere weren, he cam.</L>
<L N="28">heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at he scholde beo : A man of gret wisdom:</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore &thorn;e prince of heom : in Ane Ester-day</L>
<L>bad him prechi al &thorn;at folk : a-&yogh;ein godes lay.</L>
<L>Op-on A laddre he sette him hei&yogh;e : &thorn;at men him scholden wide i-seo
<PB REF="00000414.tif" N="366"></L>
<L N="32">And i-heoren him prechi swy&thorn;e wel<NOTE PLACE="marg1">him&mdash;wel <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> : &thorn;at is word &thorn;e bet i-scholde i-leued beo.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he was op on hei&yogh; i-set : and al &thorn;at folk him cam<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> a-boute,</L>
<L>Godes wordes he bi-gan to prechie : he nadde none doute;</L>
<L>he prechede hov he hadde dez i-&thorn;oled : and hou he in &thorn;ulke daie</L>
<L N="36">Fram de&thorn;e to liue a-ros : &thorn;at &thorn;e feond us ne scholde bi-traie,</L>
<L>And hou he us &thorn;e Deuele bi-nam : &thorn;at in his power us hadde longue,</L>
<L>And hou ech man in &thorn;ulke dai&yogh;e : godes flesch scholde a-fongue.</L>
<L>"hou geth &thorn;is?" &thorn;e prince seide : "beo stille, i &thorn;e bi-seche.</L>
<L N="40">Ich bad &thorn;e wanie<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Vern. weyue</NOTE> &thorn;i<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. &thorn;is</NOTE> fole &thorn;ou&yogh;t : and &thorn;ou bi-guynnest it more to eche!"</L>
<L>"Nay," seide seint Iacob to &thorn;e prince : "I-ne eche no folie,</L>
<L>Ake ower fole &thorn;ou&yogh;t ich wolde ou bi-nime : to seggen soth and nou&yogh;t li&yogh;e."</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince for wrath&thorn;e of his prechingue : &thorn;e laddre a-doun gan felle&mdash;</L>
<L N="44">And seint Iacob &thorn;are-opon was : &thorn;are-fore he him wolde a-quelle.</L>
<L>Fram swi&thorn;e hei&yogh;e he ful a-doun. : Ake &thorn;o he was i-falle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ech man wende &thorn;at he were ded : he a-ros up a-mong heom alle,</L>
<L>And prechede eft-sone with glade heorte : ase he er i-don hadde.</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;at folk him nomen swi&thorn;e faste : and to &thorn;e prisone him ladde.</L>
<L>&THORN;are he was in biendes strongue : fram &thorn;at was eastur-dai</L>
<L>For-to cam &thorn;are-afturward : &thorn;e furste dai of Mai.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he out of &thorn;e prisone cam : he bi-gan to prechi bliue,</L>
<L N="52">he ne liet for ei&yogh;e ne for dez : &thorn;e &yogh;wyle he was a-liue.</L>
<L>Mid one follares preche<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. perche</NOTE> : &thorn;at men tesieth opon cloth,</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e scolle he was i-smite : &thorn;at is brain out drof.</L>
<L>his soule, &thorn;o he was ded : to heouene he gan i-wiende.</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;us seint Iacob &thorn;e holie man : brou&yogh;te is lijf to ende.</L>
<L>Apostel he was, and martyr al-so : faste men scholden is eue,</L>
<L>bote for &thorn;e hei&yogh;e Easter feste : men moten it nede bi-leue.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 2 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="55" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>55 Vita sancti Bartholomei.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Bartelmev &thorn;e holie man : cam of kingues blode;<MILESTONE N="157b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Swy&thorn;e fair man and noble he was : and glad &amp; of swete mode.</L>
<L>he siwede ore louerd on eor&thorn;e here : are he deide on &thorn;e rode,</L>
<L N="4">And i-sai&yogh; is priuetez : with &thorn;e o&thorn;ere Apostles guode.
<PB REF="00000415.tif" N="367"></L>
<L>&THORN;o ore louerd was to heouene i-went : he prechede of him wel faste</L>
<L>And wende wide in mani a lond : &thorn;e &yogh;wyle is lijf i-laste.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at to &thorn;e londe of .Inde : he cam &thorn;oru&yogh; godes wille;</L>
<L N="8">At &thorn;e onende of &thorn;e lond : he bi-lefde wel stille.</L>
<L>Ase an vncouth pilegrim : he &yogh;eode up and doun,</L>
<L>he ne seide nei&thorn;er on ne o&thorn;ur : bote bi-heold &thorn;ane toun.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e temple was a fals god : a maumet lu&thorn;ur i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;are-inne was &thorn;e feond of helle : and muche folk to him drov&yogh;&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; huy cleopeden &thorn;at Maumet Astaroth. : &thorn;at &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e deoueles mi&yogh;te</L>
<L>Ofte he wolde Answerie men : and manie<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. nanie</NOTE> he bi-nam heom heore si&yogh;te,</L>
<L>heore speche and heore limes al-so : and dude<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. duden</NOTE> men wo i-nov&yogh;;</L>
<L N="16">&amp; &yogh;wane he a-&yogh;en ani sick man cam<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. cam</NOTE> : of his vuele he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. him</NOTE> with-drou&yogh;,</L>
<L>&THORN;anne was &thorn;e sike man hol anon : ase he moste nede a-mende</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane he ne hadde non o&thorn;ur vuel : bote ase &thorn;e schrewe him sende;</L>
<L>And he with-drov&yogh; him of is vuel : he moste nede hol beo.</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;e schrewe tolde &thorn;e men &thorn;anne : &thorn;at &thorn;is wonder mi&yogh;ten i-seo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hadde &thorn;oru&yogh; is mi&yogh;te : &thorn;e men i-maud hol i-nov&yogh;&mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. Al-&thorn;ei?</NOTE> &thorn;e schrewe ne dude non o&thorn;ur guod : bote of is vuele him with-drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore sike men al dai : ful &thorn;icke a-boute him sou&yogh;te</L>
<L N="24">And criden on him wel deolfulliche : &thorn;at he to hele heom brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&para; Of &thorn;ingue &thorn;at was al-so for-to come : men axeden him feor and neor</L>
<L>And he heom tolde of alle &thorn;ing : &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e deoueles pouwer;</L>
<L>Folk cam &thorn;icke a-bouten him : bi dai&yogh;e and bi ni&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="28">And he ansuerede heom of al &thorn;at huy wolden&mdash; : muche is &thorn;e deoueles mi&yogh;te!</L>
<L>Ake after &thorn;at seint Bartelmev : to &thorn;ulke cite com,</L>
<L>&THORN;e power of &thorn;at false god : clanliche he bi-nom:</L>
<L>For he ne mi&yogh;te aftur &thorn;ulke tyme : with<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> for</NOTE> no man speke ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="32">Ne &yogh;iuen Ansuere of no-&thorn;ing : so he was bi-neo&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk cam &thorn;icke a-boute him : to witen at him heore wille</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ingues, ase huy weren bi-fore i-woned : and euere he was puyr stille.</L>
<L N="35">&THORN;are-fore was wonder inov&yogh; : deol and sor al-so,</L>
<L>huy weren a-ferd to beon for-lore : and &thorn;at huy hadden ou&yogh;t misdo:
<PB REF="00000416.tif" N="368"></L>
<L>to atoun huy wenden &thorn;are-bi-side : &thorn;oru&yogh; heore alre wit,</L>
<L>to an o&thorn;ur Maumet &thorn;at was his felawe : &thorn;at huy cleopeden berit;</L>
<L>huy crieden on him wel deolfulliche : &thorn;at he heom tolde fore</L>
<L N="40">&YOGH;wi Astaroth, heore owene god : his speche hadde for-lore.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e, &yogh;e," seide &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere best : "&yogh;e ne witen nou&yogh;t hou it is?</L>
<L>with strongue chaines al fuyrie : he is i-bounde, i-wis,</L>
<L N="43">For Bartelmev, godes seriaunt : &thorn;at is &thorn;udere i-come</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e cite geth wel stilledeliche : and<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> is power him hath bi-nome</L>
<L>And i-bounde him so faste &thorn;at he ne may : enes drawe is breth,</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;oru&yogh; Anguische is clene ouer-come : ase &thorn;ei he hadde i-&thorn;oled deth."<MILESTONE N="158" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; "&YOGH;wat is [he] &thorn;ilke Bartelmeu&yogh;" : &thorn;eos o&thorn;ere him axeden a-non,</L>
<L N="48">"&THORN;at mai makien ore almi&yogh;tie god : ded so any ston?"</L>
<L>"he is," seide &thorn;is Maumat : "of gret pouwer, ase &yogh;e i-seoth,</L>
<L>he mai do with us al &thorn;at he wole : for bi-neoth&thorn;e him we beoth.</L>
<L>Eche daie an hundret si&thorn;e : and o&thorn;ur swuch bi ni&yogh;te</L>
<L N="52">he knevleth to is god in guode entente : &thorn;at &yogh;ifth him al is mi&yogh;te;</L>
<L>Aungles with him i-nowe he hath : &yogh;ware-&thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;at he may do</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at he wole with us alle : and alle &thorn;ing he wot al-so&mdash;</L>
<L>For he wot nou&thorn;e &thorn;are ase he is : al ore speche and ore &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;are-fore ich rede eov alle wel : &thorn;at &yogh;e ne wrath&thorn;i him nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>ech-manere speche &thorn;at is : he knoweth and speket al-so,</L>
<L>bote at one worde, alle &thorn;ing : he wot &yogh;wat is i-do.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &yogh;e him sechez, &thorn;ei &yogh;e come : ri&yogh;t bi him ase he is,</L>
<L N="60">&YOGH;e ne schulle him nou&yogh;t i-seo : bote him-seolf wolle, i-wis.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;us &yogh;e him mouwe i-knowe : &yogh;if &yogh;e him i-seo :</L>
<L>he is swi&thorn;e long of bodi : of ri&yogh;t fair fourme and freo,</L>
<L>Opri&yogh;t he geoth and euene i-nov&yogh; : and swi&thorn;e &yogh;wij&yogh;t is his bleo,</L>
<L N="64">his her is broun and swi&thorn;e crips : non ne mai cripsore beo,</L>
<L>Muchele ey&yogh;ene and euene nose : i-strei&yogh;t a-doun a-long,</L>
<L>his berd is long and sid i-nou&yogh; : and sum-del hor a-mong;</L>
<L>In a &yogh;wij&yogh;t Golioun he geth : he nath clo&thorn;es non mo&mdash;</L>
<L N="68">Alle &thorn;is sixe-and-twenti &yogh;er : &thorn;ar-inne he hath i-go</L>
<L>&THORN;at fram him it neuer-eft ne cam : ne hit ne a-peirez nou&yogh;t of hewe</L>
<L>Ne for-oldeth nou&yogh;t with-alle : ake is euere i-liche newe.</L>
<L>Wel he wot al &thorn;at &yogh;e spekez : and &yogh;wat &yogh;e doth alle here;
<PB REF="00000417.tif" N="369"></L>
<L N="72">&THORN;are-fore, &yogh;if he eou axeth ou&yogh;t : &yogh;e ne mowen eou nou&yogh;t skere.</L>
<L>Ake &yogh;if he him sewi<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> schewe</NOTE> so : &thorn;at &yogh;e him mowe i-seo,</L>
<L>biddez him for his louerdes loue : &thorn;a<SUP>t</SUP> he beo milde to me,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne come nou&yogh;t here nei&yogh; me : &thorn;at ich beo to grounde i-brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And i-tormented ase mi felawe is&mdash; : for i-nelle mis-don him nou&yogh;t."</L>
<L N="77">&para; &THORN;o &thorn;is fole men &thorn;is i-heorden : huy weren in gret &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And longue heom &thorn;ou&yogh;te are huy hadden : seint Bartelmev&yogh; i-sou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>huy wende a&yogh;en to heore owene temple : ake huy weren alle blinde :</L>
<L N="80">twei dai&yogh;es huy sou&yogh;ten him faste : and ne mi&yogh;ten him nou&yogh;were i-finde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>A</B> dai ase al &thorn;at folk : to &thorn;e temple was i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>for-to honouri heore false god : &thorn;at ne mi&yogh;te heom helpe nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>A guydi man &thorn;are cam al-so : &thorn;at &thorn;e deuel hadde i-beo longue</L>
<L>In him and bi-nomen him is wit : and i-tormented him ful strongue.</L>
<L>A-non so &thorn;is gidie man : in-to &thorn;is temple cam,</L>
<L N="86">&THORN;e deuel &thorn;at in him was : gret deol to him nam,</L>
<L>wel loude he gradde, "seint Bartelmeu&yogh; : ich bi-seche &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;ine oresones brennez me al : &thorn;ou haue merci of me!"</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is holie man stod &thorn;are-bi-side : and answerede him a-non :</L>
<L>"beo doumb!" he seide, "ich &thorn;e rede : &thorn;at &thorn;ou out of him gon."</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel fleu&yogh; a-non with &thorn;at word : out of him in &thorn;ulke place,<MILESTONE N="158b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="92">And &thorn;e sike man<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> bi-cam hol and sound : a-non &thorn;oru&yogh; godes grace.</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk stod al in gret wonder : &thorn;o huy i-sei&yogh;en &thorn;is cas,</L>
<L>And bi-heolden &thorn;ene holie man : &thorn;at of swuch power was,</L>
<L>And tolden wide &thorn;is holie dede : &thorn;at ne mi&yogh;te nou&yogh;t beo i-hud.</L>
<L N="96">In &thorn;usse manere seint Barthelmev&yogh; : was formest in Inde i-kud.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Pollimius hiet &thorn;e kyng : &thorn;at of &thorn;ulke contreie was :</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;e ti&thorn;ingues to him comen : of &thorn;at faire cas.</L>
<L>he hadde ane dou&yogh;ter &thorn;at was lunatyke : &thorn;at &thorn;e deuel hadde muche with to done</L>
<L N="100">And made hire witles<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> biwit</NOTE> euerech month&thorn;e : ase hit feol in &thorn;e stat of &thorn;e mone.</L>
<L>he sente to &thorn;is holie man : seint Barthelmev&yogh; wel sone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he of is dou&yogh;ter hadde reou&thorn;e : and hele hire &thorn;oru&yogh; is bone.</L>
<L>&THORN;udere wende &thorn;is holie man : and &thorn;is mayde founde</L>
<L N="104">Bitinde alle &thorn;at nei&yogh; hire come : and grenninde, faste i-bounde.
<PB REF="00000418.tif" N="370"></L>
<L>&THORN;is holie man stod and bi-heold : &thorn;ene deuel he made out wiende;</L>
<L>hire ri&yogh;te wit heo hadde a-non : euer-eft to hire liues ende.</L>
<L>Welle, glad was hire fader &thorn;o : and elles it were with wou&yogh;.</L>
<L N="108">he liet fette forth riche clo&thorn;us : and gold and seluer inou&yogh;,</L>
<L>And liet chargi Camailes &thorn;are-with : and with riche &yogh;imstones al-so,</L>
<L>to presenti with &thorn;is holie man : &thorn;at swuch dede hadde i-do.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;are nas non &thorn;at mi&yogh;te him finde : &thorn;o huy comen with al &thorn;is pruyte&mdash;</L>
<L N="112">&THORN;are-bi he mi&yogh;ten onder-stonde : &thorn;at he &thorn;ar-of tolde luyte.</L>
<L>And &thorn;o no man ne mi&yogh;te him finde : hit of-&thorn;ou&yogh;te sore &thorn;e kyngue.</L>
<L>Ake nath&thorn;eles &thorn;is holie man : ne for-&yogh;at him of none &thorn;ingue.</L>
<L N="115">A ni&yogh;t ase he lai in his bed : and on him faste &thorn;ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie man stod him bi-fore : he nuste ho him &thorn;udere brou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>"Sire king," he seide, "&yogh;wat was &thorn;e : to siende me swuch pruyte?</L>
<L>&THORN;ov ne paidest me ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t &thorn;are-with : for ich tolde &thorn;ar-of luyte;</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;at tresor &thorn;at ich of telle : &thorn;at is heouene riche,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;at ne roustez ne a-peirez nou&yogh;t : ake euere worth&thorn; i-liche.</L>
<L>And forto techen eov of godes lawe : hidere ich am i-come,</L>
<L>And makie eov leten eouwer false godes : and lieuen on godes sone;<NOTE PLACE="marg1">v. 121-2 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L>For-to techen eov &thorn;ulke lawe : hidere ich am i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="124">And maken eov leten ouwer false godes : &thorn;at ne mouwen eov helpe nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou nelt nou&yogh;t of &thorn;usse &thorn;ingue : i-lieue &thorn;at hit soth beo,</L>
<L>Cum with me to ouwer false god : and &thorn;ov schalt &thorn;e so&thorn;e i-seo."</L>
<L>&THORN;e king wende &thorn;o forth with him : to hore false god a-non.</L>
<L N="128">heore lu&thorn;ere preostes huy founden &thorn;ere : bi-fore him mani on</L>
<L>And duden to him heore sacrefise : ase huy weren i-woned to done.</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel &thorn;at wit-inne him was : wel loude he gradde sone,</L>
<L>And seide, "&yogh;e wrechches, leteth a-non : and ne Anourieth me ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="132">laste &yogh;e beon in swuch torment : ase ich am inne, i-brou&yogh;t!</L>
<L>For Iesu cristes Aungeles : &thorn;at &thorn;e giwes to de&thorn;e brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="134">here beoth faste a-boute me : and bringueth me al-to nou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>with brenninde raketei&yogh;es : huy habbeth me faste i-bounde,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; power of heore hei&yogh;e louerd : &thorn;at &thorn;e giwes &yogh;euen de&thorn;es wounde<MILESTONE N="159" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And he &thorn;are-aftur &thorn;ane &thorn;ridde day : so weilawei &thorn;e stounde,
<PB REF="00000419.tif" N="371"></L>
<L N="138">Fram de&thorn;e to liue he a-ros : and brou&yogh;te us alle to grounde,</L>
<L>And in eche side his apostles sende : to prechie godes name,</L>
<L>And on of <SUP>h</SUP>eom is nou&thorn;e here : &thorn;oru&yogh; &yogh;wam ich habbe &thorn;is schame."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at folk stod and bi-heold a-boute : and nusten &yogh;wuch he was.</L>
<L N="142">Seint Barthelmev&yogh; stod and si&yogh;te sore : and ofte seide alas,</L>
<L>And seide, "nou&thorn;e &yogh;e mouwen i-seo : &yogh;wuch lijf &yogh;e ledeth her,</L>
<L>And in &yogh;wuch a god &yogh;e bi-lieueth : and &yogh;wuch is his pouwer!</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &yogh;e wollez &thorn;at ich bidde for eov : mine louerd &thorn;at us bou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Draweth a-doun ouwer Maumat : ant to-brekez him al-to nou&yogh;te!"</L>
<L N="147">&THORN;o &thorn;e king i-heorde &thorn;is : his men he hiet ech-on</L>
<L>A-bouten him casten strongue ropes : and drawen him a-doun a-non.</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk was &thorn;o redi a-non : and ropes casten on him i-nowe.</L>
<L>Ake huy ne mi&yogh;ten him nou&yogh;t enes wawie : for al &thorn;at huy alle drowe.</L>
<L>"Doth a-wei," quath seint Barthelmev : "and ouwer ropes nimez a-doun!"</L>
<L N="152">And &thorn;o &thorn;e schrewe on-bounde was : seint Barthelmev&yogh; seide is oresoun :</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou deuel," he seide, "&thorn;at hast bi-traid : &thorn;us muche folk ech-on,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt &thorn;at I-ne make &thorn;e nou&yogh;t : to &thorn;e putte of helle gon,</L>
<L>wiend out a-non mid<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> of</NOTE> &thorn;ulke fourme : and brec hit al-to nou&yogh;te!"</L>
<L N="156">&THORN;e deuel a-non with &thorn;ulke worde : wel narewe is wei he sou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And to-bruysde al &thorn;at wrechche maumat : and wiende<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. wiend &thorn;e</NOTE> out &thorn;arof a-non;</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e maumates of &thorn;e temple : heo to-daschten euerech-on.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at folk stod and &thorn;is i-sei&yogh; : and wel loude bi-gonne to crie,</L>
<L N="160">And seiden, "&thorn;are nis bote on al-mi&yogh;ti god : i-boren of &thorn;e mayde marie!"</L>
<L>Seint Barthelmeu criede on Iesu crist : and bad is oresoun.</L>
<L>An Aungel cam so bri&yogh;t so sonne : fram heouene li&yogh;te a-doun,</L>
<L>to &thorn;e four huyrnes he fleu&yogh; a-boute : and in euereche he drou&yogh;</L>
<L N="164">with his finger a wel fair croiz : apert and cler inou&yogh;.</L>
<L>"Mi louerd," he seide, "me sende hidere : and ase he him-seolf me sede,</L>
<L>&THORN;is temple i-chulle bi-fore eou alle : clansi of eche fuyl&thorn;e-hede.</L>
<L>Ake ichulle nou&thorn;e formest &thorn;ene deuel : to eov alle schewen, i-wis,</L>
<L N="168">&THORN;at &yogh;e mouwen &thorn;e so&thorn;e i-sco : &yogh;wuch ouwer bi-leue is.
<PB REF="00000420.tif" N="372"></L>
<L>Ake &thorn;ei he beo grislich for-to bi-holde : ne habbez of him no doute,</L>
<L>Ake swuch signe ase ich habbe i-maud : in &thorn;eos four huyrnes a-boute,</L>
<L>Makiez &thorn;ulke sulue signe : in ouwer fore-heued ech-on,</L>
<L N="172">And ech lu&thorn;ur &thorn;ing euereft schal : fram eou fleon o&thorn;ur gon."</L>
<L>&THORN;o maden huy alle in heore fore-heued : &thorn;e fourme of &thorn;e rode;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Aungel heom scheuwede al a-brod : &thorn;ene deuel ase huy stode,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fourme of a grislich man : &thorn;at al for-broide were</L>
<L>And swarttore &thorn;ane euere ani blou&yogh;man : with foule farinde chere;</L>
<L>A scharp face he hadde and al for-kroked : his berd atelich and long,</L>
<L N="178">Ei&yogh;ene brode al brenninde : red and swart a-mong;</L>
<L>A-non to is fiet tilde is her : and after &thorn;e schrewe sum it drou&yogh;;</L>
<L>his hondene bi-hinden him at his rug&mdash; : huy weren &thorn;are wel i-nou&yogh;!</L>
<L>Fuyrie speldene al stinkende : out of is mouth he blaste,<MILESTONE N="159b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And fuyr of brumston at his nose : &thorn;at stonk al-so foule and faste;</L>
<L>Croked was bo&thorn;e nose and mouth : wrechchede was his bone&mdash;</L>
<L N="184">And bote it<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;is</NOTE> were and<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. ane</NOTE> hendi bacheler : a-bid for-to eft-sone!</L>
<L>Dai&thorn;et habbe swuch a louerding : and alle &thorn;at him wel loue!</L>
<L>&YOGH;eot, &thorn;ei &thorn;e schrewe gret pouwer habbe : god is euere a-boue.</L>
<L>&para; "&THORN;ou lu&thorn;ere &thorn;ing," quath &thorn;is Aungel : "&thorn;at here art nou&thorn;e onder me,</L>
<L N="188">For &thorn;ou dudest Barthelmeus heste : ichulle habbe reu&thorn;e of &thorn;e :</L>
<L>Ichulle &thorn;e onbinde, and late &thorn;e fleo : on eor&thorn;e in eche ende,</L>
<L>For-to &thorn;e dai of dame<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. dome</NOTE> come : &thorn;at &thorn;ou to helle i-wiende."</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere best onbounde was : with wel grisliche bere</L>
<L N="192">he fleu&yogh; a-wei a-mong heom alle : and neuereft ne cam &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e Aungel hadde al &thorn;is ido : to heouene<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. heouene heuene</NOTE> he wende an hei&yogh;.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eorne criede ech of heom : &thorn;at al &thorn;is wonder i-sei&yogh;,</L>
<L>And hereden god, and &thorn;ene Aungel al-so : &thorn;at &thorn;are a-mong heo[m] cam;</L>
<L>huy crieden euere on seint Barthelmev : &thorn;at he &yogh;eue heom cristindom.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at al &thorn;at ilke lond : to cristine-dom was i-brou&yogh;t &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; &thorn;e Aungele and seint barthelmev&mdash; : i-blessede beon huy bo!<NOTE PLACE="marg1">v. 197-8 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="199">Pollimius with is Quene : alle is childrene he nam</L>
<L>And liet heom<NOTE PLACE="marg1">on the margin.</NOTE> baptizen of seint barthelmev&yogh; : and seth&thorn;e al is kinedom;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at al &thorn;at ilke lond : to cristinedom was i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="202">&THORN;e king for-sok al is lond : and ne tolde &thorn;arof ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t,
<PB REF="00000421.tif" N="373"></L>
<L>And wende and siwede seint Barthelmeu&yogh; : and prechede with him wel faste,</L>
<L>And bi-cam swi&thorn;e holi man : and was bischop at &thorn;e laste.</L>
<L>&para; Ane bro&thorn;er, herre kyng &thorn;ane he was : he hadde, of grete pruyte,</L>
<L N="206">Astriages was is name : &thorn;are-bi-side a luyte.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ty&thorn;ingue of seint Barthelmeu&yogh; : wel sone to him cam,</L>
<L>Al-hou he hadde &thorn;ene king is bro&thorn;er : i-turned to cristinedam :</L>
<L>A &thorn;ousend men wel j-Armede : After him he sende</L>
<L N="210">For-to enqueri in-to al &thorn;at lond : &yogh;woder-ward he wende.</L>
<L>huy wenden and sou&yogh;ten him ful stuyrneliche : and &thorn;o he was i-founde,</L>
<L>bi-fore heore kingue Astriages : huy brou&yogh;ten him, faste i-bounde,</L>
<L>And swi&thorn;e ofte he was with heom i-pult : &thorn;at he feol a-doun to grounde.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">v. 213 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; "Bel ami," seide Astriages &thorn;e king : "hou hauest &thorn;ou on i-take?</L>
<L>hast &thorn;ou mine bro&thorn;ur with tricherie : i-maked mi godes for-sake,</L>
<L N="216">bi &thorn;e fei &thorn;at i schal to mahun : ichulle serui &thorn;e al-so</L>
<L>And make &thorn;e bi-leue &thorn;ine false god : o&thorn;ur to strongue de&thorn;e &thorn;e do.</L>
<L>And &yogh;eot, &thorn;eof, more schame opon o&thorn;ur : ase ich i-heore<NOTE PLACE="marg1">ich iheore <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> bi mannes sawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ov hast ore godes elles-&yogh;ware : defoulet and al-to-drawe."</L>
<L N="220">&para; "Sire king," quath seint Barthelmeu&yogh; : "&thorn;ou ne seist nou&yogh;t as &thorn;e hiende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at i scholde with tricherie : &thorn;ine bro&thorn;eres heorte wiende;</L>
<L>with no tricherie ne wende ich him : ake with soth&thorn;enesse and with ri&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Ich brou&yogh;te him out of mis-bi-leue : to him &thorn;at [hath]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> alle mi&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="224">Fram &thorn;e godes &thorn;at beoth al-so mi&yogh;te-lese : ase is &thorn;at dede treo</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich liet al-to-drawe. : and &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt &thorn;e so&thorn;e i-seo,</L>
<L>bring me to &thorn;ine o&thorn;ur god : and &yogh;if ich mai don swuch dede,<MILESTONE N="160" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I-lief wel &thorn;at he is mi&yogh;teles : and for-sak &thorn;ou him, ich rede.</L>
<L N="228">And with &thorn;ulke god &thorn;at ich on bi-lieue : &yogh;if &thorn;ou mi&yogh;t so on take,</L>
<L>Ich rede &thorn;at &thorn;ou a-cordi &thorn;e : and &thorn;ine owene god for-sake;<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Ich &thorn;e bihote truliche : &thorn;at ich him wole forsake.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;at ich mai &thorn;oru strenc&thorn;e of mi louerd : &thorn;inne god ouer-come,</L>
<L>For-sak &thorn;e wrechches ase huy beoth wuyr&thorn;e : for heore mi&yogh;te heom is bi-nome."
<PB REF="00000422.tif" N="374"></L>
<L N="232">Nadde he bote &thorn;is word i-seid : &thorn;at &thorn;are ne cam to &thorn;e kingue</L>
<L>A messager wel hasteliche : &thorn;at brou&yogh;te him ful sori ti&thorn;ingue :</L>
<L>&THORN;at berit is owene god : &thorn;at he wel ofte sou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>was i-falle of &thorn;e temple a-doun : and al to-dascht to nou&yogh;te.</L>
<L N="236">&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e king i-heorde &thorn;is : sori he was i-nou&yogh;,</L>
<L>he fierde ase a man &thorn;at witles were : and is clo&thorn;es al to-drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>he liet nime seint barthelmeu : and tormenti him wel faste</L>
<L>And with grete staues legge on him : &thorn;e &yogh;wyle huy wolden i-laste.</L>
<L N="240">&THORN;o he was defoulet so : &thorn;at reou&thorn;e it was to wite,</L>
<L>Ase we findez in some stude : of his liue i-write,</L>
<L>&para; He liet him don on a rode : is heued toward &thorn;e grounde,</L>
<L>Fiet and hondene to &thorn;e treo : i-nailled and faste<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> o&thorn;er</NOTE> i-bounde;</L>
<L N="244">And seth, to don him more pine : ase we findez i-w[r]ite al-so,</L>
<L>&THORN;o he hadde &thorn;eron i-honged longue : he liet him a-doun do</L>
<L>And liet huylden is fel al fram is flechs : al quik with kene knyue;</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t ase men huyldeth a ded oxe : men hulden him a-liue.</L>
<L>Alas, hou mi&yogh;ten huy habben &thorn;e heorte? : alas, &thorn;e deolfulle pine!</L>
<L>louerd, muche is &thorn;i mi&yogh;te : ase &thorn;ov scheoudest &thorn;are bi &thorn;ine hine!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="250">At&thorn;e laste &thorn;o he was i-huld : ase we findez i-writen al-so,</L>
<L>huy smiten of is holie heued : are huy mi&yogh;ten him to de&thorn;e do&mdash;</L>
<L N="252">Vnne&thorn;e huy mi&yogh;ten mid al <SUP>&thorn;</SUP>is wo : bringue is lijf to fine.</L>
<L>Muche wonder was &thorn;at ani lijf mi&yogh;te : on eor&thorn;e &thorn;olie swuch pine!<NOTE PLACE="marg1">v. 252-3 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L>his bodi was &thorn;oru&yogh; cristine men : i-bured faire i-nou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Wel &thorn;icke, ase huy dorsten : &thorn;at folk &thorn;udere-ward drou&yogh; :</L>
<L N="256">For ore louerd anon-ri&yogh;t for is loue : fair miracle &thorn;are sende;</L>
<L>&YOGH;ware-fore guode men &thorn;are-a-boute : wel &thorn;icke &thorn;udere wende.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e lu&thorn;ere king Astriages : &thorn;at him liet so a-quelle,</L>
<L>he dradde him sumdel of &thorn;e miracles : &thorn;o he heorde &thorn;ar-of telle :</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;ane &thorn;reotteo&thorn;e dai &thorn;are-afterward : &thorn;at he liet him martri &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e grete maistres he nam with him : &thorn;at of &thorn;e temple were,</L>
<L>And to is toumbe huy wenden alle : &thorn;are ase &thorn;at holie bodi lai.</L>
<L>Anon so huy &thorn;udere comen : ase al &thorn;at folk i-say,</L>
<L N="264">&THORN;e deuel, &thorn;at heore maister was : tormentede heom a-non :</L>
<L>For wreche of &thorn;at holie man : huy bi-comen guydie ech-on,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &aelig;chon</NOTE></L>
<L>And ase for-lorene wrechches huy deiden &thorn;o : he ne liet heom no leng gon;
<PB REF="00000423.tif" N="375"></L>
<L>Into helle &thorn;e soulene with him he nam : &thorn;are ne liet he nou&yogh;t on.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e ty&thorn;ingue was sone wide i-brou&yogh;t. : huy dradden heom wel sore</L>
<L>&THORN;at of mis-bi-leue weren : huy ne dorsten &thorn;o non-more,</L>
<L N="270">Ake huy for-soken hore false lawe : and beden ore louerdes ore,</L>
<L>And lieten heom cristni euerech-one : &thorn;oru&yogh; seint Barthelmeus lore.<MILESTONE N="160b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>POllonius, &thorn;at kyng was er : and &thorn;at to ore louerdes lawe him nam,</L>
<L>bischop huy maden him ouer heom alle : to holden op cristin|dom.</L>
<L N="274">he was bischop twenti &yogh;er : are he dude heonne i-wiende;</L>
<L>to &thorn;e Ioye of heouene is soule wende : at&thorn;e twenti &yogh;eres ende.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">v. 276-311 om. in Ashm. &amp; Vern.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L N="276">&THORN;are was of seint Barthelmeu&yogh; : Miracles euere i-nowe,</L>
<L>And wel &thorn;icke al-a-boute to is toumbe : muche folk euere drowe.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eot &thorn;are weren lu&thorn;ere men bi-leued : and hadden &thorn;a[r]to envie,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he bi-liefden nou&yogh;t &thorn;at ore louerd was i-bore : of &thorn;e maidene Marie :</L>
<L N="280">A veteles huy maden al of led : and &thorn;are-inne huy caste</L>
<L>&THORN;is holi bodi wel fijlliche : and dutten it swy&thorn;e faste,</L>
<L>And amidde &thorn;e se casten hit : and wolden deliueren heom so.</L>
<L>Ake &yogh;eot ore louerd cudde is mi&yogh;te : ase he hath ofte i-do :</L>
<L N="284">For &thorn;at ilke led a-&yogh;ein is kuynde : &thorn;ei it vuele were is ri&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Aboue &thorn;e watere it gan to fleote&mdash; : &thorn;are was godes mi&yogh;te!&mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at watur nadde power non : to holden it to &thorn;e grounde.</L>
<L>to &thorn;e cite of lupar it flet : and &thorn;are it was furst i-founde,</L>
<L N="288">And of cristine men op I-nome : and faire on eor&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eot ore louerd, &thorn;ei he were &thorn;are : he ne for-&yogh;at him ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t :</L>
<L>For he sende miracles riuedeliche : a-boute &thorn;e bodie &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>At&thorn;e laste some lu&thorn;ere men : &thorn;at in &thorn;e londe were</L>
<L N="292">hadden &thorn;ar-to &yogh;eot gret onde : and in a tyme bi-stelen &thorn;are-to</L>
<L>And nomen &thorn;e bones up fram &thorn;e stude : &thorn;at huy weren inne i-do,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e contreie a-boute heom bere : and casten euerech in his side,</L>
<L N="295">Some in one stude and some in o&thorn;ur : and to-spradden heom so wel wide,</L>
<L>For huy ne scholden neuereft to-gadere come : ne more miracle do.</L>
<L>So<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> longue, ase godes wille was : defoulede huy weren so.
<PB REF="00000424.tif" N="376"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="298">SEint Barthelmeu&yogh; cam seth&thorn;e : to a monek &thorn;are-bi-side :</L>
<L>"Mine bones," he seide, "beoth i-cast : and al-to-spradde wel wide :</L>
<L N="300">I-nelle non-more &thorn;at huy beon so : &thorn;are-fore &thorn;ou most gon</L>
<L>&THORN;is ny&yogh;t a-boute &thorn;are huy beoth : and to-gadere heom bringue ech-on."</L>
<L>"A, sire, merci," &thorn;is Monek seide : "hou scholde ich i-knowe heom nov?"</L>
<L>"Swi&thorn;e wel," seide &thorn;is holie man : "and ichulle &thorn;e tellen hou :</L>
<L N="304">Euerech of heom &thorn;are huy liggez : &thorn;ei it deork ni&yogh;t beo,</L>
<L>Schyne schullen ase bri&yogh;te ase sonne : &thorn;at wel feor &thorn;ou schalt heom i-seo."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is Monek wende forth bi ni&yogh;te : he ne fond of heom nou&yogh;t on</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy ne schinen ase clere ase ani sonne. : and so he gaderede heom ech-on.</L>
<L>In a schip he brou&yogh;te heom in &thorn;e se : with gret honour at-&thorn;enende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;wodere-so ore louerd wolde : &thorn;oru&yogh; is wille [he] heom sende.</L>
<L N="310">A wynd &thorn;are cam and drof &thorn;at schip : softe and euene i-nou&yogh;;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at to &thorn;e londe of a-puyle : &thorn;at schip wel euene drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;are weren &thorn;e bones faire onder-fongue : and faire in schrine i-do.</L>
<L>Mani fair Miracle &thorn;are comen sone : And &yogh;eot &thorn;are doth al-so.</L>
<L N="314">Bidde we nou&thorn;e seint Barthelmev&yogh; : &thorn;at hei&yogh; Apostle is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we moten &thorn;oru&yogh; his bone : come to heouene blis. AmeN!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="56" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>56 [Thomas ap.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Thomas &thorn;e guode Apostle : I-martred was in .Inde;<MILESTONE N="161" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of is lif we moten rede : ase we in boke doth&thorn; finde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;wyle ore louerd on eor&thorn;e was : with him he wende a-boute.</L>
<L>Men cleopeden him seth&thorn;e ane to-nome : "Thomas longue in doute :"</L>
<L>For &thorn;o ore louerd fram de&thorn;e to liue a-ros : In doute &thorn;ar-of he was;</L>
<L N="6">&THORN;e Apostles it leueden ech-one wel : bote &thorn;is ilke seint Thomas,</L>
<L>Bote he seide &thorn;at he it nolde i-leue : bote he sei&yogh;e is wounde</L>
<L N="8">And handlede as and &thorn;erinne pulte : is finguer o&thorn;ur is &thorn;ombe<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> to &thorn;e grounde</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;is Mis-bileue men him cleopeden : "Thomas longue in doute,"</L>
<L>Ase men redeth &yogh;eot in holie churche : &yogh;wan is dai cometh a-boute.</L>
<L>&para; Seth&thorn;e cam ore louerd crist : mid is woundes al a-blode</L>
<L N="12">To him and to is desciples : &thorn;are huy to-gadere stode;
<PB REF="00000425.tif" N="377"></L>
<L>Ore louerd seide, "Thomas, hider &thorn;i finguer : ant pult here into mi side,</L>
<L>And ne beo nou&yogh;t in mis-bi-leue : for mine woundene &thorn;ou sixt wide."</L>
<L N="15">&THORN;o bi-liefde he wel &thorn;at it was soth : and al-so euereft more;</L>
<L>"Mi louerd," he seide, "and mi god : ich bidde &thorn;e milce and ore!"</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at he &thorn;e so&thorn;e i-sai&yogh; : ore louerd he louede faste,</L>
<L>And prechede is manhede and cristinedom : &thorn;e &yogh;wile is lif i-laste.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; It bi-feol, longue after &thorn;e tyme : &thorn;at ore louerd to heouene wende,</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at Gondofre, &thorn;e king of Inde : wel wide a-boute sende</L>
<L>&YOGH;if man mi&yogh;hte ani Carpenter : finde, quoynte and slei&yogh;h,</L>
<L>In anie londe, &thorn;at him cou&thorn;e a-rere : a paleys noble and hei&yogh;h.</L>
<L>In &thorn;e londe of cesaree : seint Thomas was &thorn;o :</L>
<L N="24"><SUP>o</SUP>vre louerd a-li&yogh;hte a-doun fram heouene : and a&yogh;ein him cam go,</L>
<L>"Thomas," he seide, "&thorn;e king of Inde : haueth i-sent here-nei&yogh;h</L>
<L>To furie<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> seche</NOTE> after a Carpenter : &thorn;at were quointe and slei&yogh;h :</L>
<L>Cum here with me, and ichulle : &thorn;udere to him &thorn;e sende."</L>
<L N="28">"A., louerd, &thorn;in ore," quath seint Thomas : "I-ne rechche &yogh;wodere ich wiende,</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;at I-ne come nou&yogh;t in Inde : for &thorn;ar-of me deth a-grise;</L>
<L>Siend me elles &yogh;wodere &thorn;ou wolt : ac &thorn;udere in none wise!"</L>
<L>&para; "&THORN;ou schalt wiende &thorn;udere," ore louerd seide : "and ichulle beon with &thorn;e.</L>
<L N="32">And &yogh;wane &thorn;ou hast &thorn;oru&yogh;h &thorn;i prechingue : &thorn;at lond-folc i-brou&yogh;ht to me,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt &thorn;are i-martred beon : and to me &thorn;anne i-wiende.</L>
<L>Go we to &thorn;is Messager : and &thorn;udere ichulle &thorn;e siende."</L>
<L>huy come and metten &thorn;is Messager : &thorn;at brou&yogh;te &thorn;is ty&thorn;ingue,</L>
<L N="36">Ase he cam furst op of &thorn;e se : a-middes &thorn;e Chepingue&mdash;</L>
<L>Aben he was i-hote. : ore louerd hine &thorn;are mette,</L>
<L>And axede &yogh;wat he &thorn;ere sou&yogh;hte : and wel faire he him grette.</L>
<L>&para; "Mi louerd Gondofre," quath Aben : "&thorn;at is kyng of Inde,</L>
<L N="40">Sende me hidere &yogh;if &thorn;at ich mi&yogh;hte : ani quoynte Carpenter finde</L>
<L>And &thorn;at [ich], hou-so ich euere on toke : in alle manere him brou&yogh;te :</L>
<L>&THORN;at [ich] with Catele, &yogh;if he were &thorn;ral : of is louerd him bou&yogh;te</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ich him,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. him</NOTE> &yogh;if he freo man were : huyrde him deore i-nou&yogh;h;</L>
<L>And for-to do sum-&yogh;ware mi neode : hider-ward ich drou&yogh;h."
<PB REF="00000426.tif" N="378"></L>
<L>&para; "Ich habbe ane man," ore louerd seide : "&thorn;at ri&yogh;ht min owene is,</L>
<L N="46">&THORN;at &yogh;wanne ich him ofte a-boute sende : wel he wrou&yogh;hte, i-wis,<MILESTONE N="161b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And dude is mester swi&thorn;e wel : &yogh;wodere he euere i-wende,</L>
<L>And euere al &thorn;at he mi&yogh;hte bi-&yogh;ite<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &yogh;e&dotb;<SUP>i</SUP>te</NOTE> : he brou&yogh;te me o&thorn;ur sende.</L>
<L>For quoyntore bold he can make : &thorn;ane euere in Inde were;</L>
<L>Ne swuch man nis &thorn;are in Inde non : &thorn;at swuch bold cou&thorn;e a-rere."<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 2 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ore louerd tok seint Thomas : Aben bi &thorn;e honde;</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;at ope &thorn;e forewarde &thorn;at he made : ladde him to is londe.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 2 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Aben ope &thorn;is forewarde : glad and bli&thorn;e was;</L>
<L>Into schipe he wende a-non : with &thorn;e guode man seint Thomas.</L>
<L>Sone he axede seint Thomas : ase huy in &thorn;e se i-wende,</L>
<L N="56">&YOGH;we&thorn;er he puyrliche is man were : &thorn;at him &thorn;udere sende.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;if ich nadde," quath seint Thomas : "puyrliche is man i-beo,</L>
<L>Mi manhe[de]<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> his manrede</NOTE> ich wolde habbe for-sake : &thorn;o he bi-tok me &thorn;e."</L>
<L>"Sei&yogh;e &thorn;ou me," quath Aben, "&yogh;eot : &yogh;wat is &thorn;i seruise?</L>
<L N="60">&YOGH;ware-of seruest &thorn;ou &thorn;at hei&yogh;e Man : &thorn;at &yogh;e beon bo&thorn;e so wise?"</L>
<L>&para; "A carpenter," quath seint Thomas : "ich am, quoynte and slei&yogh;h,</L>
<L>paleys and bold ich can arere : swi&thorn;e noble and hei&yogh;h,</L>
<L>strong and li&yogh;t and swi&thorn;e fair : with-outen and with-inne,</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;at no man ne may it felle a-doun : with strenc&thorn;e ne with ginne,</L>
<L>Ne so strong wynd ne tempeste : &thorn;at greuie mouwe it ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>So quoynte bold nas neuere on eor&thorn;e : to no prince i-wrou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>"Deu merci," quath &thorn;is Aben : "&thorn;at &thorn;i louerd gret Man is,</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;at so quoynte Men hat onder him : i-not non swuch, i-wis!"</L>
<L>&para; "Hei&yogh;h Man he is," quath seint Thomas : "and an hei&yogh; kyngues sone.</L>
<L>Ope ane hei&yogh;e Montayngne his wonijngue is : &thorn;are he wole euere wone;</L>
<L>&THORN;are he halt is heritage : and is fader kynedom an hei&yogh;h;</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;are nis non of is fon so strong : &thorn;at mouwe come &thorn;ere-nei&yogh;h.</L>
<L>Sik man ne pouere nis &thorn;are non : so riche &thorn;at lond is;</L>
<L>So murie lond nas neuere i-sei&yogh;e : ne of swuch solas ne blis."</L>
<L>Tellinde, huy rouweden forth in &thorn;e se : so &thorn;at &thorn;oru&yogh; guod winde</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;ene seue&thorn;e day huy comen a-lond : wel a &thorn;eos half Inde.</L>
<L>&para; At ane hei&yogh;e toune huy a-riueden : &thorn;are a kyng inne lay</L>
<L>&THORN;at liet weddi to an hei&yogh;h Man : his dou&yogh;hter &thorn;at ilke day.
<PB REF="00000427.tif" N="379"></L>
<L>At &thorn;is bruydale was plei i-nou&yogh;h : song and gret hoppingue,</L>
<L N="80">Tabours and fi&thorn;ele and symphanye : stiues and harpingue.</L>
<L>Seint Thomas and &thorn;is Aben : wenden to &thorn;is feste,</L>
<L>So Manie Men wel ofte doth : with li&yogh;t biddingue o&thorn;ur heste.</L>
<L>&para; A Taborere song at&thorn;e mete : ase it is<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.; r. ire?</NOTE> ri&yogh;hte was.</L>
<L>Ase he eode singuynde op an doun : he bi-heold on seint Thomas :</L>
<L>hire<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. him</NOTE> &thorn;ou&yogh;hte &thorn;at he was cristine man : to pai&yogh;en him he gan singue</L>
<L N="86">"Cristine men habbez ane god : louerd of alle &thorn;ingue."</L>
<L>&THORN;o seint Thomas &thorn;is i-heorde : he bad hire singue eft-sone.</L>
<L>&THORN;is taborere song up an doun : and dude seint Thomas bone.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Botiler chidde with seint Thomas : for he made hire singue more,</L>
<L N="90">And smot him a boffat onder &thorn;e Ere : &thorn;at him smert ful sore.</L>
<L>&para; "I-nelle nou&yogh;t a-rise," quath seint Thomas : "heonne fram mi fere<MILESTONE N="162" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Are ich i-seo an hound bringue &thorn;ulke hond : a-mong al &thorn;is folke here."</L>
<L N="93">&THORN;o &thorn;at folk hadde al-mest i-&yogh;ete : &thorn;e Botiler wende sone</L>
<L>Out to ane welle to fechche in watur : ase he hadde &thorn;are-with to done.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he out to &thorn;e welle cam : a leon &thorn;ere cam gon</L>
<L N="96">Ant hente &thorn;ene botiler bi &thorn;e &thorn;rote : and a-stranglede him a-non,</L>
<L>And to-drou&yogh;h ech lime fram o&thorn;ur. : an hound &thorn;ere cam bi cas</L>
<L>And kipte up &thorn;e hond in is mouth : &thorn;at he smot with seint Thomas,</L>
<L>And bar as in bi-fore al &thorn;at folk : and so bi-fore &thorn;e kingue.</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;are nas non &thorn;at &thorn;is i-sai&yogh;h : &thorn;at ne wondreden of &thorn;at &thorn;ingue,</L>
<L>And seiden, "&thorn;is is an holi Man : &thorn;at god deth fore swuch dede :</L>
<L N="102">For bi &thorn;e botilere it is icome : ri&yogh;ht ase he er seide."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e kyng liet cleopie bi-fore him : seint Thomas a-non,</L>
<L>And seide, "&thorn;ou art an holi man : &thorn;at &thorn;us a-wrecxt &thorn;e of &thorn;ine fon :</L>
<L N="105">&THORN;ou schalt with me to mi dou&yogh;ter : into hire chaumbre wende</L>
<L>And blessi hire, and hire spouse : &thorn;at huy habben &thorn;e bettere ende."</L>
<L>Seint Thomas with &thorn;e king : in-to chaumbre gan gon;</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;at &yogh;ongue wif and hire spouse : a-&yogh;ein him come a-non.</L>
<L>Seint Thomas is holie hond : ope bei&yogh;e heore heuedes leide</L>
<L N="110">And blessede heom a-godes name : and is oresun seide.</L>
<L>&para; he nam is leue and wende a-&yogh;ein : and &thorn;e &yogh;ongue spouse</L>
<L>ladde him forth &amp; &thorn;onkede him : &thorn;at he cam in &thorn;e house.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">This verse on the margin.</NOTE></L>
<L>A &yogh;eord of palm cam in is hond : he nuste hou it cam,
<PB REF="00000428.tif" N="380"></L>
<L N="114">Ase he ladde seint Thomas&mdash; : wel gladliche he it nam :</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;eord was ful of Dates : wexinde ase &thorn;ei huy were.</L>
<L>Gret wonder and ioye huy [hadden] : of &thorn;is miracle &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;is &yogh;ounge Man bar is &yogh;onge wif : &thorn;is fruyt so guod and suete;</L>
<L N="118">Of &thorn;at fruyt huy nomen bo&thorn;e : and gladliche &thorn;ar-of ete.</L>
<L>&para; Sone &thorn;o huy hadden &thorn;arof i-ete : huy ne mi&yogh;hten no feor gon,</L>
<L>Ake ay&thorn;er lai a-doun bi o&thorn;ur : and softe slepen a-non.</L>
<L>Men beddeden heom ase softe ase huy mi&yogh;hten : and palles on heom caste,</L>
<L N="122">And wenden alle out bote heom-suluen two : and &thorn;e doren maden faste.</L>
<L>Ase huy lei&yogh;e bo&thorn;e and slepen : a fair king to heom cam,</L>
<L>And bi-twene heom stod, in fair Abite : and bi-tweone is Armes heom nam;</L>
<L>"Mine leoue children," he seide : "min apostle &thorn;at was her</L>
<L N="126">Blessede eov for &thorn;at &yogh;e scholden : of heouene beo parteners :</L>
<L>Doth&thorn; aftur him, and &yogh;e schullen beo : &thorn;are with-outen ende."</L>
<L>Stille he liet heom ligge and slepe : and wel softe a&yogh;ein gan wende.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o huy a-woken, huy lei&yogh;en and tolden : hou &thorn;at it beo mi&yogh;hte;</L>
<L>gret wonder huy hadden for huy nusten : nou&yogh;ht of &thorn;is noble si&yogh;hte.</L>
<L N="131">Ase huy lei&yogh;en and herof tolden : seint Thomas to hom<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. him</NOTE> wende;</L>
<L>"&THORN;e kyng," he seide, "&thorn;at with eov spak : hidere to eov me sende&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei &yogh;ates and doren beo faste imade : he hath [me] in i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &yogh;e wollez &thorn;e Ioye a-fongue : &thorn;at he haueth to eov i-wrou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>And his blessingue &thorn;at ich eov &yogh;af : &thorn;oru&yogh; me witez al-so,</L>
<L N="136">In Ioye and blisse with-outen ende : of heouene he wole eov do.</L>
<L>For &yogh;e habbez &yogh;eot ouwer Maiden-hod : &thorn;at of eche guodnesse is quene,<MILESTONE N="162b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at neuere ne a-dwynet bi-fore god : ac euere is bri&yogh;t and schene."</L>
<L>&THORN;is &yogh;ongues<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &yogh;onge &thorn;inges</NOTE> feollen a-doun : to seint Thomas a-kneo,</L>
<L N="140">And crieden on him &thorn;at he heom tei&yogh;te : in guode liue to beo.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Thomas heom prechede anon : hou it of ore louerd is,</L>
<L>And brou&yogh;te heom bo&thorn;e to cristindom : and &thorn;e kingue and alle his.</L>
<L>On of his desciples seth&thorn;e he nam : &thorn;at het dyonis,</L>
<L N="144">And made him maister of &thorn;at folk : &thorn;at huy ne wrou&yogh;ten amis;</L>
<L>&THORN;esne dyonis he made preost : and ane churche he liet arere.
<PB REF="00000429.tif" N="381"></L>
<L>&THORN;at folk cam eche daye : and heor[d]e<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. heore</NOTE> seruise &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at lond was al i-brou&yogh;t : in guod stat i-nov,</L>
<L N="148">Seint Thomas is leue nam : and toward Inde him drov.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; Anon so Aben, &thorn;at cam aftur him : to Inde mi&yogh;hte him bringue,</L>
<L>with gret Ioye he ladde him forth : and brou&yogh;te him bi-fore &thorn;e kingue.</L>
<L>To a fair place &thorn;e kyng him ladde : and axede him on alle wise</L>
<L N="152">&YOGH;if he cou&thorn;e &thorn;ere swuch bold a-rere : ase he him cou&thorn;e deuise.</L>
<L>Seint Thomas bi-heold &thorn;is noble place : "sire," he seide, "&yogh;e,</L>
<L>So fair bold nis in al &thorn;is lond : ase ich can here arere &thorn;e."</L>
<L>Ane perche he nam, and mat a-boute : hou<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> as</NOTE> ech hous scholde beo.</L>
<L N="156">&para; "Sire," he seide, "mi deuis : &thorn;ou schalt here i-seo :</L>
<L>&THORN;e halle ichulle furst arere : in &thorn;is place in alle wise,</L>
<L>Est-ward &thorn;e dore and &thorn;e proche : ri&yogh;ht ase &thorn;e sonne arisez,</L>
<L N="159">&THORN;at &thorn;e sonne &yogh;wane heo a-rist : at&thorn;e dore in schine;</L>
<L>here &yogh;ond ichulle &thorn;e chaumbres habbe :<NOTE PLACE="marg1">A v. om. : : ymete by myne lyne, Here &yogh;ond ichulle &thorn;e kuchen habbe :</NOTE> And a conduyt &thorn;are-bi-side."</L>
<L>he deuisede [al] euene inov : and longue i-nou&yogh; and wide,</L>
<L>So noble bold ne mi&yogh;hte non beo : ase he gan &thorn;are deuise.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e kyng of is sotilte : bi-gan sum-del a-grise,</L>
<L N="164">And seide, "certus, ich &yogh;iue &thorn;e pris : of &thorn;e beste Carpenter</L>
<L>And &thorn;e quoynteste &thorn;at ich euere i-knev : and best deuised<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> deuisest</NOTE> her."</L>
<L>he toc him catel<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> gareisoun</NOTE> i-nov&yogh; : swuch bold with to rere;</L>
<L>And wende him-sulf out of &thorn;e lond : &thorn;at to &yogh;er ne cam he &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="168">Seint Thomas &thorn;is tresor nam : and wide wende in londe</L>
<L>And prechede Men of cristindom : and of god to vnder-stonde;</L>
<L>&THORN;at tresor he delde pouere men : euere &yogh;ware he heom founde.</L>
<L>&para; Muche folk he brou&yogh;te to cristindom : a-boute into al &thorn;at londe;</L>
<L N="172">&para; Churchene he arerde mani on : and preostes he sette &thorn;ere&mdash;</L>
<L>Swich quoynte bold and noble it was : &thorn;at he wolde &thorn;e kyngue a-rere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde &yogh;er &thorn;e king cam hom : and wende al-&yogh;are to finde</L>
<L>his bold ase he hadde bi-speke. : and &thorn;o was it al bi-hinde.</L>
<L N="176">After seint Thomas he sende a-non : &thorn;at bi-traide him so, he seide.</L>
<L>Sone Men tolden him hou it was : and al of is dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king liet him nimen a-non : and in strongue prisone him do,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">A v. om.: &amp; Aban &thorn;at him &thorn;uder bro&yogh;te : bi him he dude also,</NOTE></L>
<L>And swor oth&thorn; &thorn;at he scholde : al quik i-huld beo</L>
<L N="180">And seth&thorn;e i-barnd al-to douste : and with &thorn;e wind a-wei fleo.
<PB REF="00000430.tif" N="382"></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e kingus bro&thorn;er, &thorn;at hei&yogh;te Gad : al at&thorn;e de&thorn;e lay :</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng al for-&yogh;at seint Thomas : for deol &thorn;at he i-sai&yogh;h;<MILESTONE N="163" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he hiet is Men witen him wel : and is felawe also,</L>
<L N="184">For-to is bro&thorn;ur were in betere point : &thorn;at he mi&yogh;hte heore dom heom do.</L>
<L>&para; So &thorn;at is bro&thorn;ur deide sone. : &thorn;e kyng made deol I-nov&yogh;h;</L>
<L>he liet him a-grei&thorn;i swi&thorn;e fayre : and elles it were wou&yogh;h;</L>
<L N="187">Four dawes he heold him inne : &thorn;at he faire a-grey&thorn;ed were</L>
<L>In pourpre and cheisel and guode &yogh;immes : &thorn;at no defaute &thorn;are nere.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he [was]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> imaud<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> agrei&thorn;ed</NOTE> with grete nobleye : &thorn;ene feor&thorn;e day huy him nome</L>
<L N="190">And with gret compaygnie of hei&yogh;e men : to is burijngue come.</L>
<L>&para; Ase huy wolden &thorn;is dede man : in is putte do,</L>
<L>With grete noblei&yogh;e and pruyte i-nov : and with wop and sor also,</L>
<L>he a-ros up fram de&thorn;e to liue : a-mong heom euerech-one.</L>
<L>&THORN;o mauden huy Ioye and blisse i-nov&yogh; : &thorn;at lusten er betere grone.</L>
<L>"Bro&thorn;er," he seide, &thorn;o he a-ros : "&thorn;ou dudest ane vuele dede,</L>
<L N="196">&THORN;at seint Thomas &thorn;e holie man : into prisone liete lede,</L>
<L>For mid god of heouene he is wel&mdash; : and &thorn;oru&yogh;h him ich am nov</L>
<L>To liue ibrou&yogh;t ase &yogh;e iseoth&thorn; : and i-chulle &yogh;ou tellen hov.</L>
<L>&para; For Aungles comen, &thorn;o ich was ded : and mine soule bere,</L>
<L N="200">And scheuwede me &thorn;e Ioye of heouene : &thorn;ei ich vnwuyr&thorn;e were.</L>
<L>&THORN;is noble bold he schewede me<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> me ek</NOTE> : &thorn;at seint Thomas liet arere</L>
<L>with &thorn;at tresor &thorn;at &thorn;ou him toke&mdash; : god &yogh;eue &thorn;at ich were &thorn;ere!</L>
<L>I-maud it is ase he deuisede &thorn;e : and noblelokur, &yogh;if it may,</L>
<L N="204">Of &yogh;immes and stones preciouse&mdash; : so noble neuere i-ne sai&yogh;.</L>
<L>'Lo,' seide &thorn;e Aungel &thorn;o : 'sixt &thorn;ou &thorn;is noble bold?</L>
<L>&THORN;is hath seint Thomas a-rerd : of &thorn;at seluer and of &thorn;at gold</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;i bro&thorn;ur him bi-tok : elles-&yogh;ware to bi-guynne;</L>
<L N="208">Ake &thorn;i bro&thorn;ur vnwuyr&thorn;e is : forto come &thorn;are-inne.'</L>
<L>'Ore louerd it &yogh;eue,' ich seide &thorn;o : '&thorn;at it ouwere wille it were</L>
<L>&thorn;at ich moste here porter beo&mdash; : for non betere wuyr&thorn;e ich nere.'</L>
<L>&para; 'we schullen,' seide an Aungel &thorn;o : 'to ore louerd for &thorn;e bi-seche</L>
<L N="212">&THORN;at &thorn;i soule wende to eor&thorn;e a-&yogh;ein : &thorn;i lijf for-to eche,</L>
<L>For-to libben on eor&thorn;e more : to don al &thorn;ine wille.</L>
<L>Ake buye out Thomas of prisone : ich rede, &thorn;at he ne a-spille.' "</L>
<L>&THORN;o he hadde &thorn;is tale i-told : he orn to seint Thomas,
<PB REF="00000431.tif" N="383"></L>
<L N="216">And feol to is fiet and &thorn;onkede him : ase he in prisone was,</L>
<L>And tolde al of him hou it was : and bad him &yogh;eorne al-so</L>
<L N="218">To for-&yogh;iue is bro&thorn;ur, &thorn;e king : &thorn;at he him hadde mis-do.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e kyng cam al-so eorne a-non : and criede him milce and ore,</L>
<L>To for-&yogh;iuen him &thorn;at he hadde mis-do : and seide he nolde non-more.</L>
<L>Out of prisone huy brou&yogh;ten him sone : with Ioye and blisse i-nou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk honourede him ase a god : and wel &thorn;icke a-boute him drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>"Muche hath ore louerd," quath seint Thomas : "for eov alle i-do,</L>
<L N="224">&THORN;at schewede eov &thorn;us is priuete : &yogh;wane &yogh;e ne beoth nou&yogh;t wuyr&thorn;e &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L>&THORN;at paleis is noble and riche i-nov : &thorn;at ich &thorn;are habbe i-wrou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>with &thorn;et tresor &thorn;at &thorn;e king me tok : to ende it is i-brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Ech man &thorn;at wole don aftur me : &thorn;udere he schal wende<MILESTONE N="163b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="228">And louerd and prince &thorn;are beo : euere with-outen ende.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e mouwe wienden in-to al &thorn;at lond : and i-seon al-a-boute</L>
<L>Ech contreie ful of churchene : &thorn;ar-of &yogh;e mowen beo proute:</L>
<L>Sire king, alle huy beoth a-rerd : of tresur &thorn;at &thorn;ou me toke.</L>
<L N="232">&YOGH;if &thorn;ou nelt nou&yogh;t i-leue me : wiend a-boute and loke!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng, and al &thorn;at o&thorn;ur folk : &thorn;at &thorn;icke a-boute him com,</L>
<L>Bi-lieueden on god for &thorn;is miracle : and turnden to cristindom</L>
<L>&para; Fourtene &thorn;ousend of men : to ore louerd tur[n]den &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="236">with-oute children and wummen : &thorn;at Manie al-so were.</L>
<L>Seint Thomas heom tei&yogh;hte &thorn;e ri&yogh;hte bi-leue : and made heom &thorn;ar-of wise;</L>
<L>At eche churche he sette ane preost : to don heom heore seruise.</L>
<L>&THORN;o huy weren alle in guod point : his leue wel faire he nam,</L>
<L N="240">And wende ferrore into &thorn;e lond : to prechi cristindom.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; In-to an o&thorn;ur contreie he cam : &thorn;are he a-stunte ane stounde;</L>
<L>he pulte him forth wel baldeliche : and prechede to grounde;</L>
<L>Deue and blinde and o&thorn;ere al-so : &thorn;at in sicknesse weren i-bounde,</L>
<L N="244">he helde a-non &thorn;oru&yogh; godes grace : &yogh;wane he anie founde.</L>
<L>Swuche Miracle ase he dude : &thorn;oru&yogh; ore louerdes sonde,</L>
<L>Nas neuere a-mong heom i-sei&yogh;e : in none stude of &thorn;e londe.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at word sprong of him wide : fale Iorneis &thorn;anne</L>
<L N="248">&THORN;at god was into Inde i-come : in a fourme of manne;</L>
<L>he was gladdore &thorn;ane ani Man : &thorn;at &thorn;udere mi&yogh;hte wende
<PB REF="00000432.tif" N="384"></L>
<L N="250">To habbe enes a si&yogh;th of him : a-boute in eche ende;</L>
<L>Gret prece cam a-bouten him : of &thorn;e contreie feor and nei&yogh;h,</L>
<L>And heolden him god in Mannes fourme : euerech &thorn;at him i-sei&yogh;h.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e riche men &thorn;at weren nei&yogh;h : ane noble croune wrou&yogh;ten</L>
<L>Of gold and of Riche &yogh;ymmes : and to &thorn;is holie Man huy<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> brou&yogh;ten,</L>
<L>And ech-manere clo&thorn;ingue also : &thorn;at a kyng werie scholde,</L>
<L N="256">For-to clo&thorn;i him ase an hei&yogh;h kyng : and crouni him with golde.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">A v. om.: Grete tresour hi bro&yogh;te him ek : &yogh;if he it fonge wolde.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Seint Thomas stod and bi-heold : no-&thorn;ing &thorn;ar-of he nolde;</L>
<L>"Mine leoue freond," he seide, "&yogh;e weneth : &thorn;at ich beo &thorn;at i-nam nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>I-nam no kyng swuch &thorn;ing to habbe : ase &yogh;e me habbuth i-wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="260">I-nam nou&yogh;ht god, ase some weneth : ake ich am is hine,</L>
<L>And he me hath hidere i-sent : to bringue eou fram helle pine</L>
<L N="262">And techen eov fur-sake eower false godes : &thorn;at ne mouwen eov helpe nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And to bi-leue on ore ri&yogh;hte louerd : &thorn;at us alle hath i-wrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; Bi-leueth on him, ich eov rede : and to Ioye &yogh;e schullen wende.</L>
<L>&THORN;at tresour &thorn;at &yogh;e bringueth me : pouere men &yogh;e it sende,</L>
<L N="266">For ri&yogh;ht nou&yogh;ht i-nelle &thorn;are-of : ake deleth it heom a-boute;</L>
<L>And bi-lieuez on Ihesu crist : and no-&thorn;ing ne schulle &yogh;e doute."<NOTE PLACE="marg1">v. 266-7 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sike men &thorn;are comen &thorn;icke : a-boute in euerech side,</L>
<L>Blinde and Doumbe and o&thorn;ere al-so : heore hele fort-abide,</L>
<L>Museles and crokede ek : and &thorn;at weren in palasye;<NOTE PLACE="marg1">v. 270-1 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L N="271">Ful &thorn;icke huy stoden in &thorn;e place : on &thorn;is holie man to crie.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Thomas alle &thorn;eos sike Men : brou&yogh;hte in one place,<MILESTONE N="164" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And a-mong heom sat a-doun a-kneo : and bad ore louerdes grace</L>
<L>&THORN;at he cudde is mi&yogh;hte and is grace : and heore hele heom sende &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at al &thorn;at folk &thorn;e so&thorn;e i-sei&yogh;e : &thorn;at al-mi&yogh;hti god he were.</L>
<L N="276">&THORN;o he hadde ore louerd &thorn;us i-bede : a-mong heom &thorn;are cam</L>
<L>So gret li&yogh;ht and cler schinyngue : &thorn;at heore si&yogh;ht heom almest bi|nam;</L>
<L N="278">&para; hit ouer-spradde furst seint Thomas : ase he lai in is beden,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e sike Men alle, &thorn;at huy fullen a-doun : euerech in his stede,</L>
<L>And lei&yogh;en &thorn;are al plat to grounde : &thorn;e mountaunce of half a tide,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;wile &thorn;is grete li&yogh;ht i-laste : ech bi o&thorn;eres side.</L>
<L N="282">A-non so &thorn;at li&yogh;ht i-passed was : &thorn;at ech mi&yogh;hte o&thorn;ur i-seo,
<PB REF="00000433.tif" N="385"></L>
<L>Ech-one huy a-risen up hole and sounde : holore ne mi&yogh;hte none men beo.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;are was Ioye and blisse i-nou&yogh; : &thorn;ere ne mi&yogh;hte beo non more;</L>
<L N="285">huy honoureden seint Thomas : and criden him milce and ore.</L>
<L>&THORN;are turnden &thorn;o nei&yogh;h a &thorn;ousend men : and i-baptizede were,</L>
<L>with-oute children and wummen : &thorn;oru&yogh; is miracle &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="288">&THORN;at cri was &thorn;o &thorn;arof so muche : &thorn;at al &thorn;at lond wel wide</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-of spac, and &thorn;udere ornen : ful &thorn;icke in euerech side.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; Carik hiet &thorn;e kingues mei : &thorn;at of &thorn;ulke londe was,</L>
<L>Migdonia hei&yogh;te is wif : &thorn;at ore louerd &yogh;af swi&thorn;e fair cas.</L>
<L N="292">For Migdonia, &thorn;is guode wif : to a wumman cam</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo knev&yogh; erore and was &thorn;o : i-turnd to cristindom,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hadde six &yogh;er blynd i-beo : and guod si&yogh;ht heo hadde &thorn;o;</L>
<L>"Leoue soster," quath &thorn;is Migdonie : "hou is &thorn;is i-go</L>
<L N="296">&THORN;at &thorn;ov hast so longue blind i-beo : and nou art i-held so?</L>
<L>&YOGH;wat is &thorn;ilke wise Man : &thorn;at s<SUP>wu</SUP>ch mi&yogh;hte may do?"</L>
<L>&para; "Certes, Dame," &thorn;is o&thorn;ur seide : "&thorn;e nobleste Man it is</L>
<L>&THORN;at euere on vr&thorn;e a-mon[g] men cam : with-oute god sulf, i-wis;</L>
<L N="300">For he heleth &thorn;e sike &thorn;at wollez beon hole : and &thorn;ar-of ne faillez he neuere.</L>
<L>haddest&thorn;ov enes him i-sei&yogh;e : &thorn;e gladdore &thorn;ou woldest beo euere."</L>
<L>"Dev merci," quath &thorn;is guode wijf : "hou may ich best<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> on take</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich hadde<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> nadde</NOTE> i-sei&yogh;e &thorn;is holie man : &thorn;at swuch wonder may make?"</L>
<L N="304">&para; "Wel, &thorn;ou schalt do," &thorn;is o&thorn;ur seide : "for to-morewe, ase he me tolde,</L>
<L>he wole come and prechi al &thorn;at folk : hov huy schullen heore bi-leue holde;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt with me &thorn;udere go : wel priueliche, ich rede,</L>
<L>And huyd &thorn;i face, with<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;i face ihud &amp; in</NOTE> o&thorn;ur clo&thorn;us : &thorn;at no man ne wite &thorn;i dede!"</L>
<L N="308">&THORN;at guode wijf ne fur-&yogh;at nou&yogh;t &thorn;is : ake dude ase he ire radde,</L>
<L>Chaungede hire clo&thorn;us and hudde ire face : and wende ase heo ire ladde.</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;is holie prechingue heo cam : &thorn;at no man ne knev hire &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="311">And i-heorde &thorn;ane holie man : hov he gan &thorn;at folk lere;</L>
<L>&THORN;e grete miracles heo i-sai&yogh;h also : &thorn;at ore louerd for him wrou&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>heo nuste &yogh;wat heo mi&yogh;hte for Ioye do : ake stod in grete &thorn;ou&yogh;hte;
<PB REF="00000434.tif" N="386"></L>
<L>heo wilnede more &thorn;anne ani-&thorn;ing : to speke with him a &thorn;rowe,</L>
<L>Ake heo ne dorste for no-&thorn;ing : laste heo were i-knowe.</L>
<L N="316">&para; heo wende hom al i-hud : ake euere heo hadde in &thorn;ou&yogh;hte</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er time with him to speke : &yogh;wane ore louerd &thorn;e time brou&yogh;te.<MILESTONE N="164b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bi-fore hire bedde heo lay any&yogh;ht : and on ore louerd criede longue</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo moste &thorn;oru&yogh; seint Thomas : cristindom a-fongue.</L>
<L>&para; At&thorn;e mid ni&yogh;ht seint Thomas cam : and bi hire stod at&thorn;e laste&mdash;</L>
<L>Nuste heo neuere &yogh;ware he cam In : &thorn;e doren weren alle faste.</L>
<L N="322">"Beo glad," he seide, "Migdonie : god hath i-heord &thorn;ine bone:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast muche i-wilned after me : ich come to &thorn;e here ful sone.</L>
<L>God wole &thorn;at &thorn;ou beo on of his : and &thorn;at &thorn;ou come &thorn;oru&yogh; me</L>
<L>To &thorn;e lif &thorn;at euere schal i-laste : and &thorn;at ich beo a-slawe for &thorn;e.</L>
<L N="326">For &thorn;e ich schal i-martred beo : and bo&thorn;e we schullen wiende</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Ioye of heuene, and &thorn;are beo : to-gadere with-outen ende."</L>
<L>&para; Seint Thomas &yogh;af hire cristindom : are he &thorn;annes wende,</L>
<L>And tei&yogh;te <SUP>h</SUP>ire al godes lawe : hire lif for-to a-mende.</L>
<L N="330">&THORN;is wif bi-cam a guod womman : and nolde neuer-eft mo</L>
<L>After &thorn;at tyme for no-&thorn;ing : to hire louerdes bedde go.</L>
<L>hire louerd was &thorn;ar-of sore a-nuyd : and &thorn;o he ne mi&yogh;hte for no &thorn;ingue</L>
<L>Maken hire enes nei&yogh;h him come : he playnede him to &thorn;e kingue.</L>
<L N="334">&para; &THORN;e kyng hiet &thorn;e Quiene a-non : &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">= heo</NOTE> scholde to hire wiende</L>
<L>And reden hire to honouri hire louerd bet : and don ase &thorn;e hende&mdash;</L>
<L>For wummen conne of o&thorn;eres rede : &thorn;are-fore &thorn;e Qu<SUP>i</SUP>ene he sende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Quiene adai wel mildeliche : to &thorn;is guode wumman wende</L>
<L N="338">And radde hire to hire louerd go : to schilden hire fram vilenie,</L>
<L>And no-&thorn;ing ne lieue &thorn;ane false man : &thorn;at radde hire to schuche folie.</L>
<L>&para; "A, dame, merci," quath &thorn;is o&thorn;ur : "&thorn;ou nost nou&yogh;t hou it is;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wustest al &thorn;at ich wot : &thorn;ou noldest nou&yogh;t so segge, i-wis.</L>
<L N="342">For so noble a man ase he is : nas neuere on eor&thorn;e ido;</L>
<L>haddest&thorn;ou him enes i-sei&yogh;e : &thorn;ou woldest segge al-so.</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou isei&yogh;e nou&thorn;e &thorn;at ich seo : &thorn;e wolde wondri, i-wis.</L>
<L>For symphor &thorn;e hei&yogh;e kny&yogh;t : &thorn;at Maister of kny&yogh;htes is,</L>
<L N="346">&para; To-dai was his sone ded : and symphor wel &yogh;eorne him sou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>&THORN;ane holie Man seint Thomas : and to is sone nou&thorn;e him brou&yogh;te:</L>
<L>And &thorn;are he hath him ri&yogh;ht nou&thorn;e : [arerd] fram de&thorn;e to liue;</L>
<L>And &thorn;are he sit nou&thorn;e in is hous : and prechez &thorn;at folk bliue;
<PB REF="00000435.tif" N="387"></L>
<L N="350">A-boute him al-so sike men : wel &thorn;icke comez nov gon,</L>
<L>Crokede and blinde and o&thorn;ur<SUP>e</SUP> al-so : and [he] heom heleth ech-on."</L>
<L>&para; "Leoue soster," quath &thorn;is Qu<SUP>i</SUP>ene : "&yogh;we&thorn;ur &thorn;is mouwe soth beo?"</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e, Dame, certes," quath &thorn;is o&thorn;ur : "and &yogh;if &thorn;ou it wolt i-seo,</L>
<L N="354">Go we &thorn;udere and &thorn;ou schalt : &thorn;e so&thorn;e finde a-non."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Quiene &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;o ful longue : are heo were &thorn;udere i-gon.</L>
<L>huy come and founden seint Thomas : ri&yogh;ht ase &thorn;is womman seide.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Quiene stod and him bi-heold : and alle is holie dede:</L>
<L N="358">&para; To is fiet heo ful a-doun : heo ne mi&yogh;hte no leng a-bide,</L>
<L>And bad him &yogh;iuen hire cristindom : and merci faste him cride.</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;o heo i-cristned was : hamward &thorn;ane wei heo nam</L>
<L N="361">To &thorn;e kyngue, and longue hire &thorn;ou&yogh;te : are heo to him cam.</L>
<L>"Sire," heo seide, "ich habbe i-founde : &thorn;is guode wijf Migdonie<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. &thorn;are-fore; <I>al.</I> so &thorn;at</NOTE></L>
<L>In grete wisdome, and ich wende er : to finde hire in folie;<MILESTONE N="165" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="364">And, gode &thorn;onk, of hire wisdom : heo partede with me:</L>
<L>And &thorn;are<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. &thorn;are-fore; <I>al.</I> so &thorn;at</NOTE> i-nelle in &thorn;ine folie : non-more siwe &thorn;e."</L>
<L>&THORN;o was &thorn;e kyng sori inov&yogh; : he nuste &yogh;wat &thorn;ar-of to do.</L>
<L>For-to quelle is wif &thorn;are-fore : none heorte he nadde &thorn;ar-to.</L>
<L N="368">&para; He cleopede Carik, is cosyn : "we beoth bi-traide," he seide,</L>
<L>"Mine Quiene ich sende, ase &thorn;ou wel wost : &thorn;i wif for-to rede,</L>
<L>To bringue hire out of fole &thorn;ou&yogh;t : ase &thorn;ou me for loue bede,</L>
<L>And nou&thorn;e ich habbe hire for-lore : forth with hire, ich drede,</L>
<L N="372">For loue of &thorn;e one i-lore bo&thorn;e : alas, &thorn;e wrechhede!</L>
<L>we moten us a-wreken of &thorn;at &thorn;eof : &thorn;at bringueth heom in swuch dede."</L>
<L>&para; He liet sienden aftur seint Thomas : &yogh;if Men him mi&yogh;hten finde;</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;is holie Man i-founde was : faste men him guonne binde,</L>
<L>And harli him forth bi-fore &thorn;e kyng : his hondene him bi-hinde:</L>
<L N="377">So &thorn;at he was to de&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t : in &thorn;e londe of Inde.</L>
<L>For &thorn;o he was bi-fore &thorn;e kyngue i-brou&yogh;t : &thorn;e kyng him hiet a-non</L>
<L>For-to honouri heore false godes : &thorn;at weren of treo and ston,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">a v. om.</NOTE></L>
<L N="380">O&thorn;ur he wolde laten him tormenti : and to-drawe is flechs fram &thorn;e bon.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is holie Man for-sok &thorn;o : is heste forto do.</L>
<L>Irene plates he liet nime : brode and longue also,
<PB REF="00000436.tif" N="388"></L>
<L>And liet heom caste a-midde &thorn;e fuyre : &thorn;at al glowinde huy weren a-non,</L>
<L N="384">And seth&thorn;e he hiet &thorn;ane holie Man : &thorn;ar-uppe bare-fot gon.</L>
<L>A-non so &thorn;is holie Man : sette is fet &thorn;are-on,</L>
<L>A welle with watur &thorn;are sprong out of &thorn;e vr&thorn;e : so cold so ani ston,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> out : of &thorn;e harde ston</NOTE></L>
<L>And a-queinte &thorn;at fuyr a-non : &thorn;at so hot and strong was;</L>
<L N="388">&THORN;e guode man eode forth &thorn;ar-on : &thorn;at neuere &thorn;e worse him nas.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o was &thorn;e king nei&yogh;h out of witte : an Ouene he liet hete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo was al glowinde fuyr : are huy wolden lete :</L>
<L>&THORN;ene holie Man huy nomen anon : and a-midde &thorn;e Ouene him caste.</L>
<L N="392">And &thorn;o he was &thorn;are-inne i-do : &thorn;at fuyr no leng ne laste,</L>
<L>Ake it bi-gan to quienche a-non : &thorn;at so gret hete er of drov&yogh;;</L>
<L>&THORN;e holie Man &thorn;are-inne was : in Ioye and Muru&thorn;e i-nov&yogh;.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e kyng &thorn;is i-sai&yogh;h : he nuste hou on take;</L>
<L>"Carik," he seide, "hou geth &thorn;is? : ore godus us habbuth for-sake;</L>
<L>we ne mowen nou&yogh;t &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere &thorn;eof : with none &thorn;ingue quelle."</L>
<L N="398">"Certus, sire," quath Car[i]k : "ano&thorn;ur ichulle &thorn;e telle:</L>
<L>we schullen nime &thorn;is [lu&thorn;ere]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> Man : and [to] ore godes him lede</L>
<L>And maken him forto honouri heom : mid ei&yogh;e and for drede,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh;h &yogh;wan he schal is louerdes wrath&thorn;e : habben out and out,</L>
<L N="402">And is merueile him beo bi-nome : &thorn;oru&yogh; &yogh;wan h<SUP>e</SUP> is so prout."</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;is Maumates &thorn;is holie man : i-brou&yogh;t was wel sone</L>
<L>Mid strenc&thorn;e forto honouri heom : ase huy weren i-woned to done.</L>
<L>Seint Thomas bi-heold &thorn;is maumates : ase he bi-fore heom stod;</L>
<L N="406">"Ich coniouri eov," he seide, "in his name : &thorn;at for us schedde is blod,</L>
<L>Ov deuelene &thorn;at &thorn;are-inne beoth : and with foles wolleth speke,<MILESTONE N="165b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e sone &thorn;arof out fleon : and &thorn;e Maumates to-breke."</L>
<L>&para; A-non so he hadde &thorn;is word i-seid : &thorn;e maumates ne mi&yogh;hte no leng duyre,</L>
<L N="410">Ake bi-gunnen al to melte awei : ase wex deth a&yogh;ein &thorn;e fuyre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy weren so alle to nau&yogh;ht i-brou&yogh;ht : ri&yogh;ht ase huy neuere nere.</L>
<L>In gret wonder stod al &thorn;at folk : &thorn;at in &thorn;at paleis<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> place</NOTE> were;</L>
<L>Ech-one huy gonne with one mou&thorn;e : wel loude grede and crie:</L>
<L N="414">"O. god is al-mi&yogh;hti one : i-boren of Mayde Marie,
<PB REF="00000437.tif" N="389"></L>
<L>Of &yogh;wam seint [Thomas] hath i-speke&mdash; : to him we wollez alle us take</L>
<L>And &thorn;eos wrechches false godes : clanliche alle for-sake."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e kyng and Carik : and &thorn;e false preostes al-so</L>
<L N="418">&THORN;at wusten &thorn;e Maumates, i-heorden &thorn;is : huy nusten &yogh;wat to do.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyng and Carick for fyn wo : out of &thorn;e place wenden,</L>
<L>&THORN;o huy i-sei&yogh;en hou &thorn;is holie Man : heore godus so foule schende;</L>
<L>huy ne dorsten for cristine Men : setten on him non hond,</L>
<L N="422">Ne al-so for &thorn;e grete Miracle : &thorn;at Man alday with him fond.</L>
<L>&para; Ake &thorn;e preostes of &thorn;e false lawe : in grete wrath&thorn;e huy stode;</L>
<L>&THORN;at on hente in is hond a strong swerd : with ful wro&thorn;e mode:</L>
<L>"Of &thorn;is &thorn;eof ichulle," he seide : "mine godes anon a-wreke,</L>
<L N="426">&THORN;at heom hath swuch schame i-do : ho-so it euere bi-speke,"</L>
<L>he leide on &thorn;is holi Man : with is swerd to grounde</L>
<L>Into al is bodi and made him sone : manie eouele woundes,</L>
<L>And a-martrede so &thorn;ane holie Man : and a-slou&yogh;h him in a stounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e cristine Men weren wro&thorn;e i-nou&yogh;h : &thorn;o huy hine ded founden;</L>
<L N="431">&THORN;ane preost huy wolden habbe i-barnd&mdash; : ake he fleu&yogh;h a-non;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e king and carik habbe a-slawe&mdash; : ake huy weren a-wei igon.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is holie bodi huy nomen a-non : and to churche it bere,</L>
<L>And bureden it with gret honour : and with grete nobleye &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at strenc&thorn;e of holie churche : wexinde euere was.</L>
<L N="436">&THORN;us cam into Inde cristindom : formest &thorn;oru&yogh;h seint Thomas.</L>
<L>Nov seint Thomas &thorn;at Cristindam : formest into Inde brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>B[r]ingue us to &thorn;e Ioye of heouene : to &yogh;wan ore louerd us bou&yogh;te.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="57" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>57 [Mathie ap.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Mathie Apostle is : ase &yogh;e schullen alle i-wite;</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh;h lot he was apostel i-maud : ase it is i-write.</L>
<L>Ivdas &thorn;at Apostel was : &thorn;o he hadde ore louerd i-sold,</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;are [nas]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> non longue in is stude : &thorn;at Apostel were i-told.</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at ore louerd : in-to heouene was i-sti&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Apostles weren alle to-gadere : and ore lauedi seinte marie:</L>
<L>&para; So &thorn;at seinte peter heom radde : ase ore louerd hadde i-bede,</L>
<L N="8">For Ivdas &thorn;at Apostle was : to nimen on in is stude.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at huy nomen and casten lot. : and ope seint Mathie it gan falle;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he, and seint powel : &thorn;e laste weren of heom alle.&mdash;
<PB REF="00000438.tif" N="390"></L>
<L>Seint Mathie cam of hei&yogh;e Men : &thorn;at nou&thorn;e apostel is;</L>
<L N="12">In &thorn;e londe of Bedlehem : i-bore he was, i-wis.</L>
<L>Seoth&thorn;e, &thorn;o he Apostel was : and huy wenden alle wide</L>
<L>And precheden Men<NOTE PLACE="marg1">overlined.</NOTE> to cristindom : euerech in his side,<MILESTONE N="166" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Into &thorn;e londe of Iudee : seint Mathie &thorn;ene wei nam;</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;are he prechede to manie Men : and brou&yogh;hte to cristindom.</L>
<L>he helde also &thorn;at sike weren&mdash; : ne may no man rikeni alle;</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh;h him &thorn;at folk into cristindom : swi&thorn;e wide it gan falle.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;are was a maister in &thorn;at lond : &thorn;at a swuch drunch made &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at alle &thorn;at &thorn;ar-of dronken : anon-ri&yogh;ht a-blende were.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at drunch men brou&yogh;ten to seint Mathie : and he it dronk anon:</L>
<L>And him nas &thorn;are-fore neuere &thorn;e worsse : ake al hol he gan forth gon.</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk hadde &thorn;er-of wonder gret : &thorn;at he ne les anon is si&yogh;hte.</L>
<L N="24">"Alas, mine leoue freond," quath seint Mathie : "&yogh;e ne seoth nou&yogh;t godes mi&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e i-seon soth&thorn;liche godes mi&yogh;hte : &thorn;at he on us sende,</L>
<L>Latez bringue here bi-fore me alle &thorn;ulke : &thorn;at &thorn;are-with weren a-blende!"</L>
<L>Men leten heom sechen wel widen out : and bringue &thorn;ere into place.</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;is holie Man heo[m] helde a-non : &thorn;oru&yogh; ore louerdes grace;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;reo hundred men and mo<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> to (=two)</NOTE> : &thorn;oru&yogh;h ore louerdes mi&yogh;hte</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;at drunch weren a-blende : he &yogh;af heom &thorn;are heore si&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk criede &yogh;eorne on him : and &thorn;icke a-bouten him cam,</L>
<L N="32">And bilieueden on god &thorn;oru&yogh; is techingue : and turnden to cristin|dom.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e lu&thorn;er Iustise of &thorn;at lond : her-of heorde telle:</L>
<L N="34">he liet nimen &thorn;is holie man : and in strongue de&thorn;e a-quelle.</L>
<L>Ake it nis nou&yogh;hwere in boke i-founde : &yogh;wat deth he hadde &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>Ake i-martred he was in strong torment : ase alle &thorn;e apostles were.</L>
<L>&para; Guode Men comen aftur-ward : and &thorn;at holi bodi nome</L>
<L N="38">And fram &thorn;e londe of Iudee : ladden it seth&thorn;e to Rome,</L>
<L>And bureden it &thorn;ere with gret honour : &thorn;are ase men schewez &yogh;uyte</L>
<L>In seinte Marie churche ofte : his heued with grete pruyte.</L>
<L>Nov god for &thorn;e loue of seint Mathi : us leue ore lif so wisse</L>
<L N="42">&THORN;at we, &yogh;wanne we heonnes wiendeth : comen to heouene blisse.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. blissa</NOTE> AmeN.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="58" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000439.tif" N="391">
<HEAD>58 hic incipit uita sancti Siluestri.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Siluestre pope was : &thorn;e furste &thorn;at &thorn;are cam</L>
<L>&thorn;at euere hadde Rome in pes : to holde up cristindom;</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;at comen bi-fore him : lu&thorn;ere Men to-drowe</L>
<L N="4">And harleden heom out of &thorn;e londe : and with tormens manie huy slowe.</L>
<L>Ake ore louerdes mi&yogh;hte euere wax : and &thorn;e strenc&thorn;e of cristindom,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at it was in betere pays : &thorn;o seint siluestre cam.</L>
<L>&para; It bi-fel &thorn;at he prechede &thorn;e Aumperoure : Costantin &thorn;at was &thorn;o;</L>
<L N="8">&thorn;at he grauntede him &thorn;e churche of Rome : in pays with-outen wo.</L>
<L>Ake erore he hadde wo i-nou&yogh;h : are it mi&yogh;hte &thorn;ar-to astonde:</L>
<L>For in prisone he was ofte ido : and ofte i-driue out of londe.</L>
<L>&para; A lu&thorn;ur Iustise cam in a time : in-to &thorn;e contreye a-boute</L>
<L N="12">For-to tormenti cristine men : and to<NOTE PLACE="marg1">overlined.</NOTE> harli with gret route;</L>
<L>he liet martri ane holie Man : &thorn;at hiet thymothe,</L>
<L>And liet him seth&thorn;e in a foul stude : casten with gret vilte.</L>
<L>Seint siluestre wente a-ni&yogh;ht : and &thorn;at bodi &thorn;annes drou&yogh;h</L>
<L N="16">And burede it with gret honour : in a fair place i-nou&yogh;h.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e Iustise seth&thorn;e it vnder-&yogh;at : siluestre faste he nam,<MILESTONE N="166b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And seide, "&thorn;eof, &thorn;ou schalt habbe : &thorn;at ilke sulue dom</L>
<L>&YOGH;wy laddest &thorn;ou a-wei &thorn;anne &thorn;eof trichour? : &yogh;wodere hast&thorn;ou him -brou&yogh;t?"</L>
<L N="20">"Certes, sire," quath siluestre : "&thorn;eof ne trichour nas he nou&yogh;ht;</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;ou art swuch on, ich wot it wel : and godes martyr he is.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;are-of &thorn;e so&thorn;e i-seo : to-ni&yogh;ht &thorn;ou schalt, i-wis,</L>
<L>In strongue de&thorn;e a-strangled [be] : and wiende to &thorn;e pine of helle."</L>
<L N="24">"A, &thorn;eof traitour," quath &thorn;e Iustise : "ra&thorn;er ichulle &thorn;e a-quelle."</L>
<L>&para; He liet nime &thorn;is holie man : and in strong prisone caste,</L>
<L>For-to he bi-sei&yogh;e him in &yogh;wat de&thorn;e : he were i-brou&yogh;t ate laste.</L>
<L>his soper he liet grei&thorn;i faire : ase he was i-woned to do,</L>
<L N="28">And with grete pruyte and noblei&yogh;e : he eode and sat &thorn;ar-to.</L>
<L>A fisches bon schet in is &thorn;rote : ase he sat and .et.,</L>
<L>&thorn;at neuereft ne cam out a-&yogh;ein : are he is lijf fur-liet;</L>
<L>For he was a-choked a-non : and toward &thorn;e de&thorn;e he drou&yogh;h,</L>
<L N="32">Vnne&thorn;e he liuede for-to mid-ni&yogh;ht : with pine and seoruwe i-nov.
<PB REF="00000440.tif" N="392"></L>
<L>&para; His Men &thorn;at weren is conseilers : comen eorninde faste</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e prisone to siluestre : and sore huy weren a-gaste,</L>
<L>And seiden, "leoue louerd, fur-&yogh;if us : &thorn;at we &thorn;e habbez mis-do!</L>
<L N="36">Gret wreche to ore Maister cam for &thorn;e : ne lat nou&yogh;ht to us so!</L>
<L>Louerd, graunte us &thorn;i guode wille : we nelleth mis-don &thorn;e non-more;</L>
<L>Go forth &yogh;ware &thorn;i wille is : we biddeth &thorn;e milce and ore."</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;is guode man wende out of prison : with honour i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L N="40">Ri&yogh;ht ase Men &thorn;ane lu&thorn;ere Iustise : to-ward &thorn;e eor&thorn;e drov&yogh;.</L>
<L>&thorn;at folk bi-leueden heore owene prince : &thorn;at huy heolden er so hei&yogh;e,</L>
<L>And alle siweden &thorn;is holi man : for miracle &thorn;at huy seien.</L>
<L>Sorie weren &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere Men &thorn;o : for heore lawe eode al-to nau&yogh;hte;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e cristine Men weren glade i-nou&yogh; : for al &thorn;e pris huy cau&yogh;hte.</L>
<L N="45">Mani he&thorn;ene Man &thorn;are-fore : tornede to cristindom,</L>
<L>And wel &thorn;e betere pais &thorn;oru&yogh; al &thorn;e lond : a-mong cristine men bi-cam.</L>
<L>&para; Seint siluestre bi-lefde pope : in guod pais &thorn;o i-nov&yogh;</L>
<L N="48">And muche folk wide a-boute : to godes lawe &thorn;are drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Preostes he made and deknene al-so : and he him-sulf furst bi-founde</L>
<L>&thorn;e ordres to maken a-&yogh;ein midewynter : &thorn;at men halt &yogh;uy[t] in al &thorn;e londe.</L>
<L>Al-so he bi-fond &thorn;at Men scholden : maken &thorn;e seruise</L>
<L N="52">with linnene cloth clene i-wasche : ope &thorn;e weuede in alle wise,</L>
<L>And helie with clene linnene cloth : ore louerdes flechs and is blod,</L>
<L>And no&thorn;er in pal ne in seolke : nere it no so guod&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; And &thorn;at was, for, &thorn;o ore louerd : bou&yogh;te us with is blode,</L>
<L N="56">Iosep of Aramathie : nam him a-doun of &thorn;e rode</L>
<L>And wond him in &yogh;wi&yogh;ht linnene cloth : ase &thorn;e godspel hath i-seid,</L>
<L>Ake no&thorn;ur in seolke ne in sendel : &thorn;o &thorn;at swete flesch was ded.</L>
<L>In swuch cloth ase is swete flechs : was i-wounde &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="60">his swete flechs schal ope &thorn;e weued : beon i-wounden euere-mo.</L>
<L>&thorn;is guode Man &thorn;reo-and-twenti &yogh;er : pope was at rome</L>
<L>And &thorn;reo mon&thorn;es and endleoue dawes : are is ende-day him come.<MILESTONE N="167" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;o he deide in godes seruise : ase he hadde longue &thorn;are-in i-beo,</L>
<L N="64">I-bured he was bi-side rome : for-so&thorn;e, Milene &thorn;reo.</L>
<L>Nou god for is swete loue : us graunti &thorn;ulke blisse</L>
<L>&thorn;at seint siluestre is inne : &thorn;at we &thorn;ar-of ne misse.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="59" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000441.tif" N="393">
<HEAD>59 [Eustas.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">lawe</NOTE>SEint Eustas &thorn;e noble kny&yogh;t : of he&thorn;ene lawe<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. londe</NOTE> was;</L>
<L>Ake are he i-cristned were : men cleopeden him placidas.</L>
<L>he was with Traian &thorn;e Aumperour : hext of alle is kni&yogh;hte,</L>
<L N="4">Maister he was of al is ost : at eche bata<SUP>i</SUP>le to fi&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>he wilnede to wite godes lawe : and of cristindom;</L>
<L>Ake no man &thorn;ar-of him ne tei&yogh;hte : ne &yogh;eme &thorn;are-to ne nam:</L>
<L>&para; his heorte him &yogh;af &thorn;at is lawe nas nou&yogh;t : and &thorn;are-fore almes-dede</L>
<L N="8">Ofte he dude for godes loue : &thorn;at he him scholde &thorn;e bet rede.</L>
<L>A wif he hadde and twei sones : &thorn;at swi&thorn;e &yogh;oungue were;</L>
<L N="10">heo wilnede &yogh;eorne &thorn;at sum man : of god hire wolde lere.&mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;is hei&yogh;e kni&yogh;htes wenden a day : on honteth mani on</L>
<L>with heore cheuenteyn placidas : to cachche hert and bocke and don.</L>
<L>&para; A-mong o&thorn;ur game huy founden ane heort : swi&thorn;e fair best with-alle:</L>
<L N="14">placidas him siwede a-non : &yogh;if he mi&yogh;hte maken him falle.</L>
<L>Fram is felawes he wende al one : &thorn;is best orn with gret pas,</L>
<L>And he siwede him fer in vncou&thorn;e stude : &thorn;at al weri he was.</L>
<L>&thorn;o huy comen opon a fair hul : &thorn;is best with-stod at&thorn;e laste.</L>
<L N="18">&thorn;is kni&yogh;ht ne dorste ner him wiende : ake bi-heold him stikele and faste.</L>
<L>Bi-twene is hornes he i-sai&yogh;h : ane creiz schine bri&yogh;hte</L>
<L>with gret leome ase it were of sonne : &thorn;at vnne&thorn;e bi-holde he it mi&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>&para; "Placidas," seide &thorn;e heort : "&yogh;wy wolt&thorn;ou weorri with me?</L>
<L N="22">I-cham god &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne knowest nou&yogh;t : ichulle schewi me to &thorn;e.</L>
<L>&thorn;ine almesse-dedes &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast i-do : a-mountede me bi-fore;</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou ne canst nou&yogh;t, i-chulle &thorn;e teche : &thorn;at &thorn;i soule ne beo for-lore.</L>
<L>&thorn;ov were a-boute to cachche me : ichulle &thorn;e cahche al-so."</L>
<L N="26">"Louerd," seide placidas : "sei&yogh;e me &yogh;wat i schal do."</L>
<L>&para; "Bote go," seide ore louerd &thorn;o : "hom to &thorn;ine wiue,</L>
<L N="28">And nim hire and evwere twei sones : and lat eou cristni bliue.</L>
<L>&thorn;us time to-moruwe cum a&yogh;ein : and ich &thorn;e wolle wisse</L>
<L>hou &thorn;ou schalt leden here &thorn;i lijf : to of-serui heouene blisse."</L>
<L>&thorn;o nuste he &yogh;ware &thorn;e heort bi-cam. : &thorn;is kni&yogh;ht in grete &thorn;ou&yogh;te</L>
<L N="32">wende hom and &thorn;onkede god : &thorn;at swuch ti&thorn;ingue him brou&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>his wiue he tolde it priueliche. : "sire, merci," heo seide,
<PB REF="00000442.tif" N="394"></L>
<L>"To-ni&yogh;ht ore louerd cam al-so to me : and ri&yogh;ht so he gan me rede."</L>
<L>&para; Huy nomen heore twey sones with heom : and to a bischop huy wende</L>
<L N="36">And lieten heom cristni alle foure : heore lif for-to amende;</L>
<L>&thorn;is kny&YOGH;th liet is name tuyrne : and liet him cleopie Eustas.</L>
<L>With o&thorn;ure kni&yogh;htes he wende eft an hontez : &thorn;udere ase he er was.</L>
<L>&thorn;is holie best he sai&yogh;h &thorn;o eft-sone : aftur he wende al-so,</L>
<L N="40">For-to he cam in-to a priue stude : ase he hadde er i-do.</L>
<L>&thorn;o criede he and fel a-doun a-kneo : "louerd," he seide, "&thorn;in ore,<MILESTONE N="167b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Tel me hou i schal mi lif lede : to saui me &thorn;oru&yogh;h &thorn;i lore."</L>
<L>Ore [louerd] spac &thorn;o in &thorn;e heortes mou&thorn;e : "loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou do after me!</L>
<L N="44">For &thorn;ov hast &thorn;ene deuel ouer-come : he armeth him a&yogh;en &thorn;e:</L>
<L>&thorn;olie &thorn;ou schalt wo and sor : ase Men schulle in bataylle;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt &thorn;olie and a-&yogh;ein him fi&yogh;hte : of is wille he schal faille.</L>
<L>he schal &thorn;e, ase he dude Iob : mid alle wo &thorn;e fonde;</L>
<L N="48">Seie me &yogh;if &thorn;ou it &thorn;olie wolt : and faste a-&yogh;ein him stonde!"</L>
<L>&para; "Louerd," seide &thorn;is guode kni&yogh;ht : "&yogh;if me studefast-hede,</L>
<L>&thorn;at ich mouwe is fondingue &thorn;ole : ase &thorn;ou me wolt wisse and rede."</L>
<L>"Ope &thorn;i-sulue it is &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt beo : studefast," ore louerd seide;</L>
<L N="52">"Ake &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt so, ichulle in &thorn;i care : bo&thorn;e witie &thorn;e and lede."</L>
<L>Mid &thorn;usse worde ore louerd wende : he nuste &yogh;ware he bi-cam.</L>
<L>&thorn;is kni&yogh;ht in grete &thorn;ou&yogh;hte of heorte : &thorn;ene wey hamward nam;</L>
<L>his wiue he tolde al hou it was : and bad hire studefast be.</L>
<L N="56">To is louerdes court, &thorn;e aumperoures : nolde he nonmore teo.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;o comen &thorn;eoues and robbeden him : of al &thorn;at euere he hadde;</L>
<L>his Orf deide al-so to grounde : nou&yogh;ht o best a-liue he nadde;</L>
<L>his hinene deiden euerechone&mdash; : &thorn;are bi-lefde non a-liue</L>
<L N="60">Bote he and [is] tweie &yogh;ongue sones : and is leoue wiue.</L>
<L>&thorn;o ne bi-lefde heom non more guod : &thorn;ane heom hieng a-boute&mdash;</L>
<L>huy &thorn;onkeden god of alle is sondene : &yogh;uyt nadden huy none doute.</L>
<L>For schame &thorn;at huy beggares weren : heore hous huy liete stonde</L>
<L N="64">And bi ni&yogh;hte stelen a-wei : to-ward an o&thorn;ur londe,</L>
<L>&para; Eustas al-one and is wijf : and is sones twei&yogh;e;</L>
<L>So &yogh;ungue weren &thorn;is children two : &thorn;at he bar heom ofte bi wei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Gret deol made &thorn;e Aumperour : &thorn;o he miste sire Eustas,</L>
<L N="68">And liet him seche al-a-boute : ake men nusten &yogh;ware he was.
<PB REF="00000443.tif" N="395"></L>
<L>Toward Egypte huy passeden &thorn;e se : for huy mosten so don nede.</L>
<L N="70">&THORN;o huy &thorn;e se ipassede hadden : &thorn;e schipman axede is mede.</L>
<L>huy seiden &thorn;at huy no&thorn;ing nadden : ake &thorn;at huy beggares were.</L>
<L>&THORN;e schipman bi-heold &thorn;at guode wif : and &thorn;ou&yogh;te him of faire chere;</L>
<L>&para; he seide, "ichulle for mi mede : &thorn;is wumman with me at-holde."</L>
<L>&THORN;e kni&yogh;ht weop and criede &yogh;eorne : ake hit ne mih&yogh;te no-&thorn;ing holde,</L>
<L>&THORN;is schipman nam<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. nan</NOTE> him and is sones : and out of &thorn;e schipe heom &thorn;raste,</L>
<L N="76">And liet heom wienden &yogh;wodere huy wolden : and heold<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. beold</NOTE> &thorn;is womman faste.</L>
<L>&THORN;e kny&yogh;ht bi-heold after-ward : ake &thorn;o it non-o&thorn;ur nas,</L>
<L>Sore he weop and wrong<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. wrond</NOTE> is honden : longue i-swowe he was.</L>
<L>"Leue sones," he seide, "&yogh;wat schulle &yogh;e nou? : &yogh;oungue &yogh;e beoth, help-les,</L>
<L N="80">In vncou&thorn;e londe; ho schal ou wite : nou&thorn;e &yogh;e beoth moder-les?</L>
<L>&para; Mi-sulf ich cou&thorn;e mine mete bi-swynke : ake inot &yogh;wat &yogh;e schulle do;</L>
<L>A feble norice ich am, alas! : i nas neuere i-tei&yogh;ht &thorn;er-to."</L>
<L>Wel softe he ladde is sones forth : and wel ofte he heom bar.</L>
<L N="84">To a deop watur he cam : and no schip ne fond he &thorn;ar:</L>
<L>he bar is o sone ouer &thorn;at watur : and &thorn;are a-doun him sette.<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Here a fol. is wanting in the MS.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Only a little fragment is left, with the beginning of the first verses : &thorn;eo &yogh;wyle he . . . . &thorn;o he was f . . . . And nam &thorn; . . . . A leon c . . . And . . . . &para; &thorn;is . . . &mdash; The text in MS. Ashm. 43 is frequently abridged, therefore I fill the gap from MS. Cott.</NOTE>; MS. Cott. Iul. D ix. continues;]</NOTE></L>
<L>[&thorn;e while he wente ouer a&yogh;en : his o&thorn;er sone to fette,</L>
<L>a-midde &thorn;e water as he was : a wolf &thorn;er com vrne</L>
<L N="88">&amp; nom &thorn;at child &amp; ber hit ford : touard &thorn;e wode &yogh;erne.</L>
<L>A leon com in &thorn;e o&thorn;er half : &amp; &thorn;is o&thorn;er child [he] nom</L>
<L>&amp; bere hit ford touard &thorn;e wode : ar &thorn;e fa&thorn;er to him com.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;is kni&yogh;t stod a-midde &thorn;e water : no wonder &thorn;e him wo were,</L>
<L N="92">whan he sei &thorn;at &thorn;is wilde bestes : his sones awei bere;</L>
<L>he wep &amp; his hondes wrong : &amp; tar him be &thorn;e here;</L>
<L>him-sulf he wolde habbe a-dreint : &yogh;if &thorn;at o&thorn;ing nere:</L>
<L>he &thorn;o&yogh;te on &thorn;at our lord sede : &thorn;at he scholde &thorn;olie sore.</L>
<L N="96">he &thorn;olede, him &thorn;o&yogh;te, sorue y-nou : noman ne mi&yogh;te more.</L>
<L>"lord," he sede, "whi&thorn;er schal ich nou?" : &amp; wente bi an vncou&thorn;e weie;</L>
<L>"kni&yogh;tes ich was y-wone&thorn; to haue : wit me of gret nobleie:
<PB REF="00000444.tif" N="396"></L>
<L>&para; Ich les hom su&thorn;&thorn;e, &amp; al my good : &thorn;at ich scholde bi le&thorn;e mi lif;</L>
<L N="100">Mene bileue&thorn;e o&thorn;er solas non : bote my sones &amp; my wif.</L>
<L>&thorn;o mi wif me was by-nome : nas me wo y-nou?</L>
<L>&yogh;if ich dorste sigge, ich was : ibro&yogh;t in more wo wit wou.</L>
<L>Me nas bileue&thorn; bote mi sones : &thorn;at al myn herten were:</L>
<L N="104">&thorn;o sei ich whare wilde bestes : awei to wode hom bere,</L>
<L>&amp; icham a wrecche &amp; frendles : bileue&thorn; nou alone,</L>
<L>al nake&thorn; &amp; bar of alle gode : as ich sprong out of &thorn;e stone!</L>
<L>&para; wel ichot &thorn;at iob hadde : y-nou of care &amp; sore;</L>
<L N="108">a lone wrecche as icham : me &thorn;inc&thorn; ichaue more:</L>
<L>for he hadde frend &amp; wif also : him forto bimene,</L>
<L>me nis bileue&thorn; wif ne frend : to solaci me ene.</L>
<L>a dunghupel warup he him reste : him was also bileue&thorn;:</L>
<L N="112">of al my god so moche y naue : &thorn;at ich mow rest op my hed.</L>
<L>of al men &thorn;at euer were : me &thorn;inch icham mest wrecche&mdash;</L>
<L>ac whan god wol so &thorn;at ich schal : of no&thorn;ing I-ne recche."</L>
<L>&thorn;o he hadde al y-mad his mone : &thorn;at reu&thorn;e hit was y-nou,</L>
<L N="116">In sorue &amp; care spitosliche<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Ashm pitosliche</NOTE> : touard toune he drou.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;er he &yogh;ede &amp; be&thorn; his mete : &thorn;at al folc reu&thorn;e hadde</L>
<L>&thorn;at so fair man &amp; stalworde : in meseise his lif ladde.</L>
<L>hai-ward hi made him of &thorn;e toun : hor corn forto wite,</L>
<L N="120">&thorn;at he mi&yogh;te in treunesse : his liflode be-&yogh;ite.</L>
<L>his lordinges he paide wel : &amp; al o&thorn;ere also&mdash;</L>
<L>for ho-so ha&thorn; wit him godes grace : he ne schal neuer mis-do.</L>
<L>for he ne cou&thorn;e no&yogh;t his mester : gret sorue he hadde ynou;</L>
<L N="124">his wo he nom in pacience : to eche godnesse he drou.</L>
<L>heyward he was fiftene &yogh;er : in gret sorue &amp; care;</L>
<L>ne com noman nei him &thorn;at him kneu : his frend him<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Ashm. frendes, him om.</NOTE> were wel bare.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; ac<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. in Ashm.</NOTE> hit bifel &thorn;at &thorn;e emperour : &thorn;at his lord er was,</L>
<L N="128">y-worre&thorn; was of a no&thorn;er king : &thorn;orou a lu&thorn;er cas.</L>
<L>sone him misse&thorn;e &thorn;is gode kni&yogh;t : &amp; ofte he sede alas.</L>
<L>to many lond he sente aboute : to seche seint eustas.</L>
<L>tuei kni&yogh;tes &thorn;at his felaues were : &thorn;at so&yogh;te him sui&thorn;e wide,</L>
<L N="132">In his baille hi mette him : as hi come &thorn;er-ford ride.</L>
<L>seint eustas i-kneu hom wel : &amp; hi him no&yogh;t wit-alle&mdash;</L>
<L>for ho-so is in meseise &amp; in sor : his heu wole sone falle.</L>
<L>&para; "knowest," hi sede, "eni man : &thorn;at hatte placidas?"</L>
<L N="136">he sede nai, &amp; sede so&thorn; : for he het eustas.</L>
<L>&thorn;o gonne &thorn;is kni&yogh;tes sike sore&mdash; : &amp; hit was nei eue:</L>
<L>&thorn;is haiward hom ba&thorn; sui&thorn;e faire : al ni&yogh;t wit him bileue.</L>
<L>&thorn;o hi come hom to his In : he made hom faire chere
<PB REF="00000445.tif" N="397"></L>
<L N="140">&amp; cortesliche serue&thorn;e hom : quinte man as he were.</L>
<L>ac euer whan he from hom turne&thorn;e : &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> teres ourne of his eie;</L>
<L>ac fair semblant he made y-nou : euer whan hi him seie.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;is kni&yogh;tes &thorn;o&yogh;te won&thorn;er gret : &thorn;at a such heiward</L>
<L N="144">of so quinte seruise was : as he were eny stuard.</L>
<L>&thorn;e lengor &thorn;at hi him bihulde : &thorn;e bet hom &thorn;o&yogh;te [hi] him kneue&mdash;</L>
<L>for whan man is fol of mete &amp; drinke : hit<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. his</NOTE> sotele&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Ashm. so tele&thorn;</NOTE> in his hwe.</L>
<L>"&thorn;is man," sede &thorn;e on to &thorn;e o&thorn;er : "ilich is placidas,</L>
<L N="148">loke we where he haue &thorn;e wounde : &thorn;at on his hed was,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he hente in &thorn;e bataile? : for &yogh;if he ha&thorn; &thorn;ilke wounde</L>
<L>In &thorn;ilke stude, siker we be&thorn; : &thorn;at we him haue&thorn; i-founde."</L>
<L>&thorn;o hi founde &thorn;is so&thorn;e tokne : in gret ioie hi were ibro&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="152">hi sede, "&thorn;u art placidas : &thorn;at we longe haue&thorn; iso&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e emperour sente after &thorn;e : to him &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> schalt come,</L>
<L>for his fon haue&thorn; moche of his lond : for &thorn;e faute<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. defaute</NOTE> of &thorn;e y-nome."</L>
<L>sein eustas made gret daunger : &amp; na&thorn;eles ate nende</L>
<L N="156">to &thorn;e emperour of rome, his lord : wit hom he gan wende.</L>
<L>glad ti&thorn;ing com to &thorn;e emperour : &thorn;o he him isay!</L>
<L>he let him greidi in fair atir : as noble kni&yogh;t &amp; hei,</L>
<L>he let &yogh;arki his ost also : mony kni&yogh;t &amp; sueyn,</L>
<L N="160">&amp; made eustas, as he was er : of hom alle cheuenteyn.</L>
<L>&para; hi wente &amp; worre&thorn;e op hor fon : to grounde fer &amp; ner;</L>
<L>hi &thorn;at er al maistres were : nadde do no poer.</L>
<L>more prouesse ne mi&yogh;te be : &thorn;an was of &thorn;is kni&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="164">for he was of bodi strong : &amp; moche cou&thorn;e of fi&yogh;te,</L>
<L>&amp; he hadde wit him godes grace : be dai &amp; by ny&yogh;te;</L>
<L>&thorn;er-fore non heden man : a&yogh;en him stonde ne mi&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;e king hor fo vn&thorn;er-&yogh;et : &thorn;at his poer noding nas,</L>
<L N="168">&amp; &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;te worre holde : a&yogh;en sein eustas,</L>
<L>&para; he flei hom in-to his owe lond : vnne&thorn;e wit &thorn;e liue.</L>
<L>seint eustas wit his gode route : after sue&thorn;e bliue;</L>
<L>of his men he let ek mony nyme : &amp; slou ek of hom riue,</L>
<L N="172">he let sle al o&thorn;er nyme : o&thorn;er out of londe hom driue.</L>
<L>&yogh;ut he suor he wolde awreke be : of &thorn;e gret schonde</L>
<L>&thorn;at hi hadde his lord y-worre&thorn; : in his owe londe.</L>
<L>&para; gret maister he wex anon&mdash; : what, whare was &thorn;o his horn?</L>
<L N="176">he ne &yogh;ede no&yogh;t in &thorn;e feld afote : to wite man<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. mannes</NOTE> corn!</L>
<L>a maister heiward he was on : wit such men to fi&yogh;te,</L>
<L>to porswy in-to his owe lond : a king of so gret mi&yogh;te!</L>
<L N="179">he let ordeine wel his ost : &amp; parti hit a-&thorn;re,]
<PB REF="00000446.tif" N="398"></L>
<L>Cheuenteynes he liet [chese]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> tweie : vnder him to beo.<MILESTONE N="168" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;are weren &yogh;oungue tweie : faire men<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. manc</NOTE> with-alle,</L>
<L>with red heued, &yogh;eolu and crips<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Ashm. Rede men wi&thorn; &yogh;elou her</NOTE>&mdash; : fair cas &thorn;are gan bi-falle:</L>
<L>For &thorn;ere nere none into al &thorn;e Ost : &thorn;at so stalewor&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> men were</L>
<L N="184">Ne of so gret prouwesse in &thorn;e bataile : ne &thorn;at so wel armes bere,</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore Evstas vnder him : cheuenteynes heom made &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="186">Ey&thorn;er is owene compay[ni]e : swi&thorn;e wel to lede and lere.</L>
<L>huy siweden heore fo in-to is lond : no-&thorn;ing a-dradde huy nere;</L>
<L>And &thorn;o huy &thorn;e se i-passed hadden : heor baneres huy lieten<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. leieten</NOTE> a-rere,</L>
<L>&para; Into al &thorn;at lond huy wenten a-boute : and nomen alle &thorn;at huy founden,</L>
<L>heore fon huy slowen &thorn;at heore pouwer : was sone i-brou&yogh;t to grounde;</L>
<L>For huy nomen some and ladden forth : with heom, faste i-bounde,</L>
<L N="192">Some huy raymeden for heore lif : of manie harde poundes.</L>
<L>Are huy heom hadden so ouer-come : huy &yogh;euen manie woundes;</L>
<L>Gult-lese men &thorn;at weren of pais : huy lieten beo hole and sounde.</L>
<L>huy come and nomen a gret cite : and &thorn;are-inne huy a-li&yogh;hte;</L>
<L N="196">Ase louerdes huy resten &thorn;ere&mdash; : so fareth &thorn;at habbeth mi&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is two cheuenteynes &thorn;at weren : onder sire Eustas,</L>
<L N="198">huy casten of heore helmes heom for-to auente : heore bodi ful weri was;</L>
<L>Vnder a chaumbre huy resten heom : in a wel fair herber,</L>
<L>huy tolden of heore grete prouwesse : &thorn;at huy duden feor and ner.</L>
<L>"Wonderliche," &thorn;at on seide : "ich am forth i-gon.</L>
<L>Mi fader was kny&yogh;ht of gret pouwer : nis nou&yogh;h were nou&thorn;e schuch on;</L>
<L>&para; he and mi moder stilleliche : lieten heom cristni beye,</L>
<L N="204">And me and mi &yogh;oungue bro&thorn;ur<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. bro&thorn;us</NOTE> : &thorn;at weren his sones tweye.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. bey &yogh;e</NOTE></L>
<L>A ni&yogh;ht he nam is wif and us : &thorn;at his sones were,</L>
<L>And ladde us into ano&thorn;ur lond : &thorn;are we neuerer nere.</L>
<L>&THORN;o we &thorn;e se i-passede hadden : &thorn;e Mariner for is huyre</L>
<L N="208">Drof us out of is schip . and ore moder ladde awey : &thorn;at us was leof and duyre.</L>
<L>&para; Ore fader nam us and ladde us forth : swi&thorn;e gret deol he made.</L>
<L>To awater we comen &thorn;at was so deop : &thorn;at we ne mi&yogh;hten nou&yogh;ht wade :</L>
<L>Mi fader bar ouer mine &yogh;ounguere bro&thorn;er : and in &thorn;at o&thorn;ur half him sette,
<PB REF="00000447.tif" N="399"></L>
<L>And cam a wolf and bar him forth : &thorn;e &yogh;wyle he [me] wolde fette;</L>
<L>And are he mi&yogh;hte to me come : a leon &thorn;are cam eorne</L>
<L N="214">And kipte me and bar me forth : to-ward &thorn;e wode wel &yogh;eorne.</L>
<L>&para; Schepherdes ornen him a-&yogh;ein : with hornes and with hounde,</L>
<L>And crieden and schoten to-ward him : &thorn;at he me liet falle to grounde;</L>
<L>huy nomen and ladden me to heore hous : and lieten me forth bringue.</L>
<L N="218">Of fader ne of moder ne can ich : telle eov no ty&thorn;ingue."</L>
<L>&para; "Louerd crist," seide &thorn;at o&thorn;ur : "i-hered beo &thorn;i mi&yogh;hte,</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;at ich moste of mine leoue bro&thorn;ur : habbe one si&yogh;hte!</L>
<L>Certes," he seide, "ich am &thorn;i bro&thorn;ur : &thorn;at &thorn;e wolf a-wei bar;</L>
<L>Ake Aker-men weren in &thorn;e feld : &thorn;at weren of him i-war,</L>
<L>with staues and with stones al-so : a&yogh;en him huy ornen bliue</L>
<L N="224">And maden him legge me a-doun : so &thorn;at ich cam to liue."</L>
<L>louerd, muche was &thorn;e Ioye : &thorn;at bi-twene heom was &thorn;ere!<MILESTONE N="168b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Mest huy bi-menden fader and moder : &thorn;at huy nusten &yogh;ware huy were.</L>
<L>&para; Heore Moder sat and heorde &thorn;is : In ane chaumbre &thorn;are-bi-side:</L>
<L>welle, louerd, &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">= heo</NOTE> was glad : &thorn;at heo mi&yogh;hte &thorn;ane day a-bide!</L>
<L>Sori heo was &thorn;at heo ne mi&yogh;hte out : with hire sones to speke&mdash;</L>
<L>Ake heo was bi-loke ase a prison : ne heo ne mi&yogh;hte &thorn;at hous breke;</L>
<L>For heo and manie o&thorn;er : in ostage weren itake.</L>
<L N="232">Bi-fore &thorn;e prince heo was seth&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t : hire fin for-to make.</L>
<L>&THORN;o isai&yogh; heo &yogh;ware hire louerd was&mdash; : a-doun heo feol to grounde,</L>
<L>"I-hered beo &thorn;ou, ihesu crist!" heo seide : "mine louerd ich habbe i-founde!"</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is guode kni&yogh;ht [gan]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> for io&yacute;e to wepe : he clupte hire and custe;</L>
<L N="236">More Ioye &thorn;ane [was heom]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> bi-twene : no man neuerer nuste.</L>
<L>"Sire, merci," heo seide : "ne haue &thorn;ou no mis-&thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For god it wot, ich am clene : and i-wemmed nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>For also-sone as &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere man : me hadde fram &thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="240">he vuelde, and deide sone : bi god &thorn;at ich habbe i-sou&yogh;t!"</L>
<L>&THORN;o was &thorn;is guode kni&yogh;ht gladore : bi muche &thorn;ane he er was!</L>
<L N="242">"Dame," he seide, "of ore leoue sones : quite we beoth, alas!</L>
<L>For a leon bar &thorn;at on a-wei : and a wolf &thorn;at o&thorn;ur also;</L>
<L>Wel ich wot &thorn;at huy to-drawe beoth : inot &yogh;wat we schullen do."</L>
<L>&para; "Sire," seide &thorn;is guode wif : "make gret Ioye with-alle,</L>
<L N="246">Among alle &thorn;e men &thorn;at euere weren : fairest us is bi-falle:
<PB REF="00000448.tif" N="400"></L>
<L>For ase ich in a chaumbre sat : kni&yogh;htes ich heorde twei&yogh;e</L>
<L>Tellen of us so &thorn;at ichwot : &thorn;at it weren ovre sones bei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Lat of-sechen &yogh;wuche huy beoth : for so&thorn;e, huy beoth of &thorn;ine.</L>
<L N="250">Beo glad and in alle Ioye : for we habbez ouer-come ore pine."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is kni&yogh;ht for Ioye liet sende a-boute : &thorn;e messagers neren nou&yogh;t bi-hynde;</L>
<L>he liet seche and crien ouer-al : &yogh;if men mi&yogh;hten anie swuche i-finde.</L>
<L>he fond &thorn;at is sones weren : onder him cheuentey[n]s,</L>
<L N="254">&THORN;at he him-sulf made for heore prouwesse : of &thorn;e ostes souereins.</L>
<L>Glade huy hadde er i-beo : ake so glade neuere huy nere,</L>
<L N="256">&THORN;o fader and moder and &thorn;e sones : to-gadere i-come were;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e fader and &thorn;e sones : &thorn;e maistrie a-wei bere<NOTE PLACE="marg1">v. 256-7 seem spurious.</NOTE></L>
<L>And maistres weren of al &thorn;at folk : to ordeinen heom and to lere.</L>
<L>&para; Louerd, muche is &thorn;i mi&yogh;hte : and &thorn;at &thorn;ou cuddest &thorn;ere&mdash;</L>
<L N="260">For &thorn;at &thorn;ou i-saued habbe wolt : no-&thorn;ing ne schal fur-pere.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;is guode kni&yogh;ht and is sones : and heore ost at&thorn;en ende</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maistrie hadden of alle heore fon : hamward huy guonne wiende</L>
<L N="263">with gret Ioye and nobleye&mdash; : of no man heom ne dradde;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e hexte men of &thorn;e londe : ase prisones with heom huy ladde.</L>
<L>Muche pris &thorn;are was of heom : ase huy wenden toward rome.</L>
<L N="266">Ake deolfole ti&thorn;ingues huy founden &thorn;ere : &thorn;o huy &thorn;udere come:</L>
<L>For huy founden hore louerd ded : &thorn;ene Aumperour traIan,</L>
<L N="268">And an o&thorn;er huy founden imad after him : &thorn;at hiet Adrian,</L>
<L>&THORN;at muche schame dude cristine men : &yogh;ware anie weren i-nome.</L>
<L>Gret Ioye he made with &thorn;is kni&yogh;htes : &thorn;o huy weren &thorn;udere i-come,<MILESTONE N="169" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For heore prouwesse, and for heore prisones : &thorn;at huy mid heom brou&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>hext prince of &thorn;at lond vnder him : sire Eustas makie he &thorn;ou&yogh;hte;</L>
<L N="273">Bote it were bi is red : no-&thorn;ing don he nolde,</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane he wende into anie stude : euere mid him he scholde.</L>
<L>&para; A dai huy comen bi heore temple : &thorn;at heore maumates inne were:</L>
<L N="276">&THORN;e Aumperour li&yogh;hte a-doun : to don &thorn;are is preiere.</L>
<L>Sire Eustas nolde nou&yogh;t &thorn;are-inne come : ake bi-lefde &thorn;ere-with-oute.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Aumperour in wrath&thorn;e axede a-non : &yogh;ware-of he hadde doute</L>
<L N="279">And &yogh;wi he ne a-li&yogh;hte, ase ri&yogh;ht were : and to is godes a-loute.</L>
<L>"Sire," seide sire Eustas, "it is for nou&yogh;t : &thorn;at &thorn;ou art &thorn;are-a-boute;
<PB REF="00000449.tif" N="401"></L>
<L N="281">I-ne rechche a-liue ho it wite : cristine ich am, i-wis.</L>
<L>Of swuch a prince ase &thorn;ou art, gret deol is : &thorn;at so schal bi-leue a-mis."</L>
<L>&para; "Ov!" seide &thorn;e Aumperour : "hast &thorn;ou &thorn;us i-seid?</L>
<L N="284">habbe ich &thorn;us i-loued &thorn;e : and &thorn;ou me hast bi-treid?</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou louest &thorn;in owene stat : torne &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t, ich rede,</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur &thorn;ou schalt segge &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne dudest : neuere so lu&thorn;er dede."</L>
<L>"Certes, sire, for nou&yogh;t it is" : &thorn;is guode kni&yogh;ht a-&yogh;ein seide,</L>
<L>"holde ichulle &thorn;at ich habbe i-take : I-ne bi-leue it for no drede."</L>
<L>wod-wroth was &thorn;e Aumperour : he liet him binde faste</L>
<L N="290">And leden hom to is paleis : and among leones him caste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy scholden for-swolewen euerech lime : of &thorn;is guode kni&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>huy a-lutten to him and lickeden him&mdash; : &thorn;are was godes mi&yogh;hte!</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;o is sones and is wif : herof heorden telle</L>
<L N="294">&THORN;at &thorn;e Aumperour heore louerd nome : him for-to a-quelle,</L>
<L>huy comen eorne with gret eyr : and axeden &yogh;ware he were,</L>
<L>And seiden huy wolden for godes<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. guodes</NOTE> loue : mid him dei&yogh;e &thorn;ere.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">v. 300 is to follow here.</NOTE></L>
<L>he schok is heued and criede loude : and ter him bi is here;</L>
<L N="298">he liet makie ane tonne of bras : for-to berne heom &thorn;are-inne.</L>
<L>Wel wusten &thorn;is guode kni&yogh;htes : &yogh;wat huy scholden &thorn;are-with iwinne.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o was &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere Aumperour : wro&thorn;ere &thorn;ane he was bi-fore.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. ere</NOTE></L>
<L>Sire Eustas sat a-doun a-kneo : and seide, "nou&thorn;e, louerd, &thorn;in ore!</L>
<L N="302">Graunte us to &thorn;e Ioye of heouene : comen aftur &thorn;is sore,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ore &thorn;ou&yogh;t studefast beo : and treowe euere-more.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">v. 303 added.</NOTE></L>
<L>Graunte us &thorn;at alle guode men : &thorn;at us habbuth in muynde</L>
<L>And of us bi-sechez help to &thorn;e : &thorn;at huy it moten finde,</L>
<L N="306">&THORN;at huy of peril beon i-brou&yogh;t : and of alle o&thorn;ure vuele al-so,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou, &yogh;if it is &thorn;i wille : into &thorn;e Ioye of heouene heom do.</L>
<L>we foure &thorn;at muche of ore lif : i-liued habbeth in wo,</L>
<L>Graunte us one stude to ore martyrdom : and to ore burijngue al-so,</L>
<L N="310">&THORN;at we in one stude forto domes-day : to-gadere resten mote,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e sike of bodie and of soule : at us habben bote."</L>
<L N="312">&para; &THORN;o cam &thorn;are a uoyz, and seide : "Eustas, glad &thorn;ou beo,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at &thorn;ou i-bede hast : god hat<SUP>h</SUP> i-graunted &thorn;e."<MILESTONE N="169b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;is tormentores nomen &thorn;is guode kni&yogh;ht : and is sones and is wif,</L>
<L>And duden heom in ane tonne of bras : to leten &thorn;are heore lijf;</L>
<L N="316">Gret fuyr huy &thorn;are-aboute maden : bi-neo&thorn;e and a-boue:
<PB REF="00000450.tif" N="402"></L>
<L>And &thorn;are huy &thorn;oleden martyrdom : for ore louerdes loue.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;is fuyr hadde longue i-barnd : a-boute &thorn;e brasene tonne,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at bras was muche i-molte : and to-gadere i-ronne,</L>
<L N="320">huy eoden ner, and &thorn;is holie men : wel faire liggen huy founde,</L>
<L>So &yogh;wijht schininde so eni milk : &thorn;e bodies hole and sounde</L>
<L>And &thorn;e soulene ore louerd bi-tai&yogh;t&mdash; : for &thorn;are nas of clo&thorn;e ne of here,</L>
<L>Ne of no stude of alle heore bodies : &thorn;at of &thorn;e fuyre i-weommede were.</L>
<L>&para; Cristine men a-wayteden heore point : and stelen &thorn;are-to bi ni&yogh;hte</L>
<L>And &thorn;eos holie bodies ladden a-wey : and longue &thorn;are-to huy ti&yogh;hte</L>
<L N="326">And bureden heom faire in one stude : to &yogh;wuche huy weren i-brou&yogh;t&mdash;</L>
<L>For ore louerd wolde &thorn;at it were : ase huy hadden him erore bi-sou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>An hondred &yogh;er i-passede weren : and twenti also</L>
<L>Aftur ore louerdes buyrtyme : &thorn;at huy weren to de&thorn;e ido.</L>
<L N="330">&THORN;us seint Eustas mid is wif : and mid is sones cam</L>
<L>To &thorn;e hei&yogh;e Ioye of heouene : &thorn;oru&yogh; strong martyrdom.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="60" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>60 [Iohan ap.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Iohan &thorn;e ewangelist : &thorn;at Apostel is,</L>
<L>was ore louerdes Aunte sone : and seint Iemes bro&thorn;ur, i-wis:</L>
<L>his Moder was ore lauedie suster : Marie cleophe,</L>
<L N="4">I-wedded heo was to is fader : &thorn;at hiet zebede;</L>
<L>&THORN;is Zebede hadde twei&yogh;e sones : bi Marie is wif:</L>
<L>&THORN;es seint Iohan and eke seint Ieme : &thorn;at ladden wel holi lijf.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Iohan was &yogh;onguore &thorn;ane ore louerd: twelf mon&thorn;e o&thorn;ur &thorn;ere-a-boute;</L>
<L N="8">For is kun he was &thorn;e betere Man : &thorn;ar-of nis no doute:</L>
<L>And natheles he was, ich wene : &thorn;ritti &yogh;er old nei&yogh;h</L>
<L>Are hee ou&yogh;t muche of ore louerd wuste : o&thorn;er are he him muche isei&yogh;h.</L>
<L>For ore louerd nas bote luyte i-knowe : ne he ne cudde him nou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="12">Are he i-baptized were : and to cristine-dom i-brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And &yogh;eot ne cudde he him nou&yogh;t a-brod : are seint Iohan &thorn;e baptist were</L>
<L>I-martred for &thorn;e lawe of holie churche : &thorn;at he gan heroudes lere.</L>
<L>&para; Ake &thorn;o seint Iohan i-martred was : ore louerd ne sparede nou&yogh;ht
<PB REF="00000451.tif" N="403"></L>
<L N="16">Forto gon and prechi a-boute : til he was to de&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>To beon is desciples furst he ches : twei&yogh;e bre&thorn;ren &thorn;o :</L>
<L>Seint petre and seint Andreu : ase he cam bi &thorn;e se go;</L>
<L>And &thorn;are he sai&yogh;h tweie bre&thorn;ren &thorn;o : seint Ieme and &thorn;es seint Iohan,</L>
<L N="20">with &thorn;e olde man Zebede : heore fader, a-fischeth gon :</L>
<L>&para; heom he cleopede al-so to him : and huy bi-lefden a-non</L>
<L>heore fader, and siweden him : and token &thorn;e betere won.</L>
<L>Seint Iohan was best with him : of is desciples echon :</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;at was i-sene &thorn;o he leonede : an<SUP>d</SUP> slep <SUP>op</SUP>on is breoste-bon;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e &yogh;wile he made is cene : ase on schere-&thorn;ores-day,</L>
<L>Seint Iohan among is desciples : to is swete breste lay.</L>
<L>A-morewe, ase on &thorn;e guode friday : ase he deide on &thorn;e rode,</L>
<L N="28">his swete moder and seint Iohan : faste bi him stode :</L>
<L>&THORN;ere in seint Iohanes warde : is swete moder he tok,<MILESTONE N="170" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To wardi ase hire owene sone : ase we findez i-write in bok.</L>
<L>&para; hire wardein he was aftur also : &thorn;at he to heouene i-wende,</L>
<L N="32">Al &thorn;e &yogh;wyle &thorn;at heo on eor&thorn;e was : for-to he aftur hire sende.</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;ht it was to wardi hire : &yogh;wane heo is Aunte was,</L>
<L>And for &thorn;are nas non o&thorn;ur<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> no&thorn;er</NOTE> of heom : &thorn;at clene mayde was;<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> nas</NOTE></L>
<L>Clene mayde to wardi o&thorn;ur : ri&yogh;ht it was i-do<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> to do</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;are-fore in is swete warde : ore louerd bi-tok hire so.&mdash;</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;at ore louerd was : to &thorn;e Ioye of heouene i-went,</L>
<L>And his desciples a-witsonenday : &thorn;ene holi gost hadde i-sent,</L>
<L>&para; huy wenden forth wel baldeliche : euerech in is side,</L>
<L N="40">A-boute in diuerse londes : and precheden wel wide.</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e londe of Asye : seint Iohan &thorn;e ewangelist</L>
<L N="42">wende, to wissi &thorn;ulke side : and prechede of Iesu crist.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Cite of Efese : at&thorn;e laste he com,</L>
<L>&THORN;are he hadde him-sulue hous and hom : and prechede cristindom.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Aumperour domician : &thorn;at lu&thorn;ur was i-nov&yogh;h,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e cristine Men &thorn;at he fond : he tormentede o&thorn;ur a-slou&yogh;h.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at seint Iohan was i-nome : &thorn;at longue hadde beo i-sou&yogh;ht;</L>
<L N="48">Bi-fore &thorn;e Aumperores Iustise : ful sone<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> to rome</NOTE> he was i-brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iustise &thorn;ou&yogh;hte anon : fram god to tuyrne is &thorn;ou&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>"Certes," quath &thorn;is holie Man : "&thorn;are-to ne bringest &thorn;ou it nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>For ichulle more don after god : &thorn;ane aftur &thorn;e, i-wis."
<PB REF="00000452.tif" N="404"></L>
<L N="52">Welle, wroth&thorn; was &thorn;e Iustise : &thorn;o he i-heorde &thorn;is!</L>
<L>Ane tonne ful of Eoyle he nam : and liet it boylie faste,</L>
<L>And al wallinde &thorn;esne holie Man : a-midde &thorn;e eolie he caste.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Iohan &thorn;are-inne sat : so longue so it was,</L>
<L N="56">he ne chaungede neuer ene his hiev : ne neuere &thorn;e worse him nas,</L>
<L>Ake al hol with-outen eni harm : out of &thorn;is eolye he a-ros&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iustise &thorn;at him &thorn;er-inne brou&yogh;te : &thorn;ar-of wel sore a-gros.</L>
<L>&THORN;is was in rome bi-fore a &yogh;at : &thorn;at &thorn;is dede was i-do,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;at men cleopeden "&thorn;e porte latin" : and &yogh;uyt men doth also.</L>
<L>A-seint Iohanes day it was : in &thorn;e bi-ginningue of may.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ulke miracle men holdez &yogh;uyt : &thorn;oru al &thorn;e lond is day;</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at &yogh;at hiet "porte latyn" : &thorn;are &thorn;e dede was i-do,</L>
<L N="64">&YOGH;uy[t] men holdeth<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> writ</NOTE> &thorn;ilke day : of seint Iohan<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> of porte latyn</NOTE> al-so.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; Domician &thorn;e Aumperour : &thorn;o he i-sai&yogh;h &thorn;is cas</L>
<L>&THORN;at seint Iohan nas no-&thorn;e worse : &thorn;at he in &thorn;e eolie was,</L>
<L>wod-wroth he was and sori i-nou&yogh;h : ake natheles he ne dorste nou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="68">For cristine Men, &thorn;at he were : &thorn;oru&yogh; him to de&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;ht;</L>
<L>he hiet him fleo out of &thorn;e londe : &thorn;at non more he ne come &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>I-harled he was out of rome : ase &thorn;ei he strong &thorn;eof were,</L>
<L>And i-outlawed ase a &thorn;eof : &thorn;at he in &thorn;e contreye ne come.</L>
<L N="72">Into &thorn;e yle of patmos : he wende out of rome,</L>
<L>And wonede &thorn;are in penaunce : twelf mon&thorn;es nei&yogh;h.</L>
<L>Of ore louerdes priuetez : wel muche he &thorn;are i-sei&yogh;h,</L>
<L>For ofte &thorn;e priuetez of heouene : ore louerd him schewede &thorn;ere.<MILESTONE N="170b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="76">&YOGH;ware-of he made &thorn;are ane bok : al-holi churche to lere,</L>
<L>&thorn;at men cleopeth "Apocalips" : &thorn;at men redez in churche al day;</L>
<L>Muche is of godes priuetez : &thorn;at he &thorn;are i-sai&yogh;.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. i sai&yogh;h</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e furste &yogh;er &thorn;at seint Iohan: &thorn;us i-outlawed was,</L>
<L N="80">Of &thorn;e Aumperour &thorn;at him drof awey : &thorn;are bi-feol a sori cas :</L>
<L>For &thorn;e senatour him a-slov&yogh; : &thorn;at was &thorn;o of rome,</L>
<L>In contek &thorn;at heom was bi-twene&mdash; : for huy conteckeden i-lome.</L>
<L>Seint Iones pays was sone i-cried : and alle o&thorn;eres also</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;at weren &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e Aumperour : in outlawingue ido.</L>
<L>Seint Iohan him wende a-&yogh;einward &thorn;o : mildeliche i-nov&yogh;;</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e cite of Efese : to is owene hous he drou&yogh;&mdash;</L>
<L>For he hadde &thorn;are hous and hom : and kun and freond i-nowe.
<PB REF="00000453.tif" N="405"></L>
<L N="88">Men and wimmen of &thorn;e toun : wel &thorn;icke a-&yogh;ein him drowe,</L>
<L>To wel-comien him with grete Ioye : and in-to toune him brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>with swi&thorn;e gret procession : ase huy ful wel ou&yogh;ten.</L>
<L>&para; Ase huy wenden &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e toun : with grete Ioye &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="92">Men and wimmen a-&yogh;ein heom comen : with ful dreorie chere :</L>
<L>For drusiane, a ded womman : toward vr&thorn;e huy bere;</L>
<L>&THORN;are was for hire deol i-nov&yogh; : and wel sorie alle huy were.</L>
<L>Gret loue &thorn;are hadde er i-beo : bi-tweone hire and seint Iohan.</L>
<L N="96">Ase sone ase &thorn;at folk him i-sai&yogh; : &thorn;e gladdore alle huy were a-non;</L>
<L>huy gonne on him to crie faste : "sire," huy seiden, "&thorn;in ore!</L>
<L>&THORN;is is drusiane, &thorn;i guode freond : &thorn;at was vnder &thorn;i lore.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wost wel heo hath &thorn;e muche i-loued : nov ne may heo nonmore,</L>
<L N="100">here heo is in &thorn;is bere ded : heo makez us carie sore.</L>
<L>&para; Heo ne wilnede non o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing : &thorn;e &yogh;wile heo sik lay,</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">= heo</NOTE> moste &thorn;e i-seon : are hire ende-day :</L>
<L>And nou&thorn;e it is so ase &thorn;ou sixt : &thorn;at, &thorn;ei &thorn;ou beo here, heo ne may!</L>
<L N="104">&THORN;ench on &thorn;e loue &thorn;at heo &thorn;e louede : seth&thorn;e heo &thorn;e furst i-say;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou woldest us swuch grace do : and a-&yogh;ein to liue hire bringue,</L>
<L>Euere we scholden herie &thorn;e : and &thorn;e kingue of alle kyngue."</L>
<L>&para; seint Iohan bi-gan to sichen sore : ase he in &thorn;ou&yogh;hte were;</L>
<L N="108">he bad heom ane stounde a-bide : and setten a-doun &thorn;e bere.</L>
<L>he sat a-doun wel softe a-kneo : and criede to ore louerd &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&THORN;is woman &thorn;at him so muche louede : &yogh;if it were is wille, a-rere.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he hadde i-seid is oresun : anon-ri&yogh;ht in &thorn;e place</L>
<L N="112">&THORN;is womman a-ros up hol and sound : &thorn;oru&yogh; ore louerdes grace,</L>
<L>And herede faste ihesu crist : and &thorn;ene holie man sein Iohan&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;are was prece of alle &thorn;e men : &thorn;at &thorn;udere mi&yogh;hten gon.</L>
<L>Seint Iohan bad hire go hom a-non : and grey&thorn;i som-&thorn;ing to mete</L>
<L N="116">Athom in hire owene hous : &thorn;at he mi&yogh;hte with hire ete.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;eos drusiane wente forth : and &yogh;a[r]kede mete i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L>And made seint Iohan fair semblaunt : and elles it were wou&yogh;.&mdash;</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">[fol. not numbered]</NOTE>In &thorn;e cite of Efese : seint Iohan bi-lefde longue,</L>
<L N="120">And prechede &thorn;at folk to gode tuyrne : and cristindom a-fongue,</L>
<L>And ordeinede preostes : and churchene liet a-rere,</L>
<L>Bischopes he made beste Men : &thorn;at folk for-to lere.
<PB REF="00000454.tif" N="406"></L>
<L>&THORN;is guode Men &thorn;at vnder him weren : bischopes and o&thorn;ere also,</L>
<L N="124">Fondeden bo&thorn;e ni&yogh;ht and day : aftur is wissingue do.</L>
<L>huy crieden on him with al hore mi&yogh;hte : alle of one<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;e</NOTE> cite :</L>
<L>For he wuste so muche and vnder-&yogh;at : of ore louerdes priuete</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;wile he with him on eor&thorn;e was : and next him euere also,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he scholde of is holie lijf : in sum guode bok do,</L>
<L>And of is kuynde &yogh;wat he was : and &thorn;at folk don to lore,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> aboute lere</NOTE></L>
<L N="130">&THORN;at huy mi&yogh;hten &thorn;e betere iwite : &yogh;wat ore swete louerd wore.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Iohan bi-sou&yogh;te &thorn;at folk &yogh;eorne : for him &thorn;at huy bede</L>
<L N="132">In fastingue and in orisones : to don a swuch holi dede;</L>
<L>And wende into a derne stude : and bad ore louerd faste</L>
<L>&THORN;at he scholde &thorn;ene holie gost : into is heorte caste,</L>
<L>&THORN;e holie Godspel of him to make : al-holie churche to lere,</L>
<L N="136">&YOGH;ware-&thorn;oru&yogh; euerech cristine man : &thorn;e betere bi-lieued were.</L>
<L>he bad al-so &thorn;at &thorn;are ne scholde : &thorn;oru&yogh; ore louerdes grace</L>
<L>wind. ne reyn. ne o&thorn;ur weder : come nei&yogh;him in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>To letten him of is holie dede : &thorn;e &yogh;wyle he &thorn;are-a-boute were.</L>
<L N="140">Ore louerd heorde is bone wel : &thorn;at no weder ne lette him &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Ne cam no wynd &yogh;eot to &thorn;is day : ase &thorn;e holie Man it bad,</L>
<L>Ne o&thorn;ur tempeste in &thorn;ulke stude : as &thorn;e bok was i-mad,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> a v. more: Holi is &thorn;e bok when so holi is &thorn;e stede</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at &thorn;er ne</NOTE> mi&yogh;hte neuereft come tempeste : ase &thorn;e holie man it bad.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">hadde ibede</NOTE></L>
<L>A-non so seint Ion bi-gan : to don &thorn;is holie dede,</L>
<L>I-tend he was of &thorn;e holie gost : &thorn;at ech del &thorn;at he seide</L>
<L>he sek of ore louerdes breoste : ase he &thorn;ar-to lay</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;wile he made is swete cene : a-schere-&thorn;oresday;</L>
<L N="148">&THORN;are he sek out &thorn;at holie wit : of &thorn;e holie godspelle</L>
<L>&THORN;at he made seth&thorn;e in Efese : a-mong cristine Men to telle.</L>
<L>he was &thorn;e feor&thorn;e Ewangelist : and herre nas &thorn;are non;</L>
<L>And is godspel he made last : of heom euerechon.</L>
<L N="152">Seint Matheu and seint Mark : and eke seint luc, i-wis,</L>
<L>heore god-spelles huy hadden longue i-maud : are he bi-guonne his.</L>
<L>Ake seint Iohan bi-gan his hext : for &thorn;are-on he bi-gan</L>
<L>Of ore louerd al &yogh;wat he was : are &thorn;at he were Man;</L>
<L N="156">he bi-gan so hei&yogh;e is godspel<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. godspell</NOTE> : of ore louerdes kuynde, i-wis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vnne&thorn;e ani Man eor&thorn;elich : entendeth &yogh;wat it is.</L>
<L>For he sou&yogh;hte so deope is kuynde : and of him bi-gan so hei&yogh;e,
<PB REF="00000455.tif" N="407"></L>
<L>In &thorn;e fourme of Ane Ern he is de-peint : ase we ofte i-seoth with ei&yogh;e.</L>
<L N="160">For &thorn;e Ern is swiftest<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. sucth (= seoth) best</NOTE> of alle foules : and hext he may fleo:</L>
<L>For &yogh;wane he is in &thorn;e lofte an hei&yogh;h : &thorn;at herre ne may non beo,</L>
<L>&YOGH;uyt he may here in &thorn;e grounde : ane luttle worm i-seo;<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> a v. more : &amp; ate se-gronde a smal fisch : to chese wider to teo.</NOTE></L>
<L>Also he may so hei&yogh;e fleo : and &thorn;e firmament so nei&yogh;h,</L>
<L N="164">&THORN;at almest is wyngene brenneth : &yogh;wane he is so hei&yogh;h.</L>
<L>&para; Se<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Seint (S<SUP>e</SUP>)</NOTE> Iohan &thorn;at is<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> is in</NOTE> &thorn;e fourme of Ern : is godspelles wel hei&yogh;e bi-gan,</L>
<L>&THORN;are-inne he tolde al is<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> our louerdes</NOTE> lif : &thorn;e &yogh;wile he was on eor&thorn; man.</L>
<L>his godspel is swi&thorn;e hei&yogh; i-holde : ase wel ri&yogh;ht it is,</L>
<L>For muche del of holi churche : &thorn;er-&thorn;oru&yogh;h i-loked is.</L>
<L>Seint Iohan cudde &thorn;is godspel sone : and prechede it faste al-so;</L>
<L N="170">&YOGH;eot &thorn;are weren lu&thorn;ere men : &thorn;at onde hadden &thorn;are-to.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; On atyme manie lu&thorn;ere Men : to-gadere heom hadden i-nome</L>
<L>And to seint Iohan &thorn;e ewangelist : in grete wrath&thorn;e come</L>
<L>And heten him wende forth with heom : to heore maumates a non</L>
<L N="174">And a-nouri as forth with heom : o&thorn;ur it scholde an-o&thorn;ur gon.</L>
<L>"Beu freres," quath &thorn;is holie Man : "ichulle segge eou a soth&thorn;&mdash;</L>
<L>Ich habbe reu&thorn;e of eov in mine heorte : &thorn;at &yogh;e nutez &yogh;wat &yogh;e doth&thorn;.</L>
<L>Ichulle don eou chois of tweiy &thorn;ingues : and &thorn;arof cheose &yogh;e:</L>
<L N="178">To gon<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at ich go</NOTE> with eou to eower temple : o&thorn;ur &yogh;e to churche with me;</L>
<L>&para; &YOGH;wane &YOGH;e to godes churche comieth : &yogh;if &yogh;e &thorn;oru&yogh; eower godes lawe</L>
<L>Mouwen make &thorn;e churche to falle : bi-lieue ichulle on heom fawe;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if ich may bi<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> so</NOTE> eower temple : bi-fore eower owene si&yogh;hte,</L>
<L N="182">Bi-leueth on Ihesu crist, ich rede : &yogh;wane &yogh;e i-seoth&thorn; is mi&yogh;hte."</L>
<L>"We grauntiez wel," &thorn;is o&thorn;ure seiden : "&thorn;ou schalt furst bi-guynne</L>
<L N="184">To cuy&thorn;e &thorn;ine louerdes mi&yogh;hte : &thorn;e maistrie forto wynne."</L>
<L>To &thorn;e false temple huy wenden furst : and &thorn;o huy weren &thorn;are-nei&yogh;h alle,</L>
<L>Seint Iohan bad heom stonde fer : &thorn;at huy ne weren of-falle.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o huy weren alle with-drawen a-feor : seint Iohan a-feor stod;</L>
<L N="188">"I-seo &yogh;e," he seide, "&thorn;is temple alle : &thorn;at &yogh;e holdeth so guod?</L>
<L>Ich hote hire in mine louerdes name : &thorn;at heo falle a-non,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e mowen &thorn;e so&thorn;e i-seon : bi-fore eou here ech-on."</L>
<L>Ne hadde he bote &thorn;at word i-seid : &thorn;at heo ne ful up &thorn;e doun,</L>
<L N="192">Fram ende to o&thorn;ur, al &thorn;is temple : with swi&thorn;e grislich soun.
<PB REF="00000456.tif" N="408"></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o al &thorn;at folk &thorn;at &thorn;are stod : &thorn;is miracle i-sei&yogh;h,</L>
<L>huy gonne to crien on Ihesu crist : and on seint Iohan an hei&yogh;h;</L>
<L>Twelf &thorn;ousend Men &thorn;are torneden : echone to cristindom,</L>
<L N="196">with-oute children and wimmen : &thorn;at turneden also mani on.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; ARistodimus, &thorn;e Bischop : and Maister of &thorn;e lawe,</L>
<L>&YOGH;uyt ne mi&yogh;hte nou&yogh;ht seint Iohan : to ore louerd is herte drawe:</L>
<L>For &thorn;o he isai&yogh;h &thorn;is faire miracle : &thorn;at &thorn;e temple ful so &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="200">&YOGH;eot nolde he it nou&yogh;ht i-leue : &thorn;at ani miracle it were;</L>
<L>he nolde i-lieue in none manere : &thorn;at ore louerd were of mi&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>Seint Iohan stod and &thorn;ou&yogh;hte longue : hou he him mi&yogh;hte bringue best to ri&yogh;hte,</L>
<L>&para; And seide, "sei&yogh;e &thorn;ou me &yogh;wat i schal do : &thorn;at &thorn;ou bi-fore &thorn;e i-seo;</L>
<L N="204">And bote &yogh;if ich it do, ne lief &thorn;ou nou&yogh;ht : &thorn;at mi louerd al-mi&yogh;hti beo."</L>
<L>"Par fey," quath &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere Man : "nov ichulle herkni &thorn;e;</L>
<L N="206">Do nou&thorn;e &thorn;at ichulle &thorn;e segge : and &thorn;ou schalt winne me.</L>
<L>Venim ich habbe, strong i-nov&yogh;h : &thorn;at ho-so &thorn;arof nimeth ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ne come &thorn;ere with-inne him neuere so luyte : to de&thorn;e he worth&thorn; i-brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg1">This verse is doubled in the MS.</NOTE>Drink &thorn;are-of bi-fore<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. b : atfore</NOTE> mine eyene<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Ey&yogh;en</NOTE> : and &yogh;if it ne greueth<NOTE PLACE="marg1">greuez</NOTE> &thorn;e nou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>To Ihesu crist, &thorn;at is &thorn;i god : ichulle take al mi &thorn;ou&yogh;ht."<MILESTONE N="171" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"&THORN;ou seist wel i-nou&yogh;," quath seint Iohan : "bring nou&thorn;e hidere to me</L>
<L N="212">&THORN;at strongue venym, and ichulle : hit drinke bi-fore &thorn;e."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e false Bischop him bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;the : for-to a-gasten him &thorn;e sarrore &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And also to seon &thorn;e so&thorn;e : &thorn;at his god of pouwer were:</L>
<L>Twey men &thorn;are weren, to de&thorn;e i-dempt : for heore lu&thorn;ere dede,</L>
<L N="216">&THORN;e false bischop dude hem bo&thorn;e : bi-fore seint Iohan lede</L>
<L>And made heom drinke of &thorn;at venym : ri&yogh;th bi-fore is ey&yogh;e.</L>
<L>A-non so it ou&yogh;t with-inne hem cam : bo&thorn;e huy gonne dey&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Iohan seth&thorn;e &thorn;e coppe tok : &thorn;o he isai&yogh;h al &thorn;is cas,</L>
<L>And dronk &thorn;are-of ane grete drau&yogh;t : and neuere &thorn;e worse him nas,</L>
<L>Ake euere &thorn;e lengore &thorn;are-aftur-ward : &thorn;e more Ioye he made and blis</L>
<L N="222">&THORN;at folk stod al in gret wonder : &thorn;o huy i-sei&yogh;en al &thorn;is.</L>
<L>&para; huy stoden and bi-heolden sein Iohan longue : &thorn;re tidene and more,
<PB REF="00000457.tif" N="409"></L>
<L N="224">And euere &thorn;e leng &thorn;e gladdore : huy sei&yogh;en him for al his sore:</L>
<L>To Ie[s]u crist huy gonne tuyrne : and criden merci a-non;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at huy to cristine-dom : &thorn;are turnde, wel many on.</L>
<L>&para; Ake Aristod[i]mus &thorn;e Bischop : was euere in lu&thorn;ere &thorn;ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="228">And ne bi-liefde nou&yogh;ht in Iesu crist : for al &thorn;at he &thorn;are wrou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;wat fayllez &thorn;e &yogh;uyt?" quath seint Iohan : "me &thorn;unchez it is with wou&yogh;h</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou ne leuest ore louerdes mi&yogh;hte&mdash; : ne sixt &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t &yogh;uyt i-nov&yogh;?"<NOTE PLACE="marg1">This v. on the margin.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Bote &thorn;ou most &yogh;uyt," quath &thorn;e Bischop : "&thorn;e dede to liue a-rere</L>
<L N="232">&THORN;at to de&thorn;e with &thorn;is venym : a-poysoned nou ri&yogh;ht were."</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou seist nou&thorn;e ful wel," quath seint Iohan : "ake &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;e so&thorn;e i-seo,</L>
<L N="234">I-nelle nou&yogh;t mi-sulf ney hem<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. him</NOTE> come : ake ope &thorn;e it schal al beo.</L>
<L>Nim mine cuyrtel here to &thorn;e : and lei&yogh;e ope hem a-non,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. anom</NOTE></L>
<L>And in &thorn;e name of Iesu crist : hot heom a-rise a[nd]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. a</NOTE> gon."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e bischop nam seint Iohanes Cuyrtel : bi-fore ri&yogh;ht &thorn;e Iustise,</L>
<L>And leide ope &thorn;e dede and het heom &thorn;o : in ore louerdes name a-rise.</L>
<L>A-non so he hadde &thorn;is word i-seid : &thorn;is men a-risen a-non</L>
<L N="240">And &yogh;eoden forth hole and sounde : and &thorn;onkeden seint Iohan.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e bischop, &thorn;o he &thorn;is i-sei&yogh;h : and &thorn;e Iustise al-so,</L>
<L>Criden merci Iesu crist : of &thorn;at huy hadden misdo,</L>
<L>And torneden &thorn;are to cristinedom : and o&thorn;ur folk also i-nou&yogh;h,</L>
<L N="244">For &thorn;e faire miracle &thorn;at huy seyen : and elles it were wou&yogh;h.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Miracle &thorn;at seint Iohan dude : no toungue telle ne may&yogh;;</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore folk him siwede faste : &thorn;at is miracle i-say&yogh;.</L>
<L>Tweye Ioliue louerdingues and wilde : &thorn;at &yogh;oungue and Ioliue<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> stronge</NOTE> were,</L>
<L N="248">Siweden him and duden al-so : ase he gan heom lere:</L>
<L>&para; Furst huy solden al heore god : &thorn;at heom ne bi-lefde nou&yogh;th,</L>
<L>And turnden hem al to Iesu crist : heore heorte and al heore &thorn;ou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>And siweden<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. siwenden</NOTE> sein Iohan swi&thorn;e faste : &thorn;at &thorn;are-to heom hadde i-brou&yogh;ht;</L>
<L>And he heom prechede of Iesu crist : &thorn;at deore heom hadde i-bou&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is twei&yogh;e &yogh;ongue men ase huy &yogh;eoden : swy&thorn;e riche men and hei&yogh;e</L>
<L N="254">with grete nobleye and pruyde i-nou&yogh; : bi &thorn;e weye huy sei&yogh;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh;ten huy, "swuch nobleye : we weren i-woned to lede<MILESTONE N="171b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000458.tif" N="410"></L>
<L>In Iolifte and in pruyte i-nou&yogh; : and nou&thorn;e we beoth in wrech-hede,</L>
<L>In Miseyse and in pouerte : and riche weren bi-fore!</L>
<L N="258">vs &thorn;inkez, sorie mouwe we beon<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. bieon</NOTE> : &thorn;at we euere weren ibore."</L>
<L>Seint Iohan wuste al heore heorte : &thorn;ei he ne heorde &thorn;are-of nou&yogh;ht:</L>
<L N="260">"&YOGH;e foles," he seide, "&yogh;wat is eou nou&thorn;e? : &yogh;wi chaunge &yogh;e eouwer &thorn;ou&yogh;ht?</L>
<L>Bowes and &yogh;eordene fechchiez me : and stones al-so!"</L>
<L>&THORN;is &yogh;ongue Men weren &thorn;are-a-boute a-non : &thorn;at &thorn;e dede were i-do.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Iohan tornede &thorn;is &yogh;eordene sone : in-to puyr gold and cler,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e stones to &yogh;immes preciouse : &thorn;oru&yogh;h ore louerdes pouwer,</L>
<L N="265">And &thorn;is twei wilde Bachilers : he &yogh;af it euer-ech del;</L>
<L>"Here-with," he seide, "&yogh;e mouwen : habbe wel manie guode Mel,</L>
<L>And also muche lond eou bugge a-&yogh;ein : and more &thorn;ane &yogh;e solden bi-fore;</L>
<L>For &yogh;e habbuth, bote &yogh;e betere do : &thorn;e Ioye of heouene fur-lore."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is &yogh;ongue Men nomen &thorn;is tresour : and wel glade &thorn;ar-of were,</L>
<L N="270">And to manie goldsmi&thorn;es : wel wide-a-bouten it bere.</L>
<L>&THORN;is goldsmi&thorn;es sworen euer-ech-on : &thorn;at &thorn;is gold i-sei&yogh;en,</L>
<L N="272">&THORN;at so clene gold ne so puyr : huy ne sei&yogh;en neuere with ei&yogh;en.</L>
<L>&para; Hou mi&yogh;te fairore miracle beo : o&thorn;ur fairore poer,</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;en</NOTE> bowes and &yogh;eordene tornede<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> torne</NOTE> &thorn;are : in so puyr gold and cler?&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; Al-so<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> As</NOTE> seint Iohan &thorn;e Ewangelist : ferrore wende &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="276">And &thorn;e twey men forth with him : &thorn;at so riche of golde were,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">This v. on the margin.</NOTE></L>
<L>A ded man toward burijngue : Men brou&yogh;hten ope one bere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Moder criede opon sein Iohan : &thorn;at he him scholde arere,</L>
<L>"Louerd," heo seide, "ich bidde &thorn;e : &thorn;at &thorn;ou habbe reu&thorn;e of me</L>
<L N="280">And of mi sone &thorn;at is ded : ibrou&yogh;t here a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e;</L>
<L>haue reu&thorn;e of him, ich bidde &thorn;e : for Iesues woundes fiue,</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;ou haddest of Drusiane : &thorn;o &thorn;ou a-rerdest hire to liue!"</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o gan seint Iohan to weope sore : and bad a-stunte &thorn;e bere,</L>
<L N="284">And bad ore louerd for is grace : &thorn;at dede bodi a-rere.</L>
<L>&THORN;is &yogh;ongue man a-non with &thorn;is word : to liue a-ros &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;o was Ioye and blisse i-nou&yogh;h : a-mong alle &thorn;at &thorn;are were!</L>
<L>&para; "Ich hote &thorn;e nou&thorn;e," quath seint Iohan : "&thorn;at ded hast i-beo &yogh;are,</L>
<L N="288">&THORN;at &thorn;ou telle &thorn;is men sum-&thorn;ing : of &thorn;at &thorn;ou sei&yogh;e elles-&yogh;ware,</L>
<L>And nameliche here to &thorn;is twei men : &thorn;at nou&thorn;e beoth for-lore,
<PB REF="00000459.tif" N="411"></L>
<L>&THORN;at beoth itornede to &thorn;e deuele a-&yogh;ein : to &yogh;wam huy serueden bi-fore."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is &yogh;ongue Man &thorn;at was to liue a-rerd : bi-heold &thorn;eos o&thorn;ure twei&yogh;e;</L>
<L N="292">"Allas," he seide, "&thorn;e wrechhede : &thorn;at ich i-seo<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> isei</NOTE> bi eou bei&yogh;e!</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke time &thorn;at &yogh;e for-soken : &thorn;is holie Mannes lore,</L>
<L>Aungles &thorn;at eou wusten er : weopen for eou ful sore,</L>
<L>And &yogh;uyt huy doth ase ich nou ri&yogh;ht i-sei&yogh;h : and &thorn;e deuelene in heore ende</L>
<L N="296">&para; Mauden for eou Ioye i-nou&yogh;h : to &yogh;wam &yogh;e gonne wiende.</L>
<L>Allas, wrechches, &thorn;e muchele pine : &thorn;at to eou is al-&yogh;are,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in helle ich sai&yogh;h to eouwer bi-hoff&thorn;e : to &yogh;wan &yogh;e schullen fare!"</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is twei Men i-heorden &thorn;is : huy bi-gonne to crie a-non,</L>
<L N="300">Deol and seoruwe huy mauden i-nou&yogh;h : and gradden opon seint Iohan.</L>
<L>"Allas, &yogh;e foles<NOTE PLACE="marg1">&yogh;e f. overlined.</NOTE>," quath seint Iohan : "&yogh;e nuteth &yogh;ware &yogh;e wollez beo.<MILESTONE N="172" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;if god wolle habbe merci of eou : &yogh;e mouwen sone i-seo.</L>
<L>To ech sunful man he is redi : &thorn;at to him wole i-wiende;</L>
<L N="304">&THORN;are-fore criez &yogh;eorne on him : for-to he eou milce siende:</L>
<L>And &thorn;e so&thorn;e &yogh;e mouwen sone under-&yogh;ite : &yogh;wane he hath eou milce i-sent,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane &thorn;is gold and &thorn;eos &yogh;immes : to heore kuynde beoth a-&yogh;en i|went."</L>
<L>&para; Huy crieden &yogh;eorne on ore louerd &thorn;o : and in penaunce huy were,</L>
<L N="308">In fastingue and in oresones : &thorn;ritti dawes &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;o tur[n]de &thorn;at gold bi-fore heore ei&yogh;ene : into bowes of treo,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e &yogh;ymmes into harde stones : ase huy hadden er i-beo.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;is &yogh;ongue men &thorn;is i-sei&yogh;en : glade huy weren i-nou&yogh;h!</L>
<L N="312">&THORN;udere a-&yogh;ein ase huy fetten heom er : huy beren euer-ech bou&yogh;h,</L>
<L>And for-soken al &thorn;e worldes pruyte : and duden ase &thorn;e wise,</L>
<L>And endeden heore lif at&thorn;e laste : in ore louerdes seruise.&mdash;</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Perdrix.</NOTE>&para; In a time ase &thorn;is holie man : wende in &thorn;e contreye,</L>
<L N="316">A &yogh;ong partrich he bar on his hond : and &thorn;are-with he gan pleye.</L>
<L>A wylde louerdyng &thorn;are cam gon : a-&yogh;ein him bi &thorn;e weye,</L>
<L>I-wepned swi&thorn;e baldeliche : he nadde of no man Ey&yogh;e.</L>
<L>A-bysemare he bi-heold seint Iohan : &thorn;o he him sai&yogh;h bere on honde
<PB REF="00000460.tif" N="412"></L>
<L N="320">&THORN;is &yogh;ongue foul and &thorn;are-with pleye&mdash; : &thorn;are-to he hadde onde.</L>
<L>"Loke," he seide, "&thorn;is olde conIoun : in his olde liue,</L>
<L N="322">&THORN;at men holdez swuch prophete : alle o&thorn;ur men to schriue!</L>
<L>wel bi-trufleth he &thorn;at folk. : here men mi&yogh;hten i-seo</L>
<L>hou he plei&yogh;ez with &thorn;is &yogh;ongue brid : he ne mi&yogh;hte nou&yogh;t wys beo."</L>
<L>&para; "Leoue bro&thorn;ur," quath seint Iohan : "ich bidde tel &thorn;ou me</L>
<L>&YOGH;wat is &thorn;at &thorn;ou berest on honde : and &yogh;ware-offe it seruez &thorn;e."</L>
<L>"Ane bouwe ich bere," quath &thorn;is o&thorn;ur : "and Arewen also &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L N="328">To scheoten wilde bestes with : and wilde foules also."</L>
<L>&para; "Biend &thorn;ine bouwe," quath seint Ioan : "to loke &yogh;wat he can do!"</L>
<L>&THORN;is &yogh;ongue Man nam and bende is bouwe : and bar it longue so.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-aftur sone he nam is bouwe : and unbende it ase he cou&thorn;e.</L>
<L N="332">"&YOGH;wy dost &thorn;ou so?" quath sein Iohan : "&yogh;wat schal he vnbend nou&thorn;e?"</L>
<L>"For he wole," quath &thorn;is o&thorn;ur : "&thorn;e smartore dryue eft-sone</L>
<L>And &thorn;e betere dunt &yogh;yue to euerech &thorn;ing : &thorn;at ich habbe with to done;</L>
<L>&para; For, &yogh;if ich hire bere longue i-bend : &thorn;e feblore heo wolle<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> wolde</NOTE> beo</L>
<L N="336">And euerech drau&yogh;ht &thorn;e worse driue&mdash; : &thorn;at may ech man<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. man may</NOTE> i-wite and seo."</L>
<L>"Leoue bro&thorn;ur," quath seint Iohan : "al-so it farez, i-wis,</L>
<L N="338">Bi mannes heorte here on eor&thorn;e : &thorn;at feble and leo&thorn;i is.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he is toward Iesu<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. Iusu</NOTE> crist : i-bend faste euere-mo,</L>
<L>Febli he schal and beo a-sad<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> al sad</NOTE> : and is strenc&thorn;e also<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> al</NOTE> a-go;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if he is o&thorn;ur-&yogh;wile onbend : and itorned to solaz,</L>
<L>he wole bieon eft-sone, &yogh;wane he is i-bend : stifore &thorn;ane he er was,</L>
<L>And in godes seruise &thorn;e bet driue &amp; duyre : and &thorn;are-to beon stif and strong.</L>
<L N="344">&THORN;are-fore mot ech holi man : solaci him a-mong</L>
<L>And tuyrne is herte to some truyfle : &yogh;wane he may ani i-se,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he mouwe to godes seruise : &thorn;e stifore and &thorn;e strengore be.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">This v. on the margin.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e Ern is foul of alle foules : &thorn;at hey&yogh;est may fleo,<MILESTONE N="172b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &yogh;uyt he mot nede, to resten him : a-&yogh;ein to grounde teo;</L>
<L>hou mi&yogh;hte he euere fleon on hei&yogh;h : bote he reste him at&thorn;e grounde?</L>
<L N="350">Nammore ne may mannes bodi : bote he reste him sum stounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore, bel amy, &thorn;ou mi&yogh;ht : herebi &thorn;at so&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;e so&thorn;e herebi &thorn;at so&thorn;e.</NOTE> ise,
<PB REF="00000461.tif" N="413"></L>
<L N="352">&THORN;at for solaz man may &thorn;e betere : in godes seruise be."&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; Seint Iohan wende a-boute wide : and churche he liet a-rere,</L>
<L>And maude preostes and bischopes : &thorn;at folk for-to lere.</L>
<L>Ake Aristod[i]mus &thorn;e bischop : &thorn;at he tornede er to cristindom,</L>
<L N="356">In &thorn;e Cite of Ephese : swi&thorn;e holi man bi-cam,</L>
<L>And ane churche of seint Iohan : in Ephese he arerde bliue&mdash;</L>
<L>And seint Iohan seth&thorn;e in &thorn;ulke churche : wende out of &thorn;is liue.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; A day ase &thorn;is holie man : his seruise hadde i-do,</L>
<L N="360">A &yogh;oung man he say &thorn;are-bi-side : stalewor&thorn;e and fair al-so;</L>
<L>Ake a li&yogh;ht red he was, and of &thorn;unne wit. : seint Iohan bi-heold him faste,</L>
<L>And opon a bischop &thorn;are-bi-side : his ei&yogh;ene a-non he caste:</L>
<L>"Ich bi-take &thorn;e," he seide, "in warde to wite : &thorn;is man here lo,</L>
<L N="364">&THORN;at &thorn;ou him loke and norichi wel : &thorn;at he nou&yogh;t ne mis-do;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ou me ansuerie of is warde : &yogh;wane &thorn;ou me comest eft to;</L>
<L N="366">witnesse ich take on ihesu crist : and on holie churche al-so."</L>
<L>&para; "Sire, wel fawe," &thorn;e bischop seide : &thorn;is &yogh;ongueman he tok wel softe.</L>
<L>Seint Iohan him chargede of is warde : and muneguede him wel ofte</L>
<L>&THORN;at he him wuste swi&thorn;e wel : ase he answerie wolde;</L>
<L>And bi-tei&yogh;hte heom bo&thorn;e Ihesu crist : and wende &yogh;wodere he scholde.</L>
<L>&THORN;is bischop nam &thorn;is Ioliue man : and ladde hom to is inne,</L>
<L N="372">And norichcede him softe and wel : seint Iones loue to winne,</L>
<L>And prechede him &yogh;eorne of Ihesu crist : to bi-nimen him his folie;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;is &yogh;oungue man to guode turnde : and merci gan to crie,</L>
<L>And faire bar him and louede wel : god and seinte marie,</L>
<L N="376">And dude al &thorn;at &thorn;e bischop wolde : and guod<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> hard</NOTE> lif gan dri&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&para; At&thorn;e laste &thorn;is bischop : sumdel is heorte gan wiende&mdash;</L>
<L>Ase ofte verlich bi-guynninge : flechchez at&thorn;en ende;</L>
<L>he soffrede &thorn;is &yogh;onge man to pleye : ant to muche habbe is wille,</L>
<L N="380">And luyte and luyte don folie : and liet him al a-spille.</L>
<L>Formest he gan haunti wakes : and for compaygnie</L>
<L>he wax a syutor of tauernes : and siwede to glotonie;</L>
<L>&THORN;o ne mi&yogh;hte he nou&yogh;ht beon with-oute : and turnde to lecherie</L>
<L N="384">And bi-cam an holer strong : and tornede al-to folie.
<PB REF="00000462.tif" N="414"></L>
<L>&para; So longue, to holden up his folie : smale &thorn;ingues he nam,</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;e smale he tok &thorn;e grete : and strong &thorn;ef he bi-cam;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he hadde gret de-deyn : smale &thorn;ef&thorn;es to do,</L>
<L N="388">For bote it were &thorn;e grettore &thorn;ing : he ne tornede nou&yogh;ht &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L>At&thorn;e laste to &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> a</NOTE> compaygnie of Outlawes : sone he gan gon;</L>
<L N="390">Vnder non o&thorn;ur he nolde beon : ake hext maister a-non;</L>
<L>O&thorn;ure &thorn;at erore maistres weren : bi-comen is men ech-on.</L>
<L>he robbede ouer-al to grounde : and slow&yogh;h<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. slowen</NOTE> al-so mani on,<MILESTONE N="173" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>More soruwe ne mi&yogh;hte beo : &thorn;ane he dude in eche ende.</L>
<L>For of[te]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. of</NOTE> vuel chastingue : to folie wolie<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> wole</NOTE> wiende.</L>
<L N="395">&para; So &thorn;at seint Iohan in a time : to &thorn;at Bischop cam,</L>
<L>Aftur &yogh;wam he bi-tok him er in warde : guode &yogh;eme a-boute he nam.</L>
<L>"Sire bischop," he seide, "&yogh;eld me up : &thorn;at guode tresor, ich rede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in warde ich &thorn;e bi-tok : and a-countes of is dede!"</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o was &thorn;e bischop sore a-drad : "sire, merci," he seide,</L>
<L N="400">"I-ne may him &thorn;e &yogh;elde nou&yogh;ht : for he is ded, ich dred[e]."</L>
<L>"Alas," quath sein Iohan, "&yogh;we&thorn;ur he beo? : in &yogh;wat manere is &thorn;is?"</L>
<L>"Certes, sire," &thorn;e bischop seide, "a-&yogh;ein god ded he is,</L>
<L>his soule is ded, &thorn;ei is bodi : &yogh;uyt a-liue beo;</L>
<L N="404">For he is outlawe strong bicome : ase al &thorn;e contreye may seo.</L>
<L>Opon an hei&yogh;h hul he wonez : with outlawes mani on,</L>
<L>And lat a-quelle and robi also : alle &thorn;at he may of-gon."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o bi-gan &thorn;is holi man : to sike and weope sore,</L>
<L N="408">For deol is clo&thorn;us he to-drou&yogh; : "louerd," he seide, "&thorn;in ore,</L>
<L>Ane feble tresorer ich me ches : and &thorn;oru&yogh;h is feble lore</L>
<L>Mi deorewuyr&thorn;e tresur ich habbe [i-lore]! : ine truste to him non|more.</L>
<L>Alas, sire bischop, &thorn;i feble warde! : ine &thorn;onki &thorn;e nou&yogh;ht &thorn;arc-fore.</L>
<L N="412">&YOGH;wane it non o&thorn;ur nis, ich mot seche : &thorn;at &thorn;ou me hast i-lore.</L>
<L>&para; Lat grey&thorn;i me an hors a-non : and ane man in ane stounde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> me mouwe &thorn;ane wey teche : forto ich him habbe i-founde."</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie man, &thorn;at feble was : and ouer-come nei&yogh;h with elde,</L>
<L N="416">Opon a strong hors he Arnde forth : ouer mor and ouer felde.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at, &thorn;are &thorn;e outlawes weren : he cam at&thorn;e laste;</L>
<L>And some of &thorn;e schrewes weren al-&yogh;are : and nomen him wel faste,</L>
<L>To robbi him and to sle : and heten him holde him stille.
<PB REF="00000463.tif" N="415"></L>
<L N="420">"Ov, beau freres," quath seint Ioan : "ich mot nede don ouwer wille;</L>
<L>&para; Ake ich bidde eou for eouwer cortesie : eouwer mayster latez [me] seo,</L>
<L>And latez him-sulf with me do : &yogh;wat is wille beo."</L>
<L>Wel i-Armed &thorn;e maister cam : prikie and ride faste;</L>
<L N="424">And a-no[n] so he on &thorn;is holie man : his ei&yogh;ene a-feor caste,</L>
<L>And wuste wel &thorn;at he it was : him gan to schamie, so sore</L>
<L>&THORN;at he bi-gan to fleo a-non : and ne kepte i-seo him non-more.</L>
<L>&para; A-non so sein Ioan &thorn;is i-sei&yogh;h : he Arnde aftur a-non</L>
<L>And siwede him al-so stifliche<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> [h]asteliche, r. hastifliche</NOTE> : ase his hors mi&yogh;hte gon;</L>
<L>he Arnde ase &thorn;ei he a &yogh;ung man were. : "mi sone," he seide, "&thorn;i ore,</L>
<L N="430">&YOGH;wy fleust&thorn;ou me? nam ich &thorn;i fader? : ne dred &thorn;e nou&yogh;t so sore!</L>
<L>Spek here with &thorn;i feble fader : vn-Armed and in elde!</L>
<L N="432">Abid me nou&thorn;e, and ichulle for &thorn;e : ore louerd resun &yogh;elde.</L>
<L>Ich am &yogh;are &thorn;ene deth a-fongue : for &thorn;ine strongue pine.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">A v. om.: As our louerd dude for us : &amp; mi soule &yogh;iue for &thorn;ine.</NOTE></L>
<L>Spek with me, bote &thorn;ou more wolle : ich hote a-godes name!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e o&thorn;ur a-stunte and vnne&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> a-bod : he ne mi&yogh;hte no[n] o&thorn;ur<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> vnne&thorn;e he mi&yogh;te</NOTE> for schame;</L>
<L>&para; He a-li&yogh;hte and vn-armede him : and weopinde ful sore</L>
<L>he ful to seint Iones fet : and cride him milce and ore,</L>
<L>And bi-h<SUP>i</SUP>et him stifliche a-godes name : &thorn;at he nold [misdo] namore,<MILESTONE N="173b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ake louien god and holi churche : and libbe al bi is lore.</L>
<L N="440">So &thorn;at he was euereft more : guod man and stable i-nou&yogh;,</L>
<L>And bi seint Iones rede ladde is lif : and to alle guodnesse he drou&yogh;.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; Seint [Iohan] leouede here so longue : and so mani his dawes were,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne mi&yogh;hte nou&yogh;ht ouer &thorn;e eor&thorn;e go : bote ase is desciples him bere;</L>
<L>huy beren him, for feblesse and for elde : to churche with<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> mid</NOTE> alle teone,</L>
<L>And euere-more he prechede hem : &thorn;at loue heom were bi-tweone.</L>
<L N="446">&THORN;o he was of an hondred &yogh;er : bote o &yogh;er wane vnne&thorn;e,</L>
<L>And seuene and sixti &yogh;er it was : aftur ore louerdes de&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="448">&para; Ore louerd with is desciples cam to him : fram heouene up an hei&yogh;h,</L>
<L>"Cum forth," he seide, "mi frend, to me : &thorn;i time is comen nei&yogh;h;</L>
<L>hit is nei&yogh;h time &thorn;at &thorn;ou come : to mine riche feste
<PB REF="00000464.tif" N="416"></L>
<L>with &thorn;ine bre&thorn;ren in mine riche : for it<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at (for om.)</NOTE> schal euere i-leste.</L>
<L N="452">For &thorn;ou schalt nou&thorn;e a-sonenday : &thorn;at &thorn;ene fifte day heonne is,</L>
<L>&THORN;e day of mine oprisingue : to me comen, i-wis."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is holie man hiet his desciples : &thorn;at huy him to churche bere&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at of him and in his name : Aristod[i]mus<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. Aristodinus</NOTE> liet a-rere.</L>
<L N="456">&THORN;at folk cam sone &thorn;icke &thorn;udere : with deol and sor i-nou&yogh;h,</L>
<L>For hit was couth swi&thorn;e sone : &thorn;at he toward is ende drou&yogh;h.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;ene sonen-ny&yogh;ht wel tyme : his seruise he gan to do,</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e he gan &thorn;at folk to wisse : and to prechi al-so;</L>
<L N="460">At&thorn;e furste cocke &thorn;at creu&yogh; : he gan to prechie faste,</L>
<L>And for-to hei&yogh;h vnderne of &thorn;e daye : his prechingue i-laste.</L>
<L>&THORN;o hiet he is desciples &thorn;at huy ane put : four-huyrned him made,</L>
<L>Faste bi-side &thorn;e hei&yogh;e weuede : with schouelene and with spade,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at huy casten out at &thorn;e churche-dore : &thorn;e eor&thorn;e, &yogh;eorne he bad.</L>
<L>With weop and with soruwe i-nou&yogh;h : &thorn;e put was &thorn;are i-mad.</L>
<L N="466">&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e put was al-&yogh;are i-maud : In alle heore ey&yogh;ene si&yogh;hte</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie man wel softeliche : &thorn;udere in gan a-li&yogh;hte;</L>
<L N="468">his hondene he huld up on hei&yogh;h : "swete louerd," he seide,</L>
<L>"Ich am cominde to &thorn;ine feste : ase &thorn;ou me erore bede.</L>
<L>&para; Louerd, muche ich &thorn;onki &thorn;e : &thorn;at it &thorn;i wille is</L>
<L>To &thorn;ine gistningue cleopie [me] : for muche ich it wilni, i-wis.</L>
<L N="472">&THORN;ine sones ich bi-take [&thorn;e] to loke : &yogh;wane i-ne may no lengore heom wite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at holie churche, &thorn;ine clene spouse : &thorn;oru&yogh; me &thorn;e hath bi-&yogh;ite.</L>
<L>Vnder-fong me with mine bre&thorn;ren : &thorn;at &thorn;ou brou&yogh;htest with &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;ou me bede to &thorn;ine holie feste : and come aftur me."</L>
<L N="476">&para; &THORN;o cam &thorn;are a-boute &thorn;is holie man : so muche li&yogh;ht a-li&yogh;the,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no man ne mi&yogh;hte for cler leome : habbe of him no si&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie man him blessede : and wel softe a-doun he lay;</L>
<L>"Mine bre&thorn;ren," he seide, "i-blessede &yogh;e beon : and habbez nou&thorn;e guod day!"</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is guode man wende out of &thorn;is world : al-clene with-oute ech pine,</L>
<L>Ase he was clene in mayden-hod&mdash; : he cam to a swete fine.</L>
<L N="482">&THORN;at clere li&yogh;ht &thorn;at a-boute him was : laste almest ane tyde;</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk ne sei&yogh;en nou&yogh;t of him&mdash; : faste huy weopen and cride.<MILESTONE N="174" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="484">&THORN;o &thorn;is li&yogh;th a-passed was : huy [lokede] in &thorn;e put to grounde:
<PB REF="00000465.tif" N="417"></L>
<L>&THORN;are-inne of &thorn;is holie Man : no-&thorn;ing huy ne sei&yogh;en ne founde;</L>
<L>&THORN;are nas inne nou&yogh;ht bote smale greynes : &thorn;at heo mi&yogh;hten vnder-&yogh;ite&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is holi &thorn;ing and is i-cleoped : Manna in holi write,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ore louerd wole<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> wule, while</NOTE> in fourme of reyn : fram heouene to vr&thorn;e sende</L>
<L>&THORN;e children of Israhel to heore mete : &thorn;o huy of<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. to</NOTE> Egypte wenden.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is Manna, &thorn;at holie greyn : &yogh;uyt to &thorn;is day dez springue</L>
<L>Op of &thorn;at put, &thorn;at manie men : bringuez to botningue.</L>
<L N="492">Non o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing of seint Iohan : men ne mi&yogh;hten on eor&thorn;e finde;</L>
<L>Al-clene, ich wene, in heouene he is : &thorn;are nis no leome bi-hinde.</L>
<L>Of euerech haluwe men founden for-so&thorn;e : &thorn;at bodi bi-leue here,</L>
<L>Bote of ore lauedy and of him : &thorn;at maydenes weren so clere.</L>
<L N="496">Fayr a &thorn;ing is Maiden-hod : ase it is on heom i-sene!</L>
<L>In &thorn;is Manere seint Iohan wende : of &thorn;is eorth&thorn;elich lif, ich wene.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; Seint Edward &thorn;at was nou&thorn;e late : In enguelonde ore king,</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie seint Iohan &thorn;e Ewangelist : he louede &thorn;oru&yogh;h alle &thorn;ing;</L>
<L N="500">Men ne scholde him no-&thorn;ing bidde : for &thorn;e loue of seint Iohan</L>
<L>&THORN;at he mi&yogh;hte do with-oute blame : &thorn;at he ne grauntede a-non.</L>
<L>A day &thorn;are cam a pouere man : with ful dreori mod</L>
<L>And bad him for seint Iohanes loue : &thorn;at he &yogh;eue him sum guod.</L>
<L N="504">&para; Seint Edward him bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;hte : &thorn;o, he ne hadde &thorn;are no-&thorn;ing</L>
<L>For-to &yogh;yue &thorn;is pouere Man : bote ane guyldene ring.</L>
<L>&THORN;ane ryng he louede wel i-nou&yogh; : and for &thorn;e loue of seint Iohan</L>
<L>&YOGH;uy[t] he hine &yogh;af &thorn;e pouere manne. : and he wende him forth a-non.</L>
<L N="508">&para; &THORN;are-aftur seth&thorn;e seint Iohan cam : to a kny&yogh;ht of Enguelonde,</L>
<L>Ase he was bi-&yogh;eonde se : Auntres for-to fonde;</L>
<L>"Wiend," he seide, "&yogh;wane &thorn;ou hom comest : to Edward, eower king,</L>
<L>And sei&yogh;e &thorn;at he for &yogh;was loue : he &yogh;af &thorn;eosne ryng</L>
<L N="512">Sende him here his ryng a-&yogh;eyn : and &thorn;onki him also."</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is kny&yogh;ht cam to enguelonde : his erinde he gan do.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Edward i-kneu&yogh;h wel &thorn;ane ring : and &thorn;are-bi onder-stod anon</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e pouere man &thorn;at he him &yogh;af : was &thorn;e guode seint Iohan.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Harl. adds:</NOTE></L>
<L N="516">Nou&thorn;e seint Iohan &thorn;e Ewangelist : &yogh;yf it &thorn;i wille is,</L>
<L>Beode ore Erinde, &thorn;at we moten : come to heouene blis. AMEN.</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke ring is &yogh;ut at westmynstre : for relik ido,</L>
<L>As me schewe&thorn; pelegrims : &thorn;at ofte come&thorn; &thorn;erto.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="61" TYPE="legend"><PB REF="00000466.tif" N="418">
<HEAD>61 [Alle halewene day]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle halewene-day we holdez : one time in &thorn;e &yogh;ere;</L>
<L>For manie enchesones holie churche : &thorn;are-to us gan lere.</L>
<L>On is, for &thorn;e grete noumbre : &thorn;at of alle halewe is,</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;at euerech ne mai nou&yogh;t at is feste : ane day habbe, i-wis.</L>
<L>An o&thorn;ur is, &thorn;at we beoth feble : &thorn;at we ne mouwen nou&yogh;ht alle</L>
<L>&THORN;e festene bi heom-sulf holde : ase huy in &thorn;e &yogh;ere doth falle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde ancheson<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> is, for &thorn;e &yogh;er is schort : ase ech ne may nou&yogh;th allone</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Ane</NOTE> feste habbe in &thorn;e &yogh;ere : &thorn;are huy habbez i-mone.</L>
<L>&THORN;e feor&thorn;e enchesun is, i-wis : for guod ri&yogh;ht it is with-alle</L>
<L>&THORN;at we of heom maken feste : &yogh;wane &thorn;e time doth falle,</L>
<L>For gret feste huy makiez in heouene : and in grete Ioye beoth<MILESTONE N="174b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="12">&YOGH;wan huy any a-mendement : of us on vr&thorn;e i-seoth;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e guod-spel seith of swich gret Ioye : &thorn;at a-mong heom in heouene is</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane ani of us a-mendi wole : of &thorn;at we doth a-mis.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 13-14 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &thorn;e fifte enchesun is, for &thorn;are was : a forbuysne &thorn;ar-of bi-gonne</L>
<L N="16">Longue are &thorn;e strenc&thorn;e of cristinedom : on vr&thorn;e were i-wonne:</L>
<L>For &thorn;e hey&yogh;e maystres of saresins : &thorn;at on vr&thorn;e weren &thorn;o her<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. here</NOTE></L>
<L>Maden ech maumat bi heom-sulf : at rome on Auter;</L>
<L>Ac natheles of eche ne mi&yogh;hte he nou&yogh;t : for here godes so fale were,</L>
<L N="20">And huy nolden nou&yogh;th &thorn;at ani god were : with-oute honour &thorn;ere:</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore huy maden on Auter : commuyn to ech-one,</L>
<L>For-to honouri alle heore godes &thorn;are : ase it were al i-mone.</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e &thorn;o cristinedom cam : and swy&thorn;e wide spradde,</L>
<L N="24">At rome and eke elles-&yogh;ware : clanliche &thorn;e maystrie hadde,</L>
<L>&para; Bonefas, &thorn;e guode pope : to &thorn;e false Auteres cam</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e Autere of alle godes : grete &yogh;eme he nam:</L>
<L>In forebuysne &thorn;ar-of : ane churche he liet a-rere</L>
<L N="28">Of ore lauedi and of alle haluwene : in &thorn;ulke place &thorn;ere&mdash;</L>
<L>Ake six hundret &yogh;er and fiue : ore louerd [&thorn;er-]bi-fore</L>
<L>of marie, is suete moder : on vr&thorn;e was i-bore.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e churche &thorn;at of ore lauedi was : and of alle halewene &thorn;o bi-founde,</L>
<L N="32">Stant &yogh;eot at rome, and is i-cleped : "Marie la rounde."
<PB REF="00000467.tif" N="419"></L>
<L>&THORN;e pope al-so Bonefaz : ane day in &thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L>In &thorn;e honour of alle halewene : he liet halewi &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And hiet al-so &thorn;oru&yogh;h al cristinedom : halewi &thorn;ilke day;</L>
<L N="36">Ake &thorn;ulke tyme he was i-holde : &thorn;e endlefte dai of may.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;e pope Gregori : &thorn;at &thorn;are-aftur longue cam,</L>
<L>I-say&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;e day to halewi was : ope al cristindom</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ri&yogh;ht was &thorn;at ech man : &thorn;e hexte and leste,</L>
<L N="40">In &thorn;e honour of alle haluwene : made &thorn;ane day feste;</L>
<L>And in<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> a skars tyme of &thorn;e &yogh;ere : ase we wyten, it was in May</L>
<L>So gret feste forto holde : ase ful to &thorn;ad<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. &thorn;at</NOTE> day:</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore he liet &thorn;ane day tuyrne : ase we him holdez &yogh;uyte,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e furste dai of nouembre : &yogh;wane ech guod nis nouh&yogh;t so luyte;</L>
<L>&para; "Me &thorn;inchez, &yogh;uyt," quath &thorn;e guode man : "&thorn;e feste feble were</L>
<L N="46">bote Men hadden &yogh;ware-with : &thorn;e wombe Ioye a-rere."&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e furste &yogh;er &thorn;are-aftur-ward : &thorn;at men &thorn;ane day &thorn;us nome,</L>
<L>Of a fair cas ich may telle : &thorn;at bi-feol in &thorn;e churche of rome.</L>
<L>&THORN;e wardein of seint peteres church : &thorn;at &yogh;uyt in rome is,</L>
<L N="50">&THORN;e feste honourede swy&thorn;e muche : of alle halewene, i-wis:</L>
<L>on alle halewene-day in churche : to ech auter he gan gon</L>
<L>And honourede ech aftur o&thorn;ur : he ne liet nou&yogh;ht on.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e hei&yogh;e auter of seint petre : ate laste he wende,</L>
<L N="54">And &thorn;are he lay a-doun an slep : ase god him grace sende.</L>
<L>him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, &thorn;are cam an Aungel : and ladde him to heouene on hei&yogh;h.</L>
<L>In a chayere with gret Ioye : ore louerd, him &thorn;ou&yogh;hte, he sei&yogh;h<MILESTONE N="175" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>with grete hei&yogh;hnesse sitte : and Aungles him al-a-boute.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o cam &thorn;are a fair leuedi : with Maydenes a gret route&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at was ore lauedi with virgines&mdash; : and ore louerd faire heo grette;</L>
<L N="60">Ore louerd a-&yogh;ein hire a-ros : and bi him fayre hire sette.</L>
<L>&THORN;o cam &thorn;are a Man in o sclaueyn : ase hit of a Camayle were,</L>
<L>And olde hore Men aftur him : and honoureden god &thorn;ere&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at was seint Iohan &thorn;e baptist : and &thorn;e profetes olde</L>
<L N="64">And also &thorn;e patriarkes : &thorn;at of ore louerd &yogh;wylene tolde.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o comen &thorn;are twelue in one route : ase bischopes it weren ech-one,</L>
<L>&THORN;e furste ase he pope were<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. huy popes weren</NOTE> : bi-fore he &yogh;eode al one&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at was seint petre : and his felawes endleuene;</L>
<L N="68">Alle huy honourede ore louerd : &thorn;are he sat in heouene.
<PB REF="00000468.tif" N="420"></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o comen &thorn;are ase hit kny&yogh;htes weren : redie for-to fi&yogh;hte,</L>
<L>Al-blodie, for-to defendi ore louerd : and holie churche ri&yogh;hte&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at weren Marty[r]s &thorn;at for god : and holie churche al-so</L>
<L N="72">&YOGH;euen heore lif ase godes kny&yogh;htes : and to de&thorn;e weren ido.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o cam &thorn;are a gret compaygnie : preostes ase &thorn;ei it were&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at weren &thorn;e confessours : &thorn;at hadden holie churche to lere,</L>
<L>Ase bischopes and Abbodes : and o&thorn;ur guode men al-so.</L>
<L N="76">Ore louerd huy honoureden alle : ase heore ri&yogh;hte was to do;</L>
<L>Of feste &thorn;at Men on vr&thorn;e maden : huy &thorn;onkeden him and bade</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;at a-ri&yogh;ht heore day heolden : and feste of heom made.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o gonne<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. goune</NOTE> huy singue heore Matines : swy&thorn;[e] murie with-alle,</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;at honouriez heore day here : ase he<SUP>o</SUP> in &thorn;e &yogh;ere doth falle.&mdash;</L>
<L>wel ou&yogh;hte we &thorn;ane day honouren : &yogh;wane huy &thorn;at ilke day</L>
<L N="82">Swuch Ioye for us in heouene maden : ase &thorn;e guode Man i-say.</L>
<L>Nou bidde alle halewene : &thorn;at we heore feste holden so</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy us bringuen to &thorn;e hey&yogh;e Ioye : &thorn;are huy buth inne i-do.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="62" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>62 [Alle soulene day]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle soulene-day on vr&thorn;e : ri&yogh;ht is to holde hei&yogh;e:</L>
<L>For alle we schullen habben neode &thorn;ar-to : for alle we schullen dei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>A fair si&yogh;ht &thorn;are-of al-so : &thorn;e Aungel &thorn;o gan bringue</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;ene Manne of Rome ase he ladde him : ase he lay in metingue.</L>
<L>him &thorn;ou&yogh;te, he sai&yogh;h manie men : liggen in beddes of golde,</L>
<L>And manie sitte at hey&yogh;e borde : and habbe al &thorn;at huy wolde;</L>
<L>And manie gon nakede : and bidde &thorn;at sum man heom scholde bi|weue,</L>
<L N="8">And manie of-hongrede, and beden also : &thorn;at men sum guod heom eue.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Aungel him seide &yogh;wat it was : al &thorn;at he sai&yogh;h &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at it was purgatorie : and &thorn;e Men soulene were;</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke &thorn;at weren at so noble bord : and in &thorn;e riche beddes also,</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;at weren men for &yogh;wam &thorn;are was : muche guod on vr&thorn;e ido,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bi-lefden freond bi-hynde heom : &thorn;at Massene leten singue</L>
<L>And duden guod for godes loue : heore soulene out of pine to bringue.</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke &thorn;at weren a-cale and of-hongred : &thorn;at no guod ne mi&yogh;hten finde,
<PB REF="00000469.tif" N="421"></L>
<L N="16">&THORN;at weren &thorn;ulke &thorn;at nadden on vr&thorn;e : none freond hem bi-hinde</L>
<L>Ne for hem late<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> To lete for hem</NOTE> masses singue : ne almes-dede for hem do;<MILESTONE N="175b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore ase helplese men : in Misayse huy &yogh;eoden so.</L>
<L>"Loke," quath &thorn;e Aungel, "&thorn;at &thorn;u telle : &thorn;e pope her-of sone,</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at men holden alle soulene-day : for it is wel to done;</L>
<L>And also wide ase holie churche : &thorn;at he make is heste,</L>
<L>&THORN;ene a-morewe aftur alle halewene-day : to holde &thorn;ulke feste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ech Man with guode wille : ase fer forth ase he may</L>
<L N="24">For alle &thorn;e soulene in purgatorie : bidde &thorn;at ilke day;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e pouere &thorn;at nath no freond : &thorn;at for him bi name ou&yogh;ht do,</L>
<L>&THORN;o[ru&yogh;]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;o</NOTE> biddingue of ech cristine Man : i-holpe huy mowen beo so."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e guode Man a-ros up a-non : &thorn;o he i-sai&yogh; al &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="28">And &thorn;onkede god of &thorn;e si&yogh;hte&mdash; : and so he wel au&yogh;hte, i-wis.</L>
<L>&THORN;e pope he tolde &thorn;at &thorn;o was : al &thorn;at he sai&yogh;h &thorn;ere;</L>
<L N="30">So &thorn;at men holdeth &thorn;ulke feste<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> festen</NOTE> : herre &thorn;ane heo er were.&mdash;</L>
<L>Ore louerd bi-fond furst purgatorie : Men &thorn;uder in to wende</L>
<L>&THORN;at hor<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. for</NOTE> penaunce here on vr&thorn;e : ne brou&yogh;hten nou&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. non</NOTE> to ende,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at Men for simple sunnes : of &yogh;wan i-schriue hy nere<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. were</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;ulke torment huy bi-lefden : for-to hy i-bette were;</L>
<L>And Men al-so &thorn;at weren i-schriue : and heore schrift a-fengue also</L>
<L N="36">Of a fol preost, and nou&yogh;ht i-nou&yogh; : to &thorn;e sunne &thorn;at was i-do,</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke schullen so to purgatorie : for-to huy habben to ende i-brou&yogh;ht</L>
<L>penaunce a-cordinde to heore sunne : and aftur &thorn;e preostes nou&yogh;ht.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 4 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;if heo is more &thorn;ane &thorn;e sunne : and a man it do, i-wis,</L>
<L N="40">Al it schal in heouene tuyrne : to echingue of his blis;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if heo is euene to his sunne : &thorn;e sunne heo wole a-quenche,</L>
<L>Ake nou&yogh;ht &yogh;if heo to luytel is. : &thorn;are-fore ech man him bi-&thorn;enche</L>
<L>And to a fol preost ne triste nou&yogh;ht : &thorn;at to luyte penaunce him set;</L>
<L N="44">For so&thorn;e, here o&thorn;ur elles-&yogh;ware : ech sunne worth i-bet.</L>
<L>&YOGH;wat, hou is hit &thorn;anne of Ianekin : and of robinet &thorn;e wilde,</L>
<L>Of annot and of Malekin : &thorn;at wollez habbe &thorn;ene preost so milde,</L>
<L>And huy seggez, "&thorn;ilke preost is to hard : god schilde us fram is loth&thorn;;</L>
<L N="48">go we to sire Gilbert &thorn;e preost : he nis neuere wroth&thorn;,</L>
<L>&para; he wollez schriue us nessche i-nou&yogh; : and ore sunnes al for-&yogh;yue."</L>
<L>bi god, &yogh;wane huy habbez al ido : hom huy goth&thorn; vn-schriue;
<PB REF="00000470.tif" N="422"></L>
<L>For heore penaunce schal beo so luyte : &thorn;at sire Gilbert and huy also</L>
<L N="52">Schullen gon a-deuelewey : bote god nime &yogh;eme heom to.&mdash;</L>
<L>In purgatorie nis no confort : bote of one &thorn;ingue :</L>
<L>of &thorn;e hope of Ioye aftur-ward : &thorn;at ore louerd heom wole bringue.&mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane Men in heore deth-beddes beoth : and heore penaunce heom is i-set,</L>
<L N="56">And huy ne mouwen nou&yogh;ht on eor&thorn;e beo : for-to heo beo ful bet,</L>
<L>So repentaunt huy mouwen beo : &thorn;at ore louerd it wole for-&yogh;yue</L>
<L>With-outen any purgatorie : &yogh;wan huy beoth wel i-schriue.</L>
<L>Ake &yogh;if his penaunce him is i-&yogh;yue : &yogh;wane he mot heonne wende,</L>
<L N="60">Of &thorn;at he is i-schriue : and he ne may it bringue to ende,</L>
<L>On of his nexte freond mi&yogh;hte : for him it swi&thorn;e wel do.</L>
<L>Ake four &thorn;ingus he moste habbe : &thorn;at scholde take on so :<MILESTONE N="176" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Furst &thorn;are moste gret loue beo : bi-twene &yogh;wam so it were&mdash;</L>
<L N="64">For with-oute loue and deol of heorte : swuch &thorn;ing nou&yogh;ht<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> no&yogh;t wor&thorn;</NOTE> nere;</L>
<L>Ake &yogh;if huy weren al-so of one blode : &thorn;e betere it were, i-wis&mdash;</L>
<L>Ake studefast heorte of guod loue : &thorn;e maistrie &thorn;ar-of is.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing is &thorn;at he schal : &thorn;oru&yogh;h de&thorn;e heonne wiende</L>
<L N="68">And &thorn;at he ne may habbe no space here : his penaunce bringue to ende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde &thorn;ing is &thorn;at hit beo : &thorn;oru&yogh;h &thorn;e preostes rede,</L>
<L>For no man ne may &thorn;are-with-oute : wel endi swuch dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e feor&thorn;e &thorn;ing is &thorn;at men him take : penaunce more &thorn;are-to</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;ane him &thorn;at &thorn;e sunne dude : &yogh;if he mi&yogh;hte penaunce do;</L>
<L>For ho-so wole for o&thorn;eres sunne : swuch penaunce here lede,</L>
<L>More penaunce man mot heom sette : &thorn;ane him &thorn;at dude &thorn;e dede.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;are-fore &yogh;wane anie of ouwer freond : hath i-brou&yogh;ht is lif to fine,</L>
<L N="76">I-seoth here hou &yogh;e mouwen bringue him : out of his pine;</L>
<L>to biete is sunne in &thorn;is manere : sikerliche &yogh;e mouwen eou beode.</L>
<L>For godus loue &thorn;enchez &thorn;aron : &yogh;wane ouwer freond habbez neode!&mdash;</L>
<L>In &yogh;wuch stude is nou&thorn;e purgatorie : manie wolden fayn i-wite.</L>
<L>hit [nis]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> nou&yogh;ht a<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> in o</NOTE> stude to alle men : ake in fif studes, it is i-write :</L>
<L>&para; On is in &thorn;e firmament : &thorn;are gret brenningue is</L>
<L N="82">Of fuyr &thorn;at hath &thorn;are is stude : and of &thorn;e sonne, i-wis.</L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;ur is in &thorn;e Ey<SUP>r</SUP> a-bouen us here : &thorn;are lu&thorn;ere gostes fleoth</L>
<L>&THORN;at tormentiez heom ny&yogh;ht and day : and neuere in reste ne beoth.
<PB REF="00000471.tif" N="423"></L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde is an vr&thorn;e a-mong us here. : &thorn;e feor&thorn;e in watere is.</L>
<L N="86">&THORN;e fifte is onder vr&thorn;e deope : bi-side helle, i-wis &mdash;</L>
<L>&para; Seint patrik on vr&thorn;e &yogh;wilene : ane stude &thorn;ar-of founde,</L>
<L N="88">Ase god wolde, bi-side &thorn;e hul : of seint brendan in his londe.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Irlond</NOTE></L>
<L>For four &thorn;ingus purgatorie : in &thorn;eos fif studen is :</L>
<L>For sum Man scholde lasse torment : &thorn;ane o&thorn;ur habbe, i-wis;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at men mi&yogh;hten &thorn;orou&yogh;h god dede : &thorn;e sonore to Ioye heom bringue;</L>
<L N="92">And &thorn;at men weren &thorn;oru&yogh;h hem i-war : bi a vision o&thorn;ur metingue;</L>
<L>And for men<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. man</NOTE> &thorn;at delitiez muche in sunne : in one place,</L>
<L>&THORN;are he schal &thorn;e sunne biete : for-to ore louerd him &yogh;iue grace.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; One tale and one faire en-saunple : &thorn;are-of we findez i-write,</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> for</NOTE> ore louerd schewez us swuch &thorn;ing : for we scholden &thorn;e so&thorn;e i-wite.</L>
<L>A preost was &yogh;wilene in one stude : &thorn;at dude him ba&thorn;ie i-lome</L>
<L N="98">In one stude priueliche : &thorn;are none men ne come.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;are cam ofte a man : ase hit were bi cas,</L>
<L>And seruede him and wuchs him wel&mdash; : ake he nuste &yogh;wat he was.</L>
<L>A day he made halibred : and &thorn;e manne hit bi-tok</L>
<L N="102">Ase for is mede for is swunch. : ake he it anon for-sok;</L>
<L>&para; "Sire," he seide, "ine may hit nou&yogh;ht : for it i-halewed is,</L>
<L N="104">And for i-nam nou&yogh;ht holi &yogh;uyt : i-ne may it nau&yogh;t, i-wis."</L>
<L>"A-godes name," quath &thorn;e preost : "ich hote and halsnie &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou me segge &yogh;wat &thorn;ou art : &thorn;at &thorn;us ofte comest to me."</L>
<L>"Ich was &yogh;wylene of &thorn;is stude : louerd," &thorn;is o&thorn;ur seide,<MILESTONE N="176b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="108">"In &thorn;is place ich delitede muche : to don a mis-dede,</L>
<L>And al mi delift<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> delit</NOTE> of &thorn;ulke sunne : so was in &thorn;is place;</L>
<L>I-ne bette nou&yogh;ht &thorn;e sunne a-liue : for ich nadde nou&yogh;ht &thorn;e grace,</L>
<L>And aftur mi deth &thorn;ere-fore : mi purgatorie here is,</L>
<L N="112">to biete mi sunne in &thorn;ulke place : &thorn;are ase ich dude amis.</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou woldest<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Ac woldestou</NOTE> for me massene singue : ich mi&yogh;hte habbe milce and ore;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou mi&yogh;ht i-wyte &thorn;at ich am sauf : &yogh;wane &thorn;ou ne finst me nonmore."</L>
<L>&THORN;e preost song for him Massene fiue : and o&thorn;ur guodnesse dude also.</L>
<L N="116">Sone he miste &thorn;at selie gost : &yogh;uyt are &thorn;e seueny&yogh;ht weren i-do :</L>
<L>For he wende to &thorn;e Ioye of heouene : &thorn;at he deore a-bou&yogh;hte.
<PB REF="00000472.tif" N="424"></L>
<L>&THORN;us Mani Man hath his purgatorie : &thorn;are he is sunne wrou&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>So may parauentur dame Aldith : &thorn;at nath non o&thorn;ur blis</L>
<L N="120">bote athom in hire halle clene : &thorn;ere ase hire Moker is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &thorn;ei heo bidde hire beden at churche : hire &thorn;ou&yogh;ht is athom more;</L>
<L>parauenture heo schal it bete &thorn;are : and a-bugge hire loue ful sore!&mdash;</L>
<L>Men habbuz here heore purgatorie : manie for swuche &thorn;ingue,</L>
<L N="124">And manie to warni some men : to helpe heom &thorn;arof to bringue.</L>
<L>Mani man his purgatorie : in wature hath al-so :</L>
<L>&THORN;arof ichulle one ensaumple segge : of &thorn;at &yogh;wilene was ido.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; Seint Tebaud &thorn;e bischop hadde : in his fot ane hote goute,</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;at poudagre icleopeod is&mdash; : he hadde &thorn;ere-offe gret doute.</L>
<L>Ase his fischares wenden a-fischez : in heruest al-a-boute,</L>
<L N="130">In heor net huy nomen ane clompe of .Is<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. ys?</NOTE>. : huy weren &thorn;are-with wel proute :</L>
<L>For &thorn;at ys &thorn;at was so cold : i-leid to heore louerdes fote</L>
<L>hit<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;at</NOTE> wolde aswagi &thorn;e hote goute : and bringue him sum bote.</L>
<L>&THORN;is bischop tebaut was wel glad. : &thorn;at ys huy leiden oft</L>
<L N="134">to is fot, and eche time : it made him li&thorn;e and softe.</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys was euere hol and sound : it ne malt for none hete.</L>
<L>Seint tebaut &thorn;ou&yogh;hte &thorn;are-of wonder : for no-&thorn;ing he nolde it lete.</L>
<L>A luyte cri him &thorn;ou&yogh;hte a day : in &thorn;at ys he heorde &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="138">he coniourede hit a-godes name : to segge him &yogh;wat it were.</L>
<L>"Ich am," quath &thorn;is o&thorn;ur, "a seli gost : and in &thorn;is ys ich am her</L>
<L N="140">In mi purgatorie, forte ich beo : of mine sunnes scker.</L>
<L>Ake &yogh;if &thorn;ou woldest for godesloue : &thorn;ritti masses singue</L>
<L>For me, ich wot &thorn;at &thorn;u mi&yogh;htest : of &thorn;is pine me bringue."</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischop grauntede him wel sone : and bi-gan a-non a-morewe</L>
<L N="144">&THORN;e Massene for &thorn;is selie gost : to bringuen it out of soruwe,</L>
<L>And ech day song so aftur o&thorn;ur. : &thorn;e deuel hadde &thorn;erto gret onde</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;uyt &thorn;at gost scholde of pine come&mdash; : his wrench he gan fonde.</L>
<L>For ase &thorn;e bischop &thorn;ene ten&thorn;e day : bi-gan is masse to singue,</L>
<L N="148">Al &thorn;e toun &thorn;e feondes hadde : i-brou&yogh;t on a fi&yogh;htyngue.</L>
<L>&THORN;e guode man bi-lefde is masse a-non : and orn a-mong heom faste,</L>
<L>And harmles &thorn;oru&yogh;h godes grace : a-passede<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> paisede</NOTE> heom at&thorn;e laste.</L>
<L>Ase he bi-gan a-morewe is masse : a gret cri &thorn;are cam al-a-boute</L>
<L N="152">&THORN;at &thorn;e toun bi-seged was : with gret ferd al with-oute,<MILESTONE N="177" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000473.tif" N="425"></L>
<L>And Men ornen into al &thorn;e toun : ase witlese for doute.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischop lefde is masse a-non : and orn to-ward &thorn;e route;</L>
<L>He made pays a-&yogh;ein &thorn;at fierd : &thorn;at huy no-&thorn;ing ne reueden.</L>
<L N="156">Ake natheles so &thorn;eo tuey dawes : his masse he bi-leuede.</L>
<L>&para; Ase he bi-gan is masse &thorn;ene &thorn;ridde day : men heten out al-a-boute,</L>
<L>For is court and muche of &thorn;e toun : a-fuyre was with-oute.</L>
<L>"&THORN;ei it al fur-berne," quath &thorn;e bischop : "and ich mi-sulf also,</L>
<L N="160">I-nelle to-day fram &thorn;is weued : are &thorn;is masse beo i-do."</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he song is masse forth : and muche folk was bisi with-oute</L>
<L>to lauien watur and quienche &thorn;at fuyr : &thorn;at orn so wide a-boute.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e Masse was i-do : &thorn;at fuyr a-queynte anon;</L>
<L>&THORN;are nas a-peired nou&yogh;ht an hous : ake hole stoden echon.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. achon</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;ulke &thorn;reo dawes &thorn;e deouel hadde : al &thorn;ulke wo i-do</L>
<L N="166">his masse forto lette : and pini &thorn;e soule so.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischop fond &thorn;at .ys. athom : i-molten al to nou&yogh;hte :</L>
<L>&THORN;o wuste he &thorn;at &thorn;oru is Masse : to Ioye &thorn;e soule he brou&yogh;hte.&mdash;</L>
<L>Manie &thorn;ingus one soule helpez : &thorn;at in purgatorie is;</L>
<L N="170">Ake &thorn;reo &thorn;ingues heom helpez mest : bi-fore alle o&thorn;ere, i-wis :</L>
<L>beden of Men, and almes-dede : singuingue of Masses al-so&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;eos &thorn;reo &thorn;ingues beoth best, i-wis : and mest guod huy wollez do.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at biddingue of beden beoth guode : &thorn;e so&thorn;e &yogh;e mouwen i-wite</L>
<L N="174">bi a tale of a clerk : &thorn;at we findez i-write.</L>
<L>A clerk hadd[e] &yogh;wilene ane wone : bi churche-hey&yogh;e &yogh;wane he come,</L>
<L>to segge for alle cristine soulene : &thorn;e "deprofundis" i-lome.</L>
<L>In a churche-&yogh;erd ones he cam late : &thorn;eoues him comen a-boute</L>
<L N="178">And a-saileden him to robbi : he nuste &yogh;wat do for doute.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bodies &thorn;at weren i-burede &thorn;are : his beden &yogh;olden a-non :</L>
<L>huy comen with wepnen him forto helpe : and sturten forth echon,</L>
<L>euer-ech with swuch-manere wepne : ase huy uyseden here a-liue,</L>
<L N="182">plou&yogh;-Man with his Aker-staf : Archer mid bouwe and knyue;</L>
<L>A-boute &thorn;is &thorn;eoues huy comen ech-one : and guonne heom sone to-driue,</L>
<L>And to heore puttes wenden seth&thorn;e a-&yogh;ein : &thorn;is clerk hamward wel bliue.</L>
<L>&THORN;us weren is beden i-&yogh;olde : &thorn;at he bad erore and ofte.</L>
<L N="186">Ich am siker, &thorn;e &thorn;eoues<NOTE PLACE="marg1">&thorn;e &thorn;. on the margin.</NOTE> ne &yogh;eoden nou&yogh;ht : aweywardes ful softe :
<PB REF="00000474.tif" N="426"></L>
<L>For ich wot wel &thorn;at non of us : ne hadde heom so sore a-gast!</L>
<L>A wonder bataille it was on : hadde it longue i-last;</L>
<L>Ich wene, &thorn;ei ani chaumpiun : &thorn;are hadde i-beo,</L>
<L N="190">Sone he wolde habbe i-nome is red : hamward for-to fleo!&mdash;</L>
<L>Almes-dede deth &thorn;e soule also : swi&thorn;e gret guod with-alle :</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e mouwen bi a cas i-seo : &thorn;at ane kny&yogh;hte dude bi-falle.</L>
<L>&para; A guod man &yogh;wyle, &thorn;at hei&yogh;te steuene : to is endingue drou&yogh;.</L>
<L N="194">A kny&yogh;ht, his freond, for is deth : made gret deol i-nou&yogh;</L>
<L>And dude for him grete almes-dede : bo&thorn;e ni&yogh;ht and day.</L>
<L N="196">&THORN;arof he i-sai&yogh; a fair bi-tokningue : ase he a-slepe lay :</L>
<L>him &thorn;ou&yogh;hte he sai&yogh; a sluper brugge : swy&thorn;e fayr and hei&yogh;,<MILESTONE N="177b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A deop watur and swart bi-neo&thorn;e : a fair mede &thorn;are was nei&yogh;</L>
<L>with swote smul and faire floures. : and ope &thorn;e brugge he sei&yogh;<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. gan</NOTE> gon</L>
<L N="200">with grete Misayse mani Men : &thorn;at fullen into &thorn;at watur a-non,</L>
<L>And manie he sai&yogh; &thorn;are-oppe gon : al-sauf with-oute drede,</L>
<L>And manie with Ioye and blisse i-nou&yogh; : pleyinde in &thorn;e Mede.</L>
<L>Ope &thorn;e brugge him &thorn;ou&yogh;hte he sai&yogh; : gon in wrechhede</L>
<L N="204">Steuene, for &yogh;wam &thorn;at he dude : &thorn;e grete almes-dede;</L>
<L>Blake men &thorn;are weren bi-neo&thorn;e : &thorn;at a-doneward him drowe,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ere &thorn;are weren in &yogh;wite clo&thorn;es : &thorn;at opward him heolden i-nowe;</L>
<L>bi-twene heom laste &thorn;e noyse longue : a&yogh;ein o&thorn;ur ech drou&yogh; faste,</L>
<L N="208">Ake euere hadden &thorn;e &yogh;wite Men : &thorn;e maistrie at &thorn;e laste.</L>
<L>&THORN;at weren &thorn;e almesdedes : &thorn;at for him weren i-do,</L>
<L N="210">&THORN;at &thorn;e kny&yogh;ht for is soule dude : &thorn;at drowen him opward so.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e blake &thorn;at him a-doneward drowen : &thorn;at weren is lu&thorn;ere dedes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wolden him to pine drawe : &yogh;if huy mi&yogh;hten for almes-dede.&mdash;</L>
<L>Massene also doth gret guod : bo&thorn;e &thorn;e quike and dede :</L>
<L N="214">&THORN;at &yogh;e mouwen i-heore bi &thorn;is tale : and bi o&thorn;ure &thorn;at ich er sede.</L>
<L>&para; Men weren &yogh;wilene in a contreye : &thorn;are a gret ston-roche stod,</L>
<L>And Men wenden &thorn;at &thorn;are-onder were : gret tresor<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. trosor</NOTE> and guod :</L>
<L>So &thorn;at huy doluen &thorn;are-aftur : ake to wro&thorn;erhele ate laste :</L>
<L N="218">For opon hem ful &thorn;e roche adoun : and heom alle ouer-caste,</L>
<L>And a-slou&yogh; heom alle, bote anne Man : &thorn;at, ase it were bi cas,</L>
<L>In a-manere dich fel and lay : and &thorn;e roche a-boue him was;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;hte of &thorn;e stude : ase i-putted he lay &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="222">his wyf nuste nou&yogh;ht of is lyf : ake wende &thorn;at he ded were :
<PB REF="00000475.tif" N="427"></L>
<L>to churche heo wende euerech day : ane masse to leten singue,</L>
<L>A lof and wyn and a candel of wex : to &thorn;e weued heo wolde bringue,</L>
<L>And al for hire louerdes soule&mdash; : heo ne bi-lefde nou&yogh;ht a day.</L>
<L N="226">&THORN;e deuel hadde &thorn;arto gret onde : &thorn;o he &thorn;at i-sai&yogh; :</L>
<L>&para; Ase &thorn;is wyf &yogh;eode a day toward churche : &thorn;e deuel cam hire to</L>
<L>And seide &thorn;at heo &yogh;eode for nau&yogh;ht : for &thorn;e Masse was i-do.</L>
<L>&THORN;at guode wyf &yogh;eode hom a-&yogh;ein : and wende &thorn;at he soth sede.</L>
<L N="230">A-morewe he made hire al-so gon hom : mid &thorn;ulke sulue dede;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ane &thorn;ridde day al-so guod. : ake &thorn;at wyf &thorn;ane feor&thorn;e day</L>
<L>Sone a-ros and to churche &yogh;eode : &thorn;o heo &thorn;ane day i-sai&yogh;h.</L>
<L>&YOGH;uyt cam &thorn;e schrewe and seide : &thorn;at &thorn;e Masse was i-do.</L>
<L N="234">&THORN;is wyf i-liefde him er fule wel : ake &thorn;o nolde heo nou&yogh;ht so,</L>
<L>Ake wende to churche, and fond &thorn;e so&thorn;e : of &thorn;at &thorn;e schrewe hire mette,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it was to bi-trayen hire : and guodnesse to lette.</L>
<L>&para; Sone hit bi-feol &thorn;are-afturward : &thorn;at Men of &thorn;e toune</L>
<L N="238">wenden to bete op &thorn;ulke roche : &thorn;at so lay &thorn;are a-doune,</L>
<L>And wenden to finde sum tresor. : huy doluen and beoten faste.</L>
<L N="240">&THORN;e selie Man bi-neo&thorn;e was of-drad : &thorn;at huy more opon him caste;</L>
<L>"Deluez," he seide, "warliche : &thorn;at &yogh;e ne slen me nou&yogh;ht!"</L>
<L>&THORN;o weren &thorn;is Men sore a-dradde : and stoden in gret &thorn;ou&yogh;ht;<MILESTONE N="178" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ake na&thorn;eles huy doluen bi-side : so &thorn;at huy to him come.</L>
<L>huy founden him ligge hol and sound : and with Ioye hine up nome.</L>
<L>huy axeden him hou he hadde i-leoued : &thorn;at hongur him ne a-slou&yogh;.</L>
<L>"Certes," he seide, "ich habbe i-haued : mete and drinke i-nou&yogh; :</L>
<L>For a lof and a picher wyn : Mi wyf me sende ech day,</L>
<L N="248">And a brennind candle : &thorn;at me li&yogh;hte &thorn;e &yogh;wile ich here lay.</L>
<L>bote &thorn;reo dawes &thorn;is o&thorn;ur wike : no-&thorn;ing heo me ne sende;</L>
<L>Ich was nei&yogh;h for hongur ded.: ake heo gan sone a-mende</L>
<L>And sende me ase heo dude er : and fedde me wel with-alle.</L>
<L N="252">Of alle wyues wor&thorn;e hire best : and best hire mote bi-falle!"</L>
<L>bi &thorn;is Miracle man may i-seo : and bi manie o&thorn;ure al-so,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Massene and almes-dede : gret guod &thorn;e soule wollez do.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;is guodnesses nellez nou&yogh;ht helpe : alle i-liche, i-wis;</L>
<L N="256">For of Men &thorn;at heonne wiendez : mani-manere &thorn;are is :</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur ri&yogh;ht guode, o&thorn;ur ri&yogh;ht vuele : o&thorn;ur ri&yogh;ht<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. ri&yogh;ht</NOTE> bi-tweone two.</L>
<L>goddede helpez some ful luyte : &thorn;at man wole for heom do,
<PB REF="00000476.tif" N="428"></L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at huy ri&yogh;ht guode beoz&mdash; : huy ne habbuth none neode mid-alle</L>
<L N="260">to none er&thorn;eliche guodnesse : &thorn;at heom mi&yogh;hte &thorn;are bi-falle;</L>
<L>For in &thorn;e Ioye of heouene huy buth : ase huy weren bi-fore.</L>
<L>Ake na&thorn;eles &thorn;at men for heom doth : ne worth nou&yogh;ht for-lore :</L>
<L>For it schal him-sulf helpe muche : &thorn;at &thorn;ulke guodnesse deth,</L>
<L N="264">And alle cristine soulene also : &thorn;at in purgatorie beoth.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;reo-manere men &thorn;are buth ri&yogh;ht guode : &thorn;at to heouene wiendez a-non</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane huy out of &thorn;is worlde farez. : &yogh;ung child is &thorn;at on</L>
<L>&THORN;at deide aftur is cristinedom : are hit dude to quede;</L>
<L N="268">And Martyrs &thorn;at for godes loue : in strong torment weren dede;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde manere so but clene men : &thorn;at are &thorn;at huy heonnes wende,</L>
<L>Alle heore sunnes betten here : ase ore louerd heom grace sende.</L>
<L>&THORN;is &thorn;reo-manere men ne mouwen nou&yogh;ht : in purgatorie bi-leue,</L>
<L N="272">Ake smitez &thorn;oru-out quiclokur : &thorn;ane &thorn;e leyte doth an eue;</L>
<L>huy ne mouwen nou&yogh;ht bi-leue &thorn;are : for er heo wenden heonne,</L>
<L>Clene huy weren of alle sunne : and ne habbut no&thorn;ing<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. no&thorn;int</NOTE> to brenne.</L>
<L>For ase wode and col fedez : &thorn;at fuyr &thorn;at here is,</L>
<L N="276">Al-so sunne fet &thorn;at fuyr : in purgatorie, i-wis;</L>
<L>And &yogh;wan &thorn;e sunne is i-brend a-wey : &thorn;e soule to heuene geth,</L>
<L>Ake wel sone &thorn;oru&yogh; he flieth : &thorn;at in clannesse &thorn;olede deth.</L>
<L>Also doth [&thorn;e]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.; H &thorn;ulke</NOTE> &thorn;reo-manere Men : of &yogh;wan ich eou er seide :</L>
<L N="280">For heouene openez a&yogh;enes heom : so sone ase heo beoth dede.&mdash;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at it beo soth of alle &thorn;reo : ensaumple &yogh;e mouwen i-seo.</L>
<L>&THORN;at a&yogh;ein children i-baptizede : heouene i-opened beo :</L>
<L>For ore louerd was nyne-and-twenti &yogh;er : and twelf daywes old</L>
<L N="284">Are he i-baptized were : ase &thorn;e bok us hath i-told :</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;at tyme non eor&thorn;elich Man : ne mi&yogh;hte enes i-wite</L>
<L>&THORN;at heouene openede ou&yogh;were aboue : &thorn;at we findez i-write;</L>
<L>bote &thorn;o he was i-baptized : of &thorn;e holie Man seint Iohan,<MILESTONE N="178b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="288">A-boue his heued with gret li&yogh;ht : heouene openede a-non.</L>
<L>&YOGH;wat bi-tocknede &thorn;ulke openingue : &thorn;at &thorn;o was and er nou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>bote &thorn;at &thorn;oru<NOTE PLACE="marg1">overlined.</NOTE> cristindom : Man was to heouene i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at heouene-dore was faste i-mad : for-to cristindom were,</L>
<L N="292">And &thorn;at a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e furste cristindom : heouene openede &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at heouene-dore i-opened is : to cristine Men al-so,
<PB REF="00000477.tif" N="429"></L>
<L>And to &yogh;ongue children forto huy habben : &thorn;oru&yogh; sunne it fur-do?</L>
<L>For huy schullen, &yogh;wane huy heonnes wiendez : heouene-dore opene finde,</L>
<L>For huy ne berez with heom no sunne : &thorn;at drawe heom bi-hinde;</L>
<L>Also quicliche ase li&yogh;httingue : &thorn;oru purgatorie huy doz gon,</L>
<L N="298">And heouene-dore findez opene : and wiendez in anon.</L>
<L>gret folie it is to weope : ase Men beoz i-wonet to done,</L>
<L N="300">For &yogh;ongue children &thorn;at dei&yogh;ez so : &thorn;at in heouene buth so sone!</L>
<L>"Awei, mi child," seith &thorn;e damme : and suou&yogh;nez a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e wowe;</L>
<L>bi crist, heo au&yogh;te &thorn;onki god : &thorn;at nam hit ase his owe!&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; A-&yogh;ein &thorn;e Martyrs &thorn;at guode buth : heouene i-opened is :</L>
<L N="304">&THORN;at Man may bi &thorn;e Martyrdom iseo : of seint steuene, i-wis.</L>
<L>For &thorn;o men him to de&thorn;e &thorn;reowen : he bi-heold to heouene an hei&yogh;h :</L>
<L>An heouene openede a-non : ase he &thorn;are i-sei&yogh;h&mdash;</L>
<L>"Lo," he seide, "nou&thorn;e ich i-seo : &thorn;oru&yogh; ihesu cristes sonde</L>
<L N="308">heouene opene, and godes sone : in is fader ri&yogh;th hond stonde."</L>
<L>And &thorn;e furste martyr he was : &thorn;at euere on vr&thorn;e cam</L>
<L N="310">Aftur godes passion : to holde up cristindom :</L>
<L>heouene openede a&yogh;en him : ase he &thorn;ene deth nam,</L>
<L>to bi-tokni &thorn;at he wolde al-so : a&yogh;en ech &thorn;at &thorn;olede guod Martyrdom.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei he were sum-del in sunne : heore deth &thorn;at huy nome</L>
<L>And heore blod heom wolde wasche : are huy to purgatorie come.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ulke also of clene liue : &thorn;at in clennesse here lif endiez,</L>
<L N="316">heouene openez a-&yogh;ein heom : &yogh;wane huy heonne wiendez :</L>
<L>&THORN;at Man may i-seo bi ensaumple : of seint Iohan &thorn;e wangelist.</L>
<L>Clannore &thorn;ane he was, no man nas : with-oute Iesu crist.</L>
<L>he seith in &thorn;e Apocalips&mdash; : &thorn;at a wel guod bok is,</L>
<L N="320">&THORN;at he i-sei&yogh;h heouene-dore : a-&yogh;en him opene, i-wis.</L>
<L>&YOGH;wat bi-toknede &thorn;at bote &thorn;is : huy scholden i-seo also</L>
<L>A-&yogh;ein heom, alle &thorn;at clene weren : heouene-dore vndo?&mdash;</L>
<L>Er&thorn;elich guodnesse helpez luyte : swyche Men, i-wisse,</L>
<L N="324">For huy nabbuth &thorn;are-to non neode : &yogh;wane huy beoth in heuene|blisse.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;anne it helpez him-sulf muche : &thorn;at deth &thorn;ulke goddede,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at beoth in purgatorie : ase ich erore sede.</L>
<L>ho-so is al-so in helle pine : it hellpez him luytel al-so
<PB REF="00000478.tif" N="430"></L>
<L N="328">Any guod-nesse &thorn;at Man may : on vr&thorn;e for him do;</L>
<L>&para; For seint Austyn seith, &yogh;if he wuste : &thorn;at is fader in helle were,</L>
<L>Non more he nolde for him bidde : &thorn;ane for ane deuel &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Ake euere it helpez him &thorn;at it doth&thorn; : and cristine soulene al-so;</L>
<L>For no guodnesse ne worth fur-lore : &thorn;at Man may on vr&thorn;e do.<MILESTONE N="179" UNIT="folio">&mdash;</L>
<L>Ake beden o&thorn;er o&thorn;ure<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> almes-dedes luyte helpuz : of fremde o&thorn;ur of kunne,</L>
<L N="334">bote he with-oute wrath&thorn;e beo : and with-oute dedlich sunne.</L>
<L>Ake a masse nis no&thorn;e-worse : for<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. of</NOTE> &yogh;wam &thorn;at heo is i-do,</L>
<L N="336">&THORN;ei it beo of a sunful preost&mdash; : of non o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing it nis so.</L>
<L>For &thorn;at dede is so hei&yogh;h : &thorn;at heo ne may a-peyri nou&yogh;ht</L>
<L>Of<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> For</NOTE> no wrechche preost &thorn;at it dez : &thorn;ei he beo in sunne i-brou&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;ei &thorn;e Masse ne beo &thorn;e worse : &thorn;e preost, bi mi swere,</L>
<L N="340">&THORN;at hire singuth in dedlich sunne : a-corie it schal ful deore!</L>
<L>For &yogh;wane sire Gileberd i-massed hath : his lif he wole so di&yogh;hte</L>
<L>At&thorn;e tauerne to beon a-day : and bi is quene bi ny&yogh;hte;</L>
<L>he seith, &yogh;wane Men cleopiez him preost : "sittez stille, mine guode i-fere,</L>
<L N="344">&THORN;e preost hanguez at churche : and ich am nou&thorn;e here"&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; his cope o&thorn;ur is surplis : &thorn;e preost he seith it isse;</L>
<L>Ake his cope schal bi-leue at hom : &yogh;wane he schal to helle, i-wisse!&mdash;</L>
<L>ho-so wole &yogh;wane he is ded<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at a ded man,</NOTE> : to<NOTE PLACE="marg1">of</NOTE> his guodnesse a-fongue,</L>
<L N="348">do it bi-time for &thorn;e dede : &thorn;are-aftur &thorn;inkez longue.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at it beo soth, man may i-s[e]o<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. so</NOTE> : bi a wonder cas</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;wylene bi a kny&yogh;ht bi-feol : &thorn;at with &thorn;e hei&yogh;e kyng charles was.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e kyng Charles his Ost aday : to strongue batayle gan lede.</L>
<L N="352">his .O. kny&yogh;ht &thorn;at with him wende : of &thorn;e de&thorn;e gan him drede.</L>
<L>A cosyn he hadde in &thorn;e route : to him he &thorn;ou&yogh;hte he mi&yogh;hte</L>
<L>best truste<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. truste to</NOTE> of alle Men : and so he au&yogh;hte with ri&yogh;hte;</L>
<L>"Cosyn," he seide, "&yogh;if ich am : here to de&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L N="356">Sul Mi stede and do<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. do guod?</NOTE> for mi soule : ne bi-lef &thorn;ou it nou&yogh;ht!"</L>
<L>&THORN;is kni&yogh;ht truste wel to is word : &thorn;at grauntede don is bone;</L>
<L>And in-to &thorn;e batayle wende forth : ase ri&yogh;ht was for-to done,</L>
<L>And fau&yogh;ht &thorn;e &yogh;wyle he mi&yogh;hte : and a-slawe was at &thorn;en ende.</L>
<L N="360">his cosin nam his stede sone : and hamward he gan wiende,</L>
<L>And to is owene bi-hof&thorn;e faste ire heold : and &thorn;ou&yogh;hte forto done
<PB REF="00000479.tif" N="431"></L>
<L>Also muche guod for &thorn;e kny&yogh;htes soule : &yogh;wane he mi&yogh;hte eft-sone.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e kny&yogh;ht cam to him eft-sone : gostliche in priuete,</L>
<L N="364">"Cosyn," he seide, "late &thorn;ou dudest : &thorn;at &thorn;ou bi-hei&yogh;htest me!</L>
<L>&THORN;ou madest me beon in purgatorie : seue ny&yogh;ht, mid-i-wisse.</L>
<L>And nou&thorn;e ich am in heouene : and &thorn;arof &thorn;ou schalt misse,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou schalt in &thorn;is ilke day : to &thorn;e pine of helle wende,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e treson &thorn;at &thorn;ou me dudest : and beon &thorn;are with-outen ende."</L>
<L>&THORN;is gost wende forth a-non : and &thorn;e false Man wel sone</L>
<L N="370">deide, and wende a-deuele wey : ase he of-seruede to done.</L>
<L>here mouwen &thorn;is false esecutores : beon<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. bieon</NOTE> i-warre bi &thorn;is tale,</L>
<L N="372">&THORN;at muche habbez of dedes godes : and deleth &thorn;are-of ful smale,</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;enchez, &yogh;wane huy riche beoth : to &yogh;elden it wel, i-wis;</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule longueth &thorn;are-aftur-ward<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;erafter sore</NOTE> : &thorn;at in purgatorie is,</L>
<L>heo a-bidez longue heore richesse : &thorn;e guode is euere bi-hinde&mdash;</L>
<L N="376">huy schullen gon a-deouele wey : and &thorn;are heore miede finde.</L>
<L>Nou Ihesus, &thorn;at us deore bou&yogh;hte : &thorn;ei we don ofte a-mis,<MILESTONE N="179b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>On alle cristine soulene haue merci : and bring us to heuene blis,</L>
<L>And led us to oure ri&yogh;hte heritage : for &thorn;ou bou&yogh;htest us &thorn;ar-to;</L>
<L N="380">Ne leos nou&yogh;ht &thorn;at &thorn;ou deore bou&yogh;htest : &thorn;ei we sumdel mis-do!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="63" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>63 [Eadmund conf.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Eadmund &thorn;e confessour : &thorn;at lyth&thorn; at pounteneye,</L>
<L>Of guode men and trewe he cam : &thorn;ei huy neren nou&yogh;ht ful hei&yogh;e;</L>
<L>In Engelonde he was i-bore : in &thorn;e toun of Abindone.</L>
<L N="4">Glad mi&yogh;htte &thorn;e moder beo : &thorn;at bar swuch a sone!</L>
<L>Mabile &thorn;e riche is moder [het] : &thorn;at guod womman was i-nou&yogh;,</L>
<L>For bo&thorn;e wif and<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. and and</NOTE> wydewe : to holie lif heo drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Lustniez nou&thorn;e and i may telle : hou and in &yogh;wat manere</L>
<L N="8">Seint Eadmund was i-bore : &yogh;if &yogh;e it wollez i-here.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 7-8 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L>A-seint Eadmundus dai &thorn;e king : &thorn;is guode child was i-bore;</L>
<L>So clene he cam fram is moder : with-oute ech-manere hore,</L>
<L>And so clene,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> drie</NOTE> &thorn;at no cloth : &thorn;at nei&yogh;h &thorn;e moder was</L>
<L>Ne nei&yogh;h &thorn;is &yogh;oungue child, &thorn;o it was<NOTE PLACE="marg1">&thorn;o&mdash;was <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> i-bore : no-&thorn;ing &thorn;e foulere<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> isoilled</NOTE> it nas.</L>
<L>&para; A-seint Eadmundes dai he was i-bore : ri&yogh;ht ase it was day;</L>
<L N="14">Fram erne morewe &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> forte</NOTE> it was eue : ase a ded &thorn;ing he lay&yogh;,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;ht ase he were ded-bore : for no &thorn;ing on him lif ne sai&yogh;;
<PB REF="00000480.tif" N="432"></L>
<L N="16">&THORN;e mide-wyues him wolden habbe i-bured : ac &thorn;e moder seide euere nay.</L>
