<L>Mest he louede on oresoun : &thorn;at was of ihesu crist</L>
<L>And of ore leuedi, is swete Moder : and of sein Ioan &thorn;e Ewangelist,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ".O. intemerata" : bi-gvynnez on latyn;</L>
<L N="214">&THORN;e bi-guynningue is wel guod : and al-so is &thorn;e fin.</L>
<L>Euereche dai bi custome : he seide &thorn;is oresun,</L>
<L N="216">he nolde bi-leue for no scole : ne for no lessoun.</L>
<L>&para; In a dai he it fur-&yogh;at : he hadde so muche to done.</L>
<L>Seint Ioan &thorn;e Ewangelist to him cam : &thorn;e ni&yogh;ht aftur-ward ful sone</L>
<L>And a paumerie bar on is hond : gret and strong i-nou&yogh;h;</L>
<L N="220">Seint Eadmund he nam bi &thorn;e hond : and is paumerie op drou&yogh;h,</L>
<L>So hei&yogh;e and with so gret Eyr : ase he him wolde al-to-driue.</L>
<L>Seint Eadmund lay and quakede : and drad was of is liue,
<PB REF="00000486.tif" N="438"></L>
<L>For, &yogh;if he him smite ase he dunt drou&yogh; : he were ded a-non;<NOTE PLACE="inter">[Here a fol. is wanting in the Laud MS.; MS. Harl. continues:]</NOTE></L>
<L N="224">[he quakede &amp; cride dulfulliche : "louerd, merci, seint Iohn!"</L>
<L>&para;"Ich wole for-&yogh;eue &thorn;e," qua&thorn; seint Ioh<SUP>a</SUP>n : "&thorn;u criest so sore;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ench bet on oure oreisoun : &amp; nefor&yogh;et hit nomore!"</L>
<L>he nefor-&yogh;at after &thorn;ulke tyme : nomore &thorn;is oreisoun,</L>
<L N="228">For no studie nefor no neode : nefor &thorn;o&yogh;t of lessoun.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; So wel lurnede &thorn;is holi man : &amp; suche grace hadde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he bigan at Oxenford : &amp; of art &thorn;er radde.</L>
<L>Of art he radde six &yogh;er : contynuelliche ynou&yogh;,</L>
<L N="232">&amp; si&thorn;&thorn;e for-[to] beo more profound : to arsmetrike he drou&yogh;,</L>
<L>&amp; arsmetrike radde in cours : in Oxenford wel faste</L>
<L>&amp; his figurs drou&yogh; aldai : &amp; his numbre caste.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; Arsmetrike is alore : &thorn;at of figurs al is</L>
<L N="236">&amp; of drau&yogh;tes as me drawe&thorn; in poudre : &amp; of<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. in</NOTE> numbre, i-wis.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; A ni&yogh;t in avisioun : his moder to him wende,</L>
<L>"Sone," heo seide, "to what figurs : woltou nou entende?"</L>
<L>"Leoue moder," qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er : "suche as we iseo&thorn;."</L>
<L N="240">"Leoue sone," qua&thorn; &thorn;e moder : "betere figurs &thorn;er beo&thorn;,</L>
<L>wherto &thorn;u most &thorn;in hurte do : &amp; &thorn;enche her-on nomore!"</L>
<L>heo nom for&thorn; his ri&yogh;t hond : &amp; wrot &thorn;er-on his lore :</L>
<L>&THORN;reo rounde cerclen heo wrot : in &thorn;e paume amidde,</L>
<L N="244">In &thorn;e tueye heo wrot fader &amp; sone : &amp; holigost in &thorn;e &thorn;ridde;</L>
<L>"Sone," heo seide, "her-afterward : entende to &thorn;is lore!"</L>
<L>To heuene a&yogh;e &thorn;e moder wende : henese&yogh; hire nomore.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">Theologia.</NOTE>&para; &THORN;o ise&yogh; seint Edmund : &thorn;at hit was al of &thorn;e Trinite,</L>
<L N="248">&amp; &thorn;at god wolde &thorn;at he schulde : ihure diuinite.</L>
<L>To diuinite, as god wolde : &thorn;is gode man him drou&yogh;;</L>
<L>&THORN;er nespedde non in Oxenford : so wel of ynou&yogh;.</L>
<L>hit nas no&yogh;t longe &thorn;er-afterward : &thorn;at &thorn;e Chanceler ne sede,</L>
<L N="252">&amp; &thorn;e hexte maystres of &thorn;e toun : &thorn;at he schulde bigynne &amp; rede.</L>
<L>he wi&thorn;sede &amp; longe<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> longe &amp;</NOTE> seide : &thorn;at he nas no&yogh;t wor&thorn;i &thorn;erto;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at moche a&yogh;en his wille : nede hi makede him hit do.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he bigan at Oxenford : of diuinite.</L>
<L N="256">So noble alosed &thorn;er nas non : in al &thorn;e vniuersite.</L>
<L>Of redinge he hadde so gode grace : &thorn;at meni on to him drou&yogh;;</L>
<L>his scolers &thorn;at ihurde of him : gode men were ynou&yogh;.</L>
<L>So pitousliche he wolde rede : &amp; so gode grace hadde &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L N="260">&THORN;at his scolers &thorn;at ihurde of him : nuste ofte what to do,</L>
<L>Ac sete as in ano&thorn;er wordle : &amp; ofte hudde here e&yogh;e
<PB REF="00000487.tif" N="439"></L>
<L>&amp; wepe &thorn;at &thorn;e teres vrne adoun : &thorn;at men hit al-aboute ise&yogh;e.</L>
<L>vne&thorn;e eni ihurde of him : &thorn;at &thorn;e betere ne bicom,</L>
<L N="264">&amp; meni bileuede al &thorn;e wordle : &amp; to religioun nom.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; A dai as &thorn;is holi man : in diuinite</L>
<L>Desputede, as hit was his wone : of &thorn;e trinite,</L>
<L>In his chaire he sat longe : er his scolers come;</L>
<L N="268">Alutel he bigan to swoudri : as a slep him nome.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;o&yogh;te him in his swoudringe : &thorn;at a whit coluere com</L>
<L>Fram heuene mid oure louerdes flesch : &amp; &thorn;e wei to him nom,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at swete flesch pulte in his mou&thorn; : &amp; si&thorn;&thorn;e fle&yogh; vp anhe&yogh;;</L>
<L N="272">heuene openede hire a&yogh;en : as &thorn;is gode man ise&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sauour of oure louerdes flesch : him &thorn;o&yogh;te, was in his mou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e clergie, him &thorn;o&yogh;te, of god : &thorn;o he awok, he cou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e pure stat of crist : &amp; of his mageste</L>
<L N="276">As [an] angel him &thorn;o&yogh;te he cou&thorn;e : &amp; of his priueite.</L>
<L>&para; he bigan so deope desputi : of &thorn;e trinite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at gret wonder me hadde : &thorn;urf al &thorn;e vniuersite;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e gretteste clerkes &thorn;at were : in Oxenforde &thorn;o</L>
<L N="280">Ne &thorn;o&yogh;te &thorn;at eni vr&thorn;lich man : so furfor&thorn; mi&yogh;te go</L>
<L>Ne wite so moche of godes stat : bote hit [an] angel were;</L>
<L>&THORN;er nere none maystres in Oxenford : &thorn;at in gret wonder &thorn;erof nere.</L>
<L>Ac he mi&yogh;te of ihesu crist iwite : more &thorn;an was in boc,</L>
<L N="284">whan he vsede oure louerdes flesch : &amp; in his mou&thorn;e toc!&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; Ne &thorn;o&yogh;te no&yogh;t &thorn;is holi man : so moche in his lessoun</L>
<L>&THORN;at euere among his &thorn;o&yogh;t nas mest : in godes passioun.</L>
<L>O tyme he was in grete studie : of his lessoun any&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="288">&THORN;at longe he sat &thorn;er-aboute : forte hit was ne&yogh; daili&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;o hit was toward &thorn;e dai : a-napped he was sore,</L>
<L>he lynede adoun vpon his boc : &thorn;o he nemi&yogh;te studie nomore;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he ful aslepe : &amp; vnywar also,</L>
<L N="292">&amp;<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. &amp;?</NOTE> ne&thorn;o&yogh;te no&yogh;t on &thorn;e passioun : as he was iwoned to do.</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel com to him wel sone : no&thorn;ing to siche he nas.</L>
<L>Seint Edmund of him was iwar : in swoudring as he was</L>
<L>he wolde him blesci wi&thorn; &thorn;e deuel : his ri&yogh;t hond he gan for&thorn; drawe :</L>
<L N="296">&THORN;e deuel him nom &thorn;erbi anon : he nemi&yogh;te him no&yogh;t wawe.</L>
<L>&THORN;o nom he for&thorn; his lift hond : to blesci him wi&thorn; also :</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel him nom &thorn;erbi faste : &thorn;at he nemi&yogh;te no&thorn;ing do.</L>
<L>vpe him he lai as a sak : &thorn;at he was al ouercome,</L>
<L N="300">he nemi&yogh;te him wawe fot ne hond : his poer him was binome.</L>
<L>Ac delyure he hadde al his &thorn;o&yogh;t : so &thorn;at he &thorn;o&yogh;te sone
<PB REF="00000488.tif" N="440"></L>
<L>Of oure louerdes passioun : as he was woned to done.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e deuel nemi&yogh;te &thorn;o bileue : vpe him none &thorn;rowe,</L>
<L N="304">For drede he ful sone adoun : bituene him &amp; &thorn;e wowe.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Edmund aros vp anon : &amp; &thorn;e deuel ouercom,</L>
<L>Strangliche &amp; harde ynou : bi &thorn;e &thorn;rote he him nom.</L>
<L>"&thorn;urf oure louerdes passioun : tel nou," he seide, "me,</L>
<L N="308">Ich axi &thorn;e hou cristene man : mai best him witie fram &thorn;e."</L>
<L>"Me neschal wi&thorn; no&thorn;ing," qua&thorn; &thorn;e deuel : "schulde fram mi poer</L>
<L>So wel as &thorn;urf his passioun : &thorn;at &thorn;u nemnedest er."</L>
<L>&para; &thorn;er lurnede &thorn;is holi man : as we mowe ek echon,</L>
<L N="312">In whiche manere we mowe best : &thorn;e deueles poer forgon,</L>
<L>For he hatie&thorn; godes passioun : as man do&thorn; his fon,]</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="314">And &yogh;wane men it habbuth in muynde : he mot fleo a-non.&mdash;<MILESTONE N="182" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Euerech tyme of daye and ny&yogh;ht : seint Eadmund him gan bi-seo</L>
<L>&THORN;at he di&yogh;hte wel to godes wille : &thorn;at he nolde idel beo;</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur he was in is oresones : o&thorn;ur at is bok,</L>
<L N="318">O&thorn;ur he .Et. o&thorn;ur slep : o&thorn;ur to o&thorn;ur &thorn;ingus he him tok.</L>
<L>&THORN;reo tymes him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at he for-les : &yogh;wene he cam &thorn;ar-to :</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane he rod, and &yogh;wane he slep : and &yogh;wane he .Et. al-so;</L>
<L>For he nas &thorn;anne in studie : ne in is beden no-&thorn;e-mo;</L>
<L N="322">Ech o&thorn;ur tyme, ase him &thorn;ou&yogh;te : to sum prou him scholde go.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; So longue &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> &thorn;is guode man : to eche holienesse drou&yogh;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is guodnesse was wide couth : and men speken &thorn;ar-of i-nov&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;e beste prechur he was i-holde : &thorn;at man ou&yogh;ware under-stod&mdash;</L>
<L>For ho-so hath with him godes grace : is dede mot nede beo guod.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at of &thorn;e Creoycerie : &thorn;e pope sente fram rome</L>
<L N="328">To &thorn;e bischopus of Enguelond : &thorn;at huy ane wise man nome</L>
<L>For-to prechi of &thorn;e creoycerie : ase ri&yogh;ht was for-to do.</L>
<L>Seint Eadmund, &thorn;e holie man : i-chose was &thorn;are-to,</L>
<L>To prechi of &thorn;e creoicerie : a-boute in &thorn;e londe,</L>
<L N="332">&THORN;at men wenden to Ierusalem : o&thorn;ur senden heore sonde.</L>
<L>&para; procracies huy &yogh;euen him also : ase he wende a-boute,</L>
<L>Of persones to nime largeliche : &thorn;at non nere with-oute.</L>
<L>bote &thorn;at nolde he do for no&thorn;ing : of no man spence take;</L>
<L N="336">And &yogh;wane persones it boden him : he it wolde for-sake.</L>
<L>For &yogh;wane he seruede ore louerd crist : to is owene spense he tok;
<PB REF="00000489.tif" N="441"></L>
<L>Of persones and of o&thorn;ur men : &yogh;iftus he fur-sok.</L>
<L>&para; he ne ferde nou&yogh;t ase &thorn;is Ercedeknes : ne as o&thorn;ure na-&thorn;e-mo,</L>
<L N="340">&THORN;at persones and &thorn;eos pouere preostes : ouer-al doth ful wo!&mdash;</L>
<L>Ase he prechede a day : of &thorn;e creoiz wel longue,</L>
<L>A &yogh;ung man wende a-mong &thorn;e o&thorn;ure : &thorn;e creoiz for-to a-fongue.</L>
<L>A womman &thorn;at him louede : so heo i-sai&yogh;h &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="344">heo hente him bi-hinde faste : and drov&yogh; him a-&yogh;ein, i-wis.</L>
<L>&para; Also stif ase ani hard bord : hire hond bi-cam a-non,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo ne mi&yogh;hte as a-welde : no&thorn;ur senuwes ne bon;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e hond was al-so fur-crokud. : heo made revlich bere.</L>
<L N="348">Seint Eadmund bi-heold a-boute : and axede &yogh;wat it were.</L>
<L>"Sire, merci," quath &thorn;is womman : "wrechchede ich am i-nov&yogh;!</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;is &yogh;ongue man wolde take &thorn;e croiz : a luyte ich him with-drou&yogh; :</L>
<L>And min hond is al for-croket : &yogh;ware-with ich him nam.</L>
<L N="352">In alle wrechhede ich am i-brou&yogh;ht : alas, &thorn;at ich here cam!"</L>
<L>&para; "Womman," quath &thorn;is holie man : "wolt&thorn;u &thorn;e croiz take?</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e, louerd," he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">= heo</NOTE> seide, "&yogh;if ich mi&yogh;hte : i-nelle hire nou&yogh;t for-sake."</L>
<L>&THORN;is wumman sat a-doun a-kneo : and of him &thorn;e creoiz he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">= heo</NOTE> nam :</L>
<L>And hire crokede hond strei&yogh;hte forth&thorn; : and a-non-ri&yogh;ht hol bi-cam;</L>
<L N="357">heo cride and hered Ihesu crist. : &thorn;is was couth a-non;</L>
<L>For &thorn;is miracle &thorn;are token &thorn;e creoiz : &thorn;e mo wel mani on.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; In a time at&thorn;e gang-dawes<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> roueisouns</NOTE> : &thorn;is holie man al-so</L>
<L N="360">prechede a day at Oxenford : ase he ofte hadde i-do,</L>
<L>In alle halewene church-&yogh;erd : In &thorn;e nor&thorn;ure side,</L>
<L>with &thorn;e Baneres at onderne : a-se men doth a-londe wel wide.</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;is holie man with al &thorn;is folk : in is prechingue was best,</L>
<L N="364">&THORN;at lodlokeste weder &thorn;at mi&yogh;hte beo : cam al fram bi west,</L>
<L>Swart and dreok<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. deork</NOTE> and grislich : and ouer-caste al &thorn;ene toun;</L>
<L>&THORN;e wynd blev&yogh; al-so swi&thorn;e grisliche : ase &thorn;e world scholde al a-doun;</L>
<L>So deork it was bi-come al-so : &thorn;at men mi&yogh;hte vnne&thorn;e i-se&mdash;</L>
<L N="368">Lodlokur wedur &thorn;ane it was : ne mi&yogh;hte neuere be.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at folk for drede of heore clo&thorn;us : faste bi-gonne to fleo.</L>
<L>"A-bidez," quath &thorn;is holie man : "ore louerd is guod and freo.</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel it is &thorn;at bringuth &thorn;is wedur : for-to destourbi godes lore;</L>
<L N="372">Ore louerd is strengore &thorn;ane he : ne drede &yogh;e eov nou&yogh;t to sore!"</L>
<L>he bi-heold upward toward god : and cride him milce and ore,
<PB REF="00000490.tif" N="442"></L>
<L>&THORN;at he schilde hem fram &thorn;e deueles mi&yogh;hte : &thorn;at he ne grefde hem nammore.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he hadde i-seid &thorn;is oresun : &thorn;at wedur bi-gan to glide</L>
<L N="376">In &thorn;e o&thorn;ur half of &thorn;e churche : al in &thorn;e sou&thorn;ere side;</L>
<L>&THORN;are it bigan to falle a-non : and nolde no leng a-bide,</L>
<L>&THORN;at vnne&thorn;e &thorn;oru&yogh;h &thorn;e hey&yogh;e stret : mi&yogh;hte ani man go o&thorn;ur ride&mdash;</L>
<L>Ake in &thorn;e northhalf of &thorn;e churche : &thorn;are &thorn;is holie man stod,</L>
<L N="380">Ne fel neuere a reynes drope : for-to destourbi a mannes Mod;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e southhalf &thorn;oru&yogh; al &thorn;e hei&yogh;e strete : it leide on for wod,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;e stret a-watere orn : ase it were a gret flod.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at folk &thorn;at fram &thorn;e prechingue : for drede of &thorn;e wedere drov&yogh;</L>
<L N="384">And &thorn;at wenden bi &thorn;e hei&yogh;e strete : hadden &thorn;ar-of i-nov&yogh;;</L>
<L>Ake huy &thorn;at bi-lefden &thorn;are : druy&yogh;e and clene were&mdash;</L>
<L>louerd, muche is &thorn;i mi&yogh;hte! : and fair miracle was &thorn;ere!&mdash;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e toun of wyricestre : bi-tidde &thorn;at selue cas,</L>
<L N="388">Ase &thorn;is holie man seint Eadmund : in is prechingue was;</L>
<L>Swuch wedur &thorn;are cam ouer him : he drof it a-wey al-so.</L>
<L>Me &thorn;inchez, ase bi is liue : fair miracle it was i-do!&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; So wide sprong is guode los : a-boute, feor and ner,</L>
<L N="392">&THORN;at men ne hulden nou&yogh;t in engelonde : of guodnesse is per.</L>
<L>At salesburi he was i-maket : Canoun seculer;</L>
<L>prouendes of churches<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> prouendre of &thorn;e hous</NOTE> he hadde : and was tresurer.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he was auauncet so : he tolde &thorn;ar-of ful luyte,</L>
<L N="396">he spendede a-boute on pouere Men : &thorn;at o&thorn;ure duden in pruyte;</L>
<L>he spendede so muche for godes loue : in is almes-dede</L>
<L>&THORN;at vnne&thorn;e he mi&yogh;hte mid is rentes : half &yogh;er is hous lede.</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;e Abbeye of stanle : he wende swi&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;anne</NOTE> i-lome</L>
<L N="400">And suiournede &thorn;are for defaute : for-to is crop him come&mdash;</L>
<L>For Maister steuene of lexintone : &thorn;at was &thorn;o Abbot &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="402">his desciple hadde i-be : &thorn;e &yogh;wyle huy at scole were.</L>
<L>his fulle .net. he neuere mo : &thorn;at ani Man mi&yogh;hte i-seo,</L>
<L>bote ase muche ase he nede moste : &thorn;et wolde in ani poynt be;<MILESTONE N="183" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of him wondrede euer-ech Man : &thorn;at isai&yogh; him ete,</L>
<L N="406">hov he mi&yogh;hte holde is lijf : with so luyte mete.</L>
<L>Of guode metes ne kepte he nou&yogh;t : &thorn;ei men it wolde him bringue;</L>
<L>&YOGH;wat lutles it was, &thorn;at he et : was al of grete &thorn;ingue.
<PB REF="00000491.tif" N="443"></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at dai &thorn;at he masse song : flechs nolde he non,</L>
<L N="410">Ne &thorn;at dai next bi-fore : for man &thorn;at mi&yogh;hte gon;</L>
<L>Fram &thorn;at Men loke alleluya : for-to cam estur-day,</L>
<L>he ne .Et. nou&yogh;ht, &thorn;at &thorn;olede deth : ase muche folk isai&yogh;h,</L>
<L>Ne in &thorn;e aduent na-&thorn;e-mo. : ake &thorn;at was luyte i-nov&yogh;</L>
<L N="414">A-&yogh;ein is o&thorn;ur penaunce : &thorn;at he al day forth drov&yogh;.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; Hit bi-fel &thorn;at &thorn;e Erchebischop : of caunterburi was ded :</L>
<L>Seint Eadmund &thorn;ar-to was chose : ase Commuyn nam heore red.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e Eleccioun was i-maud : in &thorn;e chapitle at Caunterburi,</L>
<L N="418">A-non huy senden heore messagers : to him to salesburi.</L>
<L>huy wenden toward salesbury : ake &thorn;are nas he nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>huy founden him at Calne : &thorn;o huy longue hadden i-sou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; In is chaumbre he sat priueliche : at is boke ful stille :</L>
<L N="422">No man ne dorste come him nei&yogh;h : to letten him of<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> forto wite</NOTE> is wille.</L>
<L>Ake na&thorn;eles on &thorn;at was him next : ase it were is chaumberlein,</L>
<L>Guode ti&thorn;ingue he &thorn;ou&yogh;hte him bringue : and &thorn;arof was wel fain :</L>
<L>he tolde him &thorn;at he was ichose : Erchebischop to beo.</L>
<L N="426">&THORN;is holie man gan him chide faste : and hiet him fram him fleo,</L>
<L>"Be stille, &thorn;ou fol! ich hote &thorn;e" : he seide, "and go out heonne a-non,</L>
<L>Make faste &thorn;e dore aftur &thorn;e : and ne lat &thorn;ou no man in gon</L>
<L>For-to lette me of mi studie : ake lat me in pays beo!"</L>
<L N="430">Of &thorn;at ti&thorn;ingue he tolde luyte : ase &thorn;are men mi&yogh;ten i-seo.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 2 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is Messagers bi-lefden &thorn;are oute : and carefole weren of &thorn;ou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e day passede swi&thorn;e : and heore erinde ne duden [huy] nou&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>huy wenden for heore guode ti&thorn;ingue : nobleliche beon onder-fongue,</L>
<L N="434">For &thorn;e muru&thorn;e of is semblaunt : &yogh;uyt &thorn;are hem &thorn;ou&yogh;hte longue!</L>
<L>heore &yogh;iftus huy mi&yogh;hten e&thorn;e a-bere : &thorn;at &thorn;is holie man heom caste!</L>
<L N="436">huy bi-menden, and it of-&thorn;ou&yogh;hte heom sore : heore hi&yogh;ingue &thorn;uder so faste.</L>
<L>&para; he ne a-ros nou&yogh;ht a fote fram is bok : are god &thorn;e tyme sende,</L>
<L>Ase he was an o&thorn;ur day i-woned&mdash; : ake forth&thorn; &thorn;o ful softe he wende.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he cam out of is chaumbre : &thorn;e messagers come</L>
<L N="440">And seiden heore erinde hou it was. : &thorn;ar-of he tok luyte gome.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e lettres weren i-radde : "beu freres," he sede,</L>
<L>"I-chulle loke &yogh;wat mine felawes : of &thorn;is &thorn;ing wollez rede
<PB REF="00000492.tif" N="444"></L>
<L>In &thorn;e chapitle of salesburi : ase ri&yogh;ht is &thorn;at ich do."</L>
<L>huy nadden of him non o&thorn;ur word : &thorn;o it alles cam &thorn;ar-to.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e chapitle at salesburi : i-holde was plener;</L>
<L N="446">Alle &thorn;e chanouns of &thorn;e ordre : &thorn;udere come fer and ner,</L>
<L>To conseili heom of &thorn;is &thorn;ing. : &thorn;e red was sone i-take:</L>
<L>Gladliche at one worde : alle huy stoden &thorn;are-ate.</L>
<L>"buth stille!" quath &thorn;e guode man : "&yogh;wat schal &thorn;at i-sed?<MILESTONE N="183b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="450">wuyr&thorn;e nam ich nou&yogh;t &thorn;ar-to : nimez an o&thorn;ur red!"</L>
<L>&para; "Certes," quath &thorn;e bischop &thorn;o : and &thorn;e Canones al-so,</L>
<L>"&THORN;ov ne mi&yogh;ht nou&yogh;ht beo &thorn;are-a-&yogh;ein : &thorn;ou most it nede do."</L>
<L>Seint Eadmund seide euere nay : and bi-gan to wepe sore.</L>
<L N="454">&THORN;e Chanones wepen with him al-so : and criden cristes ore;</L>
<L>To is fiet huy fullen a-kneo : and heolden up heore honde</L>
<L>And beden him for &thorn;e loue of god : betere him under-stonde</L>
<L>And habbe reu&thorn;e of holie churche : and of him-sulf al-so,</L>
<L N="458">And &thorn;enche, &yogh;wane holie churche it wolde : he moste it nede do.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e bischop also weop on him : and on him cride faste,</L>
<L>And in vertue of obedience : hiet him at &thorn;e laste</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne scholde it nou&yogh;ht bi-leue : godes wille to wurche</L>
<L N="462">And beo bou&yogh;sum to al &thorn;e lond : and nameliche to holie churche.</L>
<L>&THORN;o bi-gan &thorn;is holie man : to wepe and sike sore;</L>
<L>"Nov god," he seide, "us &yogh;iue is grace : is milce and eke is ore!</L>
<L>&para; And ich take god to witnesse : and ore leuedi al-so</L>
<L N="466">&THORN;at, &yogh;if ich ne wende suneguy dedliche : i-ne scholde it neuere do."</L>
<L>&THORN;o huy heorden &thorn;is word of him : Ioyfole i-nou&yogh; huy were,</L>
<L>And nomen him up with ioye i-nov : and to &thorn;e hei&yogh;e autere him bere,</L>
<L>And 'Te deum laudamus' songuen : swy&thorn;e murie and hei&yogh;e;</L>
<L N="470">Euere wep &thorn;e holie Man : ase &thorn;e chanones i-sei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&para; So &thorn;at he cam to caunturburi : and dude ase ri&yogh;t was &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And Erchebischop was i-maud : is vn&thorn;onkes &thorn;ei it were.</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;arf no man &thorn;ar-of esche : &yogh;we&thorn;ur he toke on wel i-nou&yogh;</L>
<L N="474">And wel wissede holie churche : and to eche guodnesse drou&yogh;!</L>
<L>&YOGH;if is lyf was holi er : wel betere it was &thorn;o;</L>
<L>In strong penaunce he was i-nov&yogh; : of fastingue and o&thorn;ur wo.</L>
<L>he hadde euere of selie bonde-men : pite and deol i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L N="478">For him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at &thorn;e hei&yogh;e men : duden hem al day wou&yogh;.&mdash;
<PB REF="00000493.tif" N="445"></L>
<L>&para; In a time on of is pouere Men : wende of lif-dawe,</L>
<L>And is beste best to heriet : men brou&yogh;te him, ase it was lawe.</L>
<L>&THORN;o cam &thorn;is selie mannes wif : &thorn;at careful widewe was,</L>
<L N="482">And mette with &thorn;is holie man : ase ore louerd &yogh;af &thorn;at cas :</L>
<L>heo cride on him deolfulliche : merci and is ore,</L>
<L>And seide him, bote &thorn;at o best : luyte guod heo hadde more;</L>
<L>heo<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Ne heo</NOTE> nuste in &yogh;wat manere : ne hou<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> for meseise</NOTE> heo mi&yogh;hte liue,</L>
<L N="486">heo bad him for &thorn;e loue of god : &thorn;at best a-&yogh;ein hire &yogh;iue.</L>
<L>&para; "Guode womman," seide &thorn;e holie man : "&thorn;ou wost wel hou it is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;at chief louerd habbe &thorn;e beste ay&yogh;te : &yogh;wane is man is ded, i-wis."</L>
<L>To is clerkes he seide a-latyn : &thorn;at &thorn;e widewe it ne under-stod :</L>
<L N="490">"Me &thorn;inchez it a lu&thorn;ur lawe : and no&thorn;ur ri&yogh;htful ne guod.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode wif hath i-lore hire louerd : &thorn;at al hire guod forht&thorn; drou&yogh;,</L>
<L>And to leose &thorn;are-aftur ire<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. is</NOTE> beste best : me &thorn;inchez it is wou&yogh;;</L>
<L>In &thorn;at on were lure<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. lu&thorn;ur</NOTE> i-nou&yogh; : &thorn;ei heo ne lore &thorn;at o&thorn;ur al-so.</L>
<L N="494">&THORN;e deueles lawe it is of helle : and &thorn;oru&yogh;h god neuere i-do.<MILESTONE N="184" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; "Guode wif," he seide, "&yogh;if ich [&thorn;e] take : a-&yogh;ein &thorn;i best to lone,</L>
<L>Wolt&thorn;ou it witie to mine bi-hof&thorn;e : for-to ich it axi eft-sone?"</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> A &yogh;e</NOTE> sire," quath &thorn;e widewe : "god &yogh;elde &thorn;e &thorn;in ore!"</L>
<L N="498">&THORN;e widewe nam hom hire best : and ne &yogh;eld it him nammore.</L>
<L>&THORN;is Auntur bi-fel ofte si&thorn;e : &yogh;wane men him wolden bidde ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>heriot of pouere men : he ne wilnede ri&yogh;ht nou&yogh;ht.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; We ne mowen rikeni nou&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> nowhar ne&yogh;</NOTE> : alle is guode dedes.</L>
<L N="502">For euere in strong penaunce i-nou&yogh; : is lif he gan lede,</L>
<L>And treuliche heold up holi churche : and wuste hire fram ech wou&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-fore hadde &thorn;e deuel of helle : to him onde i-nou&yogh; :</L>
<L>he bi-gan for-to a-rere contek : bi-tweone him a-non</L>
<L N="506">And &thorn;e king hanri &thorn;at was &thorn;o : &thorn;e kingues sone Ioan.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king and muche del of is folk : a-&yogh;ein holie churche was,</L>
<L>Ase king henri, is graunt-sire : hadde a-&yogh;ein seint Thomas;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at couent of caunturburi al-so : a-&yogh;ein him hul[d] wel faste;</L>
<L N="510">Ofte huy nomen louedai : ake &thorn;et contek euere i-laste.</L>
<L>&para; A legat was &thorn;o in engelonde : &thorn;at a-&yogh;ein him was al-so.</L>
<L>Ake studefast was euere &thorn;is holie man : &thorn;ei he luyte help hadde &thorn;ar-to.</L>
<L>huy ne mi&yogh;ten a-cordi for no-&thorn;ing : ake &thorn;e lengore &thorn;e worse it was;</L>
<L N="514">Ake euere nam &thorn;is holie man : ensaumple of seint thomas.
<PB REF="00000494.tif" N="446"></L>
<L>Wel ofte he bad &thorn;e kingue and his : &yogh;if it were heore wille,</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy ne weorreden nou&yogh;t a-&yogh;ein holi churche<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> H. ch. to werri no&yogh;t</NOTE> : ake laten hire beo stille</L>
<L>In hire fraunchise and in pays : ase heo hadde i-beo &yogh;are.</L>
<L N="518">&THORN;e king &thorn;retnede &thorn;ene holie man : bote he bi-lefde is fare.</L>
<L>&para; "Of &thorn;i &thorn;retningue ich telle luyte" : seide &thorn;is holie man,</L>
<L>"For &yogh;if &thorn;ou me drifst out of &thorn;i lond : an o&thorn;ur red ich can :</L>
<L>Ich can rede at parys : ase ich are &thorn;is habbe i-do,</L>
<L N="522">And &thorn;are-with winne me mete i-nov&yogh; : and clo&thorn;ingue al-so.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou me dest to de&thorn;e bringue : &thorn;ou paist me wel i-nov&yogh;;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou ne mi&yogh;htest don me non more honour : &thorn;ane slen me &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;i wou&yogh;."</L>
<L>&para; &YOGH;uyt eft, ase he ofte dude : to &thorn;e king he sende;</L>
<L N="526">And he answerede &thorn;e leng &thorn;e wors : and no-&thorn;ing nolde a-mende.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is holie man i-sai&yogh;h : &thorn;at non-o&thorn;ur it nolde beo,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh;h holi churche he gan to fi&yogh;hte : and a-corsede alle &thorn;eo</L>
<L>&THORN;at weorreden a-&yogh;ein<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> &thorn;e churche of caunturburi : and with on-ri&yogh;hte duden schame;</L>
<L N="530">And some &thorn;at he gulti wuste : he a-mansede bi name.</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;e king and to is conseil : &thorn;is word wel sone drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;arf no man esche : we&thorn;ur huy weren wro&thorn;e i-nov&yogh;!</L>
<L>&THORN;are was &thorn;retningue and bost i-nov&yogh;. : seint Eadmund heold him stille,</L>
<L>And stifliche heold forth &thorn;e sentence : and liet heom speke heore wille.</L>
<L>Seint Thomas cam and spak with him : and gostliche fram heouene a-li&yogh;hte,</L>
<L>And bad him beo stif and studefast : to holde up &thorn;e churches ri&yogh;hte,</L>
<L>And for non eor&thorn;elich anuy : ne for de&thorn;e, ne flechchie nou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L N="538">Ake nime ansaumple of him and o&thorn;ure : &thorn;at so deore as hadde a-bou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; Seint Eadmund feol a-doun a-kneo : and is hondene heold up al-so<MILESTONE N="184b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To cusse &thorn;is holie mannes fiet. : ake he ne moste it nou&yogh;ht do.</L>
<L>&THORN;o bi-gan he to weope sore i-nov&yogh; : and seide "louerd, &thorn;in ore!"</L>
<L N="542">"beo stille," quath seint Thomas to him : "and ne weop &thorn;ou so non|more!</L>
<L>&YOGH;wi wilnest&thorn;ou to cusse mine fiet? : it nere &thorn;e no ri&yogh;ht to do,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt newene &thorn;ine wille habbe : and cusse mine mouth al-so."
<PB REF="00000495.tif" N="447"></L>
<L>&para; Seint Eadmund aftur &thorn;ulke tyme : studefast was i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L N="546">To dei&yogh;e ra&thorn;ur for holie churche : &thorn;ane men duden hire any wov&yogh;.</L>
<L>he &thorn;ou&yogh;hte muche on seint Thomas : &thorn;at out of londe wende</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;wyle &thorn;e kyng was in mest wrath&thorn;e : &yogh;if he wolde ou&yogh;t amende:</L>
<L>Of him he nam ensaumple : and priueliche i-nov&yogh;</L>
<L N="550">he wende out of Enguelonde : and into Fraunce he drou&yogh;.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh;hte he was at pounteneye : swi&thorn;e faire under-fongue</L>
<L>And isusteyned in his anuy : &thorn;at i-laste longue;</L>
<L>&para; Also steuene of languetone : &thorn;at Erchebischop was,</L>
<L N="554">Six &yogh;er he was at pounteneye : in &thorn;at sulue cas.</L>
<L>&THORN;o<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> so</NOTE> &thorn;at seint Eadmund under-stod : of is Auncetres i-nowe,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane huy weren in contek for holie churche : to pounteneye heom drowe:</L>
<L>Also dude seint Eadmund&mdash; : to pounteneye he wende,</L>
<L N="558">For-to a-bide &thorn;e stat of holie churche : &yogh;wane ore louerd it wolde amende.</L>
<L>honoured he was faire i-nov : of alle &thorn;at &thorn;are were,</L>
<L>And euere a-bod a-mendement : fram &yogh;ere to &yogh;ere.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg2">langor.</NOTE>&para; Hit bi-fel, ase god wolde : &thorn;at seint Eadmund at&thorn;e laste</L>
<L N="562">Fielde is bodi heui i-nov&yogh; : and fieblede swi&thorn;e faste;</L>
<L>So longue, &thorn;at he was so feble : &thorn;at men ne radde him nou&yogh;ht beo &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Ake for-to soiorni elles-&yogh;ware : &thorn;are betere eir to him were.</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie man is leue nam : elles-&yogh;wodere to wiende;</L>
<L N="566">&THORN;e Monekes mauden so muche deol : &thorn;at &thorn;ar-of nas non ende.</L>
<L>&para; "beth stille," quat &thorn;is holie man : "for ichulle &thorn;oru alle &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Comen hidere a&yogh;ein to eou : a-seint Eadmundes day &thorn;e kyng."</L>
<L>Louerd, in swuche siknesse : wuch a word &thorn;at was i-seid!</L>
<L>Ake, &yogh;wane he ne mi&yogh;hte bi is liue : forewar[d] he heold heom ded!</L>
<L>Forth he wende with is men : &thorn;udere ase guod eir were:</L>
<L N="572">To &thorn;e toun of Soysi : and bi-lefde &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&para; So longue so it was, &thorn;are he eode : in grete siknesse i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L N="574">So longue &thorn;at he lay a-doun : and toward &thorn;e de&thorn;e drov&yogh;.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he Axede ore louerdes flechs : and it was him i-brou&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>he sat and bi-heold it faste i-nou&yogh; : in gret studie and in &thorn;ou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>Longue are he seide ani word : and &thorn;o spak he wel inliche:
<PB REF="00000496.tif" N="448"></L>
<L>"louerd," he seide, "&thorn;ou it art : &thorn;at ich habbe i-loued treweliche,</L>
<L>&para; And treweliche on &thorn;e ich [habbe] bi-leue[d]<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> bileued, ich habbe om.</NOTE> : and i-preched of &thorn;e al-so,</L>
<L N="580">And &thorn;ou treweliche at min ende-day : art i-come me to.</L>
<L>Ich take &thorn;e, louerd, to witnesse : &thorn;e &yogh;wyle ich habbe on vr&thorn;e i-beo,</L>
<L N="582">&THORN;at i-ne wilnede neuere aftur<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> no-&thorn;ing on vr&thorn;e : louerd, so muche ase aftur<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> &thorn;e."</L>
<L>A,. louerd, &thorn;at it<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;is</NOTE> was an hei&yogh;h word : and he &thorn;at so sede</L>
<L>Guod and holi moste he be : and swi&thorn;e holi lif lede!<MILESTONE N="185" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;o he hadde i-nome ore louerdes flechs : he sat longue in &thorn;ou&yogh;hte,</L>
<L N="586">And al lei&yogh;hinde on Englichs : &thorn;eos wordes forth he brou&yogh;hte:</L>
<L>"Men seggez &thorn;at game goth in wombe : ake i segge game goth in heorte."<NOTE PLACE="marg1">A v. om.?</NOTE></L>
<L>Of ore louerd &thorn;at he hadde i-nome : wel Ioyful he was &thorn;o,</L>
<L>And al is game was in is heorte&mdash; : for is bodi was ful of wo.</L>
<L N="590">&THORN;e more is bodi i-pined was : &thorn;e ner he was &thorn;en ende;</L>
<L>And &thorn;o is ende-day was i-come : he wuste &yogh;wodere wiende.</L>
<L>&para; Euere &thorn;e more &thorn;at he was : in sicknesse and in wo,</L>
<L>&THORN;e gladdore he was, for he wuste : &yogh;wodere he scholde go,</L>
<L N="594">And &thorn;e more he was<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> lo&yogh;</NOTE> in Ioye : and &thorn;e muregore him gan like.</L>
<L>Men nuste him nou&yogh;ht enes ligge a-doun : to groni ne to siche,</L>
<L>Ake euere he sat glad i-nou&yogh; : and lenede al-so wel ofte</L>
<L>Opon clo&thorn;es o&thorn;ur opon is hond : and deide faire and softe.</L>
<L N="598">Fair semblaunt he maude i-nov&yogh; : ase he drov to &thorn;en ende;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e moreweningue ase &thorn;e sonne a-ros : out of &thorn;is world he gan wiende.</L>
<L>&para; He deide twelf hundred &yogh;er : and to and-fourti ri&yogh;ht</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;at ore swete louerd : in is moder was a-li&yogh;ht.</L>
<L N="602">Men leten openi him a-non : &amp; is gottus take</L>
<L>And burie heom &thorn;are ase he was ded : in &thorn;e Munstre of seint Iake;</L>
<L>Men nomen is holie bodi : and wel faire gunne it lede</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Abbeye of pounteneye : ase he him-sulf er sede.</L>
<L N="606">A-seint Eadmundus dai &thorn;e king : &thorn;udere he was i-brou&yogh;ht&mdash;</L>
<L>he heold &thorn;e Monekes foreward : and ne failede heom nou&yogh;ht:</L>
<L>&para; For &thorn;o he ne cam nou&yogh;ht a-liue a&yogh;ein : ded he dude, i-wis!</L>
<L>And &thorn;are he was i-brou&yogh;ht on vr&thorn;e : and i-schrined al-so he is;</L>
<L N="610">he lith &thorn;are faire i-nov&yogh; : and with gret honour al-so.
<PB REF="00000497.tif" N="449"></L>
<L>Mani is &thorn;e faire Miracle : &thorn;at god hath for him i-do.</L>
<L N="612">Nou god for &thorn;e loue of him : and &thorn;at us deore bou&yogh;hte,</L>
<L>To &thorn;ulke blisse us bringue : &thorn;at he is soule brou&yogh;hte. AmeN</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="64" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>64 [Martyn]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint Martyn was i-bore : in &thorn;e londe of sabarie;</L>
<L>Wel &yogh;ong he was i-noriced : in &thorn;e londe of papie.</L>
<L>A noble kny&yogh;ht is fadur was : and Maister of &thorn;e fierde,</L>
<L N="4">Vnder Costantyn &thorn;e Aumperour : and al is .Ost. he stierde.</L>
<L>For<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om., r. forth?</NOTE> into batayle he brou&yogh;hte is &yogh;oungue sone : &thorn;ar-of him to lere.</L>
<L>None heorte nadde he &thorn;er-to : for huy he&thorn;ene were;</L>
<L>his heorte bar him euere to Iesu crist : &thorn;ei he i-cristned nere,</L>
<L N="8">he i-sai&yogh;h &thorn;at heore bi-leue nas nau&yogh;ht : &thorn;at huy bi-lefden &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&para; To churche, &thorn;o he was Twelf &yogh;er old : stilleliche he wende</L>
<L>And bi-hiet ore louerd cristine to beo : &yogh;wane he &thorn;e time him sende.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Aumperour het<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. h<SUP>i</SUP>et?</NOTE> into al &thorn;at lond : to euereche olde kni&yogh;te</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;at heore sones scholden into batayle comen : and for heore faderes fi&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e &yogh;ungue seint Martin : nas bote of fiftene &yogh;er</L>
<L>&THORN;o he [&thorn;e armes]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> in eche bataile : for is fadere ber.</L>
<L>A winter ase &thorn;is child rod : bi &thorn;e weye al one,</L>
<L N="16">A Miseise man he mette naked : sore sike and grone.<MILESTONE N="185b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Seint Martyn drov&yogh; out is swerd : ase we findeth in &thorn;e bok,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. boke</NOTE></L>
<L>And carf is Mantel half a-to : and &thorn;e pouere Manne it bi-tok.</L>
<L>&para; Sone aftur-ward, ase he bi-heold : to-ward heouene an hei&yogh;h,</L>
<L N="20">with is halue Mantel i-heled : ore louerd crist he sei&yogh;h:</L>
<L>"lo," he seide to is Aungles : "&thorn;is ne worth me nou&yogh;ht bi-reued;</L>
<L>Martin, &thorn;at is he&thorn;ene &yogh;uyt : here-with me hath bi-weued."</L>
<L>&THORN;o Martin &thorn;is i-herde : and ore louerd he sai&yogh;h &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="24">Glad ne bli&thorn;e nolde he beo : are he i-cristned were.</L>
<L>&para; Ei&yogh;htetene &yogh;er he was old : &thorn;o he i-cristned was;</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hadde so longue a-bide : ofte he seide alas.</L>
<L>Ake al &thorn;e to &yogh;er &thorn;are-afturward : in-to batailes he wende</L>
<L N="28">For is fader wide a-boute : ase &thorn;e Aumperor him sende.</L>
<L>hit bi-fel of a gret bataile : &thorn;at &thorn;e Aumperor hadde i-nome,</L>
<L>he het alle is kny&yogh;htes in is lond : &thorn;at huy scholden to him come;
<PB REF="00000498.tif" N="450"></L>
<L>he het<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. hiet</NOTE> Martyn with heom wende : and Armure with him take.</L>
<L N="32">"Certes, sire," Martin seide, "&thorn;ine Armes ich habbe for-sake,</L>
<L>&para; Ich am Iesu cristes kny&yogh;ht : and so ich habbe i-beo longue,</L>
<L>And none o&thorn;ure Armes bote his : i-nelle vnder-fongue."</L>
<L>"Ei, couward," seide &thorn;e Aumperour : "nou&thorn;e &thorn;ou sparest for fere</L>
<L N="36">For-to fi&yogh;hte with &thorn;ine felawes : ase &thorn;i ri&yogh;te were?"</L>
<L>"Sire," seide Martin &thorn;o : "&thorn;e so&thorn;e &thorn;ou schalt i-se,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ine Armes ne kepe i nou&yogh;ht : ake &thorn;e furste ichulle beo</L>
<L N="39">Al one bi-fore al &thorn;i folk : naked to &thorn;e bataile;</L>
<L>Mine louerdes mi&yogh;hte &thorn;ou schalt i-seo : for he me nele nou&yogh;t faile."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;at ferd al-&yogh;are was : seint Martin wende a-non</L>
<L>Vn-armed with is swerd a-drawe : among alle is fon.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he a-mong hem was i-come : &thorn;are nas of hem nou&yogh;ht on</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at mi&yogh;hte ani more hebbe up is hond : &thorn;ane it were a ston;</L>
<L>huy &yogh;olden him &thorn;e maistrie a-non : bote &thorn;at he let hem a-liue.</L>
<L>Seint Martin clepede is felawes : and het hem hom wel bliue.</L>
<L>"Sire Aumperour," he seide, "nou&thorn;e &thorn;ou sixt : &yogh;wuch is mi louerdes mi&yogh;hte;</L>
<L N="48">Are &yogh;e alle it hadden &thorn;ar-to i-brou&yogh;ht : longue &yogh;e mosten fi&yogh;hte!</L>
<L>&para; Nov &thorn;ou hast alle &thorn;ine fon i-wonne : &thorn;onke god, and nou&yogh;ht me,</L>
<L>And haue guod day, for i-nelle : no lengore serui &thorn;e."</L>
<L>he nam is leue and wende forth : &mdash;he nolde no leng a-bide&mdash;</L>
<L N="52">To &thorn;e holie bischop hyllari : &thorn;at wonede &thorn;are-bi-side.</L>
<L>Of him he was i-maud a-colite : and dude al bi is rede.</L>
<L>Ore louerd cam to him a ni&yogh;ht : and &thorn;eos wordes to him seide :</L>
<L>&para; "Ich hote &thorn;e, Martin, &thorn;at &thorn;ou go : wel ofte to &thorn;ine kunne,</L>
<L N="56">And spec with hem, &yogh;if &thorn;ov mi&yogh;ht : bringue hem out of sunne;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei &thorn;at huy he&thorn;ene beon : ne let heom nou&yogh;ht &thorn;are-fore,</L>
<L>For ech guod man schal Anouri &thorn;at kun : &thorn;at he was of i-bore.</L>
<L>Ake gret a-nuy &thorn;ov schalt habbe : &thorn;e &yogh;wile &thorn;ou gest a-boute;</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;e &yogh;wyle &thorn;ou mine grace hast : &thorn;e &thorn;arf no-wi&yogh;ht doute."</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode Man, ase ore louerd him het : to-ward is kun wende.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. hiet</NOTE></L>
<L>Strongue outlawes bi &thorn;e wei he mette : heore bouwes sone huy bende,</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode man huy nomen : and maden him mani a wounde,<MILESTONE N="186" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="64">Forth huy ladden him for-to sle : is hondene faste i-bounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e outlawes axede him &yogh;if he were : so sore a-drad euere.
<PB REF="00000499.tif" N="451"></L>
<L>"Nai, certes," quath &thorn;is holie man : "&thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> so siker</NOTE> nas ich neuere.</L>
<L>&para; Ore louerdes hel<SUP>p</SUP> was euere nei&yogh;h : &thorn;e manne &thorn;at was in care :</L>
<L N="68">So muche is &thorn;ar-to min hope : &thorn;at i-ne rechche hou ich fare."</L>
<L>Of Ihesu crist he tolde so : with heom &thorn;at him nome,</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy ful sone leten him go : and cristine for him bi-come.</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;is guode Man eode forth al one : &thorn;e deuel a-&yogh;ein him cam;</L>
<L N="72">In faire manere he axede him : &yogh;wodere &thorn;ene wei he nam.</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode Man seide, "ichulle go : ase mi louerd wole lede me."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;wodere &thorn;ou go," &thorn;e o&thorn;ur seide : "&thorn;e deuel wole a&yogh;ein &thorn;e beo."</L>
<L>&para; "&YOGH;e," seide &thorn;is guode Man : "&thorn;ou most wel al-so;</L>
<L N="76">For &yogh;wane ore louerd is min help : i-ne rechche &yogh;wat o&thorn;ure do."</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode Man eode a-mong is freond : is moder cristine he made;</L>
<L>his fader nolde cristine be : for al &thorn;at huy him bede.&mdash;</L>
<L>Seint Martin fond a &yogh;ong man ded : &thorn;at swi&thorn;e wel with him was,</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;at bi-lefde on ore louerd for him : ake i-cristned nou&yogh;t he nas.</L>
<L>&para; Gret deol made &thorn;is holie man : &thorn;at he nadde ibe i-cristned er :</L>
<L>To is burieles he eode, and bad for him : and weop wel mani a ter.</L>
<L N="83">&THORN;e dede Man bi-gan a-non : fram de&thorn;e arise to liue;</L>
<L>"Martin," he seide, "i-hered beo &thorn;ou : and ore louerdes woundes fiue!</L>
<L>Mi soule was to helle i-lad : ase alle beoth of oure kuynde,</L>
<L>Ake tweye Aungles &thorn;oru&yogh; godes grace : hadden me in muynde</L>
<L>And seiden ore louerd &thorn;at ich hadde : ouwer desciple i-beo;</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;are-fore ore louerd me dude a-rise : for &thorn;e honour of &thorn;e</L>
<L>And dude mi soule to mi bodi : for &thorn;i loue hider bringue.</L>
<L>Cristine-dom par charite : ich esche bi-fore alle &thorn;ingue."</L>
<L>&para; Gret Ioye hadde &thorn;is holie Man : of &thorn;is swete cas;</L>
<L N="92">he nolde departi fram him nou&yogh;ht : are he i-cristned was.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk nam seth&thorn;e seint Martin : for he was so guod,</L>
<L>And maden him bischop of turoyne : muche a-&yogh;ein is mod.</L>
<L>To mile with-oute &thorn;e cite : an Abbeye he liet a-rere;</L>
<L N="96">Four-score Monekes of guode liue : him-sulf he dude &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>with heom he wonede al in pays : ase he heore soueren were;</L>
<L>he ne wende nou&yogh;ht out bote &yogh;wane it neod was : &thorn;at folk for-to lere.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; So holi lif seint Martin ladde : &thorn;at he hadde to is heste</L>
<L>Fuyr., and treo., and &thorn;e kuynde of worm : of foules and of beste.</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg1">a v. om.</NOTE>A strong wind blev&yogh; a fuyr : &thorn;at to seint Martines house it wende,
<PB REF="00000500.tif" N="452"></L>
<L>And are &thorn;is guode man it onder-&yogh;ete : i-barnd was &thorn;at on ende.</L>
<L>Seint Martyn hiet a-godes name : &thorn;at fuyr a-&yogh;ein wiende :</L>
<L N="104">For is heste &thorn;at fuyr flev&yogh; : a-non a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e wynde</L>
<L>To &thorn;e stude &thorn;are it cam fram : and ne bi-lefde no-wi&yogh;ht bi-hinde,</L>
<L>And dude a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e kuynde of fuyre : a-&yogh;ein &thorn;e wynde to fle.<MILESTONE N="186b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;are was i-sene &thorn;at fuyr ne mi&yogh;hte : a-&yogh;ein is heste be.&mdash;</L>
<L N="108">&para; To is heste he hadde, ase ich seide er : &thorn;e kuynde of &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L>Ase &yogh;e mouwen bi a fair miracle : of him nou&thorn;e i-seo.</L>
<L>On a dai ase he stod under a treo : to prechi godes lawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e lu&thorn;ere men &thorn;at &thorn;are-bi stoden : &thorn;ou&yogh;hten him bringue of dawe :</L>
<L N="112">huy gunne sawie &thorn;at treo a-to : to-ward &thorn;is holie Manne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it scholde ouer-falle him&mdash; : for &thorn;are nadde he freond nanne.</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; noyse of &thorn;e crake&yogh;ingue : &thorn;e guode man i-heorde</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ut treo fel touward him. : a-&yogh;ein wel sone he it cherde;</L>
<L N="116">&para; he het &thorn;at treo a-godes name : opward a-&yogh;ein tuyrne.</L>
<L>&THORN;at treo a-ros up-ri&yogh;ht i-nou&yogh;h : for it nolde is heste werne,</L>
<L>And ouer-ful<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. ouerfalle</NOTE> in &thorn;at o&thorn;ur side : [m]anie<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. anie</NOTE> of is fon.</L>
<L N="119">huy &thorn;at leoueden, lieten heom sone : cristni euerech-on.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e worm dude is heste al-so. : for ase he cam bi a wateres brimme,</L>
<L>A lodlich Naddre he i-sai&yogh;h : stifliche a&yogh;ein him come swymme.</L>
<L>"Ich hote &thorn;e," seide &thorn;is holie Man : "&thorn;at &thorn;ov a&yogh;einward wende,</L>
<L>A[n]t &thorn;at &thorn;ou neuereft here ne come : ne nou&yogh;were in &thorn;is ende."</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;is worm turnede a-&yogh;en a-non : ase &thorn;is holie Man him het,</L>
<L>And swam in-to an o&thorn;ur lond : and &thorn;ulke contrei&yogh;e fur-let.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; Foules duden is heste al-so. : for on a time ase he gan gon,</L>
<L>he sai&yogh;h douedoppene fisches cachche : and swolewen heom in a-non.</L>
<L N="128">"Alas!" seide &thorn;is guode man : "&thorn;is is &thorn;e feondes manere :</L>
<L>Gultlese<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. gultlesse</NOTE> &thorn;ingus and vnwarre : to cachchen, ase huy doth here,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ing &thorn;at non harm ne doth : bote wenth in pay[s] to beo;</L>
<L>So farez &thorn;e deuel, a-waytez euere : for-to he is prei&yogh;e i-seo."</L>
<L N="132">he het &thorn;e foules a-godes name : ech-one &thorn;annes teo</L>
<L>And &thorn;at huy scholden in-to wildernesse : out of &thorn;at watere fleo,</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy neueref[t] &thorn;are ne comen : gultlese &thorn;ingues to take.</L>
<L>&THORN;is foules a-non with &thorn;is word : awei huy gonne schake.&mdash;</L>
<L N="136">&para; bestes duden al-so is heste. : for ase he wende a-boute,</L>
<L>Aftur ane hare he sai&yogh;h vrne : grehoundes a gret route;
<PB REF="00000501.tif" N="453"></L>
<L>"Alas," he seide, "&thorn;is seli best : &thorn;at no-&thorn;ing ne doth a-mis!</L>
<L>&THORN;is foule houndes it wollez to-drawe : gultles ase it is."</L>
<L N="140">he het &thorn;e grehoundes a-bide a-non : and ne do &thorn;at best no wo;</L>
<L>huy at-stunten a-non, and eoden a-&yogh;ein : and lieten &thorn;at best forth go.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 2 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; On atyme kene houndes comen : a-boute one of is manne;</L>
<L>he ne mi&yogh;hte him wite, so kene huy were : ne help nadde he nanne:</L>
<L N="144">"Ich hote eov," he seide, "a-godes name : and on seint Martines al-so,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e me laten a-pais wende : Min erinde for-to do."</L>
<L>&THORN;e houndes a-non with &thorn;at word : bi-gonne to stonde stille,</L>
<L>And wenden euerech in is wey : to do seint Martines wille.</L>
<L N="148">&para; A kov al-so &thorn;at was gidi : a-boute orn in &thorn;e londe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fale men slov, and bestes al-so : &yogh;ware heo fond anie stonde;</L>
<L>hire ne mi&yogh;hte no-&thorn;ing atstonde a-&yogh;ein : so strong &thorn;at foule &thorn;ing was.</L>
<L>A-&yogh;ein seint Martin heo cam eorne : ase ore louerd &yogh;af &thorn;at cas;<MILESTONE N="187" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="152">Sore weren is Men a-dradde. : &thorn;is guode Man hire het a-non</L>
<L>A-godes name stonde stille : and [n]ane<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. ane</NOTE> fot for&thorn;ere gon.</L>
<L>&THORN;at best, &thorn;ei it gidi were : a-non it gan a-bide.</L>
<L N="155">Seint Martin &thorn;ene deuel i-sai&yogh; : opon hire rugge ride.</L>
<L>&para; "&THORN;ov lu&thorn;ere &thorn;ing &yogh;wat dost&thorn;ov &thorn;er? : for euere &thorn;ou dost to quede.</L>
<L>&YOGH;wy trauailest &thorn;ou &thorn;at selie best : &thorn;at ne loueth no misdede?</L>
<L>A-corsede &thorn;ing, &thorn;ou wend a-wei : ne cum nei&yogh;h hire non-more!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel wende a-wei a-non : &yogh;eollinde suy&thorn;e sore&mdash;</L>
<L N="160">he moste nede is heste do : ase wel ase &thorn;e kov.</L>
<L>&THORN;o heo of him deliured was : ase &yogh;e i-hereth hov,</L>
<L>Mildeliche heo eode to seint Martyn : to is fet heo feol a-kneo a-non,</L>
<L>And schok hire heued, to &thorn;onki him : he nolde fram him gon.</L>
<L N="164">&para; Seint Martin hire het a-risen up : and to ire felawes wende.</L>
<L>heo lottede on him and eode forth : hom to ire owene ende.&mdash;</L>
<L>Seint Martin was apostlene pier : for &thorn;e holie gost a-li&yogh;hte</L>
<L>In him ase in &thorn;e Apostles : in fourme of fuyr wel bri&yogh;hte.</L>
<L N="168">A dai ase &thorn;is guode Man sat : allone in is celle,</L>
<L>his priue Men a-biden him &thorn;are-oute : and heorden him loude telle;</L>
<L>Al-so ase &thorn;ei it wummen were : huy heorden with him speke.</L>
<L>&THORN;are-of hem &thorn;ou&yogh;hte wonder gret : ne dorsten huy nou&yogh;t in breke.</L>
<L N="172">&para; Seth&thorn;e &thorn;o &thorn;e guode man cam out : huy fullen a-doun a-kneo,
<PB REF="00000502.tif" N="454"></L>
<L>And axeden &yogh;wat &thorn;e speche were : &thorn;at with him hadde i-beo.</L>
<L>&THORN;e guode man seide, "ich may eou telle : for &yogh;e me beoz priue:</L>
<L>It was ore lauedi and seint Anneis : &thorn;at &thorn;are-inne weren with me,</L>
<L N="176">Of &thorn;e Ioye of heouene huy speken : and ofte huy doth so.</L>
<L>Seint petre and seint powel : to me comiez ofte al-so."&mdash;</L>
<L>Seint Martin at paray<NOTE PLACE="marg1">place left vacant, paray on the margin; <I>al.</I> paris</NOTE> : mette ane Musel bi cas.</L>
<L>he custe him, and anon aftur-ward : &thorn;e Musel al hol was.&mdash;</L>
<L N="180">&para; Men ne sei&yogh;e him neuere wroth : ne li&yogh;e no-&thorn;e-mo,</L>
<L>And &yogh;wat-so-euere is Men duden : he wolde euere bi on go.</L>
<L>In wel pouere wede a day : he rod out on ane Asse;</L>
<L>hei&yogh;e Men he mette bi &thorn;e weie : &thorn;at tolden of him &thorn;e lasse.</L>
<L N="184">heore hors weren of him a-drad le : for is pouere clo&thorn;es,</L>
<L>And ornen a-bach, and felden hem a-doun. : huy weren with him ful wro&thorn;e,</L>
<L>huy sturten up and nomen &thorn;is holie Man : and beoten him ful sore.</L>
<L>Euere he was stille and ne spak no word : for &thorn;i huy beoten him &thorn;e more.</L>
<L N="188">&para; &THORN;o huy him hadden so i-bete : huy bi-lefden [him] at&thorn;en ende</L>
<L>ligginde &thorn;are, and wor&thorn;en on heore hors : forth heore wei to wende.</L>
<L>Ake heore hors nolden gon of &thorn;e stude : for al &thorn;at huy don<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> mi&yogh;ten,</L>
<L>&YOGH;uyt huy<NOTE PLACE="marg1">&yogh;uyt huy <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> smiten with &yogh;eorde and with spore : are &thorn;at huy a-li&yogh;hten</L>
<L N="192">And criden merci &thorn;is guode Man : &thorn;at huy him hadden mis-do.</L>
<L>heore hors hem bere forth a-non : &thorn;o huy token on so.&mdash;</L>
<L N="194">And in an hous &thorn;e &yogh;wile it barnde : he slep wit-oute harm;</L>
<L>his clo&thorn;es fur-barnden al-to cole : he ne fielde it no-&thorn;ing warm.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; At a gret feste, ase he scholde : &thorn;e hei&yogh;e masse singue,<MILESTONE N="187b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To churche he wende with is men : men gunne a-&yogh;ein him ringue.</L>
<L>Ane pouere Man he mette nake : &thorn;at no schroud him nadde a-boue,</L>
<L>And bad him sum-&thorn;ing to helien him with : for ore louerdes loue.</L>
<L N="200">Seint Martyn bad is Ercedekne : &thorn;at he him &yogh;eue sum cloth.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Ercedekne tolde &thorn;arof luyte : and nolde, he swor is Oth.</L>
<L>Seint Martin bote anne Cuyrtel : on him-sulf &thorn;o nadde:</L>
<L>To &thorn;e pouere Manne he hine &yogh;af : in an hous &thorn;are he him ladde.</L>
<L N="204">&para; he ne bi-lefde on him no cloth of wolle : bote is Cope al-one.</L>
<L>&THORN;e masse ne mi&yogh;hte he bi-guynne nou&yogh;ht : &thorn;at folk made &thorn;ar-of mone.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;wy nelt&thorn;ou," seide &thorn;e Ercedekne : "&thorn;ine masse bi-guynne?"
<PB REF="00000503.tif" N="455"></L>
<L>"For &thorn;ou most er ane pouere Manne : sum cloth to him i-winne."</L>
<L N="208">"Nov is &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="marg1">erased? <I>al.</I> hit</NOTE>," seide &thorn;e Ercedekne : "gret a-nuy with &thorn;e,</L>
<L>For j-ne seo no pouere Man : nou&yogh;were a-boute &thorn;e be."</L>
<L>"No," seide &thorn;is holie man : "it nele faillie &thorn;e nou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>Al redi &thorn;ou findest a pouere Man : habbe &thorn;ou &thorn;at cloth i-b<SUP>r</SUP>ou&yogh;th."</L>
<L N="212">&para; &THORN;e Ercedekne in grete wrath&thorn;e : eode into chepingue,</L>
<L>A lodlich cloth he bou&yogh;hte for fif panes : to &thorn;e bischope he gan it bringue.</L>
<L N="214">&THORN;e bischop eode into &thorn;e vestiarie : is Cope he gan of strepe.</L>
<L>he nadde under is vestimenz : to habbe on bote <SUP>&thorn;</SUP>is<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. is</NOTE> Iuype,</L>
<L>Vnne&thorn;e it heolede is derne limes : and nou&yogh;ht folliche is elbouwes;</L>
<L>For is bare Armes at&thorn;e masse : &thorn;is guode man hadde gret houwe&mdash;</L>
<L N="218">For &thorn;e uestimenz wide weren : and is Armes smale and lene;</L>
<L>laste is Armes nakede weren i-sei&yogh;e : he ne dorste hebbe op is hond ene.</L>
<L N="220">&para; Ake &thorn;o he nedlingus at &thorn;e sacrement : is hondene hebbe up scholde,</L>
<L>An Aungel schrudde is nakede armes : with tweie sleuene of golde.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Harl. 3 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e ercedekne cride and bi-hiet : &thorn;at neuere-eft mis-don him he nolde.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel hadde to &thorn;is holie man : gret onde with-alle.</L>
<L N="224">he cam in a time him to bi-traye : in riche clo&thorn;us of palle,</L>
<L>with hosen and schon of bri&yogh;te golde : swy&thorn;e fair he was of face.</L>
<L>"Martin," he seide, "wel &thorn;e beo : i-founde &thorn;ou hast mine grace:</L>
<L>Ich am &thorn;ilke &thorn;at &thorn;ou seruest wel : ichulle me schewi to &thorn;e;</L>
<L N="228">&THORN;ov most sone chaungi &thorn;i lif : and bi-time come to me."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is guode Man sat in gret &thorn;ou&yogh;ht : no word he ne sede.</L>
<L>"Martyn," he seide, "ich am &thorn;i freond : &yogh;war-of hast&thorn;ou drede,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane &thorn;in owene god spekez with &thorn;e : here mouth with mou&thorn;e?</L>
<L>Euere &thorn;ou hast of guode bi-leue i-beo : ne lat it nou&yogh;t faili &thorn;e nou&thorn;e!</L>
<L>For ich blessi alle &thorn;at on me bi-leuez : &thorn;ei huy me nou&yogh;ht ne seo,</L>
<L N="234">And er &thorn;is &thorn;ei &thorn;ov ne sei&yogh;e me nou&yogh;ht : in &thorn;ulke blessingue &thorn;ou woldest be."</L>
<L>&para; "I nuste neuere," quath &thorn;is guode man : "&thorn;at mi louerd euere sede</L>
<L N="236">&THORN;at he wolde on vr&thorn;e come : in swuche riche kingene wede;
<PB REF="00000504.tif" N="456"></L>
<L>And bote ich mouwe of mine louerdes woundes : on &thorn;e signe i-se</L>
<L>O&thorn;ur of is croyz, inelle i-leue : &thorn;at &thorn;ou mi louerd be."</L>
<L>&THORN;e foule &thorn;ing wende a-wey : and was adrad of ane boule;</L>
<L N="240">&THORN;e stude &thorn;are-Aftur swi&thorn;e longue : stonk of him ri&yogh;ht foule.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 2 vv. more.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L><MILESTONE N="188" UNIT="folio">&para; &THORN;is guode Man seide his ende-day : him was swy&thorn;e wel come.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> wel longe er hit come</NOTE></L>
<L>his desciples weopen sore : and gret deol to heom nome.</L>
<L>"Leoue fader," huy seiden, "&yogh;wat schulle we do : &thorn;at &thorn;ov us wolt for-sake?</L>
<L N="244">Vs fader-les with-oute confort : &yogh;wam wolt&thorn;u bi-take?</L>
<L>Nov wollez wilde wolues come : and alle &thorn;ine schep a-spille."</L>
<L>"Ich mot nede," seide &thorn;is guode man : "don mine louerdes wille."</L>
<L>Of Askene and of is here he made<NOTE PLACE="marg1">he m. on the margin.</NOTE> : a bed at is ende-day,</L>
<L N="248">And &thorn;aron feble a&yogh;en is de&thorn;e : opri&yogh;ht adoun him-sulue he lay;</L>
<L>And toward heouene lokede ay : so longue &thorn;at it nas non ende.</L>
<L>his Men &thorn;ou&yogh;hten it dude him harm : and wolden him helpe to wende.</L>
<L>&para; "A-bideth," seide &thorn;is holie man : "&yogh;wy wolle &yogh;e don so?</L>
<L N="252">latez me ane &yogh;wyle bi-holde &thorn;e stude : &thorn;at mi soule schal to!"</L>
<L>&THORN;o i-sai&yogh;h he &thorn;ene deuel aftur is soule : stonde &thorn;are with is feren.</L>
<L>"A-wey," he seide, "&thorn;ou lu&thorn;ere best : &thorn;ou nast nou&yogh;t to don here!</L>
<L>with me nast&thorn;ou nou&yogh;t to done : for mi louerd me wole onder fongue;</L>
<L N="256">In is name to him ich wende : &thorn;at bou&yogh;hte me swi&thorn;e strongue."</L>
<L>&para; With &thorn;usse worde he &yogh;af &thorn;ene gost&mdash; : Aungles i-redie were,</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk heorde heore murie song : ase huy &thorn;e soule bere.</L>
<L>Four hondret &yogh;er it was : and in &thorn;e sixe-and-sixti&thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L N="260">Aftur ore louerdes buyrtyme : &thorn;at &thorn;is guode Man deide &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Four-score winter he was old : are he was ded al-so.</L>
<L>God &yogh;iue us part of &thorn;ulke ioye : &thorn;at is soule wende to.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="65" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>65 [Leonard conf.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint leonard &thorn;e confessour : a-londe eode her</L>
<L>Aftur ore louerdes buyrtyme : a-boute fif hundred &yogh;er.</L>
<L>his freond and is cunnes-men : &thorn;e gretteste maystres were</L>
<L N="4">In &thorn;e kyngus house of Fraunce : grettore none &thorn;are nere;</L>
<L>And seint leonard al-so was : a gret maister with &thorn;e king;
<PB REF="00000505.tif" N="457"></L>
<L N="6">Of &thorn;at he him bidde wolde : he wernde him no-&thorn;ing.</L>
<L>he grauntede him alle &thorn;e prisones : &thorn;at he fore bidde wolde,</L>
<L>Aftur is bone ope al is lond : &thorn;at men him<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> hem</NOTE> deliueri scholde.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is holie man wende a-boute faste : prisones forte glade;</L>
<L N="10">And &yogh;wane he fond ani of luyte gult : deliuered sone he made.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i Men him cleopeden "prisones louerd" : and &yogh;uyt men doth al-so,</L>
<L>For non o&thorn;ur halewe for prisones : so fair miracle nath i-do.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e king of Fraunce him bi-sou&yogh;hte : &yogh;eorne ope al is mi&yogh;hte</L>
<L N="14">&THORN;at he scholde with him beo : bi dayes and bi ny&yogh;hte,</L>
<L>For-te &thorn;are fulle ani bischopriche : &thorn;at he him mi&yogh;hte bi-take.</L>
<L>Seint leonard nolde it graunti nou&yogh;ht : ake outri&yogh;ht it gan for-sake,</L>
<L>And wende forth a-&yogh;ein is wille : and bad him habbe guod day.</L>
<L N="18">Formest he wende to Orlians : to prechie godes lay.</L>
<L>&para; Longue he prechede &thorn;are-a-boute : &thorn;at folk for-to lere;</L>
<L N="20">And seth&thorn;e he wende to Aquitayne : for-to prechie &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Eche daye he wolde at toune beo : to prechi godes lawe,</L>
<L>And eche ni&yogh;hte he wende to &thorn;e wode : &yogh;wane it to eue gan drawe,</L>
<L>In is oresones to beon al one&mdash; : ac so sone so it was day,</L>
<L N="24">In-to &thorn;e contreye he wolde a-boute : and prechi godes lay.&mdash;<MILESTONE N="188b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e king hadde in &thorn;ulke wode : a tour of grete bolde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he mi&yogh;hte soiourni &thorn;er : &yogh;wane he euere wolde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Quene was with childe grete : &thorn;udere men gonne hire bringue,</L>
<L N="28">&YOGH;if heo &thorn;e betere mi&yogh;hte for solas : ouer-come hire childingue.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he was in trauail : heo ne mi&yogh;hte ouer-come it nou&yogh;ht;</L>
<L>So sore heo pinede &thorn;at heo was : wel nei&yogh;h to de&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e king, and alle his, gret deol maden : &thorn;at crie men heorde hem wide;</L>
<L N="32">And &thorn;o seint leonard herde &thorn;ar-of : he gan heorkni and a-bide.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he i-heorde &thorn;at it was of men : &thorn;udere he gan wende,</L>
<L N="34">&YOGH;if god wolde ani a-mendement : &thorn;oru&yogh; is bone hire<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> sende.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e king he wende a-non : and axede &yogh;wat him were.</L>
<L>"beo glad," he seide, "for of &thorn;i Quene : ne haue &thorn;ou none fere!"</L>
<L N="37">"A, Merci, sire," quath &thorn;e king : "al mi lond ichulde<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. ichulle</NOTE> &yogh;yue</L>
<L>ho-so mi&yogh;hte [it] &thorn;ar-to bringue : &thorn;at &thorn;e Quene moste liue!</L>
<L>&para; For of &thorn;e childe ne rou&yogh;hte i nou&yogh;ht : mi&yogh;hte ich habbe hire lif."
<PB REF="00000506.tif" N="458"></L>
<L>"Sire," seide &thorn;is holie Man : "lat me i-seo &thorn;i wif,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ich hire may to liue bringue : and &thorn;at child al-so,</L>
<L N="42">&THORN;oru&yogh; mine louerdes swete grace&mdash; : nere it wel i-do?"</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie Man was to &thorn;e Quene i-brou&yogh;ht : &thorn;at lai &yogh;are to de&thorn;e;</L>
<L>So clene heo was with pine ouer-come : &thorn;at vnne&thorn;e heo mi&yogh;hte bre&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&para; Seint leonard sat a-doun a-kne : and is preiere made,</L>
<L N="46">&THORN;at ore louerd hire deliueri scholde : hire freond forto glade,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at heo moste to liue come : and al-so &thorn;at child &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;at Men mi&yogh;hten seo &thorn;at &thorn;e grace : of ore louerd muche were.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Quen a-non &thorn;oru&yogh;h is bone : deliuered was of childe,</L>
<L>In guod lif, and hire child al-so&mdash; : &thorn;are was ore louerd wel milde!</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e king i-say &thorn;e Quene sauf : and &thorn;at child al-so,</L>
<L N="52">For ioye he nuste &yogh;wat he mi&yogh;hte : with &thorn;at holie man do;</L>
<L>he bad he scholde of al is guod : nime &yogh;wat he wolde.</L>
<L>Seint leonard seide, "ne kepe i nou&yogh;ht : of &thorn;i seluer ne of &thorn;i guolde,</L>
<L>Bote a place &thorn;at ich mowe : in godes seruise inne liue."</L>
<L N="56">"Certes," seide &thorn;e king, "and ichulle : al &thorn;is wode &thorn;e &yogh;iue."</L>
<L>"Ne kepe ich," quath seint leonard : "nou&yogh;ht more of &thorn;e i-bide</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;at ich may in one ni&yogh;hte : with min Asse ouer-ride."</L>
<L>&para; "Ich graunti it &thorn;e," seide &thorn;e king : "ne wende &thorn;ou no so wide,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;ei heo were quickore &thorn;ane ani best : &thorn;at is bi &thorn;is wode-side."</L>
<L>&THORN;is guode man a-boute &thorn;is wode wende : opo[n] is Asse wel stille</L>
<L>And bi-rod al-so muche place : ase it was is wille.</L>
<L>&THORN;e king, &thorn;o it i-marked was : liet wal makie a-boute,</L>
<L N="64">And Aftur is wille he liet a-rere : noble hous and proute.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;are seint leonard Monk bi-cam : ase it an Abbeye were,</L>
<L>And mani o&thorn;ere he nam in to him : ore louerdes lawe to arere.</L>
<L>he bi-gan &thorn;are a religion : of ordre swi&thorn;e strongue;</L>
<L N="68">Clerkus &thorn;at wolden guode men beo : to him he gan hem fongue.</L>
<L>Nier &thorn;ane a gret Mile wei : no watur nadden huy &thorn;ere;<MILESTONE N="189" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Seint leonard hopede amendi &thorn;at : &yogh;if godes wille it were :</L>
<L>he bi-gan openi &thorn;e eor&thorn;e a luyte : and is oresones he made.</L>
<L>A swi&thorn;e fair welle &thorn;are sprong up : &thorn;at &thorn;are-inne men mi&yogh;hte wade.</L>
<L N="73">&THORN;o mi&yogh;hten huy habbe watur i-nov&yogh; : &thorn;e &yogh;wile &thorn;at hous i-laste,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh;&yogh; godes grace and seint leonardes bone : &thorn;at heore mi&yogh;hte<NOTE PLACE="marg1">on the margin.</NOTE> &thorn;are|to casten.&mdash;
<PB REF="00000507.tif" N="459"></L>
<L>&para; "prisones louerd," seint leonard : ful wide i-cleopud was:</L>
<L N="76">Ore louerd him schewede fayr miracle : for some &thorn;ingue it was<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &amp; no&yogh;t for no&yogh;t it nas</NOTE>!</L>
<L>For &yogh;wane prisones criden to him : manie with dreorie chere,</L>
<L>heore biendes borsten alle a-to : and huy deliurede were;</L>
<L>Manie comen to &thorn;onki him : and heore feoteres with heom bere,</L>
<L N="80">And manie to serui ore louerd crist : bi-lefden with him &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&para; Seue Men with alle heore freond : &thorn;at weren of is kunne,</L>
<L>&THORN;o huy heorden of is guodnesse telle : huy solden lond and wunne,</L>
<L>And wenden and woneden &thorn;are with him : holi lif to lede;</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;is holie Man of godes lawe : gan heom wissi and rede.</L>
<L>So fair Miracle ase of him was : no man nou&yogh;were nuste;</L>
<L>Mani sik Man &thorn;are hadde bote : &thorn;at to him wel truste.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; At&thorn;e laste &thorn;o<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;e</NOTE> he scholde heonne fare : longue at-fore he it wuste;</L>
<L>his bre&thorn;ren he cleopede alle to him : and wel mildeliche hem custe,</L>
<L N="89">And wende to &thorn;e Ioye of heouene : &thorn;o god aftur him sende.</L>
<L>Gret deol alle is bre&thorn;ren maden : &thorn;o he &thorn;annes wende.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if ore louerd fair Miracle dude : on eor&thorn;e bi is liue,</L>
<L N="92">Aftur &thorn;at he was heonne i-wend : he dude swuche fiue.</L>
<L>&para; For miracle &thorn;at &thorn;are was : muche folk &thorn;udere gan falle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e place ne mi&yogh;hte nou&yogh;ht : bi manie holden alle.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at folk cride on ore louerd &yogh;eorne : &thorn;re dai&yogh;es and &thorn;re ni&yogh;ht,</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;at he scholde, &yogh;if is wille were : &thorn;ar-of don insi&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>huy i-sei&yogh;en &thorn;o &thorn;e contreie al-a-boute : i-heoled al mid snowe,</L>
<L>And a place a-midde fair and grene : Men mi&yogh;hten &thorn;aron mowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;o iseien huy &thorn;at ore louerd wolde : &thorn;at &thorn;is guode man lei&yogh;<SUP>e</SUP> &thorn;ere:</L>
<L N="100">huy lieten him bere &thorn;udere a-non : and a wel fair churche a-rere;</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;e folk &thorn;at &thorn;udere cam : ne mi&yogh;hte fulle &thorn;e place</L>
<L>&THORN;at ore louerd him hadde i-chose : &thorn;oru&yogh; is swete grace.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e scherreue of leouns : feteres made strongu[e]</L>
<L N="104">And in &thorn;e hexte tour of &thorn;e castel : &thorn;are he liet heom<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. heom heom</NOTE> hongue,</L>
<L>So hei&yogh;e, &thorn;at ech man heom mi&yogh;hte i-seo : &thorn;at bi &thorn;e wey&yogh;e scholde wiende,</L>
<L>And euerech man &thorn;at &thorn;ar-on were : &thorn;e more him for-to schende;</L>
<L>&THORN;at Men &thorn;at schuuych torment isei&yogh;en : &thorn;e more scholden drede,</L>
<L N="108">Laste huy weren &thorn;aron i-brou&yogh;ht : to don ani mis-dede.
<PB REF="00000508.tif" N="460"></L>
<L>So &thorn;at he nam ane trewe Man : for a luyte lesingue</L>
<L>And dude him binde swi&thorn;e faste : and in &thorn;ulke feoteres bringue.</L>
<L>With pine and sorewe &thorn;is seli man was : almest i-brou&yogh;t to de&thorn;e;</L>
<L N="112">To seint leonard he cride &yogh;eorne : ase he mi&yogh;hte speke onne&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&para; Seint leonard cam a ni&yogh;ht to him : in swi&thorn;e &yogh;wite wede:</L>
<L>"For &thorn;ou hast to me &yogh;eorne i-bede : here ich am," he seide;<MILESTONE N="189b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"&THORN;ine strongue feteres bring with &thorn;e : ne haue &thorn;ou none drede,</L>
<L N="116">And a-ris up sone a[nd] cum forth with me : for henne ichulle &thorn;e lede."<NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 115 &amp; 116 <I>al.</I> transposed.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Op a-ros &thorn;is selie man : with wel glade chere;</L>
<L>his feteres borsten sone a-two : for huy bi-comen ful sere,</L>
<L>And seint leonard ladde him forth : ase he is felawe were,</L>
<L N="120">To &thorn;e churche &thorn;at he inne lay : and hanguede is feteres &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Euere ase huy bi &thorn;e weye eoden : &thorn;is holie man with him tolde,</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;ey he hadde is felawe i-beo : bi &thorn;e hond he gan him holde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e schirreue cam an o&thorn;ur day : and is feteres sou&yogh;hte:</L>
<L N="124">he sai&yogh;h &thorn;at he tolde luyte of him : &thorn;at heom &thorn;udere brou&yogh;hte.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 2 vv. more.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; A lu&thorn;ur Man in gret power : in an o&thorn;ur stude was also,</L>
<L>Ane gultelese Man he hadde i-nome : and in strong prisone ido.</L>
<L>he heorde telle of seint leonard : &thorn;at &thorn;e prisones help was,</L>
<L N="128">And &thorn;ou&yogh;hte fram him is prisun wite : with som quoynte cas:</L>
<L>he liet maken of lim and ston : a wonderliche deop put,</L>
<L>And wit strongue dores of Ire and stiel : swy&thorn;e faste he was i-dut;</L>
<L>On-ouewarde &thorn;e fallinde dore : &thorn;o &thorn;e guode Man was &thorn;ar-inne,</L>
<L>A strong &yogh;wuchche of Ire he liet maken : with wel quoynte ginne:</L>
<L N="133">&THORN;are-inne he dude stalewor&thorn;e Men : &thorn;ane prison for-to wite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at seint leonard ne scholde nei&yogh;h him come : bote he were under&yogh;ite.</L>
<L>&THORN;e selie Man &thorn;at bi-neo&thorn;e was : in so strong warde i-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="136">Criede &yogh;eorne on seint leonard : &thorn;at he ne fur-&yogh;ete him nou&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>&para; A ny&yogh;ht cam &thorn;is holie man : And &thorn;e &yogh;wuchche he fond &thorn;ere:</L>
<L>Sone he &yogh;weluede hire op &thorn;e doun : and heom &thorn;at &thorn;are-inne were,</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e he brac &thorn;e Irene dore : and ase a maister he wende a-doun,</L>
<L N="140">with swy&thorn;e gret ly&yogh;ht of heouene : and spac with &thorn;at prisoun:</L>
<L>"Slepest&thorn;ou?" he seide, "ich am i-come : &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast i-cleopud so,
<PB REF="00000509.tif" N="461"></L>
<L>Godes desciple leonard. : &yogh;wat wolt&thorn;ou habbe i-do?"</L>
<L>"louerd," seide &thorn;is selie man : "al-so wis ich bidde &thorn;e</L>
<L N="144">Ase ich am gultles here i-do : &thorn;at &thorn;ou helpe me."</L>
<L>A-non-ri&yogh;ht &thorn;is holie Man : &thorn;e Gyues he to-brac,</L>
<L>And bi-tweone is Armes he bar him forth : no man a-&yogh;ein him ne spac,</L>
<L>And so hom to is owene hous : bi-twene is Armes him bar,</L>
<L N="148">he bad him beon a guod man : and sette him a-doun &thorn;ar.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is lu&thorn;ere men wit alle hore ginnes : fiebleliche habbuth a-guonne,</L>
<L>huy mi&yogh;hten hangen up heore Ax : and leuen weork<NOTE PLACE="marg1">a. l. w. <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> : for luyte huy &thorn;are wonne!&mdash;</L>
<L N="151">&para; A lu&thorn;er man in Alemaygne : an onkouth pilegrim nam</L>
<L>And brou&yogh;hte him into strong prisoun : and &yogh;af him swi&thorn;e hard dom,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bote his freond him wolden out bugge : he scholde bi-leue &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;is selie Man nadde no freond : and Maude wel reulich chere,</L>
<L>he bad for seint leonardes loue : &thorn;at he merci of him hadde;</L>
<L N="156">And he nolde him o&thorn;ur merci do : bote into &thorn;at strong prisone him ladde.</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;e louerd of &thorn;at Castel : seint leonard a-ni&yogh;ht cam</L>
<L>And [hiet] him late gon is seriaunt : &thorn;at he with vnri&yogh;hte nam.</L>
<L>An o&thorn;ur ni&yogh;ht eft-sone he cam : and &thorn;e &thorn;ridde ni&yogh;ht also,<MILESTONE N="190" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="160">And hiet him deliuri his seriaunt. : ake neuere he nolde it do.</L>
<L>&para; Seint leonard ladde &thorn;is selie man : fram &thorn;e prisone a-mong heom alle;</L>
<L>&THORN;e hei&yogh;e tour of &thorn;at Castel a-non aftur him : a-doun gan falle</L>
<L>And a-slov al &thorn;at folk &thorn;at &thorn;are was : bote &thorn;ene louerd one;</L>
<L N="164">Ake bo&thorn;e is leggues breken a-two : with fallingue of ane stone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at neuereft ne mi&yogh;hte he beon hol : no&thorn;ur of flechs ne of bone;</L>
<L>Croked he was al is lif : he nuste to &yogh;wam mene is mone.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; Also in Brutayne was a kny&yogh;ht : &thorn;at in strong prisone was i-brou&yogh;ht;</L>
<L N="168">To seint leonard he cride faste : &thorn;at he ofte hadde i-sou&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>Streite wardeines ouer him &thorn;are weren : bo&thorn;e ny&yogh;ht and day,</L>
<L>&THORN;are he with strongue feteres : in prisone i-bounde lay.</L>
<L>Seint leonard a-mong alle &thorn;e wardeins : in-to &thorn;e prisone cam</L>
<L N="172">Ase a maister &thorn;oru&yogh; heom alle : &thorn;isne selie kny&yogh;ht he nam,</L>
<L>his biendes he brac formest a-two : and ladde him bi &thorn;e hond</L>
<L>A-mong alle is wardeins : hom in-to is owene lond;</L>
<L>&para; his feoteres he tok him in is hond : &thorn;at he forth with him bar
<PB REF="00000510.tif" N="462"></L>
<L N="176">To seint leonardes Chapele : and a-mong o&thorn;ure hieng heom &thorn;ar.</L>
<L>&THORN;o ne dorste non of &thorn;e wardeines : a word speke with mou&thorn;e.</L>
<L>Swuch a man may wel mayster hote : &thorn;at so heom a-gaste cou&thorn;e!</L>
<L>&THORN;e Miracles &thorn;at he for prisones dude : ne may no man telle.</L>
<L N="180">Nov god for &thorn;e bone of seint leonard : us schilde fram &thorn;e pine of helle.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="66" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>66 [Magdalena.<NOTE PLACE="foot">This legend has been edited before in my "Sammlung altenglischer Legenden," Heilbronn, 1878; two other MSS. of the same text, Trin. Coll. Cambr. R 3, 25 and Lambeth 223, in Herrig's Archiv, 1882. It is a very old poem, in stanzas with mid &middot; rhymes, originally in the East-Midland dialect, perhaps by the author of Gregorius; the text is greatly corrupted.&mdash;All other MSS. contain a different text.</NOTE>]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Slei&yogh;e Men and egleche : and of redes wise and bolde,</L>
<L>Lustniez nou&thorn;e to mi speche : wise and vnwise, &yogh;ongue and olde :</L>
<L>No-&thorn;ing ich eov nelle rede ne teche : of none wichche ne of none scolde,</L>
<L N="4">Bote of a lif &thorn;at may beo lech<SUP>e</SUP> : to sunfule men of herte colde.</L>
<L>&para; Ich nelle eov no&thorn;er rede ne rime : of kyng ne of Eorl,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Telle nelle i<SUP>c</SUP> of no man:</NOTE> of kny&yogh;ht ne of swein,</L>
<L>Ake of a womman ichchulle ov telle<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> also i<SUP>c</SUP> can</NOTE> : &thorn;at was sunful and for-lein :</L>
<L>A swy&thorn;e fol wumman heo bi-cam : and &thorn;oru&yogh; godes grace heo was i-brou&yogh;ht a&yogh;eyn,</L>
<L N="8">And nou&thorn;e heo is to crist i-come : &thorn;e fayre Marie Maudeleyn.</L>
<L>Of hire<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> h. name</NOTE> ichulle &yogh;eou telle nou&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> : al-hou and &yogh;ware heo was i-bore,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &yogh;e to me wullez i-heore<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> lusten &amp; dwelle</NOTE> : and habben of god &thorn;onk &thorn;are-fore.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is word Marie so is bri&yogh;h[t]nesse : and bi-tokne&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. bitokne &thorn;e</NOTE> steorre of &thorn;e se,</L>
<L>And soruwe also and biturnesse : ase &thorn;e bok tellez me;</L>
<L N="13">For &yogh;wane a man fielez in is heorte : &thorn;at he hauez muche mis-do,</L>
<L>And him &thorn;are-fore biguynnez to smeorte : &thorn;at is to him<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;an is him</NOTE> bitur and wo,</L>
<L>he mournez and he sikez ofte&mdash; : &thorn;is ilke Marie fierde al-so,</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at was hire leof and softe : was seth&thorn;e hire fulle fo.</L>
<L>&para; In &thorn;e Castel of Magdale : &thorn;is faire wumman was i-bore :</L>
<L>heo was icleoped in propre name : "&thorn;e Maudeleyne" ri&yogh;ht &thorn;are-fore.</L>
<L>To speken of hire ich am wel fous : and it likez me ful murie.</L>
<L N="20">Ire fader was hoten sire Titus : and hire moder Dame Euchirie;</L>
<L>hire bro&thorn;ur was cleoped lazarus : and Martha was hire soster&mdash;</L>
<L>heo was debonere and pitiuous : and heo was a seli foster.
<PB REF="00000511.tif" N="463"></L>
<L N="23">heore fader and heore moder bo&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. bo</NOTE> : comen of riche kunne,</L>
<L>Of bolde kyngus and of Quienes<NOTE PLACE="marg1">sup. also</NOTE> : Men of muchele wunne :</L>
<L>&para; Of castles and of tounes<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. toures</NOTE> : of londes and of &thorn;eodes,<MILESTONE N="190b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of halles and of boures : of palefrei&yogh;es and of stedes;</L>
<L>large huy weren of heore metes : to heom &thorn;at hadden neode,</L>
<L N="28">To men goinde and eke sittinde<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> ysete</NOTE> : &thorn;at heore bonene wolden heom beode.</L>
<L>Wyse men and sley&yogh;e : oueral huy weren i-tolde.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at huy scholden dei&yogh;e : and so huy weren i-holde :</L>
<L>&para; Heore londes and heore leodes : huy delden alle a-&thorn;reo,</L>
<L N="32">Tounes and heore &thorn;eodes : heore guod<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. gold</NOTE> and heore feo,</L>
<L>To feoffen heore children<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Here ch. to dy&yogh;te</NOTE> : &thorn;are-wiz echon,</L>
<L>For huy ne scholden nou&yogh;t striue<NOTE PLACE="marg1">fy&yogh;te</NOTE> : &yogh;wane huy heom weren at-gon.</L>
<L>wel sone &thorn;ere-aftur : &thorn;o huy nede scholde,</L>
<L N="36">Deiden fader and Moder : ase iesu crist it wolde;</L>
<L>&para; Bi heom Men duden sone : ase huy ou&yogh;ten to done,</L>
<L>And to heore longue home : brou&yogh;ten heom ful sone&mdash;</L>
<L>Iesu crist of heouene : of heom habbe merci</L>
<L N="40">And for is names seouene : fram helle heom waraunti!</L>
<L>huy di&yogh;hten heore londes : a-mong heom, alle &thorn;reo,</L>
<L>And with heore hondene delden : heore gold and heore feo :</L>
<L>To Marie bi-lefde<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> gan falle</NOTE> : &thorn;e castel Magdale,</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;are-fore Maudeleyne<NOTE PLACE="marg1">sup. of alle</NOTE> : formest i-cleoped was heo;<NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 43-44 are wr. in one line.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lazarus hadde &thorn;at haluen-del<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> chaumpart</NOTE> : of al Ierusalem,</L>
<L>Of wodes and fieldes and of sart : al-mest to bedle<SUP>h</SUP>em;</L>
<L>Martha was i-feoffed : with &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> Betanie</L>
<L N="48">And al-so with genezarez : bote &thorn;e bok us lie.</L>
<L>&para; Marie, heo ne tolde nou&yogh;t : bote al of hire pruyde,</L>
<L N="50">Ake &thorn;ar-on was al hire &thorn;ou&yogh;ht : and faire hire to schruyde,</L>
<L>And seth&thorn;e for-to walke a-boute<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> : to don hire flechses wille,</L>
<L>To gon and eorne feor and neor<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &amp; to stalke</NOTE> : bo&thorn;e loude and stille;</L>
<L>For-so&thorn;e, heo was riche i-nou&yogh;h<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> sekirly</NOTE> : and so heo moste nede :</L>
<L>Manie riche Men hire lei&yogh;en bi : and &yogh;euen hire gret mede.</L>
<L>&para; Lazarus spendede al is &thorn;ou&yogh;ht : op-on his chiualerie,</L>
<L N="56">Of o&thorn;ur &thorn;ingus ne tok he no &yogh;eme : ne to<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Ac at o word he tolde no&yogh;t: of</NOTE> housebondrie.</L>
<L>&THORN;e selie Martha, &thorn;at o&thorn;ur suster : heo was of redes guode,
<PB REF="00000512.tif" N="464"></L>
<L>Ase &thorn;ei heo and hire soster : neren nou&yogh;t of one blode :</L>
<L>&para; Martha nam hire bro&thorn;ur lond : and hire sustres al-so,</L>
<L N="60">And dude heom teolien wel i-nou&yogh; : ase wys man scholde do;</L>
<L>&THORN;are-with heo fedde alle heore men : and clo&thorn;ede heom al-so,</L>
<L>[&amp;] pouere men and wummen : &thorn;at weren neodfole and in wo.</L>
<L>&para; So fair womman nas &thorn;are non : in none kunnes londe,</L>
<L N="64">Ase marie was of bodie<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> lycam</NOTE> : and of fote and honde;</L>
<L>So more fairore &thorn;at heo bi-cam<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> was hir fax</NOTE> : &thorn;e more of hire was prys,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. pryis</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e more fol womman heo wax : and sunful and unwys :</L>
<L>&para; Hire ri&yogh;hte name marie : ouer-al heo les &thorn;are-fore,</L>
<L N="68">Sunfole wumman men cleopeden hire<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> gan hire clepy</NOTE> : bi-hinde hire and bi-fore.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is wumman hadde i-heord : &thorn;at hire name was ilore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at heo was so bi-gyled and bicherd : wo was hire &thorn;are-fore;</L>
<L>&THORN;o Men hire cleopeden sunfule : and li<SUP>e</SUP>ten hire ri&yogh;hte name,<MILESTONE N="191" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="72">heo wax kareful and dreori of &thorn;ou&yogh;ht<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> drery &amp; carful</NOTE> : and gan sore to schame :</L>
<L>&THORN;o nolde heo no-more : bi-fore &thorn;e riche men come;</L>
<L>In-to hire castel for sorewe<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> sore</NOTE> : heo hauez hire i-nome,</L>
<L>For-to ore louerd cam and prechede : ouer al in &thorn;at londe.</L>
<L>Martha hire suster ofte bi-fore op-braid<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. apechede?</NOTE> : hire schame and hire schonde,</L>
<L N="77">And chidde hire ful ofte : for hire lecherie,</L>
<L>bo&thorn;e fastinde and eke ful : &thorn;at vnne&thorn;e he mi&yogh;hte it drie.</L>
<L>&para; A man of &thorn;at contreye : &thorn;at hei&yogh;hte symond leperous,</L>
<L N="80">Al-so &thorn;e bok us tellez : bad ore louerd to is hous,</L>
<L>And is deciples tweolue : with him, to &thorn;e mete,</L>
<L>For he ne mi&yogh;hte nou&yogh;ht him-sulf : fram heom alle ete.</L>
<L>&para; Marie &thorn;is i-heorde : and &thorn;arof was ful glad;</L>
<L N="84">A smeorieles to grei&thorn;i : &thorn;ar-to he was ful rad;</L>
<L>heo wende to symundes hous : &thorn;at no man hire ne bad,</L>
<L>To ore louerd Iesu crist.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> crist Iesus</NOTE> : and ful sore heo was of-drad,</L>
<L>&para; For &thorn;at he was so sunful : bi-fore ore louerd to come,</L>
<L N="88">Careful heo was, and sore a-ferd : forto beon i-nome;</L>
<L>heo ne dorste ore louerd repie nou&yogh;ht<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> : bi-hinde ne bi-fore,</L>
<L>Ne no Man hire nolde cleopie : and &thorn;at hire grefde sore.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o ore louerd was i-sete : in symundes house &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="92">And his Apostles to &thorn;e mete : &thorn;at with him &thorn;o were,</L>
<L>Ore louerd sat and &thorn;ou&yogh;hte muche : ake bote luyte he ne eet.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. eat</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000513.tif" N="465"></L>
<L>Marie &thorn;at was so sunful<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at of hirself ne ro&yogh;t</NOTE> : heo crep doun to is fiet,</L>
<L>&para; heo custe is fiet and wusch al-so : with hire wete teres,</L>
<L N="96">And wipede heom aftur-ward : with hire &yogh;eoluwe heres,</L>
<L>Out of hire boxe heo nam : Oynement ful guod</L>
<L>And smeorede ore louerdes heued : with ful blisful mod.</L>
<L>&para; Iudas was &thorn;are bi-side and smulde hit : and &thorn;are-fore he was nei&yogh;h wod,&mdash;</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;at swote smul him culde nei&yogh;h : and gremede is sorie blod,&mdash;</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> he</NOTE> bad don up &thorn;at riche &thorn;ing : &thorn;at heo ore louerd gan with smeore;</L>
<L>To spene it so in wasting : he seide, it was gret lure;</L>
<L>And seide, "it mai beon i-sold ful deore : to bugge with muchel mete,</L>
<L N="104">pouere Men &thorn;are-with to freueri : of drunch and of mete."<NOTE PLACE="marg1">on the margin, to drinke and to ete</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o saide ore louerd to Iudas : "lat &thorn;ou &thorn;is wumman beo!</L>
<L>Ful guod weork it was and is : &thorn;at heo wurchez in me;</L>
<L>For ai schulle &yogh;e pouere with eov habbe : and so ne worth eov me&mdash;</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;i toungue moste bien i-schaue : to speche heo is to freo."</L>
<L>&para; Symund leprous i-heorde &thorn;is : he &thorn;ou&yogh;hte wel mani-fold</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &yogh;if &thorn;es profete were al-so wys : ase he is fore i-told,</L>
<L N="111">he nolde soffri &thorn;is fole wumman : his bodi enes to reppe,</L>
<L>For no weork &thorn;at heo can do<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> do can</NOTE> : to-ward him enes steppe.</L>
<L>&para; Ore louerd wuste is lu&thorn;ere &thorn;ou&yogh;ht : ake &thorn;arof stod him non ey&yogh;e:</L>
<L>"Symund, &thorn;ou &thorn;enchest muche for nou&yogh;ht. : sum-&thorn;ing ichulle &thorn;e sei&yogh;e."</L>
<L>"Maister, seye," seide symound : "ich it bidde &thorn;e!</L>
<L N="116">For &thorn;ou noldest for no &thorn;ing<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> C pound</NOTE> : segge on-ri&yogh;ht to me."<MILESTONE N="191b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; "An vsurer was &yogh;wilene : &thorn;at hadde dettores tweyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at swy&thorn;e longue &yogh;wyle : dette him scholden bey<SUP>n</SUP>e:</L>
<L>&THORN;at on him scholde fifti panes : and twenti &thorn;ar-to,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> fyf si&thorn;e twenti</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at o&thorn;ur him scholde of dette : fifti panewes al-so.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> panes : fulle fifty</NOTE></L>
<L N="121">&para; And no&thorn;ur of heom nadde : &yogh;ware-of &thorn;e dette for-to &yogh;elde:</L>
<L>huy &yogh;olden, &thorn;o he it creuede<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> He for&yogh;af hit hem : (the MSS. are corrupt)</NOTE> : ase &thorn;e bok us telde.</L>
<L>&YOGH;we&thorn;ur of heom tweine : cudde him more loue &thorn;o?"</L>
<L N="124">"Maister, he &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at he</NOTE> more &yogh;af<NOTE PLACE="marg1">for&yogh;af</NOTE> : me &thorn;inche, so mote i go."</L>
<L>&para; "For so&thorn;e, symund leperous : &thorn;ou hauest i-demed a-ri&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>For seth&thorn;e ich cam into &thorn;in hous : &thorn;ou ne custest me no-wi&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;ou ne wusche nou&yogh;t mine fiet : with watur ne with teres</L>
<L N="128">Ne &thorn;ou ne wypedest heom nou&yogh;ht &yogh;uyt : with clo&thorn;e no with heres,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig, here, s added later.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000514.tif" N="466"></L>
<L>&para; Min heued on none halue : with no-manere Oynement</L>
<L>Ne smeordest<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. smeredest smeordest</NOTE>, with none salue : ne with no piement;</L>
<L>Seth&thorn;e ich cam in-to &thorn;in hous : &thorn;is wumman<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. wumnan</NOTE> nolde blinne</L>
<L N="132">Mine fiet to wasche and cusse : with-outen and with-inne,</L>
<L>&para; And to wipen heom seth&thorn;e aftur-ward : with hire faire here,</L>
<L>Min heued also to smeorien : with riche Oynement and dere.</L>
<L>Op aris, &thorn;ou wumman, &thorn;ine sunnes &thorn;e beoth for-&yogh;yue!</L>
<L N="136">Al-so ich nou&thorn;e can and may<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. may and can</NOTE> : of me &thorn;ou art i-schriue."</L>
<L>&para; Marie &thorn;e Maudeleyne<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> M. &thorn;at was in fere</NOTE> : ore swete louerd hire schrof,</L>
<L>Swete Iesu crist out of hire : seue deuelene he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. heo</NOTE> drof.</L>
<L>Ore louerd makede hire is procuratour : his leof and is hostesse;</L>
<L N="140">heo louede him with gret honour : in pays and in destresse.</L>
<L>&para; Martha, hire suster, was ful sik : and so heo hadde i-beo ful &yogh;ore,</L>
<L>At hire bi-hinde heo hadde i-bled : seuen &yogh;er and more;</L>
<L>heo ne mi&yogh;hte for no-&thorn;ing : no leche-craft<NOTE PLACE="marg1">craft on the margin.</NOTE> a-fongue,</L>
<L N="144">Are ore louerd, heouene king : a-mong heom &thorn;are gan &yogh;ongue,</L>
<L>And &yogh;af hire is swete blessingue : and helde hire of hire sore</L>
<L>And bad hire beon hol and sound. : and so heo was euer-eft more.</L>
<L>&para; Heore beire bro&thorn;ur lazarus : was swy&thorn;e sikel a<NOTE PLACE="marg1">overlined.</NOTE> man.</L>
<L N="148">Iesus hereborewede at heore hous : &yogh;wane he bi heom cam,</L>
<L>And his Apostles alle : &yogh;wane huy &thorn;are-forth come,</L>
<L>heore In huy gonne cleopie : an<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;at wolde to hem by falle:</NOTE> ase heore owene it nome;</L>
<L>&para; Al swuch ase &thorn;are-inne was : huy eten and huy drounke&mdash;</L>
<L N="152">Men habbez ofte note of &thorn;ing : &thorn;at luytel it habbut swounke.</L>
<L>&THORN;o Iesus hadde &thorn;are i-beo : ase longue ase he wolde,</L>
<L N="154">he wente to an o&thorn;ur contreye : for men i-seon him scholde;</L>
<L>&para; Marie he &yogh;af is blessingue : and Martha and lazarus,</L>
<L>Muchele a<SUP>n</SUP>d luttle, elde and &yogh;ongue : &thorn;at woneden in heore hous.</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;at he was i-wend : Marie was<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> wax</NOTE> egleche:</L>
<L N="158">Crist hire hauede a-boute i-sent : to sarmoni and to preche:</L>
<L>&para; To sunfole men he was ful rad : to wissi and to teche,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. toche</NOTE></L>
<L N="160">And to sike men heo wa[s] ful glad : to beon heore soule leche;</L>
<L>Mani on to cristinedom : heo brou&yogh;hte, and out of sunne,<MILESTONE N="192" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Fram lecherie and hore-dom : &thorn;oru<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> to</NOTE> schrift, to Ioye and alle wunne.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; Aftur ore louerdes passione : in &thorn;e &thorn;ritten &thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L N="164">Giwes weren proute and grimme : olme and of lu&thorn;ere chere,
<PB REF="00000515.tif" N="467"></L>
<L>Seint steuene to de&thorn;e huy stenden : &thorn;at was ore louerd ful deore,</L>
<L N="166">And manie Men huy flemden : &thorn;at cristes limes were;</L>
<L>&para; Non Apostle ne moste liue : in Giwene londe,</L>
<L>Alle huy weren of londe i-driue : with wrath&thorn;e and ny&thorn;e and onde.</L>
<L>Seint Maximus was &thorn;o : with godes apostles<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;o was w. g. a. : s. M.</NOTE> bi-come;</L>
<L N="170">Sixti .ant. Ten deciples : to-gadere heom hadden i-nome;</L>
<L>&para; Marie &thorn;e Maudeleyne : and hire bro&thorn;ur lazarus,</L>
<L>And heore suster Martha : and &thorn;e bischop Maximus,</L>
<L>Mani mo of cristine Men : wel mo &thorn;ane i can nemne,</L>
<L N="174">weren i-hote fleme : and some to quelle and brenne.</L>
<L>&para; Huy weren in .A. schip i-pult : with-outen ster and ore,</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy scholden beon fur-faren<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> i-spilt</NOTE> : and ne libben no-more;</L>
<L N="177">&THORN;are nas no&thorn;ur ido with heom : no&thorn;ur watur ne bred,</L>
<L>For huy scholden of-hongrede beon : and sone &thorn;are-aftur-ward ded.</L>
<L>&para; Huy schypeden in &thorn;e salte se : ase Iesu crist it wolde,</L>
<L N="180">For-to &thorn;at tyme scholde beo : &thorn;at huy a-riui scholde.</L>
<L>To Marcile &thorn;e wynd heom drof : a gret name-couth cite;</L>
<L>Euer-ech of heom o&thorn;ur schrof : are huy comen out of &thorn;e se.</L>
<L>&para; Huy ne founden &thorn;are no freond<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> frend non</NOTE> : &thorn;at wolde heom hereboruwe,</L>
<L>Cristine man ne no giv<NOTE PLACE="marg1">No&thorn;er gywe ne cr. man</NOTE> : an eue no&thorn;ur a-moruwe,</L>
<L>Ne &yogh;yuen heom mete ne drinke no&thorn;ur<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> : ne lissen heore soruwe,</L>
<L N="186">Ne no man, for loue ne for swunch : &thorn;at huy mi&yogh;hten of bugge ne borewe:</L>
<L>&para; In one olde porche : huy stunten al &thorn;at ny&yogh;ht,</L>
<L N="188">with-oute li&yogh;ht of torche : with-oute fuyr and candle bri&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>&THORN;e porche was an old<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. hold</NOTE> hous : of olde weorke i-wrou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;udere in huy weren alle wel vouse : &thorn;at of &thorn;e se weren i-brou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>&para; For huy nusten elle-&yogh;ware : &thorn;at huy stunte mi&yogh;hte;</L>
<L N="192">Bote huy hadde gre[t] schame and teone : and giwes with heom to fi&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>&THORN;are huy duelden al &thorn;at ny&yogh;ht : forto it was day a-moruwe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sarasins heom boden fi&yogh;ht : to echen heore soruwe.</L>
<L>&para; Alle &thorn;e Men &thorn;at fram &thorn;e se : &thorn;uder weren i-come,</L>
<L N="196">huy nusten &yogh;wodere huy mi&yogh;hte fleo : for-&thorn;i huy weren i-nome.</L>
<L>huy weren i-hote ope lyf and lime<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> on here lyf</NOTE> : Iesu crist fur-sake,</L>
<L>And, with &thorn;retningue and with strif : to heore false godus take.
<PB REF="00000516.tif" N="468"></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Marie Maudeleine : heo sai&yogh;h &thorn;at folk a-rise,</L>
<L N="200">Riche and pouere, kny&yogh;ht and sweyn : to don &thorn;at sacrefise:</L>
<L>heo was a-nuyd and of-drad : &thorn;at hire bi-gan to grise;</L>
<L N="202">To speken of god heo was ful rad : and so dude on hire wise.</L>
<L>&para; Op heo stod with wordes bolde : with bri&yogh;ht neb and glade chere,</L>
<L>And seide, "herkniez to me, &yogh;unge and elde : &thorn;at wullez beon cristes:<NOTE PLACE="marg1">rhyme om.; <I>al.</I> &thorn;at in &thorn;is place ben here</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne bi-lieuez nou&yogh;ht opon Mahun : ne on teruagaunt, is fere,</L>
<L>For huy beoth bo&thorn;e deue and doumbe : and huy ne mouwen i-seo n i-here,<MILESTONE N="192b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; Ne huy ne mouwen eov helpe nou&yogh;ht : of none kunnes &thorn;ingue</L>
<L N="208">&THORN;ei men of heom &yogh;elpen ou&yogh;t : ne no guod to eu bringue:</L>
<L>For huy bez doumbe and deue : crokede and eke blinde,</L>
<L>heore mi&yogh;hte is fallen to grounde : bi-foren and bi-hinde.</L>
<L>&para; Ake &yogh;e schulle lieuen on iesu crist : oure hei&yogh;e heouene kyng,</L>
<L N="212">&THORN;at al &thorn;is worldes maister is : with-oute ani ending:</L>
<L>For he may don is wille<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> He ou wole dy&yogh;t (of om.)</NOTE> : of euereche cunnes &thorn;ing</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e wilniez with ri&yogh;hte : and with-outen suneguyng;</L>
<L>&para; He is with-oute &thorn;e bi-guynningue : and he is with-outen ende,</L>
<L N="216">with-oute fuyl&thorn;e and sunegyng : so corteys and so hende</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;ing &thorn;at man with skile him biddez : he wole him &yogh;yue and sende,</L>
<L>To Man &thorn;at goth and eke rit : &thorn;at wole to him wende;</L>
<L>&para; He is wuryte<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. wuyrte</NOTE> of alle &thorn;ing : he makede heouene and helle,</L>
<L N="220">Ne may no kayser ne no kyng : his vertues alle telle;</L>
<L>&THORN;e man &thorn;at him seruez wel : ne may him no feond cwelle,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. dwelle</NOTE></L>
<L N="222">Ake huy &thorn;at wullez a-&yogh;ein him fi&yogh;hte : to grounde he wole heom felle;</L>
<L>&para; He makede day and eke ny&yogh;ht : steorrene and sonne and Mone;</L>
<L>&THORN;e man &thorn;at trewe is and louez him ari&yogh;t : he wole graunti him is bone</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he biddez him with treou&thorn;e : he it grauntez him ful sone,</L>
<L N="226">he helpez bo&thorn;e king and kny&yogh;ht : &thorn;e pouere alle mididone."</L>
<L>&para; A riche prince of sarazins : &thorn;udere was i-come,</L>
<L>with him is wyf and his mayne : &thorn;at with him he hadde i-nome:</L>
<L>To Maries prechingue : he lustnede ful sone;</L>
<L N="230">For &thorn;at heo was so fair a &thorn;ing : to hire huy token guod gome.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e sarazins onvele : weren fulle of ny&thorn;e and hete,
<PB REF="00000517.tif" N="469"></L>
<L N="232">&thorn;o it was time of mele : huy wenden to heore mete;</L>
<L>&thorn;o huy comen hom vnsele : and &thorn;ar-to weren i-sete,</L>
<L>Cristes Men to delen guod : ful clene huy hadden for-&yogh;ete.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;are weren of cristine men : mo &thorn;ane sixti and tene;</L>
<L N="236">No man nadde reu&thorn;e of heom : and &thorn;at was &thorn;are i-sene:</L>
<L>huy weren wit-oute mete and drunch : in gret hongur and in teone,</L>
<L>Ne huy ne duden no weork ne swunch : ne no-&thorn;ing men nolde heom lene.</L>
<L>&para; Hit was in one ny&yogh;hte : aftur &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day,</L>
<L N="240">&thorn;at &thorn;is riche princes wif : in hire bedde lay:</L>
<L>&THORN;are cam Marie Maudeleyne : and bi-foren hire heo stod:</L>
<L>"Dame, me &thorn;inchez &thorn;ou art vnhende<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> vilayne</NOTE> : for &thorn;ou hast muche guod,</L>
<L>&para; Of &thorn;e ich habbe gret feorlich : and muche me &thorn;inchez wunder</L>
<L N="244">&THORN;at &thorn;ou last Iesu cristes folk : &thorn;us steorue for hungur!</L>
<L>Bote &yogh;if &thorn;ou o&thorn;ur &thorn;i louerd : lissi heore kare,</L>
<L>Wite &yogh;e mid-i-wisse : sorewe eou schal beon ful &yogh;are:</L>
<L>&para; Swuch a fierd schal op-on eov come : &thorn;at schal eov so<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> fur-fare</L>
<L>And a-quellen eou and eouwer folk : huy nellez eov no-&thorn;ing spare."</L>
<L>&THORN;is riche princes wif &thorn;is word : nolde hire louerd nou&yogh;ht telle&mdash;</L>
<L N="250">For-so&thorn;e, heo was puyrliche vnwys : in sawe and in spelle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e o&thorn;ur ny&yogh;ht &thorn;e Maudeleyne : eft-sone &yogh;eode hire to,<MILESTONE N="193" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And spak to hire wel stuyrneliche : and &thorn;e &thorn;ridde nyht al-so;</L>
<L>And &yogh;uyt he<SUP>o</SUP> nolde hire erinde : to hire louerd do.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">a v. om.; <I>al.</I> Alle suche messageres : crist hem worche wo.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Marie cam &thorn;e feor&thorn;e ny&yogh;ht : and bi-fore &thorn;e prince heo stod:</L>
<L>"Slepestou, tyraunt, &thorn;ou deueles kny&yogh;ht : of sathanasses blod?</L>
<L N="256">&thorn;i wif, &thorn;e Naddre, heo is a-mad : ich holde hire puyr wod:</L>
<L>heo nolde &thorn;e telle &thorn;at ich bad : for vuele ne for guod.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou hauest mete and drunch i-nov&yogh; : and luytel o&thorn;ur care,</L>
<L>And soffrest cristes men with wou&yogh;h : for hungur &thorn;us fur-fare!</L>
<L N="260">Bote &thorn;ou a-mendi heore stat sone : &thorn;e is sorewe al-&yogh;are,</L>
<L>&thorn;are schal so strong<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. stronk</NOTE> folk come &thorn;e a-&yogh;ein : &thorn;at wollez &thorn;e luytel spare,</L>
<L>&para; with sweord and spere huy schullen &thorn;e sle : and al &thorn;i folk fur-fare."</L>
<L>&thorn;e Maudeleyne &yogh;eode fram him : and liet him ligge &thorn;are.</L>
<L N="264">&thorn;e Quiene<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> prince</NOTE> a-wok and si&yogh;hte sore : and tolde hire louerd<NOTE PLACE="marg1">&thorn;e quene</NOTE> so;</L>
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;ou&yogh;hte him &thorn;at he i-warned was<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;o&yogh;te heo, so dyde me:</NOTE> : &thorn;reo ny&yogh;htes and mo.</L>
<L>&para; Heo tolde him &thorn;at hire was i-seid<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. i-said</NOTE> : and al-so i-hote to do:
<PB REF="00000518.tif" N="470"></L>
<L>Feden Iesu cristes men : and lissi heom of heore wo,</L>
<L N="268">O&thorn;ur heom scholde sorewe i-nov&yogh; : and kare comen heom to.</L>
<L>&thorn;o seide &thorn;e prince : "Dame, &yogh;wat schulle we do</L>
<L>Of &thorn;isse opene warningue : &thorn;at is i-come us to?<NOTE PLACE="marg1">vv. 269-70 are written in one line. v. 270 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE></L>
<L>Betere is &thorn;at we Cristes men : swy&thorn;e wel heom fiede and schruyde,</L>
<L N="272">&thorn;ene we tellen luyte of heom : In vilte o&thorn;ur in pruyde."</L>
<L>&para; huy token Iesu cristes Men : and ladden hom<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> hem</NOTE> to heore inne;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at heom was neod, huy founden heom : with loue and alle wunne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maudeleyne heom radde wel : to witien heom fram sunne,</L>
<L N="276">So &thorn;at heom ne &thorn;orte neuere drede : of sathanases kunne.</L>
<L>&para; Opon a day heo bi-gan<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Heo bigan vpon a day</NOTE> : godes word forto preche</L>
<L>And of godes lawe, with gret wit<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Wi&thorn; grete witte of godes lay</NOTE> : ase heo &thorn;ar mi&yogh;hte a-reche;</L>
<L>To leden heore lyf in guod fey : alle he<SUP>o</SUP> gan heom teche,</L>
<L>And for-to louie god and don a-wey : wrath&thorn;e and onde and wreche.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e prince saide &thorn;o to hire : with egleche wordes and bolde:</L>
<L>"Mi&yogh;ht &thorn;ou proui with treu&thorn;e : &thorn;at &thorn;ou prechest may beo wel i-holde?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maudeleyne saide,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">corr. to seide</NOTE> "&yogh;e : ich am redi eov to teche,</L>
<L N="284">Bi ore maistres conseile : and mid is holie speche&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is seinte<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. seinte?</NOTE> petre of rome&mdash; : hov &yogh;e schullen on take</L>
<L>&THORN;e blisse of heouene for-to afongue : and &thorn;e feondes lore for-sake."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o seide &thorn;e prince a-non : and is wyf al-so:</L>
<L N="288">"We beoz bo&thorn;e redie a-non : &thorn;ine wille forto do,</L>
<L>So ase &thorn;i louerd is : of so muchel mi&yogh;hte</L>
<L>&THORN;at he may, &yogh;wane he wole : at is wille alle &thorn;ingus di&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>&para; Bide &thorn;ine louerd, heoue king : &thorn;at is us alle a-boue,</L>
<L N="292">So ase he may don alle &thorn;ing : and al-so for is moder loue,</L>
<L>And for &thorn;ine bi-sechingue<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> bisokne</NOTE> : &thorn;at he &yogh;yue a child, &thorn;at beo a sone:</L>
<L N="294">And at &thorn;ane forewarde<NOTE PLACE="marg1">tokne</NOTE> : we wollez with eov wone,</L>
<L>Ore kinedom also forth with us : his owene we wollez bi-come,</L>
<L>And we wollez &yogh;elden a-&yogh;ein to is Men : &thorn;at we heom habbez bi-nome.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o seide Marie &thorn;e Maudeleine : "&thorn;at nelle ich nou&yogh;ht bi-leue,</L>
<L>A preiere to mi louerd to make : nele me no-&thorn;ing<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;inging</NOTE> greue.</L>
<L>"Ich bidde &thorn;e, swete Iesu crist : &thorn;at makedest sonne and mone,</L>
<L N="300">&THORN;at &thorn;ou &thorn;is prince siende a child : and &thorn;at it beo a sone."</L>
<L>heo bad with guode heorte and milde. : heo was i-heord ful sone:</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at ilke ny&yogh;ht huy geten a child : ase god heom &yogh;af grace to done.
<PB REF="00000519.tif" N="471"></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e prince wuste : &thorn;at is Quiene was with childe,</L>
<L N="304">A-non-ri&yogh;ht toward Iesu crist : he wax meoke and milde;</L>
<L>huy leten heore vuele dedes : &thorn;at weren so wikke and wilde,</L>
<L>And aftur godes dedes : huy wrou&yogh;hten a[nd] gonne buylde.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o swor &thorn;e prince and seide, "bi heued min : wiende ichulle to rome</L>
<L N="308">And bi-come a pilegrim : and don aftur &thorn;e holie dome,</L>
<L>And with seint petur ichulle speke : and don aftur is redes,</L>
<L>&yogh;if it is so ase Marie seiz : of Iesu cristes dedes;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;at ich him finde : at &thorn;e court of rome,</L>
<L N="312">Of him ichulle vnder-fongue : fulloutht and cristindome."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o seide &thorn;e lauedi : "ichulle wiende with &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And, &thorn;are &thorn;ou art i-cristned : ichulle al-so beo;</L>
<L>And &yogh;wane &thorn;ou comest hidere a-&yogh;ein : ich may come with &thorn;e."</L>
<L N="316">&THORN;o seide &thorn;e prince lei&yogh;inde : to is wif a-game:</L>
<L>"And beo nou&thorn;e ase &thorn;ou seist : mi leoue swete dame,</L>
<L>&para; Bote in schipe wexez ofte soruwe<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> : peril and teone and grame;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou art nou&thorn;e with childe : couth is &thorn;at guode fame,</L>
<L N="320">In &thorn;e .se. &thorn;ou mi&yogh;htest<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;ou m. in &thorn;e se wilde</NOTE> : ful sone hente schame&mdash;</L>
<L>&YOGH;uyt hadde ich leouere ich were i-huld : and euere to ligge lame.</L>
<L>Ake bi-lef &thorn;ou athom and reste &thorn;e wel<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> : and &yogh;em alle ore &thorn;ingues;</L>
<L>At mine a&yogh;ein-come god siende me : of &thorn;e guode ti&thorn;ingues!"</L>
<L N="324">&para; &THORN;o spak &thorn;e lauedi, &thorn;e Quiene : and feol a-doun to is fote:</L>
<L>"Leue louerd, &thorn;ou let beo &thorn;at : and graunte me &thorn;at ich mote!</L>
<L N="326">&THORN;is ilke sorewe wole me a-slen : bote &thorn;ou do me bote."</L>
<L>&para; &YOGH;eot seide &thorn;e leuedi : and weop wel swi&thorn;e sore,</L>
<L>Deolful and dreori heo ful a-doun : and seide ofte, "sire, &thorn;in ore!</L>
<L>hov mi&yogh;hte ich libbe and beon glad : bote we to-gadere wore<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. were</NOTE>?</L>
<L N="330">we loueden us so &yogh;oungue : and nou&thorn;e we beoth sumdel hore."</L>
<L>&para; So longue and &yogh;eorne &thorn;is lauedi bad : hire louerd &thorn;at was so hende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he hire<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. him</NOTE> grauntede, and was ful glad : with him for-to wiende.</L>
<L>For neodfole bi-sokne : of heom and heore men,</L>
<L N="334">&THORN;e holie blessingue with hire hond : Marie makede on heom,</L>
<L>For no wickede gost : bi &thorn;e weye ne scholde hem derie,</L>
<L>&THORN;e holie rode tokningue : fram seoruwe heom scholde werie.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e Marie heo mauden wardein : of heom and of heore schipe,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. lordschipe?</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000520.tif" N="472"></L>
<L N="338">&THORN;e swete holie Maudeleyne : in cristes wurthschipe,</L>
<L>For heo was &thorn;e kingue of heouene : leof and deore and queme,</L>
<L>And bi-token hire ech-del : to witien and to &yogh;eme.</L>
<L>&para; huy nomen with heom into heore schip : bred i-nov&yogh; and wyn,</L>
<L>Venesun of heort and hynd : and of wilde swyn,<MILESTONE N="194" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="343">huy nomen with heom in heore schip : al &thorn;at hem was leof,</L>
<L>Gies and hennes, crannes and swannes : and porc, motoun and beof;</L>
<L>For huy scholden passi : &thorn;e grickische se,</L>
<L N="346">And for &thorn;at huy nusten hou longue : huy scholden &thorn;are-inne be.</L>
<L>&para; huy drowen op seil and ore : and schipeden a-non-ri&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>Alle, &thorn;e lasse and &thorn;e more : Eorl, baroun and kny&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>huy nadden bote seue ny&yogh;ht : i-seiled in &thorn;at flod,</L>
<L N="350">&THORN;at huy neren sore of-dradde : &thorn;e se wax stuyrne and wod;</L>
<L>&THORN;e se bi-gan to flowen : and &thorn;e wawes forto a-rise:</L>
<L>Some bi-gonne to swounen : and heore heortene sore a-grise;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e se bi-gan to ebbi<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> route</NOTE> : and &thorn;e wynd ful stuyrne to blowe.</L>
<L>Ase &thorn;e Quiene on hire bedde lay<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> And &thorn;e q. for doute:</NOTE> : hire token ful strongue &thorn;rowes,</L>
<L>heo swounede ful i-lomeliche<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> ylome</NOTE> : and harde pinede &thorn;are-fore,</L>
<L N="356">So for-to &thorn;at hire &yogh;oungue sone : were of hure i-bore.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at child i-bore was : &thorn;e Moder bi-gan to deye,</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk gradde "allas allas" : and weopen with heore eye.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e leuedi was ded : aftur &thorn;at &thorn;et child was i-bore,</L>
<L N="360">huy ne mi&yogh;hten it bi-leue : to<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;er was wi&thorn; hem non o&thorn;er red : but</NOTE> make deol &thorn;are-fore.</L>
<L>&THORN;at child wolde souke : and it nuste &yogh;wam,</L>
<L>&THORN;are nas no milk a-boute : ne no mielch wumman.</L>
<L>&para; "Allas," quath &thorn;e prince : "&thorn;at ich euere was i-bore!</L>
<L>Wo is me for &thorn;is &yogh;unge child : and for mi Quien &thorn;at ich habbe i-lore,</L>
<L>And nou&thorn;e it mot nede deye : for souke ne hath i[t] non,</L>
<L N="366">Ne i-not in none halue<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Wote i<SUP>c</SUP> neuer sikerly</NOTE> : &yogh;wat me is best to don."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e schipmen hiete<SUP>n</SUP> with stuyrne mod : &thorn;at men ne schulden nou&yogh;ht spare</L>
<L>&THORN;e dede Quien to casten in &thorn;at flod : o&thorn;ur elles huy mosten fur-fare:</L>
<L>"&THORN;e &yogh;wyle &thorn;at bodi is here with us : &thorn;e stormes beoth so kete,</L>
<L N="370">To quellen us huy &thorn;enchez : and &thorn;at huy nellez lete."</L>
<L>&para; huy nomen up &thorn;ad<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. &thorn;at</NOTE> dede bodi : in-to &thorn;e se for-to caste.</L>
<L>"Abidez &yogh;uyte and herkniez me!" : &thorn;e prince gradde faste;
<PB REF="00000521.tif" N="473"></L>
<L>"&YOGH;if &yogh;e nellez for mi loue it lete<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. it lete</NOTE> : ne for loue of mi wif,</L>
<L N="374">spariez for mi luytel sone : so &thorn;at he mouwe habbe is lyf!</L>
<L>For &yogh;if is moder mouwe &yogh;uyt : of hire suoweningue awake,</L>
<L>&THORN;anne may mi luytel sone : to hire tete take."</L>
<L>&para; huy lokeden heom bi-side : and sei&yogh;en an hei&yogh;h hurst</L>
<L N="378">Swi&thorn;e feor in &thorn;e se<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> In &thorn;e se wyde</NOTE> : and &thorn;e prince it i-sai&yogh; furst;</L>
<L>him &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;at wel more wisdom : to &thorn;e bodie it were</L>
<L>to burien it opon &thorn;et hei&yogh;e hurst : &thorn;ane fisches it eten &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o huy comen &thorn;udere<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> were &thorn;. ycome</NOTE> : huy ne mi&yogh;hten make no put:</L>
<L N="382">&THORN;e hurst was al of harde stone : ech faste in o&thorn;ur i-knut;</L>
<L>huy nomen &thorn;e Quiene and hire child : and wounden in a mantel,</L>
<L>And leide opon &thorn;e hei&yogh;e hurste : in a grene cantel;</L>
<L>huy leiden &thorn;at childes mouth : to &thorn;e moder tete&mdash;</L>
<L N="386">&THORN;o &thorn;e prince &thorn;at i-sai&yogh;h : with wepingue is neb he gan wete.</L>
<L>with gret deol &thorn;e Quiene and hire Child : &thorn;are huy gonne lete<MILESTONE N="194b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="388">Opon &thorn;e<SUP>t</SUP> hurst &thorn;at was so hei&yogh;h : and hard and wilde and kete.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e prince wep and wende forth : with his schip in &thorn;e se;</L>
<L>"Marie Maudeleyne," quath &thorn;e prince, "alas : &thorn;at euere kneu ich &thorn;e!</L>
<L>To don &thorn;is pelrimage : &yogh;wy raddest &thorn;ou me?</L>
<L N="392">&THORN;ov bede &thorn;i god a bone : &thorn;at mi wif with childe scholde be:</L>
<L>And nou&thorn;e is ded &thorn;us sone : bo&thorn;e hire child and heo!</L>
<L>&para; Al mi lond and al mi &thorn;ing : ich habbe i-take &thorn;e</L>
<L>To witen and to wardi : &yogh;wi schal it &thorn;anne &thorn;us be?</L>
<L N="396">Mi wif and mi &yogh;ungue child : marie, ich bi-take</L>
<L>To Ihesu crist, &thorn;i owene louerd : &thorn;at alle &thorn;ing of nou&yogh;ht gan make,</L>
<L N="398">&THORN;at, &yogh;if he is so corteys and mi&yogh;htful : ase &thorn;ou seidest to me,</L>
<L>he saue mi wif and mi child : fur-fare &thorn;at ich ne be."</L>
<L>&para; To his schyp he wende : and so forz in &thorn;e se.</L>
<L>God hem to Rome sende : for &thorn;udere wolden he.</L>
<L N="402">Seinte petur wuste wel : &thorn;at &thorn;e prince cam:</L>
<L>With milde mod and fair compaygnie : a-&yogh;eines him he nam.</L>
<L>Petur Axede him fram &yogh;wanne he cam : and &yogh;wodere he wiende wolde.</L>
<L>"To Rome," he seide, "&thorn;en wey ich take<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> nam</NOTE> : and speke with &thorn;e i<SUP>s</SUP>cholde;"</L>
<L N="406">he tolde of marie Maudeleyne : hou he to hire cam,
<PB REF="00000522.tif" N="474"></L>
<L>And hou he cristus sixti men : and tene to him nam,</L>
<L>he tolde him of is child : he tolde him of is wif,</L>
<L>hov he with milde heorte : for heom &thorn;olede strif.</L>
<L N="410">&para; Seinte petur creoysede him : opon is ri&yogh;ht scholder,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at Marie hauede i-seid : he hauede game and wonder,</L>
<L>And seide, "prince, wel-come &thorn;ou be : and &thorn;ine kni&yogh;htes alle!</L>
<L>pays and grace with &thorn;e beo : and Ioye &thorn;e mote on falle</L>
<L N="414">In bour and in halle : in field and in toun al-so,</L>
<L>In castel no&thorn;ur in boure : ne wor&thorn;e &thorn;e neuere wo,</L>
<L>In watur and in londe : and in alle stude</L>
<L>God &thorn;e fram harme schilde&mdash; : and &thorn;at ich habbe i-bede.</L>
<L N="418">&para; &THORN;ey [&thorn;i] wif slepe nou&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> nou slepe</NOTE> : and &thorn;i sone him reste,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne weope nou&yogh;t for hem<NOTE PLACE="marg1">n. f. h. om.</NOTE> : ne make deol ne cheste :</L>
<L>Mi louerd is swi&thorn;e mi&yogh;thful : he wole don is wille,</L>
<L>And he is also quoynte and sley : bo&thorn;e loude and stille,</L>
<L N="422">he can &yogh;yuen and bi-nimen : borewi and eke &yogh;ielde</L>
<L>For soruwe blisse, &yogh;wane his wille is : in toune, in watere, in fielde;</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane he is wroth, he doth wreche : ake &thorn;at fallez ful sielde;</L>
<L>Ake of[te] gret fuyr and eke stuyrne : wext of a luytel spielde."</L>
<L N="426">&para; Petur ladde &thorn;ene riche man : a&yogh;ein<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> to Ierusalem,</L>
<L>And fro &thorn;annes &thorn;ene wey he nam : with him to bedlehem,</L>
<L>Fram &thorn;annes to &thorn;e flym Iordan : an long bi &thorn;e strem&mdash;</L>
<L>I segge it ase ich ov telle can : In boke and nou&yogh;ht in drem.</L>
<L N="430">he schewede him caluarie : &thorn;are god was don on rode,</L>
<L>his fiet and is hondene : al-hou huy ronnen on blode,</L>
<L>he tolde him of &thorn;e &thorn;ornes : &thorn;at on his heued stode,<MILESTONE N="195" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And of &thorn;e nailes &thorn;at in is fiet : and in his hondene wode,</L>
<L N="434">And &yogh;et he tolde him of &thorn;e spere : &thorn;at to &thorn;e heorte him stong,</L>
<L>And hou he an hei&yogh;h opon &thorn;e rode : deide with muche wrong,</L>
<L>hou he into helle cam : with Sathanas to fi&yogh;hte,</L>
<L>And is folk &thorn;at &thorn;are-inne was : hou he it gan out di&yogh;hte,</L>
<L N="438">hou he a-ros, and to heoue steu&yogh; : to is fader sete</L>
<L>And sat him &thorn;are-inne, for he was gleu&yogh; : and was him swy&thorn;e i-mete.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o &thorn;e prince hadde i-heord : seint peteres lore,</L>
<L>he carede laste he were bi-cherd : for he hadde i-beo &thorn;are<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> was fol</NOTE> so &yogh;ore;</L>
<L N="442">he hadde i-leorned swi&thorn;e wel : al clanliche his bi-leue,
<PB REF="00000523.tif" N="475"></L>
<L>his oures and is sauter ech-del : &thorn;o seide he, "god it &yogh;eue</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich were sone : in mine owene contreye</L>
<L>And al mi folk, with flechs and blod : ri&yogh;ht ase ich wolde, sei&yogh;e!"</L>
<L N="446">Seint petur he bad par charite : cristni him a-non</L>
<L>And al is o&thorn;ur mayne : and laten heom wende hom</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne habben guod day : "and &yogh;if us &thorn;ine blessingue!</L>
<L>we wollez so bliue so we mouwen : don us to schipijngue."</L>
<L N="450">&para; "&THORN;ou schalt with-outen cristindom : wienden into &thorn;ine londe;</L>
<L>Ne drede &thorn;e nou&yogh;th, for &thorn;ou mi&yogh;ht it don : with-oute schame and schonde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maudeleyne schal beon with &thorn;e : and to &thorn;e heo schal fongue,</L>
<L>Lazarus and Martha, al &thorn;re : bi &thorn;e huy schullen stonde;</L>
<L N="454">&THORN;are &thorn;ou schalt i-cristned beo : &thorn;oru Iesu cristes sonde,</L>
<L>And muche folk al-so of &thorn;ine contreye : ne &thorn;inche &thorn;e nou&yogh;t to longue!</L>
<L>&para; An holi man schal cristni eov : &thorn;e bischop Maximus,</L>
<L>&THORN;at can is mester don swi&thorn;e wel : in Ihesu cristus hous,</L>
<L N="458">he wole beo &yogh;ep and eke rad : sley and eke vous,</L>
<L>To cristni manie he wole beo glad : to is louerd Iesous&mdash;</L>
<L>he were a fol and un-wis : &thorn;at ne were of glad and bli&thorn;e."</L>
<L>&THORN;e prince tok leue of seint petur : and &thorn;onkede him fale si&thorn;e.</L>
<L N="462">&THORN;e prince saide, "holie fader : haue nov wel guod day!</L>
<L>Ichulle wienden hamward : so bliue so ich may."</L>
<L>he dude him into &thorn;e salte flod. : his schip bi-gan to go</L>
<L>So bliue, for &thorn;e wind was guod : a[s] swaluwe swift<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> o&thorn;ur flo;</L>
<L N="466">with-inne &thorn;e seuenni&yogh;htte : &thorn;udere he was i-come</L>
<L>&THORN;are he,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">overlined.</NOTE> a&yogh;ein is wille, bi lefde : is wif and is sone.</L>
<L>&para; huy i-sei&yogh;en bi &thorn;e stronde : a luytel child gon pleye</L>
<L>with publes on is honde : bi-fore hem in &thorn;e weye.</L>
<L N="470">&THORN;e prince stap out of &thorn;e schipe : of hem alle he was &thorn;e furste,</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e stronde he &yogh;af a lupe : he hi&yogh;ede him to &thorn;e hurste.</L>
<L>&THORN;at child was swi&thorn;e sore of-drad : &thorn;o &thorn;e prince cam,</L>
<L>To his moder he was wel rad : and a-boute &thorn;e necke hire nam.</L>
<L N="474">&para; &THORN;e leuedi lai wel stille and slep : opon a grene cantel,</L>
<L>&THORN;at child for fere orn to hire and crep : under hire mantel.</L>
<L>&THORN;o saide &thorn;at child, "hiderward : a &thorn;ing, me &thorn;ou&yogh;hte, i sai&yogh; come,</L>
<L>Of him ich am ful sore a-drad : laste we beon i-nome."<MILESTONE N="195b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000524.tif" N="476"></L>
<L N="478">"Beo stille, mi sone, mi leoue child : he is mi worldes fiere;</L>
<L>For gladnesse wepe he wole : &thorn;at [he] us findez here."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e prince cam and fond hire &thorn;er : ligginde on &thorn;e hurste,</L>
<L>&THORN;are ase he bi-lefde hire er : and &thorn;at chil sek hire breste.</L>
<L N="482">For Ioye he weep and sat on is knen : and heold up his honde :</L>
<L>"&THORN;at ich euere moste &thorn;is i-seo : ich &thorn;onki ore louerdes sonde.</L>
<L>A, swete Marie Maudeleine : &thorn;at me wolde nou ri&yogh;ht &thorn;inche murie</L>
<L N="485">Mi&yogh;hte &thorn;is wumman quikie a-&yogh;ein : and liuen and hire sturie!"</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o he hadde &thorn;at word i-seid : his wif bi-gan to wake,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> quake</NOTE></L>
<L>Of a swume heo schok and braid : and sone bi-gan a-wake;</L>
<L>And [seide], "&thorn;e hende Marie Maudeleyne : heo hath i-&yogh;iue me space,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. grace</NOTE></L>
<L>Fram de&thorn;e to liue heo hauez me i-brou&yogh;t : &thorn;oru hire louerdes grace;</L>
<L N="490">heo hauez i-fed me and mi sone : and i-don us alle guode&mdash;</L>
<L>To seggen it &thorn;e &yogh;wi scholde ich schone? : &thorn;at &yogh;elde hire &thorn;e rode!</L>
<L N="492">heo hauez i-beon min hou[s]wif : mi mayde and mi norice,</L>
<L>And bote ich &thorn;e [seide] hou heo heold mi lif : for-so&thorn;e ich were nice.</L>
<L>&para; Al &thorn;at seint petur hath<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> peter : ha&thorn;</NOTE> : seth&thorn;e i-schewed &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;e swete marie Maudeleyne<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> M. M. swete</NOTE> : it hauez i-schewed me :</L>
<L N="496">heo me hauez on hire hond i-lad : ouer &thorn;e salte strem,</L>
<L>And set&thorn;e for&thorn;ere-more : to Ierusalem,</L>
<L>And set&thorn;e heo me ladde : bedlehem for-to seo,</L>
<L>&THORN;udere ase seint petur : bi-fore ladde &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="500">And seth&thorn;e to &thorn;e flum Iordan : heo ladde me ful ra&thorn;e,</L>
<L>with-oute harme and si&yogh;ht of man : and with-oute schame and sca&thorn;e,</L>
<L>And ouer-al heo me ladde : mi louerd, &thorn;are &thorn;ou were;</L>
<L>And, for &thorn;ou scholdest Ioyful beo : nou&thorn;e ri&yogh;ht heo brou&yogh;hte me here."</L>
<L N="504">&para; Quath &thorn;e prince, "ich &thorn;onki god al-mi&yogh;hti : &thorn;at ich eov habbe a|liue.</L>
<L>A-risez bo&thorn;e, &yogh;if &yogh;e mouwen : and go we to schipe ful bliue!"</L>
<L>huy duden heom to &thorn;e watere : and schipeden alle a-non,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wynd was blowinde swi&thorn;e wel : and heore schip bi-gan to gon;</L>
<L N="508">huy gonne to seili swi&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Hij hyed hem to seyle</NOTE> : in &thorn;at salte fom,</L>
<L>And hi&yogh;eden heom ful bliue : &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Hem &thorn;o&yogh;t longe &amp; eyle : or</NOTE> huy weren at hom.</L>
<L>With-inne a quartron of &thorn;e &yogh;ere : huy comen to Marcilie.</L>
<L>Mani Men of feor and ner : of heom gonne speke and spilie,
<PB REF="00000525.tif" N="477"></L>
<L>Manie hem hadden to-gadere i-nome : Eorl, baron, kny&yogh;ht, and swein,</L>
<L>Are huy weren to londe i-comen : for-to wenden heom a-&yogh;ein,</L>
<L N="514">Sarazins, and &thorn;e Giwes some : and &thorn;e Marie Maudeleyn;</L>
<L>&para; Martha cam and lazarus : of heom huy weren ful glad,</L>
<L N="516">And &thorn;e holie Bischop Maximus : to heom he was ful rad,</L>
<L>And manie of cristine Men&mdash; : huy neren no&thorn;ing of-drad</L>
<L>To comen and gon a-&yogh;einest him : and don &thorn;at he heom bad.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e prince and is wyf : weren i-come to londe,</L>
<L N="520">&THORN;e Maudeleyne with-oute strif : i-reuested &thorn;are huy founde;</L>
<L>And &thorn;o huy comen fram schipes bord : marie huy founden stonde</L>
<L>For-to prechen godes word : to heom &thorn;at were on londe.<MILESTONE N="196" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e prince tok<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. tok tok</NOTE> is wif and is sone : with heorte guod and swete,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Maudeleyne huy comen : and fellen doun to hire fete,</L>
<L>And tolden hire al heore lijf : &thorn;at heom bi-feol in &thorn;at weye;</L>
<L N="526">Pays and loue, harm and strif : al huy gonne hire sei&yogh;e.</L>
<L>huy lieten &thorn;ane Bischop Maximus : cristni heom a-non,</L>
<L N="528">Marie and Martha and lazarus : huy brou&yogh;hten heom &thorn;aron.</L>
<L>&THORN;e children and &thorn;e wummen alle : &thorn;at weren in &thorn;e londe,</L>
<L>Alle huy nomen cristindom : and &thorn;at was &thorn;oru godes sonde.</L>
<L>&para; Ich wot, huy nomen heore false godes : and casten heom &thorn;are doune</L>
<L N="532">And brenden al-to poudre : feor fram euerech toune;</L>
<L>huy duden a-rere churches : ouer al &thorn;e contreies,</L>
<L>And priories wurche : and manie guode Abbeies,</L>
<L>And preostes huy gonne makien<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Hij dude hede prestes</NOTE> : ouer-al in &thorn;e londe,</L>
<L N="536">Sudecknes and o&thorn;ur clerkus : to serui heom to honde.</L>
<L>huy mauden lazarus bischop : &thorn;e Maudeleynes bro&thorn;er;</L>
<L>&THORN;e holie bischop Maximus : maude al-so mani ano&thorn;ur.&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o al &thorn;at lond cristine was : and al &thorn;at folc &thorn;are-inne,</L>
<L N="540">Marie bi-&thorn;ou&yogh;hte a wonder cas : and stal a-wey fram hire kunne,</L>
<L>In-to wildernesse he wende : al for-to wonien &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Swuch grace god hire sende : heo was &thorn;are &thorn;ritti &yogh;eres.</L>
<L>&THORN;are nas no watur a-boute : ne &thorn;are ne wax no treo</L>
<L N="544">&THORN;at ani best mi&yogh;hte onder at-route : &thorn;e betere an ayse to beo.</L>
<L>For-so&thorn;e ichulle &yogh;eov telle : of a ferliche wonder :</L>
<L>Aungles comen euer-eche day : ri&yogh;ht a-bouten onde<SUP>r</SUP>n,
<PB REF="00000526.tif" N="478"></L>
<L>And nomen swi&thorn;e softeliche<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> softe</NOTE> : &thorn;e Marie Maudelein</L>
<L N="548">And beren hire op in-to &thorn;e lofte : and brou&yogh;hten hire eft a-&yogh;ein.</L>
<L>&para; Men nusten hou heo leouede : for noman ne sai&yogh;h hire ete;</L>
<L>Ake some huy onder-stoden : &thorn;at heo liuede bi Aungelene mete.</L>
<L>A preost &thorn;are was in marcilie : &thorn;at wilned swi&thorn;e muche</L>
<L N="552">For-to leden elinge lif : &thorn;e betere fram sunne him wite;</L>
<L>he maude him a wonijngue : in &thorn;at wildernesse</L>
<L>&THORN;are Marie, &thorn;e swete Maudeleine<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;ing</NOTE> : wonede in clennesse;</L>
<L>he ne bulde nou&yogh;ht fram Marie<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> hire stede</NOTE> : bote a wel luyte mile&mdash;</L>
<L N="556">For-to quemen god he it dude : and he &yogh;eld wel is &yogh;wile.</L>
<L>he hadde wunder for &thorn;at he sai&yogh;h : &thorn;at &thorn;e Aungles comen ofte</L>
<L>A-boute onderne eche daye : ase he stod in is crofte,</L>
<L>And hou huy beren &thorn;e Maudeleyne : an hei op on lofte,</L>
<L N="560">And al-so hou huy brou&yogh;hten hire a-&yogh;ein : and setten hire a-doun wel softe.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e preost a-ros op-on a day : and wende neor &thorn;e stude,</L>
<L>he wolde i-wite &yogh;wat he i-sai&yogh;h : and &thorn;are-fore he it dude;</L>
<L>To &thorn;ulke stude he cam so nei&yogh;h : al bote a stones caste :</L>
<L N="564">&THORN;o bi-gonne hise &thorn;eon to schrinke : and to croki swi&thorn;e faste;</L>
<L>A-drad he was, and turnde a-&yogh;ein : and so he moste nede&mdash;</L>
<L>Ne knev he nou&yogh;t &thorn;e Maudeleyne : ne hire guode dedes.</L>
<L>Eft-sone he &yogh;eode him &thorn;ude-ward : is fiet bi-gonne folde,</L>
<L N="568">his heorte and his Inneward : him gonnen al to colde.</L>
<L>he &thorn;ou&yogh;hte it was sum derne &thorn;ing : o&thorn;ur som holi priuete,</L>
<L>I-comen fram &thorn;e heuene king : &thorn;at he ne scholde it nou&yogh;ht i-seo :</L>
<L>&para; he sat a-doun opon is kneon : and bad ore louerd &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="572">&THORN;at he moste i-wite and seon : &yogh;wat &thorn;at feorlich were;</L>
<L>he gradde on eornest and on game : "&thorn;ou best in &thorn;ine celle,<MILESTONE N="196b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ich halsni &thorn;e a-godes name : of &thorn;i stat &thorn;at &thorn;ou me telle!"</L>
<L>heo bi-gan to tellen : wordes him a-&yogh;ein :</L>
<L N="576">"I segge it &thorn;e for-so&thorn;e : ich am Marie Maudeleyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e kingue of heoue : of mine sunnes ich me schrof,</L>
<L>And foule deuelene seouene : out of me he drof.</L>
<L>Ich habbe i-woned nou&thorn;e here : fulle &thorn;ritti &yogh;er,</L>
<L N="580">Ake i-ne sai&yogh;h neuere no man &thorn;us nei&yogh;h : bote &thorn;e nou&thorn;e her.</L>
<L>&para; Of no-&thorn;ing &thorn;at ani man : of &thorn;e eor&thorn;e euere bi-swonk,
<PB REF="00000527.tif" N="479"></L>
<L>I-ne .et., seth&thorn;e ich hidere cam : no mete, ne no drunch ne<NOTE PLACE="marg1">overlined.</NOTE> dronk;</L>
<L>Godes Aungles euer-ech day : habbe me here i-nome</L>
<L N="584">An ibore me alne wey : &yogh;wane ischolde come,</L>
<L>An hei&yogh;h to heouene lofte : euere &yogh;wane i<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. it</NOTE> ete scholde,</L>
<L>And hidere a&yogh;ein wel softe : &yogh;wane ich mi-sulf wolde.</L>
<L>Ich halsni &thorn;e a-godes name : &thorn;at &thorn;ou wende to Marcilie,</L>
<L N="588">And with mine freond with-oute blame : loke wel &thorn;at &thorn;ou spilie :</L>
<L>&THORN;ou gret wel Martha, mi soster, ofte : and mi bro&thorn;er lazarus,</L>
<L>And al-so gret ofte swi&thorn;e wel : &thorn;ene bischop Maximus,</L>
<L>And seie hem wel ichulle comen : a-sonenday at eue,</L>
<L N="592">with heom for-to wonie : and euere with heom bi-leue&mdash;</L>
<L>For ischal to paradis : newene fram heom fare,</L>
<L>Ake mi bodi, for-so&thorn;e i-wis : bi-leue schal with heom &thorn;are;</L>
<L>Sei&yogh;e heom &thorn;at huy kepen me : aftur &thorn;e mid-ni&yogh;hte,</L>
<L N="596">For &thorn;are ich hopie for-to beo : &thorn;oru godes swete mi&yogh;hte."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is holie preost him wende forth : and dude hire herinde anon</L>
<L>To &thorn;e bischop maximus : ase heo bad him don.</L>
<L>&THORN;e holie bischop Maximus : was glad of &thorn;at sonde,</L>
<L N="600">And for &thorn;at ti&thorn;ingue he &thorn;onkede god<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> t. ioyus : he helde</NOTE> : and to him heold up is honde;</L>
<L>hire soster and hire bro&thorn;er : weren &thorn;ar-of wel fayn :</L>
<L>"Nou comez oure Maister sone : &thorn;e marie Maudeleyn!"</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is ilke ty&thorn;ingues : huy weren swi&thorn;e glad</L>
<L N="604">&THORN;at huy hadden i-heord&mdash; : ake some weren of-drad</L>
<L>&THORN;at huy bi-trayde weren. : ake &thorn;e bischop Maximus</L>
<L>wuste wel &thorn;at hit was sothz&mdash; : to seon hire he was Ioyous,</L>
<L>And to witen hire stat euer-echdel : he was wel coraIous.</L>
<L N="608">&para; For-to seon &thorn;ane Messager : &thorn;ene sonen-ny&yogh;ht he wakede,</L>
<L>And al ny&yogh;ht was in heore queor : and his oresones he makede,</L>
<L>bi-fore &thorn;e hei&yogh;e Auter ore louerd he bad : &thorn;at he moste i-seo</L>
<L>&THORN;e Maudeleynes face : &thorn;at he &thorn;e gladdore mi&yogh;hte beo.<MILESTONE N="197" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="612">Sone aftur &thorn;e Midni&yogh;ht : are ani koc him crev,</L>
<L>&THORN;are cam a wonder muche li&yogh;ht : ake no wynd &thorn;are ne blev,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Aungles comen fram heouene : and brou&yogh;hten &thorn;e Marie,</L>
<L>huy seiden &thorn;e salmus seouene : and &thorn;e letanie;</L>
<L N="616">Fram &thorn;e eor&thorn;e huy gonne hire holden<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> helden here</NOTE> : swi&thorn;e longue stounde,
<PB REF="00000528.tif" N="480"></L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;wyle heo makede hire preyere : and seth&thorn;e lieten hire to grounde.</L>
<L>&THORN;o cam wit hire swuch a smul : among heom euerech-on,</L>
<L N="619">In churche, in halle and in bour : &thorn;at swuch ne smulden huy neuerer non.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e bischop, for &thorn;e muchele lij&yogh;ht : and for &thorn;at swote smullingue,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> smak</NOTE></L>
<L>Sumdel &thorn;are-fore he was a-ferd : and a luyte him drov&yogh; bi-hinde.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">abak</NOTE></L>
<L>Marie turnede, of wordes freo : and of vilenie quijt and sker,</L>
<L>And seide, "fader, &yogh;wy wolt&thorn;ou &thorn;i dou&yogh;ter fleo? : a-bid and cum me ner!"</L>
<L N="624">he sai&yogh;h hire neb, and turnde a-&yogh;ein : so bri&yogh;ht so sonne-bem,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at swete Maudeleine : so lij&yogh;ht so ani leom.</L>
<L>&para; heo saide, "fader Maximus : par seinte charite,</L>
<L>Schrift and hosel ich &yogh;uyrne<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> To ben ihoseled i<SUP>c</SUP> am vous</NOTE> : sone &thorn;ou graunte it me!"</L>
<L N="628">huy cleopeden alle &thorn;e preostes : and &thorn;e clerkus euerech-on</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e o&thorn;ur ministres : and duden hire wille a-non.</L>
<L N="630">heo it a-ueng wepinde : with guod deuotion,</L>
<L>And wel sore sichinde : heo lay hire-sulf a-doun,</L>
<L>&para; And seide, "Ihesu, &thorn;at deidest opon &thorn;e trco : al mi stat &thorn;ou wost;</L>
<L>Into &thorn;ine hondene ich bi-take &thorn;e : mi lijf and mi gost."</L>
<L N="634">Anon-ri&yogh;ht heo &yogh;af up hire lijf : and hire gost, i-wis.</L>
<L>heo was i-lad with-outen strif : anon-ri&yogh;ht to paradys.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischope &thorn;ou&yogh;hte murie : and &thorn;e clerkes echon,</L>
<L>And a-non-ri&yogh;ht gonne hire burien : in a Marbre-ston.</L>
<L N="638">&para; Seue ni&yogh;ht &thorn;are-aftur-ward : &thorn;at day &thorn;at heo i-bured was,</L>
<L>Ni&yogh;ht and day &thorn;at smul was &thorn;are&mdash; : it was a wonder cas.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bischop &thorn;ou&yogh;hte murie : and bad, &yogh;wane he ded were,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Men him scholden burien : bi-siden hire ri&yogh;ht &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="642">Of &thorn;e Maudeleine : &thorn;is is &thorn;e ri&yogh;hte endingue.</L>
<L>God us schilde fram peyne &middot; and to heouene us bringue! AmeN</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="67" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>67 [Ypolyt]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SEint ypolyt &thorn;e Martyr : knyht was of gret honour,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wuste seint laurence in prisone : &thorn;oru&yogh; heste of &thorn;e Aumperour,</L>
<L>And &thorn;oru&yogh;h him turnde to cristindom : and his maine al-so,</L>
<L N="4">And burede him ful stilleliche : &thorn;o he was to de&thorn;e i-do.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o he hadde seint laurence i-bured : and hit was vnder-&yogh;ite,
<PB REF="00000529.tif" N="481"></L>
<L>Me<SUP>n</SUP> ortreuweden &thorn;at he cristine were : ase huy mi&yogh;hten wel &thorn;o i-wite.</L>
<L>&THORN;ene &thorn;ridde day aftur : &thorn;at seint laurence i-bured was,</L>
<L N="8">Ypolyt wende to is owene hous : ase it were bi cas;</L>
<L>Al his mayne he grette fayre : and &yogh;af heom part al-so</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e milsfole dede &thorn;at he hadde : on seint laurence i-do.</L>
<L>&para; his meyne, &thorn;at al cristine was : fair semblaunt him made i-nou&yogh;h,</L>
<L N="12">And sone &thorn;o it time was : toward &thorn;e mete him drov&yogh;.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;at bord was i-leid : and he was &thorn;arto i-sete,</L>
<L>And his mete bi-fore him i-brou&yogh;ht : er he hadde ou&yogh;t i-&yogh;ete,<MILESTONE N="197b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e kny&yogh;htes comen in ate &yogh;ate : lu&thorn;ere men i-nowe,</L>
<L N="16">bi-fore decius &thorn;e Aumperour : wel filliche him drowe.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o decius i-sai&yogh;h him furst : a-busemare he lou&yogh;,</L>
<L>And seide : "ypolyt, hou gez &thorn;is? : turnste to &thorn;e wou&yogh;h?</L>
<L>honoure ore godes, ich [&thorn;e] rede : and do ore heste sone,</L>
<L N="20">And do, ase &thorn;ou art hiende kni&yogh;ht : ase &thorn;ou au&yogh;test for-to done!"</L>
<L>&para; "Sire, ich habbe," quath ypolyt : "in folie longue i-beo</L>
<L>And in vnconnesse mi lijf i-leoued : ase man &thorn;at ne cou&thorn;e ise;</L>
<L>Ake nou&thorn;e ich am to god i-turnd&mdash; : to late i dude so!</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;ou do bi me al &thorn;at &thorn;ou canst : for non o&thorn;ur i-nelle do."</L>
<L>&para; "No? nelt&thorn;ou?" quat &thorn;is Aumperur : "&thorn;ou schalt i-leue me,</L>
<L>Ase we serueden laurence er : we schullen nou serui &thorn;e!"</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e, god it<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> &yogh;eue," quath &thorn;is holie man : "&thorn;at it were bi me nou&thorn;e</L>
<L>Ase it mid him is &thorn;at &thorn;ou nemmest : ri&yogh;ht nou&thorn;e with lu&thorn;ere mou&thorn;e!"</L>
<L>&para; "Go<SUP>z</SUP> forth," quath &thorn;is Aumperour : "mine tormentores, a-non,</L>
<L N="30">And streputh naked &thorn;is lu&thorn;ere &thorn;ef : ri&yogh;ht to flechs and bon!"</L>
<L>&THORN;is tormentores wel &yogh;are were : to don &thorn;at sorie dede.</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;e holie man, &thorn;o he was naked : to &thorn;e Aumperour he seide;</L>
<L>&THORN;is holie man seide,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">&thorn;is&mdash;seide <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> "wenstou, wrechche, to make me naked? : nay &thorn;ou, i-wis,</L>
<L>Ake &thorn;ou bi-guinnest ra&thorn;ur to clo&thorn;ie me : with Ioye of heouene blis."</L>
<L>&para; "Nimez a-non," quath &thorn;e Aumperour : "and tormentiez him wel faste!"</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;e tormentores al redie weren : and heor clo&thorn;es of huy caste,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; scourges and with staues al-so : huy beoten him ase huy weren wode,</L>
<L>And al defouleden is holie bodi : &thorn;at is limes ronnen a-blode;
<PB REF="00000530.tif" N="482"></L>
<L>So longue, &thorn;at huy [werie] weren : and &thorn;are-fore stille huy stode.</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;e Aumperour bi-heold heom faste : with ful sorie mode.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is holie man, &thorn;o him smert sore : lude to grede he gan :</L>
<L N="42">"Ich &thorn;onki &thorn;e, louerd iesu crist : for ich am cristine man."</L>
<L>"Nimez him," quath &thorn;e Aumperour : "and ledez him up on hei&yogh;h!"</L>
<L>huy brou&yogh;hten him up-on an he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Ash. hei</NOTE> de-grece : &thorn;at muche<NOTE PLACE="marg1">al &thorn;at</NOTE> folk him i-sei&yogh;h,</L>
<L>And duden on him is noble<NOTE PLACE="marg1">on the margin.</NOTE> robe : &thorn;at he werede er</L>
<L N="46">&THORN;e &yogh;wyle he was so noble kny&yogh;ht : and of so gret power.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o he stod al-so quoynteliche : ase men him gre&thorn;i mi&yogh;hte,</L>
<L>"Ypolyt," quath &thorn;e Aumperour : "nou&thorn;e &thorn;ou hast &thorn;ine ri&yogh;hte.</L>
<L>bi-&thorn;ench &thorn;e wuch a man &thorn;ou art : and &yogh;wuch a kny&yogh;ht<NOTE PLACE="marg1">a k. om. in Ash.</NOTE> &thorn;ou hast i-beo,</L>
<L N="50">Noble and hende, ase &thorn;ou &yogh;uyt schalt : &yogh;if &thorn;ou wolt &thorn;e bi-seo;</L>
<L>bi-&thorn;ench &thorn;e of &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast i-haued : of &thorn;i noble dignete,</L>
<L>And bi-lef here in ore compaynie : ase &thorn;ou were er with me!"</L>
<L>&para; "Sire Aumperour," quath [&thorn;is] holie Man : "for nou&yogh;ht &thorn;ou spext so :</L>
<L N="54">For a newe kny&yogh;ht ich am bi-come : n<SUP>i</SUP>ewe batayle to do;</L>
<L>Godes kny&yogh;ht of heouene ich am : and al mi wille so is</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich in his batayle be<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Ash. were</NOTE> : sone i-martred, i-wis."</L>
<L>&THORN;o was &thorn;e Aumperour wroth i-nov&yogh;h : he cleopede Valerian,</L>
<L N="58">his Iustise, &thorn;at was schrewe i-nov&yogh; : and a swi&thorn;e lu&thorn;er man;</L>
<L>"Nim," he seide, "&thorn;is foule &thorn;ef : and with a strong torment<MILESTONE N="198" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>bring him of liue, ase &thorn;ou mi&yogh;ht : with hard Iuggement;</L>
<L>And wiend furst hom to is &thorn;ingue : and nim al his guod,</L>
<L N="62">For euerech del ich &yogh;iue it &thorn;e : and his flechs and his blod."</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;is holie mannes hous : &thorn;e Iustise wende a-non,</L>
<L>Al his maynie he fond &thorn;are : cristine euerechon;</L>
<L>Ech aftur o&thorn;ur he liet heom nime : and tormenti sore i-nov&yogh;;</L>
<L N="66">And bi-fore &thorn;is holie man : ech aftur o&thorn;ur drou&yogh;</L>
<L>And ech aftur o&thorn;ur bi-fore his ei&yogh;ene : with gret torment he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Ash. me</NOTE> slov&yogh; :</L>
<L>he liet alle heore hauedene smiten of : with schendnesse and wou&yogh;.</L>
<L N="69">&para; &THORN;o huy weren bi-fore &thorn;is holie man : alle to de&thorn;e i-brou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Iustise i-sai&yogh;h &thorn;at he ne mi&yogh;hte : &thorn;are-with tuyrne is &thorn;ou&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>wilde coltes and strongue : he liet fette at&thorn;e laste</L>
<L N="72">And bi &thorn;e fet &thorn;isne holie man : to heore tayle he bond faste,</L>
<L>And liet &thorn;e coltes eorne forth. : wel luyte huy wolden a-bide,
<PB REF="00000531.tif" N="483"></L>
<L>Ake ornen and drowen &thorn;ene holie Man : al-a-boute wel wide,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; scharpe breres and &thorn;ornes : and ope manie an harde stone;</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;e peces fullen &thorn;icke a-boute : of his fle<SUP>s</SUP>che fram &thorn;e bone.</L>
<L>So longue, &thorn;at he liet &thorn;at lif&mdash; : his deth was strong i-nov&yogh;,</L>
<L>&YOGH;wane ech of &thorn;is wilde coltes : at heore tayle him drov&yogh;!</L>
<L>&para; Ore louerd hat ofte for his loue : fair miracle i-do</L>
<L N="80">On hors &thorn;at weren to him i-mete : and on coltes al-so.</L>
<L>Manie Men habbuth i-said &thorn;are-fore : &yogh;wane huy &yogh;eme to hors toke :</L>
<L>"Ore louerd and seint ypolyt : &thorn;is hors saue and loke!"</L>
<L N="83">bidde we nou&thorn;e seint ypolyt : &thorn;at he ore erinde beode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at merci he<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> god</NOTE> habbe of us alle : and off alle &thorn;at habbuth neode.<NOTE PLACE="foot">After the Saints' Lives, follow in MS. Laud: 68. Sayings of St. Bernard. 69. Vision of St. Paul (both ed. by me in <I>Herrig's Archiv</I>, 1874). 70. Debate of body and soul. 71. Havelok. 72. King Horn (ed. in <I>Herrig's Archiv</I>, 1873); after this, 3 more legends written by a later hand, of which I add two in the Appendix.</NOTE> AmeN.
<PB REF="00000532.tif" N="484">
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
