<DIV1 TYPE="appendix"><PB REF="00000533.tif" N="485">
<HEAD>APPENDIX. [The following two Legends are added at the end of MS. Laud by a later hand.]</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="73" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>73 Vita &amp; passio sancti Blasii martyris.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt blase wel clene lyf ladde, wi&thorn;oute any hore;<MILESTONE N="228b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In &thorn;e lond of capadoce &thorn;is godeman was I-bore.</L>
<L>ffor his godnesse cristenemen bisschop him wolde make;</L>
<L N="4">Nolde he nat of swich power, ac gan it anon for-sake.</L>
<L>ffor he it nolde in none manere, he fley out of &thorn;e londe</L>
<L>In wildernesse to a dep valeye, .&yogh;.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">&yogh; = &amp;.</NOTE> &thorn;er he gan to astonde.</L>
<L>Pryueliche he wonede &thorn;er, .&yogh;. hudde him swi&thorn;e longe,</L>
<L N="8">And seruede god wel; in penance he duelde swi&thorn;e stronge.</L>
<L>Wilde bestes &thorn;at &thorn;er were, a-boute him comen &thorn;ikke,</L>
<L>[&yogh;] solaseden him, for he was one; his lymes &thorn;ei wolden likke.</L>
<L>Whan any of hem sike were, to him he<NOTE PLACE="marg1">= heo, hi</NOTE> wolden a-non,</L>
<L N="12">And arst ar he hem blessede, nane fot fro him nolden gon.</L>
<L>Ech sik beste sone hol was whan &thorn;ei hadde his blessinge;</L>
<L>&THORN;oru godes grace fro fer to him he comen for &thorn;is &thorn;ingge.<NOTE PLACE="marg1">v. 13-14 <I>al.</I> om.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e lu&thorn;er iustise of &thorn;e lond, &thorn;at het agrycolas,</L>
<L N="16">his men to hunten owt he sente, &thorn;er &thorn;is gode man was.</L>
<L>As &thorn;ei wenden, hem &thorn;oute wounder &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he so fewe deer founde.</L>
<L>he be-hulde into &thorn;e depe : &thorn;o seye &thorn;ei on &thorn;e grounde</L>
<L>Swi&thorn;e fele der a-boute aman, &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> sat hem a-mydde</L>
<L N="20">A-kne, &yogh; be-held to heuene-ward, his beden forto bydde;</L>
<L>&THORN;ese bestes a-louten alle to him-ward. In gret &thorn;out &thorn;es honten were;</L>
<L>he wenten &yogh; tolde &thorn;e Iustise al &thorn;at &thorn;ei seye &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>he het hem a-&yogh;en wende &yogh;. him<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> seche, &yogh;if<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. &yogh; &yogh;if</NOTE> &thorn;ei him<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> fonde &thorn;er gon,</L>
<L N="24">Any cristene man, &thorn;at hi scholde to-fore him bringge a-non.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1">= he, heo</NOTE> comen .&yogh;. seint blase founde, he seyden : "&thorn;ou schalt aryse</L>
<L>&yogh;. come wi&thorn; ous, &yogh; speke anon wi&thorn; &thorn;e heye Iustise."</L>
<L>"Mine leue sones," seint blase seyde, "&yogh;e ben to me welcome;</L>
<L N="28">ffor now ich wot &thorn;at Ihesu crist to me haue&thorn; &yogh;eme I-nome.
<PB REF="00000534.tif" N="486"></L>
<L>Go we nou for&thorn; in his name, Ich wot he wile vs lede;</L>
<L>Ne leue&thorn; nat to don be me al &thorn;at he &yogh;ou<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &yogh;oure maister</NOTE> sede."</L>
<L>As &thorn;ei ladde &thorn;is holy man toward &thorn;e Iustise,</L>
<L N="32">Prechinde he turnede many on to oure louerdes seruise;</L>
<L>Blynde .&yogh;. deue .&yogh; dombe also .&yogh;. &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> o&thorn;er siknesse hadde,</L>
<L>Many on to hele he brou&yogh;the, als me him for&thorn; ladde;</L>
<L>Wilde bestes &thorn;at sike were, ourne to him also</L>
<L N="36">As men him ladde, .&yogh;. fette here hele als &thorn;ei hadde arst i-do.&mdash;</L>
<L>A &yogh;ong child, als he et<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. het</NOTE> his mete, a bon schet in his &thorn;rote;</L>
<L>Al astrangled &yogh; ded it lay, &thorn;o it was in i-schote.</L>
<L>his moder nadde no child bote &thorn;at; greth doel &yogh;e made wi&thorn;-alle,</L>
<L N="40">To-fore seint blase &yogh;e bar &thorn;is child .&yogh;. as wod gan doun falle,</L>
<L>&yogh; bad he scholde hire sone hele. &thorn;is god man his hond vp nom</L>
<L>&yogh;. blesse[de] it : &yogh; &thorn;at bon out schet, &yogh; &thorn;at child hol be-com.</L>
<L>"Louerd," seyde &thorn;is gode man, "grante me a bone :</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at man in what yuel bidde&thorn; to me, I-here him wel sone</L>
<L>&YOGH;if he seye &thorn;ese wordes to &thorn;e : 'louerd cryst, &thorn;in ore!<MILESTONE N="229" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor loue of seint blase, &thorn;i sergeant, help [me] of &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. his</NOTE> sore!' "</L>
<L>In worschipe of godes holy name, who-so him bid &thorn;is bone</L>
<L N="48">ffor loue of seint blase in good entente, he wor&thorn; i-herd wel sone.&mdash;</L>
<L>A pouere wif-man &thorn;er was also, &thorn;at bote on sowe hadde;</L>
<L>a wolf awey to wode it ber. on seint blase loude &yogh;e gradde</L>
<L>&THORN;at he scholde of hire swyne helpe. seint blase low a-non.</L>
<L N="52">"Ne dred te no&thorn;ing of &thorn;e wolf, &thorn;ei he be an yuel swon!</L>
<L>"A-byd, mayster, &yogh; com a&yogh;eyn &yogh; bring &thorn;is swyn a-now<NOTE PLACE="marg1">orig. a-non, corr. to a-now <I>al.</I> nou</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;is pore wifman, &thorn;at ha&thorn; &thorn;erto betere ry&yogh;t &thorn;an &thorn;ou!"</L>
<L>&THORN;e wilde beste com a&yogh;en &yogh; &thorn;at swyn doun a<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. adoun</NOTE> leyde</L>
<L N="56">Al harmles ate wydewe fot, as &thorn;e holy man him seyde.</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;er nas no wilde beste &thorn;at he nadde to his heste,</L>
<L>ffor he hym<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. hem</NOTE> held, as &yogh;e habbe&thorn; i-herd, &yogh; made wi&thorn; hem gret feste.&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;o he at-fore &thorn;e iustise cam, "wel-come, blase," he seyde,</L>
<L N="60">"&THORN;ou louest oure godes &yogh; art here frend; he willen &thorn;e wisse &yogh; rede."</L>
<L>"heil be &thorn;ou, iustise," seint blase seyde, "&yogh; alle &thorn;at &thorn;e i-se&thorn;!</L>
<L>Ne clepe nat &thorn;es godes so fair a name, for pure deflen he be&thorn;.</L>
<L>ffor who &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> euere<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> hi &amp; hoso</NOTE> on hem beleue&thorn;, schullen into<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> in</NOTE> helle pyne</L>
<L N="64">Ene &yogh;. euere tormentud be, &thorn;e lord &yogh; ek his hyne."</L>
<L>&THORN;is iustise for wra&thorn;&thorn;e anon let hym strepe al nakud,</L>
<L>[&yogh;] wi&thorn; harde skourges on hym legge; many wounde on him was makud.</L>
<L>Euere he seyde, as men hym beet : "&yogh;e ne turne&thorn; nat my &thorn;out;</L>
<L N="68">My louerd ihesu is al myn help, .I ne drede &yogh;ou ry&yogh;t nowth."</L>
<L>&THORN;o he hym hadde longe i-bete &thorn;at he wery were,
<PB REF="00000535.tif" N="487"></L>
<L>he him deden in strong prison, to tormenten him &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&THORN;at wifman &thorn;at seint blase hadde &thorn;e swyn &thorn;e wolf be-nome,</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;o &thorn;at he in prison was, &yogh; &thorn;e tidinge to hire icome,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e slou &thorn;at swyn, &yogh; bar to<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> seint blase bo&thorn;e heued &yogh; feet</L>
<L>To &thorn;e prison, wel<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. wel wel</NOTE> y-sode; &yogh; &thorn;e godeman &thorn;ar-of eth.</L>
<L>"Wifman," he seyde, "for &thorn;e kyndenesse &thorn;ou hast me her I-do,</L>
<L N="76">wexe &yogh; eche &thorn;ine bestes schulle, &yogh; &thorn;in o&thorn;er &thorn;ing also.</L>
<L>&YOGH; euerich [man] her-afteward &thorn;at me haue&thorn; in mynde</L>
<L>&yogh; honoure&thorn; me wi&thorn; any of his orf, al &thorn;ulke beste kynde</L>
<L>prouen it schal &thorn;e bet wi&thorn; him, &yogh; al &thorn;at him come&thorn; to;"</L>
<L N="80">Akne he bad to oure louerd crist &thorn;at it moste ben so.&mdash;</L>
<L>Atfore &thorn;e iustise an o&thorn;er day seint blase was i-brout.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he i-say &thorn;at he ne my&yogh;tte a&yogh;en god torne his &thorn;out,</L>
<L>Mid ropes him hengen<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> hi h. him</NOTE> on a tre. be-ne&thorn;e &thorn;er stode I-nowe</L>
<L N="84">Tormentours wi&thorn; oules kene, &yogh; al his fless to-drowe;</L>
<L>as men wi&thorn; combes wolle to-drau&thorn;, his fless &thorn;er-wi&thorn; he tere.</L>
<L>Euere prechede &thorn;is holy man, as &thorn;ei him no&thorn;ing nere.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he hym ne my&yogh;tten so ouer-come, to prison a&yogh;en him bere&mdash;</L>
<L N="88">ffor his lymes him nolde bere, so he to-drawe were.</L>
<L>as me bar &thorn;e godeman, he stremede al o-blode.<MILESTONE N="229b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>seue wifmen &thorn;at cristene were, be-helde [&thorn;is]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om.</NOTE> as &thorn;ei stode :</L>
<L>&THORN;ei &yogh;eden &yogh; gadereden of &thorn;e blod, for it was holden relik,</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;er-wi&thorn; hem smere &yogh; sum to wyte, to smere &thorn;erwi&thorn; &thorn;e sike.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;e lu&thorn;ere men &thorn;is i-seye, . faste he hem toke,</L>
<L>&yogh; bad hem honure here godes; .&yogh; al &thorn;at he for-soke.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei seyde : "&yogh;our godes vn-clene be&thorn;, &thorn;erfore &yogh;e vs hem lene,</L>
<L N="96">&yogh; bring hem to &thorn;e faire water, we schullen hem wassche clene,</L>
<L>&yogh; we hem wille&thorn; honure, als &yogh;e vs wille&thorn; rede."</L>
<L>&THORN;is [iustise] was ry&yogh;th glad; his godes to &thorn;e water he let lede.</L>
<L>&THORN;es wifmen nomen &thorn;ese maumettes, wan &thorn;ider &yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="marg1">corr. to he?</NOTE> were bi-swonke,</L>
<L N="100">&yogh; casten hem into &thorn;e depe water; a-non &thorn;e schrewen sonken.</L>
<L>"Nou we bidde&thorn; &yogh;ou selue helpu&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Bidde&thorn; hi seide hom sulue helpe</NOTE> o&thorn;er &yogh;oure<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> hore</NOTE> my&yogh;tte is schronke.</L>
<L>Why nelle he nat comen vp to helpe &yogh;ou? Ich wene he be&thorn; a-dronke."</L>
<L>&THORN;es wreches wi&thorn; poles &yogh; wi&thorn; hokes here godes a-non soute;</L>
<L>wi&thorn; drery chere &yogh; vnne&thorn;e he hem to londe broutthe.</L>
<L N="105">&THORN;is Iustise was for wra&thorn;&thorn;e wod, loude he gradde &yogh; chidde;</L>
<L>A wel strong fur he let &thorn;er make .&yogh; caste &thorn;es wifmen amydde.</L>
<L>welled led &yogh;e &thorn;rewen on hem, vnne&thorn;e it &thorn;oute hem warm;</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;at fur be-gan to quenche a-non; non of hem nadde harm.</L>
<L>wel wro&thorn; was &thorn;is Iustise &thorn;o, &yogh; wel loude gradde;</L>
<L>he hem let honge opon a tre, as he arst seint blase hadde.
<PB REF="00000536.tif" N="488"></L>
<L>wi&thorn; oules he to-drowen here fless, as he be-ne&thorn;e stode;</L>
<L N="112">Non o&thorn;er &thorn;an whyt mylk out of hem com, in stede of here blode.</L>
<L>Euere &thorn;e more men hem to-drowe, &thorn;e gladdere he were;</L>
<L>"Sire Iustise, it is for nout, &thorn;us<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. &thorn;u</NOTE> ne quellest vs nat to-&yogh;ere.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou vs wilt don o&thorn;er &thorn;ing, bringge it sone to ende,</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;at we mowe to Ihesu crist; we wilne&thorn; &thorn;ider wende."</L>
<L>&THORN;is Iustise het &thorn;at me scholde here heuedes of smyte anon.</L>
<L>&THORN;ese wyfman to-ward here martirdom glade gonne gon.</L>
<L>&THORN;at on wifman hadde tweye sones, &thorn;at cristene were also;</L>
<L N="120">he wepe for here moder de&thorn;, he nuste neuere elles what do;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei hengen on hire, &yogh; nolden hire fro nat o fote gon,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e sworen &yogh;e wolden &thorn;an de&thorn; a-fonge wi&thorn; hire &thorn;er a-non.</L>
<L>Gret doel hadde &thorn;e moder of hem, for &yogh;e of elde nere;</L>
<L N="124">&YOGH;e ne<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. ne ne</NOTE> my&yogh;tte it for no&thorn;ing se &thorn;at &thorn;ei martired were,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> 2 vv. more.</NOTE></L>
<L>he criede opon &thorn;e tormentoures &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he hem ne sscholde sle:</L>
<L>&yogh; he hem let here wey so &yogh;onge alyue gon a&yogh;e,</L>
<L>And nome &yogh; smyten &thorn;e heuedes of &thorn;ese wifmen alle seuene.</L>
<L N="128">Aungles &thorn;ere soules alle ladde to &thorn;e blisse of heuene.</L>
<L>&THORN;e children gret dol for here moder maden in alle wyse;</L>
<L>&THORN;o me nolde hem asle, he ronne to &thorn;e iustise,</L>
<L>&YOGH; seyde &thorn;at &yogh;e cristene were, &yogh; &thorn;at his lawe nas nawth,</L>
<L N="132">&YOGH; &thorn;at he scholde myd his godes to pyne of helle ben brouth.</L>
<L>&THORN;e iustise let &thorn;es children nyme, &thorn;ei &yogh;e &yogh;onge were;</L>
<L>In depe prison &yogh;e weren i-cast, to tormenten hem &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>Wel glad were &thorn;es &yogh;unge, &thorn;o &yogh;e were y-nome,<MILESTONE N="230" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="136">ffor he hopeden y-martired be, &yogh; to heuene-blisse come.</L>
<L>&THORN;o let &thorn;e Iustise anon after seint blase sende,</L>
<L>&YOGH; het him<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. hem</NOTE> honure here godes, &yogh; his &thorn;out sone wende.</L>
<L>"It is for naut," seint blase seyde, "&thorn;ou ne schalt it nat make</L>
<L N="140">&THORN;at ich wreche stones honure, &yogh; Ihesu crist for-sake.</L>
<L>Do wi&thorn; my body what &thorn;ou wilt, of whom &thorn;ou hast power;</L>
<L>Of my soule ne hast &thorn;ou [non], it nis nat in &thorn;i power."</L>
<L>&THORN;er was a water swy&thorn;e depe : &thorn;e iustise atte laste,</L>
<L N="144">ffor-to adranche &thorn;is holy man, amyddes he let him caste.</L>
<L>Signe of &thorn;e crois seint blase made : vp<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. vp fro</NOTE> &thorn;e water he &yogh;ede dreye,</L>
<L>Vp &yogh; doun als vpe druye lond, ne my&yogh;te &thorn;e water him nuye.</L>
<L>"Wreche," he seyde, "her &thorn;ou my&yogh;t se wich is godes my&yogh;th!</L>
<L N="148">Loke &yogh;if &yogh;oure godes so hardi be &thorn;at &thorn;ei<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Be&thorn; &yogh;e so hardi vp &yogh;oure godes : &thorn;at &yogh;e</NOTE> doren here a-ly&yogh;th!"</L>
<L>ffifue &yogh; sixti of proute hynen lupen into &thorn;e water a-non,</L>
<L>&YOGH; treste to meche to here godes, &yogh; adreynten euerichon.</L>
<L>&THORN;o weren &thorn;o &thorn;at stode a-rowe,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;e o&thorn;ere &thorn;e arwere</NOTE> ech be o&thorn;er as &thorn;ei stode,
<PB REF="00000537.tif" N="489"></L>
<L N="152">&THORN;er ne dorste non of hem to &thorn;em go for depe of &thorn;e flode.</L>
<L>Seint blase &yogh;ede vp &yogh; doun, &yogh; an aungel to him com</L>
<L>&YOGH; seyde : "&thorn;ou take &thorn;e blisse of heuene &thorn;oru &thorn;i martirdom!"</L>
<L>&THORN;is godeman &thorn;onkede ihesu crist, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> his aungel to him sende;</L>
<L>&YOGH; &thorn;o his [fon]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. <I>al.</I> &thorn;e o&thorn;er</NOTE> ne dorste comen hym ney, a&yogh;en to londe he wende.</L>
<L>he seyde : "nou &yogh;e ben agast forto comen to me,</L>
<L>I come to &yogh;ou in godes name, for I &yogh;ou nelle fle."</L>
<L>&THORN;o schon his face as &thorn;e sonne, wi&thorn; leme swi&thorn;e bry&yogh;the;</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;er nas [non] &thorn;at for bry&yogh;thnesse his face sen<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> sen</NOTE> my&yogh;the.</L>
<L>&THORN;er were ey&yogh;tte &yogh; twenti men .&yogh; sixti men also</L>
<L>&THORN;at leueden in god for &thorn;e miracle &thorn;at &thorn;ere was I-do.</L>
<L>I-nome he were wi&thorn; &thorn;is gode man, to-fore &thorn;e iustise ben brouth.</L>
<L N="164">&THORN;e iustise bad seint blase &yogh; hem change here &thorn;out.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he sey &thorn;ei nolde it do, he het<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. let</NOTE> his men a-non</L>
<L>to smyten of wi&thorn;oute &thorn;e toun here hefdes euerichon.</L>
<L>&THORN;es twey children in prison were; loude he gonne grede</L>
<L N="168">&THORN;at me hem scholde to martyrdom wi&thorn; seint blase lede,</L>
<L>&YOGH; seyden : "wharto wilie<NOTE PLACE="marg1">= wil &yogh;e</NOTE> vs wyte, wreches, in &thorn;is hurne?</L>
<L>ffor nawth it is &thorn;at &yogh;e wene&thorn; oure &thorn;out fro gode turne."</L>
<L>Me nomen &thorn;e children &yogh; ladden hem for&thorn; wi&thorn; o&thorn;ere to martirdom.</L>
<L N="172">Seint blase him sat doun akne, &thorn;o he &thorn;ider com:</L>
<L>"Louerd ihesu, &yogh;if it is &thorn;i wille, ane bone bidde I. &thorn;e:</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at any man in his annuy habbe mynde of me,</L>
<L>In cas of peryl o&thorn;er of yuel, o&thorn;er &yogh;if &thorn;er is I-schote</L>
<L N="176">Bon o&thorn;er stre, o&thorn;er o&thorn;ur &thorn;ing I-comen<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> into eny</NOTE> in mannes &thorn;rote,</L>
<L>&YOGH; he bidde myn help to &thorn;e, be daye o&thorn;er be ny&yogh;tte,</L>
<L>Graunte me &thorn;is bone, swete ihesu, for &thorn;in holy mi&yogh;tte.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if any man assigne&thorn; aut of his in &thorn;e honour of me,<MILESTONE N="230b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="180">Of corn, of orf, of o&thorn;er &thorn;ing, Louerd, ich bidde &thorn;e</L>
<L>&THORN;at al his &thorn;ing mote<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> &thorn;e betere preue, for &thorn;i swete my&yogh;the."</L>
<L>&THORN;er cam fram heuene a bry&yogh;th myst &yogh; an-oward him a-ly&yogh;the;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-inne oure louerd ly&yogh;tte adoun, to &thorn;is holy man he seyde:</L>
<L N="184">"Blase, my leue frend, be glad, of de&thorn; haue &thorn;ou no drede!</L>
<L>Al &thorn;i bone i &thorn;e graunte &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast beden here.</L>
<L>heye &thorn;e nou, &yogh; come&thorn; wi&thorn; me, &thorn;ou &yogh; &thorn;ine twey<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> triwe</NOTE> fere!"</L>
<L>he was so glad &thorn;at god wi&thorn; him spak &yogh; grauntede him his bone,</L>
<L N="188">"Do&thorn;," seyde he to &thorn;e tormentores, "al &thorn;at &yogh;e habbe&thorn; to done."</L>
<L>&THORN;e tormentores smyten of his heued, .&yogh; alle his feren also,</L>
<L>&YOGH; &thorn;e twey childre, &thorn;at glad were he my&yogh;tten come &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L>Sebast hy&yogh;tte &thorn;at cite &thorn;er seint blase was i-bore,</L>
<L N="192">&YOGH; &thorn;er his heued was of y-smyte&mdash;him schamede nat &thorn;erfore.
<PB REF="00000538.tif" N="490"></L>
<L>&THORN;e bone &thorn;at he hadde i-bede, cristenemen it vnderstode:</L>
<L>In &thorn;e honurance of seint blase he parteden of here gode:</L>
<L>&THORN;e betere preuede al here<NOTE PLACE="marg1">on the margin added o&thorn;er</NOTE> god, .&yogh;. &yogh;eth it do&thorn; al-so,</L>
<L N="196">In &thorn;e stede wher his ymage is, . &thorn;ei finde&thorn; it wel y-do.</L>
<L>&YOGH; who is in stable beleue, &yogh; wille to sein blase crye,</L>
<L>&YOGH; &yogh;ifue of his good in honur of hym, god nelle nat for him lye.</L>
<L>God leue &thorn;at we parti mote of &thorn;e heye blisse</L>
<L>&THORN;ere &thorn;at seint blase is Inne i-brout, &thorn;at we &thorn;er-offe ne mysse. amen</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="74" TYPE="legend">
<HEAD>74 Vita &amp; passio sancte Cecilie virginis &amp; martiris.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seinte Cecilie, of noble kynde I-bore &yogh;e was at rome;</L>
<L>Oure louerd crist &yogh;e louede wel ar &yogh;e fram cradel come.</L>
<L>Stilleliche &yogh;e hire let bapti&yogh;e, as we fynden I-wryte;</L>
<L N="4">To oure louerd crist &yogh;e bad &yogh;erne hire maydenhod to wyte.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;oru streng&thorn;e of hire frendes I-spoused &yogh;e was to a man</L>
<L>Of gret nobleye &yogh; of richesse, his name was Vallerian.</L>
<L>&THORN;is mayde werede robe of pal &yogh; clo&thorn;es swi&thorn;e riche,</L>
<L N="8">Garlaundes &yogh; tressoures of gold&mdash;&thorn;e here next hire liche.</L>
<L>Whane &yogh;e herde menstrales song, . &yogh;e song in hire menstralcie,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">Ash. Wen &thorn;e m. songe hor song: of hor m.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;is mayde stiliche song of god &yogh; of his moder marye.</L>
<L>A vers of &thorn;e psalter hire song was, wer-on was mast hire &thorn;out:</L>
<L N="12">"Lat, louerd, myn herte wi&thorn;oute wem be, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> it confundet be naut!"</L>
<L>A-ny&yogh;t as &yogh;e was in riche bed wi&thorn; hire lord i-brouth,</L>
<L>Sone he hadde of folye &thorn;is clene mayde be-sout.</L>
<L>"Swete herte," &thorn;is mayde seyde, "for loue &thorn;ou hast to me,</L>
<L N="16">Graunte me y mowe &thorn;e telle a litel pryuete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ich me mowe &thorn;erof schryue, &yogh;. &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;ou it wille hele."</L>
<L>"Certes, lemman," &thorn;is &yogh;ungman seyde, "no&thorn;ing telle I nele."</L>
<L>"Suete lemman," &thorn;is mayde seyde, "in warde icham I-do:</L>
<L N="20">An aungel of heuene is my wardeyn, &yogh; my lemman &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L>Wel faste he stant her bi me. &yogh;if he vnder&yogh;ete</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou be-nome my maydenhod, no&thorn;ing nolde he lete</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne wolde harde smyte, &yogh; be-nyme &thorn;e &thorn;i my&yogh;tte<MILESTONE N="231" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="24">Of &thorn;i &yogh;ungnesse &yogh; of noble stat, for &thorn;ou ne my&yogh;th wi&thorn; him fy&yogh;tthe.</L>
<L>Ac &yogh;if he wiste &thorn;ou louedest me in gode loue &yogh; clene,</L>
<L>Wytte<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. wytie?</NOTE> he wolde &thorn;e als he de&thorn; me, &yogh; al yuel fro &thorn;e &yogh;ene."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wilt," seyde Vallerian, "&thorn;at ich I-leue &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;en angel &thorn;ou most me schewe, &thorn;at I se hym I-wis;</L>
<L>&YOGH; wanne I &thorn;at so&thorn;e i-se, &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast so&thorn; i-seyd,</L>
<L>In clenesse for-so&thorn;e &thorn;i wille I do, al after &thorn;i red.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if I se &thorn;at in folye &thorn;ou louest ano&thorn;er &thorn;an me,
<PB REF="00000539.tif" N="491"></L>
<L N="32">No-&thorn;ing ne schal &yogh;ou helpe, &thorn;at I ne sle him &yogh; &thorn;e."</L>
<L>"Swete herte," seyde &thorn;at mayde, "&yogh; &thorn;ou wile &thorn;e aungel se,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou most bileuen on Ihesu crist &yogh; I-cristned be,</L>
<L>&YOGH; sen him &thorn;ou schalt &yogh;if &thorn;ou wilt so; he &thorn;e wile wytte<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. wytie?</NOTE> fro helle,</L>
<L N="36">So gret ioye of oure loue schal be &thorn;at no tunge ne may telle.</L>
<L>Ac henne ouer &thorn;re myle &thorn;ou most gon &thorn;e wey to<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> of</NOTE> apye;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere [pore] men &thorn;ou schalt fynde on Ihesu crist faste crye,</L>
<L>Sey &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ich to hem &thorn;e sende, &yogh; &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> he &thorn;e teche anon</L>
<L N="40">Whar is seint vrban &thorn;e holi old man, for &thorn;ou most to him gon,</L>
<L>ffor priue counseil &thorn;ou wilt wi&thorn; him speke. &yogh; he &thorn;e schal bapti&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&YOGH; &thorn;anne &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;an angel se, &yogh; do as he &thorn;e wile wise."</L>
<L>Vallerian a-ros a-non, as oure louerd him &yogh;af wille,</L>
<L N="44">To &thorn;e stede &thorn;e mayde bad he wende for&thorn; wel stille.</L>
<L>&THORN;es pore men him taute a-non to &thorn;e olde seint vrban;</L>
<L>he fond him in an old for-late stede, &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg1">r. &thorn;er</NOTE> wonede neuere man,</L>
<L>Among puttes &yogh; burieles als men cristene men &thorn;reu</L>
<L N="48">After &thorn;at he martired were, men anye kneu(!)</L>
<L>To his feet he ful a-doun a-kne, als-sone as<NOTE PLACE="marg1">overlined.</NOTE> [he] to him come,</L>
<L>&YOGH; seyde &thorn;at cesilie send him &thorn;ider to asken cristendome.</L>
<L>"Louerd, I-herd be &thorn;i my&yogh;tte," seyde seint vrban,</L>
<L N="52">"We&thorn;er &thorn;is be &thorn;at Lu&thorn;ere werreor men clepu&thorn; vallerian?</L>
<L>Were cecilie haue him now y-mad, him &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> was so wilde</L>
<L>&YOGH; more tyrant &thorn;an any wolf, als a lomb he is<NOTE PLACE="marg1">om. he is</NOTE> now mylde?"</L>
<L>&THORN;o com &thorn;er go a swi&thorn;e old man a ly&yogh;tthe fro heuene &thorn;er,</L>
<L N="56">hor, wi&thorn; whyte vestemens, a swi&thorn;e fair wryt he ber.</L>
<L>&THORN;o vallerian it<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> him</NOTE> I-sey, a-doun he fel for drede;</L>
<L>Seint vrban nom him vp a&yogh;en . &yogh; gan him for&thorn; lede.</L>
<L>&THORN;is halewe of heuene tok him &thorn;at wryt, &yogh; bad him forto rede.</L>
<L N="60">Vallerian tok it anon, &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;e wordes sede:</L>
<L>"On<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. Oure</NOTE> louerd is, .&yogh;. on bi-leue, .&yogh; on bapti&yogh;ingge,</L>
<L>On god .&yogh; fader of alle &thorn;at be&thorn;, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> oueral is .&yogh; in eche &thorn;ingge."</L>
<L>"I-leuestou &thorn;is," qua&thorn; seint vrban, "&thorn;at &thorn;ou dost her I-se?"</L>
<L N="64">"&THORN;er nis no&thorn;ing," qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er, "&thorn;at bet to leue be."</L>
<L>After &thorn;is whyte man he be-held; he nuste wher he be-cam.</L>
<L>Seint vrban him nom a-non, &yogh; &yogh;af him cristendom.</L>
<L>To sein Cecilie he wente a&yogh;en, &thorn;o he was &thorn;are is fulle:<MILESTONE N="231b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="68">he fond hire chambre ly&yogh;th wi&thorn;-inne, .&yogh; swi&thorn;e swote smulle.</L>
<L>he fond cecilie, his gode spouse, &yogh; an aungel wi&thorn; hire stonde,</L>
<L>Bry&yogh;ttere &thorn;an any leme<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. lome</NOTE>; twey garlondes he hadde on honde,</L>
<L>Of rose &yogh; of lilie swote; &thorn;at on, cecilie he tok,</L>
<L N="72">&YOGH; &thorn;at o&thorn;er, vallerian, as we fynden in bok.
<PB REF="00000540.tif" N="492"></L>
<L>"Wyte&thorn; &thorn;is wi&thorn; trewe loue, wi&thorn; chaste body &yogh; clene,</L>
<L>Ich hem habbe fro heuene i-brou&yogh;th, oure lord hem do&thorn; &yogh;ou lene;</L>
<L>ffor-falewe ne olde wille &thorn;ei nat, ac euere he wille&thorn; laste.</L>
<L N="76">Two manere floures &thorn;er be&thorn; on, nelle neuere here heu caste;</L>
<L>&THORN;e lilie be-tokne&thorn; &yogh;oure maydenhod, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> is so whyt &yogh; swote,</L>
<L>&THORN;e rose be-tokne&thorn; &yogh;oure martirdom; for &thorn;er-on deye &yogh;e mote.</L>
<L>And for &thorn;ou dest, vallerian, cecilie red so sone,</L>
<L N="80">What &thorn;ou be-sekest of my lord, he wille &thorn;e graunte sone."</L>
<L>"I ne wille<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> wilny</NOTE> no&thorn;ing so miche," seyde vallerian,</L>
<L>"Bote<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> As</NOTE> &thorn;at Tiburs,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. Tiburft</NOTE> my bro&thorn;er, wi&thorn; me were cristeneman."</L>
<L>"Mi lord," qua&thorn; &thorn;is aungel, "wile &yogh;iuen &thorn;at ilke grace,</L>
<L N="84">&YOGH; bo&thorn;e &yogh;e schulle I-martired be at o tyme, in o place."</L>
<L>&THORN;e aungel [wende] wi&thorn; &thorn;is word, he nuste wher he be-com.</L>
<L>&THORN;is two clene &thorn;ingges ioye I-now ech of o&thorn;er nom.</L>
<L>Tiburs com to chambre &yogh; spac<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> to speke</NOTE> wi&thorn; his bro&thorn;er &thorn;ere:</L>
<L N="88">he stod &yogh; be-held al-a-boute als he nuste wher he were;</L>
<L>"Bro&thorn;er," he seyde, "hou go&thorn; &thorn;is? &thorn;is tyme of &thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L>So swote smul ne smelde I neuere, me &thorn;ink&thorn;, as I do here!</L>
<L>&THORN;ei &thorn;is hous were ful of newe roses &yogh; of lylie also,</L>
<L N="92">I ne my&yogh;tte hem versschere smelle, me &thorn;ink&thorn;, &thorn;an I now do.</L>
<L>So ful ich am al of &thorn;e smul, &yogh; so muche it is in my &thorn;out,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Ich am for-so&thorn;e in an-o&thorn;er wytte I-brouth."</L>
<L>"Leue bro&thorn;er," qua&thorn; vallerian, "garlandes we habbe&thorn; here</L>
<L N="96">Of floures &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne my&yogh;t i-se bote &thorn;ou were oure fere.</L>
<L>als &thorn;ou hast &thorn;ane swote smel &thorn;ar-of for oure bone,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wilt be-leue as we, &thorn;ou my&yogh;t sen hem sone."</L>
<L>"Leue bro&thorn;er," seyde &thorn;is o&thorn;er, "whe&thorn;ur it be so&thorn; &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="100">O&thorn;er I stonde in matyngge .&yogh; mete &thorn;at so it is?"</L>
<L>"In metyngge," qua&thorn; vallerian, "we habbe&thorn; euere I-be;</L>
<L>Nou we ben ferst of slepe a-waked, nou we mowe ferst i-se."</L>
<L>"Sestow nou bet," qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er, "&thorn;an &thorn;ou hast er I-do?"</L>
<L N="104">"&YOGH;e," seyde vallerian, "wel sone<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> me be-houe&thorn; so,</L>
<L>ffor my lordes aungel of heuene ha&thorn; I-&yogh;oue me sy&yogh;th;</L>
<L>&YOGH; for oure loue he &thorn;e schal also, &yogh;if &thorn;ou wile leue a-ry&yogh;th."</L>
<L>&THORN;o seyde &thorn;is holy mayde: "tibors, leue bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L>What ben maumettes bote wrechedhede? &thorn;ou sest on hem non o&thorn;er.</L>
<L>Ne sestou &thorn;at &thorn;ese maumets ben mad of old tre?</L>
<L N="110">&THORN;ing &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> ne may him-sulf helpe, hou my&yogh;te it hel[p]e &thorn;e?"<MILESTONE N="232" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"No-&thorn;ing nis so&thorn;ere," qua&thorn; tiburs,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. tiburus</NOTE> "&thorn;anne &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast i-seyd;</L>
<L N="112">Gydiere he were &thorn;an any beste &thorn;at nolde don &thorn;i red."</L>
<L>Seinte cecilie him custe a-non: "leue tiburs," he seyde,
<PB REF="00000541.tif" N="493"></L>
<L>"To-day &thorn;ou schalt my bro&thorn;er be, for &thorn;ou wilt don be rede.</L>
<L>&THORN;oru clene loue &yogh; good be-leue &thorn;i bro&thorn;er my spouse is,</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;ar-&thorn;oru &thorn;ou schalt be-come also my bro&thorn;er when &thorn;ou art his.</L>
<L>Mid Vallerian &thorn;ou most go to &thorn;e bisschop Vrban</L>
<L>&YOGH; be cristned, &yogh; do also as he &thorn;e rede can."</L>
<L>"Is &thorn;at vrban," qua&thorn; tiburs, "&thorn;at so &yogh;erne ha&thorn; be sou&yogh;th,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;at &yogh;are ha&thorn; be fleme &yogh; hud? &yogh; &yogh;if he were for&thorn; brou&yogh;th,</L>
<L>ffor-berne he scholde, &yogh; we also, &yogh;if we wi&thorn; him were;</L>
<L>&YOGH; so &thorn;e while we heuene sou&yogh;then, for-barnd we scholde ben here."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;if &thorn;er nere," qua&thorn; &thorn;is mayde, "onliche bote &thorn;is lyf,</L>
<L N="124">ffol he were &thorn;at it wolde [lese] for any-maner strif;</L>
<L>&YOGH; se&thorn;e &thorn;er is so mury lif &thorn;er &thorn;at we schulle after a-fonge,</L>
<L>ffol is &thorn;at nelle a whyle ben wo, to be in ioye so longe."</L>
<L>"Leue bro&thorn;er," qua&thorn; tiburs, "&thorn;ou haue merci of me</L>
<L N="128">&YOGH; led me to &thorn;at gode man, ich be-seche &thorn;e."</L>
<L>&THORN;at o bro&thorn;er &thorn;at o&thorn;er ladde to &thorn;e bisschop Vrban;</L>
<L>&THORN;ar he for-sok his foule lawe, &yogh; be-cam cristene man.</L>
<L>Tiburs, &thorn;o he com a&yogh;en, &thorn;an aungel sey a-non</L>
<L N="132">&THORN;at cecilie him hadde be-hote, in &thorn;e chambre wi&thorn; hire gon.&mdash;</L>
<L>Cecilie, for &yogh;e wyfman was, at hom &yogh;e moste a-byde;</L>
<L>Ak &thorn;ese bre&thorn;eren, &thorn;at men were, a-boute wenten wyde,</L>
<L>And whane me martyreden cristenemen, &thorn;ider he wolden gon</L>
<L N="136">&YOGH; stele to whan<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. whom</NOTE> he my&yogh;tte best, &yogh; burien hem<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. him</NOTE> a-non.</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ei burieden twey godemen &thorn;at y-martired were,</L>
<L>Come &thorn;e emperoures men .&yogh; nomen hem ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>To-fore &thorn;e Iustise he weren i-brouth. &thorn;ei<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> me</NOTE> askede hem<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. him</NOTE> a-non:</L>
<L N="140">"Who made &yogh;ou so hardi to burie &thorn;e emperoures foon,</L>
<L>&THORN;e mys-bi-leuede trichours &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> were a&yogh;en oure lawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; ry&yogh;th Iugement of &thorn;e lond were i-brout of dawe?"</L>
<L>"Sire, we wolde," &thorn;is o&thorn;ere seyde, "&thorn;at we wor&thorn;i were</L>
<L N="144">here knaues forto habbe I-be, &thorn;at &thorn;ou let quelle &thorn;are!</L>
<L>he leften &thorn;ing &thorn;at nas nawt, &thorn;ei it semblance hadde,</L>
<L>&YOGH; toke good &thorn;ing &thorn;at was &yogh; wor&thorn; .&yogh;. no semblance nadde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e worldes ioye, &thorn;at ha&thorn; semblance, for so[&thorn;e] nawt it nys;</L>
<L N="148">And &thorn;ei &thorn;e blisse of heuen &thorn;inke lite, . mechul &yogh; swete it is."</L>
<L>"Beaus amys, me &thorn;ynk&thorn; &thorn;at &yogh;e ben wode:</L>
<L>wor&thorn;e he is to habbe wo, who-so ne keput nat of gode."</L>
<L>"In wynter," qua&thorn; Vallerian, "Idel men sitten &yogh; drynkun,</L>
<L N="152">To bismere he leyen here<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> er&thorn;e</NOTE> tilien &thorn;at a-boute sowynge swynke&thorn;;</L>
<L>In heruest, whan &thorn;e swynkeres mowe&thorn; fair schef &yogh; good &yogh; rype,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> er&thorn;e</NOTE>In meseyse &yogh;e mowen gon vp &yogh; doun, he nabbe&thorn; neuere agripe:
<PB REF="00000542.tif" N="494"></L>
<L>Als we schulle for oure trauayl In blisse rype atte ende,<MILESTONE N="232b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="156">whanne &yogh;e schulle for &yogh;oure ioye to helle wepynde wende."</L>
<L>"Ek he<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> we</NOTE>," seyde &thorn;e Iustise, "&thorn;at Lordes scholde be,</L>
<L>Be&thorn; lasse wor&thorn; &thorn;an swiche wreches, &thorn;at nolde neuere &thorn;e?"</L>
<L>"Certes," qua&thorn; vallerian, "&thorn;ou art lasse i-told</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;an is a saly beggere a&yogh;en god, ne be &thorn;ou neuere so bold."</L>
<L>"Bel amy," qua&thorn; &thorn;e Iustise, "yne kepe nat of &thorn;i Ianglyngge.</L>
<L>Do&thorn; &yogh;oure sacrefise a-non, o&thorn;er me schal &yogh;ou to de&thorn;e bringge."</L>
<L>"Certes," qua&thorn; &thorn;is godeman, "&thorn;ou ne bringgest me neuere &thorn;erto."</L>
<L N="164">&THORN;e Iustise hem let a-non in strong prisone do.</L>
<L>Maxime &thorn;e gayler [het] &thorn;at hem in warde nom;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he &yogh; alle his &thorn;orw hem cristene bi-com.</L>
<L>Seinte cecilie com be &thorn;e prison; loude &yogh;e gan grede :</L>
<L N="168">"What do &yogh;e, godes knytes? ku&thorn;e&thorn; &yogh;our staleworthede!</L>
<L>Fy&yogh;te&thorn; nou stalewor&thorn;liche, to leue &thorn;is derkhede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &yogh;e were in &thorn;e weye i-brouth &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> to cler ly&yogh;t schal &yogh;ou lede."</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e morue, to &thorn;e maumets &thorn;is gode men were brouth.</L>
<L N="172">&THORN;e Iustise het hem don sacrifise; ac &thorn;ei ne wolde nat.</L>
<L>here heued he let of smyte, &yogh; maxime it<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> I-sey</L>
<L>Whare aungles here soules nome &yogh; to heuene baren an hey.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e Iustise he &yogh;ede anon : "cristene ich am," he sede,</L>
<L N="176">"Ich i-sey &thorn;e godemannes<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> menne</NOTE> soule aungles to heuene lede."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iustise him let nymen a non, naked he let him bete</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; stronge skourgen, faste i-bounde, forto he gan &thorn;at lif lete.</L>
<L>&THORN;e body &thorn;ei casten wi&thorn;oute &thorn;e toun. &thorn;o gan cecilie for&thorn; gon :</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;ese &thorn;re holy martires &yogh;e burede to-gydere a-non.</L>
<L>[&YOGH;e was sone i-nome &yogh; ilad before &thorn;e Iustise &thorn;o.]<NOTE PLACE="marg1">This v. om.</NOTE></L>
<L>"What," sede he, "hou go&thorn; &thorn;is? be&thorn; &thorn;er &yogh;et schrewen mo?</L>
<L>artou Vallerianus wif? be &thorn;e fey Ich owe mahoun,</L>
<L N="184">Bote &thorn;ou o&thorn;er do, &thorn;i wyth<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> wite heu</NOTE> wor&thorn; sone I-brouth a-doun.</L>
<L>Of what kynne artou of y-come, &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;us foleliche wilt<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &thorn;e do&thorn;</NOTE> lere?"</L>
<L>"Of betere kunne," qua&thorn; cecilie, "&thorn;an &thorn;ou euere were."</L>
<L>"In wich-maner lif," qua&thorn; &thorn;is o&thorn;er, "&thorn;enkest tou to lyue?"</L>
<L N="188">"ffor-so&thorn;e &thorn;ou axest as a fol, &yogh; swich ansuere me schul &thorn;e &yogh;iue.</L>
<L>for al &thorn;i poer, &thorn;ou schalt i-se, be &thorn;at &thorn;ou wost &thorn;en ende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou ne schalt fro ihesu cryst ones myn herte wende."</L>
<L>"hou come&thorn; it &thorn;e," seyde &thorn;e iustise, "to be so hardy her,</L>
<L N="192">To clepe me fol &thorn;at am &thorn;i maister? ne sixte nower my per.<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> poer</NOTE>"</L>
<L>"&THORN;i per,<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> poer</NOTE> wreche," qua&thorn; &thorn;is mayde, "wor&thorn; sone i-brou&yogh;th be-hynde,</L>
<L>for it nis bote a bladre I-blowe fol of a wreche wynde;</L>
<L>be it wi&thorn; a litel prikke I-priked, a-wey it schrinke&thorn; al :
<PB REF="00000543.tif" N="495"></L>
<L N="196">Als &thorn;i caroigne wi&thorn; siknesse, wreche, a-dwyne schal.<MILESTONE N="233" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;i poer &thorn;at &thorn;ou &yogh;elpest of, bo&thorn;e is &thorn;enne &yogh; lite."</L>
<L>"hou go&thorn; &thorn;is, dame?" seyde &thorn;e Iustise, "whenne come&thorn; al &thorn;is prute?</L>
<L>I may &thorn;e &yogh;iue de&thorn; &yogh; lif, as &thorn;ou sixt myd &thorn;in eye."</L>
<L N="200">"Certes," qua&thorn; &thorn;e mayde &thorn;o, "&thorn;ou lixt &thorn;er-of wel heye :</L>
<L>a wreche caroyne &thorn;ou my&yogh;th &yogh;iue, &yogh;<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> de&thorn; &thorn;at wel schort is,</L>
<L>Ak of lyf ne my&yogh;tte no-&thorn;ing &yogh;iue &thorn;i-selue nat, i-wis.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;e &thorn;ou my&yogh;th &yogh;iue de&thorn; &yogh; no lif, me &thorn;ink&thorn; be pur ry&yogh;tte</L>
<L N="204">&THORN;at &thorn;ou art de&thorn;es seriant, for of lif hasto no my&yogh;tte.</L>
<L>ffor<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> &amp;</NOTE> whan &thorn;ou de&thorn;es sergeant art, de&thorn; &thorn;i louerd is,</L>
<L>&YOGH; in de&thorn; wi&thorn;-outen ende &thorn;ou wilt be, I-wis."</L>
<L>"Dame," qua&thorn; &thorn;e iustise, "of &thorn;i gydihede ne kepe ich ry&yogh;th nowth.</L>
<L N="208">Do sacrifise to oure godes, o&thorn;er &thorn;ou worst to de&thorn;e i-brouth!"</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou seist &thorn;at ich gydi am," seinte cecilie sede,</L>
<L>"Ac &thorn;ou art gydi, &yogh; ek blind, i-sene is on &thorn;i rede.</L>
<L>Scholde I honure &thorn;ine [godes] ymad of ston &yogh; tre?</L>
<L N="212">I nelle it do, for-so&thorn;e, for &thorn;ou ne my&yogh;t nat I-se.</L>
<L>Bote &thorn;ou my&yogh;th i-se &thorn;at art blynd<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> Bote &thorn;<SUP>u</SUP> &THORN;<SUP>u</SUP> blynd, &THORN;<SUP>u</SUP> mi&yogh;t ise</NOTE>, . &thorn;at &thorn;is &thorn;ing so&thorn; is;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou sixt .&yogh;. ne leuest it naut, gydi &thorn;ou art, I-wys,</L>
<L>for gydi he is &thorn;at nelle I-leue &thorn;at he se&thorn; myd his eye;</L>
<L N="216">Gydi &yogh; blind &thorn;ou schalt deye, in helle pyne deye."</L>
<L>&THORN;o ferde &thorn;e schrewe as he were wod, he het &thorn;is mayde take</L>
<L>&YOGH; leden in-to an out-hous, &yogh; a greth fur make,</L>
<L>&YOGH; &thorn;er-ouer a led-ful of water, &yogh; al amydde hire caste,</L>
<L N="220">To se&thorn;e hire &thorn;er while any Lime hol on hire I-laste.</L>
<L>&THORN;o &thorn;is Iuggement was I-&yogh;iue, &yogh; men hire for&thorn; ladde,</L>
<L>Wifmen &yogh; men &thorn;at [it] i-seye, loude &yogh;e wopen &yogh; gradde,</L>
<L>"Allas," &thorn;ei seyde, "&thorn;at &thorn;is &yogh;ongge &thorn;ing,<NOTE PLACE="marg1">MS. &thorn;is</NOTE> &thorn;us fair a creature,</L>
<L N="224">Schal nou lese hire &yogh;ongge lif, &yogh; deye &thorn;oru &thorn;e fure!"</L>
<L>"Be&thorn; stille," qua&thorn; &thorn;is holi mayde, "for me ne wepe&thorn; nout!</L>
<L>Mi &yogh;ongge lif ne lese I nowth, ac to lyue Icham i-brouth.</L>
<L>Ane schorte de&thorn; I schal a-vonge, &yogh; lif wi&thorn;-outen ende;</L>
<L N="228">ffol he were &thorn;at nolde also. god he<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> om.</NOTE> me sone hyne sende."</L>
<L>Men casten hire in &thorn;e se&thorn;ing water. &thorn;ar-Inne al ny&yogh;t &yogh;e see&thorn;;</L>
<L>&THORN;e lengere &yogh;e &thorn;er-inne sat, &thorn;e fer&thorn;ere &yogh;e was hire dee&thorn;;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;e welmes &yogh;e sat &yogh; pleyde, &yogh; prechede of godes grace.</L>
<L N="232">Mo &thorn;an four hondred be-come cristene in &thorn;at place.</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iustise sey &thorn;at he my&yogh;tte in swich de&thorn; hire quelle naut :</L>
<L>he het of smyte hire heued, &thorn;at &yogh;e were to de&thorn;e i-brout.</L>
<L>&THORN;e quellere hire smot wi&thorn; al his mayn &thorn;re si&thorn;e in &thorn;e swere,</L>
<L N="236">he ne smot it nat fulliche of, hire de&thorn; was bouth to dere!
<PB REF="00000544.tif" N="496"></L>
<L>No quellere ne moste be &thorn;ulke daye smyte oftere &thorn;an &thorn;rie;<MILESTONE N="233b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>half-slawe he leuede hire so; a-weyward he gan hye.</L>
<L>Nou an yuel stede gon he mote, for he was a schrewe!</L>
<L N="240">Wo dede he &thorn;at holy mayde, gulteles hire so to hewe,</L>
<L>&YOGH; bi-lefte<NOTE PLACE="marg1"><I>al.</I> beleue</NOTE> hire so half a-lyue; welle, wo him be!</L>
<L>ffor who-so nuste of no doel, &thorn;er men my&yogh;tte it se :</L>
<L>&THORN;is holi mayde &yogh;ede a-boute, hire heued half of-smyte,</L>
<L N="244">&YOGH; was half quik &yogh; half ded, &thorn;at rew&thorn;e it was to wyte;</L>
<L>&YOGH; pouere men mechel of hire good &yogh;e delde wi&thorn; hire honde&mdash;</L>
<L>It was a wel fair grace of god &thorn;at &yogh;e aut my&yogh;tte stonde.</L>
<L>&YOGH;e prechede, &yogh; to Ihesu cryst many a god man wende,</L>
<L N="248">&YOGH; alle to seint vrban &thorn;e bisschop to bapti&yogh;e &yogh;e hem sende,</L>
<L>&YOGH; bad &thorn;at he scholde hire hous &thorn;at &yogh;e hadde woned Inne</L>
<L>halewen in oure louerdes name &yogh; a churche &thorn;er bigynne,</L>
<L>And burien &thorn;ere hire swete body, &yogh; &thorn;at oure louerdes seruise</L>
<L N="252">Vpe his poer &thorn;er-inne were i-do on alle-kynne wyse.</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde day after hire martirdom &thorn;e mayde a-doun lay,</L>
<L>And prechede to &thorn;e cristenemen, &yogh; bad hem habbe god day,</L>
<L>&YOGH; seyde : "now ich habbe i-do al &thorn;at my wille is to,</L>
<L N="256">Wende I wile to Ihesu crist, &yogh; &yogh;e schulle also."</L>
<L>&THORN;is was two hundred &yogh;er &yogh; &thorn;re &yogh; twenti ry&yogh;th</L>
<L>After &thorn;at oure louer[d] was in his moder a-ly&yogh;th.</L>
<L>Nou bidde we oure swete louerd, for hire martirdom,</L>
<L N="260">To bringge vs to &thorn;at ioye &thorn;at hire soule to com.<NOTE PLACE="foot">After this there follows: 75. S. Alexius, in six-lined stanzas, ed. by me in <I>Herrig's Archiv</I>, 1873, and by Furnivall for the Early English Text Society, Original Series, no. 69.</NOTE>&mdash;Amen.</L>
</LG>
